{
  "1": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Inhabit - To Settle",
      "hw": "آباد",
      "s": "«اَسْکَنَ» is used for inhabiting another place. (7 verses: 2:35, 2:128, 7:19, 7:161, 17:104, 23:18, 65:6)",
      "d": "«اَسْکَنَ» means to take to a place and settle there.\nFor example, in the Quran regarding Prophet Ibrahim:\n«رَبَّنَآ اِنِّىْٓ اَسْكَنْتُ مِنْ ذُرِّيَّتِيْ بِوَادٍ غَيْرِ ذِيْ زَرْعٍ» (37/14)\nTranslation: O our Lord! I have settled my progeny in a valley without cultivation."
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Populate - To Settle",
      "hw": "آباد",
      "s": "«اٰوٰی» is used for taking refuge in a safe place to escape from danger. (10 verses: 8:72، 11:43، 11:80، 12:69، 12:99، 18:10، 18:63، 23:50، 28:45، 32:19)",
      "d": "«اٰوٰی» means to give someone a place to reside, to grant shelter. Its original root is «اَوَی», meaning to join and become attached to someone (masc.) so that one may attain safety from danger.\nAs the Quran narrates the story of the People of the Cave, they hid in a cave due to fear of the oppressive polytheist regime.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِذْ اَوَى الْفِتْيَةُ اِلَى الْكَهْفِ» (18/10)\nTranslation: When the young men took refuge in the cave.\nSimilarly, when Prophet Noah (peace be upon him) called his disbelieving son to believe and board the ship to be saved from the flood, his son replied as the Quran recounts:\n«سَاٰوِيْٓ اِلٰي جَبَلٍ يَّعْصِمُنِيْ مِنَ الْمَاۗءِ» (11:43)\nTranslation: I will take refuge on a mountain; it will save me from the water.\nIn the chapter of 'Af'al' (Verbs), 'Iwa' specifically means to give someone a place to stay and settle them.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِيْنَ اٰمَنُوْا وَهَاجَرُوْا وَجٰهَدُوْا بِاَمْوَالِهِمْ وَاَنْفُسِهِمْ فِيْ سَبِيْلِ اللّٰهِ وَالَّذِيْنَ اٰوَوْا وَّنَــصَرُوْٓا اُولٰۗىِٕكَ بَعْضُهُمْ اَوْلِيَاۗءُ بَعْضٍ» (8:72)\nTranslation: Those who believed, emigrated, and strove with their wealth and lives in the cause of Allah, and those who gave shelter and aided them—they are allies of one another."
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Inhabit - To Settle",
      "hw": "آباد",
      "s": "« بَوَّا» is used for inhabiting in a suitable environment. (3 verses: 7:74, 10:93, 22:26)",
      "d": "« بَوَّا» means to settle someone according to their nature and preference.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ بَوَّاْنَا بَنِيْٓ اِسْرَاۗءِيْلَ مُبَوَّاَ صِدْقٍ وَّرَزَقْنٰھُمْ مِّنَ الطَّيِّبٰتِ» (10:93)\nTranslation: And We settled the Children of Israel in a truthful settlement and provided them with good things."
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Be Inhabited (To Reside) - To Live",
      "hw": "آباد",
      "s": "«تَبَوَّا» is used for inhabiting in a favorable and suitable environment. (5 verses: 10:87, 12:56, 39:74, 41:24, 59:9)",
      "d": "The original root of «تَبَوَّا» is «بوء». Its meaning encompasses two aspects:\n(1) Returning to a place, and (2) Being established and settled permanently (Lane's Lexicon). This word is used when the climate and environment of a residential location are agreeable and suitable for the inhabitant, or when a person chooses a residential place for a specific purpose that is fitting for that aim.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَكَذٰلِكَ مَكَّنَّا لِيُوْسُفَ فِي الْاَرْضِ ۚ يَتَبَوَّاُ مِنْهَا حَيْثُ يَشَاۗءُ» (12:56)\nTranslation: And thus, We established Joseph in the land; he could reside wherever he willed in it.\nSimilarly, the Quran addresses the Prophet (peace be upon him):\n«وَاِذْ غَدَوْتَ مِنْ اَھْلِكَ تُبَوِّئُ الْمُؤْمِنِيْنَ مَقَاعِدَ لِلْقِتَالِ» (3:121)\nTranslation: And when you left your household in the morning to post the believers at their stations for battle.\nThis means he would assign each person to specific positions based on the circumstances of the battle and its location."
    },
    {
      "id": 7,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Be Inhabited (To Reside) - To Live",
      "hw": "آباد",
      "s": "«خَلَدَ» means to take up residence in a place for a long duration where no change or corruption occurs. (84 verses: 2:25, 2:39, 2:81, 2:82, 2:162, 2:217, 2:257, 2:275, 3:15, 3:88, 3:107, 3:116, 3:136, 3:198, 4:13, 4:14, 4:57, 4:93, 4:122, 4:169, 5:80, 5:85, 5:119, 6:128, 7:20, 7:36, 7:42, 9:17, 9:22, 9:63, 9:68, 9:72, 9:89, 9:100, 10:26, 10:27, 10:52, 11:23, 11:107, 11:108, 13:5, 14:23, 16:29, 18:108, 20:76, 20:101, 20:120, 21:8, 21:34, 21:99, 21:102, 23:11, 23:103, 25:15, 25:16, 25:69, 25:76, 26:129, 29:58, 31:9, 32:14, 33:65, 39:72, 39:73, 40:76, 41:28, 43:71, 43:74, 46:14, 47:15, 48:5, 56:17, 57:12, 58:17, 58:22, 59:17, 64:9, 64:10, 65:11, 72:23, 76:19, 98:6, 98:8, 104:3)",
      "d": "«خَلَدَ» means to remain in a place for a long time where no alteration (i.e., change) and corruption occur (masc.).\nFor example, Allah addresses the people of Paradise:\n«وَلَھُمْ فِيْهَآ اَزْوَاجٌ مُّطَهَّرَةٌ وَّھُمْ فِيْهَا خٰلِدُوْنَ» (25:2)\nTranslation: And they will have therein purified spouses, and they will abide therein forever."
    },
    {
      "id": 8,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Be Inhabited (To Reside) - To Live",
      "hw": "آباد",
      "s": "«سَکَنَ» is used for coming from another place to become inhabited. (14 verses: 2:35, 6:13, 7:19, 7:161, 14:14, 14:37, 14:45, 16:80, 17:104, 23:18, 28:58, 34:15, 42:33, 65:6)",
      "d": "«سَکَنَ» is the opposite of 'disturbance' (restlessness) and 'movement'. Therefore, when used in the sense of inhabiting, it means 'to become a resident after coming from another place'.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«يٰٓاٰدَمُ اسْكُنْ اَنْتَ وَزَوْجُكَ الْجَنَّةَ» (2:35)\nTranslation: O Adam, dwell, you and your wife, in Paradise.\nThis implies their creation occurred in a place other than Paradise.\nSimilarly, when Prophet Abraham (peace be upon him) brought Hagar and Ishmael (peace be upon them) to Mecca, he said:\n«رَبَّنَآ اِنِّىْٓ اَسْكَنْتُ مِنْ ذُرِّيَّتِیْ» (14:37)\nTranslation: Our Lord, I have settled some of my descendants here."
    },
    {
      "id": 9,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Inhabit (to settle) - to reside",
      "hw": "آباد",
      "s": "«عَاشَرَ» is used to mean living together with one's family (1 verse: 4:19)",
      "d": "«عَاشَرَ» is derived from the root «عَشَرَ». It has two primary meanings:\nThe first meaning of «عَشَرَ» is the number 'ten'. The second meaning is mixing and intermingling (i.e., living together) and intervening. From this, the word «عَشِیْرَۃٌ» is derived, meaning 'tribe', and «عَاشَرَ» means to live together as a single clan or family.\nFor example: In the Quran, men who have complaints against their wives are commanded:\n«وَعَاشِرُوْھُنَّ بِالْمَعْرُوْفِ» (4:19)\nTranslation: And live with them in kindness."
    },
    {
      "id": 10,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Populate - To Settle",
      "hw": "آباد",
      "s": "«عَمَرَ» is used for populating land, constructing and inhabiting dwellings, and increasing prosperity. (5 verses: 9:17, 9:18, 11:61, 28:45, 30:9)",
      "d": "The word «عَمَرَ» means to build dwellings, increase prosperity, and populate barren and uninhabited land. According to Ibn al-Faris, its meaning also includes 'continuance' (i.e., perpetuity) and a long duration. 'Age' (عمر) is the period during which the soul remains inhabited with the body.\nThe opposite of «عَمَرَ» is «خَرَبَ», which means to ruin dwellings or fields, to lay waste, and to make uninhabited and desolate.\nFor example, the Prophet (peace be upon him) mentioned signs of the nearness of the Hour, among which is: «مَسَاجِدُھَا عَامِرَۃٌ وَّھِیَ خَرَابٌ مِّنَ الْھُدٰی»\nMeaning: At that time, mosques will be inhabited but desolate in terms of guidance.\nAnother example from the Quran:\n«اِنَّمَا يَعْمُرُ مَسٰجِدَ اللّٰهِ مَنْ اٰمَنَ بِاللّٰهِ وَالْيَوْمِ الْاٰخِرِ» (9:18)\nTranslation: Only he will populate the mosques of Allah who believes in Allah and the Last Day.\nSimilarly, elsewhere:\n«كَانُوْٓا اَشَدَّ مِنْهُمْ قُوَّةً وَّاَثَارُوا الْاَرْضَ وَعَمَرُوْهَآ اَكْثَرَ مِمَّا عَمَرُوْهَا» (30:9)\nTranslation: They were greater in strength than them and more productive in the land, and they had populated it more than they (the latter) have populated it."
    }
  ],
  "2": [
    {
      "id": 12,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Hereafter",
      "hw": "Hereafter",
      "s": "«یَوْمُ الْاٰخِرَ» refers to the Day of Judgment when people will be resurrected for account and recompense (26 verses: 2:8-2:62-2:126-2:177-2:228-2:232-2:264-3:114-4:38-4:39-4:59-4:136-4:162-5:69-9:18-9:19-9:29-9:44-9:45-9:99-24:2-29:36-33:21-58:22-60:6-65:2)",
      "d": "«یَوْمُ الْاٰخِرَ» does not refer to an ordinary day of this world, which is 24 hours long or which is spoken of in contrast to night, like day and night.\nRather, it refers to the long and unending period of the life of the Hereafter.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّ رَبَّکُمُ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ فِیۡ سِتَّۃِ اَیَّامٍ» (7:54)\nTranslation: Indeed, your Lord is Allah, who created the heavens and the earth in six days.\nThis is clear. The concept of a 'day' as we know it, which arises from the existence of the sun, cannot even be conceived before the creation of the earth and the heavens."
    },
    {
      "id": 13,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Akhirah",
      "hw": "Hereafter",
      "s": "«Yawm al-Ba'th» (the Day of Resurrection) is the day when the dead will be resurrected, referring to the Day of Judgment (1 Ayah: 30:56).",
      "d": "«Al-Yawm al-Ba'th»: Ba'th means to rise from graves for a specific purpose. Since the long era of the Akhirah will begin with this very «Ba'th», it is also called «Yawm al-Ba'th».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«Laqad labiṡtum fī kitābillāhi ilā yawm al-ba'th» (56/3)\nTranslation: Indeed, you remained in the Book of Allah until the «Day of Resurrection»."
    },
    {
      "id": 14,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Akhirah",
      "hw": "Hereafter",
      "s": "«Al-Akhirah» is generally used for the Day of Judgment, on which all humans will be resurrected and judged according to their deeds, and then granted eternal life (105 Ayahs: 2:4-2:86-2:102-2:114-2:130-2:200-2:201-2:217-2:220-3:22-3:45-3:56-3:72-3:77-3:85-3:145-3:148-3:152-3:176-4:74-4:77-4:134-5:5-5:33-5:41-6:92-6:113-6:150-7:45-7:147-7:156-8:67-9:38-9:69-9:74-10:64-11:16-11:19-11:22-11:103-12:37-12:57-12:101-13:26-13:34-14:3-14:27-16:22-16:41-16:60-16:107-16:109-16:122-17:7-17:10-17:19-17:21-17:45-17:72-17:104-20:127-22:11-22:15-23:33-23:74-24:14-24:19-24:23-27:3-27:4-27:5-27:66-28:70-29:20-29:27-30:7-30:16-31:4-33:57-34:1-34:8-34:21-38:7-39:9-39:26-39:45-40:39-40:43-41:7-41:16-41:31-42:20-43:35-53:25-53:27-57:20-59:3-60:13-68:33-74:53-75:21-79:25-87:17-92:13-93:4).",
      "d": "«Al-Akhirah» means «Dar al-Baqa» (the Abode of Eternity). (M, M. Manjad) i.e., after death, the body and soul will be reunited, humans will be resurrected, and granted an eternal, never-ending life wherein there will be no death. The righteous and the wicked will be admitted to Paradise or Hell according to their deeds.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«Wa bil-ākhirati hum yūqinūn» (4/2)\nTranslation: And they (the believers) are certain about the Hereafter.\nHere, the Hereafter refers to this very type of life. In this sense, its opposites in the Noble Quran are («Al-Ājilah», «Al-Dunyā», «Al-Adnā», «Al-Ulā») all of which are used."
    },
    {
      "id": 15,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Akhirah",
      "hw": "Hereafter",
      "s": "«Dar al-Akhirah» refers to the home whose fate will be decided on the Day of Judgment based on a person's good or bad deeds, and in which they will reside forever (9 Ayahs: 2:94-6:32-7:169-12:109-16:30-28:77-28:83-29:64-33:29).",
      "d": "«Dar al-Akhirah»: Dar means a place of residence, i.e., a home. Its plural is Diyar, and its opposite is Dar. Its meaning is very broad. For example, Dar can mean a home, a mansion, a region, a homeland, a country, or even the entire world, which is Dar al-Dunya (the Abode of the World) as a place of human residence. Its opposite is Dar al-Akhirah. However, in the life of the Hereafter, every person will be given a Dar, i.e., a place of residence, according to their deeds.\nFor example, regarding the righteous, the Divine Command states:\n«Wa la-niʿma dar al-muttaqīn» (30/16)\nTranslation: And excellent is the abode (Paradise) of the pious.\nSimilarly, regarding the disbelievers, the Divine Command states:\n«Alam tara ilā alladhīna baddalū niʿmatallāhi kufran wa aḥallū qawmahum dar al-bawār—jahannam yaṣlawnahā, wa bi'sa al-qarār» (14:28-29)\nTranslation: Have you not seen those who exchanged the favor of Allah for disbelief and led their people to the abode of ruin? It is Hell, wherein they will burn, and evil is that destination.\n(Bad home and evil destination) both refer to Hell."
    },
    {
      "id": 16,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "The Hereafter",
      "hw": "Hereafter",
      "s": "‘Dar al-Qarar’ refers to the good abode that Allah will grant to the believers in return for their righteous deeds, i.e., Paradise (1 verse: 40:39).",
      "d": "‘Dar al-Qarar’ means a place of settling, derived from ‘qarar’ meaning to settle. Since the life of the Hereafter is eternal and everlasting, it is called Dar al-Qarar. However, the term is used positively, referring to the abode of the righteous, i.e., Paradise. For disbelievers, the Quran uses the phrase ‘bi’s al-qarar’ (an evil abode) in Surah 14, verse 29, referring to Hell. The term ‘yawm’ (day) here does not refer to an ordinary 24-hour day or the day as opposed to night, but rather the long, eternal period of the Hereafter. For example, the Quran states: ‘Indeed, your Lord is Allah, who created the heavens and the earth in six days.’ (54 / 7) This is clear. The concept of a day before the creation of the earth and heavens, which comes with the existence of the sun, cannot be conceived."
    }
  ],
  "3": [
    {
      "id": 17,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Man (Human Being)",
      "hw": "انسان",
      "s": "«اٰدَمَ» commonly refers to the first human, Prophet Adam (peace be upon him). However, the word (اَدَمْ) is also used to mean 'of the same kind' and 'of the same nature'. (25 verses: 2:31, 2:33, 2:34, 2:35, 2:37, 3:33, 3:59, 5:27, 7:11, 7:19, 7:26, 7:27, 7:31, 7:35, 7:172, 17:61, 17:70, 18:50, 19:58, 20:115, 20:116, 20:117, 20:120, 20:121, 36:60)",
      "d": "The original root of «اٰدَمَ» is «اَدَمْ», meaning 'agreement' and 'compatibility'—that is, having the same nature and temperament (masc.). «اَدَام» refers to anything that is soft and pliable (Majma' al-Bayan). Evidence for this is the saying of the Prophet (peace be upon him) to Mu'adh ibn Jabal (may Allah be pleased with him) regarding a marriage proposal: «لَوْ نَظَرْتَ إِلَيْهَا فَإِنَّهُ أَحْرَى أَنْ يُؤْدَمَ بَيْنَكُمَا» meaning: 'If you look at her, it is more likely that affection and harmony will develop between you.' (Sunan al-Nasa'i; Hadith no. 3237)\nBesides this, other evidences are cited, but the correct evidence is this one because it is supported by Hadith.\nAdam: Abu al-Bashar, the name of Prophet Adam (peace be upon him). However, 'Adam' can also be used for his progeny (Majma' al-Bayan). Hence, 'Bani Adam' refers to all of humanity.\nMoreover, wherever 'Adam' or 'Bani Adam' is mentioned in the Quran, it relates to the history of humankind.\nFor example: Adam's creation from clay, the angels' prostration to Adam, humanity's honor as the best of creation, the covenant of 'Alast' (i.e., the pledge Allah took from Adam and his children in the world of spirits), Satan's misguidance of Adam and Bani Adam, and his dialogue with Allah, etc."
    },
    {
      "id": 18,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Human (Human Being)",
      "hw": "انسان",
      "s": "‘Ins’ is used when referring to the social aspect of human life (i.e., living together), and words derived from it are employed. When referring to the historical aspect, ‘Adam’ and ‘Bani Adam’ are used. When referring to the natural and innate aspect, the word ‘Bashar’ is used (16 verses: 6:112-6:128-6:130-7:38-7:179-27:17-41:25-41:29-46:18-51:56-55:33-55:39-55:56-55:74-72:5-72:6).",
      "d": "‘Ins’ (plural ‘Unas’) refers to groups of people who are distinct from each other due to tribe, family, or other reasons. For example, the Quran states: ‘Every group has recognized its watering place.’ (60:2) And ‘anasi’ refers to a very large group of people. For example, the Divine declaration: ‘We have created cattle and numerous humans.’ (49:25)"
    },
    {
      "id": 19,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Human (Insaan)",
      "hw": "انسان",
      "s": "«بَشَرَ» (Bashar) generally refers to a human being, though it is also used for the outer surface of the skin (38 verses: 3:47-3:79-5:18-6:91-11:27-12:31-14:10-14:11-15:28-15:33-16:103-17:93-17:94-18:110-19:17-19:20-19:26-21:3-21:34-22:72-23:24-23:33-23:34-23:47-25:54-26:154-26:186-30:20-36:15-38:71-41:6-42:51-54:24-64:6-74:25-74:29-74:31-74:36)",
      "d": "The fundamental meanings of «بَشَرَ» are for something to appear with its beauty and excellence (m. l.), while «اُنْس» means merely to appear.\nAnd «اَلْبَشَرَۃَ» refers to the outer surface of human skin.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَوَّاحَۃٌ  لِّلۡبَشَرِ» (74:29)\nTranslation: The fire of Hell will scorch the skin and turn it black.\nIts plural forms are «بَشَرٌ» and «اَبْشَارٌ». A human is called 'Bashar' because, compared to other animals, its skin is remarkably clean, smooth, and free from wool, hair, etc. (muf).\nThe word 'Bashar' is used for singular, plural, masculine, and feminine. However, if referring to two humans, it is «بَشَرَیْن».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَنُؤۡمِنُ لِبَشَرَیۡنِ مِثۡلِنَا» (23:47)\nTranslation: Should we believe in two humans like ourselves?\nThe term 'Bashar' is used when the intention is to mention a human's physical and material aspects, their bodily constitution, natural needs, and weaknesses. As is clear from the verse mentioned above.\nIn contrast to 'Bashar' is the term «مَلَک» (i.e., angel), which is free from material aspects, meaning external physical and natural needs. The disbelievers' constant objection was: How can we believe in a human, just like us, who is born and dies, eats and drinks, walks in the markets, and fulfills his needs just as we do? What preference does he have over us that we should believe in him? But if there were an angel, free from such needs and necessities, that would be a different matter.\nIn the following verses, Allah Almighty has answered this very objection:\n«وَ مَا مَنَعَ النَّاسَ اَنۡ یُّؤۡمِنُوۡۤا اِذۡ جَآءَہُمُ الۡہُدٰۤی اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ قَالُوۡۤا اَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ بَشَرًارَّسُوۡلًا .قُلۡ لَّوۡ کَانَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مَلٰٓئِکَۃٌ یَّمۡشُوۡنَ مُطۡمَئِنِّیۡنَ لَنَزَّلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ  السَّمَآءِ  مَلَکًا  رَّسُوۡلًا»\n(17:94-95)\nTranslation: And nothing prevented people from believing when guidance came to them except that they said, 'Has Allah sent a human as a messenger?' Say, 'If there were angels in the earth walking about in peace and security, We would have certainly sent down to them an angel as a messenger.'"
    }
  ],
  "4": [
    {
      "id": 20,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Rest / Find Comfort",
      "hw": "آرام",
      "s": "«اِرْتَفَقَ» (Irtafaqa) is used for such a state of rest where no other thing acts as an obstacle or causes disruption (2 verses: 18:29-18:31)",
      "d": "«اِرْتَفَقَ» (Irtafaqa) originates from the root «رَفَقَ» (Rafaqa). 'Rafaq' denotes mutual compatibility, contentment, agreement, unity, friendship, and closeness, free from ill-temper and harshness. Thereafter, anything that becomes a cause of comfort and contentment is called 'Rafaq'. Accordingly, «مِرْفَق» (Mirfaq) is also used for the knee, as one leans on it and feels comfort, and «مِرفَقَہ» (Mirfaqah) refers to a small cushion. «اِرْتِفَاق» (Irtifaq) is such companionship that causes comfort and compatibility, and «مَرْتَفَق» (Martafaq) is a place where comfort is available and nothing disrupts it.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«نِعۡمَ الثَّوَابُ ؕ وَ حَسُنَتۡ  مُرۡتَفَقًا» (18:31)\nTranslation: Excellent is the reward, and what an excellent place of comfort it is!"
    },
    {
      "id": 21,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Rest / Find Comfort",
      "hw": "آرام",
      "s": "«سَبَتَ» (Sabata) refers to a rest after which a person feels relief and tranquility (2 verses: 25:47-78:9)",
      "d": "«سَبَتَ» (Sabata) its fundamental meaning is relief and tranquility (m. l.), i.e., such a rest after which relief and peace are also attained (muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّجَعَلۡنَا نَوۡمَکُمۡ سُبَاتًا» (78:9)\nTranslation: And We have made your sleep a means of rest.\nMedical science research also confirms that the cells exhausted from a day's work are replenished during sleep. This is why, after a full night's sleep, a person wakes up refreshed and cheerful. This is precisely the meaning of «سَبَتَ»."
    },
    {
      "id": 22,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Rest",
      "hw": "آرام",
      "s": "«سَکَنَ» is used for physical and mental rest. (13 verses: 6:13-6:96-7:189-9:103-10:67-16:80-23:18-27:86-28:72-28:73-30:21-40:61-42:33)",
      "d": "«سَکَنَ» refers to the state of rest after movement and agitation, i.e., restlessness (m l), and the word 'sukun' is used in both external and internal meanings, such as for resting after physical fatigue.\nFor example, the Quran says: «مَنۡ اِلٰہٌ غَیۡرُاللّٰہِ یَاۡتِیۡکُمۡ بِلَیۡلٍ تَسۡکُنُوۡنَ فِیۡہِ» (73/28). Translation: Which god other than Allah comes to you in the night in which you rest?\nAnd it is also used for attaining peace from mental thoughts. For example, the Quran says: «وَ صَلِّ عَلَیۡہِمۡ ؕ اِنَّ صَلٰوتَکَ سَکَنٌ لَّہُمۡ» (103/9). Translation: And send blessings upon them, for indeed your prayer is a source of tranquility for them."
    }
  ],
  "5": [
    {
      "id": 23,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Desire - To Desire",
      "hw": "آرزو",
      "s": "«اَمَل» apparently refers to an unexpected and long-awaited desire. (3 verses: 15:3-18:46-47:25)",
      "d": "«اَمَل» refers to such a desire and hope whose fulfillment is possible but difficult. Hence, Ibn Faris has defined its meaning as 'persistence and waiting' (m-l). That is, to keep hoping for a desire and wait for its completion, to remain desirous of seeing the springs of life, as a poet said in the desire for loyalty to his friend, which correctly interprets the meaning of «اَمَل»: 'Loyalty is a deception, the length of hope is nothing.'\nFor example, the Quran says: «ذَرۡہُمۡ یَاۡکُلُوۡاوَ یَتَمَتَّعُوۡا وَ یُلۡہِہِمُ الۡاَمَلُ  فَسَوۡفَ  یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ» (15/3). Translation: (O Prophet!) Let them be in their state, that they may eat and enjoy, and (the length of) hope keeps them occupied, soon they will know (the consequence)."
    },
    {
      "id": 24,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Desire - To Desire",
      "hw": "آرزو",
      "s": "«اُمْنِیَّۃ» is used for false and baseless desire (and the desire that has a basis is «رَجَاء»). (4 verses: 2:78-2:111-4:123-57:14)",
      "d": "«اُمْنِیَّۃ» is a desire that has no strong foundation. To form an idea based on good conjecture and then desire it (muf) – thus this word comes for false and baseless desires and expectations.\nFor example, the Quran says: «وَ قَالُوۡا لَنۡ یَّدۡخُلَ الۡجَنَّۃَ اِلَّا مَنۡ کَانَ ہُوۡدًا اَوۡ نَصٰرٰی ؕ تِلۡکَ اَمَانِیُّہُمۡ  ؕ قُلۡ ہَاتُوۡا بُرۡہَانَکُمۡ  اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰدِقِیۡنَ» (2/111). Translation: And they (Jews and Christians) say, 'None will enter Paradise except a Jew or a Christian.' These are their vain desires. (O Prophet!) Say to them, 'Bring your proof if you are truthful.'\nAt another place, the divine command states: «وَمِنۡہُمۡ اُمِّیُّوۡنَ لَا یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ الۡکِتٰبَ اِلَّاۤ اَمَانِیَّ وَ اِنۡ ہُمۡ  اِلَّا یَظُنُّوۡنَ» (2/78). Translation: And among them are unlettered ones who do not know the Book except through desires and they do nothing but conjecture.\nSome scholars have taken 'amanī' in this verse to mean the narrations they had included or altered in the religion themselves, and Mujahid interpreted 'except amanī' as 'except lies,' i.e., falsehood. And some have taken 'amanī' to mean reciting without understanding (muf), as this view is supported by some other verses, and 'tamannā' means to speak falsely, 'tamaniya al-rajul' means he spoke falsely. (m-q)\nFor example, the Quran says: «اَمْ لِلْاِنْسَانِ مَا تَمَنّٰى٘ۖ» (24/53). Translation: Is it that for man is whatever he wishes for?"
    },
    {
      "id": 25,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Desire - To Desire",
      "hw": "آرزو",
      "s": "«وَدّ» refers to the love and desire for anything. (25 verses: 2:96-2:105-2:109-2:266-3:30-3:69-3:118-4:42-4:73-4:89-4:102-5:82-11:90-15:2-19:96-29:25-30:21-33:20-42:23-60:1-60:2-60:7-68:9-70:11-85:14)",
      "d": "«وَدّ» has two basic meanings: (1) to love something (2) to desire its attainment. Then this word is sometimes used in both meanings and sometimes in one meaning only.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«رُبَمَا یَوَدُّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَوۡ کَانُوۡا مُسۡلِمِیۡنَ» (2 / 15)\nTranslation: At times, the disbelievers may wish that they had been Muslims.\nIn this verse, both aspects are present.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ سَیَجۡعَلُ  لَہُمُ  الرَّحۡمٰنُ  وُدًّا» (96 / 19)\nTranslation: And those who believe and do righteous deeds, the Most Merciful will instill love (in the hearts of His creation) for them.\nIn this verse, only the first meaning is found.\nAlso see 'Desire'."
    }
  ],
  "6": [
    {
      "id": 26,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Barrier",
      "hw": "Barrier",
      "s": "«بَرْزَخ» refers to a third thing between two things, in which the characteristics of both are equally or somewhat present, and it serves as an obstacle. (3 verses: 23:100-25:53-55:20)",
      "d": "«بَرْزَخ» is a term for something that acts as a barrier between two things. When there is considerable space between the two things, this barrier is called barzakh. For example, the interval between this world and the hereafter, or the period between death and resurrection is called barzakh. However, Ibn al-Faris added the condition of 'considerable space', which is not correct because the Quran does not support it.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«مَرَجَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ یَلۡتَقِیٰنِ ، بَیۡنَہُمَا بَرۡزَخٌ  لَّا  یَبۡغِیٰنِ» (20 / 55)\nTranslation: He has released the two seas, meeting together. Between them is a barrier, which they do not transgress.\nHowever, if instead of 'considerable open space', we say 'considerable difference', it would be better.\nBarzakh is essentially a third thing between two things that also serves as a barrier, but in this third thing, i.e., barzakh, the characteristics of both things are present, whether one's characteristic is more or equal to the other's. The same is the case with the world of barzakh: for a believer, it is a place of comfort and peace in the grave, and for a disbeliever, the same grave is a place of punishment and affliction, but this comfort or punishment is of a lower degree than the hereafter.\nAnd the barzakh between two rivers is such that if one stream is warm and the other cold, then the water of this barzakh will be moderate, i.e., in between. Similarly, if one side is sweet water and the other bitter and salty, then the water of this barzakh will be of an intermediate quality."
    },
    {
      "id": 27,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Barrier",
      "hw": "Barrier",
      "s": "«حِجْر» is used for a barrier that protects something from other things. (3 verses: 6:138, 25:22, 25:53)",
      "d": "«حِجْر» generally means 'stone', which is hard and solid. Then, 'hijr' refers to anything that is hard and serves as a barrier or protection that can separate one thing from others (masc.). According to Ibn al-Faris, its meaning is: 'prohibition and encompassing something' (Lane's Lexicon).\nDrawing a fence around a village for protection, surrounding with stones, enclosing with a fort or mansion—all these fall under the meaning of 'hijr'.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یَوۡمَ یَرَوۡنَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃَ  لَا بُشۡرٰی یَوۡمَئِذٍ لِّلۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ حِجۡرًا مَّحۡجُوۡرًا» (25:22)\nTranslation: The Day they see the angels—no good news for the criminals that Day—and they will say, 'A barrier, a [full] barrier!' (Jalandhari)\nAnd Tafsir Uthmani translates it as: 'May you be barred and sealed off.'\nThe phrase «حِجْرًا مَّحجُوْرًا» was used by the Arabs metaphorically when an enemy or calamity was about to befall, like we say 'May Allah protect from it.' Then, the listener usually did not suffer any harm.\nThen, 'hijr' is also used for a mind that rejects false and invalid theories and nonsense. Thus, such a cautious mind that takes its own precaution is also called 'hijr'.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n« ہَلۡ فِیۡ ذٰلِکَ قَسَمٌ  لِّذِیۡ حِجۡرٍ» (25:53)\nTranslation: Is this [not] a sufficient oath for one of understanding?\nThen, 'hijr' is also used for something prohibited, impermissible, and forbidden.\nFor example, the Divine declaration is:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا ہٰذِہٖۤ  اَنۡعَامٌ  وَّ حَرۡثٌ حِجۡرٌ ٭ۖ لَّا یَطۡعَمُہَاۤ اِلَّا مَنۡ نَّشَآءُ بِزَعۡمِہِمۡ» (6:138)\nTranslation: And they say, 'These animals and crops are forbidden; none may eat them except whom we will,' according to their claim."
    },
    {
      "id": 29,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Hadd",
      "hw": "Barrier",
      "s": "«Hadd» refers to the ultimate limit and final edge of anything that prevents it from merging with other things (9 verses: 2:187-2:229-2:230-4:13-4:14-9:97-9:112-58:4-65:1)",
      "d": "«Hadd» its origin is «Hurr» and in its root two things are found: (1) to be free (2) to be pure from defects and shortcomings (m l). The opposite of «Hurr» is «Abd» meaning slave. And «Harra, Tahreeran» means to free a slave, so this word is specifically for freeing a slave."
    }
  ],
  "7": [
    {
      "id": 31,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to free",
      "hw": "Free",
      "s": "The word «Tahreeran» is specifically used for freeing a slave (3 verses: 4:92-5:89-58:3)",
      "d": "«Tahreeran» its origin is «Hurr» and in its root two things are found: (1) to be free (2) to be pure from defects and shortcomings (m l). The opposite of «Hurr» is «Abd» meaning slave. And «Harra, Tahreeran» means to free a slave, so this word is specifically for freeing a slave."
    },
    {
      "id": 32,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "free",
      "hw": "Free",
      "s": "«Hurr» means free in contrast to slave (2 verses: 2:178-3:35)",
      "d": "«Hurr» means free (its opposite is «Abd» meaning slave) i.e., a person who is not a slave."
    },
    {
      "id": 33,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Unrestrained",
      "hw": "Free",
      "s": "«Suddi» refers to an untethered camel upon which there is no restriction (1 verse: 75:36).",
      "d": "«Suddi al-Naqah» means the she-camel took wide steps in her gait, and 'Saadi' refers to that she-camel which takes open, wide steps (Munjid). And «Suddi» means an untethered camel upon which there is no restriction. For example, the Quran states:\n«اَیَحۡسَبُ  الۡاِنۡسَانُ اَنۡ یُّتۡرَکَ سُدًی» (36 / 75)\nTranslation: Does man think that he will be left unrestrained? (Uthmani)"
    }
  ],
  "8": [
    {
      "id": 38,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To test",
      "hw": "Test",
      "s": "«Fatana» means trial/test, and this generally occurs through things to which humans have emotional attachment (54 verses: 2:102-2:191-2:193-2:217-3:7-4:91-4:101-5:41-5:49-5:71-6:53-7:27-7:155-8:25-8:28-8:39-8:73-9:47-9:48-9:49-9:126-10:83-10:85-16:110-17:60-17:73-20:40-20:85-20:90-20:131-21:35-21:111-22:11-22:53-24:63-25:20-27:47-29:2-29:3-29:10-33:14-37:63-38:24-38:34-39:49-44:17-51:14-54:27-57:14-60:5-64:15-72:17-74:31-85:10).",
      "d": "«Fatana» means to melt silver and gold in a crucible (Munjid). Like «ibtila'», this test also involves hardship. For example, the Quran states:\n«یَوۡمَ ہُمۡ عَلَی النَّارِ یُفۡتَنُوۡنَ» (13 / 51)\nTranslation: On that day, they will be tested with fire.\nAnd the word «fitnah» is often used in a negative sense. The meanings of fitnah include trial, hardship, disgrace, madness, lesson, punishment, disease; it is used in all these meanings (Munjid). Similarly, «fattan» means an evil human, thief, or devil (Munjid). Whereas in «ibtila'», a person's test does not arise due to personal evil and malice. The difference between «ibtila'» and «fitnah» is completely clear. In «ibtila'», the negative aspect generally relates to natural events, while in «fitnah», the negative aspect is often a human-created situation. For example, the Quran states:\n«اِلَّا تَفۡعَلُوۡہُ تَکُنۡ فِتۡنَۃٌ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ فَسَادٌ کَبِیۡرٌ» (73 / 8)\nTranslation: O believers! If you do not do it, fitnah will break out in the land and great corruption will occur.\nThe difference between «ibtila'» and «fitnah» is that «fitnah» generally involves trials through things to which a person is attached and has emotional affection (M.R.). For example, the Quran states:\n«وَاعۡلَمُوۡۤا اَنَّمَاۤ اَمۡوَالُکُمۡ  وَ اَوۡلَادُکُمۡ  فِتۡنَۃٌ» (28 / 8)\nTranslation: And know that your wealth and children are a great trial.\nA strong evidence for this is in Surah Al-Baqarah, where mentioning Harut and Marut, it is said:\n«وَ مَا یُعَلِّمٰنِ مِنۡ أَحَدٍ حَتّٰی یَقُوۡلَاۤ اِنَّمَا نَحۡنُ فِتۡنَۃٌ فَلَا تَکۡفُرۡ» (102 / 2)\nTranslation: They do not teach anyone until they say: 'Indeed, we are a trial, so do not disbelieve.'\nAnd this disbelief was the desire for magic in which those people were engrossed. That very desire is referred to as «fitnah».\nNote: (A clay-made cup-like vessel used for melting silver, gold, etc., is called a crucible)."
    }
  ],
  "9": [
    {
      "id": 39,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Easy",
      "hw": "Easy",
      "s": "«Hayyin» refers to a matter or action that is very minor compared to the power and capability of the negligent one (2 verses: 19:9-19:21).",
      "d": "«Hayyin» its root is «han». which includes ease as well as softness (M.R.) provided that this softness does not involve contempt or disrespect. Rather, along with softness, it includes serenity and dignity, and this attribute is praiseworthy. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَعِبَادُ  الرَّحۡمٰنِ الَّذِیۡنَ  یَمۡشُوۡنَ عَلَی الۡاَرۡضِ ہَوۡنًا» (25/63)\nTranslation: And the servants of the Most Merciful are those who walk upon the earth modestly.\nAnd if this softness degrades someone, it becomes a matter of humiliation and disgrace, which is a blameworthy act, and for this, the word «huwn» is used. For example, the Quran states:\n«فَالۡیَوۡمَ تُجۡزَوۡنَ عَذَابَ الۡہُوۡنِ» (20 / 46)\nTranslation: So today you will be punished with the punishment of humiliation.\nTherefore, «hayyin» is an action that is completely trivial (light) compared to the doer's power and capability because its root meaning includes humility along with inferiority and humiliation. That is, a completely insignificant and trivial matter. Thus, in Surah Maryam, when the angel informed Maryam of the birth of a son without a father, she was astonished and said, which the Quran described as:\n«اَنّٰی یَکُوۡنُ لِیۡ غُلٰمٌ وَّ لَمۡ یَمۡسَسۡنِیۡ  بَشَرٌ وَّ لَمۡ اَکُ بَغِیًّا ، قَالَ کَذٰلِکِ ۚ قَالَ رَبُّکِ ہُوَعَلَیَّ ہَیِّنٌ» (21 - 20 / 19)\nTranslation: How can I have a son when no man has touched me, nor have I been unchaste? The angel said: Thus. Your Lord said: It is easy for Me."
    },
    {
      "id": 40,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Easy",
      "hw": "Easy",
      "s": "«يَسِيرٌ» means ease; it is a task that is accomplished with facility and convenience (13 verses: 4:30-4:169-12:65-22:70-29:19-33:19-33:30-35:11-50:44-57:22-64:7-74:10-84:8)",
      "d": "«يَسِيرٌ» its root is «یُسْر» which includes the meaning of ease and lightness (m l). And «یَسِیْر» is a task that is accomplished with facility and convenience. Its opposite is «عُسَیْر».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَمَنۡ یَّفۡعَلۡ ذٰلِکَ عُدۡوَانًا وَّ ظُلۡمًا فَسَوۡفَ نُصۡلِیۡہِ نَارًا ؕ وَ کَانَ ذٰلِکَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ یَسِیۡرًا» (4/30)\nTranslation: And whoever does that in transgression and injustice - We will surely burn him in the Fire. And that, for Allah, is easy."
    }
  ],
  "10": [
    {
      "id": 41,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sky",
      "hw": "Sky",
      "s": "«سَمَاء» its basic meaning is height, but there is no defined limit to this height (297 verses: 2:19-2:22-2:29-2:33-2:59-2:107-2:116-2:117-2:144-2:164-2:255-2:284-3:5-3:29-3:83-3:109-3:129-3:133-3:180-3:189-3:190-3:191-4:126-4:131-4:132-4:153-4:170-4:171-5:17-5:18-5:40-5:97-5:112-5:114-5:120-6:1-6:3-6:6-6:12-6:14-6:35-6:73-6:75-6:79-6:99-6:101-6:125-7:40-7:54-7:96-7:158-7:162-7:185-7:187-8:11-8:32-9:36-9:116-10:3-10:6-10:18-10:24-10:31-10:55-10:61-10:66-10:68-10:101-11:7-11:44-11:52-11:107-11:108-11:123-12:101-12:105-13:2-13:15-13:16-13:17-14:2-14:10-14:19-14:24-14:32-14:38-14:48-15:14-15:16-15:22-15:85-16:3-16:10-16:49-16:52-16:65-16:73-16:77-16:79-17:44-17:55-17:92-17:93-17:95-17:99-17:102-18:14-18:26-18:40-18:45-18:51-19:65-19:90-19:93-20:4-20:6-20:53-21:4-21:16-21:19-21:30-21:32-21:56-21:104-22:15-22:18-22:31-22:63-22:64-22:65-22:70-23:18-23:71-23:86-24:35-24:41-24:42-24:43-24:64-25:2-25:6-25:25-25:48-25:59-25:61-26:4-26:24-26:187-27:25-27:60-27:64-27:65-27:75-27:87-29:22-29:34-29:44-29:52-29:61-29:63-30:8-30:18-30:22-30:24-30:25-30:26-30:27-30:48-31:10-31:16-31:20-31:25-31:26-32:4-32:5-33:72-34:1-34:2-34:3-34:9-34:22-34:24-35:1-35:3-35:27-35:38-35:40-35:41-35:44-36:28-36:81-37:5-37:6-38:10-38:27-38:66-39:5-39:21-39:38-39:44-39:46-39:63-39:67-39:68-40:13-40:37-40:57-40:64-41:11-41:12-42:4-42:5-42:11-42:12-42:29-42:49-42:53-43:9-43:11-43:82-43:84-43:85-44:7-44:10-44:29-44:38-45:3-45:5-45:13-45:22-45:27-45:36-45:37-46:3-46:4-46:33-48:4-48:7-48:14-49:16-49:18-50:6-50:9-50:38-51:7-51:22-51:23-51:47-52:9-52:36-52:44-53:26-53:31-54:11-55:7-55:29-55:33-55:37-57:1-57:2-57:4-57:5-57:10-57:21-58:7-59:1-59:24-61:1-62:1-63:7-64:1-64:3-64:4-65:12-67:3-67:5-67:16-67:17-69:16-70:8-71:11-71:15-72:8-73:18-77:9-78:19-78:37-79:27-81:11-82:1-84:1-85:1-85:9-86:1-86:11-88:18-91:5)",
      "d": "«سَمَاء» and «سَمُوْء» fundamentally mean height, but there is no defined limit to this height. The scholar of lexical semantics has defined sky as: everything that is above us and casts a shadow upon us is sky (f l).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّ اَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً» (2/22)\nTranslation: And He sent down water from the sky.\nHere, 'sky' refers to clouds, which generally float at an altitude of about a mile and a half from the earth's surface. This relatively minor altitude is also referred to as 'sky'. At another instance, the Divine declaration is:\n«اِنَّا زَیَّنَّا السَّمَآءَ الدُّنۡیَا بِزِیۡنَۃِۣ الۡکَوَاکِبِ» (37/6)\nTranslation: Indeed, We have adorned the nearest heaven with an adornment of stars.\nHere, the intended height is that at which stars shine, whether it be hundreds of thousands of miles like the moon, or billions of miles like the sun, or even hundreds of billions of miles like the Scorpion, etc.\n«سَمَاء» is a relative noun, and its opposite is «اَرْض». That is, every thing is 'sky' from the perspective of what is beneath it, and that same thing is also 'earth' from the perspective of what is above it (m f). Thus, a thing that is 'sky' relative to what is beneath it is also 'earth' relative to what is above it.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ سَبۡعَ سَمٰوٰتٍ وَّ مِنَ الۡاَرۡضِ مِثۡلَہُنَّ» (65/12)\nTranslation: Allah is the One who created seven heavens and of the earth, the like thereof.\nIn this verse, these meanings are found.\nThen, just as 'sky' is used in the meaning of height, 'earth' is also used in the meaning of lowness.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ شِئۡنَا لَرَفَعۡنٰہُ بِہَا وَ لٰکِنَّہٗۤ اَخۡلَدَ اِلَی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ اتَّبَعَ ہَوٰىہُ» (7/176)\nTranslation: And if We willed, We could have elevated him thereby, but he adhered to the earth and followed his own desire."
    },
    {
      "id": 42,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Orbit",
      "hw": "Sky",
      "s": "«فَلَک» refers to the orbits (paths) of planets (2 verses: 21:33-36:40)",
      "d": "«فَلَک» generally means sky. But in reality, the orbits of planets in space or the paths in which celestial bodies revolve are called 'falak' (m r. m l. m f).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ الَّیۡلَ وَ النَّہَارَ وَ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ ؕ کُلٌّ فِیۡ فَلَکٍ یَّسۡبَحُوۡنَ» (21/33)\nTranslation: And He it is Who created the night and the day, the sun and the moon, each floating in an orbit.\nThe reason these paths are called 'falak' is that planets do not revolve in a perfect circle in space but assume an elliptical shape under certain laws of motion. Then, because of their ship-like form, they are called 'falak'. Such a ship is called 'fulk' in Arabic."
    },
    {
      "id": 945,
      "hw": "Hamd",
      "s": "«حَمْد» is praise and glorification from the tongue of Allah. (47 verses)",
      "d": "The word «حَمْد» is Arabic and its meanings are to praise and to glorify. It is one of the attributive names of Allah (SWT). Allah (SWT) is also called by the meaning of «حَمْد». The difference between «حَمْد» and «شُکر» is that «حَمْد» is praise by the tongue, while «شُکر» is gratitude by the heart for a favor.\nThe meanings of «حَمْد» include commendation, praise, and glorification.\nVerses: 1:1, 2:30, 3:144, 3:188, 6:1, 6:45, 7:43, 10:10, 13:13, 14:39, 15:98, 16:75, 17:44, 17:52, 17:111, 18:1, 20:130, 23:28, 25:58, 27:15, 27:59, 27:93, 28:70, 29:63, 30:18, 31:25, 32:15, 33:40, 34:1, 35:1, 35:34, 37:182, 39:29, 39:74, 39:75, 40:7, 40:55, 40:65, 42:5, 45:36, 47:2, 48:29, 50:39, 52:48, 61:6, 64:1, 110:3 (Total 47 verses)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَلۡحَمۡدُ لِلّٰہِ رَبِّ الْعٰلَمِیۡنَ» (1/1)\nTranslation: All praise is for Allah, Lord of the worlds.",
      "h": "to praise"
    }
  ],
  "11": [
    {
      "id": 43,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to afflict",
      "hw": "Jinn affliction",
      "s": "«اِعْتَرٰی» is used to mean afflicting someone with a physical illness. (1 verse: 11:54)",
      "d": "«اِعْتَرٰی» means to become naked, and «اَعْرٰی» means to strip someone of their clothes and make them naked. «اَعْرٰی فُلَانًا صَدِیْقَہ» means not to help someone and to abandon them. «عُرِیَ» means to be seized by the cold of fever and to shiver from fear. «عُرْوًا» means the cold of fever (menj). «اِعْتَرٰی» means to afflict someone with such a condition.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنۡ نَّقُوۡلُ  اِلَّا اعۡتَرٰىکَ بَعۡضُ اٰلِہَتِنَا بِسُوۡٓءٍ» (11/54)\nTranslation: (The people of Hud said) We only say that some of our deities have afflicted you with evil (driven you mad)."
    },
    {
      "id": 44,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Afflict (With Calamity)",
      "hw": "Jinn affliction",
      "s": "«تَخَبَّطَ» is used when an affliction (illness) is related to the mind. If the affliction (illness) is related to the body, the word «اعترٰی» is used. (1 verse: 2:275)",
      "d": "«خَبَطَ» means to beat someone repeatedly until they become bewildered (masc.). «مخبوط» means 'deficient in intellect', i.e., a person whose intellect does not function properly. According to the Arabs, this was associated with jinn and devils. They used to call a madman 'majnun' as well. That is, one who was afflicted by jinn and they had made him mad. The difference between 'majnun' and 'makhbūṭ' was that a person who became ill due to a deficiency of intellect was called 'majnun', while one who was afflicted temporarily and incidentally with this condition was called 'makhbūṭ'.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ یَاۡکُلُوۡنَ الرِّبٰوا لَا یَقُوۡمُوۡنَ اِلَّا کَمَا یَقُوۡمُ الَّذِیۡ یَتَخَبَّطُہُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ مِنَ الۡمَسِّ» (2:275)\nTranslation: Those who consume usury will not stand except as stands one whom the devil has driven to madness by [his] touch."
    }
  ],
  "12": [
    {
      "id": 47,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to burn (fire); to kindle",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«اَوْقَدَ» means to light a fire with fuel. (6 verses: 2:17, 5:64, 24:35, 28:38, 36:80, 104:6)",
      "d": "«وَقَدَ» means the blazing up of fire (menj). Ibn Faris stated its meaning as «کَلِمَۃٌ تَدُلُّ عَلیٰ اِشْتِعَالِ النَّار» (a word indicating the ignition of fire).\nWhereas «اَوْقَدَ» comes in the meaning of lighting a fire, when flames begin to appear.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَوۡقِدۡ لِیۡ یٰہَامٰنُ عَلَی الطِّیۡنِ فَاجۡعَلۡ  لِّیۡ صَرۡحًا» (28:38)\nTranslation: (Pharaoh said) O Haman! Light a fire for me upon the clay, then make for me a lofty palace.\n«اَوْقَدَ» is also used metaphorically.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ اَوۡقَدُوۡا  نَارًا لِّلۡحَرۡبِ اَطۡفَاَہَا اللّٰہُ» (5:64)\nTranslation: Whenever they kindle a fire for war, Allah extinguishes it.\nAnd «اِسْتَوْقَدَ» means to gather fuel, etc., and light a fire or lamp with great effort (muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَثَلُہُمۡ کَمَثَلِ الَّذِی اسۡتَوۡقَدَ نَارًا ۚ  فَلَمَّاۤ اَضَآءَتۡ مَا حَوۡلَہٗ ذَہَبَ اللّٰہُ بِنُوۡرِہِمۡ» (17:2)\nTranslation: Their example is like that of one who kindled a fire. Then when it illuminated what was around him, Allah took away their light."
    },
    {
      "id": 48,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to blaze (fire)",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«تَلَظّٰی» means when fire blazes intensely but without a flame. (2 verses: 70:15, 92:14)",
      "d": "«لَظٰی» refers to fire that is blazing but has no flame (f l 56). «لَظَّی النَّار» means to make fire blaze intensely, and «تَلَظّٰی» means for fire to blaze up.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَنۡذَرۡتُکُمۡ  نَارًا تَلَظّٰی» (92:14)\nTranslation: So I have warned you of a blazing fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 49,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "ember of fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«جِذْوَۃٌ» is an ember upon which ash has settled and its glow has ended. (1 verse: 28:29)",
      "d": "«جِذْوَۃٌ» is an ember upon which ash has settled and its glow has ended. (muf)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنِّیۡۤ  اٰنَسۡتُ نَارًا لَّعَلِّیۡۤ  اٰتِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا بِخَبَرٍ اَوۡ جَذۡوَۃٍ مِّنَ النَّارِ» (28:29)\nTranslation: Indeed, I have seen a fire, so I may bring you from it a report or a burning ember from the fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 50,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to burn (other things) with fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«حَرَّقَ» means to burn something with fire until it becomes ashes. (3 verses: 20:97, 21:68, 29:24)",
      "d": "«حَرَقَ» and «حَرَّقَ بِالنَّار» mean to burn something with fire until it is destroyed. «اِحْتَرَقَ» means for that thing to be burned and become ashes (muf) (this is the final stage).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡاحَرِّقُوۡہُ وَانۡصُرُوۡۤا اٰلِہَتَکُمۡ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ فٰعِلِیۡنَ» (21:68)\nTranslation: They said, 'Burn him and support your gods if you are to act.'\nAnother instance where the Lord's command is:\n«فَاَصَابَہَاۤ اِعۡصَارٌ فِیۡہِ نَارٌ فَاحۡتَرَقَتۡ» (2:266)\nTranslation: So a hurricane with fire struck it, and it burned (and became a heap of ashes)."
    },
    {
      "id": 51,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to extinguish and be extinguished (fire)",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«خَبَا» means the extinction of a flame and the settling of ash upon the ember. This is an intermediate state. (1 verse: 17:97)",
      "d": "«خَبَا» means for a fire's flame to become subdued and for ash to settle upon the coal or ember. (muf)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَا خَبَتۡ زِدۡنٰہُمۡ سَعِیۡرًا» (17:97)\nTranslation: Whenever its fire dies down, We will increase it with blazing fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 52,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to extinguish and be extinguished (fire)",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«خَمَدَ» means the extinction of a flame. (2 verses: 21:15, 36:29)",
      "d": "«خَمَدَ» refers to a fire becoming dim, where the flame is extinguished but the ember is not yet cold. «خَمِدَتِ الْحُمّٰی» means the intensity of fever subsiding. «خُمُوْد» also means coal (menj) and is metaphorically used for death (muf. m. q).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنۡ کَانَتۡ  اِلَّا صَیۡحَۃً وَّاحِدَۃً  فَاِذَا ہُمۡ خٰمِدُوۡنَ» (36:29)\nTranslation: Then it was not but a single blast, and suddenly they were extinguished (or dead)."
    },
    {
      "id": 53,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to blaze (fire); to intensify",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«سَجَّرَ» means to increase the intensity of a fire's blaze. (2 verses: 40:72, 81:6)",
      "d": "«سَجَّرَ» implies the filling of something and the presence of mixture or turmoil within it (m l). «سَجَّرَ الْتَّنُّوْر» means to fill the oven with fuel and heat it (menj) so that the fire can blaze with full intensity. Also, «سَجْر» refers to the sound of thunder and flash of lightning (menj).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ الۡبَحۡرِالۡمَسۡجُوۡرِ» (52:6)\nTranslation: And the blazing sea.\nThis means the sea is both full and boiling with turmoil. «سَجُوْر» refers to the fuel with which the oven is heated (menj). Thus, anything that is thrown into a fire to intensify it is called «سَجُوْر».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فِی الۡحَمِیۡمِ ۬ ۙ ثُمَّ  فِی النَّارِ  یُسۡجَرُوۡنَ» (40:72)\nTranslation: They will be thrown into scorching water, then into the Fire, where they will be intensely blazed."
    },
    {
      "id": 55,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Ember of fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«شِھَابٌ» A glowing, flaming ember (5 verses: 15:18-27:7-37:10-72:8-72:9)",
      "d": "«شِھَابٌ» refers to an ember that possesses both glow and flame, whether it is a fire ember or found in space (mufrad). Its plural is «شُہُب».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّاَنَّا لَمَسۡنَا السَّمَآءَ فَوَجَدۡنٰہَا مُلِئَتۡ حَرَسًا شَدِیۡدًا وَّشُہُبًا» (8/72)\nTranslation: (The jinn said) And indeed we touched the heaven and found it filled with severe guards and embers."
    },
    {
      "id": 57,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Burning other things with fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«صَھَرَ» Fire with such intense heat that it roasts meat and melts fat (1 verse: 22:20)",
      "d": "«صَھَرَ» means to heat and melt fat, etc., and «صَھَارَۃ» means melted substance. A piece of fat, the marrow of a bone, and «صَھُوْر» means one who melts or roasts meat (mufrad, manjad). Thus, «صَھَرَ» requires such intense heat as is needed to melt substances, especially fat, and to cook meat.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یُصَبُّ مِنۡ فَوۡقِ رُءُوۡسِہُمُ الۡحَمِیۡمُ ۔ یُصۡہَرُ  بِہٖ  مَا فِیۡ  بُطُوۡنِہِمۡ  وَ الۡجُلُوۡدُ» (22/19,20)\nTranslation: Scalding water will be poured over their heads. It will melt what is in their bellies and their skins."
    },
    {
      "id": 58,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Ember of fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«قَبَسٌ» A requested fire ember or flame (2 verses: 20:10-27:7)",
      "d": "«قَبَسٌ» means a requested fire ember or flame. For detailed explanation, see the entry for 'Lighting fire'."
    },
    {
      "id": 59,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Ignite Fire / To Burn",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«قَبَسَ» means to light fire from fire. (2 verses: 20:10, 27:7)",
      "d": "«قَبَسَ» means a spark of fire taken from a flame (masc.). It also means to take fire in the form of a flame. «قَبَس» means that flame which is taken from a large fire. And «قَابِس» means one who seeks fire. «قَبَسَہُ النَّار» means to bring fire for someone. «اَقْبَسَ فُلَانًا» means to give fire to someone (Majma' al-Bayan).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنِّیۡۤ اٰنَسۡتُ نَارًا لَّعَلِّیۡۤ  اٰتِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا بِقَبَسٍ  اَوۡ  اَجِدُ  عَلَی النَّارِ  ہُدًی» (20:10)\nTranslation: Indeed, I have seen a fire; perhaps I can bring you from it a torch or find at the fire some guidance.\nIn this verse, «قَبَس» comes in place of «جَذْوَۃٌ مِنَ النَّار» and is also used for the requested fire.\nThen, «قَبَسَ» is also used in the meanings of lighting fire from fire, obtaining light from a great light, and acquiring knowledge from a great scholar. «قَبَسَ الْعِلْم» means to acquire knowledge, to benefit from knowledge. And «اِقْتَبَسَ مِنْہُ النَّارَ وَالنُّور وَالْعِلْم» means to obtain fire, light, or knowledge from someone (Majma' al-Bayan).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لِلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا انۡظُرُوۡنَا نَقۡتَبِسۡ مِنۡ نُّوۡرِکُمۡ» (57:13)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, look at us; we would like to borrow some of your light.\nAnd in our language, the word 'iqtabas' (اقتباس) means to take a part or piece from someone's scholarly writing or book and present it."
    },
    {
      "id": 60,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Lighting fire; to be lit",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«قَدَحَ» The initial attempt or effort to light fire (1 verse: 100:2)",
      "d": "«زَنَّدَ» means to produce fire by striking flint (manjad). Thus, the word «قَدَحَ» is limited to the attempt and intention of producing fire only."
    },
    {
      "id": 61,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Burning other things with fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«لَفَحَ» Fire or hot wind scorching the face or skin, ruining the appearance (1 verse: 23:104)",
      "d": "The meaning of «لَفَحَ» is that fire or hot wind scorches the face or skin (muf, manjad), ruining the appearance. It is as if this is a second-degree wind.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«تَلۡفَحُ وُجُوۡہَہُمُ النَّارُ وَ ہُمۡ فِیۡہَا کٰلِحُوۡنَ» (23/104)\nTranslation: The fire of Hell will scorch their faces, and they will be grimacing therein."
    },
    {
      "id": 62,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Burning other things with fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«لَوَّحَ» Skin turning black from the heat of fire or the sun's scorching (1 verse: 74:29)",
      "d": "«لَاحَ» refers only to the skin turning blackish in color. Whether this happens from fire, heat, sun, thirst, or travel (manjad). That is, fire or heat touches someone in such a way that their complexion turns blackish. And «لَوَّحَ» means to heat something with fire (manjad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَوَّاحَۃٌ  لِّلۡبَشَرِ» (74/29)\nTranslation: (The fire of Hell) will blacken the skin (by scorching it)."
    },
    {
      "id": 63,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«نَارٌ» Used for every kind of fire (138 verses: 2:17-2:24-2:39-2:80-2:81-2:126-2:167-2:174-2:175-2:201-2:217-2:221-2:257-2:266-2:275-3:10-3:16-3:24-3:103-3:116-3:131-3:151-3:183-3:185-3:191-3:192-4:10-4:14-4:30-4:56-4:145-5:29-5:37-5:64-5:72-6:27-6:128-7:12-7:36-7:38-7:44-7:47-7:50-8:14-9:17-9:35-9:63-9:68-9:81-9:109-10:8-10:27-11:16-11:17-11:98-11:106-11:113-13:5-13:17-13:35-14:30-14:50-15:27-16:62-18:29-18:53-18:96-20:10-21:39-21:69-22:19-22:72-23:104-24:35-24:57-27:7-27:8-27:90-28:29-28:41-29:24-29:25-32:20-33:66-34:42-35:36-36:80-38:27-38:59-38:61-38:64-38:76-39:8-39:16-39:19-40:6-40:41-40:43-40:46-40:47-40:49-40:72-41:19-41:24-41:28-41:40-45:34-46:20-46:34-47:12-47:15-51:13-52:13-52:14-54:48-55:15-55:35-56:71-57:15-58:17-59:3-59:17-59:20-64:10-66:6-66:10-71:25-72:23-74:31-85:5-87:12-88:4-90:20-92:14-98:6-101:11-104:6-111:3)",
      "d": "The word «نَارٌ» is general. It applies to all kinds of fire—whether blazing, intense, or dying, with flame or without. Whereas «لظٰی» refers to a severely hot, blazing fire that has no flame (al-khalis min al-lahab, f.l. 56).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کَلَّا ؕ اِنَّہَا  لَظٰی ۔ نَزَّاعَۃً   لِّلشَّوٰی» (70/15,16)\nTranslation: No! Indeed, it is a blazing fire. A remover of the scalp."
    },
    {
      "id": 64,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Burning other things with fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«نَضِجَ» Meat cooking solely from the heat of fire (1 verse: 4:56)",
      "d": "«نَضِجَ» means meat cooking due to intense heat (mufrad) to the extent that its parts begin to separate. (This is a fourth-degree heat.)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«سَوۡفَ نُصۡلِیۡہِمۡ نَارًا ؕ کُلَّمَا نَضِجَتۡ جُلُوۡدُہُمۡ بَدَّلۡنٰہُمۡ جُلُوۡدًا غَیۡرَہَا» (4/56)\nTranslation: We will surely admit them into the Fire. Every time their skins are roasted through, We will replace them with other skins."
    }
  ],
  "13": [
    {
      "id": 66,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To inform (to tell)",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "«اَشْعَرْ» Used for giving news (2 verses: 6:109-18:19)",
      "d": "«اَشْعَرْ» is used for giving news.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَابۡعَثُوۡۤا اَحَدَکُمۡ بِوَرِقِکُمۡ ہٰذِہٖۤ  اِلَی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ فَلۡیَنۡظُرۡ اَیُّہَاۤ اَزۡکٰی طَعَامًا فَلۡیَاۡتِکُمۡ بِرِزۡقٍ مِّنۡہُ  وَ لۡـیَؔ‍‍‍تَلَطَّفۡ وَ لَا یُشۡعِرَنَّ بِکُمۡ اَحَدًا» (18/19)\nTranslation: (The people of the Cave, after a long sleep, awoke and began to talk among themselves) So send one of you with these silver coins of yours to the city. Let him look for which food is purest and bring you provision from it. And let him be gentle and not inform anyone about you."
    },
    {
      "id": 68,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to inform (to tell)",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "«اَظْھَرَ» to reveal hidden news (2 verses: 66:3-72:26)",
      "d": "«اَظْھَرَ» means to reveal something that was hidden.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«عٰلِمُ الۡغَیۡبِ فَلَا یُظۡہِرُ عَلٰی غَیۡبِہٖۤ اَحَدًا» ( 72/26 )\nTranslation: (He is Allah,) the Knower of the unseen, and He does not reveal His unseen to anyone."
    },
    {
      "id": 70,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to inform (to tell)",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "«حَدَّثَ» to tell something new (8 verses: 2:76-18:70-20:113-21:2-26:5-65:1-93:11-99:4)",
      "d": "«حَدَّثَ» means for something to occur or come into existence. It signifies something being new or the coming into being of a new thing or news (Munjid). According to Ibn al-Faris, it means 'the coming into existence of a thing that was not.' Thus, it refers to the coming into existence or manifestation of something that did not previously exist (M.L.). And the meaning of «حَدَّثَ» is to inform someone of something they did not know before, or at least the informant believes it to be so.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا لَقُوا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا قَالُوۡۤا اٰمَنَّا  ۚ ۖ  وَ اِذَا خَلَا بَعۡضُہُمۡ  اِلٰی بَعۡضٍ قَالُوۡۤا اَتُحَدِّثُوۡنَہُمۡ بِمَا فَتَحَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ لِیُحَآجُّوۡکُمۡ بِہٖ عِنۡدَ رَبِّکُمۡ» ( 2/76 )\nTranslation: And when they (the Jews) meet those who believe, they say, 'We believe,' but when they are alone with one another, they say, 'Do you (O Muhammad) inform them (the believers) of what Allah has revealed to you so that they may argue with you about it before your Lord?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 72,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to guide",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "«دَلَّ» to show the way. To inform of something or to guide (5 verses: 20:40-20:120-28:12-34:7-61:10)",
      "d": "«دَلَّ» means to guide, to show the path, to inform of something, and 'dalalat' means by which the knowledge or recognition of something is obtained, such as words indicating meanings. Or, when something begins to move, a person understands that it is a living creature, so its movement indicates life (Maf). The word «دَلَّ» is used in both material and spiritual senses.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ تَمۡشِیۡۤ اُخۡتُکَ فَتَقُوۡلُ ہُلۡ اَدُلُّکُمۡ  عَلٰی مَنۡ  یَّکۡفُلُہٗ» ( 20/40 )\nTranslation: And (O Moses) your sister went and said, 'Shall I point out to you someone who will be responsible for him?'\nAt another place, the Divine declaration states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا  الَّذِیۡنَ  اٰمَنُوۡا ہُلۡ اَدُلُّکُمۡ عَلٰی تِجَارَۃٍ  تُنۡجِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡ عَذَابٍ اَلِیۡمٍ» ( 61/10 )\nTranslation: O you who have believed, shall I guide you to a transaction that will save you from a painful punishment?"
    },
    {
      "id": 73,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to become aware",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "«شَعَرَ» to understand the subtleties and delicacy of a matter; to reach the depth of a matter. (27 verses: 2:9-2:12-2:154-3:69-6:26-6:109-6:123-7:95-12:15-12:107-16:21-16:26-16:45-18:19-23:56-26:113-26:202-27:18-27:50-27:65-28:9-28:11-29:53-39:25-39:55-43:66-49:2)",
      "d": "«شَعْر» means hair, so «شَعَرَ» means to acquire knowledge as fine as hair (Maf). To understand the subtleties and delicacy of a matter, or to deduce from circumstances and events, and reaching the depth of a matter is called «شَعْر».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَاۤ اِنَّہُمۡ ہُمُ الۡمُفۡسِدُوۡنَ وَ لٰکِنۡ لَّا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ» ( 2/12 )\nTranslation: Behold! They themselves are the corrupters, but they perceive not."
    },
    {
      "id": 74,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to become aware",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "«ظَھَرَ» this refers to knowledge obtained entirely from apparent circumstances and events. (27 verses: 2:85-6:120-6:151-7:33-9:8-9:33-9:48-13:33-18:20-18:22-18:97-24:31-30:7-30:18-30:41-31:20-34:18-40:26-40:29-43:33-48:28-57:3-57:13-61:9-61:14-66:3-72:26)",
      "d": "«ظَھَرَ» has two basic meanings: (1) 'strength' (2) to be evident (M.L.). Here it relates to the second meaning, the opposite of which is 'internal' (batn). Thus, «ظَھَرَ» refers to knowledge obtained entirely from apparent circumstances and events.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَوِ الطِّفۡلِ الَّذِیۡنَ لَمۡ  یَظۡہَرُوۡا عَلٰی عَوۡرٰتِ النِّسَآءِ» ( 24/31 )\nTranslation: or the children who have not yet become aware of the private aspects of women."
    },
    {
      "id": 75,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to become aware",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "«عَثَرَ» to learn of something unintentionally through conversations. (2 verses: 5:107-18:21)",
      "d": "«عَثَرَ» means to become aware of something that is learned unintentionally through conversations (Maf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ عُثِرَ عَلٰۤی اَنَّہُمَا اسۡتَحَقَّاۤ اِثۡمًا» ( 5/107 )\nTranslation: Then if it is discovered that they both (the two witnesses) have merited sin (by bearing false witness)."
    },
    {
      "id": 76,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to inform (to tell)",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "«عَرَّفَ» to make someone understand through signs and indications. (19 verses: 2:89-2:146-2:273-5:83-6:20-7:46-7:48-12:58-12:62-16:83-22:72-23:69-27:93-33:59-47:6-47:30-55:41-66:3-83:24)",
      "d": "«عَرَفَ» means to recognize or identify something by reflecting on its signs and indications (Maf). It is evident that in recognition, a person can sometimes make mistakes; therefore, the level of 'ma'rifat' (recognition) is lower than 'ilm' (knowledge), and the opposite of 'ma'rifat' is 'inkar' (denial).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَعَرَفَہُمۡ  وَ ہُمۡ  لَہٗ  مُنۡکِرُوۡنَ» ( 12/58 )\nTranslation: So he (Prophet Yusuf) recognized them, but they did not recognize him.\nFurthermore, «عَرَفَ» also means to perfume, and «عَرَّفَ» means to perfume or to leave a fragrance behind (Maf, Munjid). However, the general meaning of «عَرَّفَ» is to make someone familiar, to introduce, or to inform.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یُدۡخِلُہُمُ  الۡجَنَّۃَ  عَرَّفَہَا  لَہُمۡ» ( 47/6 )\nTranslation: And He will admit them to Paradise, which He has made known to them.\nAnd Imam Raghib has translated it as: And Allah has made Paradise fragrant for them (Maf)."
    },
    {
      "id": 77,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to become aware",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "«عَلِمَ» to obtain certainty regarding the reality of something. (20 verses: 2:60-2:65-2:102-2:187-2:235-7:160-8:23-8:66-12:21-12:37-24:41-45:9-48:18-48:27-50:4-56:62-60:10-73:20-81:14-82:5)",
      "d": "«عَلِمَ» If familiarity with the reality of something reaches the level of certainty, that familiarity is called 'ilm' (knowledge), and its opposite is 'jahil' (ignorance).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ عَلِمُوۡا لَمَنِ اشۡتَرٰىہُ مَا لَہٗ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ مِنۡ خَلَاقٍ» ( 2/102 )\nTranslation: And they (the Jews) certainly knew that whoever purchased that (sorcery) would have no share in the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 78,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to inform (to tell)",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "«عَلَّمَ» used in the meaning of teaching someone knowledge. (1 verse: 49:16)",
      "d": "«عَلَّمَ» is used in the meaning of teaching someone knowledge.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قُلۡ اَتُعَلِّمُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ بِدِیۡنِکُمۡ» ( 49/16 )\nTranslation: Say (O Prophet), 'Do you (pretend to) teach Allah about your religion?'"
    }
  ],
  "14": [
    {
      "id": 79,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to send ahead",
      "hw": "آگے",
      "s": "«اَسْلَفَ» for an action to pass by; generally used for predecessors (ancestors) as well. (8 verses: 2:275-4:22-4:23-5:95-8:38-10:30-43:56-69:24)",
      "d": "«سَلَفَ» means for something or an action to pass by (M. A.). For example: In Islamic jurisprudence, 'bay' salf' refers to a sale where the price is paid in advance. And 'aslaf' refers to generations that have passed in previous times. Past ancestors (Munjid).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِلَّا مَا قَدۡ سَلَفَ» ( 4/23 )\nTranslation: Except what has already passed.\nFurthermore, «سَلَفَ» also has the meaning of 'to advance' (M.L., Munjid). «سَلِیْف» means one who is ahead, one who proceeds. «اَسْلَاف» means a group of predecessors (Munjid). And «اَسْلَفَ» means an action that occurred in past time.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ہُنَالِکَ تَبۡلُوۡا کُلُّ نَفۡسٍ مَّاۤ  اَسۡلَفَتۡ» ( 10/30 )\nTranslation: (1) There, every soul will be tested in what it has sent ahead (of deeds).\nTranslation: (2) There, every soul will be examined for what it had done previously. (Translation by Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 80,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Approaching",
      "hw": "آگے",
      "s": "«اَقْبَلَ» is used to mean turning towards someone and being attentive (8 verses: 12:71-28:31-37:27-37:50-37:94-51:29-52:25-68:30)",
      "d": "«اِقْبَال» and «اِسْتِقْبَال» both mean turning towards and advancing in the direction of something (i.e., moving forward towards someone). For example, in the Quran: «فَاَقۡبَلَ بَعۡضُہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ یَّتَلَاوَمُوۡنَ» (68/30) Translation: Then they began to blame each other face to face. (Jalandhari) At another place, the divine command says: «فَلَمَّا رَاَوۡہُ عَارِضًا مُّسۡتَقۡبِلَ اَوۡدِیَتِہِمۡ ۙ قَالُوۡا ہٰذَا عَارِضٌ مُّمۡطِرُنَا» (46/24) Translation: Then when they saw it as a cloud approaching their valleys, they said, 'This is a cloud that will give us rain.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 81,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Ahead; In Front",
      "hw": "آگے",
      "s": "«بَیْنَ یَدَیْ ، بَیْنَ اَیْدِیْ» is generally used to denote time and place (38 verses: 2:66-2:97-2:255-3:3-3:50-5:46-5:48-6:92-7:17-7:57-10:37-12:111-13:11-19:64-20:110-21:28-22:76-25:48-27:63-34:9-34:12-34:31-34:46-35:31-36:9-36:45-41:14-41:25-41:42-46:21-46:30-49:1-57:12-58:12-58:13-61:6-66:8-72:27)",
      "d": "«بَیْنَ یَدَیْ ، بَیْنَ اَیْدِیْ» (literally 'between the hands') metaphorically means ahead or in front. Its opposite is «خَلَف». It is used as a time and place adverb (i.e., for both time and place). In the temporal sense, it refers to the people of that time or era, but generally it means 'previous' or 'before'. For example, in the Quran: «فَجَعَلۡنٰہَا نَکَالًا لِّمَا بَیۡنَ یَدَیۡہَا وَ مَا خَلۡفَہَا» (2/66) Translation: So We made it a lesson for those who were before it and for those who came after it. In the spatial sense, it means ahead or in front. For example: «لَہٗ مُعَقِّبٰتٌ مِّنۡۢ بَیۡنِ یَدَیۡہِ وَ مِنۡ خَلۡفِہٖ  یَحۡفَظُوۡنَہٗ  مِنۡ اَمۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (13/11) Translation: He has guardians, from before him and from behind him, who guard him by the command of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 82,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Advancing",
      "hw": "آگے",
      "s": "«سَبَقَ» conveys the meaning of advancing ahead of others in a contest (21 verses: 7:80-8:59-8:68-10:19-11:40-11:110-15:5-20:99-20:199-21:27-21:101-23:27-23:43-29:4-29:28-37:171-41:45-42:14-46:11-59:10-79:4)",
      "d": "«سَبَقَ» means to advance, to be ahead, to precede. «السَّبْقُ» is a condition set on those who advance, and «سَابِق» means a winning horse in a race. «سَبَّقَ» means to make a condition or bet. Thus, «سَبْق» implies advancing ahead in a contest. For example, in the Quran: «رَبَّنَا اغۡفِرۡ لَنَا وَ لِاِخۡوَانِنَا الَّذِیۡنَ سَبَقُوۡنَا بِالۡاِیۡمَانِ» (59/10) Translation: Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith. And «اِسْتَبَقَ» means to strive to advance quickly or to race to advance. For example: «وَ اسۡتَبَقَا الۡبَابَ وَ قَدَّتۡ قَمِیۡصَہٗ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ» (12/25) Translation: And they both raced to the door, and she tore his shirt from behind."
    },
    {
      "id": 83,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Ahead; In Front",
      "hw": "آگے",
      "s": "«قُبُل» means two things facing each other or being in front and opposite. It is necessary for them to be face to face, whereas «بَیْنَ یَدَی» does not require things to be face to face, whether in time or place. (8 verses: 6:111-12:26-18:55-27:37-28:31-46:24-51:29-57:13)",
      "d": "«قُبْل» means the front part of everything that appears first. Its opposite is «دُبُر» and «دُبْر». For example, in the Quran: «وَلَوۡ اَنَّنَا نَزَّلۡنَاۤ  اِلَیۡہِمُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃَ وَ کَلَّمَہُمُ الۡمَوۡتٰی وَ حَشَرۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ قُبُلًا مَّا کَانُوۡا لِیُؤۡمِنُوۡۤا» (6/111) Translation: Even if We had sent down angels to them and made the dead speak and gathered all things before them, they would not have believed. And «قِبَل» also means power and strength. And «قِبَل» refers to coming before something against which one has no power or strength. For example: «بَاطِنُہٗ فِیۡہِ الرَّحۡمَۃُ وَ ظَاہِرُہٗ مِنۡ قِبَلِہِ الۡعَذَابُ» (57/13) Translation: Its inside is mercy, and its outside is from the front, punishment. At another place: «اَوۡ تَاۡتِیَ بِاللّٰہِ  وَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ  قَبِیۡلًا» (17/92) Translation: Or bring Allah and the angels before us (as a proof)."
    },
    {
      "id": 84,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Advancing",
      "hw": "آگے",
      "s": "«قَدَمَ» means only to walk forward or advance, while «سَبَقَ» means to advance ahead of others in a contest, and «اَقْبَلَ» means to turn towards someone or something and advance. (14 verses: 7:34-10:2-10:49-11:98-15:24-16:61-25:23-34:30-38:60-38:61-49:1-58:12-58:13-74:37)",
      "d": "«قَدَمَ» means to walk forward, to step forward, or to go before someone. For example, in the Quran: «یَقۡدُمُ  قَوۡمَہٗ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ فَاَوۡرَدَہُمُ النَّارَ» (11/98) Translation: He will lead his people on the Day of Resurrection and will bring them into the Fire. And «اِسْتَقْدَمَ» means to intend to advance, and its opposite is «اِسْتَاخَرَ». For example: «اِذَا جَآءَ اَجَلُہُمۡ فَلَا یَسۡتَاۡخِرُوۡنَ سَاعَۃً وَّ لَا  یَسۡتَقۡدِمُوۡنَ» (10/49) Translation: When their time comes, they cannot delay it by an hour nor advance it."
    },
    {
      "id": 85,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sending Ahead",
      "hw": "آگے",
      "s": "«قَدَّمَ» means to do an act before its due time. (23 verses: 2:95-2:110-2:223-3:182-4:62-5:80-8:51-18:57-22:10-26:76-28:47-30:36-36:12-42:48-48:2-50:28-59:18-62:7-73:20-75:13-78:40-82:5-89:24)",
      "d": "«قَدَّمَ» means to do something before its required time, and its opposite is «اَخَّرَ», meaning to not do something at its proper time and to postpone it. This proper time is death, meaning that before death, whatever deeds a person has done are as if he has sent them ahead for his afterlife. For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَنۡ یَّتَمَنَّوۡہُ اَبَدًۢا بِمَا قَدَّمَتۡ اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ» (2/95) Translation: And they will never wish for it (death) because of what their hands have sent ahead (i.e., their deeds). Then, to inform someone of the consequences of an act before doing it, «قَدَّمَ» is used. For example: «قَالَ  لَا تَخۡتَصِمُوۡا لَدَیَّ وَ قَدۡ قَدَّمۡتُ اِلَیۡکُمۡ  بِالۡوَعِیۡدِ» (50/28) Translation: He will say, 'Do not dispute before Me; I had already sent you the warning beforehand.' And «اَسْلَفَ» has the same meaning as «اِرْتَفَاع» and «عَمَق»; if on the lower edge, it's called height, and if on the upper edge, it's depth. Similarly, the same act that «قَدَّمَ» conveys, in terms of timing, is called «اَسْلَفَ». As on the Day of Resurrection, Allah will say to the believers: «کُلُوۡا وَ اشۡرَبُوۡا ہَنِیۡٓـئًۢا بِمَاۤ  اَسۡلَفۡتُمۡ فِی الۡاَیَّامِ الۡخَالِیَۃِ» (69/24) Translation: Eat and drink pleasantly for what you sent ahead in the past days. Now, if this meaning is to be expressed in the present time, it would be «بِمَا قَدَّمَتْ اَیْدِیْکُمْ»."
    }
  ],
  "15": [
    {
      "id": 86,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Weapons of War",
      "hw": "جنگ",
      "s": "«اَسْلِحَۃْ» means all kinds of war equipment. It is a specific word for war equipment. (1 verse: 4:102)",
      "d": "«اَسْلِحَۃْ» is the plural of «سَلَاح». And everything that is a weapon with which fighting can be done is 'silah' (Lane's Lexicon). Thus, this word is specific for war weapons, whether they are an axe, spear, sword, or rifle and missile.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَدَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوْا لَوۡ تَغۡفُلُوۡنَ عَنۡ اَسۡلِحَتِکُمۡ وَ اَمۡتِعَتِکُمۡ» (4:102)\nTranslation: But those who disbelieve wish that you would neglect your weapons and your baggage so they could swoop down upon you in a single attack."
    },
    {
      "id": 87,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Weapons",
      "hw": "جنگ",
      "s": "«اَوْزَار» means weapons. If related to war, they are weapons of war; otherwise not. (11 verses: 6:31-6:164-16:25-17:15-20:87-20:100-35:18-39:7-47:4-53:38-94:2)",
      "d": "«اَوْزَار» is the plural of «وِزْر», which means burden, weapon, and instrument. When «وِزْرُالْحَرْب» is used, it specifically means weapons of war. However, even the word «وِرْز» alone can mean war weapons. For example, in the Quran: «حَتّٰی تَضَعَ الۡحَرۡبُ اَوۡزَارَہَا» (47/4) Translation: Until the war lays down its weapons."
    },
    {
      "id": 88,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Defensive Gear",
      "hw": "جنگ",
      "s": "«حِذْر» if used in the context of war, it means defensive war equipment. (17 verses: 2:19-2:235-2:243-3:28-3:30-4:71-4:102-5:41-5:49-5:92-9:64-9:122-24:63-28:6-39:9-63:4-64:14)",
      "d": "«حِذْر» originally means to guard, to be cautious, and to be careful. This word is general. If used in the context of war, it means defensive war equipment. This can refer to any place of protection, such as trenches, and similarly, from shield to radar, all can be meant. That is, everything and every measure by which protection and defense can be made is «حِذْر». For example, in the Quran: «وَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اِنۡ کَانَ بِکُمۡ اَذًی مِّنۡ مَّطَرٍاَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ مَّرۡضٰۤی اَنۡ تَضَعُوۡۤا اَسۡلِحَتَکُمۡ ۚ وَ خُذُوۡاحِذۡرَکُمۡ» (4/102) Translation: And there is no blame upon you if you are harmed by rain or you are ill that you lay down your arms, and take your protective gear. (Uthmani) The word «خُذُوْا» indicates that here «حِذْر» does not merely mean to be cautious (as stated by Fateh Muhammad), but rather defensive equipment should be kept with oneself in all conditions. So that the enemy, seeing you unprepared, does not take advantage."
    },
    {
      "id": 89,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Offensive Weapons",
      "hw": "جنگ",
      "s": "«شَوْکَۃ» means offensive weapons for aggressive fighting. (1 verse: 8:7)",
      "d": "«شَوْک» means a thorn (with «درمثَاکَ» meaning a thorn to pierce). «شَوْکَۃ» means a single thorn, and its plural is «اَشْوَاک». A scorpion's sting. Weapon, sharpness, strength, fight, ferocity, and «ذُوْشَوْکَۃ» means armed with weapons, armed. From «شَوْک», it is also evident that offensive weapons are meant, with which an attack can be made. For example, in the Quran: «وَ تَوَدُّوۡنَ اَنَّ غَیۡرِ ذَاتِ الشَّوۡکَۃِ تَکُوۡنُ لَکُمۡ» (8/7) Translation: And you wish that the unarmed (caravan) could be yours."
    }
  ],
  "16": [
    {
      "id": 90,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Come",
      "hw": "To come",
      "s": "«اَتٰی» (Atā) is used for something coming as a result of another action or coming with ease. (164 verses: 2:38-2:85-2:118-2:189-2:210-2:214-2:222-2:223-2:248-2:254-2:260-3:125-4:15-4:16-4:19-4:25-4:102-5:41-6:4-6:5-6:34-6:40-6:47-6:130-6:134-6:158-7:17-7:35-7:53-7:80-7:81-7:97-7:98-7:106-7:129-7:138-7:163-7:187-9:54-9:70-9:92-10:24-10:50-11:8-11:76-11:39-11:93-11:105-12:37-12:48-12:49-12:93-12:107-13:31-13:41-14:9-14:17-14:31-14:44-15:11-15:85-15:99-16:1-16:26-16:33-16:45-16:111-16:112-18:19-18:55-18:77-19:38-19:43-19:61-19:93-19:95-20:9-20:11-20:15-20:47-20:60-20:69-20:74-20:75-20:123-20:126-20:133-21:2-21:3-21:40-21:44-22:7-22:27-22:55-23:68-24:49-25:40-26:5-26:6-26:16-26:89-26:154-26:165-26:202-27:18-27:31-27:38-27:54-27:55-27:87-27:92-28:30-28:46-29:5-29:28-29:29-29:53-30:43-32:3-33:14-33:18-33:20-33:30-34:3-36:30-36:46-37:28-38:21-39:25-39:40-39:54-39:55-39:71-40:22-40:35-40:50-40:56-40:59-41:11-41:40-41:42-42:47-43:7-43:66-47:18-51:24-51:42-51:52-59:2-60:12-61:6-63:10-64:5-64:6-65:1-67:8-71:1-74:47-76:1-78:18-79:15-85:17-88:1-98:1)",
      "d": "«اَتٰی» (Atā) is used for something coming as a result of another action or coming with ease, e.g., when butter rises to the top after churning milk, it is called «اَتُوَّۃٌ» (Utuwwah), and «اٰتِیّ» (Ātiyy) is used for a flood. (Mufradat)\nThe difference between «جَاءَ» (Jā'a) and «اَتٰی» (Atā) is that unlike «جَاءَ», «اَتٰی» does not necessarily require that the act of coming has already occurred factually.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَتٰۤی اَمۡرُ اللّٰہِ فَلَا تَسۡتَعۡجِلُوۡہُ» (16/1)\nTranslation: The command of Allah (i.e., the punishment, so to speak) has come, so do not hasten it.\nIn this verse, 'amr (command) refers to the act of the Hereafter and recompense, which is yet to occur."
    },
    {
      "id": 91,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Come",
      "hw": "To come",
      "s": "«تَعَال» (Ta'āl) is used for summoning someone towards a lofty purpose or with respect. (8 verses: 3:61-3:64-3:167-4:61-5:104-6:151-33:28-63:5)",
      "d": "«عَلَو» ('Alaw) means elevation, and «تَعَال» (Ta'āl) means to summon someone towards a high place or a noble purpose (Mufradat). It is used for calling someone with respect and only the imperative mood forms are used.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قُلۡ یٰۤاَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ تَعَالَوۡا اِلٰی کَلِمَۃٍ سَوَآءٍۢ  بَیۡنَنَا وَ بَیۡنَکُمۡ اَلَّا نَعۡبُدَ اِلَّا اللّٰہَ» (3/64)\nTranslation: Say, 'O People of the Scripture! Come to a word equitable between us and you - that we worship none but Allah.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 92,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Come",
      "hw": "To come",
      "s": "«جَاءَ» (Jā'a) means 'to come'. For its usage, it is necessary that the act of coming has already occurred factually. (216 verses: 2:87-2:89-2:92-2:101-2:120-2:145-2:209-2:211-2:213-2:253-2:275-3:19-3:61-3:81-3:86-3:105-3:183-3:184-4:43-4:62-4:64-4:83-4:90-4:153-4:170-4:174-5:6-5:15-5:19-5:32-5:42-5:48-5:61-5:70-5:84-6:5-6:25-6:31-6:34-6:43-6:54-6:61-6:104-6:109-6:124-6:157-6:160-7:4-7:5-7:34-7:37-7:43-7:53-7:63-7:69-7:73-7:85-7:101-7:113-7:116-7:126-7:131-7:143-8:19-9:48-9:90-9:128-10:13-10:22-10:47-10:49-10:57-10:74-10:76-10:77-10:80-10:93-10:94-10:97-10:108-11:12-11:40-11:58-11:66-11:69-11:74-11:76-11:77-11:78-11:82-11:94-11:101-11:120-12:16-12:19-12:50-12:58-12:96-13:37-14:9-15:61-15:67-16:61-16:113-17:5-17:7-17:81-17:94-17:101-17:104-18:55-18:98-19:43-20:72-23:27-23:44-23:68-23:70-23:99-24:39-25:29-26:41-26:206-27:28-27:13-27:36-27:42-27:84-27:89-27:90-28:20-28:25-28:36-28:37-28:48-28:84-28:85-29:10-29:31-29:33-29:39-29:53-29:68-30:9-30:47-33:9-33:10-33:19-34:32-34:43-34:49-35:25-35:37-35:42-35:45-36:13-36:20-37:37-37:84-38:4-39:32-39:33-39:59-39:71-39:73-40:25-40:28-40:29-40:34-40:66-40:78-40:83-41:14-41:20-41:41-42:14-43:29-43:30-43:38-43:47-43:53-43:63-44:13-44:17-45:17-46:7-47:18-49:6-50:2-50:5-50:19-50:21-50:33-51:26-53:23-54:4-54:41-57:14-58:8-59:10-60:1-60:10-60:12-61:6-63:1-63:11-67:9-69:9-71:4-79:34-80:2-80:8-80:33-89:22-98:4-110:1)",
      "d": "«جَاءَ» (Jā'a) is the general term for 'to come'. However, for its usage, it is necessary that the act of coming has already occurred factually (Mufradat).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ جَآءُوۡۤ  اَبَاہُمۡ  عِشَآءً  یَّبۡکُوۡنَ» (12/16)\nTranslation: And they (the brothers of Yusuf) came to their father at night, weeping."
    }
  ],
  "17": [
    {
      "id": 95,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Eye",
      "hw": "Eye",
      "s": "«بَصَر» (Baṣar) includes both the physical eye and spiritual insight. (82 verses: 2:7-2:17-2:20-3:13-6:46-6:103-6:104-6:110-7:47-7:179-7:195-7:198-7:201-10:31-10:43-10:67-11:20-14:42-15:15-16:77-16:78-16:108-17:12-17:36-17:59-18:26-19:38-19:42-20:96-21:3-21:97-22:46-23:78-24:30-24:31-24:37-24:43-24:44-27:13-27:54-27:86-28:11-28:72-29:38-32:9-32:12-32:27-33:10-36:9-36:66-37:175-37:179-38:45-38:63-40:61-41:20-41:22-43:51-45:23-46:26-47:23-50:8-50:22-51:21-52:15-53:17-54:7-54:50-56:85-59:2-67:3-67:4-67:23-68:5-68:43-68:51-69:38-69:39-70:11-70:44-75:7-79:9)",
      "d": "«بَصَر» (Baṣar) includes both the physical eye and spiritual insight (Mufradat). Additionally, «بَصَرَ» (Baṣara) is used for the act of the physical eye, i.e., seeing and looking, and then for pondering over what is seen. Examples:\nExample (1): Divine revelation states:\n«الۡحَقُّ فَاِذَا ہِیَ شَاخِصَۃٌ  اَبۡصَارُ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا» (21/97)\nTranslation: And when the true promise (of the Hour) draws near, the eyes of those who disbelieved will be staring in horror.\nExample (2): For 'gaze': Divine revelation states:\n«فَکَشَفۡنَا عَنۡکَ غِطَآءَکَ فَبَصَرُکَ الۡیَوۡمَ حَدِیۡدٌ» (50/22)\nTranslation: Now We have removed from you your veil, so your sight today is sharp.\nExample (3): For spiritual insight: Divine revelation states:\n«وَعَلٰۤی اَبۡصَارِہِمۡ غِشَاوَۃٌ» (2/7)\nTranslation: And upon their eyes is a covering.\nFrom 'Baṣar', the verbal noun 'Baṣārah' (insight) and 'Baṣīrah' (perception) are derived. 'Baṣārah' refers to physical sight, weakness in which is 'ḍaʿf al-baṣar'. 'Baṣīrah' refers to spiritual insight. A poet has clarified the difference between insight and sight:\n'Ask from Allah for a seeing heart too,\nThe light of the eye is not the light of the heart!'\nNote: (Masdar: Meaning the place of issuing forth, i.e., emerging or starting; source, origin, foundation, spring, root. Masdar: It is a noun from which other verbs can be formed, but it itself is not derived from any verb.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 96,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Eye",
      "hw": "Eye",
      "s": "«حُوْر» (Ḥūr) is used for white and black eyes. In common usage, it refers to the women of Paradise. (4 verses: 44:54-52:20-55:72-56:22)",
      "d": "«حَورَتِ الْعَیْن» (Ḥūrat al-'Ayn) means the whiteness of the eye is extremely white and the blackness (of the pupil) is extremely black. And the more the whiteness in the eye's whiteness and the blackness in the pupil's blackness, the more the beauty increases. «اَحْوَرْ» (Aḥwar) and «حَوْرَاء» (Ḥawrā') are used for a man and woman possessing this quality, and their plural is «حُوْر» (Ḥūr) (Mufradat, Maqayis).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«حُوۡرٌ مَّقۡصُوۡرٰتٌ فِی  الۡخِیَامِ» (55/72)\nTranslation: (In Paradise will be) houris, restraining their glances, in pavilions.\nAt another place, both these qualities of the eye are mentioned together:\nDivine revelation states:\n«وَ حُوۡرٌ عِیۡنٌ کَاَمۡثَالِ اللُّؤۡلُوءِ  الۡمَکۡنُوۡنِ» (56:22,23)\nTranslation: And (there will be) houris with wide, lovely eyes, like guarded pearls."
    },
    {
      "id": 97,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Eye",
      "hw": "Eye",
      "s": "The word «عَیْن» ('Ayn) is used for the physical organ of sight, the eye. (35 verses: 3:13-5:45-5:83-7:116-7:179-7:195-8:44-9:92-11:31-11:37-12:84-15:88-18:28-18:86-18:101-19:26-20:39-20:40-20:131-21:61-23:27-25:74-28:9-28:13-32:17-33:19-33:51-36:66-40:19-43:71-52:48-54:14-54:37-90:8-102:7)",
      "d": "«عَیْن» ('Ayn) is the well-known organ of humans with which they see, and it also means 'spring' (as in water source), wherein there are many points of similarity between the two meanings. The plural of «عَیْن» is «اَعْیُن» (A'yun) and «عُیُوْن» ('Uyun). However, in the Quran, the plural of 'ayn (eye) is mostly «اَعْیُن», and the plural of 'ayn (spring) is «عُیُوْن». The word «عَیْن» is used only for the physical eye.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَالۡعَیۡنَ بِالۡعَیۡنِ» (5/45)\nTranslation: 'An eye for an eye' (retaliation).\nAnd in terms of qualities, two other types of eyes are mentioned in the Quran.\n«عِیْن» ('Ayn) and «حُوْر» (Ḥūr) are qualities of eyes. «عِین» ('Ayn) is for large, prominent eyes, and «حُوْر» (Ḥūr) is for extremely white whites and extremely black pupils. «بَصَر» (Baṣar) is a word that, besides the physical organ, also means the act of seeing (gaze) and then pondering over what is seen."
    }
  ],
  "18": [
    {
      "id": 99,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Wander Aimlessly",
      "hw": "آوارہ ",
      "s": "«تَاہَ» (Tāha) is used for wandering in a state of bewilderment and distress. (1 verse: 5:26)",
      "d": "«تَاہَ» (Tāha) means to wander in a state of bewilderment and distress. To roam about aimlessly in a state of misguidance (Mufradat). According to Ibn Faris, it is «جِنْسٌ مِّنَ الْحَیْرَۃ» (a specific type of confusion), and «اَتِیَہ» (Atiyah) means a barren plain where a traveler gets lost.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاِنَّہَا مُحَرَّمَۃٌ عَلَیۡہِمۡ اَرۡبَعِیۡنَ سَنَۃً ۚ یَتِیۡہُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (5/26)\nTranslation: Allah said, 'It will be forbidden to them for forty years; they will wander aimlessly in the land.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 100,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Wander Aimlessly",
      "hw": "آوارہ ",
      "s": "«ھَامَ» (Hām) is used for wandering due to love and passion. (1 verse: 26:225)",
      "d": "«ھَامَ» (Hām) means to roam in a state of frenzy. The wandering of people in the state of love (Mufradat). The author of 'Majma' writes its meaning as 'to love' and 'to wander aimlessly'.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَالشُّعَرَآءُ  یَتَّبِعُہُمُ  الۡغَاوٗنَ ۔ اَلَمۡ تَرَاَنَّہُمۡ فِیۡ کُلِّ وَادٍ یَّہِیۡمُوۡنَ» (26/224)\nTranslation: And the poets - [only] the deviators follow them. Do you not see that in every valley they ramble aimlessly?"
    }
  ],
  "19": [
    {
      "id": 101,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sound and its Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«تَصْدِیَۃ» refers to a sound like clapping (1 verse: 8:35)",
      "d": "( صَدِیَ ) means to clap with both hands (M L) and includes all musical instruments and accessories. For example: The Quran states: «وَمَا کَانَ صَلَاتُہُمۡ عِنۡدَ الۡبَیۡتِ اِلَّا مُکَآءً وَّ تَصۡدِیَۃً» (8/35). Translation: And their prayer at the House was nothing but whistling and clapping."
    },
    {
      "id": 102,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sound and Its Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«تَغَیُّظ» (Taghayyuth) is used for the sound of fury and anger, i.e., irritation and harshness. (9 verses: 3:119-3:134-9:15-9:120-22:15-25:12-33:25-48:29-67:8)",
      "d": "«تَغَیُّظ» (Taghayyuth) means fury and rage, i.e., the sound of anger and harshness (Majma'). Figuratively, it refers to the sounds produced by the intensity and fury of the Hellfire.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِذَارَاَتۡہُمۡ مِّنۡ مَّکَانٍۭ بَعِیۡدٍ سَمِعُوۡا لَہَا تَغَیُّظًا وَّ زَفِیۡرًا» (25/12)\nTranslation: When they see it from a distant place, they will hear its fury and roaring."
    },
    {
      "id": 103,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sound and its Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«حَسِیْس» is used for a very light sound like the sound of footsteps (1 verse: 21:102)",
      "d": "«حَسِیْس» means the sound of footsteps, a light sound (Munjid), the sound of a crackling fire (F L 2, 3). For example: The Quran states: «لَا یَسۡمَعُوۡنَ حَسِیۡسَہَا ۚ وَ ہُمۡ  فِیۡ مَا اشۡتَہَتۡ اَنۡفُسُہُمۡ  خٰلِدُوۡنَ» (21/102). Translation: They will not hear its slightest sound, and they will remain forever in what their souls desire. (Uthmaniؒ)"
    },
    {
      "id": 104,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sound and its Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«خُوَار» is used for the sound of a calf or bull (2 verses: 7:148, 20:88)",
      "d": "«خُوَار» means the sound of an ox, cow, or calf (F L 193). For example: The Quran states: «وَ اتَّخَذَ قَوۡمُ  مُوۡسٰی مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہٖ مِنۡ حُلِیِّہِمۡ عِجۡلًا جَسَدًا لَّہٗ خُوَارٌ» (7/148). Translation: And the people of Moses took from after him from their ornaments a calf, a body that had a lowing sound."
    },
    {
      "id": 105,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sound and its Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«رِكْزًا» is used for a very faint sound like the buzzing of a fly (1 verse: 19:98)",
      "d": "«رِکْز» means a faint and low sound (F L 193), and according to some, it means the buzzing or humming of a fly. For example: The Quran states: «وَکَمۡ اَہۡلَکۡنَا قَبۡلَہُمۡ مِّنۡ قَرۡنٍ ؕ ہَلۡ تُحِسُّ مِنۡہُمۡ مِّنۡ  اَحَدٍ اَوۡ تَسۡمَعُ لَہُمۡ رِکۡزًا» (19/98). Translation: And how many generations We destroyed before them! Can you perceive any of them or hear even a whisper from them?"
    },
    {
      "id": 107,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sound and its Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«شَھِیْق» refers to the high-pitched sound at the end of a donkey's bray (2 verses: 11:106, 67:7)",
      "d": "«شَھِیْق» is the sound when a donkey finishes braying, a high-pitched sound that then begins to decrease (F L 34). Zafir and Shahiq are opposites (M L). For example: The Quran states: «فَاَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ شَقُوۡا فَفِی النَّارِ لَہُمۡ فِیۡہَا زَفِیۡرٌ  وَّ شَہِیۡقٌ» (11/106). Translation: Then as for those who are wretched, they will be in the Fire. For them therein is sighing and weeping. These sounds may arise from the Fire of Hell which they will hear, or from the intensity of heat and thirst causing such sounds to emerge from within them."
    },
    {
      "id": 109,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sound and its Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«صَدَّ» is used for screaming, shouting, or groaning (2 verses: 15:94, 43:57)",
      "d": "«یَصِدُّ صَدِیْدًا» means the sound of screaming and shouting when a person falls (F L 192), but in the Quran, this word is used only in the meaning of screaming and shouting. For example: The Quran states: «وَ لَمَّا ضُرِبَ ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ  مَثَلًا  اِذَا قَوۡمُکَ مِنۡہُ  یَصِدُّوۡنَ» (43/57). Translation: And when the son of Mary is presented as an example, your people laugh at it."
    },
    {
      "id": 110,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sound and its Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«صَرَخَ» is used for the sound of shouting in the form of a cry for help (3 verses: 14:22, 28:18, 35:37)",
      "d": "«صَرَخَ» means the sound of shouting in distress and panic, a cry for help (F L). For example: The Quran states: «وَہُمۡ یَصۡطَرِخُوۡنَ فِیۡہَا ۚ رَبَّنَاۤ اَخۡرِجۡنَا نَعۡمَلۡ صَالِحًا غَیۡرَ الَّذِیۡ کُنَّا نَعۡمَلُ» (35/37). Translation: They will cry out therein, 'Our Lord, take us out; we will do righteous deeds, other than what we used to do.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 112,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sound and its Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«صَوْت» is used for every kind of sound, whether faint or loud, from a living being or inanimate object, meaningless or meaningful (3 verses: 17:64, 31:19, 49:2)",
      "d": "«صَوْت» in Arabic is used for every kind of sound, whether produced by speech or by the collision of objects. One definition is: 'That which emerges from the mouth, if it does not consist of words and letters, then it is sound,' but this definition is not reliable (Muheet). For example: The Quran states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا  الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَرۡفَعُوۡۤا اَصۡوَاتَکُمۡ  فَوۡقَ صَوۡتِ النَّبِیِّ» (49/2). Translation: O you who have believed, do not raise your voices above the voice of the Prophet. And evidently, the companions' speech in the presence of the Prophet ﷺ was meaningful; meaningless sounds did not occur. However, Ibn Faris has given a comprehensive definition: 'Everything that strikes the ear of a listener' (M L). Everything that strikes the listener's ear is sound. In the Quran, some sounds are from living beings and some from inanimate objects. We will mention them in the same order. Sounds from living beings: «صَد، صَرَخ، ھَمَس، حَسِیْس، مُکَاء (مَکُو) تَصْدِیَۃ، ضَبَح، خُوَار، زَفِیْر، شَھِیْق، لَھَث»"
    },
    {
      "id": 113,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sounds and Their Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«صَیْحَۃً» is used for a loud and meaningless sound (13 verses: 11:67, 11:94, 15:73, 15:83, 23:41, 29:40, 36:29, 36:49, 36:53, 38:15, 50:42, 54:31, 63:4)",
      "d": "«صَیْحَۃً» means to shout with a piercing voice. The sound of the trumpet (muf). Such a sound that causes hearts to tremble, a thunderous sound, an explosion. That is, whenever there is intensity in any sound. Every loud and meaningless sound is called «صَیْحَۃً» (faqih 26). For example, the Quran says: «فَاَخَذَتۡہُمُ الصَّیۡحَۃُ  مُشۡرِقِیۡنَ . فَجَعَلۡنَا عَالِیَہَا سَافِلَہَا» (15/73,74). Translation: So the shout seized them while they were rising. And We made the highest parts of it the lowest."
    },
    {
      "id": 114,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sound and its Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«ضَبَحَ» is used for the sound of panting while running (1 verse: 100:1)",
      "d": "«ضَبَحَ» means the sound of a horse panting due to swift running (F L 199). For example: The Quran states: «وَالۡعٰدِیٰتِ ضَبۡحًا» (100/1). Translation: By the chargers at dawn, panting."
    },
    {
      "id": 115,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sounds and Their Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«غَلْی» is used for the sound of a cauldron boiling (3 verses: 44:45, 44:46)",
      "d": "«غَلْی» means the sound of a cauldron boiling and seething. The sound of opening (muf). For example, the Quran says: «کَالۡمُہۡلِ یَغۡلِیۡ  فِی الۡبُطُوۡنِ . کَغَلۡیِ  الۡحَمِیۡمِ» (44/45,46). Translation: Like molten metal, boiling in their bellies. Like the boiling of hot water."
    },
    {
      "id": 117,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sound and its Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«لَھَثَ» refers to the sound of a dog panting or gasping due to intense heat or thirst. (1 Verse: 7:176)",
      "d": "«لَھَثَ» is the sound of a dog panting, caused by intense heat or thirst, where it sticks out its tongue and pants or gasps. (Source: Mufradat, Manjad)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَمَثَلُہٗ کَمَثَلِ الۡکَلۡبِ ۚ اِنۡ تَحۡمِلۡ عَلَیۡہِ یَلۡہَثۡ اَوۡ تَتۡرُکۡہُ یَلۡہَثۡ» (7/176)\nTranslation: The example of such a person is that of a dog; if you attack it, it pants, and if you leave it, it still pants.\nIt is also used for the sounds of inanimate objects."
    },
    {
      "id": 118,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sound and its Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«مُکَآءً» is used for producing a whistling sound from the mouth. (1 Verse: 8:35)",
      "d": "«مُکَآءً» means to whistle (Manjad), and it encompasses all melodies and tunes within it."
    },
    {
      "id": 119,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sound and its Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«ھَدّ» is used for the sound of a building, wall, pillar, etc., collapsing. (1 Verse: 19:90)",
      "d": "«ھَدّ» refers to the sound of something like a building, wall, or pillar collapsing, such as a thudding sound. (Source: F L 194)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«تَکَادُ السَّمٰوٰتُ یَتَفَطَّرۡنَ مِنۡہُ وَ تَنۡشَقُّ الۡاَرۡضُ وَ تَخِرُّ الۡجِبَالُ ہَدًّا» (19/90)\nTranslation: The heavens are almost torn apart from above it, and the earth splits open, and the mountains crash down utterly."
    },
    {
      "id": 120,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sound and its Types",
      "hw": "Sound",
      "s": "«ھَمْس» refers to any slight sound produced by a person's movement. (1 Verse: 20:108)",
      "d": "«ھَمْس» is used for the sound of any human movement (Source: F L 193), such as a rustling, whispering, or murmuring sound (Manjad). «اَلصَّوْتُ الْخَفِیِّ وَاَحَسّ» (M L) implies any soft and perceptible sound from a person.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ خَشَعَتِ الۡاَصۡوَاتُ لِلرَّحۡمٰنِ فَلَا تَسۡمَعُ اِلَّا ہَمۡسًا» (20/108)\nTranslation: And all voices will be humbled before the Most Merciful, so you will hear nothing but a whisper."
    }
  ],
  "20": [
    {
      "id": 121,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Gradually",
      "hw": " آہستہ",
      "s": "«ااِسْتِدْراج» means to approach something else degree by degree and gradually. (2 Verses: 7:182, 68:44)",
      "d": "«دَرَجَۃ» refers to the steps of a ladder when climbing up, while «ااِسْتِدْراج» means to bring one thing near another gradually and step by step (Mufradat), so that it goes unnoticed. Thus, «ااِسْتِدْراج» necessitates gradualness and caution in such matters.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَذَّبُوۡا بِاٰیٰتِنَا سَنَسۡتَدۡرِجُہُمۡ مِّنۡ حَیۡثُ لَا یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ» (7/182)\nTranslation: And those who deny Our signs, We will gradually seize them from where they perceive not. (Jalandhari) We will seize them gradually. (Osmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 123,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Gradually",
      "hw": " آہستہ",
      "s": "«رُخَاءً» refers to wind blowing so gently and softly that it does not stir anything. (1 Verse: 38:36)",
      "d": "«رُخَاءً» means wind blowing so gently and gradually that it does not move anything (Manjad). It signifies wind moving softly and slowly (Source: F L 46).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَسَخَّرۡنَا لَہُ الرِّیۡحَ تَجۡرِیۡ بِاَمۡرِہٖ رُخَآءً حَیۡثُ اَصَابَ» (38/36)\nTranslation: Then We subjected the wind to him, so it blew gently in his direction wherever he willed."
    },
    {
      "id": 125,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Gradually",
      "hw": " آہستہ",
      "s": "«عُرْفًا» refers to wind blowing with gentleness, where it carries comfort and peace. (1 Verse: 77:1)",
      "d": "«عُرْفًا» means wind blowing softly, bringing peace and comfort. «العرْف» means fragrance. It is often used for fragrance (Manjad). And such winds that generally blow at a gentle pace. The breeze of dawn.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ الۡمُرۡسَلٰتِ عُرۡفًا» (77/1)\nTranslation: By the winds sent forth, gently (Osmani)."
    },
    {
      "id": 126,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Gradually",
      "hw": " آہستہ",
      "s": "«یُسْرًا» means to accomplish a task effortlessly, with ease and facility, without any resistance. (19 Verses: 2:185, 2:280, 18:88, 19:97, 20:26, 44:58, 51:3, 54:17, 54:22, 54:32, 54:40, 65:4, 65:7, 80:20, 87:8, 92:7, 92:10, 94:5, 94:6)",
      "d": "«یُسْر» means ease and facility, and its opposite is «عُسْر», meaning hardship. The word «یُسْرًا» also describes a state where a task is accomplished effortlessly and smoothly, without any jolt or obstacle.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَالۡجٰرِیٰتِ یُسۡرًا» (51/3)\nTranslation: Then the ships sailing with ease. (Jalandhari) Then the ships moving along easily. (Osmani)\nHere, «یُسْر» does not imply slowness but rather that despite moving swiftly, there is no jolt, sway, or sound produced, making it seem as if they are moving gently and smoothly."
    }
  ],
  "21": [
    {
      "id": 127,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Boiling / Seething",
      "hw": "اُبلنا",
      "s": "«غَلْی» means to boil or surge due to heat, exceeding its original level because of an obstruction. (2 Verses: 44:45, 44:46)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «غَلَا» is to exceed one's limit and rise up. From this, «غَلَا الْقِدْر» means the pot boils, and «غَلَا السَّعْر» means prices rise. (M L)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کَالۡمُہۡلِ ۚ ۛ یَغۡلِیۡ فِی الۡبُطُوۡنِ کَغَلۡیِ الۡحَمِیۡمِ» (44/45, 46)\nTranslation: Like molten metal; it will boil within their bellies like the boiling of hot water."
    },
    {
      "id": 128,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Boiling / Seething",
      "hw": "اُبلنا",
      "s": "«فَار» means the continuous boiling or seething of something due to intensity and haste. (2 Verses: 11:40, 23:27)",
      "d": "The word «فَار» is used for something boiling in a pot, water gushing from a spring, or fire blazing. However, it is used when the boiling rises quickly and repeatedly, as «اَلْفَوْر» means very hastily. It is said «رَجَعَ مِنْ فَوْرَہٗ» meaning he returned very quickly without delay. (Manjad) The word «فوارہ» (fountain) also derives from this, where water flows continuously.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا جَآءَ اَمۡرُنَا وَ فَارَ التَّنُّوۡرُ» (11/40)\nTranslation: Until, when Our command came and the oven boiled over."
    },
    {
      "id": 129,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To boil; to surge",
      "hw": "اُبلنا",
      "s": "«نَضَخَ» means water gushing forth forcefully due to abundance and pressure (1 Verse: 55:66)",
      "d": "«نَضَخَ» means a spring gushing forth with force (munjad). However, in «نَضَخَ», the cause of surging is the abundance of water and pressure, not heat. «نَضَّاخ» is also used for a torrential downpour. And «عَیْنٌ نَضَّاخَۃٌ» is a spring that surges due to an abundance of water (m. l.).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فِیۡہِمَا عَیۡنٰنِ نَضَّاخَتٰنِ» (55/66)\nTranslation: In both (gardens) are two gushing springs."
    }
  ],
  "22": [
    {
      "id": 130,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To raise; to incite",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "«اَزَّ» means to incite someone to an evil deed in such a way that they are unaware of it (2 Verses: 2:36-19:83)",
      "d": "«اَزَّ» means to incite someone to an evil deed in such a way that they are unaware of it. And to uproot someone from their place (m. l.). «اَزِیْز» also refers to the sound of a pot boiling. This word is generally used in a negative sense.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَمۡ تَرَ اَنَّـاۤ اَرۡسَلۡنَا الشَّیٰطِیۡنَ عَلَی الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ تَؤُزُّہُمۡ اَزًّا» (19/83)\nTranslation: Do you not see that We have appointed the devils upon the disbelievers, inciting them (to evil) continually?"
    },
    {
      "id": 131,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Elevation; rise",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "«اَمْت» refers to a small hill or mound that has no order in its height and extent (1 Verse: 20:107)",
      "d": "«اَمْت» is the opposite of «عِوَجْ» (meaning depression). «عِوَجْ» and «اَمْت» mean valleys and hills. And «اَمْت» means a small hill or mound. A high place (munjad), i.e., an elevation and extent that has no order.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَّا تَرٰی فِیۡہَا عِوَجًا وَّ لَاۤ اَمۡتًا» (20/107)\nTranslation: Wherein they will see no crookedness (depression) nor any mound (or elevation)."
    },
    {
      "id": 132,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To raise; to incite",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "«جَرَمَ» is used for inciting and instigating someone towards sinful deeds (3 Verses: 5:2-5:8-40:43)",
      "d": "«جَرَمَ» (a verbal noun) refers to sin and fault. When this verb is used, its meaning is to incite someone, to instigate them towards a grave sin, i.e., a deed that causes loss of life or is harmful. Lexicons do not support this meaning, but translations, e.g., by Jalandhari, Osmani, and Tafheem ul Quran, all confirm this meaning.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا یَجۡرِمَنَّکُمۡ شَنَاٰنُ قَوۡمٍ عَلَی اَلَّا تَعۡدِلُوۡا» (5/8)\nTranslation: And let not the enmity of a people prevent you from being just."
    },
    {
      "id": 133,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Elevation",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "«حَدَب» is used for a hunchback person, and also for a mound that is low in height but wide in expanse (1 verse: 21:96)",
      "d": "«حَدَبَ الرَّجُل» means a man being hunchbacked, and «حَدَب» means hunchbackedness. Metaphorically, it is also used for high and hard ground of that shape. A mound that is wide in expanse and low in height, and this elevation or slope resembles hunchbackedness. «مُحَدَّب against مُجَوَّف» refers to spectacles used for correcting distant and near-sightedness, and «مُحَدَّب» also means a convex lens (Adasah) because such glass bulges out on both sides like a pomegranate seed. For example: The Quran states: «حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا  فُتِحَتۡ یَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ مَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ ہُمۡ  مِّنۡ  کُلِّ  حَدَبٍ  یَّنۡسِلُوۡنَ» (21/96). Translation: Until when Gog and Magog are let loose, and they swoop down from every elevated place."
    },
    {
      "id": 134,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To raise; to incite",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "«حَرَضَ» means to become severely ill, to waste away, and to be near death (3 Verses: 4:84-8:65-12:85)",
      "d": "«حَرَضَ» means to become severely ill, to waste away, and to be near death (m. l., m. q.).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا تَاللّٰہِ تَفۡتَؤُا تَذۡکُرُ یُوۡسُفَ حَتّٰی تَکُوۡنَ حَرَضًا اَوۡ تَکُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡہٰلِکِیۡنَ» (12/85)\nTranslation: (Jacob's sons said to their father): They said, \"By Allah, you will not cease to remember Joseph until you become ill (from grief) or become of those who perish.\"\nAnd «حَرَضَ» means to exhort towards something, the neglect of which causes destruction and ruin (m. l.). That is, to incite someone towards such a deed, or to create eagerness for it, that if it is not done, it leads to destruction and ruin.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّبِیُّ حَرِّضِ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ عَلَی الۡقِتَالِ ؕ اِنۡ یَّکُنۡ مِّنۡکُمۡ عِشۡرُوۡنَ صٰبِرُوۡنَ یَغۡلِبُوۡا مِائَتَیۡنِ» (8/65)\nTranslation: O Prophet! Exhort the believers to fight. If there are twenty steadfast among you, they will overcome two hundred."
    },
    {
      "id": 136,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Elevation; rise",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "«سَمْک» means to make something thick and high, such as the height and thickness of a roof (1 Verse: 79:28)",
      "d": "«سَمْک» means to raise. To make thick. And «سَمْک» is also used for a roof or the thickness of a roof. Also, it refers to the height and stature of anything that is high and thick (munjad). And «سَنَامٌ سَامِکٌ» means a camel's high hump (m. q.).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَشَدُّ خَلۡقًا اَمِ السَّمَآءُ ؕ بَنٰہَا رَفَعَ سَمۡکَہَا فَسَوّٰىہَا» (79/27,28)\nTranslation: Is your creation harder or the creation of the heaven? He raised its height and made it even."
    },
    {
      "id": 137,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Elevation; rise",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "«کَعَبْ» refers to a protruding bone. In the Noble Quran, this word was used for the ankle and for the houris with protruding breasts (1 Verse: 78:33)",
      "d": "«کَعَبْ» means ankle. Any protrusion that is like an ankle is also called 'k'ab'. «کَعَبَتِ الْجَارِیَۃ» means the girl's breasts are protruding and large. «کُعَب» means a woman's protruding breasts, and «کاعِب» is the term for a woman whose breasts are raised. Its plural is «کَوَاعِب», meaning young women (muf, munjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ لِلۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ مَفَازًا حَدَآئِقَ وَ اَعۡنَابًا وَّکَوَاعِبَ اَتۡرَابًا» (78/31,32,33)\nTranslation: Indeed, for the righteous is attainment (of Paradise), gardens and grapevines and full-bosomed maidens of equal age.\nIf the extent and height of an elevation are approximately equal, it is called «کَعَب» and «نَجَد»; the only difference is in quantity (mass). If the extent is more and the height is less, it is «حَدْب». If the extent is less and the height is more, it is «سَمک». And if there is no order or proportion in height and extent, it is «اَمْت»."
    },
    {
      "id": 138,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Elevation; rise",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "«نَجْد» is used for land that is hard and high and has no trees, etc. (1 Verse: 90:10)",
      "d": "«نَجْد» means hard, high land with no trees, etc. Like 'k'ab', it is a large hill. It also means a small mountain, a valley, and the path for ascending and descending. Also, meanings related to a woman's breasts are found (munjad, m. q.). And the word «نَجْدَیْن» is used idiomatically for a woman's two breasts, for the contrast between truth and falsehood, and for beautiful and ugly (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ ہَدَیۡنٰہُ النَّجۡدَیۡنِ . فَلَا اقۡتَحَمَ الۡعَقَبَۃَ» (90/10,11)\nTranslation: And We have shown him the two highways (of good and evil). But he has not attempted the steep path."
    }
  ],
  "23": [
    {
      "id": 139,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To bring down; to descend",
      "hw": "اتارنا ",
      "s": "In «اَحَلَّ», the act of bringing down occurs as a result of some good or evil deed of the one descending (2 Verses: 14:28-35:35)",
      "d": "«اَحَلَّ» means to bring someone else down to a place. And this happens as a result of an action of the one who descends. It comes in both good and bad contexts.\nFor example, for good: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ قَالُوا الۡحَمۡدُ لِلّٰہِ الَّذِیۡۤ اَذۡہَبَ عَنَّا الۡحَزَنَ ؕ اِنَّ رَبَّنَا لَغَفُوۡرٌ شَکُوۡرٌ ۔ الَّذِیۡۤ اَحَلَّنَا دَارَ الۡمُقَامَۃِ مِنۡ فَضۡلِہٖ» (35/34,35)\nTranslation: They will say, \"All praise is for Allah, who has removed from us all sorrow. Indeed, our Lord is Forgiving and Appreciative. Who has settled us in the eternal home by His favor.\"\nAnd for evil: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَمۡ تَرَ اِلَی الَّذِیۡنَ بَدَّلُوۡا نِعۡمَتَ اللّٰہِ کُفۡرًا وَّاَحَلُّوۡا قَوۡمَہُمۡ دَارَالۡبَوَارِ» (14/28)\nTranslation: Do you not see those who exchanged the favor of Allah for disbelief and led their people to the home of ruin?"
    },
    {
      "id": 141,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to descend / to get down",
      "hw": "اتارنا ",
      "s": "«حَلَّ» is used for the purpose of settling or staying in a place (8 verses: 11:39-14:28-20:27-20:81-20:86-35:35-39:40-90:2)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «حَلَّ» is 'to untie a knot,' and its opposite is «عَقَدَ», meaning 'to tie a knot.' «اَرْبابِ حَلّ وَ عَقْد» is a common phrase meaning 'owners of tying and untying.' That is, this quality of tying and untying luggage exists: a traveler ties his luggage and sets out on a journey, and when he needs to stay somewhere, he unties it. Therefore, the word «حَلَّ» began to be used in the sense of staying and descending (m. l.). And just as a traveler stays and unties his luggage, similarly the word «حَلَّ» comes as a result of an action. It is said: «مَنْ جَرَّبَ الْمُجَرَّبَ حَلَّتْ بِہٖ النَّدَامَۃ» meaning 'Whoever tests a tested thing, regret descends upon him.'\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«مَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡہِ عَذَابٌ یُّخۡزِیۡہِ وَ یَحِلُّ عَلَیۡہِ عَذَابٌ مُّقِیۡمٌ» (39/40)\nTranslation: Upon whom comes a punishment that will disgrace him, and upon whom comes a lasting punishment?"
    },
    {
      "id": 142,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to descend / to get down",
      "hw": "اتارنا ",
      "s": "«خَلَعَ» is used to separate something that was previously included in it (1 verse: 20:12)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «خَلَعَ» is to separate something that was previously included (m. l.). The word «خُلع» also carries this meaning: a woman separates from her husband by paying compensation, and divorce occurs.\nIn the Noble Quran, this word has been used for removing shoes from the feet (taking them off).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِنِّیۡۤ  اَنَا رَبُّکَ فَاخۡلَعۡ نَعۡلَیۡکَ ۚ اِنَّکَ بِالۡوَادِ الۡمُقَدَّسِ طُوًی» (20/12)\nTranslation: (O Moses) Indeed, I am your Lord, so remove your sandals. You are in the sacred valley, Tuwa.\nAnd there is a strange relation in «خَلَعَ» that in ancient civilizations, a woman was symbolized by the shoes on her feet."
    },
    {
      "id": 143,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to descend / to get down",
      "hw": "اتارنا ",
      "s": "The word «نَزَلَ» is general. «تَنَزُّل» is used for divine revelation, commandments, and Satanic whisperings (12 verses: 17:105-26:193-26:210-26:221-26:222-34:2-37:177-41:30-57:4-57:16-65:12-97:4)",
      "d": "The well-known meaning of «نَزَلَ» is 'to descend.' Something coming down from a height (muf). This word is used generally. «نُزُوْل» is also its opposite, meaning both «صَعُوْد» (ascending) and «عُرُوْج» (rising).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ مَا یَنۡزِلُ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ وَمَا یَعۡرُجُ فِیۡہَا» (57/4)\nTranslation: And whatever descends from the heaven and whatever ascends in it.\nAnd «تَنَزَّلَ بِہٖ» is synonymous with «نَزَلَ بِہٖ». Both words are used for the descent of angels and divine commandments.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«نَزَلَ بِہِ الرُّوۡحُ  الۡاَمِیۡنُ» (26/193)\nTranslation: The Trustworthy Spirit descended with it.\nAt another place, the Divine command states:\n« تَنَزَّلُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ وَ الرُّوۡحُ  فِیۡہَا بِاِذۡنِ رَبِّہِمۡ ۚ مِنۡ  کُلِّ  اَمۡرٍ» (97/4)\nTranslation: In it (the Night of Decree), the angels and the Spirit (Al-Amin) descend with their Lord's permission for every matter.\nBut for Satanic whisperings, only «تَنَزَّلَ بِہٖ» will be used (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«ہَلۡ اُنَبِّئُکُمۡ عَلٰی مَنۡ تَنَزَّلُ الشَّیٰطِیۡنُ تَنَزَّلُ عَلَیۡ کُلِّ اَفَّاکٍ اَثِیۡمٍ» (26:221,222)\nTranslation: Shall I inform you upon whom the devils descend? They descend upon every lying, sinful person."
    },
    {
      "id": 144,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to descend / to get down",
      "hw": "اتارنا ",
      "s": "«ھَبَطَ» is used for descending, falling, or coming out in a state of anger and helplessness (8 verses: 2:36-2:38-2:61-2:74-7:13-7:24-11:48-20:123)",
      "d": "«ھَبَطَ» means to come down from something in a state of anger and compulsion, or to fall, or to come out, like a stone falling from a height (muf). To come out involuntarily, to fall from one's status, and to go from height to lowliness—all are included in this meaning. Now observe some examples:\n(1) For descending from a mount:\nThe Divine command states:\n«قِیۡلَ یٰنُوۡحُ اہۡبِطۡ بِسَلٰمٍ مِّنَّا وَ بَرَکٰتٍ عَلَیۡکَ» (11/48)\nTranslation: It was said, 'O Noah, descend with peace from Us and blessings upon you.'\n(2) For something descending with anxiety and fear:\nThe Divine command states:\n«وَ اِنَّ مِنۡہَا لَمَا یَہۡبِطُ مِنۡ خَشۡیَۃِ اللّٰہِ» (2/74)\nTranslation: And indeed, among them are those that descend (or break off) from the fear of Allah.\n(3) For coming out having fallen from one's rank (or being humiliated):\nThe Divine command states:\n«فَاَزَلَّہُمَا الشَّیۡطٰنُ عَنۡہَا فَاَخۡرَجَہُمَا مِمَّا کَانَا فِیۡہِ ۪ وَ قُلۡنَا اہۡبِطُوۡا بَعۡضُکُمۡ لِبَعۡضٍ عَدُوٌّ» (2/36)\nTranslation: Then Satan caused them to slip from it (Paradise) and brought them out from what they were in. And We said, 'Descend (from here), some of you being enemies to others.'\nA poet expressed this meaning in these words:\nWe have heard of Adam's expulsion from Paradise,\nBut we came out from your lane having been greatly disgraced!"
    },
    {
      "id": 145,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to descend / to get down",
      "hw": "اتارنا ",
      "s": "«وَضَعَ» is used for taking something down and placing it below (7 verses: 3:36-18:49-39:69-46:15-55:7-55:10-94:2)",
      "d": "The basic meanings of «وَضَعَ» are 'to place down' (muf). The word «وَضَعَ» is also used in the meanings of removing a burden and load, and in pregnancy, the burden is removed.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ وَضَعۡنَا عَنۡکَ وِزۡرَکَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَنۡقَضَ ظَہۡرَکَ» (94/2,3)\nTranslation: And We have removed from you your burden which weighed down your back.\nThen this word began to be used generally for 'to take down'.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«حِیۡنَ تَضَعُوۡنَ ثِیَابَکُمۡ مِّنَ الظَّہِیۡرَۃِ» (24/58)\nTranslation: And when you lay aside your clothes from the midday heat."
    }
  ],
  "24": [
    {
      "id": 146,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to be arrogant / to show pride",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "«اِخْتَالَ» means to walk in an arrogant manner and to consider others contemptible (3 verses: 4:36-31:18-57:23)",
      "d": "According to Ibn Faris, «خَیْل» means 'a movement that changes its color every moment' (m. l.). «تَخَیُّلْ» means to imagine something, to be proud, and «اِخْتَال» means to walk with a swagger and to walk with the gait of pride. (Majma') Thus, the mind of such a person is on a higher level than ordinary people, and it is a degree above «مَرَحَ»."
    },
    {
      "id": 148,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to be arrogant / to show pride",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "«بَطَرَ» means to be ungrateful for Allah's blessing and to use it incorrectly (2 verses: 8:47-28:58)",
      "d": "«بَطَرَ» means to go astray due to the abundance of blessings and, according to Imam Raghib, «بَطَر» is a terror that befalls a person due to the misuse of prosperity, falling short in the right of a blessing, and incorrect use of a blessing (muf). And according to Ibn Faris, the original meaning of «بَطَر» is 'to tear.' That is, as if the abundance of a blessing has torn someone's eyes, and he does not care for anyone. Thus, in the meaning of «بَطَر», the abundance of a blessing, ingratitude, and incorrect use are present, and it is a degree above «فَرِحَ».\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ کَمۡ  اَہۡلَکۡنَا مِنۡ قَرۡیَۃٍۭ  بَطِرَتۡ مَعِیۡشَتَہَا» (28/58)\nTranslation: And how many a town We have destroyed while it was arrogant in its prosperity."
    },
    {
      "id": 149,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to be arrogant / to show pride",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "«تَکَبَّرَ» is the final degree of pride: rejecting the truth and considering people contemptible (57 verses: 2:34-2:87-2:185-4:172-4:173-5:82-6:93-7:13-6:36-7:40-7:48-7:75-7:76-7:88-7:133-7:146-7:206-10:75-14:21-16:22-16:23-16:29-16:49-21:19-22:37-23:46-23:67-25:21-28:39-29:39-31:7-32:15-34:31-34:32-34:33-37:35-38:74-38:75-39:59-39:60-39:72-40:27-40:35-40:47-40:48-40:60-40:76-41:15-41:38-45:8-45:31-46:10-46:20-59:23-63:5-71:7-74:23)",
      "d": "«تَکَبَّرَ» is the ultimate stage of pride in which a person becomes a victim of 'ujb' (self-admiration), pride, arrogance, egotism, and self-love. He considers himself better than others and free from error. And egotism reaches such an extent that he starts considering others contemptible and denies the truth. As narrated in a hadith: «الْكِبَرُ بَطَرُ الْحَقِّ وَغَمْطُ النَّاس» (Al-Adab al-Mufrad by Bukhari). Translation: 'Pride is rejecting the truth and considering people contemptible.'\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«قَالَ فَاہۡبِطۡ مِنۡہَا فَمَا یَکُوۡنُ لَکَ اَنۡ تَتَکَبَّرَ فِیۡہَا» (7/13)\nTranslation: Allah said, 'Then get out from it (Paradise), for you have no right to be arrogant in it.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 150,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to be arrogant / to show pride",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "«تَمَطّٰی» means to walk with arms spread out due to pride and arrogance (1 verse: 75:33)",
      "d": "«مُطَوَّ» means, in walking, pride, arrogance—to spread out one's arms, to show nonchalance. To walk with arms spread out with pride (f. l. 178).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَلَا صَدَّقَ وَلَا صَلّٰی وَ لٰکِنۡ کَذَّبَ وَتَوَلّٰی ثُمَّ ذَہَبَ اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہٖ یَتَمَطّٰی» (75/31,32,33)\nTranslation: So he neither believed nor prayed, but he denied and turned away. Then he went to his people, swaggering."
    },
    {
      "id": 151,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to be arrogant / to show pride",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "«فَخَرَ» means to boast about things that do not even exist within oneself (4 verses: 4:36-11:10-31:18-57:23)",
      "d": "«فَخَرَ» means to show off one's greatness, i.e., to praise oneself and to mention a quality that does not exist. For example, to boast about lineage and ancestry or to show pride in inherited wealth and property (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَلَا تُصَعِّرۡخَدَّکَ لِلنَّاسِ وَلَا تَمۡشِ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مَرَحًا ؕ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یُحِبُّ کُلَّ مُخۡتَالٍ فَخُوۡرٍ» (21/18)\nTranslation: And do not turn your cheek [in contempt] toward people and do not walk through the earth exultantly. Indeed, Allah does not like every arrogant boaster.\nIn this verse, Allah has mentioned three contemptible (bad) traits in sequence: «مَرَحَ» (exultant walking), «اِخْتَال» (swaggering), and «فَخَرَ» (boasting)."
    },
    {
      "id": 152,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Arrogance / Boasting",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "«فَرِحَ» is used to express joy and to thank God for His blessings, and also to denote arrogance and ingratitude towards them. (21 verses: 3:120-3:170-3:188-6:44-9:50-9:81-10:22-10:58-11:10-13:26-13:36-23:53-27:36-28:76-30:4-30:32-30:36-40:75-40:83-42:48-57:23)",
      "d": "«فَرِحَ» is used in two ways: «فَرِحَ الْقَلْب» (rejoicing of the heart) and «فَرِحَ النَّفْس» (rejoicing of the self). «فَرِحَ الْقَلْب» means to be sincerely grateful for a blessing, which is a good trait. For example, in the Quran: «قُلۡ بِفَضۡلِ اللّٰہِ وَ بِرَحۡمَتِہٖ فَبِذٰلِکَ فَلۡیَفۡرَحُوۡا ؕ ہُوَخَیۡرٌمِّمَّا یَجۡمَعُوۡنَ» (10/58). Translation: Say, [O Muhammad], 'It is by the grace of Allah and His mercy that you should rejoice. It is better than what they collect.' And «فَرِحَ النَّفْس» is a bad trait, meaning to become arrogant and proud instead of thanking God for His blessings. For example, in the Quran: «اِذۡ  قَالَ لَہٗ قَوۡمُہٗ لَا تَفۡرَحۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یُحِبُّ الۡفَرِحِیۡنَ» (28/76). Translation: When his people said to him, 'Do not exult. Indeed, Allah does not like the exultant.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 153,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Arrogance / Boasting",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "«فَرِہَ» is used for boasting about one's skill. (1 verse: 26:149)",
      "d": "«فَرِہَ» means to be happy, to be arrogant, and «فَرِہَ» also means to be skilled, experienced, happy, light, and «فَارِہٌ» means agile and skillful. (Manjad) Essentially, «فَرِہَ» comes for being happy, arrogant, and proud about one's craft and skill. For example, in the Quran: «وَ تَنۡحِتُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡجِبَالِ بُیُوۡتًا فٰرِہِیۡنَ» (26/149). Translation: And you carve out of the mountains, homes, [with] skill. (Jalandhari) Or, you build proud structures. (Maududi)"
    },
    {
      "id": 154,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Arrogance / Boasting",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "«مَرَحَ» means to exult with joy and to walk with pride and vanity. (3 verses: 17:37-31:18-40:75)",
      "d": "«مَرَحَ» means to begin to exult with joy, «شِدّۃُ الْفَرْحِ» (intensity of joy), to walk with pride and vanity. For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَا تَمۡشِ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مَرَحًا ۚ اِنَّکَ  لَنۡ تَخۡرِقَ الۡاَرۡضَ وَ لَنۡ تَبۡلُغَ الۡجِبَالَ طُوۡلًا» (17/37). Translation: And do not walk upon the earth exultantly. Indeed, you will never tear the earth [apart], and you will never reach the mountains in height."
    }
  ],
  "25": [
    {
      "id": 155,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To guess randomly or to fabricate stories",
      "hw": "من گھڑت",
      "s": "«اِخْتَلَقَ» means a statement that has some truth but the rest is fiction, a falsehood that seems true. (1 verse: 38:7)",
      "d": "«خَلَقَ» means to create something from pre-existing material, and «اِخْتَلَقَ» means to make a statement that has some truth mixed with falsehood, to smooth it out, to fabricate. «اِخْتِرَاع» is specifically used for a falsehood that is presented as true. (Faqih) For example, in the Quran: «مَا سَمِعۡنَا بِہٰذَا فِی الۡمِلَّۃِ  الۡاٰخَرَۃِ  ۚ ۖ اِنۡ ہٰذَاۤ اِلَّا اخۡتِلَاقٌ» (38/7). Translation: (The disbelievers) said, 'We have not heard of this in the latest religion. This is nothing but a fabrication.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 156,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To guess randomly or to fabricate stories",
      "hw": "من گھڑت",
      "s": "«اِفْتَرَاء» means lying with the intention of causing corruption. (53 verses: 3:24-3:94-4:48-4:50-5:103-6:21-6:24-6:93-6:112-6:137-6:138-6:140-6:144-7:37-7:53-7:89-7:152-10:17-10:30-10:37-10:38-10:59-10:60-10:69-11:13-11:18-11:21-11:35-11:50-12:111-16:56-16:87-16:101-16:105-16:116-17:73-18:15-20:61-21:5-23:38-25:4-28:36-28:75-29:13-29:68-32:3-34:8-34:43-42:24-46:8-46:28-60:12-61:7)",
      "d": "«اِفْتَرَاء» originates from «فَرِیَ», which means to lie and cause corruption. (Muhit) For example, in the Quran: «فَاَتَتۡ بِہٖ قَوۡمَہَا تَحۡمِلُہٗ ؕ قَالُوۡا یٰمَرۡیَمُ لَقَدۡ جِئۡتِ شَیۡئًا فَرِیًّا» (19/27). Translation: Then she brought him to her people, carrying him. They said, 'O Mary! You have certainly done a terrible thing.' This verse implies that Mary caused anger and spread corruption. And «اِفْترٰی» refers to a lie or accusation made with the intent to cause corruption, i.e., slander. (Mufradat) For example, in the Quran: «وَاِنۡ کَادُوۡا لَیَفۡتِنُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الَّذِیۡۤ اَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ اِلَیۡکَ لِتَفۡتَرِیَ عَلَیۡنَا غَیۡرَہٗ» (17/73). Translation: And they were about to tempt you away from that which We revealed to you, so that you would invent about Us something else."
    },
    {
      "id": 157,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To guess randomly or to fabricate stories",
      "hw": "من گھڑت",
      "s": "«تَقَوَّل» means to fabricate a false statement and then attribute it to someone else. (26 verses: 2:80-2:104-2:140-2:154-2:169-6:93-6:156-6:157-7:28-7:33-7:172-7:173-10:68-10:77-16:116-17:40-20:94-24:15-39:56-39:57-39:58-52:33-61:2-61:3-69:44-72:5)",
      "d": "«تَقَوَّل» is derived from 'qawl' (speech), which refers to any utterance. Sometimes it refers to something still in the heart. For example, in the Quran: «وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ فِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ لَوۡلَا یُعَذِّبُنَا اللّٰہُ» (58/8). Translation: And they say within themselves, 'Why does Allah not punish us?' And «تَقَوَّل» means to state a falsehood and then attribute it to another. (Manjad) For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَوۡ تَقَوَّلَ عَلَیۡنَا بَعۡضَ الۡاَقَاوِیۡلِ . لَاَخَذۡنَا مِنۡہُ بِالۡیَمِیۡنِ ثُمَّ لَقَطَعۡنَا مِنۡہُ الۡوَتِیۡنَ» (69:44-46). Translation: And if he [i.e., the Prophet] had made up about Us some [false] sayings, We would have seized him by the right hand; then We would have cut from him the aorta."
    },
    {
      "id": 158,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To guess randomly or to fabricate stories",
      "hw": "من گھڑت",
      "s": "«خَرَصَ» means to rely on mere speculation and estimates without reality. (4 verses: 6:116-6:148-10:66-43:20)",
      "d": "«خَرَصَ» means to act based on mere conjecture and estimation. «خَرَصَ النَّخْلَۃَ» means to estimate, by mere guess, that a date palm will bear fruit. And «خَرَّاص» refers to a person who often acts on estimates and guesses. (Manjad) Such a person is generally false and unreliable. For example, in the Quran: «قُتِلَ الۡخَرّٰصُوۡنَ» (51:10-12). Translation: Destroyed are the conjecturers, who are [now] in flux, asking, 'When is the Day of Recompense?'"
    }
  ],
  "26": [
    {
      "id": 160,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift / to carry a burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«اَقَلَّ» means to lift the burden of winds and clouds, considering them light. (2 verses: 7:57-9:38)",
      "d": "«اَقَلَّ» fundamentally has two meanings: (1) to be less, (2) to be elevated. And «اَقَلَّ» means to lift and elevate something. (Manjad) And «اَقَلَّ، اَثَارَ» is stronger and better. That is, to lift the heavy burden of winds and clouds, considering them trivial and insignificant. (Mufradat) Thus, the following verse clarifies this: For example, in the Quran: «وَہُوَالَّذِیۡ یُرۡسِلُ الرِّیٰحَ بُشۡرًۢا بَیۡنَ یَدَیۡ رَحۡمَتِہٖ ؕ حَتّٰۤی اِذَاۤ اَقَلَّتۡ سَحَابًا ثِقَالًا سُقۡنٰہُ لِبَلَدٍ مَّیِّتٍ» (7:57). Translation: And it is He who sends the winds as good tidings before His mercy until, when they have lifted heavy clouds, We drive them to a dead land..."
    },
    {
      "id": 161,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift / to carry a burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«اِلْتَقَطَ» is used for picking up something fallen. (2 verses: 12:10-28:8)",
      "d": "«لَقَطَ» means to pick up something from the ground. «لُقْطَۃ» is an item that has fallen on the ground and its owner is unknown. (Manjad) From this, «اِلْتَقَطَ» is derived, meaning to pick up something fallen whose owner is unknown. For example, in the Quran: «قَالَ قَآئِلٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ لَا تَقۡتُلُوۡا یُوۡسُفَ وَاَلۡقُوۡہُ فِیۡ غَیٰبَتِ الۡجُبِّ یَلۡتَقِطۡہُ بَعۡضُ السَّیَّارَۃِ» (12:10). Translation: One of them said, 'Do not kill Joseph but throw him into the bottom of the pit; some travelers will pick him up.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 162,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift / to carry a burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«اَنْشَرَ» is used on the Day of Resurrection for raising the dead from graves. (10 verses: 18:16-21:21-42:28-43:11-44:35-74:52-77:3-80:22-81:10-94:1)",
      "d": "«نَشَرَ» fundamentally means to spread. Its opposite is «طَوَی» (to fold). «نَشَرْتُ الْکِتَابَ» means I opened or spread the book, and «طَوَیْتُہ» means I folded or closed it. (Muhit) For example, in the Quran: «وَاِذَا الصُّحُفُ نُشِرَتۡ» (81:10). Translation: And when the records are laid open. And «نَشِرَ الْمَیِّتُ نشُوْرًا» means the dead coming back to life. (Mufradat) And «وَاِلَیْہِ النُّشُوْر» means returning to Allah after emerging from graves. It encompasses meanings of revival, rising, and spreading. Hence, «اَنْشَرَ» is a transitive verb. For example, in the Quran: «ثُمَّ  اَمَاتَہٗ  فَاَقۡبَرَہٗ ثُمَّ  اِذَا شَآءَ  اَنۡشَرَہٗ» (80:21-22). Translation: Then He causes him to die and places him in his grave; then when He wills, He will resurrect him. Note: (Transitive verb: a verb that requires an object in addition to the subject to complete its meaning.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 163,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift. To carry a burden.",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«اَنْشَزَ» is used to mean causing movement in something to lift it (2 verses: 2:259-58:11).",
      "d": "The root meanings of «نَشَزَ» are elevation, lifting, and prominence. Specifically, when this lifting causes movement, agitation, fervor, speed, and intensity in something. (Gh Q) «نَشْزَ الرَّجُل» means a sitting man stood up (Manjad). From this, the transitive verb «اَنْشَزَ» is derived.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ انۡظُرۡاِلٰی حِمَارِکَ وَ لِنَجۡعَلَکَ اٰیَۃً لِّلنَّاسِ وَ انۡظُرۡاِلَی الۡعِظَامِ کَیۡفَ نُنۡشِزُہَا ثُمَّ نَکۡسُوۡہَا لَحۡمًا» (2/259)\nTranslation: And look at your donkey, and We will make you a sign for the people, and look at the bones, how We will raise them and then clothe them with flesh. (Uthmani)\nHere, the meaning of using «اَنْشَزَ» is that movement and agitation occurred in those bones. They began to join together and stood up forming the structure of the donkey.\nNote: (Transitive verb: A verb that requires an object in addition to the subject to complete its meaning)."
    },
    {
      "id": 164,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift. To carry a burden.",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«بَعَثَ» is used for raising the dead on the Day of Resurrection (27 verses: 2:56-2:259-6:36-6:60-7:14-15:36-16:21-16:38-18:12-18:19-19:15-19:33-22:5-22:7-23:16-23:100-26:87-27:65-30:56-31:28-36:52-37:144-38:79-58:6-58:18-64:7-72:7).",
      "d": "Fundamentally, two meanings are found in «بَعَثَ»: (1) to raise/promote, (2) to send someone alone (Manjad). Sometimes the word is used for both meanings simultaneously, and sometimes for only one meaning. It is said «بَعَثْتُ الْبَعِیْر» meaning to lift the camel and set it free. Here, we are concerned with its first meaning. When this word is used in relation to the dead, both meanings are found: raising them to life and marching them to the field of Resurrection.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّاَنَّ السَّاعَۃَ اٰتِیَۃٌ لَّارَیۡبَ فِیۡہَا ۙ وَاَنَّ اللّٰہَ یَبۡعَثُ مَنۡ فِی الۡقُبُوۡرِ» (22/7)\nTranslation: And the Hour is certainly coming, there is no doubt about it, and Allah will surely raise those who are in the graves.\nThen this word has also been used for awakening from sleep (i.e., only in the first meaning), because sleep is also a light form of death.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَکَذٰلِکَ بَعَثۡنٰہُمۡ لِیَتَسَآءَلُوۡا بَیۡنَہُمۡ» (18/19)\nTranslation: And similarly, We raised them (the People of the Cave from sleep) so that they might question each other."
    },
    {
      "id": 165,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Lift; To Carry a Burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«حَمَلَ» is used for carrying a burden, whether material or spiritual. It is general. (44 verses: 2:248-2:286-6:31-6:146-7:176-7:189-9:92-11:40-12:36-12:72-13:8-16:7-16:25-17:3-17:70-19:22-19:27-19:58-20:87-20:100-20:101-20:111-22:2-23:22-24:54-29:12-29:13-29:60-31:14-33:72-35:11-35:18-36:41-40:7-40:80-41:47-46:15-54:13-62:5-65:4-65:6-69:11-69:14-69:17)",
      "d": "«حَمَلَ» is used for carrying a burden and its usage is general, applicable to both material (e.g., lifting something like luggage) and spiritual (e.g., carrying the burden of sin) meanings.\n(1) For material burden carrying: whether external or internal, such as a woman carrying the burden of a child in her womb or a tree carrying its fruit or a cloud carrying its water. In short, this word is used in all contexts.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا تَغَشّٰہَا حَمَلَتۡ حَمۡلًا خَفِیۡفًا فَمَرَّتۡ بِہٖ» (7/189)\nTranslation: When the man approaches her, she carries a light burden, and then she moves about with it.\n(2) For spiritual burden carrying: For example, Allah says:\n«وَعَنَتِ الۡوُجُوۡہُ لِلۡحَیِّ الۡقَیُّوۡمِ ؕ وَ قَدۡ خَابَ مَنۡ حَمَلَ ظُلۡمًا» (20/111)\nTranslation: And the faces will be humbled before the Ever-Living, the Self-Sustaining, and whoever carries injustice will have failed.\nAnd «حَمَلَ عَلَیٰ» means to impose a burden on someone, and «حَمَّلَ» means to cause someone to carry a burden.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَا تَحۡمِلۡ عَلَیۡنَاۤ اِصۡرًا» (2/286)\nTranslation: And do not impose a burden on us."
    },
    {
      "id": 166,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift. To carry a burden.",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«لَقَحَ» This word is specific for carrying an internal (i.e., unseen) burden (1 verse: 15:22).",
      "d": "«لَقَحَ» This word is specific for carrying an internal (unseen) burden. «لَقَحَۃُ النَّاقَۃ» means the she-camel became pregnant (Muf). Then this word is also related to winds that carry pollen from a male tree and deposit it in a female tree, or winds that carry the burden of rain clouds.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاَرۡسَلۡنَا الرِّیٰحَ لَوَاقِحَ فَاَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً» (15/22)\nTranslation: And We send the winds, fertilizing (carrying the burden of pollen), then We cause rain to descend from the sky."
    },
    {
      "id": 167,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift. To carry a burden.",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«نَاءَ» To carry a heavier burden that can be carried with difficulty. To carry a burden with toil (1 verse: 28:76).",
      "d": "(The meaning of یَنَوء is to toil strenuously and carry a burden with difficulty (M. N). To carry with difficulty due to the heaviness of the burden (M. A).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاٰتَیۡنٰہُ مِنَ الۡکُنُوۡزِ مَاۤ اِنَّ مَفَاتِحَہٗ لَتَنُوۡٓاُ بِالۡعُصۡبَۃِ اُولِی الۡقُوَّۃِ» (28/76)\nTranslation: And We gave him treasures whose keys would be a heavy burden (to carry) for a company of strong men."
    },
    {
      "id": 168,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift. To carry a burden.",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«وَزَرَ» Generally used for carrying the burden of sin (10 verses: 6:31-6:164-16:25-17:15-20:87-20:100-35:18-39:7-53:38-94:2).",
      "d": "«وَزَرَ» When a person spreads his garment, places his burden in it, and then carries it and walks away, that is the correct meaning of «وَزَرَ». Hence, sin (ذَنْب) is called «وِزْر». That is, the person takes on the burden of his committed sin. (M L) Thus, «وَزَرَ» is generally used for carrying burdens of sins.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ ہُمۡ یَحۡمِلُوۡنَ اَوۡزَارَہُمۡ عَلٰی ظُہُوۡرِہِمۡ ؕ اَلَا سَآءَ مَا یَزِرُوۡنَ» (6/31)\nTranslation: And they will be carrying their burdens on their backs. Wretched is what they will carry."
    }
  ],
  "27": [
    {
      "id": 169,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Rise",
      "hw": "اٹھنا",
      "s": "«اِنْبَعَثَ» To set out alone for a purpose. (1 verse: 91:12)",
      "d": "«بَعَثَ» means to rise for work. Due to being in the form of «اِنْفِعَال», its meaning is that a person rises by himself and sets out alone to accomplish an important purpose.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«کَذَّبَتۡ ثَمُوۡدُ بِطَغۡوٰىہَاۤ اِذِ انۡۢبَعَثَ اَشۡقٰہَا» (91/11,12)\nTranslation: Thamud denied [the truth] due to their arrogance when the most wretched of them rose up."
    },
    {
      "id": 170,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Rise",
      "hw": "اٹھنا",
      "s": "«قَامَ» To stand in any condition. General. (19 verses: 2:20-3:191-4:5-4:102-4:103-4:142-5:6-5:97-9:84-9:108-18:14-18:77-25:64-36:8-39:68-51:45-72:19-73:2-74:2)",
      "d": "«قَامَ» means for a sitting or lying person to stand up, or to stand while walking. It is used for everyone. Thus, it is generally used for standing up.\nFor example:\n(1) In the Quran:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ یَذۡکُرُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ قِیٰمًا وَّقُعُوۡدًا» (3/191)\nTranslation: Those who remember Allah while standing and sitting.\n(2) In the Quran:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الۡمُدَّثِّرُ قُمۡ فَاَنۡذِرۡ» (74/1,2)\nTranslation: O you who covers himself [with a garment], arise and warn.\n(3) In the Quran:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ اَضَآءَ لَہُمۡ مَّشَوۡا فِیۡہِ٭ۙ وَاِذَاۤ اَظۡلَمَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ قَامُوۡا» (2/20)\nTranslation: Whenever it shines upon them, they walk in it, and when it darkens over them, they stand still."
    },
    {
      "id": 171,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Rise",
      "hw": "اٹھنا",
      "s": "«نَشَرَ» Used in the meaning of rising and spreading. (5 verses: 25:3-25:40-25:47-35:19-67:15)",
      "d": "«نَشَرَ» This word is used in two meanings: (1) for the dead to rise from their graves and spread out «کَمَا مَرَّ» (2) to rise and emerge.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَّلَا یَمۡلِکُوۡنَ مَوۡتًا وَّلَا حَیٰوۃً وَّلَا نُشُوۡرًا» (25/3)\nTranslation: They have no power over death or life or resurrection.\nAt another place, Allah says:\n«ہُوَالَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الَّیۡلَ لِبَاسًا وَّالنَّوۡمَ سُبَاتًا وَّ جَعَلَ النَّہَارَنُشُوۡرًا» (25/47)\nTranslation: And He it is who made the night for you as clothing and sleep for rest and made the day for rising."
    },
    {
      "id": 172,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Rise",
      "hw": "اٹھنا",
      "s": "«نَشَزَ» Used for rising due to a movement or stir. (2 verses: 2:259-58:11)",
      "d": "«نَشَزَ» To rise due to a movement or stir. «کَمَا مَرَّ»\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ  اٰمَنُوۡۤا  اِذَا  قِیۡلَ  لَکُمۡ تَفَسَّحُوۡا فِی  الۡمَجٰلِسِ فَافۡسَحُوۡا یَفۡسَحِ اللّٰہُ  لَکُمۡ ۚ وَ  اِذَا قِیۡلَ انۡشُزُوۡا فَانۡشُزُوۡا» (58/11)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when you are told, 'Make room in the assemblies,' then make room; Allah will make room for you. And when you are told, 'Rise up,' then rise up."
    }
  ],
  "28": [
    {
      "id": 173,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Taking Permission",
      "hw": "اجازت",
      "s": "«اِستأذَنَ» to seek permission or approval for an action (9 verses: 9:44-9:45-9:83-9:86-9:93-24:58-24:59-24:62-33:13)",
      "d": "«اَذِنَ» means permission or approval. «اِسْتأذَنَ» means to obtain permission or to seek permission for an action, and «اِسْتَأذَنَ عَلَیْہِ» means to seek permission to enter. (source)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَا یَسۡتَاۡذِنُکَ الَّذِیۡنَ یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ وَالۡیَوۡمِ الۡاٰخِرِاَنۡ یُّجَاہِدُوۡا بِاَمۡوَالِہِمۡ وَاَنۡفُسِہِمۡ» (9/44)\nTranslation: Those who believe in Allah and the Last Day do not seek your permission to stay behind. Rather, they desire to strive with their wealth and lives."
    },
    {
      "id": 174,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Taking Permission",
      "hw": "اجازت",
      "s": "«اِسْتَانَسَ» to introduce oneself through some word or action.\nAnd for giving permission, only «اَذِنَ» is used.\nFor example, the Almighty says:\n«عَفَا اللّٰہُ عَنۡکَ ۚ لِمَ اَذِنۡتَ لَہُمۡ» (9/43)\nTranslation: (O Prophet ﷺ) May Allah forgive you. Why did you give permission (to the hypocrites not to participate in Jihad)? (1 verse: 24:27)",
      "d": "«اٰنَسَ» means to see something and know it. «اٰنس الصوت» means to hear a sound. «اٰنس النار» means to see fire. From this, «اِسْتَانَسَ» is derived, meaning to create familiarity or inclination through some word or action. For example, if a person stands at the door and calls out or coughs, the homeowner knows from that sound or action that so-and-so is at the door. Thus, the meaning of «اِسْتَاْنَسَ» is complete. For example, the Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَدۡخُلُوۡا بُیُوۡتًا غَیۡرَ  بُیُوۡتِکُمۡ  حَتّٰی تَسۡتَاۡنِسُوۡا وَ تُسَلِّمُوۡا عَلٰۤی اَہۡلِہَا» (24/27) Translation: O you who believe! Do not enter houses other than your own until you have sought permission and greeted their inhabitants."
    }
  ],
  "29": [
    {
      "id": 175,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Harshness",
      "hw": "اُجڈ",
      "s": "«اَعْرَاب» ill-mannered people who have no etiquette of conversation (10 verses: 9:90-9:97-9:98-9:99-9:101-9:120-33:20-48:11-48:16-49:14)",
      "d": "«اَعْرَاب» means bedouin, unlettered, rural, jungle-dweller, uncivilized, one who has no etiquette or refinement in conversation or lifestyle. (source)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَلۡاَعۡرَابُ اَشَدُّ کُفۡرًا وَّنِفَاقًا وَّاَجۡدَرُاَلَّا یَعۡلَمُوۡاحُدُوۡدَ مَاۤ اَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ عَلٰی رَسُوۡلِہٖ» (9/97)\nTranslation: The bedouins are the most severe in disbelief and hypocrisy, and most deserving of not knowing the commandments which Allah has revealed to His Messenger."
    },
    {
      "id": 176,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Harshness",
      "hw": "اُجڈ",
      "s": "«عُتُلّ» used for a harsh-tempered and rigid human (2 verses: 44:47-68:13)",
      "d": "«عَتَلَ» means to seize someone by the hair and pull or drag them harshly (singular). «عَتَلَہٗٓ اِلَی السِّجْن» means he was dragged and thrown into prison. (Quranic dictionary)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«خُذُوۡہُ فَاعۡتِلُوۡہُ  اِلٰی سَوَآءِ الۡجَحِیۡمِ» (44/47)\nTranslation: Seize him and drag him into the midst of Hell.\nAnd «عُتُلّ» means a harsh and stubborn person (Quranic dictionary), harsh-tempered (singular).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«عُتُلٍّۭ بَعۡدَ ذٰلِکَ  زَنِیۡمٍ» (68/13)\nTranslation: Harsh-tempered and besides that, of evil character."
    },
    {
      "id": 177,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Harshness",
      "hw": "اُجڈ",
      "s": "«فَظّ» foul-mouthed and using abusive language in conversation (1 verse: 3:159)",
      "d": "«فَظّ» means to be harsh-tempered, bad-natured. And «فَظُّ» means rough, harsh-tempered, harsh in speech, bitter-tongued. Its opposite is «لَیْن» which means softness in speech and temperament.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَبِمَا رَحۡمَۃٍ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ لِنۡتَ لَہُمۡ ۚ وَلَوۡ کُنۡتَ فَظًّا غَلِیۡظَ الۡقَلۡبِ لَانۡفَضُّوۡا مِنۡ حَوۡلِکَ» (3/159)\nTranslation: O Prophet ﷺ! This is a great mercy from Allah that you have been gentle with them. Had you been harsh and hard-hearted, they would have dispersed from around you."
    }
  ],
  "30": [
    {
      "id": 179,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Suddenly",
      "hw": "اچانک",
      "s": "«بَغْتَۃً» the sudden appearance of something whose occurrence was not even imagined (13 verses: 6:31-6:44-6:47-7:95-7:187-12:107-21:40-22:55-26:202-29:53-39:55-43:66-47:18)",
      "d": "«بَغْتَۃً» means something appearing suddenly, with no prior expectation of its occurrence (singular). The difference between «بَغْتَۃً» and «اِذْ» or «اِذَا» is that in «اِذَا», the subsequent event has some relation or connection to the preceding event, whereas «بَغْتَۃً» refers only to a sudden or unexpected event.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَخَذۡنٰہُمۡ  بَغۡتَۃً وَّ ہُمۡ لَا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ» (7/95)\nTranslation: Then We seized them suddenly while they did not perceive it.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا جَآءَتۡہُمُ السَّاعَۃُ  بَغۡتَۃً  قَالُوۡا یٰحَسۡرَتَنَا عَلٰی مَا فَرَّطۡنَا فِیۡہَا» (6/31)\nTranslation: Until when the Hour comes upon them suddenly, they will say, 'Alas for us for what we neglected regarding it.'"
    }
  ],
  "31": [
    {
      "id": 180,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Good, Excellent, Better",
      "hw": "اچھا",
      "s": "«نِعْمَ» a word of praise (i.e., an appreciative term) said for something good (16 verses: 2:271-3:136-3:173-4:58-8:40-13:24-16:30-18:31-22:78-29:58-37:75-38:30-38:44-39:74-51:48-77:23)",
      "d": "«نِعْمَ» is a word of praise (i.e., an appreciative term) used for all kinds of commendation and praise (singular). Its meanings are: 'How excellent!' 'How wonderful!' It is said with joy at something good. According to Ibn Faris, its original sense is inclination and leaning (root), meaning when one sees something and the nature inclines toward it, one says «نِعْم». Its opposite is «بِئْسَ», which is a word of reproach (i.e., for evil and criticism) and is used for condemnation.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَنِعۡمَ  دَارُ الۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ» (16/30)\nTranslation: And excellent is the abode of the pious."
    },
    {
      "id": 181,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Good. Excellent. Better.",
      "hw": "اچھا",
      "s": "«خَیْر» is used for every good thing, deed, or good person (170 verses: 2:54-2:61-2:103-2:105-2:106-2:110-2:148-2:158-2:180-2:184-2:197-2:215-2:216-2:220-2:221-2:263-2:269-2:271-2:272-2:273-2:280-3:15-3:26-3:30-3:54-3:104-3:110-3:114-3:115-3:150-3:157-3:178-3:180-3:198-4:19-4:25-4:46-4:59-4:66-4:77-4:114-4:127-4:128-4:149-4:170-4:171-5:48-5:114-6:17-6:32-6:57-6:158-7:12-7:26-7:85-7:87-7:89-7:155-7:169-7:188-8:19-8:23-8:30-8:70-9:3-9:41-9:61-9:74-9:88-9:109-10:11-10:58-10:107-10:109-11:31-11:84-11:86-12:39-12:57-12:59-12:64-12:80-12:109-16:30-16:76-16:95-16:126-17:11-17:35-18:36-18:40-18:44-18:46-18:81-18:95-19:73-19:76-20:73-20:131-21:35-21:73-21:89-21:90-22:11-22:30-22:36-22:58-22:77-23:29-23:56-23:61-23:72-23:109-23:118-24:11-24:12-24:27-24:33-24:60-25:10-25:15-25:24-27:36-27:59-27:89-28:24-28:26-28:60-28:80-28:84-29:16-30:38-33:19-33:25-34:39-35:32-37:62-38:32-38:76-41:40-41:49-42:36-43:32-43:52-43:58-44:37-46:11-47:21-49:5-49:11-50:25-54:43-55:70-58:12-61:11-62:9-62:11-64:16-66:5-68:12-68:32-70:21-70:41-73:20-87:17-93:4-97:3-98:7-99:7-100:8).",
      "d": "«خَیْر» is every desirable thing. For example, justice, intellect, and wealth are also called خیر (M. A). Its opposite is «شَر».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِنَّہٗ  لِحُبِّ الۡخَیۡرِلَشَدِیۡدٌ» (100/8)\nTranslation: And indeed, man is intensely in love of wealth.\nThat is, خیر refers to every good thing or virtuous deed, and its plural is خیرات.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ وَ الۡیَوۡمِ الۡاٰخِرِ وَ یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَ یَنۡہَوۡنَ عَنِ الۡمُنۡکَرِ وَ یُسَارِعُوۡنَ فِی الۡخَیۡرٰتِ» (3/114)\nTranslation: They believe in Allah and the Last Day and enjoin what is right and forbid what is wrong and hasten to good deeds.\nThe word خیر is not only used for a good thing or deed but also for good people or things, and for faith. In this case, the plural becomes اخیار.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّہُمۡ عِنۡدَنَا لَمِنَ الۡمُصۡطَفَیۡنَ الۡاَخۡیَارِ» (38/47)\nTranslation: Indeed, they are with Us among the chosen and the good.\nThus, the word خیر is used for any good thing, deed, or person. And «نِعْمَ» is said upon seeing a good thing with pleasure.\nThe following verse clarifies this:\n«وَ لَدَارُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ خَیۡرٌ ؕ وَ لَنِعۡمَ  دَارُ الۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ» (16/30)\nTranslation: But the home of the Hereafter is best, and excellent is the home of the righteous."
    },
    {
      "id": 182,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Good, Excellent, Better",
      "hw": "اچھا",
      "s": "«حَسُنَ» used for delightful and pleasing things, both apparent and spiritual beauty and goodness (57 verses: 2:83-2:138-2:245-3:14-3:37-3:148-3:195-4:59-4:69-4:95-5:12-6:152-6:160-7:137-7:180-8:17-9:107-10:26-11:3-11:88-13:18-13:29-16:62-16:67-16:75-17:110-18:2-18:31-18:86-18:88-20:8-20:86-21:101-22:58-25:76-27:11-28:61-29:8-33:52-35:8-38:25-38:40-38:49-41:50-42:23-48:16-53:31-55:70-55:76-57:10-57:11-57:18-59:24-64:17-73:20-92:6-92:9)",
      "d": "«حَسُنَ» means delightful and pleasing (singular). Its opposite is «سَاءَ». Then this word is also used for apparent beauty and facial radiance.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فِیۡہِنَّ خَیۡرٰتٌ حِسَانٌ» (55/70)\nTranslation: In them are good women, beautiful.\nIn this case, its opposite is «قَبُحَ». Besides this, the word is also used spiritually to denote excellence of character.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَحَسُنَ اُولٰٓئِکَ رَفِیۡقًا» (4/69)\nTranslation: And excellent is the companionship of those."
    },
    {
      "id": 183,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Good, Excellent, Better",
      "hw": "اچھا",
      "s": "«اَمْثَل ، مُثْلیٰ» meaning exemplary, best, ideal, worthy of imitation (2 verses: 20:63-20:104)",
      "d": "«مَثَلَ» means for something to be present before the eyes (singular). And «اَمْثَل» means exemplary, peerless, ideal, best (source).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِذۡ یَقُوۡلُ اَمۡثَلُہُمۡ طَرِیۡقَۃً» (20/104)\nTranslation: At that time, the best of them in way (i.e., the wise and sensible) will say.\nAnd «مُثْلیٰ ، اَمْثَلُ» is the feminine form.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ یَذۡہَبَا بِطَرِیۡقَتِکُمُ  الۡمُثۡلٰی» (20/63)\nTranslation: And they will put an end to your exemplary way of life."
    },
    {
      "id": 184,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Good. Excellent. Better.",
      "hw": "اچھا",
      "s": "«جَمِیْلٌ» comes for the good deeds of any person, and for good morals. In common usage, this word is also used for apparent beauty (8 verses: 12:18-12:83-15:85-16:6-33:28-33:49-70:5-73:10).",
      "d": "«جَمِیْلٌ» its root word is جمال, which means apparent goodness, splendor, dignity, pomp, and beauty (Faq 217).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا جَمَالٌ» (16/6)\nTranslation: And there is honor for you in it.\nAnd «اَجْمَلَ فِی الْعَمَل» means to perform a task in a better way (M. Q). The word جمیل also comes for choosing a better path. As when Ya'qub (AS) said to his sons:\n«بَلۡ سَوَّلَتۡ لَکُمۡ اَنۡفُسُکُمۡ اَمۡرًا ؕ فَصَبۡرٌ  جَمِیۡلٌ» (12/18)\nTranslation: Rather, your own desires have enticed you to something. So patience is good.\nAnd in the Quran, when the Prophet (ﷺ) said to his wives:\n«اِنۡ  کُنۡـتُنَّ تُرِدۡنَ  الۡحَیٰوۡفَ  الدُّنۡیَا وَ زِیۡنَتَہَا فَتَعَالَیۡنَ اُمَتِّعۡکُنَّ وَ اُسَرِّحۡکُنَّ سَرَاحًا جَمِیۡلًا» (33/28)\nTranslation: If you desire the present life and its adornment, then come, I will provide for you and send you away in a good manner.\nLater, this word began to be used for the beauty of the face as well. However, there is no example of this in the Quran."
    }
  ],
  "32": [
    {
      "id": 185,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Strange. To be a stranger.",
      "hw": "اجنبی",
      "s": "«نَکِرَ» when unfamiliarity is accompanied by dislike, it is «نَکِرَ»; when accompanied by pleasure, it is «عَجَبَ»; and when neither dislike nor pleasure is present, it is «جُنُب» (7 verses: 11:70-18:74-18:87-27:41-31:19-54:6-65:8)",
      "d": "«نَکِرَ» means to be unfamiliar with something. Its opposite is «مَعْرفَۃ». And «اَنْکَرَ» means to deny. To be unfamiliar with someone and «تَنَاکَر» means to deliberately become unfamiliar with each other and behave like strangers. And «نُکْر» bad deed, severe hardship (manjad) and «مَنْکِر» means bad deed, bad thing, unpleasant thing. So in «نَکَرَ», two things are found: unfamiliarity and dislike. For example: In the Quran: «فَلَمَّا رَاٰۤ اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ لَا تَصِلُ اِلَیۡہِ نَکِرَہُمۡ وَاَوۡجَسَ مِنۡہُمۡ خِیۡفَۃً» (11/70) Translation: So when he (Ibrahim) saw that their hands did not reach it (the food), he disliked them and felt fear from them."
    },
    {
      "id": 186,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Strange. To be a stranger.",
      "hw": "اجنبی",
      "s": "«عَجَبَ ۔ عَجَبٌ» such wonder is expressed when the reason is unknown (22 verses: 2:204-2:221-5:100-7:63-7:69-9:25-9:55-9:85-10:2-11:73-13:5-18:9-18:63-33:52-37:12-38:4-48:29-50:2-53:59-57:20-63:4-72:1)",
      "d": "«عَجَبَ ۔ عَجَبٌ» such wonder is expressed when the reason is unknown (Muf). Also, «عَجَبَ» means to like and «اَعْجَبَ» means to feel pleasure about something whose cause is unknown or not expected. Sometimes this word is also used only in the sense of pleasure. So in «عَجَبَ», two things are found: unfamiliarity and pleasure. For example: In the Quran: «قَالُوۡۤا اَتَعۡجَبِیۡنَ مِنۡ اَمۡرِ اللّٰہِ رَحۡمَتُ اللّٰہِ وَ بَرَکٰتُہٗ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اَہۡلَ الۡبَیۡتِ» (11/73) Translation: (The angels) said to (Ibrahim's wife): Do you wonder at Allah's command? May Allah's mercy and blessings be upon you, O people of the house!"
    },
    {
      "id": 187,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To be amazed. To become a stranger.",
      "hw": "اجنبی",
      "s": "«جُنُب» has two meanings: the first is used for a stranger, the second for an impure person (8 verses: 4:36-4:43-5:6-10:12-28:11-39:56-87:11-92:17).",
      "d": "«جَنْب» means side, flank. «جُنُب» means both stranger and impure. The word «جُنُب» is used in singular, dual, and plural forms, and equally for men and women. (Manjad) This word has appeared in the Quran in both these meanings. When it comes in the meaning of stranger, there is no implication of dislike or pleasure.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَالۡجَارِ ذِی الۡقُرۡبٰی وَ الۡجَارِ الۡجُنُبِ وَ الصَّاحِبِ بِالۡجَنۡۢبِ» (4/36)\nTranslation: And the neighbor who is a relative, the neighbor who is a stranger, and the companion by your side.\nAnd «جَنَبَ» means to turn aside and become distant. And the Junub (impure person) is also commanded to stay away from prayer and the mosque, hence he is called Junub.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَا جُنُبًا اِلَّا عَابِرِیۡ سَبِیۡلٍ حَتّٰی تَغۡتَسِلُوۡا» (4/43)\nTranslation: And (do not approach prayer) while you are impure, unless you are passing through, until you have bathed."
    }
  ],
  "33": [
    {
      "id": 190,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To do a favor.",
      "hw": "احسان",
      "s": "«اَنْعَمَ» is used for doing a favor upon someone other than oneself (63 verses: 1:6-2:40-2:47-2:122-2:150-2:211-2:231-3:103-3:171-3:174-4:69-4:72-5:3-5:6-5:7-5:11-5:20-5:23-5:110-8:53-11:10-12:6-14:6-14:28-14:34-16:18-16:53-16:71-16:72-16:81-16:83-16:112-16:114-16:121-17:83-19:58-26:22-27:19-28:17-29:67-31:20-31:31-33:9-33:37-35:3-37:57-39:8-39:49-41:51-43:13-43:59-44:27-46:15-48:2-49:8-52:29-54:35-68:2-68:49-73:11-89:15-92:19-93:11).",
      "d": "«اَلنَّعْمَۃ» refers to a person's good state. And نعمة is every thing that fulfills a human need and can be a cause of his prosperity. This word is generic (for the type), whether the favor is little or much. And the word نعمة and انعام are specific to humans. The meaning of «اَنْعَمَ» is to do good, kindness, or favor. But «اَنْعَمَ عَلیٰ فَرَسِہ» (to favor one's horse) will never occur (M. Q). Also, this word is not used for oneself. (Faq. L 158)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِذۡ تَقُوۡلُ لِلَّذِیۡۤ  اَنۡعَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِ وَاَنۡعَمۡتَ عَلَیۡہِ اَمۡسِکۡ عَلَیۡکَ زَوۡجَکَ» (33/37)\nTranslation: When you say to him (Zayd ibn Harithah) upon whom Allah has bestowed favor and you have bestowed favor, 'Retain your wife.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 191,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To do good",
      "hw": "احسان",
      "s": "«اَحْسَنَ» is used for every good and virtuous deed, whether it pertains to one's own self or to another's self (63 verses: 2:83-2:178-2:195-2:229-3:172-4:36-4:59-4:62-4:86-4:125-5:50-5:93-6:151-6:152-6:154-7:145-9:100-9:121-10:26-11:7-12:3-12:23-12:100-16:30-16:90-16:96-16:97-16:125-17:7-17:23-17:34-17:35-17:53-18:7-18:30-19:73-19:74-23:14-23:96-24:38-25:24-25:33-28:77-29:7-29:46-32:7-37:125-39:10-39:18-39:23-39:35-39:55-40:64-41:33-41:34-46:15-46:16-53:31-55:60-64:3-65:11-67:2-95:4)",
      "d": "«اَحْسَنَ» means every good and virtuous deed, whether it pertains to one's own self or to another's (Faq L 158). In the Hadith of Jibril (a.s.), it is narrated that Jibril (a.s.) asked the Prophet (ﷺ): What is Ihsan? He (ﷺ) replied: Ihsan is that you worship Allah as if you see Him, and if you cannot achieve that, then certainly know that He sees you. The word Ihsan is used for the smallest and largest of all good deeds. For example, Prophet Yusuf (a.s.) said while thanking Allah: «وَ قَدۡ اَحۡسَنَ  بِیۡۤ اِذۡ اَخۡرَجَنِیۡ مِنَ السِّجۡنِ وَ جَآءَ بِکُمۡ مِّنَ الۡبَدۡوِ» (12/100) Translation: And He (Allah) did me good when He brought me out of prison and brought you (all) from the countryside."
    }
  ],
  "34": [
    {
      "id": 192,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To have a choice/option",
      "hw": "اختیار",
      "s": "«خِیَرَۃ» means to choose one option from two or more things (2 verses: 28:68-33:36)",
      "d": "«خَیْر» means good and better. And «خِیَرَۃ» and «اِخْتَار» mean to choose, select, or opt for a good thing from two or more things. For example: In the Quran: «وَمَا کَانَ لِمُؤۡمِنٍ وَّلَا مُؤۡمِنَۃٍ اِذَا قَضَی اللّٰہُ وَرَسُوۡلُہٗۤ اَمۡرًا اَنۡ یَّکُوۡنَ لَہُمُ الۡخِیَرَۃُ مِنۡ اَمۡرِہِمۡ» (33/36) Translation: It is not for a believing man or a believing woman, when Allah and His Messenger have decided a matter, to have any choice in their matter."
    },
    {
      "id": 193,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To have a choice/option",
      "hw": "اختیار",
      "s": "«مَلْک» means to have the authority to dispose of something (56 verses: 2:246-2:247-4:3-4:24-4:25-4:36-5:17-5:25-5:41-5:76-7:188-10:31-10:49-12:43-12:50-12:54-12:72-12:76-13:16-16:71-16:73-17:56-17:100-18:79-19:87-20:87-20:89-20:114-23:6-23:88-23:116-24:31-24:33-24:58-24:61-25:3-29:17-30:28-33:50-33:52-33:55-34:22-34:42-35:13-39:43-43:86-46:8-48:11-59:23-60:4-62:1-70:30-72:21-78:37-82:19-114:2)",
      "d": "«مِلْک» means every thing that is in someone's possession and no one else has authority over it. And «مَلْک» and «مِلْک» are synonymous in this sense (Muf). That is, «مَلْک» refers to authority over something that is in one's ownership and possession. (And «مَلِک» refers to a king, because the public is under his possession and authority, and he is its administrator.) For example: In the Quran: «قَالُوۡا مَاۤ اَخۡلَفۡنَا مَوۡعِدَکَ بِمَلۡکِنَا» (20/87) Translation: (The Israelites) said: We did not break our promise to you by our own choice. That is, the Samiri deceived us, took the ornaments, and made the calf, so he became dominant over us in such a way that we no longer had the authority to dispose of our own things as we wished."
    },
    {
      "id": 195,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To hold (a position of power).",
      "hw": "اختیار",
      "s": "«اَمْکَنَ» when the concept of place or location is also present in the authority (1 verse: 8:71).",
      "d": "«اَمْکَنَ» and «مَکَّنَ» both mean to give power to someone in a place, to grant authority, and to make capable (Manjad). From this comes مکان (place), meaning the place where something is kept or resides. And «اَمْکَنَ الْاَمْر» means to make something possible and easy (Manjad). Thus, in «اَمْکَنَ», the meaning of authority along with place or location is found.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِنۡ یُّرِیۡدُوۡا خِیَانَتَکَ فَقَدۡ خَانُوا اللّٰہَ مِنۡ قَبۡلُ فَاَمۡکَنَ مِنۡہُمۡ» (8/71)\nTranslation: If they intend to betray you, they have already betrayed Allah before, so He gave them power over you (i.e., placed them under your control). (Jalandhari) So He made them captive. (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 196,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To choose",
      "hw": "اختیار",
      "s": "«اِسْتَحَبَّ» means to choose from two or more things that which is pleasing to the heart (4 verses: 9:23-14:3-16:107-41:17)",
      "d": "«حُبّ» means love. And «اِسْتَحَبَّ» means to choose something that one's heart desires to choose. For example: In the Quran: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡۤا اٰبَآءَکُمۡ وَ اِخۡوَانَکُمۡ اَوۡلِیَآءَ اِنِ اسۡتَحَبُّوا الۡکُفۡرَ عَلَی الۡاِیۡمَانِ» (9/23) Translation: O you who believe! Do not take your fathers and brothers as allies if they prefer disbelief over faith."
    },
    {
      "id": 197,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To choose",
      "hw": "اختیار",
      "s": "«تَحَرّٰی» means to select and seek that which is more worthy and better among two things. (1 Verse: 72:14)",
      "d": "«حَرْوٌ ، اَحْرٰی» means more worthy (m. q.) and «تَحَرّٰی» means to seek that which is more suitable and worthy. To seek the better among two things (manjad). For example: The Quran states: «فَمَنۡ اَسۡلَمَ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ تَحَرَّوۡا رَشَدًا» (72/14) Translation: And whoever submits (to Allah), it is they who will have chosen the right path."
    }
  ],
  "35": [
    {
      "id": 198,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Loan (Udhaar)",
      "hw": "قرض",
      "s": "«قَرَضَ» refers to that sum of money which is taken for personal necessities with the condition of returning it after a specified period. In a 'qard hasana' (goodly loan), the period is not specified. (9 Verses: 2:245-2:282-4:11-4:12-5:12-57:11-57:18-64:17-73:20)",
      "d": "«قَرَضَ» means a loan, i.e., such a credit which a person takes from another to fulfill his needs. According to Imam Raghib, it is wealth given with the condition that it will be returned to fulfill that need (muf). And the author of 'Muntahi al-Arab' adds this condition as well: such a credit for which no period for repayment has been specified (m. a). Because wherever the word 'qard' appears in the Quran, the word «حَسَنًا» (goodly) often accompanies it, and one condition of a 'qard hasana' is also this. For example: The Quran states: «وَاِنۡ کَانَ ذُوۡعُسۡرَۃٍ فَنَظِرَۃٌ اِلٰی مَیۡسَرَۃٍ» (2/280) Translation: And if the debtor is in difficulty, then grant him respite until ease is attained. And such a loan Allah calls a 'qard hasana' (goodly loan) and attributes it to Himself as a loan given, even though it is given only to those in need. For example: The Quran states: «مَنۡ ذَا الَّذِیۡ یُقۡرِضُ اللّٰہَ قَرۡضًا حَسَنًا فَیُضٰعِفَہٗ لَہٗ وَ لَہٗۤ اَجۡرٌ کَرِیۡمٌ» (57/11) Translation: Who is it that would lend Allah a goodly loan so He will multiply it for him and he will have a noble reward (i.e., Paradise). In this sense, every 'qard' (loan) is a 'dayn' (debt), but not every 'dayn' is a 'qard'. (Faqih 140)"
    },
    {
      "id": 199,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Debt (Dayn)",
      "hw": "قرض",
      "s": "«دَیْن» If a period is specified in a loan, then it is called 'dayn' (debt). (9 Verses: 2:245-2:282-4:11-4:12-5:12-57:11-57:18-64:17-73:20)",
      "d": "«دَیْن» If a period is specified in a loan, then it is called 'dayn' (debt). For example: The Quran states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا تَدَایَنۡتُمۡ بِدَیۡنٍ اِلٰۤی اَجَلٍ مُّسَمًّی فَاکۡتُبُوۡہُ» (2/282) Translation: O you who have believed, when you contract a debt for a specified term, write it down. And 'dayn' refers to all responsibilities of lending and borrowing, so to speak this word is more general than 'qard'. It can be taken for commercial purposes as well as for personal needs. Its example is like this: a person owes five thousand rupees to people and also has to receive eight thousand; then he is certainly a debtor (madiun) but not a creditor (muqrid). And if he has to pay eight thousand and receive five thousand, then he is both a debtor and a creditor. And if a person has taken a loan for personal needs on a specified period, then he has accepted the responsibility of repaying the loan at the appointed time, so it is not a 'qard' but a 'dayn'."
    }
  ],
  "36": [
    {
      "id": 200,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To intend (Qasd karna)",
      "hw": "ارادہ",
      "s": "«اَرَادَ» An idea or thought of something coming to mind. (24 Verses: 2:26-2:228-2:233-5:17-9:46-12:25-13:11-17:19-17:103-18:82-21:70-22:22-25:62-28:19-32:20-33:17-33:50-36:82-37:98-39:4-39:38-48:11-72:10-74:31)",
      "d": "«رَوْد» means to come and go in search of something (m. a). And «اَرَادَ» means the thought of doing something or a matter coming to mind (muf), and it means to desire it, and its opposite is «کَرِہَ» (faql 103). For example: The Quran states: «اِنَّمَاۤ اَمۡرُہٗۤ اِذَاۤ اَرَادَ شَیۡئًا اَنۡ یَّقُوۡلَ لَہٗ کُنۡ فَیَکُوۡنُ» (36/82) Translation: His command is only that when He intends a thing, He says to it, 'Be,' and it is."
    },
    {
      "id": 201,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To intend (Qasd karna)",
      "hw": "ارادہ",
      "s": "«ھَمَّ» To contemplate and deliberate over an intention that arises in the heart. (2 Verses: 9:13-9:74)",
      "d": "«ھَمَّ» When an intention remains in the heart for some time and a person continues to ponder and deliberate over it to give it a practical form, then it is termed as «ھَمَّ» (muf). For example: The Quran states: «اَلَا تُقَاتِلُوۡنَ قَوۡمًا نَّکَثُوۡۤا اَیۡمَانَہُمۡ وَ ہَمُّوۡا بِاِخۡرَاجِ الرَّسُوۡلِ» (9/13) Translation: Will you not fight a people who broke their oaths and resolved to expel the Messenger? (Uthmaniؒ)"
    },
    {
      "id": 202,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To intend (Qasd karna)",
      "hw": "ارادہ",
      "s": "«عَزَمَ» To form a firm intention after deliberation. (9 Verses: 2:227-2:235-3:159-3:186-20:115-31:17-42:43-46:35-47:21)",
      "d": "«عَزَمَ» When after deliberation a definite decision is made regarding one's intention, it is called «عَزَمَ». In the words of Ibn al-Faris, it indicates 'al-azimah' (firmness) and 'al-qat' (certainty) (m. l), i.e., to form a firm intention, then to resolve to fulfill it. For example: The Quran states: «وَشَاوِرۡہُمۡ فِی الۡاَمۡرِ ۚ فَاِذَا عَزَمۡتَ فَتَوَکَّلۡ عَلَی اللّٰہِ» (3/159) Translation: And consult them in the matter. Then when you have decided (or made a firm resolution), put your trust in Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 203,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To intend (Qasd karna)",
      "hw": "ارادہ",
      "s": "«اَبْرَمَ» To make a plan to fulfill an intention and resolve. (1 Verse: 43:79)",
      "d": "«بَرَمَ» means to twist two ropes together, and «اَبْرَمَ» means to strengthen a matter, affair, or thing (m. l. m. a). Its opposite is «نَقَصَ». And «اَبْرَام» means to adopt measures to give practical form to an intention, to make a plan, and to finalize it. For example: The Quran states: «اَمۡ اَبۡرَمُوۡۤا أَمۡرًا فَاِنَّا مُبۡرِمُوۡنَ» (43/79) Translation: Or have they planned a plan? Then indeed, We are planning (too). In this verse, the reference is to what the disbelievers of Mecca had planned to kill the Messenger of Allah. And Allah's plan was that He would save His Messenger from them."
    },
    {
      "id": 204,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To intend (Qasd karna)",
      "hw": "ارادہ",
      "s": "«اَمَّ» To intend one's destination directly without looking here and there. (1 Verse: 5:2)",
      "d": "«اَمَّ» means to intend a path or journey (m. a). And according to Imam Raghib, it means 'to be directly focused on the objective and not to incline to any side'. For example: The Quran states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تُحِلُّوۡا شَعَآئِرَ اللّٰہِ وَلَا الشَّہۡرَ الۡحَرَامَ وَلَا الۡہَدۡیَ وَلَا الۡقَلَآئِدَ وَلَاۤ آٰمِّیۡنَ الۡبَیۡتَ الۡحَرَامَ» (5/2) Translation: O you who have believed, do not violate the rites of Allah or the sacred month or the sacrificial animals or the garlands [around them] or those who have come to the Sacred House seeking bounty from their Lord."
    },
    {
      "id": 205,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To intend (Qasd karna)",
      "hw": "ارادہ",
      "s": "«تَیَمَّمْ» To intend the implementation of a Shariah ruling. (3 Verses: 2:267-4:43-5:6)",
      "d": "«تَیَمَّمْ» According to the author of 'Muntahi al-Arab', this word originally was «تَاَمَّمَ» which is derived from «اَمَّ». And Ibn al-Faris considers its root to be «تَمْ», meaning to do something knowingly or by mistake (m. l). So, this word is used for such matters where contemplation and consultation are not necessary, rather the intention to implement the commands of Shariah is meant. In the Quran, this word has been used twice: once for an 'amr' (command) and once for a 'nahi' (prohibition). For example: The Quran states: (1) «فَلَمۡ تَجِدُوۡا مَآءً فَتَیَمَّمُوۡا صَعِیۡدًا طَیِّبًا» (4/43) Translation: Then if you do not find water, then seek clean earth and wipe over your faces and hands. (Taqi Usmani) And if you do not find water, then intend (to do) tayammum with clean earth. (Jona Gadhvi) At another place, the divine command is: (2) «وَلَا تَیَمَّمُوا الۡخَبِیۡثَ مِنۡہُ تُنۡفِقُوۡنَ وَلَسۡتُمۡ بِاٰخِذِیۡہِ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ تُغۡمِضُوۡا فِیۡہِ» (2/267) Translation: And do not intend from it what is bad, spending [from it] while you would not take it [yourself] except with closed eyes."
    },
    {
      "id": 3598,
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "«خَبَرَ» To be informed. (49 Verses: 2:234-2:271-3:153-3:180-4:35-4:94-4:128-4:135-5:8-6:18-6:73-6:103-9:16-11:1-11:111-17:17-17:30-17:96-18:68-18:91-22:63-24:30-24:53-25:58-25:59-27:7-27:88-28:29-31:16-31:29-31:34-33:2-33:34-34:1-35:14-35:31-42:27-48:11-49:13-57:10-58:3-58:11-58:13-59:18-63:11-64:8-66:3-67:14-100:11)",
