  "39": [
    {
      "id": 213,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to indicate",
      "hw": "اشارہ",
      "s": "«اَشَارَ» is used to indicate with hand movement (1 verse: 19:29)",
      "d": "«اَشَارَ» means to indicate to someone with hand movement without opening the mouth (f l, 174). For example: In the Quran it is: «فَاَشَارَتۡ اِلَیۡہِ ؕ قَالُوۡا کَیۡفَ نُکَلِّمُ مَنۡ کَانَ فِی الۡمَہۡدِ صَبِیًّا» (19/29). Translation: So Maryam (peace be upon her) indicated towards the child. They said, how can we speak to one who is an infant in the cradle?"
    },
    {
      "id": 214,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to indicate",
      "hw": "اشارہ",
      "s": "«رَمَزَ» is used to indicate with lips or eyes (1 verse: 3:41)",
      "d": "«رَمَزَ» means to indicate with lips or to emit a slight sound (f l 174) and every speech that is like an indication is a ramz. For example: In the Quran it is: «قَالَ اٰیَتُکَ اَلَّا تُکَلِّمَ النَّاسَ ثَلٰثَۃَ اَیَّامٍ اِلَّا رَمۡزًا» (3/41). Translation: Allah Almighty said: Your sign is that you will not be able to speak to people for three days except by indication."
    },
    {
      "id": 216,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to indicate",
      "hw": "اشارہ",
      "s": "In «عَرَّضَ», indicating is not intended, but rather speaking by hints and implications is intended (1 verse: 2:235)",
      "d": "«عَرَضَ» means to present and «عَرَّضَ» means to speak by indication and implication, and according to Imam Raghib, 'ta'reez' means to speak in a multifaceted way (i.e., speech from which multiple meanings can emerge) that can be interpreted as true or false, and both apparent and inner (meanings) (muf). For example: In the Quran it is: «وَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ فِیۡمَا عَرَّضۡتُمۡ بِہٖ مِنۡ خِطۡبَۃِ النِّسَآءِ» (2/235). Translation: And (during the waiting period) if you send a proposal of marriage to women through hints, there is no blame on you."
    },
