  "40": [
    {
      "id": 217,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to obey (to follow, to be a follower, to carry out commands)",
      "hw": "اطاعت",
      "s": "«تَبِعَ» means to follow behind someone or to walk in their footsteps, and it is used in both outward and inward senses (150 verses: 2:38-2:102-2:120-2:143-2:145-2:166-2:167-2:168-2:170-2:208-2:262-2:263-3:7-3:20-3:31-3:53-3:55-3:68-3:73-3:95-3:162-3:167-3:174-4:27-4:83-4:115-4:125-4:135-5:16-5:48-5:49-5:77-6:50-6:56-6:106-6:116-6:142-6:148-6:150-6:153-6:155-7:3-7:18-7:90-7:142-7:157-7:158-7:175-7:176-7:193-7:203-8:64-9:42-9:100-9:117-10:15-10:35-10:36-10:66-10:89-10:90-10:109-11:27-11:59-11:60-11:97-11:99-11:116-12:38-12:108-13:37-14:21-14:36-14:44-15:18-15:42-15:65-16:123-17:47-17:63-18:28-18:66-18:70-18:85-18:89-18:92-19:43-19:59-20:16-20:47-20:78-20:90-20:93-20:108-20:123-20:134-22:3-23:44-23:71-24:21-25:8-26:40-26:52-26:60-26:111-26:215-26:224-28:35-28:42-28:47-28:49-28:50-28:57-29:12-30:29-31:15-31:21-33:2-34:20-36:11-36:20-36:21-37:10-38:26-38:85-39:18-39:55-40:7-40:38-40:47-42:15-43:61-44:23-45:18-46:9-47:3-47:14-47:16-47:28-48:15-52:21-53:23-53:28-54:3-54:24-57:27-71:21-75:18-77:17-79:7)",
      "d": "«تَبِعَ» means to follow behind someone or to walk in their footsteps (lit.) and it is used in both outward and inward senses. Inwardly, such as following the guidance of religion or following a person's habits and character.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said: «فَمَنۡ تَبِعَ ہُدَایَ فَلَا خَوۡفٌ عَلَیۡہِمۡ وَلَا ہُمۡ یَحۡزَنُوۡنَ» (2/38) Translation: Whoever follows My guidance - no fear will there be concerning them, nor will they grieve.\nAnd outwardly, for following someone behind, «اَتْبَعَ» is used.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said: «فَاَتۡبَعَہُمۡ فِرۡعَوۡنُ بِجُنُوۡدِہٖ» (20/78) Translation: Then Pharaoh pursued them with his armies. (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 218,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to obey (to follow, to be a follower, to carry out commands)",
      "hw": "اطاعت",
      "s": "«اِقْتِدَا» means to follow someone and to do as they do, and «اَقْدٰی» means to follow someone in goodness and the path of religion (Munjid) as is the case when a follower (muqtadi) follows the Imam in prayer (2 verses: 6:90-43:23)",
      "d": "«اِقْتِدَا» means to follow someone and to do as they do, and «اَقْدٰی» means to follow someone in goodness and the path of religion (Munjid) as is the case when a follower (muqtadi) follows the Imam in prayer.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said: «اُولٰٓئِکَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہَدَی اللّٰہُ  فَبِہُدٰىہُمُ اقۡتَدِہۡ» (6/90) Translation: Those are the ones whom Allah has guided, so follow their guidance.\nAnd the word iqtida can also be used in a bad sense. «قُدْوَۃ» actually refers to the state of a person when they are a follower of another (lit.) and «قُدْوَۃ» also means a leader, guide, or exemplar.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said: «اِنَّا وَجَدۡنَاۤ اٰبَآءَنَاعَلٰۤی اُمَّۃٍ وَّ اِنَّاعَلٰۤی اٰثٰرِہِمۡ مُّقۡتَدُوۡنَ» (43/23) Translation: Indeed, we found our fathers upon a community, and indeed we are followers of their footsteps."
    },
    {
      "id": 220,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to obey (to follow, to be a follower, to carry out commands)",
      "hw": "اطاعت",
      "s": "«اَطَاعَ» to carry out someone's command with happiness of heart (13 verses: 2:184-3:83-3:168-4:64-4:80-4:81-13:15-24:53-40:18-41:11-43:54-47:21-81:21)",
      "d": "«اَطَاعَ» means to carry out someone's command with happiness of heart.\n«طَوْعَ» means happiness and consent, and its opposite is «کَرْہٌ» meaning aversion, hatred, dislike. And «اَطَاعَ» refers to obedience that is performed with happiness of heart.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said: «فَقَالَ لَہَا وَ لِلۡاَرۡضِ ائۡتِیَا طَوۡعًا اَوۡ کَرۡہًا ؕ قَالَتَاۤ اَتَیۡنَا طَآئِعِیۡنَ» (41/11) Translation: Allah said to it and to the earth, 'Come, both of you, willingly or by compulsion.' They both said, 'We come willingly.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 221,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to obey (to follow, to be a follower, to carry out commands)",
      "hw": "اطاعت",
      "s": "«اِسْتَجَابَ» to accept a command and act upon it, to agree, and this is possible even from a subordinate (20 verses: 2:186-3:172-3:195-6:36-7:194-8:9-8:24-11:14-12:34-13:14-13:18-17:52-28:50-28:64-35:14-42:16-42:26-42:38-42:47-46:5)",
      "d": "«اِسْتَجَابَ» means to answer, to agree, to obey, and to accept a command. It is used in all these senses. The difference between obedience and response is that obedience is only done to a superior, while response can be done by a subordinate to a superior if it is in relation to Allah, it means accepting the servant's supplication, and if it is in relation to a servant, it means the servant accepting Allah's command (Faqih 184).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا اسۡتَجِیۡبُوۡا لِلّٰہِ وَ لِلرَّسُوۡلِ» (8/24) Translation: O you who have believed, respond to Allah and to the Messenger."
    },
    {
      "id": 222,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To obey (to follow, to show allegiance, to comply with commands)",
      "hw": "اطاعت",
      "s": "«اَسْلَمَ» to bow one's head in submission before someone's pleasure (17 verses: 2:112-2:131-3:20-3:83-4:65-4:125-5:44-6:14-6:71-22:34-27:44-37:103-39:54-40:66-49:14-49:17-72:14)",
      "d": "«As-Salam» means health and safety (M L) and means protection from external and internal harms (Mufradat), and «aslama» means to adopt obedience and to bow one's head in submission before God's commands and His pleasure to attain security and safety in the Hereafter (Mufradat). For example: In the Quran it is said: «اِذۡ قَالَ لَہٗ رَبُّہٗۤ  اَسۡلِمۡ ۙ قَالَ اَسۡلَمۡتُ لِرَبِّ الۡعٰلَمِیۡنَ» (2/131) Translation: When the Lord said to Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him), 'Submit', he said, 'I have submitted to the Lord of the worlds.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 223,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To obey (to follow, to show allegiance, to comply with commands)",
      "hw": "اطاعت",
      "s": "«قَنَتَ» such obedience in worship that also includes humility and meekness (2 verses: 3:43-33:31)",
      "d": "«Qunut» means to stand in prayer with complete and perfect silence and to exhibit humility and reverence before Allah (Munjid). And according to Imam Raghib, it means 'to be fully occupied in worship and to turn attention away from others' (Mufradat). Thus, Qunut is such obedience that is performed with complete humility, reverence, and focus. For example: In the Quran it is said: «وَ مَنۡ یَّقۡنُتۡ مِنۡکُنَّ لِلّٰہِ وَ رَسُوۡلِہٖ وَ تَعۡمَلۡ صَالِحًا نُّؤۡتِہَاۤ اَجۡرَہَا مَرَّتَیۡنِ» (33/31) Translation: And (O wives of the Prophet) whoever among you obeys Allah and His Messenger and does righteous deeds, We will give her reward twice."
    },
    {
      "id": 224,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To obey (to follow, to show allegiance, to comply with commands)",
      "hw": "اطاعت",
      "s": "«ذَعَنَ» to obey someone for one's own interests (1 verse: 24:49)",
      "d": "«Dha'ana» means to be obedient and compliant and to follow signals, and «mudh'aan» means one who easily becomes obedient (Munjid), and «naaqatun mudh'aanun» refers to a camel that is submissive and obedient to its rider (Mufradat). Thus, in «ذَعَنَ», there is an aspect of humility and degradation along with obedience. For example: In the Quran it is said: «وَ اِنۡ یَّکُنۡ  لَّہُمُ الۡحَقُّ یَاۡتُوۡۤا اِلَیۡہِ مُذۡعِنِیۡنَ» (24/49) Translation: And if the truth were to come to them, they would come to it in submission. Some exegetes have translated «مُذْعِنِیْن» as «مُطِیْعِیْن و سَارِعِیْن», meaning that if the matter is in their favor, they rush to accept it (Faqih al-Lughah, 209)."
    },
