  "43": [
    {
      "id": 232,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Regret",
      "hw": "افسوس",
      "s": "«وَیْلَ» This is an expression of regret that comes from a person's mouth in distress and calamity (38 verses: 2:79-5:31-11:72-14:2-18:49-19:37-20:61-21:14-21:18-21:46-21:97-25:28-28:80-36:52-37:20-38:27-39:22-41:6-43:65-45:7-46:17-51:60-52:11-68:31-77:15-77:19-77:24-77:28-77:34-77:37-77:40-77:45-77:47-77:49-83:1-83:10-104:1-107:4)",
      "d": "«وَیْلَ» is a word of warning that, in its origin, is used as a curse and means evil and misfortune (manjad). Destruction, severe calamity (manjad), and «تَوَایَل» meaning to curse one another (manjad). The word «وَیْل» is used in bad senses and is uttered on occasions of regret (m. r). And when a human is caught in some calamity or distress, they express regret with this word. Now see its examples:\n(1) Example in times of calamity: The Almighty says:\n«قَالُوۡا یٰوَیۡلَنَا مَنۡۢ بَعَثَنَا مِنۡ مَّرۡقَدِنَا» (36/52)\nTranslation: They will say, \"Alas! Who has raised us up from our resting places?\"\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«وَیۡلٌ یَّوۡمَئِذٍ لِّلۡمُکَذِّبِیۡنَ» (77/15)\nTranslation: \"Woe to the deniers on that Day!\"\n(2) Example in times of distress: The Almighty says:\n«فَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ غُرَابًا یَّبۡحَثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ لِیُرِیَہٗ کَیۡفَ یُوَارِیۡ سَوۡءَۃَ اَخِیۡہِ ؕ قَالَ یٰوَیۡلَتٰۤی اَعَجَزۡتُ اَنۡ اَکُوۡنَ مِثۡلَ ہٰذَا الۡغُرَابِ» (5/31)\nTranslation: \"So Allah sent a raven that scratched in the earth to show him how to hide the shame of his brother. He said, 'Alas for me! Could I not have been like this raven and so hidden my brother's shame?'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 233,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Regret",
      "hw": "افسوس",
      "s": "«لَیْتَ» is a particle of desire and comes to express regret over past shortcomings (14 verses: 4:73-6:27-18:42-19:23-25:27-25:28-28:79-33:66-36:26-43:38-69:25-69:27-78:40-89:24)",
      "d": "«لَیْتَ» is a particle of desire resembling a verb and comes to express regret over past shortcomings (muf) meaning \"if only\", \"oh that\". Regret. And it is used for a wish whose fulfillment is impossible. Like «لَیْتَ الشَّبَابُ عَائِدًا» (If only youth would return).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ یَقُوۡلُ الۡکٰفِرُ یٰلَیۡتَنِیۡ کُنۡتُ تُرٰبًا» (78/40)\nTranslation: \"And the disbeliever will say, 'If only I had been dust!'\"\nNote: (Particles resembling verbs: those particles that resemble verbs, and there are six of them: «إِنَّ، أَنَّ، کَأَنَّ، لٰـکِنَّ، لَیْتَ، لَعَلَّ»)\nParticle of desire: a word in which the expression of desire is found."
    }
  ],
  "44": [
    {
      "id": 236,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Grant Authority",
      "hw": "اقتدار",
      "s": "«مَکَّنَ» generally used to give someone authority, choice, and governance (12 verses: 6:6-7:10-8:71-12:21-12:56-18:84-18:95-22:41-28:6-28:57-46:26)",
      "d": "«مَکَّنَ» means to give power, to grant choice, to make capable (manjad). To gain a place and status. To stand firm on one's feet and to be capable of something (m. r). That is, to grant someone authority and bestow governance.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ اِنۡ مَّکَّنّٰہُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اَقَامُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَ اٰتَوُاالزَّکٰوۃَ وَاَمَرُوۡا بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَ نَہَوۡا عَنِ الۡمُنۡکَرِ» (22/41)\nTranslation: \"[They are] those who, if We give them authority in the land, establish prayer and give zakah and enjoin what is right and forbid what is wrong.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 237,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Grant Authority",
      "hw": "اقتدار",
      "s": "«اِسْتَخْلَفَ» meaning to make someone a successor or deputy (5 verses: 6:133-7:129-11:57-24:55-57:7)",
      "d": "«اِسْتَخْلَفَ» means to make someone a successor or deputy (manjad. m. r). And «خَلَفَ» means to come after or to be someone's successor.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَعَدَ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا مِنۡکُمۡ وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ لَیَسۡتَخۡلِفَنَّہُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (24/55)\nTranslation: \"Allah has promised those who have believed among you and done righteous deeds that He will surely grant them succession [to authority] upon the earth.\"\nThus, the word «اِسْتِخْلَاف» also implies that the present authority is in the hands of bad people, and those who believe in Allah and do good deeds, Allah the Almighty will change this present governance and transfer authority to them."
    }
  ],
  "45": [
    {
      "id": 239,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Confess",
      "hw": "اقرار",
      "s": "«اِعْتَرَفَ» to confess one's crime that happened in the past (3 verses: 9:102-40:11-67:11)",
      "d": "«عَرَفَ» means to recognize someone, and «اَعْتَرَفَ» means to confess one's crime and be humiliated (m. r). So, a criminal who is already aware and acquainted with their crime. When they confess it themselves, that is called confession, and that crime relates to the past, which they have confessed.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَاعۡتَرَفُوۡا بِذَنۡۢبِہِمۡ ۚ فَسُحۡقًا  لِّاَصۡحٰبِ السَّعِیۡرِ» (67/11)\nTranslation: \"Then they will confess their sins. So away with the companions of the Blaze!\""
    },
    {
      "id": 240,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Confess",
      "hw": "اقرار",
      "s": "«شَھِدَ» meaning testimony, a confession related to oneself (60 verses: 2:23-2:84-2:133-2:143-2:185-2:204-2:282-3:18-3:52-3:64-3:70-3:81-3:86-3:99-3:140-4:6-4:15-4:69-4:135-4:166-5:8-5:44-5:111-6:19-6:130-6:144-6:150-7:37-7:172-9:107-11:54-12:26-12:81-18:51-19:37-21:61-22:28-22:78-24:2-24:4-24:6-24:8-24:13-24:24-25:72-27:32-27:49-36:65-39:69-41:20-41:21-41:22-43:19-43:86-46:10-57:19-59:11-63:1-65:2-83:21)",
      "d": "«شَھِدَ» means testimony. And this testimony is of two types. One is eyewitness testimony, meaning a fact that a person has complete certainty about, and they give witness of it before a judge. The second is heart's testimony, like the testimony of faith (Shahadah). Every Muslim gives witness of it, although they have not seen Allah, and except for the Companions (ra), other Muslims have not seen the Messenger of Allah (ﷺ) either. Then when this heart's testimony is related to oneself, its meaning becomes \"to confess\".\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«قَالُوۡا شَہِدۡنَا عَلٰۤی اَنۡفُسِنَا وَ غَرَّتۡہُمُ الۡحَیٰوۃُ الدُّنۡیَا» (6/130)\nTranslation: \"They will say, 'Our Lord, we have confessed against ourselves.' And the worldly life had deluded them.\""
    }
  ],
  "46": [
    {
      "id": 241,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Unique",
      "hw": "اکیلا",
      "s": "«اَحَد» unique, peerless, used for Allah or a creation without equal (72 verses: 2:96-2:102-2:136-2:180-2:266-2:285-3:73-3:84-3:91-3:153-4:18-4:43-4:152-5:6-5:20-5:27-5:106-5:115-6:61-7:80-9:4-9:6-9:84-9:127-11:81-12:4-12:36-12:41-12:78-15:65-16:58-16:76-17:23-18:19-18:22-18:26-18:32-18:38-18:42-18:47-18:49-18:110-19:26-19:98-23:99-24:6-24:21-24:28-29:28-33:32-33:39-33:40-35:41-38:35-43:17-49:12-59:11-63:10-69:47-72:2-72:7-72:18-72:20-72:22-72:26-89:25-89:26-90:5-90:7-92:19-112:1-112:4)",
      "d": "«اَحَد» means unique, peerless (manjad). In this respect, this word is used only for the essence of Allah the Almighty. For other than Allah the Almighty, the word «وَاحِد» is used (muf m r). But in two places, «اَحَد» comes as a radif (following word) for «وَاحِد». (1) In numbers and their combinations, like «اَحَدَ عَشَرَ، اَحَدَھُمَ، اَحَدٌ مِّنْکُم، اَحَدُکُم، یَوَمُ الْاَحَد» etc. (2) In the negative form, only for beings with intellect. Like «لَیْسَ فِی الدَّارِاَحَدٌ» (There is no one in the house).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَمَا مِنۡکُمۡ مِّنۡ اَحَدٍ عَنۡہُ حٰجِزِیۡنَ» (69/47)\nTranslation: \"Then none of you will be able to hinder Us from [punishing] him.\"\nAnd the word «وَاحِد» is general. It is used equally for Allah the Almighty and all others besides Him. And Allah the Almighty has a name whose meaning is \"One\". Like «ھُوَ اللہُ الْوَاحِدُ الْقَھَّارُ». But when we say «قُلۡ ہُوَ اللّٰہُ اَحَدٌ» (112/1)\nTranslation: \"Say, 'He is Allah, the One.'\"\nWe say it means He is unique, peerless, and one of a kind. And in these meanings, this word is specific to the essence of Allah the Almighty."
    },
    {
      "id": 242,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Unique",
      "hw": "اکیلا",
      "s": "«وَحِیْد» unique, peerless, used for creations (1 verse: 74:11)",
      "d": "«وَاحِد» and «وَحِیْد» both words are used for something that is alone and unique in creation and has no equal. Like «اَلشَّمْسُ وَاحِدَۃٌ» (The sun is one). Or «فُلَانٌ وَاحِدُ عَصْرِہٖ» (So-and-so is alone in his era). And the word «وَحِیْد» comes in the same meanings.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«ذَرۡنِیۡ وَ مَنۡ خَلَقۡتُ وَحِیۡدًا» (74/11)\nTranslation: \"Leave Me and whom I created alone.\"\nThis verse is about Walid ibn al-Mughirah, who at that time had no equal in offspring and in honor and wealth."
    }
  ],
  "47": [
    {
      "id": 246,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Uprooting. To be uprooted.",
      "hw": "اکھاڑنا",
      "s": "«اِنْقَعَرَ» is used for the uprooting of large trees whose roots go deep into the ground (1 verse: 54:20).",
      "d": "The root «قَعَرَ» means the depth and lower part of something's inner surface. «اَقْعَرَ الْبِئْر» means to dig a well deep, and «اَقْعَرَ الشَّجر» means to uproot a tree. According to Ibn al-Faris, it means to uproot something whose roots have gone deep into the earth (m, l). The author of Muntaḥā al-ʿArab explains its meaning as: to uproot a tree and then throw it onto the ground (m, a).\nThus, «اَقْعَرَ» is a word used for the uprooting of very large trees whose roots have extended deep into the earth, and «اِنْقَعَر» is used when the action of doing this occurs or is apparent on that thing.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«تَنۡزِعُ  النَّاسَ ۙ کَاَنَّہُمۡ  اَعۡجَازُ نَخۡلٍ مُّنۡقَعِرٍ» (54/20)\nTranslation: (The violent wind) would snatch away people as if they were uprooted palm trunks.\nNote: (Uprooting: meaning to destroy something, to demolish, to uproot from the root, to dig up the root, to cut off the lineage, to annihilate)."
    }
  ],
  "48": [
    {
      "id": 247,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To gather. To be gathered.",
      "hw": "اکٹھا ",
      "s": "«جَمَعَ» is a general word for gathering. The word 'gathering' is used for bringing together different parts of one thing or different things (113 verses: 2:29-2:38-2:148-2:161-2:165-3:25-3:87-3:103-3:155-3:157-3:166-3:173-4:23-4:71-4:87-4:139-4:140-4:172-5:17-5:32-5:36-5:48-5:105-5:109-6:12-6:22-6:35-6:128-6:149-7:18-7:38-7:48-7:124-7:158-8:37-8:41-8:63-10:4-10:28-10:58-10:65-10:99-11:55-11:119-12:15-12:83-12:93-13:18-13:31-13:42-14:8-14:21-15:30-15:39-15:43-15:59-15:92-16:9-17:103-18:60-18:61-18:99-20:60-20:64-20:123-21:77-24:31-24:61-26:38-26:49-26:56-26:61-26:65-26:95-26:170-27:51-28:78-32:13-34:26-34:40-35:10-36:32-36:53-37:134-38:73-38:82-38:85-39:44-39:47-39:53-39:67-42:7-42:15-42:29-43:32-43:55-44:40-45:13-45:26-54:44-54:45-58:6-58:18-59:14-64:9-70:14-70:18-75:3-75:9-75:17-77:38-100:5-104:2).",
      "d": "The word «جَمَعَ» comes for bringing together different parts of one thing, or different things. These can be animate or inanimate.\nFor example: For animate things: The divine command states:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ  قَالَ لَہُمُ النَّاسُ  اِنَّ النَّاسَ قَدۡ جَمُوۡا لَکُمۡ» (3/173)\nTranslation: When those people came and said, 'Indeed, the disbelievers have gathered against you (a great army).'\nAnd for inanimate things: The divine command states:\n«الَّذِیۡ جَمَعَ  مَالًا  وَّ عَدَّدَہٗ» (104/2)\nTranslation: Who gathers wealth and counts it over and over.\nThen the word 'gathering' is also used for apparent things. It is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَتَوَلّٰی فِرۡعَوۡنُ فَجَمَعَ  کَیۡدَہٗ  ثُمَّ  اَتٰی» (20/60)\nTranslation: Then Pharaoh turned back and gathered his plan, then came (Othmani)."
    },
    {
      "id": 248,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To gather. To be gathered.",
      "hw": "اکٹھا ",
      "s": "«اِجْتَمَعَ» is used only for gathering living beings (3 verses: 17:88-22:73-26:39).",
      "d": "The word «اِجْتَمَعَ» is only used for the gathering of those with intellect (possessing reason). Whether they are of the same kind or different.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قُلۡ لَّئِنِ اجۡتَمَعَتِ الۡاِنۡسُ وَ الۡجِنُّ عَلٰۤی اَنۡ یَّاۡتُوۡا بِمِثۡلِ ہٰذَا الۡقُرۡاٰنِ لَا یَاۡتُوۡنَ بِمِثۡلِہٖ» (17/88)\nTranslation: Say, 'If mankind and the jinn gathered together to produce the like of this Quran, they could not produce the like thereof.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 249,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To gather. To be gathered.",
      "hw": "اکٹھا ",
      "s": "«حَشَرَ», meaning assembly, crowd, throng, is used for gathering living beings by raising them from their places to one location (39 verses: 2:203-3:12-3:158-4:172-5:96-6:22-6:38-6:51-6:72-6:111-6:128-8:24-8:36-10:28-10:45-15:25-17:97-18:47-19:68-19:85-20:59-20:102-20:124-20:125-23:79-25:17-25:34-27:17-27:83-34:40-37:22-41:19-46:6-50:44-58:9-59:2-67:24-79:23-81:5).",
      "d": "The word «حَشَرَ» comes for living beings, i.e., to take people from their dwellings to a certain place (mufrad), and Ibn al-Faris also confirms this meaning. He writes, «اَلْحَشْرُ الْجَمْعُ مَعَ سَوْق» (m, l).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَحَشَرَ فَنَادٰی فَقَالَ اَنَا رَبُّکُمُ الۡاَعۡلٰی» (79/23,24)\nTranslation: So (Pharaoh) gathered (his people) and called out, saying, 'I am your lord, the most high.'\nThen this word is sometimes also used in the meanings of «بَعَثَ» or «اَنْبِعَاث» (m, l), i.e., to resurrect the dead or to take to a specific purpose. See the following example in the meaning of «بَعَثَ»:\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«قَالَ رَبِّ  لِمَ حَشَرۡتَنِیۡۤ  اَعۡمٰی وَ قَدۡ کُنۡتُ  بَصِیۡرًا» (20/125)\nTranslation: He will say, 'My Lord, why have You gathered me [from the grave] blind while I was [once] a seeing [person]?'\nAnd sometimes in the usage of this word, the meanings of «تَجَمَّع , سُوْق» and «بَعَث» are all found.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یَوۡمَ نُسَیِّرُ الۡجِبَالَ وَ تَرَی الۡاَرۡضَ بَارِزَۃً ۙ وَّ حَشَرۡنٰہُمۡ  فَلَمۡ  نُغَادِرۡ  مِنۡہِمۡ اَحَدًا» (18/47)\nTranslation: And [mention] the Day We will move the mountains and you will see the earth exposed, and We will gather them and not leave from them anyone."
    },
    {
      "id": 250,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To gather. To be gathered.",
      "hw": "اکٹھا ",
      "s": "«اِدَّخَرَ» is used for gathering necessary things for the future (1 verse: 3:49).",
      "d": "The original root of «اِدَّخَرَ» is «ذَخَر» which means to store provisions, i.e., edible things, for future needs. To stockpile (mufrad). And many other living beings besides humans also do this storing. Ibn Faris writes two basic things in its meaning: to gather and to preserve it (m, l). And «اِدَّخَرَ» also comes in this same meaning. The gathered thing is called «ذخر» and «ذخیرہ».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اُنَبِّئُکُمۡ بِمَا تَاۡکُلُوۡنَ وَمَا تَدَّخِرُوۡنَ ۙ فِیۡ بُیُوۡتِکُمۡ» (3/49)\nTranslation: (Jesus, peace be upon him, said) And I inform you of what you eat and what you store in your houses."
    },
    {
      "id": 251,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Gather; To Be Gathered",
      "hw": "اکٹھا ",
      "s": "«خَزَنَ» To gather (for protection) (13 verses: 6:50-11:31-12:55-15:21-15:22-17:100-38:9-39:71-39:73-40:49-52:37-63:7-67:8)",
      "d": "The word ذخیرہ generally means to gather edible items. But «خَزَنَ» is more general than that. It often refers to gathering wealth and property, as in «خَزَنْتُ الدَّرَاھِمَ». However, the basic meaning is more about protection than gathering. It is said, «خَزَنْتُ السِّرَّ» (I kept the secret safe) (m. l). And the person who guards this gathered thing or wealth is called «خَازِنْ» and its plural is «خَزَنَۃُ».\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ  اُلۡقِیَ فِیۡہَا  فَوۡجٌ سَاَلَہُمۡ خَزَنَتُہَاۤ  اَلَمۡ یَاۡتِکُمۡ  نَذِیۡرٌ » (67/8)\nTranslation: Whenever a group is thrown into it (Hell), its keepers (guardians) will ask them: Did no warner come to you?\nAnd where something is gathered, that place is called «خِزَانَہ» and «خَزِیْنَہ», and its plural is «خَزَائِن». In the mentioned verse, the gathered things are the sinful people, Hell is the treasury, and the guardian or keeper is the خازن."
    },
    {
      "id": 253,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To gather. To be gathered.",
      "hw": "اکٹھا ",
      "s": "«کَفَتَ» meaning to gather and take into custody, to collect (1 verse: 77:25).",
      "d": "«کَفَتَ» meaning to gather something and take it into one's custody (mufrad). To collect. And «کَفِیْت» means a provision bag, in which food and provisions are collected and kept. For example: «اَللّٰھُمَّ اکْفِہٖ» meaning 'O Allah, suffice him' or 'O Allah, take care of it' (manjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَمۡ نَجۡعَلِ الۡاَرۡضَ  کِفَاتًا اَحۡیَآءً وَّاَمۡوَاتًا» (77/25,26)\nTranslation: Have We not made the earth a container [that gathers] the living and the dead?"
    },
    {
      "id": 254,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To gather. To be gathered.",
      "hw": "اکٹھا ",
      "s": "«لَمَّ» meaning to gather and to put in order, i.e., to fix (1 verse: 89:19).",
      "d": "«لَمَّ» meaning to gather something and to arrange it or to fix it (mufrad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَتَاۡکُلُوۡنَ التُّرَاثَ اَکۡلًا لَّمًّا» (89/19)\nTranslation: And you consume the inheritance, devouring it greedily."
    }
  ],
  "49": [
    {
      "id": 257,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "If",
      "hw": "اگر",
      "s": "«اِنْ» It is called the conditional particle in Arabic grammar. Used for the future. (531 verses: 2:23-2:24-2:31-2:70-2:78-2:85-2:91-2:93-2:94-2:11-2:137-2:143-2:172-2:180-2:184-2:191-2:192-2:193-2:196-2:198-2:209-2:217-2:220-2:226-2:227-2:228-2:229-2:230-2:233-2:236-2:237-2:239-2:240-2:246-2:248-2:265-2:271-2:278-2:279-2:280-2:282-2:283-2:284-2:286-3:20-3:29-3:31-3:32-3:49-3:63-3:64-3:75-3:93-3:100-3:111-3:118-3:120-3:125-3:139-3:140-3:144-3:149-3:160-3:164-3:168-3:175-3:179-3:183-3:184-3:186-4:3-4:4-4:6-4:11-4:12-4:15-4:16-4:19-4:20-4:23-4:25-4:31-4:34-4:35-4:40-4:43-4:59-4:62-4:72-4:78-4:89-4:90-4:91-4:92-4:101-4:102-4:104-4:117-4:128-4:129-4:130-4:131-4:133-4:135-4:141-4:147-4:149-4:159-4:170-4:176-5:6-5:17-5:22-5:23-5:41-5:42-5:49-5:57-5:67-5:73-5:92-5:101-5:106-5:107-5:110-5:112-5:116-5:118-6:7-6:15-6:17-6:25-6:26-6:29-6:35-6:40-6:41-6:46-6:47-6:50-6:57-6:70-6:81-6:89-6:90-6:116-6:118-6:121-6:133-6:139-6:143-6:147-6:148-6:150-6:156-7:23-7:70-7:77-7:85-7:87-7:89-7:102-7:106-7:113-7:131-7:143-7:146-7:155-7:169-7:176-7:184-7:188-7:193-7:194-7:198-8:1-8:19-8:29-8:31-8:32-8:34-8:38-8:39-8:40-8:41-8:61-8:62-8:65-8:66-8:70-8:71-8:72-9:3-9:5-9:6-9:8-9:11-9:12-9:13-9:23-9:24-9:28-9:41-9:50-9:58-9:62-9:66-9:74-9:80-9:83-9:96-9:107-9:129-10:15-10:29-10:38-10:41-10:48-10:50-10:66-10:68-10:71-10:72-10:84-10:94-10:104-10:106-10:107-11:3-11:7-11:13-11:28-11:29-11:30-11:32-11:33-11:34-11:35-11:38-11:50-11:51-11:54-11:57-11:63-11:86-11:88-12:3-12:10-12:26-12:27-12:31-12:40-12:43-12:60-12:67-12:74-12:77-12:91-12:99-12:104-13:5-13:40-14:8-14:10-14:11-14:19-14:34-14:46-15:7-15:21-15:71-15:78-16:18-16:37-16:43-16:82-16:95-16:114-16:126-17:7-17:8-17:25-17:44-17:47-17:52-17:54-17:58-17:73-17:76-17:108-18:5-18:6-18:20-18:29-18:39-18:57-18:69-18:70-18:76-19:18-19:71-19:93-20:7-20:63-20:103-20:104-21:7-21:17-21:34-21:36-21:38-21:47-21:63-21:68-21:109-21:111-22:5-22:11-22:41-22:42-22:68-22:73-23:25-23:30-23:37-23:38-23:83-23:84-23:88-23:107-23:114-24:2-24:7-24:9-24:17-24:28-24:32-24:33-24:49-24:54-25:4-25:8-25:10-25:41-25:42-25:44-26:4-26:24-26:28-26:31-26:40-26:41-26:97-26:109-26:113-26:115-26:127-26:137-26:145-26:154-26:164-26:180-26:186-26:187-26:205-26:216-27:64-27:68-27:71-27:81-28:10-28:19-28:27-28:49-28:50-28:57-28:71-28:72-29:8-29:16-29:18-29:29-30:36-30:49-30:53-30:58-31:15-31:16-32:28-33:5-33:13-33:16-33:17-33:20-33:24-33:28-33:29-33:32-33:50-33:54-34:9-34:29-34:43-34:46-34:47-34:50-35:4-35:14-35:16-35:18-35:23-35:24-35:25-35:40-35:41-36:15-36:23-36:29-36:32-36:43-36:47-36:48-36:53-36:69-37:15-37:56-37:102-37:157-37:167-38:7-38:14-38:70-38:87-39:7-39:13-39:38-39:56-40:12-40:28-40:29-40:56-41:13-41:24-41:37-41:38-41:49-41:52-42:24-42:33-42:48-43:20-43:35-43:59-43:81-44:7-44:21-44:35-44:36-45:24-45:25-45:32-46:4-46:8-46:9-46:10-46:22-46:26-47:7-47:22-47:36-47:37-47:38-48:11-48:16-48:27-49:6-49:9-49:14-49:17-52:34-52:44-53:4-53:23-53:28-54:2-55:33-56:86-56:87-56:88-56:90-56:92-57:8-58:2-58:12-59:11-60:1-60:2-60:10-60:11-61:11-62:2-62:6-62:9-63:4-64:12-64:14-64:17-65:4-65:6-66:4-66:5-67:9-67:20-67:21-67:25-67:28-67:30-68:22-68:41-68:51-71:27-72:25-73:17-74:24-74:25-77:39-81:27-86:4-87:9-96:11-96:13)",
      "d": "«اِنْ» is a conditional particle. It is used for the future. The first clause (condition) is always a verb, and the second clause (result) follows.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«اِنۡ تُعَذِّبۡہُمۡ فَاِنَّہُمۡ عِبَادُکَ» (5/118)\nTranslation: If You punish them, they are Your servants."
    },
    {
      "id": 258,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "If",
      "hw": "اگر",
      "s": "«اِمَّا» in Arabic grammar, when «اِمَّا» comes in the meaning of 'if', it has the extra particle «مَا» which comes only for emphasis ( beautification of speech) (22 verses: 2:38-6:68-7:35-7:115-7:200-8:57-8:58-9:106-10:46-17:23-17:28-18:86-19:26-19:75-20:65-20:123-23:93-40:77-41:36-43:41-47:4-76:3).",
      "d": "When «اِنْ ۔ مَا» comes as a conditional particle, only «اِنْ» gives the meaning. «مَا» is an extra particle and comes only for the beautification of speech, i.e., to make the speech eloquent.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِمَّا یَبۡلُغَنَّ عِنۡدَکَ الۡکِبَرَ اَحَدُہِمَاۤ» (17/23)\nTranslation: If one of them or both of them reaches old age in your presence.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«فَاِمَّا تَرَیِنَّ مِنَ الۡبَشَرِ اَحَدًا» (19/26)\nTranslation: Then (O Mary!) if you see any human being..."
    },
    {
      "id": 259,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "If",
      "hw": "اگر",
      "s": "In «لَوْ», the consequence is always attached to the condition (i.e., a condition is stipulated in return for an action). (214 verses: 2:20-2:64-2:96-2:102-2:103-2:109-2:251-2:165-2:167-2:220-2:221-2:253-3:30-3:69-3:91-3:110-3:154-3:156-3:159-3:167-3:168-4:9-4:39-4:42-4:46-4:64-4:66-4:78-4:82-4:83-4:89-4:90-4:102-4:113-4:129-4:135-5:36-5:48-5:65-5:66-5:81-5:100-5:106-6:7-6:8-6:9-6:27-6:28-6:30-6:35-6:58-6:88-6:93-6:107-6:111-6:112-6:137-6:148-6:149-6:152-6:157-7:43-7:96-7:100-7:155-7:176-7:188-8:8-8:19-8:23-8:31-8:42-8:43-8:50-8:63-8:68-9:32-9:33-9:42-9:46-9:47-9:57-9:59-9:81-9:113-10:11-10:16-10:19-10:42-10:43-10:54-10:82-10:97-10:99-11:80-11:91-11:110-11:118-12:17-12:24-12:94-12:103-13:18-13:31-14:21-15:2-15:7-15:14-16:9-16:35-16:41-16:61-16:93-17:42-17:74-17:88-17:95-17:100-18:18-18:58-18:77-18:109-20:129-20:134-21:17-21:22-21:39-21:99-22:40-22:73-23:24-23:71-23:75-23:114-24:10-24:14-24:20-24:21-24:35-25:42-25:45-25:51-25:77-26:102-26:113-26:198-28:10-28:47-28:64-28:82-29:41-29:53-29:64-31:27-32:12-32:13-33:14-33:20-33:52-34:14-34:31-34:51-35:14-35:18-35:45-36:47-36:66-36:67-37:57-37:143-37:168-39:4-39:26-39:47-39:57-39:58-40:14-41:14-41:44-41:45-42:8-42:14-42:21-42:27-43:20-43:33-43:60-46:11-47:4-47:21-47:30-48:22-48:25-49:5-49:7-56:65-56:70-56:76-58:22-59:3-59:9-59:21-60:2-61:8-61:9-67:10-68:9-68:33-68:49-69:44-70:11-71:4-75:15-102:5)",
      "d": "«لَوْ» is a conditional particle, but its consequence is always attached to the condition (i.e., a condition is stipulated in return for an action), and its consequence includes the particle «لَ» (lam).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَوۡ کَانَ عَرَضًا قَرِیۡبًا وَّ سَفَرًا قَاصِدًا لَّاتَّبَعُوۡکَ» (9/42)\nTranslation: If the spoils had been near and the journey short, they would have followed you (O Prophet).\nAnd if «وَ» precedes «لَوْ», as in «وَلَو», it gives the meaning of 'even if' or 'although'.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَیۡنَ مَا تَکُوۡنُوۡا یُدۡرِکۡکُّمُ الۡمَوۡتُ وَ لَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ  فِیۡ  بُرُوۡجٍ مُّشَیَّدَۃٍ» (4/78)\nTranslation: Wherever you may be, death will overtake you, even if you are in fortified towers.\nAnd adding «لَا» after «لَوْ» creates the meaning of 'if not'.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«لَوۡ لَاۤ اَنۡتُمۡ لَکُنَّا مُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ» (34/31)\nTranslation: If it were not for you, we would certainly have been believers."
    }
  ],
  "50": [
    {
      "id": 260,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To turn upside down, to invert",
      "hw": "الٹ",
      "s": "The meaning of «اَرْکَسَ» is to turn something onto its head (i.e., head down and feet up). (2 verses: 4:88-4:91)",
      "d": "The meaning of «اَرْکَسَ» is to turn something onto its head (i.e., head down and feet up), or to reverse its front and back (i.e., to invert). It is said «اَرْکَسَ الثَّوبُ فِی الصَّبْغِ» meaning to dip the cloth upside down in the dye.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اللّٰہُ اَرۡکَسَہُمۡ بِمَا کَسَبُوۡا» (4/88)\nTranslation: Allah has turned them (the hypocrites) upside down because of what they earned."
    },
    {
      "id": 261,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To turn upside down, to invert",
      "hw": "الٹ",
      "s": "«اِئْتَفَکَ» means to turn to a direction other than the correct one. (3 verses: 9:70-53:53-69:9)",
      "d": "«اَفَکَ» means to turn someone away from the correct path. And if one is turned to a direction other than the correct one, it is called «اِئْتَفَکَ».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ الۡمُؤۡتَفِکَۃَ  اَہۡوٰی» (53/53)\nTranslation: And He turned upside down the overturned towns."
    },
    {
      "id": 262,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To turn upside down, to invert",
      "hw": "الٹ",
      "s": "«جَثَمَ» means to fall or become stuck face down. (5 verses: 7:78-7:91-11:67-11:94-29:37)",
      "d": "«جَثَمَ» refers to a bird sitting on its chest on the ground and then sticking there. Figuratively, it means for a person to lie face down on the ground.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَخَذَتۡہُمُ الرَّجۡفَۃُ فَاَصۡبَحُوۡا فِیۡ  دَارِہِمۡ  جٰثِمِیۡنَ» (7/78)\nTranslation: So the earthquake seized them, and they became lying upside down in their homes."
    },
    {
      "id": 263,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To turn upside down, to invert",
      "hw": "الٹ",
      "s": "«کَبَّ» means to fall face down. (3 verses: 26:94-27:90-67:22)",
      "d": "«کَبَّ الْاِنَاءَ» means to turn the vessel upside down. And «کَبَّ فُلَانًا» means to make someone fall face down.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ جَآءَ بِالسَّیِّئَۃِ  فَکُبَّتۡ وُجُوۡہُہُمۡ  فِی النَّارِ» (27/90)\nTranslation: And whoever comes with an evil deed, their faces will be turned upside down in the Fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 264,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To turn upside down, to invert",
      "hw": "الٹ",
      "s": "«کَبْکَبَ» means to tumble and throw headfirst into a pit. (1 verse: 26:94)",
      "d": "In «کَبْکَبَ», there is reduplication which intensifies its meaning. It means to throw something down from above, tumbling it, into a pit.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَکُبۡکِبُوۡا فِیۡہَا  ہُمۡ  وَ الۡغَاوٗنَ» (26/94)\nTranslation: So they and the misguided (i.e., the idols and idolaters) will be tumbled headfirst into it."
    }
  ],
  "51": [
    {
      "id": 267,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to divide or isolate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "«فَرَقَ» means to split something apart and separate it. (32 verses: 2:50-2:53-2:102-2:136-2:185-2:285-3:4-3:84-3:103-3:105-4:130-4:150-4:152-5:25-6:153-6:159-8:29-8:41-12:39-12:67-17:106-20:94-21:48-25:1-26:63-30:14-30:32-42:13-42:14-44:4-77:4-98:4)",
      "d": "«فَرَقَ» means to split something apart and separate it. Then the separated thing is called «فِرْق». And if the separated things are groups of people, they are called factions. For example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِذۡ فَرَقۡنَا بِکُمُ الۡبَحۡرَ» (2/50)\nTranslation: And when We parted the sea for you.\nIn another instance, the Divine declaration is:\n«فَانۡفَلَقَ فَکَانَ کُلُّ فِرۡقٍ  کَالطَّوۡدِ  الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (26/63)\nTranslation: So it parted, and each portion became like a great mountain.\nThen «فَرَقَ» is also used in a spiritual sense. That is, to separate two types of things that may appear similar but are essentially different.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ رَبِّ اِنِّیۡ  لَاۤ  اَمۡلِکُ اِلَّا نَفۡسِیۡ وَ اَخِیۡ فَافۡرُقۡ بَیۡنَنَا وَ بَیۡنَ الۡقَوۡمِ الۡفٰسِقِیۡنَ» (5/25)\nTranslation: Moses said, 'My Lord, I have no control over myself or my brother, so separate between us and the defiant people.'\nAnd «فَرَّقَ» means to separate from a group, to form a separate faction.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ فَرَّقُوۡا دِیۡنَہُمۡ  وَ کَانُوۡا  شِیَعًا» (6/159)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who split their religion and became factions."
    },
    {
      "id": 268,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to divide or isolate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "«فَتَقَ» means to split something open and separate it, or to separate merged things. (1 verse: 21:30)",
      "d": "The meaning of «فَتَقَ» is to create a large fissure in something and open it. Like opening the musk pod (the sac in a deer where musk is stored). Or to separate two merged things. Its opposite is «رَتَقَ», meaning something is sewn together or joined.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَنَّ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ کَانَتَا رَتۡقًا فَفَتَقۡنٰہُمَا» (21/30)\nTranslation: The heavens and the earth were a joined entity, and We separated them."
    },
    {
      "id": 269,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Separate (To Make Separate or Distinct)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "«عَزَلَ» To separate someone from their work. (2 verses: 11:42-33:51)",
      "d": "«عَزَلَ» means to separate someone from their original work or purpose. To render idle. To set aside (m. r. manjad). معزول also comes from this. A person is called معزول who has been separated from work. And «عُزْلَت» means solitude.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ مَنِ ابۡتَغَیۡتَ مِمَّنۡ عَزَلۡتَ فَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکَ» (33/51)\nTranslation: And whoever you have separated, there is no blame on you."
    },
    {
      "id": 270,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to divide or isolate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "«جَنَبَ» means to keep someone separate and away from a calamity. (3 verses: 14:35-87:11-92:17)",
      "d": "The basic meanings of «جَنَبَ» are two: (1) side, (2) to be distant. And «جَنَبَ» means to keep someone away from a calamity or disaster, to save them.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِذۡ قَالَ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمُ رَبِّ اجۡعَلۡ ہٰذَا الۡبَلَدَ اٰمِنًا وَّاجۡنُبۡنِیۡ وَ بَنِیَّ اَنۡ نَّعۡبُدَ الۡاَصۡنَامَ» (14/35)\nTranslation: And when Abraham said, 'My Lord, make this city secure and keep me and my sons away from worshipping idols.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 271,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Separate (To Make Separate or Distinct)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "«مَازَ» To separate something from another based on superiority and preference. (2 verses: 3:179-8:37)",
      "d": "«مَازَ» means to separate something from another based on superiority and preference. And «مَا زَالشَّیء» means to give preference to one thing over others. To grant superiority (manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«مَا کَانَ اللّٰہُ لِیَذَرَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ عَلٰی مَاۤ اَنۡتُمۡ عَلَیۡہِ حَتّٰی یَمِیۡزَ الۡخَبِیۡثَ مِنَ الطَّیِّبِ» (3/179)\nTranslation: Allah will not leave the believers in the state you are in until He separates the evil from the good."
    },
    {
      "id": 273,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Become Separate (To Become Distinct or Separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "«تَفَرَّقَ» To become separate and scattered from the group. (10 verses: 3:103-3:105-4:130-6:153-12:39-12:67-30:14-42:13-42:14-98:4)",
      "d": "«تَفَرَّقَ» is the opposite of «تَجَمُّع». Meaning to become separate and scattered. To split and become separate (manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ اعۡتَصِمُوۡا بِحَبۡلِ اللّٰہِ جَمِیۡعًا وَّ لَا تَفَرَّقُوۡا» (3/103)\nTranslation: And hold firmly to the rope of Allah all together and do not become separated."
    },
    {
      "id": 275,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Become Separate (To Become Distinct or Separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "«تَجَنَّبَ» To become separate from something and go far to avoid calamity. (1 verse: 87:11)",
      "d": "«تَجَنَّبَ» means to stay away, to turn aside.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«سَیَذَّکَّرُ مَنۡ یَّخۡشٰی وَ  یَتَجَنَّبُہَا الۡاَشۡقَی» (87/10,11)\nTranslation: He who fears will be reminded, and the wretched will turn aside."
    },
    {
      "id": 276,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to be different, to be separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "«اِمْتَازَ» to be separate from others based on a characteristic (1 verse: 36:59)",
      "d": "«اِمْتَازَ» means to separate the good from the evil or the evil from the good based on excellence and preference.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَامۡتَازُوا الۡیَوۡمَ اَیُّہَا الۡمُجۡرِمُوۡنَ» (36/59)\nTranslation: And O you criminals! Separate yourselves today.\nBesides these, the following words are also used in the meanings of 'to separate': «خَلَا، خَلَو، خَلَصَ، فَصَلَ، اِنْتَبَذَ، نَبَذَ، تَزَیَّلَ، زَیَّلَ، and تَجَافٰی، جَفَو»."
    },
    {
      "id": 277,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to be different, to be separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "«خَلَا» to be separate in order to meet in solitude (9 verses: 2:14-2:76-2:214-3:119-10:102-24:34-33:38-33:62-35:24)",
      "d": "« خَلَاء ، یَخْلُو» it means empty space where there is no building or house, etc. This word is used for both time and place. For example, «خَلَا الزَّمَان» means time has passed, and in terms of place, «خَلَا الرَّجُل» means to meet someone in solitude (seclusion) (see Mufradat).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَاِذَا خَلَوۡا اِلٰی شَیٰطِیۡنِہِمۡ ۙ قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّا مَعَکُمۡ» (2/14)\nTranslation: And when they are alone with their evil ones, they say: Indeed, we are with you. (عثمانیؒ)"
    },
    {
      "id": 278,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to be different, to be separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "«خَلَصَ» to be separate from the mixture with the original thing and to remain pure (24 verses: 2:139-4:146-7:29-10:22-12:24-12:54-12:80-15:40-19:51-29:65-31:32-37:40-37:74-37:128-37:160-37:169-38:46-38:83-39:2-39:11-39:14-40:14-40:65-98:5)",
      "d": "«خَلَصَ» means to purify a thing from mixture and to separate the mixture from it, and its opposite is «خَلَطَ».\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَلَمَّا اسۡتَیۡئَسُوۡا مِنۡہُ خَلَصُوۡا نَجِیًّا» (12/80)\nTranslation: When they lost hope from him, they consulted in private.\nmeaning they went and sat apart from others in order to consult among themselves."
    },
    {
      "id": 279,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to be different, to be separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "«فَصَلَ» to separate two things from each other in such a way that a distance is created between them (20 verses: 2:249-6:65-6:97-6:98-6:114-6:119-6:126-7:32-7:52-7:133-7:174-9:11-10:5-10:24-11:1-12:94-17:12-30:28-41:3-41:44)",
      "d": "«فَصَلَ» means for two things to be separate such that a distance exists between them (see Mufradat) or to depart from a place:\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَلَمَّا فَصَلَ طَالُوۡتُ بِالۡجُنُوۡدِ  ۙ قَالَ  اِنَّ اللّٰہَ مُبۡتَلِیۡکُمۡ بِنَہَرٍ» (2/249)\nTranslation: So when Talut departed with the armies, he said: Indeed, Allah will test you with a river."
    },
    {
      "id": 280,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to be different, to be separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "«اِنْتَبَذَ» to be separate from others due to a feeling of inferiority (2 verses: 19:16-19:22)",
      "d": "«نَبَذَ» means to throw something considering it unworthy of attention (i.e., something that is forgettable and not worthy of consideration) (see Mufradat), and «اِنتَبَذَ» means to be separate from others while being in a state of self-perceived inferiority.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَاذۡکُرۡ فِی الۡکِتٰبِ مَرۡیَمَ ۘ اِذِ انۡتَبَذَتۡ مِنۡ اَہۡلِہَا مَکَانًا شَرۡقِیًّا» (19/16)\nTranslation: And mention in the Book (the story of) Maryam when she withdrew from her family to a place towards the east.\nAt this point, the word «اِنتَبَذَ» is used for Maryam (Mary) because, due to the pregnancy of Prophet Isa (Jesus), she went away in solitude to avoid people's objections and curses."
    },
    {
      "id": 281,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to be different, to be separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "«تَزَیَّلَ» to leave one's place and to move aside, to become separate (1 verse: 48:25)",
      "d": "«زَالَ» means to remove something from its place (see Mufradat), and accordingly, «تَزَیَّلَ» means for something to leave its place and scatter around, to move aside and go far away.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«لَوۡ تَزَیَّلُوۡا لَعَذَّبۡنَا الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡہُمۡ عَذَابًا اَلِیۡمًا» (48/25)\nTranslation: And if they had separated, We would have punished those among them who disbelieved with a painful punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 282,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to be different, to be separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "«تَجَافٰی» to be separate from something due to restlessness (1 verse: 32:16)",
      "d": "«جَفْوَۃٌ» and «جَفَاءٌ» mean oppression, and «جَفَا یَجْفُوا» means not to settle in one place (see Mufradat), and accordingly, «تَجَافٰی» means to change one's place or to remain separate from that place due to restlessness.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«تَتَجَافٰی جُنُوۡبُہُمۡ عَنِ الۡمَضَاجِعِ یَدۡعُوۡنَ رَبَّہُمۡ خَوۡفًا وَّ طَمَعًا» (32/16)\nTranslation: Their sides (i.e., their bodies) keep away from the beds (as they pray) while they call upon their Lord in fear and hope."
    }
  ],
  "52": [
    {
      "id": 283,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To hope",
      "hw": "امید",
      "s": "«اَمَلَ» is used for hope that is long-awaited and seemingly unexpected (3 verses: 15:3-18:46-47:25)",
      "d": "The discussion of «اَمَلَ» has passed in 'desire' (آرزو), and its meaning is such a desire and hope that is seemingly unexpected and long-awaited. Thus, «اَمَل» includes the concept of duration and waiting. In this sense, it comes to mean 'to place hope'.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ الۡبٰقِیٰتُ الصّٰلِحٰتُ خَیۡرٌ عِنۡدَ رَبِّکَ ثَوَابًا وَّخَیۡرٌاَمَلًا» (18/46)\nTranslation: And the lasting righteous deeds are better for your Lord in reward and better for hope."
    },
    {
      "id": 284,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To hope",
      "hw": "امید",
      "s": "«اَمْنٰی» is used for instilling false hopes (2 verses: 4:119-22:52)",
      "d": "«اَمْنِیَۃ» means false and vain desire, and «اَمَانِی» is its plural. This discussion has also passed in 'to desire' (آرزو کرنا), and the word «اَمْنٰی» comes in the meaning of instilling such false and vain hopes in someone.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَّ لَاُضِلَّنَّہُمۡ وَ لَاُمَنِّیَنَّہُمۡ» (4/119)\nTranslation: And I will surely mislead them and surely instill false hopes in them."
    }
  ],
  "53": [
    {
      "id": 286,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Intestines",
      "hw": "انتڑیاں",
      "s": "«حَوَایَا» is used for those intestines which appear like the coil of a snake (1 verse: 6:146)",
      "d": "«حَوَایَا» is the plural of «حَوِیَّۃ». The reference is to intestines that coil like a snake. «حَیَّۃٌ» means snake; «تَحْوِی الْحَیّۃ» means the snake coils; and «حَاوِی» is the term for one who recites a charm over a snake (a charmer). And this is that intestine or gut which, while coiling, reaches the anus, i.e., goes to the back. (M. R.)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«حَرَّمۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ شُحُوۡمَہُمَاۤ اِلَّا مَا حَمَلَتۡ ظُہُوۡرُہُمَاۤ اَوِالۡحَوَایَاۤ اَوۡمَا اخۡتَلَطَ بِعَظۡمٍ» (6/146)\nTranslation: And We have forbidden them the fat of both (the cow and the goat) except what is on their backs or the intestines or what is mixed with bone."
    },
    {
      "id": 287,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Intestines",
      "hw": "انتڑیاں",
      "s": "«اَمْعَآء» is used for all kinds of small and large intestines (1 verse: 47:15)",
      "d": "«اَمْعَآء» is the plural of «معْیٌ». This word is general and is used for all kinds of small and large intestines.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَسُقُوۡا مَآءً حَمِیۡمًا فَقَطَّعَ اَمۡعَآءَہُمۡ» (47/15)\nTranslation: And they will be given to drink boiling water which will cut their intestines."
    }
  ],
  "54": [
    {
      "id": 290,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Wait",
      "hw": "انتظار",
      "s": "«تَرَبُّص» is waiting for a period to gain benefit or for a specified period (12 verses: 2:226, 2:228, 2:234, 4:141, 9:24, 9:52, 9:98, 20:135, 23:25, 52:30, 52:31, 57:14)",
      "d": "«رَبَصَ» and «تَرَبُّص» are used in the same meaning, and this waiting is either for a specific period or for the occurrence or disappearance of something for which there is an expectation. (Muf) For example, waiting for the rise and fall of prices of goods. «تَرَبُّص بِسِلْعَۃٍ» means waiting for the price of goods to fall (Munjid).\nSimilarly, for a woman, waiting to complete her 'iddah (waiting period) will be called «تَرَبُّص», and it also means waiting to gain more benefit. (Faq. 59)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«قُلۡ ہَلۡ تَرَبَّصُوۡنَ بِنَاۤ اِلَّاۤ اِحۡدَی الۡحُسۡنَیَیۡنِ ؕ وَنَحۡنُ نَتَرَبَّصُ بِکُمۡ اَنۡ یُّصِیۡبَکُمُ اللّٰہُ بِعَذَابٍ مِّنۡ عِنۡدِہٖۤ اَوۡبِاَیۡدِیۡنَا ۫ ۖ فَتَرَبَّصُوۡۤا اِنَّا مَعَکُمۡ مُّتَرَبِّصُوۡنَ» (9/52)\nTranslation: Say, 'Do you wait for us except one of the two good things (martyrdom or victory)? And we are waiting for you that Allah will afflict you with a punishment from Himself or by our hands. So wait, indeed we, with you, are waiting.'"
    }
  ],
  "55": [
    {
      "id": 293,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Outcome (of an action)",
      "hw": "انجام",
      "s": "«عَاقِبَۃ» is used for the outcome of an action and its recompense (32 verses: 3:137-6:11-6:135-7:84-7:86-7:103-7:128-10:39-10:73-11:49-12:109-16:36-20:132-22:41-27:14-27:51-27:69-28:37-28:40-28:83-30:9-30:10-30:42-31:22-35:44-37:73-40:21-40:82-43:25-47:10-59:17-65:9)",
      "d": "«عَقَبَ» means heel, and «عَقَّبْ» means to follow behind someone and to come behind, and «عَاقِبَۃ» is the end of everything or the outcome of an action (see Mufradat). Then in the meaning of 'عقب', intensity and hardship are also found. «عَاقَبَہٗ» means to seize someone in return for their action, and the word «عِقَاب» is generally used for the recompense of a bad deed.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَجٰدَلُوۡا بِالۡبَاطِلِ لِیُدۡحِضُوۡا بِہِ الۡحَقَّ فَاَخَذۡتُہُمۡ ۟ فَکَیۡفَ کَانَ عِقَابِ» (40/5)\nTranslation: And they argued by falsehood to refute the truth, so I seized them. So how was My punishment?\nThus, the word «عَاقِبَۃ» is applied not only to the outcome of an action but also to its recompense.\nFor example, for good, the divine command is:\n«اِنَّ الۡاَرۡضَ لِلّٰہِ ۟ ۙ یُوۡرِثُہَا مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ مِنۡ عِبَادِہٖ ؕ وَ الۡعَاقِبَۃُ  لِلۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ» (7/128)\nTranslation: Indeed, the earth belongs to Allah; He causes to inherit it whom He wills of His servants. And the (good) outcome is for the pious.\nAnd for evil, the divine command is:\n«قَدۡ خَلَتۡ مِنۡ قَبۡلِکُمۡ سُنَنٌ ۙ فَسِیۡرُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ فَانۡظُرُوۡا کَیۡفَ کَانَ عَاقِبَۃُ الۡمُکَذِّبِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: There have already passed before you ways of life. So travel through the earth and observe how was the end of the deniers."
    }
  ],
  "56": [
    {
      "id": 294,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Estimate",
      "hw": "اندازہ ",
      "s": "«خَرَصَ» is an estimate based on conjecture and guess rather than knowledge and reality. And it is unreliable (4 verses: 6:116, 6:148, 10:66, 43:20)",
      "d": "«خَرَصَ» means to take a matter based merely on conjecture and estimate. «خَرَصَ النَّخْلَۃ» means to estimate merely by guess how much fruit will be on that date palm tree. And «خَرَّاص» is the term for a person who makes such an estimate (Munjid). And «خَرَّاص» also means a great liar, because such a person speaks without knowledge and reality, and this is the very basis of lying.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِنۡ تَتَّبِعُوۡنَ اِلَّا الظَّنَّ وَ اِنۡ اَنۡتُمۡ اِلَّا تَخۡرُصُوۡنَ» (6/148)\nTranslation: You follow not except assumption, and indeed, you do nothing but lie."
    },
    {
      "id": 295,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Estimate",
      "hw": "اندازہ ",
      "s": "«قَدَّرَ» refers to those natural laws which Allah, the Exalted, has decreed with His knowledge and wisdom, and they are firmly established. And «قَدَّرَ» is the term for an estimate based on such laws (11 verses: 13:26, 17:30, 28:82, 29:62, 30:37, 34:36, 34:39, 39:52, 42:12, 65:7, 89:16)",
      "d": "«قَدَرَ» means to devise a matter, to prepare something, and to manage it (Munjid). And «قَدَرْ» refers to those natural laws under which a thing comes into existence and is organized (Muf). And this attribute is specific to Allah, the Exalted, and comes only in good meanings. (Faq. 157)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِنَّا کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ خَلَقۡنٰہُ بِقَدَرٍ» (54/49)\nTranslation: We have created all things according to a precise measure.\nAnd «قَدَّرَ» means to create and train something in a particular manner as wisdom demands. And this word is general; this estimate can be good or bad (Faq. 157), as is included in the creed: «وَالْقَدْرِ خَیْرِہٖ وَشَرِّہٖ مِنَ اللہِ تَعَالیٰ» (And the measure, its good and its evil, is from Allah, the Exalted).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ الشَّمۡسَ ضِیَآءً وَّ الۡقَمَرَ نُوۡرًا وَّ قَدَّرَہٗ  مَنَازِلَ  لِتَعۡلَمُوۡا عَدَدَ السِّنِیۡنَ وَ الۡحِسَابَ» (10/5)\nTranslation: It is He who made the sun a shining light and the moon a derived light and determined for it phases that you may know the number of years and the account."
    }
  ],
  "57": [
    {
      "id": 298,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Inside",
      "hw": "اندر",
      "s": "«جَوْف» is the internal cavity of something (1 verse: 33:4)",
      "d": "«جَوِفَ» means to be hollow, and «جَوَّف» means to hollow out. «جَوْف» refers to the belly or inner part. «جَوفَ الْبَیْت» is the inner part of the house, and «مُجَّوَف» is a hollow thing (Munjid). Thus, in «جَوِفَ», where the concept of inside or inner part is found, simultaneously the concept of hollowness, spaciousness, or cavity is also found.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«مَا جَعَلَ اللّٰہُ  لِرَجُلٍ مِّنۡ قَلۡبَیۡنِ فِیۡ جَوۡفِہٖ» (33/4)\nTranslation: Allah has not made for any man two hearts within his chest."
    }
  ],
  "58": [
    {
      "id": 299,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Blind",
      "hw": "اندھا",
      "s": "«اَعْمٰی» means blind (28 verses: 2:18, 2:171, 6:50, 6:104, 7:64, 10:43, 11:24, 11:28, 13:16, 13:19, 17:72, 17:97, 20:124, 20:125, 22:46, 24:61, 25:73, 27:81, 28:66, 30:53, 35:19, 40:58, 41:17, 41:44, 43:40, 47:23, 48:17, 80:20)",
      "d": "«اَعْمٰی» means blind, sightless, deprived of sight. Blindness of the eyes. (Fal. 39)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«ہَلۡ یَسۡتَوِی الۡاَعۡمٰی وَ الۡبَصِیۡرُ» (13/16)\nTranslation: Are the blind and the seeing equal?\nAlthough the application of this word is generally for physical blindness of the eyes, sometimes it is also used for blindness of the heart.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَمَاۤ اَنۡتَ بِہٰدِی الۡعُمۡیِ عَنۡ ضَلٰلَتِہِمۡ» (27/81)\nTranslation: And you cannot guide the blind away from their error."
    },
    {
      "id": 300,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Blind",
      "hw": "اندھا",
      "s": "«اَکْمَہَ» is used for a person who is congenitally blind (2 verses: 3:49-5:110)",
      "d": "«اَکْمَہَ» refers to a person who is blind from birth (m. l. manjad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ تُبۡرِیُٔ الۡاَکۡمَہَ وَ الۡاَبۡرَصَ بِاِذۡنِیۡ»\nTranslation: And (O Jesus PBUH) you used to cure the congenitally blind and the leper with My permission."
    }
  ],
  "59": [
    {
      "id": 302,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Justice",
      "hw": "انصاف",
      "s": "The word «قِسْط» is used for giving someone their full right, whether all at once or in installments. (24 verses: 2:282-3:18-3:21-4:3-4:127-4:135-5:8-5:42-6:152-7:29-10:4-10:47-10:54-11:85-17:35-21:47-26:182-33:5-49:9-55:9-57:25-60:8-72:14-72:15)",
      "d": "The meaning of «قِسْط» is to give someone their full right completely; its fundamental meaning is to avoid injustice. (muf) In this sense, its meaning is taken as 'to do justice'. Its application is on doing justice in apparent matters. Therefore, the scales and measures for weighing are also called «قِسْط» (faql 194).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاَقِیۡمُوا الۡوَزۡنَ بِالۡقِسۡطِ وَلَا تُخۡسِرُواالۡمِیۡزَانَ» (55/9)\nTranslation: And establish weight in justice and do not make the scale deficient.\nThen, the word «قِسْط» is from the category of words with opposite meanings (al-iddād). If «قَسَطَ یَقْسُطُ» is used, its meanings are as stated above. If «قَسَطَ یَقْسِطُ» is used, its meanings are to oppress someone, to act against the right, and to transgress the right. (muf). (manjad)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاَمَّا الۡقٰسِطُوۡنَ فَکَانُوۡا لِجَہَنَّمَ حَطَبًا» (72/15)\nTranslation: And those who were unjust (oppressive) became fuel for Hell. (Uthmani RA)\nThen, whether someone's right is to be paid in one handful or in several parts, the words «قِسْط» and «اَقْسَاط» are used for that. Thus, the word «قِسْط» is used for the payment of a right in both its entirety and its parts. However, in the Quran, it is not used in these meanings. But if the chapter is of verbs (af'āl), it will come in the meanings of doing justice.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اَقۡسِطُوۡا ؕ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُحِبُّ الۡمُقۡسِطِیۡنَ» (49/9)\nTranslation: And do justice. Indeed, Allah loves those who do justice.\nNote: (Al-iddād refers to words that have two separate meanings that are opposite and contradictory to each other)."
    }
  ],
  "60": [
    {
      "id": 304,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Deny",
      "hw": "انکار",
      "s": "«اَبٰی» means to refuse to accept something, to reject, to not agree, to not acknowledge. (9 verses: 2:34-9:8-9:32-15:31-17:89-17:99-20:56-20:116-25:50)",
      "d": "«اَبٰی» means to not acknowledge something, to refuse firmly. (muf) Disobedience, not accepting, rejecting (m. r.), and «اَبٰی» also means to consider something detestable, i.e., disapproving of it, to be displeased with something. (manjad)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِذۡ قُلۡنَا لِلۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ اسۡجُدُوۡا لِاٰدَمَ فَسَجَدُوۡۤا اِلَّاۤ اِبۡلِیۡسَ ؕ اَبٰی وَ اسۡتَکۡبَرَ ٭۫ وَکَانَ مِنَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (2/34)\nTranslation: And when We said to the angels, 'Prostrate before Adam,' they all prostrated except Iblis. He refused and became arrogant, and he became one of the disbelievers."
    },
    {
      "id": 305,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Deny",
      "hw": "انکار",
      "s": "«اَنْکَرَ» means to deny something because one does not recognize it. (7 verses: 12:58-13:36-16:22-16:83-21:50-23:69-40:81)",
      "d": "The meaning of «نَکَرَ» is to not recognize something, to be a stranger to something or a matter (m. r.) Such a matter which a person's heart does not accept and which seems strange and astonishing. Whether one does not understand it due to ignorance. (muf) And its opposite is «عَرَفَ», meaning to recognize something.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَجَآءَ اِخۡوَۃُ یُوۡسُفَ فَدَخَلُوۡا عَلَیۡہِ فَعَرَفَہُمۡ وَہُمۡ لَہٗ مُنۡکِرُوۡنَ» (12/58)\nTranslation: And the brothers of Yusuf came and entered upon him; he recognized them, but they did not recognize him.\nAt another place, the declaration of the Lord Almighty is:\n«وَہٰذَا ذِکۡرٌ مُّبٰرَکٌ اَنۡزَلۡنٰہُ ؕ اَفَاَنۡتُمۡ لَہٗ مُنۡکِرُوۡنَ» (21/50)\nTranslation: And this is a blessed reminder which We have revealed. So do you deny it?"
    },
    {
      "id": 306,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Deny",
      "hw": "انکار",
      "s": "«جَحَدَ» means to deny something while having certainty about it in the heart. (12 verses: 6:33-7:51-11:59-16:71-27:14-29:47-29:49-31:32-40:63-41:15-41:28-46:26)",
      "d": "«جَحَدَ» means to deny something knowingly after having knowledge of it (m. r.) To deny with the tongue something which the heart truly acknowledges.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَجَحَدُوۡا بِہَا وَ اسۡتَیۡقَنَتۡہَاۤ اَنۡفُسُہُمۡ ظُلۡمًا وَّعُلُوًّا» (27/14)\nTranslation: And they denied them while their souls were convinced of them, out of injustice and arrogance."
    },
    {
      "id": 307,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Deny",
      "hw": "انکار",
      "s": "«کَفَرَ» means to deny while covering up the truth. (297 verses: 2:6-2:26-2:28-2:39-2:61-2:85-2:88-2:89-2:90-2:91-2:93-2:99-2:102-2:105-2:108-2:121-2:126-2:152-2:161-2:171-2:212-2:217-2:253-2:256-2:257-2:258-3:4-3:10-3:12-3:19-3:21-3:52-3:55-3:56-3:70-3:72-3:80-3:86-3:90-3:91-3:97-3:98-3:101-3:106-3:112-3:115-3:116-3:127-3:149-3:151-3:156-3:167-3:176-3:177-3:178-3:196-4:42-4:46-4:51-4:56-4:60-4:76-4:84-4:89-4:101-4:102-4:131-4:136-4:137-4:140-4:150-4:155-4:156-4:167-4:168-4:170-5:3-5:5-5:10-5:12-5:17-5:36-5:41-5:61-5:64-5:68-5:72-5:73-5:78-5:80-5:86-5:103-5:110-5:115-6:1-6:7-6:25-6:30-6:70-6:89-7:66-7:90-8:12-8:15-8:30-8:35-8:36-8:38-8:50-8:52-8:55-8:59-8:65-8:73-9:3-9:12-9:17-9:23-9:26-9:30-9:37-9:40-9:54-9:66-9:74-9:80-9:84-9:90-9:97-9:107-10:4-10:70-11:7-11:17-11:27-11:60-11:68-13:5-13:7-13:27-13:30-13:31-13:32-13:33-13:43-14:7-14:8-14:9-14:13-14:18-14:22-14:28-15:2-16:39-16:55-16:72-16:84-16:88-16:106-16:112-17:69-17:98-18:29-18:37-18:56-18:80-18:102-18:105-18:106-19:37-19:73-19:77-19:82-21:30-21:36-21:39-21:94-21:97-22:19-22:25-22:55-22:57-22:72-23:24-23:33-24:39-24:55-24:57-25:4-25:32-27:40-27:67-28:48-29:12-29:23-29:25-29:52-29:66-29:67-30:16-30:34-30:44-30:51-30:58-31:12-31:23-32:29-33:25-34:3-34:7-34:17-34:31-34:33-34:43-34:53-35:7-35:14-35:26-35:36-35:39-36:47-36:64-37:170-38:2-38:27-39:7-39:8-39:63-39:71-40:4-40:6-40:10-40:12-40:22-40:42-40:84-41:9-41:26-41:27-41:29-41:41-41:50-41:52-43:33-45:11-45:31-46:3-46:7-46:10-46:11-46:20-46:34-47:1-47:3-47:4-47:8-47:12-47:32-47:34-48:22-48:25-48:26-49:7-51:60-52:42-54:14-57:15-57:19-59:2-59:11-59:16-60:1-60:2-60:4-60:5-61:14-63:3-64:5-64:6-64:7-64:10-66:7-66:10-67:6-67:27-68:51-70:36-73:17-74:31-80:17-80:42-84:22-85:19-88:23-90:19-98:1-98:6)",
      "d": "«کَفَرَ» means to not recognize the truth (m. r.) and its fundamental meanings are to conceal something and to place a cover over it. A farmer (kisfār) is also called a kāfir (manjad) because he covers the seed in the earth. And this word has been used in the Quran in these meanings as well.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کَمَثَلِ غَیۡثٍ اَعۡجَبَ الۡکُفَّارَ نَبَاتُہٗ» (57/20)\nTranslation: Like the example of rain whose vegetation pleases the farmers.\nAnd the opposite of kufr is īmān (faith), and it is called kufr because it conceals īmān (m. l).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ لَہٗ صَاحِبُہٗ وَ ہُوَیُحَاوِرُہٗۤ اَکَفَرۡتَ بِالَّذِیۡ خَلَقَکَ مِنۡ تُرَابٍ» (18/37)\nTranslation: So his companion, while he was arguing with him, said: 'Do you disbelieve in He who created you from dust?' (Uthmani RA)\nAnd «کَفَرَ» also means ingratitude. In this meaning, its opposite is «شَکَرَ» (14/7)."
    }
  ],
  "61": [
    {
      "id": 308,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Fingers",
      "hw": "انگلیاں",
      "s": "«اَصَابِع» is used for the joints of the fingers. (2 verses: 2:19-71:7)",
      "d": "«اَصَابِع» is the plural of «اَصْبِع». It refers to the joint of the finger that has a nail. It is the combination of the bend and the joint. (muf)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یَجۡعَلُوۡنَ اَصَابِعَہُمۡ فِیۡۤ اٰذَانِہِمۡ» (2/19)\nTranslation: They place their fingers in their ears.\nAnd for the joints alone, the word «بَنَان» has come, whose singular is «بَنَانَۃ».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«بَلٰی قٰدِرِیۡنَ عَلٰۤی اَنۡ نُّسَوِّیَ بَنَانَہٗ» (75/4)\nTranslation: Yes, We are able to proportion his fingertips."
    },
    {
      "id": 309,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Fingers",
      "hw": "انگلیاں",
      "s": "«اَنَامِل» refers to the tips of the fingers where the nails are. (1 verse: 3:119)",
      "d": "«اَنَامِل» is the plural of «اَنْمَلَۃٌ». It refers to the upper part of the finger and its sides. (muf)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا خَلَوۡاعَضُّوۡاعَلَیۡکُمُ الۡاَنَامِلَ مِنَ الۡغَیۡظِ» (3/119)\nTranslation: And when they are alone with you, they bite their fingertips in rage."
    }
  ],
  "62": [],
  "63": [
    {
      "id": 313,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Children",
      "hw": "اولاد",
      "s": "«اَوْلَاد» means sons, daughters, grandsons, granddaughters, and so on. (22 verses: 2:233-3:10-3:116-4:11-6:137-6:140-6:151-8:28-9:55-9:69-9:85-17:31-17:64-34:35-34:37-57:20-58:17-60:3-60:12-63:9-64:14-64:15)",
      "d": "«اَوْلَاد» is the plural of «وُلِد», meaning a born child. And «اَوْلَاد» is generally applied to sons, daughters, grandsons, granddaughters, and downwards.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یُوۡصِیۡکُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡۤ اَوۡلَادِکُمۡ لِلذَّکَرِ مِثۡلُ حَظِّ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ» (4/11)\nTranslation: Allah instructs you concerning your children: for the male, the share of two females."
    },
    {
      "id": 314,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Offspring",
      "hw": "اولاد",
      "s": "«Asbāt» refers to grandsons, granddaughters, and beyond (5 verses: 2:136-2:140-3:84-4:163-7:160)",
      "d": "The meaning of «Sibṭ» is the children of children (i.e., the second generation), but this word is mostly specific to grandsons. As for «Ḥafīd» or «Ḥafdah» for grandsons (منجد) and «Asbāt» means the children of daughters, i.e., grandsons, granddaughters, and then beyond. Moreover, Asbāt is generally used for the offspring of Prophet Isaac (peace be upon him) (مف منجد). For example, in the Quran: «Am taqūlūna inna Ibrāhīma wa Ismā'īla wa Isḥāqa wa Ya'qūba wal-Asbāta kānū hūdan aw Naṣārā» ( 2/140 ). Translation: (O Jews and Christians) Do you claim that Abraham, Ishmael, Isaac, Jacob, and their descendants were Jews or Christians?"
    },
    {
      "id": 315,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Offspring",
      "hw": "اولاد",
      "s": "«Dhurriyah» includes grandsons, granddaughters, all are included, used for all (30 verses: 2:124-2:128-2:266-3:34-3:36-3:38-4:9-6:84-6:87-6:133-7:172-7:173-10:83-13:23-13:38-14:37-14:40-17:3-17:62-18:50-19:58-25:74-29:27-36:41-37:77-37:113-40:8-46:15-52:21-57:26)",
      "d": "Some lexicologists derive it from «Dhurr» meaning small ants (منجد) and «Dhurrah» is its singular, and «Dhurriyah» refers to small children (مف). For example, in the Quran: «Wa āṣābahul-kibaru wa lahu dhurriyyunḍu'a'ā» ( 2/266 ). Translation: And old age befell him, and he had young children. Then this word began to be applied to all offspring, and some derive it from «Dhara'a» meaning to produce. «Dhara'al-ard» means to sow in the earth (منجد) and according to Ibn Faris, every thing that can be sown and cultivated (م ل) and this word is general for offspring. It includes sons, daughters, grandsons, granddaughters, great-grandsons, great-granddaughters, all. (ف ل 206) For example, in the Quran: «Qāla innī jā'iluka lin-nāsi imāmā. Qāla wa min dhurriyatī. Qāla lā yanālu 'ahdīẓ-ẓālimīn» ( 2/124 ). Translation: Allah said to Abraham: I will make you a leader for people. He said: (O Lord) from my offspring too. Allah said: My covenant does not include the wrongdoers."
    },
    {
      "id": 316,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Offspring",
      "hw": "اولاد",
      "s": "«'Aqib» one can call the offspring of someone after death as 'Aqib, but not during their life (1 verse: 43:28)",
      "d": "«'Aqab» means heel, son, grandson, and «'Aqqaba» means to follow behind, and «A'qaba» means to be a successor (منجد) and «'Aqib» is applied to the offspring left behind after a person's death. For example, in the Quran: «Waja'alahā kalimatan bāqiyatan fī 'aqibih» ( 43/28 ). Translation: And he left it as a lasting word among his descendants."
    },
    {
      "id": 317,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Offspring",
      "hw": "اولاد",
      "s": "«Nasl» all the lower generations of a person are called his lineage (2 verses: 2:205-32:8)",
      "d": "«Nasala» lexically means to run swiftly or to run from height to low (منجد) For example, in the Quran: «Hattā idhā futiḥat yājūju wa mājūju wa hum min kulli ḥadabin yansilūn» ( 21/96 ). Translation: Until when Gog and Magog are opened, and they will surge from every slope. And its second meaning is something separating from a living body, and «Nusālah» refers to beard hair that falls out or birds' feathers that shed. And since offspring are also a part of parents' body that separates, therefore offspring are termed as «nasl» (مف) Ibn Faris also mentioned these two meanings (م ل). «Nasl» refers to all the generations of a particular person. Thus, this word is more general than «dhurriyah» and others. For example, in the Quran: «Wa badā khalqal-insāni min ṭīnin thumma ja'ala naslahu min sulālatim mā'in muhīn» ( 32/7،8 ). Translation: And the creation of man began from clay, then his progeny was made from an extract of disdained water."
    },
    {
      "id": 318,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Offspring",
      "hw": "اولاد",
      "s": "«Ḥafdah» is applied to sons-in-law and children, covering relatives from both sides (1 verse: 16:72)",
      "d": "«Ḥafada» means to show diligence in work (مف منجد) In the supplication of Qunut, the words «wa ilayka nas'ā wa naḥfidu» convey the same meaning. And «ḥāfid» means one who performs service with eagerness, whether stranger or relative (مف) and both «ḥāfid» and «ḥafīd» mean grandson (مف منجد) and the plural of «ḥāfid» is «ḥafdah». According to Imam Raghib, «ḥafdah» is applied to sons-in-law and children, females are not included. For example, in the Quran: «Waja'ala lakum min azwājikum banīna wa ḥafdah» ( 16/72 ). Translation: And He has made for you from your wives sons and grandsons."
    }
  ],
  "64": [
    {
      "id": 320,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Wool",
      "hw": "اُون",
      "s": "«Ṣawf» refers to the wool sheared from the body of sheep, goats, etc. (1 verse: 16:80)",
      "d": "«Ṣawf» refers to the wool sheared from the body of sheep, goats, etc. (ف ل 30) For example, in the Quran: «Wa min aṣwāfihā wa aubārihā wa ash'ārihā athāthan wa matā'an ilā ḥīn» ( 16/80 ). Translation: And from their wool, fur, and hair, you make furnishings and goods for a time."
    },
    {
      "id": 321,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Wool",
      "hw": "اُون",
      "s": "«عِھْن» refers to wool dyed in various colors (2 verses: 70:9-101:5)",
      "d": "«عِھْن» refers to wool dyed in various colors. For example, the Quran states: «یَوۡمَ تَکُوۡنُ السَّمَآءُ کَالۡمُہۡلِ وَ تَکُوۡنُ الۡجِبَالُ کَالۡعِہۡنِ» ( 70/8،9 ). Translation: 'On the Day the sky will be like molten brass, and the mountains will be like dyed wool.'"
    }
  ],
  "65": [
    {
      "id": 322,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Ibil» is a generic noun used for all types of camels, both male and female (2 verses: 6:144-88:17)",
      "d": "«Ibil» is a generic noun used for all types of camels, both male and female. Its dual and plural forms do not occur, and this word also refers to the camel's hump (مف). For example, in the Quran: «Afalā yanẓurūna ilā al-ibili kayfa khuliqat» ( 88/17 ). Translation: Do these people not look at the camels how they are created?"
    },
    {
      "id": 323,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Ba'īr» when a camel becomes four years old and capable of carrying loads, it is called «Ba'īr» (2 verses: 12:65-12:72)",
      "d": "«Ba'īr» a young and strong camel, a generic noun. When a camel becomes four years old and capable of carrying loads, it is called «Ba'īr», and this word is used for both male and female. (مف فل 27) For example, in the Quran: «Qālū nafqidu ṣuwā'al-maliki wa liman jā'a biḥi ḥimlu ba'īrin wa anā bihi za'īm» ( 12/72 ). Translation: They said: We have lost the king's cup, and for whoever brings it is the load of a camel, and I am responsible for it."
    },
    {
      "id": 324,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Jamal» a male camel over five years old. A beautiful camel. (2 verses: 7:40-77:33)",
      "d": "«Jamal» a male camel over five years old. A beautiful camel. (ف ل 27) Its plural «jimālatun» occurs. For example, in the Quran: «Innahā tarmī bishararin kal-qasri kāannahu jimālatun ṣufr» ( 77/32،33 ). Translation: Indeed, it will throw sparks as if they were yellow camels."
    },
    {
      "id": 325,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Hīm» a camel suffering from extreme thirst (1 verse: 56:55)",
      "d": "«Hām» has two meanings: (1) to wander in a state of passionate madness, and (2) to suffer from extreme thirst. Here the second meaning is under discussion, and «Hiyām» is a disease in camels where they become so thirsty that they do not quench their thirst (منجد) and «Hīm» refers to a camel that is extremely thirsty. For example, in the Quran: «Fashāribūna 'alayhi min al-ḥamīmi fashāribūna sharba al-hīmi» ( 56/54،55 ). Translation: And they will drink from the scalding water, and they will drink as the thirsty camels drink."
    },
    {
      "id": 326,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Rikāb» refers to the place where a rider places their feet while mounting. (10 verses: 11:41, 11:42, 16:8, 18:71, 29:65, 36:42, 40:79, 43:12, 59:6, 84:19)",
      "d": "The root «Rakaba» means 'to ride'. «Rikāb» is the specific place on a mount where the rider places their feet. (In our usage, 'rikāb' carries the same meaning.) Later, this word began to be used for every rider and mount. (Majid) In common parlance, the word 'rākib' is specifically used for a camel rider, and its plurals are «rukbān, rakab», and «rukūb» (Mufradāt). The term «rikāb» is also used for the hump of camels, similar to how 'khayl' is used for the collective of horses. For example, the Quran states: «فَمَاۤ اَوۡجَفۡتُمۡ عَلَیۡہِ مِنۡ خَیۡلٍ وَّ لَا رِکَابٍ» (59/6). Translation: For it, you neither drove forth any horses nor camels."
    },
    {
      "id": 327,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Ḍāmir» means a lean, thin, and swift camel, applicable to both male and female. (1 verse: 22:27)",
      "d": "«Ḍamara» means 'to have a flat belly' (i.e., lean and thin), possessing a beautiful physique. And «ḍāmir» refers to any mount (horse or camel) that is swift due to exercise and training, not due to lack of food. «Miḍmār» is the place where such animals are exercised and trained. (M. R.) Thus, «ḍāmir» means lean and long-bodied, swift horses or camels, whether male or female. Since camel riding is common among Arabs, this term is mostly applied to such camels. For example, the Quran states: «وَاَذِّنۡ فِی النَّاسِ بِالۡحَجِّ یَاۡتُوۡکَ رِجَالًا وَّعَلٰی کُلِّ ضَامِرٍ یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیۡقٍ» (22/27). Translation: And proclaim to the people the Hajj; they will come to you on foot and on every lean camel, coming from every distant path."
    },
    {
      "id": 328,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Budna» refers to a sacrificial camel that is taken to the Sacred House (Ka'bah) to be slaughtered. (1 verse: 22:36)",
      "d": "«Budna» is the plural of «badanah». It refers to those sacrificial camels that are taken to the Sacred House (Ka'bah) to be slaughtered. (M. R.) Or those taken to Makkah al-Mukarramah to be slaughtered (Majid, Mufradāt). «Badanah» is named so due to the corpulence and fatness of these two animals (camel and cow), in relation to 'body'. In common usage, it specifically refers to the sacrificial camel taken to Makkah to be slaughtered. For example, the Quran states: «وَ الۡبُدۡنَ جَعَلۡنٰہَا لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ شَعَآئِرِ اللّٰہِ» (22/36). Translation: And the sacrificial camels, We have made them for you among the symbols of Allah. And «shā'ā'irullāh» refers to those acts of reverence that are performed in the name of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 329,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Nāqah» is a she-camel that has reached the age of maturity and is capable of breeding. (7 verses: 7:73, 7:77, 11:64, 17:59, 26:155, 54:27, 91:13)",
      "d": "«Nāq» is the term for a she-camel that has reached the age of maturity (i.e., capable of breeding). (F. L. 17) For example, the Quran states: «وَیٰقَوۡمِ ہٰذِہٖ نَاقَۃُ اللّٰہِ لَکُمۡ اٰیَۃً» (11/64). Translation: And (Salih) said, 'O my people! This is the she-camel of Allah, a sign for you.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 330,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«ʿIshār» refers to pregnant she-camels that have completed ten months of gestation. (2 verses: 34:45, 81:4)",
      "d": "«ʿIshār» is the plural of «ʿashrā'». «ʿAshar» means ten. «ʿAshrā'» is the term for a she-camel that has been pregnant for ten months. (M. R.) Such a she-camel was considered very precious, as she was expected to give birth very soon. For example, the Quran states: «وَاِذَا الۡعِشَارُعُطِّلَتۡ» (81/4). Translation: And when the ten-month pregnant she-camels are abandoned. (Meaning: When such precious things are left unattended, no one will have the sense to manage them.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 331,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«بَحِیْرَۃ»، «سَائِبَۃ»، «وَصِیْلَۃ», and «حَام» were terms used in the pre-Islamic period for animals dedicated as vows or sacrifices to idols under various conditions. (1 verse: 5:103)",
      "d": "When a she-camel or she-goat gave birth to ten offspring, the Arabs would dedicate it for sacrifice to their idols, pierce its ears as a mark, set it free, and no one could milk it. And upon its death, its meat was considered lawful for men but forbidden for women."
    },
    {
      "id": 333,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«وَصِیْلۃ» (the she-camel that has consecutively given birth to female offspring and has not produced any male) (1 verse: 5:103)",
      "d": "«وَصِیْلۃ» was the term for a young she-camel that gives birth to a female offspring the first time and then again a female the second time. They would also set it free in the name of their idols, but only if she consecutively gives birth to two females without any male offspring in between."
    },
    {
      "id": 334,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«حَام» refers to a male camel from whose semen at least ten offspring have been born. (1 verse: 5:103)",
      "d": "«حَام» is the male camel from whose semen at least ten offspring have been born. And when he has produced so many offspring, they would also set him free in the name of their idols, not ride him or load him.\nNow observe the divine decree regarding such sacrifices:\n«مَا جَعَلَ اللّٰہُ مِنۡۢ بَحِیۡرَۃٍ  وَّ لَا سَآئِبَۃٍ  وَّ لَا وَصِیۡلَۃٍ وَّ لَا حَامٍ ۙ وَّ لٰکِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا یَفۡتَرُوۡنَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ الۡکَذِبَ» (5/103)\nTranslation: Allah has not appointed any such thing as bahirah, or sa'ibah, or wasilah, or ham. But those who disbelieve invent lies against Allah.\nThe disbelievers had themselves coined these names and claimed that this was the law of Abraham and that it brought them closer to Allah."
    }
  ],
  "66": [
    {
      "id": 335,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Drowsiness",
      "hw": "اُونگھ",
      "s": "«Nuʿās» refers to the initial state of drowsiness or light sleep. (2 verses: 3:154, 8:11)",
      "d": "«Naʿas» is the initial state of sleep, meaning drowsiness. (F. L. 34) When, due to sleep, the senses become sluggish and its effect becomes apparent on the eyes, it is called «nuʿās». For example, the Quran states: «اِذۡ یُغَشِّیۡکُمُ النُّعَاسَ اَمَنَۃً مِّنۡہُ» (8/11). Translation: When He (Allah) enveloped you in drowsiness as a security from Him."
    },
    {
      "id": 336,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Drowsiness",
      "hw": "اُونگھ",
      "s": "«Sinah» is a drowsiness where one feels heaviness in the head and the head begins to nod. It is an intermediate state between drowsiness and sleep. (2 verses: 2:255, 33:19)",
      "d": "«Sinah» means drowsiness. It is a drowsiness where one feels heaviness in the head and the head begins to nod. It is the next degree after drowsiness, an intermediate state between drowsiness and sleep. (F. L. 161) For example, the Quran states: «اَللّٰہُ لَاۤ اِلٰہَ اِلَّا ہُوَۚ اَلۡحَیُّ الۡقَیُّوۡمُ ۬ ۚ لَا تَاۡخُذُہٗ سِنَۃٌ وَّلَا نَوۡمٌ» (2/255). Translation: Allah, there is no deity except Him, the Ever-Living, the Sustainer of existence. Neither drowsiness nor sleep overtakes Him."
    }
  ],
  "67": [
    {
      "id": 337,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Fuel",
      "hw": "ایندھن",
      "s": "«حَطَبَ» refers to plant-based fuel, worthless wood that is only fit for burning (2 verses: 72:15-111:4)",
      "d": "«حَطَبَ» is plant-based fuel. Worthless wood, twigs, and brush that are only fit for burning.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّامۡرَاَتُہٗ ؕ حَمَّالَۃَ الۡحَطَبِ» (111/4)\nTranslation: And his (Abu Lahab's) wife also carries firewood on her back.\nAnd wood that is useful is called «خَشَب»."
    },
    {
      "id": 338,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Fuel",
      "hw": "ایندھن",
      "s": "«حَصَب» refers to mineral-based fuel. For example, sulfur, potash, and other flammable substances (5 verses: 17:68-21:98-29:40-54:34-67:17)",
      "d": "«حَصَب» means stones, pebbles, and the like; and «حَاصِبْ» refers to the fierce wind that carries pebbles and small stones (manjada). Thus, this word is used in the Quran to mean a shower of stones (67/17). And «حَصَب» also means fuel (manjada), referring to mineral-based fuel such as sulfur, potash, and other flammable substances. And stones, etc., in short, anything that intensifies fire is «حَصَب» (f l 16).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّکُمۡ وَ مَا تَعۡبُدُوۡنَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ حَصَبُ جَہَنَّمَ» (21/98)\nTranslation: On that Day, you and those you worship besides Allah will be the fuel of Hell."
    },
    {
      "id": 339,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Fuel",
      "hw": "ایندھن",
      "s": "«وَقُوْد» refers to burning fuel, regardless of its type (4 verses: 2:24-3:10-66:6-85:5)",
      "d": "«وَقَدَ» means to kindle a fire, and «وَقُوْد» is any fuel that burns by producing flames (f l 31), whether it be wood, stone, or humans. Sometimes, the intensity of fire reaches such an extent that water, instead of extinguishing it, causes it to burn more fiercely. In such a case, water also becomes part of the fuel. Any type of fuel, when burning, is called «وَقُود», not before.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاتَّقُوا النَّارَ الَّتِیۡ وَقُوۡدُہَا النَّاسُ وَ الۡحِجَارَۃُ» (2/24)\nTranslation: So fear the Fire whose fuel will be people and stones."
    }
  ],
  "69": [
    {
      "id": 340,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Father",
      "hw": "باپ",
      "s": "«وَالِدٌ» is used exclusively for father (22 verses: 2:83-2:180-2:215-2:233-4:7-4:33-4:36-4:135-5:110-6:151-14:41-17:23-19:14-19:32-27:19-29:8-31:14-31:33-46:15-46:17-71:28-90:3)",
      "d": "«وَالِدٌ» is used exclusively for father. Similarly, the word for mother is used only for a woman who has given birth.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَّا یَجۡزِیۡ وَالِدٌ عَنۡ وَّلَدِہٖ وَلَا مَوۡلُوۡدٌ ہُوَجَازٍعَنۡ وَّالِدِہٖ شَیۡئًا» (31/33)\nTranslation: Neither will a father be of any benefit to his child, nor will a child be of any benefit to his father.\nAnd for both parents, the word «والدین» is used.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَنِ اشۡکُرۡ لِیۡ وَ لِوَالِدَیۡکَ» (31/14)\nTranslation: Be grateful to Me and to your parents."
    },
    {
      "id": 341,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Father",
      "hw": "باپ",
      "s": "«اَبْ» is used broadly for father, grandfather, great-grandfather, and all paternal ancestors (104 verses: 2:133-2:170-2:200-4:11-4:22-5:104-6:74-6:87-6:91-6:148-7:27-7:28-7:70-7:71-7:95-7:173-9:23-9:24-9:114-10:78-11:62-11:87-11:109-12:4-12:6-12:8-12:9-12:11-12:16-12:17-12:38-12:40-12:59-12:61-12:63-12:65-12:68-12:78-12:80-12:81-12:93-12:94-12:97-12:99-12:100-13:23-14:10-16:35-18:5-18:80-18:82-19:28-19:42-19:43-19:44-19:45-21:44-21:52-21:53-21:54-22:78-23:24-23:68-23:83-24:31-24:61-25:18-26:26-26:70-26:74-26:76-26:86-27:67-27:68-28:23-28:25-28:26-28:36-31:21-33:5-33:40-33:55-34:43-36:6-37:17-37:69-37:85-37:102-37:126-40:8-43:22-43:23-43:24-43:26-43:29-44:8-44:36-45:25-53:23-56:48-58:22-60:4-80:35-111:1)",
      "d": "«اَبْ» is used in a very broad sense. This word is used for father, grandfather, great-grandfather, and all paternal ancestors. And for both parents, «اَبْوَیْن» or «اَبْوَان» is used contextually.\nNow, consider these examples:\n(1) Used only for parents:\n(Allah says)\n«وَ اَمَّا الۡغُلٰمُ فَکَانَ اَبَوٰہُ  مُؤۡمِنَیۡنِ» (18/80)\nTranslation: As for the boy, his parents were believers.\n(2) Used for several generations:\n(Allah says)\n«مَّا سَمِعۡنَا بِہٰذَا فِیۡۤ  اٰبَآئِنَا  الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (23/24)\nTranslation: We have not heard of this from our forefathers of old.\nAnd these ancestors can be many generations.\nAs in (Allah says):\n«مِلَّۃَ اَبِیۡکُمۡ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ ؕ ہُوَ سَمّٰىکُمُ الۡمُسۡلِمِیۡنَ» (22/78)\nTranslation: (And for you) the religion of your father Abraham is (approved). He named you Muslims.\nNote that between the Prophet ﷺ and Abraham, there were about 62 generations. Even for Adam, the ultimate ancestor of humanity, the word «اَب» is used.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یٰبَنِیۡۤ اٰدَمَ لَا یَفۡتِنَنَّکُمُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ کَمَاۤ اَخۡرَجَ اَبَوَیۡکُمۡ مِّنَ الۡجَنَّۃِ» (7/27)\nTranslation: O children of Adam! Do not let Satan deceive you as he expelled your parents from Paradise.\n«اَب» originally is «اَبَوَ», which implies providing nourishment and upbringing (m l). Therefore, when a son addresses his father, he usually uses «اَبّ», as when Prophet Yusuf said to his father:\n(Allah says)\n«یٰۤاَبَتِ ہٰذَا تَاۡوِیۡلُ رُءۡیَایَ مِنۡ قَبۡلُ» (12/100)\nTranslation: My dear father! This is the interpretation of my dream from before.\nThen, the word «اَب» is sometimes used due to a particular attribute, such as calling a host «اَبُوالْاضِیَاف» and a warrior «اَبُوالْحَرَب». In the Quran, «ابولھب» is used due to this attribute because his complexion was radiant like a flame. Similarly, kuniyas (nicknames) are given due to relation and affection, such as Abu Hurairah and Abu Turab, etc."
    }
  ],
  "70": [
    {
      "id": 343,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be blessed",
      "hw": "بابرکت",
      "s": "«اَیْمَن» refers to goodness and blessings that are naturally present. Blessings (5 verses: 19:52-20:80-28:30-56:8-90:18)",
      "d": "«یَمِیْن» means right hand or right side, and «اَصْحٰبُ الْیَمِیْن» means both those on the right hand/side and companions of goodness and blessings (muf). And «یَمَنَ یَیْمَنُ» means to be blessed, to be fortunate. «تَیَمُّن» means to seek blessings, to take a good omen. And «مَیْمُون» means blessed (manjada). According to Imam Raghib, «مَیْمُون» means fortunate (muf). Thus, just as happiness is innate, «اَیْمَن» is something in whose nature blessings are innate.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ اَتٰىہَا نُوۡدِیَ مِنۡ شَاطِیَٔ الۡوَادِ الۡاَیۡمَنِ» (28/30)\nTranslation: Then when he (Musa) came to it, he was called from the right side of the valley, in a blessed spot."
    }
  ],
  "71": [
    {
      "id": 345,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speech",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "«قَوْل» refers to any speech, whether meaningless or meaningful, whether in the heart or ideological (327 verses: 2:8-2:26-2:58-2:59-2:68-2:69-2:71-2:79-2:80-2:83-2:102-2:104-2:113-2:117-2:118-2:136-2:140-2:142-2:154-2:169-2:200-2:201-2:204-2:214-2:235-2:263-3:7-3:16-3:47-3:64-3:75-3:78-3:79-3:124-3:147-3:154-3:167-3:181-4:5-4:8-4:9-4:43-4:46-4:51-4:63-4:73-4:75-4:78-4:81-4:94-4:108-4:148-4:150-4:155-4:156-4:157-4:171-5:19-5:41-5:52-5:53-5:63-5:73-5:83-5:109-5:116-6:22-6:25-6:33-6:50-6:53-6:73-6:93-6:105-6:112-6:148-6:156-6:157-7:28-7:33-7:53-7:105-7:161-7:162-7:169-7:172-7:173-7:205-8:49-9:30-9:40-9:49-9:50-9:61-9:65-9:124-10:18-10:20-10:28-10:31-10:38-10:48-10:65-10:68-10:77-11:7-11:8-11:10-11:12-11:13-11:18-11:31-11:35-11:40-11:53-11:54-11:91-12:66-12:81-13:5-13:7-13:10-13:27-13:33-13:43-14:27-14:44-15:97-16:27-16:32-16:40-16:86-16:103-16:116-17:16-17:23-17:28-17:40-17:42-17:43-17:47-17:51-17:53-17:108-18:5-18:22-18:23-18:42-18:49-18:52-18:88-18:93-19:26-19:34-19:35-19:66-19:79-19:80-20:7-20:28-20:40-20:44-20:47-20:89-20:94-20:97-20:104-20:109-20:130-21:4-21:27-21:38-21:46-21:110-22:24-22:30-22:40-23:27-23:68-23:70-23:85-23:87-23:89-23:109-24:15-24:26-24:47-24:51-25:17-25:19-25:22-25:27-25:65-25:74-26:16-26:203-26:226-27:19-27:49-27:71-27:82-27:85-28:28-28:47-28:51-28:62-28:63-28:65-28:74-28:82-29:2-29:10-29:46-29:55-29:61-29:63-30:58-31:25-32:3-32:13-32:28-33:4-33:12-33:13-33:32-33:37-33:66-33:70-34:29-34:31-34:40-34:42-36:7-36:48-36:58-36:70-36:76-36:82-37:31-37:36-37:52-37:151-37:167-38:17-38:84-39:18-39:38-39:56-39:57-39:58-40:28-40:44-40:47-40:68-41:25-41:33-41:50-42:24-42:44-43:9-43:13-43:87-44:34-46:8-46:11-46:17-46:18-47:20-47:21-47:30-48:11-48:15-49:2-49:14-50:18-50:29-50:30-52:33-50:39-50:45-51:8-52:30-52:33-52:44-54:2-54:8-54:44-56:47-57:13-58:1-58:2-58:8-59:10-59:11-60:4-61:2-61:3-63:4-63:7-63:8-63:10-66:8-67:13-67:25-68:51-69:19-69:25-69:40-69:41-69:42-69:44-72:4-72:5-73:5-73:10-74:25-74:31-75:10-78:40-79:10-81:19-81:25-86:13-89:15-89:16-89:24-90:6)",
      "d": "The plural of «قَوْل» is «اَقْوَال» and the collective plural is «اَلْجَمْعُ اَقَاوِیْل». Generally, it is understood that any speech uttered by the tongue is a saying, whether meaningless or meaningful. However, in the Quran, this word is used in three contexts: (1) for speech that is uttered, (2) for speech that is not uttered but remains in the heart, and (3) for a doctrine or ideology.\nExamples:\n(1) For uttered speech, Allah says:\n«قَالَ قَآئِلٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ کَمۡ لَبِثۡتُمۡ» (18/19)\nTranslation: One of them said, 'How long have you stayed?'\n(2) For speech in the heart, Allah says:\n«وَیَقُوۡلُوۡنَ فِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ لَوۡلَا یُعَذِّبُنَا اللّٰہُ» (58/8)\nTranslation: And they say within themselves, 'If this were true, Allah would not punish us.'\n(3) For a doctrine, Allah says:\n«ذٰلِکَ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ ۚ قَوۡلَ الۡحَقِّ الَّذِیۡ  فِیۡہِ  یَمۡتَرُوۡنَ» (19/34)\nTranslation: That is Jesus, son of Mary - a statement of truth about which they are in doubt."
    },
    {
      "id": 346,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speech",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "«حَدِیْث» refers to new speech, something that common people are unfamiliar with (28 verses: 4:42-4:78-4:87-4:140-6:68-7:185-12:6-12:21-12:101-12:111-18:6-20:9-23:44-31:6-33:53-34:19-39:23-45:6-51:24-52:34-53:59-56:81-66:3-68:44-77:50-79:15-85:17-88:1)",
      "d": "«حَدَثَ» means for something to appear, for an event to occur, for a new thing or speech to come into existence (manjada). Its opposite is «عَدَمَ». In Ibn Faris's words, it is the coming into existence of something that did not exist before (m l). And «حَدِیْث» refers to new speech or a doctrine that relates to common people and with which most people were previously unfamiliar.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَا تَدۡرِیۡ لَعَلَّ اللّٰہَ یُحۡدِثُ بَعۡدَ ذٰلِکَ اَمۡرًا» (65/1)\nTranslation: You do not know; perhaps Allah will bring about after that a new situation.\nAlso, Allah says:\n«اَللّٰہُ نَزَّلَ اَحۡسَنَ الۡحَدِیۡثِ» (39/23)\nTranslation: Allah has sent down the best of statements.\nHere, «حَدِیْث» refers to the Quran, and evidently, according to the views and ideas of the people of that time, this was something new. Then, the word «حَدِیْث» is also used for an old saying or event that has generally faded from people's minds. In such a case, its meaning would be a forgotten story or tale.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَا جَآءَ اُمَّۃً  رَّسُوۡلُہَا کَذَّبُوۡہُ  فَاَتۡبَعۡنَا بَعۡضَہُمۡ بَعۡضًا وَّ جَعَلۡنٰہُمۡ اَحَادِیۡثَ» (23/44)\nTranslation: Whenever a messenger came to a nation, they denied him. So We made some of them follow others, and We made them into tales."
    },
    {
      "id": 347,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Word",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "«کَلِمَۃُ» refers only to meaningful speech, God's commands, and wonders of creation, etc. (47 verses: 2:37-2:75-2:124-3:39-3:45-3:64-4:46-4:171-5:13-5:41-6:34-6:115-7:137-7:144-7:158-8:7-9:6-9:40-9:74-10:19-10:33-10:64-10:82-10:96-11:110-11:119-14:24-14:26-18:5-18:27-18:109-20:129-23:100-31:27-35:10-37:171-39:19-39:71-40:6-41:45-42:14-42:21-42:24-43:28-48:15-48:26-66:12)",
      "d": "«کَلِمَۃُ» linguistically means 'meaningful speech' that can be heard and understood (muf). For example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّہَا کَلِمَۃٌ ہُوَ قَآئِلُہَا» (23/100)\nTranslation: It will be a single statement, and he who says it.\nBut when the word «کَلِمَۃ» is attributed to Allah, it refers to the wonders of His power, the laws of nature, and His creative works (Tafhim al-Quran). For example, the Quran states:\n«قُلۡ لَّوۡ کَانَ الۡبَحۡرُ مِدَادًا لِّکَلِمٰتِ رَبِّیۡ لَنَفِدَ الۡبَحۡرُقَبۡلَ اَنۡ تَنۡفَدَ کَلِمٰتُ رَبِّیۡ وَ لَوۡجِئۡنَا بِمِثۡلِہٖ مَدَدًا» (18/109)\nTranslation: Say, 'If the sea were ink for [writing] the words of my Lord, the sea would be exhausted before the words of my Lord were exhausted, even if We brought the like of it in addition.'\nAnd when the word is attributed from Allah to humans, it refers to His commands and decrees:\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَفَمَنۡ حَقَّ عَلَیۡہِ کَلِمَۃُ الۡعَذَابِ ؕ اَفَاَنۡتَ تُنۡقِذُ مَنۡ فِی النَّارِ» (39/19)\nTranslation: Then, is he who has deserved the decree of punishment [any better]? So can you save one who is in the Fire?"
    },
    {
      "id": 348,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To speak",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "«کَلَّمَ» is a general term for conversation, usually used for brief and immediate dialogue (24 verses: 2:118-2:174-2:253-3:41-3:46-3:77-4:164-5:110-6:111-7:143-7:148-11:105-12:54-13:31-19:10-19:26-19:29-23:108-24:16-27:82-30:35-36:65-42:51-78:38)",
      "d": "«کَلَّمَ» means to converse, to talk (manjada). It is generally used for brief conversations or for matters where a response can be given immediately upon hearing. Moreover, «کَلَّمَ» does not necessarily imply two-way conversation; it can sometimes be one-way.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَا یُکَلِّمُہُمُ اللّٰہُ وَلَا یَنۡظُرُ اِلَیۡہِمۡ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (3/77)\nTranslation: And Allah will not speak to them or look at them on the Day of Resurrection."
    },
    {
      "id": 349,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speech",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "«ḥāwara» is a conversation in the style of question and answer that is conducted with thought and understanding and is lengthy (3 verses: 18:34-18:37-58:1)",
      "d": "Ibn Faris says that in «ḥawran», there are basically two things: (1) to refer to speech and (2) to turn a thing to one side and then to the other side (m l). And the author of Munajid writes the meanings of «ḥāra» as to return and also to be perplexed (astonished). Thus, «ḥāwara» means such conversation that is in the form of question and answer. And the listener has to give the answer after thinking and understanding. Such conversation is generally lengthy. From this, the word 'muhawarah' (proverb) is derived. Which means that the speech is said after thinking and understanding and is also common, famous, and comprehensible.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«قَالَ لَہٗ صَاحِبُہٗ وَ ہُوَ یُحَاوِرُہٗۤ اَکَفَرۡتَ بِالَّذِیۡ خَلَقَکَ مِنۡ تُرَابٍ ثُمَّ مِنۡ نُّطۡفَۃٍ ثُمَّ سَوّٰىکَ رَجُلًا» (18/37)\nTranslation: So his companion, who was conversing with him, will say: Do you disbelieve in Him who created you from dust, then from a sperm-drop, then proportioned you as a man?"
    },
    {
      "id": 350,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speech",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "«khāṭaba» is generally a one-sided speech. Or one gives a reply if the addressee prefers or deems it necessary (3 verses: 11:37-23:27-25:63)",
      "d": "«khāṭaba» also comes in the meanings of speaking (Munajid). And 'khatbah' means sermon, exhortation, and speech, which is generally one-sided. The khatib (speaker) means one who delivers a sermon, speaks with clarification (m q). And sometimes it happens that the listener gives a brief reply and silences the one addressing.\nThus, in the Quran, Allah Almighty says to Prophet Noah (peace be upon him):\n«وَاصۡنَعِ الۡفُلۡکَ بِاَعۡیُنِنَا وَ وَحۡیِنَا وَ لَا تُخَاطِبۡنِیۡ فِی الَّذِیۡنَ ظَلَمُوۡا» (11/37)\nTranslation: And construct the ship under Our observation and Our inspiration, and do not address Me concerning those who have wronged.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty, describing the attributes of His servants, says:\n«وَّاِذَا خَاطَبَہُمُ الۡجٰہِلُوۡنَ  قَالُوۡا سَلٰمًا» (25/63)\nTranslation: And when the ignorant address them, they say [words of] peace."
    }
  ],
  "72": [
    {
      "id": 351,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Sovereignty",
      "hw": "بادشاہی",
      "s": "«sulṭān» when the expression of authority and grandeur is intended, then «sulṭān» is used, and when the expression of the vastness of territory is intended, then the word «mulk» is used (39 verses: 3:151-4:90-4:91-4:144-4:153-6:81-7:33-7:71-10:68-11:96-12:40-14:10-14:11-14:22-15:42-16:99-16:100-17:33-17:65-17:80-18:15-22:71-23:45-27:21-28:35-30:35-34:21-37:30-37:156-40:23-40:35-40:56-44:19-51:38-52:38-53:23-55:33-59:6-69:29)",
      "d": "The word «sulṭān» comes in three meanings:\n(1) Meaning evidence that has the status of a document or certificate. Authority. In these meanings, this word appears frequently in the Quran.\n(2) Kingdom or sovereignty. In this meaning, it appears only once in the Quran.\n(3) Meaning king (plural: sultans). In these meanings, this word does not appear in the Quran, and the meaning of sultan as king is not from the literal language but is a derived meaning.\nWhen this word comes in the meanings of kingdom or sovereignty, it refers to the territory that is under the control of a person, institution, or king, and over which he has dominion.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said that the disbeliever will say on the Day of Judgment:\n«مَاۤ اَغۡنٰی عَنِّیۡ مَالِیَہۡ ہَلَکَ عَنِّیۡ سُلۡطٰنِیَہۡ» (69/28,29)\nTranslation: My wealth has availed me not; gone is my sovereignty."
    }
  ],
  "73": [
    {
      "id": 354,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Cloud",
      "hw": "بادل",
      "s": "«ghammām» when the cloud becomes thick and provides shade, then it is called ghamām (4 verses: 2:57-2:210-7:160-25:25)",
      "d": "«ghamm» means to cover (Munajid). And «ghammām» is that cloud which becomes thick layer upon layer and prevents the sunlight from reaching the earth. (f l 254) i.e., it becomes shade-casting on the earth.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«وَ ظَلَّلۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡغَمَامَ وَ اَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡمَنَّ وَ السَّلۡوٰی» (2/57)\nTranslation: And We shaded you with the cloud and sent down upon you manna and salwa."
    },
    {
      "id": 355,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Cloud",
      "hw": "بادل",
      "s": "«ʿāriḍ» is a cloud in which the beginning of rainfall has already started (1 verse: 46:24)",
      "d": "Then when from the thick and spread-out cloud, rainfall also begins, then it is called «ʿāriḍ» (f l 254)\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«قَالُوۡا ہٰذَا عَارِضٌ مُّمۡطِرُنَا ؕ بَلۡ ہُوَمَا اسۡتَعۡجَلۡتُمۡ بِہٖ ؕ رِیۡحٌ  فِیۡہَا عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ» (46/24)\nTranslation: They said, 'This is a cloud that will rain upon us.' Rather, it is that for which you were impatient: a wind within it a painful punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 356,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Cloud",
      "hw": "بادل",
      "s": "«muʿṣirāt» clouds full of water (1 verse: 78:14)",
      "d": "«ʿaṣara» means to wring clothes and (to extract juice from fruits, etc.). Also, the extracted juice is called 'ʿaṣr' (m l). And «aʿṣara al-qawm» means to send rain upon the people (Munajid). And «muʿṣirāt» is the plural of «muʿṣirah», i.e., such clouds that are laden with water and are about to rain, dripping clouds.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«وَّاَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ الۡمُعۡصِرٰتِ مَآءً  ثَجَّاجًا» (78/14)\nTranslation: And We sent down from the rain-bearing clouds water in abundance."
    },
    {
      "id": 357,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Cloud",
      "hw": "بادل",
      "s": "«muzn» white shining clouds (1 verse: 56:69)",
      "d": "«mazana» means to fill a skin (i.e., a water container) with water, etc. And «ibn al-muznah» refers to the moon that appears from among the clouds (muf). And «mazan» refers to white and shining clouds (muf. f l 255). And «ḥabb al-muzn» refers to hail (Munajid). And «muzn» refers to rain-bearing clouds (Munajid).\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَنۡزَلۡتُمُوۡہُ مِنَ الۡمُزۡنِ اَمۡ نَحۡنُ الۡمُنۡزِلُوۡنَ» (56/69)\nTranslation: Is it you who brought it down from the clouds, or are We the bringers?"
    },
    {
      "id": 358,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Cloud",
      "hw": "بادل",
      "s": "«ṣayyib» is said for a cloud with intense thunder (1 verse: 2:19)",
      "d": "«ṣayyib» is a cloud with intense thunder (f l 255). Whereas the author of al-Muntahi al-Arb takes it to mean a heavy rain (m. l). According to Munajid, any rain-bearing cloud is «ṣayyib».\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«اَوۡ کَصَیِّبٍ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فِیۡہِ ظُلُمٰتٌ وَّ رَعۡدٌ وَّ بَرۡقٌ» (2/19)\nTranslation: Or [it is] like a rainstorm from the sky within which is darkness, thunder, and lightning."
    }
  ],
  "74": [
    {
      "id": 359,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Time, Occasion, Instance",
      "hw": "بار ",
      "s": "«marrah» is a general word for time, occasion, or instance (13 verses: 6:94-6:110-8:56-9:13-9:80-9:83-9:126-17:7-17:51-18:48-20:37-36:79-41:21)",
      "d": "«marra» means to pass by a place (muf) and also to pass in time. And in this sense, it means to pass once or to do something once. Its dual is «marratan» or «marratayn», and plural is «marat» and «mararan» (meaning many times).\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«اَوَلَا یَرَوۡنَ اَنَّہُمۡ یُفۡتَنُوۡنَ فِیۡ کُلِّ عَامٍ مَّرَّۃً اَوۡ مَرَّتَیۡنِ» (9/126)\nTranslation: Do they not see that they are tried every year once or twice?"
    },
    {
      "id": 361,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Time, Occasion, Instance",
      "hw": "بار ",
      "s": "«tārah» meaning sometimes at some time, again doing that work which has been done before (2 verses: 17:69-20:55)",
      "d": "«tārah» some have included it under «tawr» and some under «tār». And its meaning is «iʿādatan baʿda marrah» (m. q) and meaning time and once (m. r). i.e., sometimes at some time, again doing that work «faʿaltu tārah hādhā aw tārah dhāk» meaning I have done this work sometimes and that sometimes (Munajid). Thus, «tārah» is a repetition of an action that was done at some time in the past.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«مِنۡہَا خَلَقۡنٰکُمۡ وَ فِیۡہَا نُعِیۡدُکُمۡ وَمِنۡہَا نُخۡرِجُکُمۡ تَارَۃً اُخۡرٰی» (20/55)\nTranslation: From it We created you, and into it We will return you, and from it We will bring you out a second time."
    }
  ],
  "75": [
    {
      "id": 362,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "«مَطَر» is used for all types of rain. It is a generic term (9 verses: 4:102--7:84-8:32-11:82-15:74-25:40-26:173-27:58-46:24)",
      "d": "«مَطَر» is a general term for rain. Whether the rain is beneficial or harmful, whether water or something else falls, the word «مَطَر» can be used for all, and «اَمْطَرَ» means to send rain.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَاَمۡطَرۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ مَّطَرًا ۚ فَسَآءَ مَطَرُالۡمُنۡذَرِیۡنَ» (26/173)\nTranslation: And We sent upon them a severe rain. So evil was the rain of those who were warned."
    },
    {
      "id": 363,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "«مَآءَ» literally means water, but is used metaphorically for rain (34 verses: 2:22-2:164-4:43-5:6-6:99-8:11-13:17-14:16-14:32-15:22-16:10-16:65-20:53-22:63-23:18-24:39-24:45-25:48-27:60-28:23-29:63-30:24-31:10-32:8-35:27-39:21-43:11-47:15-50:9-72:16-77:20-77:27-78:14-86:6)",
      "d": "«مَآءَ» literally means water; «مِیَاہ» is used metaphorically for rain.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَّاَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً فَاَخۡرَجَ بِہٖ مِنَ الثَّمَرٰتِ رِزۡقًا لَّکُمۡ» (2/22)\nTranslation: And We sent down from the sky water, then We brought forth thereby fruits as provision for you."
    },
    {
      "id": 364,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "«طَلّ» means dew or light rain (1 verse: 2:265)",
      "d": "«طَلّ» means a very light and weak rain (F L 256. M L). The word «طَلّ» is used for both dew and light rain (F. M).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَاِنۡ لَّمۡ یُصِبۡہَا وَابِلٌ فَطَلٌّ» (2/265)\nTranslation: Then if no heavy rain befalls it, then a light rain is sufficient."
    },
    {
      "id": 365,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "«وَدْق» means continuous and gentle rain (2 verses: 24:43, 30:48)",
      "d": "«وَدْق» is the term for rain that continues continuously (F L 258). Such rain generally is slow and lasts for a long time.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«ثُمَّ یَجۡعَلُہٗ رُکَامًا فَتَرَی الۡوَدۡقَ یَخۡرُجُ مِنۡ خِلٰلِہٖ» (24/43)\nTranslation: Then He makes them layers, and you see the rain coming forth from between them."
    },
    {
      "id": 366,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "«غَیْث» is rain that occurs at the time of need and according to the need (3 verses: 31:34, 42:28, 57:20)",
      "d": "«غَیْث» is the rain that comes at the time of need and according to the need (F L 258. M L).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«کَمَثَلِ غَیۡثٍ اَعۡجَبَ الۡکُفَّارَ نَبَاتُہٗ» (57/20)\nTranslation: Like the rain whose growth delights the disbelievers."
    },
    {
      "id": 368,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "«غَدَق» is rain that is abundant in water and also beneficial, i.e., causes vegetation to grow (1 verse: 72:16)",
      "d": "According to Ibn al-Faris, «غَدَق» is rain that has abundance of water and is also beneficial (M L). And «غَدَقَۃٌ» means a flowing spring, and «غَدَقَ الْمَکَان» means a place becoming wet from rain, becoming green. And «غَدِق» means a green place (Munjid). Thus, «غَدَق» is the term for rain that causes vegetation.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَّاَنۡ لَّوِ اسۡتَقَامُوۡاعَلَی الطَّرِیۡقَۃِ لَاَسۡقَیۡنٰہُمۡ مَّآءً غَدَقًا» (72/16)\nTranslation: And if they had remained steadfast on the path, We would have given them abundant water to drink."
    },
    {
      "id": 369,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "«صَیِّب» is a forceful rain with large droplets (1 verse: 2:19)",
      "d": "«صَیِّب» refers to such a forceful rain in which there are loud thundering clouds and flashing lightning (F L 255. M R). And according to Ibn al-Faris, it is rain that pours down heavily (M L). Such rain is called 'phanda' in Punjabi.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اَوۡ کَصَیِّبٍ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فِیۡہِ ظُلُمٰتٌ وَّ رَعۡدٌ وَّ بَرۡقٌ» (2/19)\nTranslation: Or [it is] like a rain from the sky within which are darknesses, thunder, and lightning."
    },
    {
      "id": 370,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "«وَابِل» is such a severe rain that carries away straw and chaff (i.e., grass, twigs, rubbish) (2 verses: 2:264, 2:265)",
      "d": "«وَبَل» means to beat continuously with a stick (Munjid). In its meaning, intensity and weight are found. Ibn Faris says that «وَبَل» gives the meaning of intensity and abundance in something, and «وَابِل» means a severe type of rain (M L). Thus, «وَابِل» is the rain that, due to the abundance of water and its intensity and speed, carries away straw and chaff (i.e., grass, twigs, rubbish), and this is the highest degree of rain.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَمَثَلُہٗ کَمَثَلِ صَفۡوَانٍ عَلَیۡہِ تُرَابٌ فَاَصَابَہٗ وَابِلٌ فَتَرَکَہٗ صَلۃً» (2/264)\nTranslation: Its example is like a rock on which a little dust is lying, and a heavy rain falls on it and cleans it."
    }
  ],
  "76": [
    {
      "id": 372,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to return",
      "hw": "باز",
      "s": "«اِنَّفَکَ» means to free someone from a bond or to forcibly stop someone from doing something (1 verse: 98:1)",
      "d": "«فَکّ» means to free someone from a bond. «فَکُ الْاَسِیْر» means to free a prisoner. And «اِنْفِکَاک» means to separate oneself, to become free. «اِنْفِکَاکُ الْعَبْد» means the slave becoming free. Also, «اِنْفَکَّ الْعَظْمُ» means the shoulder moving from its place due to weakness (Munjid. Muf). This means that in «اِنْفِکَاک», to remain back is involuntary (i.e., forced), meaning to separate from the place where one was stuck (by force).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«لَمۡ یَکُنِ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ وَالۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ مُنۡفَکِّیۡنَ حَتّٰی تَاۡتِیَہُمُ الۡبَیِّنَۃُ» (98/1)\nTranslation: Those who disbelieved from among the People of the Book and the polytheists were not ones to desist until the clear proof came to them.\nAnd this clear proof was the Prophethood and the dominance of Islam, which forced them to desist from disbelief and polytheism."
    }
  ],
  "77": [
    {
      "id": 373,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "arm",
      "hw": "بازو",
      "s": "«جَنَاح» refers to the part from the shoulder to the fingertips (6 verses: 6:38, 15:88, 17:24, 20:22, 26:215, 28:32)",
      "d": "«جَنَاح» means the wing of a bird or the arm. The dual form «جَنَاحَیْن» then, metaphorically, the two sides of something are also called «جَنَاحَیْن». «جَنَاحَا الْعَسْکَر» means the two wings or sides of the army. Similarly, this word is used for both arms of a human as well, so «جَنَاحَ» is used for right or left side, or flank, or arm everywhere. And by arm is meant the part from the shoulder to the fingertips.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَّ اضۡمُمۡ اِلَیۡکَ جَنَاحَکَ مِنَ الرَّہۡبِ» (28/32)\nTranslation: And for protection from fear, draw your arm close to yourself."
    },
    {
      "id": 374,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Arm",
      "hw": "بازو",
      "s": "«عَضُدُ» refers to the part between the shoulder and elbow (2 verses: 18:51-28:35)",
      "d": "«عَضُدُ» means the part from the elbow to the shoulder (detailed). And «عَضدْتُہٗ» means 'I struck it on the forearm.' Also, it can mean 'I grasped its forearm and supported it.' Therefore, this word, like «یَدْ», is used metaphorically to mean 'helper' or 'supporter' (detailed). For example, in the Quran: «وَ مَا کُنۡتُ مُتَّخِذَ الۡمُضِلِّیۡنَ عَضُدًا» (18/51) Translation: 'And I was not one to take the misguidance ones as helpers.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 375,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Arm",
      "hw": "بازو",
      "s": "«ذِرَاع» refers to the part from the elbow to the tip of the middle finger (2 verses: 18:51-28:35)",
      "d": "«ذِرَاع» means the part from the elbow to the tip of the middle finger, and its translation is generally 'hand.' (detailed) For example, in the Quran: «وَكَلْبُهُمْ بَاسِطٌ ذِرَاعَيْهِ بِالْوَصِیدِ» (18/18) Translation: 'And their dog was stretching out its forepaws at the threshold.' Then, «ذِرَاع» in measurement refers to the length from the elbow to the tip of the middle finger. This length is called a 'hand.' Since a person's height varies in different eras, this measurement has also varied. Manjad states it is 50 to 70 centimeters, i.e., approximately 20 to 28 inches. Some translators have also translated it as 'cubit' as well. For example, in the Quran: «ثُمَّ فِي سِلْسِلَةٍ ذَرْعُهَا سَبْعُونَ ذِرَاعًا فَاسْلُكُوهُ» (69/32) Translation: 'Then in a chain whose length is seventy forearms, put him in.'"
    }
  ],
  "78": [
    {
      "id": 376,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Garden",
      "hw": "باغ",
      "s": "«جَنَّۃ» refers to a garden whose ground is not visible due to trees and grass (143 verses: 2:25-2:35-2:82-2:111-2:214-2:221-2:265-2:266-3:15-3:133-3:136-3:142-3:185-3:195-3:198-4:13-4:57-4:122-4:124-5:12-5:65-5:72-5:85-5:119-6:99-6:141-7:19-7:22-7:27-7:40-7:42-7:43-7:44-7:46-7:49-7:50-9:21-9:72-9:89-9:100-9:111-10:9-10:26-11:23-11:108-13:4-13:23-13:35-14:23-15:45-16:31-16:32-17:91-18:31-18:32-18:33-18:35-18:39-18:40-18:107-19:60-19:61-19:63-20:76-20:117-20:121-22:14-22:23-22:56-23:19-25:8-25:10-25:15-25:24-26:57-26:85-26:90-26:134-26:147-29:58-31:8-32:19-34:15-34:16-35:33-36:26-36:34-36:55-37:43-38:50-39:73-39:74-40:8-40:40-41:30-42:7-42:22-43:70-43:72-44:25-44:52-46:14-46:16-47:6-47:12-47:15-48:5-48:17-50:9-50:31-51:15-52:17-53:15-54:54-55:46-55:54-55:62-56:12-56:89-57:12-57:21-58:22-59:20-61:12-64:9-65:11-66:8-66:11-68:17-68:34-69:22-70:35-70:38-71:12-74:40-76:12-78:16-79:41-81:13-85:11-88:10-89:30-98:8)",
      "d": "«جَنَّۃ» comes from «جَنَّ» meaning to conceal and hide something, and «جَنّۃٌ» is a garden whose ground is not visible due to trees and grass (detailed). According to Manjad, «جَنَّۃٌ» is a lush garden with trees, whether earthly or heavenly. For example, in the Quran: «کَمَثَلِ جَنَّۃٍۭ بِرَبۡوَۃٍ اَصَابَہَا وَابِلٌ فَاٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا ضِعۡفَیۡنِ» (2/265) Translation: 'Like a garden on a height; heavy rain fell on it and it yielded double its produce.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 377,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Garden",
      "hw": "باغ",
      "s": "«حَدَآئِق» refers to such gardens or orchards that have a four-walled enclosure built around them for protection (3 verses: 27:60-78:32-80:30)",
      "d": "«حَدَآئِق» is the plural of «حَدِیْقَۃ», and «حَدِیْقَۃ» comes from «حَدَقَ» meaning to surround something on all sides. Therefore, «حَدِیْقَۃ» is a garden or orchard that has a four-walled enclosure built around it for protection (Manjad). For example, in the Quran: «فَاَنۡۢبَتۡنَا بِہٖ حَدَآئِقَ ذَاتَ بَہۡجَۃٍ» (27/60) Translation: 'Then We grew thereby gardens of delightful beauty.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 378,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Garden",
      "hw": "باغ",
      "s": "«رَوْضَۃ» refers to that part or place within a garden which is very lush and spring-like. And usually, pavilions or similar structures are built in such places (2 verses: 30:15-42:22)",
      "d": "«رَوْضَۃ» has the plural «رَوْضَات», and the word «رَوْض» implies vastness and spaciousness (m. l). And «رَوَّضَ الْمَطْرُالْاَرْضَ» means the rain makes the earth into a garden. And «رَوْضَۃ» also means a lush plot of land (Manjad). So, «رَوْضَہ» is that part or place within a garden which is very lush, and usually, pavilions or similar structures are built there. For example, in the Quran: «فَاَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ فَہُمۡ فِیۡ رَوۡضَۃٍ یُّحۡبَرُوۡنَ» (30/15) Translation: 'Then those who believed and did righteous deeds, they will be in a garden, receiving honor.'"
    }
  ],
  "79": [
    {
      "id": 379,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Keep/Leave",
      "hw": "باقی",
      "s": "«اَبْقٰی» means to keep something's existence established and enduring (14 verses: 2:248-2:278-11:86-11:116-20:71-20:73-20:127-20:131-28:60-42:36-53:51-55:27-74:28-87:17)",
      "d": "«بَقٰی» means something's remaining forever (m. l), and its opposites are «فَنٰی» and «ھَلَکَ», meaning something's non-existence and destruction. And «اَبْقٰی» means to keep something established and enduring. For example, in the Quran: «وَاَنَّہٗۤ اَہۡلَکَ عَادَۨا الۡاُوۡلٰیوَاَنَّہٗۤ اَہۡلَکَ عَادَۨا الۡاُوۡلٰی وَثَمُوۡدَا۠ فَمَاۤ اَبۡقٰی» (53/50,51) Translation: 'And that He destroyed the former ʿĀd and that He destroyed the former ʿĀd and Thamūd, so He left none.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 380,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Keep/Leave",
      "hw": "باقی",
      "s": "«اَثْبَتَ» means to keep something in its state, enduring and established (12 verses: 2:250-3:147-8:11-8:12-8:45-11:120-13:39-14:27-16:102-17:74-25:32-47:7)",
      "d": "«ثَبَتَ» means something remaining in its state, and its opposite is «زَالَ», meaning something moving from its place. And «اَثْبَتَ» means to keep something in its original state, established and firm (detailed). For example, in the Quran: «یَمۡحُوا اللّٰہُ مَا یَشَآءُ وَ یُثۡبِتُ» (13/39) Translation: 'Allah eliminates what He wills and confirms what He wills.' (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 381,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Keep/Leave",
      "hw": "باقی",
      "s": "«غَادَرَ» means to leave one thing among many things (2 verses: 18:47-18:49)",
      "d": "«غَدَرَ» means to break a covenant and violate a promise (m. l). It also means to leave behind (m. r). And «غَادَرَ» means to leave something intentionally during accounting or not count it (detailed). For example, in the Quran: «وَیَقُوۡلُوۡنَ یٰوَیۡلَتَنَا مَالِ ہٰذَا الۡکِتٰبِ لَا یُغَادِرُ صَغِیۡرَۃً وَّ لَا کَبِیۡرَۃً  اِلَّاۤ اَحۡصٰہَا» (18/49) Translation: 'And they will say, 'Woe to us! What is this book that leaves nothing small or large except that it has enumerated it?'"
    }
  ],
  "80": [
    {
      "id": 382,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Hair",
      "hw": "بال",
      "s": "«شَعْر» refers to the hair of all living beings, including humans (1 verse: 16:80)",
      "d": "«شَعْر» is the hair of all living beings, including humans. This word is general, and its plural is «اشعار» (f l 98)."
    },
    {
      "id": 383,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Hair",
      "hw": "بال",
      "s": "«وَبْر» refers to the hair of camels and birds (1 verse: 16:80)",
      "d": "«وَبْر» is the hair of camels and birds, and it is flowing. Its plural is «اَوْبَار» (f l 98)."
    },
    {
      "id": 384,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Wool",
      "hw": "بال",
      "s": "«صُوْف» is used for the wool and hair of sheep, goats, etc. (1 Verse: 16:80)",
      "d": "«صُوْف» is used for the wool and hair of sheep, goats, etc. Its plural is «اَصْوَاف» (F L 98).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَمِنۡ اَصۡوَافِہَا وَاَوۡبَارِہَا وَاَشۡعَارِہَاۤ اَثَاثًا وَّمَتَاعًا اِلٰی حِیۡنٍ» (16/80)\nTranslation: And from their wool, their hair, and their fur, they make domestic articles and wares that last for a time."
    }
  ],
  "81": [
    {
      "id": 385,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Barren (Woman)",
      "hw": "بانجھ",
      "s": "«عَاقِر» refers to a woman who previously bore children but has since become barren. (3 Verses: 3:40, 19:5, 19:8)",
      "d": "The original root of «عَاقِر» is «عَقَر», which carries the meaning of inflicting a wound or cut (M L). «اَلْکَلْبُ الْعَقُوْر» means a cutting dog, and «عَقَرَ النَّخلَۃ» means to cut down a palm tree by its roots.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَکَذَّبُوۡہُ  فَعَقَرُوۡہَا» (91/14)\nTranslation: So they denied him and they hamstrung the she-camel.\nThen, «اَلْعَقْر» also refers to the last child after whom no offspring follows (Muf). Thus, «عَاقِر» is used for a woman who was fertile but later, due to a wound in her womb, cessation of menstruation, or another reason, ceased to bear children. Moreover, this word is used for both men and women.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِنِّیۡ خِفۡتُ الۡمَوَالِیَ مِنۡ وَّرَآءِیۡی وَ کَانَتِ امۡرَاَتِیۡ عَاقِرًا فَہَبۡ لِیۡ مِنۡ لَّدُنۡکَ  وَلِیًّا» (19/5)\nTranslation: (Prophet Zakariya supplicated to God) And I fear my heirs after me, and my wife is barren, so grant me from Yourself an heir."
    },
    {
      "id": 386,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Barren (Person)",
      "hw": "بانجھ",
      "s": "«عَقِیْم» refers to a woman who does not bear children, and a man whose sperm does not result in conception. It is used for both barren women and men. (4 Verses: 22:55, 42:50, 51:29, 51:41)",
      "d": "«عَقِیْم» is also used for both masculine and feminine, like «عَاقِر». «عَقِیْم» also refers to a mound of sand or a barren piece of land (M. R). And «رِیْحٌ عَقِیْمٌ» refers to a wind devoid of goodness.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَفِیْ عَادٍ اِذْ اَرْسَلْنَا عَلَیْہِمُ الرِّیْحَ الْعَقِیْمَۚ» (51/41)\nTranslation: And in 'Ad (there is a sign) when We sent against them the barren wind.\nAnd «عَقِیْم» is a person whose reproductive material is absent or whose semen is dead (in common terms, a man lacking the ability to procreate). Similarly, «عَقِیْم» refers to a woman who does not accept a man's semen at all (M. R). Thus, «عَقِیْم» is a man or woman who has never had any offspring from the beginning.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَوۡ یُزَوِّجُہُمۡ ذُکۡرَانًا وَّاِنَاثًا ۚ وَیَجۡعَلُ مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ عَقِیۡمًا» (42/50)\nTranslation: Or He grants them both sons and daughters, and He makes whom He wills barren."
    }
  ],
  "82": [
    {
      "id": 387,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Tie/Bind",
      "hw": "باندھنا",
      "s": "«رَبَطَ» means to tie something with a rope. And «رَبَطَ اللہُ عَلیٰ قَلْبِہٖ» is a phrase meaning God strengthens someone's heart and grants them patience. (3 Verses: 8:11, 18:14, 28:10)",
      "d": "«رَبَطَ» means to tie firmly. «مِرْبَطُ» is a rope or means for tying animals. «مَرْبَطُ» is a place for tying livestock. «رَبَّاط» means a rope or cord. «رَبَیْطَہ» means tied animals. And «رَبَطَ اللہُ عَلیٰ قَلْبِہٖ» is an idiom. God has tied that person's heart, i.e., He fortified their heart and granted them patience (Manjad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنۡ کَادَتۡ لَتُبۡدِیۡ بِہٖ لَوۡلَاۤ اَنۡ رَّبَطۡنَا عَلٰی قَلۡبِہَا» (28/10)\nTranslation: Had We not fortified her heart, she would almost have disclosed the matter."
    },
    {
      "id": 389,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Chains/Miser",
      "hw": "باندھنا",
      "s": "«غُلّ» refers to a miserly person. That is, such a person's hands are tied from spending. (3 Verses: 5:64, 12:23, 17:29)",
      "d": "«غُلّ» its plural is «اَغْلَال». It refers to anything that is used to shackle a limb and tie it in the middle, meaning a fetter or chain. By extension, «مَغْلُولُ الْیَد» refers to a miserly person, i.e., a person whose hands are tied from spending (Muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَقَالَتِ الۡیَہُوۡدُ یَدُ اللّٰہِ مَغۡلُوۡلَۃٌ ؕ غُلَّتۡ اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ وَ لُعِنُوۡا بِمَا قَالُوۡا ۘ بَلۡ یَدٰہُ مَبۡسُوۡطَتٰنِ ۙ یُنۡفِقُ کَیۡفَ یَشَآءُ» (5/64)\nTranslation: And the Jews say, 'The hand of Allah is chained.' Chained are their hands, and cursed are they for what they say. Nay, both His hands are widely outstretched; He spends how He wills."
    }
  ],
  "83": [
    {
      "id": 390,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Idol",
      "hw": "بت",
      "s": "«صَنَم» refers to idols carved from silver, copper, or wood. (5 Verses: 6:74, 7:138, 14:35, 21:57, 26:71)",
      "d": "The plural of «صَنَم» is «اَصْنَام». It means self-carved idols and statues made of silver, copper, or wood, which are transferable and can be bought and sold (Muf M L). «صَنَّاعَۃُ الْاَصْنَام» refers to the craft and profession of idol-making. Prophet Abraham's father, Azar, practiced this profession. And Prophet Abraham supplicates to his Lord:\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّاجۡنُبۡنِیۡ وَ بَنِیَّ اَنۡ نَّعۡبُدَ الۡاَصۡنَامَ» (14/35)\nTranslation: And (O my Lord) keep me and my sons away from worshipping idols."
    },
    {
      "id": 392,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Idol (Natural Object of Worship)",
      "hw": "بت",
      "s": "«وَثْن» refers to beginning the worship of God's attributes in specific places like rocks, trees, stars, or rivers, etc. (3 Verses: 22:30, 29:17, 29:25)",
      "d": "The plural of «وَثْن» is «اَوْثَان». It means idols that remain fixed and stationary in their place. These are not carved or erected idols. Rather, worship begins by holding the belief of God's attributes in specific places like rocks, trees, stars, or rivers, etc. «اَلْوَثَنِیٌّ» refers to an idolater, and «اَلْوَثَنِیَّۃ» refers to idolatry (Manjad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاجۡتَنِبُواالرِّجۡسَ مِنَ الۡاَوۡثَانِ وَاجۡتَنِبُوۡا قَوۡلَ الزُّوۡرِ» (22/30)\nTranslation: So avoid the impurity of idols and avoid false speech."
    },
    {
      "id": 393,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Idol/Sorcery",
      "hw": "بت",
      "s": "«جِبْت» means idol, soothsayer, divination, and anything that contains no good. For example, magic spells. (1 Verse: 4:51)",
      "d": "«جِبْت» means idol, soothsayer, divination, and anything that contains no good. For example, magic spells (M. R). This word is essentially an umbrella term for superstitions, illusions, and myths. It includes magic, incantations, amulets, the influences of stars, talismans, engravings, etc."
    },
    {
      "id": 394,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "False Deity/Tyrant",
      "hw": "بت",
      "s": "«طَاغُوْت» refers to all false and rebellious systems or powers that incline towards opposing God's commands and are accepted as such. (15 Verses: 2:256, 2:257, 4:51, 4:60, 4:76, 5:60, 16:36, 37:30, 38:55, 39:17, 51:53, 52:32, 68:31, 69:5, 78:22)",
      "d": "«طَاغُوْت» means 'idol, tyrant, sorcerer, soothsayer, falsehood, idol, and worship of other than God, and rebellious' (M. R). Thus, «طَاغُوْت» refers to all false and rebellious systems or powers that incline towards opposing God's commands and are accepted as such.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَلَمۡ تَرَ اِلَی الَّذِیۡنَ اُوۡتُوۡا نَصِیۡبًا مِّنَ الۡکِتٰبِ یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ بِالۡجِبۡتِ وَالطَّاغُوۡتِ» (4/51)\nTranslation: Have you not seen those who were given a portion of the Scripture believing in the idol and the false deity?"
    }
  ],
  "84": [
    {
      "id": 395,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Lightning",
      "hw": "بجلی",
      "s": "«بَرْق» refers to the flashing or striking lightning. (6 Verses: 2:19, 2:20, 13:12, 24:43, 30:24, 75:7)",
      "d": "«بَرْق» refers to the flashing or striking lightning that nearly blinds the eyes. And «بَرِقَ الْبَصَرُ» means the eyes to become dazzled.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یَکَادُ الۡبَرۡقُ یَخۡطَفُ اَبۡصَارَہُمۡ» (2/20)\nTranslation: The lightning almost snatches away their sight."
    },
    {
      "id": 396,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Lightning",
      "hw": "بجلی",
      "s": "«رَعْد» refers to the crackling and rumbling lightning (2 verses: 2:19-13:13)",
      "d": "«رَعْد» is the crackling and rumbling lightning. It is also used for clouds that have thunder and lightning (m.f.). For example, in the Quran: «وَ یُسَبِّحُ الرَّعۡدُ بِحَمۡدِہٖ وَالۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ مِنۡ خِیۡفَتِہٖ» (13/13) Translation: And the thunder and the angels glorify Him with praise out of awe of Him."
    },
    {
      "id": 397,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Lightning",
      "hw": "بجلی",
      "s": "«Ṣāʿiqah» is a striking lightning from the sky that burns and destroys completely. (7 verses: 2:19, 2:55, 4:153, 13:13, 41:13, 41:17, 51:44)",
      "d": "«Ṣāʿiqah» is a striking lightning from the sky that burns and destroys completely. Therefore, it is also metaphorically used for Divine punishment or death. Imam Rāghib says that it refers to a terrifying explosion related to celestial bodies, while its counterpart «ṣaqaʿa» is specific to terrestrial bodies, but both have the same meaning. (Mufradāt) Some scholars define its meaning as emitting fire from the sky with a severe crash, or a sound so intense that hearing it causes unconsciousness. (M. R.) In this sense, «ṣāʿiqah» is the extreme form of «raʿd» (thunder). The plural of «ṣāʿiqah» is «ṣawāʿiq». For example, the Quran states: «وَیُرۡسِلُ الصَّوَاعِقَ فَیُصِیۡبُ بِہَا مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ» (13/13). Translation: And He sends the thunderbolts, striking therewith whom He wills."
    }
  ],
  "85": [
    {
      "id": 398,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To save",
      "hw": "بچانا",
      "s": "«وَقٰی» means to save someone from the punishment of a bad deed by frightening them away from that deed and its punishment (1 verse: 66:6)",
      "d": "«وَقٰی» means to save from the punishment of a bad deed by frightening one away from that deed and its punishment. (m.f.) For example, in the Quran: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا قُوۡۤا اَنۡفُسَکُمۡ وَاَہۡلِیۡکُمۡ نَارًا» (66/6) Translation: O you who believe! Save yourselves and your families from the Fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 399,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To save",
      "hw": "بچانا",
      "s": "«مَنَعَ» means to save by creating a barrier or obstacle from misfortune (13 verses: 2:114-4:141-7:12-9:54-12:63-17:59-17:94-18:55-20:92-21:43-38:75-59:2-107:7)",
      "d": "«مَنَعَ» means to prevent or stop, and its opposite is «اَلْاِعْطَاء» meaning to give something. (m. l) It also means to block or create an obstacle to save from a calamity or affliction. For example, in the Quran: «وَظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہُمۡ مَّانِعَتُہُمۡ حُصُوۡنُہُمۡ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ» (59/2) Translation: And they thought that their fortresses would protect them from Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 401,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To save",
      "hw": "بچانا",
      "s": "«اَحْصَنَ» means to save by guarding and protecting oneself (8 verses: 4:24-4:25-5:5-21:91-24:4-24:23-59:14-66:12)",
      "d": "«حَصَنَ» means fortress or refuge. According to Ibn al-Faris, its meanings are essentially three: (1) protection (2) enclosure (3) refuge. (m l) Therefore, «اَحْصَنَ» will also have these meanings: i.e., to prevent, to save, and to guard completely. For example, in the Quran: «وَمَرۡیَمَ  ابۡنَتَ عِمۡرٰنَ الَّتِیۡۤ اَحۡصَنَتۡ فَرۡجَہَا» (66/12) Translation: And Maryam, the daughter of Imran, who guarded her chastity."
    },
    {
      "id": 403,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To save",
      "hw": "بچانا",
      "s": "«عَصَم» means to save someone from a calamity or danger by taking them under one's protection (4 verses: 5:67-11:43-12:32-33:17)",
      "d": "«عَصَم» means to hold back or keep something with oneself to save it from a calamity that it might fall into. (m. l) In Ibn Faris's words, «ع ۔ ص ۔ م» is \"a word indicating holding, preventing, and adhering from the evil that befalls it.\" (m. l) For example, in the Quran: «یٰۤاَیُّہَاالرَّسُوۡلُ بَلِّغۡ  مَاۤ اُنۡزِلَ اِلَیۡکَ مِنۡ رَّبِّکَ ؕ وَاِنۡ لَّمۡ تَفۡعَلۡ فَمَا بَلَّغۡتَ رِسَالَتَہٗ ؕ وَاللّٰہُ یَعۡصِمُکَ مِنَ النَّاسِ» (5/67) Translation: O Messenger! Convey what has been revealed to you from your Lord. And if you do not, then you have not conveyed His message. And Allah will protect you from the people. In another place in the Quran, the son of Prophet Nuh answers him: «سَاٰوِیۡۤ  اِلٰی جَبَلٍ یَّعۡصِمُنِیۡ  مِنَ الۡمَآءِ» (11/43) Translation: I will resort to a mountain that will protect me from the water."
    },
    {
      "id": 404,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be saved",
      "hw": "بچانا",
      "s": "«اِتَّقٰی اور تَقْوٰی» means to save oneself from bad deeds and their punishment by adopting piety (223 verses: 2:2-2:21-2:24-2:41-2:48-2:63-2:66-2:103-2:123-2:177-2:179-2:180-2:183-2:187-2:189-2:194-2:196-2:197-2:203-2:206-2:212-2:223-2:224-2:231-2:233-2:237-2:241-2:278-2:281-2:282-2:283-3:15-3:28-3:50-3:76-3:102-3:115-3:120-3:123-3:125-3:130-3:131-3:133-3:138-3:172-3:179-3:186-3:198-3:200-4:1-4:9-4:77-4:128-4:129-4:131-5:2-5:4-5:7-5:8-5:11-5:27-5:35-5:46-5:57-5:65-5:88-5:93-5:96-5:100-5:108-5:112-6:32-6:51-6:69-6:72-6:153-6:155-7:26-7:35-7:63-7:65-7:96-7:128-7:156-7:164-7:169-7:171-7:201-8:1-8:25-8:29-8:34-8:56-8:69-9:4-9:7-9:36-9:44-9:108-9:109-9:115-9:119-9:123-10:6-10:31-10:63-11:49-11:78-12:57-12:90-12:109-13:35-15:45-15:69-16:2-16:30-16:31-16:52-16:81-16:128-19:13-19:18-19:63-19:72-19:85-19:97-20:113-20:132-21:48-22:1-22:32-22:37-23:23-23:32-23:52-23:87-24:34-24:52-25:15-25:74-26:11-26:90-26:106-26:108-26:110-26:124-26:126-26:131-26:132-26:142-26:144-26:150-26:161-26:163-26:177-26:179-26:184-27:53-28:83-29:16-30:31-31:33-33:1-33:32-33:37-33:55-33:70-36:45-37:124-38:28-38:49-39:10-39:16-39:20-39:24-39:28-39:33-39:57-39:61-39:73-40:9-41:18-43:35-43:63-43:67-44:51-45:19-47:15-47:17-47:36-48:26-49:1-49:3-49:10-49:12-49:13-50:31-51:15-52:17-53:32-54:54-57:28-58:9-59:7-59:18-60:11-64:16-65:1-65:2-65:4-65:5-65:10-68:34-69:48-71:3-73:17-74:56-77:41-78:31-91:8-92:5-92:17-96:12)",
      "d": "«اِتَّقٰی اور تَقْوٰی» means to save oneself from the punishment of bad deeds by avoiding those bad deeds and their punishment, adopting piety. For example, in the Quran: «خُذُوۡا مَاۤ اٰتَیۡنٰکُمۡ بِقُوَّۃٍ وَّ اذۡکُرُوۡا مَا فِیۡہِ لَعَلَّکُمۡ تَتَّقُوۡنَ» (2/63) Translation: Take what We have given you with determination and remember what is in it, so that you may be saved."
    },
    {
      "id": 405,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be saved",
      "hw": "بچانا",
      "s": "«تَحَصَّنَ» means to save something by guarding and protecting it (3 verses: 12:48-21:80-24:33)",
      "d": "«تَحَصَّنَ» means to guard and protect something to save it. This word is generally used for protecting one's chastity. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَا تُکۡرِہُوۡا فَتَیٰتِکُمۡ عَلَی الۡبِغَآءِ اِنۡ اَرَدۡنَ تَحَصُّنًا لِّتَبۡتَغُوۡا عَرَضَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ الدُّنۡیَا» (24/33) Translation: And do not compel your slave girls to prostitution if they desire chastity, seeking the temporary benefits of worldly life."
    },
    {
      "id": 406,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be saved",
      "hw": "بچانا",
      "s": "«اِجْتَنَبَ» means to save oneself by staying away from something or an action (8 verses: 4:31-5:90-16:36-22:30-39:17-42:37-49:12-53:32)",
      "d": "«اِجْتَنَبَ» means to save oneself by keeping away from something or an action. For example, in the Quran: «فَاجۡتَنِبُوا الرِّجۡسَ مِنَ الۡاَوۡثَانِ وَاجۡتَنَبُوۡا قَوۡلَ الزُّوۡرِ» (22/30) Translation: So avoid the impurity of idols and avoid false speech."
    },
    {
      "id": 407,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be saved",
      "hw": "بچانا",
      "s": "«اِسْتَعْصَمَ» means to save oneself from sin or defect and to protect (1 verse: 12:32)",
      "d": "«اِسْتَعْصَمَ» means to save oneself from sin or defect and to protect. For example, in the Quran: «ولَقَدۡ رَاوَدۡتُّہٗ عَنۡ نَّفۡسِہٖ فَاسۡتَعۡصَمَ» (12/32) Translation: Indeed, she sought to seduce him from himself, but he protected himself. Note: Besides the words mentioned above, «حَذَرَ» and «تَعَفُّف» are also used in the Quran with the meaning of saving."
    },
    {
      "id": 408,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be cautious / to avoid",
      "hw": "بچانا",
      "s": "«Ḥadhar» means to be cautious against an anticipated danger and to avoid it. (17 verses: 2:19, 2:235, 2:243, 3:28, 3:30, 4:71, 4:102, 5:41, 5:49, 5:92, 9:64, 9:122, 24:63, 28:6, 39:9, 63:4, 64:14)",
      "d": "«Ḥadhar» means to be cautious and vigilant against an expected danger. (Mufradāt, Majid) For example, the Quran states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَاالَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِنَّ مِنۡ اَزۡوَاجِکُمۡ وَاَوۡلَادِکُمۡ عَدُوًّا لَّکُمۡ فَاحۡذَرُوۡہُمۡ» (64/14). Translation: O you who have believed, indeed, among your wives and your children are enemies to you, so beware of them."
    },
    {
      "id": 409,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be cautious / to avoid",
      "hw": "بچانا",
      "s": "«Taʿaffuf» means to abstain from forbidden things and to remain chaste/pure. (4 verses: 2:273, 4:6, 24:33, 24:60)",
      "d": "«ʿAffa» means to refrain from forbidden or disliked acts, to remain chaste. «Taʿaffuf» means to abstain from forbidden things and to remain chaste/pure. (Majid, M. R.) For example, the Quran states: «یَحۡسَبُہُمُ الۡجَاہِلُ اَغۡنِیَآءَ مِنَ التَّعَفُّفِ ۚ تَعۡرِفُہُمۡ بِسِیۡمٰہُمۡ ۚ لَا یَسۡئَلُوۡنَ النَّاسَ اِلۡحَافًا» (2/273). Translation: The ignorant think them rich because of their restraint (from asking). You know them by their mark; they ask not from people with importunity."
    }
  ],
  "86": [
    {
      "id": 412,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Child (Boy)",
      "hw": "لڑکا",
      "s": "«طِفْل» immature child (4 آیات: 22:5-24:31-24:59-40:67)",
      "d": "«طَفِلَ» means soft and delicate, and «طَفْلَۃٌ» refers to a woman with a tender body. Therefore, as long as the child remains soft and delicate, he is «طِفْل» (pl. أَطْفَال). However, it refers to children who have not yet reached puberty. Its plural is أَطْفَال.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا بَلَغَ الۡاَطۡفَالُ مِنۡکُمُ الۡحُلُمَ فَلۡیَسۡتَاۡذِنُوۡا کَمَا اسۡتَاۡذَنَ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ» (24/59)\nTranslation: And when your children reach puberty, they should seek permission as those before them used to do.\nThis verse clarifies that after puberty, the child exits the stage of childhood and enters the stage of adulthood."
    },
    {
      "id": 413,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Child (Boy)",
      "hw": "لڑکا",
      "s": "«صَبِیٌّ» ignorant child engaged in childish habits and play (2 آیات: 19:12-19:29)",
      "d": "«صَبِیٌّ» is a child who is still in the age of ignorance and play (م ۔ ر). This term is more related to childish habits than to a specific age. If a boy, even after reaching puberty, remains ignorant and engaged in play, he is still considered «صَبِیٌّ». It means a child with childish habits and behavior.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یٰیَحۡیٰی خُذِ الۡکِتٰبَ بِقُوَّۃٍ ؕ وَاٰتَیۡنٰہُ الۡحُکۡمَ صَبِیًّا» (19/12)\nTranslation: O Yahya! Hold the Book with strength. And We gave him wisdom while he was still a child (i.e., at an age when other children are occupied with play)."
    },
    {
      "id": 414,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Child (Boy)",
      "hw": "لڑکا",
      "s": "«غُلَامٌ» a boy who has reached puberty (13 آیات: 3:40-12:19-15:53-18:74-18:80-18:82-19:7-19:8-19:19-19:20-37:101-51:28-52:24)",
      "d": "«غُلَامٌ» refers to a boy in whom sexual desires have awakened (م ۔ ل), i.e., one who has reached puberty. A youth. The phrase «اِغْتَلَمَ الْفَحْلُ غُلْمَۃً» means that the male's desire for intercourse has become dominant. «غَلِیْم» means a young man, and «اِغلَام» means to engage in foreplay. The plural of «غُلَام» is «غِلْمَۃٌ» and «غِلْمَانٌ».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَیَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ غِلۡمَانٌ لَّہُمۡ کَاَنَّہُمۡ لُؤۡلُؤٌ مَّکۡنُوۡنٌ» (52/24)\nTranslation: And young boys will circulate among them, as if they were hidden pearls."
    }
  ],
  "87": [
    {
      "id": 416,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To spread",
      "hw": "بچھانا",
      "s": "«سَطَحَ» to spread or lay out and then level it (1 آیات: 88:20)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «سَطَحَ» is to spread and then level. «سَطَحَ الْبَیْتَ» means to level the roof of a house, and «مَسْطَحْ» refers to tools for leveling. The upper part of a building and its roof are called «سَطْح». According to Imam Raghib, «اَلسَّطْحُ اَعْلَی الْبَیْتِ جُعِلَ سَوِیًّا» (the roof is the highest part of the house made level).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاِلَی الۡاَرۡضِ کَیۡفَ سُطِحَتۡ» (88/20)\nTranslation: And (do they not look) at the earth, how it is spread out (i.e., how its surface has been made level)?"
    },
    {
      "id": 417,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To spread",
      "hw": "بچھانا",
      "s": "«فَرَشَ» to spread something completely or lay it out and level it (5 آیات: 2:22-6:142-51:48-55:54-56:34)",
      "d": "«فَرَشَ» means to spread a cloth, etc., to lay a bed, and anything that is spread is called «فرش» or «فِراش» (meaning a spread). The fundamental meaning of فرش is to spread, widen, and expand something (م ۔ ل). That is, to spread something completely. «فَرَشَ الدَّار» means to lay a carpet. Spreading bricks and stones (منجد).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الۡاَرۡضَ فِرَاشًا وَّالسَّمَآءَ بِنَآءً» (2/22)\nTranslation: Who has made the earth a spread for you and the sky a canopy."
    },
    {
      "id": 418,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To spread",
      "hw": "بچھانا",
      "s": "«مَھَدَ» to spread while also providing means of upbringing (7 آیات: 3:46-5:110-19:29-20:53-30:44-43:10-74:14)",
      "d": "According to Al-Munjid, just as «سَطَحَ» is used for spreading and leveling a roof, «مَھَدَ» is used for leveling the earth. However, «مَھْد» also refers to a mother's lap, which includes the aspect of upbringing. And «مَھَدَ الْاَرْض» means to spread the earth in such a way that its inhabitants are also provided with means of sustenance. The Quran supports this.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّمَہَّدۡتُّ لَہٗ  تَمۡہِیۡدًا ثُمَّ  یَطۡمَعُ اَنۡ اَزِیۡدَ» (74/14,15)\nTranslation: And I have spread out for him every kind of ease. Yet he desires that I give more!\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«وَالۡاَرۡضَ فَرَشۡنٰہَا فَنِعۡمَ الۡمٰہِدُوۡنَ» (51/48)\nTranslation: And the earth We have spread out; how excellent are the Spreaders!\nThis verse also proves that «مَھَدَ» has a broader meaning than «فَرَشَ», i.e., preparing related provisions beyond necessity."
    }
  ],
  "88": [
    {
      "id": 419,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Spread",
      "hw": "بچھونا",
      "s": "«مِھَاد» metaphorically refers to the earth, which provides a place of upbringing and rest for all creatures (7 verses: 2:206-3:12-3:197-7:41-13:18-38:56-78:6)",
      "d": "«مَھَدَ» means to spread and provide means of upbringing. As detailed above. Allah has described the earth as «مِھَاد» because both these aspects are found in it.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَلَمۡ  نَجۡعَلِ الۡاَرۡضَ مِہٰدًا» (78/6)\nTranslation: Have We not made the earth a spread?"
    },
    {
      "id": 420,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Spread (noun)",
      "hw": "بچھونا",
      "s": "«فِرَاش» generally used for bed or sheet (5 آیات: 2:22-6:142-51:48-55:54-56:34)",
      "d": "«فَرَشَ» means to spread and level. «اَلْفَرَش» in its original meaning refers to spreading a cloth (مف). However, فرش also means to lay a carpet of bricks or stones, as in «فَرَشَ الرَّجُلُ» meaning both to spread a sheet and to lay a floor (منجد). And «فِرَاش» means a spread or bed, and metaphorically, it is used for each spouse (مف). As the Prophet ﷺ said: «اَلْوَلَدُ لِلْفِرَاشِ» and «لِلْعَاہِرِ الْحَجَر» (the child belongs to the husband, and the adulterer gets the stone). The Quran has used this word both for the earth and for a bed. Its plural is «فُرُشٍ».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«مُتَّکِئِیۡنَ عَلٰی فُرُشٍۭ بَطَآئِنُہَا مِنۡ اِسۡتَبۡرَقٍ» (55/54)\nTranslation: Reclining on beds, whose linings are of rich brocade."
    }
  ],
  "89": [
    {
      "id": 422,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Stinginess",
      "hw": "بخل",
      "s": "«بَخِلَ» Not spending from one's accumulated wealth even in places where spending is required. (7 verses: 3:180-4:37-9:76-47:37-47:38-57:24-92:8)",
      "d": "«بَخِلَ» Not spending from one's accumulated wealth even in places where spending is required. (Muf.) Stinginess is of two types: (1) Being stingy in fulfilling others' rights or in spending in the way of Allah, i.e., in Allah's path. (2) Not spending even on one's legitimate necessities. Both types of stinginess are condemnable, i.e., bad and detestable. And this word is general that can be used for all forms of stinginess.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ یَبۡخَلُوۡنَ وَ یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ النَّاسَ بِالۡبُخۡلِ وَیَکۡتُمُوۡنَ مَاۤ اٰتٰہُمُ اللّٰہُ مِنۡ فَضۡلِہٖ ؕ وَاَعۡتَدۡنَا لِلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ عَذَابًا مُّہِیۡنًا» (4/37)\nTranslation: Those who are stingy themselves and enjoin stinginess upon others and conceal what Allah has bestowed upon them of His bounty. And We have prepared for the disbelievers a humiliating punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 423,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Stinginess",
      "hw": "بخل",
      "s": "«اَمْسَکَ» To hold back whatever one has; it is also used in the meaning of stinginess. (22 verses: 2:231-2:256-4:15-5:4-7:170-16:59-16:79-17:100-22:65-31:22-33:37-35:2-35:41-38:39-39:38-39:42-43:21-43:43-60:10-65:2-67:19-67:21)",
      "d": "The meaning of «اَمْسَکَ» is not to let something one possesses slip from one's hand and to hold it back. Or to cling to something and protect it. (Muf.) And «اِمْسَاک» means stinginess, and «مُمْسِک» also means a miser. (Maj.)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قُلۡ لَّوۡ اَنۡتُمۡ تَمۡلِکُوۡنَ خَزَآئِنَ رَحۡمَۃِ رَبِّیۡۤ اِذًالَّاَمۡسَکۡتُمۡ خَشۡیَۃَ الۡاِنۡفَاقِ» (17/100)\nTranslation: Say, [O Muhammad], 'If you possessed the treasures of the mercy of my Lord, then you would surely hold back [from spending] for fear of expenditure.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 424,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be stingy",
      "hw": "بخل",
      "s": "«اَوْعٰی» to hold and not let decrease, used for anything worth preserving (2 آیات: 69:12-70:18)",
      "d": "«اَلْاِیْعَاء» means to hold something (wealth, etc.) in a pouch and then close its mouth (مف). According to Al-Munjid, it is used in all three meanings: (1) to remember something, (2) to collect, and (3) to be stingy. According to Ibn al-Faris, its basic meaning is only to close the mouth. And «وِعَاء» refers to any container whose mouth is closed or sealed (م ۔ ل).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«تَدۡعُوۡا مَنۡ اَدۡبَرَوَ تَوَلّٰی وَ جَمَعَ فَاَوۡعٰی» (70/17,18)\nTranslation: It will call those who turned away and disobeyed and collected and hoarded (wealth).\nAnd «اُذُنٌ وَّاعِیَۃٌ» (69/12) means an ear that listens attentively and remembers, referring to a person who listens carefully, remembers well, and does not allow any addition or omission in the words or meaning. As the Messenger of Allah ﷺ said in his famous Farewell Sermon delivered at Mina while mounted on his camel: نَضَّرَ اللہُ عَبْدًا سَمِعَ مَقَالَتِیْ فَوَعَاھَا ثُمَّ اَدَّاھَا وَبَلَّغَھَا (May Allah bless a servant who hears my speech, retains it, and then conveys it and explains it). Thus, the word «وعٰی» is general for anything worth preserving, not just wealth."
    },
    {
      "id": 425,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Stinginess",
      "hw": "بخل",
      "s": "«اَکْدٰی» To stop after a little spending or to intend but not complete [spending]. (2 verses: 7:58-53:34)",
      "d": "«کُدْیَۃٌ» refers to hard ground. And «حَفَرَ فَاَکْدٰی» means to dig until reaching hard ground. (Muf. Fal 262) And when related to spending wealth, «اَکْدٰی» means to stop after spending a little. Or to intend to spend but then stop.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَفَرَءَیۡتَ الَّذِیۡ تَوَلّٰی وَاَعۡطٰی قَلِیۡلًا وَّاَکۡدٰی» (53/33,34)\nTranslation: Have you seen the one who turned away and gave a little, then stopped?"
    },
    {
      "id": 426,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Stinginess",
      "hw": "بخل",
      "s": "«اَقْتَرَ» To be stingy in providing for one's family and dependents or to be stingy in spending on oneself as well. (2 verses: 2:236-25:67)",
      "d": "The meaning of «قَتَرَ» is to spend very little. (Muf.) And «اِقْتَار» is the opposite of israf (extravagance). That is, to spend less than necessary even on one's legitimate needs and to be stingy. According to the author of 'Muntahi al-Arab', its meaning is 'a person who has made the maintenance (nafaqah) for his family and dependents very tight.' (Maj.) Allah Almighty, describing the attributes of His servants, says:\nArshad Bari Ta'ala says:\n«وَالَّذِیۡنَ اِذَاۤ اَنۡفَقُوۡا لَمۡ یُسۡرِفُوۡاوَلَمۡ یَقۡتُرُوۡا وَکَانَ بَیۡنَ ذٰلِکَ قَوَامًا» (25/67)\nTranslation: And those who, when they spend, are not extravagant and not stingy, but are moderate between that [extremity]."
    },
    {
      "id": 427,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Stinginess",
      "hw": "بخل",
      "s": "«ضَنَّ» To be stingy in giving something desirable and beloved. (2 verses: 20:124-81:24)",
      "d": "«ضَنَّ» means to be stingy in giving something desirable and beloved. (Muf.) And «اَلضَّنَائِن» are things with which one is stingy due to their preciousness. (Maj.) For example, a physician being stingy in sharing his proven remedy.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ مَا ہُوَ عَلَی الۡغَیۡبِ بِضَنِیۡنٍ» (81/24)\nTranslation: And he (the Prophet, peace be upon him) is not stingy regarding the unseen (i.e., he does not conceal knowledge of the unseen)."
    },
    {
      "id": 428,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Stinginess",
      "hw": "بخل",
      "s": "«شُحَّ» When both stinginess and greed combine, it is called «شُحَّ». (4 verses: 4:128-33:19-59:9-64:16)",
      "d": "The meaning of «شُحَّ» is to be stingy and to crave and be greedy. (Maj.) When both stinginess and greed combine, it is called «شُحَّ». (Fal 33, Maj.) And its other name is 'shiddat al-hirs' (intensity of greed), meaning to constantly worry about amassing wealth and to be stingy in spending.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یُّوۡقَ شُحَّ نَفۡسِہٖ  فَاُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمُ  الۡمُفۡلِحُوۡنَ» (59/9)\nTranslation: And whoever is saved from the stinginess of his soul, it is they who will be the successful.\nAnd «شَحِیْحٌ» means a miser and greedy person; its plurals are «شِحَاحٌ» and «اَشِحَّۃٌ».\nFor example: The command of Allah Almighty is:\n«فَاِذَا ذَہَبَ الۡخَوۡفُ سَلَقُوۡکُمۡ بِاَلۡسِنَۃٍ حِدَادٍ  اَشِحَّۃً عَلَی الۡخَیۡرِ» (33/19)\nTranslation: Then when fear departs, they will assail you with sharp tongues, being stingy with regard to wealth. (Jalandhari) They are niggardly regarding good. (Osmani)"
    }
  ],
  "90": [
    {
      "id": 430,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Misfortune",
      "hw": "بدبختی",
      "s": "«شِقْوَۃ» A person who is inherently unfortunate or ill-fated, and misfortune is his destined lot. (9 verses: 11:105-11:106-19:4-19:32-19:48-23:106-87:11-91:12-92:15)",
      "d": "«شِقْوَۃ» and «شِقَاوَۃ» both mean misfortune, and its opposite is «سَعَادَۃ». And just as «سَعَادَۃ» is among the accidental attributes (i.e., additional characteristics), similarly «شِقَاوَۃ» and «شِقْوَۃ» are also among the accidental attributes. And «شَقِی» is a person who is inherently unfortunate or ill-fated. (Muf.)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا رَبَّنَا غَلَبَتۡ عَلَیۡنَا شِقۡوَتُنَا وَ کُنَّا قَوۡمًا ضَآلِّیۡنَ» (23/106)\nTranslation: They (the disbelievers) will say, 'Our Lord, our misfortune has overcome us, and we were a people astray.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 431,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Misfortune",
      "hw": "بدبختی",
      "s": "«نَحُوْسَۃ» Meaning a time of misfortune and hardship. (2 verses: 41:16-54:19)",
      "d": "The meaning of «نُحَاس» is also brass, and a flame of fire whose color is like brass. And «نَحَسَ» means the sky turning red and taking on the color of brass, and this is a proverb for ill-omen. And «نَحُسَ» and «نَحُوْسَۃ» mean a time of hardship and misfortune. The opposite of «نَحَس» is «سَعْد».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ رِیۡحًا صَرۡصَرًا فِیۡۤ اَیَّامٍ نَّحِسَاتٍ» (41/16)\nTranslation: So We sent upon them a furious wind during days of misfortune."
    },
    {
      "id": 433,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Misfortune",
      "hw": "بدبختی",
      "s": "«شَئُوْم ۔ شَامَۃ» Such misfortune that is expected as a result of one's actions. (2 verses: 56:9-90:19)",
      "d": "«الشَّأمَۃَ الْمَشْئَمَۃ» means ill-omen, lack of blessing, and the left side (i.e., left-hand side). (Maj.) The left side is also considered a sign of ill-omen. And 'shamat' actually refers to such bad omen that is expected as a result of one's actions. 'Shamat-i-a'mal' is a famous phrase. And «تَشَاءُم» means to take a bad omen, and its opposite is «تَیَمُّن» (taking a good omen).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ کَانَ مِنَ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَتَوَاصَوۡا بِالصَّبۡرِ وَتَوَاصَوۡا بِالۡمَرۡحَمَۃِ اُولٰٓئِکَ اَصۡحٰبُ الۡمَیۡمَنَۃِ وَالَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا بِاٰیٰتِنَا ہُمۡ اَصۡحٰبُ الۡمَشۡئَمَۃِ» (90/17,18,19)\nTranslation: Then they (the believers) will be among those who have believed and advised one another to patience and advised one another to mercy. Those are the companions of the right. But those who disbelieved in Our signs, they are the companions of the left."
    },
    {
      "id": 434,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Devastating Calamity",
      "hw": "بدبختی",
      "s": "«حُسُوْم» A calamity that erases all traces of a person (1 Verse: 69:7)",
      "d": "«اَلْحَسَمَ» means to cut off something and erase its name and signs. And «حُسَام» means sword. Then «حُسُومُ» also refers to such a calamity or punishment that erases a person's very trace (muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاَمَّا عَادٌ فَاُہۡلِکُوۡا بِرِیۡحٍ صَرۡصَرٍعَاتِیَۃٍ سَخَّرَہَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ سَبۡعَ لَیَالٍ وَّثَمٰنِیَۃَ اَیَّامٍ ۙ حُسُوۡمًا ۙ فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی ۙ کَاَنَّہُمۡ اَعۡجَازُنَخۡلٍ خَاوِیَۃٍ» ( 69/6،7 )\nTranslation: As for 'Ad, they were utterly destroyed by a furious, screaming wind that We made rage against them for seven nights and eight days consecutively. So you could see the people lying prostrate as if they were hollow trunks of palm trees."
    }
  ],
  "91": [
    {
      "id": 435,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Curse",
      "hw": "بددعا ",
      "s": "«لَعَنَ» A curse invoking distance from God's mercy and success (34 Verses: 2:88-2:89-2:159-2:161-3:61-3:87-4:46-4:47-4:52-4:93-4:118-5:13-5:60-5:64-5:78-7:38-7:44-9:68-11:18-11:60-11:99-13:25-15:35-24:7-24:23-28:42-29:25-33:57-33:64-33:68-38:78-40:52-47:23-48:6)",
      "d": "«لَعَنَ» means to distance someone in anger and to revile them. When attributed to Allah Almighty, it means being distanced from His mercy and success (muf). It also means to revile, to remove from goodness, and to curse. It is a general and comprehensive word for cursing and invoking evil (manjad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لُعِنَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡۢ بَنِیۡۤ اِسۡرَآءِیۡلَ عَلٰی لِسَانِ دَاوٗدَ وَعِیۡسَی ابۡنِ مَرۡیَمَ» ( 5/78 )\nTranslation: Those among the Children of Israel who disbelieved were cursed on the tongue of David and Jesus, the son of Mary."
    },
    {
      "id": 437,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Curse",
      "hw": "بددعا ",
      "s": "«سُحْقًا» Used for cursing. Its meaning carries more intensity than «بُعْدًا» (1 Verse: 67:11)",
      "d": "«سَحَقَ» means to grind medicine, etc. And «اَسْحَقَ الثَّوْب» means for a garment to become old. And «اَسْحَقَہُ اللہ» means may Allah destroy him (muf). Also, «سَحِقَ سُحْقًا» means to be far away, and «اِسْتَحَقَ» means to drive away (manjad). So this is also a word of cursing, meaning separation from goodness, but with more intensity than «بُعْدًا».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاعۡتَرَفُوۡا بِذَنۡۢبِہِمۡ ۚ فَسُحۡقًا لِّاَصۡحٰبِ السَّعِیۡرِ» ( 67/11 )\nTranslation: So they will confess their sins. So away with the companions of the Blaze! (Jalandhariؒ)"
    }
  ],
  "92": [
    {
      "id": 439,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Deform / To Become Ugly",
      "hw": "بدصورت",
      "s": "«مَسَخَ» Used for spoiling a good form and shape and making it bad (1 Verse: 36:67)",
      "d": "«مَسَخَ» means to spoil the form and shape and to ruin it (muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَوۡ نَشَآءُ لَمَسَخۡنٰہُمۡ عَلٰی مَکَانَتِہِمۡ فَمَا اسۡتَطَاعُوۡا مُضِیًّا وَّلَا یَرۡجِعُوۡنَ» ( 36/67 )\nTranslation: And if We willed, We could have deformed them in their places, so they would not be able to move forward nor return."
    },
    {
      "id": 440,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Deform / To Become Ugly",
      "hw": "بدصورت",
      "s": "«کَلَحَ» Used for the face and its surroundings becoming temporarily ugly due to some affliction, trouble, or emotion (1 Verse: 23:104)",
      "d": "«کَلَحَۃ» means the mouth and the area around it. And «كَالِحُ» is a person whose lips are not closed but remain open. And «کَلَحَ ، کَلَّحَ» means to frown (i.e., to wrinkle the nose and mouth). And «اِکْلَوَّحَ» means to show teeth while frowning (manjad). According to the scholar of philology, this is the extreme degree of frowning (see 'frowning'). In this, a person's appearance becomes distorted, and due to showing teeth, they look very ugly.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«تَلۡفَحُ وُجُوۡہَہُمُ النَّارُ وَہُمۡ فِیۡہَا کٰلِحُوۡنَ» ( 23/104 )\nTranslation: The Fire will scorch their faces, and they will be grimacing in it."
    },
    {
      "id": 441,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Deform / To Become Ugly",
      "hw": "بدصورت",
      "s": "«قَبُحَ» To be inherently ugly in form and shape, and also used for bad qualities (1 Verse: 28:42)",
      "d": "«قَبُحَ» means to be ugly, to be ill-favored. And «قَبِیْح» means bad, ill-favored, ugly. The word «قَبُحَ» is also used metaphorically to mean a statement, action, or form being bad (manjad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَیَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ ہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡمَقۡبُوۡحِیۡنَ» ( 28/42 )\nTranslation: And on the Day of Resurrection, they will be among the despised.\nIn this verse, «مَقْبُوحِیْن» carries both meanings."
    }
  ],
  "93": [
    {
      "id": 442,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Adultery / Fornication",
      "hw": "بدکاری",
      "s": "«زِنَا» A well-known term. Committing illicit sexual relations with someone other than one's husband or wife (3 Verses: 17:32-24:2-24:3)",
      "d": "«زِنَا» is a well-known term. That is, a man having illicit sexual relations with a woman other than his wife, or a woman having illicit relations with a man other than her husband, is called zina (muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَا تَقۡرَبُوا الزِّنٰۤی اِنَّہٗ کَانَ فَاحِشَۃً ؕ وَسَآءَ سَبِیۡلًا» ( 17/32 )\nTranslation: And do not approach adultery. Indeed, it is an abomination and an evil way."
    },
    {
      "id": 443,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Adultery / Fornication",
      "hw": "بدکاری",
      "s": "«بِغَاء» A slave girl committing adultery or a prostitute making fornication her profession (18 Verses: 2:90-2:213-3:19-6:146-7:33-10:23-10:90-16:90-19:20-19:28-22:60-24:33-38:24-42:14-42:39-45:17-49:9-55:20)",
      "d": "«بَغِیَ» means to transgress, to disobey, to commit excess and injustice. And «بَاغَتِ الْاَمَۃُ بِغَآءً» means a slave girl committing adultery. And «بَغِیّ» means an adulteress, a promiscuous woman (manjad). That is, the word «بِغَاء» is either specific to a slave girl committing adultery or specific to a professional prostitute—a woman notorious for fornication among people. The Quran supports both meanings.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَا تُکۡرِہُوۡا فَتَیٰتِکُمۡ عَلَی الۡبِغَآءِ» ( 24/33 )\nTranslation: And do not compel your slave girls to prostitution.\nAt another place in the Quran, the Jews, addressing Mary (peace be upon her), say:\n«یٰۤاُخۡتَ ہٰرُوۡنَ مَا کَانَ  اَبُوۡکِ امۡرَ اَ سَوۡءٍ وَّ مَا  کَانَتۡ  اُمُّکِ  بَغِیًّا» ( 19/28 )\nTranslation: O sister of Aaron! Your father was not a man of evil, nor was your mother a fornicatress."
    },
    {
      "id": 444,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Adultery / Fornication",
      "hw": "بدکاری",
      "s": "«سَافَحَ» To openly maintain illicit sexual relations with someone other than one's husband or wife (3 Verses: 4:24-4:25-5:5)",
      "d": "«سَفَحَ» means to spill blood or water. And «سَافَحَ» means to commit fornication (manjad). In Ibn al-Faris's words: «صَبَّ الْمَاء بِلَا عَقْدِ نِکَاحٍ» i.e., to commit fornication without a marriage contract. So, the difference between fornication (zina) and «سَافَحَ» is that the latter implies repetition. The Quran has confirmed this by using the word «مُسَافِحِیْن» in contrast to «مُحْصِنِیْن». Thus, «سَافَحَ» means in our language 'to keep as a concubine' (i.e., a woman with whom one establishes a sexual relationship without marriage). And «مُسَافِح» means such a woman or man who have open, public relations with each other. The word 'ashna' is also used nowadays in this very sense.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَانۡکِحُوۡہُنَّ بِاِذۡنِ اَہۡلِہِنَّ وَ اٰتُوۡہُنَّ اُجُوۡرَہُنَّ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ مُحۡصَنٰتٍ غَیۡرَ مُسٰفِحٰتٍ وَّ لَا مُتَّخِذٰتِ اَخۡدَانٍ» ( 4/25 )\nTranslation: Then marry them with the permission of their owners and give them their dowry according to what is reasonable, [being] chaste women, not those who commit open fornication, nor those who take paramours."
    },
    {
      "id": 445,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Adultery / Fornication",
      "hw": "بدکاری",
      "s": "«فَاحِشَۃ» Used for acts and words that lead towards adultery. Or it refers to an accusation of adultery that requires evidence (23 Verses: 2:169-2:268-3:135-4:15-4:19-4:22-4:25-6:151-7:28-7:33-7:80-12:24-16:90-17:32-24:19-24:21-27:54-29:28-29:45-33:30-42:37-53:32-65:1)",
      "d": "«فَحَشَ» means any statement or action that is excessive in ugliness (corruption) and evil (muf m l). And 'fahisha' refers to such statements and actions that lead towards adultery—i.e., obscene acts and words. The Quran has used this word repeatedly in these meanings. For adultery itself, the phrase «فَاحِشَۃٍ مُبَیِّنَۃ» (clear adultery) is used.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَا تَعۡضُلُوۡہُنَّ لِتَذۡہَبُوۡا بِبَعۡضِ مَاۤ اٰتَیۡتُمُوۡہُنَّ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡنَ بِفَاحِشَۃٍ مُّبَیِّنَۃٍ» ( 4/19 )\nTranslation: And do not withhold from them [their due] in order to take [back] some of what you gave them, unless they commit a clear immorality.\nAnd the word 'fahisha' is used for an act of adultery where the proof is not yet established.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَالّٰتِیۡ یَاۡتِیۡنَ الۡفَاحِشَۃَ مِنۡ نِّسَآئِکُمۡ فَاسۡتَشۡہِدُوۡا عَلَیۡہِنَّ اَرۡبَعَۃً مِّنۡکُمۡ» ( 4/15 )\nTranslation: O believers! Those among your women who commit lewdness—bring four witnesses from among you against them."
    }
  ],
  "94": [
    {
      "id": 446,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To substitute",
      "hw": "بدل",
      "s": "«بَدَّلَ» means to terminate one thing and bring another in its place (33 verses: 2:59-2:61-2:108-2:181-2:211-4:2-4:56-6:34-6:115-7:95-7:162-9:39-10:15-14:28-14:48-16:101-18:27-18:81-24:55-25:70-27:11-33:23-33:52-34:16-40:26-47:38-48:15-50:29-56:61-66:5-68:32-70:41-76:28)",
      "d": "«بَدَلَ» is a well-known term meaning to bring one thing in place of another (transitive). Essentially, the original intention was for the first thing, but something else took its place."
    },
    {
      "id": 450,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To change",
      "hw": "بدل",
      "s": "«نَکَّرَ» to change the form (1 آیات: 27:41-)",
      "d": "In «نَکَّرَ», two basic elements are found: (1) strangeness and (2) dislike. The opposite of تنکیر is تعریف, and the opposite of منکر is معروف. تنکیر means not to recognize someone, and تعریف means to recognize someone. اسم نکرہ and اسم معرفہ are well-known terms. And منکر means bad deeds, while معروف means good deeds. «نَکَّرَ» also means to make something indefinite (منجد), and to change the form of something so that it appears strange.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَ نَـکِّرُوۡا لَہَا عَرۡشَہَا» (27/41)\nTranslation: Solomon ﷺ said, Change the appearance of her throne for her."
    },
    {
      "id": 451,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To change",
      "hw": "بدل",
      "s": "«دَاوَل» to exchange and bring to a better state (1 آیات: 3:140)",
      "d": "«اَلدَّوْلَۃ وَالدُّوْلَۃ» means to rotate or alternate. The opposite of «دَالَ» is «دَارَ». The words «دَوْر» and «دَائِرَۃ» come in contexts of poverty, adversity, and the rotation of days. And «دَوْلَۃُ» refers to turning from bad days to days of prosperity. And «دَاوَل» means to exchange days of prosperity or to alternate them (مف منجد).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ تِلۡکَ الۡاَیَّامُ نُدَاوِلُہَا بَیۡنَ النَّاسِ» (3/140)\nTranslation: And those days – We alternate them among the people."
    }
  ],
  "95": [
    {
      "id": 452,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Compensation",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "«بَدَلَ» is the general term for compensation, whether less or more, good or bad (6 verses: 18:50-24:55-25:70-33:52-66:5-68:32)",
      "d": "«بَدَلَ» means to bring one thing in place of another (transitive), and this can be less or more, good or bad, similar or different. Essentially, it is a general term for compensation. We limit ourselves to two examples here:\n\n(1) For example, the Quran says: «اَفَتَتَّخِذُوۡنَہٗ وَذُرِّیَّتَہٗۤ اَوۡلِیَآءَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِیۡ وَہُمۡ لَکُمۡ عَدُوٌّ ؕ بِئۡسَ لِلظّٰلِمِیۡنَ بَدَلًا» (18/50)\nTranslation: Do you take Satan and his offspring as allies instead of Me, while they are your enemies? Evil is the compensation for the wrongdoers. (Jalandhari)\n\nAt another place, God Almighty says:\n(2) «اِلَّا مَنۡ تَابَ وَاٰمَنَ وَعَمِلَ عَمَلًا صَالِحًا فَاُولٰٓئِکَ یُبَدِّلُ اللّٰہُ سَیِّاٰتِہِمۡ حَسَنٰتٍ» (25/70)\nTranslation: But whoever repents, believes, and does righteous deeds, for them Allah will change their evil deeds into good ones."
    },
    {
      "id": 454,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Just compensation",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "«عَدْل» means balanced, equal, and proportionate compensation to the original thing (24 verses: 2:48-2:123-2:282-4:3-4:58-4:129-4:135-5:8-5:95-5:106-6:1-6:70-6:115-6:150-6:152-7:159-7:181-16:76-16:90-27:60-42:15-49:9-65:2-82:7)",
      "d": "«عَدْل» is compensation that is balanced, equal, and proportionate to the original thing. (See details under 'to do justice').\n\nFor example, the Quran says: «وَّلَا یُقۡبَلُ مِنۡہَا شَفَاعَۃٌ وَّلَا یُؤۡخَذُ مِنۡہَا عَدۡلٌ» (2/48)\nTranslation: Neither intercession will be accepted from it, nor will any compensation be taken from it."
    },
    {
      "id": 455,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Reward",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "«اَجْر» predetermined reward. Compensation for service. (87 verses: 2:62-2:112-2:262-2:274-2:277-3:136-3:171-3:172-3:179-3:199-4:40-4:67-4:74-4:95-4:100-4:114-4:146-4:162-5:9-6:90-7:113-7:170-8:28-9:22-9:120-10:72-11:11-11:29-11:51-11:115-12:56-12:57-12:90-12:104-16:41-16:96-16:97-17:9-18:2-18:30-18:77-25:57-26:41-26:109-26:127-26:145-26:164-26:180-28:25-28:26-28:27-28:54-29:27-29:58-33:29-33:31-33:35-33:44-34:47-35:7-36:11-36:21-38:86-39:10-39:35-39:74-41:8-42:23-42:40-48:10-48:16-48:29-49:3-52:40-57:7-57:11-57:18-57:19-57:27-64:15-65:5-67:12-68:3-68:46-73:20-84:25-95:6)",
      "d": "«اَجْر» and «اُجْرَۃ» is the reward that has been predetermined by a prior covenant, or at the time of need, «آجِر» (the one who gives reward) announces the reward, and «اَجِیْر» (the one to whom reward is given) accepts it and starts the work. This is compensation for work. And it is generally used for beneficial reward. The word أَجْر comes for both religious and worldly rewards. But the word أُجْرَة is generally used for worldly compensation. And «اٰجِرْ» refers to the one who takes on work, and «اَجِیْر» to the one who gives work, the servant, or the one receiving compensation (Muf). And «اِسْتَاْجَرَ» means to hire someone as a laborer or servant. The use of أَجْر is mentioned in the Quran in both religious and worldly contexts.\n\nExample (1): The Quran says:\n«وَلَاَجۡرُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ خَیۡرٌ لِّلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَکَانُوۡا یَتَّقُوۡنَ» (12/57)\nTranslation: And for those who believed and remained conscious of Allah, the reward of the Hereafter is best.\n\nExample (2): The Quran says:\n«قَالَ اِنِّیۡۤ  اُرِیۡدُ اَنۡ اُنۡکِحَکَ اِحۡدَی ابۡنَتَیَّ ہٰتَیۡنِ عَلٰۤی اَنۡ تَاۡجُرَنِیۡ ثَمٰنِیَ حِجَجٍ» (28/27)\nTranslation: He said, \"Indeed, I wish to marry one of my two daughters to you, on the condition that you serve me for eight years.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 457,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Reward",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "«ثَوَاب» meaning good reward for good deeds. (16 verses: 2:103-2:125-3:145-3:148-3:153-3:195-4:134-5:60-5:85-18:31-18:44-18:46-19:76-28:80-48:18-83:36)",
      "d": "The basic meanings of «ثَوَاب» are to come again and return. And «یَثُوْبُ اِلَیْہِ النَّاس» means that people come and go to that person frequently. In the Quran, this word has been used in these meanings as well.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَاِذۡ جَعَلۡنَا الۡبَیۡتَ مَثَابَۃً لِّلنَّاسِ وَ اَمۡنًا» (2/125)\nTranslation: And when We made the House a place of return for the people and [a place of] security.\n\nThus, the reward that a person receives for his deeds is called ثواب (Muf). Although its use can be for both good and evil, but generally it comes for good reward for good deeds.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«فَاٰتٰىہُمُ اللّٰہُ ثَوَابَ الدُّنۡیَا وَ حُسۡنَ ثَوَابِ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ» (3/148)\nTranslation: So Allah gave them the reward of this world and the good reward of the Hereafter.\n\nAt another place, the divine command says:\n«ہَلۡ  ثُوِّبَ الۡکُفَّارُ  مَا کَانُوۡا یَفۡعَلُوۡنَ» (83/36)\nTranslation: Then the disbelievers will be recompensed for what they used to do.\nIn this verse, the word ثواب has been used sarcastically."
    },
    {
      "id": 460,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Reward",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "«وَبَال» severe punishment in the form of recompense. (4 verses: 5:95-59:15-64:5-65:9)",
      "d": "The basic meanings of «وَبَل» include «شِدَّۃ» and «ثَقَل» (Muf, Majma). And it means to beat with a stick. And the word وبال is used for the severe punishment of a bad deed. This punishment may be in this world or the Hereafter. But mostly it is found in the form of worldly seizure or recompense.\n\nNow see examples:\nExample (1): وبال in the form of expiation:\nThe divine command says:\n«اَوۡ کَفَّارَۃٌ  طَعَامُ مَسٰکِیۡنَ اَوۡ عَدۡلُ ذٰلِکَ صِیَامًا لِّیَذُوۡقَ وَبَالَ اَمۡرِہٖ» (5/95)\nTranslation: Or an expiation: the feeding of the poor or the equivalent of that in fasting, so that he may taste the consequence of his deed.\n\nExample (2): The divine command says:\n«کَمَثَلِ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ قَرِیۡبًا ذَاقُوۡا وَبَالَ اَمۡرِہِمۡ ۚ وَلَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ» (59/15)\nTranslation: Their example is that of those who, before them, tasted the consequence of their deeds; and for them is a painful punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 461,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Reward",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "«قِصَاص» retribution for unjust killing and bodily harm. (4 verses: 2:178-2:179-2:194-5:45)",
      "d": "«قِصَاص» means to recompense for an action (Majma). And قصاص generally relates to human blood and its limbs and organs. An example of this has already passed under the same title in section b, however, it is not necessary.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«اَلشَّہۡرُالۡحَرَامُ بِالشَّہۡرِالۡحَرَامِ وَالۡحُرُمٰتُ قِصَاصٌ» (2/194)\nTranslation: The sacred month is for the sacred month, and the sacred things are [subject to] retaliation."
    },
    {
      "id": 463,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Blood money",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "«دِیَۃٌ» means blood money paid by the killer or his heirs to the heirs of the victim (1 verse: 4:92)",
      "d": "«( وَدِی ) وَدَی یَدِیْ وَدْیًا وَدِیَۃً» means for the killer or his heirs to pay blood money to the heirs of the victim. «اَوْدٰی» means to shed someone's blood unlawfully, and «دِیَۃٌ» is the wealth given in place of the victim's life by the killer or his heirs (transitive).\n\nFor example, the Quran says: «وَ مَنۡ قَتَلَ مُؤۡمِنًا خَطَئًا فَتَحۡرِیۡرُ رَقَبَۃٍ مُّؤۡمِنَۃٍ وَّ دِیَۃٌ مُّسَلَّمَۃٌ اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہٖۤ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ یَّصَّدَّقُوۡا» (4/92)\nTranslation: And whoever kills a believer unintentionally, then he must free a believing slave and pay blood money to the victim's heirs, unless they remit it as charity."
    },
    {
      "id": 465,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To take revenge",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "«عَذَّبَ» is used for severe punishment (45 verses: 2:284-3:56-3:128-3:129-4:173-5:18-5:40-5:115-5:118-7:164-8:33-8:34-9:14-9:26-9:39-9:55-9:66-9:74-9:85-9:101-9:106-17:15-17:54-17:58-18:86-18:87-20:47-26:138-26:213-27:21-29:21-33:24-33:73-34:35-37:59-48:6-48:14-48:16-48:17-48:25-58:8-59:3-65:8-88:24-89:25)",
      "d": "«عَذُبَ» means to abandon food due to severe thirst, and «عَذْب» means sweet and pleasant drink or food, and «مَاءٌ عَذْبٌ» means cold and pleasant water, and «اَعْذَبْ» means to reach sweet water (Mufradat al-Mujam). However, this word in the form «باب تفعیل» loses its basic meaning and «عَذَّبَ» means to inflict severe hardship or punishment, to torment. Abuhawal defines it as «اَلْاَ لَمَ الْمُسْتَقِرّ» (i.e., something fixed and stable) (Fiqh al-Lughah 198). For example, in the Quran: «وَمَا کُنَّا مُعَذِّبِیۡنَ حَتّٰی نَبۡعَثَ رَسُوۡلًا» (17/15). Translation: And we do not punish until we send a messenger."
    },
    {
      "id": 466,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To take revenge",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "«دَانَ» is used to highlight the aspect of ruler and subject in reward and punishment (84 verses: 1:3-2:132-2:193-2:217-2:256-3:19-3:24-3:73-3:83-3:85-4:46-4:125-4:146-4:171-5:3-5:54-5:57-5:77-6:70-6:137-6:159-6:161-7:29-7:51-8:39-8:49-8:72-9:11-9:12-9:29-9:33-9:36-9:122-10:22-10:104-10:105-12:40-12:76-15:35-16:52-22:78-24:2-24:25-24:55-26:82-29:65-30:30-30:32-30:43-31:32-33:5-37:20-37:53-38:78-39:2-39:3-39:11-39:14-40:14-40:26-40:65-42:13-42:21-48:28-49:16-51:6-51:12-56:56-56:86-60:8-60:9-61:9-70:26-74:46-82:9-82:15-82:17-82:18-83:11-95:7-98:5-107:1-109:6-110:2)",
      "d": "The word «اَلدَّیْن» is used in a broad sense. Briefly, it has four meanings: (1) complete sovereignty; (2) complete worship and servitude. For example, in the Quran: «اَلَا لِلّٰہِ الدِّیۡنُ الۡخَالِصُ» (39/3). Translation: Know that sincere worship is due only to Allah. In this verse, the meanings of sovereignty and worship are both found. The third meaning is the law of reward and punishment. The fourth meaning is, according to this law, to give reward or punishment for good and bad deeds. For example, in the Quran: «مٰلک یومِ الدین» (1/3). Translation: Master of the Day of Recompense. In this verse, the third and fourth meanings are found. Another statement from Allah: «فَلَوۡ لَاۤ اِنۡ  کُنۡتُمۡ غَیۡرَ مَدِیۡنِیۡنَ تَرۡجِعُوۡنَہَاۤ اِنۡ  کُنۡتُمۡ صٰدِقِیۡنَ» (56/86،87). Translation: Then if you are free from being held accountable, why do you not return the soul (when it is leaving)? If you are truthful."
    },
    {
      "id": 467,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To take revenge",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "«عَاقَبَ» means to follow someone behind to take revenge for what they did (3 verses: 16:126-22:60-11:60)",
      "d": "The root «عَقَب» means heel and back, and «عَقَبَ» means to follow behind, and «عَاقِب» means to follow someone behind to call them to account and to punish (Mujam). For example, in the Quran: «وَ اِنۡ عَاقَبۡتُمۡ فَعَاقِبُوۡا بِمِثۚ مَا عُوۡقِبۡتُمۡ بِہٖ» (16/126). Translation: And if you punish, then punish with the like of what you were punished with."
    },
    {
      "id": 468,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To take revenge",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "«اِنْتَقَمَ» means to take revenge, to inflict punishment (12 verses: 3:4-5:95-7:136-14:47-15:79-30:47-32:22-39:37-43:25-43:41-43:55-44:16)",
      "d": "The verb «نَقَمَ» means to consider something bad and to find fault in it (Mujam, etc.). For example, in the Quran: «وَ مَا نَقَمُوۡا مِنۡہُمۡ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یُّؤۡمِنُوۡا بِاللّٰہِ الۡعَزِیۡزِالۡحَمِیۡدِ» (85/8). Translation: They found nothing blameworthy in them except that they believed in Allah, the Mighty, the Praiseworthy. And «اِنْتَقَام» means to take revenge, to inflict punishment, or to deprive someone of a blessing in anger over their bad deeds. According to Abu al-Balal al-Askari, the opposite of revenge is reward, and revenge means to deprive of reward (to take away) (Fiqh al-Lughah 199). For example, in the Quran: «وَمَنۡ اَظۡلَمُ مِمَّنۡ ذُکِّرَ بِاٰیٰتِ رَبِّہٖ ثُمَّ اَعۡرَضَ عَنۡہَا ؕ اِنَّا مِنَ الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ مُنۡتَقِمُوۡنَ» (32/22). Translation: And who is more unjust than one who is reminded of the signs of his Lord but then turns away from them? Indeed, we will take revenge from the criminals."
    }
  ],
  "96": [
    {
      "id": 470,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To become insane",
      "hw": "بدمست",
      "s": "«نَزَفَ» means the gradual, little-by-little cessation of a person's reason, degree by degree, i.e., to become insane (2 verses: 37:47-56:19)",
      "d": "«نَزَفَ» means the gradual, little-by-little cessation of something, degree by degree. «نَزَفَ الْمَاءَ الْبِئْرَ» means to draw out all the water little by little from a well, and «نُزِفَ الْمَآء» means the water gradually ceases. Likewise, «نُزِفَ دَمْعَہٗ» means tears cease to flow from the eyes or dry up. And «نُزِفَ الرَّجُلُ» means a person's reason gradually ceases, degree by degree, i.e., to become insane, regardless of the cause (Mujam al-Mujam). For example, in the Quran: «لَّا یُصَدَّعُوۡنَ عَنۡہَا وَلَا یُنۡزِفُوۡنَ» (56/19). Translation: They will not suffer a headache from it, nor will they utter nonsense (Ottoman)."
    },
    {
      "id": 472,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To become insane",
      "hw": "بدمست",
      "s": "«سَکَرَ» refers to intoxication caused by drink; however, this word is also used in contexts of overwhelming love or terror (6 verses: 4:43-15:15-15:72-16:67-22:2-50:19)",
      "d": "The term «سُکَر» is generally used when intoxication occurs due to drink and the mind is lost; and «سَکَر» means any intoxicating substance. That is, whenever someone experiences intoxication, whether from overwhelming love or from the severity of death causing loss of mind, the term «سکّر» is used. «سَکْرَاتُ الْمَوْت» is a well-known expression. For example, in the Quran: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَقۡرَبُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَاَنۡتُمۡ سُکٰرٰی» (4/43). Translation: O you who have believed! Do not approach prayer while you are intoxicated."
    }
  ],
  "97": [
    {
      "id": 473,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bad / Evil",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "«بِئْسَ» is used to condemn a bad deed or evil statement (39 verses: 2:90-2:93-2:102-2:126-2:206-3:12-3:151-3:162-3:187-3:197-5:62-5:63-5:79-5:80-7:150-8:16-9:73-11:98-11:99-13:18-14:29-16:29-18:29-18:50-22:13-22:72-24:57-38:56-38:60-39:72-40:76-43:38-49:11-57:15-58:8-62:5-64:10-66:9-67:6)",
      "d": "«بِئْسَ» means bad; it is a word of blame, i.e., a word of condemnation, a past-tense invariant verb. It is used to condemn a bad deed or evil statement (Mujam). Its opposite is «نِعْمَ», meaning excellent, wonderful, how good, used for any kind of praise. For example, in the Quran: «فَحَسۡبُہٗ جَہَنَّمُ ؕ وَ لَبِئۡسَ الۡمِہَادُ» (2/206). Translation: Then Hell is sufficient for him, and what a wretched resting place! Note: (Invariant verb: a verb that remains only in one form and does not undergo conjugation, called an invariant verb, e.g., «نِعۡم» «عسی», etc.)."
    },
    {
      "id": 474,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bad / Evil",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "«شَرّ» means evil; it is used in the senses of bad, wickedness, and affliction — anything that everyone dislikes or that causes harm (29 verses: 2:216-3:180-5:60-8:22-8:55-10:11-12:77-17:11-17:83-19:75-21:35-22:72-24:11-25:34-38:55-38:62-41:49-41:51-70:20-72:10-76:7-76:11-98:6-99:8-113:2-113:3-113:4-113:5-114:4)",
      "d": "«شَرّ» is anything that everyone dislikes or that causes harm; its opposite is «خَیْر», meaning what is good and liked by all (Mujam). The word «شَرّ» is used in the senses of bad, wickedness, and affliction. A spark of fire is called a «شرارة», and its plural is «شرر». Moreover, «شرارت» is any hidden act whereby harm can be done to someone. A wicked person is called a «شریر», and its plural is «أَشْرَار». For example, in the Quran: «وَ عَسٰۤی اَنۡ تَکۡرَہُوۡا شَیۡئًا وَّ ہُوَ خَیۡرٌ لَّکُمۡ ۚ وَ عَسٰۤی اَنۡ تُحِبُّوۡا شَیۡئًا وَّ ہُوَ شَرٌّ لَّکُمۡ» (2/216). Translation: Perhaps you dislike something while it is good for you, and perhaps you like something while it is bad for you. Another statement from Allah: «وَ قَالُوۡا مَا لَنَا لَا نَرٰی رِجَالًا کُنَّا نَعُدُّہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡاَشۡرَارِ» (38/62). Translation: And the inhabitants of Hell will say, 'What is the matter that we do not see men whom we used to count among the wicked?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 475,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bad / Evil",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "«سَاءَ» means to be ugly or bad, both outwardly and inwardly; its opposite is «حَسُنَ» (139 verses: 2:49-2:81-2:169-2:271-3:30-3:120-3:174-3:193-3:195-4:17-4:18-4:22-4:31-4:38-4:78-4:79-4:85-4:97-4:110-4:115-4:123-4:148-4:149-5:12-5:65-5:66-6:31-6:54-6:136-6:157-6:160-7:73-7:95-7:131-7:141-7:153-7:165-7:167-7:168-7:177-7:188-8:29-9:9-9:37-9:98-9:102-10:27-11:10-11:54-11:64-11:78-11:114-12:24-12:25-12:51-12:53-13:6-13:11-13:18-13:21-13:22-13:25-14:6-16:25-16:27-16:28-16:34-16:45-16:59-16:60-16:94-16:119-17:7-17:32-17:38-18:29-19:28-20:22-20:101-21:74-21:77-23:96-25:40-25:66-25:70-26:156-26:173-27:5-27:11-27:12-27:46-27:58-27:62-27:90-28:32-28:54-28:84-29:4-29:7-30:10-30:36-33:17-35:8-35:10-35:43-37:177-39:24-39:47-39:48-39:51-39:61-40:9-40:37-40:40-40:45-40:52-40:58-41:34-41:46-42:25-42:40-42:48-45:15-45:21-45:33-46:16-47:2-47:14-48:5-48:6-48:12-53:31-58:15-60:2-63:2-64:9-65:5-66:8-67:27)",
      "d": "«سَاءَ» means to be ugly or reprehensible (Mujam); it denotes bad appearance or evil, both outwardly and inwardly. Its opposite is «حَسُنَ». Likewise, «سَیِّئَات» means bad deeds, whose opposite is «حَسَنَات». Only past and present (future) forms are derived from «سَاءَ». (1) For moral evil: For example, in the Quran: «وَ ہُمۡ یَحۡمِلُوۡنَ اَوۡزَارَہُمۡ عَلٰی ظُہُوۡرِہِمۡ ؕ اَلَا سَآءَ  مَا یَزِرُوۡنَ» (6/31). Translation: And they carry their burdens on their backs — look at what burdens they carry! How evil it is. (2) For outward ugliness: For example, a statement from Allah: «فَلَمَّا رَاَوۡہُ   زُلۡفَۃً  سِیۡٓئَتۡ وُجُوۡہُ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا» (67/27). Translation: So when they see it approaching — the promise — the faces of the disbelievers will become grim. Moreover, from «سَآءَ» comes the transitive verb «اَسَآءَ», meaning to spoil, to ruin, to do evil. For example, a statement from Allah: «فَاِذَا جَآءَ وَعۡدُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ  لِیَسُوۡٓءٗا  وُجُوۡہَکُمۡ» (17/7). Translation: Then when the promise of the Hereafter comes, (we have sent Our messengers) to disgrace your faces. And «سَوْء» means evil, wickedness, inherent in something; «اِمْرَأَسَوْءٍ» means a wicked woman; «سُوْءٓ» means a defect, an evil deed; and «مُسِیْء» means one who does evil, a wrongdoer. For example, a statement from Allah: «وَ الَّذِیۡنَ  اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ وَ لَا الۡمُسِیۡٓءُ» (40/58). Translation: And those who believe and do good deeds — and no wrongdoer (will be equal to them)."
    },
    {
      "id": 476,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bad / Evil",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "«قَبَحَ» means to be in a bad state or to have a bad appearance; it is used for the evil of speech, action, and form; generally used outwardly (1 verse: 28:42)",
      "d": "«قَبَحَ» means that speech, action, or form is evil, and «قبیح» means evil; «بَدَنما» (Mujam) indicates that this word is generally used for outward evil condition, and «قَبِیْح» means a bad state (Mujam), i.e., having a bad appearance or being ugly (Mujam). For example, in the Quran: «وَاَتۡبَعۡنٰہُمۡ فِیۡ ہٰذِہِ الدُّنۡیَا لَعۡنَۃً ۚ وَ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ ہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡمَقۡبُوۡحِیۡنَ» (28/42). Translation: And we have followed them in this world with a curse, and on the Day of Resurrection they will be among those who are made ugly."
    },
    {
      "id": 477,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To speak ill",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "«ذَمَّ» means to disgrace someone by mentioning their faults (3 verses: 17:18-17:22-68:49)",
      "d": "«ذَمَّ» means to do evil, to find faults. «أذَمَّ» means to consider insignificant and «تَذَمَّمَ» means to avoid someone and consider them shameful and disgraceful for oneself (Munjid). And «ذِمَام» means sanctity and honor, and «ذَمَّمَہٗ» means he greatly disgraced him (M. Q.). Thus, the word «ذَمَّ» is used for fault-finding or disgraceful acts that bring shame to the doer, and its opposite is «مَدَحَ» (to praise).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«ثُمَّ جَعَلۡنَا لَہٗ جَہَنَّمَ ۚ یَصۡلٰىہَا مَذۡمُوۡمًا مَّدۡحُوۡرًا» (17/18)\nTranslation: Then We have prepared for him Hell, wherein he will enter disgraced and humiliated."
    },
    {
      "id": 478,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To speak ill",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "«عَتَبَ» means to express mild reproach or resentment to remove displeasure (4 verses: 16:84-30:57-41:24-45:35)",
      "d": "«عَتَبَ» means to reproach, to show resentment. (This word is from lexical opposites.) «عَاتِب» means to reproach and to be angry, and also to address with disdain. And «اَعْتَبَ» means to cause displeasure to be removed, and «اِسْتَعْبَبَ» means to satisfy someone and to appease someone who is angry (Munjid). Thus, «عِتَاب» refers to such mild reproaches and criticisms whose ultimate purpose is to gain satisfaction and acceptance. And the use of 'ataab' also applies to ruining relationships of friendship and compassion (Faqih 39).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَاِنۡ یَّسۡتَعۡتِبُوۡا فَمَا ہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡمُعۡتَبِیۡنَ» (41/24)\nTranslation: If they seek to be appeased, they will not be the ones who are appeased.\nNote: (Lexical opposites are words that have two separate meanings that are opposite to each other.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 479,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To speak ill",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "«لَامَ» means to blame someone for their action or to warn them of its consequences (11 verses: 5:54-14:22-17:29-17:39-23:6-37:142-51:40-51:54-68:30-70:30-75:2)",
      "d": "«لَامَ» means to consider an action bad and then blame the doer (Mufradat), whether the action is inherently bad or not, and also to warn someone about the consequences of their action (Faqih 39).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«یُجَاہِدُوۡنَ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ وَلَا یَخَافُوۡنَ لَوۡمَۃَ لَآئِمٍ» (5/54)\nTranslation: They strive in the way of Allah and do not fear the blame of any blamer."
    },
    {
      "id": 481,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To speak ill",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "«ثَرَّبَ» means to reproach and scold someone for their bad deed (1 verse: 12:92)",
      "d": "«ثَرَّبَ» means to reproach and scold someone for their bad deed (Mufradat)\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«لَا تَثۡرِیۡبَ عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡیَوۡمَ ؕ یَغۡفِرُ اللّٰہُ لَکُمۡ» (12/92)\nTranslation: (Prophet Yusuf said to his brothers) There is no blame on you today. May Allah forgive you."
    },
    {
      "id": 482,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To seem bad",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "«نُکُر» means anything that is offensive or disliked in the eyes of common people (7 verses: 11:70-18:74-18:87-27:41-31:19-54:6-65:8)",
      "d": "«نُکُر» essentially has two aspects: (1) strangeness, (2) offensiveness. And «اَنْکَرَ» means to deny, and also to be amazed (i.e., to consider something surprising). And «مُنْکَر» means anything that is disliked in the eyes of common society or that Sharia has declared disliked. And «نُکُر» means such a bad thing that is offensive to everyone and seems bad.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«فَتَوَلَّ عَنۡہِمۡ ۘ یَوۡمَ یَدۡعُ الدَّاعِ اِلٰی شَیۡءٍ نُّکُرٍ» (54/6)\nTranslation: So turn away from them until the Day when the caller will call to something offensive."
    }
  ],
  "98": [
    {
      "id": 484,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Equality ۔ To be equal ۔ To make equal",
      "hw": "برابر",
      "s": "«عَدْل» refers to equality in things related to measurement, weight, or perceptible by external senses (24 verses: 2:48-2:123-2:282-4:3-4:58-4:129-4:135-5:8-5:95-5:106-6:1-6:70-6:115-6:150-6:152-7:159-7:181-16:76-16:90-27:60-42:15-49:9-65:2-82:7)",
      "d": "«عَدْل» refers to equality in things related to measurement, weight, or perceptible by external senses (Mufradat). Based on these external senses, 'adl' is also called justice.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«اَوۡعَدۡلُ ذٰلِکَ صِیَامًا لِّیَذُوۡقَ وَبَالَ اَمۡرِہٖ» (5/95)\nTranslation: Or the equivalent of that in fasting, so that he may taste the consequence of his deed."
    },
    {
      "id": 485,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Equality ۔ To be equal ۔ To make equal",
      "hw": "برابر",
      "s": "«سَوَاء ، اَسْتَوٰی» is used for the state or quantity being completely equal (54 verses: 2:6-2:29-2:108-3:64-3:113-4:89-4:95-5:12-5:60-5:77-5:100-6:50-7:193-8:58-9:19-11:24-13:10-13:16-14:21-16:71-16:75-16:76-18:37-21:109-22:25-26:136-28:22-30:28-32:9-32:18-35:12-35:19-35:22-36:10-37:55-38:22-39:9-39:29-40:58-41:10-41:34-44:47-45:21-48:29-52:16-53:3-57:10-59:20-60:1-63:6-79:28-82:7-91:7-91:14)",
      "d": "«سَوَاء ، اَسْتَوٰی» are used for equality in state and quantity (Mufradat, Faqih 128).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا سَوَآءٌ عَلَیۡہِمۡ ءَاَنۡذَرۡتَہُمۡ اَمۡ لَمۡ تُنۡذِرۡہُمۡ» (2/6)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who disbelieve, it is all the same to them whether you warn them or do not warn them.\nAt another place, Allah says:\n«ہَلۡ یَسۡتَوِی الۡاَعۡمٰی وَ الۡبَصِیۡرُ ۬ ۙ اَمۡ ہَلۡ تَسۡتَوِی الظُّلُمٰتُ وَ النُّوۡرُ» (13/16)\nTranslation: Can the blind and the seeing be equal? Or can the darkness and the light be equal?\nAnd «اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی» means to sit firmly on something. And for making quantity or state equal, the word «سَوّٰی» is used. In the following verse, both words appear together:\n«الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَکَ فَسَوّٰىکَ فَعَدَلَکَ» (82/7)\nTranslation: The One who created you, then made you firm, then made you equal (proportionate and balanced).\nAnd the word «سَوّٰی» is also wide in meaning. It includes completing, making equal, making correct and proper, everything."
    }
  ],
  "99": [
    {
      "id": 487,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be wasted. To do (to be wasted. To do)",
      "hw": "برباد",
      "s": "«حَبِطَ» meaning that an action does not yield results due to some other reasons. Good deeds being wasted due to bad deeds. (16 verses: 2:217-3:22-5:5-5:53-6:88-7:147-9:17-9:69-11:16-18:105-33:19-39:65-47:9-47:28-47:32-49:2)",
      "d": "«حَبِطَ» means to be wasted, to become void, to be rendered useless, and «حَبَِطَ دَمُّ الْقَتِیْل» means the blood of the murdered is wasted (Majma). That is, an action does not yield results due to some other reasons. Good deeds being wasted due to bad deeds (and if bad deeds are eliminated due to good deeds, that is called takfir, Fiqh 196).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ لَوۡ اَشۡرَکُوۡا لَحَبِطَ عَنۡہُمۡ  مَّا کَانُوۡا یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ» (6/88)\nTranslation: And if they had associated partners with Allah, whatever they used to do would have been wasted.\n\nAnd «اَحْبَطَ» means to make useless or to render wasted and destroyed.\nFor example: The Quran says:\nذٰلِکَ بِاَنَّہُمۡ کَرِہُوۡا مَاۤ  اَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ فَاَحۡبَطَ اَعۡمَالَہُمۡ (47/9)\nTranslation: That is because they disliked what Allah revealed, so He rendered their deeds worthless."
    },
    {
      "id": 488,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be wasted ۔ To waste (To be lost ۔ To lose)",
      "hw": "برباد",
      "s": "«بَطَلَ» means an opposing action that nullifies a previous action (10 verses: 2:264-7:118-7:173-8:8-10:81-29:48-30:58-40:78-45:27-47:33)",
      "d": "«بَطَلَ» means an invalid and baseless action is called «بَاطِل». Its opposite is truth. After investigation, that in which stability and permanence are not seen is batil (Mufradat). And «بَطَلَ» means to be futile and ineffective due to not having results. Like bad omen treatment makes the benefit ineffective, or treatment eliminates the effects of disease and ends it.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«فَوَقَعَ الۡحَقُّ وَ بَطَلَ مَا کَانُوۡا یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ» (7/118)\nTranslation: Then the truth prevailed, and what they used to do became false.\nAnd «اَبْطَلَ» means to make an action ineffective and fruitless, which is caused by an opposing action.\nFor example, Allah says:\n«لَا تُبۡطِلُوۡا صَدَقٰتِکُمۡ بِالۡمَنِّ وَالۡاَذٰی» (2/264)\nTranslation: Do not invalidate your charities by reminding (people of your favors) and causing them pain."
    },
    {
      "id": 489,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be wasted ۔ To waste (To be lost ۔ To lose)",
      "hw": "برباد",
      "s": "«اَضَاعَ» means to waste or ruin something for any reason (1 verse: 19:59)",
      "d": "«اَضَاعَ» means to waste, to destroy, to ruin, whether for any reason—it is general.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«فَخَلَفَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہِمۡ خَلۡفٌ اَضَاعُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَ اتَّبَعُوا الشَّہَوٰتِ فَسَوۡفَ یَلۡقَوۡنَ  غَیًّا» (19/59)\nTranslation: Then after them succeeded [unworthy] successors who neglected prayer and pursued desires. So they will meet evil."
    }
  ],
  "100": [
    {
      "id": 490,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Endurance",
      "hw": "برداشت",
      "s": "«حَلُمَ» means to maintain composure in times of grief and anger, and to delay punishment for one deserving of it, and to grant respite. (15 verses: 2:225-2:235-2:263-3:155-4:12-5:101-9:114-11:75-11:87-17:44-22:59-33:51-35:41-37:101-64:17)",
      "d": "«حَلُمَ» means to be forbearing and patient. This is a constant attribute that remains present in a patient person at all times. That is, when he hears something unpleasant, or suffers harm, or is disgraced, or hears something very pleasing, then no fluctuation occurs in his nature, or if it does, it is minor and remains stable. This is a highly praiseworthy attribute. Abu Halaal explains its meaning as «اِمھَال بِتَخِیْرِ الْعِقَابِ الْمُسْتَحَقٌ» (i.e., to delay the punishment of one deserving of it and grant respite). For example, the Quran states: «فَبَشَّرۡنٰہُ بِغُلٰمٍ حَلِیۡمٍ» (37/101). Translation: We gave Prophet Abraham (AS) the glad tidings of a forbearing son."
    },
    {
      "id": 492,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Endurance",
      "hw": "برداشت",
      "s": "«کَظَمَ» means to suppress grief and anger, no matter how intense, and not allow its expression. (6 verses: 3:134-12:84-16:58-40:18-43:17-68:48)",
      "d": "«کَظْم» refers to the windpipe. «کَظَمَ السِّقَاء» means to fill a skin with water and then close its mouth (figuratively). «کَظِیْم» and «مَکْظُوْم» describe a person filled with grief or anger up to the windpipe but who does not express it, nor is allowed to express it. For example, the Quran states: «وَابۡیَضَّتۡ عَیۡنٰہُ مِنَ الۡحُزۡنِ فَہُوَ کَظِیۡمٌ» (12/84). Translation: And Jacob's eyes turned white due to grief, and he was filled with grief. Regarding Prophet Yunus (AS), it is stated: «اِذۡ نَادٰی وَہُوَ مَکۡظُوۡمٌ» (68/48). Translation: When he called out while he was filled with grief and anger. Describing the believers, it is said: «وَالۡکٰظِمِیۡنَ الۡغَیۡظَ وَ الۡعَافِیۡنَ عَنِ النَّاسِ» (3:134). Translation: And those who suppress their anger and forgive people."
    }
  ],
  "101": [
    {
      "id": 494,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Great (Magnificent)",
      "hw": "بزرگ ",
      "s": "«عَظِیْم» in which greatness is accompanied by strength and intensity. Just as insignificant is lower than minor, similarly عظیم is above akbar. (110 verses: 2:7-2:49-2:105-2:114-2:255-3:74-3:105-3:172-3:174-3:176-3:179-4:13-4:27-4:40-4:48-4:54-4:67-4:73-4:74-4:93-4:95-4:113-4:114-4:146-4:156-4:162-5:9-5:33-5:41-5:119-6:15-7:59-7:116-7:141-8:28-8:29-8:68-9:20-9:22-9:63-9:72-9:89-9:100-9:101-9:111-9:129-10:15-10:64-12:28-14:6-15:87-16:94-16:106-17:40-19:37-21:76-22:1-23:86-24:11-24:14-24:15-24:16-24:23-26:63-26:135-26:156-26:189-27:23-27:26-28:79-31:13-33:29-33:35-33:53-33:71-37:60-37:76-37:107-37:115-38:67-39:13-40:9-41:35-42:4-43:31-44:57-45:10-46:21-48:5-48:10-48:29-49:3-56:46-56:74-56:76-56:96-57:10-57:12-57:21-57:29-61:12-62:4-64:9-64:15-68:4-69:33-69:52-73:20-78:2-83:5)",
      "d": "The opposite of «عَظِیْم» is «حَقِیْر» and the basic meanings of «اَعْظَمَ ، عَظْمٌ» include greatness along with strength and intensity. And these spiritual attributes are found collectively or individually. And bones are also called «عَظْم» due to their strength and intensity (Muf). Both «عَظْم» and «عَظِیْم» have the plural «عِظَام». The word «عَظِیْم» is used for both bodies and entities (i.e., great person or great rank) (Muf). And «اَعْظَمَ» is a detailed noun meaning very great and magnificent or the greatest and most magnificent.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n(1) «وَّ لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ عَظِیۡمٌ» (2/7)\nTranslation: And for those disbelievers is a great punishment.\n(2) «فَسَبِّحۡ  بِاسۡمِ  رَبِّکَ الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (56/96)\nTranslation: So glorify the name of your Lord, the Most Great.\n\nIn a group, there can be many «کَبِیْر» and «اَکْبَر», but «عَظِیْم» is only one (Fiqh 150)."
    },
    {
      "id": 495,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Great (Magnificent)",
      "hw": "بزرگ ",
      "s": "«ذُوالْجَلَال» greatness in honor and status; specifically for the blessed essence of Allah alone. (2 verses: 55:27-55:78)",
      "d": "«جَلَال» means greatness in honor and status. «ذُوْالْجَلَال» means «عَظِیمُ الْمَرْتَبَت» i.e., of great rank, and «جَلِیْل» means one who creates great and magnificent things (Muf) and means the entity worthy of praise due to His magnificent works (Fiqh 150).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«تَبٰرَکَ اسۡمُ رَبِّکَ ذِی الۡجَلٰلِ وَالۡاِکۡرَامِ» (55/78)\nTranslation: Blessed is the name of your Lord, the Possessor of Majesty and Honor. (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 496,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Great (Magnificent)",
      "hw": "بزرگ ",
      "s": "«مَجِیْد» the entity that has reached the utmost limit in glory, honor, and nobility. (4 verses: 11:73-50:1-85:15-85:21)",
      "d": "The meanings of «مَجِیْد» are to be vast in glory and honor (Muf). And according to Ibn al-Faris: one who has reached the utmost limit in grace, honor, and nobility (M. L). And «مَجِیْد» means one who is great in people's sight (M. Q).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَہُوَالۡغَفُوۡرُ الۡوَدُوۡدُ ذُوالۡعَرۡشِ الۡمَجِیۡدُ» (85:14,15)\nTranslation: And He is the Forgiving, the Affectionate, the Owner of the Throne, the Magnificent."
    },
    {
      "id": 498,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Greatness (Magnificence)",
      "hw": "بزرگ ",
      "s": "«جَلَالْ» the ultimate degree of greatness in honor and status. (2 verses: 55:27-55:78)",
      "d": "«جَلَالْ» is greatness in honor and status, the ultimate degree after which there is no other rank. And the word «ذُوالجلال» is specific only to Allah the Almighty. Whereas «جَلِیْل» can be for other things as well. And «جَلِیْل» is everything that is great and strong in all matters. Magnificent (Muf).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«تَبٰرَکَ اسۡمُ رَبِّکَ ذِی الۡجَلٰلِ وَالۡاِکۡرَامِ» (55/78)\nTranslation: Blessed is the name of your Lord, the Possessor of Majesty and Honor."
    },
    {
      "id": 499,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Greatness (Magnificence)",
      "hw": "بزرگ ",
      "s": "«جَدّ» divine grace, as He grants greatness to others as well. (1 verse: 72:3)",
      "d": "«جَدّ» means divine grace and means luck and fortune. «جُدِدْتُ» means became fortunate and blessed. And «جَدَّ» means to bestow worldly wealth and status on someone. Also «جَدّ» means ancestral lineage (Muf). «جَدّ» means grandfather; plural «اَجْدَاد». And means good fortune, greatness, wealth, sustenance, and «فُلَانٌ ذُوْجَدٍّ» means that person is very fortunate (Majma).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَّاَنَّہٗ تَعٰلٰی جَدُّ رَبِّنَا مَا اتَّخَذَ صَاحِبَۃً وَّلَا وَلَدًا» (72/3)\nTranslation: And indeed, the greatness of our Lord is exalted; He has not taken a wife or a son."
    }
  ],
  "102": [
    {
      "id": 502,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Increase and Causing Increase",
      "hw": "بڑھنا",
      "s": "«ضَاعَفَ» is used to mean double or even more (10 verses: 2:245-2:261-3:130-4:40-11:20-25:69-33:30-57:11-57:18-64:17)",
      "d": "«ضِعْفٌ» means double; its opposite is «نِصْف». «ضَعَفَ الشَّيء» means to have an amount equal to something else (whether the increase is in quantity or number). And «ضَعَّف» means to double, while «ضَاعَفَ» carries a greater degree of emphasis.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاللّٰہُ یُضٰعِفُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ ؕ وَاللّٰہُ وَاسِعٌ عَلِیۡمٌ» (2/261)\nTranslation: And Allah gives increase manifold to whom He wills. And Allah is All-Encompassing and Knowing."
    },
    {
      "id": 503,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Increase and to Cause to Increase",
      "hw": "بڑھنا",
      "s": "«عَفَا» means to leave something in its state so that it may increase. (2 verses: 2:219-7:95)",
      "d": "«عَفَا» generally means to forgive, but literally means to leave something so it may increase. «عَفَا اَلْشَعْر» means to leave hair to grow long. The Prophetic saying: «قَصُّوا الشَّوَارِبَ وَاعْفُوا اللُّحْیٰ» (Trim mustaches, let beards grow). This word is both intransitive and transitive. Example: «ثُمَّ بَدَّلۡنَا مَکَانَ السَّیِّئَۃَ الۡحَسَنَۃَ حَتّٰی عَفَوۡا» (7/95). Translation: Then We replaced the bad with the good until they increased. «عَفْو» also means surplus/unnecessary things. Example: «وَیَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ مَا ذَا یُنۡفِقُوۡنَ ۬ ؕ قُلِ الۡعَفۡوَ» Translation: They ask what to spend. Say: the surplus."
    },
    {
      "id": 504,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Increase and Causing Increase",
      "hw": "بڑھنا",
      "s": "«تَطَوُّع» means to do a good deed or give charity, etc., of one's own free will (7 verses: 2:158-2:184-3:83-9:53-9:79-13:15-41:11)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «طَوْع» is to obey with happiness of the heart. The original meaning of «تَطَوُّع» is to perform a command with great effort. However, in common usage, it refers to good deeds and acts of worship performed voluntarily, beyond the obligatory duties, out of one's own desire—such as voluntary prayers and charities.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَعَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ یُطِیۡقُوۡنَہٗ فِدۡیَۃٌ طَعَامُ مِسۡکِیۡنٍ ؕ فَمَنۡ تَطَوَّعَ خَیۡرًا فَہُوَ خَیۡرٌ لَّہٗ» (2/184)\nTranslation: And for those who cannot afford it, the expiation is the feeding of a poor person. Then whoever volunteers good (by doing more than the minimum), it is better for him."
    },
    {
      "id": 505,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Increase and Augmentation",
      "hw": "بڑھنا",
      "s": "«نَافِلَۃً» refers to voluntary acts of worship such as charity, tahajjud prayer, voluntary fasts, etc. (3 verses: 8:1-17:79-21:72)",
      "d": "«نَفْل» means addition to obligatory acts (pl.) and «اَنْفَال» refers to spoils of war. The difference between «نَفْل» and «تَطَوُّع» is that «تَطَوُّع» requires willingness and eagerness of the heart, for example: The Quran states: «وَمِنَ الَّیۡلِ فَتَہَجَّدۡ بِہٖ نَافِلَۃً لَّکَ» (17/79) Translation: And wake up at night and perform the tahajjud prayer. This is an increase for you."
    },
    {
      "id": 506,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Increase and Augmentation",
      "hw": "بڑھنا",
      "s": "«اَرْبٰی» means to nurture or raise something. (6 verses: 2:275-2:276-2:278-3:130-4:161-30:39)",
      "d": "«رِبَا الْمَال» means increase in wealth. And «رِبٰو» means usury. Extra addition without effort on the principal. «رِبَا الْفَرْس» means a horse's breathing becoming heavy, and «رِبَا الْوَلْد» means a child's growth and learning. And «اَرْبٰی» means to nurture or raise something. For example: The Quran states: «یَمۡحَقُ اللّٰہُ الرِّبٰوا وَیُرۡبِی الصَّدَقٰتِ» (2/276) Translation: Allah destroys usury and increases charities."
    }
  ],
  "103": [
    {
      "id": 507,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Settlement and its Inhabitants",
      "hw": "بستی",
      "s": "«قَرْیَۃ» means a settlement (village or city) and its residents. Any place where people gather and settle. (37 verses: 2:58-2:259-4:75-6:123-7:4-7:82-7:88-7:94-7:161-7:163-10:98-12:82-15:4-16:112-17:16-17:58-18:77-21:6-21:11-21:74-21:95-22:45-22:48-25:40-25:51-26:208-27:34-27:56-28:58-29:31-29:34-34:34-36:13-43:23-43:31-47:13-65:8)",
      "d": "«قَرْیَۃ» refers to any place where people gather and settle, whether it's a small settlement, village, town, or city. Its plural is «قُریٰ». And «اُمُّ الْقُرٰی» means the central settlement or city. Mecca is also called «اُمُّ الْقُرٰی». «قَرْیَۃ» can mean both the settlement and its inhabitants or residents (pl.). For example: The Quran states: «وَسۡئَلِ الۡقَرۡیَۃَ الَّتِیۡ کُنَّا فِیۡہَا» (12/82) Translation: And ask the people of the settlement in which we used to reside."
    },
    {
      "id": 508,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Settlement and its Inhabitants",
      "hw": "بستی",
      "s": "«بَدْوُ» means countryside, villages. Such a place where due to lack of tall structures, everything is clearly visible. (1 verse: 12:100)",
      "d": "«بَدْوُ» means village, countryside, or remote area. «بَدَا» means to appear, and «بَدْوُ» refers to a place where, due to absence of tall buildings, everything is prominently visible (pl.). From this, «بَادِیَۃٌ» means desert, «بَادِیٌ» means desert dweller, and «بَدَوِیٌّ» means rural. For example: The Quran states: «وَقَدۡ اَحۡسَنَ بِیۡۤ اِذۡ اَخۡرَجَنِیۡ مِنَ السِّجۡنِ وَجَآءَ بِکُمۡ مِّنَ الۡبَدۡوِ» (12/100) Translation: And He (Allah) favored me when He took me out of prison and brought you from the countryside."
    }
  ],
  "104": [
    {
      "id": 510,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Goat",
      "hw": "بکری",
      "s": "«غَنَم» is used specifically for herds of goats. (4 verses: 6:146-8:41-20:18-21:78)",
      "d": "Originally, «غَنَم» meant property that comes into one's possession without prior ownership. Then this word was used for goat herds that were acquired. Later, it also applied to spoils taken from the enemy in battle. For example: The Quran states: «وَاعۡلَمُوۡۤا اَنَّمَا غَنِمۡتُمۡ مِّنۡ شَیۡءٍ» (8/41) Translation: And know that whatever you have taken as spoils. Then the usage of this word became specific to goat herds. For example: The Quran states: «وَدَاوٗدَ وَ سُلَیۡمٰنَ اِذۡ یَحۡکُمٰنِ فِی الۡحَرۡثِ اِذۡ نَفَشَتۡ فِیۡہِ غَنَمُ الۡقَوۡمِ» (21/78) Translation: And (mention) David and Solomon when they judged concerning the field when the people's goats had grazed therein at night (and damaged it)."
    },
    {
      "id": 511,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Goat",
      "hw": "بکری",
      "s": "«مَعَزَ» is used in the sense of separating goats from sheep. (1 verse: 6:143)",
      "d": "«مَعَزَ» is used in the sense of separating goats from sheep. Goats are a single gender category. Both goat and he-goat are referred to by the same term, and its singular is «مَاعِز». For example: The Quran states: «مِنَ الضَّاۡنِ اثۡنَیۡنِ وَمِنَ الۡمَعۡزِاثۡنَیۡنِ» (6/143) Translation: From the sheep, two (male and female), and from the goats, two (male and female)."
    }
  ],
  "105": [
    {
      "id": 512,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Scattering (to be dispersed)",
      "hw": "بکھرنا",
      "s": "«اِنْبَثَّ» means to become scattered and spread far and wide. (Without intention) (1 verse: 56:6)",
      "d": "«بَثَّ» means to scatter and spread far and wide. And «اِنْبَثَّ» means for something to become scattered and spread in all directions far away. There is no element of intention in its scattering. For example: The Quran states: «وَّ  بُسَّتِ الۡجِبَالُ  بَسًّا فَکَانَتۡ ہَبَآءً  مُّنۡۢبَثًّا» (56/5,6) Translation: And the mountains will be broken into pieces, so they will become dust scattered about."
    },
    {
      "id": 513,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Scattering (to be dispersed)",
      "hw": "بکھرنا",
      "s": "«اِنْتَشَرَ» means a group dispersing and each going their own way. (By their own intention) (4 verses: 30:20-33:53-54:7-62:10)",
      "d": "«نشر» means to spread and make known. And «اِنْتَشَر» means for people to rise from a gathering and each take their own path. (By their own intention) For example: The Quran states: «فَاِذَا قُضِیَتِ الصَّلٰوۃُ فَانۡتَشِرُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَابۡتَغُوۡا مِنۡ فَضۡلِ اللّٰہِ» (62/10) Translation: Then when the prayer is concluded, disperse in the land and seek the bounty of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 514,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Scattering (to be dispersed)",
      "hw": "بکھرنا",
      "s": "«اِنْفَضَّ» means the gradual scattering of all parts of something and dispersing. (3 verses: 3:159-62:11-63:7)",
      "d": "«فَضَّ» means to break something in such a way that it becomes separate pieces. And «اِنْفِضَاض» means for glass, etc., to break into pieces and become separate gradually. So «اِنْفَضَّ» means for all parts of something to become scattered and dispersed. For example: The Quran states: «وَاِذَا رَاَوۡتِجَارَۃً اَوۡ لَہۡوَۨا انۡفَضُّوۡۤا اِلَیۡہَا وَتَرَکُوۡکَ قَآئِمًا» (62/11) Translation: And when they see a transaction or a diversion, they scatter towards it and leave you standing."
    },
    {
      "id": 515,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Scattering (Becoming Scattered)",
      "hw": "بکھرنا",
      "s": "«اِنْتَثَرَ» means to separate and fall down (used for non-living things) (1 verse: 82:2)",
      "d": "«نَثَرَ» refers to anything that falls off and separates from something else, scatters. And «اِنْتِشَار» means to scatter by blowing the nose. (According to Ibn Faris) the meaning of «نَثَر» is to throw a scattered thing down. In his own words, it is «کلمۃ تَدُلُّ عَلیٰ اِلْقَاءِ شَیْءٍ مُّتَفَرِّقٍ». Also, «نَثَر» is used for non-verse prose (i.e., prose without order or meter). Furthermore, «اِنْتَثَر» is used only for non-living things.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِذَا السَّمَآءُ انۡفَطَرَتۡ وَاِذَا الۡکَوَاکِبُ انۡتَثَرَتۡ» (82/1,2)\nTranslation: When the heaven splits asunder, and when the stars scatter."
    },
    {
      "id": 516,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to scatter (to become dispersed)",
      "hw": "بکھرنا",
      "s": "«اِسْتَطَارَ» means for something to scatter and spread out in the air (1 verse: 76:7)",
      "d": "«طَارَ» means to fly (like a winged creature or thing) in the air, and «طَائِرُ» means a bird, its plural is «طَيْرٌ». «اِسْتَطَار» means for something to rise high in the air and then scatter and disperse.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یُوۡفُوۡنَ بِالنَّذۡرِ وَیَخَافُوۡنَ یَوۡمًا کَانَ شَرُّہٗ  مُسۡتَطِیۡرًا» (76/7)\nTranslation: They fulfill their vows and fear a day whose evil will be widespread."
    }
  ],
  "106": [
    {
      "id": 517,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to raise (to make high)",
      "hw": "بلند",
      "s": "«رَفَعَ» means to lift something from the ground, to make it high (22 verses: 2:63-2:93-2:127-2:253-4:154-4:158-6:83-6:165-7:176-12:76-12:100-13:2-19:57-24:36-35:10-43:32-49:2-55:7-58:11-79:28-88:18-94:4)",
      "d": "The meaning of «رَفَعَ» is to raise. If this verb relates to lifting and raising something from the ground, its opposite is «وَضَعَ». If it relates to raising a voice, its opposite is «خَفَضَ».\nFor example, for raising something, the Quran states:\n«وَاِذۡ یَرۡفَعُ  اِبۡرٰہٖمُ  الۡقَوَاعِدَ مِنَ الۡبَیۡتِ وَ اِسۡمٰعِیۡلُ» (2/127)\nTranslation: And when Abraham and Ishmael were raising the foundations of the House.\nAnd for raising a voice, the Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَرۡفَعُوۡۤا اَصۡوَاتَکُمۡ  فَوۡقَ صَوۡتِ النَّبِیِّ» (49/2)\nTranslation: O you who believe! Do not raise your voices above the voice of the Prophet."
    },
    {
      "id": 518,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to raise (to make high)",
      "hw": "بلند",
      "s": "«اَنْشَأ» means to create something. To nurture and to raise up (35 verses: 2:259-6:6-6:83-6:98-6:133-6:141-11:61-13:12-21:11-21:21-23:14-23:19-23:31-23:42-23:78-25:3-25:40-25:47-28:45-29:20-35:9-36:79-43:11-43:18-44:35-53:32-53:47-55:24-56:35-56:61-56:62-56:72-67:15-67:23-88:22-)",
      "d": "«نَشَو» means for something to rise and become high (intransitive). Its meaning also includes nurturing and bringing something to maturity (transitive). «نَشَاۃ» is used in the meaning of raising. Here, the aspect of 'becoming high' of this word is under discussion. And «اَنْشَأ» means to create something, to raise it, and to bring it to maturity.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ہُوَالَّذِیۡ یُرِیۡکُمُ  الۡبَرۡقَ خَوۡفًا وَّطَمَعًا وَّ یُنۡشِئُ السَّحَابَ الثِّقَالَ» (13/12)\nTranslation: He it is who shows you the lightning, causing fear and hope, and He creates the heavy clouds. (Jalandhari) He raises them. (Osmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 519,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to become high. to be elevated",
      "hw": "بلند",
      "s": "The use of «عَلَا» is general, but it is used for the height of tall trees, especially date palms (6 verses: 4:34-9:40-19:50-19:57-23:91-28:4)",
      "d": "«عَلَا» means to become high, and its opposite is «سَفَلَ». This word is used in both places for bodies/entities (i.e., for the rank of something) and for physical height. That is, it is used for the height of a place and a body, and also for the elevation of rank. Moreover, this word is used in both blameworthy (negative description) and praiseworthy (positive description) contexts.\nNow, observe the examples:\n(1) For the height of a place, the Quran states:\n«وَّرَفَعۡنٰہُ مَکَانًا عَلِیًّا» (19/57)\nTranslation: And We raised him to a high station. (Jalandhari) And We elevated him to an exalted place. (Osmani)\n(2) For the elevation of rank, the Quran states:\n«وَجَعَلۡنَا لَہُمۡ لِسَانَ صِدۡقٍ عَلِیًّا» (19/50)\nTranslation: And We granted them a high reputation for truth. (Jalandhari) And We made for them a true, exalted speech. (Osmani)\n(3) Example of a blameworthy context: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّ فِرۡعَوۡنَ عَلَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (28/4)\nTranslation: Indeed, Pharaoh exalted himself in the land."
    },
    {
      "id": 520,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to become high. to be elevated",
      "hw": "بلند",
      "s": "«بَسَقَ» literally means to become high. It is used for the height of tall and lofty trees, especially date palms (1 verse: 50:10)",
      "d": "«بَسَقَ» is used specifically for tall and lofty trees, especially the height of date palms. (F L 43)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَالنَّخۡلَ بٰسِقٰتٍ لَّہَا طَلۡعٌ نَّضِیۡدٌ» (50/10)\nTranslation: And the date-palms, tall, with their fruit in clusters."
    },
    {
      "id": 521,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to become high. to be elevated",
      "hw": "بلند",
      "s": "«شَمَخٌ» is used for the height of mountains and lofty buildings (1 verse: 77:27)",
      "d": "The word «شَمَخٌ» indicates that something is great and high (M L). It is used for the height of mountains and lofty buildings (F L 43), sky-touching height. For example: The Quran states:\n«وَّجَعَلۡنَا فِیۡہَا رَوَاسِیَ شٰمِخٰتٍ» (77/27)\nTranslation: And We placed therein lofty, firmly-set mountains."
    }
  ],
  "107": [
    {
      "id": 522,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to make",
      "hw": "بنانا",
      "s": "«جَعَلَ» its meanings are to make, but its usage is general, whether that work pertains to origination/creation or merely to arranging/giving a state (305 verses: 2:19-2:22-2:30-2:66-2:125-126-2:128-2:143-2:224-2:259-2:260-3:41-3:61-3:126-3:156-3:176-4:5-4:15-4:19-4:33-4:75-4:90-4:91-4:141-4:144-5:6-5:13-5:20-5:48-5:60-5:97-5:103-6:1-6:6-6:9-6:25-6:39-6:91-6:96-6:97-6:100-6:107-6:112-6:122-6:123-6:124-6:125-6:136-6:165-7:10-7:27-7:47-7:69-7:74-7:138-7:143-7:150-7:189-7:190-8:10-8:29-8:37-9:19-9:40-10:5-10:14-10:24-10:59-10:67-10:73-10:85-10:87-10:100-11:82-11:118-12:15-12:55-12:62-12:70-12:100-13:3-13:16-13:33-13:38-14:30-14:35-14:37-14:40-15:16-15:20-15:74-15:91-15:96-16:56-16:57-16:62-16:72-16:78-16:80-16:81-16:91-16:93-16:124-17:2-17:6-17:8-17:12-17:18-17:22-17:29-17:33-17:39-17:45-17:46-17:60-17:80-17:99-18:1-18:7-18:32-18:48-18:52-18:57-18:59-18:90-18:94-18:95-18:96-18:98-19:6-19:7-19:10-19:21-19:24-19:30-19:31-19:32-19:49-19:50-19:96-20:29-20:53-20:58-21:8-21:15-21:30-21:31-21:32-21:34-21:58-21:70-21:72-21:73-21:91-22:25-22:34-22:36-22:53-22:67-22:78-23:13-23:41-23:44-23:50-23:94-24:40-24:43-24:63-25:10-25:20-25:23-25:31-25:35-25:37-25:45-25:47-25:53-25:54-25:61-25:62-25:74-26:21-26:29-26:84-26:85-27:34-27:61-27:62-27:86-28:4-28:5-28:35-28:38-28:41-28:71-28:72-28:73-28:83-29:10-29:15-29:27-29:67-30:21-30:48-30:54-32:8-32:9-32:23-32:24-33:4-34:18-34:19-34:33-35:11-35:39-36:8-36:9-36:27-36:34-36:80-37:63-37:77-37:98-37:158-38:5-38:26-38:28-39:6-39:8-39:21-40:61-40:64-40:79-41:9-41:10-41:29-41:44-42:8-42:11-42:50-42:52-43:3-43:10-43:12-43:15-43:19-43:28-43:33-43:45-43:56-43:59-43:60-45:18-45:21-45:23-46:26-48:26-48:27-49:13-50:26-51:42-51:51-56:36-56:65-56:70-56:73-56:82-57:7-57:26-57:27-57:28-59:10-60:5-60:7-65:2-65:3-65:4-65:7-67:5-67:15-67:23-68:35-68:50-69:12-71:7-71:12-71:16-71:19-72:25-73:17-74:12-74:31-75:39-76:2-77:21-77:25-77:27-78:6-78:9-78:10-78:11-78:13-87:5-90:8-105:2-105:5)",
      "d": "The use of «جَعَلَ» for making is general. Whether that work pertains to origination and creation or merely to arranging/giving a state.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الۡاَرۡضَ فِرَاشًا وَّ السَّمَآءَ بِنَآءً» (2/22)\nTranslation: Who has made the earth a resting place for you and the sky a canopy."
    },
    {
      "id": 523,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to make",
      "hw": "بنانا",
      "s": "«بَنٰی» means to build a structure, etc. (10 verses: 9:109-9:110-16:26-18:21-37:97-40:36-50:6-51:47-61:4-78:12)",
      "d": "«بَنٰی» means to build a structure, etc. And «بُنْیَان» means structure, wall, or any construction (transitive). According to Ibn Faris, «بَنَاءَ الشَّیْ بِضَمٍّ بَعْضَہٗ اِلی١ بَعْضٍ» (M. L) (i.e., to build something in such a way that one part is joined to another).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَالسَّمَآءَ  بَنَیۡنٰہَا بِاَیۡىدٍ وَّ اِنَّا لَمُوۡسِعُوۡنَ» (51/47)\nTranslation: And the sky We built with might, and indeed, We are expanders."
    },
    {
      "id": 524,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to make",
      "hw": "بنانا",
      "s": "«صَنَعَ» means to make something with skilled craftsmanship (18 verses: 5:14-5:63-7:137-11:16-11:37-11:38-13:31-16:112-18:104-20:39-20:41-20:69-21:80-23:27-24:30-27:88-29:45-35:8)",
      "d": "«صَنَعَ» means to make something beautifully with skilled craftsmanship (transitive). And «صَنَّاع» refers to a skilled craftsman or artist. And «اِصْطَنَعَ» means to make something with skilled craftsmanship and special attention (transitive).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاصۡنَعِ الۡفُلۡکَ بِاَعۡیُنِنَا وَ وَحۡیِنَا» (11/37)\nTranslation: And construct the ship under Our observation and Our inspiration.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَاصۡطَنَعۡتُکَ لِنَفۡسِیۡ» (20/41)\nTranslation: And I chose you for Myself."
    },
    {
      "id": 525,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to make",
      "hw": "بنانا",
      "s": "«اِتَّخَذَ», by taking two objects, means to make, and it implies continuity (i.e., the action of continuing persistently). (117 verses: 2:51-2:67-2:80-2:92-2:116-2:125-2:165-2:231-3:28-3:64-3:80-3:118-3:140-4:25-4:89-4:119-4:125-4:139-4:144-4:150-4:153-5:5-5:51-5:57-5:58-5:81-5:116-6:14-6:70-6:74-7:30-7:51-7:74-7:146-7:148-7:152-9:16-9:23-9:31-9:98-9:99-9:107-10:68-11:92-12:21-13:16-16:51-16:67-16:68-16:92-16:94-17:2-17:40-17:73-17:111-18:4-18:15-18:21-18:50-18:51-18:56-18:61-18:63-18:86-18:102-18:106-19:17-19:35-19:81-18:88-19:92-21:17-21:21-21:24-21:26-21:36-23:91-23:110-25:2-25:3-25:18-25:27-25:28-25:30-25:41-25:43-25:57-26:29-26:129-28:9-29:25-29:41-31:6-35:6-36:23-36:74-38:63-39:3-39:4-39:43-42:6-42:9-43:16-43:32-45:9-45:10-45:23-45:35-46:28-58:16-60:1-63:2-72:3-73:9-73:19-76:29-78:39)",
      "d": "«اَخَذَ» means to take, to grasp, to acquire something. To take into possession. And «اِتَّخَذَ», by taking two objects, becomes a continuous form of «جَعَلَ». (transitive) In it, neither arrangement nor creation is involved. And it implies continuity (i.e., the action of continuing persistently).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَقَالَ الَّذِی اشۡتَرٰىہُ مِنۡ مِّصۡرَ لِامۡرَاَتِہٖۤ اَکۡرِمِیۡ مَثۡوٰىہُ عَسٰۤی اَنۡ یَّنۡفَعَنَاۤ  اَوۡنَتَّخِذَہٗ وَلَدًا» (12/21)\nTranslation: And the one who bought him from Egypt said to his wife, 'Honor his lodging; perhaps he will benefit us, or we will adopt him as a son.'"
    }
  ],
  "108": [
    {
      "id": 526,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to close; to be closed",
      "hw": "بند",
      "s": "«غَلَّقَ» is used for closing doors, etc. (1 verse: 12:23)",
      "d": "«غَلَقَ» means to close, and its opposite is «فَکَّ» meaning to open or release. (M. L.) And «غَلْق» means lock or bolt. (Munjid) And «غَلَّقَ الْبَاب» means to close the door firmly, to put a bolt, or to lock it.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَغَلَّقَتِ الۡاَبۡوَابَ وَ قَالَتۡ ہَیۡتَ لَکَ» (12/23)\nTranslation: And that woman (Zulaikha) closed the doors and said, 'Come quickly, O Joseph.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 527,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Close; To Be Closed",
      "hw": "بند",
      "s": "«وَصَدَ» means to close something in such a way that nothing can come out (10 verses: 2:217-4:167-13:33-16:88-27:43-40:37-47:1-47:32-47:34-48:25)",
      "d": "«وَصَدَ» means to close in a manner that the closed thing cannot let anything out. According to Ibn Faris, «اَلْوَصْدُ خَتْمُ شَیْءٍ اِلیٰ شَیْءٍ» and «اَوْصَدْتُ الْقِدْرَ» means to cover the pot so that steam cannot escape. «اَوْصَدْتُ الْبَابَ» means to close the door. However, this applies only when there is no other window, door, or opening left open.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«عَلَیۡہِمۡ نَارٌمُّؤۡصَدَۃٌ» (90/20)\nTranslation: Upon them will be a fire closed (in on them)."
    },
    {
      "id": 528,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Close; To Be Closed",
      "hw": "بند",
      "s": "«قَصَرَ» is used in the meaning of being confined or closed in a place (5 verses: 7:74-22:45-25:10-55:72-77:32)",
      "d": "«قَصَرَ» is fundamentally used in two meanings: (1) for a thing not reaching its limit or goal, (2) «حَبَسَ» meaning to be confined or closed. The second meaning is under discussion here. One says «قَصَرَ فِی بَیْتِہٖ» meaning he became confined or closed in his house.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«حُوۡرٌ مَّقۡصُوۡرٰتٌ فِی الۡخِیَامِ» (55/72)\nTranslation: (There will be) Houris, confined in pavilions."
    },
    {
      "id": 529,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to close; to be closed",
      "hw": "بند",
      "s": "«قَبَضَ» means to grasp something in the fist and take it into one's grasp. (6 verses: 2:245-9:67-20:96-25:46-39:67-67:19)",
      "d": "«قَبَضَ» means to grasp something in the fist, and «قَبَضَۃٌ» is the fist. (Maf) Therefore, «قَبَضَ» is used in meanings of shrinking, decreasing, tightening, and closing.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ بِالۡمُنۡکَرِ وَیَنۡہَوۡنَ عَنِ الۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَیَقۡبِضُوۡنَ اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ» (9/67)\nTranslation: (Hypocrites) enjoin evil and forbid good, and they keep their hands closed (from spending)."
    }
  ],
  "109": [
    {
      "id": 530,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to weave",
      "hw": "بُننا",
      "s": "«حَبَکَ» is used in the sense of weaving something, such as weaving cloth. (1 verse: 51:7)",
      "d": "«حَبَّاک» means weaver (one who weaves cloth), and «حَبَکَ الثَّوْبَ» means he wove the cloth. (M. Q.) And «حَبَکَ حَابِکَ الثَّوْب» means the weaver weaves the cloth skillfully. (Munjid) And «حَبَک» also means path, and its plural is «حُبُک». (Maf. Munjid)\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَالسَّمَآءِ ذَاتِ الۡحُبُکِ» (51/7)\nTranslation: And by the sky possessing a web. (Meaning the sky is spread with a network of stars.) (Uthmani) And by the sky in which there are paths. (Jalandhri)"
    },
    {
      "id": 531,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to weave",
      "hw": "بُننا",
      "s": "«وَضَنَ» is said for weaving something firmly. (1 verse: 56:15)",
      "d": "«وَضَنَ» originally means armor-making (i.e., working with gold threads on cloth). And by extension, it is said for anything woven firmly. (Maf) And «مَوضُون» means finely woven or made of gold and silver. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«عَلٰی سُرُرٍ مَّوۡضُوۡنَۃٍ مُّتَّکِئِیۡنَ عَلَیۡہَا مُتَقٰبِلِیۡنَ» (56/15,16)\nTranslation: On thrones, well-woven (or inlaid), reclining on them, facing each other."
    }
  ],
  "110": [
    {
      "id": 532,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«ثَقَلَ» generally refers to a traveler's luggage and other heavy things (25 verses: 4:40-7:8-7:57-7:187-7:189-9:41-10:61-13:12-16:7-21:47-23:102-29:13-31:16-34:3-34:22-35:18-52:40-55:31-68:46-73:5-76:27-99:2-99:7-99:8-101:6)",
      "d": "«ثَقَلَ» means a traveler's luggage, burden, weight, etc. It is generally used for material and tangible burdens. The opposite of «ثَقِیْل» is «خفیف», meaning light in weight.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنۡفِرُوۡا خِفَافًا وَّ ثِقَالًا» (9/41)\nTranslation: March forth, whether you are light or heavy (in burden).\nThe plural of «ثَقَل» is «اَثقَال».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَتَحۡمِلُ اَثۡقَالَکُمۡ اِلٰی بَلَدٍ لَّمۡ تَکُوۡنُوۡا بٰلِغِیۡہِ اِلَّا بِشِقِّ الۡاَنۡفُسِ» (16/7)\nTranslation: And they carry your loads to a land you could not reach except with great personal hardship. Indeed, your Lord is Full of Pity, Most Merciful.\n«ثَقِیْل» can also be used metaphorically for heavy and burdensome things.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّا سَنُلۡقِیۡ عَلَیۡکَ قَوۡلًا ثَقِیۡلًا» (73/5)\nTranslation: We will soon cast upon you a weighty Word. Here, «ثَقِیْل» refers to a matter, speech, or command that is very burdensome on one's nature and acting upon it requires great courage."
    },
    {
      "id": 533,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«حَمْل» refers to a burden that the bearer carries within themselves, such as a child in the womb, fruit on a tree, or water in a cloud. (43 verses: 2:248-2:286-6:31-6:146-7:189-9:92-11:40-12:36-12:72-13:8-16:7-16:25-17:3-17:70-19:22-19:27-19:58-20:87-20:100-20:101-20:111-22:2-23:22-24:54-29:12-29:13-29:60-31:14-33:72-35:11-35:18-36:41-40:7-40:80-41:47-46:15-54:13-62:5-65:4-65:6-69:11-69:14-69:17)",
      "d": "«حَمَلَ» means to carry a burden, and «حَمْل» is such a burden that is contained within. For example, a child in the womb, fruit on a tree, or water in a cloud. (Maf)\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا تَغَشّٰہَا حَمَلَتۡ حَمۡلًا خَفِیۡفًا فَمَرَّتۡ بِہٖ» (7/189)\nTranslation: When the man approaches her, she conceives a light burden, then she moves about with it.\nAnd «حِمْل» is the burden that is carried on the back in a sensory way. (Maf) But according to the author of 'Muntahi al-Arb', «حِمْل» means bar-i-sir or bar-i-pusht, i.e., the maximum load that a carrier can carry. And this definition seems more correct. And the Quran supports this meaning:\n«قَالُوۡا نَفۡقِدُ صُوَاعَ الۡمَلِکِ وَلِمَنۡ جَآءَ بِہٖ حِمۡلُ بَعِیۡرٍ وَّاَنَا بِہٖ زَعِیۡمٌ» (12/72)\nTranslation: They said, 'We have lost the measure of the king, and for whoever brings it is the reward of a camel's load, and I am responsible for it.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 534,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«وَقْر» is generally used for a spiritual burden. And «وِقر» means the maximum possible spiritual burden according to the strength of the bearer (7 verses: 6:25-17:46-18:57-31:7-41:5-41:44-51:2)",
      "d": "The word «وَقْر» is used metaphorically for a spiritual burden. One says «فِیْ صَدْرِہٖ وَقْرٌ» meaning 'there is a burden (of malice) in his heart.' Similarly, «فِیْ اُذُنِہٖ وَقْرٌ» means 'there is a burden in his ears,' i.e., he suffers from heaviness in hearing or deafness, and he hears only loud sounds. Some interpret «وَقْر» as earwax, but the first meaning is more eloquent, as earwax limits hearing.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّجَعَلۡنَا عَلٰی قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ اَکِنَّۃً اَنۡ یَّفۡقَہُوۡہُ وَفِیۡۤ اٰذَانِہِمۡ وَقۡرًا» (17/46)\nTranslation: And We have placed covers on their hearts so they do not understand it, and (We have placed) deafness in their ears.\nThe word «وِقْر» refers to the maximum amount of this spiritual burden that is in accordance with the bearer's capacity and strength.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالذّٰرِیٰتِ ذَرۡوًا فَالۡحٰمِلٰتِ وِقۡرًا» (51/1,2)\nTranslation: By the scatterers scattering, then the carriers bearing a heavy load."
    },
    {
      "id": 535,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«وِزْر» is generally used for the burdens of sins. (10 verses: 6:31-6:164-16:25-17:15-20:87-20:100-35:18-39:7-53:38-94:2)",
      "d": "Ibn Faris writes that when a person spreads out his garment and places his burden in it and carries it, that is «وِزْر». Therefore, «اَلْذَنْبُ» (sin) is called «وِزْر» (burden), i.e., the burden of one's deeds. Similarly, «وِزْر» is also said for weapons, and its plural is «اَوْزَار». (M. L.) And «اَوْزَرَ اِیْزَارًا» means to hide, to take away, to give refuge, etc. (Munjid) Similarly, «وَزَرُ» means a place of refuge in a mountain. (Maf) And «وِزْر» is mostly used for the heavy burdens of sins.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَہُمۡ یَحۡمِلُوۡنَ اَوۡزَارَہُمۡ عَلٰی ظُہُوۡرِہِمۡ ؕ اَلَا سَآءَ مَا یَزِرُوۡنَ» (6/31)\nTranslation: And they will bear their burdens on their backs. Evil is what they bear."
    },
    {
      "id": 536,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«اِصْر» means covenant and pledge, responsibilities of religious commands, or bonds of tradition (3 verses: 2:286-3:81-7:157)",
      "d": "«اَلْاِصْر» has two meanings: (1) to bind with a rope and (2) to forcibly restrain something. In this sense, the burden of adhering to one's covenant and fulfilling religious obligations is «اِصْر». According to Ibn Faris, every contract, covenant, and relationship is an «اِصْر».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«رَبَّنَا وَلَا تَحۡمِلۡ عَلَیۡنَاۤ اِصۡرًا کَمَا حَمَلۡتَہٗ عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِنَا» (2/286)\nTranslation: \"Our Lord, do not impose upon us a burden like that which You imposed upon those before us.\"\nFurthermore, «اِصْر» is also applied to the obstacles that arise from a society's traditions when choosing the path of truth.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَیَضَعُ عَنۡہُمۡ اِصۡرَہُمۡ وَ الۡاَغۡلٰلَ الَّتِیۡ کَانَتۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ» (7/157)\nTranslation: \"And He will remove from them their burden and the shackles which were upon them.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 537,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«کَلٌّ» refers to the burden of raising an orphan who is helpless and weak (1 verse: 16:76)",
      "d": "«کَلٌّ» means needy, dependent, orphan, helpless, feeble, and burden. The meaning here is the responsibility of upbringing or the burden of maintenance and provision.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَحَدُہُمَاۤ اَبۡکَمُ لَا یَقۡدِرُعَلٰی شَیۡءٍ وَّہُوَ کَلٌّ عَلٰی مَوۡلٰىہُ ۙ اَیۡنَمَا یُوَجِّہۡہُّ لَایَاۡتِ بِخَیۡرٍ» (16/76)\nTranslation: \"One of them is mute, unable to do anything, and is a burden on his master. Wherever he directs him, he does not bring any good.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 538,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«وَزْن، مَوَازِیْن» is the weight placed on a scale for weighing (12 verses: 7:8-7:9-17:35-18:105-21:47-23:102-23:103-26:182-55:9-83:3-101:6-101:8)",
      "d": "«مَوَازِیْن» means scales by which something is weighed. «وَزْن» is the weight placed on one of the scale's pans for weighing. «میزان» means both the scales and the amount of weight; its plural is «مَوَازِیْن».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَمَّا مَنۡ ثَقُلَتۡ مَوَازِیۡنُہٗ فَہُوَ فِیۡ عِیۡشَۃٍ رَّاضِیَۃٍ» (101/6,7)\nTranslation: \"Then as for one whose scales are heavy [with good deeds], he will be in a pleasant life.\""
    }
  ],
  "111": [
    {
      "id": 539,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Become Heavy (or Burdensome)",
      "hw": "بوجھل",
      "s": "«ثَقُلَ» means for something to become heavy in weight (16 verses: 7:8-7:57-7:187-7:189-9:41-13:12-16:7-23:102-29:13-35:18-52:40-68:46-73:5-76:27-99:2-101:6)",
      "d": "«ثَقُلَ» means to become heavy in weight.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَمَّا مَنۡ ثَقُلَتۡ مَوَازِیۡنُہٗ فَہُوَ فِیۡ عِیۡشَۃٍ رَّاضِیَۃٍ» (101/6,7)\nTranslation: \"Then as for one whose scales are heavy [with good deeds], he will be in a pleasant life.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 540,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Become Heavy (or Burdensome)",
      "hw": "بوجھل",
      "s": "«کَسَلَ» means for one's nature to become heavy and sluggish due to laziness (2 verses: 4:142-9:54)",
      "d": "«کَسَلَ» means for one's nature to become heavy and sluggish due to laziness. «اَلْکَسْل» means to show heaviness (burden) in a matter where heaviness is inappropriate.\nFor example, regarding the hypocrites, Allah says:\n«وَلَا یَاۡتُوۡنَ الصَّلٰوۃَ اِلَّا وَ ہُمۡ کُسَالٰی» (9/54)\nTranslation: \"And they do not attend to prayer except while they are lazy.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 541,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Become Heavy (or Burdensome)",
      "hw": "بوجھل",
      "s": "«اٰدَ» means for one's nature to become heavy due to excessive toil and hardship (1 verse: 2:255)",
      "d": "«اٰدَ» means for one's nature to become heavy due to excessive toil and hardship.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَا یَئُوۡدُہٗ حِفۡظُہُمَا ۚ وَ ہُوَالۡعَلِیُّ الۡعَظِیۡمُ» (2/255)\nTranslation: \"And their preservation tires Him not, and He is the Most High, the Most Great.\""
    }
  ],
  "112": [
    {
      "id": 543,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Old Age",
      "hw": "بوڑھا",
      "s": "«شَیْخ» means old (elderly). It is generally used for an elderly person. It is also used for someone honored and respected, or a scholar (4 verses: 11:72-12:78-28:23-40:67)",
      "d": "«شَیْخ» means an elder, whether old in age or high in rank, knowledge, and virtue. (According to Majma' al-Bayan) 'Sheikh' is essentially a word of respect. «شَیْخُ الْمِرْأَۃ» is also used for a woman's husband, even if he is young. However, in the Quran, this word has been used only in the sense of old age (see 'Shuyukh').\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ لِتَبۡلُغُوۡۤا اَشُدَّکُمۡ ثُمَّ لِتَکُوۡنُوۡا شُیُوۡخًا» (40/67)\nTranslation: Then that you reach your maturity, then that you become elderly."
    },
    {
      "id": 544,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Old Age",
      "hw": "بوڑھا",
      "s": "«شِیْب» refers to a person whose hair has started turning white (3 verses: 19:4-30:54-73:17)",
      "d": "«شَابَ» means to have white hair. One says «شَابَتْ رُءُوْسُ الْاٰکَام» meaning the peaks of the mountains turned white with snow. And «اَشْیَب» means very white-haired. «شِیْب» is its plural. (According to Majma' al-Bayan) scholars of language consider «شَیْب» to be the middle stage between youth and old age, attributing an age of 30 to 40 years. However, «شِیْب» can be the state of having just started to get white hair.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَکَیۡفَ تَتَّقُوۡنَ اِنۡ کَفَرۡتُمۡ یَوۡمًا یَّجۡعَلُ الۡوِلۡدَانَ شِیۡبَۨا» (73/17)\nTranslation: So how will you be, if you disbelieve, on a Day that will make children white-haired?"
    },
    {
      "id": 545,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Old (Elderly)",
      "hw": "بوڑھا",
      "s": "«کَھَل» is used for middle age, between forty and sixty years (2 verses: 3:46-5:110)",
      "d": "«کَھَل» means to be of middle age. «کَھْل» refers to someone between 30 and 50 years. «کَاہَلَ الرَّجُل» means for a man to marry. According to the scholar of language, it is used for the middle age between forty and sixty years. In their words: \"Then what remains between thirty and forty is a youth. Then he is \"kahil\" until he reaches sixty.\"\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ یُکَلِّمُ النَّاسَ فِی الۡمَہۡدِ وَ کَہۡلًا» (3/46)\nTranslation: \"And he will speak to the people in the cradle and in maturity.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 546,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Old (Elderly)",
      "hw": "بوڑھا",
      "s": "«عَجُوْز» is used for an old woman (it is exclusively feminine) (4 verses: 11:72-26:171-37:135-51:29)",
      "d": "«عَجُوْز» is exclusively feminine, meaning an old woman who can no longer bear children. «عَجُزَۃ» refers to one's last child.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَتۡ یٰوَیۡلَتٰۤیءَ اَلِدُ وَ اَنَا عَجُوۡزٌ وَّ ہٰذَا بَعۡلِیۡ شَیۡخًا» (11/72)\nTranslation: \"She said, \"Woe to me! Shall I give birth while I am an old woman, and this, my husband, is an old man?\"\""
    },
    {
      "id": 547,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Aged",
      "hw": "بوڑھا",
      "s": "«Mu'ammar»: one who lives beyond sixty years of age (11 verses: 2:96-10:16-15:72-16:70-21:44-22:5-26:18-28:45-35:11-35:37-36:68)",
      "d": "«Mu'ammar» means one who lives to a ripe old age.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَمَا یُعَمَّرُ مِنۡ مُّعَمَّرٍ وَّلَا یُنۡقَصُ مِنۡ عُمُرِہٖۤ اِلَّا فِیۡ کِتٰبٍ» (35/11)\nTranslation: And no long-lived person is granted increase in age nor is his life shortened except that it is recorded in a book."
    }
  ],
  "113": [
    {
      "id": 550,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To become rotten",
      "hw": "بوسیدہ",
      "s": "«Wahiya»: for something's joints to become loose (1 verse: 69:16)",
      "d": "«Wahiya»: for something's joints to become loose (m l) «وَحْیَ الثَّوْبَ وَالْحَبْل», meaning clothes or rope start to tear due to rot (f l 39) or leather cracking due to decay (m l).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَانۡشَقَّتِ السَّمَاءُ فَہِیَ یَوۡمَئِذٍ وَّاہِیَۃٌ» (69/16)\nTranslation: And the sky will split open, so on that day it will be weak (and rotten)."
    },
    {
      "id": 552,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To become rotten",
      "hw": "بوسیدہ",
      "s": "«Rafata»: to crumble into pieces due to decay (2 verses: 17:49-17:98)",
      "d": "«Rafata» means to break, shatter, and «رَفَتَ الْعَظْم» means for bones to become crumbled. And «الرَّفَات» means every broken thing. Rotten (manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَقَالُوۡۤاءَ اِذَا کُنَّا عِظَامًا وَّرُفَاتًاءَ اِنَّا لَمَبۡعُوۡثُوۡنَ خَلۡقًا جَدِیۡدًا» (17/49)\nTranslation: And they say, 'When we are bones and crumbled pieces, will we indeed be raised as a new creation?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 553,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To become rotten",
      "hw": "بوسیدہ",
      "s": "«Nakhira»: (of bones) to become hollow inside due to decay (1 verse: 79:11)",
      "d": "«Nakhira» means to become rotten and crumbled (manjad). «نَخِرَۃٌ» means for a bone to become rotten and hollow inside or to have holes in it.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ ءَاِنَّا لَمَرۡدُوۡدُوۡنَ فِی الۡحَافِرَۃِ ءَ اِذَا کُنَّا عِظَامًا نَّخِرَۃً» (79:10-11)\nTranslation: They say, 'Will we indeed be returned to the earth, even when we are hollow bones?'"
    }
  ],
  "114": [
    {
      "id": 555,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speaking",
      "hw": "بولنا",
      "s": "«نَطَقَ» means to utter understandable speech, i.e., to say something whose meaning can be comprehended (11 verses: 21:63-21:65-23:62-27:16-27:85-37:92-41:21-45:29-51:23-53:3-77:35)",
      "d": "«نَطَقَ» means to say something whose meaning can be understood. «اَلْمَالُ النَّاطِقُ وَالصَّامِت»: the 'speaking property' refers to animals, and the 'silent property' refers to gold and silver. Since animals are also 'speaking' (they communicate and understand each other's languages), and «مَنْطِقَ الطَّیْر» means the language of birds. However, this word is intrinsically used only for humans. Logicians consider only humans as 'speaking animals' (animal rationale), and from «نُطْقٌ» they derive the faculty of speech (Aristotle first termed humans as 'speaking animals'). But etymologically, this word can be used for beings endowed with reason.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَمَا یَنۡطِقُ عَنِ الۡہَوٰی اِنۡ ہُوَاِلَّا وَحۡیٌ یُّوۡحٰی» (53/3,4)\nTranslation: And he (Muhammad ﷺ) does not speak from his own desire. This (Quran) is nothing but revelation that is revealed.\nRegarding Prophet Solomon (peace be upon him), the Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّاسُ عُلِّمۡنَا مَنۡطِقَ الطَّیۡرِ» (27/16)\nTranslation: O people! We have been taught the language of birds. Here, «نَطَقَ» is used in relation to Solomon's (peace be upon him) understanding and the birds' speaking.\nJust as «نَطَقَ» is external and refers to comprehensible speech, it is also internal, referring to understanding, perception, or the language of the heart (state).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ہٰذَا کِتٰبُنَا یَنۡطِقُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ بِالۡحَقِّ ؕ اِنَّا کُنَّا نَسۡتَنۡسِخُ مَا کُنۡتُمۡ تَعۡمَلُوۡنَ» (45/29)\nTranslation: This, our record, speaks the truth about you. Indeed, We were recording all that you used to do."
    },
    {
      "id": 558,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To speak",
      "hw": "بولنا",
      "s": "«Takallama»: to bring a meaningful utterance to the tongue, which another hears (10 verses: 3:41-5:110-11:105-19:10-23:108-24:16-27:82-30:35-36:65-78:38)",
      "d": "«Kallama» means to converse or talk, and «Takallama» means to speak or to bring an utterance to the tongue.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«لَّا یَتَکَلَّمُوۡنَ اِلَّا مَنۡ اَذِنَ لَہُ الرَّحۡمٰنُ» (78:38)\nTranslation: No one will speak except he whom the Most Merciful permits."
    },
    {
      "id": 559,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To speak",
      "hw": "بولنا",
      "s": "«Lahina»: to adopt a different manner of speech deviating from the common way (1 verse: 47:30)",
      "d": "«Lahina» means to turn away from the commonly used method and style, and «لحن القول» means to employ a method other than the prevailing style of speech. And «اللحن» also refers to eloquent speech (m q) and a fluent and eloquent person (muf). And «لَحَّنَ» means to recite with a melodious voice. The lahn of David is famous. However, the original meaning of «لَحَن» is change of tone, so with it, the same sentence can become positive, negative, or interrogative.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَلَتَعۡرِفَنَّہُمۡ  فِیۡ لَحۡنِ الۡقَوۡلِ» (47:30)\nTranslation: And you will recognize them by the tone of their speech."
    }
  ],
  "115": [
    {
      "id": 560,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To cause to flow and to flow",
      "hw": "بہنا",
      "s": "«Asala»: to cause any flowing thing to flow (3 verses: 13:17-34:12-34:16)",
      "d": "«Sala» means (for liquids) to flow or gush out, and «Sayl» means flowing water, flood. And «Sayyal» means flowing vigorously (manjad). Also, every flowing thing is called «Sayyal». And «Asala» means to cause (a flowing or liquid thing) to flow.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَاَسَلۡنَا لَہٗ عَیۡنَ الۡقِطۡرِ» (34:12)\nTranslation: And We caused a spring of molten copper to flow for him."
    },
    {
      "id": 562,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To cause to flow and to flow",
      "hw": "بہنا",
      "s": "«Sakaba»: to pour a flowing substance in such quantity that it flows (1 verse: 56:31)",
      "d": "«Sakaba» means to pour (water, etc.) and cause to flow. And «الأسْکُوب» means continuous rain or rain with large drops (m r - manjad). That whose water flows out. And «الأسْکُوب» also means continuous drizzle (manjad). So «Sakaba» implies continuity or duration along with the pouring or flowing of water, etc. And «مَآءٍ مَّسْکُوْبٍ» means flowing water.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَّظِلٍّ مَّمۡدُوۡدٍ وَّمَآءٍ مَّسۡکُوۡبٍ» (56:31)\nTranslation: And extended shade and flowing water. (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 563,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To cause to flow and to flow",
      "hw": "بہنا",
      "s": "«Safaka»: commonly used for shedding blood (2 verses: 2:30-2:84)",
      "d": "«Safaka» means to shed blood or water. But it is mostly used for shedding blood. And «سفّاک» means a bloodshedding person (m r).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَاِذۡ اَخَذۡنَا مِیۡثَاقَکُمۡ لَا تَسۡفِکُوۡنَ دِمَآءَکُمۡ» (2:84)\nTranslation: And [recall] when We took your covenant, [saying], 'You shall not shed one another's blood.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 564,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Cause to Flow / To Flow",
      "hw": "بہنا",
      "s": "«سَفَحَ» denotes the rapid flowing of a fluid (3 verses: 4:24-4:25-5:5)",
      "d": "The literal meaning of «سَفَحَ» is also to flow blood or water (m.f.) and to mean the swift flowing and continuity of something that flows (faqih 257). In the Quran, «دَمًا مَّسْفُوْحًا» appears in the sense of flowing blood. However, this word is generally used for illicitly flowing or fornicating: «مُسَافِحٌ» means a fornicating man and «مُسَافِحَۃ» a fornicating woman.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاُحِلَّ لَکُمۡ مَّا وَرَآءَ ذٰلِکُمۡ اَنۡ تَبۡتَغُوۡا بِاَمۡوَالِکُمۡ مُّحۡصِنِیۡنَ غَیۡرَ مُسٰفِحِیۡنَ» (4/24)\nTranslation: And all women are lawful for you beyond those [already mentioned]. Thus, marry them with your wealth, seeking chastity and not fornication."
    },
    {
      "id": 565,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Cause to Flow / To Flow",
      "hw": "بہنا",
      "s": "«فَجَرَ» means to spread over a wide area (9 verses: 2:60-2:74-17:90-17:91-18:33-36:34-54:12-76:6-82:3)",
      "d": "The primary meaning of «فَجَرَ» is to tear something widely (m.f.), and when used for flowing things, it indicates extensiveness.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَقَالُوۡا لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لَکَ حَتّٰی تَفۡجُرَ لَنَا مِنَ الۡاَرۡضِ یَنۡۢبُوۡعًا»\nTranslation: (The disbelievers) said, 'We will never believe you until you cause a spring to gush forth for us from the ground.'\nFor flowing, «سَالَ» and «فَاضَ» have already been discussed above. Now see their examples.\n(1) Example of «سَالَ»: The Quran states:\n«اَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً فَسَالَتۡ اَوۡدِیَۃٌۢ بِقَدَرِہَا» (13/17)\nTranslation: He sent down water from the sky, so the valleys flowed according to their capacity.\n(2) Example of «فَاضَ»: The Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا سَمِعُوۡا مَاۤ اُنۡزِلَ اِلَی الرَّسُوۡلِ تَرٰۤی اَعۡیُنَہُمۡ تَفِیۡضُ مِنَ الدَّمۡعِ مِمَّا عَرَفُوۡا مِنَ الۡحَقِّ» (5/83)\nTranslation: And when they hear what has been revealed to the Messenger, you see their eyes overflowing with tears because they recognize the truth."
    },
    {
      "id": 566,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Cause to Flow / To Flow",
      "hw": "بہنا",
      "s": "«جَرٰی» means to flow or move continuously over a distance or time (60 verses: 2:25-2:164-2:266-3:15-3:136-3:195-3:198-4:13-4:57-4:122-5:12-5:85-5:119-6:6-7:43-9:72-9:89-9:100-10:9-10:22-11:42-13:2-13:35-14:23-14:32-16:31-18:31-20:76-21:81-22:14-22:23-22:65-25:10-29:58-30:46-31:29-31:31-35:13-36:38-38:36-39:5-39:20-43:51-45:12-47:12-48:5-48:17-51:3-54:14-55:50-57:12-58:22-61:12-64:9-65:11-66:8-69:11-85:11-88:12-98:8)",
      "d": "«جَرْیًا وَجِرْیَانًا» originally, this word is used for water and similar fluid things flowing and moving (m.f.).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فِیۡہَا عَیۡنٌ جَارِیَۃٌ» (88/12)\nTranslation: In it (Paradise) is a flowing spring.\nThen this word began to be used for anything that flows or moves continuously over distance or time. Thus, its usage became common in both temporal and spatial contexts. For instance, in the Quran, it is used for winds or the movement of the moon and sun. Moreover, it is used metaphorically, such as the famous term 'Sunnah Jariyah' (continuous tradition)."
    }
  ],
  "116": [
    {
      "id": 567,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Excuse: Making an Excuse",
      "hw": "بہانہ",
      "s": "«العُذْر» means to present a reason to dismiss an accusation, and «مَعْذِرَۃٌ» is used for making a false excuse. (6 verses: 7:164-9:90-18:76-30:57-40:52-77:6)",
      "d": "«اَلْعُذْر» means to present a reason to dismiss an accusation. According to Imam Raghib, it is an attempt by which a person seeks to erase their sins. And «عَذَرَ» means to accept an excuse, «عَذَّرَ» means to give a small excuse or state a false and weak reason, and «اِعْتَذَرَ» means to present an excuse. Now, this excuse also has three types: the first type is «فِتْنَۃٌ»."
    },
    {
      "id": 568,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Excuse: Making an Excuse",
      "hw": "بہانہ",
      "s": "«فِتْنَۃٌ» is when a person uses falsehood to deny an accusation or sin. (1 verse: 6:23)",
      "d": "«فِتْنَۃٌ» is when a person uses falsehood to deny that very accusation or sin. For this, the Quran has used the word «فِتْنَۃٌ».\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«ثُمَّ لَمۡ تَکُنۡ فِتۡنَتُہُمۡ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ قَالُوۡا وَاللّٰہِ رَبِّنَا مَا کُنَّا مُشۡرِکِیۡنَ» (6/23)\nTranslation: Then their [attempted] excuse will not be except that they will say, 'By Allah, our Lord, we were not polytheists.'\nThe word 'fitnah' is also used for testing, examining, and scrutinizing someone."
    },
    {
      "id": 569,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Excuse: Making an Excuse",
      "hw": "بہانہ",
      "s": "«عُذْر» means to present an excuse for not doing something, whether the excuse is false or true. (6 verses: 7:164-9:90-18:76-30:57-40:52-77:6)",
      "d": "«عُذْر» is when a person presents a false reason or lie to absolve themselves. Therefore, the Quran has used the word «عَذَّرَ».\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ جَآءَ الۡمُعَذِّرُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡاَعۡرَابِ لِیُؤۡذَنَ لَہُمۡ» (9/90)\nTranslation: And some of the desert Arabs came to you to be excused [from Jihad] so that they may be permitted [to stay behind].\nIt is also possible that the excuse is actually valid and reasonable. For this, the words «عُذْر» and «مَعْذِرَۃٌ» appear in the Quran.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَاِذۡ قَالَتۡ اُمَّۃٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ لِمَ تَعِظُوۡنَ قَوۡمَۨا ۙ اللّٰہُ مُہۡلِکُہُمۡ اَوۡ مُعَذِّبُہُمۡ عَذَابًا شَدِیۡدًا ؕ قَالُوۡا مَعۡذِرَۃً اِلٰی رَبِّکُمۡ  وَلَعَلَّہُمۡ یَتَّقُوۡنَ» (7/164)\nTranslation: And when a group among them said, 'Why do you advise a people whom Allah will destroy or punish with a severe punishment?' They said, '[We advise them] as an excuse to your Lord, and perhaps they may fear [Allah].'"
    }
  ],
  "117": [
    {
      "id": 570,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Slander",
      "hw": "بہتان",
      "s": "«بُھْتَان» is an accusation that throws people into a pit of astonishment (8 verses: 2:258-4:20-4:112-4:156-21:40-24:16-33:58-60:12)",
      "d": "«بَھَتَ» means to be astonished and bewildered (m.f.) or to become silent and speechless due to amazement (minjadd). And «بُھْتَان» is a statement that, upon hearing, makes people lose their senses, remain astonished and perplexed, and cannot believe that such a thing is possible.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَوۡلَاۤ اِذۡ سَمِعۡتُمُوۡہُ قُلۡتُمۡ مَّا یَکُوۡنُ لَنَاۤ اَنۡ نَّتَکَلَّمَ بِہٰذَا ٭ۖ سُبۡحٰنَکَ ہٰذَا بُہۡتَانٌ عَظِیۡمٌ» (24/16)\nTranslation: And why did you not, when you heard it, say, 'It is not for us to speak of this. Exalted are You! This is a great slander.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 571,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Slander",
      "hw": "بہتان",
      "s": "«اِفْک» is a baseless accusation, a fabricated story by distorting the original matter (12 verses: 7:17-24:11-24:12-25:4-26:45-29:17-34:43-37:151-46:11-46:22-46:28-51:9)",
      "d": "«اَفَکَ» means to turn something away from its correct direction (m.f.).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَجِئۡتَنَا لِتَاۡفِکَنَا عَنۡ اٰلِہَتِنَا» (46/22)\nTranslation: They (the people of 'Ad) said, 'Have you come to turn us away from our gods?'\nSimilarly, turning from truth to falsehood, or from good to evil, is called «اِفْک». And in this sense, fabricated and false statements and accusations are also called «اِفْک». And «اَفَّاک» refers to one who fabricates false and made-up stories and spreads accusations. According to Abu Hala al-Askari, «اِفْک» is a lie related to «فَاحِشَ اَلْقُبْح» (shameful evil).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَوۡلَاۤ اِذۡ سَمِعۡتُمُوۡہُ ظَنَّ الۡمُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ وَالۡمُؤۡمِنٰتُ بِاَنۡفُسِہِمۡ خَیۡرًا ۙ وَّقَالُوۡا ہٰذَاۤ اِفۡکٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ» (24/12)\nTranslation: When you heard it, why did the believing men and women not think well of themselves and say, 'This is a clear fabrication'?\nThus, «اِفْک» is such that it is based on baseless talks and such a big lie that sound reason is stunned, considering it a slander."
    }
  ],
  "118": [
    {
      "id": 574,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Mislead and to be Misled",
      "hw": "بہکنا",
      "s": "«غَوٰی» means to become entangled in a wrong action due to ignorance. (13 verses: 2:256-7:16-7:146-7:202-11:34-15:39-19:59-20:121-28:18-28:63-37:32-38:82-53:2)",
      "d": "«غَوٰی» means to become entangled in a wrong action due to ignorance (m. r.) and then to become hopeless from the right path (m. r.), and its usage is only in religious matters. (Faqih 177)\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَعَصٰۤی اٰدَمُ رَبَّہٗ فَغَوٰی» (20/121)\nTranslation: And Adam disobeyed his Lord and became astray.\nThe opposite of «غَوٰی» is «رُشْد», meaning to become established on the straight path and adopt good conduct. And «رَشِید» means guided.\nFor example, Allah says:\n«قَدۡ تَّبَیَّنَ الرُّشۡدُ مِنَ الۡغَیِّ» (2/256)\nTranslation: Guidance has become clear from misguidance.\nAt another place, Allah says:\n«مَا ضَلَّ صَاحِبُکُمۡ وَمَا غَوٰی» (53/2)\nTranslation: Your companion [Muhammad] has neither strayed nor become astray."
    },
    {
      "id": 575,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Mislead and to be Misled",
      "hw": "بہکنا",
      "s": "«تَاہَ» refers to a flat plain where one who walks becomes lost. (1 verse: 5:26)",
      "d": "«تَاہَ، تِیْہ، تِیْھَاء» refer to a flat plain where one who walks becomes lost. And «تَاہَ» means to wander in a bewildered and confused state (Manjad).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«قَالَ فَاِنَّہَا مُحَرَّمَۃٌ عَلَیۡہِمۡ اَرۡبَعِیۡنَ سَنَۃً ۚ یَتِیۡہُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (5/26)\nTranslation: Allah said, 'Then indeed, it is forbidden to them for forty years; they will wander throughout the land.'"
    }
  ],
  "119": [
    {
      "id": 576,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Flee / To Cause to Flee",
      "hw": "بھاگنا",
      "s": "«فَرَّ» means to flee, especially of an accused person (10 verses: 18:18-26:21-33:13-33:16-51:50-62:8-71:6-74:51-75:10-80:34)",
      "d": "«فَرَّ» generally means to flee, especially for an accused person or from any kind of fear or danger. «فَرَّمِنَ الْحَرْبِ فِرَارًا» means to leave the battlefield or to escape from fighting. And «مَفَرّ» is a place where one can flee for refuge. And مفرور is the accused who flees.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قُلۡ لَّنۡ یَّنۡفَعَکُمُ الۡفِرَارُ اِنۡ فَرَرۡتُمۡ مِّنَ الۡمَوۡتِ اَوِالۡقَتۡلِ وَاِذًا لَّا تُمَتَّعُوۡنَ اِلَّا قَلِیۡلًا» (33/16)\nTranslation: Say, 'Your fleeing will not benefit you if you flee from death or killing, and then you will not be given enjoyment except for a little.'\nMoreover, this word also occurs in the sense of running swiftly in competition. «اَلْفَرَّار» refers to a swift runner. And «مَفَرٌ مِّنَ الْخَیْل» is that swift-running horse which is useful when fleeing (minjadd). This word has been used in the Quran in these meanings as well.\nThe divine command states:\n«فَفِرُّوۡۤا اِلَی اللّٰہِ ؕ اِنِّیۡ لَکُمۡ  مِّنۡہُ نَذِیۡرٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ» (51/50)\nTranslation: 'So flee to Allah. Indeed, I am to you from Him a clear warner.'\nIn this verse, both the aforementioned meanings are found."
    },
    {
      "id": 577,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Flee / To Cause to Flee",
      "hw": "بھاگنا",
      "s": "«اَبَق» means for a slave to flee from his master or to escape from responsibilities (1 verse: 37:140)",
      "d": "The word «اَبَق» is specific for a slave fleeing from his master (m.f., minjadd), especially when there is no danger from the master (f.l. 31). This word is also used for escaping from one's responsibilities.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاِنَّ یُوۡنُسَ لَمِنَ الۡمُرۡسَلِیۡنَ اِذۡاَبَقَ اِلَی الۡفُلۡکِ الۡمَشۡحُوۡنِ» (37/140)\nTranslation: And indeed, Jonah was among the messengers when he fled to the laden ship.\nIn this verse, the word «اَبَقَ» conveys all these meanings."
    },
    {
      "id": 578,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Flee / To Cause to Flee",
      "hw": "بھاگنا",
      "s": "«زَھَقَ» means to flee after being weakened and defeated (1 verse: 17:81)",
      "d": "«زَھَقَ» means to flee after being defeated (m.r.). «زَھَقَتْ نَفْسُہٗ» means his soul departed. This word is from opposite-rooted words (addad). «زَاهِقُ» means both a very fat animal and a very thin and weak one (minjadd). Therefore, «اَزْھَقَ» means to flee after being defeated or after becoming weak and emaciated.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَقُلۡ جَآءَ الۡحَقُّ وَ زَہَقَ الۡبَاطِلُ ؕ اِنَّ الۡبَاطِلَ کَانَ زَہُوۡقًا» (17/81)\nTranslation: And say, 'Truth has come and falsehood has vanished. Indeed, falsehood is bound to vanish.' (Jalandhari)\nAnd say, 'Has truth come and falsehood fled?' Indeed, falsehood is one that flees. (Osmani)\nNote: (In lexicology, addad are words that have two opposite meanings.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 579,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Flee / To Cause to Flee",
      "hw": "بھاگنا",
      "s": "«ھَرْبَ» means for a criminal to flee in such a way during the commission of a crime as to avoid being caught (1 verse: 72:12)",
      "d": "«ھَرْبَ» means to flee due to the risk of being caught oneself (f.l. 31), such as a thief fleeing upon being detected during theft or stealing goods and taking them away. And «تَھْرِیْب» means tax evasion, and «مُھَرِّبْ» is used in the sense of smuggling (Qamus al-Jadid).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّاَنَّا ظَنَنَّاۤ اَنۡ لَّنۡ نُّعۡجِزَاللّٰہَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَلَنۡ نُّعۡجِزَہٗ ہَرَبًا» (72/12)\nTranslation: And we thought that we could not escape Allah in the land, nor could we flee from Him by running away."
    },
    {
      "id": 580,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Flee / To Cause to Flee",
      "hw": "بھاگنا",
      "s": "«اِسْتَنْفَرَ» means to flee in fright (7 verses: 4:71-9:38-9:39-9:41-9:81-9:122-74:50)",
      "d": "«نَفَرَ» means to go out for war, etc., and «اِسْتَنْفَرَ» means to flee in fright from something (m.f.).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کَاَنَّہُمۡ حُمُرٌ مُّسۡتَنۡفِرَۃٌ فَرَّتۡ مِنۡ قَسۡوَرَۃٍ» (74/50-51)\nTranslation: As if they were donkeys fleeing from a lion."
    },
    {
      "id": 581,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To flee; to cause to flee",
      "hw": "بھاگنا",
      "s": "«شَرَّدَ الْبَعِیْر» is an exemplary punishment that causes others to flee (1 verse: 8:57)",
      "d": "«شَرَّدَ الْبَعِیْر» means the camel fled in terror. And «شَرَّدَ» means to do something such that others do not do the same (as per Mufradat), and also means to drive away, frighten, cause to flee (as per Majma). Thus, its meaning is to cause others to flee by treating someone exemplarily. For example, the Quran says: «فَاِمَّا تَثۡقَفَنَّہُمۡ فِی الۡحَرۡبِ فَشَرِّدۡ بِہِمۡ مَّنۡ خَلۡفَہُمۡ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَذَّکَّرُوۡنَ» (8/57). Translation: If you find them in war, then inflict such a punishment on them that those behind them may flee and take heed."
    }
  ],
  "120": [
    {
      "id": 582,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Brother",
      "hw": "بھائی",
      "s": "«اِخوَۃٌ» is used for both brothers and sisters (14 verses: 4:11-4:23-4:176-12:5-12:7-12:8-12:58-12:69-12:100-20:42-24:31-24:61-33:55-49:10)",
      "d": "«اِخوَۃٌ» means brothers and siblings. It is used for kinship relations (as per Majma and Mufradat) and includes all brothers and sisters. For example, the Quran says: «فَاِنۡ کَانَ لَہٗۤ اِخۡوَۃٌ» (4/11). Translation: If the deceased has brothers too. In this verse, the word «اِخْوَۃٌ» is for both brothers and sisters. (as per Mufradat)"
    },
    {
      "id": 583,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "brother",
      "hw": "بھائی",
      "s": "«اِخْوَانٌ» is used for brotherhood, fraternal relations, and friendship (21 verses: 2:220-3:103-3:156-3:168-6:87-7:202-9:11-9:23-9:24-15:47-17:27-26:106-26:124-26:142-26:161-33:5-33:18-50:13-58:22-59:10-59:11)",
      "d": "The word «اِخْوَانٌ» denotes sincerity, friendship, and brotherhood.\nFor example, in the Quran: \n«یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ رَبَّنَا اغۡفِرۡ لَنَا وَلِاِخۡوَانِنَا الَّذِیۡنَ سَبَقُوۡنَا بِالۡاِیۡمَانِ» (59/10)\nTranslation: They say, 'Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith.'\nAnd the command of Allah is: \n«اِنَّمَا الۡمُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ اِخۡوَۃٌ» (49/10)\nTranslation: The believers are but brothers.\nIn this verse, it is indicated that the believers should not be considered merely as having a relationship of sincerity and friendship, but should be regarded as a fraternal bond like blood relations."
    }
  ],
  "121": [
    {
      "id": 584,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To fill",
      "hw": "بھرنا",
      "s": "«مَلَاَ» means to fill a vessel (6 verses: 3:91-7:18-11:119-32:13-38:85-50:30)",
      "d": "«مَلَاَ الاِنَاءَ» means to fill a vessel, and «مِلْءُ» is the amount with which a vessel is filled (as per Mufradat, Lisan, and Majma). For example, the Quran says: «فَلَنۡ یُّقۡبَلَ مِنۡ اَحَدِہِمۡ مِّلۡءُ الۡاَرۡضِ ذَہَبًا وَّلَوِ افۡتَدٰی بِہٖ» (3/91). Translation: (If a disbeliever seeks salvation) by offering gold equivalent to filling the earth in exchange, it will never be accepted. And «اِمْتَلَأَ» means to become full of something. For example, God Almighty says: «یَوۡمَ نَقُوۡلُ لِجَہَنَّمَ ہَلِ امۡتَلَاۡتِ وَ تَقُوۡلُ ہَلۡ مِنۡ مَّزِیۡدٍ» (50/30). Translation: On that Day, We will ask Hell, 'Have you been filled?' and it will reply, 'Is there more?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 585,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To fill",
      "hw": "بھرنا",
      "s": "«دَھَقَ» means a cup being filled with a drink (1 verse: 78:34)",
      "d": "«دَھَقَ» is used for a cup being filled with a drink (as per Farhang-e-Lughat). For example, the Quran says: «اِنَّ لِلۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ مَفَازًا، حَدَآئِقَ وَ اَعۡنَابًا، وَّکَوَاعِبَ اَتۡرَابًا، وَّ کَاۡسًا دِہَاقًا» (78/31,32,33,34). Translation: Indeed, for the righteous there is success (i.e., gardens and grapevines, and youthful maidens of equal age, and overflowing cups)."
    },
    {
      "id": 586,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Loading (a vessel)",
      "hw": "بھرنا",
      "s": "«شَحْنُ» is used for a loaded ship or vessel (3 verses: 26:119, 36:41, 37:140)",
      "d": "«شَحْنُ» means to fill a boat or ship with passengers and cargo (F L 69). For example, the Quran states: «اِذۡ اَبَقَ اِلَی الۡفُلۡکِ الۡمَشۡحُوۡنِ» (37:140). Translation: When he (Prophet Yunus) ran away to the fully laden ship."
    }
  ],
  "122": [
    {
      "id": 587,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Hunger",
      "hw": "بھوک",
      "s": "«جُوْع» refers to the state when a person feels the need to eat, i.e., the state of hunger (5 verses: 2:155, 16:112, 20:118, 88:7, 106:4)",
      "d": "«جُوْع» means the emergence of the desire to eat, and this is the initial degree of hunger (F L 161). Its opposite is «شَبَعَ» (to become satiated after eating) (M L). For example, the Quran states: «الَّذِیۡۤ اَطۡعَمَہُمۡ مِّنۡ جُوۡعٍ ۬ ۙ وَّاٰمَنَہُمۡ مِّنۡ خَوۡفٍ» (106:4). Translation: Who fed them from hunger and secured them from fear."
    },
    {
      "id": 588,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Hunger (Famine)",
      "hw": "بھوک",
      "s": "«مَسْغَبَۃ» refers to a period of famine and drought (1 verse: 90:14)",
      "d": "«سَغَبَ» means to be hungry, and «اَسْغَبَ» means for a people to be afflicted with famine. «سَغَابُ» is also used for hunger. This is the second degree of hunger (F L 161). For example, the Quran states: «اَوۡ اِطۡعٰمٌ فِیۡ یَوۡمٍ ذِیۡ مَسۡغَبَۃٍ» (90:14). Translation: Or feeding on a day of famine."
    },
    {
      "id": 589,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Hunger (Emaciation)",
      "hw": "بھوک",
      "s": "«مَخْمَصَۃ» refers to becoming thin-bellied due to lack of food (2 verses: 5:3, 9:120)",
      "d": "«خَمَصَہُ الْجُوْع» means hunger makes someone thin-bellied. «مَخْمَصَۃ» means an empty stomach from lack of food (Munjid). It means becoming lean and weak due to scarcity of food and excessive labor, and the stomach becoming gaunt (R L). This is the third degree of hunger (F L 161). For example, the Quran states: «فَمَنِ اضۡطُرَّ فِیۡ مَخۡمَصَۃٍ غَیۡرَ مُتَجَانِفٍ لِّاِثۡمٍ ۙ فَاِنَّ اللّٰہَ غَفُوۡرٌرَّحِیۡمٌ» (5:3). Translation: But whoever is forced by necessity, without willful disobedience, then indeed, Allah is Forgiving and Merciful."
    },
    {
      "id": 590,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Hunger (Destitution)",
      "hw": "بھوک",
      "s": "«خَصَاصَۃ» refers to reaching the point of fasting due to poverty and need (1 verse: 59:9)",
      "d": "«خَصَّ» means to be needy and destitute. «خَصَاصَۃً» is a verbal noun, and «خُصَاصَۃ» means a little and scant (Munjid). It means reaching the state of fasting due to poverty and necessity. For example, the Quran states: «وَ یُؤۡثِرُوۡنَ عَلٰۤی اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ وَلَوۡ کَانَ بِہِمۡ خَصَاصَۃٌ» (59:9). Translation: And they give preference to others over themselves, even if they are in a state of destitution."
    }
  ],
  "123": [
    {
      "id": 591,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To forget, to cause to forget",
      "hw": "بھولنا",
      "s": "«نَسِیَ» meaning 'to forget' is used generally, regardless of the reason—whether due to negligence, abandonment of restraint, or anything else (24 verses: 2:106, 2:286, 6:68, 7:51, 9:67, 12:42, 18:24, 18:57, 18:61, 18:63, 18:73, 19:23, 19:64, 20:52, 20:88, 20:115, 20:126, 32:14, 36:78, 39:8, 45:34, 58:19, 59:19, 87:6)",
      "d": "«نَسِیَ» is the general word for 'to forget', whether the cause is negligence, abandonment of self-control, or something else (Muf). For example, the Quran states: «وَ ضَرَبَ لَنَا مَثَلًا وَّ نَسِیَ خَلۡقَہٗ» (36:78). Translation: And he (man) strikes for Us a similitude and forgets his own creation. And «اَنْسٰی» means to cause someone to forget something. For example, the Quran states: «فَاَنۡسٰہُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ ذِکۡرَ رَبِّہٖ» (12:42). Translation: But Satan caused him to forget the mention of his Lord."
    },
    {
      "id": 594,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To forget, to cause to forget",
      "hw": "بھولنا",
      "s": "«ذَھَل» means to forget due to terror and distress (1 verse: 22:2)",
      "d": "«ذَھَلَ ، ذَھُوْلًا» When the cause of forgetting is terror or such preoccupation that leads to grief and distress, it is called «ذَھُوْل» (Muf). «ذَھَلَ ، ذَھُوْلًا» also means to be heedless, to forget, and «ذَھِلَ ذَھُوْلًا» means to be bewildered, to be astonished (Munjid). For example, the Quran states: «یَوۡمَ تَرَوۡنَہَا تَذۡہَلُ کُلُّ مُرۡضِعَۃٍ عَمَّاۤ اَرۡضَعَتۡ وَتَضَعُ کُلُّ ذَاتِ حَمۡلٍ حَمۡلَہَا وَ تَرَی النَّاسَ سُکٰرٰی وَ مَا ہُمۡ بِسُکۡرٰی» (22:2). Translation: On the Day you will see it, every nursing mother will be distracted from her child, and every pregnant woman will abort her pregnancy, and you will see the people appearing intoxicated while they are not intoxicated."
    }
  ],
  "124": [
    {
      "id": 595,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To roast",
      "hw": "بھوننا",
      "s": "«شَوٰی» means to roast meat etc. on fire (2 verses: 18:29, 70:16)",
      "d": "«شَوٰی» means to roast meat etc. in fire (Muf, Munjid). For example, the Quran states: «وَاِنۡ یَّسۡتَغِیۡثُوۡا یُغَاثُوۡا بِمَآءٍ کَالۡمُہۡلِ یَشۡوِی الۡوُجُوۡہَ» (18:29). Translation: And if they seek help, they will be helped with water like molten brass, which scalds [i.e., roasts] the faces."
    },
    {
      "id": 596,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To roast",
      "hw": "بھوننا",
      "s": "«حَنَذَ» means intense heat (1 verse: 11:69)",
      "d": "«اَلْحَنَذَۃٌ» means intense heat, and «حَنِیْذ» means hot water as well as roasted meat. And «حَنَذَتْہُ الشَّمْس» means the sun scalds someone (Munjid). The original meaning of «حَنَذَ» is to remove moisture and dampness (i.e., wetness and humidity) by any means of heat (Muf). For example, the Quran states: «فَمَا لَبِثَ اَنۡ جَآءَ بِعِجۡلٍ حَنِیۡذٍ» (11:69). Translation: He did not tarry long and came with a roasted calf."
    }
  ],
  "125": [
    {
      "id": 597,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To send",
      "hw": "بھیجنا",
      "s": "«اَرْسَلَ» means to send someone with a message, letter, or command (131 verses: 2:119, 2:151, 4:64, 4:79, 4:80, 5:70, 6:6, 6:42, 6:48, 6:61, 7:6, 7:57, 7:59, 7:75, 7:87, 7:94, 7:105, 7:111, 7:133, 7:134, 7:162, 9:33, 11:25, 11:52, 11:57, 11:70, 11:96, 12:12, 12:19, 12:31, 12:45, 12:63, 12:66, 12:109, 13:13, 13:30, 13:38, 14:4, 14:5, 14:9, 15:10, 15:22, 15:58, 16:43, 16:63, 17:54, 17:59, 17:68, 17:69, 17:77, 17:105, 18:40, 18:56, 19:17, 19:83, 20:47, 20:134, 21:5, 21:7, 21:25, 21:107, 22:52, 23:23, 23:32, 23:44, 23:45, 25:20, 25:48, 25:56, 26:13, 26:17, 26:27, 26:53, 27:35, 27:45, 27:63, 28:34, 28:47, 29:14, 29:40, 30:46, 30:47, 30:48, 30:51, 33:9, 33:45, 34:16, 34:28, 34:34, 34:44, 35:2, 35:9, 35:24, 36:14, 36:16, 37:72, 37:147, 39:42, 40:23, 40:70, 40:78, 41:14, 41:16, 42:48, 42:51, 43:6, 43:23, 43:24, 43:45, 43:46, 46:23, 48:8, 48:28, 51:32, 51:33, 51:38, 51:41, 54:19, 54:27, 54:31, 54:34, 55:35, 57:25, 57:26, 61:9, 67:17, 71:1, 71:11, 73:15, 83:33, 105:3)",
      "d": "«اَرْسَلَ» means to send someone with a message, a letter, or a command (Munjid). And «رَسُول» means a messenger or one who delivers a message, who can be from among humans or from among the angels. For example, the Quran states: «قَالُوۡۤا اَرۡجِہۡ وَاَخَاہُ وَاَرۡسِلۡ فِی الۡمَدَآئِنِ حٰشِرِیۡنَ» (7:111). Translation: They (the courtiers of Pharaoh) said, 'Postpone [the matter of] him and his brother and send gatherers to the cities.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 598,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to send",
      "hw": "بھیجنا",
      "s": "«بَعَثَ» means to send someone alone for the accomplishment of a purpose (54 verses: 2:56-2:129-2:213-2:246-2:247-2:259-3:164-4:35-5:12-5:31-6:36-6:60-6:65-7:14-7:103-7:167-10:74-10:75-15:36-16:21-16:36-16:38-16:84-16:89-17:5-17:15-17:79-17:94-18:12-18:19-19:15-19:33-22:5-22:7-23:16-23:100-25:41-25:51-26:36-26:87-27:65-28:59-30:56-31:28-36:52-37:144-38:79-40:34-58:6-58:18-62:2-64:7-72:7-91:12)",
      "d": "«بَعَثَ» basically has two meanings: (1) to raise, to lift, and (2) to send alone. Then sometimes only one meaning is taken. For example, «بَعَثْتُ الْبَعِیْر» means I let the camel go after lifting it. And when it means to send, it implies sending for the accomplishment of a purpose or mission.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«فَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ غُرَابًا یَّبۡحَثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (5/31)\nTranslation: And God sent a crow that began to scratch the earth.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«ہُوَالَّذِیۡ بَعَثَ فِی الۡاُمِّیّٖنَ رَسُوۡلًا مِّنۡہُمۡ یَتۡلُوۡاعَلَیۡہِمۡ اٰیٰتِہٖ وَیُزَکِّیۡہِمۡ» (62/2)\nTranslation: He it is who sent among the unlettered a messenger from themselves, reciting to them His verses and purifying them."
    }
  ],
  "126": [
    {
      "id": 599,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to describe",
      "hw": "بیان",
      "s": "«وَصَفَ» means to describe the state of something (14 verses: 6:100-6:139-12:18-12:77-16:62-16:116-21:18-21:22-21:112-23:91-23:96-37:159-37:180-43:82)",
      "d": "«وَصَفَ» means to describe the state and definition of something (whether true or false), to depict. (mufrad)\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«قَالَ بَلۡ سَوَّلَتۡ لَکُمۡ اَنۡفُسُکُمۡ اَمۡرًا ؕ فَصَبۡرٌ جَمِیۡلٌ ؕ وَاللّٰہُ الۡمُسۡتَعَانُ عَلٰی مَا تَصِفُوۡنَ» (12/18)\nTranslation: Jacob (peace be upon him) said, \"Rather, you have fabricated a matter yourselves. So patience is most fitting. And God is the one sought for help against what you describe.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 600,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to describe",
      "hw": "بیان",
      "s": "«قَصَّ» means to narrate a story or event (20 verses: 3:62-4:164-6:57-6:130-7:7-7:35-7:101-7:176-11:100-11:120-12:3-12:5-12:111-16:118-18:13-18:64-20:99-27:76-28:25-40:78)",
      "d": "«قَصَّ» means to follow someone's footsteps (mufrad).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«فَارۡتَدَّا عَلٰۤی اٰثَارِہِمَا قَصَصًا» (18/64)\nTranslation: So they both turned back, following their footprints.\nFrom this, «قَصَّ» also means to follow gradually, i.e., to proceed step by step (manjad), meaning to narrate an event or story that has been passed down through generations.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«نَحۡنُ نَقُصُّ عَلَیۡکَ اَحۡسَنَ الۡقَصَصِ بِمَاۤ اَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ اِلَیۡکَ ہٰذَا الۡقُرۡاٰنَ» (12/3)\nTranslation: We relate to you the best of stories in what We have revealed to you of this Quran.\nThen this word came to be used for narrating any general event or story.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«فَلَمَّا جَآءَہٗ وَقَصَّ عَلَیۡہِ الۡقَصَصَ ۙ قَالَ لَا تَخَفۡ ٝ۟ نَجَوۡتَ مِنَ الۡقَوۡمِ الظّٰلِمِیۡنَ» (28/25)\nTranslation: When Moses came to him and narrated his story to him, he said, \"Do not fear; you have escaped from the wrongdoing people.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 601,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to describe",
      "hw": "بیان",
      "s": "«ضَرَبَ ، مَثَلًا» means to give an example or parable (30 verses: 2:26-13:17-14:24-14:25-14:45-16:74-16:75-16:76-16:112-17:48-18:32-18:45-22:73-24:35-25:9-25:39-29:43-30:28-30:58-36:13-36:78-39:27-39:29-43:17-43:57-43:58-47:3-59:21-66:10-66:11)",
      "d": "«مَثَلًا» means to state something in a way that another thing can be understood from it (mufrad). To give an example or parable. «ضَرْبُ الْمِثْل» is a famous phrase.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یَسۡتَحۡیٖۤ اَنۡ یَّضۡرِبَ مَثَلًا مَّا بَعُوۡضَۃً فَمَا فَوۡقَہَا» (2/26)\nTranslation: Indeed, God is not ashamed to set forth an example of a mosquito or what is smaller than it."
    },
    {
      "id": 602,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to describe",
      "hw": "بیان",
      "s": "«حَدَّثَ» means to inform of something that common people are unaware of (8 verses: 2:76-18:70-20:113-21:2-26:5-65:1-93:11-99:4)",
      "d": "«حَدَثَ» means for something to come into existence that was not present before (m. l). And «حَدَّثَ» means to inform of something that common people are unaware of.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَقَالَ الۡاِنۡسَانُ مَا لَہَا ، یَوۡمَئِذٍ تُحَدِّثُ اَخۡبَارَہَا» (99/3،4)\nTranslation: And man will say, \"What is the matter with her?\" On that Day, she will narrate her news."
    },
    {
      "id": 604,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to describe",
      "hw": "بیان",
      "s": "«صَرَّفَ» means to shed light on different aspects of a matter (26 verses: 3:152-6:16-6:46-6:65-6:105-7:47-7:58-7:146-9:127-10:32-12:24-12:33-12:34-17:41-17:89-18:53-18:54-20:113-24:43-25:19-25:50-25:65-39:6-40:69-46:27-46:29)",
      "d": "«صَرَّفَ» means to turn something from one state to another, and «صَرَّفَ» means to repeat and describe something (mufrad). That is, to explain a matter by presenting it in different ways and shedding light on its various aspects.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«اُنۡظُرۡ کَیۡکَ نُصَرِّفُ الۡاٰیٰتِ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَفۡقَہُوۡنَ» (6/65)\nTranslation: See how We diversify the verses so that they may understand."
    },
    {
      "id": 605,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to describe",
      "hw": "بیان",
      "s": "«فَصَلَ» means to state something in an ordered and separate manner (33 verses: 2:249-6:55-6:97-6:98-6:114-6:119-6:126-7:32-7:52-7:133-7:174-9:11-10:5-10:24-11:1-12:94-13:2-17:12-22:17-30:28-32:25-37:21-38:20-41:3-41:44-42:21-44:40-60:3-77:13-77:14-77:38-78:17-86:13)",
      "d": "«فَصَلَ» means for one thing to be separate from another such that there is a distance between them. And «فَصَّلَ» means to separate and arrange a matter and state it in an ordered manner.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَکُلَّ شَیۡءٍ فَصَّلۡنٰہُ تَفۡصِیۡلًا» (17/12)\nTranslation: And We have detailed everything in detail."
    },
    {
      "id": 606,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to describe",
      "hw": "بیان",
      "s": "«فَسَّرَ» means to explain ambiguous and difficult passages (1 verse: 25:33)",
      "d": "«اَلْفَسَر» means to state the spiritual attributes of something (mufrad). Also, «فَسَرَ» means to explain the meaning and intent. And «فَسَّرَ» means to remove the veil from something (m. l. manjad). And this is generally done with two words: 1. With «اَیْ» the ambiguous (i.e., that which is not clear in meaning and not understood) is explained, and with «اَوْ» the meaning and intent are explained. And it means to state each word of a sentence clearly and consider the revelation (faq l 43).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَلَا یَاۡتُوۡنَکَ بِمَثَلٍ اِلَّا جِئۡنٰکَ بِالۡحَقِّ وَاَحۡسَنَ  تَفۡسِیۡرًا» (25/33)\nTranslation: And they do not come to you with an example except that We bring you the truth and the best explanation."
    }
  ],
  "127": [
    {
      "id": 607,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "son and daughter",
      "hw": "بیٹا",
      "s": "«وَلَدُ» literal meaning is boy (40 verses: 2:116-2:233-3:47-4:11-4:12-4:75-4:98-4:127-4:171-4:176-6:101-10:68-12:21-17:111-18:4-18:39-19:15-19:33-19:35-19:77-19:88-19:91-19:92-21:26-23:91-25:2-26:18-28:9-31:33-37:152-39:4-43:81-56:17-58:2-71:21-72:3-73:17-76:19-90:3-112:3)",
      "d": "«وَلَدُ» refers to every child that the mother gives birth to; it is called «وَلَدُ، وَلِیْد، مَوْلُوْد». These three words are used for both masculine and feminine. Lexically, the feminine of «وَلِیْد» is «وَلِیْدَۃ», but the Quran does not use the word «وَلِیْدَۃ». Among these three words, if there is any difference, it is that «وَلَدُ» is used for someone of any age. An old man is also the «وَلَدُ» of his father or mother as he was at birth. And «وَلِیْد» is used from birth until before puberty. For example, in the Quran, Pharaoh said to Moses (peace be upon him):\n«اَلَمۡ نُرَبِّکَ فِیۡنَا وَلِیۡدًا» (26/18)\nTranslation: Did we not raise you among us as a child?\nAnd «مَوْلُوْد» is generally attributed to the father. It is rarely attributed to the mother. And «مولود» comes in the meaning of son. Its application is generally for a young child (manjad), but it can also be for an adult. As the Almighty says:\n«وَلَا مَوۡلُوۡدٌ ہُوَ جَازٍعَنۡ وَّالِدِہٖ شَیۡئًا» (31/33)\nTranslation: And no son will bear the burden of his father."
    }
  ],
  "128": [
    {
      "id": 609,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to sit",
      "hw": "بیٹھنا",
      "s": "«جَلَسَ» means to sit after lying down, standing, or moving, i.e., after any movement (1 verse: 58:11)",
      "d": "«جَلَسَ» is commonly used in the meaning of sitting. Whether one sits after lying down or after coming from somewhere or after standing, and its opposite is «قَامَ». And «جَلْسٌ» means high and hard ground, and «جَلَسَ» means to place one's seat on hard ground and sit. The place of sitting is called «مَجْلِس», and those who sit together are also called «مَجْلِس». Its plural is «مَجَالِس». And «جَلْسَہ» is a repeated noun, meaning to sit once or the state of sitting. (muf. manjad)\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا قِیۡلَ لَکُمۡ تَفَسَّحُوۡا فِی الۡمَجٰلِسِ فَافۡسَحُوۡا یَفۡسَحِ اللّٰہُ لَکُمۡ» (58/11)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when it is said to you, \"Make room in the assemblies,\" then make room; God will make room for you."
    },
    {
      "id": 610,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To sit",
      "hw": "بیٹھنا",
      "s": "«قَعَدَ» means to sit (20 verses: 2:127-3:168-3:191-4:103-4:140-6:68-7:16-7:86-9:5-9:46-9:81-9:83-9:90-16:26-17:22-17:29-24:60-54:55-72:9-85:6)",
      "d": "«قَعَدَ» is used in several meanings. For example: (1) To sit down from a standing position, and «قَعْدَۃ» is the noun of instance, meaning to sit once, as in sitting between two prostrations (as per Mufradat and Qamus). For example, the Quran says: «فَلَا تَقۡعُدۡ بَعۡدَ الذِّکۡرٰی مَعَ الۡقَوۡمِ الظّٰلِمِیۡنَ» (6/68). Translation: Do not sit with the wrongdoers after the remembrance (of God). (2) To remain seated, to do nothing, to turn away from the actual work. For example, the Quran says: «وَجَآءَ الۡمُعَذِّرُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡاَعۡرَابِ لِیُؤۡذَنَ لَہُمۡ وَقَعَدَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَذَبُوا اللّٰہَ وَرَسُوۡلَہٗ» (9/90). Translation: And some of the desert Arabs came to seek permission, and those who lied to God and His Messenger remained seated (at home). (3) To stand; «قَعَدَ» is from the category of words with opposite meanings (adhad), and «قَعُوْدًا» means both seated and standing. Similarly, «مَقْعَد» means both a seat and a place (as per Mufradat, Raghib, and Majma). For example, the Quran says: «فِیۡ مَقۡعَدِ صِدۡقٍ عِنۡدَ مَلِیۡکٍ مُّقۡتَدِرٍ» (54/55). Translation: They will be in gardens and rivers, i.e., in a pure place (a true seat) in the presence of an honorable, all-powerful King. (4) Then, as «قَعَدَ» comes in the meanings of sitting or not doing work, it also comes in the meaning of being prepared to sit for a task. As in «قَعَدَ لِلْحَرْبِ» means to sit prepared for battle (as per Mufradat). For example, the Quran says: «فَاقۡتُلُواالۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ حَیۡثُ وَجَدۡتُّمُوۡہُمۡ وَخُذُوۡہُمۡ وَاحۡصُرُوۡہُمۡ وَاقۡعُدُوۡا لَہُمۡ کُلَّ مَرۡصَدٍ» (9/5). Translation: Kill the polytheists wherever you find them, capture them, besiege them, and lie in wait for them at every place of ambush. And «قَعِیْدَہ» is the term for a woman who is the guardian and protector of the house, staying within it, and its plural is «قواعد». For example, the Quran says: «وَالۡقَوَاعِدُ مِنَ النِّسَآءِ الّٰتِیۡ لَا یَرۡجُوۡنَ نِکَاحًا» (24/60). Translation: And women who sit (at home) and do not hope for marriage. Note: (Adhad words are those that have two opposite meanings)."
    }
  ],
  "129": [
    {
      "id": 612,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Sick",
      "hw": "بیمار",
      "s": "«سَقِیْم» is used only for minor physical ailments (2 verses: 37:89-37:145)",
      "d": "«سَقِمَ» means sickness, disease, etc., and also means incorrect speech (i.e., false talk) (as per Majma). The word «سَقِمَ» is specific for physical sickness (as per Mufradat). According to the expert in etymology, the first degree of sickness is 'alailat' when one's health is slightly off, then 'saqim' when it worsens, and when very sick, it's 'marid' (as per Farhang-e-Lughat, page 123). For example, the Quran says: «فَنَظَرَ نَظۡرَۃً فِی النُّجُوۡمِ، فَقَالَ اِنِّیۡ سَقِیۡمٌ» (37/88,89). Translation: Then he (Abraham) looked at the stars and said, 'I am indeed sick.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 613,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Sick (general)",
      "hw": "بیمار",
      "s": "«مَرِیْض» is used for all types of sickness—physical, mental, minor, or severe (23 verses: 2:10-2:184-2:185-2:196-4:43-4:102-5:6-5:52-8:49-9:91-9:125-22:53-24:50-24:61-26:80-33:12-33:32-33:60-47:20-47:29-48:17-73:20-74:31)",
      "d": "«مَرِیْض» is a degree higher than «سَقِیْمٌ» in terms of sickness. And «مَرَضُ الْمَوْت» refers to a sickness that proves fatal. The word «مرض» is used for both physical and mental ailments.\nExample: The Quran states: «فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ مَّرَضٌ ۙ فَزَادَہُمُ اللّٰہُ مَرَضًا» (2/10)\nTranslation: There is a disease in their hearts, and Allah has increased them in disease.\nAnd by 'mental ailments' are meant vile morals, such as cowardice, stinginess, hypocrisy, disbelief, etc.\nThe plural of «مَرِیْض» is «مَرْضٰی», and its plural is «اَمْرَاض».\nExample: The Quran states: «لَیۡسَ عَلَی الضُّعَفَآءِ وَلَا عَلَی الۡمَرۡضٰی وَلَاعَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ لَا یَجِدُوۡنَ مَا یُنۡفِقُوۡنَ حَرَجٌ» (9/91)\nTranslation: There is no blame upon the weak, nor upon the sick, nor upon those who find nothing to spend (for Jihad)."
    },
    {
      "id": 614,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Sick (severe/terminal)",
      "hw": "بیمار",
      "s": "«حَرَضَ» refers to a patient who is emaciated, weak, and near death (1 verse: 12:85)",
      "d": "«حَرَضَ» means to be afflicted with a severe illness, becoming emaciated and weak. «اَحْرَضَہُ الْمَرَضَ اَوِ الْحُزْن» means the sickness or grief has made him emaciated. (Ref: Manjad) And «حَرَضَ» means to become severely emaciated and reach the point of death. (Ref: Quran)\nExample: The Quran states: «قَالُوۡا تَاللّٰہِ تَفۡتَؤُا تَذۡکُرُ  یُوۡسُفَ حَتّٰی تَکُوۡنَ حَرَضًا اَوۡ تَکُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡہٰلِکِیۡنَ» (12/85)\nTranslation: They said, 'By Allah, you will not cease remembering Yusuf until you become gravely ill or become of those who perish.'"
    }
  ],
  "130": [
    {
      "id": 615,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Wife",
      "hw": "بیوی",
      "s": "«زَوْج» is used for wife in Arabic (72 verses: 2:25-2:35-2:102-2:230-2:232-2:234-2:240-3:15-4:1-4:12-4:20-4:57-6:139-6:143-7:19-7:189-9:24-11:40-13:3-13:23-13:38-15:88-16:72-20:53-20:117-20:131-21:90-22:5-23:6-23:27-24:6-25:74-26:7-26:166-30:21-31:10-33:4-33:6-33:28-33:37-33:50-33:52-33:53-33:59-35:11-36:36-36:56-37:22-38:58-39:6-40:8-42:11-42:50-43:12-43:70-44:54-50:7-51:49-52:20-53:45-55:52-56:7-58:1-60:11-64:14-66:1-66:3-66:5-70:30-75:39-78:8-81:7)",
      "d": "«زَوْج» means pair. Then, in a pair, each is the «زَوْج» of the other. Husband and wife are each other's «زَوْج». For example, for a woman, the Quran says: «وَ قُلۡنَا یٰۤاٰدَمُ اسۡکُنۡ اَنۡتَ وَ زَوۡجُکَ الۡجَنَّۃَ» (2/35). Translation: And We said, 'O Adam, dwell you and your wife in Paradise.' And for a man, the Quran says: «قَدۡ سَمِعَ اللّٰہُ قَوۡلَ الَّتِیۡ تُجَادِلُکَ فِیۡ زَوۡجِہَا» (58/1). Translation: Indeed, God has heard the statement of the woman who disputes with you regarding her husband. And together, they both remain a pair."
    },
    {
      "id": 616,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Wife",
      "hw": "بیوی",
      "s": "«حَلَائِل» means a woman who is in one's marriage (1 verse: 4:23)",
      "d": "«حَلَائِل» is the plural of «حَلِیْلَہ». It means 'halal' (lawful) wife or married woman. And «حَلِیْلَۃٌ» is the feminine form of «حَلِیْل». For a man, his wife is «حَلِیْلَۃٌ», and for a woman, her husband is «حَلِیْل». The plural of both «حَلِیْل» and «حَلِیْلَۃٌ» is «حَلَائِل» (as per Majma). There is no example of «حَلِیْل» in the Quran, and the example of «حَلِیْلَۃٌ» is: God Almighty says: «وَ حَلَآئِلُ اَبۡنَآئِکُمُ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ اَصۡلَابِکُمۡ» (4/23). Translation: And your wives from among those whom you have married by consummation."
    },
    {
      "id": 617,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Wife (general woman)",
      "hw": "بیوی",
      "s": "«اِمْرَاَۃٌ» means a general woman and is also used for a wife (25 verses: 2:282-3:35-3:40-4:12-4:128-7:83-11:71-11:81-12:21-12:30-12:51-15:60-19:5-19:8-27:23-27:57-28:9-28:23-29:32-29:33-33:50-51:29-66:10-66:11-111:4)",
      "d": "«اِمْرَاَۃٌ» means a general woman, and this word has also been used for a wife.\nExample: The Quran states: «ضَرَبَ اللّٰہُ مَثَلًا  لِّلَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوا امۡرَاَتَ نُوۡحٍ وَّامۡرَاَتَ لُوۡطٍ» (66/10)\nTranslation: Allah has set forth an example for those who disbelieve: the wife of Noah and the wife of Lot."
    },
    {
      "id": 618,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Wife",
      "hw": "بیوی",
      "s": "«نِسَاءٌ» means woman and is also used for wives (51 verses: 2:49-2:187-2:222-2:223-2:226-2:231-2:232-2:235-2:236-3:14-3:42-3:61-4:1-4:3-4:4-4:7-4:11-4:15-4:19-4:22-4:23-4:24-4:32-4:34-4:43-4:75-4:98-4:127-4:176-5:6-7:81-7:127-7:141-14:6-24:31-24:60-27:55-28:4-33:30-33:32-33:52-33:55-33:59-40:25-48:25-49:11-58:2-58:3-65:1-65:4)",
      "d": "«اِمْرَأَۃٌ» is a non-plural form meaning general women. This word has also been used for wives. For example, the Quran says: «یٰنِسَآءَ النَّبِیِّ لَسۡتُنَّ کَاَحَدٍ مِّنَ النِّسَآءِ» (33/32). Translation: O wives of the Prophet, you are not like other women."
    },
    {
      "id": 619,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Wife (honorific)",
      "hw": "بیوی",
      "s": "«صَاحِبَۃ» is used as an honorific to address a woman, e.g., 'Mrs.' and is also used for a wife (4 verses: 6:101-70:12-72:3-80:36)",
      "d": "«صَاحِب» means companion and friend. From it, the feminine «صَاحِبَۃ» is derived, which has been used in the meaning of a wife.\nExample: The Quran states: «یَوۡمَ یَفِرُّالۡمَرۡءُ مِنۡ اَخِیۡہِ ، وَاُمِّہٖ وَاَبِیۡہِ ، وَصَاحِبَتِہٖ وَ بَنِیۡہِ» (80/34,35,36)\nTranslation: The Day when a man will flee from his brother, his mother, his father, his wife, and his children."
    },
    {
      "id": 620,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Wife (household/family)",
      "hw": "بیوی",
      "s": "«اَھْل» refers to a person's relatives or those who live in the same house, and «اَھْلَ الرَّجُل» can also mean his wife (1 verse: 12:25)",
      "d": "«اَھْلَ الرَّجُل» means a person's relatives or those who live in the same house. Then, this word is also used for a person's close relatives. And sometimes, «اَھْلَ الرَّجُل» means his wife.\nExample: The Quran states: «قَالَتۡ مَا جَزَآءُ مَنۡ اَرَادَ بِاَہۡلِکَ سُوۡٓءً» (12/25)\nTranslation: She [Zulaikha] said to her husband, 'What is the punishment for one who intends evil against your wife?'"
    }
  ],
  "131": [
    {
      "id": 622,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Injustice; to do injustice",
      "hw": "نا انصافی",
      "s": "«ظَلَمَ» refers to any injustice, whether related to God's rights or others' rights (128 verses: 2:54-2:57-2:59-2:150-2:165-2:231-2:272-2:279-2:281-3:25-3:108-3:117-3:135-3:161-4:10-4:30-4:40-4:49-4:64-4:77-4:110-4:124-4:148-4:153-4:160-4:168-5:39-6:21-6:45-6:82-6:93-6:131-6:144-6:157-6:160-7:9-7:23-7:37-7:103-7:160-7:162-7:165-7:177-8:25-8:60-9:36-9:70-10:13-10:17-10:44-10:47-10:52-10:54-11:18-11:37-11:67-11:94-11:101-11:113-11:116-11:117-13:6-14:44-14:45-16:33-16:41-16:61-16:85-16:111-16:118-17:59-17:71-18:15-18:33-18:49-18:57-18:59-18:87-19:60-20:111-20:112-21:3-21:47-22:25-22:39-23:27-23:62-25:4-25:19-26:227-27:11-27:14-27:44-27:52-27:85-28:16-29:40-29:46-29:68-30:9-30:29-30:57-31:13-32:22-34:19-34:42-36:54-37:22-38:24-39:32-39:47-39:51-39:69-40:17-40:31-42:41-42:42-43:39-43:65-43:76-45:22-46:12-46:19-51:59-52:47-53:52-61:7-65:1)",
      "d": "«ظَلَمَ» is primarily used in two ways: (1) To place something in a place other than its rightful place unjustly, and (2) to mean darkness, which is the opposite of light and brightness. And «ظُلْمَتْ» means darkness, its plural is «ظُلُمٰت», and the plural form «اَلْجَمْعُ ظَّلَام» is also used (as per Mufradat). In the first meaning, the opposite of injustice is justice. And any act of injustice, whether it pertains to God's rights or the rights of His servants, is considered injustice. This term is general in usage. For example, the Quran says: «یٰبُنَیَّ لَا تُشۡرِکۡ بِاللّٰہِ ؕ ؔاِنَّ الشِّرۡکَ لَظُلۡمٌ عَظِیۡمٌ» (31/13). Translation: O my son! Do not associate anything with God. Indeed, associating partners with Him is a great injustice. At another place, God Almighty says: «لَا یُحِبُّ اللّٰہُ الۡجَہۡرَ بِالسُّوۡٓءِ مِنَ الۡقَوۡلِ اِلَّا مَنۡ ظُلِمَ» (4/148). Translation: God does not like the public utterance of hurtful speech unless it is by one who has been wronged."
    },
    {
      "id": 623,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Injustice or doing injustice",
      "hw": "نا انصافی",
      "s": "«حَافَ» means to show bias in fulfilling the rights of another and to give less (1 verse: 24:50)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «حَافَ» is «اَلْمَیْل» or inclination towards a side (m. l.), i.e., to lean towards one side while judging and not to do justice (muf). Then, the meanings of «حَافَ» also include to diminish something from its sides and to reduce it (manjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَمۡ یَخَافُوۡنَ اَنۡ یَّحِیۡفَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ وَ رَسُوۡلُہٗ» (24/50)\nTranslation: Or do they fear that Allah and His Messenger will deal unjustly with them?"
    },
    {
      "id": 624,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Injustice or doing injustice",
      "hw": "نا انصافی",
      "s": "«عَالَ» To commit such an injustice wherein the right of another is also violated, and the one whose right is suppressed also feels burdened (1 verse: 4:3)",
      "d": "«عَالَ» means to commit injustice. To deviate from the straight path (manjad). And «اَلْعَوْل» is used for every such thing or action that burdens a person and causes them to be crushed under its weight. So, its meaning is to wrongfully take more than one's rightful share, i.e., to commit injustice by taking more than one's due right (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ خِفۡتُمۡ اَلَّا تَعۡدِلُوۡا فَوَاحِدَۃً اَوۡ مَا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ ؕ ذٰلِکَ اَدۡنٰۤی اَلَّا تَعُوۡلُوۡا» (4/3)\nTranslation: And if you fear that you will not deal justly with the orphan girls, then marry those that please you of [other] women, one or two or three or four. But if you fear that you will not be just, then [marry only] one or those your right hands possess. That is more suitable that you may not incline [to injustice]."
    },
    {
      "id": 625,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Injustice or doing injustice",
      "hw": "نا انصافی",
      "s": "«ضَازَ» To commit extreme lawlessness in the determination of rights (1 verse: 53:22)",
      "d": "«ضَازَ» means to commit injustice; to give less than the due right. «ضَیْز» means crookedness, perversion. And «قِسْمَۃٌ ضِیْزٰی» means a deficient and unjust division (manjad). i.e., in determining one's own and others' rights, to completely disregard all demands of justice, to practice fraud.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَکُمُ الذَّکَرُ وَلَہُ الۡاُنۡثٰی ، تِلۡکَ اِذًا قِسۡمَۃٌ ضِیۡزٰی» (53:21,22)\nTranslation: [O disbelievers], for you is the male, and for Him is the female? That is a great division indeed."
    }
  ],
  "132": [
    {
      "id": 627,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be averse (to women)",
      "hw": "بے رغبتی",
      "s": "«حَصُور» means a person who is averse to women (1 verse: 3:39)",
      "d": "«حَصَرَ» means to confine by constricting. «حَصِر» means to be confined or restricted. And «حَصُوْر» is the term for a person who remains aloof from women and does not have inclination towards them.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَنَّ اللّٰہَ یُبَشِّرُکَ بِیَحۡیٰی مُصَدِّقًۢا بِکَلِمَۃٍ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ وَ سَیِّدًا وَّ حَصُوۡرًا وَّ نَبِیًّا مِّنَ الصّٰلِحِیۡنَ» (3/39)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah gives you glad tidings of John, who will confirm a word from Allah and [be] a master of etiquette, chaste, and a prophet from among the righteous."
    }
  ],
  "133": [
    {
      "id": 631,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To feel aversion/disgust",
      "hw": "بیزار",
      "s": "«مَقْت» Intense dislike and aversion towards a reprehensible (evil) act (5 verses: 4:22-35:39-40:10-40:35-61:3)",
      "d": "«مَقْت» means to be intensely angry and disgusted upon committing a vile act. And it is the next degree after «قَلٰی» (f.l. 166).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَلَا تَنۡکِحُوۡا مَا نَکَحَ اٰبَآؤُکُمۡ مِّنَ النِّسَآءِ اِلَّا مَا قَدۡ سَلَفَ ؕ اِنَّہٗ کَانَ فَاحِشَۃً وَّ مَقۡتًا ؕ وَسَآءَ سَبِیۡلًا» (4/22)\nTranslation: And do not marry those [women] whom your fathers married, except what has already occurred. Indeed, it was an immorality and hateful, and how evil was the practice."
    }
  ],
  "134": [
    {
      "id": 632,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Indeed, Verily",
      "hw": "بیشک",
      "s": "«اِنَّ ، اَنَّ» Both these particles come for emphasis and affirmation. «اِنّ» comes at the beginning of a sentence, and «اَنَّ» comes in the middle (1605 verses: 2:6-2:12-2:13-2:14-2:20-2:25-2:26-2:30-2:32-2:33-2:37-2:45-2:46-2:47-2:54-2:61-2:62-2:67-2:68-2:69-2:70-2:71-2:74-2:77-2:97-2:98-2:103-2:106-2:107-2:109-2:110-2:115-2:119-2:120-2:122-2:124-2:127-2:128-2:129-2:130-2:132-2:140-2:143-2:144-2:145-2:146-2:148-2:149-2:153-2:156-2:158-2:159-2:161-2:164-2:165-2:167-2:168-2:173-2:174-2:176-2:181-2:182-2:186-2:187-2:190-2:192-2:194-2:195-2:196-2:197-2:199-2:203-2:208-2:209-2:211-2:214-2:215-2:218-2:220-2:222-2:223-2:226-2:227-2:231-2:233-2:235-2:237-2:243-2:244-2:247-2:248-2:249-2:252-2:258-2:259-2:260-2:267-2:270-2:273-2:275-2:277-2:282-2:283-3:4-3:5-3:8-3:9-3:10-3:13-3:16-3:18-3:19-3:21-3:24-3:26-3:30-3:32-3:33-3:35-3:36-3:37-3:38-3:39-3:42-3:45-3:49-3:51-3:52-3:55-3:59-3:62-3:63-3:64-3:68-3:73-3:75-3:76-3:77-3:78-3:86-3:87-3:89-3:90-3:91-3:92-3:96-3:97-3:112-3:116-3:119-3:120-3:128-3:154-3:155-3:159-3:165-3:173-3:176-3:177-3:181-3:183-3:186-3:190-3:192-3:193-3:194-3:195-3:199-4:1-4:2-4:10-4:11-4:16-4:18-4:22-4:23-4:24-4:29-4:32-4:33-4:34-4:35-4:36-4:40-4:43-4:46-4:48-4:56-4:58-4:60-4:64-4:66-4:72-4:76-4:86-4:94-4:97-4:101-4:102-4:103-4:104-5:105-4:106-4:107-4:116-4:127-4:128-4:129-4:131-4:135-4:137-4:139-4:140-4:142-4:145-4:149-4:150-4:157-4:163-4:167-4:168-4:170-5:1-5:2-5:3-5:4-5:7-5:8-5:12-5:13-5:14-5:17-5:22-5:23-5:24-5:25-5:26-5:28-5:29-5:32-5:34-5:36-5:39-5:40-5:42-5:44-5:45-5:49-5:51-5:53-5:56-5:58-5:59-5:65-5:66-5:67-5:69-5:72-5:73-5:82-5:87-5:97-5:98-5:106-5:107-5:109-5:111-5:115-5:116-5:118-6:14-6:15-6:19-6:21-6:28-6:33-6:37-6:50-6:54-6:56-6:57-6:58-6:71-6:74-6:78-6:79-6:81-6:83-6:94-6:95-6:99-6:109-6:111-6:114-6:117-6:119-6:120-6:121-6:128-6:130-6:134-6:135-6:139-6:141-6:142-6:144-6:145-6:146-6:150-6:157-6:158-6:159-6:161-6:162-6:165-7:5-7:13-7:15-7:21-7:22-7:27-7:28-7:30-7:31-7:37-7:40-7:50-7:54-7:55-7:56-7:59-7:60-7:64-7:66-7:71-7:75-7:76-