9:3-49:4-49:5-49:7-49:9-49:12-49:13-49:14-49:18-50:37-50:43-51:6-51:8-51:15-51:16-51:23-51:30-51:32-51:46-51:47-51:50-51:51-51:55-51:58-51:59-52:7-52:17-52:26-52:28-52:31-52:47-52:48-53:27-53:28-53:30-53:32-53:43-53:44-53:45-53:48-53:49-53:50-53:52-54:10-54:19-54:24-54:27-54:28-54:31-54:34-54:47-54:49-54:54-56:35-56:45-56:47-56:49-56:51-56:66-56:76-56:77-56:82-56:95-57:9-57:17-57:18-57:22-57:24-57:25-58:1-58:2-58:5-58:7-58:12-58:15-58:18-58:19-58:20-58:21-58:22-59:2-59:4-59:7-59:10-59:11-59:13-59:14-59:16-59:17-59:18-60:4-60:5-60:6-60:8-60:12-61:4-61:5-61:6-62:6-62:8-63:1-63:2-63:3-63:6-64:6-64:14-65:3-65:12-66:4-66:8-67:12-67:13-67:19-68:3-68:4-68:7-68:17-68:26-68:29-68:31-68:32-68:34-68:38-68:39-68:45-68:51-69:11-69:20-69:33-69:40-69:48-69:49-69:50-69:51-70:6-70:15-70:19-70:28-70:30-70:39-70:40-71:1-71:2-71:4-71:5-71:7-71:8-71:9-71:10-71:21-71:27-72:1-72:3-72:4-72:5-72:6-72:7-72:8-72:9-72:10-72:11-72:12-72:13-72:14-72:19-72:21-72:22-72:23-72:27-73:5-73:6-73:7-73:12-73:15-73:19-73:20-74:16-74:18-74:35-74:54-75:17-75:19-75:28-76:2-76:3-76:4-76:5-76:10-76:22-76:23-76:27-76:29-76:30-77:32-77:41-77:44-77:46-78:17-78:21-78:27-78:31-78:40-79:10-79:17-79:26-79:39-79:41-80:11-80:25-81:19-82:10-82:13-82:14-83:4-83:7-83:15-83:16-83:18-83:22-83:29-83:32-84:6-84:13-84:14-84:15-85:10-85:11-85:12-85:13-86:8-86:13-86:15-87:7-87:18-88:25-88:26-89:14-92:4-92:12-92:13-94:5-94:6-96:6-96:8-97:1-98:6-98:7-100:6-100:7-100:8-100:11-103:2-104:3-104:8-108:1-108:3-110:3)",
      "d": "«اِنَّ ، اَنَّ» Both these particles enter upon a noun. «اِنّ» comes at the beginning of a sentence.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ عَلٰی کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ قَدِیۡرٌ » (2/20)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah is over all things competent.\nBut «اَنَّ» comes in the middle.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَعۡلَمُ  اَنَّ اللّٰہَ  عَلٰی کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ قَدِیۡرٌ» (2/259)\nTranslation: I know that Allah is over all things competent.\nIt is necessary to remember that after «قَالَ» and its derivatives, «اِنَّ» will also come in the middle of the speech.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالَ اِنَّہٗ یَقُوۡلُ اِنَّہَا بَقَرَۃٌ» (2/68)\nTranslation: He (Moses) said, 'Indeed, he says, 'It is a cow.''\nGrammatically, after «عَلِمَ» and «شَہِدَ», «اَنَّ» should come in the middle of the speech (as in the example above). However, there is an instance in the Quran where «اِنَّ» is used after «عَلِمَ» and «شَہِدَ» as well.\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«وَاللّٰہُ یَعۡلَمُ  اِنَّکَ لَرَسُوۡلُہٗ ؕ وَاللّٰہُ یَشۡہَدُ اِنَّ الۡمُنٰفِقِیۡنَ لَکٰذِبُوۡنَ» (63/1)\nTranslation: And Allah knows that you are His Messenger, and Allah bears witness that the hypocrites are liars."
    },
    {
      "id": 633,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Indeed, Verily",
      "hw": "بیشک",
      "s": "«لَاجَرَمَ» In Arabic grammar, this word is used for additional emphasis and affirmation (5 verses: 11:22-16:23-16:62-16:109-40:43)",
      "d": "There is scholarly disagreement regarding the meaning of «لَاجَرَمَ». Most translators write its meaning as 'indeed' or 'verily'. Al-Munjid writes its meaning as 'By Allah's oath'. This word appears three times in the Quran, and all three times it comes before «اَنَّ» (11/22, 16/23, 16/109), which means it comes for additional affirmation. However, if we take Al-Munjid's meaning of 'By Allah's oath', it is also correct and adds further emphasis.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَا جَرَمَ اَنَّہُمۡ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ ہُمُ الۡاَخۡسَرُوۡنَ» (11/22)\nTranslation: Indeed, those will be the greatest losers in the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 634,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Indeed, Verily",
      "hw": "بیشک",
      "s": "«قَدْ» When it enters upon a past tense verb, it gives the meaning of affirmation and also brings it close to the present tense. That is, it changes the past tense verb to the recent past (212 verses: 2:60-2:75-2:108-2:118-2:134-2:137-2:141-2:144-2:231-2:237-2:246-2:247-2:256-2:269-3:13-3:20-3:40-3:49-3:101-3:118-3:137-3:140-3:143-3:144-3:154-3:165-3:173-3:183-3:184-3:185-3:192-4:21-4:22-4:23-4:48-4:54-4:60-4:72-4:80-4:100-4:112-4:116-4:119-4:136-4:140-4:153-4:161-4:164-4:167-4:170-4:174-5:5-5:12-5:15-5:19-5:61-5:72-5:75-5:77-5:102-5:113-5:116-6:5-6:16-6:31-6:33-6:56-6:80-6:89-6:97-6:98-6:104-6:119-6:126-6:128-6:140-6:157-7:26-7:38-7:44-7:53-7:71-7:73-7:85-7:89-7:95-7:105-7:149-7:160-7:185-8:16-8:19-8:31-8:38-8:71-9:40-9:50-9:66-9:94-10:16-10:45-10:51-10:57-10:89-10:91-10:108-11:32-11:36-11:57-11:62-11:76-12:30-12:77-12:80-12:90-12:100-12:101-12:110-13:6-13:30-13:42-14:12-14:46-15:13-16:26-16:91-17:33-17:77-18:76-18:91-19:8-19:9-19:24-19:43-20:36-20:47-20:48-20:61-20:64-20:75-20:80-20:81-20:85-20:99-20:111-20:125-21:97-22:42-23:1-23:66-24:41-24:63-24:64-25:4-25:19-25:77-26:6-28:78-29:18-29:38-31:22-33:18-33:36-33:50-33:58-33:71-34:53-35:4-35:25-37:105-39:50-39:59-40:9-40:28-40:48-40:85-41:25-41:43-43:63-44:13-46:17-46:18-46:21-47:18-48:21-48:23-50:4-50:28-54:12-57:8-57:17-58:1-58:5-60:1-60:4-60:5-60:13-65:1-65:3-65:10-65:11-65:12-66:2-66:4-67:9-68:43-71:14-71:24-72:28-87:14-91:9-91:10)",
      "d": "«قَدْ» When it enters upon a past tense verb, it gives the meaning of affirmation and also brings it close to the present tense. That is, it changes the past tense verb to the recent past.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَدۡ سَمِعَ اللّٰہُ قَوۡلَ الَّتِیۡ» (58/1)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah has heard the statement of the woman..."
    }
  ],
  "135": [
    {
      "id": 635,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To be restless / agitated",
      "hw": "گھبرانا",
      "s": "«فَرَغَ» The heart being empty of patience and composure (1 verse: 28:10)",
      "d": "«فَرَغَ» means to be empty, and its opposite is «شَغَلَ», meaning to be occupied with some work. And «قَلْبُ فَارِغٌ» is a state wherein there is no occupation (f.l. 70), i.e., no courage or patience remains, and one becomes restless.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَاَصۡبَحَ فُؤَادُ اُمِّ مُوۡسٰی فٰرِغًا ؕ اِنۡ کَادَتۡ لَتُبۡدِیۡ بِہٖ لَوۡلَاۤ اَنۡ رَّبَطۡنَا عَلٰی قَلۡبِہَا» (28/10)\nTranslation: And the heart of the mother of Moses became empty [of patience]. She would have disclosed [the matter] had We not bound her heart [with conviction]."
    },
    {
      "id": 636,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Restlessness; Anxiety",
      "hw": "گھبرانا",
      "s": "«jaz'a» to become impatient and start wailing from the tongue (1 verse: 14:21)",
      "d": "«jaz'a» to become impatient and start wailing from the tongue. And its opposite is «sabara» (to be patient). This word is used when a person, instead of being patient upon pain or calamity, starts expressing grief and sorrow verbally (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Quran: «سَوَآءٌ عَلَیۡنَاۤ اَجَزِعۡنَاۤ اَمۡ صَبَرۡنَا مَا لَنَا مِنۡ مَّحِیۡصٍ» (14/21)\nTranslation: It is equal for us whether we show restlessness or patience; there is no escape for us. (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 638,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Restlessness; Anxiety",
      "hw": "گھبرانا",
      "s": "«karuba» such restlessness that also includes an element of grief (4 verses: 6:64-21:76-37:36-37:115)",
      "d": "«karuba» such restlessness that includes grief (F. L. 170) restlessness, anxiety, and agitation.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَنُوۡحًا اِذۡ نَادٰی مِنۡ قَبۡلُ فَاسۡتَجَبۡنَا لَہٗ فَنَجَّیۡنٰہُ وَاَہۡلَہٗ مِنَ الۡکَرۡبِ الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (21/76)\nTranslation: And (remember) Noah when he called Us before, so We responded to him and saved him and his companions from the great distress."
    },
    {
      "id": 639,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Restlessness; Anxiety",
      "hw": "گھبرانا",
      "s": "«hal'a» the extreme state of impatience (1 verse: 70:19)",
      "d": "«hal'a» the extreme state of impatience, and according to the scholar of language, it is the extreme degree of «jaz'a» (F L 48) to be without courage and impatient.\nFor example, in the Quran: «اِنَّ الۡاِنۡسَانَ خُلِقَ ہَلُوۡعًا اِذَا مَسَّہُ الشَّرُّ جَزُوۡعًا» (70/19,20)\nTranslation: Indeed, man is created weak. When evil touches him, he becomes despairing."
    },
    {
      "id": 640,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Restlessness; Anxiety",
      "hw": "گھبرانا",
      "s": "«iṭṭar ra» to be restless for the fulfillment of a necessary need (8 verses: 2:126-2:173-5:3-6:119-6:145-16:115-27:62-31:24)",
      "d": "«ḍar ra» and «ḍur ra» mean to cause trouble to someone, to inflict loss. And «aḍarra fulanan 'ala al-amri» means to force someone into something. And «iṭṭar ra» means to force someone, to make needy (Munjid). Thus, «iṭṭarar» is such restlessness that is connected to some need of a person.\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَمَنِ اضۡطُرَّ غَیۡرَ بَاغٍ وَّلَا عَادٍ فَلَاۤ اِثۡمَ عَلَیۡہِ» (2/173)\nTranslation: Then whoever is forced, without being rebellious or transgressing, there is no sin upon him."
    },
    {
      "id": 641,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Restlessness; Anxiety",
      "hw": "گھبرانا",
      "s": "«istafazza» to cause someone to be in a state of agitation (3 verses: 17:64-17:76-17:103)",
      "d": "«fazza» means to deprive someone of their senses, to cause someone to be in agitation and then remove them. And «istafazza» means to make someone restless and anxious, (Mufradat) and also comes in the meaning of considering someone humiliated.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَاسۡتَفۡزِزۡ مَنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتَ مِنۡہُمۡ بِصَوۡتِکَ» (17/64)\nTranslation: And incite whoever you can among them with your voice."
    }
  ],
  "136": [
    {
      "id": 642,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Idleness",
      "hw": "بےکار",
      "s": "«faragha» the intermediate pause after finishing one task and before starting another (2 verses: 55:31-94:7)",
      "d": "«faragha» to be free from a task, and its opposite is «shaghil» (Mufradat) meaning a person being free after completing a task.\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَاِذَا فَرَغۡتَ فَانۡصَبۡ وَاِلٰی رَبِّکَ فَارۡغَبۡ» (94/7,8)\nTranslation: So when you have free time, strive (in worship) and turn to your Lord."
    },
    {
      "id": 643,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Idleness",
      "hw": "بےکار",
      "s": "«'at ala» idleness that is not within one's control or not by one's choice (2 verses: 22:45-81:4)",
      "d": "«'at ala» means a laborer being idle or a woman being without jewelry (Mufradat). And «'at tala» means to leave someone idle.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَاِذَا الۡعِشَارُعُطِّلَتۡ» (81/4)\nTranslation: And when the she-camels are left untended."
    }
  ],
  "137": [
    {
      "id": 644,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Deprived; Unfortunate",
      "hw": "بے نصیب",
      "s": "«mahrum» is used for one who is economically deprived or unfortunate. And it is used in meanings of being forbidden, prohibited, denied, prevented, haram, forbidden (4 verses: 51:19-56:67-68:27-70:25)",
      "d": "«mahrum» is used for one who is unfortunate in terms of economy. And haram is that from which one is prohibited. Then this prohibition sometimes is enticing (to attract or make obedient), sometimes coercive, and sometimes Shariah. And mahrum is the person from whom abundance of sustenance and prosperity has been withheld (Mufradat). The word mahrum appears in the Quran probably three times, and in every context it means the destitute.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَالَّذِیۡنَ فِیۡۤ اَمۡوَالِہِمۡ حَقٌّ مَّعۡلُوۡمٌ . لِّلسَّآئِلِ وَالۡمَحۡرُوۡمِ» (70/24,25)\nTranslation: And in their wealth is a known share for the asker and the deprived."
    },
    {
      "id": 645,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Deprived; Unfortunate",
      "hw": "بے نصیب",
      "s": "«shaqiyyan» is used for an unfortunate and ill-fated person (9 verses: 11:105-11:106-19:4-19:32-19:48-23:106-87:11-91:12-92:15)",
      "d": "The opposite of «shaqi» is «sa'id». And «sa'id» is the person who is naturally fortunate. Similarly, «shaqi» is the person who is naturally deprived of good fortune.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَّلَمۡ اَکُنۡۢ بِدُعَآئِکَ رَبِّ شَقِیًّا» (19/4)\nTranslation: (Prophet Zakariya said) And O my Lord, I have never been deprived in my supplication to You."
    }
  ],
  "138": [
    {
      "id": 646,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Independent; Self-sufficient",
      "hw": "بے نیاز",
      "s": "«ghani» the essence that has no need for anyone else (35 verses: 2:263-2:267-2:273-3:97-3:181-4:6-4:130-4:131-4:135-6:133-9:28-9:74-9:93-10:68-14:8-22:64-24:32-24:33-27:40-29:6-31:12-31:26-35:15-39:7-47:38-53:48-57:24-59:7-60:6-64:6-80:5-80:37-92:8-93:8-96:7)",
      "d": "«ghani» the essence that has no need for anyone else. And its opposite is faqir, meaning needy. And the word «ghani» often comes in the meaning of being independent of wealth and riches, and «ghani» is also used for a wealthy person, and its plural is «aghniya'». Meaning, at least wealthy enough that in terms of livelihood, he has no need for others (Mufradat, Munjid).\nFor example, in the Quran: «یَحۡسَبُہُمُ الۡجَاہِلُ اَغۡنِیَآءَ مِنَ التَّعَفُّفِ» (2/273)\nTranslation: The ignorant person considers them rich due to their not asking."
    },
    {
      "id": 647,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Independent",
      "hw": "بے نیاز",
      "s": "«صَمَد» refers to a being that is not in need of anyone, but all others are in need of it. (1 verse: 112:2)",
      "d": "In «صَمَد», there are two fundamental aspects: (1) something being solid and strong, (2) people turning towards it from all directions (m. l. manjad). That is, a being that is not dependent on anyone, but all others are dependent on it.\nThe difference between «غَنِی» and «صَمَد» is that «غَنِی» relates more to financial matters, while «صَمَد» is independent in all aspects and others are dependent on it.\nFor example, in the Quran: «قُلۡ ہُوَاللّٰہُ اَحَدٌ اَللّٰہُ الصَّمَدُ» (112/1,2)\nTranslation: Say, 'He is Allah, the One. Allah, the Independent.'"
    }
  ],
  "139": [
    {
      "id": 648,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Futile Speech",
      "hw": "بے ہودہ کلام",
      "s": "«لَغُوْ» means idle talk, nonsense, and thoughtless noise. (11 verses: 2:225-5:89-19:62-23:3-25:72-28:55-41:26-52:23-56:25-78:35-88:11)",
      "d": "«لَغٰی ، یَلْغُوا» means to speak without thought and to engage in nonsense. And «لَغَی الطَیرُبَا صْواتِھا» refers to birds chirping in their own languages. The common word 'language' is derived from this. It means mixed or common speech. And 'laghw' is used for all futile speech and the barking of a dog. «لَاغِیْۃ» means obscene and bad speech (manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran: «لَا یَسۡمَعُوۡنَ فِیۡہَا لَغۡوًا اِلَّا سَلٰمًا» (19/62)\nTranslation: They will not hear any idle talk therein except peace.\nAnother example: «لَّا تَسۡمَعُ فِیۡہَا لَاغِیَۃً» (88/11)\nTranslation: They will not hear any nonsense therein. (Osmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 650,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Futile Speech",
      "hw": "بے ہودہ کلام",
      "s": "«نَزَفَ» means stammering, nonsensical talk that a drunk person engages in. (2 verses: 37:47-56:19)",
      "d": "«نَزَفَ» means the end or cessation of something. (m. l) «نَزِفَ دَمُہٗ» means all his blood has been drained. «نَزِیْف» refers to a person whose intellect has been taken away, i.e., senseless and intoxicated (m. l). And «نَزَفَ الْمَاء» means to draw water gradually (muf). So, «نَزَفَ» refers to the stammering, nonsensical talk that a person, unfortunate due to the use of an intoxicant or any other reason, engages in when their intellect and senses diminish.\nFor example, in the Quran: «بَیۡضَآءَ لَذَّۃٍ لِّلشّٰرِبِیۡنَ ، لَا فِیۡہَا غَوۡلٌ وَّلَا ہُمۡ عَنۡہَا یُنۡزَفُوۡنَ» (37/46,47)\nTranslation: White, delicious for the drinkers, in which there is no headache, nor are they made senseless by it."
    }
  ],
  "140": [
    {
      "id": 651,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Be Stunned",
      "hw": "بیہوش",
      "s": "«صَعِقَ» means to be stunned due to a heavenly event. (3 verses: 7:143-39:68-52:45)",
      "d": "«صَعِقَ» means to be stunned due to terror and panic (f. l 130). And «صَاعِقَہ» refers to a falling lightning or that terrifying explosion related to celestial bodies (see lightning for details).\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَلَمَّا تَجَلّٰی رَبُّہٗ  لِلۡجَبَلِ جَعَلَہٗ دَکًّا وَّخَرَّ مُوۡسٰی صَعِقًا» (7/143)\nTranslation: When his Lord manifested Himself to the mountain, He made it [appear as] a dust mote, and Moses fell stunned."
    },
    {
      "id": 652,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Be Intoxicated",
      "hw": "بیہوش",
      "s": "«سَکَرَ» generally refers to intoxication from alcohol or intoxicants. (4 verses: 15:15-15:72-16:67-50:19)",
      "d": "«سَکَرَ» generally refers to intoxication from alcohol or intoxicants. And «سُکْر» is the state when a person loses their intellect and senses (muf).\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَجَآءَتۡ سَکۡرَۃُ الۡمَوۡتِ بِالۡحَقِّ» (50/19)\nTranslation: And the intoxication of death will come with truth.\nAnother example: «وَمِنۡ ثَمَرٰتِ النَّخِیۡلِ وَالۡاَعۡنَابِ تَتَّخِذُوۡنَ مِنۡہُ سَکَرًا وَّرِزۡقًا حَسَنًا» (16/67)\nTranslation: And from the fruits of the date-palm and grapes, you take intoxicants and good provision.\nAnd «سَکِر» means to become intoxicated from wine, and the adjective is 'skran'. The feminine form is «سَکْرٰی» and its plural is «سُکٰرٰی» (manjad)."
    },
    {
      "id": 653,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Be Stunned",
      "hw": "بیہوش",
      "s": "«غَمِرَ» means to be stunned due to calamities and hardships. (4 verses: 6:93-23:54-23:63-51:11)",
      "d": "«غَمِرَ» means to be overcome by stupor. «غَمَرَاتُ الْمَوْت» means the agonies and hardships of death, during which a person's senses diminish (manjad). «غَمَرَۃٌ» also refers to deep water whose depth is unknown. Ibn al-Faris writes that «غَمِرَ» means to have one's intellect and senses impaired due to severe hardships (m. l).\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَلَوۡ تَرٰۤی اِذِ الظّٰلِمُوۡنَ فِیۡ غَمَرٰتِ الۡمَوۡتِ وَالۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ بَاسِطُوۡۤا اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ» (6/93)\nTranslation: And if you could see when the wrongdoers are in the agonies of death and the angels are extending their hands.\nAnother verse: «بَلۡ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ فِیۡ غَمۡرَۃٍ مِّنۡ ہٰذَا» (23/63)\nTranslation: No! Their hearts are in a stupor from this. (Osmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 654,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Be Stunned",
      "hw": "بیہوش",
      "s": "«صَرَعَ» means to fall to the ground due to fainting. (1 verse: 69:7)",
      "d": "«صَرَعَ» means to die or refers to the well-known disease 'mother of children' where a person faints and falls to the ground. And «صَرَع» means to fall to the ground due to restlessness and panic (f. l 130).\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی» (69/7)\nTranslation: Then you will see the people prostrated therein. (Osmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 655,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Be Stunned",
      "hw": "بیہوش",
      "s": "«غَشِیَ» means to be stunned due to terror, illness, or any other reason. (23 verses: 2:7-3:154-7:54-7:189-8:11-10:27-11:5-13:3-14:50-20:78-24:40-29:55-31:32-33:19-36:9-44:11-45:23-47:20-53:16-53:54-71:7-91:4-92:1)",
      "d": "«غَشَا» means to cover something and veil it. When a person's intellect is veiled and their senses don't function, it's called 'ghashy'. The cause could be terror, fear, or anything else. And «مُغَشِّی» is the person who has been stunned.\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَاِذَا جَآءَ الۡخَوۡفُ رَاَیۡتَہُمۡ یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ اِلَیۡکَ تَدُوۡرُ اَعۡیُنُہُمۡ کَالَّذِیۡ یُغۡشٰی عَلَیۡہِ مِنَ الۡمَوۡتِ» (33/19)\nTranslation: Then when fear comes, you will see them looking at you, their eyes revolving like those who are overwhelmed by the pangs of death."
    }
  ],
  "141": [
    {
      "id": 656,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Near",
      "hw": "پاس",
      "s": "«عِنْد» means near, whether in terms of place or time. (185 verses: 2:54-2:62-2:76-2:79-2:80-2:89-2:94-2:101-2:103-2:109-2:110-2:112-2:140-2:191-2:198-2:217-2:255-2:262-2:274-2:277-2:282-3:7-3:14-3:15-3:19-3:37-3:59-3:73-3:78-3:126-3:156-3:163-3:165-3:169-3:195-3:198-3:199-4:78-4:81-4:82-4:94-4:134-4:139-5:43-5:52-5:60-6:2-6:50-6:57-6:58-6:59-6:109-6:124-6:127-6:148-7:29-7:31-7:131-7:134-7:157-7:187-7:206-8:4-8:10-8:22-8:28-8:32-8:35-8:55-9:7-9:19-9:20-9:22-9:36-9:52-9:99-10:2-10:18-10:68-10:76-11:28-11:31-11:83-12:17-12:42-12:60-12:79-13:8-13:39-13:43-14:37-14:46-15:21-16:95-16:96-17:23-17:38-18:46-18:65-18:86-19:55-19:76-19:78-19:87-20:52-21:19-21:84-22:30-22:47-23:117-24:13-24:15-24:39-24:61-27:40-27:47-28:27-28:37-28:48-28:49-28:60-28:78-29:17-29:50-30:39-31:34-32:12-33:5-33:53-33:63-33:69-34:23-34:31-34:37-35:39-37:48-37:168-38:9-38:25-38:40-38:47-38:52-39:31-39:34-40:25-40:35-40:83-41:38-41:50-41:52-42:16-42:22-42:36-43:35-43:49-43:85-44:5-46:10-46:23-47:16-48:5-49:3-49:13-50:4-51:34-52:37-52:41-53:14-53:15-53:35-54:35-54:55-57:19-61:3-62:11-63:7-64:15-66:11-67:26-68:34-68:47-73:20-81:20-92:19-98:8)",
      "d": "«عِنْد» means near. It is used for both temporal (time) and spatial (place) contexts. «عِنْدَ الْمَکَان» means near a place or location. «عِنْدَ الْلَیْل» means at night or near night, i.e., a little before or after sunset. (m. r)\nFor example, in the Quran: «مَاعِنۡدَکُمۡ یَنۡفَدُ وَمَا عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ بَاقٍ» (16/96)\nTranslation: Whatever is with you will perish, and whatever is with Allah will remain.\nSometimes «مِنْ» comes before «عِنْد» for emphasis, meaning 'from near' or 'from the side of'.\nFor example: «قُلۡتُمۡ اَنّٰی ہٰذَا ؕ قُلۡ ہُوَ مِنۡ عِنۡدِ اَنۡفُسِکُمۡ» (3/165)\nTranslation: You said, 'Whence is this?' Say, 'It is from yourselves.'\nWhen «مِنْ» is included, it adds more emphasis."
    },
    {
      "id": 658,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Near",
      "hw": "پاس",
      "s": "«تِلْقَاء» means to meet someone, to face, to encounter by chance. (4 verses: 7:47-10:15-21:103-28:22)",
      "d": "«لَقِیَ یَلْقِیْ لِقَاءً» means for something to come before something else, to meet, and «تِلْقَاء ، لِقَاء» is used in the sense of facing or confronting. One says «جَلَسَ تِلْقَاءِیْ» meaning he sat facing him or opposite him.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَلَمَّا تَوَجَّہَ تِلۡقَآءَ مَدۡیَنَ» (28/22)\nTranslation: And when he turned his face towards Madyan.\nAnd «تِلْقَاءَ نَفْس» means by oneself, spontaneously. «فَعَلَ الْاَمْر مَنْ تلْقاءِ نَفْسِہٖ» means he did the matter by himself, without anyone's help or compulsion (manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran: «قُلۡ مَا یَکُوۡنُ لِیۡۤ اَنۡ اُبَدِّلَہٗ مِنۡ تِلۡقَآیِٔ  نَفۡسِیۡ» (10/15)\nTranslation: Say, 'It is not for me to alter it from my own inclination.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 659,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Around",
      "hw": "پاس",
      "s": "«حَوْل» means to be around something or in its vicinity (16 verses: 2:17-3:159-6:92-8:24-9:101-9:120-17:1-19:68-26:25-26:34-27:8-29:67-39:75-40:7-42:7-46:27)",
      "d": "«حَالَ» has the basic meaning of change, movement, and transfer. And «حَوْلَ الشَّیْء» means the side of something towards which it can be turned. (muf) Later, this word began to be used in the meanings of around something or in its vicinity. (manjad)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ اَضَآءَتۡ مَا حَوۡلَہٗ ذَہَبَ اللّٰہُ بِنُوۡرِہِمۡ» (2/17)\nTranslation: 'Then when the fire illuminated what was around it, Allah took away their light.'"
    }
  ],
  "142": [
    {
      "id": 660,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Pure",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "«سُبْحَان» is the Being who is free from all kinds of flaws, deficiencies, and shortcomings, and it is only Allah (41 verses: 2:32-2:116-3:191-4:171-5:116-6:100-7:143-9:31-10:10-10:18-10:68-12:108-16:1-16:57-17:1-17:43-17:93-17:108-19:35-21:22-21:26-21:87-23:91-24:16-25:18-27:8-28:68-30:17-30:40-34:41-36:36-36:83-37:159-37:180-39:4-39:67-43:13-43:82-52:43-59:23-68:29)",
      "d": "According to Ibn Faris, the word «سَبَحَ» has two basic meanings: (1) a form of worship, (2) a form of running. (m. l)\nAnd Imam Raghib writes that the meaning of «سَبَحَ» is to swim or glide in water or air, or to pass with swiftness. (muf) «سَبَّاح» means a great swimmer. And «فَرَسٌ سَبُوْحٌ» is a horse that does not sway from side to side due to its speed. (manjad)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَہُوَالَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ الَّیۡلَ وَالنَّہَارَ وَالشَّمۡسَ وَالۡقَمَرَ ؕ کُلٌّ فِیۡ فَلَکٍ یَّسۡبَحُوۡنَ» (21/33)\nTranslation: 'And He it is Who created the night and the day, the sun and the moon. Each one is floating in an orbit.'\nAt another place, the divine command says:\n«وَّالسّٰبِحٰتِ سَبۡحًا» (79/3)\nTranslation: 'And by the angels who float (in space).'\nThen this word began to be used for doing something with speed and haste.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اِنَّ لَکَ فِی النَّہَارِ سَبۡحًا طَوِیۡلًا» (73/7)\nTranslation: 'Indeed, you have in the day a prolonged occupation.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 661,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Pure",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "«سُبْحَان» refers to a Being who is free from all imperfections (41 verses: 2:32-2:116-3:191-4:171-5:116-6:100-7:143-9:31-10:10-10:18-10:68-12:108-16:1-16:57-17:1-17:43-17:93-17:108-19:35-21:22-21:26-21:87-23:91-24:16-25:18-27:8-28:68-30:17-30:40-34:41-36:36-36:83-37:159-37:180-39:4-39:67-43:13-43:82-52:43-59:23-68:29)",
      "d": "«سُبْحَان» is derived from «سَبَح». Just as «غَفَر» gives «غُفْرَان», millions and billions of planets are revolving at great speed in space. In them, there is no vibration, oscillation, collision, or impact. This clearly indicates that the Administrator who controls them with such firm determination and management can only be an existence completely free from any flaw or deficiency. And this is the meaning of «سُبْحَان». Furthermore, it is necessary that such a Managing Being, who runs the universe with such firm management, could, if He willed, introduce disruption and disorder into that system. Therefore, «سُبْحَان» means an existence that is free from flaws and deficiencies, and is also All-Powerful without any partner, and holds complete control over all things in the universe.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَقَالُوااتَّخَذَ اللّٰہُ وَلَدًا ۙ سُبۡحٰنَہٗ  ؕ بَلۡ لَّہٗ مَا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَالۡاَرۡضِ  ؕ کُلٌّ لَّہٗ قٰنِتُوۡنَ» ( 2/116 )\nTranslation: \"And these people say, 'Allah has taken a son.' Exalted is He! Rather, to Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth, and all are devoutly obedient to Him.\"\nAnd the coordinated and orderly motion of all things in the universe is itself testifying that the Managing Being who administers it is a Pure Essence, free from all kinds of flaws, deficiencies, and polytheism.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«سَبَّحَ لِلّٰہِ مَا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَمَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ ۚ وَہُوَالۡعَزِیۡزُالۡحَکِیۡمُ» ( 61/1)\nTranslation: \"Whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth exalts Allah, and He is the Exalted in Might, the Wise.\"\nThen, another aspect of this coordinated and orderly operation of the universe and all its contents is that its system, regulation, administration, and regularity, where even a moment's precedence is impossible, has no oscillation, collision, or impact. Seeing all these things, man drowns in an ocean of wonder, and his tongue involuntarily begins to glorify and praise the Administrator of the universe. Hence, the word «سُبْحَان» is also used at a time when the artistry and creation of the universe's Creator plunge man into an ocean of wonder. And generally, \"Glory be to Your power\" is said on such occasions.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَسۡرٰی بِعَبۡدِہٖ لَیۡلًا مِّنَ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ اِلَی الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡاَقۡصَا» ( 17/1 )\nTranslation: \"Exalted is He who took His Servant by night from al-Masjid al-Haram to al-Masjid al-Aqsa...\"\nThe use of «سُبْحَان» at this point is evidence that this journey was spiritual, not physical."
    },
    {
      "id": 662,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Pure",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "«قُدُّوْس» is the name of Allah, the Exalted. A being or station that is pure and blessed from shirk and similar evils (10 verses: 2:30-2:87-2:253-5:21-5:110-16:102-20:12-59:23-62:1-79:16)",
      "d": "The meaning of «قَدُسَ» is to be pure and clean. (muf) And according to the author of al-Munjid, it means to be pure and blessed.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«قُلۡ نَزَّلَہٗ رُوۡحُ الۡقُدُسِ مِنۡ رَّبِّکَ بِالۡحَقِّ» (16/102)\nTranslation: 'Say, \"The Pure Spirit has brought it down from your Lord in truth.\"'\nSo here, by Ruh al-Quds is meant that Jibril (peace be upon him) kept Allah's word pure and free from all kinds of impurity and filth, and delivered it to the prophets. That is why he is also called Ruh al-Amin at another place. And by Ard al-Muqaddasah is meant that pure and blessed land which became blessed due to the birth and burial of prophets and remained pure from the filth of polytheism due to their propagation.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«یٰقَوۡمِ ادۡخُلُوا الۡاَرۡضَ الۡمُقَدَّسَۃَ الَّتِیۡ کَتَبَ اللّٰہُ لَکُمۡ» (5/21)\nTranslation: 'O my people, enter the holy land which Allah has assigned to you.'\nAnd «قُدُّوْس» is the name of Allah, the Exalted, meaning the entity that is pure from shirk and all evil, and blessed. (manjad)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«یُسَبِّحُ لِلّٰہِ مَا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ مَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ الۡمَلِکِ الۡقُدُّوۡسِ الۡعَزِیۡزِالۡحَکِیۡمِ» (62/1)\nTranslation: 'Whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth glorifies Allah, the King, the Pure, the Exalted in Might, the Wise.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 663,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Pure",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "«زَکِیَّۃ» means the purity of the soul from evil traits and its refinement (26 verses: 2:129-2:151-2:174-2:232-3:77-3:164-4:49-9:103-18:19-18:74-18:81-19:13-19:19-20:76-24:21-24:28-24:30-35:18-53:32-62:2-79:18-80:3-80:7-87:14-91:9-92:18)",
      "d": "«زَکٰی ، زُكُوًّا» means to grow, to develop, and to be excellent. And «زَکّٰی» means to make something excellent, to improve it, and to advance it. And «زَکّٰی نَفْسَہٗ» means to praise oneself or to be self-satisfied.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَا تُزَکُّوۡۤا اَنۡفُسَکُمۡ ؕ ہُوَاَعۡلَمُ بِمَنِ اتَّقٰی» ( 53/32 )\nTranslation: \"So do not claim purity for yourselves. He is most knowing of who fears Him.\" (Jalandhari)\nTranslation: \"So do not boast of your virtues; He knows best who it is that guards against evil.\" (Osmani)\nAnd «تَزْکِیَہ» is generally used for the soul. And تزکیہ نفس means to purify the soul from spiritual diseases, filth, and evil traits, and to instill good qualities. (Mufradat)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَدۡ اَفۡلَحَ مَنۡ زَکّٰىہَا وَقَدۡ خَابَ مَنۡ دَسّٰىہَا» ( 91:9,10 )\nTranslation: \"He who purifies it (the soul) has succeeded, and he who corrupts it has failed.\"\nAnd a pure soul is one that is innocent and free from all accusations.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَ اَقَتَلۡتَ نَفۡسًا زَکِیَّۃًۢ بِغَیۡرِ نَفۡسٍ ؕ لَقَدۡ جِئۡتَ شَیۡئًا نُّکۡرًا» ( 18/74 )\nTranslation: \"[Moses] said, 'You have killed a pure soul for no reason. You have certainly done a terrible thing.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 664,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Pure",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "«طُهُوْرُ» means to be clean and pure from dirt, filth, and impurity (26 verses: 2:25-2:125-2:222-2:232-3:15-3:42-3:55-4:57-5:6-5:41-7:82-8:11-9:103-9:108-11:78-22:26-25:48-27:56-33:33-33:53-56:79-58:12-74:4-76:21-80:14-98:2)",
      "d": "«طُهُوْرُ» is that which is clean and pure from dirt, filth, and impurity. According to Imam Raghib, it means being free from perceptible filth. And the opposite of «طَھَرَ» is «دَنَسَ», meaning dirt, filth, etc. (M, L).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَسَقٰہُمۡ رَبُّہُمۡ شَرَابًا طَہُوۡرًا» ( 76/21 )\nTranslation: \"And their Lord will give them a drink of pure wine.\"\nSimilarly, a woman becoming pure from menstruation and postpartum bleeding is also طہر.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاعۡتَزِلُوا النِّسَآءَ فِی الۡمَحِیۡضِ ۙ وَلَا تَقۡرَبُوۡہُنَّ حَتّٰی یَطۡہُرۡنَ» ( 2/222 )\nTranslation: \"So keep away from women during menstruation and do not approach them until they are pure.\"\nAnd «طَھَّرَ» (Form IV) is used for purification from both external and internal impurities.\nFor example, for removing external impurities, the divine command is:\n«وَرَبَّکَ فَکَبِّرۡ ۪وَثِیَابَکَ فَطَہِّرۡ» ( 74/3،4 )\nTranslation: \"And glorify your Lord and purify your clothing.\"\nAnd for cleansing internal evils, the divine command is:\n«اِنَّمَا یُرِیۡدُ اللّٰہُ لِیُذۡہِبَ عَنۡکُمُ الرِّجۡسَ اَہۡلَ الۡبَیۡتِ وَیُطَہِّرَکُمۡ تَطۡہِیۡرًا» ( 33/33 )\nTranslation: \"Allah intends only to remove from you, O [people of the] household [of the Prophet], any impurity and to purify you with [ thorough] purification.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 665,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Pure",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "«طَیَّب» means outwardly pure, lawful, and pleasant (43 verses: 2:57-2:168-2:172-2:267-3:38-3:179-4:2-4:3-4:43-4:160-5:4-5:5-5:6-5:87-5:88-5:100-7:32-7:58-7:157-7:160-8:26-8:37-8:69-9:72-10:22-10:93-14:24-16:32-16:72-16:97-16:114-17:70-20:81-22:24-23:51-24:26-24:61-34:15-35:10-40:64-45:16-46:20-61:12)",
      "d": "«طَابَ» means for something to be pleasing to the heart, to be of good taste.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَانۡکِحُوۡا مَا طَابَ لَکُمۡ مِّنَ النِّسَآءِ» (4/3)\nTranslation: 'So marry those that please you among women.' (Osmani)\nAnd «طِیْب» means fragrance. (manjad) And «طِیِّبَۃ» means heart's pleasure and satisfaction. (m. q) And «طَیِّب» is everything that is pleasant, pure, and lawful. (muf) And its opposite is «خَبِیْث».\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا کُلُوۡا مِنۡ طَیِّبٰتِ مَا رَزَقۡنٰکُمۡ» (2/172)\nTranslation: 'O you who have believed, eat from the good things which We have provided for you.'\nAnd «بَلَدَۃً طَٰیِّبَۃً» is a city that is clean, pleasant, with a good environment, and fertile."
    },
    {
      "id": 666,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To purify",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "«مَحَصَ» means to purify something from external and internal impurities and weaknesses (2 verses: 3:141-3:154)",
      "d": "«مَحَصَ» means to cleanse something from bran, filth, and mixture. And «مَحَصَ الذَّھَبَ» means to put gold in a crucible and melt it on fire to remove its dirt and mixture and make it pure. (muf. manjad)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَلِیُمَحِّصَ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَیَمۡحَقَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (3/141)\nTranslation: 'And that Allah may purify the believers [through trials] and destroy the disbelievers.'\nAt this place, Allah is mentioning the practical weaknesses of the Muslims and guiding them to improvement. So «مَحَّصَ» here means to purify a person from weaknesses and demands in practical life."
    },
    {
      "id": 667,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To purify",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "«زَکیّٰ» means to purify the self from bad ethics (26 verses: 2:129-2:151-2:174-2:232-3:77-3:164-4:49-9:103-18:19-18:74-18:81-19:13-19:19-20:76-24:21-24:28-24:30-35:18-53:32-62:2-79:18-80:3-80:7-87:14-91:9-92:18)",
      "d": "«زَکیّٰ» means to purify the self from spiritual filth, diseases, and bad ethics.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«قَدْ اَفْلَحَ مَنْ تَزَكّٰى» (87/14)\nTranslation: 'Indeed, he who purifies himself has succeeded.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 668,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To purify",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "«طَھَّرَ» means to be free from both external and internal impurities, and also to purify from shirk and evil suggestions (26 verses: 2:25-2:125-2:222-2:232-3:15-3:42-3:55-4:57-5:6-5:41-7:82-8:11-9:103-9:108-11:78-22:26-25:48-27:56-33:33-33:53-56:79-58:12-74:4-76:21-80:14-98:2)",
      "d": "«طَھَّرَ» means to remove external impurities. And also to purify the heart from shirk and satanic suggestions. Details have passed in «طُهُوْرُ»."
    },
    {
      "id": 669,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to purify",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "«صَفَّا» means for something to be pure and free from all kinds of admixture (1 verse: 47:15)",
      "d": "«صَفَّا» means for a thing to be pure and free from all kinds of mixture (intransitive) and «صَفّٰی» means to make a thing pure and clean. For example, honey is purified from wax and impurities. For instance, in the Quran: «وَاَنۡہٰرٌ مِّنۡ عَسَلٍ مُّصَفًّی» (47:15) Translation: And (in Paradise) rivers of pure, clear honey."
    },
    {
      "id": 670,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Clear",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "«بَرَّاَ» means to clear someone from a slander or defect (1 verse: 33:69)",
      "d": "«بَرِءَ» means to recover from an illness. «اَبْرَاَ» means to make healthy. And «بَرَّأَ» means to clear someone from a slander or defect, to declare innocent (i.e., to acquit of a crime). (Munajid, Mufradat)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَبَرَّاَہُ اللّٰہُ مِمَّا قَالُوۡا ؕ وَکَانَ عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ وَجِیۡہًا» ( 33/69 )\nTranslation: \"So Allah cleared him of the charge they had brought against him, and he was in the sight of Allah, distinguished.\""
    }
  ],
  "143": [
    {
      "id": 671,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Find",
      "hw": "پانا",
      "s": "«وَجَدَ» means to find or see something that exists (35 verses: 3:37-4:64-4:82-4:89-5:104-7:28-7:44-7:102-9:5-10:78-12:65-12:75-12:79-18:49-18:65-18:77-18:86-18:90-18:93-21:53-24:39-26:74-27:23-27:24-28:15-28:23-31:21-38:44-43:22-43:23-43:24-51:36-72:8-93:7-93:8)",
      "d": "«وَجَدَ» is a general term for finding or seeing something that exists and can be used everywhere. (Mufradat)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَا دَخَلَ عَلَیۡہَا زَکَرِیَّا الۡمِحۡرَابَ ۙ وَجَدَ عِنۡدَہَا رِزۡقًا» ( 3/37 )\nTranslation: \"Whenever Zakariya entered upon her in the prayer chamber, he found with her provision.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 672,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Skillfully Acquire",
      "hw": "پانا",
      "s": "«ثَقَفَ» means to use skill and expertise in obtaining something. To capture desired individuals during war (6 verses: 2:191-3:112-4:91-8:57-33:61-60:2)",
      "d": "«ثَقَفَ» means to use prudence and skill in obtaining something or doing a task. (Mufradat) And «ثَقَفَ» refers to an expert and master in war and fighting. (M, R) «ثَقِیْف» means wise (prudent) and alert. And «ثَقَافَتْ» means wisdom (prudence) and skill. And «ثَقَفَ» means to capture someone, to get good information about them, and to achieve victory over them. (M, R)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاقۡتُلُوۡہُمۡ حَیۡثُ ثَقِفۡتُمُوۡہُمۡ وَاَخۡرِجُوۡہُمۡ مِّنۡ حَیۡثُ اَخۡرَجُوۡکُمۡ» ( 2/191 )\nTranslation: \"And kill them wherever you overtake them and expel them from wherever they have expelled you.\"\nAt another place, for exactly the same situation, the word «وَجَدَ» was used instead of «ثَقَفَ», which indicates the generality of «وَجَدَ».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَخُذُوۡہُمۡ وَ اقۡتُلُوۡہُمۡ حَیۡثُ وَجَدۡتُّمُوۡہُمۡ» ( 4/89 )\nTranslation: \"Then seize them and kill them wherever you find them.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 673,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Encounter",
      "hw": "پانا",
      "s": "«اَلْفٰی» means to find something by chance. To find something present when a veil is lifted. To find something spontaneously (3 verses: 2:170-12:25-37:69)",
      "d": "«لفو» means for a thing's veil to be removed from before it and for it to become apparent. (M, L) And «اَلْفٰی» means for something to come into one's knowledge spontaneously or for something to appear.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اسۡتَبَقَا الۡبَابَ وَ قَدَّتۡ قَمِیۡصَہٗ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ وَّ اَلۡفَیَا سَیِّدَہَا لَدَا الۡبَابِ» ( 12/25 )\nTranslation: \"And they both raced to the door, and she tore his shirt from the back, and they found her husband at the door.\"\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«قَالُوۡا بَلۡ نَتَّبِعُ مَاۤ اَلۡفَیۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ اٰبَآءَنَا» ( 2/170 )\nTranslation: \"They say, 'Rather, we will follow that on which we found our fathers.'\"\nIn this verse, «اَلْفٰی» is used in the sense that the thing was inherited by them from generation to generation. At another place, for exactly the same situation, the word «وَجَدَ» was used instead of «اَلْفٰی», which indicates the generality of «وَجَدَ».\nFor example, the divine command states:\n«قَالُوۡا حَسۡبُنَا مَا وَجَدۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ اٰبَآءَنَا» ( 5/104 )\nTranslation: \"They say, 'What we found our fathers upon is enough for us.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 674,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Reach the End",
      "hw": "پانا",
      "s": "«اَدْرَکَ» means to reach the extremity of something and thus obtain it (8 verses: 4:78-4:100-4:145-6:103-10:90-20:77-26:61-36:40)",
      "d": "«دَرَکَ» and «دَرَجَ» are two names for the same thing. When climbing stairs from bottom to top, it is called «دَرَجَ» or «دَرَجَۃً». And when coming down from top to bottom, it is called «دَرَکَ». Hence, the phrases «دَرَجَاتُ الْجَنَّۃ» (degrees of Paradise) and «دَرَکَاتُ النَّار» (levels of Hell) are used. (Mufradat)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّ الۡمُنٰفِقِیۡنَ فِی الدَّرۡکِ الۡاَسۡفَلِ مِنَ النَّارِ» ( 4/145 )\nTranslation: \"Indeed, the hypocrites will be in the lowest depths of the Fire.\"\nAnd the meaning of «اَدْرَکَ» is to reach the degree of something step by step, or to obtain it, or to reach something at its appointed time. (Mufradat) «اَدْرَکَ الثَّمَرُ» means the fruit has ripened. And «اَدْرَکَ الْوَلَد» means the boy has reached puberty. (Munajid) And Ibn al-Faris gives its meaning as to meet or join one thing with another (i.e., to catch up, to overtake, or to reach). (M, L) For more detail, see in [Gharana].\nFor example, the divine command states:\n«لَا تُدۡرِکُہُ الۡاَبۡصَارُ وَہُوَ یُدۡرِکُ الۡاَبۡصَارَ» ( 6/103 )\nTranslation: \"Vision perceives Him not, but He perceives [all] vision; and He is the Subtle, the Acquainted.\" (Osmani)"
    }
  ],
  "144": [
    {
      "id": 675,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its Types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«حَمِیْم» means hot water (19 verses: 6:70-10:4-22:19-26:101-37:67-38:57-40:18-40:72-41:34-44:46-44:48-47:15-55:44-56:42-56:54-56:93-69:35-70:10-78:25)",
      "d": "«حَمِیْم» means water becoming hot. And «حَمّٰی» means fever or heat. (Munajid) And «حَمِیْم» refers to such hot water which becomes intensely hot and sometimes also foul-smelling due to the sun (in springs, etc.). The author of فِقْہُ الْلُغَۃ gives its meaning as \"intensely hot water\".\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیْنَ کَفَرُوْا لَہُمْ شَرَابٌ مِّنْ حَمِیْمٍ» (10/4)\nTranslation: \"And for those who disbelieve is a drink of scalding water.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 676,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its Types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«غَسَّاق» means cold and foul water or pus (2 verses: 38:57-78:25)",
      "d": "The translation of «غَسَّاق» is generally given as pus or flowing pus. However, the author of فِقْہُ الْلُغَۃ and the author of مُنْجِد both give its meaning as cold and foul water. (F L 260. Munajid) The Quran also supports this meaning because the words «حَمِیْم» and «غَسَّاق» are used twice in opposition to each other.\nExample for «حَمِیْم»: The divine command states:\n«لَا یَذُوۡقُوۡنَ فِیۡہَا بَرۡدًا وَّلَا شَرَابًا اِلَّا حَمِیۡمًا وَّغَسَّاقًا» (78/24,25)\nTranslation: \"They will not taste therein any coolness or drink except scalding water and pus.\" (Jalandhari)\nExample for «غَسَّاق»: The divine command states:\n«جَہَنَّمَ ۚ یَصۡلَوۡنَہَا ۚ فَبِئۡسَ الۡمِہَادُ ہٰذَا ۙ فَلۡیَذُوۡقُوۡہُ حَمِیۡمٌ وَّغَسَّاقٌ» (38/56,57)\nTranslation: \"Hell, which they will [enter to] burn, and wretched is the resting place. They will have nothing therein but scalding water and pus.\" (Jalandhari)"
    },
    {
      "id": 678,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«غَوْر» meaning water that is underground (2 verses: 18:41-67:30)",
      "d": "«غَوْر» is the water that is deep underground (F L 259). And the author of Munjid writes the meaning of «غَوْر» as 'water that is absorbed into the earth'."
    },
    {
      "id": 679,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«مَعِیْن» meaning water that flows gently on the surface of the earth (4 verses: 23:50-37:45-56:18-67:30)",
      "d": "«مَعَنَ» means water flowing with a gentle pace (Munjid) and «مَعِیْن» is water that flows on the surface (F L 259), like a flood but not with intensity and speed, rather flowing with gentleness and ease (M. L).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«قُلۡ اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ اِنۡ اَصۡبَحَ مَآؤُکُمۡ غَوۡرًا فَمَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡکُمۡ بِمَآءٍ مَّعِیۡنٍ» (67/30)\nTranslation: Say, 'Tell me, if your water becomes sunken, who can bring you flowing water?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 680,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«عَذْبٌ» meaning cold and sweet water (2 verses: 25:53-35:12)",
      "d": "«عَذْبٌ» means sweet and pleasant water (source) cold and sweet water that is desirable to drink. (detailed)"
    },
    {
      "id": 681,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«فُرَاتٌ» meaning cool and sweet water when it is in large quantity (3 verses: 25:53-35:12-77:27)",
      "d": "«فُرَاتٌ» means sea. It is also the name of a great river that falls into the Persian Gulf, and «فُرَاتَان» refers to the rivers Dajla and Furat. And «فَرَتِ الْمَاءِ» means water being very sweet and pleasant (Munjid). So, «فُرَاتٌ» has the quality of «عَذْبٌ» (sweet) when it is in large quantity."
    },
    {
      "id": 682,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«مِلْحٌ» salty water, sea water (2 verses: 25:53-35:12)",
      "d": "«مِلْحٌ» means brackish water, salty water, sea water, water with salt (F. L 33)."
    },
    {
      "id": 683,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«اُجَاجٌ» bitter and salty water (3 verses: 25:53-35:12-56:70)",
      "d": "«اُجَاجٌ» means water that is both salty and bitter (F L 33), intensely salty and hot, burning the chest (Maf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ مَا یَسۡتَوِی الۡبَحۡرٰنِ ٭ۖ ہٰذَا عَذۡبٌ فُرَاتٌ سَآئِغٌ  شَرَابُہٗ  وَہٰذَا مِلۡحٌ اُجَاجٌ» (35/12)\nTranslation: 'And the two seas are not equal. This one is sweet, pleasant to drink, and this one is salty, bitter.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 684,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water's paths and reserves",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«اَوْدِیَۃ» meaning streams, rivulets (2 verses: 13:17-46:24)",
      "d": "It is the plural of «وَادِی». Originally, 'wadi' refers to a wide valley between mountains and the slope that is between mountains where water flows (Maf). Due to being between mountains, it is necessary for streams to flow in that valley. These are the paths of rainwater and melted glacial water flowing from the mountains. Then the word 'wadi' is sometimes used in the meaning of a wide valley and sometimes in the meaning of streams and rivulets.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ  مَآءً  فَسَالَتۡ اَوۡدِیَۃٌۢ بِقَدَرِہَا» (13/17)\nTranslation: He sent down water from the sky, so the valleys flowed according to their capacity."
    },
    {
      "id": 685,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Paths and reserves of water",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«عَیْن» spring, lake, etc. (21 verses: 2:60-7:160-15:45-18:86-26:57-26:134-26:147-34:12-36:34-44:25-44:52-51:15-54:12-55:50-55:66-76:6-76:18-77:41-83:28-88:5-88:12)",
      "d": "«عَیْن» means spring. If water springs from a place in mountains or earth and collects in a low area, it is a spring. And springs can be so large that rivers and streams start flowing from them. Such springs are called lakes today, and its plural is «عُیُوْن». For example, in the Quran: «حَتّٰۤی اِذَا بَلَغَ مَغۡرِبَ الشَّمۡسِ وَجَدَہَا تَغۡرُبُ فِیۡ عَیۡنٍ حَمِئَۃٍ» (18/86) Translation: 'Until when he reached the setting place of the sun, he found it setting in a spring of dark mud.' And according to historical research, this is the place where the Aegean Sea takes the form of small rivers. Here, the Quran used «عَیْن» instead of «بَحْر», which aligns with the lexical meaning of «عَیْن» (i.e., spring)."
    },
    {
      "id": 687,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water's paths and reserves",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«سَرِیٌّ» meaning a small stream (1 verse: 19:24)",
      "d": "In «سَرِیٌّ», two concepts are found: (1) moving at night, (2) being small. «سَرِیَّةُ» means a small army and a small boat. Its plural is «سَرَایَا». And «سَارِیَہ» means a small army moving at night. And «سَرِیٌّ» means a small flowing stream (Munjid. F L 36).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«قَدۡ جَعَلَ  رَبُّکِ  تَحۡتَکِ سَرِیًّا» (19/24)\nTranslation: Your Lord has made a stream flow beneath you."
    },
    {
      "id": 688,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Paths and reserves of water",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«یَمّ» a large water reserve that flows downhill (7 verses: 7:136-20:39-20:78-20:97-28:7-28:40-51:40)",
      "d": "«یَمّ» is often defined by lexicographers as a very large water reserve, river, sea. (detailed, source) But in our opinion, «یَمّ» is used for that water reserve which is flowing towards a downhill area, i.e., a river. For example, in the Quran: «اَنِ اقۡذِفِیۡہِ فِی التَّابُوۡتِ فَاقۡذِفِیۡہِ فِی الۡیَمِّ فَلۡیُلۡقِہِ الۡیَمُّ بِالسَّاحِلِ یَاۡخُذۡہُ عَدُوٌّ لِّیۡ وَ عَدُوٌّ لَّہٗ» (20/39) Translation: '(We revealed to Moses' mother:) Put him into the box and put the box into the river, so the river will throw it onto the bank, and an enemy of Mine and an enemy of his will take him.' At another place, the divine command states: «وَ قَالَتۡ لِاُخۡتِہٖ قُصِّیۡہِ ۫ فَبَصُرَتۡ بِہٖ عَنۡ جُنُبٍ  وَّ ہُمۡ لَا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ» (28/11) Translation: 'And she said to his sister, \"Follow him.\" So she observed him from a distance while they were unaware.' These verses prove that «یَمّ» is that water reserve which flows like rivers and streams towards a downhill area. And for that, we have a specific word in our language, i.e., river."
    },
    {
      "id": 689,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Paths and reserves of water",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«بَحْر» used for sea or river (39 verses: 2:50-2:164-5:96-6:59-6:63-6:97-7:138-7:163-10:22-10:90-14:32-16:14-17:66-17:67-17:70-18:60-18:61-18:63-18:79-18:109-20:77-22:65-24:40-25:53-26:63-27:61-27:63-30:41-31:27-31:31-35:12-42:32-44:24-45:12-52:6-55:19-55:24-81:6-82:3)",
      "d": "«بَحْر» its plural is «اَبْحُرْ». Lexicographers define «بَحْر» as river or sea. But in modern times, «بَحْر» refers to that large water reserve which collects in a downhill area and water keeps flowing into it from all sides. If the collected water in a downhill area is small, it is called a joeh (small stream), if more, a lake, if even more, a small sea («بُحَیِرَہ»), and if very large, it is called «بَحْر». In the Quran, for «بُحَیِرَہ» and «بَحْر», the word «بَحْر» is used. For example, in the Quran: «وَ اِذۡ فَرَقۡنَا بِکُمُ الۡبَحۡرَ فَاَنۡجَیۡنٰکُمۡ وَ اَغۡرَقۡنَاۤ اٰلَ فِرۡعَوۡنَ» (2/50) Translation: 'And when We parted the sea for you and saved you and drowned the people of Pharaoh.' And historical research indicates that this 'sea' was the Red Sea. Sometimes, the collected water in the sea is stationary. Often, winds create waves in it and keep it moving. Although this movement is not towards a downhill area. Then, within the collected water of the sea, rivers also flow towards the downhill, and sometimes two rivers flow together, one with warm water, the other cold, or one sweet, the other bitter, and they do not mix with each other. Although this is also against the nature of water. And all this happens under the perfect power of Allah. Referring to this, the divine command states: «مَرَجَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ یَلۡتَقِیٰنِ بَیۡنَہُمَا بَرۡزَخٌ  لَّا یَبۡغِیٰنِ» (55/19,20) Translation: 'He has released the two seas, meeting together. Between them is a barrier, they do not transgress.' In this verse, the word «بَحْر» is used for rivers because such rivers flow in the sea."
    },
    {
      "id": 690,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Asking for water",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«اِسْتَسْقٰی» meaning asking for water to drink (24 verses: 2:60-2:71-7:160-9:19-12:41-12:70-13:4-14:16-15:22-16:66-23:21-25:49-26:79-28:23-28:24-28:25-47:15-72:16-76:17-76:21-77:27-83:25-88:5-91:13)",
      "d": "«سَقٰی» means to give someone water to drink, and «اَسْقٰی» means to give water to someone else to drink. And «اِسْتَسْقٰی» means to ask for water to drink. For example, in the Quran: «وَ اِذِ اسۡتَسۡقٰی مُوۡسٰی لِقَوۡمِہٖ فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ الۡحَجَرَ» (2/60) Translation: 'And when Moses asked for water for his people, We said, \"Strike the rock with your staff.\"'"
    }
  ],
  "145": [
    {
      "id": 692,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Foot (paer)",
      "hw": "پاؤں",
      "s": "«رِجْلٌ» refers to the part from below the ankle to the toes of the foot (18 verses: 2:239-5:6-5:33-5:66-6:65-7:124-7:195-17:64-20:71-22:27-24:24-24:31-24:45-26:49-29:55-36:65-38:42-60:12)",
      "d": "«رِجْلٌ» refers to the part from below the ankle to the toes (masc.) and its plural is «اَرْجُلٌ». For example, in the Quran: «اُرۡکُضۡ بِرِجۡلِکَ ۚ ہٰذَا مُغۡتَسَلٌۢ بَارِدٌ وَّ شَرَابٌ» (38/42) Translation: (We said to Job) Strike with your foot. This is a cool bath and a refreshing drink. And «رَجُلٌ» means man and its plural is «رِجَالٌ». If «رِجَالًا» is used as an adjective, it means on foot, and its opposite is «رُکْبَانًا» (meaning mounted). For example, in the Quran: «فَاِنۡ خِفۡتُمۡ فَرِجَالًا اَوۡ رُکۡبَانًا» (2/239) Translation: If you fear (an enemy), then (pray) on foot or mounted (in whatever condition you are)."
    },
    {
      "id": 693,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Foot (paer)",
      "hw": "پاؤں",
      "s": "«قَدَمَ» is the part of the leg that touches the ground (1 verse: 16:94)",
      "d": "The distance between the back foot and the front foot while walking is called «قَدَمَ». Its plural is «اَقْدَام» (masc.). In English, both «رِجْل» and «قَدَمَ» are translated as 'FOOT'. A foot is also a unit of measurement equal to 12 inches. Therefore, in modern Arabic, this unit of length is also called «قَدَمَ». Forty feet in Arabic is «اَرْبَعِیْنَ اَقْدَام». When used as a verb, «قَدَمَ» means to move forward or advance. As a noun, «قَدَمَ» is also used for «رِجْلٌ» (foot). Essentially, the difference between «رِجْل» and «قَدَمَ» is similar to the difference between «عَیْن» and «بَصَر», details of which have been covered under 'Eye'. For example, in the Quran: «یُعۡرَفُ الۡمُجۡرِمُوۡنَ بِسِیۡمٰہُمۡ فَیُؤۡخَذُ بِالنَّوَاصِیۡ وَ الۡاَقۡدَامِ» (55/41) Translation: The criminals will be recognized by their appearance and will be seized by their forelocks and feet."
    }
  ],
  "146": [
    {
      "id": 694,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Stone",
      "hw": "پتھر",
      "s": "«حَجَرَ» means a hard and large stone (11 verses: 2:24-2:60-2:74-7:160-8:32-11:82-15:74-17:50-51:33-66:6-105:4)",
      "d": "«حَجَرَ» means a hard stone, and its plurals are «اَحْجَار» and «حِجَارَۃ» (masc.). For example, in the Quran: «وَ اِنَّ مِنَ الۡحِجَارَۃِ لَمَا یَتَفَجَّرُ مِنۡہُ الۡاَنۡہٰرُ» (2/74) Translation: And indeed, among stones are some from which rivers burst forth."
    },
    {
      "id": 695,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Stone",
      "hw": "پتھر",
      "s": "«حَصْب» means small pebbles and tiny stones (5 verses: 17:68-21:98-29:40-54:34-67:17)",
      "d": "«حَصْب» means small pebbles and gravel. «حَاصِب» refers to the fierce wind that carries such pebbles. In the Quran, «حَاصِب» is used for a wind that brings showers of pebbles. For example, in the Quran: «اَمۡ اَمِنۡتُمۡ مَّنۡ فِی السَّمَآءِ اَنۡ یُّرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ حَاصِبًا» (67/17) Translation: Or do you feel secure from Him who is in the heaven that He will send upon you a storm of pebbles?"
    },
    {
      "id": 696,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Stone",
      "hw": "پتھر",
      "s": "«سِجِّیْل» means clay pebbles (3 verses: 11:82-15:74-105:4)",
      "d": "«سِجِّیْل» means pebbles (masc.). It refers to those sharp pebbles that contain soil, and from which pebbles are formed along with soil. For example, in the Quran: «فَلَمَّا جَآءَ اَمۡرُنَا جَعَلۡنَا عَالِیَہَا سَافِلَہَا وَاَمۡطَرۡنَا عَلَیۡہَا حِجَارَۃً  مِّنۡ سِجِّیۡلٍ ۬ ۙ مَّنۡضُوۡدٍ» (11/82) Translation: So when Our command came, We made its highest part its lowest and rained upon it stones of baked clay, layer upon layer."
    }
  ],
  "147": [
    {
      "id": 697,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Last",
      "hw": "پچھلا",
      "s": "«اٰخِر» means the last part or end of anything (14 verses: 3:72-5:114-10:10-26:84-37:78-37:108-37:119-37:129-43:56-56:14-56:40-56:49-57:3-77:17)",
      "d": "«اٰخِر» means the last part or end of anything. Its opposite is «اَوَّلْ». This word carries a general meaning. It is used as an adverb of time (i.e., its reference is to time). For example, in the Quran: «ثُلَّۃٌ مِّنَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ وَ ثُلَّۃٌ مِّنَ الۡاٰخِرِیۡنَ» (56/39,40) Translation: A group from the former and a group from the latter."
    },
    {
      "id": 698,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Last",
      "hw": "پچھلا",
      "s": "«خَلَفَ» means to be a successor (representative, deputy) (41 verses: 2:66-2:255-3:170-4:9-6:133-7:17-7:69-7:74-7:129-7:142-7:150-7:169-8:57-9:81-9:118-9:120-10:92-11:57-13:11-19:59-19:64-20:97-20:110-21:28-22:76-24:55-25:62-27:62-34:9-36:9-36:45-41:14-41:25-41:42-43:60-46:21-48:11-48:15-48:16-57:7-72:27)",
      "d": "«خَلَفَ» means to be a successor (representative, deputy) and refers to the generation that comes after a particular people or group. Its opposite is «سَلَفَ». Generally, «خَلْف» is used in a negative sense, meaning an unworthy or incompetent generation. For example, in the Quran: «فَخَلَفَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہِمۡ خَلۡفٌ اَضَاعُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَاتَّبَعُوا الشَّہَوٰتِ فَسَوۡفَ یَلۡقَوۡنَ غَیًّا» (19/59) Translation: Then, after them, succeeded an unworthy generation who neglected prayer and followed desires. So they will soon face evil consequences. The opposite of «خَلْف» is also «بَیْنَ یَدَیْ» or «بَیْنَ اَیْدِی», and these terms are used both temporally and spatially. In a temporal sense, «خَلْف» refers to later people without any specific distinction. For example, in the Quran: «فَجَعَلۡنٰہَا نَکَالًا لِّمَا بَیۡنَ یَدَیۡہَا وَمَا خَلۡفَہَا» (2/66) Translation: So We made it a lesson for those who were before it and for those who came after it. However, when «خَلْف» is used spatially in contrast to «بَیْنَ یَدَیْ», it means 'behind' rather than 'last'. For example, in the Quran: «لَہٗ مُعَقِّبٰتٌ مِّنۡۢ بَیۡنِ یَدَیۡہِ وَمِنۡ خَلۡفِہٖ  یَحۡفَظُوۡنَہٗ  مِنۡ اَمۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (13/11) Translation: For him are successive (angels) before him and behind him who guard him by the command of Allah."
    }
  ],
  "148": [
    {
      "id": 699,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To regret",
      "hw": "پچھتانا",
      "s": "«نَدَمَ» means to regret or be remorseful over a bad deed (5 verses: 5:31-5:52-23:40-26:157-49:6)",
      "d": "«نَدَمَ» is commonly used to mean being remorseful or regretful over a bad action one has committed. For example, in the Quran: «فَعَسَی اللّٰہُ اَنۡ یَّاۡتِیَ بِالۡفَتۡحِ اَوۡ اَمْرٍ مِّنۡ عِنۡدِہٖ فَیُصۡبِحُوۡا عَلٰی  مَاۤ اَسَرُّوۡا فِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ نٰدِمِیۡنَ» (5/52) Translation: So perhaps Allah will bring victory or a matter from Himself; then they will become, on account of what they concealed within themselves, regretful."
    },
    {
      "id": 701,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To regret",
      "hw": "پچھتانا",
      "s": "«سُقِطَ فِیْ یَدِہٖ» means to be embarrassed or to have one's argument proven wrong, leading to regret or distress (1 verse: 7:149)",
      "d": "«سُقِطَ فِیْ یَدِہٖ» is an idiom meaning that when one's statement or proof is proven false, they feel embarrassed, humiliated, and regretful in front of others. For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَمَّا سُقِطَ فِیۡۤ  اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ وَ رَاَوۡا اَنَّہُمۡ قَدۡ ضَلُّوۡا» (7/149) Translation: And when they regretted and saw that they had gone astray."
    }
  ],
  "149": [
    {
      "id": 703,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Old / To be old",
      "hw": "پرانا",
      "s": "«قَدِیْم» means old, ancient, from old times (3 verses: 12:95-36:39-46:11)",
      "d": "«قَدِیْم» means old, from ancient times, or longstanding. Its opposite is «جَدِیْد» (meaning new). «قَدَمَ» as a verb means to advance or move forward, while «قَدُمَ» means to become old. For example, in the Quran: «قَالُوۡا تَاللّٰہِ اِنَّکَ لَفِیۡ ضَلٰلِکَ الۡقَدِیۡمِ» (12/95) Translation: They said, 'By Allah, indeed you are in your old error.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 704,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Old / To be old",
      "hw": "پرانا",
      "s": "«عَتِیْق» refers to something that is ancient and old, yet its honor and greatness remain unchanged (2 verses: 22:29-22:33)",
      "d": "«اَلْعِتْقُ» as a verbal noun means pure origin, beauty, honor, greatness. Old. (Majid) «عَتِیْق» is that thing which, despite being ancient and old, suffers no diminution in its honor and greatness. Hence, the Ka'bah is called «بَیْتُ الْعَتِیْق». For example, the Noble Quran states: «ثُمَّ لۡیَقۡضُوۡا تَفَثَہُمۡ وَ لۡیُوۡفُوۡا نُذُوۡرَہُمۡ وَلۡیَطَّوَّفُوۡا بِالۡبَیۡتِ الۡعَتِیۡقِ» (22/29). Translation: Then let them (the pilgrims) remove their impurities, fulfill their vows, and perform Tawaf around the Ancient House (i.e., the House of Allah)."
    }
  ],
  "150": [
    {
      "id": 705,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Veil / Cover",
      "hw": "پردہ",
      "s": "«غِطَاء» means to completely cover something that has an open part (3 verses: 18:101-50:22-79:29)",
      "d": "«غِطَاء» is anything placed over something to cover or veil it completely. (Mufradat) For example, the lid of a pot. This term is generally used for things that are open on one side, and something is placed on them to cover them completely; then it is called «غِطَاء». For «غِطَاء», it is necessary that it be thick enough to completely cover and obscure. (Fiqh, p. 238) For example, the Noble Quran states: «فَکَشَفۡنَا عَنۡکَ غِطَآءَکَ فَبَصَرُکَ الۡیَوۡمَ حَدِیۡدٌ» (50/22). Translation: So We have removed from you the covering (of your eyes), so your sight today is sharp."
    },
    {
      "id": 706,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Veil / Cover",
      "hw": "پردہ",
      "s": "«غِشَاوَۃ» means to cover something with a very thin cloth so that something of it is still visible (23 verses: 2:7-3:154-7:54-7:189-8:11-10:27-11:5-13:3-14:50-20:78-24:40-29:55-31:32-33:19-36:9-44:11-45:23-47:20-53:16-53:54-71:7-91:4-92:1)",
      "d": "«غَشِی» means to cover something with such a thin thing that something of it remains visible. (Fiqh, p. 238) And this is more general than «غِطَاء». And «غَشِی» refers to the disease from which the senses are veiled and they give a wrong response. Similarly, this veil can be of cloth, etc., or of darkness. And this word is used in both apparent and spiritual senses. For example, the Noble Quran states: «خَتَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلٰی قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ وَعَلٰی سَمۡعِہِمۡ ؕ  وَعَلٰۤی اَبۡصَارِہِمۡ غِشَاوَۃٌ» (2/7). Translation: Allah has set a seal upon their hearts and upon their hearing, and over their vision is a veil."
    },
    {
      "id": 707,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Veil / Cover",
      "hw": "پردہ",
      "s": "«غَلَفَ» means the thing that covers something from all sides (2 verses: 2:88-4:155)",
      "d": "«غَلَفَ» means to cover something from all sides so that it becomes completely hidden. «غَلَّفْتُ السَّیْف» means I put the sword in its sheath. (Mufradat) And «غِلَاف» is that thing in which something is hidden. Its plural is «غُلْف». For example, the Noble Quran states: «وَ قَالُوۡا قُلُوۡبُنَا غُلۡفٌ ؕ بَلۡ لَّعَنَہُمُ اللّٰہُ بِکُفۡرِہِمۡ» (2/88). Translation: And they (the Jews) say, 'Our hearts are covered (from understanding).' No, but Allah has cursed them for their disbelief."
    },
    {
      "id": 708,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Veil / Cover",
      "hw": "پردہ",
      "s": "«اَکْمَام» refers to the outer covers on fruits of trees (2 verses: 41:47-55:11)",
      "d": "«کَمَّ» means to hide, and «کَمَّ الْبَعِیْر» means to put a cloth (i.e., a muzzle) on the mouth of a camel. (Majid) And the word «کَمِّ» comes for the husk of dates. And its plural is «اَکْمَام». (Mufradat) For example, the Noble Quran states: «فِیۡہَا فَاکِہَۃٌ ۪ۙ  وَّ النَّخۡلُ  ذَاتُ الۡاَکۡمَامِ» (55/11). Translation: In it ( Paradise ) are fruits and date-palms having sheaths (or covers)."
    },
    {
      "id": 712,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Veil / Cover",
      "hw": "پردہ",
      "s": "«عَوْرَۃ» means a gap, fissure. Refers to the places of 'Awrah (private parts) and their covering (3 verses: 24:31-24:58-33:13)",
      "d": "«اَلْعَوَارُ وَالْعَوْرَۃُ» means for a garment or a house to have a hole or tear. A crack appears. For example, the Noble Quran states: «اِنَّ بُیُوۡتَنَا عَوۡرَۃٌ  ؕ وَ مَا ہِیَ بِعَوۡرَۃٍ» (33/13). Translation: They (the hypocrites) said, 'Our houses are open (and exposed).' While they were not open. Meaning, there were no cracks or openings in those houses through which someone could enter. And «عَوْرَۃ» means every thing that causes shame (disgrace). And metaphorically, it refers to the human organs that are covered out of shame. The 'Awrah (private parts). (Mufradat, Majid) For example, the Noble Quran states: «اَوِالطِّفۡلِ الَّذِیۡنَ لَمۡ یَظۡہَرُوۡا عَلٰی عَوۡرٰتِ النِّسَآءِ» (24/31). Translation: Or (such) children who are not yet aware of the private aspects of women. And a woman is called 'awrah because it is necessary for her to cover her entire body except her face and hands. And being uncovered is considered a cause of shame and modesty. So, the word 'awrah also means a gap or fissure. It means the 'Awrah (private parts) and also covering them. Then this word has also come in the meanings of covering only. For example, the Noble Quran states: «ثَلٰثُ عَوۡرٰتٍ لَّکُمۡ» (24/58). Translation: There are three times of privacy for you (i.e., times when it is not permissible to enter houses without permission)."
    },
    {
      "id": 713,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Veil / Cover",
      "hw": "پردہ",
      "s": "«سُرَادِق» refers to the awning of a tent, the curtain around a tent, a canopy (1 verse: 18:29)",
      "d": "«سُرَادِق» is a word borrowed (i.e., taken) from Persian, meaning a curtain. (Mufradat) (Borrowed: a word that originally belongs to another language and is made Arabic with slight modification.) And «سُرَادِق» means thick cloth walls. Awnings or canopies or such tents that have no roof. For example, the Noble Quran states: «اِنَّاۤ اَعۡتَدۡنَا لِلظّٰلِمِیۡنَ نَارًا ۙ اَحَاطَ بِہِمۡ سُرَادِقُہَا» (18/29). Translation: Indeed, We have prepared for the wrongdoers a fire, surrounding which will be its awnings (or curtains). Note: («مُعَرَّب» : a word that originally belongs to another language and is made Arabic with slight modification.)"
    }
  ],
  "151": [],
  "152": [
    {
      "id": 720,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To read / To recite",
      "hw": "پڑھنا",
      "s": "«قَرَأَ» is generally used for reading. Whether it is little or much. Whether it is a book or a letter, etc. (77 verses: 2:185-4:82-5:101-6:19-7:204-9:111-10:15-10:37-10:61-10:94-12:2-12:3-13:31-15:1-15:87-15:91-16:98-17:9-17:14-17:41-17:45-17:46-17:60-17:71-17:78-17:82-17:88-17:89-17:93-17:106-18:54-20:2-20:113-20:114-25:30-25:32-27:1-27:6-27:76-27:92-28:85-30:58-34:31-36:2-36:69-38:1-39:27-39:28-41:3-41:26-41:44-42:7-43:3-43:31-46:29-47:24-50:1-50:45-54:17-54:22-54:32-54:40-55:2-56:77-59:21-69:19-72:1-73:4-73:20-75:17-75:18-76:23-84:21-85:21-87:6-96:1-96:3)",
      "d": "«قَرَأَ» is generally used for reading and studying. Whether one reads any writing, a book, or even one or two words. (Fiqh, p. 48) And the Quran is called Quran because it is recited frequently and repeatedly, and the word Quran contains the meaning of intensity (mubalaghah). For example, the Noble Quran states: «فَاَمَّا مَنۡ اُوۡتِیَ کِتٰبَہٗ  بِیَمِیۡنِہٖ ۙ فَیَقُوۡلُ ہَآؤُمُ اقۡرَءُوۡا کِتٰبِیَہۡ» (69/19). Translation: Then as for he who is given his record in his right hand, he will say, 'Here, read my record!' And «اَقْرَأَ» means to make someone else read. For example, the Noble Quran states: «سَنُقۡرِئُکَ فَلَا تَنۡسٰۤی» (87/6). Translation: We will surely make you recite (O Muhammad), so you will not forget."
    },
    {
      "id": 722,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To read / To recite",
      "hw": "پڑھنا",
      "s": "«رَتَّلَ» means to read with pauses and with proper elocution (2 verses: 25:32-73:4)",
      "d": "«رَتِلَ» means for something to be in order and with proper method. (M, R) And «رَتَّلَ» means to utter words with method and order. (Mufradat) And «تَرْتِیْل» means good recitation (husn al-hal), i.e., reciting with a good voice and observing the proper pronunciation of letters, and reciting slowly and distinctly. (Majid) For example, the Noble Quran states: «وَ رَتِّلِ الۡقُرۡاٰنَ  تَرۡتِیۡلًا» (73/4). Translation: And recite the Quran with measured (slow, distinct) recitation. (Jalandhari) And recite the Quran clearly (Uthmani)."
    },
    {
      "id": 723,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To read / To recite",
      "hw": "پڑھنا",
      "s": "«دَرَسَ» is used for regular learning, memorizing, and preserving (6 verses: 3:79-6:105-6:156-7:169-34:44-68:37)",
      "d": "«دَرَسَ» is used for regular learning, memorizing, and preserving. «دَرَسَ» also has a meaning of becoming old and worn out, as in «دَرَسَ الثَّوْب» meaning the cloth became old and worn out. And «دَرَسَ الْعِلْم» means to be attentive to knowledge in order to memorize it. (Majid) And according to Imam Raghib, its meaning is to acquire the effect of knowledge by preserving and memorizing it. And since this can only be achieved through continuous reading, therefore «دَرَسَ» comes in the meaning of continuous and regular reading. (Mufradat) For example, the Noble Quran states: «وَلٰکِنۡ کُوۡنُوۡا رَبّٰنِیّٖنَ بِمَا کُنۡتُمۡ تُعَلِّمُوۡنَ الۡکِتٰبَ وَ بِمَا کُنۡتُمۡ  تَدۡرُسُوۡنَ» (3/79). Translation: But be you scholars (rabbani) by what you teach the Book and by what you yourselves study (or read). And «دَرَسَ ، دِرَاسَۃً» means to read and teach. And «دَارَسَ ، دِرَاسًا» means to read to each other, to recite mutually, to study together. (Majid) For example, the Noble Quran states: «اَنۡ تَقُوۡلُوۡۤا اِنَّمَاۤ اُنۡزِلَ الۡکِتٰبُ عَلٰی طَآئِفَتَیۡنِ مِنۡ قَبۡلِنَا ۪ وَاِنۡ  کُنَّا عَنۡ دِرَاسَتِہِمۡ  لَغٰافِلِیۡنَ» (6/156). Translation: So that you (O people of the Scripture) do not say, 'The Book was only sent down to two groups before us, and we were unaware of what they were studying (or reading).'"
    },
    {
      "id": 724,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To read / To recite",
      "hw": "پڑھنا",
      "s": "«اَمْلٰی» Reciting a written text aloud (2 verses: 2:282-25:5)",
      "d": "The term «اَلْاِمْلَاءُ» is derived by lexicographers from two roots: (1) «اَمَلَّ یُمِلُّ اِمْلَاءً (ملل)» and (2) «اَمْلٰی یُمْلِیْ اِمْلَاءً (ملی)». In both forms, «اِمْلَاء» has the same meaning: to cause to be written or to have written (dictation). Since «اِمْلَاء» typically involves one person speaking and another writing, in this context «تُمْلٰی» is also understood by some to mean reciting a written text aloud.\nIn the Quran:\n«وَقَالُوۡۤا اَسَاطِیۡرُ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ اکۡتَتَبَہَا فَہِیَ تُمۡلٰی عَلَیۡہِ  بُکۡرَۃً وَّاَصِیۡلًا» (25/5)\nTranslation (1): And they say, 'These are the tales of the ancients which he has caused to be written down, and they are dictated to him morning and evening.' (Jalandhari)\nTranslation (2): And they say, 'These are fables of the ancients which he has had written down, so they are dictated to him morning and evening.' (Osmani)"
    }
  ],
  "153": [
    {
      "id": 726,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To like / To prefer",
      "hw": "پسند",
      "s": "«وَدَّ» Comes for extreme love or the desire to attain something (25 verses: 2:96-2:105-2:109-2:266-3:30-3:69-3:118-4:42-4:73-4:89-4:102-5:82-11:90-15:2-19:96-29:25-30:21-33:20-42:23-60:1-60:2-60:7-68:9-70:11-85:14)",
      "d": "The meaning of «وَدَّ» is to love intensely (M, R). According to Imam Raghib, it means to love something and sometimes merely to wish for its existence. This word is also used separately in both these meanings (Muf). 'Muaddat' means intense love, and 'Wadud' is one who loves intensely. This word is also used in the meanings of merely preferring something or desiring something.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یَوَدُّ  الۡمُجۡرِمُ لَوۡ  یَفۡتَدِیۡ مِنۡ عَذَابِ یَوۡمِئِذٍۭ بِبَنِیۡہِ» (70/11)\nTranslation: The criminal will wish that he could ransom himself from the punishment of that Day with his sons.\nAt another place, the Divine command states:\n«رُبَمَا یَوَدُّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَوۡ کَانُوۡا مُسۡلِمِیۡنَ» (15/2)\nTranslation: There will be times when the disbelievers will wish that they had been Muslims."
    },
    {
      "id": 727,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To like / To prefer",
      "hw": "پسند",
      "s": "«اِرْتَضٰی» To accept something with one's heart's pleasure (3 verses: 21:28-24:55-72:27)",
      "d": "«رَضِیَ» means to be pleased with or satisfied with someone. And «اِرْتَضٰی» means to accept something with one's heart's pleasure.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَا یُظۡہِرُ عَلٰی غَیۡبِہٖۤ اَحَدًا اِلَّا مَنِ ارۡتَضٰی مِنۡ رَّسُوۡلٍ» (72/26,27)\nTranslation: Allah does not reveal the unseen to anyone except whom He is pleased with from His messengers."
    }
  ],
  "154": [
    {
      "id": 732,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To call out",
      "hw": "پکارنا",
      "s": "«جَھَرَ» To call out loudly enough for at least those nearby to hear (14 verses: 2:55-4:148-4:153-6:3-6:47-7:205-13:10-16:75-17:110-20:7-21:110-49:2-67:13-87:7)",
      "d": "«جَھَرَ» means to call out or speak loudly enough that those nearby can hear. Its opposite is «اَسَرَّ», meaning to speak so softly that those nearby cannot hear, as in the case of followers reciting in prayer.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ تَجۡہَرۡ بِالۡقَوۡلِ فَاِنَّہٗ یَعۡلَمُ السِّرَّ وَاَخۡفٰی» (20/7)\nTranslation: If you call out loudly, indeed He knows the secret and what is even more hidden."
    }
  ],
  "155": [
    {
      "id": 733,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To seize / To grasp",
      "hw": "پکڑنا",
      "s": "«اَخَذَ» To take hold of something; a general word for seizing (121 verses: 2:48-2:55-2:63-2:83-2:84-2:93-2:206-2:229-2:255-2:260-2:267-3:11-3:81-3:160-3:187-4:20-4:21-4:71-4:89-4:91-4:102-4:118-4:153-4:154-4:161-5:12-5:14-5:41-5:70-6:42-6:44-6:46-6:70-7:31-7:73-7:78-7:91-7:94-7:95-7:96-7:130-7:144-7:145-7:150-7:154-7:155-7:165-7:169-7:171-7:172-7:199-8:52-8:68-8:70-9:5-9:50-9:103-9:104-10:24-11:56-11:64-11:67-11:94-11:102-12:76-12:78-12:79-12:80-13:32-15:73-15:83-16:46-16:47-16:113-18:77-18:79-19:12-19:78-19:87-20:21-20:39-20:94-22:44-22:48-23:41-23:64-23:76-24:2-26:189-28:40-29:14-29:37-29:40-33:7-33:61-34:51-35:26-36:49-38:44-40:5-40:21-40:22-41:17-43:48-44:47-48:15-48:19-48:20-51:16-51:40-51:44-54:42-55:41-57:8-57:15-59:7-69:10-69:30-69:45-73:16-79:25)",
      "d": "«اَخَذَ» is a general word for seizing or taking hold of something; to acquire or encompass something (Muf). It is used in both literal and metaphorical senses.\nLiteral example: The Divine command states:\n«قَالَ یَبۡنَؤُمَّ  لَا تَاۡخُذۡ بِلِحۡیَتِیۡ  وَلَا بِرَاۡسِیۡ» (20/94)\nTranslation: (Aaron said to Moses) 'Do not seize my beard or my head hair.'\nMetaphorical example: The Divine command states:\n«خُذُوۡا مَاۤ اٰتَیۡنٰکُمۡ بِقُوَّۃٍ وَّ اسۡمَعُوۡا» (2/93)\nTranslation: Take firmly what We have given you and listen."
    },
    {
      "id": 734,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To seize / To grasp",
      "hw": "پکڑنا",
      "s": "«بَطَشَ» A firm and overpowering grip (8 verses: 7:195-26:130-28:19-43:8-44:16-50:36-54:36-85:12)",
      "d": "«بَطَشَ» means to seize something with strength and power (M, L) or to take something forcefully (Muf). It signifies a firm, overpowering grip, seizing with severity and awe (M, Q). Like «اَخَذَ», it is used in both literal and metaphorical senses.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا بَطَشۡتُمۡ  بَطَشۡتُمۡ  جَبَّارِیۡنَ» (26/130)\nTranslation: And when you seize (people), you seize as tyrants."
    },
    {
      "id": 735,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To seize / To grasp",
      "hw": "پکڑنا",
      "s": "«تَنَاوَش» To make an effort to reach for something distant (1 verse: 34:52)",
      "d": "«نَاشَ» means to reach for something from such a distance that the hand can barely touch it; to seek (Manjad). And «تَنَاوَش» means to be able to reach a desired thing; to have access.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاَنّٰی لَہُمُ التَّنَاوُشُ مِنۡ مَّکَانٍۭ بَعِیۡدٍ» (34/52)\nTranslation: And how could they reach (faith) from such a distant place?"
    },
    {
      "id": 736,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To seize / To grasp",
      "hw": "پکڑنا",
      "s": "«قَبَضَ» To take something in one's fist (6 verses: 2:245-9:67-20:96-25:46-39:67-67:19)",
      "d": "«قَبَضَ» means to take something in one's fist. And «قَبْضَۃ» means a fist.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَ بَصُرۡتُ بِمَا لَمۡ یَبۡصُرُوۡا بِہٖ فَقَبَضۡتُ قَبۡضَۃً  مِّنۡ اَثَرِالرَّسُوۡلِ» (20/96)\nTranslation: (The Samiri) said, 'I saw what they did not see, so I took a handful from the trace of the messenger (angel).'"
    },
    {
      "id": 737,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To seize / To grasp",
      "hw": "پکڑنا",
      "s": "«خَطَفَ» To snatch something quickly and run away; to snatch away (6 verses: 2:20-8:26-22:31-28:57-29:67-37:10)",
      "d": "«خَطَفَ» means to seize and carry off; to take something quickly and run away (FL 170). To snatch away. For example, (a bird) snatching something quickly.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَمَنۡ یُّشۡرِکۡ بِاللّٰہِ فَکَاَنَّمَا خَرَّ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ فَتَخۡطَفُہُ الطَّیۡرُ اَوۡ تَہۡوِیۡ بِہِ الرِّیۡحُ فِیۡ مَکَانٍ سَحِیۡقٍ» (22/31)\nTranslation: And whoever associates partners with Allah is as if he had fallen from the sky, and the birds snatch him away, or the wind carries him to a far-off place."
    },
    {
      "id": 738,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To seize / To grasp",
      "hw": "پکڑنا",
      "s": "«سَطَاَ» To seize as if attacking (1 verse: 22:72)",
      "d": "«سَطَاَ» means to overpower someone by attacking them (Manjad). According to Imam Raghib, it means to seize with severity during an attack (Muf). And «سَطْوَۃ» means «اَلْبَطْشُ بِرَفْعِ الْیَدِ»—to seize someone with a raised hand, to strike (M, Q).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا تُتۡلٰی عَلَیۡہِمۡ اٰیٰتُنَا بَیِّنٰتٍ تَعۡرِفُ فِیۡ  وُجُوۡہِ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوا الۡمُنۡکَرَ ؕ یَکَادُوۡنَ یَسۡطُوۡنَ بِالَّذِیۡنَ یَتۡلُوۡنَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ اٰیٰتِنَا» (22/72)\nTranslation: And when Our clear verses are recited to them, you will recognize the denial in the faces of those who disbelieve. They are about to assault those who recite Our verses to them."
    },
    {
      "id": 739,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To catch",
      "hw": "پکڑنا",
      "s": "«اِعْتَصَمَ» to hold something firmly with both palms (5 verses: 3:101, 3:103, 4:146, 4:175, 22:78)",
      "d": "«عَصَم» means to protect and save something (Munjid), and «اِعْتَصَمَ» means to hold firmly with both palms and to grasp (Fal 174). For example, the Quran states: «وَاعۡتَصِمُوۡا بِحَبۡلِ اللّٰہِ جَمِیۡعًا وَّلَا تَفَرَّقُوۡا» (3/103). Translation: And hold firmly, all together, to the rope of Allah and do not become divided."
    },
    {
      "id": 740,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To catch",
      "hw": "پکڑنا",
      "s": "«اِسْتَمْسَک» to hold firmly what one has grasped or possesses (24 verses: 2:231, 2:256, 4:15, 5:4, 7:170, 11:113, 16:59, 16:79, 17:100, 19:45, 22:65, 31:22, 33:37, 35:2, 35:41, 38:39, 39:38, 39:42, 43:21, 43:43, 60:10, 65:2, 67:19, 67:21)",
      "d": "«اَمْسَکَ» means not to let something go from one's hand, to retain, to cling, and «تَمَسَّک» and «اِسْتَمْسَک» mean to hold firmly, to cling, and to grasp firmly (Munjid). For example, the Quran states: «فَمَنۡ یَّکۡفُرۡ بِالطَّاغُوۡتِ وَ یُؤۡمِنۡۢ بِاللّٰہِ فَقَدِ اسۡتَمۡسَکَ بِالۡعُرۡوَۃِ الۡوُثۡقٰی» (2/256). Translation: So whoever disbelieves in false deities and believes in Allah has grasped the most trustworthy handhold."
    },
    {
      "id": 741,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To catch",
      "hw": "پکڑنا",
      "s": "«دَرَکَ» to catch something from behind (7 verses: 4:78, 4:100, 6:103, 10:90, 20:77, 26:61, 36:40)",
      "d": "«دَرَکَ» means to meet and catch something from behind (M. L.), and «دَرْک» also refers to the depth of the sea and the rope tied to reach that depth (Maf). Thus, «دَرَکَ» conveys the meaning of reaching, catching from behind, or overtaking. For example, the Quran states: «لَا الشَّمۡسُ یَنۡۢبَغِیۡ لَہَاۤ اَنۡ تُدۡرِکَ الۡقَمَرَ» (36/40). Translation: It is not for the sun to overtake the moon."
    }
  ],
  "156": [
    {
      "id": 742,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Refuge / Place of refuge",
      "hw": "پناہ",
      "s": "«وَزَرَ» refers to a cave or hollow in a mountain where one can take shelter (1 verse: 75:11)",
      "d": "«وَزَرَ» refers to a mountain and also to a place of refuge (M. R.). According to Imam Raghib, it means a place of refuge in a mountain, such as a cave or hollow (Maf). For example, the Quran states: «کَلَّا لَا وَزَرَ ، اِلٰى رَبِّكَ یَوۡمَئِذِ اِ۟لْمُسْتَقَرُّؕ» (75/11-12). Translation: No! Indeed, there is no refuge. That Day, the only place of rest is with your Lord."
    },
    {
      "id": 743,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Refuge / Place of refuge",
      "hw": "پناہ",
      "s": "«مَوْئِلًا» a self-made place of refuge built to be safe from theft, robbery, and other dangers (1 verse: 18:58)",
      "d": "«وَالَّۃ» refers to the pen or enclosure for camels and sheep, and «اِستِیْئَال» means the gathering of camels (M. R.). According to Ibn Faris, it implies gathering and denotes safety and salvation. Thus, «مَوْئِلًا» is a self-made place built to be safe from theft, robbery, and other dangers. For example, the Quran states: «بَلۡ لَّہُمۡ مَّوۡعِدٌ  لَّنۡ یَّجِدُوۡا مِنۡ  دُوۡنِہٖ  مَوۡئِلًا» (18/58). Translation: But they have an appointed time from which they will find no refuge besides Him."
    },
    {
      "id": 744,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Refuge / Place of refuge",
      "hw": "پناہ",
      "s": "«اَکْنَان» a safe place for protection from the sun, rain, etc. (1 verse: 16:81)",
      "d": "«کَنَّ» means to hide something in a house and to protect from the sun, etc. (Munjid), and «کِنّ» is a safe place where one can take shelter from the sun and rain (M. R.), or anything in which something can be hidden. The plural of «کِنّ» is «اَکْنَان» and «اَکِنَّۃً» occurs. For example, the Quran states: «وَّ جَعَلَ لَکُمۡ  مِّنَ الۡجِبَالِ اَکۡنَانًا» (16/81). Translation: And He has made for you from the mountains places of shelter."
    },
    {
      "id": 745,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Refuge / Place of refuge",
      "hw": "پناہ",
      "s": "«مَلْجَاَ» a fortress or enclosure where protection from the enemy is arranged (3 verses: 9:57, 9:118, 42:47)",
      "d": "«لَجَا» means to take refuge in a fortress, etc. (Munjid), and «لَجْاَ» also refers to a fortress; its plural is «اَلْجَاء» (M. Q.). «مَلْجَاَ» means a fortress or enclosure where protection from the enemy is arranged. For example, the Quran states: «مَا لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ مَّلۡجَاٍ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ وَّ مَا لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ نَّکِیۡرٍ» (42/47). Translation: That Day, you will have no refuge and no denial."
    },
    {
      "id": 746,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Refuge / Place of refuge",
      "hw": "پناہ",
      "s": "«مَحِیْص» a place of safety from hardships and calamities (5 verses: 4:121, 14:21, 41:48, 42:35, 50:36)",
      "d": "«حَیْص» means distress and hardship (M. R.). «حَیْص» and «بَیْص» are generally used together and are near synonyms, meaning a difficulty and perplexity from which there is no escape. «مَحِیْص» is a place where protection from pain and calamity is available. For example, the Quran states: «اُولٰٓئِکَ مَاۡوٰىہُمۡ جَہَنَّمُ ۫ وَ لَا یَجِدُوۡنَ عَنۡہَا  مَحِیۡصًا» (4/121). Translation: Those will have Hell as a refuge, and they will not find from it any escape."
    },
    {
      "id": 747,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Refuge / Place of refuge",
      "hw": "پناہ",
      "s": "«مَفَازَۃ» to reach a place of safety after being saved from hardships, where peace and security are also attained (3 verses: 3:188, 39:61, 78:31)",
      "d": "«فَازَ» means to attain salvation, to reach a place of safety after being saved from calamities (Maf). Hence, «فَازَالرَّجُل» and «فَوَّزَ الرَّجُل» also mean to die and perish. This word is from the category of words with opposite meanings (Dhawi Al-Addad). Thus, a person is saved from the world's troubles and calamities. «مَفَازَۃ» is a place of peace and safety where one finds relief from hardships and tranquility from worries. It also means a place of destruction and its cause (Munjid). For example, the Quran states: «وَ یُنَجِّی اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ اتَّقَوۡا بِمَفَازَتِہِمۡ ۫ لَا یَمَسُّہُمُ السُّوۡٓءُ» (39/61). Translation: And Allah will save those who fear Him through their success; no evil will touch them."
    }
  ],
  "157": [
    {
      "id": 751,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To ask",
      "hw": "پوچھنا",
      "s": "«سَاَلَ» is the general word for asking and questioning (93 verses: 2:61, 2:108, 2:119, 2:134, 2:141, 2:186, 2:189, 2:215, 2:217, 2:219, 2:220, 2:222, 2:273, 4:32, 4:153, 5:4, 5:101, 5:102, 6:90, 7:6, 7:163, 7:187, 8:1, 8:12, 9:65, 10:72, 10:94, 11:29, 11:46, 11:47, 11:51, 12:50, 12:82, 12:104, 14:34, 15:92, 16:43, 16:56, 16:93, 17:85, 17:101, 18:70, 18:76, 18:83, 20:105, 20:132, 21:7, 21:13, 21:23, 21:63, 23:72, 23:113, 25:57, 25:59, 26:109, 26:127, 26:145, 26:164, 26:180, 28:78, 29:13, 29:61, 29:63, 31:25, 33:8, 33:20, 33:53, 33:63, 34:25, 34:47, 36:21, 38:86, 39:38, 42:23, 43:9, 43:19, 43:44, 43:45, 43:87, 47:36, 47:37, 51:12, 52:40, 55:29, 55:39, 60:10, 67:8, 68:46, 70:1, 70:10, 75:6, 79:42, 102:8)",
      "d": "The basic meanings of «سَاَلَ» are two: (1) «اِسْتِفْسَار» meaning to inquire and question, and (2) to ask for something and desire it in return. The first meaning is under discussion here. Its usage is general in the sense of «اِسْتِفْسَار». For example, the Quran states: «کُلَّمَاۤ اُلۡقِیَ فِیۡہَا فَوۡجٌ سَاَلَہُمۡ خَزَنَتُہَاۤ اَلَمۡ یَاۡتِکُمۡ  نَذِیۡرٌ» (67/8). Translation: Every time a group is thrown into it, its keepers will ask them, 'Did there not come to you a warner?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 752,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To ask",
      "hw": "پوچھنا",
      "s": "«اِسْتَفْتَاء» seeking a religious ruling on a difficult issue (10 verses: 4:127-4:176-8:19-12:43-12:46-14:15-18:22-27:32-37:11-37:149)",
      "d": "«فتوٰی» and «فُتْیَا» refer to the answer to a difficult issue (Maf). And «اِسْتَفْتَاء» means to seek a fatwa. To ask a scholar for a religious ruling on a difficult issue, to seek advice or opinion on a difficult matter.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«یَسۡتَفۡتُوۡنَکَ ؕ قُلِ اللّٰہُ یُفۡتِیۡکُمۡ فِی الۡکَلٰلَۃِ» (4/176)\nTranslation: People ask you for the ruling regarding inheritance. Say, 'Allah gives you the ruling regarding kalalah.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 753,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To ask",
      "hw": "پوچھنا",
      "s": "«اِسْتَنْبَاء» asking about an important piece of news (3 verses: 10:53-4:94-49:6)",
      "d": "«نَبَاَ» refers to news that is both important and related to the one asking or answering. Whether it is an event that has happened or is about to happen. The words prophethood and prophet originate from this. A prophet is one who receives such news from Allah through revelation and conveys it to people, whether that news relates to past events or future occurrences. And «اِسْتَنْبَاء» means to inquire about news, to investigate news (Munjid).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَیَسۡتَنۡۢبِئُوۡنَکَ اَحَقٌّ ہُوَ  ؕ ؔ قُلۡ اِیۡ وَ رَبِّیۡۤ اِنَّہٗ لَحَقٌّ» (10/53)\nTranslation: They ask you if it is true. Say, 'Yes, by my Lord, it is certainly true.'\nAccording to Imam Raghib, «نَبَا» is news in which there is no possibility of falsehood (Maf). But this condition does not seem correct.\nBecause the divine command is:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِنۡ جَآءَکُمۡ فَاسِقٌۢ بِنَبَاٍ فَتَبَیَّنُوۡۤا» (49/6)\nTranslation: O believers! If a sinner brings you news, then verify it.\nSimilarly, the hoopoe bird brought «نَبَا» to Prophet Sulaiman. He considered it necessary to investigate due to the possibility of falsehood."
    }
  ],
  "158": [
    {
      "id": 755,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Complete. Whole (all)",
      "hw": "سب",
      "s": "«کَامِلْ» meaning complete, in which no part or deficiency remains, and fulfills its purpose and objective. It comes in opposition to deficient (3 verses: 2:196-2:233-16:25)",
      "d": "«کَامِلْ» is the opposite of «نَاقِصْ». That is, a thing whose parts are complete and whose attributes are perfect, meaning it fulfills its purpose and objective (Munjid).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَالۡوَالِدٰتُ یُرۡضِعۡنَ اَوۡلَادَہُنَّ حَوۡلَیۡنِ کَامِلَیۡنِ» (2/233)\nTranslation: And mothers shall nurse their children for two complete years."
    },
    {
      "id": 756,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Complete. Whole (all)",
      "hw": "سب",
      "s": "«کَافَّۃً» is used for all individuals of a group or all aspects of a matter. Entirely. All. Used in these meanings (4 verses: 2:208-9:36-9:122-34:28)",
      "d": "«اَلْکِفَاف» refers to the complete encirclement of something. And «کَافّ» is an active participle, and its feminine form is «کَافَّۃً». «جَآءَ النَّاسَ کَافَّۃً» means all the people came (منجد). This word is more eloquent than «کَامِلْ» (complete) because it encompasses not only the parts but all aspects as well.\n\nNow observe its examples:\n\nFor instance, in the Quran:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا ادۡخُلُوۡا فِی السِّلۡمِ  کَآفَّۃً وَلَا تَتَّبِعُوۡا خُطُوٰتِ الشَّیۡطٰنِ» (2/208)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, enter into Islam completely and do not follow the footsteps of Satan.\n\nAt another place, the command of Allah is:\n«وَمَاۤ اَرۡسَلۡنٰکَ اِلَّا کَآفَّۃً  لِّلنَّاسِ بَشِیۡرًا وَّ نَذِیۡرًا» (34/28)\nTranslation: And We have not sent you, [O Muhammad], except as a bringer of good tidings and a warner to all mankind."
    },
    {
      "id": 757,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Complete. Whole (all)",
      "hw": "سب",
      "s": "«سَلَمٌ» such a thing that is sound in itself and upon which no one else has a right (2 verses: 39:29-68:43)",
      "d": "«سَلَمٌ» means sound, correct, and intact (m. r). «اَلسَّلم» means to be free from apparent and inner faults and to remain safe. And «سَلَمٌ» is such a thing that is sound in itself and upon which no one else has a right (muf).\n\nFor instance, in the Quran:\n«رَّجُلًا فِیۡہِ  شُرَکَآءُ مُتَشٰکِسُوۡنَ وَ رَجُلًا سَلَمًا لِّرَجُلٍ ؕ ہَلۡ یَسۡتَوِیٰنِ مَثَلًا» (39/29)\nTranslation: Allah has given an example: There is a man whose property is shared by many partners who dispute with each other, and another man who is entirely owned by one man. Can they be equal in comparison?"
    },
    {
      "id": 760,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To complete. To be.",
      "hw": "سب",
      "s": "«اَوْفٰی» comes for fulfilling a covenant, measure, wage, status, and life (64 verses: 2:40-2:177-2:272-2:281-3:25-3:55-3:57-3:76-3:161-3:185-3:193-4:15-4:97-4:173-5:1-5:117-6:60-6:61-6:152-7:37-7:85-7:126-8:50-8:60-9:111-10:46-10:104-11:15-11:85-11:109-11:111-12:59-12:88-12:101-13:20-13:40-16:28-16:32-16:70-16:91-16:111-17:34-17:35-17:63-22:5-22:29-24:25-24:39-26:181-32:11-35:30-39:10-39:42-39:70-40:67-40:77-46:19-47:27-48:10-53:37-53:41-76:7-78:26-83:2)",
      "d": "«وَفٰی» is used for fulfilling a covenant, measure, life, condition, or reward (muf). Its opposite is «عُذَر» meaning breach of promise.\n\nNow observe its examples:\n\n(1) For covenant:\n«اَوۡفُوۡا بِعَہۡدِیۡۤ اُوۡفِ بِعَہۡدِکُمۡ» (2/40)\nTranslation: Fulfill the covenant you made with Me, and I will fulfill the covenant I made with you.\n\n(2) For measure:\n«فَاَوۡفُوا الۡکَیۡلَ وَالۡمِیۡزَانَ وَلَا تَبۡخَسُوا النَّاسَ اَشۡیَآءَہُمۡ» (7/85)\nTranslation: Fulfill the measures and weights and do not deprive people of their due.\n\n(3) For vow, pledge, and condition:\n«وَ لۡیُوۡفُوۡا نُذُوۡرَہُمۡ» (22/29)\nTranslation: And they must fulfill their vows.\n\n(4) For payment of reward or wage:\n«وَاَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ فَیُوَفِّیۡہِمۡ اُجُوۡرَہُمۡ» (3/57)\nTranslation: And those who believe and do righteous deeds, Allah will give them their rewards in full."
    },
    {
      "id": 761,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To complete. To be.",
      "hw": "سب",
      "s": "«قَضٰی» when attributed to a human, it means to be free after fulfilling one's responsibility (58 verses: 2:117-2:200-2:210-3:47-4:65-4:103-6:2-6:8-6:58-6:60-8:42-8:44-10:11-10:19-10:47-10:54-10:71-10:93-11:44-11:110-12:41-12:68-14:22-15:66-17:4-17:23-19:21-19:35-19:39-19:71-20:72-20:114-22:29-27:78-28:15-28:28-28:29-28:44-33:23-33:36-33:37-34:14-35:36-39:42-39:69-39:75-40:20-40:68-40:78-41:12-41:45-42:14-42:21-43:77-45:17-46:29-62:10-80:23)",
      "d": "«قَضٰی» when attributed to a human, it means to be free after fulfilling one's responsibility (muf. m q).\n\nFor instance, in the Quran:\n«فَاِذَا قَضَیۡتُمۡ مَّنَاسِکَکُمۡ فَاذۡکُرُوا اللّٰہَ کَذِکۡرِکُمۡ اٰبَآءَکُمۡ» (2/200)\nTranslation: Then when you have completed your Hajj rituals, remember Allah as you used to remember your ancestors.\n\nSimilarly, at another place:\n«فَمِنۡہُمۡ مَّنۡ قَضٰی نَحۡبَہٗ وَمِنۡہُمۡ مَّنۡ یَّنۡتَظِرُ» (33/23)\nTranslation: Among them are some who have fulfilled their vows, and among them are some who are still waiting."
    }
  ],
  "159": [
    {
      "id": 763,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Clothing",
      "hw": "پوشاک",
      "s": "«Labisa yalbasu» means to wear clothing. That which is for one's own use is clothing, and that which is prepared for another is «kiswah» (12 verses: 2:187-7:26-7:27-16:14-16:112-18:31-22:23-25:47-35:12-35:33-44:53-78:10)",
      "d": "«Labisa yalbasu» in the past tense, «ب» comes with a zer (under) and in the imperfect with a pesh (over). It means to wear clothing. And «libas» means one's own clothing.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«یُحَلَّوۡنَ فِیۡہَا مِنۡ اَسَاوِرَ مِنۡ ذَہَبٍ وَّلُؤۡلُؤًا ۚ وَ لِبَاسُہُمۡ فِیۡہَا حَرِیۡرٌ» (35/33)\nTranslation: They will be adorned therein with bracelets of gold and pearls, and their clothing therein will be of silk."
    },
    {
      "id": 764,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Clothing",
      "hw": "پوشاک",
      "s": "«Kiswah» is used for the clothing or garment of another (5 verses: 2:233-2:259-4:5-5:89-23:14)",
      "d": "«Kasa yaksu» means to clothe another, and «kiswah» means the clothing or garment of another.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَعَلَی الۡمَوۡلُوۡدِ لَہٗ رِزۡقُہُنَّ وَ کِسۡوَتُہُنَّ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ» (2/233)\nTranslation: And for the child, his provision and clothing are the responsibility of the father according to custom."
    }
  ],
  "160": [
    {
      "id": 765,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Mountain",
      "hw": "پہاڑ",
      "s": "«جَبَل» is a generic term meaning mountain (37 verses: 2:260-7:74-7:143-7:171-11:42-11:43-13:31-14:46-15:82-16:68-16:81-17:37-18:47-19:90-20:105-21:79-22:18-24:43-26:149-27:88-33:72-34:10-35:27-38:18-52:10-56:5-59:21-69:14-70:9-73:14-77:10-78:7-78:20-79:32-81:3-88:19-101:5)",
      "d": "«جَبَل» is a generic term meaning mountain. This word applies to every kind of mountain, whether small or big, high or low, all are included. And its plural is جبال. (Fal 266)\n\nFor instance, in the Quran:\n«ثُمَّ اجۡعَلۡ عَلٰی کُلِّ جَبَلٍ مِّنۡہُنَّ جُزۡءًا» (2/260)\nTranslation: Then put a portion of them on every mountain."
    },
    {
      "id": 766,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Mountain",
      "hw": "پہاڑ",
      "s": "«رَوَاسِیَ» firm and stable mountains. Mountain range. (10 verses: 13:3-15:19-16:15-21:31-27:61-31:10-34:13-41:10-50:7-77:27)",
      "d": "«رَسْوُ» means something that is settled, firm, and stable. «رَسَا السَّفِیْنَۃ» means the ship anchored. And «مَرْسٰی» is a harbor (minjada), and «رَاسِیَ» also refers to a large cauldron that is fixed in one place due to its size (34/13). And «رَاسِیَۃٌ» means firm and stable mountains (m. r minjada). And «رَوَاسِیَ» means mountain range; this is generally used in plural, meaning mountains spread far and wide.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ جَعَلۡنَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ رَوَاسِیَ اَنۡ تَمِیۡدَ بِہِمۡ» (21/31)\nTranslation: \"And We have placed firm mountains in the earth so that it may not convulse with them.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 767,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Mountain",
      "hw": "پہاڑ",
      "s": "«طَوْد» a very large and high mountain or a sand mound. (1 verse: 26:63)",
      "d": "«طَوْد» means a very large mountain that is both high and extensive (fal 267). According to the author of *muntaḥā al-ʿarab*, it is also used for very large mounds of sand besides large mountains (m. r).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«فَانۡفَلَقَ فَکَانَ کُلُّ فِرۡقٍ کَالطَّوۡدِ الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (26/63)\nTranslation: \"So it parted, and each became like a huge mountain.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 768,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Mountain",
      "hw": "پہاڑ",
      "s": "«صَخْرَۃ» a small high mountain, a large high rock, a cliff. (3 verses: 18:63-31:16-89:9)",
      "d": "«صَخْرَۃ» means a cliff. A small, elevated mountain. A hard rock (muf). Essentially, «صَخْرَۃ» refers to a very large rock of considerable height. Ibn Faris writes its meaning as «حِجْرٌ عَظِیْم» (a great rock) (m. l).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ ثَمُوۡدَ الَّذِیۡنَ جَابُوا الصَّخۡرَ بِالۡوَادِ» (89/9)\nTranslation: \"And [with] Thamud, who carved rocks in the valley.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 769,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Mountain",
      "hw": "پہاڑ",
      "s": "«اَعْلَام» used metaphorically for mountains; originally means anything that is elevated and prominent among its peers. (2 verses: 42:32-55:24)",
      "d": "The plural of «عَلَم» is «اَعْلَام». And «عَلَم» means a sign, a landmark, a banner, a lighthouse, and also a mountain. And «اَعْلَام» refers to anything that is elevated and prominent among its equals, such as famous people, mountains, etc. When «اَعْلَام» is accompanied by a context that indicates it, then its meaning certainly becomes mountain.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ لَہُ الۡجَوَارِ الۡمُنۡشَئٰتُ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ کَالۡاَعۡلَامِ» (55/24)\nTranslation: \"And to Him belong the ships [that] sail in the sea like mountains.\""
    }
  ],
  "161": [
    {
      "id": 770,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To recognize",
      "hw": "پہچاننا",
      "s": "«عَرَفَ» to recognize something through its signs and marks. (19 verses: 2:89-2:146-2:273-5:83-6:20-7:46-7:48-12:58-12:62-16:83-22:72-23:69-27:93-33:59-47:6-47:30-55:41-66:3-83:24)",
      "d": "«عَرَفَ» means to recognize something by considering its signs and marks. Its opposite is «نَکِرَ». The degree of «عَرَفَ» is lower than «عَلَّمَ» (muf).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ جَآءَ اِخۡوَۃُ یُوۡسُفَ فَدَخَلُوۡا عَلَیۡہِ فَعَرَفَہُمۡ وَہُمۡ لَہٗ مُنۡکِرُوۡنَ» (12/58)\nTranslation: \"And the brothers of Yusuf came and entered upon him; he recognized them, but they were unaware of him.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 771,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To recognize",
      "hw": "پہچاننا",
      "s": "«تَوَسَّم» to discern signs and indications through one's understanding and intuition before recognizing. (8 verses: 2:273-7:46-7:48-15:75-47:30-48:29-55:41-68:16)",
      "d": "«وَسَمَ» means to mark or brand (muf). It also means to engrave or carve on the body, etc. (m. l). And «وَسْمُ» and «وِسَامٌ» are the thing with which one brands or colors. And «وَسِیْم» means beautiful (m. q). And «تَوَسَّمْ» means to state something with insight, to seek a sign, to recognize (minjada).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«اِنَّ  فِیۡ ذٰلِکَ  لَاٰیٰتٍ  لِّلۡمُتَوَسِّمِیۡنَ» (15/75)\nTranslation: \"Indeed in that are signs for those who discern.\""
    }
  ],
  "162": [
    {
      "id": 772,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "First",
      "hw": "پہلے",
      "s": "«اَوَّل» is used in three ways: (1) in terms of numerical order, (2) in terms of sequential order or artistic system (i.e., to order a task or thing first, then do or build it), (3) in terms of temporal order (i.e., according to the sequence of time). And «اُوْلٰی» means first, used only for numerical order. (82 verses: 2:41-3:96-5:107-5:114-6:14-6:25-6:94-6:110-6:163-7:38-7:39-7:143-8:31-8:38-9:13-9:83-9:100-9:108-15:10-15:13-16:24-17:7-17:51-17:59-18:48-18:55-20:21-20:51-20:65-20:133-21:5-21:104-23:24-23:68-23:81-23:83-25:5-26:26-26:51-26:137-26:184-26:196-27:68-28:36-28:43-28:70-33:33-35:43-36:79-37:17-37:59-37:71-37:126-37:168-39:12-41:21-43:6-43:8-43:81-44:8-44:35-44:56-46:17-50:15-53:25-53:50-53:56-56:13-56:39-56:48-56:49-56:62-57:3-59:2-68:15-77:16-77:38-79:25-83:13-87:18-92:13-93:4)",
      "d": "«اَوَّل» means first, and its feminine form is «اُوْلٰی» meaning first. And «اوّل» is used in three ways:\n(1) In terms of numerical order: meaning the number before which there is no other number; thus, first (i.e., the first) is followed by second (i.e., the second), then third (i.e., the third), etc.\n(2) In terms of sequential order or artistic system (i.e., to order a task or thing first, then do or build it). For example, «الاَسُّ اوّلا ثمَّ البناء» means the foundation will be laid first, then the construction.\n(3) In terms of temporal order (i.e., according to the sequence of time). In this sense, the opposite of «اوّل» is «اٰخِرْ» meaning last.\nAnd «اُوْلٰی» means first (i.e., the first world), used only for numerical order. And the opposite of «اُوْلٰی» is «اٰخِرَت» (meaning the Hereafter).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«قُلۡ اِنَّ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ وَالۡاٰخِرِیۡنَ لَمَجۡمُوۡعُوۡنَ  ۙ اِلٰی مِیۡقَاتِ یَوۡمٍ مَّعۡلُوۡمٍ» (56/49,50)\nTranslation: \"Say, 'Indeed, the former and the latter will be gathered together for an appointed time known.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 773,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "First",
      "hw": "پہلے",
      "s": "«سَبَقَ» means to go ahead, to precede. «مَسْبُوْق» means one who is left behind or comes later. (28 verses: 7:80-8:59-8:68-9:100-10:19-11:40-11:110-15:5-20:99-20:129-21:27-21:101-23:27-23:43-23:61-29:4-29:28-29:39-35:32-36:40-37:171-41:45-42:14-46:11-56:10-57:21-59:10-79:4)",
      "d": "The original meaning of «سَبَقَ» is to go ahead oneself and leave others behind.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«رَبَّنَا اغۡفِرۡ لَنَا وَلِاِخۡوَانِنَا الَّذِیۡنَ سَبَقُوۡنَا بِالۡاِیۡمَانِ» (59/10)\nTranslation: \"Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 774,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "First",
      "hw": "پہلے",
      "s": "«قَبْل» means ahead, before, previously, in front. Used for all types of precedence (temporal, spatial, sequential). In the Quran, it is used only for temporal precedence. (236 verses: 2:4-2:21-2:25-2:89-2:91-2:108-2:118-2:183-2:198-2:214-2:237-2:254-2:286-3:4-3:11-3:93-3:137-3:143-3:144-3:164-3:183-3:184-3:186-4:26-4:47-4:60-4:94-4:131-4:136-4:159-4:162-4:164-5:5-5:34-5:57-5:59-5:75-5:77-5:102-6:6-6:10-6:28-6:34-6:42-6:84-6:148-6:156-6:158-7:38-7:53-7:101-7:123-7:129-7:155-7:173-8:52-8:54-8:71-9:30-9:48-9:50-9:69-9:70-9:107-10:13-10:16-10:39-10:74-10:91-10:94-10:102-11:17-11:49-11:62-11:78-11:109-11:116-12:3-12:6-12:26-12:37-12:64-12:76-12:77-12:80-12:100-12:109-13:6-13:30-13:32-13:38-13:42-14:9-14:22-14:31-14:44-15:10-15:27-16:26-16:33-16:35-16:43-16:63-16:118-17:58-17:77-17:107-18:109-19:7-19:9-19:23-19:67-19:74-19:98-20:71-20:90-20:114-20:115-20:128-20:130-20:134-21:6-21:7-21:24-21:25-21:34-21:41-21:51-21:76-22:42-22:52-22:78-23:83-24:34-24:55-24:58-24:59-25:20-26:49-27:38-27:39-27:40-27:42-27:46-27:68-28:12-28:46-28:48-28:52-28:53-28:78-29:3-29:18-29:48-30:4-30:9-30:42-30:43-30:47-30:49-32:3-32:26-33:15-33:38-33:49-33:62-34:44-34:45-34:53-34:54-35:4-35:25-35:44-36:31-37:71-38:3-38:12-38:16-39:8-39:25-39:50-39:54-39:55-39:65-40:5-40:21-40:34-40:67-40:74-40:78-40:82-41:25-41:43-41:48-42:3-42:47-43:21-43:23-43:45-44:17-44:37-46:4-46:12-46:17-46:18-47:10-48:15-48:16-48:23-50:12-50:36-50:39-51:16-51:46-51:52-52:26-52:28-53:52-54:9-55:56-55:74-56:45-57:10-57:16-57:22-58:3-58:4-58:5-59:9-59:15-62:2-63:10-64:5-67:18-69:9-71:1)",
      "d": "«قَبْل» is the opposite of «بَعَد». It is used for all types of precedence (temporal, spatial, sequential). However, in the Quran, this word has been used only in the sense of «تَقَدّم» (temporal precedence).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَالَّذِیۡنَ یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ بِمَاۤ اُنۡزِلَ اِلَیۡکَ وَمَاۤ اُنۡزِلَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِکَ» (2/4)\nTranslation: \"And those who believe in what has been revealed to you, [O Muhammad], and what was revealed before you.\""
    }
  ],
  "163": [
    {
      "id": 775,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Side",
      "hw": "پہلو",
      "s": "«جَنْب» applies to both living and non-living things; means side, aspect, flank. (12 verses: 4:36-10:12-17:68-17:83-19:52-20:80-28:29-28:44-28:46-37:8-39:56-41:51)",
      "d": "«جَنْب» means side, aspect, flank, or position. And «جَنْب» can be any one side or aspect of something.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَاِذَا مَسَّ الۡاِنۡسَانَ الضُّرُّ دَعَانَا لِجَنۡۢبِہٖۤ اَوۡ قَاعِدًا اَوۡ قَآئِمًا» (10/12)\nTranslation: \"And when adversity touches man, he calls upon Us, whether lying on his side or sitting or standing.\"\nAdditionally, it can refer to something nearby or adjacent. For example, «صاحِبِ بِالْجَنَب» means a companion sitting nearby, and «جَانِب» or «طَرَف» also, as in «جَنْبِ الْحَائِط» meaning the side of the wall (muf). Fundamentally, «جَنْب» has been used in two senses: (1) side, (2) to be distant (m. l).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَالۡجَارِ الۡجُنُبِ وَ الصَّاحِبِ بِالۡجَنۡۢبِ وَ ابۡنِ السَّبِیۡلِ» (4/36)\nTranslation: \"And the neighbor who is a stranger and the companion by your side and the traveler.\"\nAnd «جَارِالْجَنْب» refers to the distant neighbor, and «صَاحِبِ بِالْجَنْب» means the one who resides nearby. And by the same analogy, it is also used for \"in favor of\" or \"regarding.\"\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«اَنۡ تَقُوۡلَ نَفۡسٌ یّٰحَسۡرَتٰی عَلٰی مَا فَرَّطۡتُّ فِیۡ جَنۡۢبِ اللّٰہِ» (39/56)\nTranslation: \"Lest a soul should say, 'Oh, woe to me for what I neglected regarding Allah.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 776,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Side",
      "hw": "پہلو",
      "s": "'Janāḥ' is used for the side of living beings and to describe the quality of humility and meekness (6 verses: 6:38-15:88-17:24-20:22-26:215-28:32)",
      "d": "'Janāḥ' generally means the feather of birds. Its dual is «جَنَاحَیْن» and plural «اَجْنِحَۃٌ». Then this word began to be used for a person's arm as well, referring to the part from the shoulder to the palm (manjad), and «جَنَحَ» means to incline. If this inclination is towards good, it is called «جَنَاح», and if towards evil, «جُنَاح». (Muf) In the following verses, «جَنَاح» means arm or side, but its inclination is towards good. For example, in the Quran: «وَ اخۡفِضۡ جَنَاحَکَ لِمَنِ اتَّبَعَکَ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ» (26/215) Translation: And lower your wing of mercy for those believers who follow you. At another place, the command of Allah is: «وَ اخۡفِضۡ لَہُمَا جَنَاحَ الذُّلِّ مِنَ الرَّحۡمَۃِ» (17/24) Translation: And lower for them the wing of humility from mercy (Uthmani). And the word «جُنَاح» does not denote inclination towards good but gives the meaning of sin or inclination towards it."
    },
    {
      "id": 777,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Side",
      "hw": "پہلو",
      "s": "'Iṭf' is used to describe a state of excess and arrogance (1 verse: 22:9)",
      "d": "'Aṭafa' means to turn one side of something towards another, to double. And 'aṭāf' refers to a two-layered cloak (Muf). And 'ʿaṭf' means crookedness and inclination (Manjad). And 'ʿiṭf' means side and edge. And 'ʿiṭf al-rajul' means both sides of a man. And 'thanaʿ iṭfihi' means to turn one's face away and to exceed. And 'marra thaniya iṭfihi' means to walk with arrogance (Manjad). Thus, the word 'ʿiṭf' when used in the meaning of side, comes to describe a state of excess and arrogance. For example, in the Quran: «ثَانِیَ عِطۡفِہٖ لِیُضِلَّ عَنۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ» (22/9) Translation: And he turns his side (with arrogance) to lead people astray from the path of Allah."
    }
  ],
  "164": [
    {
      "id": 778,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Reach",
      "hw": "پہنچنا",
      "s": "'Balağa' means to reach the utmost or final limit of a purpose (49 verses: 2:196-2:231-2:232-2:234-2:235-3:40-4:6-5:67-6:19-6:128-6:152-7:62-7:68-7:79-7:93-9:6-11:57-12:22-13:14-17:23-17:34-17:37-18:60-18:61-18:76-18:82-18:86-18:90-18:93-19:8-22:5-24:58-24:59-28:14-33:10-33:39-34:45-37:102-40:36-40:67-40:80-46:15-46:23-48:25-53:30-56:83-65:2-72:28-75:26)",
      "d": "'Balağa' means to reach the utmost or final limit of a purpose (Muf). For example, in the Quran: «وَابۡتَلُوا الۡیَتٰمٰی حَتّٰۤی اِذَا بَلَغُوا النِّکَاحَ» (4/6) Translation: And test the orphans until they reach the age of marriage."
    },
    {
      "id": 779,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Reach",
      "hw": "پہنچنا",
      "s": "'Aṣāba' means for hardship or goodness to reach a person from Allah (28 verses: 2:156-2:264-2:265-2:266-3:117-3:146-3:153-3:165-3:166-3:172-4:62-4:72-4:73-4:79-5:106-11:81-11:89-16:34-22:11-22:35-30:48-31:17-38:36-39:51-42:30-42:39-57:22-64:11)",
      "d": "'Ṣawb' means for something to descend and settle. And 'al-ṣawb' is also said for rain to fall. And 'aṣāba' means for an arrow etc. to hit the exact target. And 'ṣawāb' means correct and exact. And its opposite is 'khaṭā' (Manjad). And 'muṣībah' originally refers to that which hits the exact target. Then in common usage, 'muṣībah' is generally used in a bad sense. For example, in the Quran: «الَّذِیۡنَ اِذَاۤ اَصَابَتۡہُمۡ مُّصِیۡبَۃٌ  ۙ قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّا لِلّٰہِ وَاِنَّاۤ اِلَیۡہِ رٰجِعُوۡنَ» (2/156) Translation: Those who, when a calamity befalls them, say, 'Indeed, we belong to Allah, and indeed, to Him we will return.' (Uthmani) Thus, 'aṣāba' is used for hardship, calamity, and trouble that reaches a person from Allah. Although its usage is mostly in a bad sense, it can also be used in a good sense. For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَئِنۡ اَصَابَکُمۡ فَضۡلٌ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ» (4/73) Translation: And if you are granted a favor from Allah (Uthmani)."
    },
    {
      "id": 780,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Reach",
      "hw": "پہنچنا",
      "s": "'Nāla' means to reach and obtain that which a person desires (10 verses: 2:124-3:92-5:94-7:37-7:49-7:152-9:74-9:120-22:37-33:25)",
      "d": "'Nāla' means to reach or obtain that which a person desires (Muf). 'Ārāe hāthhon lenā' (Q. J.) and 'nayl' means purpose and objective, and 'naylah' means the desired thing (Manjad). For example, in the Quran: «لَنۡ تَنَالُوا الۡبِرَّ حَتّٰۤی تُنۡفِقُوۡا مِمَّا تُحِبُّوۡنَ» (3/92) Translation: You will never attain goodness until you spend from what you love."
    },
    {
      "id": 781,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Reach",
      "hw": "پہنچنا",
      "s": "'Nāwasha' means to reach out and grasp something (1 verse: 34:52)",
      "d": "'Nāsha' means to seize something, to seek (Manjad). And it also means to consume. And 'nāsha fulānan' means to rush to seize his head and beard (M. Q.). 'Nāla' and 'nāsha' are nearly synonymous words, meaning to reach out and grasp with the hand or to reach something with the hand. The difference is only that 'nāla' is used specifically for obtaining a desirable thing, while 'nāsha' is general. For example, in the Quran: «وَّ قَالُوۡۤا اٰمَنَّا بِہٖ ۚ وَ اَنّٰی لَہُمُ التَّنَاوُشُ مِنۡ مَّکَانٍۭ بَعِیۡدٍ» (34/52) Translation: And they will say, 'We believe in it,' but how can they reach it from a distant place?"
    },
    {
      "id": 783,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Reach",
      "hw": "پہنچنا",
      "s": "'Waṣala' means to reach something and to meet or join (18 verses: 2:27-4:10-4:90-6:136-11:81-13:21-13:25-14:29-17:18-28:35-28:51-38:56-58:8-82:15-84:12-87:12-92:15-111:3)",
      "d": "'Waṣala' means for something to reach another thing and to meet or join, like the diameter of a circle meeting the circumference at both ends (Muf). Therefore, its meanings include to reach, to join, and to connect (Manjad. M. Q.). Then this word is used in these three meanings separately as well. (1) Example of the meaning of reaching: The command of Allah is: «قَالُوۡا یٰلُوۡطُ اِنَّا رُسُلُ رَبِّکَ  لَنۡ یَّصِلُوۡۤا اِلَیۡکَ» (11/81) Translation: They said, 'O Lot! Indeed, we are messengers of your Lord; they will never reach you.' (2) Example of the meaning of joining and connecting: The command of Allah is: «وَ یَقۡطَعُوۡنَ مَاۤ اَمَرَ اللّٰہُ بِہٖۤ  اَنۡ یُّوۡصَلَ» (2/27) Translation: And they sever what Allah has ordered to be joined."
    },
    {
      "id": 784,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Reach",
      "hw": "پہنچنا",
      "s": "'Afaḍā' idiomatically means for a husband to reach his wife or to have marital relations (1 verse: 4:21)",
      "d": "'Faḍā' means an open and empty space between the earth and sky (Muf. M. L.). And 'maqām fāḍin' refers to a place that is open, spacious, and empty (Manjad). And 'afaḍā ilayhi bi-sirrihi' means to tell someone a secret. And 'afaḍā bi-fulānin' means to take someone to an open field (Manjad). And 'afaḍā ilā amraʾatihi' is idiomatically used to mean to have marital relations with one's wife. For example, in the Quran: «وَ کَیۡفَ تَاۡخُذُوۡنَہٗ وَ قَدۡ  اَفۡضٰی بَعۡضُکُمۡ  اِلٰی بَعۡضٍ» (4/21) Translation: And how can you take it (back) while some of you have already reached others? (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 785,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Reach",
      "hw": "پہنچنا",
      "s": "The original meaning of 'Massa' is to touch. Sometimes, due to translation needs, it is translated as 'to reach' (58 verses: 2:80-2:214-2:236-2:237-2:275-3:24-3:47-3:120-3:140-3:174-4:43-5:6-5:73-6:7-6:17-6:49-7:73-7:95-7:188-7:201-8:68-10:12-10:21-10:107-11:10-11:48-11:64-11:113-12:88-15:48-15:54-16:53-17:67-17:83-19:20-19:45-20:97-21:46-21:83-24:14-24:35-26:156-30:33-33:49-35:35-36:18-38:41-39:8-39:49-39:61-41:49-41:50-41:51-50:38-54:48-56:79-70:20-70:21)",
      "d": "The original meaning of 'Massa' is for one thing to touch another. But in translation, sometimes this word is given the meaning of 'to reach'. For example, in the Quran: «ثُمَّ بَدَّلۡنَا مَکَانَ السَّیِّئَۃَ الۡحَسَنَۃَ حَتّٰی عَفَوۡا وَّ قَالُوۡا قَدۡ مَسَّ اٰبَآءَنَا الضَّرَّآءُ وَ السَّرَّآءُ» (7/95) Translation: Then We replaced the bad with good until they increased and said, 'Indeed, hardship and ease have touched our fathers.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 786,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Reach",
      "hw": "پہنچنا",
      "s": "'Warda' means to reach a water source or well (2 verses: 21:99-28:23)",
      "d": "'Warda' lexically means for a person to reach a well or water source in search of water, and its opposite is 'ṣadara', meaning to return with water after drinking or being quenched (Muf). For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَمَّا وَرَدَ مَآءَ مَدۡیَنَ وَجَدَ عَلَیۡہِ اُمَّۃً مِّنَ النَّاسِ یَسۡقُوۡنَ» (28/23) Translation: And when he reached the water of Madyan, he found a group of people watering (their flocks)."
    },
    {
      "id": 787,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To convey/deliver",
      "hw": "پہنچنا",
      "s": "«بَلَّغَ» is generally used for conveying a message.\n«اَبْلَغَ» means to bring something or a message to its final limit, conclusion (49 verses: 2:196-2:231-2:232-2:234-2:235-3:40-4:6-5:67-6:19-6:128-6:152-7:62-7:68-7:79-7:93-9:6-11:57-12:22-13:14-17:23-17:34-17:37-18:60-18:61-18:76-18:82-18:86-18:90-18:93-19:8-22:5-24:58-24:59-28:14-33:10-33:39-34:45-37:102-40:36-40:67-40:80-46:15-46:23-48:25-53:30-56:83-65:2-72:28-75:26)",
      "d": "Both «بَلَّغَ» and «اَبْلَغَ» come with the meaning of bringing something or a message to its final limit, conclusion.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ اَحَدٌ مِّنَ الۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ اسۡتَجَارَکَ فَاَجِرۡہُ حَتّٰی یَسۡمَعَ کَلٰمَ اللّٰہِ ثُمَّ اَبۡلِغۡہُ مَاۡمَنَہٗ» (9/6)\nTranslation: If any of the polytheists seeks your protection, then grant him protection until he hears the word of Allah. Then deliver him to his place of security.\nAt another place, the Divine command states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الرَّسُوۡلُ بَلِّغۡ  مَاۤ اُنۡزِلَ اِلَیۡکَ  مِنۡ رَّبِّکَ» (5/67)\nTranslation: O Messenger! Convey that which has been revealed to you from your Lord."
    },
    {
      "id": 788,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To convey/deliver",
      "hw": "پہنچنا",
      "s": "«اَوْرَدَ» means to bring someone to the brink/edge (1 verse: 11:98)",
      "d": "«اَوْرَدَ» means to bring another person to the brink/edge (transitive).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یَقۡدُمُ  قَوۡمَہٗ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ فَاَوۡرَدَہُمُ النَّارَ ؕ وَ بِئۡسَ الۡوِرۡدُ  الۡمَوۡرُوۡدُ» (11/98)\nTranslation: He (Pharaoh) will precede his people on the Day of Resurrection and lead them to the Fire. And evil is the watering place to which they will be brought."
    },
    {
      "id": 789,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To convey/deliver",
      "hw": "پہنچنا",
      "s": "«جَبَا» means to gather something and then deliver it to another place (1 verse: 28:57)",
      "d": "In the basic meanings of «جَبَا», two things are found: (1) to gather or collect something, (2) then to deliver it to another place. The phrase «جَبَتِ الْخِرَاجُ جَبَایَۃً» is an idiom used for collecting the revenues/tribute and then sending them to the original place.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَوَ لَمۡ نُمَکِّنۡ لَّہُمۡ حَرَمًا اٰمِنًا یُّجۡبٰۤی اِلَیۡہِ ثَمَرٰتُ کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ» (28/57)\nTranslation: Did We not establish for them a secure sanctuary to which the fruits of all things are delivered?"
    },
    {
      "id": 790,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To convey/deliver",
      "hw": "پہنچنا",
      "s": "«اَدْلٰی اِلٰی فُلَانٍ» means to transfer one's matter/case to another person and to resort to kinship, bribery, and intercession (10 verses: 2:188-7:22-12:19-20:40-20:120-28:12-34:7-34:14-53:8-61:10)",
      "d": "«دَلْوُ» means an empty bucket, and «اَدْلٰی» means to lower that empty bucket into a well to gradually reach the water (transitive). And «اَدْلٰی اِلٰی فُلَانٍ» means to bring or take one's matter or dispute etc. to another person for a decision, or to resort to kinship or intercession as a means.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَا تَاۡکُلُوۡۤا اَمۡوَالَکُمۡ بَیۡنَکُمۡ بِالۡبَاطِلِ وَ تُدۡلُوۡا بِہَاۤ اِلَی الۡحُکَّامِ لِتَاۡکُلُوۡا فَرِیۡقًا مِّنۡ اَمۡوَالِ النَّاسِ بِالۡاِثۡمِ» (2/188)\nTranslation: And do not consume one another's wealth unjustly or send it [in bribery] to the rulers so that you might knowingly consume a portion of the wealth of the people in sin."
    }
  ],
  "165": [
    {
      "id": 791,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To tear/rip",
      "hw": "پھاڑنا",
      "s": "«خَرَقَ» means to tear something in order to spoil and ruin it (3 verses: 6:100-17:37-18:71)",
      "d": "The meaning of «خَرَقَ» is to tear something and ruin it completely. To smash and destroy. Or to break in order to spoil. And «خَرْقَہ» refers to the tatters of cloth, and «خَارِق» refers to something contrary to custom/norm.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَانۡطَلَقَا ٝحَتّٰۤی اِذَا رَکِبَا فِی السَّفِیۡنَۃِ خَرَقَہَا ؕ قَالَ اَخَرَقۡتَہَا لِتُغۡرِقَ اَہۡلَہَا» (18/71)\nTranslation: So they both set out until, when they had boarded the ship, he tore it. [Moses] said, \"Did you tear it to drown its people?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 792,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To tear/rip",
      "hw": "پھاڑنا",
      "s": "«قَدَّ» means to tear something lengthwise (4 verses: 12:25-12:26-12:27-12:28)",
      "d": "«قَدَّ» means to tear something lengthwise. And «قَدّ» means a person's length, stature. And «قَدِیْد» refers to long strips of dried meat.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اسۡتَبَقَا الۡبَابَ وَ قَدَّتۡ قَمِیۡصَہٗ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ» (12/25)\nTranslation: And they both raced to the door, and she tore his shirt from the back."
    },
    {
      "id": 793,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To tear/rip",
      "hw": "پھاڑنا",
      "s": "«فَطَرَ» means to make a fissure and to cut/scratch (18 verses: 6:14-6:79-11:51-12:101-14:10-17:51-19:90-20:72-21:56-30:30-35:1-36:22-39:46-42:5-42:11-43:27-67-3-73:18-82:1)",
      "d": "«فَطَرَ» means to tear something lengthwise in such a way that a fissure/crack appears. To cut and scratch. In this sense, «فَطَرَ» also means to create and originate. And «فُطُوْر» means a fissure/crack.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَارۡجِعِ  الۡبَصَرَ ۙ ہَلۡ  تَرٰی مِنۡ فُطُوۡرٍ» (67/3)\nTranslation: Then look again. Do you see any rifts?\"\nAt another place, the Divine command states:\n«فِطۡرَتَ اللّٰہِ  الَّتِیۡ فَطَرَ  النَّاسَ عَلَیۡہَا» (30/30)\nTranslation: [Adhere to] the fitrah of Allah upon which He has created the people. (Or: That is the cutting/scratching of Allah upon which He has cut/scratch the people.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 794,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To tear/rip",
      "hw": "پھاڑنا",
      "s": "«فَجَرَ» means to tear something on a wide scale and to make it flow/gush (18 verses: 2:60-2:74-2:187-17:78-17:90-17:91-18:33-24:58-36:34-54:12-71:27-75:5-76:6-80:42-82:3-89:1-91:8-97:5)",
      "d": "«فَجَرَ» means to tear something on a wide scale. And «فَجْر» (dawn) is called so because it appears across the entire horizon. And «فَجُور» means to boldly transgress the commands of religion. From this comes «فَاجِر» and «فُجَّار». Also, in the sense of making water flow over a long distance, «فَجَرَ» and «فَجَّرَ» are used.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لَکَ حَتّٰی تَفۡجُرَ لَنَا مِنَ الۡاَرۡضِ  یَنۡۢبُوۡعًا» (17/90)\nTranslation: And they said, \"We will not believe you until you cause a spring to gush forth for us from the earth.\"\nAnd the verb «فَجَّر» is used specifically in the meaning of opening a long path for water to flow.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّ فَجَّرۡنَا خِلٰلَہُمَا نَہَرًا» (18/33)\nTranslation: And We caused a river to gush forth between them."
    },
    {
      "id": 795,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To tear/rip",
      "hw": "پھاڑنا",
      "s": "«مَخَرَ» means for a ship to tear the water, which also produces a sound (2 verses: 16:14-35:12)",
      "d": "«مَخَرَ» is used for the cutting and tearing of water. It is said «مَخَرَ الْمَاءُ الْاَرْضَ» meaning the water tears and cuts the earth and makes a whirlpool in it. And «مَخَرَالسَّفِیْنَۃَ» means for the ship to cut through the water with its prow and tear it, and to produce a sound. And «مَاخِر» is the name for that ship which tears the water and produces a sound in it. The plural of «مَاخِر» is «مَوَاخِر».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ تَرَی الۡفُلۡکَ مَوَاخِرَ فِیۡہِ» (16/14)\nTranslation: And you see the ships in it, cutting through [the water]."
    }
  ],
  "166": [
    {
      "id": 799,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To split/rupture",
      "hw": "پھٹنا",
      "s": "«تَفَطَّرَ» and «اِنْفَطَر» mean to split open and develop a fissure lengthwise in something (2 verses: 73:18-82:1)",
      "d": "«تَفَطَّرَ» and «اِنْفَطَر» mean to split open and develop a fissure/crack lengthwise in something.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِذَا السَّمَآءُ انۡفَطَرَتۡ» (82/1)\nTranslation: When the sky splits open."
    },
    {
      "id": 803,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To burst/split open",
      "hw": "پھٹنا",
      "s": "«تَمَیَّزَ» to burst from inner turmoil (3 verses: 3:179-8:37-67:8)",
      "d": "«مَازَ، مَیَّزَ» means to separate one thing from another based on superiority. And «اِمْتِاز» and «تَمَیَّزَ» mean to be distinct from others. And «تَمَیَّزَ» means to become separate and to burst into pieces. The phrase «تَمَیَّزَ فُلَانٌ مِّنَ الْغَیْظ» means someone burst from anger. (Manjad)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«تَکَادُ تَمَیَّزُ مِنَ الۡغَیۡظِ» (67/8)\nTranslation: Hell almost bursts from intense rage."
    }
  ],
  "167": [
    {
      "id": 804,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To revolve/circle",
      "hw": "پھرنا",
      "s": "«دَارَ» to revolve, to make a circle, to turn in circular motion (4 verses: 5:52-9:98-33:19-48:6)",
      "d": "«دَوْر» means to revolve in a circle, to go around, to make a circuit, to experience the turning of time. (Manjad) And «دَائِرَہ» is a well-known word. Its plural is «دَوَائِر», meaning the rotation of days, the vicissitudes of time and calamities. (Maf) This word is used in a negative sense. The opposite of «دَوْرَۃ» is «دَوْلَۃً», which refers to a time of prosperity. (Maf)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَ الۡخَوۡفُ رَاَیۡتَہُمۡ یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ اِلَیۡکَ تَدُوۡرُ اَعۡیُنُہُمۡ کَالَّذِیۡ یُغۡشٰی عَلَیۡہِ مِنَ الۡمَوۡتِ» (33/19)\nTranslation: Then when fear comes, you will see them looking towards you, their eyes revolving as those of a person overcome by death."
    },
    {
      "id": 805,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To revolve/circle",
      "hw": "پھرنا",
      "s": "«طَافَ» to go around something, to circle (10 verses: 2:158-22:29-37:45-43:71-52:24-55:44-56:17-68:19-76:15-76:19)",
      "d": "«طَوْفَ» means to circle around another thing, to go around something, or to make a circuit. (M. L) And «مَطَاف» refers to the place where one circles. (Manjad)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ وِلۡدَانٌ مُّخَلَّدُوۡنَ» (56/17)\nTranslation: Eternal youths will circulate among them."
    },
    {
      "id": 806,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To revolve/circle",
      "hw": "پھرنا",
      "s": "«حَارَ» to circle and return to the original point (1 verse: 84:14)",
      "d": "«حَارَ» means to circle and return to the same place from where one started. According to Ibn Faris, its basic meanings are: (1) to return, (2) «اَنْ یَدُوْرَ الشَّئُ دَوَرًا» meaning something goes around in a circle. «حَارَ الْمَاءِ فِی الْغَدِیْرِ» means the water started circulating in the pool. And «مَحُوْر» refers to the wood around which a spinning top rotates, i.e., the pivot of a spinning top. (Maf)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّہٗ ظَنَّ اَنۡ لَّنۡ یَّحُوۡرَ» (84/14)\nTranslation: He (the sinner) thought he would never return (to God)."
    },
    {
      "id": 807,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To turn/change",
      "hw": "پھرنا",
      "s": "«تَقَلَّبَ، اِنْقَلَبَ» to completely change from one state to its opposite state (32 verses: 2:143-2:144-3:127-3:144-3:149-3:174-3:196-5:21-6:110-7:119-7:125-9:48-9:95-12:62-16:46-18:18-18:36-22:11-24:37-24:44-26:50-26:219-26:227-29:21-33:66-40:4-43:14-47:19-48:12-67:4-83:31-84:9)",
      "d": "The word «قَلَبَ» is used in the sense of changing the direction of something, i.e., turning the upper part of something to the lower side or the inner part to the outer side. (Manjad) And in Imam Raghib's words, it means to change from one state to another, to turn. (Maf) And «تَقَلَّبَ» and «اِنْقَلَاب» mean to turn oneself or to change the previous state.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَدۡ نَرٰی تَقَلُّبَ وَجۡہِکَ فِی السَّمَآءِ» (2/144)\nTranslation: (O Muhammad ﷺ) We see you turning your face towards the heaven repeatedly.\nAnd the word «اِنْقَلَاب» is used for both good and evil.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ ارۡجِعِ الۡبَصَرَ کَرَّتَیۡنِ یَنۡقَلِبۡ اِلَیۡکَ الۡبَصَرُ خَاسِئًا وَّہُوَ حَسِیۡرٌ» (67/4)\nTranslation: Then look again and again; your sight will return to you humbled and weary.\nAnd for evil or for returning from good, the idioms «اِنقلبَ علٰی عَقِبِہٖ» and «عَلٰی وَجْھہٖ» are both used.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَفَا۠ئِنۡ مَّاتَ اَوۡ قُتِلَ انۡقَلَبۡتُمۡ عَلٰۤی اَعۡقَابِکُمۡ» (3/144)\nTranslation: If Muhammad (ﷺ) dies or is killed, will you then turn back on your heels? (i.e., will you become apostates?)\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ اِنۡ اَصَابَتۡہُ فِتۡنَۃُۨ انۡقَلَبَ عَلٰی وَجۡہِہٖ» (22/11)\nTranslation: And if a trial befalls him, he turns back on his face (in despair)."
    },
    {
      "id": 808,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To turn back",
      "hw": "پھرنا",
      "s": "«نَکَصَ علٰی عَقِبِہٖ» to turn back from good deeds (10 verses: 2:143-3:144-3:149-6:71-8:48-13:41-23:66-27:10-28:31-43:28)",
      "d": "«نَکَصَ» means to retreat. And «نَکَصَ عَنِ الْاَمْرِ» means to refrain from a matter, to stop. And «نَکَصَ عَلٰی عَقِبِہٖ» means to turn back on one's heels, to retreat from the previous matter. (Manjad) And its usage is only for turning back from good deeds. (M. L) So this word is more specific than «اِنْقَلَبَ».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَدۡ کَانَتۡ اٰیٰتِیۡ تُتۡلٰی عَلَیۡکُمۡ فَکُنۡتُمۡ عَلٰۤی اَعۡقَابِکُمۡ تَنۡکِصُوۡنَ» (23/66)\nTranslation: My verses were recited to you, but you used to turn back on your heels."
    },
    {
      "id": 809,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To turn away",
      "hw": "پھرنا",
      "s": "«اِنْصَرَف» to turn away, to change from one state to another, whether slight or major (26 verses: 3:152-6:16-6:46-6:65-6:105-7:47-7:58-7:146-9:127-10:32-12:24-12:33-12:34-17:41-17:89-18:53-18:54-20:113-24:43-25:19-25:50-25:65-39:6-40:69-46:27-46:29)",
      "d": "The word «صَرَفَ» is more general than «نَکَبَ» (to be crooked). And «نَکِبَ» is used for complete change, meaning to turn upside down. While «صَرَفَ» is used for both changing direction and complete change. «تَصْرِیْفِ الرِّیَاح» means the changing of winds' direction, whether the change is very slight.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا مَاۤ اُنۡزِلَتۡ سُوۡرَۃٌ نَّظَرَ بَعۡضُہُمۡ اِلٰی بَعۡضٍ ؕ ہَلۡ یَرٰىکُمۡ مِّنۡ اَحَدٍ ثُمَّ انۡصَرَفُوۡا» (9/127)\nTranslation: And when a surah is revealed, they look at each other (saying), 'Does anyone see you?' Then they turn away."
    },
    {
      "id": 810,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To turn away",
      "hw": "پھرنا",
      "s": "«وَلّٰی، تَوَلّٰی» meaning to turn away, to avoid, and to go far (41 verses: 2:64-2:83-2:144-2:148-2:205-3:23-3:82-3:111-4:80-4:115-5:92-7:79-7:93-8:16-9:3-9:25-10:72-12:84-18:18-20:48-20:60-24:47-27:10-28:24-28:31-31:7-33:15-47:22-48:16-51:39-53:29-53:33-54:45-59:12-64:12-70:17-75:32-80:1-88:23-92:16-96:13)",
      "d": "«وَلّٰی، تَوَلّٰی» means to turn away, to avoid, and to go far. And «وَلَّی الدُّبُر» means to turn one's back and flee.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاٰہَا تَہۡتَزُّ کَاَنَّہَا جَآنٌّ وَّلّٰی مُدۡبِرًا» (27/10)\nTranslation: Then when he saw it trembling as if it were a snake, he turned and fled.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«فَتَوَلّٰی عَنۡہُمۡ وَ قَالَ یٰقَوۡمِ لَقَدۡ اَبۡلَغۡتُکُمۡ رِسَالَۃَ رَبِّیۡ» (7/79)\nTranslation: Then he (Salih) turned away from them and said, 'O my people, I have certainly conveyed to you the message of my Lord.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 811,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To turn back/revert",
      "hw": "پھرنا",
      "s": "«اِرْتَدَّ» to turn back considering something unacceptable, to apostatize from religion (8 verses: 2:217-5:21-5:54-12:96-14:43-18:64-27:40-47:25)",
      "d": "«رَدّ» means to not accept something and to turn it back. (M. Q) And «مَرْدُود» is that thing which is returned because it is unacceptable. And «اِرْتَدَّ» means to turn back from something with dislike, to return, and «اِرْتَدَّ عَنْ دِیْنِہٖ» means to turn back from religion or to become an apostate.\nThe Quran states:\n«فَارۡتَدَّا عَلٰۤی اٰثَارِہِمَا قَصَصًا» (18/64)\nTranslation: So they turned back, following their footprints, retracing their steps.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّرۡتَدِدۡ مِنۡکُمۡ عَنۡ دِیۡنِہٖ فَیَمُتۡ وَ ہُوَ کَافِرٌ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ حَبِطَتۡ اَعۡمَالُہُمۡ فِی الدُّنۡیَا وَ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ» (2/217)\nTranslation: And whoever among you apostatizes from his religion and dies while a disbeliever - for those, their deeds will become worthless in this world and the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 812,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To turn one's back",
      "hw": "پھرنا",
      "s": "«اَدْبَرَ» to turn one's back and leave, to avoid (20 verses: 3:111-4:47-5:21-8:15-8:16-8:50-9:25-15:65-17:46-33:15-47:25-47:27-48:22-50:40-52:49-59:12-70:17-74:23-74:33-79:22)",
      "d": "«دُبُر» its plural is «اَدْبَار», meaning back, rear. Its opposite is «قَبْل». And «دَبَرَ فَلَانٌ» means so-and-so turned his back. (Maf) And «اَدْبَرَ» means to turn one's back and leave.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ نَظَرَ ثُمَّ عَبَسَ وَبَسَرَ ثُمَّ اَدۡبَرَ وَاسۡتَکۡبَرَ» (74/21,22,23)\nTranslation: Then he looked, then he frowned and scowled, then he turned his back and acted arrogantly."
    }
  ],
  "168": [
    {
      "id": 814,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Turn",
      "hw": "پھیرنا",
      "s": "«صَرَفَ» is used in the meaning of merely turning the direction. (37 verses: 3:152-6:16-6:46-6:65-6:105-7:47-7:58-7:146-9:127-10:32-12:24-12:33-12:34-17:41-17:89-18:53-18:54-20:113-24:43-25:19-25:50-25:65-39:6-40:69-46:27-46:29)",
      "d": "«صَرَفَ» is used in the meaning of merely turning the direction.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا صُرِفَتۡ اَبۡصَارُہُمۡ تِلۡقَآءَ اَصۡحٰبِ النَّارِ» ( 7/47 )\nTranslation: And when their sights are turned towards the companions of the Fire. (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 815,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Turn",
      "hw": "پھیرنا",
      "s": "«وَلّٰی» means to turn away, to ignore, and to become distant. (41 verses: 2:64-2:83-2:144-2:148-2:205-3:23-3:82-3:111-4:80-4:115-5:92-7:79-7:93-8:16-9:3-9:25-10:72-12:84-18:18-20:48-20:60-24:47-27:10-28:24-28:31-31:7-33:15-47:22-48:16-51:39-53:29-53:33-54:45-59:12-64:12-70:17-75:32-80:1-88:23-92:16-96:13)",
      "d": "«وَلّٰی» means to turn away, to ignore, to become distant, and to cause to turn away.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَنُوَلِّیَنَّکَ قِبۡلَۃً  تَرۡضٰہَا» ( 2/144 )\nTranslation: So, We will surely turn you towards a direction you will be pleased with."
    },
    {
      "id": 816,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Turn",
      "hw": "پھیرنا",
      "s": "«ردّ» means to turn something back because it is unacceptable. (44 verses: 2:85-2:109-2:217-2:228-3:100-3:149-4:47-4:59-4:83-4:86-4:91-5:108-6:27-6:28-6:62-6:71-6:147-7:53-9:94-9:101-9:105-10:30-11:76-12:65-12:110-13:11-14:9-16:70-17:6-18:36-18:87-21:40-22:5-28:13-30:43-33:25-38:33-40:43-41:47-42:44-42:47-62:8-79:10-95:5)",
      "d": "«ردّ» means to turn something back because it is unacceptable, to return, to repel.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَمَّا فَتَحُوۡا مَتَاعَہُمۡ وَجَدُوۡا بِضَاعَتَہُمۡ رُدَّتۡ  اِلَیۡہِمۡ» ( 12/65 )\nTranslation: And when they opened their baggage, they found their merchandise returned to them."
    },
    {
      "id": 817,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Turn",
      "hw": "پھیرنا",
      "s": "«لَفَتَ» means to turn to the right or left. (4 verses: 10:78-11:81-15:65-75:29)",
      "d": "«لَفَت» and «اِلتَفَتَ» mean to turn something to the right or left, to pay attention, to turn and look, to look by turning one's face. (Munjid)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَجِئۡتَنَا لِتَلۡفِتَنَا عَمَّا وَجَدۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ اٰبَآءَنَا» ( 10/78 )\nTranslation: The courtiers of Pharaoh said, \"Have you come to turn us away from that on which we found our fathers?\"\nAt another place, the Lord says:\n«وَ لَا یَلۡتَفِتۡ مِنۡکُمۡ اَحَدٌ» ( 11/81 )\nTranslation: And let none of you turn back to look!"
    },
    {
      "id": 818,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Turn",
      "hw": "پھیرنا",
      "s": "«اَفَکَ» means to turn from the correct direction to the wrong one. (12 verses: 7:117-24:11-24:12-25:4-26:45-29:17-34:43-37:151-46:11-46:22-46:28-51:9)",
      "d": "«اَفَکَ» means to turn from the correct and right direction (transitive), and «اِفْک» means falsehood and slander.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَجِئۡتَنَا لِتَاۡفِکَنَا عَنۡ اٰلِہَتِنَا» ( 46/22 )\nTranslation: They (the people of 'Ad) said, \"Have you come to turn us away from our gods?\""
    }
  ],
  "169": [
    {
      "id": 819,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Slip / To Cause to Slip",
      "hw": "پھسلنا",
      "s": "«زَلَقَ» means for a foot to slip. (2 verses: 18:40-68:51)",
      "d": "«زَلَقَ» means to slip. Its opposite is «ثَبَتَ». (M. L.) «زَلَقَتِ الْقَدَمُ» means the foot slipped, and «زَلَقَ بَدَنٌ» means to make a body slippery by applying oil, etc., causing it to slip.\nAnd «مَزْلَقُ» refers to a place where one slips and the foot cannot find firm ground.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡہَا حُسۡبَانًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فَتُصۡبِحَ  صَعِیۡدًا  زَلَقًا» ( 18/40 )\nTranslation: And He will send upon it a [torment] from the sky, and it will become a smooth, slippery plain. (i.e., so smooth that a person slips)\nAnd «اَزْلَقَ» means to cause someone to slip by frightening or through deceit and trickery. And «اَزْلَقَ بِبَصَرِہٖ» is an idiom meaning to glare at someone with angry, sharp eyes. (Munjid)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّکَادُ  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَیُزۡلِقُوۡنَکَ بِاَبۡصَارِہِمۡ» ( 68/51 )\nTranslation: And indeed, those who disbelieve would almost make you slip with their eyes."
    },
    {
      "id": 820,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Slip / To Cause to Slip",
      "hw": "پھسلنا",
      "s": "«زَلَّ» means to slip and to become unsteady or fall from one's place. (4 verses: 2:36-2:209-3:155-16:94)",
      "d": "«زَلَّ» means to slip and to move from one's place. Its opposite is «رَسَخَ». (M. L.) Some hold that its meanings are to slip and to fall. (M. Q.) Its opposite «ثَبَتَ» also applies, and the Quran confirms this.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡۤا اَیۡمَانَکُمۡ  دَخَلًۢا بَیۡنَکُمۡ فَتَزِلَّ قَدَمٌۢ  بَعۡدَ ثُبُوۡتِہَا» ( 16/94 )\nTranslation: And do not take your oaths as [means of] deceit between you, lest a foot slip after it was [once] firm.\nAnd «اَزَلَّ» means to cause someone else to slip in such a way that they become unsteady from their place. Both «زَلَّ» and «اَزَلَّ» are used in both literal and figurative senses.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَزَلَّہُمَا الشَّیۡطٰنُ عَنۡہَا فَاَخۡرَجَہُمَا مِمَّا کَانَا فِیۡہِ» ( 2/36 )\nTranslation: Then Satan caused them to slip from it and brought them out from where they had been."
    },
    {
      "id": 822,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Slip / To Cause to Slip",
      "hw": "پھسلنا",
      "s": "«ھَالَ» means for sand, etc., to slip down from a dune. (1 verse: 73:14)",
      "d": "«ھَیْل» means for sand or dust to slip down from the top of a dune. And «اَلْھَیْل» and «اَلْھَیَال» refer to fallen sand. (Munjid)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ کَانَتِ الۡجِبَالُ  کَثِیۡبًا مَّہِیۡلًا» ( 73/14 )\nTranslation: And the mountains will be as [if they were] heaps of sand, slipping down."
    },
    {
      "id": 823,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Slip / To Cause to Slip",
      "hw": "پھسلنا",
      "s": "«رَاوَدَ» means to entice someone toward sin from their intention. (7 verses: 12:23-12:26-12:30-12:32-12:51-12:61-54:37)",
      "d": "«رَوْد ، رَادَ» means to search for something and to come and go. And «اَرَادَ» means for an idea to come to mind. And «رَاوَدَ» means to make someone share the same thought or intention when there is no harmony, and this word is used for incitement toward evil and sin. That is, to entice and seduce someone toward sin. (transitive)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَ مَا خَطۡبُکُنَّ اِذۡ رَاوَدۡتُّنَّ یُوۡسُفَ عَنۡ نَّفۡسِہٖ» ( 12/51 )\n1 - Translation: He (the king of Egypt) said to the women, \"What was your case when you sought to seduce Joseph?\"\n2 - Translation: The king said to the women, \"What is the truth of your matter when you attempted to turn Joseph from guarding himself?\" (Uthmani)"
    }
  ],
  "170": [
    {
      "id": 824,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Fruit",
      "hw": "پھل",
      "s": "«ثَمَرَ» is the general word for fruit. (22 verses: 2:22-2:25-2:126-2:155-2:266-6:99-6:141-7:57-7:130-13:3-14:32-14:37-16:11-16:67-16:69-18:34-18:42-28:57-35:27-36:35-41:47-47:15)",
      "d": "«ثَمَرَ» means fruit. The use of this word is general. Whether fresh or dried, and of any kind, it can apply to all. Its plurals are «اَثْمَار» and «ثَمَرَات».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَخۡرَجَ بِہٖ مِنَ الثَّمَرٰتِ رِزۡقًا لَّکُمۡ» ( 2/22 )\nTranslation: Then He brings forth from it its produce as provision for you."
    },
    {
      "id": 825,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Fruit",
      "hw": "پھل",
      "s": "«فَاکِھَۃ» is used for fruits other than dates and pomegranates, and according to some, for delicious fruits or dried fruits (11 verses: 36:57-38:51-43:73-44:55-52:22-55:11-55:52-55:68-56:20-56:32-80:31)",
      "d": "«فَاکِھَۃ» refers to all fruits except dates, grapes, and pomegranates, and its plural is «فَوَاکِہَ» (M. L.). According to some scholars, all fruits including grapes, except dates and pomegranates, are «فَاکِھَۃ». For example, the Quran states: «فِیۡہِمَا فَاکِھَۃٌ وَّ نَخۡلٌ وَّ رُمَّانٌ» (55/68). Translation: In them are fruits and date-palms and pomegranates. This indicates that dates and pomegranates are distinct from «فَاکِھَۃ». Some interpret «فَوَاکِہَ» as dried fruits. The meaning of «فَکِہَ» is pleasant disposition, being cheerful. «فَکَّہَ» also means to offer fruit. And to please someone with sweet speech. Hence, according to Ibn Faris, «فَاکِھَۃ» is the fruit from which pleasure and delight are obtained. (M. L.) (And Allah knows best)."
    },
    {
      "id": 826,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Fruit",
      "hw": "پھل",
      "s": "«جَنِی» fresh, freshly fallen or hanging fruit on the tree (2 verses: 19:25-55:54)",
      "d": "«جَنِی» means fresh fruit. That is, fruit that is completely ripe and ready to be picked. Whether it is still on the tree or has been harvested (Maf). According to Majma' al-Bayan, «جَنِیَ» also means to pick fruit or to harvest fresh fruit. For example, the Quran states: «وَجَنَا الۡجَنَّتَیۡنِ دَانٍ» (55/54). Translation: And the fruits of both gardens will be within reach (hanging low)."
    },
    {
      "id": 827,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Fruit",
      "hw": "پھل",
      "s": "«اُکُل» the part of a fruit-bearing tree or plant that serves as human food (7 verses: 2:265-6:141-13:4-13:35-14:25-18:33-34:16)",
      "d": "«اُکُل» refers to any produce of trees and plants that becomes food for humans (Maf). According to the author of Majma' al-Bayan, its meanings are fruit, food, and ample provision. For example, the Quran states: «کَمَثَلِ جَنَّۃٍۭ بِرَبۡوَۃٍ اَصَابَہَا وَابِلٌ فَاٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا ضِعۡفَیۡنِ» (2/265). Translation: Their example is like a garden on a high ground; upon which a heavy rain fell and it yielded its fruits double."
    },
    {
      "id": 828,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Fruit to ripen",
      "hw": "پھل",
      "s": "«یَنَعَ» for fruit to become ripe and ready (1 verse: 6:99)",
      "d": "«یَنَعَ» means for fruit to become completely ripe and ready. And ripe fruit is called «یَانِعَۃٌ» or «مُوْنِعَۃٌ» (Maf). For example, the Quran states: «اُنۡظُرُوۡۤا اِلٰی ثَمَرِہٖۤ اِذَاۤ اَثۡمَرَ وَیَنۡعِہٖ» (6/99). Translation: Look at its fruit when it begins to bear and at its ripening."
    }
  ],
  "171": [
    {
      "id": 830,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To blow / To blow upon",
      "hw": "پھونک",
      "s": "«نَفَخَ» to blow upon. General usage. And according to some, to blow into a body (18 verses: 3:49-5:110-6:73-15:29-18:96-18:99-20:102-21:91-23:101-27:87-32:9-36:51-38:72-39:68-50:20-66:12-69:13-78:18)",
      "d": "«نَفْخ» means the swelling of the belly, and «مَنْفُوخ» refers to a person with a large or fat belly. «نَفَخَ» means to blow into a body, inserting air (M. R.). According to the author of Majma' al-Bayan, the meaning of «نَفَخَ» is only 'to blow upon'. And «مِنْفَاخُ» is the term for a blacksmith's bellows. For example, the Quran states: «فَاَنۡفُخُ فِیۡہِ فَیَکُوۡنُ طَیۡرًۢا بِاِذۡنِ اللّٰہِ» (3/49). Translation: Then I blow into it (the clay bird), and by Allah's permission it becomes a (real) bird."
    },
    {
      "id": 831,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To blow / To blow upon",
      "hw": "پھونک",
      "s": "«نَقَرَ» to blow into a sounding or hollow object (1 verse: 74:8)",
      "d": "«نَقَرَ» means to blow into a sounding object to make it sound. And «نَاقُوْر» is any object that is shrill and hollow inside, such as a trumpet, bugle, or any instrument that is blown (Maf). For example, the Quran states: «فَاِذَا نُقِرَ فِی النَّاقُوۡرِ» (74/8). Translation: Then when the Trumpet is blown."
    },
    {
      "id": 832,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To blow / To blow upon",
      "hw": "پھونک",
      "s": "«نَفَثَ» to spit lightly. The blowing of one who blows (spells) (1 verse: 113:4)",
      "d": "The meaning of «نَفَثَ» is to spit lightly, to expel a little (Fl 190). To blow (spells) or to expel venom (Maf). And «نَفْثُ الدَّم» is the name for the ailment where blood comes with spit. For example, the Quran states: «وَ مِنۡ شَرِّ النَّفّٰثٰتِ فِی الۡعُقَدِ» (113/4). Translation: 'And from the evil of those who blow (spells) on knots'."
    },
    {
      "id": 833,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To blow / To blow upon",
      "hw": "پھونک",
      "s": "«اَطْفَاَ» to blow out a lamp or extinguish a fire (3 verses: 5:64-9:32-61:8)",
      "d": "«طَفَئَتِ النَّار» means for fire to go out. And «اَطْفَاَ» means to extinguish by blowing (Maf). It is also used for snuffing out a lamp or light (F. L 133). For example, the Quran states: «یُرِیۡدُوۡنَ لِیُطۡفِئُوۡا نُوۡرَاللّٰہِ بِاَفۡوَاہِہِمۡ» (61/8). Translation: 'They desire to extinguish the light of Allah with their mouths (by blowing upon it)'."
    }
  ],
  "172": [
    {
      "id": 837,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To spread",
      "hw": "پھیلانا",
      "s": "«نَشَرَ» to raise, to spread, and to publicize (11 verses: 17:13-18:16-21:21-42:28-43:11-44:35-74:52-77:3-80:22-81:10-94:1)",
      "d": "The meanings of «نَشَرَ» are to spread something, to publicize news (M R). Its opposite is «طَوَي» meaning to fold. It is said: «نَشَرَتُ الْکِتَابَ ثُمَّ طَوَیْتُہٗ» - I opened the book then closed it. For example, the Quran states: «وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ یُنَزِّلُ الۡغَیۡثَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ مَا قَنَطُوۡا وَ یَنۡشُرُ رَحۡمَتَہٗ» (42/28). Translation: 'And He it is Who sends down the rain after they have despaired, and spreads His mercy (i.e., the blessings of the rain) abroad.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 838,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To spread",
      "hw": "پھیلانا",
      "s": "«بَسَطَ» meaning to open, to spread, and to make vast (22 verses: 2:245-2:247-5:11-5:28-6:93-7:69-13:14-13:26-17:29-17:30-18:18-28:82-29:62-30:37-30:48-34:36-34:39-39:52-42:12-42:27-60:2-71:19)",
      "d": "The meanings of «بَسَطَ» are to open something, to spread it, and to make it vast. And «بَسَاطُ» means vast land. And expanse (Maf). Its opposites are also «قَبَضَ» and «قَدَرَ». For example, the Quran states: «اَللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡ یُرۡسِلُ الرِّیٰحَ فَتُثِیۡرُ سَحَابًا فَیَبۡسُطُہٗ فِی السَّمَآءِ کَیۡفَ یَشَآءُ» (30/48). Translation: 'Allah is He Who sends the winds, so they raise clouds, then He spreads them in the sky as He wills.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 839,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to spread",
      "hw": "پھیلانا",
      "s": "«بَثَّ» to spread in such a way that its parts are scattered and dispersed (8 verses: 2:164-4:1-31:10-42:29-45:4-56:6-88:16-101:4)",
      "d": "«بَثَّ» means scattered (i.e., scattered, dispersed, scattered, distributed). And «بَثَّ» is also used for a distressed state and intense grief (manjad). Thus, «بَثَّ» is used in the meanings of spreading such that the parts of that thing are scattered. Like dust or the wick of a lamp.\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّاسُ اتَّقُوۡا رَبَّکُمُ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَکُمۡ مِّنۡ نَّفۡسٍ وَّاحِدَۃٍ وَّ خَلَقَ مِنۡہَا زَوۡجَہَا وَ بَثَّ مِنۡہُمَا رِجَالًا کَثِیۡرًا وَّ نِسَآءً» (4/1)\nTranslation: O people! Fear your Lord, who created you from a single soul, and created from it its mate, and then spread many men and women from them both across the earth."
    }
  ],
  "173": [
    {
      "id": 840,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To throw",
      "hw": "پھینکنا",
      "s": "«نَبَذَ» to throw something away without regard, i.e., to discard it (10 verses: 2:100-2:101-3:187-8:58-20:96-28:40-37:145-51:40-68:49-104:4)",
      "d": "«نَبَذَ» means to throw something considering it useless and worthless, to discard it without regard (muf. Fal 190).\n\nFor instance, in the Quran:\n«اَوَ کُلَّمَا عٰہَدُوۡا عَہۡدًا نَّبَذَہٗ فَرِیۡقٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ» (2/100)\nTranslation: Whenever they made a covenant, a group among them would throw it away (disregard it)."
    },
    {
      "id": 841,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To throw",
      "hw": "پھینکنا",
      "s": "«طَرَحَ» to throw something considering it worthless and reject it. (1 verse: 12:9)",
      "d": "«طَرَحَ» to throw something considering it worthless and reject it. To throw away from people's sight, i.e., to throw far away (muf). «رَاَیْتُہٗ مِنْ طَرْح» means I saw it from afar. And «طَرُوْحُ» means a distant place. And «طَرَحَ» is said for something thrown away as worthless.\n\nFor instance, in the Quran:\n«اقۡتُلُوۡا یُوۡسُفَ اَوِ اطۡرَحُوۡہُ  اَرۡضًا یَّخۡلُ لَکُمۡ وَجۡہُ  اَبِیۡکُمۡ» (12/9)\nTranslation: (The brothers of Yusuf said) Either kill Yusuf or throw him into some land, so that your father's attention may be solely towards you."
    },
    {
      "id": 842,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To throw",
      "hw": "پھینکنا",
      "s": "«رَجَمَ» to throw stones from a distance to kill or to stone (6 verses: 11:91-18:20-18:22-19:46-36:18-44:20)",
      "d": "«رَجَمَ» to throw stones and pebbles to kill someone, to stone (Fal 189).\n\nFor instance, in the Quran:\n«اِنَّہُمۡ اِنۡ یَّظۡہَرُوۡا عَلَیۡکُمۡ یَرۡجُمُوۡکُمۡ اَوۡ یُعِیۡدُوۡکُمۡ فِیۡ مِلَّتِہِمۡ» (18/20)\nTranslation: If they gain power over you, they will stone you or force you back into their religion."
    },
    {
      "id": 844,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To throw",
      "hw": "پھینکنا",
      "s": "«جَفَاَ» for a river to throw its foam or a pot's scum to the banks (1 verse: 13:17)",
      "d": "«اَلْجَفَاء» means the waste that remains on both banks of a valley or the dirt from a pot's boiling that scatters around. It is said «اَجْفَاْتِ الْقِدْرِزَ بَدَہَا» meaning the pot threw its scum.\n\nFor instance, in the Quran:\n«فَاَمَّا الزَّبَدُ فَیَذۡہَبُ جُفَآءً» (13/17)\nTranslation: And the foam goes away as scum (i.e., the river throws it onto the banks where it dries up)."
    }
  ],
  "174": [
    {
      "id": 845,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Thirsty. To be thirsty.",
      "hw": "پیاسا",
      "s": "«ظَمْاٰن» to be restless from thirst (3 verses: 9:120-20:119-24:39)",
      "d": "«ظَمَاَ» means to be thirsty. And «ظَمْاٌ» means thirst. And «ظَمْاٌ» is a degree higher than «عَطْشَ» (thirst) (Fal 162). And «ظَمْاٰن» is the intensive form of the noun, meaning a person who is very restless from thirst, extremely thirsty.\n\nFor instance, in the Quran:\n«وَالَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡۤا اَعۡمَالُہُمۡ کَسَرَابٍۭ بِقِیۡعَۃٍ یَّحۡسَبُہُ الظَّمۡاٰنُ مَآءً» (24/39)\nTranslation: And the deeds of those who disbelieved are like a mirage in a lowland which the thirsty one thinks is water."
    },
    {
      "id": 846,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Thirsty. To be thirsty.",
      "hw": "پیاسا",
      "s": "«وِرْد» A thirsty person who sets out in search of water (2 verses: 11:98-19:86)",
      "d": "«وِرْد» refers to a thirsty man or caravan that sets out in search of water (m.f.) and «وَرَدَ» means to reach a water source to drink (12/90). Also, «وِرْد» means water source (11/98), and «مَوْرُوْد» also means water source. The opposite of «وَرَدَ» is «صَدَرَ», meaning to return after drinking water.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّ نَسُوۡقُ الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ اِلٰی جَہَنَّمَ وِرۡدًا» (19/86)\nTranslation: And We will drive the criminals to Hell, thirstily."
    },
    {
      "id": 847,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Thirsty. To be thirsty.",
      "hw": "پیاسا",
      "s": "«ھِیْم» Extremely thirsty, such that the thirst is never quenched (1 verse: 56:55)",
      "d": "«اَلْھَیَام» means extreme thirst (m.l. f.l. 162). «ھَامَ» means to be intensely thirsty (manjada). And «هُيَامُ» is a disease in camels where the camel remains extremely thirsty. And «ھِیْم» is a camel suffering from a disease where its thirst is never quenched.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَشٰرِبُوۡنَ عَلَیۡہِ مِنَ الۡحَمِیۡمِ فَشٰرِبُوۡنَ شُرۡبَ الۡہِیۡمِ» (56:54,55)\nTranslation: And they will drink boiling water on top of it, and they will drink as the intensely thirsty camel drinks."
    },
    {
      "id": 848,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Thirsty. To be thirsty.",
      "hw": "پیاسا",
      "s": "«لَھَثَ» The tongue protruding due to severe thirst (1 verse: 7:176)",
      "d": "«لَھَثَ» means to protrude the tongue and pant due to severe thirst. According to some, this word is used for both desperation (compulsion and helplessness) and thirst (m.f.). «لُھْثَۃٌ» means severe thirst, and «لُهَاثُ» is the thirst caused by internal heat or stomach heat (Q.m.).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَمَثَلُہٗ  کَمَثَلِ الۡکَلۡبِ ۚ اِنۡ تَحۡمِلۡ عَلَیۡہِ یَلۡہَثۡ اَوۡ تَتۡرُکۡہُ یَلۡہَثۡ» (7/176)\nTranslation: So his example is like that of a dog: if you chase it, it pants with its tongue out, and if you leave it, it still pants with its tongue out."
    }
  ],
  "175": [
    {
      "id": 850,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "cup",
      "hw": "پیالہ",
      "s": "«کَاْس» a cup filled with drink. (6 verses: 37:45-52:23-56:18-76:5-76:17-78:34)",
      "d": "«کَاْس» a cup filled with drink. Goblet. A clinking goblet. And if it is not filled with drink, it is called «قَدَحَ» (f. l 30). «کَاْس» generally refers to a cup filled with wine. And «کَاْس» also means wine (manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«یَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  وِلۡدَانٌ مُّخَلَّدُوۡنَ ۔ بِاَکۡوَابٍ وَّ اَبَارِیۡقَ ۬ ۙ وَ کَاۡسٍ مِّنۡ مَّعِیۡنٍ ۔ لَّا یُصَدَّعُوْنَ عَنْہَا وَ لَا یُنْزِفُوۡنَۙ» (56/18)\nTranslation: Eternal young boys will circulate among them with cups and pitchers and a cup from a flowing spring. They will not suffer headache from it, nor will they be intoxicated."
    },
    {
      "id": 851,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Cup",
      "hw": "پیالہ",
      "s": "«سِقَایۃ» A cup or vessel for drinking water (3 verses: 9:19, 12:70, 76:21)",
      "d": "«سَقٰی» means to give water or present any drink. And «سِقَایۃ» refers to both the one who gives water to drink and the vessel from which one drinks (masc.). For example, the Quran states: «فَلَمَّا جَہَّزَہُمۡ بِجَہَازِہِمۡ جَعَلَ السِّقَایَۃَ فِیۡ رَحۡلِ اَخِیۡہِ» (12:70). Translation: When Yusuf (AS) prepared his brothers' luggage, he placed his cup in the luggage of his brother."
    }
  ],
  "176": [
    {
      "id": 853,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Pus",
      "hw": "پیپ",
      "s": "«غِسْلِیْن» Water that has been used to wash wounds or dirt (1 verse: 69:36)",
      "d": "«غَسَلَ» means to cleanse something with water and remove dirt. And «غِسْل» is any water used for washing something or cleansing dirt (majid). «غِسْلِیْن» refers to dirty, filthy, and polluted water or the water used for washing wounds, which includes pus, blood, and dirt. For example, the Quran states: «وَّلَا طَعَامٌ اِلَّا مِنۡ غِسۡلِیۡنٍ لَّا یَاۡکُلُہٗۤ اِلَّا الۡخَاطِئُوۡنَ» (69:36). Translation: And there will be no food for them except filthy pus, which only the sinners will eat."
    },
    {
      "id": 854,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Pus",
      "hw": "پیپ",
      "s": "«غَسَّاق» Foul-smelling, cold water or flowing pus (2 verses: 38:57, 78:25)",
      "d": "«غَسَّاق» is generally translated as pus or flowing pus. Scholars like Sahib al-Munjid, Sahib al-Fiqh al-Lughah, and Sahib al-Muntaha al-Arab explain its meaning as cold and foul-smelling water. Sahib al-Maqayis al-Lughah writes its meaning as «مَا تَقْطُرُ مِنْ جُلُوْدِ اَھْلِ النَّارِ» meaning what drips drop by drop from the skin of the people of Hell. In the Quran, the word «غَسَّاق» is used in two places in contrast to «حَمِیْم», indicating its meaning is more appropriately cold and foul-smelling water. Examples from the Quran: «اِلَّا حَمِیۡمًا وَّغَسَّاقًا» (78:25). Translation: Except boiling water and pus. And in another place: «ہٰذَا ۙ فَلۡیَذُوۡقُوۡہُ حَمِیۡمٌ وَّ غَسَّاقٌ» (38:57). Translation: This is the boiling water and pus; so let them taste it."
    }
  ],
  "177": [
    {
      "id": 856,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Back / Spine",
      "hw": "پشت",
      "s": "«ظَھَرَ» The outer rear part of a living being from the anus up to the neck (16 verses: 2:101, 2:189, 3:187, 6:31, 6:94, 6:138, 6:146, 7:172, 9:35, 11:92, 21:39, 35:45, 42:33, 43:13, 84:10, 94:3)",
      "d": "«ظَھَرَ» is the outer rear part of a living being from the anus up to the neck; its plural is «ظَھُور». For example, the Quran states: «وَاَمَّا مَنۡ اُوۡتِیَ کِتٰبَہٗ وَرَآءَ ظَہۡرِہٖ» (84:10). Translation: And as for the one who is given his book behind his back."
    },
    {
      "id": 857,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Back / Spine",
      "hw": "پشت",
      "s": "«دُبُر» The anus (posterior) and the rear part of everything (31 verses: 3:11, 4:47, 5:21, 8:15, 8:16, 8:50, 9:25, 12:25, 12:27, 12:28, 15:65, 17:46, 21:57, 27:10, 27:80, 28:31, 30:52, 33:15, 37:90, 40:33, 47:25, 47:27, 48:22, 50:40, 52:49, 54:45, 59:12, 70:17, 74:23, 74:33, 79:22)",
      "d": "«دُبُر» means the anus (posterior) and the rear part of everything (masc.). Its plural is «اَدْبَار» and its opposite is «قُبُل». «دُبُر» and «اَدْبَار» also mean 'after' or 'behind' in terms of time, e.g., «دُبُرُ الصَّلوٰۃ» means after the prayer, and «اَدْبَارُ السُّجُوْد» means after the prostrations. Thus, the meaning of «دُبُر» is broader than «ظَھَرَ». For example, the Quran states: «وَاتَّبِعۡ اَدۡبَارَہُمۡ» (15:65). Translation: And follow behind them. Another example: «سَیُہۡزَمُ الۡجَمۡعُ وَ یُوَلُّوۡنَ الدُّبُرَ» (54:45). Translation: The army will be routed, and they will turn their backs (flee)."
    },
    {
      "id": 858,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Back / Spine",
      "hw": "پشت",
      "s": "«صُلْب» The spinal bone, including fat and flesh; the spine (1 verse: 86:7)",
      "d": "«صَلَبَ الْعَظْم» means to extract fat from bone. And «صُلْب» refers to the fat and flesh of the spinal bone (majid). Since this bone is in the middle of the back, its translation is taken as back or spine. For example, the Quran states: «یَّخۡرُجُ مِنۡۢ بَیۡنِ الصُّلۡبِ وَ التَّرَآئِبِ» (86:7). Translation: That which emerges from between the backbone and the ribs."
    }
  ],
  "178": [
    {
      "id": 859,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Follow / Pursue",
      "hw": "پیچھا",
      "s": "«اِبْتِغَاء» To search for a desired thing and pursue it (46 verses: 2:187, 2:198, 2:207, 2:265, 2:272, 3:7, 3:85, 4:24, 4:94, 4:104, 4:114, 4:139, 5:2, 5:35, 6:35, 6:114, 9:48, 13:17, 13:22, 16:14, 17:12, 17:28, 17:42, 17:57, 17:66, 17:110, 23:7, 24:33, 28:55, 28:73, 28:77, 29:17, 30:23, 30:46, 33:51, 35:12, 45:12, 48:29, 57:27, 59:8, 60:1, 62:10, 66:1, 70:31, 73:20, 92:20)",
      "d": "«بَغٰی» means to search, to seek, to desire. And «اِبْتِغَاء» means to search for a desired thing and pursue it. For example, the Quran states: «وَ لَا تَہِنُوۡا فِی ابۡتِغَآءِ الۡقَوۡمِ» (4:104). Translation: And do not become weak in pursuing the enemy."
    },
    {
      "id": 860,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Follow / Pursue",
      "hw": "پیچھا",
      "s": "«قَصَّ» To follow behind, to proceed by tracing a trail (2 verses: 18:64, 28:11)",
      "d": "«قَصَّ» means to follow behind, to proceed by tracing a trail or mark (masc.). For example, the Quran states: «وَقَالَتۡ لِاُخۡتِہٖ قُصِّیۡہِ» (28:11). Translation: And she said to his sister, 'Follow him.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 861,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Follow / Pursue",
      "hw": "پیچھا",
      "s": "«اَتْبَعَ» To follow someone and go with them (150 verses: 2:38, 2:102, 2:120, 2:143, 2:145, 2:166, 2:167, 2:168, 2:170, 2:208, 2:262, 2:263, 3:7, 3:20, 3:31, 3:53, 3:55, 3:68, 3:73, 3:95, 3:162, 3:167, 3:174, 4:27, 4:83, 4:115, 4:125, 4:135, 5:16, 5:48, 5:49, 5:77, 6:50, 6:56, 6:106, 6:116, 6:142, 6:148, 6:150, 6:153, 6:155, 7:3, 7:18, 7:90, 7:142, 7:157, 7:158, 7:175, 7:176, 7:193, 7:203, 8:64, 9:42, 9:100, 9:117, 10:15, 10:35, 10:36, 10:66, 10:89, 10:90, 10:109, 11:27, 11:59, 11:60, 11:97, 11:99, 11:116, 12:38, 12:108, 13:37, 14:21, 14:36, 14:44, 15:18, 15:42, 15:65, 16:123, 17:47, 17:63, 18:28, 18:66, 18:70, 18:85, 18:89, 18:92, 19:43, 19:59, 20:16, 20:47, 20:78, 20:90, 20:93, 20:108, 20:123, 20:134, 22:3, 23:44, 23:71, 24:21, 25:8, 26:40, 26:52, 26:60, 26:111, 26:215, 26:224, 28:35, 28:42, 28:47, 28:49, 28:50, 28:57, 29:12, 30:29, 31:15, 31:21, 33:2, 34:20, 36:11, 36:20, 36:21, 37:10, 38:26, 38:85, 39:18, 39:55, 40:7, 40:38, 40:47, 42:15, 43:61, 44:23, 45:18, 46:9, 47:3, 47:14, 47:16, 47:28, 48:15, 52:21, 53:23, 53:28, 54:3, 54:24, 57:27, 71:21, 75:18, 77:17, 79:7)",
      "d": "«اَتْبَعَ» means to follow someone and go with them (masc.). For example, the Quran states: «فَاَتۡبَعُوۡہُمۡ مُّشۡرِقِیۡنَ فَلَمَّا تَرَآءَ الۡجَمۡعٰنِ قَالَ اَصۡحٰبُ مُوۡسٰۤی اِنَّا لَمُدۡرَکُوۡنَ» (26:60-61). Translation: So they pursued them at sunrise. And when the two parties saw each other, the companions of Musa (AS) said, 'Indeed, we will be overtaken.'"
    }
  ],
  "179": [
    {
      "id": 862,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Behind / After",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«بَعْدُ» (In terms of time) A past time, a previous era (189 verses: 2:27, 2:51, 2:52, 2:56, 2:64, 2:74, 2:75, 2:87, 2:92, 2:109, 2:120, 2:133, 2:145, 2:159, 2:164, 2:178, 2:181, 2:209, 2:211, 2:213, 2:230, 2:246, 2:253, 2:259, 3:8, 3:19, 3:61, 3:65, 3:80, 3:82, 3:86, 3:89, 3:90, 3:94, 3:100, 3:105, 3:106, 3:152, 3:154, 3:160, 3:172, 4:11, 4:12, 4:24, 4:115, 4:153, 4:163, 4:165, 5:12, 5:32, 5:39, 5:41, 5:43, 5:94, 5:106, 5:108, 5:115, 6:6, 6:54, 6:68, 6:71, 6:133, 7:56, 7:69, 7:74, 7:85, 7:89, 7:100, 7:103, 7:129, 7:148, 7:150, 7:153, 7:169, 7:173, 7:185, 8:6, 8:75, 9:12, 9:27, 9:28, 9:66, 9:74, 9:113, 9:115, 9:117, 10:3, 10:14, 10:21, 10:32, 10:74, 10:75, 11:7, 11:10, 12:9, 12:35, 12:45, 12:48, 12:49, 12:100, 13:25, 13:37, 14:9, 14:14, 16:41, 16:65, 16:70, 16:91, 16:92, 16:94, 16:106, 16:110, 16:119, 17:17, 17:104, 18:76, 19:59, 20:85, 21:11, 21:57, 21:105, 22:5, 23:15, 23:31, 23:42, 23:44, 24:5, 24:33, 24:47, 24:55, 24:58, 25:29, 26:120, 26:227, 27:11, 28:43, 28:58, 28:87, 29:63, 30:3, 30:4, 30:19, 30:24, 30:50, 30:51, 30:54, 31:27, 33:52, 33:53, 34:32, 35:2, 35:9, 35:41, 36:28, 38:35, 38:88, 39:6, 40:5, 40:31, 40:34, 41:50, 42:14, 42:16, 42:28, 42:41, 42:44, 45:5, 45:6, 45:17, 45:23, 46:30, 47:4, 47:25, 47:32, 48:24, 49:11, 53:26, 57:10, 57:17, 59:10, 61:6, 65:1, 65:7, 66:4, 68:13, 77:50, 79:30, 95:7, 98:4)",
      "d": "«بَعْدُ» means behind, afterwards, or thereafter. It is a temporal adverb (majid) and its opposite is «قَبْل» meaning before. For example, the Quran states: «ثُمَّ بَعَثۡنٰکُمۡ مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِ مَوۡتِکُمۡ لَعَلَّکُمۡ تَشۡکُرُوۡنَ» (2:56). Translation: Then We revived you after your death, so that you might be grateful."
    },
    {
      "id": 863,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Behind/After",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«اَدْبَار» refers to something happening immediately after the completion of an action, or right after it. Its opposite is «قُبْل». (37 verses: 3:11-4:47-5:21-8:15-8:16-8:50-9:25-12:25-12:27-12:28-15:65-17:46-21:57-27:10-27:80-28:31-30:52-33:15-37:90-40:33-47:25-47:27-48:22-50:40-52:49-54:45-59:12-70:17-74:23-74:33-79:22)",
      "d": "«دُبْر» refers to the rear or back part of anything, and its opposite is «قُبل». It is used as a temporal adverb meaning 'after' or 'subsequently', i.e., immediately after the completion of an action. For example, «دُبْرُ الصَّلوٰۃ» means 'after the prayer', and its plural is «اَدْبَار».\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«وَ مِنَ الَّیۡلِ فَسَبِّحۡہُ  وَاَدۡبَارَ السُّجُوۡدِ» ( 50/40 )\nTranslation: And glorify Him during the night and after the prostrations (i.e., after the prayers).\nAnd «اِدْبَار» can also mean turning one's back and disappearing.\nThus, at another place, the Almighty declares:\n«وَ مِنَ الَّیۡلِ فَسَبِّحۡہُ وَ اِدۡبَارَ النُّجُوۡمِ» ( 52/49 )\nTranslation: And glorify Him during part of the night and at the setting of the stars.\nIn this verse, the eloquence is that the meaning of «اِدْبَار» also brings in the meaning of «اَدْبَار»."
    },
    {
      "id": 865,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Behind/Ahead",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«وَرَآء» means ahead or behind, this side or that side, here or there, this side or that side (it is a word of opposites). (24 verses: 2:91-2:101-3:187-4:24-4:102-6:94-11:71-11:92-14:16-14:17-18:79-19:5-23:7-23:100-33:53-42:51-45:10-49:4-57:13-59:14-70:31-76:27-84:10-85:20)",
      "d": "«وَرَآء» means ahead or behind (it is a word of opposites). It is masculine and feminine (as per 'Manjad') and is used as both a temporal and spatial adverb. Now consider its examples:\n(1) Spatial adverb meaning 'behind':\nThe Almighty declares:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ یُنَادُوۡنَکَ مِنۡ وَّرَآءِ الۡحُجُرٰتِ» ( 49/4 )\nTranslation: Indeed, those who call you from behind the partitions (from outside).\n(2) Temporal adverb meaning 'after':\nThe Almighty declares:\n«فَبَشَّرۡنٰہَا بِاِسۡحٰقَ ۙ وَ مِنۡ وَّرَآءِ اِسۡحٰقَ یَعۡقُوۡبَ» ( 11/71 )\nTranslation: So We gave her glad tidings of Isaac and, after Isaac, of Jacob.\n(3) Spatial adverb meaning 'ahead':\nThe Almighty declares:\n«وَ کَانَ  وَرَآءَہُمۡ مَّلِکٌ یَّاۡخُذُ کُلَّ  سَفِیۡنَۃٍ غَصۡبًا» ( 18/79 )\nTranslation: And there was a king before them (ahead of them) who seized every ship by force.\nThen this word is also used to mean 'besides' or 'other than'.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«فَمَنِ ابۡتَغٰی وَرَآءَ ذٰلِکَ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمُ الۡعٰدُوۡنَ» ( 23/7 )\nTranslation: And whoever seeks beyond that, they are the transgressors.\nAnd «وَرَآءَ الْاِنْسَان» means 'grandson'. As is also clear from example 2 above. So, «وَرَآء» means 'beyond', 'this side or that side', 'here or there'. And it is both temporal and spatial. As is clear from the following verse:\nFor instance, the Almighty declares:\n«فَاِذَا سَجَدُوۡا فَلۡیَکُوۡنُوۡا مِنۡ وَّرَآئِکُمۡ ۪ وَ لۡتَاۡتِ طَآئِفَۃٌ اُخۡرٰی لَمۡ یُصَلُّوۡا فَلۡیُصَلُّوۡا مَعَکَ» ( 4/102 )\nTranslation: When you have prostrated, let them (the other group) be behind you, and let another group who have not yet prayed come and pray with you."
    },
    {
      "id": 866,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Come Behind",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«خَلَفَ» is used in all these meanings: those who come after, later people, successors, past, offspring of the elders, heir, offspring, deputy, successor. (14 verses: 6:133-7:69-7:74-7:129-7:142-7:150-7:169-11:57-19:59-24:55-27:62-43:60-46:21-57:7)",
      "d": "«خَلَفَ» is the opposite of «سَلَفَ» and comes as a temporal adverb. It means 'to come after', 'to be a deputy', 'to be a successor' (as per 'Manjad'). And generally, «خَلْفٌ» refers to unworthy and incompetent successors.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«فَخَلَفَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہِمۡ خَلۡفٌ اَضَاعُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَاتَّبَعُوا الشَّہَوٰتِ فَسَوۡفَ یَلۡقَوۡنَ غَیًّا» ( 19/59 )\nTranslation: Then, after them succeeded [other] generations who neglected prayer and pursued desires. So they will soon face perdition.\nAnd «خِلْفَۃً» means two things coming one after the other, one after the other, one following the other continuously. (as per 'Manjad')\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«وَہُوَ الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ الَّیۡلَ وَ النَّہَارَ خِلۡفَۃً» ( 25/62 )\nTranslation: And it is He who made the night and day in succession (one following the other)."
    },
    {
      "id": 869,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Leave Behind",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«اَخَّرَ» means to leave someone behind or push back in terms of time. (6 verses: 3:153-7:38-7:39-11:8-75:13-82:5)",
      "d": "«تَاخِیْرًا» is the opposite of «تَقْدِیم». It is used as a temporal adverb, meaning to leave behind or push back. Then this word is also used to postpone an action, and if it relates to someone else, it is used in the meaning of granting respite.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«یُنَبَّؤُا الۡاِنۡسَانُ یَوۡمَئِذٍۭ بِمَا قَدَّمَ وَاَخَّرَ» ( 75/13 )\nTranslation: On that Day, man will be informed of what he sent ahead and what he left behind."
    },
    {
      "id": 870,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Leave Behind",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«خَلَّفَ» means to leave someone behind (spatial adverb), to be behind someone, to remain behind, to catch someone from behind. (6 verses: 9:81-9:118-9:120-48:11-48:15-48:16-)",
      "d": "«خَلَّفَ» means to leave behind. It is used when both temporal and spatial contexts apply.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«وَّ عَلَی الثَّلٰثَۃِ الَّذِیۡنَ خُلِّفُوۡا» ( 9/118 )\nTranslation:\n1 - And upon the three who were left behind (i.e., their matter was deferred). (Jalandhari)\n2 - And upon those persons who were kept behind (i.e., did not join the expedition). (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 871,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Remain Behind",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«تَاَخَرَّ» means to remain behind by one's own will and choice. (10 verses: 2:203-7:34-10:49-15:5-15:24-16:61-23:43-34:30-48:2-74:37)",
      "d": "«تَاَخَرَّ» means to remain behind by one's own will and choice.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«فَمَنْ تَعَجَّلَ فِي یَوْمَیۡنِ فَلَا إِثْمَ عَلَیۡهِ وَمَنْ تَأَخَّرَ فَلَا إِثْمَ عَلَیۡهِ» ( 2/203 )\nTranslation: So whoever hastens [his departure] by two days, there is no sin upon him; and whoever delays [his departure], there is no sin upon him."
    },
    {
      "id": 872,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Remain Behind",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«خَالَفَ» means to remain behind due to deficiency and shortcoming. (3 verses: 9:83-9:87-9:93)",
      "d": "«خَالَفَ» means to remain behind due to deficiency and shortcoming (as per 'Mufradat'). Its other meaning is 'to oppose'. And «خَالِفْ» refers to one who remains behind due to his laziness or incompetence (as per 'Mufradat'). And «خَالِف» also means 'foolish' and one who sits back after someone has left (as per 'Manjad').\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّکُمۡ رَضِیۡتُمۡ بِالۡقُعُوۡدِ اَوَّلَ مَرَّۃٍ  فَاقۡعُدُوۡا مَعَ الۡخٰلِفِیۡنَ» ( 9/83 )\nTranslation: You were satisfied with sitting back the first time, so sit [now] with those who remain behind.\nAnd the feminine form of «خَالِفْ» is «خَالِفَۃٌ», and generally it refers to a housewife who stays at home during jihad. And its plural is «خَوَالِف» (as per 'Mufradat'). For instance, the Quran states:\n«رَضُوۡا بِاَنۡ یَّکُوۡنُوۡا مَعَ الۡخَوَالِفِ» ( 9/87 )\nTranslation: They are pleased to be with those [women] who remain behind (at home)."
    },
    {
      "id": 873,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Remain Behind",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«غَبَرَ» means to remain behind from one's companions due to failure or shortcoming. (7 verses: 7:83-15:60-26:171-27:57-29:32-29:33-37:135)",
      "d": "«غَبَرَ» means to remain behind from one's companions due to failure or shortcoming. (as per 'Mufradat')\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«فَاَنۡجَیۡنٰہُ وَ اَہۡلَہٗۤ  اِلَّا امۡرَاَتَہٗ  ۫ ۖکَانَتۡ مِنَ الۡغٰبِرِیۡنَ» ( 7/83 )\nTranslation: And We saved him and his family, except his wife; she was of those who remained behind."
    },
    {
      "id": 874,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Postpone/Put Back",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«اَخَّرَ» means to postpone or put back from an appointed time, or to grant respite. (10 verses: 4:77-11:104-14:10-14:42-14:44-16:61-17:62-35:45-63:11-71:4)",
      "d": "«اَخَّرَ» means to postpone from an appointed time or to grant respite (as per 'Manjad' and 'Mufradat'). This word is used generally.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«وَلَنۡ یُّؤَخِّرَ اللّٰہُ  نَفۡسًا اِذَا جَآءَ اَجَلُہَا» ( 63/11 )\nTranslation: And Allah will not delay a soul when its appointed time has come."
    },
    {
      "id": 875,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Postpone/Put Back",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«اَرْجٰی» means a delay in which there is a possibility of attaining joy and happiness; to delay something while hoping for it. (1 verse: 33:51)",
      "d": "«رَجَاء» means an expectation in which there is a possibility of attaining joy (as per 'Mufradat'). Its opposite is «خَوْف». And «رَجَاء» and «خَوْف» are concomitant (i.e., both are necessary for each other). When there is hope for attaining a beloved thing, there will also be anxiety about its loss. Similarly, in the opposite situation, anxiety about loss is accompanied by hope for attainment. And «اَرْجٰی» means to postpone something in which there is a possibility of attaining joy (happiness).\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«تُرۡجِیۡ مَنۡ تَشَآءُ مِنۡہُنَّ وَ تُـئۡوِیۡۤ  اِلَیۡکَ مَنۡ تَشَآءُ» ( 33/51 )\nTranslation: You may defer whom you will of them, and you may receive whom you will of them."
    },
    {
      "id": 876,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to delay or postpone",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«اَرْجَہَ» refers to a delay made with caution so that the matter can be corrected (2 verses: 7:111-26:36)",
      "d": "The meaning of «رَجَہَ» is to hold something with the teeth, and «اَرْجَہَ الْاَمْر» means to postpone a matter (minjad). That is, in «اَرْجَہَ», the cause of delay is caution and strength, so that the expected results from that matter can be achieved.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَرۡجِہۡ  وَاَخَاہُ وَاَرۡسِلۡ فِی الۡمَدَآئِنِ حٰشِرِیۡنَ» ( 7/111 )\nTranslation: They said, 'Give him and his brother respite and send heralds to the cities.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 877,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to delay or postpone",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«نَسَأَ» means to be hasty in one matter and to delay in another (1 verse: 9:37)",
      "d": "«نَسَأَ» means to postpone something. It is an idiom. «نَسَاَکَ اللہُ فِیْٓ اَجَلِکَ» means 'May Allah prolong your life' (muf). And «نَسِیْءُ» also refers to delay and credit. That is, in buying and selling and transactions, paying the money later. And the word «نَسِیْءُ» has been used by the Noble Quran in the meanings of precedence and postponement, and in reality, that is its meaning. That is, to be hasty in one matter and to delay in another (m. q.). The disbelievers of Mecca used to do this: they would change the order of the months of Hajj (bring forward and push back) according to the season so that the crops would ripen and the offerings for the servants of the Ka'bah would be easier to fulfill. Allah Almighty has declared this kind of alteration as disbelief.\nFor example: The command of Allah Almighty is:\n«اِنَّمَا النَّسِیۡٓءُ زِیَادَۃٌ فِی الۡکُفۡرِ  یُضَلُّ بِہِ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا یُحِلُّوۡنَہٗ عَامًا وَّ یُحَرِّمُوۡنَہٗ عَامًا» ( 9/37 )\nTranslation: To remove a sacred month and then insert it elsewhere is only an addition to disbelief, whereby those who disbelieve are led astray. They make it lawful one year and forbidden another year."
    },
    {
      "id": 878,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To follow. To be followed.",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«اَتْبَعَ» To go behind, to accompany, to follow, to be a follower, to come after someone, to be subordinate. It is used in all these meanings (150 verses: 2:38-2:102-2:120-2:143-2:145-2:166-2:167-2:168-2:170-2:208-2:262-2:263-3:7-3:20-3:31-3:53-3:55-3:68-3:73-3:95-3:162-3:167-3:174-4:27-4:83-4:115-4:125-4:135-5:16-5:48-5:49-5:77-6:50-6:56-6:106-6:116-6:142-6:148-6:150-6:153-6:155-7:3-7:18-7:90-7:142-7:157-7:158-7:175-7:176-7:193-7:203-8:64-9:42-9:100-9:117-10:15-10:35-10:36-10:66-10:89-10:90-10:109-11:27-11:59-11:60-11:97-11:99-11:116-12:38-12:108-13:37-14:21-14:36-14:44-15:18-15:42-15:65-16:123-17:47-17:63-18:28-18:66-18:70-18:85-18:89-18:92-19:43-19:59-20:16-20:47-20:78-20:90-20:93-20:108-20:123-20:134-22:3-23:44-23:71-24:21-25:8-26:40-26:52-26:60-26:111-26:215-26:224-28:35-28:42-28:47-28:49-28:50-28:57-29:12-30:29-31:15-31:21-33:2-34:20-36:11-36:20-36:21-37:10-38:26-38:85-39:18-39:55-40:7-40:38-40:47-42:15-43:61-44:23-45:18-46:9-47:3-47:14-47:16-47:28-48:15-52:21-53:23-53:28-54:3-54:24-57:27-71:21-75:18-77:17-79:7)",
      "d": "«اَتْبَعَ» is used both as a intransitive (لازم) and transitive (متعدی) verb. When intransitive, its meaning is to go behind or to pursue.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَتۡبَعُوۡہُمۡ مُّشۡرِقِیۡنَ» (26/60)\nTranslation: So the courtiers of Pharaoh pursued them at sunrise.\nAnd when transitive, its meaning is to make someone follow.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اَتۡبَعۡنٰہُمۡ فِیۡ ہٰذِہِ الدُّنۡیَا لَعۡنَۃً» (28/42)\nTranslation: And We followed them in this world with a curse.\nNote:\nIntransitive verb (فعل لازم): A verb that completes the sentence only with its subject.\nTransitive verb (فعل متعدی): A verb that requires an object in addition to its subject to complete the sentence."
    },
    {
      "id": 880,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to follow or to be followed",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«اَغْرٰی» means to incite or urge something, causing others to follow behind it (2 verses: 5:14-33:60)",
      "d": "The meaning of «أَغْرَيَ» is to incite or urge a dog or a hunting animal and make it follow the prey (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَغۡرَیۡنَا بَیۡنَہُمُ الۡعَدَاوَۃَ وَ الۡبَغۡضَآءَ» ( 5/14 )\nTranslation: Then We cast enmity and hatred between them. (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 882,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "other derivatives of 'following'",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "«خَنَّسَ» means to take one step back while walking straight, or to retreat while watching, or to retreat stealthily and secretly (2 verses: 81:15-114:4)",
      "d": "«خَنَّسَ ، خَنْس» means to retreat and shrink (minjad), and also means to take one step back while walking straight (muf), to retreat while watching, or to retreat stealthily and secretly. (m. l) And «خَانِسْ» means one who retreats. Its plural is «خنَّس».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَاۤ اُقۡسِمُ  بِالۡخُنَّسِ الۡجَوَارِ الۡکُنَّسِ» ( 81/15،16 )\nTranslation: So I swear by the stars that retreat, that move about, and that vanish.\nAnd «خَنَّاس» has more emphasis than «خَانِسْ». That is, one who has made retreating his habit repeatedly.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«مِنۡ شَرِّ الۡوَسۡوَاسِ ۙ الۡخَنَّاسِ» ( 114/4 )\nTranslation: (I seek refuge in Allah) from the evil of the whisperer who withdraws (to deceive)."
    }
  ],
  "180": [
    {
      "id": 884,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to create",
      "hw": "پیدا",
      "s": "«بَدَعَ» means to make or create for the first time without a model or imitation (3 verses: 2:117-6:101-46:9)",
      "d": "«بَدَعَ» means to make or create for the first time without a model or imitation. (muf) And 'badee' means one who creates something unique (minjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«بَدِیۡعُ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ» ( 2/117 )\nTranslation: He is the Originator of the heavens and the earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 885,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to create",
      "hw": "پیدا",
      "s": "«فَطَرَ» means to fashion beautifully by carving and shaping (14 verses: 6:14-6:79-11:51-12:101-14:10-17:51-20:72-21:56-30:30-35:1-36:22-39:46-42:11-43:27-67-3)",
      "d": "The meaning of «فَطَرَ» is to create beautifully by carving and shaping.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فِطۡرَتَ اللّٰہِ الَّتِیۡ فَطَرَ  النَّاسَ عَلَیۡہَا» ( 30/30 )\nTranslation: So direct your face toward the religion, inclining to truth. [It is] the fitrah of Allah upon which He has created [all] people.\nAt another place, the command of Allah Almighty is:\n«اَلۡحَمۡدُ لِلّٰہِ فَاطِرِ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ» ( 35/1 )\nTranslation: All praise is [due] to Allah, Originator of the heavens and the earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 886,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to create",
      "hw": "پیدا",
      "s": "«خَلَقَ» means to make a thing whose material already exists (210 verses: 2:21-2:29-2:164-2:228-3:47-3:49-3:59-3:190-3:191-4:1-4:28-4:119-5:17-5:18-5:110-6:1-6:2-6:73-6:94-6:100-6:101-6:102-7:11-7:12-7:54-7:69-7:181-7:185-7:189-7:191-9:36-10:3-10:4-10:5-10:6-10:34-11:7-11:119-13:5-13:16-14:19-14:32-15:26-15:27-15:28-15:33-15:85-16:3-16:4-16:5-16:8-16:17-16:20-16:48-16:70-16:81-17:49-17:51-17:61-17:70-17:98-17:99-18:37-18:48-18:51-19:9-19:67-20:4-20:50-20:55-21:16-21:33-21:37-21:104-22:5-22:73-23:12-23:14-23:17-23:91-23:115-24:45-25:2-25:3-25:49-25:54-25:59-26:78-26:166-26:184-27:60-27:64-28:68-29:17-29:19-29:20-29:44-29:61-30:8-30:11-30:20-30:21-30:22-30:27-30:30-30:40-30:54-31:10-31:11-31:25-31:28-32:4-32:7-32:10-34:7-35:1-35:3-35:11-35:16-35:40-36:36-36:42-36:68-36:71-36:77-36:78-36:79-36:81-37:11-37:96-37:125-37:150-38:27-38:71-38:75-38:76-39:4-39:5-39:6-39:38-39:62-40:57-40:62-40:67-41:9-41:15-41:21-41:37-42:29-42:49-43:9-43:12-43:16-43:19-43:87-44:38-44:39-45:4-45:22-46:3-46:4-46:33-49:13-50:15-50:16-50:38-51:49-51:56-52:35-52:36-53:45-54:49-55:3-55:14-55:15-56:57-56:59-57:4-59:24-64:2-64:3-65:12-67:2-67:3-67:14-70:19-70:39-71:14-71:15-74:11-75:38-76:2-76:28-77:20-78:8-79:27-80:18-80:19-82:7-86:5-86:6-87:2-88:17-89:8-90:4-92:3-95:4-96:1-96:2-113:2)",
      "d": "The word «خَلَقَ» is used in many meanings.\nFor example:\n(1) To conceive or design something for making (muf). That is, creation can also be a mental act, and its attribution can also be to other than Allah.\n(2) Sometimes it also comes in the meaning of «خَلَقَ ، اِبْدَاع» (innovation). As in the Noble Quran «خَلَقَ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَالْاَرْضِ» appears, similarly «بَدِیْعُ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَالْاَرْضِ» also appears. In this case, its attribution cannot be to other than Allah.\n(3) And the general meaning of «خَلَقَ» is that one thing is made from another. If the primary material exists, then another thing is created from it.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«خَلَقَکُمۡ مِّنۡ نَّفۡسٍ وَّاحِدَۃٍ وَّ خَلَقَ مِنۡہَا زَوۡجَہَا وَ بَثَّ مِنۡہُمَا رِجَالًا کَثِیۡرًا وَّ نِسَآءً» ( 4/1 )\nTranslation: He created you from one soul and created from it its mate and dispersed from both of them many men and women.\nIn this case, its attribution can also be to other than Allah. As when Allah Almighty says to Prophet Jesus (peace be upon him):\n«وَاِذۡ تَخۡلُقُ مِنَ الطِّیۡنِ کَہَیۡئَۃِ الطَّیۡرِ» ( 5/110 )\nTranslation: And when you design from clay [a figure] like that of a bird. (Uthmani)\nFurthermore, at another place, the command of Allah Almighty is:\n«فَتَبٰرَکَ اللّٰہُ  اَحۡسَنُ  الۡخٰلِقِیۡنَ» ( 23/14 )\nTranslation:\n1 - So blessed is Allah, the best of creators. (Jalandhari)\n2 - The best creator. (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 887,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to create",
      "hw": "پیدا",
      "s": "«اَنْشَاَ» means to create and to nurture/grow (23 verses: 6:6-6:98-6:133-6:141-11:61-21:11-23:14-23:19-23:31-23:42-23:78-28:45-29:20-36:79-43:18-53:32-53:47-55:24-56:35-56:61-56:62-56:72-67:23)",
      "d": "«اَنْشَاَ» basically has two meanings: (1) to create something, and (2) then to nurture and grow it (m. l. minjad). And this word is used in both these meanings separately and also in a combined sense.\n(1) Example of the meaning of creation:\nThe command of Allah Almighty is:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَنۡشَاَکُمۡ مِّنۡ نَّفۡسٍ وَّاحِدَۃٍ» ( 6/98 )\nTranslation: And He is the One Who produced you from a single soul.\n(2) Example of the meaning of nurturing:\nThe command of Allah Almighty is:\n«اَوَ مَنۡ یُّنَشَّؤُا فِی الۡحِلۡیَۃِ» ( 43/18 )\nTranslation: Or is He [to be compared to one] who is brought up in adornments? (i.e., idols)\n(3) Example of the combined act of creation and growth:\nThe command of Allah Almighty is:\n«ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَنۡشَاۡتُمۡ شَجَرَتَہَاۤ  اَمۡ نَحۡنُ الۡمُنۡشِئُوۡنَ» ( 56/72 )\nTranslation: Have you caused to grow it, or are We the grower?"
    }
  ],
  "181": [
    {
      "id": 889,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to present",
      "hw": "پیش",
      "s": "«عَرَضَ» means to present, to bring forward; it is used for non-rational things, i.e., things that do not possess reason (11 verses: 2:31-11:18-18:48-18:100-33:72-38:31-40:46-42:45-46:20-46:34-69:18)",
      "d": "«عَرَضَ» means to present, to bring forward (minjad). And it generally comes for non-rational beings (i.e., things that do not possess reason). Such as petitions, presentations, reports, messages, or other objects, and generally used in a spiritual sense. (muf)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ عَلَّمَ اٰدَمَ الۡاَسۡمَآءَ کُلَّہَا ثُمَّ عَرَضَہُمۡ عَلَی الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ» ( 2/31 )\nTranslation: And He taught Adam the names - all of them. Then He showed them to the angels and said, 'Inform Me of the names of these, if you are truthful.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 890,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Present",
      "hw": "پیش",
      "s": "«أَحْضَرَ» means to present or bring someone forward, to make present, and the existence and observation of that thing are necessary.",
      "d": "«حَضَر» means to come forward, to be present. And «أَحْضَرَ» means to present or bring someone forward, to make present, and in this, the existence and observation of that thing are necessary (m. l). And this generally comes for those of sound intellect (i.e., those who possess intellect). And it is used in a negative sense, such as presenting a criminal, and the word 'ihdar' indicates anger and wrath (f. l 77).\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«فَوَ رَبِّکَ لَنَحۡشُرَنَّہُمۡ وَ الشَّیٰطِیۡنَ ثُمَّ لَنُحۡضِرَنَّہُمۡ حَوۡلَ جَہَنَّمَ جِثِیًّا» (19/68)\nTranslation: By your Lord! We will surely gather them and the devils as well, then We will bring them all around Hell, humbled."
    }
  ],
  "182": [
    {
      "id": 891,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Forehead (Temple)",
      "hw": "پیشانی",
      "s": "«جَبِین» refers to one side of the forehead, right or left.",
      "d": "«جَبِین» means the edge of the forehead (manjad), and the two sides of the forehead (right and left) are called «اَجْبِیَان».\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ اَسۡلَمَا و تَلَّہٗ لِلۡجَبِیۡنِ» (37/103)\nTranslation: When both submitted, the father laid the son prostrate on his forehead."
    },
    {
      "id": 892,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Forehead (Temple)",
      "hw": "پیشانی",
      "s": "«جَبِہَ» means the middle part of the forehead.",
      "d": "«جَبِہَ» means the breadth and beauty of the forehead (manjad). «جَبِہَ» actually refers to the front and middle part of the forehead that touches the ground during prostration. And its plural is «جِبَاہ».\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«فَتُکۡوٰی بِہَا جِبَاہُہُمۡ وَ جُنُوۡبُہُمۡ وَ ظُہُوۡرُہُمۡ» (9/35)\nTranslation: Then their foreheads, their sides, and their backs will be branded with it."
    },
    {
      "id": 893,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Forehead (Temple)",
      "hw": "پیشانی",
      "s": "«نَاصِیَۃ» means the forehead or the hair of the forehead when they are long (manjad).",
      "d": "«نَاصِیَۃ» means the forehead or the hair of the forehead when they are long (manjad). Its application is to the hair on the forehead as well as the forehead itself. Its plural is «نَوَاصِی».\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«یُعۡرَفُ الۡمُجۡرِمُوۡنَ بِسِیۡمٰہُمۡ فَیُؤۡخَذُ بِالنَّوَاصِیۡ وَ الۡاَقۡدَامِ» (55/41)\nTranslation: The criminals will be recognized by their marks, then they will be seized by the forelocks and the feet."
    }
  ],
  "183": [
    {
      "id": 896,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Adversaries of the Prophets",
      "hw": "پیغمبر",
      "s": "«سَاحِر» means a sorcerer, one who acquires satanic sciences in opposition to the sciences of prophethood.",
      "d": "«سَاحِر» means a sorcerer, one who acquires satanic sciences in opposition to the sciences of prophethood. The prophets and messengers were often granted miracles by Allah, sometimes on their own, sometimes at the demand of the disbelievers, and sometimes under extreme necessity, so the disbelievers immediately accuse them of being sorcerers.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«اِقۡتَرَبَتِ السَّاعَۃُ وَ انۡشَقَّ الۡقَمَرُ ، وَاِنۡ یَّرَوۡا اٰیَۃً یُّعۡرِضُوۡا وَیَقُوۡلُوۡا سِحۡرٌ مُّسۡتَمِرٌّ» (54/1,2)\nTranslation: The Hour has drawn near, and the moon has split. And if they see a sign, they turn away and say, 'This is continuous magic.'\nHere, after describing the miracle of the moon's splitting, the reality is immediately stated that the disbelievers' habit is to dismiss miracles as magic. Therefore, it is necessary to understand the difference between magic and miracle. The differences are as follows:\n(1) In magic, the essence and reality of things do not change; rather, magic is performed on people's eyes, and they begin to see something as something else. Regarding the snakes that the magicians made from ropes and staffs against Moses (peace be upon him), the divine command says:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ اَلۡقَوۡا سَحَرُوۡۤا اَعۡیُنَ النَّاسِ وَاسۡتَرۡہَبُوۡہُمۡ وَجَآءُوۡ بِسِحۡرٍعَظِیۡمٍ» (7/116)\nTranslation: When the magicians threw their staffs, they deceived the people's eyes and terrified them, and they brought a great magic.\nWhereas in the case of a miracle, the essence and reality of the thing change. For example, when Moses (peace be upon him) threw his staff, it became a snake, but upon picking it up, it returned to its original state.\n(2) In the case of a miracle, the newly created thing either remains in that state or returns to its original state. For example, the spring of Zamzam or the bursting of twelve springs, or returning to the original state like the splitting of the moon, the staff of Moses, or the shining hand. A miracle cannot be destroyed or countered, whereas magic can be destroyed or countered. For example, the snakes made by the magicians were swallowed by Moses' staff (snake).\n(The word 'miracle' does not appear in the Quran. Instead, words like «اٰیَۃ ، اٰیَۃٌ بَیِّنَۃ ، مُبْصِرَۃ» and «بُرْھَان» are used. From the Quran's style, context, and wording, it is immediately known whether the word is used in its common meaning or in the meaning of miracle. And sometimes none of these words appear; the miracle is evident only from the style of expression. For example, in «سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَسۡرٰی», the word «سُبْحَان» is an exclamation of wonder, which is a clear proof that this was a physical, not spiritual, journey and a miracle.)\n(3) Magic is an art acquired through practice and effort, whereas a miracle is a divine gift that is not acquired through practice and effort. This is why the magicians who came against Moses, who were at the pinnacle of the art of magic, realized that what Moses presented was above the art of magic. Therefore, they immediately embraced faith.\n(4) The character and conduct of magicians is detestable, and people fear their evil. Whereas the lives of prophets are extremely pure, and in this regard, they are honored and beloved among people."
    },
    {
      "id": 898,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Adversaries of the Prophets",
      "hw": "پیغمبر",
      "s": "«مَجْنُوْنٌ» means a person whose intellect is veiled and who speaks nonsensically.",
      "d": "«مَجْنُوْنٌ» means a person whose intellect is veiled and who speaks nonsensically. The Arabs used to call a madman 'majnun' because, according to their belief, if a jinn enters a human, it deprives him of his senses and he starts speaking irrationally. Since the teachings of the prophets were against the society's intellect and customs, the disbelievers also addressed the prophets as 'majnun'.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«کَذٰلِکَ مَاۤ اَتَی الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ  مِّنۡ رَّسُوۡلٍ اِلَّا قَالُوۡا سَاحِرٌ اَوۡمَجۡنُوۡنٌ» (51/52)\nTranslation: Similarly, there never came to those before them any messenger but they said, 'A sorcerer or a madman.'\nThe basic difference between a prophet and a madman is that the prophet's call, though contrary to the society's intellect and customs, he always remains firm on himself, demonstrates it through action, and establishes the seal of verification on his words through his pure character and conduct. Whereas a madman is devoid of these three things."
    }
  ],
  "184": [
    {
      "id": 899,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Drink",
      "hw": "پینا",
      "s": "«شَرِبَ» means to drink water or any other drinkable thing.",
      "d": "«شَرِبَ» means to drink water or any other drinkable thing. (Maf) It is general for drinking. 'Sharab' means any drinkable thing. «شِرْب . شِرْبَۃ» means a drink or a single drink. And «مَشْرَب» means a place to drink. Ghat (manjad)\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«فَمَنۡ شَرِبَ مِنۡہُ فَلَیۡسَ مِنِّیۡ» (2/249)\nTranslation: So whoever drinks from it will not be from me."
    },
    {
      "id": 900,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Drink",
      "hw": "پینا",
      "s": "«جَرَّعَ» means to drink in gulps.",
      "d": "«جَرَّعَ» means to drink in gulps (manjad). And «جُرْعَۃ» means a gulp, and «اِجْتَرَعَ» means to drink in one go (manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«یَّتَجَرَّعُہٗ  وَلَا یَکَادُ یُسِیۡغُہٗ» (14/17)\nTranslation: He will gulp it down and will hardly swallow it."
    },
    {
      "id": 901,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Drink",
      "hw": "پینا",
      "s": "«سَاغ» means to drink easily and smoothly due to the pleasant taste of the beverage.",
      "d": "«سَاغ» means for a drink to go down the throat easily (muf). To drink smoothly and easily. And «سَاغِیَۃ» means a pleasant drink or beverage (sarrah). Its opposite is «غَصَّ» which means something that does not go down easily and gets stuck.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«نُسۡقِیۡکُمۡ  مِّمَّا فِیۡ بُطُوۡنِہٖ مِنۡۢ  بَیۡنِ  فَرۡثٍ وَّ دَمٍ لَّبَنًا خَالِصًا سَآئِغًا لِّلشّٰرِبِیۡنَ» (16/66)\nTranslation: We give you to drink from what is in their bellies, between feces and blood, pure milk, palatable for the drinkers."
    }
  ],
  "185": [
    {
      "id": 902,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Star (Types)",
      "hw": "تارا",
      "s": "«نَجْم» means to appear, to become visible, the rising of stars.",
      "d": "«نَجْم» basically comes in two meanings: (1) Plants without stems, i.e., herbs and shrubs. (2) Planets that rise and set. And its plural is 'nujoom'. And 'najm' is used as a generic noun.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«وَ بِالنَّجۡمِ  ہُمۡ  یَہۡتَدُوۡنَ» (16/16)\nTranslation: And by the stars, they are guided."
    },
    {
      "id": 903,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Star (Types)",
      "hw": "تارا",
      "s": "«کَوَاکِب» refers to every large star, whether it is a star or a planet (5 verses: 6:76, 12:4, 24:35, 37:6, 82:2)",
      "d": "«کَوْکِبَۃٌ» is the name for a large star (Munjid) and «کَوْکَب» is used for every large star, whether a star or a planet (F. L). Its plural is «کَوَاکِب». «کَوْکَبَ الْجَدِیْد» means the shining, glittering of iron (Munjid). Essentially, «کَوکَب» refers to any star that is both large and luminous.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّا زَیَّنَّا السَّمَآءَ  الدُّنۡیَا بِزِیۡنَۃِۣ الۡکَوَاکِبِ» (37/6)\nTranslation: Indeed, We have adorned the nearest heaven with an adornment of stars.\nThe Quran mentions the following types of stars:\n(1) «شِعْرٰی»: The name of a bright star that rises in the intense heat season (Maf). In pre-Islamic times, it was worshipped. For more details, see 'Ma'boodan-e-Batil' (1/5). Allah Almighty told the polytheists:\n«وَاَنَّہٗ ہُوَ رَبُّ الشِّعۡرٰی» (53/49)\nTranslation: And that He is the Lord of Shi'ra (the bright star).\n(2) «خُنَّس ، خَنَسَ»: Meaning to move backward or shrink (Munjid). To take one step back while moving forward (Maf). To retreat while keeping an eye out or stealthily (M. L). «خَانِسْ» means the one that retreats, and «خُنَّس» is its plural. Thus, «خُنَّس» refers to planets that, while moving forward, sometimes reverse their course.\nAccording to some, these are the five planets: Venus, Jupiter, Saturn, Mars, and Mercury (Munjid). Hence, they are also called «خمسہ متحیرہ» (the five wonders).\n(3) «جَوَار ، جَار ، جَوْرًا»: Meaning to deviate from the path (Munjid). «جَوَار» refers to planets that move in a straight course but occasionally change direction slightly.\n(4) «کُنَّس ، کَنَّسَ»: Meaning to hide, to disappear (M. L). «كِنَاسُ» refers to the refuge of every deer, and «کَانَس» refers to every deer that enters its refuge. The plural of «کَانَس» is «کُنَّس». That is, those planets that, while moving, suddenly disappear.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَاۤ اُقۡسِمُ  بِالۡخُنَّسِ الۡجَوَارِ الۡکُنَّسِ» (81/15,16)\nTranslation: So, I swear by the retreating stars, the moving planets, and the disappearing ones."
    }
  ],
  "186": [
    {
      "id": 904,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Darkness Covering",
      "hw": "تاریکی",
      "s": "«عَسْعَسَ» means the evening twilight/darkness that covers immediately after sunset (1 verse: 81:17)",
      "d": "«عَسْعَسَ» means the dusk, the light darkness of the evening. The darkness that covers right after sunset. Similarly, the light darkness before sunrise (Maf).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ الَّیۡلِ اِذَا عَسۡعَسَ وَالصُّبۡحِ اِذَا تَنَفَّسَ» (81/17)\nTranslation: And by the night when it covers, and by the morning when it appears."
    },
    {
      "id": 905,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Darkness Covering",
      "hw": "تاریکی",
      "s": "«غَسَقَ» the initial part of the night (2 verses: 17:78, 113:3)",
      "d": "«غَسَقَ» means after the disappearance of the twilight (the reddish glow visible on the horizon at sunrise and sunset). It refers to the darkness of the early night, the first part of the night (F. L 34).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَقِمِ الصَّلٰوۃَ  لِدُلُوۡکِ الشَّمۡسِ اِلٰی غَسَقِ الَّیۡلِ وَ قُرۡاٰنَ الۡفَجۡرِ» (17/78)\nTranslation: Establish prayer from the declining of the sun until the darkness of the night and the Quran of dawn (i.e., the recitation of the Quran in the morning prayer). (Jalandhari)"
    },
    {
      "id": 906,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Darkness Covering",
      "hw": "تاریکی",
      "s": "«اَغْطَشَ» such darkness that objects are not clearly visible (1 verse: 79:29)",
      "d": "«غَطَشَ» means the night to be dark. And «غَطَشُ» means weak or dim sight. Similarly, «غَطَاش» refers to both the darkness of the night and weakness of sight (Munjid). That is, such darkness in which objects appear dim.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اَغۡطَشَ لَیۡلَہَا وَ اَخۡرَجَ ضُحٰہَا» (79/29)\nTranslation: And He made its night dark and brought forth its daylight."
    },
    {
      "id": 907,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Darkness Covering",
      "hw": "تاریکی",
      "s": "«وَقَبَ» such darkness that objects become completely hidden within it (1 verse: 113:3)",
      "d": "«وَقْب» refers to a pit or hollow in a rock, etc. And «وَقَبَ» means to enter a pit and disappear. «وَقَبَ الشَّمْس» means the sunset. And «وَقَبَ الظَّلَام» means such darkness covers that objects become invisible within it (Maf).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَمِنۡ شَرِّ غَاسِقٍ اِذَا وَقَبَ» (113/3)\nTranslation: And from the evil of the darkness when it covers."
    },
    {
      "id": 908,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Darkness Covering",
      "hw": "تاریکی",
      "s": "«سَجٰی» the stillness and darkness of the night (1 verse: 93:2)",
      "d": "«سَجَی الْلَیْل» means the night to be still and silent. And «سَجَی الْمَیِّتَ» means to cover a corpse with a shroud and hide it. «سَجَّ مَعَائِبِ اَخِیْکَ» means to hide your brother's faults (Munjid). Thus, the concept of both covering and stillness is present in this word. That is, so much of the night has passed that everyone is asleep and the darkness has fully settled.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالضُّحٰی وَ الَّیۡلِ اِذَا سَجٰی» (93:1,2)\nTranslation: By the day and its brightness, and by the night when it covers."
    }
  ],
  "187": [
    {
      "id": 910,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Fresh",
      "hw": "تازہ",
      "s": "«طَرِیّ» means fresh and tender; generally used for meat (2 verses: 16:14, 35:12)",
      "d": "«طَرِیّ» means fresh and tender. Its usage is generally for meat (F. L 54). «طَرَاوَتٌ» means freshness and tenderness.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مِنۡ کُلٍّ تَاۡکُلُوۡنَ لَحۡمًا طَرِیًّا وَّ تَسۡتَخۡرِجُوۡنَ حِلۡیَۃً تَلۡبَسُوۡنَہَا» (35/12)\nTranslation: And from each (sea) you eat tender meat and extract ornaments which you wear."
    },
    {
      "id": 911,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Fresh",
      "hw": "تازہ",
      "s": "«رَطَبَ» means fresh and tender; specifically used for ripe dates (2 verses: 6:59, 19:25)",
      "d": "«رَطَبَ» means fresh and tender; its opposite is «یَابِس» meaning dried. However, in common usage, «رَطَبَ» is specifically used for ripe and fresh dates (Maf).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ ہُزِّیۡۤ  اِلَیۡکِ بِجِذۡعِ النَّخۡلَۃِ  تُسٰقِطۡ عَلَیۡکِ  رُطَبًا جَنِیًّا» (19/25)\nTranslation: And shake the trunk of the palm tree toward you; it will drop upon you fresh ripe dates."
    },
    {
      "id": 912,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Fresh",
      "hw": "تازہ",
      "s": "«نَضْرَۃً» the freshness and radiance of a face and the purity of an atmosphere (3 verses: 75:22, 76:11, 83:24)",
      "d": "«نَضَرَ» means to be soft, fresh, and beautiful (Munjid, M. L). And «نَضْرَۃً» refers to the beauty of complexion and grace (M. L). The freshness, radiance, and cheerfulness of a face.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَوَقٰہُمُ  اللّٰہُ  شَرَّ ذٰلِکَ الۡیَوۡمِ وَلَقّٰہُمۡ نَضۡرَۃً  وَّ سُرُوۡرًا» (76/11)\nTranslation: So, Allah will protect them from the evil of that Day and will grant them freshness and joy."
    },
    {
      "id": 913,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Fresh",
      "hw": "تازہ",
      "s": "«نَاعِمَۃٌ» the freshness of faces due to abundance of blessings and prosperity (1 verse: 88:8)",
      "d": "«نَاعِمَۃٌ» means a life of prosperity. Prosperity (Munjid). The freshness of faces resulting from the abundance of blessings and a prosperous state.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وُجُوۡہٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ نَّاعِمَۃٌ لِّسَعۡیِہَا رَاضِیَۃٌ» (88:8,9)\nTranslation: Faces on that Day will be fresh, pleased with their effort."
    }
  ],
  "188": [
    {
      "id": 915,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "So that",
      "hw": "تاکہ",
      "s": "«کَیْ» Meaning 'so that'. It comes after a verb to state the purpose of that verb. In Arabic grammar, it is called the 'lightened imperfect particle of subordination' – the particle that makes the verb subjunctive. Often, the preposition 'lam' (ل) accompanies 'kay' (کَیْ), and this 'lam' is frequently omitted. (3 verses: 20:33-20:40-28:13)",
      "d": "«کَیْ» Meaning 'so that'. It comes after a verb to state the purpose of that verb. In Arabic grammar, it is called the 'lightened imperfect particle of subordination' – the particle that makes the verb subjunctive. Often, the preposition 'lam' (ل) accompanies 'kay' (کَیْ), and this 'lam' is frequently omitted.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n« كَيْ تَقَرَّ عَیۡنُہَا وَ لَا تَحۡزَنَ» (20/40)\nTranslation: So that her eyes may be cooled and she may not grieve."
    },
    {
      "id": 916,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "In order to",
      "hw": "تاکہ",
      "s": "«أن» is referred to as a 'masdar particle' in Arabic grammar because when combined with a verb, it imparts the meaning of a verbal noun (masdar). (488 verses: 2:26-2:27-2:67-2:75-2:90-2:96-2:105-2:108-2:114-2:125-2:158-2:169-2:177-2:184-2:198-2:210-2:214-2:216-2:224-2:228-2:229-2:230-2:232-2:233-2:235-2:237-2:248-2:254-2:258-2:266-2:267-2:280-2:282-3:28-3:73-3:79-3:80-3:93-3:122-3:124-3:142-3:143-3:145-3:147-3:161-3:188-3:193-4:6-4:19-4:23-4:24-4:25-4:27-4:28-4:29-4:44-4:47-4:48-4:58-4:60-4:66-4:84-4:88-4:90-4:91-4:92-4:99-4:101-4:102-4:113-4:116-4:127-4:128-4:129-4:131-4:135-4:140-4:144-4:150-4:153-4:171-4:172-4:176-5:2-5:3-5:11-5:17-5:19-5:29-5:31-5:33-5:34-5:37-5:41-5:49-5:52-5:59-5:80-5:84-5:91-5:108-5:111-5:112-5:113-5:116-5:117-6:14-6:23-6:25-6:35-6:37-6:51-6:56-6:65-6:70-6:72-6:80-6:111-6:125-6:131-6:145-6:156-6:158-7:5-7:13-7:20-7:33-7:43-7:44-7:46-7:50-7:63-7:69-7:82-7:89-7:97-7:98-7:100-7:105-7:110-7:115-7:117-7:123-7:126-7:129-7:160-7:169-7:172-7:185-8:7-8:26-8:62-8:67-9:13-9:16-9:17-9:18-9:32-9:44-9:52-9:54-9:62-9:64-9:74-9:81-9:85-9:86-9:102-9:108-9:110-9:113-9:118-9:120-10:2-10:10-10:15-10:35-10:37-10:72-10:83-10:87-10:100-10:104-10:105-11:3-11:12-11:14-11:26-11:34-11:46-11:47-11:62-11:69-11:87-11:88-11:89-12:13-12:15-12:21-12:24-12:25-12:37-12:38-12:66-12:76-12:79-12:83-12:94-12:96-12:100-12:107-13:21-13:25-13:31-13:36-13:38-14:5-14:10-14:11-14:22-14:31-14:35-15:31-15:54-16:2-16:15-16:33-16:36-16:40-16:45-16:68-16:92-16:123-17:8-17:16-17:46-17:51-17:59-17:68-17:69-17:74-17:79-17:88-17:94-17:99-17:103-18:24-18:35-18:40-18:55-18:57-18:63-18:66-18:77-18:79-18:80-18:81-18:82-18:86-18:94-18:97-18:102-18:109-19:11-19:35-19:45-19:91-19:92-20:39-20:45-20:59-20:63-20:65-20:71-20:77-20:86-20:94-20:97-20:114-20:134-21:17-21:31-21:57-21:87-22:15-22:22-22:26-22:40-22:65-23:24-23:27-23:32-23:95-23:98-24:8-24:16-24:17-24:19-24:22-24:29-24:36-24:50-24:51-24:60-24:61-24:63-25:18-25:42-25:57-25:62-26:10-26:12-26:14-26:17-26:22-26:35-26:49-26:51-26:52-26:63-26:82-26:197-27:8-27:19-27:38-27:39-27:40-27:45-27:56-27:60-27:72-27:91-27:92-28:5-28:7-28:9-28:10-28:19-28:22-28:27-28:30-28:31-28:33-28:34-28:47-28:67-28:82-28:86-29:2-29:4-29:24-29:29-29:33-30:10-30:20-30:21-30:25-30:43-30:46-30:49-31:10-31:12-31:14-31:15-32:20-33:6-33:36-33:37-33:49-33:50-33:51-33:52-33:53-33:59-33:72-34:11-34:14-34:33-34:43-34:46-35:41-36:40-36:60-36:61-36:81-36:82-37:104-38:4-38:6-38:75-39:4-39:11-39:17-39:54-39:55-39:56-40:26-40:28-40:66-40:78-41:22-42:13-42:47-42:51-43:5-43:33-43:66-44:18-44:19-44:20-45:21-45:25-46:15-46:17-46:33-47:18-47:22-47:29-48:12-48:15-48:24-48:25-49:2-49:6-49:11-49:12-49:17-50:2-51:57-53:26-53:39-55:33-56:61-57:16-57:22-58:3-58:4-58:13-59:2-59:3-60:1-60:7-60:8-60:9-60:10-60:12-61:3-63:10-64:7-65:1-65:4-66:5-66:8-67:16-67:17-68:14-68:22-68:24-68:32-68:49-70:38-70:41-71:1-71:3-72:5-72:7-72:12-72:16-72:28-73:20-74:15-74:37-74:52-74:56-75:4-75:25-75:36-75:40-76:30-79:18-80:2-81:28-81:29-84:14-85:8-90:5-90:7-96:7)",
      "d": "«أن» is referred to as a 'masdar particle' in Arabic grammar because when combined with a verb, it imparts the meaning of a verbal noun (masdar).\nFor example: In the Quran: «ذٰلِکَ اَدۡنٰۤی  اَنۡ تَقَرَّ اَعۡیُنُہُنَّ» (33/51)\nTranslation: This is more likely to cool their eyes."
    },
    {
      "id": 917,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "So that",
      "hw": "تاکہ",
      "s": "«کَیْ لَا» Meaning 'so that'. It comes after a verb to state the purpose of that verb. In Arabic grammar, it is called the 'lightened imperfect particle of subordination' – the particle that makes the verb subjunctive. (1 verse: 59:7)",
      "d": "«کَیْ لَا» Meaning 'so that'. It comes after a verb to state the purpose of that verb. In Arabic grammar, it is called the 'lightened imperfect particle of subordination' – the particle that makes the verb subjunctive.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«كَيْ لَا یَکُوۡنَ دُوۡلَۃًۢ  بَیۡنَ الۡاَغۡنِیَآءِ مِنۡکُمۡ» (59/7)\nTranslation: So that (the wealth) does not become a commodity between the rich among you."
    },
    {
      "id": 918,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "So that",
      "hw": "تاکہ",
      "s": "«لِکَیْلَا» Meaning 'so that'. It comes after a verb to state the purpose of that verb. In Arabic grammar, it is called the 'lightened imperfect particle of subordination' – the particle that makes the verb subjunctive. 'لِکَیْ' is written combined with the negative particle 'لَا'. لِکَیْ + لَا = لِکَیْلَا (6 verses: 3:153-16:70-22:5-33:37-33:50-57:23)",
      "d": "«لِکَیْلَا» Meaning 'so that'. It comes after a verb to state the purpose of that verb. In Arabic grammar, it is called the 'lightened imperfect particle of subordination' – the particle that makes the verb subjunctive. 'لِکَیْ' is written combined with the negative particle 'لَا'. لِکَیْ + لَا = لِکَیْلَا\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لِّکَیۡلَا تَحۡزَنُوۡا عَلٰی مَا فَاتَکُمۡ» (3/153)\nTranslation: So that you may not grieve over what has escaped you."
    },
    {
      "id": 919,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "In order to",
      "hw": "تاکہ",
      "s": "«لِئَلَّا» means 'lest' or 'so that not'. (3 verses: 2:150-4:165-57:29)",
      "d": "«لِئَلَّا» means 'lest' or 'so that not'.\nFor example: In the Quran: «لِئَلَّا یَکُوۡنَ  لِلنَّاسِ عَلَیۡکُمۡ حُجَّۃٌ» (2/150)\nTranslation: lest the people have an argument against you."
    }
  ],
  "189": [
    {
      "id": 920,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Molten copper",
      "hw": "تانبا",
      "s": "«قِطْر» Molten copper (3 verses: 14:50-18:96-34:12)",
      "d": "«قِطْر» is a specific word for molten copper (m.f. manjada).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اَسَلۡنَا لَہٗ عَیۡنَ الۡقِطۡرِ» (34/12)\nTranslation: And We made for him a spring of molten copper."
    },
    {
      "id": 921,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Molten copper",
      "hw": "تانبا",
      "s": "«مُھْل» Molten metals other than copper, and any loathsome, flowing discharge (3 verses: 18:29-44:45-70:8)",
      "d": "«مُھْل» means 'فَلَذَات' – mineral substances that can be melted, like gold, silver, iron, copper. Molten metals. Thin pitch (flowing sulfur). Poison. Pus (manjada). And «مُھْل» and «مُھْلَۃ» mean yellowish water (pus, foul matter from a wound or boil, or the corrupt fluid that oozes from a corpse). That is, the thin yellowish discharge that comes out of a corpse (manjada. m.q.). So, «مُھْل» refers to molten metals other than copper, as well as any flowing yellowish discharge (yellowish filth). Therefore, some scholars have also translated it as 'pus'.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّسۡتَغِیۡثُوۡا یُغَاثُوۡا بِمَآءٍ کَالۡمُہۡلِ یَشۡوِی الۡوُجُوۡہَ ؕ بِئۡسَ الشَّرَابُ» (18/29)\nTranslation: And if they seek help, they will be helped with water like molten metal, which scalds their faces. Wretched is the drink, and evil is the resting place."
    }
  ],
  "190": [
    {
      "id": 922,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Throne",
      "hw": "تخت",
      "s": "«عَرَش» Used for a royal throne (29 verses: 2:259-7:54-9:129-10:3-11:7-12:100-13:2-17:42-18:42-20:5-21:22-22:45-23:86-23:116-25:59-27:23-27:26-27:38-27:41-27:42-32:4-39:75-40:7-40:15-43:82-57:4-69:17-81:20-85:15)",
      "d": "«عَرَش» is used for a royal throne. (f.l. 230)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ رَفَعَ اَبَوَیۡہِ عَلَی الۡعَرۡشِ» (12/100)\nTranslation: And he (Yusuf) raised his parents to the throne.\nAnd «عَرْشَ الْبَیْت» refers to the roof of a house. And «عَرَشَ یَعْرِشُ» means to build a house of wood. So, «عَرْشَ الْبَیْت» refers to a roof made of beams and planks, etc."
    }
  ],
  "191": [
    {
      "id": 926,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Plank/Tablet",
      "hw": "تختہ",
      "s": "«الألواح» refers to wooden planks or writing tablets. (5 verses: 7:145-7:150-7:154-54:13-85:22)",
      "d": "«الألواح» – its singular is «لَوْح», meaning a plank of a ship, etc.\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ حَمَلۡنٰہُ عَلٰی ذَاتِ اَلۡوَاحٍ  وَّدُسُرٍ» (54/13)\nTranslation: And We carried him on a ship made of planks and nails.\nAlso, «لَوْح» refers to a plank or tablet of wood, etc., on which something is written.\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ کَتَبۡنَا لَہٗ  فِی الۡاَلۡوَاحِ  مِنۡ کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ مَّوۡعِظَۃً» (7/145)\nTranslation: And We wrote for him on the tablets [of the Torah] a lesson from every thing."
    }
  ],
  "192": [
    {
      "id": 927,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to deliberate",
      "hw": "تدبیر",
      "s": "«دَبَّرَ» means to consider with foresight regarding the outcome of an affair (9 verses: 4:82, 10:3, 10:31, 13:2, 23:68, 32:5, 38:29, 47:24, 79:5)",
      "d": "«دَبَّرَ» means to keep the outcome in view, to ponder over it, and to determine its course (muf). For example, the Quran states: «وَ مَنۡ یُّدَبِّرُ الۡاَمۡرَ ؕ فَسَیَقُوۡلُوۡنَ اللّٰہُ» (10:31). Translation: And who manages the affairs of the world? They will say, 'Allah!'"
    },
    {
      "id": 928,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To Devise / To Plot",
      "hw": "تدبیر",
      "s": "«کَیْد» (Kaid) is a secret scheme or plot that causes someone to encounter something detestable or evil. On a small scale, it is called «مَکَر» (makr), and on a large scale, it is called «کَیْد» (kaid). (29 verses: 3:120-4:76-7:183-7:195-8:18-11:55-12:5-12:28-12:33-12:34-12:50-12:52-12:76-20:60-20:64-20:69-21:57-21:70-22:15-37:98-40:25-40:37-52:42-52:46-68:45-77:39-86:15-86:16-105:2)",
      "d": "«کَیْد» (Kaid) means to devise a secret plan to accomplish something. It means to plot or to scheme (muf). And «کَیْدُ سَاحِرٍ» (kaid-u saahirin) means the tricks or stratagems of a sorcerer (muf). If the purpose of such a scheme is righteous and good, then it is permissible and correct. For example, the Quran states: «کَذٰلِکَ کِدۡنَا لِیُوۡسُفَ» (12/76) - 'Thus did We devise a plan for Joseph.' And if the purpose is evil, then it is reprehensible. For example, the Quran states: «فَاِنۡ کَانَ لَکُمۡ کَیۡدٌ فَکِیۡدُوۡنِ» (77/39) - 'If you plot against me, I too can plot.' «مَکَرَ» (Makara) is correct for good purposes and unlawful for bad ones, though the word often appears in a negative context."
    },
    {
      "id": 929,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To Devise / To Plot",
      "hw": "تدبیر",
      "s": "«مَکَرَ» (Makara) means deception, fraud, a secret scheme by which another person is prevented from achieving their goal. (23 verses: 3:54-6:123-6:124-7:99-7:123-8:30-10:21-12:31-12:102-13:33-13:42-14:46-16:26-16:45-16:127-27:50-27:51-27:70-34:33-35:10-35:43-40:45-71:22)",
      "d": "«مَکَرَ» (Makara) means to use cunning and trickery to accomplish something (m. l), and fundamentally, to secretly cause someone to encounter something detestable (fiqh, 214). This word generally appears in a negative sense. «مَکَرَ» (Makara) means deception and cunning (m. r). Imam Raghib defines it as turning someone away from their goal through pretexts and excuses (muf). When this word is attributed to Allah, it appears as a response to the actions of deceitful people. For example, the Divine statement is: «اَللہُ یَسْتَھْزِئُ بِھِمْ» - 'Allah mocks them.' And in the context of mutual deception (musakhkhalat), this is permissible (in the art of badi', musakhkhalat means expressing one meaning through another word not originally intended for it but associated with it). For example, the Divine statement is: «وَمَکَرُوۡا وَمَکَرَ اللّٰہُ ؕ وَاللّٰہُ خَیۡرُ الۡمٰکِرِیۡنَ» (3/54) - 'And they plotted, and Allah too plotted. And Allah is the best of plotters.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 930,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To Devise / To Plot",
      "hw": "تدبیر",
      "s": "«حِیْلَۃ» (Hiyalah) means to gain control or power over someone through cleverness and cunning. (1 verse: 4:98)",
      "d": "«حُوَّل ، حَوْل» (Hawwal, Hawl) means strength, power, cleverness, and foresight. The ability to act and its plural forms are «حِیَل» (hiyal) and «حِوَل» (hiwal) (Manjad). And it also means deception and fraud (m. q). «حیلہ» (Hilah) essentially refers to an act done to gain benefit or avert harm in such a way that it evades the grasp of the law. For example, before the zakat year ends, one donates their wealth and wife as a gift (hibah) to avoid paying zakat, and after the time passes, they take it back from the wife. This is cleverness, deception, and planning. Unlike «مکر» (makr) or «کَیْد» (kaid), it is not a secret scheme. For example, the Quran states: «اِلَّا الۡمُسۡتَضۡعَفِیۡنَ مِنَ الرِّجَالِ وَالنِّسَآءِ وَالۡوِلۡدَانِ لَا یَسۡتَطِیۡعُوۡنَ حِیۡلَۃً وَّلَا یَہۡتَدُوۡنَ سَبِیۡلًا» (4/98) - 'Except the weak among men, women, and children who cannot devise a plan nor are they guided to a way.'"
    }
  ],
  "193": [
    {
      "id": 931,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Scale",
      "hw": "ترازو",
      "s": "«مِیْزَان» (Meezan) is the instrument for weighing, the scale on which human deeds will be weighed on the Day of Judgment, and according to which reward and punishment will be given. (9 verses: 6:152-7:85-11:84-11:85-42:17-55:7-55:8-55:9-57:25)",
      "d": "«مِیْزَان» (Meezan) is an instrument for weighing. This word is general for any instrument that weighs something equal to a standard weight. And each weight placed on the scale's pan is also called a 'mizan'. For example, the Quran states: «اَلَّا تَطۡغَوۡا فِی الۡمِیۡزَانِ وَ اَقِیۡمُوا الۡوَزۡنَ بِالۡقِسۡطِ وَلَا تُخۡسِرُوا الۡمِیۡزَانَ» (55:8,9) - 'Do not transgress in the balance, and establish weight in justice and do not make the balance deficient.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 932,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Scale",
      "hw": "ترازو",
      "s": "«قِسْطَاس» (Qistas) refers to a scale that is very sensitive. (2 verses: 17:35-26:182)",
      "d": "«قِسْطَاس» (Qistas) is a word from Roman (Byzantine) language that entered Arabic (f. l 286). It refers to a scale that is very sensitive (m. r). It is a scale where even a slight inclination requires a notch to be seen. For example, the Quran states: «وَ زِنُوۡا بِالۡقِسْطَاسِ الۡمُسۡتَقِیۡمِ» (17/35) - 'And weigh with an even scale.'"
    }
  ],
  "194": [
    {
      "id": 933,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To Carve / To Hew",
      "hw": "تراشنا",
      "s": "«نَحَتَ» (Naḥata) is used for carving or hewing something. (4 verses: 7:74-15:82-26:149-37:95)",
      "d": "«نَحَتَ» (Naḥata) comes in the meanings of carving or hewing a hard thing, like wood, stone, metal, etc. And «نُحَاتَۃُ» (nuhāṭah) means the chips or splinters of wood or stone that fall while carving (muf). For example, the Quran states: «اَتَعۡبُدُوۡنَ مَا تَنۡحِتُوۡنَ» (37/95) - 'Do you worship what you yourselves carve?' And evidently, these idols were made from stone, wood, or metals. At another place, the Divine statement is: «وَّ تَنۡحِتُوۡنَ الۡجِبَالَ بُیُوۡتًا» (7/74) - 'And you carve houses out of the mountains.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 934,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To Carve / To Hew",
      "hw": "تراشنا",
      "s": "«جَابَ» (Jāba) means to cut, to make a fissure, and to hew. It is also related to heavy work. (1 verse: 89:9)",
      "d": "«جَابَ» (Jāba) means to cut (muf), to make a hole or fissure (Manjad), and then to shape it by hewing and chipping. So to speak, «نَحَتَ» (Naḥata) is suitable for fine work, and «جَابَ» (Jāba) is suitable for heavy work. For example, the Quran states: «وَ ثَمُوۡدَ الَّذِیۡنَ جَابُوا الصَّخۡرَ بِالۡوَادِ» (89/9) - 'And Thamud, who carved (or hewed) the rocks in the valley.'"
    }
  ],
  "195": [
    {
      "id": 935,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Greens / Vegetables",
      "hw": "ترکاری",
      "s": "«قَضْب» (Qaḍb) is that greens or vegetable which is eaten fresh after cutting. (1 verse: 80:28)",
      "d": "«قَضْب» (Qaḍb) is that greens or vegetable which is eaten fresh after cutting (Manjad). The authors of 'Sahib-i Mufradat' and 'Sahib-i Muntaha al-Arab' also include fresh grass (i.e., fodder for animals) under it, where the leaves are above ground and the edible part for humans is underground. For example, carrots, radishes, turnips, etc. The definition given by the author of 'Tafsir-i Muhammad' citing 'Ma'alim al-Tanzil' seems better: every vegetable or green whose leaves do not remain in winter, and the edible part for humans is underground. For example, the Quran states: «فَاَنْۢبَتْنَا فِيْہَا حَبًّا وَّعِنَبًا وَّقَضْبًا وَّ زَیۡتُوۡنًا وَّ نَخۡلًا» (80/29) - 'Then We produced therein grain, and grapes, and greens, and olives, and dates.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 936,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Greens / Vegetables",
      "hw": "ترکاری",
      "s": "«بَقْل» (Baql) is every kind of vegetable and greens that grows from a seed, not from a root. (1 verse: 2:61)",
      "d": "According to Imam Raghib, «بَقْل» (Baql) refers to vegetables whose roots and stems do not remain in winter (muf). And according to 'Sahib-i Muntaha al-Arab', «بَقْل» is every vegetable and green that grows from a seed, not from a root, like hemp, etc. But the correct understanding seems to be that the word «بَقْل» is general, encompassing all kinds of vegetables and greens. And «بَقّال» (baqqal) is the vegetable seller who sells all kinds of vegetables. For example, the Quran states: «فَادۡعُ لَنَا رَبَّکَ یُخۡرِجۡ لَنَا مِمَّا تُنۡۢبِتُ الۡاَرۡضُ مِنۡۢ بَقۡلِہَا» (2/61) - 'So invoke your Lord for us, that He may bring forth for us from what the earth grows of its vegetables.'"
    }
  ],
  "196": [
    {
      "id": 937,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Glorification and Sanctification (Declaring Purity)",
      "hw": "پاکیزگی",
      "s": "«سَبَّحَ» (Sabbaha) means to glorify. To say 'Subhan Allah'. To mention the attributes of Allah's blessed essence and to praise Him. (42 verses: 2:30-3:41-7:206-13:13-15:98-17:44-19:11-20:33-20:130-21:20-21:79-24:36-24:41-25:58-32:15-33:42-37:143-37:166-38:18-39:75-40:7-40:55-41:38-42:5-48:9-50:39-50:40-52:48-52:49-56:74-56:96-57:1-59:1-59:24-61:1-62:1-64:1-68:28-69:52-76:26-87:1-110:3)",
      "d": "«سَبَّحَ» (Sabbaha) means to glorify. To say 'Subhan Allah' or to mention 'Subhan Allah'. To declare, with tongue or state, the attributes of that Blessed Essence who is free from every kind of defect, deficiency, and weakness. To positively mention His perfections and to praise Him. (For details, see 'Purity')."
    },
    {
      "id": 938,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Tasbih wa Taqdis (Declaring Purity)",
      "hw": "پاکیزگی",
      "s": "«قَدَّسَ» To mention a being or thing while negating negative or imperfect attributes. (8 verses: 2:30-2:87-2:253-5:21-5:110-16:102-20:12-79:16)",
      "d": "«قُدُّوْس» is a name of Allah (SWT). It means a Being who is not in need of any partner and is pure from all forms of association and impurities. (See details under 'Purity'). And «قَدّسَ» means to declare the purity of the Essence of the Almighty and to negate all things that are unbefitting for Allah (SWT).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ نَحۡنُ نُسَبِّحُ بِحَمۡدِکَ وَ نُقَدِّسُ لَکَ» (2/30)\nTranslation: (The angels said) And we continuously glorify You with praise and declare Your purity."
    },
    {
      "id": 939,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Tasbih wa Taqdis (Declaring Purity)",
      "hw": "پاکیزگی",
      "s": "«حَاشَ» is an exclamatory word, used in meanings similar to 'Subhan'. It comes to forcefully deny an accusation, either against oneself or someone else. (2 verses: 12:31-12:51)",
      "d": "«حَاشَ» is an exclamatory word (indicating wonder and astonishment). It is synonymous with «حَاشَا لِلّٰہِ، سُبْحَانَ اللہ». However, its usage is very limited. This word is for Tanzih (declaring a Being free from all flaws and deficiencies) and is also a word of exception (muf). It is not used in the sense of an exclamatory word (muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاَیۡنَہٗۤ  اَکۡبَرۡنَہٗ وَ قَطَّعۡنَ اَیۡدِیَہُنَّ وَ قُلۡنَ حَاشَ لِلّٰہِ مَا ہٰذَا بَشَرًا ؕ اِنۡ  ہٰذَاۤ  اِلَّا مَلَکٌ  کَرِیۡمٌ» (12/31)\nTranslation: When those women saw him (Prophet Yusuf), his majesty overwhelmed them to such an extent that (while cutting fruit) they cut their own hands and exclaimed spontaneously: 'Subhan Allah! (What a stature and character!) This is not a human; this is none but a noble angel.'\nAt another place, the command of the Almighty states:\n«قَالَ مَا خَطۡبُکُنَّ اِذۡ رَاوَدۡتُّنَّ یُوۡسُفَ عَنۡ نَّفۡسِہٖ ؕ قُلۡنَ حَاشَ لِلّٰہِ مَا عَلِمۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ مِنۡ سُوۡٓءٍ» (12/51)\nTranslation: The king said (calling those women): What was your matter when you attempted to seduce Yusuf? They all said: 'Hasha lillah! We did not find any evil in him at all!'\nSometimes the word 'kalla' is also used with 'hasha'. «حَاشَ وَکَلَّا» which comes to forcefully deny an accusation against oneself or another. Its usage is not found in the Quran. Thus, the aspect of forceful denial is included in «حَاشَ»."
    }
  ],
  "197": [
    {
      "id": 940,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Taskeen (Consolation)",
      "hw": "تسکین",
      "s": "«سَکِیْنَۃٌ» The word 'sakeenah' is used for peace and tranquility from grief and anxieties. (6 verses: 2:248-9:26-9:40-48:4-48:18-48:26)",
      "d": "«سَکُون» refers to stillness after movement. This can be physical, mental, or cardiac. If it is mental or cardiac, it is called «سَکِیْنَۃ». That is, the heart finding relief from thoughts, grief, and worries. And attaining stability.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِذۡ یَقُوۡلُ لِصَاحِبِہٖ لَا تَحۡزَنۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ مَعَنَا ۚ فَاَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ سَکِیۡنَتَہٗ عَلَیۡہِ» (9/40)\nTranslation: When the Prophet (ﷺ) consoled his companion, saying 'Do not grieve, indeed Allah is with us,' then Allah sent down His tranquility upon him."
    },
    {
      "id": 941,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Taskeen (Consolation)",
      "hw": "تسکین",
      "s": "«اِطْمَئِنَّ» The word 'itmi'nan' comes for relief from doubts and suspicions. (12 verses: 2:260-3:126-4:103-5:113-8:10-10:7-13:28-16:106-16:112-17:95-22:11-89:27)",
      "d": "«اِطْمَئِنَّ» means to attain tranquility. It is the soul finding peace after restlessness, anxiety, hesitation, and doubt. (muf) The natural state becoming calm.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ اَوَ لَمۡ تُؤۡمِنۡ ؕ قَالَ بَلٰی وَ لٰکِنۡ لِّیَطۡمَئِنَّ قَلۡبِیۡ» (2/260)\nTranslation: (Allah) said: 'Have you not believed?' He (Ibrahim AS) said: 'Yes, but (I ask this) so that my heart may be at peace.' (Ibn Kathir)"
    }
  ],
  "198": [
    {
      "id": 942,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Interpreting (Dreams)",
      "hw": "تعبیر",
      "s": "«عَبَرَ» and «تَعْبِیْر» are words specifically used for stating the outcome (interpretation) of a dream. (7 verses: 3:13-12:43-12:111-16:66-23:21-24:44-79:26)",
      "d": "«عَبَرَ» means to cross a valley or river. And «عِبَارَۃَ الرُّؤْیَا» and «عَبَّرَ الرُّؤْیَا» mean to explain the interpretation of a dream. «عَبَّار» means one who gives dreams (manjad). And «اَلْعِبْرَۃ وَالْاِعْتِبَار» means to reach the seen results from something seen. And 'ta'beer' means to tell the outcome of a dream. (muf)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ لِلرُّءۡیَا تَعۡبُرُوۡنَ» (12/43)\nTranslation: If you are able to interpret dreams."
    },
    {
      "id": 943,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Interpreting (Dreams)",
      "hw": "تعبیر",
      "s": "«تَاَوَّلَ» To state the outcome of a matter or event; generally used for interpreting dreams. (15 verses: 3:7-4:59-7:53-10:39-12:6-12:21-12:36-12:37-12:44-12:45-12:100-12:101-17:35-18:78-18:82)",
      "d": "«تَاوِیْل» means to return something to its ultimate end or outcome. This word is more specific than 'ta'beer' because 'tawil' means to state the outcome of any matter in general, whether it is a dream or something else. Whereas the word 'ta'beer' is specific to stating the outcome of a dream. And according to 'Sahib al-Furq al-Lughawiyyah', 'tawil' is done for ambiguous (mutashabih) things only. (Faq. L 43)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ قَالَ الۡاٰخَرُ اِنِّیۡۤ  اَرٰىنِیۡۤ  اَحۡمِلُ فَوۡقَ رَاۡسِیۡ خُبۡزًا تَاۡکُلُ الطَّیۡرُ مِنۡہُ ؕ نَبِّئۡنَا بِتَاۡوِیۡلِہٖ» (12/36)\nTranslation: The other (prisoner) said: 'I see myself carrying bread on my head from which birds are eating. Inform us of its interpretation.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 944,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Interpreting (Dreams)",
      "hw": "تعبیر",
      "s": "«اَفْتٰی» To provide a solution to a difficult and complex problem, which includes the interpretation of a dream. (5 verses: 4:127-4:176-12:43-12:46-27:32)",
      "d": "«اَفْتٰی» means to provide a solution to a difficult and complex problem. «فَتْوٰی» is a Shariah term meaning to present the Shariah solution for a difficult and complex problem. To explain. And 'istiftah' means to ask a scholar for the solution to a difficult and complex problem. In the Quran, the word «اَفْتٰی» has come for the interpretation of a dream only because the dream whose interpretation was sought was very complex and difficult.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الۡمَلَاُ  اَفۡتُوۡنِیۡ فِیۡ رُءۡیَایَ» (12/43)\nTranslation: The king of Egypt said: O chiefs! Explain to me my dream.\nAnd those interpreters dismissed this complex dream by saying:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَضۡغَاثُ اَحۡلَامٍ ۚ وَ مَا نَحۡنُ بِتَاۡوِیۡلِ الۡاَحۡلَامِ بِعٰلِمِیۡنَ» (12/44)\nTranslation: The people said: 'These are confused dreams, and we are not experts in the interpretation of such dreams.'\nThen the freed companion of Yusuf said:\n«یُوۡسُفُ اَیُّہَا الصِّدِّیۡقُ اَفۡتِنَا فِیۡ سَبۡعِ بَقَرٰتٍ سِمَانٍ» (12/46)\nTranslation: Yusuf! O truthful one, explain to us the interpretation of the seven fat cows."
    }
  ],
  "199": [
    {
      "id": 946,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Gratitude (Thankfulness)",
      "hw": "تعریف",
      "s": "«شُکر» Thanking; it occurs in the context of acknowledging a favor or blessing. (43 verses)",
      "d": "«شُکر» is the word used for the conception and expression of someone's favors and bounties. (muf) And its opposite is «کُفْر». It means to disregard a favor or to hide a blessing and not let it be apparent. Ingratitude or denial of a blessing. Thus, «شُکْر» is also specific compared to «حَمْد». If we say, 'How beautifully Allah (SWT) has run the system of the universe,' this is «حَمْد». And if we say, 'Allah alone feeds us and gives us drink,' this is «شُکْر».\nVerses: 2:52, 2:56, 2:152, 2:172, 2:185, 2:243, 3:123, 4:147, 5:6, 5:89, 7:10, 7:58, 8:26, 10:60, 12:38, 14:7, 14:37, 16:14, 16:78, 16:114, 22:36, 23:78, 27:19, 27:40, 27:73, 28:73, 29:17, 30:46, 31:12, 31:14, 32:9, 34:13, 34:15, 35:12, 36:35, 36:73, 39:7, 40:61, 45:12, 46:15, 54:35, 56:70, 67:23 (Total 43 verses)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَئِنۡ شَکَرۡتُمۡ لَاَزِیۡدَنَّکُمۡ وَ لَئِنۡ کَفَرۡتُمۡ اِنَّ عَذَابِیۡ لَشَدِیۡدٌ» (14/7)\nTranslation: If you are grateful, I will surely increase you (in favor). And if you are ungrateful, indeed My punishment is severe!"
    },
    {
      "id": 947,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "حامد",
      "hw": "حامد",
      "s": "«حامد» that person which Allah of تعریف and ثنا کرتا is ۔",
      "d": "«حامد» of word عربی زبthese from is and this means تعریف کرنے of ۔ this Allah the Exalted of صفاتی ناموں in from is ۔ Allah the Exalted to «حَمْد» of meaning in also پکارا جاتا is ۔ «حَمْد» and «شُکر» in this فرق is that «حَمْد» زبthese from تعریف کرنا is and «شُکر» heart from احسthese ماننا is ۔\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَلۡحَمۡدُ لِلّٰہِ رَبِّ الْعٰلَمِیۡنَ» ( 1/1 )\nTranslation: all تعریف Allah Lord العالمین for is ۔"
    }
  ],
  "200": [
    {
      "id": 947,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Glorification",
      "hw": "تعظیم",
      "s": "«عَظَّم» To regard someone as great and honorable from the heart. This is used for both animate and inanimate things. (5 verses: 6:146-19:4-22:30-22:32-65:5)",
      "d": "The meanings of «عَظْم» are 'to be great' and 'bone'. Thus, in «عَظْم», the concept of greatness along with firmness, strength, or hardness is also found. And «عَظَّمَ» means to regard someone as great and honorable from the heart. And it is used for both animate and inanimate things.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَمَنۡ یُّعَظِّمۡ شَعَآئِرَ اللّٰہِ فَاِنَّہَا مِنۡ تَقۡوَی الۡقُلُوۡبِ» (22/32)\nTranslation: And whoever glorifies the symbols of Allah, then indeed that (glorification) comes from the piety of hearts."
    }
  ],
  "201": [
    {
      "id": 949,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Until",
      "hw": "تک",
      "s": "«اِلٰی» In Arabic grammar, 'ila' is a preposition (harf jar) used to indicate the limit or end of something. (653 verses: [long list of references])",
      "d": "«اِلٰی» is called a preposition (harf jar) in Arabic grammar. It is used to state the limit or end of something. It can also govern a pronoun. For example, «اِلَیْکمْ», and in this case, it gives the meaning of 'towards'. But «حتّٰی» can only govern a demonstrative pronoun (ism dhahir). It does not govern a pronoun. It governs a noun or a verb only.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«حَتّٰی نَرَی اللّٰہَ جَہۡرَۃً» (2/55)\nTranslation: Until we see Allah openly."
    },
    {
      "id": 950,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Until",
      "hw": "تک",
      "s": "«حَتّٰی» is called a preposition in Arabic grammar, used to indicate the extremity or end of something. (138 verses: 2:55-2:102-2:109-2:120-2:187-2:191-2:193-2:196-2:214-2:217-2:221-2:222-2:230-2:235-3:92-3:152-3:179-3:183-4:6-4:15-4:18-4:43-4:65-4:89-4:140-5:22-5:68-6:25-6:31-6:34-6:44-6:61-6:68-6:124-6:148-6:152-7:37-7:38-7:40-7:57-7:87-7:95-8:39-8:53-8:67-8:72-9:6-9:24-9:29-9:43-9:48-9:115-9:118-10:22-10:24-10:88-10:90-10:93-10:97-10:99-10:109-11:40-12:35-12:66-12:80-12:85-12:110-13:11-13:31-15:99-17:15-17:34-17:90-17:93-18:60-18:70-18:71-18:74-18:77-18:86-18:90-18:93-18:96-19:75-20:91-21:15-21:44-21:96-22:55-23:25-23:54-23:64-23:77-23:99-23:110-24:27-24:28-24:33-24:39-24:62-25:18-26:201-27:18-27:32-27:84-28:23-28:59-34:23-36:39-37:174-37:178-38:32-39:71-39:73-40:34-41:20-41:53-43:29-43:38-43:83-46:15-47:4-47:16-47:31-49:5-49:9-51:43-52:45-57:14-60:4-63:7-65:6-70:42-72:24-74:47-97:5-98:1-102:2)",
      "d": "«حَتّٰی» is called a preposition in Arabic grammar, used to indicate the extremity or end of something. And «حَتّٰی» is more eloquent than «اِلٰی», as in «حَتَّی الْاٰن» (until now) can be said, but «اِلی الْاٰن» is not said. The meaning of «اِلٰی» is only 'up to', while «حَتّٰی» means 'up to here'.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«وَ قٰتِلُوۡہُمۡ حَتّٰی لَا تَکُوۡنَ فِتۡنَۃٌ»\nTranslation: And fight them until there is no fitnah."
    }
  ],
  "202": [
    {
      "id": 951,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "harm, damage",
      "hw": "تکلیف",
      "s": "«ضَرَّ» means loss, any material or spiritual harm or damage. Its opposite is «نَفَعَ» meaning benefit. (13 verses: 2:231, 4:95, 5:76, 7:188, 9:107, 10:49, 13:16, 20:89, 25:3, 34:42, 41:50, 48:11, 72:21)",
      "d": "«ضَرَّ» means loss. Any material or spiritual harm or damage. Its opposite is «نَفَعَ». Sometimes this harm or damage can be good, such as the harm from bitter medicine (faq l 162). For example, the Quran states: «قُلۡ اَتَعۡبُدُوۡنَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ مَا لَا یَمۡلِکُ لَکُمۡ ضَرًّا وَّلَا نَفۡعًا» (5:76). Translation: Say, 'Do you worship besides Allah that which has no power to harm or benefit you?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 952,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "harm, damage",
      "hw": "تکلیف",
      "s": "«ضُرّ» is used for physical affliction and illness. (36 verses: 2:102, 3:111, 3:120, 3:144, 3:176, 3:177, 4:113, 5:42, 5:105, 6:17, 6:71, 9:39, 10:12, 10:18, 10:106, 10:107, 11:57, 12:88, 16:53, 16:54, 17:56, 17:67, 21:66, 21:83, 21:84, 22:12, 22:13, 23:75, 25:55, 26:73, 30:33, 36:23, 39:8, 39:38, 39:49, 47:32)",
      "d": "«ضُرّ» carries an element of exaggeration and generally refers to physical affliction. It is used for misfortune, sickness, wounds, or other physical and mental ailments (muf. manj) and has a negative connotation (faq l 162). For example, the Quran states: «وَ اِذَا مَسَّ الۡاِنۡسَانَ الضُّرُّ دَعَانَا لِجَنۡۢبِہٖۤ اَوۡ قَاعِدًا اَوۡ قَآئِمًا» (10:12). Translation: And when harm touches man, he calls upon Us while lying on his side, sitting, or standing."
    },
    {
      "id": 953,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "harm, damage",
      "hw": "تکلیف",
      "s": "«ضَرَّآء» is used for periods of outward difficulties and misfortune. (8 verses: 2:214, 2:177, 3:134, 6:42, 7:94, 7:95, 10:21, 11:10)",
      "d": "«ضَرَّآء» means a period of calamities and misfortune. It refers to loss of life, wealth, or offspring, or famine (manj. m. q). Its opposite is «نَعْمَاء» meaning prosperity. «ضَرَّآء» denotes outward calamities that are visible to others (faq l 163). For example, the Quran states: «مَسَّتۡہُمُ الۡبَاۡسَآءُ وَالضَّرَّآءُ وَ زُلۡزِلُوۡا حَتّٰی یَقُوۡلَ الرَّسُوۡلُ وَ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا مَعَہٗ مَتٰی نَصۡرُ اللّٰہِ» (2:214). Translation: They were afflicted by poverty and hardship and were shaken until the Messenger and those who believed with him said, 'When will the help of Allah come?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 954,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "harm, damage",
      "hw": "تکلیف",
      "s": "«اَذًی» is used for light affliction. (12 verses: 2:196, 2:222, 2:262, 2:263, 2:264, 3:111, 3:186, 4:102, 9:61, 33:57, 33:58, 61:5)",
      "d": "«اَذًی» is used for light affliction. It means «اَلضُّرُّ الْیَسِیْر» (m. q), i.e., minor harm. For example, the Quran states: «لَنۡ یَّضُرُّوۡکُمۡ  اِلَّاۤ اَذًی» (3:111). Translation: They will not harm you except for a little [hurt]. This light affliction can also be mental, such as hurting someone's feelings or using abusive language. For example, the Quran states: «وَ مِنۡہُمُ الَّذِیۡنَ یُؤۡذُوۡنَ النَّبِیَّ وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ ہُوَ اُذُنٌ» (9:61). Translation: And among them are those who hurt the Prophet and say, 'He is all ear.' It can also be physical, as the Quran describes menstruation as «اَذًی», which is also translated as impurity or uncleanness."
    },
    {
      "id": 957,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To Bear Hardship, To Give Hardship",
      "hw": "تکلیف",
      "s": "«اٰذٰی» is used for ordinary hardship, whether mental or physical (4 verses: 2:64-4:16-14:12-33:69)",
      "d": "«اٰذٰی» is used for ordinary hardship, whether mental or physical.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«لَا تَکُوۡنُوۡا کَالَّذِیۡنَ اٰذَوۡا مُوۡسٰی» (33/69)\nTranslation: And do not be like those who harmed Moses."
    },
    {
      "id": 958,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To Bear Hardship, To Give Hardship",
      "hw": "تکلیف",
      "s": "«ضَرَّ» is used for great hardship and loss (13 verses: 2:231-4:95-5:76-7:188-9:107-10:49-13:16-20:89-25:3-34:42-41:50-48:11-72:21)",
      "d": "«ضَرَّ» is used for great hardship and loss.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«وَاِنۡ تَصۡبِرُوۡا وَ تَتَّقُوۡا لَا یَضُرُّکُمۡ کَیۡدُہُمۡ شَیۡئًا» (3/120)\nTranslation: And if you are patient and fear Allah, their plot will not harm you at all.\nAnd «ضَارَّ، یُضَارُّ» meaning to harm one another, to cause loss or hardship.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«لَا تُضَآرَّ وَالِدَۃٌۢ بِوَلَدِہَا وَ لَا مَوۡلُوۡدٌ لَّہٗ بِوَلَدِہٖ» (2/233)\nTranslation: A mother should not be harmed by her child, nor a father by his child."
    },
    {
      "id": 960,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to impose a burden; to give",
      "hw": "تکلیف",
      "s": "«کَلَّفَ» means to take from something more than its capacity and strength. (7 verses: 2:233, 2:286, 4:84, 6:152, 7:42, 23:62, 65:7)",
      "d": "«کَلَّفَ» means to take from something more than its capacity and strength (muf) or to command a difficult task (manj). For example, the Quran states: «لَا یُکَلِّفُ اللّٰہُ نَفۡسًا اِلَّا وُسۡعَہَا» (2:286). Translation: Allah does not burden a soul beyond its capacity. Affliction can be praiseworthy (good) or blameworthy (bad). The praiseworthy one is when a task is undertaken because it is easy and beloved, and this is the religiously prescribed burden. The blameworthy one is what is called «تَکَلُّف», meaning an artificial burden or affectation."
    },
    {
      "id": 961,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to impose a burden; to give",
      "hw": "تکلیف",
      "s": "«مُشَقَّۃ» is used for taking more work than one's strength allows. (6 verses: 13:34, 16:7, 20:2, 20:117, 20:123, 28:27)",
      "d": "«شَقّ» also means to split. «شَقَّ یُشَقُّ» means to take from someone more than their strength allows or to involve them in hardship and toil (manj). For example, the Quran states: «وَمَاۤ اُرِیۡدُ اَنۡ اَشُقَّ عَلَیۡکَ» (28:27). Translation: And I do not wish to impose a hardship on you."
    },
    {
      "id": 962,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to impose a burden; to give",
      "hw": "تکلیف",
      "s": "«عَنَتَ» is for affliction where there is a risk of destruction. (4 verses: 2:220, 3:118, 9:128, 49:7)",
      "d": "«عَنَتَ» is an affliction in which there is a fear of destruction (muf) and means «اَشَدَّہ الضَّرَر» or extreme affliction (m. q). For example, the Quran states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡا بِطَانَۃً مِّنۡ دُوۡنِکُمۡ لَا یَاۡلُوۡنَکُمۡ خَبَالًا ؕ وَدُّوۡا مَا عَنِتُّمۡ» (3:118). Translation: O you who believe! Do not take as intimates those outside your ranks; they will not fail to harm you. They desire to harm you severely. And «اَعْنَتَ» means to cause someone such hardship. For example, the Quran states: «وَ لَوۡ شَآءَ اللّٰہُ  لَاَعۡنَتَکُمۡ» (2:220). Translation: And if Allah had willed, He could have imposed hardship on you."
    },
    {
      "id": 963,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To bear hardship. To give.",
      "hw": "تکلیف",
      "s": "«سَامَ» is used for an affliction that includes an element of humiliation (3 verses: 2:49-7:141-14:6)",
      "d": "«سَامَ» means to afflict someone, and the phrase «سَامَ خَسْفًا» means to humiliate and disgrace someone (Majid). «سَامَ» conveys an affliction that also involves humiliation and degradation.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«یَسُوۡمُوۡنَکُمۡ سُوۡٓءَ الۡعَذَابِ یُذَبِّحُوۡنَ اَبۡنَآءَکُمۡ وَ یَسۡتَحۡیُوۡنَ نِسَآءَکُمۡ» (2/49)\nTranslation: They used to afflict you with the worst torment, slaughtering your sons and sparing your women."
    }
  ],
  "203": [
    {
      "id": 964,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To become healthy. To heal.",
      "hw": "تندرست",
      "s": "«شَفٰی» means to recover from illness (6 verses: 9:14-10:57-16:69-17:82-26:80-41:44)",
      "d": "«شِفَاء» means to be saved from illness, to be granted safety. And «شَفٰی یَشْفِیْ» means to save from illness, to heal (Majid).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا مَرِضۡتُ فَہُوَ یَشۡفِیۡنِ» (26/80)\nTranslation: And when I fall ill, it is He who cures me.\nAnd «شَفٰی» is used for physical illnesses, similarly it also comes for salvation from spiritual illnesses.\nFor example, the Divine Command states:\n«وَ یَشۡفِ صُدُوۡرَ قَوۡمٍ  مُّؤۡمِنِیۡنَ» (9/14)\nTranslation: And He will heal the hearts of a group of believers."
    },
    {
      "id": 965,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To become healthy. To heal.",
      "hw": "تندرست",
      "s": "«اَبْرَءَ» means to save from a severe illness (2 verses: 3:49-5:110)",
      "d": "«بَرَءَ» means to be averse to. And «بُرْءُ» means to be saved from a detestable act, and «رَجُلٌ بَزِیْءٌ» means a pure and innocent person. And «بَرَءَ مِنَ الْمَرْض» means to recover, to be saved from illness. And «اَبْرَءَ الْمَرِیْض» means to heal the patient from his illness.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَاُبۡرِئُ الۡاَکۡمَہَ وَ الۡاَبۡرَصَ وَ اُحۡیِ الۡمَوۡتٰی بِاِذۡنِ اللّٰہِ» (3/49)\nTranslation: And I heal the blind and the leper, and I bring the dead to life by the permission of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 966,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To become healthy. To heal.",
      "hw": "تندرست",
      "s": "«اَفَاقَ» means to regain consciousness after unconsciousness (1 verse: 7:143)",
      "d": "«اَفَاقَ» means to come to senses from a state of intoxication or stupor, or to return from weakness to strength (Majid, Qanoon). According to «صَاحِبِ فِقْہُ الْلُغَۃ», the word «اَفَاقَ» is used specifically for regaining consciousness after unconsciousness (Fathul-Lateef, p.131).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا تَجَلّٰی رَبُّہٗ  لِلۡجَبَلِ جَعَلَہٗ  دَکًّا وَّ خَرَّ مُوۡسٰی صَعِقًا ۚ فَلَمَّاۤ  اَفَاقَ قَالَ سُبۡحٰنَکَ» (7/143)\nTranslation: So when his Lord manifested Himself to the mountain, He made it [into] dust, and Moses fell unconscious. Then when he recovered, he said, \"Exalted are You!\""
    }
  ],
  "204": [
    {
      "id": 967,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Poverty, destitution",
      "hw": "تنگدستی",
      "s": "«فَقْرُ» means destitution, poverty, extreme poverty (8 verses: 2:268-2:271-2:273-9:60-24:32-35:15-47:38-59:8)",
      "d": "«فَقْرُ» means destitution, poverty, extreme poverty. «فَقِرَ» and «فِقْرَۃٌ». The base of the spine is called «فِقْرَۃٌ». Its plural is «فِقَار». «فِقْرَۃٌ» means the base of the spine. And «فَقْرٌ» also means the base of the spine or breaking the waist. It is said «فَقْرَتْہُ الدَّاھِیَۃُ» meaning a calamity befell him that broke his waist (Majid). Thus, «فَقْر» implies extreme destitution that breaks one's back.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اِنۡ یَّکُوۡنُوۡا فُقَرَآءَ یُغۡنِہِمُ اللّٰہُ مِنۡ فَضۡلِہٖ» (24/32)\nTranslation: If they are poor, Allah will enrich them from His bounty."
    },
    {
      "id": 969,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Poverty, destitution",
      "hw": "تنگدستی",
      "s": "«عَیْلَۃً» means being crushed under the expenses of one's family and dependents (1 verse: 9:28)",
      "d": "«عَوْل» is everything that burdens a person and crushes them under its weight. And «عَیَال» refers to those individuals for whom a person is responsible for their livelihood expenses, thus becoming a burden (Majid). Thus, «عَیْلَۃ» is that destitution and need which occurs because of dependents.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ خِفۡتُمۡ عَیۡلَۃً فَسَوۡفَ یُغۡنِیۡکُمُ اللّٰہُ مِنۡ فَضۡلِہٖۤ» (9/28)\nTranslation: And if you fear poverty, Allah will enrich you from His bounty, if He wills."
    },
    {
      "id": 970,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Poverty, destitution",
      "hw": "تنگدستی",
      "s": "«اِمْلَاق» means the fear of becoming destitute (2 verses: 6:151-17:31)",
      "d": "«اِمْلَاق» actually does not denote destitution and need itself, but rather the anxiety that the existing wealth and property might be spent and lost. It is said: «اَمْلَقَ الدَّھْرُ مَللَہٗ» meaning time stripped him of his wealth (Majid). And «اَمْلَقَ» means the loss of existing wealth and property.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَقۡتُلُوۡۤا اَوۡلَادَکُمۡ خَشۡیَۃَ  اِمۡلَاقٍ» (17/31)\nTranslation: And do not kill your children for fear of poverty.\nThis same meaning is expressed in another verse with the phrase «خَشْیْۃَ اِنْفَاق» as well."
    },
    {
      "id": 971,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Poverty, destitution",
      "hw": "تنگدستی",
      "s": "«قَتْر» means being stingy in spending on one's dependents (2 verses: 2:236-25:67)",
      "d": "«قَتْر» means need, destitution, and poverty.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ مَتِّعُوۡہُنَّ ۚ عَلَی الۡمُوۡسِعِ قَدَرُہٗ  وَعَلَی الۡمُقۡتِرِ قَدَرُہٗ» (2/236)\nTranslation: And give them [something] [upon] the capacity of the wealthy and according to the capacity of the poor.\nHowever, linguists define its meaning as \"to make nafaqah (maintenance) tight for one's dependents\" (Maqayis, Mu'jam Maqayis). That is, «مُقْتِر» is a person who is not actually poor but is stingy in spending on his dependents according to his capacity.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ اِذَاۤ اَنۡفَقُوۡا لَمۡ یُسۡرِفُوۡا وَلَمۡ یَقۡتُرُوۡا وَکَانَ بَیۡنَ ذٰلِکَ قَوَامًا»\nTranslation: And those who, when they spend, are neither extravagant nor stingy, but are moderate between that."
    },
    {
      "id": 972,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Poverty, destitution",
      "hw": "تنگدستی",
      "s": "«بَاْسَآءِ» means a time of poverty and destitution (5 verses: 2:177-2:214-6:42-7:94-22:28)",
      "d": "«بَئِسَ یَبْئَسُ» means to be in severe need. And «بَاسْ» means punishment, war, and famine (Majid). And «بَاْسَآءِ» generally refers to times of financial difficulties and poverty. Its opposite is «سَرَّاء», meaning times of prosperity and comfort. That is, «مُسَرَّۃٌ فِی الْیُسْر» and «بَاسَاء» means an affliction that also includes fear (Fathul-Lateef, p.163).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَکُلُوۡا مِنۡہَا وَ اَطۡعِمُوا الۡبَآئِسَ الۡفَقِیۡرَ» (22/28)\nTranslation: So eat from it and feed the desperate poor.\nAt another place, the Divine Command states:\n«مَسَّتۡہُمُ الۡبَاۡسَآءُ وَ الضَّرَّآءُ وَ زُلۡزِلُوۡا» (2/214)\nTranslation: They were touched by poverty and hardship and were shaken [to their core].\nIn this verse, «بَاْسَاء» refers to economic hardship and «ضَرَّاء» refers to other afflictions and calamities."
    },
    {
      "id": 973,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Poverty, destitution",
      "hw": "تنگدستی",
      "s": "«مَتْرَبَۃ» means to become mixed with dust due to poverty (1 verse: 90:16)",
      "d": "«تُرَاب» means dry soil. And «تَرِبَ الرَّجُل» means a man became so poor that he mixed with the dust.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اَوۡ اِطۡعٰمٌ فِیۡ یَوۡمٍ ذِیۡ مَسۡغَبَۃٍ یَّتِیۡمًا ذَا مَقۡرَبَۃٍ اَوۡ مِسۡکِیۡنًا ذَا مَتۡرَبَۃٍ» (90/14,15,16)\nTranslation: Or [giving] food on a day of severe hunger to an orphan near of kin, or a needy person in misery [who is mixed with dust]."
    }
  ],
  "205": [
    {
      "id": 974,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Constriction",
      "hw": "تنگی",
      "s": "«عُسْر» is used for times of constriction (9 verses: 2:185-2:280-9:117-18:73-54:8-65:7-92:10-94:5-94:6)",
      "d": "«عُسْر» meaning constriction or a time of constriction. Calamity and distress (m l) whether this constriction is economic or of another kind. This word is general and its opposite is «یُسْر» meaning ease and prosperity.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اِنَّ مَعَ الۡعُسۡرِ  یُسۡرًا» (94:6)\nTranslation: Indeed, with constriction comes ease."
    },
    {
      "id": 975,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Constriction",
      "hw": "تنگی",
      "s": "«حَرَج» is used for constriction and narrowing of the heart (11 verses: 4:65-5:6-6:125-7:2-9:91-22:78-24:61-33:37-33:38-33:50-48:17)",
      "d": "«حَرَج» meaning narrowing of the heart. The heart feeling constricted due to unlawful restrictions (f l 54).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ مَا جَعَلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ فِی الدِّیۡنِ مِنۡ حَرَجٍ» (22:78)\nTranslation: And He has not placed upon you in the religion any constriction."
    },
    {
      "id": 976,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Constriction",
      "hw": "تنگی",
      "s": "«ضَنْک» is used for constriction of life and distresses or for being debilitated by thoughts (1 verse: 20:124)",
      "d": "«ضَنْک» meaning constriction in lifestyle and living. (f l 54) restlessness and anxiety of the heart, remaining engrossed in thoughts. «ضَنَاکَۃ» meaning a constricted life (minjd).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ مَنۡ اَعۡرَضَ عَنۡ ذِکۡرِیۡ فَاِنَّ لَہٗ مَعِیۡشَۃً ضَنۡکًا» (20:124)\nTranslation: And whoever turns away from My reminder - indeed, his life will be constricted."
    },
    {
      "id": 977,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Constriction",
      "hw": "تنگی",
      "s": "«ضَیْق» is used for constriction of space (11 verses: 6:125-9:25-9:118-11:77-15:97-16:127-25:13-26:13-27:70-29:33-65:6)",
      "d": "«ضَیْق» is used for constriction of space. (f l 54) and its opposite is «سَعَۃٌ» meaning spaciousness. (m l)\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَاِذَاۤ اُلۡقُوۡا مِنۡہَا مَکَانًا ضَیِّقًا» (25:13)\nTranslation: And when they are thrown into a constricted place from it.\nSometimes its opposite «رَحُبَ» also occurs.\nFor example, the divine declaration is:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا ضَاقَتۡ عَلَیۡہِمُ الۡاَرۡضُ بِمَا رَحُبَتۡ» (9:118)\nTranslation: Until the earth, despite its spaciousness, became constricted for them.\nThen sometimes «ضَیْق» is used in the meaning of «حَرَج» i.e., constriction of the heart. So this is the metaphorical use of «ضَیْق».\nFor example, the divine declaration is:\n«وَ لَا تَکُ فِیۡ  ضَیۡقٍ مِّمَّا یَمۡکُرُوۡنَ» (16:127)\nTranslation: And do not be constricted in heart by what they plot."
    },
    {
      "id": 978,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Constriction",
      "hw": "تنگی",
      "s": "«حَاجَۃ» is that constriction and narrowness that arises from the non-fulfillment of a desire or need (3 verses: 12:68-40:80-59:9)",
      "d": "«اَلْحَوْج» meaning need, necessity, and poverty. And «حَاجَ» meaning to be in need. And «حَاجَۃ» meaning necessity. That constriction which is felt in the heart due to the non-fulfillment of a desire or need.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ لَا یَجِدُوۡنَ  فِیۡ صُدُوۡرِہِمۡ حَاجَۃً  مِّمَّاۤ اُوۡتُوۡا» (59:9)\nTranslation: And they do not find in their hearts any constriction from what they are given."
    }
  ],
  "206": [
    {
      "id": 979,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To constrict / To become constricted",
      "hw": "تنگ ",
      "s": "«ضَاقَ» is used for constriction of space (4 verses: 9:25-9:118-11:77-29:33)",
      "d": "«ضَاقَ» indicates constriction of space.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَاِذَاۤ اُلۡقُوۡا مِنۡہَا مَکَانًا ضَیِّقًا» (25:13)\nTranslation: And when they are thrown into a constricted place from it."
    },
    {
      "id": 980,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To constrict / To become constricted",
      "hw": "تنگ ",
      "s": "«قَدَرَ» if associated with provision, then it is used for constriction of provision (11 verses: 13:26-17:30-28:82-29:62-30:37-34:36-34:39-39:52-42:12-65:7-89:16)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «قَدَرَ» is to estimate something, to manage and devise for it (minjd), but when this word is associated with provision, then it means constriction of provision, and its opposite is «بَسَطَ».\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اَللّٰہُ یَبۡسُطُ الرِّزۡقَ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ مِنۡ عِبَادِہٖ وَیَقۡدِرُ لَہٗ» (29:62)\nTranslation: Allah extends provision for whom He wills of His servants and constricts it for whom He wills."
    },
    {
      "id": 981,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To constrict / To become constricted",
      "hw": "تنگ ",
      "s": "«قَبَضَ» meaning to seize something with the full fist (2 verses: 2:245-9:67)",
      "d": "The meaning of «قَبَضَ» is to seize something with the full fist, to enclose in the fist and to contract (muf). And «قَبْضَۃٌ» meaning a fist and what is enclosed in it. Its opposite is «بَسَطَ». And «قَبَضَ» is used when constriction or reduction is made in something that was previously abundant. Whether it be provision or something else.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«مَنۡ ذَا الَّذِیۡ یُقۡرِضُ اللّٰہَ  قَرۡضًا حَسَنًا فَیُضٰعِفَہٗ لَہٗۤ اَضۡعَافًا کَثِیۡرَۃً ؕ وَ اللّٰہُ یَقۡبِضُ وَ یَبۡصُۜطُ» (2:245)\nTranslation: Who is it that would loan Allah a goodly loan so He will multiply it for him many times over? And Allah withholds and expands [provision]."
    },
    {
      "id": 982,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To constrict / To become constricted",
      "hw": "تنگ ",
      "s": "«حَصِرَ» (it is a masdar) is used for constriction and distress of the heart (4 verses: 2:196-2:273-4:90-9:5)",
      "d": "«حَصِرَ» meaning to be constricted. To be confined, and «حَصِرَ الرَّجُل» meaning to feel pressure on the heart, the heart to be constricted, to become distressed. (minjd)\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اِلَّا الَّذِیۡنَ یَصِلُوۡنَ اِلٰی قَوۡمٍۭ بَیۡنَکُمۡ وَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ مِّیۡثَاقٌ اَوۡ جَآءُوۡکُمۡ حَصِرَتۡ صُدُوۡرُہُمۡ اَنۡ یُّقَاتِلُوۡکُمۡ اَوۡ یُقَاتِلُوۡا قَوۡمَہُمۡ» (4:90)\nTranslation: Except for those who join a people between whom and you there is a treaty, or those who come to you with their hearts constricted from fighting you or fighting their own people."
    },
    {
      "id": 983,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To constrict / To become constricted",
      "hw": "تنگ ",
      "s": "«حَفَا» comes in the meaning of constricting someone through exaggeration and insistence in asking (3 verses: 7:187-19:47-47:37)",
      "d": "The lexical meaning of «حَفَا» is to exaggerate and insist in seeking something. (muf. m. q) And «حَفِیُّ» means one who has complete knowledge about something. One who exaggerates in honor, respect, and showing happiness. One who inquires too much about someone's condition and insists on asking (minjd). So from this exaggeration and insistence, sometimes the meaning of constricting arises.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اِنۡ یَّسۡئَلۡکُمُوۡہَا  فَیُحۡفِکُمۡ  تَبۡخَلُوۡا» (47:37)\nTranslation: And if he asks you for it and constricts you [by making excessive demands], you become stingy."
    }
  ],
  "207": [
    {
      "id": 984,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to break",
      "hw": "توڑنا",
      "s": "«نَکَثَ» is used for breaking a sale, an oath, and a covenant, or for tearing down something built (6 verses: 7:135, 9:12, 9:13, 16:92, 43:50, 48:10)",
      "d": "«نَکَثَ» means to tear down something built or constructed. And «نِكْث» refers to old tents or quilts etc., which are torn down to re-spin the threads. And «نَكَّاث» refers to one who tears down something built or woven. (Majid) And it is generally used for breaking a covenant, oath, and sale (i.e., breaking a promise, violating an agreement). For example, the Quran states: «أَلَا تُقَاتِلُوۡنَ قَوۡمًا نَّكَثُوۡۤا أَيۡمَانَہُمۡ» (9:13). Translation: Why do you not fight a people who broke their oaths?"
    },
    {
      "id": 985,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to break",
      "hw": "توڑنا",
      "s": "«نَقَضَ» comes for unraveling anything, scattering a weave, and breaking a firm covenant or oath, or ruining it through trickery (9 verses: 2:27, 4:155, 5:13, 8:56, 13:20, 13:25, 16:91, 16:92, 18:77)",
      "d": "«نَقَضَ» means to scatter the weave of something, and its opposite is «اَبْرَم», i.e., to make a matter firm and strong. (Mufradat) This word is more general than «نَكَثَ». For example, «نَقَضتُ الْبِنَاء» means to demolish a building. «اَلْعَظْمُ» means to break a bone. «اَلْعَقْدُ» means to untie a knot. Similarly, «نَقَضْتُ الْحَبْلَ» also means to untie a rope. Then, «نَقَضَ» is more eloquent (stronger) than «نَكَثَ». And it is used for breaking a covenant or oath that has been firmly established. For example, the Quran states: «وَأَوۡفُوۡا بِعَہۡدِ اللّٰہِ إِذَا عَٰهَدۡتُمۡ وَلَا تَنۡقُضُوا الۡأَيۡمَانَ بَعۡدَ تَوۡكِیۡدِہَا» (16:91). Translation: And fulfill the covenant of Allah when you have taken it, and do not break oaths after their confirmation. At another place, the divine command states: «الَّذِیۡنَ یَنۡقُضُوۡنَ عَہۡدَ اللّٰہِ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ مِیۡثَاقِہٖ» (2:27). Translation: Those who break the covenant of Allah after its confirmation."
    },
    {
      "id": 986,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to break",
      "hw": "توڑنا",
      "s": "«اَنْقَضَ» means to break something in such a way that a cracking sound is produced (1 verse: 94:3)",
      "d": "«اَنْقَضَ» means to break something in such a way that a cracking sound is heard. (Mufradat) Then its application began on various occasions. For example, «اَنْقَضَتِ الدُّجَاجَة» means the sound of an egg cracking when laid. «الادِیم» means the rustling of leather. And «اَنْقَضَ أَصَابِعَہٗ» means to snap one's fingers. (Majid) And «اَنْقَضَ الْحَمَلُ الظَّھْرَ» means to load so much weight on the back that it cracks and becomes doubled. For example, the Quran states: «وَضَعۡنَا عَنۡکَ وِزۡرَکَ الَّذِیۡۤ أَنۡقَضَ ظَہۡرَکَ» (94:2,3). Translation: And We have removed from you your burden which had broken your back."
    },
    {
      "id": 987,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to break",
      "hw": "توڑنا",
      "s": "«فَقَرَ» is a specific word for breaking the spine (1 verse: 75:25)",
      "d": "«فَقَرَ» is more specific than «اَنْقَضَ». It only means to break the spine. Whereas «اَنْقَضَ» is general. «اَلْفَقْرَۃُ» and «اَلْفِقْرَۃُ» refer to the vertebra of the spine which has a hole, and its plurals are «فِقَار» and «فِقْرَات». And «فَقَرَ الْخَرْزَ» means to make a hole in a pearl for stringing. And «فَاقِرَۃٌ» refers to a calamity that breaks the spine. (Majid) For example, the Quran states: «وَوُجُوۡہٌ یَّوۡمَئِذٍۭ بَاسِرَۃٌ تَظُنُّ أَنۡ یُّفۡعَلَ بِہَا فَاقِرَۃٌ» (75:24,25). Translation: And many faces on that day will be gloomy, thinking that a calamity that will break their spine will be inflicted upon them. (Uthmaniؒ)"
    },
    {
      "id": 988,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to break",
      "hw": "توڑنا",
      "s": "«جَذَّ» means to break something hard and shatter it into pieces (2 verses: 11:108, 21:58)",
      "d": "«جَذَّ» means to break something hard and shatter it into pieces (see detailed cutting)."
    }
  ],
  "208": [
    {
      "id": 989,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to grant success/facilitate",
      "hw": "توفیق",
      "s": "«وَفَّقَ اللہُ» means Allah makes circumstances favorable or suitable for a task (1 verse: 4:35)",
      "d": "«وَفْق» means compatibility and harmony between two things. (Mufradat) And «وَفَّقَ» means to make compatible. And «وَفَّقَ اللہ» means Allah makes circumstances favorable for a task. For example, the Quran states: «إِنۡ یُرِیۡدَاۤ إِصۡلَاحًا یُّوَفِّقِ اللّٰہُ بَیۡنَہُمَا» (4:35). Translation: If they both desire reconciliation, Allah will bring about harmony between them."
    },
    {
      "id": 990,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to grant success/facilitate",
      "hw": "توفیق",
      "s": "«اَوْزَعَ اللہُ» means Allah makes someone's heart favorable or suitable for a task (2 verses: 27:19, 46:15)",
      "d": "«وَزَعَ» means to restrain. «وَزَعَ الْجَیْش» means to keep the army in orderly ranks. And «وَزَّع» and «اَوْزَعَ» mean to distribute, to scatter, to disperse. (Al-Ighad) And «اَوْزَعَ الشَّیْ» means to inspire. And «اِسْتَوْزَعَ اللہُ شُکْرَہ» means to seek the grace of gratitude from Allah. (Majid) And «اَوْزَعَ اللہُ فُلَانًا» means Allah inspired so-and-so with gratitude. (Mufradat) For example, the Quran states: «قَالَ رَبِّ أَوۡزِعۡنِیۡۤ أَنۡ أَشۡکُرَ نِعۡمَتَکَ الَّتِیۡۤ أَنۡعَمۡتَ عَلَیَّ وَ عَلٰی وَالِدَیَّ» (27:19, 46:15). Translation: He said, 'My Lord, grant me success so that I may be grateful for Your favors which You have bestowed upon me and upon my parents.' Note: (Al-Ighad refers to words that have two distinct, opposite meanings)."
    }
  ],
  "209": [
    {
      "id": 992,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "layered/stacked",
      "hw": "تہ",
      "s": "«رَکَمَ» means to pile something up without any order or arrangement, above or below, or forward or backward (3 verses: 8:37, 24:43, 52:44)",
      "d": "«رَکَمَ» means to pile up. (Majid) Without any order or arrangement, to gather something together by mixing it up, above or below, or forward or backward. And «رُکَام» and «مَرْکُوْم» mean layered/stacked. For example, the Quran states: «أَلَمۡ تَرَ أَنَّ اللّٰہَ یُزۡجِی سَحَابًا ثُمَّ یُؤَلِّفُ بَیۡنَہٗ ثُمَّ یَجۡعَلُہٗ رُکَامًا» (24:43). Translation: Do you not see that Allah drives the clouds, then He joins them together, then He makes them into a heap? At another place, the divine command states: «لِیَمِیۡزَ اللّٰہُ الۡخَبِیۡثَ مِنَ الطَّیِّبِ وَ یَجۡعَلَ الۡخَبِیۡثَ بَعۡضَہٗ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ فَیَرۡکُمَہٗ جَمِیۡعًا فَیَجۡعَلَہٗ فِیۡ جَہَنَّمَ» (8:37). Translation: So that Allah may separate the evil from the good, and He will heap the evil upon the evil and cast them into Hell."
    },
    {
      "id": 993,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "layered/stacked",
      "hw": "تہ",
      "s": "«تَرَاكِب» means to place something in an ordered and systematic way, above or below, or forward or backward, so that they are connected to each other (2 verses: 6:99, 84:19)",
      "d": "«رَکِبَ» means to ride. And «رَکِیْب» means the rear rider among two, or something connected like a bezel in a ring. (Majid) And «تَرَاكِب» means to be layered/stacked in such a way that a particular order and arrangement is found in them. And «مُتَرَاكِب» means one upon another, riding upon another. For example, the Quran states: «فَأَخۡرَجۡنَا مِنۡہُ خَضِرًا نُّخۡرِجُ مِنۡہُ حَبًّا مُّتَرَاكِبًا» (6:99). Translation: Then We bring forth from it green vegetation, from which We bring forth close-packed grains."
    },
    {
      "id": 995,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "layered/stacked",
      "hw": "تہ",
      "s": "«کِسَفَ» means to place something porous, like wool or clouds, above or below. (Porous: meaning hollow inside, fluffy, full of holes) (5 verses: 17:92, 26:187, 30:48, 34:9, 52:44)",
      "d": "«کِسْفَۃٌ» means a piece of a porous body, like a cloud or wool, and its plural is «کِسْفٌ». And «کِسَفًا» means to place porous pieces, whether small or large, one upon another. (Mufradat) For example, the Quran states: «اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡ یُرۡسِلُ الرِّیٰحَ فَتُثِیۡرُ سَحَابًا فَیَبۡسُطُہٗ فِی السَّمَآءِ کَیۡفَ یَشَآءُ وَ یَجۡعَلُہٗ کِسَفًا» (30:48). Translation: Allah is the One Who sends the winds, so they raise clouds, then He spreads them in the sky as He wills, and makes them layered."
    }
  ],
  "210": [
    {
      "id": 996,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to get tired",
      "hw": "تھکنا",
      "s": "«سَئَمَ» to become weary or disgusted with something due to prolonged engagement (3 verses: 2:282-41:38-41:49)",
      "d": "«سَئَمَ» means to become weary or disgusted in heart due to staying with something for a long time. To become bored with something from the heart. To become satiated while doing a task. This is the initial state of getting tired.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَا یَسۡئَمُ الۡاِنۡسَانُ مِنۡ دُعَآءِ الۡخَیۡرِ» (41/49)\nTranslation: Man does not get tired of praying for good."
    },
    {
      "id": 997,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to get tired",
      "hw": "تھکنا",
      "s": "«نَصِبَ» to get very tired, to become emaciated due to exhaustion (6 verses: 9:120-15:48-18:62-35:35-88:3-94:7)",
      "d": "The literal meaning of «نَصِبَ» is 'to peg' or 'to fix'. And if it is from the pattern «عَلِمَ یَعْلَمُ», the meanings reverse, i.e., a person cannot keep his body straight and firm due to exhaustion. Therefore, «نَصِبَ» means to toil hard, and to be exhausted due to toil.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا جَاوَزَا قَالَ لِفَتٰىہُ اٰتِنَا غَدَآءَنَا ۫ لَقَدۡ لَقِیۡنَا مِنۡ سَفَرِنَا ہٰذَا نَصَبًا» (18/62)\nTranslation: When they had passed beyond that, he (Moses) said to his young companion: 'Bring us our morning meal; indeed, we have encountered much fatigue from this journey of ours.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 998,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to get tired",
      "hw": "تھکنا",
      "s": "«لَغَبَ» to become weak due to exhaustion (2 verses: 35:35-50:38)",
      "d": "«لَغَبَ» means to get tired and become weak due to excessive work or toil. To become incapable (of doing more).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ وَ مَا بَیۡنَہُمَا فِیۡ سِتَّۃِ اَیَّامٍ ٭ۖ وَّ مَا مَسَّنَا مِنۡ لُّغُوۡبٍ» (50/38)\nTranslation: And We created the heavens and the earth and whatever is between them in six days, and We were not touched by any fatigue."
    },
    {
      "id": 999,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to get tired",
      "hw": "تھکنا",
      "s": "«عَیَّ» to be unable to do more work due to exhaustion (2 verses: 46:33-50:15)",
      "d": "«عَیَّ» means to be unable to do more work due to exhaustion and to become incapable. «اَلْعَیُّ» and «اَلْعَیَّانُ» refer to one who is tired, and «دَاءٌ عَیَاءٌ» refers to an incurable disease.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَوَ لَمۡ یَرَوۡا اَنَّ اللّٰہَ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ وَ لَمۡ یَعۡیَ بِخَلۡقِہِنَّ» (46/33)\nTranslation: Do they not see that Allah, Who created the heavens and the earth, was not wearied by their creation?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1001,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to get tired",
      "hw": "تھکنا",
      "s": "«اٰدَ» to get tired due to burden and heavy weight (1 verse: 2:255)",
      "d": "The original meaning of «اٰدَ، یَؤُدُّ» is to deviate from one's path due to burden and heaviness (heavy weight). In common usage, it means to get tired due to burden and heaviness.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَسِعَ کُرۡسِیُّہُ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ ۚ وَلَا یَئُوۡدُہٗ حِفۡظُہُمَا ۚ وَ ہُوَ الۡعَلِیُّ الۡعَظِیۡمُ» (2/255)\nTranslation: His Kursi (throne) extends over the heavens and the earth, and their preservation does not tire Him. And He is the Most High, the Most Great."
    }
  ],
  "211": [
    {
      "id": 1002,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop/rest",
      "hw": "رکنا",
      "s": "«سَکَنَ» is general; used for the cessation of movement of any thing (20 verses: 2:231-2:256-4:15-5:4-6:13-6:96-7:170-7:189-9:103-10:67-16:79-16:80-23:18-25:45-27:86-28:72-28:73-30:21-40:61-42:33-)",
      "d": "«سَکَنَ» refers to the pause after the movement of any thing. It is used in both external and spiritual senses. Its opposite is movement and agitation.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنۡ یَّشَاۡ یُسۡکِنِ الرِّیۡحَ» (42/33)\nTranslation: If He wills, He can calm the wind."
    },
    {
      "id": 1003,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop/rest",
      "hw": "رکنا",
      "s": "«سَکَتَ» to stop while speaking, to become silent (2 verses: 7:154-17:100)",
      "d": "«سَکَتَ» means to become silent. To stop while talking. To cease. «سَکِیْت» and «سَاکُوْت» describe one who is habitually silent. And «سَکَتَ الْغَضَب» means for anger to subside.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَمَّا سَکَتَ عَنۡ مُّوۡسَی الۡغَضَبُ» (7/154)\nTranslation: And when the anger subsided from Moses..."
    },
    {
      "id": 1004,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop/rest",
      "hw": "رکنا",
      "s": "«رَھْوًا» used for the calming of waves and surges on water (1 verse: 44:24)",
      "d": "«رَھَا، یَرْھُوْا» means to move with gentle pace. And «رَھَا الْبَحْرَ» means the sea becomes calm. That is, the waves and surges on water subside. It also means water gathered in a smooth, level place.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اتۡرُکِ الۡبَحۡرَ رَہۡوًا» (44/24)\nTranslation: And leave the sea as calm (or parted)."
    }
  ],
  "212": [
    {
      "id": 1005,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "a little",
      "hw": "تھوڑا",
      "s": "«قَلِیل» used for anything that is little in comparison to something more. Its usage is general (70 verses: 2:41-2:79-2:83-2:88-2:126-2:174-2:246-2:249-3:77-3:187-3:197-3:199-4:46-4:66-4:77-4:83-4:142-4:155-5:13-5:44-7:3-7:10-7:86-8:26-8:43-8:44-9:9-9:38-9:82-11:40-11:116-12:47-12:48-16:95-16:117-17:52-17:62-17:74-17:76-17:85-18:22-23:40-23:78-23:114-26:54-27:62-28:58-31:24-32:9-33:16-33:18-33:20-33:60-34:13-34:16-38:24-39:8-40:58-44:15-48:15-51:17-53:34-56:14-67:23-69:41-69:42-73:2-73:3-73:11-77:46)",
      "d": "«قَلِیل» is the opposite of «کثیر». That is, little in comparison to more. Its usage is general. It is used for quantity, weight, distance, duration, etc., everywhere.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَشۡتَرُوۡا بِاٰیٰتِیۡ ثَمَنًا قَلِیۡلًا» (2/41)\nTranslation: And do not exchange My verses for a small price."
    },
    {
      "id": 1006,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "a little",
      "hw": "تھوڑا",
      "s": "«فَتِیل» used for a very small quantity (3 verses: 4:49-4:77-17:71)",
      "d": "«فَتَلَ» means to twist a rope, etc. And «فَتِیل» refers to a twisted rope. Its feminine form is «فَتِیْلَۃٌ», which means a wick (for a lamp). Also, «فَتِیْلَۃٌ» refers to that thin thread which is in the crack of a date stone. And from this word, a very small quantity is understood.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَا یُظۡلَمُوۡنَ فَتِیۡلًا» (4/49)\nTranslation: And they will not be wronged by a thread (i.e., an iota)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1008,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "A little",
      "hw": "تھوڑا",
      "s": "«قِطْمِیْر» (Qitmir) refers to an extremely small quantity, so minute it is as if it does not exist (1 verse: 35:13).",
      "d": "«قِطْمِیْر» (Qitmir) is the thin membrane or skin (manjad) covering the pit of a date, and by extension, it signifies an extremely negligible amount, equivalent to nothing. The idiom is «مَآ أَصَبْتُ عَنْهُ قِطْمِیْرًا» meaning 'I gained absolutely nothing from it.'\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ تَدۡعُوۡنَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِہٖ مَا یَمۡلِکُوۡنَ مِنۡ قِطۡمِیۡرٍ» (35/13)\nTranslation: 'And those you call upon besides Him do not possess even the skin of a date pit.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1009,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "A little",
      "hw": "تھوڑا",
      "s": "«فَوَاق» (Fawaq) denotes a very short period of time or a brief pause.\nNote: Similarly, in the Quran, «خَرْدَل» (a grain of mustard) and «ذَرّۃ» (a speck) also represent an extremely small quantity (1 verse: 38:15).",
      "d": "«فَوَاق» (Fawaq) is the interval between two milkings, the moment between pressing and releasing the udder. It signifies a very short time or duration.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَا یَنۡظُرُ ہٰۤؤُلَآءِ إِلَّا صَیۡحَۃً وَاحِدَۃً مَّا لَہَا مِنۡ فَوَاقٍ» (38/15)\nTranslation: 'And these [disbelievers] await only one blast [of the Horn] which will have no delay.'"
    }
  ],
  "213": [
    {
      "id": 1012,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to prepare",
      "hw": "تیار",
      "s": "«اَعَدَّ» means to complete everything and bring it forth, ready. (20 verses: 2:24, 3:131, 3:133, 4:93, 4:102, 8:60, 9:46, 9:89, 9:100, 33:8, 33:29, 33:35, 33:44, 33:57, 33:64, 48:6, 57:21, 58:15, 65:10, 76:31)",
      "d": "«اَعَدَّ» means to prepare. To bring forth ready (manj), i.e., to complete each thing one by one and present it. «عَدَّ» means to count and enumerate. «اَعَدَّ» means to complete everything related to its preparation and present it ready. For example, the Quran states: «فَاتَّقُوا النَّارَ الَّتِیۡ وَقُوۡدُہَا النَّاسُ وَ الۡحِجَارَۃُ  ۚ ۖ اُعِدَّتۡ لِلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (2:24). Translation: So fear the Fire whose fuel is men and stones, prepared for the disbelievers. Often, lexicologists include «اَعْتَدَ» under «عَدَدَ». According to Imam Raghib, «اَعْتَدْنَا» was originally «اَعْدَدْنَا». The change from the first radical (د) to (ت) made it «اَعْتَدْنَا» (muf). Thus, according to most lexicologists, «اَعَدَّ» and «اَعْتَدَ» have the same meaning."
    }
  ],
  "214": [
    {
      "id": 1014,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Arrow",
      "hw": "تیر",
      "s": "«سَھْمٌ» (Sahm) refers to an arrow used in gambling, for drawing lots, and also a general arrow (1 verse: 37:141).",
      "d": "«سَھْمٌ» (Sahm) is an arrow for gambling, for drawing lots, and also a general arrow. Its plural is «سَھَام» (Saham) and «سَاہَمَ» (Sahama) means to draw lots. «تَسَاہَمَ» (Tasahama) means to divide something among themselves by lot. «سَھْم» means a divided share, a lot, or destiny.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَسَاہَمَ فَکَانَ مِنَ الۡمُدۡحَضِیۡنَ» (37/141)\nTranslation: 'Then they drew lots, and he was among the losers.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1015,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Arrow",
      "hw": "تیر",
      "s": "«زَلَمُ» (Zalam) is a featherless arrow, a divining arrow, used for drawing lots (2 verses: 5:3, 5:90).",
      "d": "«زَلَمُ» (Zalam) is a featherless arrow, an arrow used for divination (azlam). In pre-Islamic Arabia, people used arrows to determine fate. They would write 'permission' or 'prohibition' on arrows, place them in a container, and draw one to decide on an action. If the drawn arrow had 'permission,' they proceeded; if 'prohibition,' they refrained. Its plural is «اَزْلَام» (Azlam). It is a small arrow without feathers or a nock, a gambling arrow.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِنَّمَا الۡخَمۡرُ وَ الۡمَیۡسِرُ وَ الۡاَنۡصَابُ وَ الۡاَزۡلَامُ رِجۡسٌ مِّنۡ عَمَلِ الشَّیۡطٰنِ فَاجۡتَنِبُوۡہُ لَعَلَّکُمۡ تُفۡلِحُوۡنَ» (5/90)\nTranslation: 'O you who have believed, indeed, intoxicants, gambling, [sacrificing on] stone altars, and divining arrows are but defilement from the work of Satan, so avoid it that you may be successful.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1017,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Sharp",
      "hw": "تیر",
      "s": "«سَلَقَ» (Salaqa) means to speak or act with harshness (anger) and force (power) (1 verse: 33:19).",
      "d": "«سَلَقَ» (Salaqa) means to speak or act with force and severity. «سَلَقَ الْلِسَان» (Salaqa al-lisan) means to speak sharply, to run the tongue swiftly.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاِذَا ذَہَبَ الۡخَوۡفُ سَلَقُوۡکُمۡ بِاَلۡسِنَۃٍ حِدَادٍ أَشِحَّۃً عَلَی الۡخَیۡرِ» (33/19)\nTranslation: 'Then when fear departs, they will assail you with sharp tongues, stingy toward good.'"
    }
  ],
  "215": [
    {
      "id": 1018,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Oil",
      "hw": "تیل",
      "s": "«زَیْت» (Zayt) specifically refers to olive oil.\nAnd «دُھْن» (Duhn) refers to all kinds of oil, including olive oil.\nAnd «دِھَان» (Dihan) refers to the dregs or residue of oil (6 verses: 6:99, 6:141, 16:11, 24:35, 80:29, 95:1).",
      "d": "«زَیْت» (Zayt) is the oil from the olive tree. The fruit is called «زَیْتُونَۃٌ» (Zaytunah). «زَاتَ الطَّعَام» (Zata at-ta'am) means to add olive oil to food or to season it with olive oil.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یَّکَادُ زَیۡتُہَا یُضِیۡٓءُ وَ لَوۡ لَمۡ تَمۡسَسۡہُ نَارٌ» (24/35)\nTranslation: 'Its oil would glow [with light], almost, without even touching it, fire.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1019,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Oil",
      "hw": "تیل",
      "s": "«دُھْن» (Duhn) is a general term for grease and fat (1 verse: 23:20).",
      "d": "«دُھْن» (Duhn) means oil, grease, fat. It is a general term for any kind of oil, whether plant-based or animal-based. «دَھَنَ» (Dahana) and «اَدْھَنَ» (Adhana) mean to deceive, to practice hypocrisy. «تَدَھَّنَ» (Tadahhanna) means to anoint with oil.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ شَجَرَۃً تَخۡرُجُ مِنۡ طُوۡرِ سَیۡنَآءَ تَنۡۢبُتُ بِالدُّہۡنِ» (23/20)\nTranslation: 'And [He brought forth] a tree, growing from the mount of Sinai, which produces oil and [its] seasoning.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1020,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Oil",
      "hw": "تیل",
      "s": "«دِھَان» (Dihan) is the dregs or residue of oil (the sediment that settles at the bottom) (1 verse: 55:37).",
      "d": "«دِھَان» (Dihan) means the dregs or lees of oil (the muddy or greasy sediment that settles at the bottom). It also means a slippery place, a stain, or paint.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاِذَا انۡشَقَّتِ السَّمَآءُ فَکَانَتۡ وَرۡدَۃً کَالدِّہَانِ» (55/37)\nTranslation: 'And when the heaven is split open and becomes rose-colored like oil [or: like a dye].'"
    }
  ],
  "216": [
    {
      "id": 1021,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To frown",
      "hw": "تیوری",
      "s": "«عَبَسَ» (Abasa) means for a frown to appear between the two eyes on the forehead (2 verses: 74:22, 80:1).",
      "d": "«عَبَسَ» (Abasa) means to frown, to knit the brows. It signifies a wrinkle forming on the forehead between the eyes. It conveys meanings like sternness, lack of mercy, crookedness in conduct, sullenness, and a scowling expression. This is the primary meaning.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«عَبَسَ وَ تَوَلّٰۤی أَنۡ جَآءَہُ الۡاَعۡمٰی» (80/1)\nTranslation: '[The Prophet] frowned and turned away because there came to him the blind man.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1022,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To Contort the Face",
      "hw": "تیوری",
      "s": "«کَلَحَ» refers to wrinkles appearing on the face in such a way that the shape distorts. (1 verse: 23:104)",
      "d": "«کَلَحَ» is the next degree after «عَبَسَ». Meaning: wrinkles appear on the face causing distortion of features. (F. L 139) Some scholars say it means raising the lips such that teeth become visible and the face looks ugly. (M. Q)\nFor example, the Quran states: «تَلۡفَحُ وُجُوۡہَہُمُ النَّارُ وَ ہُمۡ فِیۡہَا کٰلِحُوۡنَ» (23/104)\nTranslation: The Fire will scorch their faces, and they will be disfigured therein."
    },
    {
      "id": 1023,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To Contort the Face",
      "hw": "تیوری",
      "s": "«بَسَرَ» when the act of raising the nose/mouth (facial contortion) reaches its extreme, it is called «بَسَرَ». (1 verse: 74:22)",
      "d": "«بَسَرَ» is the final degree of «عَبَسَ». When the act of raising the nose/mouth (facial contortion) reaches its extreme, it is called «بَسَرَ». Meaning: to frown severely. (F. L 139)\nFor example, the Quran states: «ثُمَّ نَظَرَ ثُمَّ عَبَسَ وَ بَسَرَ» (74/21,22)\nTranslation: Then he looked, then he contorted his face and scowled."
    }
  ],
  "217": [
    {
      "id": 1024,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "Piece",
      "hw": "ٹکڑا",
      "s": "«جُزء» means a part of something that completes it. (3 verses: 2:260, 15:44, 43:15)",
      "d": "«جُزء» means a piece or a separated part of something. Its opposite is «کُلّ» and its plural is «اَجْزَاء». That is, the parts of something that when combined make it complete. And «جَزَءَ الشَّیْء» means dividing something into different parts. Taking a portion. (Munjid)\nFor example, the Quran states: «ثُمَّ اجۡعَلۡ عَلٰی کُلِّ جَبَلٍ مِّنۡہُنَّ جُزۡءًا» (2/260)\nTranslation: Then place a portion of them on every mountain."
    },
    {
      "id": 1026,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "Piece",
      "hw": "ٹکڑا",
      "s": "«بُقْعَۃ» is that piece of land which is distinct from others. (1 verse: 28:30)",
      "d": "According to the author of Muqayyas al-Lughah, «بُقْعَۃ» is a piece of land that is prominent from surrounding pieces. (M. L)\nFor example, the Quran states: «فَلَمَّاۤ اَتٰىہَا نُوۡدِیَ مِنۡ شَاطِیَٔ الۡوَادِ الۡاَیۡمَنِ فِی الۡبُقۡعَۃِ الۡمُبٰرَکَۃِ مِنَ الشَّجَرَۃِ» (28/30)\nTranslation: When he came to it, he was called from the right side of the valley in the blessed spot from the tree."
    },
    {
      "id": 1027,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "Piece",
      "hw": "ٹکڑا",
      "s": "«کِسَف» means pieces of porous bodies such as clouds, wool, or sky. (5 verses: 17:92, 26:187, 30:48, 34:9, 52:44)",
      "d": "«کِسَف» is the plural of «کِسْفَۃ». Meaning: pieces of porous bodies like clouds or wool (Muf) that can be easily separated and joined.\nFor example, the Quran states: «فَاَسۡقِطۡ عَلَیۡنَا کِسَفًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ اِنۡ کُنۡتَ مِنَ الصّٰدِقِیۡنَ» (26/187)\nTranslation: If you are truthful, then drop a piece from the sky upon us."
    },
    {
      "id": 1028,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "Piece",
      "hw": "ٹکڑا",
      "s": "«زُبُر» means iron sheets, leaves (of books). (8 verses: 3:184, 16:44, 18:96, 23:53, 26:196, 35:25, 54:43, 54:52)",
      "d": "«زُبُر» is the plural of «زُبْرَةُ». Meaning: large pieces of iron, iron sheets, planks (Munjid). Then it applies to any spread-out thing that has less thickness but more width. For example, sheets of paper, book leaves, scrolls, etc.\nFor example, the Quran states: «اٰتُوۡنِیۡ زُبَرَ الۡحَدِیۡدِ» (18/96)\nTranslation: So bring me iron sheets (large pieces).\nAt another place, God Almighty says: «وَ اِنَّہٗ لَفِیۡ زُبُرِ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (26/196)\nTranslation: And indeed, it is in the scriptures of the earlier peoples.\n«زُبُر» has also been used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example, God Almighty says: «فَتَقَطَّعُوۡۤا اَمۡرَہُمۡ بَیۡنَہُمۡ زُبُرًا» (23/53)\nTranslation:\n1 - Then they cut off their matter between themselves into fragments (Jalandhariؒ)\n2 - Then they broke and made their work into pieces. (Osmaniؒ)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1029,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "Piece",
      "hw": "ٹکڑا",
      "s": "«اِنْکَاث» means pieces of woven wool or felt. (6 verses: 7:135, 9:12, 9:13, 16:92, 43:50, 48:10)",
      "d": "«اِنْکَاث» is the plural of «نُکْث». Meaning: a blanket or tent that is turned upside down for re-weaving. And «نَکَّاث» refers to one who turns upside down a woven or wrapped thing (Munjid). Then, since in turning upside down, such things become damaged and torn into pieces, therefore «اِنْکَاث» means such pieces.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ لَا تَکُوۡنُوۡا کَالَّتِیۡ نَقَضَتۡ غَزۡلَہَا مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ قُوَّۃٍ اَنۡکَاثًا» (16/92)\nTranslation: And do not be like the woman who, after having spun her yarn with strength, tore it into pieces."
    },
    {
      "id": 1030,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "Piece",
      "hw": "ٹکڑا",
      "s": "«عَضِیْن» means pieces of meat, limbs. (2 verses: 3:119, 15:91)",
      "d": "«اَلْعُضْو» and «اَلْعِضْو» mean a part of the body, and its plural is «اَعْضاء». And «عَضَا یَعْضُوا» means to tear into pieces. And «اَلْعِضَۃُ» means a piece, a faction. Its plural is «عِضِیِن» and «عَضُوْن» (Munjid). And according to the author of Muqayyas al-Lughah, «عَضَنَ» means to tear something into pieces. From it comes «عُضْو» and «عِضْو». (M. L) Pieces of meat. Limbs.\nFor example, the Quran states: «الَّذِیۡنَ جَعَلُوا الۡقُرۡاٰنَ عِضِیۡنَ» (15/91)\nTranslation:\n1 - That is, they tore the Quran into pieces (by accepting some and rejecting others) (Jalandhariؒ)\n2 - Those who have made the Quran into fragments (Osmaniؒ)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1031,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "Piece",
      "hw": "ٹکڑا",
      "s": "«جُذَاذُ» means filings and small pieces of precious metals. (1 verse: 21:58)",
      "d": "«جَذَّ» means to cut, to break. And «جِذَّ» means small pieces of something cut. Its plural is «جُذَاذُ» and «جُذَّاذَات». Meaning: small pieces or filings of something cut. «جُذَاذَةُ مِنَ الْفِضَّۃ» means pieces of silver, and «جُذَاذ» also refers to gold lumps. (Munjid) So «جُذَاذُ» is used for small pieces or filings of precious metals.\nFor example, the Quran states: «فَجَعَلَہُمۡ جُذٰذًا اِلَّا کَبِیۡرًا لَّہُمۡ لَعَلَّہُمۡ اِلَیۡہِ یَرۡجِعُوۡنَ» (21/58)\nTranslation: Then he broke them into pieces, except the largest one, so that they might return to it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1032,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "Piece",
      "hw": "ٹکڑا",
      "s": "«فِرْق» generally means one part of two parts of something. (32 verses: 2:50-2:53-2:102-2:136-2:185-2:285-3:4-3:84-3:103-3:105-4:130-4:150-4:152-5:25-6:153-6:159-8:29-8:41-9:122-12:39-12:67-17:106-20:94-21:48-25:1-26:63-30:14-30:32-42:13-42:14-77:4-98:4)",
      "d": "«فِرْق» means a broken or cut piece (Munjid). It generally involves the concept of two pieces. One piece that is cut and separated. The other that remains after cutting. And «فَرْق» also refers to the middle parting of hair on the head (Munjid), and «فَرَق» refers to the gap between the two front teeth (Munjid).\nFor example, the Quran states: «فَانۡفَلَقَ فَکَانَ کُلُّ فِرۡقٍ کَالطَّوۡدِ الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (26/63)\nTranslation: Then it split, and each part became like a huge mountain.\n(For the difference between «فِرق» and «فِلق», see \"Phaarna\" (To Split).)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1033,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "portion",
      "hw": "ٹکڑا",
      "s": "«بَعْض» is used for a 'part' in contrast to the 'whole' and for an individual or some individuals in contrast to a group (86 verses: 2:36-2:73-2:76-2:85-2:145-2:251-2:253-2:259-2:283-3:34-3:50-3:64-3:155-3:195-4:19-4:21-4:25-4:32-4:34-4:150-5:49-5:51-6:53-6:65-6:112-6:128-6:129-6:158-6:165-7:24-8:37-8:72-8:73-8:75-9:67-9:71-9:127-10:46-11:12-11:54-12:10-13:4-13:36-13:40-16:71-17:21-17:55-17:88-18:19-18:99-20:123-22:40-23:44-23:91-23:113-24:40-24:58-24:62-24:63-25:20-26:198-27:72-29:25-30:41-33:6-34:31-34:42-35:40-37:27-37:50-38:22-38:24-40:28-40:77-43:32-43:63-43:67-45:19-47:4-47:26-49:2-49:12-52:25-66:3-68:30-69:44)",
      "d": "«بَعْض» is commonly used. It is also used for a 'part' of a 'whole'. For example, the Quran states: «فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبُوۡہُ بِبَعۡضِہَا» (2/73) Translation: Then we said, 'Strike him (the slaughtered cow) with some of it.' And if there is a collection of several things, it is also used for an individual. Such as «بَعْضُ الْلَیَالِی» meaning 'one of the nights' or «بَعْضُ النَّاس» meaning 'some person' (singular, as per the dictionary). For example, the Quran states: «فَاَقۡبَلَ بَعۡضُہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡعٍ یَّتَلَاوَمُوۡنَ» (68/30) Translation: Then some of them began to blame each other. Moreover, 'some' is also used in a spiritual sense. For example, the divine command states: «وَ لِاُبَیِّنَ  لَکُمۡ بَعۡضَ الَّذِیۡ تَخۡتَلِفُوۡنَ فِیۡہِ» (43/63) Translation: And to explain to you some of the matters in which you differ."
    }
  ],
  "218": [
    {
      "id": 1036,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "to collapse",
      "hw": "ٹوٹنا",
      "s": "«اِنْقَضَّ» means a building or wall etc. to collapse or develop a crack (10 verses: 2:27-4:155-5:13-8:56-13:20-13:25-16:91-16:92-18:77-94:3)",
      "d": "«نَقَضَ» means to break, and «اِنْقَضَّ» means a building or wall etc. to collapse, to crack, or to develop a fissure. And «اَلنَّقْض» means the collapsed part of a building etc. (as per the dictionary) a wall etc. cracking and having a fissure and falling to one side broken. For example, the Quran states: «فَوَجَدَا فِیۡہَا جِدَارًا یُّرِیۡدُ اَنۡ یَّنۡقَضَّ فَاَقَامَہٗ» (18/77) Translation: Then they found a wall that wanted to collapse, so he (Khidr) set it upright."
    },
    {
      "id": 1037,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "to be severed",
      "hw": "ٹوٹنا",
      "s": "«تَقَطَّعَ» means to break or be cut into pieces (8 verses: 2:166-5:33-6:94-9:110-21:93-23:53-29:29-47:22)",
      "d": "«تَقَطَّعَ» means a thing breaking or being cut apart. It is used both literally and metaphorically. For example, the Quran states: «وَ رَاَوُا  الۡعَذَابَ وَ تَقَطَّعَتۡ بِہِمُ الۡاَسۡبَابُ» (2/166) Translation: And they will see the punishment and their ties will be cut off."
    }
  ],
  "219": [
    {
      "id": 1038,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "to become cool",
      "hw": "ٹھنڈا",
      "s": "«بَرَدَ» is generally used for coolness (5 verses: 21:69-24:43-38:42-56:44-78:24)",
      "d": "«بَرَدَ» means to become cool. And «بَرْد ۔ بُرُوْدَت» means coolness or cold. And «بَرَد» means hail. «بُرِدَتِ الْاَرَض» means hail fell on the earth (as per the dictionary). And «بَارِدْ» means any cool thing. For example, the Quran states: «اُرۡکُضۡ بِرِجۡلِکَ ۚ ہٰذَا مُغۡتَسَلٌۢ  بَارِدٌ وَّ  شَرَابٌ» (38/42) Translation: 'Strike with your foot; this is a cool bath and a drink.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1039,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "to become cool (pleasant)",
      "hw": "ٹھنڈا",
      "s": "«قَرَّ» refers to coolness that is pleasant and brings comfort (7 verses: 19:26-20:40-25:74-28:9-28:13-32:17-33:51)",
      "d": "«قَرَّ الْیَوْم» means the day becomes cool. «یَوْمٌ قَرٌّ» means a cool day. «لَیْلَۃٌ قَرَّۃٌ» means a cool night. Then it is also used metaphorically. Such as «قَرَّتْ ( قُرَۃٌ وقُرَّۃٌ ) عَیْنُہٗ» means one's eyes become cool; heart's happiness and desire are fulfilled (lexically). That is, such coolness that is also pleasant, for which the word «قَرَّ» is used. For example, the Quran states: «فَکُلِیۡ وَ اشۡرَبِیۡ وَ قَرِّیۡ عَیۡنًا» (19/26) Translation: 'So eat and drink and cool your eyes.'"
    }
  ],
  "220": [
    {
      "id": 1040,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "to stop (meaning to halt)",
      "hw": "ٹھہرنا",
      "s": "«سَکَنَ» means for something to stop after movement (20 verses: 2:231-2:256-4:15-5:4-6:13-6:96-7:170-7:189-9:103-10:67-16:79-16:80-23:18-25:45-27:86-28:72-28:73-30:21-40:61-42:33-)",
      "d": "«سَکَنَ» is used for stopping after movement (lexically)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1041,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "to stop (meaning to halt)",
      "hw": "ٹھہرنا",
      "s": "«رَکَدَ» means for a moving thing to stop firmly and steadily with its support (2 verses: 42:33-53:34)",
      "d": "«رَکَدَ» means for a moving thing to stop firmly and steadily with its support. (lex.) «رَکَدَ الْمِیْزَان» means the scale becomes balanced and stops. And «رَکَدَ الَشَّمْس» means the sun appears to have stopped at its zenith. For example, the Quran states: «اِنۡ یَّشَاۡ یُسۡکِنِ الرِّیۡحَ فَیَظۡلَلۡنَ رَوَاکِدَ عَلٰی ظَہۡرِہٖ» (42/33) Translation: If He wills, He can calm the wind so that they remain motionless on its surface."
    },
    {
      "id": 1042,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "to stop (meaning to halt)",
      "hw": "ٹھہرنا",
      "s": "«جَمَدَ» means to become completely still; for inanimate objects to have a permanent stop (1 verse: 27:88)",
      "d": "«جَمَدَ» means for inanimate objects to be completely senseless and motionless. «جَمَدَ الْمَاء» means water freezes. And «جَمَدَ الدَّمْ» means blood dries up. And «جَمْد» means frozen water. For example, the Quran states: «وَ تَرَی الۡجِبَالَ تَحۡسَبُہَا جَامِدَۃً  وَّ  ہِیَ تَمُرُّ مَرَّ السَّحَابِ» (27/88) Translation: And you see the mountains, thinking them solid, but they will pass like the passing of clouds."
    },
    {
      "id": 1043,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "to stop (meaning to halt)",
      "hw": "ٹھہرنا",
      "s": "«رَھْوًا» means the surface of water becoming calm, or an open space between two stable things (1 verse: 44:24)",
      "d": "«رَھْوًا» means the cessation of waves and surges on the sea or water surface (as per the dictionary). Alternatively, it means an open space or path between two elevations (lex.). This word appears only once in the Quran and conveys both meanings. For example, the Quran states: «وَ اتۡرُکِ  الۡبَحۡرَ رَہۡوًا» (44/24) Translation: And leave the sea as a calm expanse."
    },
    {
      "id": 1044,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "to stop (meaning to halt)",
      "hw": "ٹھہرنا",
      "s": "«قَرَّ» means for something to settle in a place; to remain stopped for some time (1 verse: 22:5)",
      "d": "«قَرَّ» means to settle in a place (as per the dictionary); to become stationary. For example, the Quran states: «وَ نُقِرُّ  فِی الۡاَرۡحَامِ مَا نَشَآءُ  اِلٰۤی اَجَلٍ مُّسَمًّی» (22/5) Translation: And We settle in the wombs whatever We will for a specified term."
    },
    {
      "id": 1045,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "to stop (meaning to halt)",
      "hw": "ٹھہرنا",
      "s": "«وَقَفَ» To stop in the middle of an action, to take a brief pause (7 verses: 2:87-5:46-6:27-6:30-34:31-37:24-57:27)",
      "d": "«وَقَفَ» To stand still, without movement or sensation (intransitive). To stop in the middle of an action for a short while (e.g., like a bus stopping), or a pause after which the initial movement or action is expected. This word is used both as intransitive and transitive.\nIntransitive example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ تَرٰۤی اِذۡ  وُقِفُوۡا عَلٰی رَبِّہِمۡ» ( 6/30 )\nTranslation: And if you could see when they are made to stand before their Lord.\nTransitive (meaning to make someone stop):\nFor example: The Divine command states:\n«وَ قِفُوۡہُمۡ   اِنَّہُمۡ  مَّسۡئُوۡلُوۡنَ» ( 37/24 )\nTranslation: And make them wait; indeed, they will be questioned."
    },
    {
      "id": 1046,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "to reside (meaning to inhabit)",
      "hw": "ٹھہرنا",
      "s": "«لَبِثَ» Used to mean residing for a very long period (26 verses: 2:259-10:16-10:45-11:69-12:42-17:52-17:76-18:12-18:19-18:25-18:26-20:40-20:103-20:104-23:112-23:113-23:114-26:18-29:14-30:55-30:56-33:14-34:14-37:144-46:35-79:46)",
      "d": "«لَبِثَ» Meaning to settle and remain permanently in a place (intransitive).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَبِثُوۡا فِیۡ  کَہۡفِہِمۡ ثَلٰثَ مِائَۃٍ سِنِیۡنَ وَ ازۡدَادُوۡا  تِسۡعًا» ( 18/25 )\nTranslation: And they remained in their cave for three hundred years and added nine."
    },
    {
      "id": 1047,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "to reside (meaning to inhabit)",
      "hw": "ٹھہرنا",
      "s": "«مَکَثَ» Used to mean waiting in a place (7 verses: 13:17-17:106-18:3-20:10-27:22-28:29-43:77)",
      "d": "«مَکَثَ» To wait in a place (intransitive).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَقَالَ  لِاَہۡلِہِ  امۡکُثُوۡۤا  اِنِّیۡۤ اٰنَسۡتُ نَارًا» ( 20/10 )\nTranslation: Moses said to his family, 'Wait here; indeed, I have perceived a fire.'\nAt another instance, the Divine command states:\n«فَمَکَثَ غَیۡرَ بَعِیۡدٍ» ( 27/22 )\nTranslation: Then he (the hoopoe) stayed not but a little while.\nAt a third instance:\n«وَ قُرۡاٰنًا فَرَقۡنٰہُ لِتَقۡرَاَہٗ  عَلَی النَّاسِ عَلٰی  مُکۡثٍ» ( 17/106 )\nTranslation: And a Quran which We have divided, that you may recite it to mankind at intervals.\nHowever, later this word deviated from its original meaning and became synonymous with «لَبِثَ».\nFor example:\n«مَّاکِثِیۡنَ فِیۡہِ اَبَدًا» ( 18/3 )\nTranslation: They will abide therein forever."
    },
    {
      "id": 1048,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "to reside (meaning to inhabit)",
      "hw": "ٹھہرنا",
      "s": "«عَکَفَ» To reside in a sacred place for worship.\nNote: See also «سَکَنَ، خَلَدَ» etc. (8 verses: 2:125-2:187-7:138-20:91-20:97-21:52-22:25-26:71)",
      "d": "«عَکَفَ» Meaning to turn towards something with reverence and remain attached to it (intransitive), and also meaning to seclude oneself, to improve oneself, and to keep oneself (from sins) (transitive). That is, to reside and remain in a sacred place for worship.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تُبَاشِرُوۡہُنَّ وَ اَنۡتُمۡ عٰکِفُوۡنَ  ۙ فِی الۡمَسٰجِدِ» ( 2/187 )\nTranslation: And do not approach them (your wives) while you are in a state of i'tikaf (seclusion) in the mosques."
    }
  ],
  "221": [
    {
      "id": 1049,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "elevated land and its types",
      "hw": "ٹیلہ",
      "s": "«رَبْوَۃ» means elevated, soft, sandy land. (2 verses: 2:265, 23:50)",
      "d": "«رَبْوَۃ» means a high and elevated place with ups and downs (i.e., uneven terrain) (m. r). «رَبَا ، یَرْبُوا» means to increase and flourish. «رَبْوَۃً» refers to sandy land whose surface is elevated and is generally a lush, green place. For example, the Quran states: « کَمَثَلِ جَنَّۃٍۭ بِرَبۡوَۃٍ اَصَابَہَا وَابِلٌ فَاٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا ضِعۡفَیۡنِ» (2:265). Translation: Like a garden on elevated ground, upon which heavy rain falls and it yields its fruits double."
    },
    {
      "id": 1051,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "hill and its types",
      "hw": "ٹیلہ",
      "s": "«حَدَبَ» A hill that is wider in extent but lower in height (1 verse: 21:96)",
      "d": "«حَدَبَ» Its literal meaning is prominence and crookedness. And metaphorically, it is also used for high and hard land of this shape (intransitive). That is, a hill that is wider in extent but lower in height. «مُحَدَّب» is the opposite of «مُجَوَّف». Concave lenses used for correcting near and farsightedness are called «عَدْسَہ» because they are bulging out on both sides like the shape of a lentil seed.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا  فُتِحَتۡ یَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ مَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ ہُمۡ  مِّنۡ  کُلِّ  حَدَبٍ  یَّنۡسِلُوۡنَ» ( 21/96 )\nTranslation: Until when Gog and Magog are released, and they swoop down from every elevated place."
    },
    {
      "id": 1052,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "Hill and its Types",
      "hw": "ٹیلہ",
      "s": "«رِیَعَ» refers to valleys between mountains that are suitable for habitation (1 verse: 26/128)",
      "d": "«رِیَعَ» is the plural of «رِیْعَۃ». It means a high valley. Valleys between mountains suitable for habitation (m. r.) and «رِیْعَۃ» means a high hill. The place from which water flows due to the valley's height. A wide mountain path (manjad). For example, the Quran states: «اَتَبۡنُوۡنَ بِکُلِّ رِیۡعٍ  اٰیَۃً  تَعۡبَثُوۡنَ» (26/128). Translation: Do you build a monument on every high place to amuse yourselves?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1053,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "hill and its types",
      "hw": "ٹیلہ",
      "s": "«اَحْقَاف» Sand dunes; long and winding hills of sand (1 verse: 46:21)",
      "d": "«اَحْقَاف» is the plural of «حَقَفَ». Meaning a sandy, uneven (high and low) hill (intransitive). A long and winding hill of sand, i.e., a sand dune. And «اَحْقَاف» also means sand hills. A desert. The name of a desert.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اذۡکُرۡ  اَخَا عَادٍ ؕ اِذۡ  اَنۡذَرَ قَوۡمَہٗ بِالۡاَحۡقَافِ» ( 46/21 )\nTranslation: And remember the brother of 'Ad, when he warned his people in the Ahqaf (the sand dunes)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1054,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "hill and its types",
      "hw": "ٹیلہ",
      "s": "«نَجَدَ» A mountain pass and the path to ascend and descend it (1 verse: 90:10)",
      "d": "«نَجَدَ» High and hard land. It is used for a hill and also for a ridge (according to Manjad). Meaning a small mountain.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ ہَدَیۡنٰہُ  النَّجۡدَیۡنِ فَلَا  اقۡتَحَمَ الۡعَقَبَۃَ» ( 90/10،11 )\nTranslation: And We have shown him the two highways (of good and evil), but he has not ascended the steep path."
    }
  ],
  "222": [
    {
      "id": 1055,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "Crookedness (Bent) to be Crooked",
      "hw": "ٹیڑھا",
      "s": "«عِوَجَ» means the upper part of a vertical object, such as a wall or tree, being crooked. In a metaphorical sense, it means complexity, entanglement, or ambiguity (9 verses: 3:99-7:45-7:86-11:19-14:3-18:1-20:107-20:108-39:28)",
      "d": "«عِوَجَ» refers to the top part of a standing object like a wall or tree being crooked. «اَعْوَج» means a person with a crooked gait. «اَلْعَرْج» is the crookedness visible to the outward eye, while «اَلْعِوَج» is the crookedness perceived by reason and insight (muf). However, the following verse suggests otherwise. And Allah knows best! The Divine declaration states: «لَّا  تَرٰی  فِیۡہَا عِوَجًا  وَّ  لَاۤ   اَمۡتًا» (20/107). Translation: Wherein you will see no unevenness or roughness. «عِوَجَ» and «أَمْتُ» are antonymous words. They mean high and low, and these two words are synonymous or interchangeable (m. l). However, «عِوَجَ» has a broad meaning. In physical objects, it means unevenness and bends; in metaphorical things, it means complexity, entanglement, or ambiguity. For example, the Quran states: «اَلۡحَمۡدُ لِلّٰہِ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَنۡزَلَ عَلٰی عَبۡدِہِ الۡکِتٰبَ  وَ لَمۡ  یَجۡعَلۡ  لَّہٗ عِوَجًا» (18/1). Translation: All praise is for Allah who sent down the Book upon His servant (Muhammad ﷺ) and made it free from all crookedness."
    },
    {
      "id": 1056,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "Crookedness (Deviation) To Become Crooked",
      "hw": "ٹیڑھا",
      "s": "«زَیْغ» is used for crookedness in angle of vision and viewpoints (6 verses: 3:7, 9:117, 33:10, 38:63, 53:17, 61:5)",
      "d": "«زَاغَ» means to deviate from the path of truth. «زَاغَ الْبَصَر» means the sight became weary (manjad) and, according to Imam Raghib, the sight erred and turned aside (muf). This word is generally used in a spiritual sense, and its meaning is a change in angle of vision or point of view, crookedness, and deviation.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ زَیۡغٌ فَیَتَّبِعُوۡنَ مَا تَشَابَہَ مِنۡہُ» (3/7)\nTranslation: Then as for those in whose hearts is deviation, they follow the ambiguous parts of it.\nAt another place, the Lord Almighty declares:\n«فَلَمَّا زَاغُوۡۤا اَزَاغَ اللّٰہُ قُلُوۡبَہُمۡ» (61/5)\nTranslation: So when they deviated, Allah made their hearts deviate."
    },
    {
      "id": 1058,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "Crookedness (Deviation) To Become Crooked",
      "hw": "ٹیڑھا",
      "s": "«جَوْر» is used for straying (going astray) in the implementation of Shariah commands (1 verse: 16:9)",
      "d": "«جَارَ» means «مَیْل عَنِ الطَّرِیْق» (m. l.), i.e., to incline to one side from the path, and also means to stop at the commands of Shariah (manjad). This crookedness (deviation) relates to deviating from and disobeying the commands of Shariah (faqila 199). And «جَائِر» means inclined to one side, leaning towards excess.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ قَصۡدُ السَّبِیۡلِ وَ مِنۡہَا جَآئِرٌ» (16/9)\nTranslation: And upon Allah lies the direction of the path, and some of them are crooked (i.e., they do not reach it) (Jalandhariؒ)."
    }
  ],
  "223": [
    {
      "id": 1060,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "To Lean (To Rely On)",
      "hw": "ٹیک ",
      "s": "«اِتَّکَاَ» comes for leaning on any thing (9 verses: 18:31, 36:56, 38:51, 43:34, 52:20, 55:54, 55:76, 56:16, 76:13)",
      "d": "«اَتْکَاَ» means to make something a support for someone. And «اَتْکَاَ عَلَی الشَّیْ» means to take support, to lean on. «تَوَکَّاَ عَلَی الْعَصَا» means he leaned on the staff. And «تَکَاَۃٌ» means that on which one leans, e.g., a staff, sword, bow, etc. And «اِتَّکَاَ» means to sit while leaning (manjad. m. q).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«مُّتَّکِئِیۡنَ فِیۡہَا عَلَی الۡاَرَآئِکِ» (76/13)\nTranslation: They will be reclining in it (Paradise) on thrones."
    },
    {
      "id": 1061,
      "a": "ٹ",
      "h": "To Lean (To Rely On)",
      "hw": "ٹیک ",
      "s": "«اِرْتَفَقَ» comes specifically for leaning on comfortable things (3 verses: 18:16, 18:29, 18:31)",
      "d": "«مِرْفَق» means elbow and every thing from which support is taken. And «مِرْفَقَۃ» means a small support or cushion. And «اِرْتَفَقَ» means to lean on the elbow or support. And «مُرْتَفَق» is a place where supports are placed and all kinds of comfort are available (manjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«نِعۡمَ الثَّوَابُ ؕ وَ حَسُنَتۡ مُرۡتَفَقًا» (18/31)\nTranslation: What an excellent reward! And what a beautiful place of rest!"
    }
  ],
  "224": [
    {
      "id": 1062,
      "a": "ث",
      "h": "To Be Established / True",
      "hw": "ثابت",
      "s": "«حَقَّ» is used for truth, veracity (252 verses: 2:26, 2:42, 2:61, 2:71, 2:91, 2:109, 2:119, 2:121, 2:144, 2:146, 2:147, 2:149, 2:176, 2:180, 2:213, 2:236, 2:241, 2:252, 2:282, 3:3, 3:21, 3:60, 3:62, 3:71, 3:86, 3:102, 3:108, 3:112, 3:154, 3:181, 4:105, 4:122, 4:151, 4:155, 4:170, 4:171, 5:27, 5:48, 5:77, 5:83, 5:84, 5:107, 5:116, 6:5, 6:30, 6:57, 6:62, 6:66, 6:73, 6:91, 6:93, 6:114, 6:141, 6:151, 7:8, 7:30, 7:33, 7:43, 7:44, 7:53, 7:89, 7:105, 7:118, 7:146, 7:159, 7:169, 7:181, 8:4, 8:5, 8:6, 8:7, 8:8, 8:32, 8:74, 9:29, 9:33, 9:48, 9:111, 10:4, 10:5, 10:23, 10:30, 10:32, 10:33, 10:35, 10:36, 10:53, 10:55, 10:76, 10:77, 10:82, 10:94, 10:96, 10:103, 10:108, 11:17, 11:45, 11:79, 11:120, 12:51, 12:100, 13:1, 13:14, 13:17, 13:19, 14:19, 14:22, 15:8, 15:55, 15:64, 15:85, 16:3, 16:36, 16:38, 16:102, 17:16, 17:26, 17:33, 17:81, 17:105, 18:13, 18:21, 18:29, 18:44, 18:56, 18:98, 19:34, 20:114, 21:18, 21:24, 21:55, 21:97, 21:112, 22:6, 22:18, 22:40, 22:54, 22:62, 22:74, 22:78, 23:41, 23:62, 23:70, 23:71, 23:90, 23:116, 24:25, 24:49, 25:26, 25:33, 25:68, 27:79, 28:3, 28:13, 28:39, 28:48, 28:53, 28:63, 28:75, 29:44, 29:68, 30:8, 30:38, 30:47, 30:60, 31:9, 31:30, 31:33, 32:3, 32:13, 33:4, 33:53, 34:6, 34:23, 34:26, 34:43, 34:48, 34:49, 35:5, 35:24, 35:31, 36:7, 36:70, 37:31, 37:37, 38:14, 38:22, 38:26, 38:64, 38:84, 39:2, 39:5, 39:19, 39:41, 39:67, 39:69, 39:71, 39:75, 40:5, 40:6, 40:20, 40:25, 40:55, 40:75, 40:77, 40:78, 41:15, 41:25, 41:53, 42:17, 42:18, 42:24, 42:42, 43:29, 43:30, 43:78, 43:86, 44:39, 45:6, 45:22, 45:29, 45:32, 46:3, 46:7, 46:17, 46:18, 46:20, 46:30, 46:34, 47:2, 47:3, 48:27, 48:28, 50:5, 50:14, 50:19, 50:42, 51:19, 51:23, 53:28, 56:95, 57:16, 57:27, 60:1, 61:9, 64:3, 69:51, 70:24, 78:39, 84:2, 84:5, 103:3)",
      "d": "«حَقَّ» means to be established, to be binding (manjad). Its opposite is «بَطَلَ» (m. l). And «حَقٌّ» means an established statement, truth, fidelity. Its opposite is «بَاطِل».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَفَسَقُوۡا فِیۡہَا فَحَقَّ عَلَیۡہَا الۡقَوۡلُ فَدَمَّرۡنٰہَا تَدۡمِیۡرًا» (17/16)\nTranslation: So they committed evil deeds therein. Then the word [of punishment] was established against it, and We destroyed it completely."
    },
    {
      "id": 1063,
      "a": "ث",
      "h": "To Be Established / True",
      "hw": "ثابت",
      "s": "«حَصْحَص» is for a truth that remained hidden due to some pressure (1 verse: 12:51)",
      "d": "«حَصْحَص» means a truth that remained hidden due to some pressure, and then after the pressure is lifted or ends, it becomes clearly apparent (muf). The manifestation of truth after it remained hidden (manjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالَتِ امۡرَاَتُ الۡعَزِیۡزِ الۡئٰنَ حَصۡحَصَ الۡحَقُّ ۫ اَنَا رَاوَدۡتُّہٗ عَنۡ نَّفۡسِہٖ» (12/51)\nTranslation: The wife of Al-Aziz said, \"Now the truth has become manifest. Indeed, it was I who sought to seduce him.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 1064,
      "a": "ث",
      "h": "To Remain Steadfast / To Hold Firm",
      "hw": "ثابت",
      "s": "«ثَبَتَ» means to remain firm on something (13 verses: 2:250, 3:147, 8:11, 8:12, 8:45, 11:120, 13:39, 14:24, 14:27, 16:102, 17:74, 25:32, 47:7)",
      "d": "«ثَبَتَ» means to become firm on something, to remain in one's place, to be steadfast. Its opposite is «زَلَّ».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا لَقِیۡتُمۡ فِئَۃً فَاثۡبُتُوۡا» (8/45)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when you meet a force, stand firm."
    },
    {
      "id": 1065,
      "a": "ث",
      "h": "To Remain Steadfast / To Hold Firm",
      "hw": "ثابت",
      "s": "«اِسْتَقَام» means to proceed on a correct path and remain steadfast, to adopt constancy (perpetuity) on it (4 verses: 9:7, 41:30, 46:13, 72:16)",
      "d": "«قَامَ عَلَی الْاَمْر» means to remain firm on a matter or statement. And «اَقَاَمَ الشَّئْ» means to make something stand or straight. And «اِسْتَقَام» means to keep something established and ongoing, and to be constant (manjad). Also, «اِسْتَقَام» means to walk on the straight path and remain steadfast on it (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ قَالُوۡا رَبُّنَا اللّٰہُ ثُمَّ اسۡتَقَامُوۡا فَلَا خَوۡفٌ عَلَیۡہِمۡ وَ لَا ہُمۡ یَحۡزَنُوۡنَ» (46/13)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who have said, \"Our Lord is Allah,\" and then remained steadfast—no fear will there be concerning them, nor will they grieve."
    },
    {
      "id": 1066,
      "a": "ث",
      "h": "To Remain Steadfast / To Hold Firm",
      "hw": "ثابت",
      "s": "«اِصْطَبَرَ» means to present a chest like a shield before calamities and hardships and to make it a habit (3 verses: 19:65, 20:132, 54:27)",
      "d": "«صَابَرَ» and «صَبَرَ» mean to restrain oneself from impermissible acts at the time of distress or calamity (muf). Its opposite is «جَزَعَ». And «صَبَرَ الدَّایَۃ» means to keep an animal tied without fodder. «صَابَرَ» means to advise someone to remain steadfast and be patient (manjad). And «اِصْطَبِر» means to make a habit of presenting a chest like a shield before calamities and hardships, to be constant on it, to be resolute.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اۡمُرۡ اَہۡلَکَ بِالصَّلٰوۃِ وَ اصۡطَبِرۡ عَلَیۡہَا» (20/132)\nTranslation: And enjoin upon your people prayer, and be constant in it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1067,
      "a": "ث",
      "h": "To Remain Steadfast / To Hold Firm",
      "hw": "ثابت",
      "s": "«رَابَطَ» means to remain steadfast on a task whose stability and protection is necessary (5 verses: 3:200, 8:11, 8:60, 18:14, 28:10)",
      "d": "«رَبَطَ الْفَرَس» means to tie a horse for protection at a place. And «رَبَاط» is that station where protective detachments remain, a sentry post, a fortress. «رَبَاطَ الجَّیْش» means to station an army at a place (muf). And «رَابَطَ الْجَّیْش» means to keep the army permanently encamped at the enemy's border. And «رَابَطَ اْلاَمْرَ» means to adopt constancy on a matter (manjad). So, «رَابَطَ» will come for adopting constancy on a task related to its protection and strength.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا اصۡبِرُوۡا وَ صَابِرُوۡا وَ رَابِطُوۡا» (3/200)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, persevere and endure and remain stationed [in readiness] (Jalandhariؒ).\nAnd for holding firm, «ثَبَّتَ» is used.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ کُلًّا نَّقُصُّ عَلَیۡکَ مِنۡ اَنۡۢبَآءِ الرُّسُلِ مَا نُثَبِّتُ بِہٖ فُؤَادَکَ» (11/120)\nTranslation: And each [story] We relate to you from the news of the messengers is that by which We strengthen your heart."
    }
  ],
  "225": [
    {
      "id": 1068,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To Spy",
      "hw": "جاسوسی",
      "s": "«تَجَسَّس» generally carries a negative meaning. It means to search for someone's faults and to investigate them, by any means (1 verse: 49/12)",
      "d": "«جَسّ» means to touch with the hand to find out. «جَسَّ بِعَیْنِہٖ» means to look intently or stare. «جَسَّسَ» and «تَجَسَّس» mean to investigate, to search for someone's faults, to be on their trail. It is generally used in a negative sense. «جَسِیْس» means a spy (m. q). For example, the Quran states: «وَّ لَا تَجَسَّسُوۡا وَ لَا یَغۡتَبۡ بَّعۡضُکُمۡ بَعۡضًا» (49/12). Translation: And do not spy or backbite one another."
    },
    {
      "id": 1069,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To Spy",
      "hw": "جاسوسی",
      "s": "«سَمَّاع» is a person who eavesdrops to spy and then informs others (3 verses: 5:41-5:42-9:47)",
      "d": "«سَمِعَ» means to hear. «سَامِع» means a listener. «سَمَّاع» means one who secretly listens to spy on others; a spy (m. q). For example, the Quran states: «سَمّٰعُوۡنَ لِلۡکَذِبِ سَمّٰعُوۡنَ لِقَوۡمٍ اٰخَرِیۡنَ ۙ  لَمۡ  یَاۡتُوۡکَ» (5/41). Translation: They are listeners to falsehood, listeners for other people who have not come to you."
    }
  ],
  "226": [
    {
      "id": 1070,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To Know",
      "hw": "جاننا",
      "s": "«عَلِمَ» means to know something correctly and accurately (448 verses: 2:13-2:22-2:26-2:30-2:32-2:33-2:42-2:75-2:77-2:78-2:80-2:101-2:102-2:103-2:106-2:107-2:113-2:118-2:120-2:140-2:143-2:144-2:145-2:146-2:151-2:169-2:184-2:188-2:194-2:196-2:197-2:203-2:209-2:216-2:220-2:223-2:230-2:231-2:232-2:233-2:235-2:239-2:244-2:247-2:255-2:259-2:260-2:267-2:270-2:280-3:7-3:18-3:19-3:29-3:36-3:61-3:66-3:71-3:75-3:78-3:135-3:140-3:142-3:166-3:167-4:25-4:43-4:45-4:63-4:83-4:113-4:157-4:162-4:166-5:34-5:40-5:49-5:61-5:92-5:94-5:97-5:98-5:99-5:104-5:109-5:113-5:116-6:3-6:33-6:37-6:50-6:53-6:58-6:59-6:60-6:67-6:80-6:81-6:91-6:97-6:100-6:105-6:108-6:114-6:117-6:119-6:124-6:135-6:140-6:143-6:144-6:148-7:7-7:28-7:32-7:33-7:38-7:52-7:62-7:75-7:89-7:123-7:131-7:182-7:187-7:188-8:24-8:25-8:27-8:28-8:34-8:40-8:41-8:60-8:70-9:2-9:3-9:6-9:11-9:16-9:36-9:41-9:42-9:43-9:63-9:78-9:93-9:97-9:101-9:104-9:123-10:5-10:18-10:39-10:40-10:55-10:68-10:89-10:93-11:5-11:6-11:14-11:31-11:39-11:46-11:47-11:49-11:79-11:93-12:21-12:22-12:40-12:46-12:51-12:52-12:68-12:73-12:76-12:77-12:80-12:81-12:86-12:89-12:96-13:8-13:19-13:33-13:37-13:42-13:43-14:9-14:38-14:52-15:3-15:24-15:96-15:97-16:8-16:19-16:23-16:25-16:27-16:38-16:39-16:41-16:43-16:55-16:56-16:70-16:74-16:75-16:78-16:91-16:95-16:101-16:103-16:125-17:12-17:25-17:36-17:47-17:54-17:55-17:84-17:85-17:102-17:107-18:5-18:12-18:19-18:21-18:22-18:26-18:65-19:43-19:65-19:70-19:75-20:7-20:52-20:71-20:98-20:104-20:110-20:114-20:135-21:4-21:7-21:24-21:28-21:39-21:65-21:74-21:79-21:110-22:3-22:5-22:8-22:54-22:68-22:70-22:71-22:76-23:84-23:88-23:96-23:114-24:15-24:19-24:25-24:29-24:31-24:33-24:63-24:64-25:6-25:42-26:49-26:112-26:132-26:188-26:197-26:227-27:15-27:25-27:40-27:42-27:52-27:61-27:65-27:66-27:74-27:84-28:13-28:14-28:37-28:38-28:50-28:56-28:57-28:69-28:75-28:78-28:80-28:85-29:3-29:8-29:10-29:11-29:16-29:32-29:41-29:42-29:45-29:49-29:52-29:64-29:66-30:6-30:7-30:29-30:30-30:34-30:56-30:59-31:6-31:15-31:20-31:25-31:34-32:17-33:5-33:18-33:50-33:51-33:63-34:2-34:6-34:14-34:21-34:28-34:36-35:11-36:16-36:26-36:36-36:76-37:158-37:170-38:69-38:88-39:9-39:26-39:29-39:39-39:49-39:52-39:70-40:7-40:19-40:42-40:57-40:70-40:83-41:3-41:22-41:47-42:14-42:18-42:25-42:35-43:20-43:61-43:85-43:86-43:89-44:32-44:39-45:17-45:18-45:23-45:24-45:26-46:4-46:8-46:23-47:16-47:19-47:26-47:30-47:31-48:25-48:27-49:7-49:16-49:18-50:16-50:45-52:47-53:28-53:30-53:32-53:35-54:26-56:61-56:76-57:4-57:17-57:20-57:25-57:29-58:7-58:11-58:14-60:1-60:10-61:5-61:11-62:9-63:1-63:8-64:4-65:12-67:14-67:17-67:26-67:29-68:7-68:33-68:44-69:49-70:39-71:4-72:24-72:28-73:20-74:31-78:4-78:5-82:12-84:23-87:7-96:5-96:14-100:9-102:3-102:4-102:5)",
      "d": "«عَلِمَ» means to perceive the reality of something, to know, to find out (muf). For example, the Quran states: «قَدۡ عَلِمَ کُلُّ اُنَاسٍ مَّشۡرَبَہُمۡ» (2/60). Translation: Every tribe came to know its watering place."
    },
    {
      "id": 1071,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To Know",
      "hw": "جاننا",
      "s": "«اَدْرٰی» means to have knowledge of something indirectly, i.e., through a means (28 verses: 4:11-10:16-21:109-21:111-31:34-33:63-42:17-42:52-45:32-46:9-65:1-69:3-69:26-72:10-72:25-74:27-77:14-80:3-82:17-82:18-83:8-83:19-86:2-90:12-97:2-101:3-101:10-104:5)",
      "d": "«اَدْرٰی» means to know, to understand. To have knowledge of something through another thing, a means, a plan, or a trick (muf). This knowledge is imperfect (weak) because it is obtained indirectly. And it is always accompanied by a negative particle like «لَا», «مَا», or an interrogative «اِنْ». For example, the Quran states: «قُلۡ  اِنۡ  اَدۡرِیۡۤ  اَقَرِیۡبٌ مَّا تُوۡعَدُوۡنَ اَمۡ  یَجۡعَلُ  لَہٗ  رَبِّیۡۤ   اَمَدًا» (72/25). Translation: Say, 'I do not know whether what you are promised is near or whether my Lord will appoint for it a distant term.' At another place, the Divine declaration states: «وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا ہِیَہۡ نَارٌ حَامِیَۃٌ» (101/10,11). Translation: And do you know what the Crusher is? It is a blazing Fire. Similarly, at another place, the Divine declaration states: «لَا تَدۡرِیۡ  لَعَلَّ اللّٰہَ  یُحۡدِثُ بَعۡدَ ذٰلِکَ  اَمۡرًا» (65/1). Translation: You do not know; perhaps Allah will bring about after that a change of circumstances."
    },
    {
      "id": 1072,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To Know",
      "hw": "جاننا",
      "s": "«اَحَسَّ» means to know something through outward senses (2 verses: 3:52-21:12)",
      "d": "«اَحَسَّ» means to reach or know something through the sense of touch (muf). To know something through the five outward senses, to perceive. It can be called 'near knowledge' (muf). For example, the Quran states: «فَلَمَّاۤ  اَحَسَّ عِیۡسٰی مِنۡہُمُ الۡکُفۡرَ» (3/52). Translation: Then when Jesus perceived their disbelief..."
    }
  ],
  "227": [
    {
      "id": 1074,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Side (Direction)",
      "hw": "جانب",
      "s": "«طَرْف» means the farthest limit or edge of something (6 verses: 3:127-11:114-13:41-20:130-21:44-42:45)",
      "d": "«طَرْف» means the farthest limit or edge of something, and its plural is «اَطْرَاف» (muf, m, l). The word «طَرْف» is not typically used for direction in Arabic; however, its usage is common in Urdu. In the Quran, wherever this word appears, it is in the meaning of the farthest limit or edge. Or it refers to the limit of sight and vision. For example, the Quran states: «وَ اَقِمِ الصَّلٰوۃَ طَرَفَیِ النَّہَارِ وَ زُلَفًا مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ» (11/114). Translation: And establish prayer at the two ends of the day and at the approach of the night. At another place, the Divine declaration states: «یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ مِنۡ طَرۡفٍ خَفِیٍّ» (42/45). Translation: They will be looking with a subdued glance."
    },
    {
      "id": 1076,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Side (Direction)",
      "hw": "جانب",
      "s": "«شَطْر» means to face something from a distant and remote place (3 verses: 2:144-2:149-2:150)",
      "d": "«شَطْر» has two primary meanings: (1) «نِصْفُ الشَّئْ» meaning half of something. (2) «اَلْبُعْد وَالْمَوَاجِھَۃ» (m, l), i.e., in «شَطْر», besides being opposite, distance is also necessary. Whereas in «وِجْھَۃ», distance is not necessary; facing from a distant place towards a specific direction is sufficient. For example, the Quran states: «وَ مِنۡ حَیۡثُ خَرَجۡتَ فَوَلِّ وَجۡہَکَ شَطۡرَ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ» (2/149). Translation: And from wherever you go out, turn your face toward the Sacred Mosque."
    },
    {
      "id": 1077,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Side (Direction)",
      "hw": "جانب",
      "s": "«تِلْقَائَ» means towards the front, to be opposite something (3 verses: 7:47-10:15-28:22)",
      "d": "«لَقِیَ» means to come before something and to find it (muf, manjad). «تِلْقَاءِ ، لِقَاء» is a verbal noun meaning the place of meeting. Like «جَلَسَ تِلْقَاءَہٗ» means he sat opposite him. «فَعَلَ الْاَمْرُ مِنْ تِلْقَاءِ نَفْسِہٖ» means he did the action of his own accord; no one forced him (manjad). For example, the Quran states: «قُلۡ مَا یَکُوۡنُ لِیۡۤ اَنۡ اُبَدِّلَہٗ  مِنۡ تِلۡقَآیِٔ  نَفۡسِیۡ» (10/15). Translation: Say, 'It is not for me to alter it from my own inclination.' That is, I cannot change it of my own will. At another place, the Divine declaration states: «وَ لَمَّا تَوَجَّہَ  تِلۡقَآءَ مَدۡیَنَ» (28/22). Translation: And when he turned his face toward Madyan..."
    },
    {
      "id": 1078,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "side (direction)",
      "hw": "جانب",
      "s": "«قِبَلَ» means towards the front, the direction in which something is visible. (21 Verses: 2:142-2:143-2:144-2:145-2:177-6:111-10:87-12:26-12:71-18:55-27:37-28:31-37:27-37:50-37:94-46:24-51:29-52:25-57:13-68:30-70:36)",
      "d": "«قِبَلَ» also means confrontation, and for one thing to be in front of another. It is as if «قِبَل» is that side which is visible in front.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«لَیۡسَ الۡبِرَّ اَنۡ تُوَلُّوۡا وُجُوۡہَکُمۡ  قِبَلَ الۡمَشۡرِقِ وَ الۡمَغۡرِبِ وَ لٰکِنَّ الۡبِرَّ مَنۡ اٰمَنَ بِاللّٰہِ وَ الۡیَوۡمِ الۡاٰخِرِ» ( 2/177 )\nTranslation: Righteousness is not that you turn your faces toward the east or the west, but righteousness is in one who believes in Allah and the Last Day..."
    }
  ],
  "228": [
    {
      "id": 1079,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "when",
      "hw": "جب",
      "s": "«اِذْ» comes for the remembrance of a past event. (218 Verses: 2:30-2:34-2:49-2:50-2:51-2:53-2:54-2:55-2:58-2:60-2:61-2:63-2:67-2:72-2:83-2:84-2:93-2:124-2:125-2:126-2:127-2:131-2:133-2:165-2:166-2:246-2:258-2:260-3:8-3:35-3:42-3:44-3:45-3:55-3:80-3:81-3:103-3:121-3:122-3:124-3:152-3:153-3:164-3:187-4:64-4:72-4:108-5:7-5:11-5:20-5:27-5:110-5:111-5:112-5:116-6:27-6:30-6:43-6:71-6:74-6:91-6:93-6:144-7:5-7:12-7:69-7:74-7:80-7:86-7:89-7:141-7:160-7:161-7:163-7:164-7:167-7:171-7:172-8:7-8:9-8:11-8:12-8:17-8:26-8:30-8:32-8:42-8:43-8:44-8:48-8:49-8:50-9:25-9:40-9:115-10:61-10:71-12:4-12:8-12:51-12:89-12:100-12:102-14:6-14:7-14:35-15:28-15:52-17:47-17:60-17:61-17:94-17:101-18:10-18:14-18:16-18:21-18:39-18:50-18:55-18:60-18:63-19:3-19:16-19:39-19:42-20:10-20:38-20:40-20:92-20:104-20:116-21:52-21:76-21:78-21:83-21:87-21:89-22:26-24:12-24:15-24:16-25:29-26:10-26:70-26:72-26:98-26:106-26:124-26:142-26:161-26:177-27:7-27:54-28:44-28:46-28:76-28:87-29:16-29:28-31:13-32:12-33:7-33:9-33:10-33:12-33:13-33:37-34:31-34:32-34:33-34:51-36:13-36:14-37:84-37:85-37:124-37:134-37:140-38:21-38:22-38:31-38:41-38:69-38:71-39:32-40:10-40:18-40:47-40:71-41:14-43:26-43:39-46:11-46:21-46:26-46:29-48:18-48:26-50:17-51:25-51:38-51:41-51:43-53:16-53:32-59:16-60:4-61:5-61:6-66:3-66:11-68:17-68:48-74:33-79:16-85:6-91:12)",
      "d": "«اِذْ» is used for the past tense, and a sentence follows it, or the sentence is omitted (implied).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ اِذۡ قَالَ رَبُّکَ لِلۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ اِنِّیۡ جَاعِلٌ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ خَلِیۡفَۃً» ( 2/30 )\nTranslation: And when your Lord said to the angels, 'I am going to place a vicegerent on earth.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1080,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "When",
      "hw": "جب",
      "s": "«إِذَا» is an adverb of time in Arabic grammar that carries a conditional meaning. It often enters into past tense verbs, transforming their meaning into the future. (326 verses: 2:11-2:13-2:14-2:20-2:76-2:91-2:117-2:145-2:156-2:170-2:177-2:180-2:186-2:196-2:205-2:206-2:231-2:232-2:233-2:282-3:25-3:47-3:119-3:135-3:152-3:156-4:6-4:8-4:18-4:41-4:58-4:61-4:62-4:67-4:77-4:83-4:86-4:94-4:101-4:102-4:140-4:142-5:2-5:5-5:6-5:58-5:61-5:83-5:89-5:93-5:104-5:105-5:106-5:107-6:25-6:31-6:44-6:54-6:56-6:61-6:68-6:99-6:109-6:124-6:141-6:152-7:28-7:37-7:38-7:47-7:57-7:90-7:135-7:201-7:203-7:204-8:2-8:15-8:24-8:31-8:45-9:38-9:58-9:86-9:91-9:92-9:94-9:95-9:118-9:122-9:124-9:127-10:12-10:15-10:21-10:22-10:23-10:24-10:49-10:51-10:90-10:106-11:31-11:40-11:102-12:14-12:62-12:79-12:110-13:11-15:8-16:24-16:40-16:53-16:54-16:58-16:85-16:86-16:91-16:101-17:16-17:35-17:42-17:45-17:46-17:67-17:73-17:75-17:76-17:83-17:100-17:107-18:14-18:17-18:20-18:24-18:57-18:71-18:74-18:77-18:86-18:90-18:93-18:96-19:35-19:58-19:73-19:75-21:12-21:36-22:72-21:45-21:96-22:35-22:52-23:34-23:35-23:64-23:77-23:91-23:99-24:39-24:40-24:48-24:51-24:59-24:62-25:12-25:13-25:41-25:60-25:63-25:67-25:72-25:73-26:20-26:42-26:80-26:130-27:18-27:34-27:62-27:80-27:82-27:84-28:53-28:55-29:48-29:65-30:20-30:25-30:33-30:36-30:48-30:52-31:7-31:21-31:32-32:15-33:16-33:36-33:37-33:49-33:53-34:7-34:23-34:43-36:24-36:45-36:47-36:82-37:13-37:14-37:35-39:8-39:45-39:49-39:71-39:73-40:12-40:34-41:20-41:51-42:29-42:37-42:39-42:48-43:13-43:17-43:38-43:47-43:50-43:57-45:9-45:25-45:32-46:6-46:7-46:15-47:4-47:16-47:18-47:27-48:15-53:1-53:22-53:46-54:24-56:1-56:4-56:83-58:8-58:9-58:11-58:12-60:10-60:12-62:9-62:11-63:1-63:4-63:5-63:11-65:1-67:7-68:15-70:20-70:21-71:4-72:24-74:34-75:26-76:19-76:20-76:28-77:9-77:10-77:11-77:48-79:12-80:22-81:1-81:2-81:3-81:4-81:5-81:6-81:7-81:8-81:10-81:11-81:12-81:13-81:17-81:18-82:1-82:2-82:3-82:4-83:2-83:3-83:13-83:30-83:31-83:32-84:1-84:3-84:18-84:21-89:4-89:15-89:16-89:21-91:2-91:3-91:4-92:1-92:2-92:11-93:2-96:10-99:1-100:9-110:1-113:3-113:5)",
      "d": "«إِذَا» is an adverb of time in Arabic grammar that carries a conditional meaning. It often enters into past tense verbs, transforming their meaning into the future.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا لَقُوا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا قَالُوۡۤا اٰمَنَّا» ( 2/14 )\nTranslation: And when they meet those who believe, they say, \"We believe.\"\nSimilarly, in another instance, the Divine declaration states:\nإِذَا جَاءَ رَمَضَانُ، فُتِحَتْ أبْوَاب الجَنَّةِ .\nTranslation: When Ramadan comes, the gates of Paradise are opened.\nIn another instance, the Divine declaration states:\n«اِذَا الشَّمۡسُ کُوِّرَتۡ» ( 81/1 )\nTranslation: When the sun is wrapped up.\nSometimes, with a tanwīn (nunation), it specifies a future time, meaning \"at that time\", \"in that situation\", or \"in that state\".\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِذًا لَّارۡتَابَ الۡمُبۡطِلُوۡنَ» ( 29/48 )\nTranslation: At that time, those who reject the truth will be in doubt.\nAdding it after «حِیْن» forms «حِیْنَئِذٍ», meaning \"at that time\". Adding it after «یَوْمَ» forms «یَوْمَئِذٍ», specifying \"on that day\". All these are used as adverbs of time referring to the future.\nOccasionally, this particle also enters into the imperfect (present/future) verb.\nNote: (Adverb of time: a noun in which the meaning of time or period is present, e.g., morning, evening, today, tomorrow, month, week, century, etc.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1081,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "When",
      "hw": "جب",
      "s": "«لَمَّا» is called a negative particle in Arabic grammar and comes for condition in the past tense. (150 verses: 2:17-2:33-2:89-2:101-2:214-2:246-2:249-2:250-2:259-3:36-3:52-3:142-3:165-4:77-5:117-6:5-6:44-6:76-6:77-6:78-7:22-7:116-7:126-7:134-7:135-7:143-7:149-7:150-7:154-7:155-7:165-7:166-7:189-7:190-8:48-9:16-9:76-9:114-10:12-10:13-10:23-10:39-10:54-10:76-10:77-10:80-10:81-10:98-11:58-11:66-11:70-11:74-11:77-11:82-11:94-11:101-11:111-12:15-12:22-12:28-12:31-12:50-12:54-12:59-12:63-12:65-12:66-12:68-12:69-12:70-12:80-12:88-12:94-12:96-12:99-14:22-15:61-17:67-18:59-18:61-18:62-19:49-20:11-21:12-25:37-26:21-26:41-26:61-27:8-27:10-27:13-27:36-27:40-27:42-27:44-28:14-28:19-28:22-28:23-28:25-28:29-28:30-28:31-28:36-28:48-29:31-29:33-29:65-29:68-31:32-32:24-33:22-33:37-34:14-34:33-34:43-35:42-37:102-37:103-40:25-40:66-40:83-40:84-40:85-41:41-42:44-43:30-43:35-43:47-43:50-43:55-43:57-43:63-46:7-46:24-46:29-49:14-50:5-59:16-61:5-61:6-62:3-66:3-67:27-68:26-68:51-69:11-72:13-72:19-80:23)",
      "d": "«لَمَّا» is called a negative particle in Arabic grammar and comes for condition in the past tense.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا أَن جَاءَ الْبَشِيرُ» (12/96)\nTranslation: So when the bearer of good news arrived."
    },
    {
      "id": 1082,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "When",
      "hw": "جب",
      "s": "«كُلَّمَا» is used to encompass certain matters (actions). (15 verses: 2:20-2:25-2:87-2:100-3:37-4:56-5:64-5:70-7:38-11:38-17:97-22:22-32:20-67:8-71:7)",
      "d": "«كُلَّمَا» is used to encompass certain matters (actions). It means 'whenever', 'every time'. It comes as a temporal adverb (past) to encompass many matters (actions).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«أَفَكُلَّمَا جَاءَكُمْ رَسُولٌ بِمَا لَا تَهْوَى أَنْفُسُكُمْ اسْتَكْبَرْتُمْ» (2/87)\nTranslation: So whenever a messenger came to you with what your souls did not desire, you grew arrogant."
    }
  ],
  "229": [
    {
      "id": 1083,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Root",
      "hw": "جڑ",
      "s": "«أَصْل» is used for the root of trees and plants. (3 verses: 14:24-37:64-59:5)",
      "d": "«أَصْل» means the foundation or basis of something, and the root of trees and plants. Its opposite is «فَرْع» meaning 'branch'. Its plural is «أُصُول». (See Mufradat, Majma') And 'usul' also refers to the rules upon which a science is based (Majma').\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«مَثَلًا كَلِمَةً طَيِّبَةً كَشَجَرَةٍ طَيِّبَةٍ أَصْلُهَا ثَابِتٌ وَفَرْعُهَا فِي السَّمَاءِ» (14/24)\nTranslation: A goodly word is like a goodly tree, whose root is firm [i.e., firmly fixed in the earth] and whose branches are in the sky."
    },
    {
      "id": 1084,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Root",
      "hw": "جڑ",
      "s": "«أَعْجَاز» are those parts of a tree's root that become embedded in the ground. (2 verses: 54:20-69:7)",
      "d": "«أَعْجَازُ النَّخْلِ» means the roots of the palm tree (Majma'). The root of a tree divides into many parts that become embedded in the ground. Those parts of the root are called «أَعْجَاز».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَتَرَى الْقَوْمَ فِيهَا صَرْعَى كَأَنَّهُمْ أَعْجَازُ نَخْلٍ خَاوِيَةٍ» (69/7)\nTranslation: Then you will see the people fallen prone, as if they were hollow palm trunks."
    },
    {
      "id": 1085,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Root (from rope, etc.)",
      "hw": "جڑ",
      "s": "«دَابِر» is used for uprooting. It also refers to the root or foundation of any thing's corruption. (4 verses: 6:45-7:72-8:7-15:66)",
      "d": "«دُبُر» means 'back', 'posterior', and the rear part of anything. And «دَابِر» means the end or origin of anything. «قَطَعَ اللَّهُ دَابِرَهُمْ» means 'May Allah uproot them' (Majma'). And «إِدْبَار» also means 'ill omen', opposite to «إِقْبَال». And «دَابِر» actually refers to the remaining or residual bad effects of something.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«يُرِيدُ اللَّهُ أَنْ يُحِقَّ الْحَقَّ بِكَلِمَاتِهِ وَيَقْطَعَ دَابِرَ الْكَافِرِينَ» (8/7)\nTranslation: Allah intends to establish the truth by His words and to cut off the root of the disbelievers.\nNote: (To destroy. To uproot the root. To dig up the root. To cut off the lineage. To ruin completely.)"
    }
  ],
  "230": [
    {
      "id": 1086,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Body",
      "hw": "جسم",
      "s": "«جِسْم» is every material thing that has a body. (2 verses: 2:247-63:4)",
      "d": "«جِسْم» is every material thing that has length, width, and depth, and possesses a body (Majma'). Whether it is animate or inanimate. Its plural is «أَجْسَام» (Mufrad). Jism means 'bulk', 'stature', 'tall and big'.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ إِذَا رَأَيْتَهُمْ تُعْجِبُكَ أَجْسَامُهُمْ» (63/4)\nTranslation: And when you see them, their bodies [i.e., their physical appearance] impress you."
    },
    {
      "id": 1087,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Body",
      "hw": "جسم",
      "s": "«جَسَد» is specific to the body, meaning the body of a living being in which blood has dried up. (4 verses: 7:148-20:88-21:8-38:34)",
      "d": "«جَسَد» is specific to the body, meaning the body of a living being in which blood has dried up.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَأَخْرَجَ لَهُمْ عِجْلًا جَسَدًا لَهُ خُوَارٌ» (20/88)\nTranslation: So he brought out for them a calf, a [mere] body [i.e., without life], which had a lowing sound.\nIn another place, the divine revelation states:\n«وَمَا جَعَلْنَاهُمْ جَسَدًا لَا يَأْكُلُونَ الطَّعَامَ وَمَا كَانُوا خَالِدِينَ» (21/8)\nTranslation: And We have not made them [i.e., the prophets] bodies that do not eat food, nor were they immortal.\nTherefore, a dead human is called 'jasad khaaki' (dust body) or 'jasad unsuri' (elemental body)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1088,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Body",
      "hw": "جسم",
      "s": "«بَدَن» meaning a living being's body in which blood is flowing or has not yet dried. (1 verse: 10:92)",
      "d": "«بَدَن» meaning a living being's body in which blood is flowing or has not yet dried.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَالْيَوْمَ نُنَجِّيكَ بِبَدَنِكَ لِتَكُونَ لِمَنْ خَلْفَكَ آيَةً» (10/92)\nTranslation: So today We will save you in your body [i.e., your corpse] that you may be a sign for those after you."
    }
  ],
  "231": [
    {
      "id": 1089,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To bind (with rope, etc.)",
      "hw": "جکڑنا",
      "s": "«وَثَقَ» is used only for binding with rope, etc. (4 verses: 2:256-31:22-47:4-89:26)",
      "d": "«وَثَقَ» means to tie with a rope and to give a knot. And «وَثَاق» and «وِثَاق» refer to the thing with which one is bound, i.e., a rope, etc. (Majma'). Also, «وَثْق» refers to the rope with which animals are tied.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«حَتَّى إِذَا أَثْخَنْتُمُوهُمْ فَشُدُّوا الْوَثَاقَ» (47/4)\nTranslation: When you have overcome them, then bind [i.e., capture] them firmly.\nIn this verse, the inclusion of «شَدَّ» (to make firm) gives «وَثَقَ» the meaning of 'to bind firmly' or 'to tie tightly'."
    },
    {
      "id": 1090,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To tie (with rope, etc.)",
      "hw": "جکڑنا",
      "s": "«قَرَّنَ» refers to a rope whose connection is also with another thing for additional strength. (4 verses: 14:49, 25:13, 38:38, 43:13)",
      "d": "«قَرَن» means to bind one thing with another and mix. And «قَرَن» is the term for a rope with which two or more she-camels are tied (m.f.) and its meanings also include 'mixed with' (manjad). And such a friend is also called who is of the same age or companion. And «قَرَّنَ» contains emphasis (intensification). For example, in the Quran: «وَّ اٰخَرِیۡنَ مُقَرَّنِیۡنَ فِی الۡاَصۡفَادِ» (38/38) Translation: And others too who were bound in chains."
    }
  ],
  "232": [
    {
      "id": 1091,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Place",
      "hw": "جگہ",
      "s": "«مَقَام» means the place of standing or remaining. (18 verses: 2:125-3:97-5:107-10:71-14:14-17:79-19:73-25:66-25:76-26:58-27:39-33:13-35:35-37:164-44:26-44:51-55:46-79:40)",
      "d": "«قَامَ» means to stand. And «مَقَام» is used for the place where one stands.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اتَّخِذُوۡا مِنۡ مَّقَامِ اِبۡرٰہٖمَ مُصَلًّی» ( 2/125 )\nTranslation: And take the place where Abraham stood as a place of prayer.\nAnd «مُقَام», with a mīm prefix, is a mīmetic source (مصدرِ میمی) from «قَامَ», meaning to stand.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ  لِمَنۡ خَافَ مَقَامَ  رَبِّہٖ  جَنَّتٰنِ» ( 55/46 )\nTranslation: And for whoever fears the standing before his Lord, there will be two gardens.\nNote: (\"Mimetic source\" is a type of verbal noun where an extra mīm is added at the beginning.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1092,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Place",
      "hw": "جگہ",
      "s": "«مَکَان» means place, location, spot. (47 verses: 4:20, 5:60, 6:6, 6:135, 7:10, 7:95, 7:143, 10:22, 10:28, 11:93, 11:121, 12:21, 12:54, 23:13, 12:56, 12:77, 12:78, 14:17, 16:101, 16:112, 18:84, 18:95, 22:41, 19:16, 19:22, 19:57, 19:75, 20:58, 22:26, 22:31, 24:55, 25:12, 25:13, 25:34, 28:6, 28:57, 28:82, 34:51, 34:52, 34:53, 36:67, 39:39, 41:44, 46:26, 50:41, 77:21, 81:20)",
      "d": "«مَکَان» means a building or place built for living, residence, house. And it is also called the place that encompasses a body. And the one living in it is called «مَکِیْن» (m.f.) (provided it is used as a noun of place). For example, in the Quran: Pharaoh said to Musa: «فَاجۡعَلۡ بَیۡنَنَا وَ بَیۡنَکَ مَوۡعِدًا لَّنُخۡلِفُہٗ نَحۡنُ وَ لَاۤ اَنۡتَ مَکَانًا سُوًی» (20/58) Translation: Appoint a time between us and you which we will not violate, neither we nor you, and (the contest) will be in an open place (field)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1093,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Place",
      "hw": "جگہ",
      "s": "«مَرَاغَم» means a place gained through struggle and effort. (1 verse: 4/100)",
      "d": "«رَغِمَ» (verb) means to become dusty, «رَغِمَ اَنْفُ فُلَانٍ» means his nose became dusty or he is humiliated (a word of anger). And «رَاغَمَ» means to try to humiliate another and to quarrel. And «مَرَاغَم» is the term for a place gained from others through quarrel and effort (m.f.). For example, in the Quran: «وَ مَنۡ یُّہَاجِرۡ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ یَجِدۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مُرٰغَمًا کَثِیۡرًا وَّ سَعَۃً» (4/100) Translation: And whoever migrates in the way of Allah will find in the earth many places of refuge and abundance."
    }
  ],
  "233": [
    {
      "id": 1094,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Exile",
      "hw": "جلا وطنی",
      "s": "«جَلَاء» means to exile someone. (1 verse: 59/3)",
      "d": "«جَلَا» means to clarify something. Clear and open matter. And «جَلَا اَلْرَجُلُ عَنْ بَلَدِہٖ» means to remove someone from his city or country. To exile. «جَلَا النَّحْل» means to drive bees with smoke to extract honey. And «اَلْجَالِی» means those traveler people who leave their homeland and come (manjad). For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَوۡ لَاۤ اَنۡ کَتَبَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمُ الۡجَلَآءَ لَعَذَّبَہُمۡ فِی الدُّنۡیَا» (59/3) Translation: And if Allah had not decreed for them the exile, He would have punished them in the world."
    },
    {
      "id": 1095,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Exile",
      "hw": "جلا وطنی",
      "s": "«نَفٰی» means to remove someone with humiliation and disgrace. (1 verse: 5/33)",
      "d": "«نَفٰی» means not to exist, to deny the existence of something. And its opposite is «ثَبَتَ». And «مَنْفٰی» means annihilated, destroyed, removed. And «نَفٰی الْرَجُلُ مِنْ بَلَدِہٖ» means to banish someone from the city (manjad). And «نَفٰی ، یَنْفُوا» means to imprison (manjad m. q). And to throw out something, like flour from a mill, or boiling pot's boiling water, or flood throwing away garbage (m. q). And «اَلنِّفَایَۃ» is the term for rejected thing that is thrown away (m. l). So «نَفٰی ، یَنْفُوا» includes meaning of helplessness and humiliation. For example, in the Quran: «اِنَّمَا جَزٰٓؤُا الَّذِیۡنَ یُحَارِبُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ وَ رَسُوۡلَہٗ وَ یَسۡعَوۡنَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ فَسَادًا اَنۡ یُّقَتَّلُوۡۤا اَوۡ یُصَلَّبُوۡۤا اَوۡ تُقَطَّعَ اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ وَ اَرۡجُلُہُمۡ مِّنۡ خِلَافٍ اَوۡ یُنۡفَوۡا مِنَ الۡاَرۡضِ» (5/33) Translation: The punishment of those who wage war against Allah and His Messenger and strive upon earth to cause corruption is that they be killed, or crucified, or have their hands and feet cut off from opposite sides, or be exiled from the land."
    }
  ],
  "234": [
    {
      "id": 1096,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To hurry",
      "hw": "جلدی",
      "s": "«سَرِعَ» means to complete a task quickly, to hurry. (12 verses: 2:202, 3:19, 3:199, 5:4, 6:62, 6:165, 7:167, 10:21, 13:41, 14:51, 24:39, 40:17)",
      "d": "«سَرِعَ» means not to delay in doing a work (m.f.). Not to leave today's work for tomorrow. Not to be lazy. To complete a task on time or a bit earlier. And this is a praiseworthy trait, and its opposite is «بَطَأَ» meaning to delay (due to laziness, etc.). And hurrying is good when it is better and correct to hurry (faq. l 168). For example, in the Quran: «اُولٰٓئِکَ لَہُمۡ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّمَّا کَسَبُوۡا ؕ وَ اللّٰہُ سَرِیۡعُ الۡحِسَابِ» (2/202) Translation: Those will have a share (i.e., reward prepared) of what they earned, and Allah is swift in account."
    },
    {
      "id": 1097,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To hurry",
      "hw": "جلدی",
      "s": "«عَجِلَ» means hastiness, trying to obtain something before its appropriate time so that it is not properly fulfilled. (32 verses: 2:203, 6:57, 6:58, 7:150, 10:11, 10:50, 10:51, 13:6, 16:1, 17:11, 17:18, 18:58, 19:84, 20:83, 20:84, 20:114, 21:37, 22:47, 26:204, 27:46, 27:72, 29:53, 29:54, 37:176, 38:16, 42:18, 46:24, 46:35, 48:20, 51:14, 51:59, 75:16)",
      "d": "«عَجِلَ» means to try to obtain something before its time (m.f.). To be hasty. And this is a blameworthy trait. Hurrying where one should not hurry. For example, in the Quran: «وَ یَدۡعُ الۡاِنۡسَانُ بِالشَّرِّ دُعَآءَہٗ بِالۡخَیۡرِ ؕ وَ کَانَ الۡاِنۡسَانُ عَجُوۡلًا» (17/11) Translation: And man prays for evil as he prays for good, and man is ever hasty. And «اِسْتَعْجَل» means to demand something hastily or before time. For example, in the Quran: «وَ یَسۡتَعۡجِلُوۡنَکَ بِالسَّیِّئَۃِ قَبۡلَ الۡحَسَنَۃِ وَ قَدۡ خَلَتۡ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمُ الۡمَثُلٰتُ ؕ» (13/6) Translation: And they ask you to hasten the punishment before the good, when indeed exemplary punishments have passed before them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1098,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To hurry",
      "hw": "جلدی",
      "s": "«بَدَرَ» means to hurry by reducing the required time for a task. (1 verse: 4/6)",
      "d": "«بَدَرَ» means to do a task in less time than required. To do it earlier. For example, in a Hadith: «لَا تُبَادِ رُوْنِیْ بِالرُّکُوْعِ وَ السُّجُوۡدِ» Translation: Do not precede me in ruku and sujud. (Ahmad, Abu Dawood, Ibn Majah). And in the Quran: «وَ لَا تَاۡکُلُوۡہَاۤ اِسۡرَافًا وَّ بِدَارًا» (4/6) Translation: And do not consume it wastefully and hastily."
    },
    {
      "id": 1099,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To hurry",
      "hw": "جلدی",
      "s": "«فَوْر» means to do something with zeal and enthusiasm. (4 verses: 3:125, 11:40, 23:27, 67:7)",
      "d": "«فَارَ» means to boil and seethe. And «فَوْر» means very fast. Like «رَجَعَ مِنْ فَوْرِہٖ» he returned without delay, very fast (manjad). That is, to do something immediately with zeal. For example, in the Quran: «بَلٰۤی ۙ اِنۡ تَصۡبِرُوۡا وَ تَتَّقُوۡا وَ یَاۡتُوۡکُمۡ مِّنۡ فَوۡرِہِمۡ ہٰذَا یُمۡدِدۡکُمۡ رَبُّکُمۡ بِخَمۡسَۃِ اٰلٰفٍ مِّنَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ مُسَوِّمِیۡنَ» (3/125) Translation: Yes, if you are patient and fear Allah, and they come upon you in a sudden attack, your Lord will reinforce you with five thousand marked angels."
    }
  ],
  "235": [
    {
      "id": 1101,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Group",
      "hw": "جماعت",
      "s": "«جَمْعُ» refers to a gathering of people, people assembling at a place.",
      "d": "«جَمْعُ» means a gathering of people, or people assembling at a place. This word is general for any group, whether it's a small gathering or a large one, of any kind.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«سَیُہۡزَمُ الۡجَمۡعُ وَ  یُوَلُّوۡنَ الدُّبُرَ» ( 54/45 )\nTranslation: Soon this group will be defeated, and they will turn their backs and flee.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ اِنَّا  لَجَمِیۡعٌ  حٰذِرُوۡنَ» ( 26/56 )\nTranslation: And indeed, we are a large group, watchful against them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1102,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Group",
      "hw": "جماعت",
      "s": "«رَھْط» is a group of young men from the same family, numbering up to ten, and having a leader. (3 verses: 11:91-11:92-27:48)",
      "d": "«رَھْط» refers to a small group of young men from the same family, consisting of 3 to 10 individuals, with a designated leader. (F. L. 205) According to Imam Rāghib, this number can extend up to forty. (Muf) The author of Munjid adds the condition that no women are included. (Munjid) If the reference is to the number, then individuals and persons are meant. For example, «عِشْرُوْنَ رَھْطًا» means twenty persons. (Munjid)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ کَانَ فِی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  تِسۡعَۃُ  رَہۡطٍ یُّفۡسِدُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ لَا یُصۡلِحُوۡنَ» ( 27/48 )\nTranslation: And in the city were nine men who caused corruption in the land and did not amend [it].\nIn another instance, the Divine declaration states:\n«قَالَ یٰقَوۡمِ اَرَہۡطِیۡۤ اَعَزُّ  عَلَیۡکُمۡ  مِّنَ اللّٰہِ» ( 11/92 )\nTranslation: [Shu'ayb] said, \"O my people, is my family more esteemed to you than Allah?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 1104,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Group",
      "hw": "جماعت",
      "s": "«عُصْبَۃٌ» is a small, strong, and powerful group that supports and aids one another. (4 verses: 12:8-12:14-24:11-28:76)",
      "d": "«عُصْبَۃٌ» is a small, strong, and powerful group that supports and aids one another. (Muf) In terms of size, it is larger than «شِرذِمَۃ» (F. L. 205), but this does not seem correct to the author of Fiqh al-Lughah. Because the Quran has used this term for the ten brothers of Prophet Yusuf as well.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا  لَئِنۡ  اَکَلَہُ  الذِّئۡبُ وَ نَحۡنُ عُصۡبَۃٌ  اِنَّاۤ   اِذًا  لَّخٰاسِرُوۡنَ» ( 12/14 )\nTranslation: They said, \"If a wolf has eaten him while we were a strong group, indeed we, then, are losers.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 1108,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Group",
      "hw": "جماعت",
      "s": "«ثُلَّۃٌ» is used specifically for a large number. (3 verses: 56:13-56:39-56:40)",
      "d": "«ثُلَّۃٌ» refers to a heap of wool (Muf) and also to a flock of sheep (Muf). It also refers to a group of people (Munjid). (Thus, its basis is a large quantity or number.) It is said, «فُلَانٌ لَا یُفَرَّقُ بَیْنَ الثَّلَّۃَ وَالثُّلَّۃَ» meaning \"So-and-so does not distinguish between flocks of sheep and groups of people.\" According to the author of Fiqh al-Lughah, in terms of number, «ثُلَّۃٌ» is greater than «طَآئِفَۃ» and less than «فِرَقَۃَ». (F. L. 205)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ثُلَّۃٌ  مِّنَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ وَ قَلِیۡلٌ  مِّنَ الۡاٰخِرِیۡنَ» ( 56/13،14 )\nTranslation: A large number from the former [people] and a few from the latter."
    },
    {
      "id": 1109,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Group",
      "hw": "جماعت",
      "s": "«زُمْرَۃٌ» refers to small, separate groups that move in scattered formation from a larger group. (2 verses: 39:71-39:73)",
      "d": "According to the author of Fiqh al-Lughah, «زُمْرَۃٌ» refers to a group larger than «ثُلَّۃٌ» and its plural is «زُمَر». (F. L. 205)\nImam Rāghib holds that «زُمْرَۃٌ» refers to a small group. And «شَاۃٌ زَمِرَۃٌ» means a sheep with little wool. And «زَمِرٌ» refers to an ungenerous person (Muf). The Quran also supports this meaning. That is, when a large group moves in small parties or detachments, those units are called «زُمُر».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ سِیۡقَ الَّذِیۡنَ اتَّقَوۡا رَبَّہُمۡ  اِلَی الۡجَنَّۃِ زُمَرًا» ( 39/73 )\nTranslation: And those who feared their Lord will be driven to Paradise in groups."
    },
    {
      "id": 1110,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Group",
      "hw": "جماعت",
      "s": "«عِزِیْن» refers to people of the same lineage. (1 verse: 70:37)",
      "d": "The plural of «اَلْعِزَۃ» is «عِزِیْن» and «عِزُوْن». And «اَلْعِزَۃُ» means a group of people of the same lineage (Muf). And «اَلْاِعْتِزَآءُ فِی الْحَرْبِ» means to mention one's lineage during battle (Muf).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَمَالِ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا قِبَلَکَ مُہۡطِعِیۡنَ عَنِ الۡیَمِیۡنِ وَ عَنِ الشِّمَالِ عِزِیۡنَ» ( 70/36،37 )\nTranslation: So what is [the matter] with those who disbelieve, hastening toward you from the right and from the left in groups?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1111,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Group",
      "hw": "جماعت",
      "s": "«حِزْب» means a party, a faction, or a group that attempts to interfere in the affairs of a state. (17 verses: 5:56-11:17-13:36-18:12-19:37-23:53-30:32-33:20-33:22-35:6-38:11-38:13-40:5-40:30-43:65-58:19-58:22)",
      "d": "«حِزْب» refers to a group in which intensity and severity are found (Muf). And «حِزْب» means party, faction, group, weapon, an army of men, and like-minded companions who provide support and strength (Munjid). People gathered under one banner (M. Q). Thus, the word «حِزْب» also comes in the meanings of a political party or an army, with the aim of interfering in state affairs.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَمَّا رَاَ  الۡمُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ الۡاَحۡزَابَ ۙ قَالُوۡا ہٰذَا مَا وَعَدَنَا اللّٰہُ  وَ رَسُوۡلُہٗ» ( 33/22 )\nTranslation: And when the believers saw the [allied] forces, they said, \"This is what Allah and His Messenger had promised us.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 1112,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Group",
      "hw": "جماعت",
      "s": "«مَعْشَرُ» refers to all members of a group with a specific purpose, wherein there is mutual harmony and agreement. (3 verses: 6:128-6:130-55:33)",
      "d": "«عَشَرَ» means ten, and «عَشِیْرَۃ» refers to all members of a family who are related through the father. In this sense, «مَعْشَرُ» refers to all members of a group whose purpose and objective are one, and among whom there is harmony and agreement (M. L).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یٰمَعۡشَرَ الۡجِنِّ وَ الۡاِنۡسِ  اِنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتُمۡ اَنۡ  تَنۡفُذُوۡا مِنۡ  اَقۡطَارِ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ فَانۡفُذُوۡا» ( 55/33 )\nTranslation: O company of jinn and mankind, if you are able to pass beyond the regions of the heavens and the earth, then pass. You will not pass except by authority [from Allah]."
    },
    {
      "id": 1113,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Group",
      "hw": "جماعت",
      "s": "«ثَقَلَان» refers to the two great creations: jinn and humans. (1 verse: 55:31)",
      "d": "«ثِقْل» means burden, weight, heaviness. And «ثَقِیْل» and «ثِقَال» mean a heavy or weighty thing. And «ثَقَلَان» means two heavy groups, two great kinds, i.e., jinn and humans. (Munjid. F. L. 134)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«سَنَفۡرُغُ   لَکُمۡ  اَیُّہَ  الثَّقَلٰنِ» ( 55/31 )\nTranslation: \"We will attend to you, O two heavy groups.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 1114,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Community / Group",
      "hw": "جماعت",
      "s": "«اُمَّۃ» refers to a group of similar beings (humans, animals, birds) or people of the same creed who follow a single Imam. (54 verses: 2:143-2:213-3:104-3:110-3:113-4:41-5:48-5:66-6:38-6:42-6:108-7:34-7:38-7:159-7:160-7:164-7:168-7:181-10:19-10:47-10:49-11:8-11:48-11:118-12:45-13:30-15:5-16:36-16:63-16:84-16:89-16:92-16:93-16:120-21:92-22:34-22:67-23:43-23:44-23:52-27:83-28:23-28:75-29:18-35:24-35:42-40:5-41:25-42:8-43:22-43:23-43:33-45:28-46:18)",
      "d": "«اُمَّۃ» means a group of similar beings (humans, animals, birds) or people of the same creed who follow a single Imam.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَا مِنۡ  دَآبَّۃٍ  فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ لَا طٰٓئِرٍ یَّطِیۡرُ  بِجَنَاحَیۡہِ  اِلَّاۤ  اُمَمٌ  اَمۡثَالُکُمۡ» ( 6/38 )\nTranslation: And there is no creature on earth or bird that flies with its wings except [that they are] communities like you.\nAnd when this term is applied to humans, it refers to people of the same creed. For example: The Divine Command states:\n«کَانَ النَّاسُ اُمَّۃً  وَّاحِدَۃً» ( 2/213 )\nTranslation: [Initially] all people were one community.\nAnd in common usage, «اُمَّۃ» refers to the community of like-minded people formed by a prophet or messenger.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«کُنۡتُمۡ خَیۡرَ اُمَّۃٍ اُخۡرِجَتۡ لِلنَّاسِ» ( 3/110 )\nTranslation: [O believers] you are the best community ever raised for mankind.\nAnd the word «اُمّۃ» has also been used in the Noble Quran for Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him) as an individual. The reason is that Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him) single-handedly accomplished the work of an entire community in proclaiming the truth. And according to some, «اُمَّۃ» also means Imam, i.e., a leader or guide. (Jalandhari, Osmani).\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«اِنَّ  اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ کَانَ اُمَّۃً  قَانِتًا لِّلّٰہِ حَنِیۡفًا» ( 16/120 )\nTranslation: Indeed, Ibrahim was a community, obedient to Allah and inclined to truth [alone]."
    },
    {
      "id": 1115,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Group (of animals)",
      "hw": "جماعت",
      "s": "«رَکْب» refers to that caravan of camels in which there are ten or more riders (1 verse: 8:42)",
      "d": "The word «رَکْب» is also used to mean a herd of camels, a caravan, and a camel rider (mufradat).\nFor example: In the Quran: «اِذۡ اَنۡتُمۡ بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الدُّنۡیَا وَ ہُمۡ  بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الۡقُصۡوٰی وَ الرَّکۡبُ اَسۡفَلَ  مِنۡکُمۡ» (8/42)\nTranslation: When you were on the near bank and they were on the far bank, and the caravan was below you."
    },
    {
      "id": 1116,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Group (of animals)",
      "hw": "جماعت",
      "s": "«خَیْل» refers to a caravan of horses, and the term is also used for the collective of horses and riders (4 verses: 3:14-8:60-16:8-59:6)",
      "d": "«خَیْل» means a herd of horses; then, like «رَکْب», the word «خَیْل» is also applied to a horse rider (meaning faras) (manjad, mufradat), and it is also used for the collective of horses and riders (mufradat).\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ اَعِدُّوۡا لَہُمۡ مَّا اسۡتَطَعۡتُمۡ مِّنۡ قُوَّۃٍ وَّ مِنۡ رِّبَاطِ الۡخَیۡلِ تُرۡہِبُوۡنَ بِہٖ عَدُوَّ اللّٰہِ وَ عَدُوَّکُمۡ » (8/60)\nTranslation: And (O believers) prepare against them whatever force and cavalry you can, by which you may terrify the enemy of Allah and your enemy."
    },
    {
      "id": 1117,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Group (of animals)",
      "hw": "جماعت",
      "s": "«غَنَم» is used for a flock of goats/sheep (3 verses: 6:146-20:18-21:78)",
      "d": "«غَنَم» is used for a flock of goats/sheep. (mufradat)\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ دَاوٗدَ  وَ سُلَیۡمٰنَ  اِذۡ یَحۡکُمٰنِ فِی الۡحَرۡثِ  اِذۡ  نَفَشَتۡ فِیۡہِ غَنَمُ  الۡقَوۡمِ» (21/78)\nTranslation: And (mention) David and Solomon when they judged concerning the field - when the people's sheep grazed therein."
    }
  ],
  "236": [
    {
      "id": 1119,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Jinn",
      "hw": "جن",
      "s": "«جِنّ» refers to another hidden and fiery creation besides humans, which is accountable under Sharia (31 verses: 6:100-6:112-6:128-6:130-7:38-7:179-7:184-11:119-17:88-18:50-23:25-23:70-27:17-27:39-32:13-34:8-34:12-34:14-34:41-34:46-37:158-41:25-41:29-46:18-46:29-51:56-55:33-72:1-72:5-72:6-114:6)",
      "d": "«اَلْجِنّ وَالْجِنَّۃ» is a generic noun. Another major creation besides humans that is accountable under Sharia. A hidden creation created from fire. Fiery creation. Jinn. Pari. Devil, and «جَآنٌّ». «جِن» is the plural form.\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ مَا خَلَقۡتُ الۡجِنَّ وَ الۡاِنۡسَ  اِلَّا لِیَعۡبُدُوۡنِ» (51/56)\nTranslation: And I did not create the jinn and mankind except to worship Me."
    },
    {
      "id": 1121,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Jinn",
      "hw": "جن",
      "s": "«مَارِد» refers to that devil who reaches the extreme in causing harm and mischief and rebellion (1 verse: 37:7)",
      "d": "If a devil reaches the limit in his rebellion and causing harm, he is called «مَارِدْ» (F L 135).\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ  حِفۡظًا مِّنۡ کُلِّ شَیۡطٰنٍ مَّارِدٍ» (37/7)\nTranslation: And (a means of) protection from every devil, rebellious (or) rebellious devil."
    },
    {
      "id": 1122,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Jinn",
      "hw": "جن",
      "s": "«خَنَّاس» refers to the devil who casts evil suggestions into hearts and minds (1 verse: 114:4)",
      "d": "«خَنَسَ» means to retreat and shrink, and «خَانِس، خُنَّس» are terms for those stars that, while moving straight, start moving backwards, e.g., Saturn, Jupiter, Mars, etc. (mufradat). And «خَنَّاس» is an intensive form, meaning one who always retreats and then advances. And by it is meant the devil who practices insinuation, who constantly insinuates in this manner to mislead humans at every moment, whether from jinn or humans.\nFor example: In the Quran: «مِنۡ  شَرِّ الۡوَسۡوَاسِ  ۬ ۙ الۡخَنَّاسِ . الَّذِیۡ یُوَسۡوِسُ فِیۡ صُدُوۡرِ النَّاسِ . مِنَ الۡجِنَّۃِ وَ النَّاسِ» (114/4,5,6)\nTranslation: From the evil of the retreating whisperer, who whispers [evil] into the breasts of mankind, from among the jinn and mankind."
    },
    {
      "id": 1123,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Jinn",
      "hw": "جن",
      "s": "«عِفْرِیْت» refers to a very strong, powerful, and tall jinn (1 verse: 27:39)",
      "d": "«عِفْرِیْت» means a very strong, powerful, and tall jinn. (F L 135)\nFor example: In the Quran: «قَالَ عِفۡرِیۡتٌ مِّنَ الۡجِنِّ اَنَا اٰتِیۡکَ بِہٖ قَبۡلَ  اَنۡ  تَقُوۡمَ مِنۡ مَّقَامِکَ» (27/39)\nTranslation: A powerful one from among the jinn said, \"I will bring it to you before you rise from your place.\""
    }
  ],
  "237": [
    {
      "id": 1124,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Paradise and its various names",
      "hw": "جنت",
      "s": "«جَنَّۃٌ» means garden; in common usage, it is used for Paradise (143 verses: 2:25-2:35-2:82-2:111-2:214-2:221-2:265-2:266-3:15-3:133-3:136-3:142-3:185-3:195-3:198-4:13-4:57-4:122-4:124-5:12-5:65-5:72-5:85-5:119-6:99-6:141-7:19-7:22-7:27-7:40-7:42-7:43-7:44-7:46-7:49-7:50-9:21-9:72-9:89-9:100-9:111-10:9-10:26-11:23-11:108-13:4-13:23-13:35-14:23-15:45-16:31-16:32-17:91-18:31-18:32-18:33-18:35-18:39-18:40-18:107-19:60-19:61-19:63-20:76-20:117-20:121-22:14-22:23-22:56-23:19-25:8-25:10-25:15-25:24-26:57-26:85-26:90-26:134-26:147-29:58-31:8-32:19-34:15-34:16-35:33-36:26-36:34-36:55-37:43-38:50-39:73-39:74-40:8-40:40-41:30-42:7-42:22-43:70-43:72-44:25-44:52-46:14-46:16-47:6-47:12-47:15-48:5-48:17-50:9-50:31-51:15-52:17-53:15-54:54-55:46-55:54-55:62-56:12-56:89-57:12-57:21-58:22-59:20-61:12-64:9-65:11-66:8-66:11-68:17-68:34-69:22-70:35-70:38-71:12-74:40-76:12-78:16-79:41-81:13-85:11-88:10-89:30-98:8)",
      "d": "«جَنَّۃٌ» means garden; its plural is «جَنَّاتٌ، جَنَّ» meaning to cover, and «جَنَّۃٌ» refers to a garden whose ground is not visible due to trees or cultivation (mufradat).\nFor example: In the Quran: «اَیَوَدُّ اَحَدُکُمۡ اَنۡ تَکُوۡنَ لَہٗ جَنَّۃٌ مِّنۡ نَّخِیۡلٍ وَّ اَعۡنَابٍ» (2/266)\nTranslation: Would any of you wish to have a garden of palm trees and grapevines?\nAnd «اَلْجَنَّۃ» and «جَنَّۃ» are frequently used in the Quran for that garden in the Hereafter where the righteous and pious will reside. Paradise. For example: The divine declaration is: «وَ بَشِّرِ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ اَنَّ لَہُمۡ جَنّٰتٍ تَجۡرِیۡ مِنۡ تَحۡتِہَا الۡاَنۡہٰرُ» (2/25)\nTranslation: And give good tidings to those who believe and do righteous deeds that they will have gardens beneath which rivers flow."
    },
    {
      "id": 1125,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Paradise and its various names",
      "hw": "جنت",
      "s": "«جَنّٰتُ عَدْنٍ» means gardens of eternal abode (i.e., Paradise) (11 verses: 9:72-13:23-16:31-18:31-19:61-20:76-35:33-38:50-40:8-61:12-98:8)",
      "d": "«عَدَنَ» means to settle in a place, to adopt permanent residence, and to remain in that place forever. (M R) Thus, «جَنّٰتُ عَدْنٍ» will be such gardens that remain established for a long duration, and the people of Paradise will dwell in them forever.\nFor example: In the Quran: «جَزَآؤُہُمۡ عِنۡدَ  رَبِّہِمۡ جَنّٰتُ عَدۡنٍ تَجۡرِیۡ مِنۡ تَحۡتِہَا الۡاَنۡہٰرُ» (98/8)\nTranslation: Their reward with their Lord is gardens of perpetual residence beneath which rivers flow."
    },
    {
      "id": 1126,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Paradise and its various names",
      "hw": "جنت",
      "s": "«جَنّٰتُ الْفِرْدَوْس» refers to lush, densely shaded, and cool gardens (i.e., Paradise) (2 verses: 18:107-23:11)",
      "d": "«فِرْدَوْس» means a lush valley (manjad), and «فردوس» means a garden situated between a large river or canal, containing all kinds of fruits and flowers. Thus, «جَنّٰتُ الْفِرْدَوْس» refers to lush, densely shaded, and cool gardens, fragrant with flowers and abundant in all kinds of fruits. That part of Paradise for which the Holy Prophet ﷺ taught Muslims to pray: «اَللّٰھُمَّ اِنِّیْ اَسْئَلُکَ الْجَنَّۃَ الْفِرْدَوْس».\nAnd in the Quran: «اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ کَانَتۡ لَہُمۡ  جَنّٰتُ الۡفِرۡدَوۡسِ نُزُلًا» (18/107)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who have believed and done righteous deeds - for them are the gardens of Paradise as a lodging."
    },
    {
      "id": 1127,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Paradise and its various names",
      "hw": "جنت",
      "s": "«جَنّٰتُ النَّعِیْمِ» refers to gardens that, in addition to the beauties of a garden, also possess other amenities of comfortable living (11 verses: 5:65-10:9-22:56-26:85-31:8-37:43-52:17-56:12-56:89-68:34-70:38)",
      "d": "«نَعْم» means comfort, ease, luxury, and a pure life (m. l). Thus, «جَنَّاتُ النَّعِیْم» are gardens that, besides the beauties of a garden, also contain other amenities of comfortable living.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ  لِلۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ عِنۡدَ رَبِّہِمۡ جَنّٰتِ النَّعِیۡمِ» ( 68/34 )\nTranslation: For the pious, there are gardens of bliss with their Lord."
    }
  ],
  "238": [
    {
      "id": 1128,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "War",
      "hw": "جنگ",
      "s": "«قِتَال» means to intend to kill another person. It signifies war and the battlefield (10 verses: 2:216-2:217-2:246-3:121-3:167-4:77-8:16-8:65-33:25-47:20)",
      "d": "«قَتَل» means to kill someone. And «قِتَال» means a fight in which there is an intention to kill another.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«کُتِبَ عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡقِتَالُ وَ ہُوَ کُرۡہٌ لَّکُمۡ» ( 2/216 )\nTranslation: Fighting has been prescribed for you (in the way of Allah), and you dislike it.\nSometimes «قِتَال» also means «مَقْتَل» or the battlefield. The Divine Command states:\n«وَ اِذۡ غَدَوۡتَ مِنۡ اَہۡلِکَ تُبَوِّئُ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ مَقَاعِدَ لِلۡقِتَالِ» ( 3/121 )\nTranslation: And (remember) when you left your home in the morning to post the believers at their stations for the battle."
    },
    {
      "id": 1129,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "War",
      "hw": "جنگ",
      "s": "«حَرْب» means to fight and to seize property from an enemy (4 verses: 2:279-5:64-8:57-47:4)",
      "d": "«حَرَبَ» means to loot or seize. And «حَرْبَۃٌ» also means a spear or lance (Manjad). And «اَحْرَبَ الْحَرْب» means to incite fighting or to guide someone to loot the enemy's property (Manjad). The word «حَرْب» is used in a broader sense than «قِتَال». It includes the concept of gaining spoils of war in addition to fighting. Moreover, this word encompasses the entire period, including the causes, results, and affected circumstances of the conflict.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ  اَوۡقَدُوۡا  نَارًا لِّلۡحَرۡبِ اَطۡفَاَہَا اللّٰہُ» ( 5/64 )\nTranslation: Whenever they kindle a fire for war, Allah extinguishes it. (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1130,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "War",
      "hw": "جنگ",
      "s": "«زَحْفًا» means the slow, steady advance of a large army towards the battlefield (1 verse: 8:15)",
      "d": "«زَحَفَ» means to crawl slowly on one's knees or shins. And «زَحَفَ الْعَسْکَرُ اِلَی الْعَدُوِّ» means the army, due to its large numbers, advances slowly and steadily towards the enemy. And «اَلزَّحْفُ» refers to a massive, advancing army (Manjad). Thus, the literal meaning of «زَحْفًا» is not merely to fight or the battlefield, but the slow, steady advance of a large army towards the battlefield, where they become densely packed (m. q). And «زَحُوْف» and «زَھَافَات» refer to animals that move by pressing their bellies to the ground, like snakes, etc.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا  اِذَا لَقِیۡتُمُ  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا  زَحۡفًا  فَلَا  تُوَلُّوۡہُمُ  الۡاَدۡبَارَ» ( 8/15 )\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when you meet those who disbelieve in battle, do not turn your backs to them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1131,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "War",
      "hw": "جنگ",
      "s": "«بَأس» refers to the hardships and physical damage encountered during war (26 verses: 2:177-2:214-4:84-6:42-6:43-6:147-6:148-7:4-7:5-7:94-7:97-7:98-12:110-16:81-17:5-18:2-21:12-21:80-27:33-33:18-40:29-40:84-40:85-48:16-57:25-59:14)",
      "d": "The fundamental meaning of «بَأس» is hardship, severity, strength, and aversion. (m l. maf) Whether it is in livelihood, such as poverty and destitution, or in the form of punishment. Generally, the word «بَأسَآء» is used for it, whether in the context of punishment or fighting. The author of Manjad has written the meanings of «بَأس» as courage, bravery, strength, fear, and punishment. And when the word «بَأس» comes in the context of war or the battlefield, it refers to the hardships, trials, and physical damage of the fight.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الصّٰبِرِیۡنَ فِی الۡبَاۡسَآءِ وَ الضَّرَّآءِ  وَ حِیۡنَ الۡبَاۡسِ» ( 2/177 )\nTranslation: And those who are patient in [the face of] hardship and illness and in the heat of battle."
    },
    {
      "id": 1132,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "War",
      "hw": "جنگ",
      "s": "«جِھَاد» means to fight solely for the exaltation of religion, leaving behind personal motives and interests (30 verses: 2:218-3:142-4:95-5:35-5:54-8:72-8:74-8:75-9:16-9:19-9:20-9:24-9:41-9:44-9:73-9:81-9:86-9:88-16:110-22:78-25:52-29:6-29:8-29:69-31:15-47:31-49:15-60:1-61:11-66:9)",
      "d": "«جِھَاد» means to exert one's utmost effort in a matter. And Jihad fi Sabilillah (striving in the way of Allah) is every such effort that is made solely for the elevation of Allah's word, leaving aside personal motives. And «جِھَاد» is a Shariah term that is generally used in the meaning of «جِھَاد بِالسَّیْف», i.e., fighting against disbelievers solely for the elevation of the Word of Allah and the religion, leaving aside one's personal motives.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَاۤ اُنۡزِلَتۡ سُوۡرَۃٌ اَنۡ اٰمِنُوۡا بِاللّٰہِ وَ جَاہِدُوۡا مَعَ رَسُوۡلِہِ اسۡتَاۡذَنَکَ اُولُوا الطَّوۡلِ مِنۡہُمۡ وَ قَالُوۡا ذَرۡنَا نَکُنۡ مَّعَ الۡقٰعِدِیۡنَ » ( 9/86 )\nTranslation: When a Surah is revealed [that says], 'Believe in Allah and strive along with His Messenger,' the affluent among them ask your permission [to stay back] and say, 'Leave us to be with those who sit [at home].'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1133,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "War",
      "hw": "جنگ",
      "s": "«غَزٰی» means to set out with the intention of fighting an enemy for the sake of Jihad (1 verse: 3:156)",
      "d": "«غَزْوَۃٌ» means to set out with the intention of fighting an enemy. And a Ghazi is one who sets out with that intention. Its plurals are «غُزَاۃٌ» and «غُزٌّ» (maf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَکُوۡنُوۡا کَالَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا وَ قَالُوۡا لِاِخۡوَانِہِمۡ اِذَا ضَرَبُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اَوۡ کَانُوۡا غُزًّی لَّوۡ کَانُوۡا عِنۡدَنَا مَا مَاتُوۡا وَ مَا قُتِلُوۡا» ( 3/156 )\nTranslation: O you who have believed, do not be like those who disbelieved and said about their brothers when they traveled throughout the land or were fighting, 'If they had been with us, they would not have died or been killed.'"
    }
  ],
  "239": [
    {
      "id": 1134,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To give birth",
      "hw": "جننا",
      "s": "«وَضَعَ» is used in the meaning of laying down a burden (19 verses: 3:36-3:96-4:102-7:157-18:49-21:47-22:2-24:58-24:60-35:11-39:69-41:47-46:15-47:4-55:7-55:10-65:4-65:6-94:2)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «وَضَعَ» is to place something down (maf). «وَضَعْتُ الْحَمْل» means I laid down the burden (maf). When the word «حَمَلَ» (to bear a burden) comes with «وَضَعَ» and its relation is to a female (mudhakkar), it means to give birth to a child. The phrase 'wada' al-haml' (to lay down the burden) is general and is used for humans as well as animals. And it is a temporary action.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا وَضَعَتۡہَا قَالَتۡ رَبِّ اِنِّیۡ وَضَعۡتُہَاۤ  اُنۡثٰی» ( 3/36 )\nTranslation: When she delivered her, she said, 'My Lord, I have delivered a female.'\nAt another place, the Divine Command states:\n«وَ تَضَعُ کُلُّ ذَاتِ حَمۡلٍ حَمۡلَہَا» ( 22/2 )\nTranslation: And every pregnant one will deliver her burden."
    },
    {
      "id": 1135,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To give birth",
      "hw": "جننا",
      "s": "«وَلَدَ» is generally used for the purpose of having offspring (35 verses: 2:116-2:233-3:47-4:11-4:12-4:171-4:176-6:101-10:68-12:21-17:111-18:4-18:39-19:15-19:33-19:35-19:77-19:88-19:91-19:92-21:26-23:91-25:2-26:18-28:9-31:33-37:152-39:4-43:81-58:2-71:21-71:26-72:3-90:3-112:3)",
      "d": "«وَلَدَ» generally comes for humans. And the relation of parenthood is not temporary but permanent. A mother is always the mother of her offspring (child), but she is not always the one who laid down the burden (gave birth). Furthermore, in «وَلَدَ», there is not only the relation of giving birth (procreation) but also the upbringing of the offspring. And «وَلَدَ الولد» means he raised the child.\nFor example: In the Quran, Pharaoh, addressing Prophet Musa (AS), said:\n«قَالَ اَلَمۡ نُرَبِّکَ فِیۡنَا وَلِیۡدًا وَّ لَبِثۡتَ فِیۡنَا مِنۡ عُمُرِکَ سِنِیۡنَ» ( 26/18 )\nTranslation: Pharaoh said, 'Did we not raise you among us as a child? And you remained among us for years of your life.'"
    }
  ],
  "240": [
    {
      "id": 1136,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To answer",
      "hw": "جواب",
      "s": "«اَجَابَ» means to answer a question (2 verses: 5:109-28:65)",
      "d": "«اَجَابَ» is the opposite of «سَاَلَ». «سَاَلَ» means to ask a question or to request something. Similarly, «اَجَابَ» also means to answer a question. And if something is requested, it also means to accept or give it. Here, the answer to a question is under discussion.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَوۡمَ یَجۡمَعُ اللّٰہُ الرُّسُلَ فَیَقُوۡلُ مَا ذَاۤ اُجِبۡتُمۡ» ( 5/109 )\nTranslation: The Day Allah will gather the messengers and say, 'What was the response [you received]?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1137,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to answer",
      "hw": "جواب",
      "s": "Responding to a letter with «رَجَعَ» (98 verses: 2:18-2:28-2:196-2:210-2:245-2:281-3:55-3:72-3:83-3:109-5:48-5:105-6:36-6:60-6:108-6:164-7:150-7:168-7:174-8:44-9:83-9:94-9:122-10:4-10:23-10:46-10:56-10:70-11:4-11:34-11:123-12:46-12:50-12:62-12:63-12:81-19:40-20:40-20:86-20:89-20:91-21:13-21:35-21:58-21:64-21:95-22:76-23:99-23:115-24:28-24:64-27:28-27:35-27:37-28:39-28:70-28:88-29:8-29:17-29:57-30:11-30:41-31:15-31:23-32:11-32:12-32:21-33:13-34:31-35:4-36:22-36:31-36:50-36:67-36:83-37:68-39:7-39:44-40:77-41:21-41:50-43:28-43:48-43:85-45:15-46:27-50:3-56:87-57:5-57:13-60:10-63:8-67:3-67:4-86:8-86:11-89:28-96:8)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «رَجَعَ» is to turn back, return. And «اَلْرَجْعُ» (masdar) means to answer a letter (manjad). For example, in the Quran: «اِذۡہَبۡ بِّکِتٰبِیۡ ہٰذَا فَاَلۡقِہۡ  اِلَیۡہِمۡ ثُمَّ تَوَلَّ عَنۡہِمۡ فَانۡظُرۡ  مَا ذَا یَرۡجِعُوۡنَ» (27/28) Translation: Take this letter of mine and deliver it to them, then turn away from them and see what they will answer."
    },
    {
      "id": 1138,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to answer",
      "hw": "جواب",
      "s": "Issuing a fatwa with «اَفْتٰی» for a difficult and complex issue. Giving a fatwa. (5 verses: 4:127-4:176-12:43-12:46-27:32)",
      "d": "«اَفْتٰی» means to answer a difficult and complex issue, whether it is a religious matter or related to worldly affairs. And «فتوٰی» in Islamic terminology means to seek an answer to a complex issue from a scholar. And «اِسْتِفْتَاء» means to seek an answer to such an issue. For example, in the Quran: «یَسۡتَفۡتُوۡنَکَ ؕ قُلِ اللّٰہُ یُفۡتِیۡکُمۡ فِی الۡکَلٰلَۃِ» (4/176) Translation: People ask you for a fatwa. Say, 'Allah gives you a fatwa regarding kalalah.'"
    }
  ],
  "241": [
    {
      "id": 1139,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "youth",
      "hw": "جوانی",
      "s": "«حَلَمَ» meaning a boy becoming mature, reaching youth. (2 verses: 24:58-24:59)",
      "d": "«حُلُمًا» means a boy becoming mature (manjad) and «حُلُم» means having intercourse in a dream (m. r.). So when a boy experiences wet dream for the first time, that age is called «حُلُم» or the age of puberty, i.e., the beginning of youth. For example, in the Quran: «وَ اِذَا بَلَغَ  الۡاَطۡفَالُ مِنۡکُمُ الۡحُلُمَ فَلۡیَسۡتَاۡذِنُوۡا کَمَا اسۡتَاۡذَنَ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ» (24/59) Translation: And when your children reach puberty, they should seek permission as those before them used to seek permission."
    },
    {
      "id": 1140,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "youth",
      "hw": "جوانی",
      "s": "«اَشُدَّ» meaning to reach the maturity of intellect or age. (8 verses: 6:152-12:22-17:34-18:82-22:5-28:14-40:67-46:15)",
      "d": "«اَشُدَّ» means to reach the maturity of intellect or age (manjad) and this is approximately middle age. Full youth after which signs of old age begin. For example, in the Quran: «حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا بَلَغَ  اَشُدَّہٗ  وَ بَلَغَ  اَرۡبَعِیۡنَ سَنَۃً» (46/15) Translation: Until when he reaches full maturity and reaches forty years."
    }
  ],
  "242": [
    {
      "id": 1141,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "pair",
      "hw": "جوڑا",
      "s": "«زَوَّجَ» each of the male and female in a pair is called a spouse. (72 verses: 2:25-2:35-2:102-2:230-2:232-2:234-2:240-3:15-4:1-4:12-4:20-4:57-6:139-6:143-7:19-7:189-9:24-11:40-13:3-13:23-13:38-15:88-16:72-20:53-20:117-20:131-21:90-22:5-23:6-23:27-24:6-25:74-26:7-26:166-30:21-31:10-33:4-33:6-33:28-33:37-33:50-33:52-33:53-33:59-35:11-36:36-36:56-37:22-38:58-39:6-40:8-42:11-42:50-43:12-43:70-44:54-50:7-51:49-52:20-53:45-55:52-56:7-58:1-60:11-64:14-66:1-66:3-66:5-70:30-75:39-78:8-81:7)",
      "d": "The meanings of «زَوَّجَ» are very extensive. «زَوْج» means (1) wife or female (woman, feminine) (2) husband or male (man, masculine) (3) both husband and wife or male and female together are also one pair. And the pairing of male and female is called zawj. And unlike «نَکَحَ», «زَوَّجَ» is also applied to everything that has existence or consciousness of male and female, such as plants (i.e., things that grow from the earth, grass, herbs, plants, vegetables, etc.). Now, the pair has two parts. One is male things, called «ذَکَر» (plural «ذُکُوْر» and «ذُکْرَان»), and the other is female, called «اُنْثٰی» (plural «اُنَاث»). Then for «زَوَّجَ», it is not necessary that their sexual union occurs, but the word is applied even if one male and one female are separated. For example, in the Quran: «یَہَبُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ  اِنَاثًا وَّ یَہَبُ  لِمَنۡ  یَّشَآءُ   الذُّکُوۡرَ اَوۡ یُزَوِّجُہُمۡ ذُکۡرَانًا وَّ اِنَاثًا» (42/49,50) Translation: He grants daughters to whom He wills and grants sons to whom He wills, or He grants them both sons and daughters."
    },
    {
      "id": 1142,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "pair",
      "hw": "جوڑا",
      "s": "«شَفْعُ» meaning to pair one thing with another similar thing. (1 verse: 89:3)",
      "d": "«شَفْعُ» is applied to things in which male and female are not distinguished. And «شَفْعُ» means to pair one thing with another similar thing, and a pair is called «شَفْعٌ», and that which has no similar thing with it is called «وَتْر». And in numbers, those numbers that are divisible by two, such as two, four, six, eight, etc., are called «شَفْعُ» or «جُفْت». And numbers not divisible by two are called witar or taq, such as one, three, five, seven, etc. For example, in the Quran: «وَ الۡفَجۡرِ وَ  لَیَالٍ عَشۡرٍ وَّ الشَّفۡعِ وَ الۡوَتۡرِ» (89/1,2,3) Translation: By the dawn and ten nights and the pair and the odd. And «شَفَعَ» means to make pairs of such things. This word does not appear in the Quran. However, «شَفَعَ» comes in the meaning of intercession. For example, in the Quran: «مَنۡ ذَا الَّذِیۡ یَشۡفَعُ  عِنۡدَہٗۤ  اِلَّا بِاِذۡنِہٖ» (2/255) Translation: Who is it that can intercede with Him except by His permission?"
    }
  ],
  "243": [
    {
      "id": 1143,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to join",
      "hw": "جوڑنا",
      "s": "«وَصَلَ» meaning to mix and join. (3 verses: 2:27-13:21-13:25)",
      "d": "«وَصَلَ» means to mix and join (m. l.). In terms of mixing, its opposite is «فَصَلَ». And in terms of joining, its opposite is «قَطَعَ». And «وَصَلَ» means to mix one thing with another in such a way that they become connected. This word is used in both material and spiritual contexts. For example, in the Quran: «وَ یَقۡطَعُوۡنَ مَاۤ اَمَرَ اللّٰہُ بِہٖۤ  اَنۡ یُّوۡصَلَ» (2/27) Translation: And they cut off what Allah has ordered to be joined."
    },
    {
      "id": 1144,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to join",
      "hw": "جوڑنا",
      "s": "«خَصَفَ» meaning to join and patch. (2 verses: 7:22-20:121)",
      "d": "«خَصَفْ» refers to that piece of leather (or form or die) on which leather is placed to cut the size for new shoes (muf). And «خَصَفَ» means to sew shoes, to patch shoes. And «خَصَفَ الشَّیءُ عَلَی الشَّیء» means to place one thing on another and join and patch (manjad). For example, in the Quran: «بَدَتۡ لَہُمَا سَوۡاٰتُہُمَا وَ طَفِقَا یَخۡصِفٰنِ عَلَیۡہِمَا مِنۡ وَّرَقِ الۡجَنَّۃِ» (7/22) Translation: Then their private parts became apparent to them, and they began to patch themselves with leaves from Paradise."
    },
    {
      "id": 1145,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to join",
      "hw": "جوڑنا",
      "s": "«رَصَّ» meaning to join two things and plaster with mortar, etc. (1 verse: 61:4)",
      "d": "«رَصَّ» means to mix one thing with another, to stick, to plaster (manjad). And also means to join two things together (muf). Also, «رَصَّهُ» means to tin with solder (i.e., to apply a coating on utensils, to whiten, to varnish, to make shiny). And «رَصَاص» means solder (manjad). That is, the meaning of «رَصَّ» is to join something with some mortar, etc., to make it strong. For example, in the Quran: «اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُحِبُّ الَّذِیۡنَ یُقَاتِلُوۡنَ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِہٖ  صَفًّا کَاَنَّہُمۡ  بُنۡیَانٌ  مَّرۡصُوۡصٌ» (61/4) Translation: Indeed, Allah loves those who fight in His cause in ranks as if they were a solid structure, cemented together."
    }
  ],
  "244": [
    {
      "id": 1146,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "where, wherever",
      "hw": "جہاں",
      "s": "«حَیْثُ» its meaning is (where, wherever). (29 verses: 2:35-2:58-2:144-2:149-2:150-2:191-2:199-2:222-4:89-4:91-6:124-7:19-7:27-7:161-7:182-9:5-12:56-12:68-15:65-16:26-16:45-20:69-38:36-39:25-39:74-59:2-65:3-65:6-68:44)",
      "d": "«حَیْثُ» its meaning is (where, wherever) for an ambiguous place (i.e., hidden, concealed, unknown). And the sentence after it explains and clarifies it. For example, in the Quran: «وَ مِنۡ حَیۡثُ خَرَجۡتَ فَوَلِّ وَجۡہَکَ شَطۡرَ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ» (2/149) Translation: And from wherever you come out, turn your face toward the Sacred Mosque."
    },
    {
      "id": 1147,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "where, wherever",
      "hw": "جہاں",
      "s": "«حَیْثُمَا» means 'wherever' (1 verse: 2:149)",
      "d": "«حَیْثُمَا» means 'wherever'. The addition of «ما» is only for the sake of breadth in meaning.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ مِنۡ حَیۡثُ خَرَجۡتَ فَوَلِّ وَجۡہَکَ شَطۡرَ» (2/149)\nTranslation: And wherever you may be, turn your face towards it (the Sacred Mosque)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1148,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "where, wherever",
      "hw": "جہاں",
      "s": "«اَیْنَمَا» means 'where'. It is used to ask about a place (19 verses: 2:115, 2:148, 3:112, 4:78, 6:22, 7:37, 16:27, 16:76, 19:31, 26:92, 28:62, 28:74, 33:61, 40:73, 41:47, 57:4, 58:7, 75:10, 81:26)",
      "d": "«اَیْن» means 'where'. It comes to ask about a place. And «اَیْنَمَا» means 'any place'. In this way, «اَیْنَمَا» and «حَیْثُمَا» become synonymous. However, conditional meanings are also found in «اَیْنَمَا» (see Manjad. Q).\nFor example, in the Quran: «اَیۡنَمَا ثُقِفُوۡۤا اُخِذُوۡا وَ قُتِّلُوۡا تَقۡتِیۡلًا» (33/61)\nTranslation: Wherever you find them, seize them and kill them utterly."
    }
  ],
  "245": [
    {
      "id": 1149,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to scold, to rebuke",
      "hw": "جھڑکنا",
      "s": "«زَجَرَ» means to scold, to rebuke (3 verses: 37:2, 37:19, 79:13)",
      "d": "«زَجَرَ» means to warn someone in a loud voice. To scold. To drive away. To rebuke. And «زَجْرَۃٌ» means a rebuke.\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَالزّٰجِرٰتِ زَجۡرًا» (37/2)\nTranslation: Then (I swear by) the rebuking angels who rebuke."
    },
    {
      "id": 1150,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to scold, to rebuke",
      "hw": "جھڑکنا",
      "s": "«اِزْدَجَرَ» means to expel by scolding, to drive away (2 verses: 54:4, 54:9)",
      "d": "«اِزْدَجَرَ» means to drive someone away by scolding (transitive).\nFor example, in the Quran: «کَذَّبَتۡ قَبۡلَہُمۡ قَوۡمُ نُوۡحٍ فَکَذَّبُوۡا عَبۡدَنَا وَ قَالُوۡا مَجۡنُوۡنٌ وَّ ازۡدُجِرَ» (54/9)\nTranslation: Before them, the people of Noah denied Our servant and said, 'He is mad!' and he was driven away with scolding."
    },
    {
      "id": 1151,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to scold, to rebuke",
      "hw": "جھڑکنا",
      "s": "«نَھَرَ» means to scold harshly (2 verses: 17:23, 93:10)",
      "d": "«نَھَرَ» means for a liquid thing to flow forcefully. And «نَھَرَ السَّائِل» means to scold the asker and to use severity in scolding and rebuking (see Manjad). «اَلزَّجْرُ الْغَلِیْظ» (see Farahidi 188).\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ اَمَّا السَّآئِلَ فَلَا تَنۡہَرۡ» (93/10)\nTranslation: And as for the asker, do not scold him harshly."
    }
  ],
  "246": [
    {
      "id": 1152,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to incline, to lean",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "«جَنَحَ» means a natural inclination towards good, to be prone (1 verse: 8:61)",
      "d": "«جَنَحَ» means to incline to one side. «جَنَحَتِ السَّفِیْنَۃ» means the ship inclined to one side. And «جَنَاح» means a bird's wing, a person's side, and its dual is «جَنَاحَیْن». «جَنَاحَ» also means inclination towards goodness (virtue), while «جُنَاح» means inclination towards evil (sin).\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ اِنۡ جَنَحُوۡا لِلسَّلۡمِ فَاجۡنَحۡ لَہَا» (8/61)\nTranslation: And if they incline towards peace, then you too incline towards it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1153,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to incline, to lean",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "«مَالَ» means a natural inclination of the temperament towards something (2 verses: 4:27, 4:129)",
      "d": "«اَلْمَیْل» means natural leaning, i.e., the temperament's inclination. Attraction (see Manjad). The temperament's leaning towards something.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ لَنۡ تَسۡتَطِیۡعُوۡۤا اَنۡ تَعۡدِلُوۡا بَیۡنَ النِّسَآءِ وَ لَوۡ حَرَصۡتُمۡ فَلَا تَمِیۡلُوۡا کُلَّ الۡمَیۡلِ» (4/129)\nTranslation: And you will never be able to be equal between wives, even if you try hard. So do not incline entirely (towards one)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1156,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to incline, to lean",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "«رَکَنَ» means to incline for the sake of gaining strength or refuge (3 verses: 11:80, 11:113, 17:74)",
      "d": "«رُکن» means strength, dominance, fortress, strong side. And «رَکَنَ» means to rely on something and incline towards it from which strength is gained (see Manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ لَوۡ لَاۤ اَنۡ ثَبَّتۡنٰکَ لَقَدۡ کِدۡتَّ تَرۡکَنُ اِلَیۡہِمۡ شَیۡئًا قَلِیۡلًا» (17/74)\nTranslation: And had We not strengthened you, you would have almost inclined towards them a little."
    },
    {
      "id": 1157,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to incline, to lean",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "«مَادَ» means to bend due to movement or weight, to sway (3 verses: 16:15, 21:31, 31:10)",
      "d": "«مَادَ» means for something to bend due to movement occurring in it. To shake and bend in any direction due to movement (M. L). To move, to shake, to tremble (see Manjad). «مَادَتِ الغَّصْن» means the branch bent (see Manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ جَعَلۡنَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ رَوَاسِیَ اَنۡ تَمِیۡدَ بِہِمۡ» (21/31)\nTranslation: And We placed firm mountains in the earth lest it should sway with them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1158,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to incline, to lean",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "«خَشَعَ» means to bend with fear and humility, whose effect is apparent on the limbs (15 verses: 2:45, 3:199, 20:108, 21:90, 23:2, 33:35, 41:39, 42:45, 54:7, 57:16, 59:21, 68:43, 70:44, 79:9, 88:2)",
      "d": "«خَشَعَ» means to bend due to humility. Such fear whose effect is apparent on the limbs (transitive). This generally comes for the bending of the eye, face, voice, and heart. And it includes fear as well.\nFor example, for the voice, in the Quran: «وَ خَشَعَتِ الۡاَصۡوَاتُ لِلرَّحۡمٰنِ» (20/108)\nTranslation: And the voices will be humbled before the Most Merciful.\nFor example, for the eye, in the Quran: «خَاشِعَۃً اَبۡصَارُہُمۡ تَرۡہَقُہُمۡ ذِلَّۃٌ» (70:44)\nTranslation: Their eyes will be humbled, and humiliation will cover them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1159,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "«ذَلَّ» means to bend due to force, oppression, or pressure (25 verses: 2:61-3:26-3:112-3:123-5:54-7:152-10:26-10:27-11:27-16:70-17:24-17:111-20:134-22:5-26:111-27:34-27:37-36:72-42:45-58:20-63:8-67:15-68:43-70:44-76:14)",
      "d": "«ذَلَّ» means to bend due to force, oppression, and pressure. To become humiliated (intransitive), and its opposite is «عَزَّ». The natural intensity and harshness being overcome spontaneously (intransitive).\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ دَانِیَۃً  عَلَیۡہِمۡ  ظِلٰلُہَا وَ ذُلِّلَتۡ قُطُوۡفُہَا تَذۡلِیۡلًا» (76/14)\nTranslation: They will be close to them (the fruit-laden branches and their shades). And the bunches of fruits will be hanging bent down."
    },
    {
      "id": 1160,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "«عَالَ» means such a bending in which another's right is violated (4 verses: 4:3-10:83-23:46-44:31)",
      "d": "«عَول» means to oppress. To deviate from the straight path (from Munjid). «اَلْعَوْل» is used for every such thing that overpowers a person and they are crushed under its burden (intransitive). This refers to such a bending in which someone's right is violated.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«فَاِنۡ خِفۡتُمۡ اَلَّا تَعۡدِلُوۡا فَوَاحِدَۃً اَوۡ مَا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ ؕ ذٰلِکَ اَدۡنٰۤی اَلَّا تَعُوۡلُوۡا» (4/3)\nTranslation: If you fear that you will not be able to treat all women equally, then one (woman) is sufficient, or a slave woman whom you own. This is so that you do not incline to one side (Uthmani)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1161,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "«دَنٰی» means to bend and become close (13 verses: 2:282-4:3-5:108-6:99-30:3-33:51-33:59-53:8-53:9-55:54-69:23-73:20-76:14)",
      "d": "«دَنٰی» means to be near. To be close. And if its relation is towards some height, then it will mean to bend and become close.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ  جَنَا  الۡجَنَّتَیۡنِ  دَانٍ» (55/54)\nTranslation: And the ripe fruits of both gardens will be bending (i.e., becoming close to the ground)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1162,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "«جَنَفَ» means to bend due to partisanship (1 verse: 2:182)",
      "d": "«جَنَفَ» means to practice partisanship. To favor a side. The direction of bending towards one party.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«فَمَنۡ خَافَ مِنۡ مُّوۡصٍ جَنَفًا اَوۡ اِثۡمًا» (2/182)\nTranslation: Then whoever fears from the testator any partisanship or injustice."
    },
    {
      "id": 1163,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "«صَبَا» means to incline towards childish, undignified movements due to childhood, to be inclined towards childlike actions (1 verse: 12:33)",
      "d": "«صَبُو , صَبِیٌّ» means child, little boy, and its plural is « صِبْیَان» and «صَبَا» comes meaning to be inclined towards childlike movements. And «تَصَبِّی» means to be inclined towards play (M. Q.). Thus, «صَبَاءَ» refers to such an inclination that is due to childhood.\nFor example, in the Quran it is, Joseph (peace be upon him) said:\n«وَ اِلَّا تَصۡرِفۡ عَنِّیۡ کَیۡدَہُنَّ اَصۡبُ  اِلَیۡہِنَّ» (12/33)\nTranslation: (O Allah!) If You do not turn away from me their plot, I will incline towards them."
    }
  ],
  "247": [
    {
      "id": 1164,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکانا",
      "s": "«خَفَضَ» is used for bending or lowering (4 verses: 15:88-17:24-26:215-56:3)",
      "d": "«خَفَضَ» means to bend. To lower. And its opposite is «رَفَعَ» meaning to raise, to elevate. «خَفَضَ» is used in both literal and metaphorical senses. «خَافِضُ» and «رَافِعُ» are both names of Allah.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ اخۡفِضۡ لَہُمَا جَنَاحَ الذُّلِّ مِنَ الرَّحۡمَۃِ» (17/24)\nTranslation: And while treating them with love, bend yourself before them with humility."
    },
    {
      "id": 1165,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکانا",
      "s": "«غَضَّ» is used for lowering the gaze or reducing the voice (4 verses: 24:30-24:31-31:19-49:3)",
      "d": "«غَضَّ» is specific for lowering the gaze or reducing the voice (M. Q.).\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«قُلۡ لِّلۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ یَغُضُّوۡا مِنۡ  اَبۡصَارِہِمۡ» (24/30)\nTranslation: Tell the believing men to lower their gaze."
    },
    {
      "id": 1166,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکانا",
      "s": "«رَکَعَ» means to bend the body, specifically to bend the waist in the state of bowing (7 verses: 2:43-2:125-3:43-22:26-22:77-48:29-77:48)",
      "d": "«رَکَعَ» means to bend the body, to lower the head. To bend the waist (intransitive). Metonymically, it means to perform prayer.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ  اِذَا قِیۡلَ لَہُمُ  ارۡکَعُوۡا  لَا  یَرۡکَعُوۡنَ» (77/48)\nTranslation: And when it is said to them, 'Bend (in prayer),' they do not bend."
    },
    {
      "id": 1167,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To Bow / Lower (the head)",
      "hw": "جھکانا",
      "s": "نَکَسَ means to turn upside down or reverse. (2 verses: 21:65-36:68)",
      "d": "نَکَسَ means to turn upside down or reverse. And «نَکَسَ رَأْسَہٗ» means to bow one's head. To be humbled. To lower one's head in shame and regret. And «تَنَکَّسَ الْعَلَم» means the flag is lowered (hanging down). And «اِنْتَکَسَ» means to fall flat on one's face. And «نَکَسَ عَلٰی رَاْسِہٖ» is an idiom meaning to become speechless and lower one's head in shame.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ  نُکِسُوۡا عَلٰی  رُءُوۡسِہِمۡ ۚ لَقَدۡ  عَلِمۡتَ مَا ہٰۤؤُلَآءِ  یَنۡطِقُوۡنَ» ( 21/65 )\nTranslation: Then they lowered their heads [in shame]. [Even after that, they said to Ibrahim], 'You surely know that these [idols] do not speak!'"
    }
  ],
  "248": [
    {
      "id": 1168,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "«شَجَرَ» means to have a difference of opinion (1 verse: 4:65)",
      "d": "«شَجَرَ» means to argue and disagree (intransitive). To discuss. To have differing opinions (from Munjid). To argue based on a difference of opinion while the parties agree on principles and the argument is of a subsidiary nature (minor issues, small matters).\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«فَلَا وَ رَبِّکَ لَا یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ حَتّٰی  یُحَکِّمُوۡکَ فِیۡمَا شَجَرَ  بَیۡنَہُمۡ» (4/65)\nTranslation: So by your Lord, they will not believe until they make you a judge in what they dispute among themselves."
    },
    {
      "id": 1169,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "«تَنَازَعَ» to engage in a tug-of-war over a difference of opinion (7 verses: 3:152-4:59-8:43-8:46-18:21-20:62-52:23)",
      "d": "«تَنَازَعَ» means to disagree and pull towards oneself (manjad) and «نَزَع» means to pull something from its place of residence, to tug, to prolong a quarrel (muf). For example, in the Quran: «فَاِنۡ تَنَازَعۡتُمۡ فِیۡ شَیۡءٍ فَرُدُّوۡہُ اِلَی اللّٰہِ وَ الرَّسُوۡلِ» (4/59) Translation: Then if you quarrel about something, refer it to Allah and the Messenger."
    },
    {
      "id": 1170,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "«حَاجَّ» to argue on the basis of evidence (11 verses: 2:76-2:139-2:258-3:20-3:61-3:65-3:66-3:73-6:80-40:47-42:16)",
      "d": "«حَجَّ» means to prevail in evidence. And «حُجَّۃٌ» means evidence. And «اِحْتَجَّ» means to present evidence for one's claim (manjad). Thus, «حَاجّ» refers to debating with evidence and refuting another's statement with proof. For example, in the Quran: «اَلَمۡ تَرَ اِلَی الَّذِیۡ حَآجَّ اِبۡرٰہٖمَ فِیۡ رَبِّہٖۤ» (2/258) Translation: Have you not seen the one who argued with Abraham about his Lord?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1171,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "«جَدَلَ» to try to gain superiority over another in conversation (26 verses: 4:107-4:109-6:25-6:121-7:71-8:6-11:32-11:74-13:13-16:111-16:125-18:54-18:56-22:3-22:8-22:68-29:46-31:20-40:4-40:5-40:35-40:56-40:69-42:35-43:58-58:1)",
      "d": "«جَدَلَ» means to try to gain superiority over another in conversation, to repeat unnecessarily (muf). And «جَدَلَ» also means to wrangle and bring down to the ground (manjad), and in the context of question and answer, to argue (m. q). According to the author of Maqayis al-Lughah, it means to prolong a quarrel with lengthy talk (m. l). For example, in the Quran: «یُجَادِلُوۡنَکَ فِی الۡحَقِّ بَعۡدَ مَا تَبَیَّنَ» (8/6) Translation: They argue with you about the truth after it has become clear."
    },
    {
      "id": 1172,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "«مَارَ» to argue about something in which there is hesitation to accept (5 verses: 18:22-42:18-53:12-53:55-54:36)",
      "d": "«مِرْیَۃ» means hesitation and doubt. And «مَارَ» means to argue about something in which there is hesitation to accept (muf). For example, in the Quran: «مَا کَذَبَ الۡفُؤَادُ ی مَا  رَاٰی اَفَتُمٰرُوۡنَہٗ  عَلٰی مَا یَرٰی» (53/11,12) Translation: The heart did not deny what he saw. Do you then argue with him about what he sees?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1173,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "«خَصْم» to argue with others on the basis of being a claimant to something (13 verses: 2:204-3:44-22:19-26:96-27:45-36:49-38:21-38:22-38:69-39:31-43:18-43:58-50:28)",
      "d": "«خَصْم» means claimant. The claimant (the one making a claim) and the one against whom the claim is made, or either one. The opposing party. Whether an individual or a group. A dispute or case in which the rights of the parties are under discussion. And «اَخْصَمَ» means to provide evidence against someone, to present proof (manjad). For example, in the Quran: «وَ ہَلۡ  اَتٰىکَ نَبَؤُا الۡخَصۡمِ» (38/21) Translation: Has there come to you the news of the disputants? (Jalandhari) And: Has there reached you the news of those who claim (Uthmani ؒ)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1174,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "«لَدّ» meaning severe quarrel (2 verses: 2:204-19:97)",
      "d": "«لَدّ» means «شدّۃ الخصومۃ» i.e., severe quarrel (f. l 48). And «اَلَدّ» means a severe quarreler. A person who considers another's statement suitable, worthy of attention, understands it, and makes a noise for his own point. For example, in the Quran: «وَ یُشۡہِدُ اللّٰہَ عَلٰی مَا فِیۡ  قَلۡبِہٖ  ۙ وَ ہُوَ  اَلَدُّ  الۡخِصَامِ» (2/204) Translation: And he makes Allah a witness over what is in his heart, and he is a severe quarreler."
    },
    {
      "id": 1175,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "«تَشَاکَسَ» to argue with each other for one's right due to ill-nature and stinginess (1 verse: 39:29)",
      "d": "«اَلشِّکْس» means an ill-natured person. And «تَشَاکَسَ» means to quarrel with each other due to ill-nature (muf). And «شَکَسَ» means to be of harsh nature and stingy (manjad). Thus, «تَشَاکَسَ» means to pull and tug with each other for one's own right due to stinginess, harsh nature, and ill-temper. For example, in the Quran: «ضَرَبَ اللّٰہُ  مَثَلًا رَّجُلًا فِیۡہِ  شُرَکَآءُ مُتَشٰکِسُوۡنَ وَ رَجُلًا سَلَمًا  لِّرَجُلٍ ؕ ہَلۡ  یَسۡتَوِیٰنِ مَثَلًا» (39/29) Translation: Allah sets forth an example: a man with partners who are at odds with each other, and a man who is entirely owned by one man. Are they equal in example?"
    }
  ],
  "249": [
    {
      "id": 1176,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "falsehood",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "«کِذْب» lie, statement contrary to fact (36 verses: 3:75-3:78-3:94-4:50-5:41-5:42-5:70-5:103-6:21-6:24-6:93-6:144-7:37-7:89-10:60-10:69-11:18-12:18-12:110-16:105-16:116-18:5-18:15-20:61-23:38-29:68-34:8-39:32-39:60-42:24-53:11-56:2-58:14-61:7-72:5-78:35)",
      "d": "«کِذْب» means to give false information knowingly (manjad), lack of harmony between heart and tongue (muf), or to say something contrary to fact. Its opposite is «صِدْق». For example, in the Quran: «وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ الۡکَذِبَ وَ ہُمۡ  یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ» (3/78) Translation: And they speak falsehood against Allah while they know."
    },
    {
      "id": 1177,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Falsehood / Lie",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "«بَاطِل» means something non-lasting and baseless; in a very broad sense, it includes كذب (lying). (25 verses: 2:42-2:188-3:71-3:191-4:29-4:161-7:139-8:8-9:34-11:16-13:17-16:72-17:81-18:56-21:18-22:62-29:52-29:67-31:30-34:49-38:27-40:5-41:42-42:24-47:3)",
      "d": "«بَاطِل» means something in which, after investigation, no strength or permanence is found. Unjust, baseless, useless, and frivolous talk. Its opposite is «حَقّ», meaning truth, reality, and veracity. Thus, the word باطل is used in a wide sense, one meaning of which is كذب or lie.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ لِمَ تَلۡبِسُوۡنَ الۡحَقَّ بِالۡبَاطِلِ» ( 3/71 )\nTranslation: O People of the Scripture, why do you mix the truth with falsehood?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1178,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "falsehood",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "«زُوْرُ» meaning lie against the truth and associating partners with Allah (5 verses: 18:17-22:30-25:4-25:72-58:2)",
      "d": "«زَوْرُ» means the crookedness of the upper part of the chest. And «زُوْر» means lie against the truth and associating partners with Allah (manjad). And «زَاوَرَ» means to deviate from the path of truth, to turn aside from the straight path. In the Quran, the words «قَوْلَ الزُّوْر» (false statement) are contrasted with «قَوْلًا سَدِیْدًا» (a straightforward statement) which means a statement without any defect, ambiguity, confusion, or complexity. And «قَوْلَ الزُّوْر» is a statement that has these qualities. According to Abu al-Halal al-Askari, «زُوْر» is a lie that is fabricated and presented to appear good and correct (f. l 34). For example, in the Quran: «فَاجۡتَنِبُوا الرِّجۡسَ مِنَ الۡاَوۡثَانِ وَ اجۡتَنِبُوۡا  قَوۡلَ  الزُّوۡرِ» (22/30) Translation: So avoid the impurity of idols and avoid false statements."
    },
    {
      "id": 1179,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Lie",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "«اِفْک» means to fabricate something with malicious intent, and it is also related to slander. (12 verses: 7:117-24:11-24:12-25:4-26:45-29:17-34:43-37:151-46:11-46:22-46:28-51:9)",
      "d": "«اَفَکَ» means to turn away from the correct direction with malice (singular). To make something into something else. Fabricating stories. Accusation. Slander. And this is the worst type of lie. According to the author of 'Furūq al-Lughawiyyah', this lie is related to the slander of heinous acts like adultery (Furūq 33).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«لَوۡ لَاۤ اِذۡ سَمِعۡتُمُوۡہُ ظَنَّ الۡمُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ وَ الۡمُؤۡمِنٰتُ بِاَنۡفُسِہِمۡ خَیۡرًا ۙ وَّ قَالُوۡا ہٰذَاۤ اِفۡکٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ» (24/12)\nTranslation: When you heard it, why did the believing men and women not think good of themselves and say, 'This is a clear scandal.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1180,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Telling or making a lie",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "«کَذَبَ» means to speak a statement contrary to reality or to lie. (41 verses: 2:10-3:61-6:28-7:66-9:42-9:43-9:77-9:90-9:107-11:27-11:93-12:26-12:27-12:74-16:39-16:62-16:86-16:105-23:90-24:7-24:8-24:13-26:186-26:223-27:27-28:38-29:3-29:12-36:15-37:152-38:4-39:3-40:24-40:28-40:37-54:25-54:26-58:18-59:11-63:1-96:16)",
      "d": "«کَذَبَ» means to deliberately give a report that is contrary to the facts.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ إِن كَانَ قَمِيصُهُ قُدَّ مِن دُبُرٍ فَكَذَبَتْ وَهُوَ مِنَ الصَّادِقِينَ» (12/27)\nTranslation: And if his shirt is torn from the back, then she has lied and he is of the truthful."
    },
    {
      "id": 1181,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Telling or making a lie",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "«اَفَکَ» means to slander someone. (2 verses: 26:222-45:7)",
      "d": "«اَفَکَ» means to turn something away. To fabricate something with malice, as mentioned above. And this is the worst type of lie.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«هَلْ أُنَبِّئُكُمْ عَلَى مَنْ تَنَزَّلُ الشَّيَاطِينُ تَنَزَّلُ عَلَى كُلِّ أَفَّاكٍ أَثِيمٍ» (26:221,222)\nTranslation: (Well) shall I tell you upon whom the devils descend? They descend upon every sinful liar."
    }
  ],
  "250": [
    {
      "id": 1184,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To deny",
      "hw": "جھٹلانا",
      "s": "«اَبْطَلَ» is used to prove something false through evidence, experience, and observations. (10 verses: 2:264-7:118-7:173-8:8-10:81-29:48-30:58-40:78-45:27-47:33)",
      "d": "«بَاطِل» means unjust and transient, and its opposite is «حَقْ». Just as truth has the meaning of truth, similarly «بَاطِل» also has the meaning of falsehood. And «اَبْطَلَ» means to deny something or prove it false with circumstances and events.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«لِيُحِقَّ الْحَقَّ وَيُبْطِلَ الْبَاطِلَ وَلَوْ كَرِهَ الْمُجْرِمُونَ» (8/8)\nTranslation: So that Allah may establish the truth and destroy the falsehood, even if the criminals dislike it."
    }
  ],
  "251": [
    {
      "id": 1185,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Key",
      "hw": "کنجی",
      "s": "«مَقَالِید» is the plural of «مَقْلَد», meaning keys. (2 verses: 39:63-42:12)",
      "d": "«قَلَدَ» means to make iron pliable and to bend or twist something into a clasp. And «قِلَادُ» or «اِقْليْدُ» refers to a string of copper or brass used in a necklace. And «قِلَادَةُ» means a necklace. «مِقلَد» is the iron key that is bent into a lock to open it. Its plurals are «مَقالِدُ» and «مَقَالِیْد». For example, the Quran says:\n«لَهُ مَقَالِيدُ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضِ يَبْسُطُ الرِّزْقَ لِمَنْ يَشَاءُ وَيَقْدِرُ» (42/12)\nTranslation: To Him belong the keys of the heavens and the earth. He expands provision for whom He wills and restricts [for whom He wills]."
    },
    {
      "id": 1186,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Key",
      "hw": "کنجی",
      "s": "«مَفاتِح» means keys, and it is also used in the sense of opening something or removing restrictions and complexities. (3 verses: 6:59-24:61-28:76)",
      "d": "«فَتَحَ» means to open or to remove restrictions and complexities (mufrad). This word is used in various meanings: opening a door, opening a lock, opening a path for water to flow, deciding a case, and conquering a land. The plural of «مِفْتَحٌ» is «مَفَاتِح», which means keys and also water channels. (According to the lexicon) The plural of «مِفْتَاحٌ» is «مَفَاتِيْحُ». (According to the lexicon) This word is not used in the Quran. Thus, the word «مَفَاتِحُ» is more specific than «مَقَالِیْد», as it pertains to removing and opening all kinds of restrictions and obstacles.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَعِنْدَهُ مَفَاتِيحُ الْغَيْبِ لَا يَعْلَمُهَا إِلَّا هُوَ» (6/59)\nTranslation: And with Him are the keys of the unseen; none knows them except Him."
    }
  ],
  "252": [
    {
      "id": 1187,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Cloak",
      "hw": "چادر",
      "s": "«خُمُر» means a shawl, dupatta, or veil. (1 verse: 24:31)",
      "d": "«خُمُر» is the plural of «خِمَار», meaning a shawl, dupatta, or veil. (According to the lexicon) «خِمَار» is a small cloak or dupatta with which one can cover the face and also cover the sides and chest.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَلْيَضْرِبْنَ بِخُمُرِهِنَّ عَلَى جُيُوبِهِنَّ» (24/31)\nTranslation: And let them draw their shawls over their bosoms."
    },
    {
      "id": 1188,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Cloak",
      "hw": "چادر",
      "s": "«جَلَابِیْب» means a cloak or shirt. (1 verse: 33:59)",
      "d": "«جَلَابِیْب» is the plural of «جِلْبَاب», meaning a cloak or shirt. And «جَلْبَبَ» means to wear a cloak or shirt. (According to the lexicon) «جَلْبَاب» is actually a large cloak that can cover the entire body from head to toe.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا النَّبِيُّ قُل لِّأَزْوَاجِكَ وَبَنَاتِكَ وَنِسَاءِ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ يُدْنِينَ عَلَيْهِنَّ مِن جَلَابِيبِهِنَّ ۚ ذَٰلِكَ أَدْنَىٰ أَن يُعْرَفْنَ فَلَا يُؤْذَيْنَ» (33/59)\nTranslation: O Prophet, tell your wives and your daughters and the women of the believers to bring down over themselves [part] of their outer garments. That is more suitable that they will be recognized and not be harmed."
    }
  ],
  "253": [
    {
      "id": 1189,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Fodder",
      "hw": "چارہ",
      "s": "«مَرْعٰی» is used for fresh fodder. (2 verses: 79:31-87:4)",
      "d": "«رَعٰی» means for livestock to graze on grass. The word «مَرْعٰی» also means pasture. And it also means fresh grass or fodder. (According to the lexicon)\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَالَّذِي أَخْرَجَ الْمَرْعَى فَجَعَلَهُ غُثَاءً أَحْوَى» (87:4,5)\nTranslation: And who has brought forth the pasture and made it dark stubble."
    },
    {
      "id": 1190,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Fodder",
      "hw": "چارہ",
      "s": "«اَبّ» is fodder that is dry. (1 verse: 80:31)",
      "d": "«اَبّ» is grass that is completely ready for animals to graze on and be cut (mufrad). According to the author of the lexicon, this word applies to all kinds of fodder, wet or dry, that is animal feed, such as chopped fodder, grass, hay, etc. Or fodder that can be stored. Just as «فَاکِھَۃ» (fruits) is for humans, «اَبّ» is for livestock. «فَاکِھَۃ» means fruits, whether dry or fresh. Similarly, «اَبّ» is used for dry and fresh fodder. (m. q.)\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَفَاكِهَةً وَأَبًّا مَتَاعًا لَّكُمْ وَلِأَنْعَامِكُمْ» (80:31,32)\nTranslation: And [He produced] fruits and fodder as provision for you and for your livestock."
    },
    {
      "id": 1191,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "fodder",
      "hw": "چارہ",
      "s": "«عَصْف» is that part of fodder which animals leave after grazing, i.e., leftover fodder (3 verses: 55:12-77:2-105:5)",
      "d": "«عَصْف» refers to the husks and chaff of grain (per some lexicographers), straw, etc. And «عصف ماکول» is that part or stalk (of any vegetable or leaf that is attached to a branch) which animals leave after grazing. According to the author of Munjid, they are the stalks of crops and straw stalks. «عَصَفَ» means to blow violently (wind), and «عَاصِفَہ» refers to a storm. And that storm which blows away grass, fodder, and its stalks is also called «عَصْف». For example, the Quran states: «فَجَعَلَہُمۡ کَعَصۡفٍ مَّاۡکُوۡلٍ» (105/5) Translation: So He made them like eaten straw."
    }
  ],
  "254": [
    {
      "id": 1192,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "moon",
      "hw": "چاند",
      "s": "«اَھِلَّۃ» is the plural of «ھَلَال». It refers only to the new moon or crescent-shaped moon, i.e., from the 26th day's moon up to the third (day's moon) (27 verses: 2:189-6:77-6:96-7:54-10:5-12:4-13:2-14:33-16:12-21:33-22:18-25:61-29:61-31:29-35:13-36:39-36:40-39:5-41:37-54:1-55:5-71:16-74:32-75:8-75:9-84:18-91:2)",
      "d": "«اَھِلَّۃ» is the plural of «ھَلَال». And «ھَلَال» means new moon, and «ھَلَّ» means the appearance of a crescent. And «اَھَلَّ» means to make something known. For example, when people see the new moon, they point it out, show it, and make it known to each other. For example, the Quran states: «یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الۡاَہِلَّۃِ  ؕ قُلۡ ہِیَ مَوَاقِیۡتُ لِلنَّاسِ وَ الۡحَجِّ» (2/189) Translation: (O Prophet) people ask you about the new moons. Say, 'They are appointed times for people and for Hajj.'"
    }
  ],
  "255": [
    {
      "id": 1194,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To Will / Desire (Divine Will)",
      "hw": "چاہنا",
      "s": "«شَآءَ» is a wish or intention that is subordinate to Allah's decree and does not occur before or after its appointed time. (190 verses: 2:20-2:70-2:90-2:105-2:142-2:212-2:213-2:220-2:247-2:251-2:253-2:255-2:261-2:269-2:272-2:284-3:6-3:13-3:26-3:27-3:37-3:40-3:47-3:73-3:74-3:129-3:179-4:48-4:49-4:90-4:116-4:133-5:17-5:18-5:40-5:48-5:54-5:64-6:35-6:39-6:41-6:80-6:83-6:88-6:107-6:111-6:112-6:128-6:133-6:137-6:138-6:148-6:149-7:89-7:100-7:128-7:155-7:156-7:188-8:31-9:15-9:27-9:28-10:16-10:25-10:49-10:99-10:107-11:33-11:87-11:107-11:108-11:118-12:56-12:76-12:99-12:100-12:110-13:13-13:26-13:27-13:31-13:39-14:4-14:11-14:19-14:27-16:2-16:9-16:31-16:35-16:93-17:18-17:30-17:54-18:24-18:29-18:39-18:69-21:9-22:5-22:18-23:24-24:21-24:35-24:38-24:43-24:45-24:46-25:10-25:16-25:45-25:57-26:4-27:87-28:27-28:56-28:68-28:82-29:21-29:62-30:5-30:37-30:48-30:54-33:24-33:51-34:9-34:13-34:36-34:39-35:1-35:8-35:16-35:22-36:43-36:47-36:66-36:67-37:102-39:4-39:23-39:34-39:52-39:68-39:74-40:15-41:14-42:8-42:12-42:13-42:19-42:22-42:27-42:29-42:33-42:49-42:50-42:51-42:52-43:20-43:60-47:4-47:30-48:14-48:25-48:27-50:35-53:26-56:65-56:70-57:21-57:29-59:6-62:4-73:19-74:31-74:37-74:55-74:56-76:29-76:30-76:31-78:39-80:12-80:22-81:28-81:29-82:8-87:7)",
      "d": "The root of «شَآءَ» is «شَیْء», meaning 'a thing'. And «شَیْء» is that which can be known and about which information can be given. Its plural is أشیاء. «شِیْئَۃ» and «مَشِیْئَۃ» are nouns meaning 'intention'. Originally, «مَشِیْئَۃ» means the creation of something or obtaining it. But since Allah alone is the One who brings everything into existence and manages it, the term مشیئت is used only in the meaning of Divine Will.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَخۡلُقُ مَا یَشَآءُ ؕ یَہَبُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ اِنَاثًا وَّ یَہَبُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ الذُّکُوۡرَ» (42/49)\nTranslation: He creates what He wills. He grants to whom He wills daughters and grants to whom He wills sons."
    },
    {
      "id": 1195,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To Will / Desire (General Intention)",
      "hw": "چاہنا",
      "s": "«اَرَادَ» is general, meaning a wish or intention that may or may not be subordinate to Divine Will and can occur before or after its appointed time. (94 verses: 2:26-2:108-2:185-2:228-2:233-2:253-3:108-3:152-3:176-4:26-4:27-4:28-4:35-4:44-4:60-4:88-4:91-4:134-4:144-4:150-5:1-5:6-5:17-5:29-5:37-5:49-5:91-5:113-6:52-7:110-8:7-8:62-8:67-8:71-9:32-9:46-9:55-9:85-10:107-11:15-11:34-11:79-11:88-11:107-12:25-13:11-14:10-17:18-17:19-17:103-18:28-18:77-18:82-20:63-21:70-22:14-22:16-22:22-23:24-25:62-26:35-28:5-28:19-28:27-28:79-28:83-30:38-30:39-32:20-33:13-33:17-33:33-33:50-34:43-35:10-36:82-37:86-37:98-38:6-39:4-39:38-40:31-42:20-48:11-48:15-51:57-52:42-61:8-72:10-74:31-74:52-75:5-76:9-85:16)",
      "d": "There is also a difference between Divine Will (مشیئت) and Divine Intention (ارادہ). مشیئت is an intention whose occurrence is necessary according to Allah's knowledge and decree.\nFor example: A blessed Hadith states: «مَا شَآءَ اللہُ کَانَ وَ مَا لَمْ یَشَآءُ لَمْ یَکُنْ» (Sunan Abu Dawood, Hadith No. 5075). Meaning: Whatever Allah wills happens, and whatever He does not will does not happen. Whereas Divine Intention (ارادہ) is not necessarily indicative of its final occurrence.\nAnd for example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یُرِیۡدُ اللّٰہُ بِکُمُ الۡیُسۡرَ وَ لَا یُرِیۡدُ بِکُمُ الۡعُسۡرَ» ( 2/185 )\nTranslation: Allah intends for you ease and does not intend for you hardship.\nSimilarly, at another place, the Divine Command states:\n«وَ مَا اللّٰہُ یُرِیۡدُ ظُلۡمًا  لِّلۡعِبَادِ» ( 40/31 )\nTranslation: And Allah intends no injustice for [His] servants.\nEven though it is evident that hardship, constriction, and injustice are found among people. Because مشیئت necessitates these things. When the verb «شَاءَ» is attributed to a human, it refers to a wish or intention that is subordinate to Allah's decree.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ مَا تَشَآءُوۡنَ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یَّشَآءَ اللّٰہُ  رَبُّ الۡعٰلَمِیۡنَ» ( 81/29 )\nTranslation: And you do not will except what Allah wills, Lord of the worlds.\nWhereas a human's intention is free from this restriction; it can be against Divine Will. For example, a person wishes that death would not come to him. But such an occurrence is against Divine Will. Hence, it cannot happen.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یُرِیۡدُوۡنَ  لِیُطۡفِئُوۡا  نُوۡرَ اللّٰہِ  بِاَفۡوَاہِہِمۡ وَ اللّٰہُ  مُتِمُّ  نُوۡرِہٖ  وَ لَوۡ  کَرِہَ  الۡکٰفِرُوۡنَ» ( 61/8 )\nTranslation: They desire to extinguish the light of Allah with their mouths, but Allah will perfect His light, even if the disbelievers dislike it.\nFurthermore, the clear difference between intention (ارادہ) and Divine Will (مشیئت) is that intention can occur before or after [its appointed time], but the time of Divine Will is fixed and cannot be before or after. (Fuqaha)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1196,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to desire",
      "hw": "چاہنا",
      "s": "«اِشْتَھٰی» means to desire desirable things, to crave natural inclinations (8 verses: 16:57-21:102-34:54-41:31-43:71-52:22-56:21-77:42)",
      "d": "«اِشْتَھٰی» means the self being drawn towards something it naturally likes. Natural inclinations such as hunger, lust, greed, etc. (Mufradat). Its opposite is «نَفَرَ». And the author of Munjid writes its meaning as desiring desirable things (Munjid) such desires in which intention is not involved (Faqih al-Lugha, p. 98). For example, the Quran states: «وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَا تَشۡتَہِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسُکُمۡ وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَا تَدَّعُوۡنَ» (41/31) Translation: And there you will have whatever your selves desire, and you will have whatever you call for."
    },
    {
      "id": 1197,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to desire",
      "hw": "چاہنا",
      "s": "«بَغٰی» means to go beyond the limits of moderation in seeking something (79 verses: 2:90-2:187-2:198-2:207-2:213-2:265-2:272-3:7-3:19-3:83-3:85-3:99-4:24-4:34-4:94-4:104-4:114-4:139-5:2-5:35-5:50-6:35-6:114-6:146-6:164-7:33-7:45-7:86-7:140-9:47-9:48-10:23-10:90-11:19-12:65-13:17-13:22-14:3-16:14-16:90-17:12-17:28-17:42-17:57-17:66-17:110-18:64-18:108-22:60-23:7-24:33-28:55-28:73-28:76-28:77-29:17-30:23-30:46-33:51-35:12-38:22-38:24-42:14-42:27-42:39-42:42-45:12-45:17-48:29-49:9-55:20-57:27-59:8-60:1-62:10-66:1-70:31-73:20-92:20)",
      "d": "«بَغٰی» means to desire beyond the limits of moderation in seeking something (Mufradat). And this trait can be praiseworthy (good), such as going beyond obligatory duties to perform voluntary acts of worship. And it can be blameworthy (bad), such as inclining towards falsehood by exceeding the bounds of truth. For example, the Quran states: «قَالُوۡا  یٰۤاَبَانَا مَا نَبۡغِیۡ ؕ ہٰذِہٖ  بِضَاعَتُنَا رُدَّتۡ اِلَیۡنَا» (12/65) Translation: They said, 'O our father, what more could we desire? This our merchandise has been returned to us.' It seems that this 'merchandise' that came out of the belongings of Yusuf's brothers, they had no right to it, yet they obtained it. And «اِبْتَغٰی» means to seek something with effort (Mufradat), i.e., to do more than the necessary effort. For example, the Quran states: «اِلَّا ابۡتِغَآءَ  وَجۡہِ  رَبِّہِ الۡاَعۡلٰی» (92/20) Translation: But only seeking the pleasure of his Lord, the Most High."
    }
  ],
  "256": [
    {
      "id": 1199,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to become silent; to remain",
      "hw": "چپ",
      "s": "«سَکَتَ» means to become silent while speaking (2 verses: 7:154-17:100)",
      "d": "«سَکَتَ» means to stop while talking, to cease, to become silent. (Munjid, Lisan al-Arab) In this meaning, this word has not been used in the Quran. However, it is used for the cessation of anger. For example, the Quran states: «وَ لَمَّا سَکَتَ عَنۡ  مُّوۡسَی الۡغَضَبُ» (7/154) Translation: And when the anger of Musa subsided."
    },
    {
      "id": 1200,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To Be Silent / Remain",
      "hw": "چپ",
      "s": "«صَمَتَ» is used for a person of a silent nature or one who speaks little. (1 verse: 7:193)",
      "d": "«صَمَتَ» means to remain silent, to be of a silent or taciturn nature.\nFor example: The Noble Hadith states: «مَنْ صَمَتَ نَجَا» meaning: The one who remains silent is saved. The opposite of «صَمَتَ» is «نَطَقَ». And (مال صامت) refers to cash and currency, whereas (مال ناطق) refers to livestock. (Munjid)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«سَوَآءٌ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اَدَعَوۡتُمُوۡہُمۡ  اَمۡ  اَنۡتُمۡ  صَامِتُوۡنَ» ( 7/193 )\nTranslation: It is all the same for you whether you invite them or you are silent."
    },
    {
      "id": 1201,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to be silent; to remain",
      "hw": "چپ",
      "s": "«اَنْصَتَ» means to listen silently to someone else's speech (2 verses: 7:204-46:29)",
      "d": "«نَصَتَ» and «اَنْصَتَ» mean to listen to someone else's speech while remaining silent (Munjid). For example, the Quran states: «وَ اِذَا قُرِئَ الۡقُرۡاٰنُ فَاسۡتَمِعُوۡا لَہٗ وَ اَنۡصِتُوۡا  لَعَلَّکُمۡ  تُرۡحَمُوۡنَ» (7/204) Translation: And when the Quran is recited, listen to it attentively and remain silent so that you may be shown mercy."
    }
  ],
  "257": [
    {
      "id": 1202,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Lamp",
      "hw": "چراغ",
      "s": "«مَصْبَاح» is that which has a light that is white or bright. (3 verses: 24:35-41:12-67:5)",
      "d": "«صَبَحَ» means to be bright and shining. «صَبَحَ الشَّعْر» means the hair became shiny. And «صَبَح الْحَدِیْد» means the iron became bright and shiny. And «صَبِیْح» and «صَبْحَان» come in the sense of beautiful. (Munjid) And Ibn Faris writes that the word «صَبَحَ» fundamentally denotes a reddish color. Morning (صبح) is called so because of its redness. And «مِصْبَاح» (lamp) is also called مصابح because of this redness. (M L)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«مَثَلُ نُوۡرِہٖ کَمِشۡکٰوۃٍ  فِیۡہَا مِصۡبَاحٌ» ( 24/35 )\nTranslation: The example of His light is like a niche within which is a lamp.\nThen the word «مِصْبَاح» is also used in the Noble Quran for bright stars.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ  زَیَّنَّا السَّمَآءَ الدُّنۡیَا بِمَصَابِیۡحَ» ( 67/5 )\nTranslation: And We have certainly adorned the nearest heaven with lamps [i.e., stars]."
    },
    {
      "id": 1203,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Lamp",
      "hw": "چراغ",
      "s": "«Siraaj» is that which has a reddish light (4 verses: 25:61-33:46-71:16-78:13)",
      "d": "Ibn Faris says that the word «saraj» implies beauty, adornment, and elegance. And «siraaj» (lamp) is called «siraaj» because of its light and adornment. A horse's saddle is also called «saraj» because it is its adornment. It is said «sarraj wajhahu» meaning he adorned his face. «Sarraj sha'rahu» meaning he groomed or braided his hair. (M. L.)\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«تَبٰرَکَ الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ فِی السَّمَآءِ بُرُوۡجًا وَّ جَعَلَ فِیۡہَا سِرٰجًا وَّ قَمَرًا مُّنِیۡرًا» (25/61)\nTranslation: (God) is the Most Blessed who has placed constellations in the heavens and made therein a lamp (the sun) and a luminous moon.\n\nThe lexical research presented above from Ibn al-Faris's Maqayis al-Lughah is not supported by the Quran; rather, the matter appears contrary to it. The Quran has called the sun «siraaj» (35/61) and «siraajan wa haajan» (78/13), even though its light is reddish, not white. Similarly, the Quran has called the stars «masabih», even though their light is white, not red. Therefore, the reality is that: «siraaj» is that which has reddish light, and «misbaah» is that which has white light. And Allah knows best!"
    }
  ],
  "258": [
    {
      "id": 1204,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Grazing",
      "hw": "چرانا",
      "s": "«Ra'aa» meaning to graze an animal and to protect and care for it (2 verses: 20:54-28:23)",
      "d": "«Ra'aa» meaning to graze an animal and to protect and care for it. And «ra'i» meaning herdsman. «Gadriya» (one who takes livestock to pastures and grazes them) is a service. And «mar'aa» meaning both pasture and grazing ground. (Muf) To save something from being wasted. And to remove external dangers. And its opposite is «ihmaal» meaning without a herdsman. (Faq l 15)\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«کُلُوۡا وَ ارۡعَوۡا اَنۡعَامَکُمۡ» (20/54)\nTranslation: Eat yourselves and graze your cattle.\n\nThe basic meaning of «ra'aa» is upbringing and care, so it can also be applied to humans. A king is a herdsman, and the public is the flock."
    },
    {
      "id": 1205,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Grazing",
      "hw": "چرانا",
      "s": "«Asama» meaning to take animals to graze (1 verse: 16:10)",
      "d": "The basic meanings of «sawama» are two: (1) to seek (2) to set out. Meaning to set out in search of something. «Samatu al-ibil» meaning the camels set out for grazing grounds. And «asama» meaning to go for grazing. (Muf)\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَّ مِنۡہُ شَجَرٌ فِیۡہِ تُسِیۡمُوۡنَ» (16/10)\nTranslation: And from it (the rain) are trees in which you graze your livestock."
    }
  ],
  "259": [
    {
      "id": 1206,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ascending (upwards)",
      "hw": "چڑھنا",
      "s": "«'Araja» is used for ascending with pauses (5 verses: 15:14-32:5-34:2-57:4-70:4)",
      "d": "Two things are found in the meanings of «'araja»: inclination and height. (M. L.) «'Araja» meaning to walk with a limp, and «a'raj» is used for a limp person. And «'araja fi al-salam» meaning to ascend a ladder.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ لَوۡ فَتَحۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ بَابًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فَظَلُّوۡا فِیۡہِ یَعۡرُجُوۡنَ لَقَالُوۡۤا اِنَّمَا سُکِّرَتۡ اَبۡصَارُنَا» (15/14,15)\nTranslation: And even if We opened for them a gate from the heaven and they kept ascending therein, they would surely say, 'Our eyes are only dazzled.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1207,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ascending (upwards)",
      "hw": "چڑھنا",
      "s": "«Raqiya» is used for ascending according to one's capacity (1 verse: 17:93)",
      "d": "The meanings of «raqiya» include to blow away and to ascend to a height. In such a way that one expends effort according to one's capacity. To ascend gradually and gently. (Munjid) For example: «irqi 'ala zil'ika» meaning ascend according to your capacity. Do not burden your soul beyond its strength. (Munjid. Muf) And as in: «raqaytu fi al-'ilmi wa al-sharaf» I have progressed in knowledge and honor. (Faq l 152) So its usage is general.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«اَوۡ تَرۡقٰی فِی السَّمَآءِ ؕ وَ لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لِرُقِیِّکَ حَتّٰی تُنَزِّلَ عَلَیۡنَا کِتٰبًا نَّقۡرَؤُہٗ» (17/93)\nTranslation: Or you ascend into the sky, and we will not believe in your ascension until you bring down to us a book that we can read."
    },
    {
      "id": 1208,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ascending (upwards)",
      "hw": "چڑھنا",
      "s": "«Sa'ada» is used for ascending with difficulty (4 verses: 3:153-6:125-35:10-72:17)",
      "d": "Two basic things are found in the meaning of «sa'ada»: (1) height (2) difficulty. (M. L.) Meaning to ascend to a high place with difficulty. And «su'ud» means heights and valleys. And the difficult path ascending them is also called that. (Munjid) Something rising with difficulty, like smoke rising. And «mus'ad al-khar ba'iyah» means elevator. (Muf) And «as'ada» and «sa''ada» mean to ascend with time and difficulty.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«یَجۡعَلۡ صَدۡرَہٗ ضَیِّقًا حَرَجًا کَاَنَّمَا یَصَّعَّدُ فِی السَّمَآءِ» (6/126)\nTranslation: He makes his breast narrow and constricted, as if he is ascending into the sky.\n\nNote: The opposite of the three words «'araja», «raqiya», and «sa'ada» is «nazala»."
    },
    {
      "id": 1209,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ascending (upwards)",
      "hw": "چڑھنا",
      "s": "«Zahara» is used for ascending to the top (27 verses: 2:85-6:120-6:151-7:33-9:8-9:33-9:48-13:33-18:20-18:22-18:97-24:31-30:7-30:18-30:41-31:20-34:18-40:26-40:29-43:33-48:28-57:3-57:13-61:9-61:14-66:3-72:26)",
      "d": "«Zahara» meaning to become apparent, to prevail, to ascend, and to ascend to the top, whether there are steps or not, even if climbing without steps.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«فَمَا اسۡطَاعُوۡۤا اَنۡ یَّظۡہَرُوۡہُ وَ مَا اسۡتَطَاعُوۡا لَہٗ نَقۡبًا» (18/97)\nTranslation: Then they were not able to ascend it, nor were they able to bore through it.\n\nAt another place, the command of God is:\n«لِبُیُوۡتِہِمۡ سُقُفًا مِّنۡ فِضَّۃٍ وَّ مَعَارِجَ عَلَیۡہَا یَظۡہَرُوۡنَ» (43/33)\nTranslation: We will make their roofs of silver and stairs upon which they will ascend."
    },
    {
      "id": 1210,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ascending (upwards)",
      "hw": "چڑھنا",
      "s": "«Rahaqa» is used for one thing climbing over another and covering it (9 verses: 10:26-10:27-18:73-68:43-70:44-72:6-72:13-74:17-80:41)",
      "d": "«Rahaqa» meaning one thing climbing over another and covering it (there is an element of necessity in it). «Rahhaqahu al-amr» meaning the matter overwhelmed him with force and domination. (Muf) i.e., covered him. (M. L.)\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ وُجُوۡہٌ یَّوۡمَئِذٍ عَلَیۡہَا غَبَرَۃٌ تَرۡہَقُہَا قَتَرَۃٌ» (80/40,41)\nTranslation: And faces on that day will have dust over them, and darkness will cover them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1211,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ascending (upwards)",
      "hw": "چڑھنا",
      "s": "«Tasawwara» is used for climbing over a wall or jumping over it (1 verse: 38:21)",
      "d": "«Sawr» meaning a fortified city or a high wall that cannot be jumped over to enter. (M. L.) And «sara» meaning to climb a wall or jump over it, to leap. And «tasawwara» means to climb over a wall and jump over it, and also to wear a bracelet. «Siwar, sawar» plural «asawira» and «aswara» is derived from it meaning bracelet. (Nukila)\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ ہَلۡ اَتٰىکَ نَبَؤُا الۡخَصۡمِ ۘ اِذۡ تَسَوَّرُوا الۡمِحۡرَابَ» (38/21)\nTranslation: Has there come to you the news of the disputants when they climbed over the wall of the prayer chamber?"
    }
  ],
  "260": [
    {
      "id": 1212,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "«'Ayn» a spring of flowing water (63 verses: 2:60-3:13-5:45-5:83-7:116-7:160-7:179-7:195-8:44-9:92-11:31-11:37-12:84-15:45-15:88-18:28-18:86-18:101-19:26-20:39-20:40-20:131-21:61-23:27-23:50-25:74-26:57-26:134-26:147-26:34-28:9-28:13-32:17-33:19-33:51-34:12-36:66-37:45-37:48-40:19-43:71-44:25-44:52-44:54-51:15-52:20-52:48-54:12-54:14-54:37-55:50-55:66-56:18-56:22-67:30-76:6-76:18-77:41-83:28-88:5-88:12-90:8-102:7)",
      "d": "«'Ayn» means an eye, and its plural in the Quran is «a'yun». Then, because water flows from the eye, the mouth of a waterskin is also called «'ayn». Similarly, the spring from which water flows is also called «'ayn». (Muf) And its plural in the Quran is «'uyun».\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَّ فَجَّرۡنَا الۡاَرۡضَ عُیُوۡنًا فَالۡتَقَی الۡمَآءُ عَلٰۤی اَمۡرٍ قَدۡ قُدِرَ» (54/12)\nTranslation: And We caused the earth to burst with springs, so the water met for a matter that was predestined.\n\nAnd «'ayn» can also refer to a lake or a river."
    },
    {
      "id": 1213,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring / Fountain",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "«یَنْبُوْع» is a spring of water that gushes forth from the earth. (1 verse: 17:90)",
      "d": "«نَبَعَ» means for water to gush forth from a spring. And «مَنْبَع» is the place from where water gushes forth. And «یَنْبُوع» is a spring from which water flows abundantly. (Muf) Its plural is یَنَابِیْع. \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لَکَ حَتّٰۤی تَفۡجُرَ  لَنَا مِنَ  الۡاَرۡضِ  یَنۡۢبُوۡعًا» ( 17/90 )\nTranslation: And they said, 'We will not believe you until you cause a spring to gush forth for us from the earth.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1214,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring / Fountain",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "«سَرِیٌّ» is a flowing spring that takes the form of a small river. (1 verse: 19:24)",
      "d": "«سَرِیٌّ» means a small river, a flowing river. (F L 261 Munjid) Its plural is اَسْرِیَۃٌ and سُرْیَان. And «سَرِیَّۃ» also refers to a small army or military unit, whose plural is سرایا. And «ساریہ» means a small army that moves at night. (Munjid) Thus, the concept of smallness is inherent in it. (Munjid)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَدۡ جَعَلَ  رَبُّکِ  تَحۡتَکِ  سَرِیًّا» ( 19/24 )\nTranslation: [Allah said], 'And shake the trunk of the palm tree toward you, and it will drop upon you fresh ripe dates. So eat and drink and be contented.' (Note: The verse refers to a stream being made to flow beneath her)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1215,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Gushing and Flowing of a Spring",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "«فَارَ» means for water to gush up while boiling. (4 verses: 3:125-11:40-23:27-67:7)",
      "d": "«فَارَ» means to boil and gush forth. (Munjid) And «فَوْر» means to boil, to open, to gush forth. (M L) «فَارَ الْقِدْر» means the pot boils. «فَارَ الْمَاء» means the water boils. And «فَارَ الْعِرْق» means the vein throbs and is agitated. (Munjid) Thus, in «فَارَ», the concept is of water gushing up, not flowing away, especially when there is pressure from below and the hole is narrow. From this, the famous word فوارہ (fountain) is derived.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا جَآءَ اَمۡرُنَا وَ فَارَ التَّنُّوۡرُ» ( 11/40 )\nTranslation: Until, when Our command came and the oven overflowed [with water]."
    },
    {
      "id": 1216,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "The Bursting and Flowing of a Spring",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "«نَضَخَ» means water gushing out and falling down (1 Verse: 56:66)",
      "d": "«نَضَخَ» means water forcefully gushing out from a spring. And «اِنْضَخَ» means water splashing and falling down. «نَضَّاخ» refers to a torrential downpour, and «مِنْضَخَة» refers to a sprinkling device (manjad). Thus, in this word, the concept is of boiling and gushing upwards rather than simply flowing. For example, the Quran states: «فِیۡہِمَا عَیۡنٰنِ نَضَّاخَتٰنِ» (55/66). Translation: In them (both gardens) are two springs gushing forth."
    },
    {
      "id": 1217,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "The Bursting and Flowing of a Spring",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "«اَنْبَجَسَ» means water gushing out from a spring when the exit point is narrow (1 Verse: 7:160)",
      "d": "«اَنْبَجَسَ» means something opening up due to water, whether it be earth, stone, or a mountain (M. L.). According to the expert in linguistic jurisprudence, the word «اَنْبَجَسَ» is specifically used for water gushing out and flowing from a mountain or stony ground (F. L. 259). For example, the Quran states: «وَ  اَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ  اِلٰی مُوۡسٰۤی  اِذِ  اسۡتَسۡقٰىہُ قَوۡمُہٗۤ  اَنِ اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ الۡحَجَرَ ۚ فَانۡۢبَجَسَتۡ مِنۡہُ اثۡنَتَا عَشۡرَۃَ عَیۡنًا» (7/160). Translation: And when his people asked Moses for water, We inspired him: 'Strike the rock with your staff.' Then twelve springs gushed out from it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1218,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "The Bursting and Flowing of a Spring",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "«اِنْفَجَرَ» means water gushing out from a spring when the exit point becomes wide (9 Verses: 2:60, 2:74, 17:90, 17:91, 18:33, 36:34, 54:12, 76:6, 82:3)",
      "d": "«اِنْفَجَرَ» and «اِنْبَجَسَ» are near-synonymous terms. In the Quran, both words have been used for the same event. The verse related to «اِنْفَجَرَ» is: For example, the Divine declaration is: «وَ اِذِ اسۡتَسۡقٰی مُوۡسٰی لِقَوۡمِہٖ فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ الۡحَجَرَ  ؕ فَانۡفَجَرَتۡ مِنۡہُ اثۡنَتَاعَشۡرَۃَ عَیۡنًا» (2/60). Translation: And when Moses asked for water for his people, We said: 'Strike the rock with your staff.' Then twelve springs burst forth from it. The subtle difference between them is that when the mouth of the spring is not fully open and the water rises a little, the word «اِنْبَجَسَ» is used. And when the mouth opens fully and the water flows out at the mouth, the word «اِنْفَجَرَ» is used. The second difference is that «اِنْبَجَسَ» is specifically used for a spring gushing from a mountain or rocky ground, while «اِنْفَجَرَ» is general and can be used for both mountainous and flat land. During the flood of Noah, water gushed out from ordinary ground. For example, the Divine declaration is: «وَّ فَجَّرۡنَا الۡاَرۡضَ عُیُوۡنًا فَالۡتَقَی الۡمَآءُ عَلٰۤی  اَمۡرٍ  قَدۡ  قُدِرَ» (54/12). Translation: And We split the earth into springs, and the water met (its course) for a matter already decreed."
    },
    {
      "id": 1219,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "The Bursting and Flowing of a Spring",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "«سَالَ» involves the concept of only water or a liquid flowing (3 Verses: 13:17, 34:12, 34:16)",
      "d": "In «سَالَ», only the concept of water flowing is found, whether it is rainwater or spring water. For example, the Quran states: «اَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ  مَآءً  فَسَالَتۡ اَوۡدِیَۃٌۢ بِقَدَرِہَا» (13/17). Translation: He sent down water from the sky, so the valleys flowed according to their capacity. Similarly, at another place, the Divine declaration is: «وَ اَسَلۡنَا لَہٗ  عَیۡنَ الۡقِطۡرِ» (34/12). Translation: And We made for him a flowing spring of molten copper. The word is derived from «سَیْل», which refers to anything that flows downwards like water. Thus, «سَیْل» implies the concept of flowing forcefully downwards. And «سَیْل» is called 'seelab' (flood) in Urdu. For example, the Quran states: «فَاَعۡرَضُوۡا فَاَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ سَیۡلَ الۡعَرِمِ» (34/16). Translation: They turned away, so We sent upon them the flood of 'Aarim'."
    },
    {
      "id": 1220,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Flowing",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "«جَرٰی» means water or any other thing moving continuously at a moderate pace, for a long time or over a long distance (57 Verses: 2:25, 2:164, 2:266, 3:15, 3:136, 3:195, 3:198, 4:13, 4:57, 4:122, 5:12, 5:85, 5:119, 6:6, 7:43, 9:72, 9:89, 9:100, 10:9, 10:22, 11:42, 13:2, 13:35, 14:23, 14:32, 16:31, 18:31, 20:76, 21:81, 22:14, 22:23, 22:65, 25:10, 29:58, 30:46, 31:29, 31:31, 35:13, 36:38, 38:36, 39:5, 39:20, 43:51, 45:12, 47:12, 48:5, 48:17, 54:14, 55:50, 57:12, 58:22, 61:12, 64:9, 65:11, 66:8, 85:11, 98:8)",
      "d": "«جَرٰی» means water flowing and being in motion. When the slope is not steep and the water's force is not strong. It means water flowing or moving at a moderate pace, whether it is a spring, a river, or a stream. For example, the Quran states: «فِیۡہِمَا عَیۡنٰنِ  تَجۡرِیٰنِ» (55/50). Translation: In them (both gardens) are two flowing springs. At another place, the Divine declaration is: «لَہُمۡ جَنّٰتٍ تَجۡرِیۡ مِنۡ تَحۡتِہَا الۡاَنۡہٰرُ» (2/25). Translation: For them are gardens beneath which rivers flow. And «جَرٰی» is a general term used in the Quran not only for flowing liquids but also for winds, the sun, the moon, etc., moving. Additionally, it is used metaphorically, such as the famous phrase 'Sunnah Jariyah' (continuous tradition). However, an example of this metaphorical use is likely not present in the Quran. It is used in both temporal and spatial contexts, meaning to continue flowing or moving over a long time or distance."
    },
    {
      "id": 1221,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Flowing",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "«فَاضَ» means water or any other thing begins to flow due to sheer abundance and excess (OVER FLOW) (6 Verses: 2:199, 5:83, 7:50, 9:92, 10:61, 46:8)",
      "d": "Two concepts are found in «فَیْض»: (1) abundance of something, (2) becoming uncontrollable due to abundance. «فَاضَ السَّیْلُ» means the water is abundant and flows out over the banks (manjad). And «اَفَاضَ الْاِنَاء» means the vessel filled so much that water started flowing over the edges (OVER FLOW) (manjad, maf). For example, the Quran states: «تَرٰۤی اَعۡیُنَہُمۡ تَفِیۡضُ مِنَ  الدَّمۡعِ مِمَّا عَرَفُوۡا مِنَ الۡحَقِّ» (5/83). Translation: You will see their eyes overflowing with tears because they recognize the truth. That is, the eyes become so full of tears that they begin to flow. At another place, the Divine declaration is: «ثُمَّ  اَفِیۡضُوۡا مِنۡ حَیۡثُ اَفَاضَ النَّاسُ» (2/199). Translation: Then depart from where the people depart. Here, 'people' refers to the crowd, throng, or abundance of people. Their abundance compels them to accompany and return. This act of accompanying and returning is expressed by «اَفَاضَ». Similarly, it is used for extreme zeal or engrossment in an activity. For example, the Quran states: «اِذۡ تُفِیۡضُوۡنَ فِیۡہِ» (10/61). Translation: When you are engrossed in it."
    }
  ],
  "261": [
    {
      "id": 1222,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Walking",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«مَشٰی» means to walk at a normal pace. It is the general word for walking (20 Verses: 2:20, 6:122, 7:195, 17:37, 17:95, 20:40, 20:128, 24:45, 25:7, 25:20, 25:63, 28:25, 31:18, 31:19, 32:26, 38:6, 57:28, 67:15, 67:22, 68:11)",
      "d": "«مَشٰی» means to walk with the intention and purpose of moving from one place to another (muf). To walk step by step. To walk, to move about. To walk at a normal pace. (F. L. 176) This is generally the word used for walking. For example, the Quran states: «وَ قَالُوۡا مَالِ ہٰذَا الرَّسُوۡلِ یَاۡکُلُ الطَّعَامَ وَ یَمۡشِیۡ  فِی الۡاَسۡوَاقِ» (25/7). Translation: And they say, 'What is this messenger? He eats food and walks in the marketplaces.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1223,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Walking",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«دَبّ» means to walk with a slightly lighter gait than «مَشٰی» (18 Verses: 2:164, 6:38, 8:22, 8:55, 11:6, 11:56, 16:49, 16:61, 22:18, 24:45, 27:82, 29:60, 31:10, 34:14, 35:28, 35:45, 42:29, 45:4)",
      "d": "«دَبّ» means to walk at a normal but slightly lighter pace than «مَشٰی». 'حَرَکَۃِ عَلَی الْاَرْضِ اَخَفُّ مِنَ الْمَشْیِ' (M. L.) It includes crawling, walking like a snake, or a baby learning to walk on hands and knees (M. Q.). And whatever moves and walks on the earth is called «دَابَّۃ» (M. L.). For example, the Quran states: «وَ مَا مِنۡ دَآبَّۃٍ  فِی الۡاَرۡضِ  اِلَّا عَلَی اللّٰہِ  رِزۡقُہَا» (11/6). Translation: And there is no creature on the earth but its provision is upon Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1224,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«اِنطَلَق» meaning to set off, to start walking (9 verses: 18:71, 18:74, 18:77, 26:13, 38:6, 48:15, 68:23, 77:29, 77:30)",
      "d": "«طَلَقَ» means to free from a bond (transitive), and «اِنطَلَق» means to walk after a stop (i.e., to start moving), to set off, to depart. It can mean a prisoner walking after release or starting to speak after remaining silent. For example, the Quran says: «فَانۡطَلَقَا  ٝ حَتّٰۤی اِذَا رَکِبَا فِی السَّفِیۡنَۃِ» (18/71). Translation: Then they both set off until they boarded a ship. At another place, the divine command states: «وَ لَا یَنۡطَلِقُ لِسَانِیۡ فَاَرۡسِلۡ  اِلٰی ہٰرُوۡنَ» (26/13). Translation: (Moses pbuh said) And my tongue is not fluent, so send revelation to Aaron as well (to be my helper)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1225,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«سَلَک» meaning to walk along a path (12 verses: 15:12, 16:69, 20:53, 23:27, 26:200, 28:32, 39:21, 69:32, 71:20, 72:17, 72:27, 74:42)",
      "d": "«سَلَک» has two meanings: (1) to follow a specific path and not deviate (manjad), to walk and lead on a path (transitive). For example, the Quran says: «ثُمَّ  کُلِیۡ مِنۡ کُلِّ الثَّمَرٰتِ فَاسۡلُکِیۡ سُبُلَ رَبِّکِ ذُلُلًا» (16/69). Translation: (O honeybee) eat of all fruits and walk along the smooth paths of your Lord. And (2) the second meaning is «نُفُوذَ الشَّیْء» i.e., the penetration of one thing into another, to enter, to do, to permeate. For example, the Quran says: «اُسۡلُکۡ یَدَکَ فِیۡ جَیۡبِکَ تَخۡرُجۡ بَیۡضَآءَ مِنۡ غَیۡرِ سُوۡٓءٍ» (28/32). Translation: And (O Moses) put your hand in your bosom; it will come out white without any evil."
    },
    {
      "id": 1226,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«سَرَبَ» meaning to go down into a hollow, to descend into a ditch (1 verse: 18:61)",
      "d": "«سَرَب» means to go down into a depression (downhill), to walk while sinking. And «سَرْب» means the hole or ditch of wild animals, an underground pit, a cellar, a prison (muf). It is said «اِنْسَرَبَتِ الْحَیَّۃُ اِلٰی جُحْرِھَا» i.e., the snake entered its hole (muf). For example, the Quran says: «فَاتَّخَذَ سَبِیۡلَہٗ  فِی الۡبَحۡرِ  سَرَبًا» (18/61). Translation: So it (the fish) took its way in the sea as a tunnel."
    },
    {
      "id": 1229,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«مَضٰی» meaning the passing of time or walking with time (5 verses: 8:38, 15:65, 18:60, 36:67, 43:8)",
      "d": "«مَضٰی» means to pass, to go away, and to become empty (m. q). In «مَضٰی», either the concept of mere time or era passing is found, referring to the past elapsed time, or it means the proceeding and passing of something with time and era. «مَضٰی مَا مَضٰی» means what happened, happened; what passed, passed (manjad). For example, the Quran says: «فَاَہۡلَکۡنَاۤ  اَشَدَّ مِنۡہُمۡ بَطۡشًا وَّ مَضٰی مَثَلُ  الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (43/8). Translation: So We destroyed those who were stronger than them in power, and the example of the former people has passed away. At another place, the divine command states: «حَتّٰۤی اَبۡلُغَ  مَجۡمَعَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ اَوۡ اَمۡضِیَ حُقُبًا» (18/60). Translation: Until I reach the confluence of the two seas or I spend years walking (i.e., proceed for many years). Here, «مَضٰی» is used in the sense of time, meaning not to turn back, but to proceed for many years."
    },
    {
      "id": 1231,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«سَارَ» meaning to walk around, to travel (3 verses: 12:19, 13:10, 28:29)",
      "d": "«سَارَ» means to walk around, to travel, to stroll, regardless of the purpose. A walking person is called «سَائِر», and a group walking together is «سَیَّارَۃ». The Quran says: «فَلَمَّا قَضٰی مُوۡسَی الۡاَجَلَ وَ سَارَ بِاَہۡلِہٖۤ» (28/29). Translation: When Moses fulfilled his term and traveled with his family."
    },
    {
      "id": 1233,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«رَجِلَ» meaning to walk on foot when some are also mounted (3 verses: 2:239, 17:64, 22:27)",
      "d": "«رَجِلَ» means to walk on foot. It is used when in a confrontation, some are mounted and some are on foot. For example, the Quran says: «یَاۡتُوۡکَ  رِجَالًا وَّ عَلٰی کُلِّ ضَامِرٍ »(22/27). Translation: They will come to you on foot and also on every lean camel. At another place, the divine command states: «فَاِنۡ خِفۡتُمۡ فَرِجَالًا اَوۡ رُکۡبَانًا» (2/239). Translation: And if you fear (the enemy), then pray standing or while riding. And if there are no mounts, then «مَشٰی» (walking) would be used."
    },
    {
      "id": 1234,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to cause to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«سَاقَ» meaning to drive, to make walk by driving from behind (4 verses: 8:6, 19:86, 32:27, 75:30)",
      "d": "«سَاقَ» means to drive, to make someone walk by pushing from behind, like a shepherd driving cattle (f l 187). A driver is called «سَوَّاق» (q j). For example, the Quran says: «وَّ نَسُوۡقُ الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ اِلٰی جَہَنَّمَ وِرۡدًا» (19/86). Translation: And We will drive the criminals to Hell in thirst."
    },
    {
      "id": 1236,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to cause to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«اَزْجٰی» meaning to drive slowly (2 verses: 17:66, 24:43)",
      "d": "«اَزْجٰی» means to drive gently, to make walk slowly, and «مُزَجّٰی» means weak (manjad). For example, the Quran says: «اَلَمۡ  تَرَ  اَنَّ اللّٰہَ یُزۡجِیۡ سَحَابًا ثُمَّ  یُؤَلِّفُ بَیۡنَہٗ» (24/43). Translation: Do you not see that Allah drives the clouds, then He joins them together?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1237,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to cause to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«سَلَک» meaning to make walk on a path or to pave a way (12 verses: 15:12, 16:69, 20:53, 23:27, 26:200, 28:32, 39:21, 69:32, 71:20, 72:17, 72:27, 74:42)",
      "d": "«سَلَک» has two meanings: (1) to cause to walk on a specific path and to lead (both transitive and intransitive). (2) to cause something to penetrate into another, to enter, to do, to permeate. This word is specifically related to a path. For example, the Quran says: «الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الۡاَرۡضَ مَہۡدًا وَّ سَلَکَ  لَکُمۡ  فِیۡہَا سُبُلًا» (20/53). Translation: Who has made the earth a bed for you and has made roads for you to traverse therein."
    },
    {
      "id": 1238,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to cause to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«سَیَّر» to cause to walk, to lead (19 verses: 6:11-10:22-12:109-13:31-16:36-18:47-22:46-27:69-29:20-30:9-30:42-34:18-35:44-40:21-40:82-47:10-52:10-78:20-81:3)",
      "d": "«سَارَ» means to walk, to roam, to travel. And «سَیَّر» means to cause to walk, to cause to travel, to send on a journey.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ یُسَیِّرُکُمۡ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ» (10/22)\nTranslation: He it is who causes you to travel on land and sea."
    },
    {
      "id": 1239,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to travel by night",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«اَسْرٰی» to travel by night, to cause to travel by night (6 verses: 11:81-15:65-17:1-20:77-26:52-44:23)",
      "d": "«سَرٰی, یَسْرِیْ» means to travel by night. And «اَسْرٰی» means to cause to travel by night, to cause to travel, to send on a journey.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَاَسۡرِ  بِاَہۡلِکَ بِقِطۡعٍ مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ» (11/81)\nTranslation: So travel by night with your family in a part of the night.\nAt another place, the Lord says:\n«سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَسۡرٰی بِعَبۡدِہٖ لَیۡلًا» (17/1)\nTranslation: Glorified is He who took His servant by night."
    }
  ],
  "262": [
    {
      "id": 1240,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk; to scream",
      "hw": "چیخنا",
      "s": "«نَعَقَ» to shout loudly (1 verse: 2:171)",
      "d": "«نَعَقَ» means to call out loudly, to shout. The crow cawing loudly, the shepherd calling the flock from afar. (f l 194)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ مَثَلُ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا کَمَثَلِ الَّذِیۡ یَنۡعِقُ بِمَا لَا یَسۡمَعُ اِلَّا دُعَآءً  وَّ  نِدَآءً» (2/171)\nTranslation: And the example of those who disbelieve is like that of one who shouts to that which hears no more than a call and a shout."
    },
    {
      "id": 1241,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk; to scream",
      "hw": "چیخنا",
      "s": "«صَدَّ» to make noise indiscriminately (2 verses: 15:94-43:57)",
      "d": "«یَصِدُّ» means to make noise indiscriminately, to shout, to clamor. And «صَدَّد» means to clap (source: manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَمَّا ضُرِبَ ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ  مَثَلًا  اِذَا قَوۡمُکَ مِنۡہُ  یَصِدُّوۡنَ» (43/57)\nTranslation: And when the son of Mary is presented as an example, your people laugh at it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1242,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk; to scream",
      "hw": "چیخنا",
      "s": "«جَئَرَ» to groan loudly due to distress (3 verses: 16:53-23:64-23:65)",
      "d": "«جَئَرَ» means to groan loudly, to wail (source: manjad). To make a loud sound when distressed, like wild animals such as deer. (muf)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَاۤ  اَخَذۡنَا مُتۡرَفِیۡہِمۡ بِالۡعَذَابِ اِذَا ہُمۡ  یَجۡئَرُوۡنَ» (23/64)\nTranslation: Until when We seize their affluent ones with punishment, at that they cry out (or groan)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1243,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk; to scream",
      "hw": "چیخنا",
      "s": "«اِسْتَصْرَخَ» to cry for help and shout (2 verses: 14:22-28:18)",
      "d": "«صَرَخَ» means to scream and shout so that others may come to help, to cry out. And «اَصْرَخَ» means to hear someone's cry and come to their aid. And «اِسْتَصْرَخَ» means to call for help by shouting in front of those present.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَاِذَا  الَّذِی اسۡتَنۡصَرَہٗ  بِالۡاَمۡسِ یَسۡتَصۡرِخُہٗ» (28/18)\nTranslation: Then the one who had sought help from him the day before is now crying out to him."
    },
    {
      "id": 1244,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk; to scream",
      "hw": "چیخنا",
      "s": "«صَرَّ» to scream (1 verse: 51:29)",
      "d": "«صَرَ الرَّجُل» means for a man to shout loudly (source: manjad). And «صَرَّۃ» means a scream (source: maf).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَاَقۡبَلَتِ امۡرَاَتُہٖ  فِیۡ صَرَّۃٍ  فَصَکَّتۡ وَجۡہَہَا وَ قَالَتۡ عَجُوۡزٌ  عَقِیۡمٌ» (51/29)\nTranslation: So his wife came forward, crying out, and she struck her face and said, 'What! An old woman, and barren!'"
    }
  ],
  "263": [
    {
      "id": 1245,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to cling",
      "hw": "چمٹنا",
      "s": "«اَلْحَفَ» to cling to someone and urge them to do something (1 verse: 2:273)",
      "d": "«لِحَاف» means a blanket. idiom: «اَلْحَفْتُہٗ فَالْتَحَفَ» I covered him with a blanket, so he clung to it. And «اِلْحَاف» means to cling and beg, i.e., to importune (source: maf).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«تَعۡرِفُہُمۡ بِسِیۡمٰہُمۡ ۚ لَا یَسۡئَلُوۡنَ النَّاسَ اِلۡحَافًا» (2/273)\nTranslation: You will know them by their mark; they do not ask people importunately."
    },
    {
      "id": 1246,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to cling",
      "hw": "چمٹنا",
      "s": "«لَزَبَ» to stick or cling due to being sticky or viscous (1 verse: 37:11)",
      "d": "«لَازِبْ» refers to something that becomes firmly attached and clings (source: maf). And according to scholars of language, «لَازِبْ» means sticky and viscous mud (source: f l 268). In the Quran, this word is used only for mud. Thus, both meanings are supported.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اِنَّا خَلَقۡنٰہُمۡ مِّنۡ طِیۡنٍ لَّازِبٍ» (37/11)\nTranslation: Indeed, We created them from sticky mud."
    },
    {
      "id": 1247,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to cling",
      "hw": "چمٹنا",
      "s": "«لَزِمَ» for one thing to adhere to another for a long time (2 verses: 20:129-25:77)",
      "d": "«لَزِمَ» implies both fixation and duration. i.e., for something to remain fixed or attached in one place for a long time (source: maf). According to this meaning, this word is translated into different words in Urdu at different contexts.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَا کَلِمَۃٌ سَبَقَتۡ مِنۡ رَّبِّکَ لَکَانَ لِزَامًا  وَّ  اَجَلٌ  مُّسَمًّی» (20/129)\nTranslation: And if not for a word that preceded from your Lord, it would have been an obligation [to punish them immediately] and a specified time."
    }
  ],
  "264": [
    {
      "id": 1248,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Shining",
      "hw": "چمک",
      "s": "«بَزَغَ» means the glittering or shining of stars, planets, moon, and sun at the time of rising. (2 verses: 6:77-6:78)",
      "d": "«بَزَغَ» means the rising of the sun while its light is spreading. (lex.) It is used for the light of the sun, moon, stars, or celestial bodies when they are rising. And «نُجُوْمٌ بَوَازِغٌ» refers to the stars that are rising.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «فَلَمَّا رَاَ الشَّمۡسَ بَازِغَۃً  قَالَ ہٰذَا رَبِّیۡ» (6/78)\n\nTranslation: Then when he saw the sun rising, he said, 'This is my Lord.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1249,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Shining",
      "hw": "چمک",
      "s": "«اَشْرَقَ» means light falling on something and spreading, and illuminating it. (2 verses: 38:18-39:69)",
      "d": "«شَرَقَ» means the opening or spreading of light (root). And «اَشْرَقَ» means to illuminate something. To cast full light on it so that it shines. (lex.)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «وَ اَشۡرَقَتِ  الۡاَرۡضُ بِنُوۡرِ رَبِّہَا» (39/69)\n\nTranslation: And the earth shone with the light of its Lord."
    },
    {
      "id": 1250,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Shining",
      "hw": "چمک",
      "s": "«ثَقَبَ» means the piercing passage of red and intense light. (2 verses: 37:10-86:3)",
      "d": "«ثَقَبَ» means the blazing of fire. The shining of a star. And «ثَقُب» means being like fire in redness, i.e., fiery. (dict.) The meaning is the complete penetration and passage of light. (lex.) «ثَقَبَ» means to pierce through something, and «ثَاقِب» means so bright that its rays pierce through whatever they fall on. (lex.) Thus, «ثَقَبَ» conveys the idea of intensity and fiery red light.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «اِلَّا مَنۡ خَطِفَ الۡخَطۡفَۃَ فَاَتۡبَعَہٗ شِہَابٌ  ثَاقِبٌ» (37/10)\n\nTranslation: But whoever snatches away the snatch, a blazing flame will follow him."
    },
    {
      "id": 1251,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Shining",
      "hw": "چمک",
      "s": "«سَنَا» is the light that dazzles the eyes. (1 verse: 24:43)",
      "d": "«سَنَا» means (the flash of lightning) that dazzles. The light that dazzles the eyes. (dict.)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «یَکَادُ سَنَا بَرۡقِہٖ یَذۡہَبُ بِالۡاَبۡصَارِ» (24/43)\n\nTranslation: The flash of its lightning almost takes away the sight."
    }
  ],
  "265": [
    {
      "id": 1253,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Few",
      "hw": "چند",
      "s": "«مَعْدُوْدَۃٌ» means few in count, opposite of many. (7 verses: 2:80-2:184-2:203-3:24-11:8-11:104-12:20)",
      "d": "«مَعْدُوْدَۃٌ» means few in number, one, or little. Opposite of many. Just as hundreds are few compared to thousands. (lex.)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «وَ شَرَوۡہُ بِثَمَنٍۭ بَخۡسٍ دَرَاہِمَ مَعۡدُوۡدَۃٍ» (12/20)\n\nTranslation: And they sold him for a small price, a few coins."
    },
    {
      "id": 1254,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Few",
      "hw": "چند",
      "s": "«بِضْع» is used for numbers from 3 to 9 only. (2 verses: 12:42-30:4)",
      "d": "«بِضْع» can be said for each number from three to ten (f l 76. lex.) Only the odd numbers from 3 to 9 are «بِضْع». (lex.)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «وَ ہُمۡ مِّنۡۢ  بَعۡدِ غَلَبِہِمۡ سَیَغۡلِبُوۡنَ فِیۡ بِضۡعِ سِنِیۡنَ» (30/3,4)\n\nTranslation: And they will soon prevail after their defeat, in a few years."
    },
    {
      "id": 1255,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Few",
      "hw": "چند",
      "s": "«نَفَرٌ» means a group of three to ten individuals. It is used for rational beings. (3 verses: 18:34-46:29-72:1)",
      "d": "«اَلنَّفَرُ» means many people as well, and a group of three to ten, and «ثَلَاثَۃُ نَفَرٍ اَوْ اَنْفَازٍ» means three men. (dict.)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «قُلۡ  اُوۡحِیَ  اِلَیَّ  اَنَّہُ  اسۡتَمَعَ  نَفَرٌ مِّنَ الۡجِنِّ فَقَالُوۡۤا  اِنَّا سَمِعۡنَا قُرۡاٰنًا عَجَبًا» (72/1)\n\nTranslation: Say, 'It has been revealed to me that a group of jinn listened and said, 'Indeed, we have heard a wonderful Quran.'"
    }
  ],
  "266": [
    {
      "id": 1256,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Choosing",
      "hw": "چن",
      "s": "«اِخْتار» means to choose a better thing from many things. (2 verses: 7:155-28:68)",
      "d": "«خَیْر» means every thing or matter that is desirable to all. (lex.) And «اِخْتار» means to choose a better thing from many things of the same kind. (lex.)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «وَ اخۡتَارَ مُوۡسٰی قَوۡمَہٗ سَبۡعِیۡنَ رَجُلًا لِّمِیۡقَاتِنَا» (7/155)\n\nTranslation: And Moses chose seventy men from his people for Our appointment."
    },
    {
      "id": 1257,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Choosing",
      "hw": "چن",
      "s": "«اِصْطَفٰی» means to choose something based on its purity and cleanliness. (12 verses: 2:130-2:132-2:247-3:33-3:42-7:144-22:75-27:59-35:32-37:153-38:47-39:4)",
      "d": "«اَلصَّفَا» and «صَفْوُ» mean pure and clean. (lex.) «اَلصَّفِیُّ» and «اَلصَّفْوَۃ» mean a sincere friend. (dict.) And «اِصْطَفٰی» means to choose something based on purity and cleanliness of the soul.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «اِنَّ اللّٰہَ اصۡطَفٰۤی اٰدَمَ وَ نُوۡحًا وَّ اٰلَ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ  وَ اٰلَ عِمۡرٰنَ عَلَی الۡعٰلَمِیۡنَ» (3/33)\n\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah chose Adam, Noah, the family of Abraham, and the family of Imran over the worlds."
    },
    {
      "id": 1258,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Choosing",
      "hw": "چن",
      "s": "«اِجْتَبٰی» means to choose someone and make them one's close confidant. (10 verses: 3:179-6:87-7:203-12:6-16:121-19:58-20:122-22:78-42:13-68:50)",
      "d": "«جَبُو» has two meanings: (1) to gather something (2) then to carry it somewhere. «یُجْمَعُ وَ یُحْمَلْ» (lex.) In Ibn Faris's words, «جَمْعُ الشَّیءُ وَالْتَجَمَّعُ» are the meanings. (dict.) Also, the word «جَبُو» generally comes for gathering a product (tax) which includes carrying it to the treasury. And «مُجْبٰی» means kharaj. (kharaj is a tax collected from non-Muslims in Islamic governments)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «یُّجۡبٰۤی  اِلَیۡہِ  ثَمَرٰتُ  کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ» (28/57)\n\nTranslation: Meaning, in Mecca, the fruits of all things are drawn and brought. (Ottoman) or delivered. (Jalandhri)\n\nAnd «اِجْتَبٰی» means to choose a noble thing and bring it close, to make it a confidant and chosen one.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «وَ کَذٰلِکَ یَجۡتَبِیۡکَ رَبُّکَ وَ یُعَلِّمُکَ مِنۡ تَاۡوِیۡلِ الۡاَحَادِیۡثِ» (12/6)\n\nTranslation: And thus your Lord will choose you and teach you the interpretation of events."
    },
    {
      "id": 1259,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Selecting",
      "hw": "چن",
      "s": "«اِسْتَخْلَصَ» means to choose someone for a specific purpose.",
      "d": "«خَلَصَ» means to be pure, free from mixture and impurity. «خَلَّص» means to make pure (cf. manjad), and its opposite is «خَلَطَ». Therefore, «اِسْتَخْلَصَ» means to choose someone and designate them exclusively for oneself.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ قَالَ الۡمَلِکُ ائۡتُوۡنِیۡ بِہٖۤ  اَسۡتَخۡلِصۡہُ لِنَفۡسِیۡ» (12/54). Translation: The king of Egypt ordered: 'Bring Joseph to me. I will make him my special attendant.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1260,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Selecting",
      "hw": "چن",
      "s": "«اِصْطَنَعَ» means to choose someone for a specific purpose and train them in a suitable manner.",
      "d": "«صَنَعَ» means to make something with technical skill. And «اِصْطَنَعَ» means to choose a suitable person for a specific purpose and train them specially.\nFor example, regarding Prophet Moses, Allah says: «وَ اصۡطَنَعۡتُکَ  لِنَفۡسِیۡ» (20/41). Translation: 'And (O Moses) I have chosen you for My work.'"
    }
  ],
  "267": [
    {
      "id": 1261,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Animals",
      "hw": "چوپائے",
      "s": "«وُحُوْش» means wild animals, beasts.",
      "d": "«وُحُوْش» is the plural of «وَحَشَ». And «وَحَشْ» is the opposite of «اِنْس», meaning creatures that are not familiar with humans. Wild animals and beasts, etc. (mufradat)\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ  اِذَا  الۡوُحُوۡشُ حُشِرَتۡ» (81/5). Translation: 'And when the wild animals are gathered together.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1262,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Animals",
      "hw": "چوپائے",
      "s": "«بَھَائِم» means cattle excluding wild animals; generally used for sheep and cows.",
      "d": "«بَھَائِم» is the plural of «بَھِیْمَہ». It applies to all types of cattle except wild ones (mufradat), whether land or sea animals (manjad). However, it is mostly used for sheep and cows (manjad). «بَھِم» refers to a lamb (mufradat), and one definition of «بَھِیْمَہ» is cattle (excluding predators) that lack the power of speech (manjad). Also, «بُھِم» means a difficult task, and «اَبْھَمْ» means mute (manjad)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1263,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Animals",
      "hw": "چوپائے",
      "s": "«اَنعَام» means cattle, generally used for camels.",
      "d": "«اَنعَام» is the plural of «نَعْم». Although this word can apply to all animals except predators, it is mostly used for camels (fala 134) because for Arabs, there was no greater blessing than a camel. In the Quran, the word 'an'am' also appears in singular form.\nFor example, the Quran states: «مَّتَاعًا  لَّکُمۡ  وَ لِاَنۡعَامِکُمۡ» (80/32). Translation: 'This is all provisions for you and your cattle.'\nSimilarly, at another place, Allah says: «کُلُوۡا وَ ارۡعَوۡا اَنۡعَامَکُمۡ» (20/54). Translation: 'Eat and graze your cattle.'\nBut the word «بَھِیْمَۃ» (in singular form) often comes with the word 'an'am'.\nFor example, the Quran states: «مِّنۡۢ بَہِیۡمَۃِ  الۡاَنۡعَامِ ۚ فَکُلُوۡا مِنۡہَا وَ اَطۡعِمُوا  الۡبَآئِسَ  الۡفَقِیۡرَ» (22/28). Translation: 'So eat from the cattle of 'an'am' and feed the poor and needy.'\nSimilarly, at another place, Allah says: «اُحِلَّتۡ لَکُمۡ بَہِیۡمَۃُ  الۡاَنۡعَامِ  اِلَّا مَا یُتۡلٰی عَلَیۡکُمۡ» (5/1). Translation: 'Cattle (grazing animals) are made lawful for you, except what is recited to you.'"
    }
  ],
  "268": [
    {
      "id": 1265,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Scattered Fragments",
      "hw": "ریزہ",
      "s": "«ھَشِیْم» means cut, dry grass; dry fragments of all kinds of plants. Hay (2 verses: 18:45-54:31)",
      "d": "«ھَشَمَ» means to cut. And «ھَشِیْم» refers to cut, dry grass (manjad), and by it is meant the fragments, debris, and chaff of all kinds of plants.\nFor example, the Quran states: «اِنَّاۤ  اَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ صَیۡحَۃً  وَّاحِدَۃً فَکَانُوۡا کَہَشِیۡمِ  الۡمُحۡتَظِرِ» (54/31). Translation: 'Then We sent upon them a single blast, and they became like the dry, broken remains of a hedge.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1266,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Scattered Fragments",
      "hw": "ریزہ",
      "s": "«حُطَام» means dry plants; fragments made by grinding and crushing (6 verses: 27:18-39:21-56:65-57:20-104:4-104:5)",
      "d": "«حَطَمَ» means to break, to shatter. And «حَطُوْم» refers to a violent, fierce wind that breaks and shatters everything. And «حُطَام» means something broken, shattered, or reduced to fragments (manjad). This word is also used for something ground and reduced to dust (mufradat).\nFor example, the Quran states: «ثُمَّ یُخۡرِجُ بِہٖ زَرۡعًا مُّخۡتَلِفًا  اَلۡوَانُہٗ  ثُمَّ یَہِیۡجُ  فَتَرٰىہُ مُصۡفَرًّا ثُمَّ یَجۡعَلُہٗ  حُطَامًا» (39/21). Translation: 'Then Allah brings forth from it vegetation of various colors, then it matures, and you see it turning yellow, then He makes it into scattered fragments.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1267,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Scattered Fragments",
      "hw": "ریزہ",
      "s": "«غُثَآء» means debris, rubbish, trash (2 verses: 23:41-87:5)",
      "d": "«غُثَآء» means trash caught in the foam of floodwater; rotten leaves of trees mixed in foam (manjad). And «غَثِیَ الْکَلَام» means to mix truth and falsehood in speech. Also, «غُثَآء» refers to fragments of grass and rubbish (mufradat).\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَخۡرَجَ  الۡمَرۡعٰی فَجَعَلَہٗ  غُثَآءً  اَحۡوٰی» (87:4-5). Translation: 'He who brings forth the pasture, then makes it into black debris.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1268,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Scattered Fragments",
      "hw": "ریزہ",
      "s": "«ھَبَآء» means dust, flying particles of everything (2 verses: 25:23-56:6)",
      "d": "«ھَبَآء» means dust that is blown by the wind; flying dust (fala 253), fine particles of soil spread in the air. And «اَلْھَبْوَۃٌ» refers to whirlwinds of dust (manjad).\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ قَدِمۡنَاۤ اِلٰی مَا عَمِلُوۡا مِنۡ عَمَلٍ فَجَعَلۡنٰہُ  ہَبَآءً  مَّنۡثُوۡرًا» (25/23). Translation: 'And We will turn to whatever deeds they did, and We will make them scattered dust.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1269,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Scattered Fragments",
      "hw": "ریزہ",
      "s": "«رُفَات» means to become scattered fragments due to decay (2 verses: 17:49-17:98)",
      "d": "«رَفَتَ» means to break and crush (manjad). And «رُفَات» means crushed, pulverized; decayed (manjad). This word is used for something that becomes scattered fragments due to decay.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ قَالُوۡۤاءَ اِذَا کُنَّا عِظَامًا  وَّ  رُفَاتًاءَ اِنَّا  لَمَبۡعُوۡثُوۡنَ  خَلۡقًا جَدِیۡدًا» (17/49). Translation: 'And they say, 'When we are bones and fragments, will we indeed be raised as a new creation?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1270,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Crushed to Pieces or Fragmented",
      "hw": "ریزہ",
      "s": "«بَسَّ» means for stones or something to be crushed to pieces (1 Verse: 56:5)",
      "d": "«بَسَّ» means for stones to be crushed to fragments (mufrad). According to the author of Mu‘jam Maqayis al-Lughah, its two basic meanings are: (1) to crush something and (2) to mix it with something else. Both meanings are supported in the Noble Quran.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«وَّ  بُسَّتِ الۡجِبَالُ  بَسًّا فَکَانَتۡ ہَبَآءً  مُّنۡۢبَثًّا» ( 56/5،6 )\nTranslation: And the mountains will be crushed to pieces, so they will become dust scattered about."
    }
  ],
  "269": [
    {
      "id": 1272,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To Steal",
      "hw": "چوری",
      "s": "«سَرَق» is the general term for stealing (6 Verses: 5:38-12:70-12:73-12:77-12:81-60:12)",
      "d": "«سَرَق» is a well-known word meaning to secretly take someone else's owned property from a secure place.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ السَّارِقُ وَ السَّارِقَۃُ فَاقۡطَعُوۡۤا اَیۡدِیَہُمَا» ( 5/38 )\nTranslation: Cut off the hands of the male thief and the female thief.\nAnd «اِسْتَرَق» means to attempt to steal. And «اِسْتَرَقُ السَّمْع» means to eavesdrop secretly.\nFor example, the Divine declaration is:\n«اِلَّا مَنِ اسۡتَرَقَ السَّمۡعَ فَاَتۡبَعَہٗ شِہَابٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ» ( 15/18 )\nTranslation: But whoever seeks to eavesdrop, a clear flame will pursue him."
    },
    {
      "id": 1273,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To Steal",
      "hw": "چوری",
      "s": "«غَلَّ» is a blended form of theft and betrayal (1 Verse: 3:161)",
      "d": "«غَلَّ» means to secretly take something and keep it in one's belongings (manjad, Mu‘jam). This is essentially a blend of theft and betrayal. Therefore, this word can be translated as both 'to steal' and 'to betray'. For example, taking something from shared war spoils that does not fulfill the conditions of lawful acquisition, etc.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّغۡلُلۡ یَاۡتِ بِمَا غَلَّ  یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» ( 3/161 )\nTranslation: And whoever comes on the Day of Resurrection with a sin, he will come with it. (Ibn Kathir)"
    }
  ],
  "270": [
    {
      "id": 1274,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Guard",
      "hw": "چوکیدار",
      "s": "«حَرَسَ» a guard who supervises and protects for a specified period (1 Verse: 72:8)",
      "d": "«حَرَسَ» means to take into custody, to guard, to keep watch, to supervise a prisoner. According to Ibn Faris, two concepts are found in «حَرَسَ»: (1) protection (2) time period (m, l), meaning to supervise for a certain duration. And «حَرَسَ الْمَلِکْ» means the royal guard, bodyguard (manjad).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ اَنَّا لَمَسۡنَا السَّمَآءَ  فَوَجَدۡنٰہَا مُلِئَتۡ حَرَسًا شَدِیۡدًا وَّ  شُہُبًا» ( 72/8 )\nTranslation: And we (the jinn) indeed touched the sky but found it filled with severe guards and meteors."
    },
    {
      "id": 1275,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Guard",
      "hw": "چوکیدار",
      "s": "«رَصَد» a guard lying in ambush, ready to seize prey the moment it appears (6 Verses: 9:5-9:107-72:9-72:27-78:21-89:14)",
      "d": "«رَصَد» means to sit in wait, to lie in ambush. And «مرصاد» means the place of lying in ambush. And «رَاصِد» means the one lying in ambush; its plural is «رُصَّد» and «رَصَد».\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اِلَّا مَنِ ارۡتَضٰی مِنۡ رَّسُوۡلٍ فَاِنَّہٗ یَسۡلُکُ مِنۡۢ  بَیۡنِ یَدِیۡہِ  وَ مِنۡ خَلۡفِہٖ رَصَدًا» ( 72/27 )\nTranslation: But whomsoever He chooses from His messengers, He indeed sends guardians before him and behind him."
    }
  ],
  "271": [
    {
      "id": 1277,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To Be Hidden (To Be Absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "«غَابَ» for something to be out of the reach of the five senses—i.e., grasp, power, and authority (52 Verses: 2:3-2:33-3:44-3:179-4:34-5:94-6:50-6:59-6:73-7:7-7:188-9:94-9:105-10:20-11:31-11:49-11:123-12:52-12:81-12:102-13:9-16:77-18:22-18:26-19:61-19:78-21:49-23:92-27:20-27:65-27:75-32:6-34:3-34:14-34:53-35:18-35:38-36:11-39:46-49:18-50:33-52:41-53:35-57:25-59:22-62:8-64:18-67:12-68:47-72:26-81:24-82:16)",
      "d": "The word «غَابَ» is general. «غَیْب» refers to something concealed. Anything that becomes hidden from sight for any reason or at any time (m, l). Therefore, its usage is general. Its opposite is «حَضَرَ». However, according to the scholar of fiqh al-lughah, everything is 'ghaib' (absent) that is hidden from human knowledge and senses, though a conception of it can be formed in the heart (Fall 16).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَا مِنۡ غَآئِبَۃٍ  فِی السَّمَآءِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ  اِلَّا  فِیۡ  کِتٰبٍ  مُّبِیۡنٍ» ( 27/75 )\nTranslation: And there is not a thing hidden within the heavens and the earth except that it is in a clear Book."
    },
    {
      "id": 1278,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To Be Hidden (To Be Absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "«اَفَلَ» this word is used for the setting or disappearance of celestial bodies (e.g., sun, moon, stars) (3 Verses: 6:76-6:77-6:78)",
      "d": "«اَفَلَ» is used for the setting or disappearance of celestial bodies (e.g., sun, moon, stars) (mufrad).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاَ الۡقَمَرَ بَازِغًا قَالَ ہٰذَا رَبِّیۡ ۚ فَلَمَّاۤ اَفَلَ قَالَ لَئِنۡ لَّمۡ یَہۡدِنِیۡ رَبِّیۡ لَاَکُوۡنَنَّ مِنَ الۡقَوۡمِ الضَّآلِّیۡنَ» ( 6/77 )\nTranslation: So when he saw the moon rising, he said, 'This is my Lord.' But when it set, he said, 'If my Lord does not guide me, I will surely be among the people astray.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1279,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To Be Hidden (To Be Absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "«غَرَبَ» the setting of the sun (15 Verses: 2:115-2:142-2:177-2:258-7:137-18:17-18:86-20:130-24:35-26:28-28:44-50:39-55:17-70:40-73:9)",
      "d": "«غَرَبَ» this word is used for the setting or disappearance of the sun. Just as «شَرَقَ» is used for rising and «طَلَعَ» includes the sun along with all planets (mufrad).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ تَرَی الشَّمۡسَ  اِذَا طَلَعَتۡ  تَّزٰوَرُ عَنۡ کَہۡفِہِمۡ ذَاتَ الۡیَمِیۡنِ وَ اِذَا غَرَبَتۡ تَّقۡرِضُہُمۡ ذَاتَ الشِّمَالِ» ( 18/16 )\nTranslation: And you will see the sun when it rises, inclining away from their cave towards the right, and when it sets, passing away from them towards the left."
    },
    {
      "id": 1280,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To Be Hidden (To Be Absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "«عَزَبَ» to become absent due to moving far away (2 Verses: 10:61-34:3)",
      "d": "«عَزَبَ» means to become invisible to the eyes by moving far away. And «عَازَب» is said about a man who goes far away from his family in search of pasture. And «عَزَّب» means to remain absent for a long time (manjad).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَا یَعۡزُبُ عَنۡ رَّبِّکَ مِنۡ مِّثۡقَالِ  ذَرَّۃٍ» ( 10/61 )\nTranslation: And not a thing, the weight of a speck of dust, is absent from your Lord."
    },
    {
      "id": 1281,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To Be Hidden (To Be Absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "«وَقَبَ» to sink into a pit and become hidden (1 Verse: 113:3)",
      "d": "«وَقَبَ» means to sink into a pit and become hidden. The phrase «وَقَبَتِ الشَّمْس» is a metaphor for the sun setting. And «وَقَبَ الظَّلَام» means for darkness to spread (mufrad). «اَلْوَقْب» means a pit in a rock where water collects. And «وَقَبَ» means to enter a pit (manjad).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مِنۡ  شَرِّ غَاسِقٍ  اِذَا وَقَبَ» ( 113/3 )\nTranslation: And from the evil of the darkness when it settles."
    },
    {
      "id": 1282,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To hide (to be absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "«بَطَنَ» means to be completely hidden (5 verses: 3:35-6:151-7:33-24:45-37:144)",
      "d": "«بَطَنَ» means belly or the inner part of something. And since the inner part is completely hidden, therefore «بَطَنَ» is used for something being completely hidden and its opposite is «ظَھَرَ». (Mufradat)\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«قُلۡ  اِنَّمَا حَرَّمَ رَبِّیَ الۡفَوَاحِشَ مَا ظَہَرَ  مِنۡہَا وَ  مَا بَطَنَ» ( 7/33 )\nTranslation: Say, 'My Lord has forbidden all kinds of indecencies, whether they are apparent or hidden.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1284,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To hide (to be absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "«خَفِی» means to be hidden from others. This word is more general than «غَابَ» (31 verses: 2:271-2:284-3:5-3:29-3:118-3:154-4:108-4:149-5:15-6:28-6:63-6:91-7:55-11:5-13:10-14:38-19:3-20:7-20:15-24:31-27:25-32:17-33:37-33:54-40:16-40:19-41:40-42:45-60:1-69:18-87:7)",
      "d": "«خَفِی» its opposite is «بَدَا» and «عَلَنَ». Meaning to be hidden from others. In this word, there is more generality than «غَابَ» (Mufradat) i.e., something that remains hidden whose concept cannot even be imagined.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ  لَا  یَخۡفٰی عَلَیۡہِ شَیۡءٌ  فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ لَا فِی السَّمَآءِ» ( 3/5 )\nTranslation: Nothing in the earth or the heavens is hidden from Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1285,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To hide (to be absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "«کَنَّ» means to hide in a safe place (4 verses: 37:49-52:24-56:23-56:78)",
      "d": "«کِنّ» means a safe place or a cave in a mountain where one can take refuge. And its plural is «اَکْنَان» and «اَکِنَّۃ». And «کَنَّ» means to be hidden in a safe place which is out of reach of common people. (Mufradat. Manjad)\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«کَاَنَّہُنَّ بَیۡضٌ مَّکۡنُوۡنٌ» ( 37/49 )\nTranslation: They are like eggs in a safe place."
    }
  ],
  "272": [
    {
      "id": 1286,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To conceal",
      "hw": "چھپانا",
      "s": "«کَتَمَ» is generally used for deliberately hiding testimony, faith, and the truth (20 verses: 2:33-2:42-2:72-2:140-2:146-2:159-2:174-2:228-2:283-3:71-3:167-3:187-4:37-4:42-5:61-5:99-5:106-21:110-24:29-40:28)",
      "d": "«کَتَمَ» means to deliberately keep something hidden in the heart. (Fiqh 237) This word is generally used for hiding the truth, faith, and testimony. Its opposite is «اَبْدَا». Now see their examples:\nDivine revelation says:\n(1) «وَ مَنۡ اَظۡلَمُ مِمَّنۡ کَتَمَ شَہَادَۃً عِنۡدَہٗ مِنَ اللّٰہِ» ( 2/140 )\nTranslation: Who is more unjust than one who conceals the testimony of Allah that he has (in the Book of Allah)?\nDivine revelation says:\n(2) «اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ یَکۡتُمُوۡنَ مَاۤ اَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ الۡبَیِّنٰتِ» ( 2/159 )\nTranslation: Those who conceal what We have revealed of clear signs.\nDivine revelation says:\n(3) «وَ قَالَ رَجُلٌ  مُّؤۡمِنٌ ٭ۖ مِّنۡ اٰلِ فِرۡعَوۡنَ یَکۡتُمُ  اِیۡمَانَہٗۤ» ( 40/28 )\nTranslation: And a believing man from the family of Pharaoh said who was concealing his faith."
    },
    {
      "id": 1287,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To conceal",
      "hw": "چھپانا",
      "s": "«وَارٰی» is used for hiding a reality from people (5 verses: 5:31-7:20-7:26-16:59-38:32)",
      "d": "«وَرٰی» is basically used in two meanings: (1) to ignite fire or produce fire. They say: «وَرِيَ الزَّنْدُ» he produced fire from the flint. And (2) to cover a reality. Here the second meaning is under discussion.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَوَسۡوَسَ لَہُمَا الشَّیۡطٰنُ لِیُبۡدِیَ لَہُمَا مَا وٗرِیَ عَنۡہُمَا مِنۡ سَوۡاٰتِہِمَا» ( 7/20 )\nTranslation: Then Satan whispered to them to reveal to them what was hidden from them of their private parts.\nAnd «وَارٰی یُوَارِیْ» means to hide a reality behind some cover or screen so that it becomes invisible to others. (Mufradat)\nFor example, Divine revelation says:\n«فَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ غُرَابًا یَّبۡحَثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ لِیُرِیَہٗ کَیۡفَ یُوَارِیۡ سَوۡءَۃَ اَخِیۡہِ» ( 5/31 )\nTranslation: Then Allah sent a crow that scratched in the earth to show him how to hide the shame of his brother."
    },
    {
      "id": 1288,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To conceal",
      "hw": "چھپانا",
      "s": "«اَکَنَّ» is used for hiding something in a safe place (6 verses: 2:235-6:25-16:81-17:46-18:57-41:5)",
      "d": "«اَکَنَّ» in its root, two things are basically found: (1) to hide and (2) protection (M. L.) or in other words, this word is used for hiding something in a safe place for protection (Fiqh 238) whether something is hidden in the heart or something is hidden elsewhere. «کنّ» means a cave or small cave in a mountain where one can take refuge, and its plural is «اَکْنَان». And «اَکِنَّۃ» means such veils, screens, or covers behind which something cannot proceed or enter.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ جَعَلۡنَا عَلٰی قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ  اَکِنَّۃً  اَنۡ یَّفۡقَہُوۡہُ» ( 6/25 )\nTranslation: And We have placed covers on their hearts so that they cannot understand it.\nAnd «اَکَنَ» in the Quran is generally used in a spiritual sense and its opposite is «عَلَنَ».\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ لَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ فِیۡمَا عَرَّضۡتُمۡ بِہٖ مِنۡ خِطۡبَۃِ النِّسَآءِ اَوۡ اَکۡنَنۡتُمۡ فِیۡۤ  اَنۡفُسِکُمۡ» ( 2/235 )\nTranslation: There is no blame on you for what you mention indirectly regarding women or what you conceal in your hearts.\nAnd similarly, in the Quran, the words «نُفُوس ، نَفْس ، صُدُوْر» and «قُلُوب» are generally used for this safe place."
    },
    {
      "id": 1289,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To conceal",
      "hw": "چھپانا",
      "s": "«اَسَرَّ» is used for hiding a secret out of necessity (11 verses: 5:52-10:54-12:19-12:77-13:10-20:62-21:3-34:33-66:3-67:13-71:9)",
      "d": "«سِرّ» means a secret matter and its plural is «اَسْرَار». And «اَسَرَّ» means to hide a secret in the heart. Whether it is a truth or not. Rather, it is hidden only due to necessity. Its opposite is «جَھَرَ» and also «عَلَنَ». And «سَارَّ» means to whisper or to talk secretly with each other. (Manjad) In the Quran, this word is used in both apparent and spiritual senses.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«قَالَ یٰبُشۡرٰی ہٰذَا غُلٰمٌ ؕ وَ اَسَرُّوۡہُ بِضَاعَۃً» ( 12/19 )\nTranslation: He said, 'O good news! This is a boy.' And they concealed him as merchandise.\nAt another place, Divine revelation says:\n«وَ اِذۡ  اَسَرَّ النَّبِیُّ  اِلٰی  بَعۡضِ  اَزۡوَاجِہٖ حَدِیۡثًا» ( 66/3 )\nTranslation: And when the Prophet confided a matter to one of his wives."
    },
    {
      "id": 1290,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To conceal",
      "hw": "چھپانا",
      "s": "«اَخْفٰی» is that hidden matter which a person hides in his heart and does not reveal to others (4 verses: 20:7-20:15-32:17-60:1)",
      "d": "«خَفِىّ» its usage is general. Whether a matter or thought is hidden in the heart or a thing is hidden elsewhere. Whether there is any truth or interest in it or not. It is used in both apparent and spiritual senses and its opposite is «بَدَا» and also «عَلَنَ». And also «جَلٰی ، جَلَو». And spiritually, it is more general than «سِرٌّ» because «سِرٌّ» is limited to hiding a matter, whereas «خَفِىّ» includes imaginations (conjectures, concepts) and whispers as well.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَاِنَّہٗ یَعۡلَمُ السِّرَّ وَ اَخۡفٰی» ( 20/7 )\nTranslation: Indeed, He knows the secret and the most hidden."
    },
    {
      "id": 1291,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To conceal",
      "hw": "چھپانا",
      "s": "«خَبۡءَ» hidden and concealed treasure (1 verse: 27:25)",
      "d": "«خَبَأَ» means to hide something. And «خَابَاَ» means to speak in riddles or to speak secretly or mysteriously. And «اِخْتَبَا لَہٗ خَبِیْئًا» means to ask someone about something hidden from them. (Manjad) And «خَبۡءَ» means hidden and concealed treasure. (Mufradat) «خَبۡءَ الْاَرْض» means the vegetation of the earth, the power of growth (i.e., the act of growing or causing to grow). And «خَبۡءَ السَّمَاء» means rainfall. And «اَخْرَجَ خَبۡءَ السَّمَآءِ خَبۡءَ الْاَرْضِ» means the rainfall of the sky brought forth growth on the earth, made the plants appear and grow. (Manjad)\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اَلَّا یَسۡجُدُوۡا  لِلّٰہِ الَّذِیۡ یُخۡرِجُ الۡخَبۡءَ فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ وَ یَعۡلَمُ مَا تُخۡفُوۡنَ  وَ مَا  تُعۡلِنُوۡنَ» ( 27/25 )\nTranslation: Why should they not prostrate to Allah who brings forth what is hidden in the heavens and the earth and knows what you conceal and what you reveal?"
    }
  ],
  "273": [
    {
      "id": 1292,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Roof",
      "hw": "چھت",
      "s": "«عَرْش» roofing a house with wood (29 verses: 2:259-7:54-9:129-10:3-11:7-12:100-13:2-17:42-18:42-20:5-21:22-22:45-23:86-23:116-25:59-27:23-27:26-27:38-27:41-27:42-32:4-39:75-40:7-40:15-43:82-57:4-69:17-81:20-85:15)",
      "d": "«عَرَشَ یَعْرِشُ» means to build a wooden house. To put wood on a house, e.g., to put beams on a house as a roof. And to train grapevines, etc. And «عَرَش» basically has two meanings: (1) throne (2) wood used in roofing (Manjad) Then this word is also used for the roof of a room, tent, canopy, and that which provides shade. (M. R.) In the Quran, this word is used in both meanings. See the example for roof and its wood:\nFor example, Divine revelation says:\n«اَوۡ کَالَّذِیۡ مَرَّ عَلٰی قَرۡیَۃٍ وَّ ہِیَ خَاوِیَۃٌ عَلٰی عُرُوۡشِہَا» ( 2/259 )\nTranslation: Or like the one who passed by a town that had fallen upon its roofs.\nAnd the example for throne:\nDivine revelation says:\n«وَ رَفَعَ اَبَوَیۡہِ عَلَی الۡعَرۡشِ» 12/100\nTranslation: And he raised his parents upon the throne."
    },
    {
      "id": 1293,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "ceiling",
      "hw": "چھت",
      "s": "«سَقْف» refers to the inner part of the ceiling seen from inside the room (4 verses: 16:26-21:32-43:33-52:5)",
      "d": "«سَقْف» refers to the inner part of the ceiling seen from inside the room (CEI LING) or the ceiling (M R). Plural «سُقَف».\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَخَرَّ عَلَیۡہِمُ السَّقۡفُ مِنۡ فَوۡقِہِمۡ» (16/26)\nTranslation: Then the ceiling fell upon them from above."
    },
    {
      "id": 1294,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "ceiling",
      "hw": "چھت",
      "s": "«بِنَآء» means constructed building. (2 verses: 2:22-40:64)",
      "d": "«بِنَآء» means construction, any constructed building, and every part of a building can also be called «بَنَاء», whether it is the foundation, wall, ceiling, or the entire building. And when the word «بِنَآء» is used in contrast to the floor, its meaning is only ceiling, because the word «بِنَآء» also implies the height of a structure (M L).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الۡاَرۡضَ فِرَاشًا وَّ السَّمَآءَ بِنَآءً» (2/22)\nTranslation: The One who has made the earth a bed for you and the sky a ceiling."
    }
  ],
  "274": [
    {
      "id": 1295,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to leave",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "«تَرَکَ» means to leave something. (34 verses: 2:17-2:180-2:248-2:264-4:7-4:9-4:11-4:12-4:33-4:176-6:94-7:176-9:16-11:87-12:17-12:37-16:61-18:99-23:100-26:146-29:2-29:35-35:45-37:78-37:108-37:119-37:129-44:24-44:25-51:37-54:15-59:5-62:11-75:36)",
      "d": "«تَرَکَ» is a general term. Meaning to leave something, intentionally or unintentionally, optionally or necessarily (Muf). It can be used in every context.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اِنۡ تَرَکَ خَیۡرَۨا  ۚ ۖ  الۡوَصِیَّۃُ لِلۡوَالِدَیۡنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبِیۡنَ» (2/180)\nTranslation: If (a person) leaves good (property) then the bequest is for the parents and the near relatives.\nThis was an urgent situation. Now see an example of optional or intentional:\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ تَرَکۡنَا یُوۡسُفَ عِنۡدَ مَتَاعِنَا» (12/17)\nTranslation: And we left Yusuf (Joseph) with our belongings."
    },
    {
      "id": 1296,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to leave",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "«ھَجَرَ» means to leave relations or homeland. (26 verses: 2:218-3:195-4:34-4:89-4:97-4:100-8:72-8:74-8:75-9:20-9:100-9:117-16:41-16:110-19:46-22:58-24:22-25:30-29:26-33:6-33:50-59:8-59:9-60:10-73:10-74:5)",
      "d": "«ھَجَرَ» is used for a person to cut off relations with another person or people (M L).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ اصۡبِرۡ عَلٰی مَا یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ وَ اہۡجُرۡہُمۡ ہَجۡرًا جَمِیۡلًا» (73/10)\nTranslation: And be patient with what they say and leave them (disassociate from them) in a good manner.\nThen another form of cutting off relations is to leave the area itself. In this case, the meaning of Hijrah is to leave the homeland.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ  ہَاجَرُوۡا وَ جٰہَدُوۡا فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ» (2/218)\nTranslation: And those who left their homeland and strove in the way of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1297,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to leave",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "«عَطَّلَ» means to leave someone idle or unemployed. (2 verses: 22:45-81:4)",
      "d": "«عَطَّلَ» means to leave something idle, to make a worker idle. (Muf) «تعطیل» means holiday from work. And «مُعَطّل» refers to an employee who is still employed but has been stopped from working.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ  اِذَا الۡعِشَارُ عُطِّلَتۡ» (81/4)\nTranslation: And when the ten-month pregnant she-camels are left (idle).\nAnd «بِئْرٌ مُعَطَّلَۃٌ» refers to wells that are ruined, deserted, or uninhabited."
    },
    {
      "id": 1299,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to leave",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "«یَذَرُ» means to leave something considering it insignificant. (43 verses: 2:234-2:240-2:278-3:179-4:129-6:70-6:91-6:110-6:112-6:120-6:137-7:70-7:73-7:127-7:180-7:186-9:86-10:11-11:64-12:47-15:3-19:72-20:106-21:89-23:54-26:166-37:125-40:26-43:83-48:15-51:42-52:45-62:9-68:44-70:42-71:23-71:26-71:27-73:11-74:11-74:28-75:21-76:27)",
      "d": "«وَذَرَ» is an incomplete verb. Only its present tense and imperative are used; past tense is not used. It is used in two contexts:\n(1) To leave something considering it insignificant (M Q).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ ذَرِ الَّذِیۡنَ اتَّخَذُوۡا دِیۡنَہُمۡ لَعِبًا وَّ لَہۡوًا» (6/70)\nTranslation: And leave those who have taken their religion as play and amusement.\n(2) Not giving permission to someone to interfere or object in doing a work. In English, its equivalent is LET. And «ذَرْنِیْ» means (LET ME DO THIS).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«ذَرۡنِیۡ  وَ مَنۡ خَلَقۡتُ وَحِیۡدًا» (74/11)\nTranslation: Leave me and whom I have created alone.\nThe meaning is that I know and he is. You do not intervene in this matter."
    },
    {
      "id": 1300,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to leave",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "«دَعْ» means to leave someone in a peaceful manner. (2 verses: 33:48-93:3)",
      "d": "«دَعْ» is also an incomplete verb, only present and imperative are used; past is not used. And its meanings are to leave something in a peaceful way (Muf).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ دَعۡ  اَذٰىہُمۡ  وَ  تَوَکَّلۡ  عَلَی اللّٰہِ» (33/48)\nTranslation: And leave their annoyance and trust in Allah!\nAnd «وَدَّعَ» means to bid farewell to a traveler or to dismiss with happiness, honor, and dignity, which includes the aspect of separating oneself and leaving them.\nFor example: The divine command is:\n«مَا وَدَّعَکَ رَبُّکَ وَ مَا قَلٰی» (93/3)\nTranslation: Your Lord has neither left you nor is He displeased."
    },
    {
      "id": 1301,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To Leave/Abandon",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "«غَادَرَ» means to leave someone due to some defect or flaw (2 Verses: 18:47, 18:49)",
      "d": "The word «غَدَرَ» is used for betrayal and disloyalty. And 'ghadar' means unfaithful and treacherous (muf). Its opposite is «وَفٰی». And «غَادَرَ» means to leave something due to a defect occurring in it, or to leave behind (muf). For example, the Quran states: «وَّ حَشَرۡنٰہُمۡ  فَلَمۡ  نُغَادِرۡ  مِنۡہِمۡ اَحَدًا» (18/47). Translation: We will gather them, then We will not leave any of them behind. That is, no one's deeds, whatever they may be, will be left behind. At another place, the Divine declaration is: «مَالِ ہٰذَا الۡکِتٰبِ لَا یُغَادِرُ صَغِیۡرَۃً وَّ لَا کَبِیۡرَۃً  اِلَّاۤ  اَحۡصٰہَا» (18/49). Translation: This is a book that leaves no small or great thing unrecorded."
    }
  ],
  "275": [
    {
      "id": 1303,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to snatch away",
      "hw": "چھڑانا",
      "s": "«اَنْقَذَ» is used for snatching someone away from calamity or saving them. (5 verses: 3:103-22:73-36:23-36:43-39:19)",
      "d": "«اَنْقَذَ» means to snatch a person from calamity or punishment, to save or deliver (Muf).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اَفَاَنۡتَ تُنۡقِذُ مَنۡ فِی النَّارِ» (39/19)\nTranslation: Can you snatch away the one who is in the Fire?\nAnd «اِسْتَنْفَذَ» means to snatch something away with full effort and desire.\nFor example: The divine command is:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّسۡلُبۡہُمُ الذُّبَابُ شَیۡئًا لَّا یَسۡتَنۡقِذُوۡہُ  مِنۡہُ ؕ ضَعُفَ الطَّالِبُ وَ الۡمَطۡلُوۡبُ» (22/73)\nTranslation: And if the fly snatches something from them, they cannot snatch it away from him. Weak is the seeker and the sought."
    }
  ],
  "276": [
    {
      "id": 1304,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to touch",
      "hw": "چھونا",
      "s": "«مَسَّ» means the contact of some part of the body with something. (58 verses: 2:80-2:214-2:236-2:237-2:275-3:24-3:47-3:120-3:140-3:174-4:43-5:6-5:73-6:7-6:17-6:49-7:73-7:95-7:188-7:201-8:68-10:12-10:21-10:107-11:10-11:48-11:64-11:113-12:88-15:48-15:54-16:53-17:67-17:83-19:20-19:45-20:97-21:46-21:83-24:14-24:35-26:156-30:33-33:49-35:35-36:18-38:41-39:8-39:49-39:61-41:49-41:50-41:51-50:38-54:48-56:79-70:20-70:21)",
      "d": "«مَسَّ» means the contact of some part of the body with something (Muf). This word is also used in the Quran in this meaning.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ اَیُّوۡبَ اِذۡ نَادٰی رَبَّہٗۤ  اَنِّیۡ مَسَّنِیَ الضُّرُّ» (21/83)\nTranslation: And Ayub (Job) when he called his Lord: Indeed, harm has touched me.\nAt another place, the divine command is:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا لَنۡ تَمَسَّنَا النَّارُ اِلَّاۤ اَیَّامًا مَّعۡدُوۡدَۃً» (2/80)\nTranslation: And they say: The Fire will not touch us except for a few numbered days."
    },
    {
      "id": 1305,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Touching",
      "hw": "چھونا",
      "s": "«لَمَسَ» to touch or feel something with the hand or fingers (1 verse: 72:8)",
      "d": "«لَمَسَ» means to touch or feel something with the hand or fingers. Whether the desired thing is obtained or not (mufrad). This word has also been used in the Quran in these meanings.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّ اَنَّا لَمَسۡنَا السَّمَآءَ  فَوَجَدۡنٰہَا مُلِئَتۡ حَرَسًا شَدِیۡدًا وَّ  شُہُبًا» ( 72/8 )\nTranslation: And (the jinn said) we touched the sky and found it filled with severe guards and meteors."
    },
    {
      "id": 1306,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Touching",
      "hw": "چھونا",
      "s": "«طَمَثَ» meaning menstrual blood (2 verses: 55:56-55:74)",
      "d": "«طَمَثَ» means menstrual blood (f l 115) and «طَمَثَ یَطْمِثُ» also means a woman having her period (manjad). And for a man to remove the veil of a woman's private parts (mufrad). So this word is specific to the meaning of intercourse (mubasharat) for the first time of intercourse, and in the first two meanings, this word is not used in the Quran. Also see 'Intercourse'."
    }
  ],
  "277": [
    {
      "id": 1307,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Snatching or Taking Away",
      "hw": "چھین",
      "s": "«سَلْب» to take something forcefully from someone (1 verse: 22:73)",
      "d": "«سَلْب» to take something from someone forcefully. (manjad) To snatch or take something away right in front of someone, even if the taker is weak.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّسۡلُبۡہُمُ الذُّبَابُ شَیۡئًا لَّا یَسۡتَنۡقِذُوۡہُ  مِنۡہُ» ( 22/73 )\nTranslation: If the fly snatches something from them, they cannot recover it from him."
    },
    {
      "id": 1308,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Snatching or Taking Away",
      "hw": "چھین",
      "s": "«غَصَبَ» for a powerful person to forcefully seize something from a weak person (1 verse: 18:79)",
      "d": "«غَصَبَ» to take something by oppression, excess, force, or deceit (manjad). But for taking something by deceit or trickery, there is a separate word «غَبَنَ» (m. q). Therefore, the meanings given by Imam Raghīb are more correct. That is, for a powerful person to forcefully seize something from a weak person with oppression and excess (mufrad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ کَانَ  وَرَآءَہُمۡ مَّلِکٌ یَّاۡخُذُ کُلَّ  سَفِیۡنَۃٍ  غَصۡبًا» ( 18/79 )\nTranslation: And there was a king behind them who used to seize every ship by force."
    },
    {
      "id": 1310,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Snatching or Taking Away",
      "hw": "چھین",
      "s": "«خَطِفَ» to snatch something quickly with speed, to grab (6 verses: 2:20-8:26-22:31-28:57-29:67-37:10)",
      "d": "«خَطِفَ» to snatch something and run away quickly (mufrad. fal). To grab. To snatch.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یَکَادُ الۡبَرۡقُ یَخۡطَفُ اَبۡصَارَہُمۡ» ( 2/20 )\nTranslation: Lightning almost snatches away their sight."
    }
  ],
  "278": [
    {
      "id": 1311,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Need",
      "hw": "حاجت",
      "s": "«حَاجَۃ» a need whose non-fulfillment causes constriction in the heart (3 verses: 12:68-40:80-59:9)",
      "d": "«اَلْحُوْج» means neediness and poverty (manjad). A need or desire whose non-fulfillment causes constriction and tightness in the heart.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَا کَانَ یُغۡنِیۡ عَنۡہُمۡ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ مِنۡ شَیۡءٍ اِلَّا حَاجَۃً فِیۡ نَفۡسِ یَعۡقُوۡبَ قَضٰہَا» ( 12/68 )\nTranslation: And this plan of theirs would not avail them against Allah at all, except that it was a desire in the soul of Ya'qub which he fulfilled.\nAt another place, the Lord says:\n«وَ لَا یَجِدُوۡنَ  فِیۡ صُدُوۡرِہِمۡ حَاجَۃً  مِّمَّاۤ اُوۡتُوۡا» ( 59/9 )\nTranslation: And they find no dissatisfaction in their hearts for what they are given.\nThat is, even though they are given little, they are patient and grateful, and do not feel constriction or tightness in their hearts."
    },
    {
      "id": 1312,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Need",
      "hw": "حاجت",
      "s": "«مَاٰرِب» needs that are fulfilled (2 verses: 20:18-24:31)",
      "d": "«اَرْب ، اَرِب» and «اِرب» refer to a need without which one cannot do, and for which one must strive.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«غَیۡرِ اُولِی الۡاِرۡبَۃِ مِنَ الرِّجَالِ» ( 24/31 )\nTranslation: meaning male servants who do not yet have the need (for marriage).\nAnd «مَاٰرِب» is the plural of «مَارِبَۃ», which means the fulfillment of a need or requirement.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ ہِیَ عَصَایَ ۚ اَتَوَکَّؤُا عَلَیۡہَا وَ اَہُشُّ بِہَا عَلٰی غَنَمِیۡ وَ لِیَ فِیۡہَا مَاٰرِبُ  اُخۡرٰی» ( 20/18 )\nTranslation: Moses said, 'This is my staff; I lean on it and I use it to beat down leaves for my sheep, and I have other needs for it.' (meaning other needs are also fulfilled with it)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1313,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Need",
      "hw": "حاجت",
      "s": "«وَطَرَ» need for sexual intercourse; this word is used in the Quran but its meaning is broad (1 verse: 33:37)",
      "d": "«وَطَرَ» means (1) need, desire (manjad). (2) cohabitation, lust (m. q). And its plural is «اَوْطَار». In the Quran, this word is used only in the second meaning.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا قَضٰی زَیۡدٌ مِّنۡہَا وَطَرًا» ( 33/37 )\nTranslation: Then when Zayd had fulfilled his need of her."
    }
  ],
  "279": [
    {
      "id": 1314,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Being Present",
      "hw": "حاضر",
      "s": "«حَضَرَ» meaning to exist, to be present (24 verses: 2:133-2:180-2:196-2:282-3:30-4:8-4:18-4:128-5:106-7:163-18:49-19:68-23:98-28:61-30:16-34:38-36:32-36:53-36:75-37:57-37:127-37:158-46:29-81:14)",
      "d": "«حَضَرَ» is the opposite of «غَابَ». «حَضَرَ» means to be present, to come before (mufrad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا حَضَرُوۡہُ قَالُوۡۤا  اَنۡصِتُوۡا» ( 46/29 )\nTranslation: So when they came to him, they said, 'Be silent.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1315,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Being Present",
      "hw": "حاضر",
      "s": "«شَھِدَ» to exist. To see and to testify (60 verses: 2:23-2:84-2:133-2:143-2:185-2:204-2:282-3:18-3:52-3:64-3:70-3:81-3:86-3:99-3:140-4:6-4:15-4:69-4:135-4:166-5:8-5:44-5:111-6:19-6:130-6:144-6:150-7:37-7:172-9:107-11:54-12:26-12:81-18:51-19:37-21:61-22:28-22:78-24:2-24:4-24:6-24:8-24:13-24:24-25:72-27:32-27:49-36:65-39:69-41:20-41:21-41:22-43:19-43:86-46:10-57:19-59:11-63:1-65:2-83:21)",
      "d": "«شَھِدَ» this word is used in many meanings. But two relevant meanings are:\n(1) to be present.\nFor example: The Lord says:\n«اَمۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃَ  اِنَاثًا  وَّ ہُمۡ شٰہِدُوۡنَ» ( 37/150 )\nTranslation: Or did We create the angels as females while they were present?\n(2) to be present and to see something with one's own eyes. Then to testify before a judge (faq l 30). This means testimony.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَا یَاۡبَ الشُّہَدَآءُ اِذَا مَا دُعُوۡا» ( 2/282 )\nTranslation: And let not the witnesses refuse when they are called."
    }
  ],
  "280": [
    {
      "id": 1317,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "State/Condition",
      "hw": "حالت",
      "s": "«بَال» is used for the current state when asking questions (2 verses: 12:50-20:51)",
      "d": "«بَال» means the present state or condition. This word is general.\nFor example, in the Quran: «قَالَ فَمَا بَالُ الۡقُرُوۡنِ الۡاُوۡلٰی. قَالَ عِلۡمُہَا عِنۡدَ رَبِّیۡ» (20/51,52)\nTranslation: Pharaoh asked Prophet Moses (PBUH), \"What is the state of the former nations?\" He said, \"Their knowledge is with my Lord.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 1318,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "State/Condition",
      "hw": "حالت",
      "s": "«خَطْبُ» is used for inquiring about an undesirable matter (5 verses: 12:51-15:57-20:95-28:23-51:31)",
      "d": "«خَطْبُ» means affair, state, matter—whether big or small. Generally, it is used for an undesirable matter (Munjid).\nIn the Quran: «قَالَ فَمَا خَطۡبُکُمۡ اَیُّہَا الۡمُرۡسَلُوۡنَ. قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّاۤ اُرۡسِلۡنَاۤ اِلٰی قَوۡمٍ مُّجۡرِمِیۡنَ» (51/31,32)\nTranslation: Prophet Abraham (PBUH) said to the angels, \"What is your motive?\" The angels said, \"We have been sent to a criminal people.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 1319,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "State/Condition",
      "hw": "حالت",
      "s": "«دَأب» is used for habits and conduct (4 verses: 3:11-8:52-8:54-40:31)",
      "d": "«دَأب» means to continue continuously, permanent habit, habits and manners, gait (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Quran: «کَدَاۡبِ اٰلِ فِرۡعَوۡنَ» (3/11)\nTranslation: (Their state is) like that of the people of Pharaoh."
    },
    {
      "id": 1320,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "State/Condition",
      "hw": "حالت",
      "s": "«طَوْر» comes for one form after another (1 verse: 71:14)",
      "d": "«طَوْر» means form, state, manner, turn, and «اَلنَّاسُ اَطْوَارٌ» means people are of various kinds (Munjid). And «تَطَوُّر» means to change from one state to another. So «طَوْر» refers to a state or form that is expected to change after some time according to its pattern.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ قَدۡ خَلَقَکُمۡ اَطۡوَارًا» (71/14)\nTranslation: And Allah has created you in various forms."
    }
  ],
  "281": [
    {
      "id": 1321,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Authority",
      "hw": "حاکم",
      "s": "«حَاکِمْ» means a just judge who decides and prevents oppression (6 verses: 4:60-7:87-10:109-11:45-12:80-95:8)",
      "d": "«حَکَمَ» means \"preventing oppression\" (Munjid), i.e., a judgment that prevents injustice and excess towards others. And «حَکَّمَ» means to appoint someone as a judge or ruler. And «تحاکم» means to take one's case to a ruler for judgment. (Munjid) So a ruler is one who judges people's cases and prevents the oppressor from oppression.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ اِذَا حَکَمۡتُمۡ بَیۡنَ النَّاسِ اَنۡ تَحۡکُمُوۡا بِالۡعَدۡلِ» (4/58)\nTranslation: And when you judge between people, judge with justice."
    },
    {
      "id": 1322,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Authority",
      "hw": "حاکم",
      "s": "«اُولِی الْاَمْر» means those in authority, rulers whose commands are executed (2 verses: 4:59-4:83)",
      "d": "«اُولِی الْاَمْر» is the plural of «وَلِیُّ الْاَمْر». And «وَلّٰی» means to appoint someone as a ruler, governor, or king over a region. So etymologically, this term refers to the administrative authority of a country. However, it can also apply to judicial rulers.\nFor example, in the Quran: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اَطِیۡعُوا اللّٰہَ وَ اَطِیۡعُوا الرَّسُوۡلَ وَ اُولِی الۡاَمۡرِ مِنۡکُمۡ» (4/59)\nTranslation: O you who believe! Obey Allah and obey the Messenger and those in authority among you."
    },
    {
      "id": 1323,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Authority",
      "hw": "حاکم",
      "s": "«قَوَّام» refers to any person responsible for running an individual's, institution's, or system's affairs fairly (3 verses: 4:34-4:135-5:8)",
      "d": "«قَامَ» means to stand. And «اَقَامَ» means to straighten or establish firmly. And «قَوَّمَ» means to set right or adjust something (i.e., to make it even and correct) (Munjid). And «قَوَّام» or «قیَّم» is a person who is responsible for running the affairs of an individual, institution, or system in a proper manner, and for its protection, supervision, and providing its necessities. (F. Q.)\nFor example, in the Quran: «اَلرِّجَالُ قَوّٰمُوۡنَ عَلَی النِّسَآءِ بِمَا فَضَّلَ اللّٰہُ بَعۡضَہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ وَّ بِمَاۤ اَنۡفَقُوۡا مِنۡ اَمۡوَالِہِمۡ» (4/34)\nTranslation: Men are protectors/maintainers of women, because Allah has favored some of them over others and because they spend from their wealth."
    }
  ],
  "282": [
    {
      "id": 1324,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding the Limit / Excess",
      "hw": " زیادتی",
      "s": "«جَاوَزَ» means to go beyond a designated limit (4 verses: 2:249-7:138-10:90-18:62)",
      "d": "«جَاوَزَ» means to go beyond a specific place or a prescribed and designated limit (Munjid). To pass through while traveling, and «جَوَّزَ الطَّرِیّق» means the middle of the road. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَلَمَّا جَاوَزَا قَالَ لِفَتٰىہُ اٰتِنَا غَدَآءَنَا ۫ لَقَدۡ لَقِیۡنَا مِنۡ سَفَرِنَا ہٰذَا نَصَبًا» (18/62)\nTranslation: When they both went beyond (that place), he said to his servant, \"Bring us our morning meal; we have certainly encountered fatigue from this journey of ours.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 1325,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding the Limit / Excess",
      "hw": " زیادتی",
      "s": "«اَسْرَفَ» means to exceed the limit of moderation (19 verses: 5:32-6:141-7:31-7:81-10:12-10:83-17:33-20:127-21:9-25:67-26:151-36:19-39:53-40:28-40:34-40:43-43:5-44:31-51:34)",
      "d": "«اَسْرَفَ» means to go beyond the limit of moderation in a task. Not paying attention to the prescribed limits while doing something. «سَرَفَ فِی الْاَمْر» means to be negligent or heedless in a matter. And «اَسْرَفَ» means to do excess. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Quran: «کُلُوۡا وَ اشۡرَبُوۡا وَ لَا تُسۡرِفُوۡا» (7/31)\nTranslation: Eat and drink, but do not exceed."
    },
    {
      "id": 1326,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding the Limit / Excess",
      "hw": " زیادتی",
      "s": "«بَغْیُ» means to exceed limits in fulfilling a desire (79 verses: 2:90-2:187-2:198-2:207-2:213-2:265-2:272-3:7-3:19-3:83-3:85-3:99-4:24-4:34-4:94-4:104-4:114-4:139-5:2-5:35-5:50-6:35-6:114-6:146-6:164-7:33-7:45-7:86-7:140-9:47-9:48-10:23-10:90-11:19-12:65-13:17-13:22-14:3-16:14-16:90-17:12-17:28-17:42-17:57-17:66-17:110-18:64-18:108-22:60-23:7-24:33-28:55-28:73-28:76-28:77-29:17-30:23-30:46-33:51-35:12-38:22-38:24-42:14-42:27-42:39-42:42-45:12-45:17-48:29-49:9-55:20-57:27-59:8-60:1-62:10-66:1-70:31-73:20-92:20)",
      "d": "«بَغْیُ» means to go beyond the appropriate limit in seeking or fulfilling a desire (Mufradat). To try to claim more than one's right unjustly. And accordingly, to suppress the rights of others.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ اِنَّ کَثِیۡرًا مِّنَ الۡخُلَطَآءِ لَیَبۡغِیۡ بَعۡضُہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ» (38/24)\nTranslation: And indeed, many of the partners wrong each other."
    },
    {
      "id": 1328,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding Limits; Doing Excess",
      "hw": " زیادتی",
      "s": "«فَرَطَ» to act hastily or exceed without thinking (2 verses: 18:28-20:45)",
      "d": "«فَرَطَ» means to act first, to get ahead, to hurry. «فَرَطَ مِنْہُ الْقَول» means to speak without thinking (Majid). Essentially, this word is used for exceeding limits without thinking or in haste. And «فَرَّطَ» is used for deficiency and shortcoming (lexicon of opposites). Example: In the Quran it is: «وَ اتَّبَعَ ہَوٰىہُ  وَ کَانَ   اَمۡرُہٗ   فُرُطًا» (18/28) Translation: And he followed his desire, and his affair was excessive."
    },
    {
      "id": 1329,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding Limits; Doing Excess",
      "hw": " زیادتی",
      "s": "«سَلَقَ» to exceed against others with hand or tongue (1 verse: 33:19)",
      "d": "«سَلَقَ» means to overreach with hand or tongue (Majid), to come aggressively (Majid). To exceed against others with hand or tongue. Example: In the Quran it is: «فَاِذَا  ذَہَبَ الۡخَوۡفُ سَلَقُوۡکُمۡ بِاَلۡسِنَۃٍ حِدَادٍ  اَشِحَّۃً عَلَی الۡخَیۡرِ» (33/19) Translation: Then when the fear is gone, they will overreach you with sharp tongues in greed for wealth."
    },
    {
      "id": 1330,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding Limits; Doing Excess",
      "hw": " زیادتی",
      "s": "«غَلَا» to exceed in someone's worth and status due to extreme belief; to take an extremist approach (2 verses: 4:171-5:77)",
      "d": "«غَلَا» means to become expensive. «غَلَا السِّعْر» means prices to rise. «غَلَا السَّہَم» means to throw an arrow to an extreme distance. «غَلَا فِی الْاَمْرِ» means to exaggerate, to exceed. To go beyond limits in someone's worth and status due to extreme belief (Majid), i.e., to take an extremist approach. Example: In the Quran it is: «یٰۤاَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰابِ لَا تَغۡلُوۡا فِیۡ دِیۡنِکُمۡ وَ لَا تَقُوۡلُوۡا عَلَی اللّٰہِ  اِلَّا الۡحَقَّ ؕ اِنَّمَا الۡمَسِیۡحُ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ رَسُوۡلُ اللّٰہِ وَ کَلِمَتُہٗ» (4/171) Translation: O People of the Book, do not exceed in your religion and do not say about Allah except the truth. Indeed, the Messiah, Jesus, the son of Mary, was the messenger of Allah and His word."
    },
    {
      "id": 1331,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding Limits; Doing Excess",
      "hw": " زیادتی",
      "s": "«شَطَطًا» to exaggerate in falsehood to such an extent that reason cannot accept it (3 verses: 18:14-38:22-72:4)",
      "d": "«شَطَطًا» means to exceed in exaggeration, to go far beyond limits (Majid), to lie and exaggerate in it (Majid). Example: In the Quran it is: «لَنۡ نَّدۡعُوَا۠ مِنۡ دُوۡنِہٖۤ  اِلٰـہًا لَّقَدۡ قُلۡنَاۤ  اِذًا  شَطَطًا» (18/14) Translation: We will not invoke any deity besides Him; if we did, we would have certainly said an excessive lie."
    }
  ],
  "283": [
    {
      "id": 1332,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Falling Short; Deficiency",
      "hw": "حد ",
      "s": "The word «فَرَّطَ» is used for not properly completing a task and for negligence (5 verses: 6:31-6:38-6:61-12:80-39:56)",
      "d": "The word «فَرَّطَ» is from the lexicon of opposites (addad). As explained earlier, «فَرَطَ» means to go beyond limits or to exceed without thinking or in haste. And «فَرَّطَ» means to fall behind limits or to be deficient or negligent without thinking or in haste. Example: In the Quran it is: «اَنۡ تَقُوۡلَ نَفۡسٌ یّٰحَسۡرَتٰی عَلٰی مَا فَرَّطۡتُّ فِیۡ جَنۡۢبِ اللّٰہِ» (39/56) Translation: Lest a soul should say, 'Alas, my regret over what I neglected in regard to Allah.' Note: (Lexicon of opposites refers to words that have two distinct meanings that are opposite to each other.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1333,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Falling Short; Deficiency",
      "hw": "حد ",
      "s": "«قَصَرَ» is used for deficiency in quantity (3 verses: 4:101-7:202-48:27)",
      "d": "«قَصَرَ» means to reduce within a specified limit or to remain less. «قَصَرَ السَّھْم» means the arrow not reaching the target. «قَصَرَ الصَّلوٰۃ» means not completing the prayer but shortening it. «قَصَّرَ الشَّعْر» means to cut some hair, and «قَصُرَ» means to be small (Majid). From this, words like «قَصُور» (short), «تَقْصِیْر» (shortening), and «قَاصِر» (limited) are famous in our language. Example: In the Quran it is: «فَلَیۡسَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ جُنَاحٌ اَنۡ تَقۡصُرُوۡا مِنَ الصَّلٰوۃِ» (4/101) Translation: There is no blame upon you if you shorten the prayer."
    }
  ],
  "284": [
    {
      "id": 1334,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Forbidden",
      "hw": "حرام",
      "s": "«حَرَامٌ» things or matters that Sharia has strictly prohibited (40 verses: 2:85-2:173-2:275-3:50-3:93-4:23-4:160-5:3-5:26-5:72-5:87-5:96-6:119-6:138-6:139-6:140-6:143-6:144-6:145-6:146-6:148-6:150-6:151-7:32-7:33-7:50-7:157-9:29-9:37-10:59-16:35-16:115-16:116-16:118-17:33-21:95-24:3-25:68-28:12-66:1)",
      "d": "«حَرَامٌ» refers to things or matters that Sharia has strictly prohibited. In the words of the author of Maqayis al-Lughah, its meaning is 'al-man' al-shadeed' (the severe prohibition). This word is general. For example, disobedience to parents is also forbidden. The meat of predators is also forbidden. And usury is also forbidden, and Paradise is also forbidden for polytheists. And its opposite is halal, i.e., things for which general permission is granted. Example: In the Quran it is: «وَ اَحَلَّ اللّٰہُ الۡبَیۡعَ وَ حَرَّمَ الرِّبٰوا» (2/275) Translation: Allah has permitted trade and forbidden usury."
    },
    {
      "id": 1335,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Forbidden",
      "hw": "حرام",
      "s": "«سُحْت» is used for illicit and forbidden earnings (3 verses: 5:42-5:62-5:63-)",
      "d": "The word «سُحْت» is specific for earnings and wealth. And its meaning is sustenance that causes shame and disgrace, such as the price of a pig or a dog (Fall 12). Wealth earned through illicit means. Forbidden earnings, bribe, etc. Example: In the Quran it is: «سَمّٰعُوۡنَ لِلۡکَذِبِ اَکّٰلُوۡنَ لِلسُّحۡتِ» (5/42) Translation: They are listeners to falsehood, devourers of the forbidden."
    }
  ],
  "285": [
    {
      "id": 1336,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Part; Portion",
      "hw": "حصہ",
      "s": "«جُزْء» any one part or piece of something (3 verses: 2:260-15:44-43:15)",
      "d": "«جُزْء» means a part or piece of something, and its plural is «اجزاء». Meaning: those parts or pieces that together make up that thing or compose it (Majid). Example: In the Quran it is: «ثُمَّ اجۡعَلۡ عَلٰی کُلِّ جَبَلٍ مِّنۡہُنَّ جُزۡءًا» (2/260) Translation: Then place on every mountain a portion thereof."
    },
    {
      "id": 1337,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Part; Portion",
      "hw": "حصہ",
      "s": "«زُلْف» the initial part of the night (1 verse: 11:114)",
      "d": "«زُلْف» means the initial part of the night or the early hours (F. L. 34). The basic meanings of «زُلْف» are rank and proximity. The initial part of the night is called «زُلْف» because it is the nearest and closest part of the entire night. Example: In the Quran it is: «اَقِمِ الصَّلٰوۃَ طَرَفَیِ النَّہَارِ وَ زُلَفًا مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ» (11/114) Translation: Establish prayer at the two ends of the day and the early hours of the night."
    },
    {
      "id": 1338,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Share/Portion",
      "hw": "حصہ",
      "s": "«حَظّ» means a share of goodness, virtue, and wealth (5 Verses: 3:176, 4:11, 4:176, 5:13, 5:14)",
      "d": "«حَظّ» means a share of goodness and virtue (M. A.) (F. Q. 135) and also means wealth or good fortune. Happiness (manjad). In the Quran, this word comes for the prescribed shares in inheritance (wealth), which is also related to goodness, virtue, and wealth. And also to happiness and bliss. For example, the Quran states: «فَلِلذَّکُرِ مِثۡلُ حَظِّ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ» (4/176). Translation: For the male, there is the share equal to that of two females."
    },
    {
      "id": 1339,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Khalaq",
      "hw": "حصہ",
      "s": "«خَلَاق» is the specific portion one receives as a result of their character (4 verses: 2:102, 2:200, 3:77, 9:69)",
      "d": "«خَلَاق» refers to a definite share of all kinds of goodness (m. r.), a great portion of goodness (manjad) (muf) (Faqih Lane 136). That is, the excellence a person attains through their character. This share is connected to a person's deeds.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَمِنَ النَّاسِ مَنۡ یَّقُوۡلُ رَبَّنَاۤ  اٰتِنَا فِی الدُّنۡیَا وَ مَا لَہٗ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ  مِنۡ خَلَاقٍ» (2/200)\nTranslation: Then among them are some who say, 'Our Lord, grant us in this world,' and for such people there will be no portion in the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 1340,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Naseeb",
      "hw": "حصہ",
      "s": "«نَصِیْب» is the portion that is destined, whether small or large (18 verses: 2:202, 3:23, 4:7, 4:32, 4:33, 4:44, 4:51, 4:53, 4:85, 4:118, 4:141, 6:136, 7:37, 11:109, 16:56, 28:77, 40:47, 42:20)",
      "d": "«نَصَب» means to fix or plant something. And «نَصِیْب» means a stone planted as a marker on a path. And «نَصِیْب» refers to the fixed portion written in one's destiny (muf), whether it relates to something beloved or disliked (na-pasandidah) (Faqih Lane 135).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ ابۡتَغِ  فِیۡمَاۤ  اٰتٰىکَ اللّٰہُ  الدَّارَ الۡاٰخِرَۃَ  وَ لَا تَنۡسَ نَصِیۡبَکَ مِنَ الدُّنۡیَا» (28/77)\nTranslation: And seek through what Allah has given you the abode of the Hereafter, and do not forget your portion of this world."
    },
    {
      "id": 1341,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Kifl",
      "hw": "حصہ",
      "s": "«کِفْل» is a share as recompense for a good or bad deed (2 verses: 4:85, 57:28)",
      "d": "«کِفْل» means guarantee or surety. It also means a share and the necessary recompense for an action, whether good or bad. According to Al-Munjid, it means double reward or double sin.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَنۡ یَّشۡفَعۡ شَفَاعَۃً حَسَنَۃً یَّکُنۡ لَّہٗ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّنۡہَا ۚ وَ مَنۡ یَّشۡفَعۡ شَفَاعَۃً سَیِّئَۃً یَّکُنۡ لَّہٗ کِفۡلٌ مِّنۡہَا» (4/85)\nTranslation: Whoever intercedes with a good intercession will have a share from it, and whoever intercedes with an evil intercession will have a share from it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1342,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Ba'dh",
      "hw": "حصہ",
      "s": "«بَعْض» is a part of a complete thing, or one or some among similar things (86 verses: 2:36, 2:73, 2:76, 2:85, 2:145, 2:251, 2:253, 2:259, 2:283, 3:34, 3:50, 3:64, 3:155, 3:195, 4:19, 4:21, 4:25, 4:32, 4:34, 4:150, 5:49, 5:51, 6:53, 6:65, 6:112, 6:128, 6:129, 6:158, 6:165, 7:24, 8:37, 8:72, 8:73, 8:75, 9:67, 9:71, 9:127, 10:46, 11:12, 11:54, 12:10, 13:4, 13:36, 13:40, 16:71, 17:21, 17:55, 17:88, 18:19, 18:99, 20:123, 22:40, 23:44, 23:91, 23:113, 24:40, 24:58, 24:62, 24:63, 25:20, 26:198, 27:72, 29:25, 30:41, 33:6, 34:31, 34:42, 35:40, 37:27, 37:50, 38:22, 38:24, 40:28, 40:77, 43:32, 43:63, 43:67, 45:19, 47:4, 47:26, 49:2, 49:12, 52:25, 66:3, 68:30, 69:44)",
      "d": "«بَعْض» means a portion, a piece. It is also used for a part of a whole.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبُوۡہُ بِبَعۡضِہَا» (2/73)\nTranslation: So we said, 'Strike him (the slain man) with some of it (the cow).'\nAnd if there is a collection of several distinct things, the word 'ba'dh' can also be used for an individual. As in «بَعْضَ النَّاس» meaning 'some people' or «بَعْضَ الَلَیَالِی» meaning 'some nights'.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«بَعۡضُکُمۡ لِبَعۡضٍ عَدُوٌّ» (2/36)\nTranslation: Some of you are enemies to others.\nAdditionally, this word is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«وَ لِاُبَیِّنَ  لَکُمۡ بَعۡضَ الَّذِیۡ تَخۡتَلِفُوۡنَ فِیۡہِ» (43/63)\nTranslation: So that I may clarify for you some of that in which you differ."
    }
  ],
  "286": [
    {
      "id": 1343,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Hifazat Karna",
      "hw": "حفاظت",
      "s": "«حَفِظَ» to save something from being lost or destroyed (29 verses: 2:238, 2:255, 4:34, 5:44, 5:89, 6:61, 6:92, 9:112, 12:12, 12:63, 12:64, 12:65, 12:81, 13:11, 15:9, 15:17, 21:82, 23:5, 23:9, 24:30, 24:31, 33:35, 37:7, 41:12, 70:29, 70:34, 82:10, 83:33, 86:4)",
      "d": "«حَفِظَ» is the opposite of «اَضَاعَ». It means to save from loss and destruction (manjad), to guard (m. r.), to try to protect something from external dangers (Faqih Lane 15).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ نَحۡفَظُ اَخَانَا وَ نَزۡدَادُ کَیۡلَ  بَعِیۡرٍ» (12/65)\nTranslation: We will protect our brother and also bring an increased measure of grain."
    },
    {
      "id": 1344,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Hifazat Karna",
      "hw": "حفاظت",
      "s": "«رَعٰی» to protect and remove the causes of external threats (2 verses: 20:54, 28:23)",
      "d": "«رَعٰی» means to protect something and to remove the causes that lead to external threats. And «رَاعِیْ» means a shepherd, a guardian. Its opposite is «اِھْمَال», meaning a flock grazing without a shepherd (Faqih Lane 15).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  لِاَمٰنٰتِہِمۡ وَ عَہۡدِہِمۡ رٰعُوۡنَ» (23/8)\nTranslation: Who are guardians of their trusts and their covenants."
    },
    {
      "id": 1345,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Hifazat Karna",
      "hw": "حفاظت",
      "s": "«اَحْصَنَ» to protect by means of a four-walled enclosure (8 verses: 4:24, 4:25, 5:5, 21:91, 24:4, 24:23, 59:14, 66:12)",
      "d": "«حِصْن» means a fortress or a secure place, and its plural is «حُصُوْن» (59/2). In «حَصَن», two fundamental aspects are found: «اَلْحِفْظُ وَالْحَیَاطَۃ» (m. l.), i.e., protection, enclosure. According to Al-Munjid, it means to secure in a strong place. It also means for a woman to protect her chastity.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ مَرۡیَمَ  ابۡنَتَ عِمۡرٰنَ  الَّتِیۡۤ  اَحۡصَنَتۡ فَرۡجَہَا» (66/12)\nTranslation: And Maryam, daughter of Imran, who guarded her chastity.\nIt also has a meaning of entering into marriage. Because marriage also serves as a fortress against immorality.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّ الۡمُحۡصَنٰتُ مِنَ النِّسَآءِ  اِلَّا مَا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ» (4/24)\nTranslation: And [also prohibited are] married women, except those whom your right hands possess."
    },
    {
      "id": 1346,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Hifazat Karna",
      "hw": "حفاظت",
      "s": "«کَلَأَ» to keep something safe and sound by guarding it (1 verse: 21:42)",
      "d": "«کَلَأَ» means to constantly watch over something and keep it intact. Essentially, two aspects are found here: (1) vigilance (2) stability (m. l. muf). It also means to save something from harm and from inclining towards calamity (Faqih Lane 169).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قُلۡ مَنۡ یَّکۡلَؤُکُمۡ  بِالَّیۡلِ وَ النَّہَارِ مِنَ الرَّحۡمٰنِ» (21/42)\nTranslation: Say, 'Who can protect you by night and by day from the Most Merciful?'"
    }
  ],
  "287": [
    {
      "id": 1347,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Haq-e-Mehr",
      "hw": "حق مہر",
      "s": "In «صَدُقَۃ», all the obligations of a woman, including the dowry (mehr), are included. (1 verse: 4:4)",
      "d": "«صَدُقَۃ» has the plural «صَدُقٰت». If the 'dal' in «صَدَقَۃ» has a zabar (fat-ha), its meaning is 'sadaqah' (charity). If it has a zer (kasra), its meaning is taken as 'haq-e-mehr' (right of dowry). And «اَصْدَقَ الْاِبْنَۃَ» means to determine the dowry for one's daughter (manjad). Although «صَدُقَۃ» is used in a broader sense than just 'mehr'. 'Mehr' is the specified amount whose payment is obligatory, while «صُدَاق» refers to that charity or expenditure upon which the marriage is based. Thus, «صُدَاق» includes not only the 'mehr' but also 'naan wa nafaqah' (maintenance and expenses) (Faqih Lane 139).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اٰتُوا النِّسَآءَ صَدُقٰتِہِنَّ نِحۡلَۃً» (4/4)\nTranslation: And give the women their dowries graciously."
    },
    {
      "id": 1348,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Haq-e-Mehr",
      "hw": "حق مہر",
      "s": "«اَجْر» is used in all meanings: dowry (mehr), salary, wages, remuneration, reward, gift, compensation, and reward in the Hereafter (5 verses: 4:24, 4:25, 5:5, 33:50, 60:10)",
      "d": "«اَجْر» has the plural «اُجُوْر». «اَجْر» means remuneration or the agreed-upon compensation between «اٰجِر» (the one who hires) and «اَجِیْر» (the hired one). Since in marriage, a woman accepts the compensation for her chastity as 'mehr', which is settled by mutual consent. Therefore, the word «اَجْر» is used metaphorically in the Quran for the right of dowry.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اٰتُوۡہُنَّ اُجُوۡرَہُنَّ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ» (4/25)\nTranslation: And give them their dowry as an obligation."
    },
    {
      "id": 1349,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Right of Mahr",
      "hw": "حق مہر",
      "s": "«فَرِیْضَۃ» means to prescribe, determine, or make obligatory (2 verses: 2:236-2:237).",
      "d": "«فَرْضَ» means to prescribe, determine, or make obligatory. And «فَرِیْضَۃ» means a prescribed or determined portion (manjid). The word 'fardh' is also used metaphorically for the right of mahr because determining the amount of mahr at the time of marriage by mutual consent is necessary.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ اِنۡ طَلَّقۡتُمُوۡہُنَّ مِنۡ قَبۡلِ اَنۡ تَمَسُّوۡہُنَّ وَ قَدۡ فَرَضۡتُمۡ لَہُنَّ فَرِیۡضَۃً فَنِصۡفُ مَا فَرَضۡتُمۡ» (2/237)\nTranslation: And if you divorce them before you have touched them, but you have already prescribed for them a portion, then [pay] half of what you prescribed."
    }
  ],
  "288": [
    {
      "id": 1351,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To Command",
      "hw": "حکم",
      "s": "«اَذِنَ» refers to a command that is necessitated by divine will; otherwise, it means to grant permission or approval (46 verses: 2:97-2:102-2:213-2:221-2:249-2:251-2:255-3:49-3:145-3:152-3:166-4:25-4:64-5:16-5:110-7:58-8:66-9:43-10:3-10:59-10:100-11:105-12:80-13:38-14:1-14:11-14:23-14:25-20:109-22:39-22:65-24:36-24:62-33:46-34:12-34:23-35:32-40:78-42:21-42:51-53:26-58:10-59:5-64:11-78:38-97:4).",
      "d": "«اَذِنَ» means to grant permission or approval. And when it means 'to command,' it refers to a command that is necessitated by divine will (muf).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«فِیۡ  بُیُوۡتٍ اَذِنَ اللّٰہُ  اَنۡ تُرۡفَعَ وَ یُذۡکَرَ فِیۡہَا اسۡمُہٗ» (24/36)\nTranslation: [They are] houses which Allah has permitted to be raised and in which His name is remembered."
    },
    {
      "id": 1353,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To Command",
      "hw": "حکم",
      "s": "«اَوْصٰی» when attributed to Allah, means an emphatic command (18 verses: 2:132-2:180-2:182-2:240-4:11-4:12-4:131-5:106-6:144-6:151-6:152-6:153-19:31-29:8-31:14-36:50-42:13-46:15).",
      "d": "«اَوْصٰی» means to take a covenant regarding something, to command, and to bequeath (manjid). And when attributed to Allah, it means an emphatic command.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ اَوۡصٰنِیۡ بِالصَّلٰوۃِ  وَ الزَّکٰوۃِ مَا دُمۡتُ  حَیًّا» (19/31)\nTranslation: And [He has enjoined upon me] prayer and zakah as long as I am alive.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«یُوۡصِیۡکُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡۤ  اَوۡلَادِکُمۡ ٭ لِلذَّکَرِ مِثۡلُ حَظِّ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ» (4/11)\nTranslation: Allah instructs you concerning your children: for the male, the equivalent of the share of two females."
    }
  ],
  "289": [
    {
      "id": 1354,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To Attack",
      "hw": "حملہ",
      "s": "«سَطَا» means to attack forcefully and to try to overpower (1 verse: 22:72).",
      "d": "«سَطْوَۃٌ  بِہٖ وَعَلَیْہِ» means to overpower someone by attacking them. And «سَطَا الْفَرَس» means for a horse to run while taking long strides (manjid). And «سَطَا» means to seize forcefully or to attack (muf).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«یَکَادُوۡنَ یَسۡطُوۡنَ بِالَّذِیۡنَ یَتۡلُوۡنَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ اٰیٰتِنَا» (22/72)\nTranslation: It is as if they were about to attack those who recite Our verses to them."
    }
  ],
  "290": [
    {
      "id": 1356,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To Be Perplexed",
      "hw": "حیران",
      "s": "«حَیْرَان» means bewildered, perplexed, astonished, dumbfounded; it is used in all these meanings (1 verse: 6:71).",
      "d": "«حَیْرَان» is a general term. It means to remain in doubt due to not finding the path of righteousness (the path of goodness), regardless of the situation.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«کَالَّذِی اسۡتَہۡوَتۡہُ الشَّیٰطِیۡنُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ حَیۡرَانَ ۪ لَہٗۤ  اَصۡحٰبٌ یَّدۡعُوۡنَہٗۤ  اِلَی الۡہُدَی ائۡتِنَا» (6/71)\nTranslation: Like one whom the devils have led astray in the land, [while] he is perplexed, having friends who call him to guidance, [saying], 'Come to us.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1357,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To Be Stunned",
      "hw": "حیران",
      "s": "«بَھِتَ» means to lose one's senses suddenly due to astonishment (2 verses: 2:258-21:40).",
      "d": "«بَھِتَ» means to become suddenly speechless and silent due to astonishment, to lose consciousness (m.q., manjid). To remain bewildered and stunned. To be dumbfounded. The word «مَبْھُوت» is derived from this.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«فَبُہِتَ الَّذِیۡ کَفَرَ» (2/258)\nTranslation: And the disbeliever was stunned.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«بَلۡ تَاۡتِیۡہِمۡ بَغۡتَۃً  فَتَبۡہَتُہُمۡ» (21/40)\nTranslation: But it will come to them suddenly and will stupefy them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1358,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To Be Amazed",
      "hw": "حیران",
      "s": "«عَجِبَ» means to be amazed at something whose cause is unknown (14 verses: 7:63-7:69-9:55-9:85-10:2-11:73-13:5-18:9-18:63-37:12-38:4-50:2-53:59-72:1).",
      "d": "«اَلْعَجْب» refers to amazement whose cause is unknown (muf). And «عَجِبَ» means to be amazed, to wonder.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«بَلۡ عَجِبُوۡۤا اَنۡ جَآءَہُمۡ مُّنۡذِرٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ» (50/2)\nTranslation: But they wonder that a warner has come to them from among themselves."
    }
  ],
  "291": [
    {
      "id": 1359,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Menstruation",
      "hw": "حیض",
      "s": "«مَحِیْضٌ» is used in the meaning of menstruation (2 verses: 2:222-65:4).",
      "d": "«مَحِیْضٌ» is used in the meaning of menstruation. 'Haidh' is a well-known word. And «مَحِیْضٌ» can mean menstruation itself, the time of menstruation, or the place of menstruation (muf). And «حَاضَتِ الْمِرْأَۃ» means the woman had her menstruation.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الۡمَحِیۡضِ» (2/222)\nTranslation: And they ask you about menstruation."
    },
    {
      "id": 1360,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Menstrual Period / Purity",
      "hw": "حیض",
      "s": "«قُرُوْء» is used in the meaning of a woman becoming pure from menstruation (1 verse: 2:228).",
      "d": "«قُرُوْء» is the plural of «قَرْءُ». It means a woman's «طھر» (purity), i.e., entering the state of menstruation. Therefore, this word is lexically applied to both «طھر» (purity) and menstruation, and it is among the words with contradictory meanings (al-dhaad). (Al-dhaad refers to words that have two separate, opposite meanings.)\nHowever, according to the Hadith of the Prophet ﷺ, «اُقْعُدِیْ عَنِ الصَّلٰوۃِ اَیَّامِ اَقْرَائِک» (Abstain from prayer during the days of your menstruation), its translation has been determined as referring to menstruation.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ الۡمُطَلَّقٰتُ یَتَرَبَّصۡنَ بِاَنۡفُسِہِنَّ ثَلٰثَۃَ قُرُوۡٓءٍ» (2/228)\nTranslation: And divorced women shall wait [before marrying another] for three menstrual periods."
    }
  ],
  "292": [
    {
      "id": 1361,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "husband",
      "hw": "خاوند",
      "s": "«بَعْل» refers to a husband who has consummated the marriage (4 verses: 2:228-4:128-11:72-24:31)",
      "d": "«بَعْل» means husband. The plural is «بَعُول», and wife is called «بَعْل» and «بَعْلَۃ». «بَاعَلَ» means to establish marriage or kinship between tribes (Munjid). This also indicates that when spouses belong to different tribes, this term is used. And Allah knows best. According to the author of Furūq al-Lughawiyyah, a person cannot be called «بَعْل» until consummation occurs. And this is argued from the Prophetic hadith: «یوم اکل و شرب و یعال» (Fath al-Bari 236). For example, in the Quran: «قَالَتۡ یٰوَیۡلَتٰۤیءَ اَلِدُ وَ اَنَا عَجُوۡزٌ وَّ ہٰذَا بَعۡلِیۡ شَیۡخًا» (11/72). Translation: She said, 'Woe is me! How can I bear a child while I am old, and this husband of mine is an old man?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1362,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Spouse",
      "hw": "خاوند",
      "s": "«زَوْج» is general for both those with intellect and those without. It is also used for both husband and wife (72 verses: 2:25-2:35-2:102-2:230-2:232-2:234-2:240-3:15-4:1-4:12-4:20-4:57-6:139-6:143-7:19-7:189-9:24-11:40-13:3-13:23-13:38-15:88-16:72-20:53-20:117-20:131-21:90-22:5-23:6-23:27-24:6-25:74-26:7-26:166-30:21-31:10-33:4-33:6-33:28-33:37-33:50-33:52-33:53-33:59-35:11-36:36-36:56-37:22-38:58-39:6-40:8-42:11-42:50-43:12-43:70-44:54-50:7-51:49-52:20-53:45-55:52-56:7-58:1-60:11-64:14-66:1-66:3-66:5-70:30-75:39-78:8-81:7).",
      "d": "«زَوْج» its plural is azwaaj. It means a pair. Both husband and wife are each other's «زَوْج». Then each of them is the «زَوْج» of the other. For the husband, the wife is his «زَوْج», and for the wife, the husband is her «زَوْج».\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«قَدۡ سَمِعَ  اللّٰہُ  قَوۡلَ  الَّتِیۡ تُجَادِلُکَ فِیۡ زَوۡجِہَا» (58/1)\nTranslation: Allah has heard the statement of the woman who disputes with you concerning her husband."
    }
  ],
  "293": [
    {
      "id": 1364,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Khabar",
      "hw": "خبر",
      "s": "Khabar is that news which relates to the essence of the listener and can affect them. (2 verses: 27:7-28:29)",
      "d": "Khabar: its plural is Akhbar. It is a well-known word. An event of which a person has no knowledge, and he is informed of it through someone else, that is news. Knowledge of the circumstances and events.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«قَالَ لِاَہۡلِہِ امۡکُثُوۡۤا اِنِّیۡۤ اٰنَسۡتُ نَارًا لَّعَلِّیۡۤ اٰتِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا بِخَبَرٍ» (28/29)\nTranslation: Moses pbuh said to his family, 'Wait here. I have seen a fire. Perhaps I can bring you some news from there.'\nAt another place, the command of Allah is:\n«قُلۡ لَّا تَعۡتَذِرُوۡا لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لَکُمۡ قَدۡ نَبَّاَنَا اللّٰہُ مِنۡ اَخۡبَارِکُمۡ» (9/94)\nTranslation: Say, 'Do not make excuses; we will not believe you. Allah has already informed us of your circumstances.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1365,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "news",
      "hw": "خبر",
      "s": "«خُبْر» news, information, notice, used in all meanings (2 verses: 18:68-18:91)",
      "d": "«خُبْر» means knowledge of the reality of an event, experience, insight. It is said «صَدَّقَ الْخَبْرَ الْخُبْرَ» meaning experience and observation have confirmed the heard news (Munjid). For example, in the Quran: «وَ کَیۡفَ تَصۡبِرُ عَلٰی مَا لَمۡ تُحِطۡ بِہٖ خُبۡرًا» (18/68). Translation: And how can you have patience for that which you do not encompass in knowledge?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1366,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "news",
      "hw": "خبر",
      "s": "«نَبَاَ» to give news about an important and major matter (76 verses: 2:31-2:33-3:15-3:44-3:49-5:14-5:27-5:48-5:60-5:105-6:5-6:34-6:60-6:67-6:105-6:108-6:143-6:159-6:164-7:101-7:175-9:64-9:70-9:94-9:105-10:18-10:23-10:53-10:71-11:49-11:100-11:120-12:15-12:36-12:37-12:45-12:102-13:33-14:9-15:49-15:51-18:13-18:78-18:103-20:99-22:72-24:64-26:6-26:69-26:221-27:22-28:3-28:66-29:8-31:15-31:23-33:20-34:7-35:14-38:21-38:67-38:88-39:7-41:50-49:6-53:36-54:4-54:28-58:6-58:7-62:8-64:5-64:7-66:3-75:13-78:2)",
      "d": "«نَبَاَ» means to give news about an important matter, especially news that the listener is also related to. And whether this news relates to past events or future circumstances. For example, in the Quran: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِنۡ جَآءَکُمۡ فَاسِقٌۢ بِنَبَاٍ فَتَبَیَّنُوۡۤا» (49/6). Translation: O you who have believed, if there comes to you a disobedient one with news, investigate it."
    }
  ],
  "294": [
    {
      "id": 1367,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "to end",
      "hw": "ختم",
      "s": "«نَفَدَ» means for something to end completely and not remain, to perish. In it, the original thing perishes or slips from the hand, whereas in «خَتَمَ» the thing remains restored, but no deficiency or excess can occur in it (4 verses: 16:96-18:109-31:27-38:54)",
      "d": "«نَفَدَ» means for something to end completely and not remain. To perish (M. L.). And its opposite is «بَقِیَ». For example, in the Quran: «مَا عِنۡدَکُمۡ یَنۡفَدُ وَ مَا عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ بَاقٍ» (16/96). Translation: Whatever you have will perish, and whatever Allah has is lasting."
    },
    {
      "id": 1368,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Khatam",
      "hw": "ختم",
      "s": "Khatam: meaning seal, stamp (6 verses: 2:7-6:46-33:40-36:65-42:24-45:23)",
      "d": "Khatam: to seal something after it is complete, stamping it so that no addition or subtraction can occur (etc.) It means ultimately and end of work, i.e., to be finished with a task, and Khatam al-Kitab means to have read the entire book (Manjad).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«مَا کَانَ مُحَمَّدٌ اَبَاۤ اَحَدٍ مِّنۡ رِّجَالِکُمۡ وَ لٰکِنۡ رَّسُوۡلَ اللّٰہِ وَ خَاتَمَ النَّبِیّٖنَ» (33/40)\nTranslation: Muhammad pbuh is not the father of any of your men, but he is the Messenger of Allah and the seal of the prophets (i.e., the one who ended them)."
    }
  ],
  "295": [
    {
      "id": 1369,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "servant",
      "hw": "خدمتگار",
      "s": "«غُلَام» young domestic servant (13 verses: 3:40-12:19-15:53-18:74-18:80-18:82-19:7-19:8-19:19-19:20-37:101-51:28-52:24)",
      "d": "«غُلَام» refers to a boy or young man who has reached puberty and whose sexual desires are awakened. «اِغْتَلَمَ الْفَحْلُ غُلْمَۃً» means for a male animal to become eager for mating. And «غَلِیْم» means a young man. And «اَغْلَام» means to fondle. The plural of «غُلَام» is «غِلْمَۃٌ» and «غِلْمَانٌ» comes. From another perspective, «غُلَام» and «غِلْمَان» refer to boys kept in wealthy households for minor chores. In this context, either they are given nominal compensation or their compensation is training and education. In this case, the term «غُلَام» can also apply to a completely underage boy. For example, in the Quran: «قَالَ یٰبُشۡرٰی ہٰذَا غُلٰمٌ ؕ وَ اَسَرُّوۡہُ بِضَاعَۃً» (12/19). Translation: They said, 'This is a good boy!' and they concealed him as a treasure. At another place: «وَ یَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ غِلۡمَانٌ لَّہُمۡ کَاَنَّہُمۡ لُؤۡلُؤٌ مَّکۡنُوۡنٌ» (52/24). Translation: And there will circulate among them boys [servants] as if they were hidden pearls."
    },
    {
      "id": 1370,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "servant",
      "hw": "خدمتگار",
      "s": "«فَتٰی» young servant and workers (4 verses: 12:30-18:60-18:62-21:60)",
      "d": "«فَتٰی» and «تَفَتّٰی» mean to become young. The period from youth in terms of age to reaching full maturity. Its plural is «فَتَیَان». And its feminine is «فَتَاۃ» and its plural is also «فَتَیَان». In terms of service, «فَتٰی» is used very widely. «فَتٰی» and «فتاۃ» are also used for slave boys and girls. For servants and workers, and for one's own servant companions. And «فِتْیَۃٌ» means a group of young people. For example, in the Quran: «فَلَمَّا جَاوَزَا قَالَ لِفَتٰىہُ اٰتِنَا غَدَآءَنَا» (18/62). Translation: When they had passed beyond it, he said to his young companion, 'Bring us our morning meal.' And this companion was Joshua son of Nun, who was also a special disciple of Moses and a servant. At another place: «وَ قَالَ لِفِتۡیٖانِہِ اجۡعَلُوۡا بِضَاعَتَہُمۡ فِیۡ رِحَالِہِمۡ» (12/62). Translation: And Joseph said to his servants, 'Place their merchandise in their saddlebags.' And at a third place: «وَ لَا تُکۡرِہُوۡا فَتَیٰتِکُمۡ عَلَی الۡبِغَآءِ» (24/33). Translation: And do not compel your slave girls to prostitution."
    },
    {
      "id": 1371,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "servant",
      "hw": "خدمتگار",
      "s": "«سُخْرِیًّا» means forced, compelled, for service (24 verses: 2:164-7:54-13:2-14:32-14:33-16:12-16:14-16:79-21:79-22:36-22:37-22:65-29:61-31:20-31:29-35:13-38:18-38:36-39:5-43:13-43:32-45:12-45:13-69:7)",
      "d": "«سَخِرَ، یَسْخَرُ» means to mock. And «سَخَرَ، یَسْخُرُ» and «سَخَّرَ» mean to force someone into subservience. For example, in the Quran: «سَخَّرَ لَکُمۡ مَّا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ مَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (31/20). Translation: And He has subjected for you whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth. And «سُخْرِیَّا» also means taking work from someone without wages or salary (M. Q.) and also service with compensation. But in it, the aspect of compulsion (force) is prominent. That is, to be forced by necessities to serve or work. For example, in the Quran: «وَ رَفَعۡنَا بَعۡضَہُمۡ فَوۡقَ بَعۡضٍ دَرَجٰتٍ لِّیَتَّخِذَ بَعۡضُہُمۡ بَعۡضًا سُخۡرِیًّا» (43/32). Translation: And We have raised some of them above others in degrees so that some of them may take others as servants."
    }
  ],
  "296": [
    {
      "id": 1373,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Corruption",
      "hw": "خرابی",
      "s": "«مَعَرَّۃٌ» is corruption that occurs as a result of an inappropriate act (1 verse: 48:25)",
      "d": "«مَعَرَّۃٌ» is used for all kinds of loss and damage. «عَیَّرَ» means to be scabbed or infected. And «مَعَرَّۃ» is applied to all kinds of pain, suffering, corruption, hardship, and affliction (Majid, Muf) and according to Ibn al-Faris, «مَعَرَّۃ» refers to pain and suffering that befall a person as a result of a sin or inappropriate act (M, L). For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَوۡ لَا رِجَالٌ مُّؤۡمِنُوۡنَ وَ نِسَآءٌ  مُّؤۡمِنٰتٌ لَّمۡ تَعۡلَمُوۡہُمۡ  اَنۡ  تَطَئُوۡہُمۡ فَتُصِیۡبَکُمۡ مِّنۡہُمۡ مَّعَرَّۃٌۢ  بِغَیۡرِ عِلۡمٍ» (48/25) Translation: And if there were not believing men and believing women whom you did not know, lest you trample them and thus cause you, unknowingly, corruption from them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1374,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Corruption",
      "hw": "خرابی",
      "s": "«فَسَاد» is corruption arising from imbalance within the limits of moderation, the spoilage of society (47 verses: 2:11-2:12-2:27-2:30-2:60-2:205-2:220-2:251-3:63-5:32-5:33-5:64-7:56-7:74-7:85-7:86-7:103-7:127-7:142-8:73-10:40-10:81-10:91-11:85-11:116-12:73-13:25-16:88-17:4-18:94-21:22-23:71-26:152-26:183-27:14-27:34-27:48-28:4-28:77-28:83-29:30-29:36-30:41-38:28-40:26-47:22-89:12)",
      "d": "«فَسَاد» its opposite is correction. Fasad is such corruption that appears when something exceeds or falls short of its limit of moderation and disrupts its balance (Muf). For example, in the Quran: «ظَہَرَ الۡفَسَادُ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ بِمَا کَسَبَتۡ اَیۡدِی  النَّاسِ» (30/41) Translation: Corruption has appeared on land and sea because of what the hands of people have earned."
    }
  ],
  "297": [
    {
      "id": 1377,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Corrupt / To Be Corrupted",
      "hw": "خراب",
      "s": "«عَاب» means to corrupt something inherently (1 verse: 18:79)",
      "d": "«عیب» means a flaw or defect in the form or interior of something (Muf). And «عَابَ» means to make something flawed or corrupt it. It applies to living or non-living things, and in all forms of speech and action (Fiqh al-Lughah 39). For example, in the Quran: «اَمَّا السَّفِیۡنَۃُ  فَکَانَتۡ لِمَسٰکِیۡنَ یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ فَاَرَدۡتُّ اَنۡ اَعِیۡبَہَا» (18/79) Translation: As for the ship, it belonged to poor people working at sea, and I intended to make it flawed."
    },
    {
      "id": 1378,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Corrupt / To Be Corrupted",
      "hw": "خراب",
      "s": "«اَسَنَ» is used for water becoming corrupted and foul-smelling (1 verse: 47:15)",
      "d": "«اَسَنَ الْمَاءُ» means water changing and becoming foul. And «اَسِنَ الرَّجُل» means to become unconscious or dizzy from entering a well with rotten water (Majid, Muf). Thus, «اَسَنَ» is used for water becoming corrupted, altered, and foul-smelling. For example, in the Quran: «فِیۡہَاۤ اَنۡہٰرٌ  مِّنۡ  مَّآءٍ غَیۡرِ اٰسِنٍ» (47/15) Translation: In it are rivers of water that does not become foul."
    },
    {
      "id": 1379,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Corrupt / To Be Corrupted",
      "hw": "خراب",
      "s": "«سَنَّ» is used for things that become corrupted after a long period (3 verses: 15:26-15:28-15:33)",
      "d": "«سِنّ» means both teeth and age. And «سُنَّۃ» means way, custom. And «سَنَّ سُنَّۃ» means he established or made a way customary (Majid, Muf). Thus, «سَنَّ» conveys the concept of duration and continuity. And «مَسْنُوْن» is used for something that becomes corrupted and foul after a period of time. However, this word is generally used for mud and similar things. For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ مِّنۡ حَمَاٍ مَّسۡنُوۡنٍ» (15/26) Translation: And We created man from an extract of clay, from altered black mud."
    },
    {
      "id": 1380,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Corrupt / To Be Corrupted",
      "hw": "خراب",
      "s": "«سَنِہَ» is used for food and drink items becoming bad (1 verse: 2:259)",
      "d": "«سَنِہَ» means very old. «سَنِہَ الطَّعَام وَالشَّرَاب» means food or drink changing, spoiling. And «تَسَنَّہَ الْخُبْزُ» means bread rotting, becoming foul (Majid). For example, in the Quran: «فَانۡظُرۡ اِلٰی طَعَامِکَ وَ شَرَابِکَ لَمۡ یَتَسَنَّہۡ» (2/259) Translation: Then look at your food and your drink; they have not become bad."
    }
  ],
  "298": [
    {
      "id": 1381,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Spend",
      "hw": "خرچ",
      "s": "«اَنْفَقَ» is the general term for spending. «بَخِلَ» means not to spend even on necessary needs or to spend less. «اِقْتَرَ» means to be stingy in spending on one's family. «اَسْرَفَ» means to spend beyond necessity. «بَذَّر» means to spend wastefully and without need (57 verses: 2:3-2:195-2:215-2:219-2:254-2:261-2:262-2:264-2:265-2:267-2:270-2:272-2:273-2:274-3:17-3:92-3:117-3:134-4:34-4:38-4:39-5:64-8:3-8:36-8:60-8:63-9:34-9:53-9:54-9:91-9:92-9:98-9:99-9:121-13:22-14:31-16:75-17:100-18:42-22:35-25:67-28:54-32:16-34:39-35:29-36:47-42:38-47:38-57:7-57:10-60:10-60:11-63:7-63:10-64:16-65:6-65:7)",
      "d": "«اَنْفَقَ» is the general term for spending. Generally, it means to spend wealth. However, it conveys the idea that wealth comes in from one side and goes out in spending from the other. «نَفَقَ» refers to a tunnel with both ends open. And «نیفق السّراویل» means the seam of pajamas. And «نَافَقَ الْیَرْبُوْعُ وَ نَفَقَ» means a wild mouse entered from one end of its burrow and exited from the other. And in Shariah terminology, hypocrisy refers to the manner where a person enters Islam through one path and exits through another (Muf). For example, in the Quran: «وَ اَنۡفِقُوۡا مِنۡ مَّا  رَزَقۡنٰکُمۡ مِّنۡ  قَبۡلِ اَنۡ یَّاۡتِیَ  اَحَدَکُمُ  الۡمَوۡتُ» (63/10) Translation: And spend from what We have provided you before death approaches any of you. See also «بُخْل» and «اَقْتَرَ» under 'stinginess', and «اَسْرَفَ» and «بَذَّرَ» under 'extravagance'."
    },
    {
      "id": 1382,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Spend",
      "hw": "خرچ",
      "s": "«اَھْلَکَ» means to spend a large amount of wealth in evil purposes (63 verses: 2:195-2:205-3:117-4:176-5:17-6:6-6:26-6:47-6:131-7:4-7:129-7:155-7:164-7:173-8:42-8:54-9:42-10:13-11:117-12:85-14:13-15:4-17:16-17:17-17:58-18:59-19:74-19:98-20:128-20:134-21:6-21:9-21:95-22:45-23:48-26:139-26:208-27:49-28:43-28:58-28:59-28:78-28:88-29:31-32:26-36:31-38:3-40:34-43:8-44:37-45:24-46:27-46:35-47:13-50:36-53:50-54:51-67:28-69:5-69:6-69:29-77:16-90:6)",
      "d": "The original meaning of «اَھْلَکَ» is to destroy, ruin, or waste something. And when attributed to wealth, it means to spend all of it. And it is generally used for spending wealth in bad places. For example, in the Quran: «یَقُوۡلُ  اَہۡلَکۡتُ مَالًا  لُّبَدًا» (90/6) Translation: Man says, 'I have wasted a great amount of wealth.'"
    }
  ],
  "299": [
    {
      "id": 1384,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Buying and Selling",
      "hw": "خرید و فروخت",
      "s": "Shira: buying and selling when the intention is to fulfill personal need. However, \"Ishtara\" is specific to the meaning of buying. (22 verses: 2:16-2:41-2:79-2:86-2:90-2:102-2:174-2:175-3:77-3:177-3:187-3:199-4:44-4:74-5:44-5:106-9:9-9:111-12:20-12:21-16:95-31:6)",
      "d": "Like Bay (sale), Shira is also from the category of opposite words (Azdad) and is used in both meanings: buying and selling. However, the word Ishtara is specific to buying. And Mushtari means buyer.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ اشۡتَرٰی مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ وَ اَمۡوَالَہُمۡ بِاَنَّ لَہُمُ الۡجَنَّۃَ» (9/111)\nTranslation: Allah has purchased from the believers their lives and their wealth in exchange for Paradise.\nNote: (Azdad are words that have two separate meanings that are opposite and contradictory to each other.)"
    }
  ],
  "300": [
    {
      "id": 1386,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Treasure",
      "hw": "خزانہ",
      "s": "«قِنْطَار» a large quantity of wealth (3 verses: 3:14-3:75-4:20)",
      "d": "«قِنْطَار» is a heavy amount of gold, silver, or cash, and its plural is «قَنَاطِیْر». According to the expert in language, this amount is four thousand dinars or more, or twelve thousand uqiyyah. For example, in the Quran: «وَ مِنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ مَنۡ  اِنۡ تَاۡمَنۡہُ بِقِنۡطَارٍ یُّؤَدِّہٖۤ  اِلَیۡکَ» (3/75) Translation: And among the People of the Book is he who, if you entrust him with a treasure (qintar), will return it to you."
    },
    {
      "id": 1387,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Treasure",
      "hw": "خزانہ",
      "s": "«کَنْز» hidden accumulated wealth (5 verses: 9:34-9:35-11:12-18:82-25:8)",
      "d": "«کَنْز» its plural is «کُنُوز». It refers to accumulated wealth that is hidden from people, whether in the form of a buried treasure or through other means. According to Ibn al-Faris, it is any wealth that is sealed or stored. And «کَنَزَ المال» means to accumulate wealth, to store it. (M. Q)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ اَمَّا الۡجِدَارُ فَکَانَ لِغُلٰمَیۡنِ یَتِیۡمَیۡنِ فِی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  وَ کَانَ تَحۡتَہٗ کَنۡزٌ لَّہُمَا» ( 18/82 )\nTranslation: And as for the wall, it belonged to two orphaned boys in the city, and beneath it was a treasure belonging to them."
    }
  ],
  "301": [
    {
      "id": 1389,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Dry Up",
      "hw": "خشک",
      "s": "«یَبَسَ» the word is general for dryness (1 verse: 20:77)",
      "d": "«یَبَسَ» its opposite is «رَطَبَ». This word is general. It means the cessation of water or moisture from something or a place. The drying up of something.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَسۡرِ بِعِبَادِیۡ فَاضۡرِبۡ لَہُمۡ طَرِیۡقًا فِی الۡبَحۡرِ یَبَسًا» ( 20/77 )\nTranslation: O Moses! Take My servants by night, then strike for them a dry path through the sea."
    },
    {
      "id": 1390,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Dry Up",
      "hw": "خشک",
      "s": "«ھَاجَ» for plants (things that grow from the earth) to naturally become dry and yellow after maturing (2 verses: 39:21-57:20)",
      "d": "«ھَاجَ» means for plants to become yellow and dry due to natural demands or lack of water. The complete maturation of plants and then their decline when they ripen, turn yellow, and become ready for harvesting (figurative). And «ھَاجَ النَّبَتُ» means grass dries up. And «ھَاجَتُ الْاَرْض» means the earth's grass begins to dry. (M. L)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«ثُمَّ یُخۡرِجُ بِہٖ زَرۡعًا مُّخۡتَلِفًا  اَلۡوَانُہٗ  ثُمَّ یَہِیۡجُ  فَتَرٰىہُ مُصۡفَرًّا ثُمَّ یَجۡعَلُہٗ  حُطَامًا» ( 39/21 )\nTranslation: Then He brings forth from it vegetation in diverse colors. Then it dries up, and you see it turning yellow, then He makes it chaff."
    },
    {
      "id": 1391,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Dry Up",
      "hw": "خشک",
      "s": "«ھَمَدَ» for plants to dry up and wither when the cause is lack of water or the land becoming barren (1 verse: 22:5)",
      "d": "«ھَمَدَ» means for the land to become dry and barren due to lack of water, or for plants to dry up and wither (figurative). «نَبَاتٌ ھَامِدَۃٌ» means withered grass. And «اَرْضٌ ھَامِدَۃٌ» means dry and barren land. (Munjid)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ تَرَی الۡاَرۡضَ ہَامِدَۃً  فَاِذَاۤ  اَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہَا الۡمَآءَ   اہۡتَزَّتۡ وَ  رَبَتۡ وَ  اَنۡۢبَتَتۡ مِنۡ  کُلِّ  زَوۡجٍۭ  بَہِیۡجٍ» ( 22/5 )\nTranslation: Then you see the earth lifeless. But when We send down water upon it, it stirs and swells and brings forth every kind of beautiful growth."
    },
    {
      "id": 1393,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Diminish, To Recede",
      "hw": "خشک",
      "s": "«غَاضَ» to dry up and diminish, to shrink, for water to subside (2 verses: 11:44-13:8)",
      "d": "«غَاضَ» means to decrease something and for it to decrease on its own (figurative). To shrink something or for it to shrink. It can come in both transitive and intransitive forms (figurative).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَللّٰہُ یَعۡلَمُ مَا تَحۡمِلُ کُلُّ اُنۡثٰی وَ مَا تَغِیۡضُ الۡاَرۡحَامُ وَ  مَا تَزۡدَادُ» ( 13/8 )\nTranslation: Allah knows what every female carries and what the wombs diminish [of their pregnancies] and what they increase.\nAnd when «غَاضَ» is related to water, it means the water dries up. And for the earth to absorb and cause the surface water to subside (Munjid).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ قِیۡلَ یٰۤاَرۡضُ ابۡلَعِیۡ مَآءَکِ وَ یٰسَمَآءُ اَقۡلِعِیۡ وَ غِیۡضَ الۡمَآءُ» ( 11/44 )\nTranslation: And it was said, 'O earth, swallow your water, and O sky, cease [raining].' And the water subsided."
    }
  ],
  "302": [
    {
      "id": 1394,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To Attain Salvation; To Grant Salvation; Deliverance; Release",
      "hw": "رہائی",
      "s": "«نَجَات» the word is general. It is used for attaining release from a predicament, sudden calamity, punishment, affliction, etc. (52 verses: 2:49-2:50-6:63-6:64-7:64-7:72-7:83-7:89-7:141-7:165-10:22-10:23-10:73-10:92-10:103-11:58-11:66-11:94-11:116-12:45-12:110-14:6-17:67-19:72-20:40-20:80-21:9-21:71-21:74-21:76-21:88-23:28-26:65-26:119-26:170-27:53-27:57-29:15-29:24-29:32-29:65-31:32-37:76-37:115-37:134-39:61-40:41-41:18-44:30-54:34-61:10-70:14)",
      "d": "«نَجَات» means to escape from a sudden calamity, a difficult matter, an affliction, or a punishment. And «اَنْجٰی» means to grant release to someone else. This word is general.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ اِذۡ  اَنۡجَیۡنٰکُمۡ مِّنۡ اٰلِ فِرۡعَوۡنَ» ( 7/141 )\nTranslation: When We saved you from the people of Pharaoh.\nAnd «نَجَات» means salvation, release, and deliverance. (Munjid)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ یٰقَوۡمِ مَا لِیۡۤ  اَدۡعُوۡکُمۡ  اِلَی النَّجٰوۃِ وَ تَدۡعُوۡنَنِیۡۤ   اِلَی  النَّارِ» ( 40/41 )\nTranslation: And O my people, what is [the matter] with me? I invite you to salvation while you invite me to the Fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 1396,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To Attain Salvation; To Grant Salvation; Deliverance; Release",
      "hw": "رہائی",
      "s": "«اَنْقَذَ» this word is more specific than salvation. It comes for granting release from danger or destruction or punishment.\nAlso see 'To Attain Salvation' (5 verses: 3:103-22:73-36:23-36:43-39:19)",
      "d": "«اَنْقَذَ» means to save someone from danger or destruction. To rescue and save (figurative).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَفَاَنۡتَ تُنۡقِذُ مَنۡ فِی النَّارِ» ( 39/19 )\nTranslation: Then can you save whoever is in the Fire?"
    }
  ],
  "303": [
    {
      "id": 1397,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Creation; The Created",
      "hw": "مخلوق",
      "s": "«بَرِیَّۃ» means to bring something from non-existence into existence. Therefore, everything that exists is included in «بَرِیَّۃ» (2 verses: 98:6-98:7)",
      "d": "It is derived from «بَرَء». It means to bring something from non-existence into existence. Therefore, everything that exists is included in «بَرِیَّۃ». The entire creation. All of the universe, the earth and the heavens, other planets are also included in it.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِنَّ  الَّذِیۡنَ  اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ ۙ اُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمۡ خَیۡرُ الۡبَرِیَّۃِ» ( 98/7 )\nTranslation: Indeed, those who believe and do righteous deeds - they are the best of creation."
    },
    {
      "id": 1398,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Creation; The Created",
      "hw": "مخلوق",
      "s": "«اَنَام» is used for every type of creature on earth (1 verse: 55:10)",
      "d": "«اَنَام» the word is used for every type of creature on earth. Whether animate or inanimate.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ الۡاَرۡضَ وَضَعَہَا لِلۡاَنَامِ» ( 55/10 )\nTranslation: And He laid the earth for the creatures.\nAnd «اَلْوَرٰی» means the creation that exists on earth at one time. It does not include past and future generations (figurative). However, this word is not used in the Noble Quran. And its plural is «وَرَایَا»."
    }
  ],
  "304": [
    {
      "id": 1400,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Dream",
      "hw": "خواب",
      "s": "«مَنَام» the word is general for sleep (4 verses: 8:43-30:23-37:102-39:42)",
      "d": "«مَنَام» means the state of sleep. And what a human sees in sleep is also «مَنَام», whether it has some reality or not.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِذۡ یُرِیۡکَہُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡ مَنَامِکَ قَلِیۡلًا» ( 8/43 )\nTranslation: When Allah showed them to you in your dream as few."
    },
    {
      "id": 1402,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Dream",
      "hw": "خواب",
      "s": "Ahlam: disjointed, nonsensical, and frightening dreams (2 verses: 12:44-21:5)",
      "d": "Ahlam: plural of Hulm. Halama means to become young and mature. And Hulm means a dream of youth. Nonsensical and frightening dreams (etc.).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَضۡغَاثُ اَحۡلَامٍ ۚ وَ مَا نَحۡنُ بِتَاۡوِیۡلِ الۡاَحۡلَامِ بِعٰلِمِیۡنَ» (12/44)\nTranslation: They said, 'These are confused dreams, and we are not skilled in interpreting dreams.'"
    }
  ],
  "305": [
    {
      "id": 1404,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Desire",
      "hw": "خواہش",
      "s": "Hawa: evil desires or natural desires used in an evil way (7 verses: 2:87-4:135-5:70-38:26-53:3-53:23-79:40)",
      "d": "Hawa: its plural is Ahwa, meaning desires of the self and inclination towards them. Hawa yahwi means to fall from above. And Al-Mahwah means a pit. And Ahwa are those desires by pursuing which a person loses his worth and status (Manjad). This word is generally used in a negative sense. In the words of Ibn Faris, 'Hawa an-nafs khalun min kulli khair' meaning desires of the self are those in which there is no good.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ اَمَّا مَنۡ خَافَ مَقَامَ رَبِّہٖ وَ نَہَی النَّفۡسَ عَنِ الۡہَوٰی فَاِنَّ الۡجَنَّۃَ ہِیَ الۡمَاۡوٰی» (79/40)\nTranslation: And whoever feared the standing before his Lord and restrained his soul from evil desires, then indeed, Paradise is the refuge."
    }
  ],
  "306": [],
  "307": [
    {
      "id": 1410,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Food. Bringing Food",
      "hw": "خوراک",
      "s": "Qut: that amount of food by which a living being can survive (1 verse: 41:10)",
      "d": "Qut: meaning food, sustenance. That amount of food by which a living being can survive. Its plural is Aqwat. And Qata means to provide food. And Aqat means to give something from which strength is obtained. They say 'Ma lahu quwtu laylatin' meaning he has no food even for a night (etc.).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ جَعَلَ فِیۡہَا رَوَاسِیَ مِنۡ فَوۡقِہَا وَ بٰرَکَ فِیۡہَا وَ قَدَّرَ فِیۡہَاۤ اَقۡوَاتَہَا فِیۡۤ اَرۡبَعَۃِ اَیَّامٍ» (41/10)\nTranslation: And He placed therein mountains from above it, and blessed it, and decreed its sustenance in four days."
    },
    {
      "id": 1411,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Food. Bringing Food",
      "hw": "خوراک",
      "s": "Mara: to bring food for family and dependents, and Mayr: grain or edible provisions that are stored. (1 verse: 12:65)",
      "d": "Mayr: meaning food, sustenance. And Miyarah means collected food. Its plural is Mayr. And Mara and Amara ayalahu means to bring food for one's family. And Mayir and Mayyar means the one who brings food (Manjad). Thus, Mayr refers to those provisions that are stored.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ نَمِیۡرُ اَہۡلَنَا وَ نَحۡفَظُ اَخَانَا وَ نَزۡدَادُ کَیۡلَ بَعِیۡرٍ» (12/65)\nTranslation: And we will bring provisions for our family and protect our brother and increase the load of a camel."
    },
    {
      "id": 1412,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Food. Bringing food",
      "hw": "خوراک",
      "s": "'Māra' meaning to bring food for one's family and 'Mīr' stored grain or edible provisions (1 verse: 12:65)",
      "d": "'Mīr' meaning food. Sustenance. And 'Mīrah' meaning collected food. Its plural is 'Mīr' and 'Māra' and 'Amāra 'ayāluhu' meaning to bring food for one's family. And 'Mā'ir' and 'Miyyār' meaning the one who brings food (Manjad). So 'Mīr' refers to edible provisions that are stored. For example: In the Quran: 'وَ نَمِیۡرُ اَہۡلَنَا وَ نَحۡفَظُ اَخَانَا وَ نَزۡدَادُ کَیۡلَ  بَعِیۡرٍ' (12/65) Translation: And (this time) we will bring provisions for our family and protect our brother and increase the load of a camel."
    }
  ],
  "308": [
    {
      "id": 1413,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy. To do and to feel",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "'Raḍiya' is used merely for expressing preference (26 verses: 2:144-4:24-5:3-5:119-9:38-9:58-9:59-9:83-9:87-9:93-9:96-9:100-10:7-19:6-19:55-20:109-27:19-33:51-46:15-48:18-58:22-69:21-88:9-89:28-98:8-101:7)",
      "d": "'Raḍiya' is a well-known word. Meaning to be pleased. To express preference. And its opposite is 'Sakhaṭa' meaning to be displeased or angry (muf. m l). For example: In the Quran: 'لَقَدۡ رَضِیَ اللّٰہُ  عَنِ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ  اِذۡ یُبَایِعُوۡنَکَ تَحۡتَ الشَّجَرَۃِ' (48/18) Translation: Indeed, Allah was pleased with the believers when they gave you their pledge under the tree."
    },
    {
      "id": 1416,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy. To do and to feel",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "'Habara' happiness from the cleanliness, beauty, and springiness of the surroundings (2 verses: 30:15-43:70)",
      "d": "'Habara' meaning to make happy and joyful. And 'Habira' meaning to be happy. And 'Habira al-ard' meaning the land produces abundant crops. To be very green. And 'Tahabbara' meaning to be adorned. To be excellent (Manjad). So 'Habara' refers to happiness that comes from the cleanliness, beauty, and springiness of the surroundings. For example: In the Quran: 'فَاَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ فَہُمۡ فِیۡ رَوۡضَۃٍ یُّحۡبَرُوۡنَ' (30/15) Translation: Then those who believed and did righteous deeds, they will be in a garden, joyful."
    },
    {
      "id": 1417,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy. To do and to feel.",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "«اِسْتَبْشَرَ» means to have one's face light up upon receiving good news or a good thing (8 verses: 3:170-3:171-9:111-9:124-15:67-30:48-39:45-80:39).",
      "d": "«بَشَر» means to peel skin, and «بَشْرَۃ» means the surface of the skin. «اِسْتَبْشِر» denotes joy whose effects become visible on the skin or face. Having one's face light up. When one becomes happy upon hearing good news or receiving a good thing, the word «اِسْتَبْشَرَ» is used. And «بَشَّرَ» means to give good news that makes another happy. To announce glad tidings.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاسۡتَبۡشِرُوۡا بِبَیۡعِکُمُ الَّذِیۡ بَایَعۡتُمۡ بِہٖ» (9/111)\nTranslation: Rejoice in the bargain which you have concluded.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«وَ بَشَّرُوۡہُ بِغُلٰمٍ عَلِیۡمٍ» (51/28)\nTranslation: And (the angels) gave him glad tidings of a knowledgeable boy."
    },
    {
      "id": 1418,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy. To do and to feel.",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "«طَاب» is a joy that also engages the senses (1 verse: 4:3).",
      "d": "«طَاب» is a joy that engages not only the heart but also the senses of a person. (مف) «طَیِّبٰت» means pure things, and «طِیْب» means fragrance. (منجد)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَانۡکِحُوۡا مَا طَابَ لَکُمۡ مِّنَ النِّسَآءِ» (4/3)\nTranslation: Marry those women who please you."
    },
    {
      "id": 1419,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy. To do and to feel.",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "«فَرِحَ» means to become happy and start boasting. To celebrate joy. (21 verses: 3:120-3:170-3:188-6:44-9:50-9:81-10:22-10:58-11:10-13:26-13:36-23:53-27:36-28:76-30:4-30:32-30:36-40:75-40:83-42:48-57:23)",
      "d": "«فَرِحَ» means to become happy upon receiving a blessing. And it has two types: «فَرِحَ الْقَلْب» when a person becomes happy upon receiving a blessing and thanks Allah, which is a praiseworthy trait.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَرِحِیۡنَ بِمَاۤ اٰتٰہُمُ اللّٰہُ مِنۡ فَضۡلِہٖ» (3/170)\nTranslation: They are happy with what Allah has bestowed upon them of His favor.\n«فَرِحَ النَّفْس» when a person, instead of thanking Allah for a blessing, starts boasting. Meaning to celebrate joy. And this is a blameworthy trait.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لِّکَیۡلَا تَاۡسَوۡا عَلٰی مَا فَاتَکُمۡ وَلَا تَفۡرَحُوۡا بِمَاۤ اٰتٰىکُمۡ» (57/23)\nTranslation: So that you may not grieve over what you have missed nor exult over what He has given you.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«لَا تَفۡرَحۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یُحِبُّ الۡفَرِحِیۡنَ» (28/76)\nTranslation: Do not exult. Indeed, Allah does not like the exultant."
    },
    {
      "id": 1420,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy, to do, and to seem",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "«فَکِہَ» to engage in cheerful banter and to have a happy disposition (1 verse: 83:31)",
      "d": "«فَکِہَ» to engage in merry talk, to have a cheerful disposition, and to laugh and make others laugh (Fal 145). «طَیِّبَ النَّفْس» or happy disposition (M. L). For example: In the Noble Quran: «وَاِذَا انۡقَلَبُوۡۤا اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہِمُ انۡقَلَبُوۡا فَکِہِیۡنَ» (83/31). Translation: And when they return to their homes, they return cheerful."
    },
    {
      "id": 1421,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy. To do and to feel.",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "«اَشْمَتَ» means to be happy at an enemy's misfortune (1 verse: 7:150).",
      "d": "«شَمِتَ» means to be happy at a calamity. And «اَشْمَتَ» means for others to be happy at one's own misfortune. «شَمَاتَتَ اَعْداء» is a famous phrase meaning to be happy at an enemy's trouble.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَا تُشۡمِتۡ بِیَ الۡاَعۡدَآءَ» (7/150)\nTranslation: (Haroon (AS) said: O Musa (AS)) Do not give the enemies an occasion to rejoice over me."
    },
    {
      "id": 1422,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy, to do, and to seem",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "«اَعْجَبَ» to feel a delightful wonder in the heart, where the cause is unknown, a blend of joy and amazement (8 verses: 2:204-2:221-5:100-9:25-33:52-48:29-57:20-63:4)",
      "d": "«اَعْجَبَ» means something is pleasing to the heart. To seem good. With wonder such that the cause is unknown (intensive). For example: In the Noble Quran: «وَ مِنَ النَّاسِ مَنۡ یُّعۡجِبُکَ قَوۡلُہٗ فِی الۡحَیٰوۃِ الدُّنۡیَا» (2/204). Translation: And among people is he whose speech may delight you in worldly life."
    }
  ],
  "309": [
    {
      "id": 1425,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Prosperity",
      "hw": "خوشحالی",
      "s": "«طُوْبٰی» that prosperity with which the heart is also content (43 verses: 2:57-2:168-2:172-2:267-3:38-3:179-4:2-4:43-4:160-5:4-5:5-5:6-5:87-5:88-5:100-7:32-7:58-7:157-7:160-8:26-8:37-8:69-9:72-10:22-10:93-13:29-14:24-16:32-16:72-16:97-16:114-17:70-20:81-22:24-23:51-24:26-24:61-34:15-35:10-40:64-45:16-46:20-61:12)",
      "d": "«طَابَ» means to attain such happiness that besides the heart, the senses also become delighted (intensive). And «طَیِّب» means pure, and «طِیْب» means fragrance (lexicon). And «طُوبٰی» means such prosperity in which the heart is content and joyful. For example: In the Noble Quran: «اَلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ طُوۡبٰی لَہُمۡ  وَحُسۡنُ مَاٰبٍ» (13/29). Translation: For those who believe and do righteous deeds, there is prosperity and a good return."
    }
  ],
  "310": [
    {
      "id": 1426,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Bunches (of fruit)",
      "hw": "خوشے",
      "s": "«طَلَعَ» is used for the emergence of a fruit bunch from its sheath. And «قِطْف» is the state of being ripe and ready to be picked. And «قِنْو» is the intermediate state. But «قِنْو» is used only for date and grape bunches. (4 verses: 6:99-26:148-37:65-50:10)",
      "d": "«طَلَعَ» lexically means to emerge and to appear (M. L). For stars, rising and setting are famous terms. And «طَلَعَ» is also used for that new bunch when it begins to emerge from its sheath or date bud (lexicon). For example: In the Noble Quran: «وَ النَّخۡلَ بٰسِقٰتٍ  لَّہَا طَلۡعٌ  نَّضِیۡدٌ» (50/10). Translation: And the towering date palms, having layered bunches."
    },
    {
      "id": 1427,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Bunches (of fruit)",
      "hw": "خوشے",
      "s": "«قُطُوْف» is such ripe fruit that is completely ready to be picked (2 verses: 69:23-76:14)",
      "d": "«قُطُوْف» is plural of «قِطْف». And «قِطْف» is such ripe fruit that is completely ready to be picked, and the Quran supports this meaning. According to lexicon, it means 'picked fruit. A grape bunch when picked.' For example: In the Noble Quran: «فَہُوَفِیۡ عِیۡشَۃٍ رَّاضِیَۃٍ فِیۡ جَنَّۃٍ عَالِیَۃٍ قُطُوۡفُہَا دَانِیَۃٌ» (69/21،22،23). Translation: He will be in a pleasing life, in a lofty garden, whose bunches are within reach. This makes it clear that the fruit on the trees is as if ripe and ready to be picked, yet still on the trees, and for this Allah has used the word «قُطُوْف»."
    },
    {
      "id": 1428,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Bunches (of fruit)",
      "hw": "خوشے",
      "s": "«قِنْوَان» such grape and date bunches that are not yet ready to be picked (1 verse: 6:99)",
      "d": "«قِنْوَان» is plural of «قِنْو». And this word is specific to such date and grape bunches that are not yet ready to be picked. For example: In the Noble Quran: «وَمِنَ النَّخۡلِ مِنۡ طَلۡعِہَا قِنۡوَانٌ دَانِیَۃٌ» (6/99). Translation: And from the date palms, from their fruit bunches, hanging clusters."
    }
  ],
  "311": [
    {
      "id": 1429,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Betrayal",
      "hw": "خیانت",
      "s": "«خَانَ» means breach of covenant and consuming entrusted property by trickery, whereas «غَلّ» involves theft in betrayal. (8 verses: 4:105-5:13-8:27-8:58-8:71-12:52-40:19-66:10)",
      "d": "«خَانَ» means to betray, and its opposite is amanah (trust). And this betrayal occurs in covenant as well as in entrusted property. For example, taking all or part of property by trickery and usurpation. Similarly, it applies to breaking a covenant and not fulfilling it. Deceit (intensive). For example: In the Noble Quran: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَخُوۡنُوا اللّٰہَ وَالرَّسُوۡلَ وَتَخُوۡنُوۡۤا اَمٰنٰتِکُمۡ» (8/27). Translation: O you who believe! Do not betray Allah and the Messenger, nor betray your trusts."
    },
    {
      "id": 1430,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Betrayal",
      "hw": "خیانت",
      "s": "«غَلَّ» means to betray (1 verse: 3:161)",
      "d": "«غَلَّ» means to take something secretly into one's possession and then conceal it so that it is not apparent (lexicon, M. R). And ghalool means to betray, to conceal, and to be stingy – all meanings apply (lexicon). Thus, «غَلَّ» includes theft besides betrayal, or the means of betrayal is theft. For example: In the Noble Quran: «وَمَا کَانَ لِنَبِیٍّ اَنۡ یَّغُلَّ ؕ وَمَنۡ یَّغۡلُلۡ یَاۡتِ بِمَا غَلَّ  یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (3/161). Translation: And it is not for a prophet to betray. And whoever betrays will bring what he betrayed on the Day of Resurrection."
    }
  ],
  "312": [
    {
      "id": 1431,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tent. Canopy.",
      "hw": "خیمہ",
      "s": "«خِیَامٌ» means tent (1 verse: 55:72).",
      "d": "«خِیَامٌ» (plural of خیمہ) خیمہ is a well-known word. It refers to canopies made of thick cloth or canvas for protection from sun and rain, which usually do not have flat roofs but are sloped. According to the author of Minjd, any covered house not made of bricks, stones, or mud. And «خیم» also refers to a camel's howdah or litter. (Minjd) The Quran states:\n«حُوۡرٌ مَّقۡصُوۡرٰتٌ فِی الۡخِیَامِ» (55/72)\nTranslation: Who are confined in the tents."
    },
    {
      "id": 1432,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tent. Canopy.",
      "hw": "خیمہ",
      "s": "«ظُلَّۃٌ» meaning shade (2 verses: 7:171-26:189)",
      "d": "«ظُلَّۃٌ» is such a canopy that has only a roof and no walls. «ظُلَّۃ» is also used for an umbrella, and «ظلیل» for a shady tree (manjad), and «ظِلّ» meaning shade; its plural is «ظِلَال» and «ظِلًّا ظَلِیْلًا» means long and dense shade.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَاِذۡ نَتَقۡنَا الۡجَبَلَ فَوۡقَہُمۡ کَاَنَّہٗ ظُلَّۃٌ» (7/171)\nTranslation: And when We raised the mountain over them as if it were a canopy."
    },
    {
      "id": 1433,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tent. Canopy.",
      "hw": "خیمہ",
      "s": "«سُرَادِق» meaning tent, shamiana, pavilion (1 verse: 18:29)",
      "d": "«سُرَادِق» is the plural of «سَرْدَقَ» and refers to a shamiana that has only walls. Such canopies are used in weddings. This word is of Persian origin (i.e., a word adopted into Arabic with slight modification).\nFor example, in the Quran: «اِنَّاۤ اَعۡتَدۡنَا لِلظّٰلِمِیۡنَ نَارًا ۙ اَحَاطَ بِہِمۡ سُرَادِقُہَا» (18/29)\nTranslation: We have prepared for the wrongdoers a fire, surrounding them are its canopies."
    }
  ],
  "313": [
    {
      "id": 1435,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To enter. To make enter.",
      "hw": "داخل",
      "s": "«وَلَجَ» to enter a tight space (8 verses: 3:27-7:40-22:61-31:29-34:2-35:13-57:4-57:6)",
      "d": "«اَلْوَلْوَج» means to enter a tight space (intransitive), with difficulty, to squeeze in.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَلَا یَدۡخُلُوۡنَ الۡجَنَّۃَ حَتّٰی یَلِجَ الۡجَمَلُ فِیۡ سَمِّ الۡخِیَاطِ» (7/40)\nTranslation: And they will not enter Paradise until the camel enters through the eye of the needle.\nFor entering or squeezing into a tight space, «اَوْلَج» is used (transitive).\nFor example: «یُوۡلِجُ الَّیۡلَ  فِی النَّہَارِ  وَ یُوۡلِجُ النَّہَارَ فِی الَّیۡلِ» (22/61)\nTranslation: Allah causes the night to enter the day and causes the day to enter the night."
    },
    {
      "id": 1436,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To enter. To make enter.",
      "hw": "داخل",
      "s": "«صَلَی» meaning to enter fire (15 verses: 4:10-4:90-11:81-14:29-28:35-36:64-38:56-52:16-58:8-69:31-82:15-84:12-87:12-88:4-111:3)",
      "d": "«صَلَی» is specifically used for entering fire. Meaning to enter fire and burn (intransitive).\nFor example: «جَہَنَّمَ ۚ یَصۡلَوۡنَہَا ؕ وَبِئۡسَ الۡقَرَارُ» (14/29)\nTranslation: They will enter Hell, and evil is the resting place.\nFor causing to enter fire or burn, «صَلّٰی» is used (transitive).\nFor example: «خُذُوۡہُ فَغُلُّوۡہُ ثُمَّ الۡجَحِیۡمَ صَلُّوۡہُ» (69/30,31)\nTranslation: Seize him and chain him, then cast him into Hell."
    },
    {
      "id": 1437,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To enter. To make enter.",
      "hw": "داخل",
      "s": "«سَلَکَ» to pull one thing into another or to enter (12 verses: 15:12-16:69-20:53-23:27-26:200-28:32-39:21-69:32-71:20-72:17-72:27-74:42)",
      "d": "«سَلَکَ» is used in many meanings and both transitive and intransitive forms, and in all, the meaning of entering is found.\nExamples:\n(1) To thread or pierce, like threading a needle.\nFor example: «کَذٰلِکَ سَلَکۡنٰہُ  فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِ الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ» (26/200)\nTranslation: Thus have We inserted disbelief into the hearts of the criminals. (Jalandhari) / Ghasaa diya (Osmani).\n(2) To put in, to enter. Like putting a hand in a pocket.\nFor example: «اُسۡلُکۡ یَدَکَ فِیۡ جَیۡبِکَ تَخۡرُجۡ بَیۡضَآءَ مِنۡ غَیۡرِسُوۡٓءٍ» (28/32)\nTranslation: Put your hand into your bosom, it will come out white without any disease.\nNote that the same verse elsewhere uses «اَدْخِلْ» instead of «اُسْلُک».\nFor example: «وَاَدۡخِلۡ یَدَکَ فِیۡ جَیۡبِکَ تَخۡرُجۡ بَیۡضَآءَ مِنۡ غَیۡرِ سُوۡٓءٍ» (27/12)\nTranslation: And put your hand into your bosom, it will come out white without any disease.\n(3) To go along a path.\nFor example, Allah says to the bee: «فَاسۡلُکِیۡ سُبُلَ رَبِّکِ ذُلُلًا» (16/69)\nTranslation: Then follow the ways of your Lord submissively.\nIn this verse, «اُسْلُکِیْ» is also translated as «اُدْخُلِیْ» (m. q.).\nAlso: «مَا سَلَکَکُمۡ  فِیۡ سَقَرَ» (74/42)\nTranslation: What has caused you to enter Hell?\nConsidering all these, the author of 'Muntahi al-Arb' states the briefest meaning of «سَلَکَ» as 'pulling one thing into another', i.e., to draw one thing into another or to draw one thing out of another. According to 'Manjad', it means to place one thing into another. And according to 'Maqayis al-Lughah', its basic meanings are two: (1) to go along a path, (2) to enter one thing into another, to thread."
    }
  ],
  "314": [
    {
      "id": 1438,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Guardian.",
      "hw": "داروغہ",
      "s": "«خَزَنَ» means guardian, keeper (5 verses: 15:22-39:71-39:73-40:49-67:8).",
      "d": "«خَزَنَ» often comes in the context of gathering wealth, such as خَزَنْتُ الدَّرَاھِمَ (I gathered the coins), but its basic meaning is more about guarding than collecting. One says خَزَنْتُ السِّرَّ (I kept the secret safe). And the person who guards such gathered things or wealth is called «خَازِن», and its plural is خَزَنَةُ.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ اُلۡقِیَ فِیۡہَا فَوۡجٌ سَاَلَہُمۡ خَزَنَتُہَاۤ اَلَمۡ یَاۡتِکُمۡ نَذِیۡرٌ» (67/8)\nTranslation: Whenever a group is thrown into it (Hell), its keepers will ask them, 'Did no warner come to you?'\nThe difference between «خَازِن» and «مُصَیْطِر» is the same as between حفیظ (guardian) and رقیب (supervisor). The responsibility of «خَازِن» is merely to guard the gathered items, while «مُصَیْطِر» also has strict oversight because he has authority over them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1439,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Guardian.",
      "hw": "داروغہ",
      "s": "«مُصَیْطِر» means supervisor, keeper, guardian (2 verses: 52:37-88:22).",
      "d": "«مُصَیْطِر» linguists write this word with س instead of ص. And in the Quran, it is written with ص but with a small س above. Then some linguists derive it from the root «سطر», and some from «سَیْطر». «سَیْطَرَ عَلٰی» means to prevail over someone and become their supervisor. And «سیطر» means an overseer (to whom a task is entrusted) and supervisor.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَذَکِّرۡ ؕ اِنَّمَاۤ اَنۡتَ مُذَکِّرٌ لَسۡتَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِمُصَۜیۡطِرٍ» (88/21,22)\nTranslation: So remind. You are only a reminder; you are not a guardian over them.\nMeaning, you have no authority over them to compel them to accept your message."
    }
  ],
  "315": [
    {
      "id": 1440,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To brand. To mark.",
      "hw": "داغ ",
      "s": "«وَسَم» meaning to inscribe on the body, to dig etc. (8 verses: 2:273-7:46-7:48-15:75-47:30-48:29-55:41-68:16)",
      "d": "«وَسَم» means to mark, to brand (intransitive). And meaning to inscribe on the body, to dig etc. (transitive). And «وَسَّم» means to dye, and «وَسَام» and «وَسَمَہ» is the thing with which one brands or colors.\nFor example: «سَنَسِمُہٗ عَلَی الۡخُرۡطُوۡمِ» (68/16)\nTranslation: So We will brand him on the snout (or nose)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1442,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To brand. To mark.",
      "hw": "داغ ",
      "s": "«شِیَۃ» such a brand or mark that is different from the body's color (1 verse: 2:71)",
      "d": "«وَشِیَ» «وَشَیْتُ الشَّیْءُ وَشْیًا» means to put a different color on something against its general color. And «وَشْیۃ» and «شِیَۃ» mean a brand or mark of a color different from the body's color (intransitive).\nFor example: «مُسَلَّمَۃٌ لَّا شِیَۃَ فِیۡہَا» (2/71)\nTranslation: (The cow) should be without any blemish, no spot on it."
    }
  ],
  "316": [
    {
      "id": 1444,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Emaciated. Thin.",
      "hw": "دبلا",
      "s": "«ضَامِر» is that which becomes thin and lean due to exercise and hardship (1 verse: 22:27)",
      "d": "«ضَمَر ، اَلْاَضْمَار» means the field of horse racing, the training ground for horses, the end of the racing field, and the period of training horses. And «ضَامِر» is an animal that becomes thin and lean due to exercise and hardship, not due to lack of food. It signifies swiftness to win in a race. In Arabic, «ضِامِر» became specific to camels, whether male or female.\nFor example: «وَ اَذِّنۡ فِی النَّاسِ بِالۡحَجِّ  یَاۡتُوۡکَ  رِجَالًا وَّ عَلٰی کُلِّ ضَامِرٍ یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیۡقٍ» (22/27)\nTranslation: And proclaim to the people the Hajj; they will come to you on foot and on every lean camel, coming from every distant path."
    }
  ],
  "317": [
    {
      "id": 1447,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To be distant / To make distant",
      "hw": "دراز",
      "s": "«بَاعَدَ» to increase the distance between two things and make it long (1 Verse: 34:19)",
      "d": "«بَعُدَ» means to be far. And «بَاعَدَ» means to increase the distance between two things.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَقَالُوۡا رَبَّنَا بٰعِدۡ بَیۡنَ اَسۡفَارِنَا» (34/19)\nTranslation: So they said: O our Lord! Create distance between our journeys."
    }
  ],
  "318": [
    {
      "id": 1448,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To be behind / To follow",
      "hw": "درپے",
      "s": "«تَصَدّٰی» to be behind something temporarily and incidentally (1 Verse: 80:6)",
      "d": "«تَصَدّٰی» means to be behind something like an echo. To pay attention (transitive). (An echo is the sound that returns after striking a mountain or dome, etc.)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اَمَّا مَنِ اسۡتَغۡنٰی فَاَنۡتَ لَہٗ تَصَدّٰی» (80/5,6)\nTranslation: As for him who is indifferent, you are behind him (paying attention to him)."
    }
  ],
  "319": [
    {
      "id": 1451,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Trees and Plants",
      "hw": "درخت",
      "s": "«نَجْم» plants without trunks, shrubs, creeping plants (13 Verses: 6:97-7:54-16:12-16:16-22:18-37:88-52:49-53:1-55:6-56:75-77:8-81:2-86:3)",
      "d": "«نَجْم» means both star and plants without trunks. That is, shrubs, creeping plants, etc. (transitive)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَّ النَّجۡمُ وَ الشَّجَرُ یَسۡجُدٰنِ» (55/6)\nTranslation: And the plants (or stars) and the trees are prostrating (to Allah)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1452,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Trees and Plants",
      "hw": "درخت",
      "s": "«اَثْل» plants with strong roots and thorny trees (1 Verse: 34:16)",
      "d": "«اَثَلَ» means to take root in the earth. And «اَثْل» is every tree whose roots are strong. Generally, it is applied to thorny trees (transitive. See Manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ بَدَّلۡنٰہُمۡ بِجَنَّتَیۡہِمۡ جَنَّتَیۡنِ ذَوَاتَیۡ اُکُلٍ خَمۡطٍ وَّ اَثۡلٍ وَّ شَیۡءٍ مِّنۡ سِدۡرٍ قَلِیۡلٍ» (34/16)\nTranslation: And We replaced their two gardens with two other gardens bearing bitter fruit, and some thorny shrubs, and a few lote trees."
    },
    {
      "id": 1453,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Trees and Plants",
      "hw": "درخت",
      "s": "«یَقْطِیْن» the plant that has no trunk, like the vine of a cucumber, pumpkin, gourd, etc. (1 Verse: 37:146)",
      "d": "«یَقْطِیْن» means every tree that has no trunk. (transitive) It is generally applied to vine plants and specifically to the pumpkin vine.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ اَنۡۢبَتۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ شَجَرَۃً مِّنۡ یَّقۡطِیۡنٍ» (37/146)\nTranslation: And We caused a gourd tree to grow over him."
    },
    {
      "id": 1454,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Trees and Plants",
      "hw": "درخت",
      "s": "«ضَرِیْع» thorny shrubs (1 Verse: 88:6)",
      "d": "«ضَرِیْع» means a thorny shrub or a bush with thorns (transitive)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«لَیۡسَ لَہُمۡ طَعَامٌ اِلَّا مِنۡ ضَرِیۡعٍ» (88/6)\nTranslation: They will have no food except from thorny shrubs."
    },
    {
      "id": 1455,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Trees and Plants",
      "hw": "درخت",
      "s": "«زَقُّوْم» the Zaqqum tree, whose leaves are broad, thick, thorny, and extremely bitter in taste (3 Verses: 37:62-44:43-56:52)",
      "d": "«زَقُّوْم» means the Zaqqum tree whose leaves are broad, thick, and thorny. And it is extremely bitter in taste.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اِنَّ شَجَرَتَ الزَّقُّوۡمِ طَعَامُ الۡاَثِیۡمِ» (44/43,44)\nTranslation: Indeed, the tree of Zaqqum is the food of the sinful."
    }
  ],
  "320": [
    {
      "id": 1456,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Correct / Right",
      "hw": "درست",
      "s": "«صَوَاب» correctness is related to a person's statement or opinion, while truth is everything that is proven correct through experience and observation (1 Verse: 78:38)",
      "d": "«صَوَاب» means correct, right, proper. (See Manjad) Its opposite is «خَطَا». And «صَابَ واَصَابَ السَّھْم» means an arrow hits the exact target. And «اِسْتِصْوَاب» means to find a opinion or action correct. To think rightly. And «صَوَیْب» and «مُصِیْب» mean one with correct opinion. A righteous worker (See Manjad). And if an arrow hits the exact target and stays there, it is called «مُصِیْبَۃٌ», which is applied to every painful accident (transitive). «صَوَاب» generally relates to speech and opinion, and sometimes to action as well.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«لَّا یَتَکَلَّمُوۡنَ اِلَّا مَنۡ اَذِنَ لَہُ الرَّحۡمٰنُ وَ قَالَ صَوَابًا» (78/38)\nTranslation: They will not speak except for him whom the Most Merciful permits, and he will say what is correct."
    },
    {
      "id": 1457,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Correct / Right",
      "hw": "درست",
      "s": "«حَقّ» is used for truth, veracity (252 Verses: 2:26-2:42-2:61-2:71-2:91-2:109-2:119-2:121-2:144-2:146-2:147-2:149-2:176-2:180-2:213-2:236-2:241-2:252-2:282-3:3-3:21-3:60-3:62-3:71-3:86-3:102-3:108-3:112-3:154-3:181-4:105-4:122-4:151-4:155-4:170-4:171-5:27-5:48-5:77-5:83-5:84-5:107-5:116-6:5-6:30-6:57-6:62-6:66-6:73-6:91-6:93-6:114-6:141-6:151-7:8-7:30-7:33-7:43-7:44-7:53-7:89-7:105-7:118-7:146-7:159-7:169-7:181-8:4-8:5-8:6-8:7-8:8-8:32-8:74-9:29-9:33-9:48-9:111-10:4-10:5-10:23-10:30-10:32-10:33-10:35-10:36-10:53-10:55-10:76-10:77-10:82-10:94-10:96-10:103-10:108-11:17-11:45-11:79-11:120-12:51-12:100-13:1-13:14-13:17-13:19-14:19-14:22-15:8-15:55-15:64-15:85-16:3-16:36-16:38-16:102-17:16-17:26-17:33-17:81-17:105-18:13-18:21-18:29-18:44-18:56-18:98-19:34-20:114-21:18-21:24-21:55-21:97-21:112-22:6-22:18-22:40-22:54-22:62-22:74-22:78-23:41-23:62-23:70-23:71-23:90-23:116-24:25-24:49-25:26-25:33-25:68-27:79-28:3-28:13-28:39-28:48-28:53-28:63-28:75-29:44-29:68-30:8-30:38-30:47-30:60-31:9-31:30-31:33-32:3-32:13-33:4-33:53-34:6-34:23-34:26-34:43-34:48-34:49-35:5-35:24-35:31-36:7-36:70-37:31-37:37-38:14-38:22-38:26-38:64-38:84-39:2-39:5-39:19-39:41-39:67-39:69-39:71-39:75-40:5-40:6-40:20-40:25-40:55-40:75-40:77-40:78-41:15-41:25-41:53-42:17-42:18-42:24-42:42-43:29-43:30-43:78-43:86-44:39-45:6-45:22-45:29-45:32-46:3-46:7-46:17-46:18-46:20-46:30-46:34-47:2-47:3-48:27-48:28-50:5-50:14-50:19-50:42-51:19-51:23-53:28-56:95-57:16-57:27-60:1-61:9-64:3-69:51-70:24-78:39-84:2-84:5-103:3)",
      "d": "«حَقّ» means truth, veracity, reality. That is, everything that is proven correct through experience and observation. (transitive) Its opposite is «باطل» (falsehood).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«سَنُرِیۡہِمۡ اٰیٰتِنَا فِی الۡاٰفَاقِ وَ فِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ حَتّٰی یَتَبَیَّنَ لَہُمۡ اَنَّہُ الۡحَقُّ» (41/53)\nTranslation: We will show them Our signs in the horizons and within themselves until it becomes clear to them that it (the revelation or Quran) is the truth."
    },
    {
      "id": 1458,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To correct",
      "hw": "درست",
      "s": "«اَصْلَحَ» is used to correct moral and material corruption, while «سَوّٰی» is used to correct creative flaws (40 Verses: 2:11-2:160-2:182-2:220-2:224-2:228-3:89-4:16-4:35-4:114-4:128-4:129-4:146-5:39-6:48-6:54-7:35-7:56-7:85-11:88-17:142-7:170-8:1-10:81-11:117-13:23-16:119-21:90-24:5-26:152-27:48-28:19-33:71-40:8-42:40-46:15-47:2-47:5-49:9-49:10)",
      "d": "The opposite of «اِصْلَاح» is «فَسَاد» meaning corruption. And «اَصْلَحَ» means to correct corruption. To remove mischief and corruption. To correct the corruption caused by excess or deficiency (surplus or shortage) in something. (transitive)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اِنۡ اُرِیۡدُ اِلَّا الۡاِصۡلَاحَ مَا اسۡتَطَعۡتُ» (11/88)\nTranslation: (Prophet Shuaib (AS) said to his people) I only intend to correct (reform) what I am able to (in your affairs)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1459,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To Correct / To Make Straight",
      "hw": "درست",
      "s": "«سَوّٰی» means to correct, smooth, equalize, or straighten a task or thing. (13 verses: 4:42-15:29-19:10-19:17-19:43-20:58-20:135-26:98-38:72-67:22-75:4-75:38-87:2)",
      "d": "«سَوٰی یَسْوِی» means for a thing's form and shape to be correct. And «سَوّٰی» means to correct, smooth, equalize, and straighten a task or thing (Munjid). According to Ibn al-Faris, its meaning is «اَلْاِسْتِقَامَۃ وَالْاِعْتِدَال» (uprightness and balance), which conveys exactly the same meaning.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ فَسَوّٰی» (87:2)\nTranslation: Who created and then proportioned (or made straight)."
    }
  ],
  "321": [
    {
      "id": 1460,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Between",
      "hw": "درمیان",
      "s": "«بَیْن» is a preposition that indicates separation or distinction between two distinct things. (181 verses: 2:68-2:102-2:113-2:136-2:164-2:182-2:188-2:213-2:224-2:232-2:237-2:282-2:285-3:19-3:23-3:30-3:55-3:64-3:84-3:103-3:140-4:23-4:29-4:35-4:58-4:65-4:73-4:90-4:92-4:105-4:114-4:128-4:129-4:141-4:143-4:150-4:152-5:14-5:17-5:18-5:25-5:42-5:48-5:49-5:64-5:91-5:106-6:19-6:53-6:58-6:94-7:44-7:46-7:87-7:89-8:1-8:24-8:63-8:72-9:107-10:19-10:28-10:29-10:45-10:47-10:54-10:93-11:43-11:110-12:100-13:43-15:85-16:66-16:92-16:94-16:124-17:45-17:53-17:96-17:110-18:19-18:21-18:32-18:52-18:61-18:78-18:93-18:94-18:95-18:96-19:37-19:64-19:65-20:6-20:58-20:62-20:94-20:103-21:16-21:93-22:17-22:56-22:69-23:53-23:101-24:43-24:48-24:51-24:63-25:38-25:50-25:53-25:59-25:67-26:24-26:28-26:118-27:61-27:78-28:28-29:25-29:52-30:8-30:21-32:4-32:25-34:18-34:19-34:26-34:54-37:5-37:158-38:8-38:10-38:22-38:26-38:27-38:66-39:3-39:46-39:69-39:75-40:48-41:5-41:34-41:45-42:14-42:15-42:21-42:38-43:32-43:38-43:52-43:65-43:85-44:7-44:38-45:17-46:3-46:8-48:29-49:9-49:10-50:38-54:25-54:28-55:20-55:44-56:60-57:13-57:20-59:7-59:14-60:3-60:4-60:7-60:10-65:6-65:12-78:37-86:7)",
      "d": "«بَیْن» is a preposition that indicates separation or distinction between two distinct things. And «بَانَ» means to be distant. Therefore, «بَیْن» comes for indicating distance or separation between two things. According to Ibn al-Faris, three elements are found in «بَیْن»: (1) separation, (2) distance, (3) clarity. (M.L.) That is, a thing being distinct from another and clear.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«بَیۡنَ السَّمَآءِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ» (2:164)\nTranslation: Between the heavens and the earth.\nThen this word is also used in a spiritual sense, just as it is used in a physical sense.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«فَاحۡکُمۡ بَیۡنَنَا بِالۡحَقِّ» (38:22)\nTranslation: Judge between us with truth!"
    },
    {
      "id": 1461,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Between.",
      "hw": "درمیان",
      "s": "«خِلٰل» means between different parts of the same thing or between two related things (8 verses: 9:47-14:31-17:5-17:91-18:33-24:43-27:61-30:48).",
      "d": "«خِلٰل» refers to a space between two things that are connected to each other. «اَلْخِلَال» also means the tool for cleaning the spaces between teeth, and the act of cleaning those spaces. Similarly, during ablution, water is passed between the fingers of the hand or the beard hairs.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ فَجَّرۡنَا خِلٰلَہُمَا نَہَرًا» (18/33)\nTranslation: And We caused a river to flow between them (the two gardens).\nThen this word is also used for the space between separate parts of the same thing.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَتَرَی الۡوَدۡقَ یَخۡرُجُ مِنۡ خِلٰلِہٖ» (24/43)\nTranslation: Then you see the rain droplets coming out from within it (the cloud)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1462,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Between.",
      "hw": "درمیان",
      "s": "«وَسْط» means the middle of something in terms of number, quantity, or distance (2 verses: 2:143-2:238).",
      "d": "«وَسْط» is the middle point of anything where the distance to both sides is equal. Or if there are more than two sides, the number on both sides is equal. Essentially, it's the point of moderation between deficiency and excess. Then this word is used in both material and spiritual contexts.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«حٰفِظُوۡا عَلَی الصَّلَوٰتِ وَ الصَّلَوۃِ الۡوُسۡطٰی» (2/238)\nTranslation: Guard the prayers, especially the middle prayer.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«وَ کَذٰلِکَ جَعَلۡنٰکُمۡ اُمَّۃً وَّسَطًا» (2/143)\nTranslation: And thus We have made you a moderate nation."
    },
    {
      "id": 1464,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Moderation / The Middle Path",
      "hw": "درمیان",
      "s": "«قَصْد» means the path of moderation, the middle way. (3 verses: 9:42-16:9-31:19)",
      "d": "«قَصْد» means moderation. The way or path that lies between excess and deficiency. Neither too much nor too little. For example, generosity between extravagance and stinginess, or courage between bravery and cowardice. And «قَصَدَ» and «اِقْتَصَدَ فِی الْنَفَقَۃ» means to spend in moderation, avoiding excess and deficiency. And «قَصَدَ السَّبِیْل» means to walk straight on the path. Not to deviate here and there. (Mufradat, Munjid)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اقۡصِدۡ فِیۡ مَشۡیِکَ وَ اغۡضُضۡ مِنۡ صَوۡتِکَ» (31:19)\nTranslation: And be moderate in your pace and lower your voice."
    }
  ],
  "322": [
    {
      "id": 1465,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy / Enmity",
      "hw": "دشمن",
      "s": "«عَدُوّ» means enemy. (49 verses: 2:36-2:97-2:98-2:168-2:208-3:103-4:45-4:92-4:101-5:14-5:64-5:82-5:91-6:112-6:142-7:22-7:24-7:129-7:150-8:60-9:83-9:114-9:120-12:5-17:53-18:50-20:39-20:80-20:117-20:123-25:31-26:77-28:8-28:15-28:19-35:6-36:60-41:19-41:28-41:34-43:62-43:67-46:6-60:1-60:2-60:4-61:14-63:4-64:14)",
      "d": "«عَدُوّ» its plural is «اَعْدَاء». Such an enemy who is malevolent, harboring malice. One who thinks of evil and harm and is pleased by causing distress. And its opposite is «صِدِّیْق» (truthful friend) (F.L. 168).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ الشَّیۡطٰنَ لَکُمَا عَدُوٌّ مُّبِیۡنٌ» (7:22)\nTranslation: Indeed, Satan is to you both a clear enemy!\nAnd «عَدَاوَۃٌ» means enmity and malevolence. And this is the first degree of enmity. (F.L. 169) And it also means to withdraw from someone's help. Its opposite is «وَلَایَة» (guardianship, friendship). (Faqih al-Lughah 106)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1466,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy / Enmity",
      "hw": "دشمن",
      "s": "«بَغْضَاء» means to detest or feel aversion towards something or someone. (5 verses: 3:118-5:14-5:64-5:91-60:4)",
      "d": "«بُغْض» means to detest something or someone. This is the second degree of enmity and its opposite is «حُبّ» (love). And «بُغْضَۃٌ» means to intend to degrade and humiliate someone (Faqih al-Lughah 106).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَلۡقَیۡنَا بَیۡنَہُمُ الۡعَدَاوَۃَ وَ الۡبَغۡضَآءَ اِلٰی یَوۡمِ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (5:64)\nTranslation: And We have cast between them enmity and hatred until the Day of Resurrection."
    },
    {
      "id": 1467,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy / Enmity",
      "hw": "دشمن",
      "s": "«شَانِیءَ» means to harbor enmity. (3 verses: 5:2-5:8-108:3)",
      "d": "«شَنَأَ» means to harbor enmity. To bear malice. To hate (Munjid). And its masdar (verbal noun) is «شَنَأٰن».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا یَجۡرِمَنَّکُمۡ شَنَاٰنُ قَوْمٍ عَلٰۤی اَلَّا تَعۡدِلُوۡا» (5:8)\nTranslation: And let not the hatred of a people prevent you from being just.\nAnd «شَانِیء» is a person who is both malevolent (wishing ill) and harboring malice. That is, he holds enmity and also «بَعْض» (some, i.e., the worst kind). Thus, he is the worst enemy, and this is the third degree of enmity. (F.L. 169)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ شَانِئَکَ ہُوَ الۡاَبۡتَرُ» (108:3)\nTranslation: Indeed, your enemy will be the one cut off (without progeny)."
    }
  ],
  "323": [
    {
      "id": 1470,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To Pray / To Give",
      "hw": "دعا",
      "s": "«حَیَّیَ» means to give a prayer for long life. (1 verse: 4:86)",
      "d": "«حَیَّ» means to live. And «حَیَّیَ , تَحِیَّۃً» means to say «حَیَّاکَ اللہ» to someone. That is, 'May Allah grant you long life' (Munjid). Then this word is generally used for any good prayer. And it is also used in the sense of a prayer for safety, or in the meanings of «سَلَّم» or «سَلَام». Thus, «سَلَّم» is specific, while «حَیَّ» is general. (F.L. 44)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا حُیِّیۡتُمۡ بِتَحِیَّۃٍ فَحَیُّوۡا بِاَحۡسَنَ مِنۡہَاۤ اَوۡ رُدُّوۡہَا» (4:86)\nTranslation: And when you are greeted with a greeting, greet in return with a better one or at least return it."
    }
  ],
  "324": [
    {
      "id": 1472,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«قَلْب» means (the heart) the famous organ. The source and center of spirit, life, intellect, understanding, and contemplation. (124 verses: 2:7-2:10-2:74-2:88-2:93-2:97-2:118-2:204-2:225-2:260-2:283-3:7-3:8-3:103-3:126-3:151-3:154-3:156-3:159-3:167-4:63-4:155-5:13-5:41-5:52-5:113-6:25-6:43-6:46-7:100-7:101-7:179-8:2-8:10-8:11-8:12-8:24-8:49-8:63-8:70-9:8-9:15-9:45-9:60-9:64-9:77-9:87-9:93-9:110-9:117-9:125-9:127-10:74-10:88-13:28-15:12-16:22-16:106-16:108-17:46-18:14-18:28-18:57-21:3-22:32-22:35-22:46-22:53-22:54-23:60-23:63-24:37-24:50-26:89-26:194-26:200-28:10-30:59-33:4-33:5-33:10-33:12-33:26-33:32-33:51-33:53-33:60-34:23-37:84-39:22-39:23-39:45-40:18-40:35-41:5-42:24-45:23-47:16-47:20-47:24-47:29-48:4-48:11-48:12-48:18-48:26-49:3-49:7-49:14-50:33-50:37-57:16-57:27-58:22-59:2-59:10-59:14-61:5-63:3-64:11-66:4-74:31-79:8-83:14)",
      "d": "«قَلْب» means (the heart) the famous organ. Its plural is «قُلُوب». It is the source and center of spirit and life. Allah the Exalted has chosen the heart for intellect, understanding, thought, and reflection. That is, what modern physiology has declared related to the brain, the Noble Quran has declared related to the heart.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَہُمۡ قُلُوۡبٌ لَّا یَفۡقَہُوۡنَ بِہَا» (7:179)\nTranslation: They have hearts with which they do not understand."
    },
    {
      "id": 1473,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Proof/Evidence",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«Bayyinah»: A clear and manifest matter, a proof with which the claimant can invalidate the other party's statement (74 verses: 2:87, 2:92, 2:99, 2:159, 2:185, 2:209, 2:211, 2:213, 2:253, 3:86, 3:97, 3:105, 3:183, 3:184, 4:19, 4:153, 5:32, 5:110, 6:57, 6:157, 7:73, 7:85, 7:101, 7:105, 8:42, 9:70, 10:13, 10:15, 10:74, 11:17, 11:28, 11:53, 11:63, 11:88, 14:9, 16:44, 17:101, 19:73, 20:72, 20:133, 22:16, 22:72, 24:1, 24:34, 24:46, 28:36, 29:35, 29:39, 29:49, 30:9, 30:47, 33:30, 34:43, 35:25, 40:22, 40:28, 40:34, 40:50, 40:66, 40:83, 43:63, 45:17, 45:25, 46:7, 47:14, 57:9, 57:25, 58:5, 61:6, 64:6, 65:1, 65:11, 98:1, 98:4)",
      "d": "«Bayyinah» means a clear and manifest matter, a proof. Some explanation of «Bayyinah» is also derived from this saying of the Prophet (peace be upon him): 'Al-Bayyinatu ‘alā al-mudda‘ī wa-al-yamīnu ‘alā al-mudda‘ā ‘alayhi' (Bukhari). Meaning: Providing proof is the responsibility of the claimant, and if he cannot, then the oath is upon the one against whom the claim is made. Now consider, for example, if Zaid claims a sum of money from Bakr and Bakr denies it. If Zaid has in his possession any writing from Bakr that can prove this claim or assist in proving it, that writing is a «Bayyinah». Similarly, if Zaid can prove it by presenting witnesses, that too is a «Bayyinah». «Bayyinah» is such a proof before which the other party is rendered speechless. The very existence of the Quran is a «Bayyinah». Against which, despite confrontation, the disbelievers cannot present any proof. Similarly, its verses are also «Bayyināt». For example, the Quran states: «Bal huwa āyātun bayyinātun fī ṣudūri alladhīna ūtū al-‘ilma. Wa-mā yajḥadu bi-āyātinā illā al-ẓālimūn» (29:49). Translation: Rather, it [i.e., the Quran] is clear verses [preserved] within the breasts of those given knowledge. And none deny Our verses except the wrongdoers. In this verse, the word «Jahd» is used to indicate that they acknowledge in their hearts that these verses are clear proofs, even though they deny them with their tongues."
    },
    {
      "id": 1474,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«ṣadr» means chest (41 verses: 3:29-3:118-3:119-3:154-4:90-5:7-6:125-7:2-7:43-8:43-9:14-10:57-11:5-11:12-15:47-15:97-16:106-17:51-20:25-22:46-26:13-27:74-28:69-29:10-29:49-31:23-35:38-39:7-39:22-40:19-40:56-40:80-42:24-57:6-59:9-59:13-64:4-67:13-94:1-100:10-114:5)",
      "d": "«ṣadr» means chest; its plural is «ṣudūr». The heart is located within the chest.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَٰكِن تَعْمَى الْقُلُوبُ الَّتِي فِي الصُّدُورِ» (22/46)\nTranslation: But the hearts which are within the chests become blind.\nTherefore, sometimes by saying only «fī ṣ-ṣudūr», hearts (qulūb) are intended, as in «شِفَاءٌ لِمَا فِي الصُّدُورِ» (10/57). Since «ṣadr» is related to a place of residence, if the mention of the heart's constriction or expansion is intended, the word «ṣadr» will be used.\nFor example, the Divine declaration is:\n«وَلَقَدْ نَعْلَمُ أَنَّكَ يَضِيقُ صَدْرُكَ بِمَا يَقُولُونَ» (15/97)\nTranslation: And We know that your heart is constricted by what they say.\nIn another instance, the Divine declaration is:\n«أَلَمْ نَشْرَحْ لَكَ صَدْرَكَ» (94/1)\nTranslation: Did We not expand for you your chest?\nAnd «sharḥ ṣadr» or «inširāḥ ṣadr» is an idiom. When a correct path (right opinion) occurs in the heart regarding a difficult and complex matter, it is called «sharḥ ṣadr». Then, since a place of residence is needed to conceal something, the use of «ṣadr» will also occur in mentioning secrets, thoughts, and whispers. For example, the Quran states:\n«يَعْلَمُ خَائِنَةَ الْأَعْيُنِ وَ مَا تُخْفِي الصُّدُورُ» (40/19)\nTranslation: He knows the betrayal of the eyes and what the hearts conceal.\nSimilarly, in another instance, the Divine declaration is:\n«إِنَّ اللَّهَ عَلِيمٌ بِذَاتِ الصُّدُورِ» (5/7)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah is Acquainted with the contents of the hearts.\nIn yet another instance, the Divine declaration is:\n«الَّذِي يُوَسْوِسُ فِي صُدُورِ النَّاسِ» (114/5)\nTranslation: Who [Satan] whispers into the hearts of mankind."
    },
    {
      "id": 1475,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«nafs»: the center of desires. Used for expressing happiness and concealing things (268 verses: 2:9-2:44-2:48-2:54-2:57-2:72-2:84-2:85-2:87-2:90-2:102-2:109-2:110-2:123-2:130-2:155-2:187-2:207-2:223-2:228-2:231-2:233-2:234-2:235-2:240-2:265-2:272-2:281-2:284-2:286-3:25-3:28-3:30-3:61-3:69-3:93-3:117-3:135-3:145-3:154-3:161-3:164-3:165-3:168-3:178-3:185-3:186-4:1-4:4-4:29-4:49-4:63-4:64-4:65-4:66-4:79-4:84-4:95-4:97-4:107-4:110-4:111-4:113-4:128-4:135-5:25-5:30-5:32-5:45-5:52-5:70-5:80-5:105-5:116-6:12-6:20-6:24-6:26-6:54-6:70-6:93-6:98-6:104-6:123-6:130-6:151-6:152-6:158-6:164-7:9-7:23-7:37-7:42-7:53-7:160-7:172-7:177-7:188-7:189-7:192-7:197-7:205-8:53-8:72-9:17-9:20-9:35-9:36-9:41-9:42-9:44-9:55-9:70-9:81-9:85-9:88-9:111-9:118-9:120-9:128-10:15-10:23-10:30-10:44-10:49-10:54-10:100-10:108-11:21-11:31-11:101-11:105-12:18-12:23-12:26-12:30-12:32-12:51-12:53-12:54-12:68-12:77-12:83-13:11-13:16-13:33-13:42-14:22-14:45-14:51-16:7-16:28-16:33-16:72-16:89-16:111-16:118-17:7-17:14-17:15-17:25-17:33-18:6-18:28-18:35-18:51-18:74-20:15-20:40-20:41-20:67-20:96-21:35-21:43-21:47-21:64-21:102-23:62-23:103-24:6-24:12-24:61-25:3-25:21-25:68-26:3-27:14-27:40-27:44-27:92-28:16-28:19-28:33-29:6-29:40-29:57-30:8-30:9-30:21-30:28-30:44-31:12-31:28-31:34-32:13-32:17-32:27-33:6-33:37-33:50-34:19-34:50-35:8-35:18-35:32-36:36-36:54-37:113-39:6-39:15-39:41-39:42-39:53-39:56-39:70-40:10-40:17-41:31-41:46-41:53-42:11-42:45-43:71-45:15-45:22-47:38-48:10-49:11-49:15-50:16-50:21-51:21-53:23-53:32-57:14-57:22-58:8-59:9-59:18-59:19-61:11-63:11-64:16-65:1-65:7-66:6-73:20-74:38-75:2-75:14-79:40-81:7-81:14-82:5-82:19-86:4-89:27-91:7)",
      "d": "«nafs» means soul, life, self, or essence. Its plural is «nufūs». From it comes the meaning of the origin (starting point) of desires and a place of refuge. The heart that desires and rejoices is intended.\nAs far as concealing hidden matters and thoughts is concerned, this attribute is shared between «nufūs» and «ṣudūr».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ تُخْفِی فِی نَفْسِکَ مَا اللّٰہُ مُبْدِیْہِ» (33/37)\nTranslation: And you were concealing within yourself that which Allah was to reveal.\nThe connection of desires is with the «nafs», whether good or bad.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«إِنْ یَّتَّبِعُوْنَ إِلَّا الظَّنَّ وَ مَا تَهْوَى الْأَنْفُسُ» (53/23)\nTranslation: They follow not except assumption and what the selves desire.\nRejoicing is also connected to the «nafs».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَإِنْ طِبْنَ لَكُمْ عَنْ شَيْءٍ مِنْهُ نَفْسًا فَكُلُوهُ هَنِیئًا مَرِیئًا» (4/4)\nTranslation: Then if they are pleased to give you some of it, consume it with [good] enjoyment and gratitude."
    },
    {
      "id": 1476,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Putting a thought into the heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«waḥy», «ilhām», and «ilqāʾ» can come from Allah or from Satan, while «waswasah» and «hamz» are exclusively from Satan.\n«waḥy» is related to teaching, beliefs, commands, and matters of the unseen. «ilhām» is related only to the doing or not doing of a specific action, and «ilqāʾ» is related only to teaching.\n«waswasah» refers only to the arrival of evil thoughts in the heart, while «hamz» also includes incitement and urging from Satan along with evil thoughts.\nAny «waḥy», «ilhām», or «ilqāʾ» that conforms to the texts of Sharia is Rahmanī (from the Most Merciful); if not, it is Shayṭānī. (70 verses: 3:44-4:163-5:111-6:19-6:50-6:93-6:106-6:112-6:121-6:145-7:117-7:160-7:203-8:12-10:2-10:15-10:87-10:109-11:12-11:36-11:37-11:49-12:3-12:15-12:102-12:109-13:30-14:13-16:43-16:68-16:123-17:39-17:73-17:86-18:27-18:110-19:11-20:13-20:38-20:48-20:77-20:114-21:7-21:25-21:45-21:73-21:108-23:27-26:52-26:63-28:7-29:45-33:2-34:50-35:31-38:70-39:65-41:6-41:12-42:3-42:7-42:13-42:51-42:52-43:43-46:9-53:4-53:10-72:1-99:5)",
      "d": "«waḥy» lexically means only hidden (concealed) and a swift indication. And «awḥā» means to indicate swiftly regarding a hidden and unknown matter (mufrad). Then, there are several types of «waḥy». One is related to commanding affairs.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ أَوْحَى فِی کُلِّ سَمَاءٍ أَمْرَهَا» (41/12)\nTranslation: And He decreed within each heaven its command.\nNatural guidance is also referred to as «waḥy», such as a newborn baby instinctively turning to its mother's breast.\nFor example, the Divine declaration is:\n«وَ أَوْحَى رَبُّكَ إِلَی النَّحْلِ» (16/68)\nTranslation: And your Lord inspired the bees.\nThus, «waḥy» comes from Allah to inanimate objects, animals, and humans alike. And such «waḥy» can also come to non-prophets.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ أَوْحَیْنَا إِلَی أُمِّ مُوسَی أَنْ أَرْضِعِیهِ» (28/7)\nTranslation: And We inspired the mother of Moses, \"Suckle him.\"\nIn all these examples, the word «waḥy» is used in its lexical meaning. Furthermore, a person can also «waḥy» (inspire) another person in this sense.\nFor example, the Divine declaration is:\n«فَأَوْحَی إِلَیْهِمْ أَنْ سَبِّحُوا بُکْرَةً وَ عَشِیًّا» (19/11)\nTranslation: So he inspired them that they should exalt [Allah] morning and evening.\nEven Satan inspires others in this manner.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ إِنَّ الشَّیَاطِینَ لَیُوحُوْنَ إِلَی أَوْلِیَائِهِمْ لِیُجَادِلُوكُمْ» (6/121)\nTranslation: And indeed, the devils will inspire [to] their allies [among mankind] to dispute with you.\nThus, «waḥy» can be Rahmanī or Shayṭānī. Rahmanī «waḥy» is always based on good, and any «waḥy» contrary to Rahmanī «waḥy» is Shayṭānī. In the terminology of Sharia, «waḥy» refers to the teachings, commands, and news of the unseen that Allah sends to His chosen human (prophet) for the guidance of the common people. Three forms of it are mentioned in the Quran:\n(1) Allah directly puts a thought into the heart, (2) He sends an angel to the messenger, and (3) He speaks from behind a veil (as with Moses). However, the most common usage is that Allah, through Jibrīl, places His message upon the hearts of the prophets and messengers, which then issues from the prophet's tongue.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قُلْ مَنْ کَانَ عَدُوًّا لِّجِبْرِیلَ فَإِنَّهُ نَزَّلَهُ عَلَی قَلْبِکَ بِإِذْنِ اللّٰہِ» (2/97)\nTranslation: Say, \"Whoever is an enemy to Gabriel – then indeed he brought it [i.e., the Qur’ān] down upon your heart by permission of Allah.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 1477,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Putting a thought into the heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«ilhām» in common parlance refers to a matter that is cast into the heart by Allah (1 verse: 91:8)",
      "d": "«ilhām» is that thought which is cast into someone's heart by Allah (mufrad) and means granting understanding and insight. Granting success (munjad). Like «waḥy», «ilhām» can also be Shayṭānī, especially when it cannot be substantiated by any verse or textual evidence. Therefore, apart from the class of Sufis, no scholar considers «ilhām» as legally binding (m. m). The difference between «waḥy» and «ilhām» is that «ilhām» applies only to people of intellect, while «waḥy» is general. Secondly, «ilhām» is related to the doing or not doing of a specific action, while «waḥy» has much broader scope (m. m).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَأَلْهَمَهَا فُجُورَهَا وَ تَقْوَاهَا» (91/8)\nTranslation: Then He inspired it [i.e., humanity] with its [capacity for] wickedness and righteousness."
    },
    {
      "id": 1478,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Putting a thought into the heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«ilqāʾ» lexically means only to throw or cast. (66 verses: 2:37-3:44-4:90-4:91-4:94-4:171-5:64-7:115-7:107-7:116-7:117-7:120-7:150-8:12-10:80-10:81-12:10-12:93-12:96-15:19-16:15-16:28-16:86-16:87-17:39-20:20-20:39-20:65-20:66-20:69-20:70-20:87-22:52-22:53-25:8-25:13-26:32-26:43-26:44-26:45-26:46-26:223-27:6-27:10-27:28-27:29-28:7-28:31-28:86-31:10-37:97-38:34-40:15-41:35-41:40-43:53-50:7-50:24-50:26-50:37-54:25-60:1-67:7-67:8-75:15-84:4)",
      "d": "«ilqāʾ» lexically means only to throw or cast. And «alqā ʿalā» means to teach (m. m).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ءَأُلْقِیَ الذِّکْرُ عَلَیْهِ مِنْ بَیْنِنَا» (54/25)\nTranslation: Is the message [i.e., the Qur’ān] sent down upon him from among us?\nAnd «talaqqā š-šayʾ minhu» means to learn something. To acquire knowledge (munjad).\nFor example, the Divine declaration is:\n«فَتَلَقَّی آدَمُ مِنْ رَبِّهِ کَلِمَاتٍ» (2/37)\nTranslation: Then Adam received from his Lord [some] words.\nThus, «ilqāʾ» refers only to a thought that has been cast into the heart and is related to teaching and learning. Like «waḥy» and «ilhām», «ilqāʾ» can also be Shayṭānī.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَیَنْسَخُ اللّٰہُ مَا یُلْقِی الشَّیْطَانُ» (22/52)\nTranslation: Then Allah will abolish what the devil casts."
    },
    {
      "id": 1479,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Putting a thought into the heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«waswās» is Satan putting whispers into a person's heart (5 verses: 7:20-20:120-50:16-114:4-114:5)",
      "d": "«waswās» from a medical perspective is a disease that, due to overwhelming melancholy, disturbs the mind and causes a person to utter futile things that were not previously in his heart and in which there is no goodness (m. m). And «wiswās» means the disease of doubt. An evil or useless thought that enters the heart. And it means Satan's incitement to evil and continuously casting evil thoughts (mufrad). And it means the initial state of madness (f l 135). Thus, «waswās» is every evil thought that arises in the heart or is cast by Satan, and its attribution is exclusively to Satan.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«مِنْ شَرِّ الْوَسْوَاسِ الْخَنَّاسِ الَّذِی یُوَسْوِسُ فِی صُدُورِ النَّاسِ» (114/4,5)\nTranslation: From the evil of the retreating whisperer – Who whispers [evil] into the breasts of mankind."
    },
    {
      "id": 1480,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Putting a thought into the heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«hamazāt» is Satan creating evil and filthy thoughts in the heart (1 verse: 23:97)",
      "d": "«hamaza yadullu ʿalā ḍaghṭin wa-ʿaṣrin» (m. l) meaning to pinch. To prod. To press. And it means to prod a beast's side or muscle with a pointed stick, etc., so that it moves swiftly. Actually, the Punjabi phrase \"chohambaṛ dēna\" (to prod with a stick) is very suitable for this meaning. That is, Satan casting an evil thought into a heart and then inciting it. The attribution of this word is also exclusively to Satan.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ قُلْ رَبِّ أَعُوذُ بِکَ مِنْ هَمَزَاتِ الشَّیَاطِینِ» (23/97)\nTranslation: And say, \"My Lord, I seek refuge in You from the incitements of the devils.\""
    }
  ],
  "325": [
    {
      "id": 1481,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Proof",
      "hw": "دلیل",
      "s": "«dalīl» is to obtain guidance from one thing for the recognition of another (1 verse: 25:45)",
      "d": "«dalālat» and «dalīl» mean that guidance by which one's knowledge and recognition are attained. For example, by seeing movement in a living being, one knows that it is alive, or as written words indicate their meanings. In common speech too, words are a means of expressing meaning and are evidence of that meaning (mufrad). And «dalla» means to show. To inform. To guide. To be a means of knowledge and recognition.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«أَلَمْ تَرَ إِلَی رَبِّکَ کَیْفَ مَدَّ الظِّلَّ وَلَوْ شَاءَ لَجَعَلَهُ سَاکِنًا ثُمَّ جَعَلْنَا الشَّمْسَ عَلَیْهِ دَلِیلًا» (25/45)\nTranslation: Have you not considered your Lord – how He extends the shadow, and if He willed, He could have made it stationary? Then We made the sun for it an indication.\nThus, the increase and decrease of shadows and the setting of the sun are both evidence of each other. The correct determination of the sun's direction can be known from the increase and decrease of shadows. Similarly, it can be for telling time. And by seeing the sun's direction, the direction and length of the shadow can be estimated."
    },
    {
      "id": 1483,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Proof",
      "hw": "دلیل",
      "s": "«bayyinah» is a clear and manifest statement, a proof with which the claimant can invalidate the opponent's claim (74 verses: 2:87-2:92-2:99-2:159-2:185-2:209-2:211-2:213-2:253-3:86-3:97-3:105-3:183-3:184-4:19-4:153-5:32-5:110-6:57-6:157-7:73-7:85-7:101-7:105-8:42-9:70-10:13-10:15-10:74-11:17-11:28-11:53-11:63-11:88-14:9-16:44-17:101-19:73-20:72-20:133-22:16-22:72-24:1-24:34-24:46-28:36-29:35-29:39-29:49-30:9-30:47-33:30-34:43-35:25-40:22-40:28-40:34-40:50-40:66-40:83-43:63-45:17-45:25-46:7-47:14-57:9-57:25-58:5-61:6-64:6-65:1-65:11-98:1-98:4)",
      "d": "«bayyinah» means a clear and manifest statement. Proof. Some explanation of «bayyinah» is also derived from the saying of the Prophet ﷺ: \"Al-bayyinah ʿalā al-muddaʿī wa-l-yamīn ʿalā al-muddaʿā ʿalayhi\" (Bukhārī) meaning: The burden of proof is upon the claimant, and if he cannot provide it, then the oath is upon the one against whom the claim is made.\nNow consider, for example, Zaid claims a sum of money from Bakr, and Bakr denies it. If Zaid has in his possession a document from Bakr that can prove this matter or assist in proving it, that document is a «bayyinah». Similarly, if Zaid can prove it by presenting witnesses, that too is a «bayyinah». «Bayyinah» is such a proof before which the opponent becomes speechless. The very existence of the Quran is a «bayyinah». Against which, despite confrontation, the disbelievers cannot present any proof. Similarly, its verses are also «bayyināt».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«بَلْ هُوَ آیَاتٌ بَیِّنَاتٌ فِی صُدُورِ الَّذِینَ أُوتُوا الْعِلْمَ ۚ وَ مَا یَجْحَدُ بِآیَاتِنَا إِلَّا الظَّالِمُونَ» (29/49)\nTranslation: Rather, it [i.e., the Qur’ān] is clear verses in the breasts of those given knowledge. And none reject Our verses except the wrongdoers.\nIn this verse, by using the word «jahd», reference is made to the fact that they acknowledge from the heart that these verses are clear proofs, even though they deny them with their tongues."
    },
    {
      "id": 1484,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Proof",
      "hw": "دلیل",
      "s": "«Burhan» is a proof that is clear and definitively established, and is also supported by divine revelation. (8 verses: 2:111-4:174-12:24-21:24-23:117-27:64-28:32-28:75)",
      "d": "«Barah» means white and shining. And «Burhan» is a proof that is clear and definitively established, and is also supported by divine revelation (Muf). According to some, «Burhan» is derived from the Persian word «Burran» meaning a sharp-edged sword. And «Burhan» refers to a proof that ends a dispute (Faqih 55).\nFor example, in the Quran: «tilka amaniyyuhum qul hatu burhanakum in kuntum sadiqin» (2/111).\nTranslation: These are merely their idle desires. Say, 'Bring your proof if you are truthful.'\nAt another place, the divine command states: «fa-dhalika burhanani min rabbika ila fir'awna wa malaihi» (28/32).\nTranslation: These two proofs (the staff of Moses and the radiant hand) are from your Lord; go to Pharaoh and his courtiers with them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1485,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Proof",
      "hw": "دلیل",
      "s": "«Sultan» is a proof that is clearly established through divine revelation. (38 verses: 3:151-4:91-4:144-4:153-6:81-7:33-7:71-10:68-11:96-12:40-14:10-14:11-14:22-15:42-16:99-16:100-17:33-17:65-17:80-18:15-22:71-23:45-27:21-28:35-30:35-34:21-37:30-37:156-40:23-40:35-40:56-44:19-51:38-52:38-53:23-55:33-59:6-69:29)",
      "d": "«Sultan» means authority, power, and control (Munjid). Royal decree (Munjid). Authority letter. A proof that is clearly established through divine revelation. Evidence. And the plural of «Sultan» is «Sultanin» meaning kings, which is a metaphorical meaning, not literal. Nor has the Quran used this word in those meanings.\nFor example, in the Quran: «atujadilunani fi asma sammaytumuhum antum wa abaukum ma nazzalallahu biha min sultan» (7/71).\nTranslation: Do you argue with me about names which you have named—you and your fathers—for which Allah has not sent down any authority?"
    }
  ],
  "326": [
    {
      "id": 1486,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Day and its times",
      "hw": "دن",
      "s": "«Nahar» refers to the time from sunrise to sunset. (50 verses: 2:164-2:274-3:27-3:72-3:190-6:13-6:60-7:54-10:6-10:24-10:45-10:50-10:67-11:114-13:3-13:10-14:33-16:12-17:12-20:130-21:20-21:33-21:42-22:61-23:80-24:44-25:47-25:62-27:86-28:72-28:73-30:23-31:29-34:33-35:13-36:37-36:40-39:5-40:61-41:37-41:38-45:5-46:35-57:6-71:5-73:7-73:20-78:11-91:3-92:2)",
      "d": "«Nahar» means day, and its opposite is «Layl» meaning night. «Nahar» refers to the time from sunrise to sunset. The day is divided into 12 hours (or 12 ghadi) which are named respectively: «alshuruq, bukur, ghudwah, duha, hajira, zahira, rawah, asr, qasr, sayl, ashiyy, ghurub» (Fal 292). (The mention of night and day together appears frequently in the Quran.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1487,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Day and its times",
      "hw": "دن",
      "s": "«Yawm» means the combination of day and night, i.e., 24 hours. (262 verses: 2:48-2:85-2:113-2:123-2:174-2:203-2:212-2:254-2:259-2:281-3:9-3:25-3:30-3:55-3:77-3:106-3:155-3:161-3:166-3:180-3:185-3:194-4:87-4:109-4:141-4:159-5:14-5:36-5:64-5:109-5:119-6:12-6:15-6:22-6:73-6:128-6:130-6:141-6:158-7:14-7:32-7:51-7:53-7:59-7:163-7:167-7:172-8:41-9:3-9:25-9:35-9:36-9:77-9:108-10:15-10:28-10:45-10:60-10:93-11:3-11:8-11:26-11:60-11:77-11:84-11:98-11:99-11:103-11:105-14:18-14:31-14:41-14:42-14:44-14:48-15:36-15:38-16:25-16:27-16:80-16:84-16:89-16:92-16:111-16:124-17:13-17:52-17:58-17:62-17:71-17:97-18:19-18:47-18:52-18:105-19:15-19:33-19:37-19:38-19:39-19:85-19:95-20:59-20:100-20:101-20:102-20:104-20:124-21:47-21:103-21:104-22:2-22:9-22:17-22:47-22:55-22:69-23:16-23:100-23:113-24:24-24:37-24:64-25:17-25:22-25:25-25:26-25:27-25:69-26:38-26:87-26:88-26:135-26:155-26:156-26:189-27:83-27:87-28:41-28:42-28:61-28:62-28:65-28:71-28:72-28:74-29:13-29:25-29:55-30:12-30:14-30:43-30:55-31:33-32:5-32:14-32:25-32:29-33:44-33:66-34:30-34:40-35:14-37:144-38:79-38:81-39:13-39:15-39:24-39:31-39:47-39:60-39:67-39:71-40:15-40:16-40:18-40:30-40:32-40:33-40:46-40:49-40:51-40:52-41:9-41:12-41:19-41:40-41:47-42:7-42:45-42:47-43:65-43:83-44:10-44:16-44:41-45:17-45:26-45:27-45:34-46:5-46:20-46:21-46:34-46:35-50:20-50:30-50:34-50:41-50:42-50:44-51:13-51:60-52:9-52:13-52:45-52:46-54:6-54:8-54:19-54:48-55:29-56:50-57:12-57:13-58:6-58:7-58:18-60:3-62:9-64:9-66:8-68:39-68:42-70:4-70:8-70:42-70:43-73:14-73:17-74:9-75:1-75:6-76:7-76:10-76:27-77:12-77:35-78:18-78:38-78:40-79:6-79:35-79:46-80:34-82:19-83:5-83:6-86:9-90:14-101:4)",
      "d": "«Yawm» means day. From sunset to the next day's sunset. The combination of night and day, 24 hours. The plural of «Yawm» is «Ayyam». Time and periods are calculated by «Ayyam».\nFor example, in the Quran: «faman lam yajid fasiyama thalathati ayyamin filhaji wa sab'atin idha raja'tum» (2/196).\nTranslation: And whoever cannot afford a sacrifice should fast for three days during the Hajj and seven when you return.\nAnd «Yawm» in this context is for humans. Its concept can only be formed after the creation of the sun and earth; otherwise, with Allah, «Yawm» is a long period, whether it spans hundreds of thousands of years according to our calculation.\nFor example, the divine command states: «qul a-innakum latakfuru bialladhi khalaqa alarda fi yawmayn» (41/9).\nTranslation: Do you disbelieve in Him who created the earth in two days?\nSimilarly, when «Yawm» is mentioned in the context of the creation of the earth and heavens, it refers to a long period.\nFor example, the divine command states: «wa inna yawman inda rabbika kalalfi sanatin mimma ta'uddun» (22/47).\nTranslation: And indeed, a day with your Lord is like a thousand years of what you count.\nAt another place, the divine command states: «ta'ruju almalakatu wa alrruhu ilayhi fi yawmin kana miqdaruhu khamsina alfa sanatin» (70/4).\nTranslation: The angels and the Spirit ascend to Him in a day the extent of which is fifty thousand years.\nSimilarly, the Day of Judgment will also be a long period, with its duration mentioned in Hadith as fifty thousand years."
    },
    {
      "id": 1488,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Day and its times",
      "hw": "دن",
      "s": "«Al-yawm» means today's day, from sunrise to sunset. (47 verses: 2:249-5:3-5:5-6:93-7:51-8:48-10:92-11:43-12:54-12:92-16:27-16:63-17:14-19:26-19:38-20:64-20:126-23:65-23:111-25:14-34:42-36:54-36:55-36:59-36:64-36:65-37:26-40:16-40:17-40:29-43:39-43:68-45:28-45:34-45:35-46:20-50:22-57:12-57:15-66:7-68:24-69:35-70:44-76:11-78:39-83:34-85:2)",
      "d": "«Al-yawm» means today's day. And the duration of «Al-yawm» is according to «Nahar», not «Yawm», meaning it refers to the time from sunrise to sunset (Munjid). «Zillal-yawm» means the shade of today (Munjid), as in the case of Pharaoh's drowning when Allah the Almighty said: «fal-yawma nunajjika bibidannika litakuna liman khalfaka ayatan» (10/92).\nTranslation: So today We save you in your body that you may be a sign for those after you.\nAnd «Al-yawm» is also used in the Quran for the Day of Judgment.\nFor example, in the Quran: «qala kathalika atatka ayatuna fanasitaha wa kathalika al-yawma tunsa» (20/126).\nTranslation: He will say, 'Thus did Our signs come to you, and you forgot them. And thus today you will be forgotten.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1489,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Day and its times",
      "hw": "دن",
      "s": "«Yawma-idhin» means that day, that very day. (69 verses: 3:167-4:42-6:16-7:8-8:16-11:66-14:49-16:87-18:99-18:100-20:102-20:108-20:109-22:56-23:101-24:25-25:22-25:24-25:26-27:89-28:66-30:4-30:14-30:43-30:57-37:33-40:9-42:47-43:67-45:27-52:11-55:39-69:15-69:16-69:17-69:18-70:11-74:9-75:10-75:12-75:13-75:22-75:24-75:30-77:15-77:19-77:24-77:28-77:34-77:37-77:40-77:45-77:47-77:49-79:8-80:37-80:38-80:40-82:19-83:10-83:15-88:2-88:8-89:23-89:25-99:4-99:6-100:11-102:8)",
      "d": "«Yawma-idhin» is formed by adding «idh» after «yawm». It is used to refer to a specific time. Meaning that day or that very day (Muf).\nFor example, in the Quran: «wujuhun yawma-idhin musfiratun dahikatun mustabshiratun» (80/38,39).\nTranslation: Faces on that day will be bright, laughing, and rejoicing."
    }
  ],
  "327": [
    {
      "id": 1490,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "World and its various names",
      "hw": "دنیا",
      "s": "«Dunya» commonly refers to the planet we live on. (111 verses: 2:85-2:86-2:114-2:130-2:200-2:201-2:204-2:212-2:217-2:220-3:14-3:22-3:45-3:56-3:117-3:145-3:148-3:152-3:185-4:74-4:77-4:94-4:109-4:134-5:33-5:41-6:29-6:32-6:70-6:130-7:32-7:51-7:152-7:156-8:42-8:67-9:38-9:55-9:69-9:74-9:85-10:7-10:23-10:24-10:64-10:70-10:88-10:98-11:15-11:60-12:101-13:26-13:34-14:3-14:27-16:30-16:41-16:107-16:122-18:28-18:45-18:46-18:104-20:72-20:131-22:9-22:11-22:15-23:33-23:37-24:14-24:19-24:23-24:33-28:42-28:60-28:61-28:77-28:79-29:25-29:27-29:64-30:7-31:15-31:33-33:28-33:57-35:5-37:6-39:10-39:26-40:39-40:43-40:51-41:12-41:16-41:31-42:20-42:36-43:32-43:35-45:24-45:35-46:20-47:36-53:29-57:20-59:3-67:5-79:38-87:16)",
      "d": "«Dunya» means near, close. And this word is used in all aspects—place, time, rank, etc.—to mean near. According to Islamic belief, there are two lives: one is the present life, called «shahdat al-ula» (first creation), and the other is life after death, called «shahdat al-akhra» or second. Since the present life is near in terms of time, it is called «Dunya», and its opposite is «Akhirah». And this word is generally used for the present life.\nFor example, in the Quran: «ula'ika alladhina ishtaraw alhayata alddunya bil-akhira» (2/86).\nTranslation: Those are the ones who have purchased the worldly life for the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 1491,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "World and its various names",
      "hw": "دنیا",
      "s": "«Adna» is used in meanings of lower rank, inferior, small, and insignificant. (12 verses: 2:61-2:282-4:3-5:108-7:169-30:3-32:21-33:51-33:59-53:9-58:7-73:20)",
      "d": "«Adna» besides temporal nearness, also means lower in rank, inferior. And «Adna» comes in the meaning of «Arzal» and insignificant (Muf). Its opposite is «A'la» and also «Akhra».\nFor example, in the Quran: «fakhalafa min ba'dihim khalaf warithu alkitaba ya'khudhuna 'aradha hada al-adna» (7/169).\nTranslation: Then after them succeeded an evil generation who inherited the Scripture, taking only the mundane gains of this worldly life."
    },
    {
      "id": 1492,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "World and its various names",
      "hw": "دنیا",
      "s": "«Ajilah» means haste and quickness. (3 verses: 17:18-75:20-76:27)",
      "d": "«Ajilah» is opposite to «Akhirah». And «'Ajl» means haste and quickness. And «Ajilah» means that which comes quickly, the present world, and its material possessions (Muf).\nFor example, in the Quran: «kalla bal tuhibbuna al-'ajilata wa tazaruna al-akhira» (75/20,21).\nTranslation: No! But you love the present life and neglect the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 1493,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "World and its various names",
      "hw": "دنیا",
      "s": "«Ula» is used in meanings of first, previous, earlier, prior, better, superior, etc. (17 verses: 20:21-20:51-20:133-28:43-28:70-33:33-37:59-44:35-44:56-53:25-53:50-53:56-56:62-79:25-87:18-92:13-93:4)",
      "d": "«Ula» means first. And the feminine of «awwal» means first. That is, the first or present life, and its opposite is «akhra» and «akhirah» meaning the last or the Hereafter.\nFor example, in the Quran: «wa inna lana lil-akhirati wa al-ula» (92/13).\nTranslation: And indeed, the Hereafter and the first life are both Ours."
    }
  ],
  "328": [
    {
      "id": 1494,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Distant",
      "hw": "دور",
      "s": "«بَعِیْد» is generally used for time or place (25 verses: 2:176-3:30-4:60-4:116-4:136-4:167-11:83-11:89-14:3-14:18-21:109-22:12-22:53-25:12-27:22-34:8-34:52-34:53-41:44-41:52-42:18-50:3-50:27-50:31-70:6)",
      "d": "The opposite of «بُعْد» is «قُرْب», meaning distance. This distance can be in terms of space or time. Its usage is general.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ اِنۡ  اَدۡرِیۡۤ  اَقَرِیۡبٌ اَمۡ بَعِیۡدٌ مَّا تُوۡعَدُوۡنَ» (21/109)\nTranslation: And I do not know whether what you are promised is near or far.\nBesides sensory perception, it is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example, the divine declaration is: «وَ یُرِیۡدُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ اَنۡ یُّضِلَّہُمۡ ضَلٰلًۢا بَعِیۡدًا» (4/60)\nTranslation: Satan intends to lead them astray to a far deviation."
    },
    {
      "id": 1495,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Distant",
      "hw": "دور",
      "s": "«سَحِیْق» meaning a distant place. This is used only for location. (1 verse: 22:31)",
      "d": "«سَحَقَ» means to crush, to pulverize. «سَحِیْقَ» means to be far. And «سُحْقًا» means to be far from Allah's mercy. Curse. (Manjad) «سَحَقَ الرِّیْحُ الْاَرْضَ» means the wind, due to its intensity, has peeled the earth. And «سُحْقًا» means a distant place. This is used only for location (f l 29).\nFor example, the Quran states: «فَکَاَنَّمَا خَرَّ  مِنَ السَّمَآءِ فَتَخۡطَفُہُ الطَّیۡرُ  اَوۡ تَہۡوِیۡ بِہِ الرِّیۡحُ فِیۡ مَکَانٍ  سَحِیْقٍ» (22/31)\nTranslation: (The example of a disbeliever is) as if he fell from the sky, and the birds snatch him, or the wind carries him to a distant place."
    },
    {
      "id": 1496,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Distant",
      "hw": "دور",
      "s": "«عَمِیْق» meaning deep/distant paths, rugged terrain (1 verse: 22:27)",
      "d": "«عَمَقْ» means depth and «عَمِیْق» means deep. «فَجٍّ عَمِیْق» means a rugged, up-and-down path, a difficult and distant route.\nFor example, the Quran states: «یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیْقٍ» (22/27)\nTranslation: They will come from every distant, rugged path."
    },
    {
      "id": 1497,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Distant",
      "hw": "دور",
      "s": "«قَصِیًّا» a distance that also implies direction (distance and direction). See also ‘‘to keep far’’ under ‘‘to avoid’’ (5 verses: 8:42-17:1-19:22-28:20-36:20)",
      "d": "«قَصِی ، قَصٰی» means to be far. «اَقْصَا» and «قُصْوٰی» mean extremely far (Manjad). And «اَقْصَا» means the farthest edge or the opposite shore.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ جَآءَ رَجُلٌ مِّنۡ اَقۡصَا الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ یَسۡعٰی» (28/20)\nTranslation: And a man came running from the farthest edge of the city.\nThus, in «اَقْصَا» and «قَصِیًّا», the concept of direction along with distance is present.\nFor example, the divine declaration is: «فَحَمَلَتۡہُ  فَانۡتَبَذَتۡ بِہٖ مَکَانًا قَصِیًّا» (19/22)\nTranslation: So she conceived him and withdrew with him to a distant place.\nMeaning, Maryam first went to an eastern place, then went even farther to a distant location."
    },
    {
      "id": 1501,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To remove. To be.",
      "hw": "دور",
      "s": "«کَفَّرَ» (عَنْ) means for Allah to forgive sins because of good deeds (17 verses: 2:271-3:193-3:195-4:31-5:12-5:45-5:65-5:89-5:95-8:29-29:7-39:35-47:2-48:5-64:9-65:5-66:8).",
      "d": "«کَفَرَ» means to cover. And «کُفْرَۃ» means the darkness of night. And «کَفَّارَۃ» is the act whose performance covers over a sin. And when «کَفَّرَ» is attributed to Allah, it means to remove evils. And «کَفَّرَ» is related to سیّئات (sins), whereas «غَفَرَ» is related to ذنوب (transgressions).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ اَنَّ اَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ اتَّقَوۡا لَکَفَّرۡنَا عَنۡہُمۡ سَیِّاٰتِہِمۡ» (5/65)\nTranslation: And if the People of the Book had believed and feared Allah, We would have surely removed their evils from them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1502,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To Distance. To Be.",
      "hw": "دور",
      "s": "«قَضٰی» means to do something as a completion after finishing a major task (58 verses: 2:117-2:200-2:210-3:47-4:65-4:103-6:2-6:8-6:58-6:60-8:42-8:44-10:11-10:19-10:47-10:54-10:71-10:93-11:44-11:110-12:41-12:68-14:22-15:66-17:4-17:23-19:21-19:35-19:39-19:71-20:72-20:114-22:29-27:78-28:15-28:28-28:29-28:44-33:23-33:36-33:37-34:14-35:36-39:42-39:69-39:75-40:20-40:68-40:78-41:12-41:45-42:14-42:21-43:77-45:17-46:29-62:10-80:23)",
      "d": "The literal meaning of «قَضٰی» is not 'to distance' but when it is attributed to a human, it means to fulfill responsibility. For example, in the Quran: «فَلَمَّا قَضٰی مُوۡسَی الۡاَجَلَ» (28/29) Translation: When Moses had completed his appointed term. However, in the following verse, according to the idiom of the language, its meaning is taken as 'to distance' because it is also part of completing a task. For example, the divine command states: «ثُمَّ لۡیَقۡضُوۡا تَفَثَہُمۡ وَ لۡیُوۡفُوۡا نُذُوۡرَہُمۡ» (22/29) Translation: Then they should remove their filth and fulfill their vows. Note: (Completion: That thing with which something is completed, or the content related to the original (book or treatise, etc.), that part related to the book or annotations that is included as a completion.)"
    }
  ],
  "329": [
    {
      "id": 1503,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To Run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«سَرَعَ» to run quickly (4 verses: 6:62-10:21-50:44-70:43)",
      "d": "«سَرَعَ» means not to delay in doing a work and to do it immediately (muf). And in terms of speed, «سَرَعَ» means only fast movement. To run quickly when there is no danger (f l 33). Its opposite is «بَطَاَ».\nFor example, the Quran states: «یَوۡمَ یَخۡرُجُوۡنَ  مِنَ الۡاَجۡدَاثِ سِرَاعًا» (70/43)\nTranslation: On the Day they will emerge from the graves running swiftly."
    },
    {
      "id": 1504,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To Run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«سَعٰی» a moderate pace between walking and running (14 verses: 2:114-2:205-17:19-20:15-20:20-20:66-28:20-36:20-53:39-57:12-66:8-79:22-79:35-80:8)",
      "d": "«سَعٰی» is a moderate pace between walking and running. «سَعْی» is that pace like the one between Safa and Marwah (fl 177).\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ جَآءَ مِنۡ اَقۡصَا الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  رَجُلٌ یَّسۡعٰی» (36/20)\nTranslation: And from the farthest side of the city, a man came running."
    },
    {
      "id": 1506,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To Run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«رَکَضَ» to run at full gallop (3 verses: 21:12-21:13-38:42)",
      "d": "«رَکَضَ» means to dig in the heels. «رَکَضَ الرَّجُلُ دَآبَّتَہٗ» he made his animal gallop to get ahead (m l). To make a horse gallop. To run at full gallop.\nFor example, the Quran states: «فَلَمَّاۤ  اَحَسُّوۡا بَاۡسَنَاۤ  اِذَا ہُمۡ  مِّنۡہَا یَرۡکُضُوۡنَ» (21/12)\nTranslation: When they sensed Our might, at that they were fleeing from it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1507,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To Run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«جَمَحَ» to break loose and become uncontrollable (1 verse: 9:57)",
      "d": "«جَمَحَ» means to snap the ropes. A horse running fast and the rider losing control (Manjad).\nFor example, the Quran states: «لَوۡ  یَجِدُوۡنَ مَلۡجَاً  اَوۡ مَغٰرٰتٍ اَوۡ  مُدَّخَلًا لَّوَلَّوۡا  اِلَیۡہِ  وَ ہُمۡ  یَجۡمَحُوۡنَ» (9/57)\nTranslation: If they find a refuge, or caves, or (underground) hiding places, they would turn towards them while snapping their ropes (i.e., fleeing in panic)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1508,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«harʿa» to run hastily, to run out of control due to emotions (2 verses: 11:78-37:70)",
      "d": "«harʿa» to run hastily. To run out of control due to emotions. To run with trembling limbs (a trembling person is one whose body is affected by shivering). To run hastily or to run in agitation. To run in a state of anger, weakness, fear, or cold (M. Q). For example, in the Quran: «وَ جَآءَہٗ  قَوۡمُہٗ یُہۡرَعُوۡنَ  اِلَیۡہِ» (11/78) Translation: And the people of Lot came to him running hastily."
    },
    {
      "id": 1509,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«nasala» to run from a high place downwards (2 verses: 21:96-36:51)",
      "d": "«nasala» to run from a height downwards. According to al-Munjid, it means to run swiftly and to cause to fall. And according to Ibn al-Faris, it means to gradually extract one thing from another (M. L). However, this meaning is not intended in the following verse. For example, in the Quran: «حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا  فُتِحَتۡ یَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ مَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ ہُمۡ  مِّنۡ  کُلِّ  حَدَبٍ  یَّنۡسِلُوۡنَ» (21/96) Translation: Until when Ya'juj and Ma'juj are released, and they are running down from every height."
    },
    {
      "id": 1511,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«haṭaʿa» to come running with fixed gaze and obedience (3 verses: 14:43-54:8-70:36)",
      "d": "«haṭaʿa» to run forward with fixed gaze, obedient and submissive (M. L). For example, in the Quran: «مُّہۡطِعِیۡنَ  اِلَی الدَّاعِ ؕ یَقُوۡلُ الۡکٰفِرُوۡنَ ہٰذَا یَوۡمٌ  عَسِرٌ» (54/8) Translation: They will be running towards the caller, and the disbelievers will say, 'This is a difficult day.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1512,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«ḍabaḥa» (of a horse) to run so fast that it starts panting (1 verse: 100:1)",
      "d": "«ḍabaḥa» a horse running so fast that it starts panting. For example, in the Quran: «وَ الۡعٰدِیٰتِ ضَبۡحًا» (100/1) Translation: By the runners panting."
    },
    {
      "id": 1513,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«sabaqa, istabaqa» to run in an attempt to get ahead in a competition (26 verses: 2:148-5:48-7:80-8:59-8:68-10:19-11:40-11:110-12:17-12:25-15:5-20:99-20:199-21:27-21:101-23:27-23:43-29:4-29:28-36:66-37:171-41:45-42:14-46:11-59:10-79:4)",
      "d": "«sabaqa» means to get ahead, to advance in a competition, to race. And «istabaqa» means to strive to get ahead of one another in a competition. For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَا یَحۡسَبَنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا سَبَقُوۡا ؕ اِنَّہُمۡ  لَا  یُعۡجِزُوۡنَ» (8/59) Translation: And let not the disbelievers think they have outstripped [Allah's plan]. Indeed, they will never frustrate [Him]. At another place, the Almighty says: «وَ اسۡتَبَقَا الۡبَابَ وَ قَدَّتۡ قَمِیۡصَہٗ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ» (12/25) Translation: And they both raced to the door, and she tore his shirt from the back."
    }
  ],
  "330": [
    {
      "id": 1514,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to run (horse etc.)",
      "hw": "گھوڑا",
      "s": "«awḍaʿa» to run around causing destruction (1 verse: 9:47)",
      "d": "«waḍaʿa» means to place something down, to humiliate, to degrade. And «waḍaʿa» or «awḍaʿa al-baʿīr» means to make a camel run with its head lowered, which has no good aspect (Munjid). And «awḍaʿa» means to run around causing turmoil and corruption. For example, in the Quran: «لَوۡ خَرَجُوۡا فِیۡکُمۡ مَّا زَادُوۡکُمۡ  اِلَّا خَبَالًا وَّ لَا۠اَوۡضَعُوۡا خِلٰلَکُمۡ یَبۡغُوۡنَکُمُ الۡفِتۡنَۃَ» (9/47) Translation: If they had gone forth among you, they would not have added to you except [fitna] and would have run around among you seeking to cause corruption."
    },
    {
      "id": 1515,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to run (horse etc.)",
      "hw": "گھوڑا",
      "s": "«awjaf» to run swiftly due to restlessness (1 verse: 59:6)",
      "d": "«wajafa» means to be restless, agitated, uneasy. And «qalbun wājifun» means an uneasy heart (Maf). And «awjafa» means to make (a horse etc.) run swiftly. For example, in the Quran: «وَ مَاۤ  اَفَآءَ اللّٰہُ  عَلٰی رَسُوۡلِہٖ  مِنۡہُمۡ فَمَاۤ اَوۡجَفۡتُمۡ عَلَیۡہِ مِنۡ خَیۡلٍ وَّ لَا رِکَابٍ» (59/6) Translation: And whatever Allah has bestowed upon His Messenger from them, you did not hasten [to take] any horses or camels for it."
    }
  ],
  "331": [
    {
      "id": 1516,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Hell and its different places",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "«al-nār» meaning fire (102 verses: 2:24-2:39-2:80-2:81-2:126-2:167-2:174-2:175-2:201-2:217-2:221-2:257-2:275-3:10-3:16-3:24-3:103-3:116-3:131-3:151-3:183-3:185-3:191-3:192-4:145-5:29-5:37-5:72-6:27-6:128-7:36-7:38-7:44-7:47-7:50-8:14-9:17-10:8-10:27-11:16-11:17-11:98-11:106-11:113-13:5-13:17-13:35-14:30-14:50-16:62-18:53-20:10-21:39-22:72-23:104-24:57-27:8-27:90-28:29-28:41-29:24-29:25-32:20-33:66-34:42-38:27-38:59-38:61-38:64-39:8-39:16-39:19-40:6-40:41-40:43-40:46-40:47-40:49-40:72-41:19-41:24-41:28-41:40-45:34-46:20-46:34-47:12-47:15-51:13-52:14-54:48-56:71-57:15-58:17-59:3-59:17-59:20-64:10-66:10-74:31-85:5-87:12)",
      "d": "«nār, nūr» means fire. It is a well-known word. When the definite article «al-» is added to it and no other distinguishing sign is present, then «al-nār» refers to Hell. For example, in the Quran: «اِنَّہُمۡ صَالُوا النَّارِ» (38/59) Translation: Indeed, they will be the inhabitants of the Fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 1517,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Hell and its different places",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "«jahannam» is commonly used for Hell (77 verses: 2:206-3:12-3:162-3:197-4:55-4:93-4:97-4:115-4:121-4:140-4:169-7:18-7:41-7:179-8:16-8:36-8:37-9:35-9:49-9:63-9:68-9:73-9:81-9:95-9:109-11:119-13:18-14:16-14:29-15:43-16:29-17:8-17:18-17:39-17:63-17:97-18:100-18:102-18:106-19:68-19:86-20:74-21:29-21:98-23:103-25:34-25:65-29:54-29:68-32:13-35:36-36:63-38:56-38:85-39:32-39:60-39:71-39:72-40:49-40:60-40:76-43:74-45:10-48:6-50:24-50:30-52:13-55:43-58:8-66:9-67:6-72:15-72:23-78:21-85:10-89:23-98:6)",
      "d": "«jahannam» is derived from the Persian word jahnam (a foreign word adopted into Arabic with slight modification). It means the house of punishment, retribution, and penalty (Maf). Lexicographers generally derive it from the root meaning 'to be angry' or 'to scorch'. For example, in the Quran: «جَہَنَّمَ ۚ یَصۡلَوۡنَہَا ۚ فَبِئۡسَ الۡمِہَادُ» (38/56) Translation: They will enter Hell, and how evil is that resting place."
    },
    {
      "id": 1518,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Hell and its different places",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "«jahīm» meaning fiercely blazing fire (26 verses: 2:119-5:10-5:86-9:113-22:51-26:91-37:23-37:55-37:64-37:68-37:97-37:163-40:7-44:47-44:56-52:18-56:94-57:19-69:31-73:12-79:36-79:39-81:12-82:14-83:16-102:6)",
      "d": "«jahama» means a lion's glare and fierce eyes. And «jahm» means the fierce blazing of fire. And «jahīm» means fiercely blazing fire (Maf) and «jahīm» means a pit with intensely burning fire, a scorching place, Hell (Munjid). For example, in the Quran: «خُذُوۡہُ فَاعۡتِلُوۡہُ  اِلٰی سَوَآءِ الۡجَحِیۡمِ» (44/47) Translation: Seize him and drag him into the midst of the Blaze."
    },
    {
      "id": 1519,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Hell and its various places",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "«سَقَر» means intense heat that burns the skin (4 verses: 54:48-74:26-74:27-74:42)",
      "d": "«سَقَر» means intense heat that burns the skin.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ  مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا سَقَرُ لَا  تُبۡقِیۡ  وَ لَا  تَذَرُ لَوَّاحَۃٌ  لِّلۡبَشَرِ» ( 74/27،28،29 )\nTranslation: And do you know what Sagar is? It neither spares nor leaves any, it will scorch the skin black."
    },
    {
      "id": 1520,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Hell and its various places",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "«سَعِیْر» means fire that is constantly blazing (17 verses: 4:10-4:55-17:97-22:4-25:11-31:21-33:64-34:12-35:6-42:7-48:13-67:5-67:10-67:11-76:4-81:12-84:12)",
      "d": "«سَعَرَ» means to ignite and intensify fire (transitive). Hence, Hell is called «سعیر». That is, fire that is constantly blazing.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ سَیَصۡلَوۡنَ  سَعِیۡرًا» ( 4/10 )\nTranslation: Soon they will enter a blazing fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 1521,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Names of some layers of Hell",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "«غَیّ» misguidance that occurs due to erroneous belief (4 verses: 2:256-7:146-7:202-19:59-)",
      "d": "«غَوٰی» means to go astray and choose the wrong path. It is a degree beyond «ضَلَال». And «غَیّ» refers to misguidance that occurs due to erroneous belief (transitive). «غَیّ» is also the name of a valley or layer of Hell where such misguided people will be thrown.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَخَلَفَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہِمۡ خَلۡفٌ اَضَاعُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَ اتَّبَعُوا الشَّہَوٰتِ فَسَوۡفَ یَلۡقَوۡنَ  غَیًّا» ( 19/59 )\nTranslation: Then after them succeeded an evil generation who neglected prayer and followed their desires. So they will soon meet «غَیّ»."
    },
    {
      "id": 1522,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Names of some layers of Hell",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "«ھَاوِیَۃ» is the name of a deep pit in Hell (1 verse: 101:9)",
      "d": "«ھَوٰی یَھْوِیْ» means to fall from a height to the ground. And «اُھْوِیَّۃ» refers to a deep well. And «اُھْوِیَّۃ» means a deep pit (Najd). And «ھَاوِیَۃ» is the name of a deep pit in Hell.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَاُمُّہٗ  ہَاوِیَۃٌ وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا ہِیَہۡ نَارٌ حَامِیَۃٌ» ( 101/9،10،11 )\nTranslation: Its resting place is «Hawiyah». And do you know what it is? It is a fiercely blazing fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 1523,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Names of some layers of Hell",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "«اَلْحُطَمَۃ» is the name of a layer of Hell (2 verses: 104:4-104:5)",
      "d": "«حَطَمَ» means to crush, to pulverize. And «حُطَمَۃ» is the name of a layer of Hell.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ  مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا  الۡحُطَمَۃُ نَارُ اللّٰہِ الۡمُوۡقَدَۃُ» ( 104/5،6 )\nTranslation: And do you know what «Al-Hutamah» is? It is Allah's kindled fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 1524,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Angels of Hell",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "«خَزْنَۃ» are the guards and sentinels of Hell (5 verses: 15:22-39:71-39:73-40:49-67:8)",
      "d": "«خَزْنَۃ» is the plural of «خَازِن». In «خَزَن», the concepts of collecting and protecting are found. And «خَازِن» means one who protects collected wealth: a treasurer, a guardian, a jailer, a warden. The guards and sentinels of the people of Hell.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«سَاَلَہُمۡ خَزَنَتُہَاۤ  اَلَمۡ یَاۡتِکُمۡ  نَذِیۡرٌ» ( 67/8 )\nTranslation: The keepers (wardens) of Hell will ask them: Did no warner come to you?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1525,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Angels of Hell",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "«زَبَانِیَۃ» are the harsh and fierce angels of Hell who will drive the people of Hell into it (1 verse: 96:18)",
      "d": "«زَبَانِیَۃ» is the plural of «زَبْنِیَۃ». «زَبَانِی الْعَقْرَب» means the scorpion's sting (Najd). «زَبَانِیَۃ» are the harsh and fierce angels of Hell who will drive the people of Hell into it.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَلۡیَدۡعُ نَادِیَہٗ سَنَدۡعُ  الزَّبَانِیَۃَ» ( 96/18 )\nTranslation: Then let him call upon his council; we will call upon the guards of Hell (to seize him)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1526,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Angels of Hell",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "«مَالِک» is the name of the chief guardian of Hell (1 verse: 43:77)",
      "d": "«مَالِک» is the name of the chief of the guardians of Hell.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ نَادَوۡا یٰمٰلِکُ لِیَقۡضِ عَلَیۡنَا رَبُّکَ» ( 43/77 )\nTranslation: And they will cry out: O Malik! Let your Lord finish us off."
    }
  ],
  "332": [
    {
      "id": 1527,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«قَرِیْن» means a companion, equal in age and status (6 verses: 4:38-37:51-43:36-43:38-50:23-50:27)",
      "d": "«اَلْقَرَن» is the rope with which two camels are tied. And «اَلْقِرْنَ» means equal, counterpart. It applies to both animate and inanimate things (Faqih 235). And «قِرْاٰنُ السَّعْدَیْن» means the conjunction of two fortunate stars in one mansion. According to Imam Raghib, «قَرِیْن» is a person who is of the same age as another or is his equal in bravery, strength, and other qualities. (Mufradat) This word is generally used in a negative sense.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا جَآءَنَا قَالَ یٰلَیۡتَ بَیۡنِیۡ وَ بَیۡنَکَ بُعۡدَ الۡمَشۡرِقَیۡنِ فَبِئۡسَ الۡقَرِیۡنُ» ( 43/38 )\nTranslation: Until when he comes to us, he will say: Would that there were a vast distance between me and you. What an evil companion you are!"
    },
    {
      "id": 1528,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«رَفِیْق» means a compassionate and kind friend (1 verse: 4:69)",
      "d": "«اَلرِّفْق» means gentle conduct, kind treatment, and that from which help is sought. And «مِرْفَقَۃ» means a small pillow (Najd). And «رَفِیْق» means a compassionate companion, kind, one who agrees and stays close (M. L). And the opposite of «رَفَقَ» is «عَنَفَ», meaning harshness and severity (M. L).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَاُولٰٓئِکَ مَعَ الَّذِیۡنَ اَنۡعَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ النَّبِیّٖنَ وَ الصِّدِّیۡقِیۡنَ وَ الشُّہَدَآءِ وَ الصّٰلِحِیۡنَ ۚ وَ حَسُنَ اُولٰٓئِکَ رَفِیۡقًا» ( 4/69 )\nTranslation: Those will be with those upon whom Allah has bestowed His favor: the Prophets, the truthful, the martyrs, and the righteous. And excellent are those as companions."
    },
    {
      "id": 1529,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«وَلِی» means helper and protector, supporter and helper (35 verses: 2:107-2:120-2:257-2:286-3:68-3:150-4:33-6:51-6:62-6:70-8:40-9:51-9:74-9:116-10:30-13:37-16:76-17:111-18:26-19:5-22:13-22:78-29:22-32:4-33:5-41:34-42:8-42:31-42:44-44:41-45:19-47:11-57:15-66:2-66:4)",
      "d": "«اَلْوَلَاءِ» means love, friendship, closeness, kinship (masc.) and «وَلِی» means helper, protector, one who comes to help in times of trouble. For example, in the Quran: «اَللّٰہُ وَلِیُّ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا ۙ یُخۡرِجُہُمۡ مِّنَ الظُّلُمٰتِ اِلَی النُّوۡرِ» (2/257) Translation: Allah is the friend of the believers who brings them out of darkness into light. And «اَلْوَلَاء» means guardianship, inheritance of legacy. And «مَوَالِی (singular مولی)» means heirs of the legacy. For more details, see under inheritance. For example, in the Quran: «وَ لِکُلٍّ جَعَلۡنَا مَوَالِیَ  مِمَّا تَرَکَ الۡوَالِدٰنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبُوۡنَ» (4/33) Translation: And for everyone, We have appointed heirs from what parents and close relatives leave behind."
    },
    {
      "id": 1530,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«صَدِیْق» one who maintains friendship, one who agrees from the heart.\nAnd «صِدّیق» truthful, honest, and one who maintains friendship (8 verses: 4:69-5:75-12:46-19:41-19:56-24:61-26:101-57:19)",
      "d": "«صَدِیْق» true and loyal friend, a friend who maintains friendship. And «صداقت» means agreement of hearts (sincere and selfless love) (Faq l 98/236).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَّ لَا عَلٰۤی  اَنۡفُسِکُمۡ اَنۡ تَاۡکُلُوۡا مِنۡۢ بُیُوۡتِکُمۡ  ۔۔۔۔۔۔۔۔۔ اَوۡ صَدِیۡقِکُمۡ» (24/61)\nTranslation: Nor is there any blame upon you for eating from your houses.... or from your friend's houses.\nAnd «صِدِّیْق» is an intensive form, meaning confidant and true friend.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«یُوۡسُفُ اَیُّہَا الصِّدِّیۡقُ اَفۡتِنَا فِیۡ سَبۡعِ بَقَرٰتٍ سِمَانٍ یَّاۡکُلُہُنَّ سَبۡعٌ عِجَافٌ» (12/46)\nTranslation: O Yusuf, the truthful one, inform us about seven fat cows; seven lean ones will devour them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1531,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«خَلِیْل» a firm and close friend with whom there is heartfelt love (3 verses: 4:125-17:73-25:28)",
      "d": "«خُلَّۃَ» and «خِلَال» mean friendship entering the heart (maternal), firm and close friendship, and «خَلِیْل» means sincere and close friend, and its plural is «اَخِلَّاء».\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ اتَّخَذَ اللّٰہُ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ خَلِیۡلًا» (4/125)\nTranslation: And Allah the Exalted made Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him) His close friend."
    },
    {
      "id": 1532,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«حَمِیْم» one who shows warm affection (19 verses: 6:70-10:4-22:19-26:101-37:67-38:57-40:18-40:72-41:34-44:46-44:48-47:15-55:44-56:42-56:54-56:93-69:35-70:10-78:25)",
      "d": "«حَمِیْم» is basically used in three meanings: (1) to be black (2) to be hot (3) to be close (maternal). And «حَمَّ» means to heat. And «حَمَّ الظَّھِیْرَۃ» means intense heat at midday (Manjad). And «حَمِیْم» means a friend who shows warm affection or a close friend.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ لَا یَسۡئَلُ  حَمِیۡمٌ حَمِیۡمًا یُّبَصَّرُوۡنَہُمۡ» (70/10,11)\nTranslation: And on that day, no friend will ask about his friend (even though they will be seeing each other face to face) (Jalandhari)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1533,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«وَلِیْجَۃ» such a trusted friend who also intervenes in affairs (1 verse: 9:16)",
      "d": "«وَلَجَ» means to enter. And «وَلِیْجَۃ» is such a friend who intervenes in someone's affairs. Trusted (i.e., one who is trusted). And its second meaning is 'a person who is also attached to another group' (Manjad). Both meanings are almost the same.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ لَمَّا یَعۡلَمِ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ جٰہَدُوۡا مِنۡکُمۡ وَ لَمۡ یَتَّخِذُوۡا مِنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ وَ لَا رَسُوۡلِہٖ وَ لَا الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ  وَلِیۡجَۃً» (9/16)\nTranslation: While Allah has not yet seen who among you strive in jihad, and does Allah take anyone other than Himself, His Messenger, and the believers as a special confidant?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1534,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«بَطَانَۃ» confidant or one who knows secrets (1 verse: 3:118)",
      "d": "«بَطَن» means belly and the inner part of everything. And «بَطَانَۃ» means secret, the inner garment (i.e., the inner cloth), a person's family and inner circle (Manjad). And «بَطَانَۃ» refers to such a friend who is a confidant or knows secrets and is familiar with someone's inner affairs (maternal).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡا بِطَانَۃً مِّنۡ دُوۡنِکُمۡ لَا یَاۡلُوۡنَکُمۡ خَبَالًا» (3/118)\nTranslation: O believers, do not take as confidant anyone other than yourselves, for they will not fail to cause you harm."
    },
    {
      "id": 1535,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«خَذُوْل» one who betrays when the time comes (3 verses: 3:160-17:22-25:29)",
      "d": "«خَذَل» means not to help someone and to abandon them. And «خَذُوْل» refers to such a friend who verbally upholds friendship but abandons when the time comes (Manjad), a betrayer.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ کَانَ الشَّیۡطٰنُ لِلۡاِنۡسَانِ خَذُوۡلًا» (25/29)\nTranslation: And Satan is a betrayer to man."
    },
    {
      "id": 1536,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«اَخْدَان» acquaintances, companions, immoral friends (2 verses: 4:25-5:5)",
      "d": "«اَخْدَان» is the plural of «خِدْنُ» and «خِذْنَۃٌ», meaning companion, immoral person, amorous, companion, acquaintance, immoral, friend, one who has secret friendships, one who fulfills sexual desires. It is used for both masculine and feminine.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«مُحۡصَنٰتٍ غَیۡرَ مُسٰفِحٰتٍ وَّ لَا مُتَّخِذٰتِ اَخۡدَانٍ» (4/25)\nTranslation: Chaste women, neither promiscuous nor those who take secret companions."
    },
    {
      "id": 1537,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«تَوَلّٰی» is used in the meaning of making someone a friend (2 verses: 7:196-22:4)",
      "d": "«تَوَلّٰی» is used in the meaning of making someone a friend.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«کُتِبَ عَلَیۡہِ  اَنَّہٗ  مَنۡ تَوَلَّاہُ  فَاَنَّہٗ یُضِلُّہٗ» (22/4)\nTranslation: It is decreed for him that whoever takes him as a friend, he will mislead him."
    }
  ],
  "333": [
    {
      "id": 1538,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دھتکارا",
      "s": "«دھتکارا ہوا» means accursed and cursed (6 verses: 3:36-15:17-15:34-16:98-38:77-81:25)",
      "d": "«رَجَم» means to throw stones or pebbles from a distance (maternal), used in both material and spiritual senses. And «رَجِیْم» means accursed, rejected.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَاِذَا  قَرَاۡتَ الۡقُرۡاٰنَ  فَاسۡتَعِذۡ بِاللّٰہِ مِنَ  الشَّیۡطٰنِ  الرَّجِیۡمِ» (16/98)\nTranslation: So when you recite the Quran, seek refuge with Allah from the accursed Satan."
    }
  ],
  "334": [
    {
      "id": 1541,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To become dim; to appear cloudy",
      "hw": "دھندلا",
      "s": "«اِنْکَدَرَ» is used for something's color fading or becoming muddy (1 verse: 81:2)",
      "d": "«کَدَرٌ» means muddiness; its opposite is «صَفَاءٌ» (clarity). And «کُدْرَۃٌ» means the color becoming muddy, faded, or light (mudh). For example, the Quran states: «وَ  اِذَا  النُّجُوۡمُ  انۡکَدَرَتۡ» (81/2). Translation: And when the stars lose their light."
    },
    {
      "id": 1542,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To become dim; to appear cloudy",
      "hw": "دھندلا",
      "s": "«اَبْیَضَّ عَیْنُہٗ» is used for an eye losing its light (12 verses: 2:187, 3:106, 3:107, 7:108, 12:84, 20:22, 26:33, 27:12, 28:32, 35:27, 37:46, 37:49)",
      "d": "«بَیَاض» means whiteness; its opposite is «سَوَاد» (blackness). «بَیَاضُ الْعَیْن» means the whiteness of the eye. «اِبْیَضَّتْ عَیۡنٰہُ» means his eye became white or lost its light. For example, the Quran states: «وَ ابۡیَضَّتۡ عَیۡنٰہُ مِنَ الۡحُزۡنِ فَہُوَ کَظِیۡمٌ» (12/84). Translation: And Jacob's eyes turned white from grief, and he was suppressing his pain."
    }
  ],
  "335": [
    {
      "id": 1545,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Smoke",
      "hw": "دھواں",
      "s": "«دُخَان» means smoke (2 verses: 41:11, 44:10)",
      "d": "«دُخَان» means smoke. It is a well-known term. However, Imam Raghib specified that it refers to smoke that emerges with flames of fire (mudh), even though smoke can emerge before fire. It is still called «دُخَان». For example, the Quran states: «ثُمَّ  اسۡتَوٰۤی  اِلَی السَّمَآءِ وَ ہِیَ دُخَانٌ» (41/11). Translation: Then Allah turned towards the heaven, which was (then) but smoke."
    },
    {
      "id": 1546,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Smoke",
      "hw": "دھواں",
      "s": "«نُحَاس» refers to smoke with a copper-like color (1 verse: 55:35)",
      "d": "«نُحَاس» means copper. It refers to fire with a color like copper, and also to smoke in which flames of copper-colored fire are intertwined (mudh)—red, intensely hot smoke. When fire and smoke are mixed, this quality is produced. For example, the Quran states: «یُرۡسَلُ عَلَیۡکُمَا شُوَاظٌ مِّنۡ نَّارٍ ۙ وَّ نُحَاسٌ فَلَا  تَنۡتَصِرٰنِ» (55/35). Translation: A flame of fire and copper-like smoke will be sent upon you both; then you will not be able to resist."
    },
    {
      "id": 1547,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Smoke",
      "hw": "دھواں",
      "s": "«یَحْمُوْم» refers to thick, black smoke (1 verse: 56:43)",
      "d": "One of the basic meanings of «حَمَّ» is also 'to be black' (m. l.). «حُمَّۃ» means a pit of coals, ashes, and everything mixed in fire (manjadd). «یَحْمُوْم» refers to smoke that is both hot and black and thick. For example, the Quran states: «فِیۡ  سَمُوۡمٍ  وَّ  حَمِیۡمٍ وَّ ظِلٍّ  مِّنۡ  یَّحۡمُوۡمٍ» (56:42-43). Translation: In scorching heat and boiling water, and in the shade of black smoke."
    }
  ],
  "336": [
    {
      "id": 1548,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Sunlight",
      "hw": "دھوپ",
      "s": "«شَمْس» means sun and is also used for sunlight (32 verses: 2:258, 6:78, 6:96, 7:54, 10:5, 12:4, 13:2, 14:33, 16:12, 17:78, 18:17, 18:86, 18:90, 20:130, 21:33, 22:18, 25:45, 27:24, 29:61, 31:29, 35:13, 36:38, 36:40, 39:5, 41:37, 50:39, 55:5, 71:16, 75:9, 76:13, 81:1, 91:1)",
      "d": "«شَمْس» means both the sun's disc and sunlight. «شَمَسَ یَوْمُنَا» means our day is sunny, not clouded (mudh). «شَمَّسَ» means to expose someone to sunlight. When «شَمْس» refers to sunlight, it can refer to any time, but generally it implies intense sunlight and its heat. For example, the Quran states: «لَا یَرَوۡنَ فِیۡہَا شَمۡسًا وَّ  لَا  زَمۡہَرِیۡرًا» (76:13). Translation: They will not see therein (any) intense sunlight or severe cold."
    },
    {
      "id": 1549,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Sunlight",
      "hw": "دھوپ",
      "s": "«ضُحٰی» means the sunlight of the forenoon (7 verses: 7:98, 20:59, 20:119, 79:29, 79:46, 91:1, 93:1)",
      "d": "«ضُحٰی» means the time when the sun rises high and its light spreads—the time of forenoon. It applies both to that time and to the sunlight of that time (mudh). For example, the Quran states: «وَ اَغۡطَشَ لَیۡلَہَا وَ اَخۡرَجَ ضُحٰہَا» (79:29). Translation: And He made its night dark and brought forth its forenoon brightness."
    },
    {
      "id": 1550,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Sunlight",
      "hw": "دھوپ",
      "s": "«حَرّ» means the intense midday sunlight (2 verses: 9:81, 16:81)",
      "d": "«حَرَّ» and «حَرَارَت» mean heat and the time of heat. Since the time of heat is connected to the sun and the intensity of sunlight (heat), the intense midday sun is also called «حَرّ», as is the hot season. For example, the Quran states: «وَ قَالُوۡا لَا تَنۡفِرُوۡا فِی الۡحَرِّ ؕ قُلۡ نَارُ جَہَنَّمَ اَشَدُّ حَرًّا» (9:81). Translation: And they said, 'Do not go forth in the heat.' Say, 'The fire of Hell is more intense in heat.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1551,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Sunlight",
      "hw": "دھوپ",
      "s": "«حَرُوْر» refers to heat waves arising from intense sunlight (1 verse: 35:21)",
      "d": "The opposite of «حَرُوْر» is «ظَلّ» (shade). «حَرُوْر» means hot wind, heat waves that arise from intense sunlight (mudh). For example, the Quran states: «وَ لَا الظُّلُمٰتُ وَ لَا  النُّوۡرُ وَ لَا الظِّلُّ  وَ لَا  الۡحَرُوۡرُ» (35:20-21). Translation: And neither are the darknesses and the light equal, nor the shade and the heat."
    }
  ],
  "337": [
    {
      "id": 1552,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To Deceive",
      "hw": "دھوکا",
      "s": "«غَرَّ» means to deceive by taking advantage of someone's negligence (21 verses: 3:24-3:185-3:196-4:120-6:70-6:112-6:130-7:22-7:51-8:49-17:64-31:33-33:12-35:5-35:40-40:4-45:35-57:14-57:20-67:20-82:6)",
      "d": "«غَرَّ» means to take advantage of someone's heedlessness to deceive them, to trick (masc.), and «غُرُوْر» and «مَتَاعُ الْغُرُوْر» mean «اَبَاطِیْلُ الدُّنْیَا» (vanities of the world), and «غُرُوْر» means to deceive, and «غَرُوْر» (with fatḥa on غ) means the deceiver. And «غُرُوْر» means every delusion that causes trouble to humans, like giving water to a thirsty person (faq l 214). For example, in the Quran: «وَ غَرَّتۡکُمُ الۡاَمَانِیُّ حَتّٰی جَآءَ  اَمۡرُ اللّٰہِ  وَ غَرَّکُمۡ بِاللّٰہِ الۡغَرُوۡرُ» (57/14) Translation: And your vain desires have deceived you until the command of Allah came, and the deceiver has deceived you about Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1553,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Deception",
      "hw": "دھوکا",
      "s": "«خَدَعَ» means to hide the truth to achieve one's objective and deceive the opponent (3 verses: 2:9-4:142-8:62)",
      "d": "«خَدَعَ» means to keep someone in darkness by concealing the truth (M. L.) and to hide the correct path from someone so that they fall into undesirable actions (F. L. 214). By showing something other than what is in the heart to turn someone away from what they desire. To trick (Muf) and «طَرِیْقَ الْخُدُوٌع» refers to a path that sometimes appears and sometimes disappears. And the Messenger of Allah ﷺ said: 'War is stratagem.' Here «خُدْعَۃٌ» does not mean deception or trickery but rather a war tactic, such as arranging the army in a way that seems much larger than it is, or feigning retreat to lure the enemy into an ambush. Thus, by such tactics, the opponent is kept in darkness while one's objective is achieved. There is no deception or trickery in this. And if the intention is good, it is permissible; otherwise, it is not.\n\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«یُخٰدِعُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ وَ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا ۚ وَ مَا یَخۡدَعُوۡنَ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ» (2/9)\nTranslation: The hypocrites seek to deceive Allah and the believers, but in reality, they deceive only themselves."
    },
    {
      "id": 1554,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Deception",
      "hw": "دھوکا",
      "s": "«خَانَ» means to secretly breach a covenant, trust, or commit treachery in religion (8 verses: 4:105-5:13-8:27-8:58-8:71-12:52-40:19-66:10)",
      "d": "«خَانَ» means to secretly break a covenant. And this word is specific for covenant, trust, and hypocrisy (treachery in religion) (Muf). And «خَوَّان» is the intensive form meaning a great deceiver, a major traitor.\n\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ  اِمَّا  تَخَافَنَّ مِنۡ قَوۡمٍ خِیَانَۃً  فَانۡۢبِذۡ اِلَیۡہِمۡ عَلٰی سَوَآءٍ ؕ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ  لَا یُحِبُّ الۡخَآئِنِیۡنَ» (8/58)\nTranslation: And if you fear treachery from a people, then throw back their covenant to them on equal terms. Indeed, Allah does not like the treacherous."
    },
    {
      "id": 1555,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Deception",
      "hw": "دھوکا",
      "s": "«خَذَلَ» means to deceive a friend when the time comes (3 verses: 3:160-17:22-25:29)",
      "d": "«خَذَلَ» refers to one who verbally professes friendship but betrays when needed (see details under 'friend')."
    },
    {
      "id": 1557,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Deception",
      "hw": "دھوکا",
      "s": "«خَتَرَ» means to act treacherously in a bad way and continuously (1 verse: 31:32)",
      "d": "«خَتَرَ» means to act treacherously in a vile manner. And «تَخَتَّرَ» means to be weak, to be sluggish (Munjid). According to Imam Raghib, «اَلْخَتْر» is such treachery done with so much effort that a person becomes weak and their limbs become limp (Muf), i.e., to continue deceiving and acting treacherously.\n\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ مَا یَجۡحَدُ بِاٰیٰتِنَاۤ  اِلَّا  کُلُّ  خَتَّارٍ  کَفُوۡرٍ» (31/32)\nTranslation: And none deny Our signs except every treacherous ingrate."
    }
  ],
  "338": [
    {
      "id": 1558,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Seeing",
      "hw": "دیکھنا",
      "s": "«رَاٰی» is used for contemplating something (56 verses: 3:143-4:61-6:40-6:46-6:47-6:68-10:50-10:59-11:28-11:63-11:88-12:4-17:62-18:63-19:77-20:92-21:36-25:43-26:75-26:205-27:10-27:40-28:31-28:71-28:72-33:19-35:8-35:40-39:37:55-38-41:52-45:23-46:4-46:10-47:20-53:13-53:19-53:33-56:58-56:63-56:68-56:71-59:21-63:4-63:5-67:28-67:30-76:19-76:20-81:23-96:7-96:9-96:11-96:13-107:1-110:2)",
      "d": "«رَاٰی» means to perceive something, to see, whether through eyesight or through contemplation, intellect, insight, or imagination and thought. Its usage is general, whether in a state of wakefulness or in a dream, and it means the final look. To see with contemplation and reflection. To perceive something with the eyes.\n\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«اِنِّیۡ  رَاَیۡتُ اَحَدَعَشَرَ کَوۡکَبًا» (12/4)\nTranslation: I saw eleven stars.\n\nAnd to contemplate and reflect on something to perceive it.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«اَرَءَیۡتَ  الَّذِیۡ یُکَذِّبُ بِالدِّیۡنِ» (107/1)\nTranslation: Have you seen the one who denies the Recompense?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1559,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Seeing",
      "hw": "دیکھنا",
      "s": "«نَظَرَ» is generally used for looking (102 verses: 2:50-2:55-2:104-2:162-2:210-2:259-2:280-3:77-3:88-3:137-3:143-4:46-4:50-5:75-6:8-6:11-6:24-6:46-6:65-6:99-6:158-7:14-7:15-7:53-7:84-7:86-7:103-7:129-7:143-7:185-7:195-7:198-8:6-9:127-10:14-10:39-10:43-10:71-10:73-10:101-11:55-12:109-15:8-15:36-15:37-16:33-16:36-16:85-17:21-17:48-18:19-20:97-21:40-22:15-25:9-26:203-27:14-27:27-27:28-27:33-27:41-27:51-27:69-28:40-29:20-30:9-30:42-30:50-32:29-33:19-35:43-35:44-36:49-37:19-37:73-37:88-37:102-38:15-38:79-38:80-39:68-40:21-40:82-42:45-43:25-43:66-44:29-47:10-47:18-47:20-50:6-51:44-56:84-57:13-59:18-74:21-78:40-80:24-83:23-83:35-86:5-88:17)",
      "d": "«نَظَرَ» means to look, to see, so that something becomes visible, whether that thing is seen or not. Its usage is also in both ways.\n\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ  اِذَا مَاۤ  اُنۡزِلَتۡ سُوۡرَۃٌ  نَّظَرَ  بَعۡضُہُمۡ اِلٰی بَعۡضٍ» (9/127)\nTranslation: And whenever a surah is revealed, some of them look at others.\n\nAt another place, the Divine command says:\n«فَانۡظُرِیۡ مَاذَا تَاۡمُرِیۡنَ» (27/33)\nTranslation: Then see what you will command.\n\nHowever, the usage of 'nazar' generally pertains to seeing with the eyes."
    },
    {
      "id": 1562,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Seeing",
      "hw": "دیکھنا",
      "s": "«زَارَ» is used for going to see something or to visit (1 verse: 102:2)",
      "d": "«زَارَہٗ» means to go to meet someone (Munjid) and to mean to come to see something and to meet it. To visit (M. Q). And «زَوْر» means the upper part of the chest. And «زُرۡتُ فَلَانًا» means I turned my chest towards him or intended his chest, i.e., to meet (Muf).\n\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«اَلۡہٰکُمُ  التَّکَاثُرُ حَتّٰی زُرۡتُمُ  الۡمَقَابِرَ» (102/1,2)\nTranslation: You are preoccupied with rivalry in worldly increase until you visit the graves."
    },
    {
      "id": 1563,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Seeing (Quality of Sight)",
      "hw": "دیکھنا",
      "s": "«شَخَصَ» means the eyes becoming fixed (2 verses: 14:42-21:97)",
      "d": "«شَخَصَ» means for the eyes to become fixed, to lose light, and not to blink (F. L. 103).\n\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ اقۡتَرَبَ الۡوَعۡدُ الۡحَقُّ فَاِذَا ہِیَ شَاخِصَۃٌ  اَبۡصَارُ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا» (21/97)\nTranslation: And the true promise will approach, then behold, the sights of the disbelievers will be fixed."
    },
    {
      "id": 1564,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Seeing (Quality of Sight)",
      "hw": "دیکھنا",
      "s": "«لَمَحَ» means the blinking of the eye (2 verses: 16:77-54:50)",
      "d": "«لَمَحَ» means the swiftness of a glance. To look quickly at something. The blinking of the eye (F. L. 102).\n\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ مَاۤ اَمۡرُ السَّاعَۃِ  اِلَّا کَلَمۡحِ الۡبَصَرِ اَوۡ ہُوَ اَقۡرَبُ» (16/77)\nTranslation: And the coming of the Hour is no more than the blink of an eye or even quicker."
    },
    {
      "id": 1565,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Seeing (Quality of Sight)",
      "hw": "دیکھنا",
      "s": "«ھَطَعَ» means to look with fixed gaze while running (3 verses: 14:43-54:8-70:36)",
      "d": "«ھَطَعَ» means to look with fixed gaze while running.\n\n«مُہۡطِعِیۡنَ مُقۡنِعِیۡ رُءُوۡسِہِمۡ لَا یَرۡتَدُّ اِلَیۡہِمۡ  طَرۡفُہُمۡ» (14/43)\nTranslation: People will be running with their heads raised, their glances not returning to them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1568,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To see (quality of sight)",
      "hw": "دیکھنا",
      "s": "«زَاغَ البَصَر»: the sight becoming weary and deviating (4 verses: 33:10-38:63-53:17-61:5)",
      "d": "«زَاغَ البَصَر» means to deviate from the path of truth. And «زَاغَ الْبَصَرُ» means the sight becoming weary (according to Majid) and, according to Imam Raghib, the sight erred and turned aside. For example, the Quran states: «مَا زَاغَ الۡبَصَرُ وَ مَا طَغٰی» (53/17). Translation: (The Prophet's ﷺ) sight neither deviated nor transgressed."
    },
    {
      "id": 1571,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To show",
      "hw": "دکھلانا",
      "s": "«بَصَّرَ»: to show in such a way that another recognizes (1 verse: 70:11)",
      "d": "«بَصَّرَ» means to show so that another understands and recognizes. To make aware through signs and indications (muf). For example, the Quran states: «وَ لَا یَسۡئَلُ حَمِیۡمٌ حَمِیۡمًا یُّبَصَّرُوۡنَہُمۡ» (70/11). Translation: No friend will ask about his friend (even though) they will be seeing each other face to face."
    }
  ],
  "340": [
    {
      "id": 1574,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Religion (Sharia)",
      "hw": "دین",
      "s": "«شَرِیْعَۃ»: those divine commands that change according to the needs of the time (4 verses: 5:48-42:13-42:21-45:48)",
      "d": "The lexical meaning of «شَرَعَ» is to establish a clear path (muf). And «شَرِیْعَۃ» refers to those commands that change according to the needs and circumstances of the time. For example, among Adam's children, marriage between siblings was permissible because it was an emergency (compulsory) matter, which was later forbidden in subsequent Sharias. In the marriage of Ya'qub, there were two full sisters, which was later forbidden. Similarly, in that era, prostration of reverence was permissible, which was later forbidden. In previous Sharias, benefit from wealth was not permissible, which was made permissible for the Muslim Ummah. In short, there are numerous such examples. The difference between 'Din' (religion) and 'Sharia' was explained by the Prophet ﷺ himself in these words: «اَلْاَنْبِیَاءُ اِخْوَۃُ الْعَلَّاتِ أُمَّھَاتُھُمْ شَتّٰی وَ دِیْنُھُمْ وَاحِدٌ» (Agreed upon). \"The Prophets are paternal half-brothers (brothers who share the same father but have different mothers). Their mothers (i.e., their Sharias) are different, and their religion (i.e., their father) is one.\" For example, the Quran states: «شَرَعَ لَکُمۡ مِّنَ الدِّیۡنِ» (42/13). Translation: He (Allah) has established for you a path from the religion."
    },
    {
      "id": 1575,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Religion (Millat)",
      "hw": "دین",
      "s": "«مِلَّت»: that system which a prophet establishes among his followers (adherents) by enforcing divine commands (15 verses: 2:120-2:130-2:135-3:95-4:125-6:161-7:88-7:89-12:37-12:38-14:13-16:123-18:20-22:78-38:7)",
      "d": "In Din and Sharia, everything is mentioned in the divinely revealed book. First, the prophet himself is bound to act upon those commands. Along with that, he propagates those divine commands, forms a community of followers, makes all of them bound to those commands, and establishes the Islamic system. The name of this system is Millat. Thus, Millat is not the name of commands and decrees but the name of that system in which the prophet is the leader, and the followers of that prophet are appointed, and their constitution is the divine commands (Din, Sharia), and obedience to the leader is made obligatory upon the community. Translators briefly write the translation of Millat as 'Din', although Din is one for all prophets; however, Millat can be attributed only to a specific prophet. For example, the Quran states: «فَاتَّبِعُوۡا مِلَّۃَ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ حَنِیۡفًا» (3/95). Translation: So follow the Millat of Ibrahim, who was upright and turned away from all that is false."
    }
  ],
  "341": [
    {
      "id": 1576,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To give",
      "hw": "دینا",
      "s": "«اٰتٰی»: to give something to someone (150 verses: 2:43-2:53-2:63-2:83-2:87-2:93-2:110-2:121-2:146-2:177-2:200-2:201-2:211-2:229-2:233-2:251-2:253-2:258-2:265-2:277-3:81-3:148-3:170-3:180-3:194-4:2-4:4-4:19-4:20-4:24-4:25-4:33-4:37-4:54-4:67-4:77-4:153-4:163-5:5-5:12-5:20-5:46-5:48-6:20-6:83-6:89-6:114-6:141-6:154-6:165-7:38-7:144-7:171-7:175-7:189-7:190-9:5-9:11-9:18-9:59-9:75-9:76-10:88-11:28-11:63-11:110-12:22-12:31-12:66-12:101-13:36-14:34-15:81-15:87-16:55-16:122-17:2-17:26-17:55-17:59-17:101-18:10-18:33-18:62-18:65-18:84-18:96-19:12-19:30-20:99-21:48-21:51-21:74-21:79-21:84-22:41-22:78-23:49-23:60-24:33-24:56-25:35-27:7-27:15-27:36-27:39-27:40-28:14-28:29-28:43-28:52-28:76-28:77-29:27-29:47-29:66-30:34-30:38-30:39-31:12-32:13-32:23-33:33-33:50-33:51-33:68-34:10-34:44-34:45-35:40-37:117-38:20-40:53-41:45-43:21-44:33-45:16-45:17-47:17-51:16-52:18-57:23-57:27-58:13-59:7-60:10-60:11-65:6-65:7-73:20)",
      "d": "«اٰتٰی» means to give. To give something to someone. It is used in common meanings and is general in usage. For example, the Quran states: «وَ اٰتَی الۡمَالَ عَلٰی حُبِّہٖ» (2/177). Translation: And he gives his wealth out of love for it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1577,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To give",
      "hw": "دینا",
      "s": "«اَعْطٰی»: to give as a reward, favor, or in return for service and obedience (11 verses: 9:29-9:58-11:108-17:20-20:50-38:39-53:34-78:36-92:5-93:5-108:1)",
      "d": "«اَعْطٰی» comes in two meanings: (1) to give something to someone purely as a gift (muf). For example, the Quran states: «قَالَ رَبُّنَا الَّذِیۡۤ اَعۡطٰی کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ خَلۡقَہٗ ثُمَّ ہَدٰی» (20/50). Translation: Musa (Moses) ﷺ said to Pharaoh: Our Lord is He who gave everything its form and shape, then guided it. And «اَعْطٰی» also means to be obedient and submissive and to serve (according to Majid). Therefore, to give someone more in return for their service, effort, and obedience is also «اَعْطٰی». A gift, reward, given gladly and more than the effort or service. For example, the Quran states: «وَ اَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ سُعِدُوۡا فَفِی الۡجَنَّۃِ خٰلِدِیۡنَ فِیۡہَا مَا دَامَتِ السَّمٰوٰتُ وَ الۡاَرۡضُ اِلَّا مَا شَآءَ رَبُّکَ ؕ عَطَآءً غَیۡرَ مَجۡذُوۡذٍ» (11/108). Translation: But those who are blessed will be in Paradise, abiding therein as long as the heavens and earth endure, except what your Lord wills: a gift without end."
    },
    {
      "id": 1578,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To give",
      "hw": "دینا",
      "s": "«اَدَاءٌ»: to pay rights and settle financial transactions (2 verses: 2:178-2:283)",
      "d": "«اَدَاءٌ» means to give someone their right fully and completely at once. This word is generally used for transactions like lending, borrowing, and dues, etc. For example, the Quran states: «فَاِنۡ اَمِنَ بَعۡضُکُمۡ بَعۡضًا فَلۡیُؤَدِّ الَّذِی اؤۡتُمِنَ اَمَانَتَہٗ» (2/283). Translation: And if one of you entrusts another, then the trustee should fulfill his trust and return it to its owner."
    },
    {
      "id": 1580,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To give",
      "hw": "دینا",
      "s": "«اَثَابَ»: more general than «اَعْطٰی»; to give a reward greater than the actual compensation for any deed (3 verses: 3:153-5:85-48:18)",
      "d": "«اَثَابَ» is more general than «اَعْطٰی». It comes for the compensation of any deed, whether good or bad. However, this word is generally used for the reward of good deeds. Also, like «اَعْطٰی», it has the particularity that the compensation for the deed is given fully or more. For example, the Quran states: «فَاَثَابَہُمُ اللّٰہُ بِمَا قَالُوۡا جَنّٰتٍ تَجۡرِیۡ مِنۡ تَحۡتِہَا الۡاَنۡہٰرُ» (5/85). Translation: So Allah rewarded them for what they said with gardens beneath which rivers flow."
    },
    {
      "id": 1581,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To give",
      "hw": "دینا",
      "s": "«وَھْبَ»: to give without compensation and not expecting any return or benefit later (21 verses: 3:8-3:38-6:84-14:39-19:5-19:19-19:49-19:50-19:53-21:72-21:90-25:74-26:21-26:83-29:27-33:50-37:100-38:30-38:35-38:43-42:49)",
      "d": "«وَھْبَ» means to give something to someone without compensation and effort, and not expecting any benefit or return later (muf). For example, the Quran states: «یَہَبُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ اِنَاثًا وَّ یَہَبُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ الذُّکُوۡرَ» (42/49). Translation: Allah grants daughters to whom He wills, and grants sons to whom He wills."
    },
    {
      "id": 1582,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To give",
      "hw": "دینا",
      "s": "«رَفَدَ»: to give aid, stipend, or support to a poor and needy person (1 verse: 11:99)",
      "d": "«رَفَدَ» means to give and help. Its meanings basically include two things: giving something to a poor and needy person as a gift; giving a stipend; fixing a stipend. And «رَفَادَہ» is that fund which the Quraysh used to collect to help poor pilgrims. And «اَرْفَدَ» means to fix a gift for someone so that they keep taking from that fixed amount (muf). And «رَفَدَ» means stipend, aid. For example, the Quran states: «وَ اُتۡبِعُوۡا فِیۡ ہٰذِہٖ لَعۡنَۃً وَّ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ ؕ بِئۡسَ الرِّفۡدُ الۡمَرۡفُوۡدُ» (11/99). Translation: And they were followed in this (world) with a curse, and on the Day of Resurrection. Evil is the gift that will be given to them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1584,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Gift",
      "hw": "دینا",
      "s": "«ھَدِیَّۃ» Giving gifts and presents to strengthen relationships (1 verse: 27:35)",
      "d": "«ھَدِیَّۃ» refers to those gifts which we present to each other to strengthen relationships. And «مِھْدٰی» refers to the thing in which the gift is placed.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَمَاۤ  اٰتٰىنِۦَ اللّٰہُ خَیۡرٌ  مِّمَّاۤ   اٰتٰىکُمۡ  ۚ بَلۡ  اَنۡتُمۡ  بِہَدِیَّتِکُمۡ  تَفۡرَحُوۡنَ» (27/36)\nTranslation: (Prophet Solomon PBUH said) What Allah has given me is better than what you have given, so remain happy with your gift."
    }
  ],
  "342": [
    {
      "id": 1586,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Wall",
      "hw": "دیوار",
      "s": "«جِدَار» A wall of a building or enclosure (3 verses: 18:77-18:82-59:14)",
      "d": "«جِدَار» comes from the plurals «جُدُر» and «جُدْرَان». «جِدَار» refers to any one of the walls of a building or fortress. «جَدَرَ» means to be surrounded by walls (as per Manjad), and in the words of Ibn al-Faris, «ھُوَ الْحَائِطُ» meaning the wall of an enclosed structure.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ اَمَّا الۡجِدَارُ فَکَانَ لِغُلٰمَیۡنِ یَتِیۡمَیۡنِ فِی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ» (18/82)\nTranslation: And as for the wall, it belonged to two orphaned boys in the city."
    },
    {
      "id": 1587,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Wall",
      "hw": "دیوار",
      "s": "«سَدّ» A barrier or wall built between two things that serves as an obstruction (3 verses: 18:93-18:94-36:9)",
      "d": "«سَدّ» means obstruction. A barrier. A large wall built between two things that serves as an obstruction and is constructed. And if this wall or barrier is natural, it is called «سُدّ» (muf) and «سَدَّ» means to seal a crack with stones. And «سِدَاد» refers to the method with which crevices, holes, or cracks are filled, and «سُدَّۃ» in the terminology of physicians refers to the lodging of corrupt matter in the intestines.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَہَلۡ نَجۡعَلُ لَکَ خَرۡجًا عَلٰۤی اَنۡ  تَجۡعَلَ بَیۡنَنَا وَ  بَیۡنَہُمۡ  سَدًّا» (18/94)\nTranslation: (O Dhul-Qarnayn!) Should we collect some money for you so that you build a barrier between us and them?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1588,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Wall",
      "hw": "دیوار",
      "s": "«رَدْم» A wall or barrier whose all holes and cracks are sealed (1 verse: 18:95)",
      "d": "«رَدْم» This word is more specific than «سَدّ». That is, a wall or barrier whose all holes and cracks are sealed (muf). A thick wall. A strong barrier. And «رَدَمَ» means to seal crevices, holes, or cracks. And «رَدْمَ الثَّوْب» means to patch a garment (manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَاَعِیۡنُوۡنِیۡ بِقُوَّۃٍ  اَجۡعَلۡ بَیۡنَکُمۡ وَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ  رَدۡمًا» (18/95)\nTranslation: (Dhul-Qarnayn replied) Give me strength from your manpower so that I may build a strong barrier between you and them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1589,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Wall",
      "hw": "دیوار",
      "s": "«سُوْر» A high wall of a fortress or enclosure that cannot be scaled (2 verses: 38:21-57:13)",
      "d": "«سُوْر» A high wall of a fortress or enclosure that cannot be scaled. In the words of Ibn al-Faris, «یَدُلُّ عَلٰی عُلُوِّ وَ اِرْتِفَاعِ (م ۔ ل)» meaning a high and elevated wall that cannot be scaled over. And this wall is not of a building but of a fortress enclosure or fence. And «سُوْرَۃ اَلْمَدِیْنَۃ» refers to the city of refuge (muf).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَضُرِبَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ بِسُوۡرٍ لَّہٗ  بَابٌ» (57/13)\nTranslation: So a wall will be placed between them, having a gate."
    },
    {
      "id": 1590,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Wall",
      "hw": "دیوار",
      "s": "«بُنْیَان» A wall or structure whose parts are firmly interlocked and rooted (6 verses: 9:109-9:110-16:26-18:21-37:97-61:4)",
      "d": "«بَنٰی» means to build. To construct a building, such that all its parts are interlocked. And «بُنْیَان» refers to any construction that fulfills this condition, whether it is just a foundation, a wall, or a complete building.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُحِبُّ الَّذِیۡنَ یُقَاتِلُوۡنَ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِہٖ  صَفًّا کَاَنَّہُمۡ  بُنۡیَانٌ  مَّرۡصُوۡصٌ» (61/4)\nTranslation: Allah loves those who fight in His cause in ranks, as if they were a wall cemented firmly."
    }
  ],
  "343": [
    {
      "id": 1592,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Madness. Insanity",
      "hw": "دیوانہ",
      "s": "«خَبَطَ» Impairment and deficiency in intellect, which is temporary (1 verse: 2:275)",
      "d": "«خَبَطَ» means to beat someone until they lose consciousness (muf). And «مَخْبُوط» means mentally impaired (i.e., a person whose intellect has been impaired). That is, whose intellect does not function properly. According to Arabs, this was also due to jinn and devils.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ یَاۡکُلُوۡنَ الرِّبٰوا لَا یَقُوۡمُوۡنَ اِلَّا کَمَا یَقُوۡمُ الَّذِیۡ یَتَخَبَّطُہُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ مِنَ الۡمَسِّ» (2/275)\nTranslation: Those who consume usury will not stand except as one stands who is driven to madness by the touch of the devil.\nThe difference between «خَبَط» and «جُنُوْن» is that «خَبَط» is a temporary illness, while «جُنُوْن» is long-term."
    },
    {
      "id": 1593,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Madness. Insanity",
      "hw": "دیوانہ",
      "s": "«مَفْتُوْن» Madness caused by events of the time (1 verse: 68:6)",
      "d": "«فَتَنَ» means to entice into temptation. To allure, incline, and cause amazement. And «مَفْتُوْن» means mad and insane (manjad). And «مَفْتُوْن» refers to such a mad person whom events of time have made mentally impaired and unconscious.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَسَتُبۡصِرُ وَ یُبۡصِرُوۡنَ بِاَىیِّکُمُ  الۡمَفۡتُوۡنُ» (68/6)\nTranslation: So you will see and they will see which of you is insane."
    },
    {
      "id": 1594,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Madness. Insanity",
      "hw": "دیوانہ",
      "s": "«سُعُر» Impairment resulting from immediate agitation of nature (2 verses: 54:24-54:47)",
      "d": "«سَعَرَ» means for fire to blaze and flames to emerge. Then metaphorically, this word is also used in the meanings of inciting or becoming agitated. «اِسْتَعَرَّ الِلصَّوْص» means the robbers became agitated. «اِسْتَعَرَّ الْحَرَب» means the battle blazed. And «مِسْعَرْ» refers to the stick with which fire is kindled (muf). And «سُعُر» refers to such madness where a person immediately becomes agitated over something and starts doing wrong, and his intellect does not function properly. Foolish.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَقَالُوۡۤا اَبَشَرًا مِّنَّا وَاحِدًا نَّتَّبِعُہٗۤ ۙ اِنَّاۤ  اِذًا  لَّفِیۡ ضَلٰلٍ  وَّ  سُعُرٍ» (54/24)\nTranslation: They said, 'Shall we follow a human being from among ourselves? Then indeed we would be in error and madness.'"
    }
  ],
  "344": [
    {
      "id": 1595,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To throw",
      "hw": "ڈالنا",
      "s": "«اَلْقٰی» To throw, cast, or place something in such a way that others can see it (66 verses: 2:37-3:44-4:90-4:91-4:94-4:171-5:64-7:115-7:107-7:116-7:117-7:120-7:150-8:12-10:80-10:81-12:10-12:93-12:96-15:19-16:15-16:28-16:86-16:87-17:39-20:20-20:39-20:65-20:66-20:69-20:70-20:87-22:52-22:53-25:8-25:13-26:32-26:43-26:44-26:45-26:46-26:223-27:6-27:10-27:28-27:29-28:7-28:31-28:86-31:10-37:97-38:34-40:15-41:35-41:40-43:53-50:7-50:24-50:26-50:37-54:25-60:1-67:7-67:8-75:15-84:4)",
      "d": "«لَقِیَ» means for two opposing things to meet face to face. To meet. But in the chapter of verbs, the basic meanings change. «اَلْقٰی» means to throw, cast, or place something in such a way that others can see it (muf).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَاَلۡقٰی عَصَاہُ  فَاِذَا ہِیَ ثُعۡبَانٌ  مُّبِیۡنٌ» (7/107)\nTranslation: So he threw his staff, and at once it was a clear serpent.\nAnd «اَلْقٰی» is also used metaphorically.\nFor example, the divine command says:\n«وَ اَلۡقَیۡتُ عَلَیۡکَ مَحَبَّۃً مِّنِّیۡ» (20/39)\nTranslation: And I have cast upon you love from Me.\nThen this word is also used for 'implanting a thought in the heart', and it is called «اِلْقَاء». This discussion is in 'implanting a thought in the heart'."
    },
    {
      "id": 1596,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To Throw",
      "hw": "ڈالنا",
      "s": "«سَلَکَ» to throw one thing into another, to insert (12 verses: 15:12-16:69-20:53-23:27-26:200-28:32-39:21-69:32-71:20-72:17-72:27-74:42)",
      "d": "The discussion of «سَلَکَ» has passed under 'to insert'. Its basic meaning is to draw one thing into another or to place one thing into another. In this sense, this word sometimes means 'to throw'.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«اُسۡلُکۡ یَدَکَ فِیۡ جَیۡبِکَ» (28/32)\nTranslation: Put your hand into your bosom."
    },
    {
      "id": 1597,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To Throw",
      "hw": "ڈالنا",
      "s": "«نَبَذَ» to throw something behind without considering it worthy of attention (10 verses: 2:100-2:101-3:187-8:58-20:96-28:40-37:145-51:40-68:49-104:4)",
      "d": "The basic meanings of «نَبَذَ» are to throw something without considering it worthy of attention or to throw it behind (see this discussion in 'to throw'). Like «سَلَکَ», its translation is sometimes also 'to throw'.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«فَنَبَذۡنٰہُ  بِالۡعَرَآءِ  وَ  ہُوَ  سَقِیۡمٌ» (37/145)\nTranslation: So We threw him onto the barren ground while he was sick."
    },
    {
      "id": 1598,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To Throw",
      "hw": "ڈالنا",
      "s": "«قَذَفَ» to throw or to throw with force and intensity (8 verses: 20:39-20:87-21:18-33:26-34:48-34:53-37:8-59:2)",
      "d": "«قَذَفَ» means to throw from a distance (see this discussion in 'to throw'), but in some places its translation is also done as 'to throw'.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ قَذَفَ فِیۡ  قُلُوۡبِہِمُ  الرُّعۡبَ» (59/2)\nTranslation: And Allah has cast terror into their hearts."
    },
    {
      "id": 1599,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To Throw",
      "hw": "ڈالنا",
      "s": "«اَفْرَغَ» to throw or pour in such a manner as water is poured slowly from a jug (3 verses: 2:250-7:126-18:96)",
      "d": "«فَرَغَ» means to be free from work, and also to become empty. Its opposite is «شَغَل». And «اَفْرَغَ الدَّلْو» means to pour water from the jug and empty it (masc.), i.e., to throw or pour something slowly.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«رَبَّنَاۤ  اَفۡرِغۡ عَلَیۡنَا صَبۡرًا وَّ ثَبِّتۡ اَقۡدَامَنَا» (2/250)\nTranslation: Our Lord! Pour upon us patience and plant our feet firmly.\nAt another place, the divine command is:\n«قَالَ اٰتُوۡنِیۡۤ  اُفۡرِغۡ عَلَیۡہِ قِطۡرًا» (18/96)\nTranslation: He (Dhul-Qarnayn) said, 'Bring me blocks of iron.' Then when he filled the valley between the two mountain walls, he said, 'Blow (upon it),' until when he made it fire, he said, 'Bring me molten copper to pour over it.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1600,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To Throw",
      "hw": "ڈالنا",
      "s": "«اَوْقَعَ» to throw something and then make it settle (19 verses: 4:100-5:91-7:71-7:118-7:134-7:171-10:51-18:53-27:82-27:85-42:22-51:6-52:7-56:1-56:2-56:75-69:15-70:1-77:7)",
      "d": "The basic meanings of «وَقَعَ» are two: (1) to be established, (2) to fall down (masc.). And «اَوْقَعَ» means to cause to happen, i.e., to throw something and then make it settle (majd).\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«اِنَّمَا یُرِیۡدُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ اَنۡ  یُّوۡقِعَ  بَیۡنَکُمُ الۡعَدَاوَۃَ  وَ الۡبَغۡضَآءَ» (5/91)\nTranslation: Satan only wants to cause between you animosity and hatred."
    }
  ],
  "345": [],
  "346": [
    {
      "id": 1603,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To Fear",
      "hw": "ڈرنا",
      "s": "«خَافَ» to fear an upcoming danger (105 verses: 2:38-2:62-2:112-2:155-2:182-2:229-2:239-2:262-2:274-2:277-3:170-3:175-4:3-4:9-4:34-4:35-4:83-4:101-4:128-5:23-5:28-5:54-5:69-5:94-5:108-6:15-6:48-6:51-6:80-6:81-7:35-7:49-7:56-7:59-8:26-8:48-8:58-9:28-10:15-10:62-10:83-11:3-11:26-11:70-11:84-11:103-12:13-13:12-13:21-14:14-16:47-16:50-16:112-17:57-17:60-19:5-19:45-20:21-20:45-20:46-20:68-20:77-20:112-24:37-24:50-24:55-26:12-26:14-26:21-26:135-27:10-28:7-28:25-28:31-28:33-28:34-29:33-30:24-30:28-32:16-33:19-38:22-39:13-39:16-39:36-40:26-40:30-40:32-41:30-43:68-46:13-46:21-48:27-50:45-51:28-51:37-55:46-59:16-72:13-74:53-76:7-76:10-79:40-91:15-106:4)",
      "d": "«خَافَ» means to apprehend an upcoming danger based on evidence and signs (masc.). Its opposite is security. That is, «خَافَ» generally relates to the future.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«قَالُوۡا لَا تَخَفۡ  اِنَّاۤ  اُرۡسِلۡنَاۤ  اِلٰی  قَوۡمِ  لُوۡطٍ» (11/70)\nTranslation: They said, 'Fear not. Indeed, we have been sent to the people of Lot.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1604,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To Fear",
      "hw": "ڈرنا",
      "s": "«خَشِیَ» to fear due to the greatness of something (13 verses: 2:74-4:25-4:77-17:31-17:100-18:80-20:94-21:28-23:57-36:11-50:33-59:21-98:8)",
      "d": "«خَشِیَ» is such a fear that befalls the heart due to someone's greatness (masc.).\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ لَا تَقۡتُلُوۡۤا  اَوۡلَادَکُمۡ  خَشۡیَۃَ  اِمۡلَاقٍ» (17/31)\nTranslation: And do not kill your children for fear of poverty."
    },
    {
      "id": 1605,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To Fear",
      "hw": "ڈرنا",
      "s": "«خَشَعَ» such a fear whose effect also falls on limbs and organs (15 verses: 2:45-3:199-20:108-21:90-23:2-33:35-41:39-42:45-54:7-57:16-59:21-68:43-70:44-79:9-88:2)",
      "d": "«خَشَعَ» refers to such fear whose effects become apparent on limbs and organs besides the heart. The heart becoming soft (masc.). Therefore, this word is also used for 'limbs'.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«خَاشِعَۃً  اَبۡصَارُہُمۡ» (70/44)\nTranslation: Their eyes will be humbled.\nAt another place, the divine command is:\n«وُجُوۡہٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ خَاشِعَۃٌ» (88/2)\nTranslation: Faces on that Day will be humbled.\nAt another place, the divine command is:\n«وَ خَشَعَتِ الۡاَصۡوَاتُ» (20/108)\nTranslation: And voices will be lowered.\nAt another place, the divine command is:\n«اَلَمۡ یَاۡنِ  لِلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا  اَنۡ  تَخۡشَعَ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ  لِذِکۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (57/16)\nTranslation: Has the time not come for those who have believed that their hearts should become humble for the remembrance of Allah?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1606,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To Fear",
      "hw": "ڈرنا",
      "s": "«اِتَّقٰی» to avoid sins due to fear of consequences (223 verses: 2:2-2:21-2:24-2:41-2:48-2:63-2:66-2:103-2:123-2:177-2:179-2:180-2:183-2:187-2:189-2:194-2:196-2:197-2:203-2:206-2:212-2:223-2:224-2:231-2:233-2:237-2:241-2:278-2:281-2:282-2:283-3:15-3:28-3:50-3:76-3:102-3:115-3:120-3:123-3:125-3:130-3:131-3:133-3:138-3:172-3:179-3:186-3:198-3:200-4:1-4:9-4:77-4:128-4:129-4:131-5:2-5:4-5:7-5:8-5:11-5:27-5:35-5:46-5:57-5:65-5:88-5:93-5:96-5:100-5:108-5:112-6:32-6:51-6:69-6:72-6:153-6:155-7:26-7:35-7:63-7:65-7:96-7:128-7:156-7:164-7:169-7:171-7:201-8:1-8:25-8:29-8:34-8:56-8:69-9:4-9:7-9:36-9:44-9:108-9:109-9:115-9:119-9:123-10:6-10:31-10:63-11:49-11:78-12:57-12:90-12:109-13:35-15:45-15:69-16:2-16:30-16:31-16:52-16:81-16:128-19:13-19:18-19:63-19:72-19:85-19:97-20:113-20:132-21:48-22:1-22:32-22:37-23:23-23:32-23:52-23:87-24:34-24:52-25:15-25:74-26:11-26:90-26:106-26:108-26:110-26:124-26:126-26:131-26:132-26:142-26:144-26:150-26:161-26:163-26:177-26:179-26:184-27:53-28:83-29:16-30:31-31:33-33:1-33:32-33:37-33:55-33:70-36:45-37:124-38:28-38:49-39:10-39:16-39:20-39:24-39:28-39:33-39:57-39:61-39:73-40:9-41:18-43:35-43:63-43:67-44:51-45:19-47:15-47:17-47:36-48:26-49:1-49:3-49:10-49:12-49:13-50:31-51:15-52:17-53:32-54:54-57:28-58:9-59:7-59:18-60:11-64:16-65:1-65:2-65:4-65:5-65:10-68:34-69:48-71:3-73:17-74:56-77:41-78:31-91:8-92:5-92:17-96:12)",
      "d": "«تَقْوٰی» means to fear the outcomes of one's actions. Inclining the nature towards avoiding sins and doing good deeds (masc.). To keep in mind Allah's commands and prohibitions (i.e., what He has commanded and what He has forbidden) out of His fear (majd). Its opposite is «عُدْوَان». And «اِتَّقٰی» means to try to avoid sins by fearing their consequences. To adopt piety.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n« کَذٰلِکَ یُبَیِّنُ اللّٰہُ  اٰیٰتِہٖ لِلنَّاسِ لَعَلَّہُمۡ  یَتَّقُوۡنَ» (2/187)\nTranslation: Thus does Allah make clear His verses to the people so that they may become pious (fear and avoid)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1608,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To Fear",
      "hw": "ڈرنا",
      "s": "«رَاعَ» to be astonished, to fear from a fictitious and imaginary danger (1 verse: 11:74)",
      "d": "«رَاعَ» means to alarm and to cause astonishment (majd). «رَوْعَ» means heart, and «رَعْتُہٗ» means to frighten, to alarm. And «نَاقَۃٌ رَوْعَاء» means a fearful she-camel (masc.). And «اَلرَّوْع» refers to such a state where a person is both astonished by an event and also perceives some fictitious and imaginary danger, causing him to be alarmed.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«فَلَمَّا ذَہَبَ عَنۡ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ الرَّوۡعُ» (11/74)\nTranslation: Then when the fear left Abraham."
    },
    {
      "id": 1609,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "to fear",
      "hw": "ڈرنا",
      "s": "«اَوْجَسَ» to fear in the heart and attempt to conceal it (3 verses: 11:70-20:67-51:28)",
      "d": "«وَجْسٌ» means to be concealed (of the ear) to perceive a sound. To feel fear from something heard (Manjad). And «اَوْجَسَ» means to try to hide one's fear. And not allowing signs of fear to appear on the face.\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَلَمَّا رَاٰۤ  اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ لَا تَصِلُ  اِلَیۡہِ  نَکِرَہُمۡ وَ اَوۡجَسَ مِنۡہُمۡ خِیۡفَۃً» ( 11/70 )\nTranslation: When (Prophet Ibrahim ﷺ saw that their hands did not reach towards it, he disliked them and concealed his fear from them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1610,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "to fear",
      "hw": "ڈرنا",
      "s": "«وَجَفَ» the heart beating due to fear, anxiety and restlessness (1 verse: 79:8)",
      "d": "«وَجَفَ» means to be restless, anxious, and agitated. The heart beating. And it means to fall due to fear (Manjad). In «وَجَفَ», two things are found: restlessness and fear. And from these, the heart starts beating.\nFor example, in the Quran: «قُلُوۡبٌ یَّوۡمَئِذٍ وَّاجِفَۃٌ» ( 79/8 )\nTranslation: On that day, (people's) hearts will be fearful (Jalandhari). Beating hearts. (Osmani)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1611,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "to fear",
      "hw": "ڈرنا",
      "s": "«وَجِلَ» to feel fear in the heart due to one's shortcomings and to be restless (5 verses: 8:2-15:52-15:53-22:35-23:60)",
      "d": "«وَجِلَ» means to feel fear in the heart (Muf) and means to have one's hair stand on end (M. Q.). To increase in fear. To become old (Manjad). And it means to fear someone due to one's shortcomings and to be restless (Faq. L 202).\nFor example, in the Quran: «اِنَّمَا الۡمُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ الَّذِیۡنَ اِذَا ذُکِرَ اللّٰہُ وَجِلَتۡ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ» ( 8/2 )\nTranslation: The believers are only those who, when Allah is mentioned, their hearts fear (become fearful)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1612,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "to fear",
      "hw": "ڈرنا",
      "s": "«رَھَبَ» a fear that includes caution and anxiety and is prolonged (8 verses: 2:40-7:116-7:154-8:60-16:51-21:90-28:32-59:13)",
      "d": "«رَھَبَ» is such a fear that includes anxiety and caution. Its opposite is «رَغِبَ» and «رَاہِبْ» means people who fear Allah. Recluses and worshippers. From this is «رَھْبَاِنیَۃ» meaning to abandon worldly pleasures (Manjad). And it means «طول الخوف و استمرارہ» (Faq L 200) i.e., to remain in fear continuously.\nFor example, in the Quran: «اِنَّہُمۡ کَانُوۡا یُسٰرِعُوۡنَ فِی الۡخَیۡرٰتِ وَ یَدۡعُوۡنَنَا رَغَبًا وَّ رَہَبًا» ( 21/90 )\nTranslation: They used to hasten towards good deeds and call upon Us with hope and fear."
    },
    {
      "id": 1613,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "to fear",
      "hw": "ڈرنا",
      "s": "«رَعَبَ» intensity of fear and terror (5 verses: 3:151-8:12-18:18-33:26-59:2)",
      "d": "«رُعْب» means the intensity of fear, terror. And «رَعَبَ» means to be filled with fear (Muf), to shrink due to someone's fear.\nFor example, in the Quran: «لَوِ اطَّلَعۡتَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ لَوَلَّیۡتَ مِنۡہِمۡ فِرَارًا  وَّ  لَمُلِئۡتَ مِنۡہِمۡ  رُعۡبًا» ( 18/18 )\nTranslation: If you could see them, you would turn away from them in flight and be filled with terror from them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1614,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "to fear",
      "hw": "ڈرنا",
      "s": "«اَشْفَقَ» to fear for someone's well-being along with hoping for their good, mixed feelings of fear and mercy (10 verses: 18:49-21:28-21:49-23:57-33:72-42:18-42:22-52:26-58:13-70:27)",
      "d": "«شَفِقَ عَلٰی» means to wish well for someone. And «اَشْفَقَ» means to fear for someone's well-being along with hoping for their good (Muf), and means to be concerned with reform and goodness. To have mercy. To be kind. And «شَفَقَۃ» means kindness, mercy, fear with kindness. And «اَشْفَقَ مِنْہُ» means to fear. To be greedy (Manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ وُضِعَ الۡکِتٰبُ فَتَرَی الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ مُشۡفِقِیۡنَ  مِمَّا فِیۡہِ» ( 18/49 )\nTranslation: And the record (of deeds) will be placed, and you will see the criminals fearful of what is in it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1617,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "to frighten",
      "hw": "ڈرنا",
      "s": "«اَوْعَدَ» to frighten, to threaten, to give a warning (41 verses: 6:134-7:86-11:17-11:81-14:14-15:43-18:48-18:58-18:59-19:75-20:58-20:59-20:86-20:87-20:97-20:113-21:103-21:109-23:36-23:93-26:206-36:63-38:53-41:30-43:83-46:16-46:35-50:14-50:20-50:28-50:32-50:45-51:5-51:22-51:60-54:46-70:42-70:44-72:24-72:25-77:7-)",
      "d": "«اَوْعَدَ» the word 'wa'd' is general. Meaning to give someone hope. But 'wa'id' refers to the consequence of a bad deed and its punishment, a threat. And «اَوْعَدَ» means to threaten, to frighten (Manjad), whether verbally or by practically providing such means.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ لَا تَقۡعُدُوۡا بِکُلِّ صِرَاطٍ تُوۡعِدُوۡنَ وَ تَصُدُّوۡنَ عَنۡ  سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ» ( 7/86 )\nTranslation: And do not sit on every path, threatening and turning people away from the way of Allah."
    }
  ],
  "347": [
    {
      "id": 1618,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "bucket",
      "hw": "ڈول",
      "s": "«دَلْو» a bucket that is completely empty.\nAnd «ذَنُوْب» a bucket that is filled with water.\nAnd «سِجْل» a bucket that has some water in it (1 verse: 12:19)",
      "d": "«دَلْو» a vessel for drawing water from a well. Bucket, pail, etc. (provided that it is empty of water (F L. 32))\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ جَآءَتۡ سَیَّارَۃٌ  فَاَرۡسَلُوۡا وَارِدَہُمۡ فَاَدۡلٰی دَلۡوَہٗ» ( 12/19 )\nTranslation: And a caravan came, and they sent their water-drawer, and he let down his bucket (into the well)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1619,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "bucket",
      "hw": "ڈول",
      "s": "«ذنُوْب» a vessel for drawing water. (1 verse: 51:59)",
      "d": "«ذنُوْب» a vessel for drawing water. Bucket or pail, etc., when it is filled with water (FL 31)\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَاِنَّ لِلَّذِیۡنَ ظَلَمُوۡا ذَنُوۡبًا مِّثۡلَ ذَنُوۡبِ اَصۡحٰبِہِمۡ» ( 51/59 )\nTranslation: So indeed, for those who wronged, a bucket (of sins) like the bucket of their companions (has been filled)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1620,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "shield",
      "hw": "ڈول",
      "s": "«جُنّٓۃ» meaning shield, the weapon used for protection from attacks (2 verses: 58:16-63:2)",
      "d": "«جُنّٓۃ» means shield. The shield is the well-known weapon used to protect oneself from the enemy's attack by holding it in front to block the strike and safeguard oneself. Its use is in both material and spiritual contexts.\nFor example, in the Quran: «اِتَّخَذُوۡۤا  اَیۡمَانَہُمۡ جُنَّۃً  فَصَدُّوۡا عَنۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ» ( 58/16 )\nTranslation: They have taken their oaths as a shield, and they turn people away from the way of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1621,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "Shield",
      "hw": "ڈول",
      "s": "«عُرْضَۃً» any thing that serves as a shield for protection (1 verse: 2:224)",
      "d": "«عَرَضَ» means to present. And «عُرْضَۃ» is any thing that, when placed in front, can provide protection, whether it is a shield or something else (M. Q). And «عُرْضَۃ» also means a target. And «ھُوَ عُرْضَۃٌ لِلنَّاسِ» means he has become a target of people's taunts and criticism. And «ھُوَ عُرْضَۃٌ لِلْکَلَامِ» means he is a target of objections (Majid). Thus «عُرْضَۃً» is used in a broader sense than «جُنَّۃ». For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَا تَجۡعَلُوا اللّٰہَ عُرۡضَۃً  لِّاَیۡمَانِکُمۡ» (2/224). Translation: And do not make Allah a target for your oaths."
    }
  ],
  "348": [
    {
      "id": 1622,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To cover, to conceal",
      "hw": " ڈھانپنا",
      "s": "«جَنَّ» to cover and hide from sight (1 verse: 6:76)",
      "d": "«جَنَّ» means to cover and conceal something so that it becomes hidden from sight (Muf). The creature that remains hidden from sight is called «جَنِّيْن» and the fetus in the mother's womb is called «جَنِیْن». For example, in the Quran: «فَلَمَّا جَنَّ عَلَیۡہِ الَّیۡلُ  رَاٰ کَوۡکَبًا» (6/76). Translation: Then when night covered them with its darkness, they (Prophet Abraham) saw a star."
    }
  ],
  "349": [
    {
      "id": 1626,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To incline, to slope",
      "hw": "ڈھلنا",
      "s": "«دُلُوْک» meaning to incline for the setting of the sun (1 verse: 17:78)",
      "d": "«دَلَکَتِ الشَّمْسُ دُلُوْکًا» means the sun inclines for its setting, and «اَلْدَلْک» means laxity (Majid). For example, in the Quran: «اَقِمِ الصَّلٰوۃَ  لِدُلُوۡکِ الشَّمۡسِ اِلٰی غَسَقِ  الَّیۡلِ وَ  قُرۡاٰنَ  الۡفَجۡرِ» (17/78). Translation: Establish prayer from the declining of the sun until the darkness of the night, and recite the Quran at dawn."
    }
  ],
  "350": [
    {
      "id": 1631,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To search",
      "hw": "ڈھونڈنا",
      "s": "«اِلْتَمَسَ» to repeatedly attempt to find something (2 verses: 57:13-72:8)",
      "d": "«لَمَسَ» means to feel something with the hand or fingers. And «اَلْتَمَسَ» means to search for something bit by bit. (Ful 171) repeatedly asking, making continuous effort to search. For example, in the Quran: «قِیۡلَ ارۡجِعُوۡا وَرَآءَکُمۡ فَالۡتِمِسُوۡا نُوۡرًا» (57/13). Translation: It will be said to them, 'Turn back and seek light behind you.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1632,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To search",
      "hw": "ڈھونڈنا",
      "s": "«جَاسَ» to reach the extreme in seeking something, to search intensely (1 verse: 17:5)",
      "d": "«جَاسَ» means to reach the utmost in seeking something. (Ful 171) to search for something with great eagerness (M. Q). For example, in the Quran: «بَعَثۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  عِبَادًا  لَّنَاۤ   اُولِیۡ  بَاۡسٍ  شَدِیۡدٍ فَجَاسُوۡا خِلٰلَ الدِّیَارِ» (17/5). Translation: We sent upon you Our servants of severe military might, who penetrated the dwellings."
    },
    {
      "id": 1633,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To search",
      "hw": "ڈھونڈنا",
      "s": "«بَعْثَرَ» to rummage and extract something (2 verses: 82:4-100:9)",
      "d": "«بَعْثَرَ» means to rummage and extract. And «بَعْثَرَ الْمَتَاعَ» means to overturn belongings (Majid). And the word «بُعْثِرَ» is derived from «بُعِثَ» and «عُثِرَ», containing the meanings of both verbs, i.e., to overturn and raise the dead (Muf). For example, in the Quran: «وَ  اِذَا الۡقُبُوۡرُ بُعۡثِرَتۡ» (82/4). Translation: And when the graves are overturned. Another guidance from Allah: «اَفَلَا یَعۡلَمُ  اِذَا بُعۡثِرَ مَا فِی الۡقُبُوۡرِ» (100/9). Translation: Does he not know when what is in the graves will be brought out?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1634,
      "a": "ڈ",
      "h": "To search",
      "hw": "ڈھونڈنا",
      "s": "«تَحَرّٰی» to seek what is better and more suitable (1 verse: 72:14)",
      "d": "«حَرُّو» or «حَرّٰی» and «اَلْاَحْرٰی» mean more fitting, more suitable, better. And «تَحَرّٰی» means to seek what is more suitable and fitting for use, to seek the better of two things (Majid). For example, in the Quran: «وَّ اَنَّا مِنَّا  الۡمُسۡلِمُوۡنَ وَ مِنَّا الۡقٰسِطُوۡنَ ؕ فَمَنۡ  اَسۡلَمَ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ تَحَرَّوۡا  رَشَدًا» (72/14). Translation: And indeed, among us are those who submit and those who are unjust; so whoever submits, those are the ones who seek guidance."
    }
  ],
  "351": [
    {
      "id": 1635,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "To slaughter",
      "hw": "ذبح کرنا",
      "s": "«ذَبَحَ» to slaughter an animal according to the prescribed Islamic method (9 verses: 2:49-2:67-2:71-5:3-14:6-27:21-28:4-37:102-37:107)",
      "d": "«ذَبَحَ» means to cut the throat of an animal with a knife in the prescribed Islamic manner, thereby removing the innate heat (i.e., the natural bodily warmth on which life depends) (Muf). For example, in the Quran: «فَذَبَحُوۡہَا وَ مَا کَادُوۡا یَفۡعَلُوۡنَ» (2/71). Translation: So they slaughtered it, though they were hardly doing it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1636,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "To slaughter",
      "hw": "ذبح کرنا",
      "s": "«ذَکّٰی» to slaughter an animal with consideration for its ease (1 verse: 5:3)",
      "d": "«ذَکّٰی» means to slaughter an animal in such a way that its life departs swiftly and easily (M. L), and also meaning: 'a hunted animal upon which the takbīr is pronounced and then it is left, after which it is slaughtered according to the specific legal method' (Muf). For example, in the Quran: «وَ مَاۤ اَکَلَ السَّبُعُ اِلَّا مَا ذَکَّیۡتُمۡ» (5/3). Translation: And the beast of prey does not eat except what you have slaughtered properly."
    },
    {
      "id": 1637,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "To slaughter",
      "hw": "ذبح کرنا",
      "s": "«نَحَرَ» any form of cutting the throat, whether it is slaughter or sacrifice or any other form (1 verse: 108:2)",
      "d": "«نَحَرَ» means to strike the chest, to slaughter. And «نَحْر» means the upper part of the chest, whose plural is «نَحُوْر». And «اِنْتَحَرَ» means to commit suicide. And «یَوْمُ النَّحْر» means the day of sacrifice, i.e., the tenth day of Dhu al-Hijjah (Majid). And «نَحَرَ» in the sense of sacrifice or cutting the throat or confrontation (M. Q). Thus the root meaning of «نَحْر» is to cut the throat, whether it is merely slaughter or sacrifice, whether with a sword or a knife, and whether the animal is standing or lying down. For example, in the Quran: «فَصَلِّ  لِرَبِّکَ وَ انۡحَرۡ» (108/2). Translation: So pray to your Lord and sacrifice."
    }
  ],
  "352": [
    {
      "id": 1638,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Means",
      "hw": "ذریعہ",
      "s": "«سَبَب» That which serves as a means to reach something else (9 verses: 2:166-18:84-18:85-18:89-18:92-22:15-38:10-40:36-40:37)",
      "d": "«سَبَب» refers to the rope with which one climbs and descends a date palm. Then, by extension, every thing that serves as a means to reach something else is called 'cause'. Furthermore, this term is also applied to a path and its related equipment.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اٰتَیۡنٰہُ مِنۡ کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ سَبَبًا فَاَتۡبَعَ سَبَبًا» (18/84)\nTranslation: We had granted Dhul-Qarnayn every kind of means, so he pursued a course."
    },
    {
      "id": 1639,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Means",
      "hw": "ذریعہ",
      "s": "«وَسِیْلَۃ» The means chosen to attain proximity (2 verses: 5:35-17:57)",
      "d": "«وَسَلَ» means to reach something with desire (i.e., to seek). And «وَسَلَ اِلَی اللہ» means to attain proximity to Allah. «اَلْوَاسَطَہ» and «اَلْوَسِیْلَۃ» mean the means of proximity, rank, or status.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ ابۡتَغُوۡۤا اِلَیۡہِ الۡوَسِیۡلَۃَ وَ جَاہِدُوۡا فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِہٖ» (5/35)\nTranslation: And seek the means of nearness to Him and strive hard in His way."
    }
  ],
  "353": [
    {
      "id": 1640,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Humiliation",
      "hw": "ذلت",
      "s": "«ذِلَّۃ» To bow before the powerful and authoritative, becoming subservient (7 verses: 2:61-3:112-7:152-10:26-10:27-68:43-70:44)",
      "d": "«ذِلَّۃ» means subjugation (i.e., being overpowered), weakness, and being crushed before strength and power. Its opposite is «عِزّۃ», meaning supremacy and authority.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ضُرِبَتۡ عَلَیۡہِمُ الذِّلَّۃُ اَیۡنَ مَا ثُقِفُوۡۤا» (3/112)\nTranslation: Wherever they are found, humiliation has been decreed for them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1641,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Humiliation",
      "hw": "ذلت",
      "s": "«صَغَار» Humiliation of becoming small after greatness and acknowledging it (1 verse: 6:124)",
      "d": "«صَغَار» means the humiliation of being diminished after greatness and its acknowledgment. It also means enduring the humiliation of becoming a subject after having been a ruler or free.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«سَیُصِیۡبُ الَّذِیۡنَ اَجۡرَمُوۡا صَغَارٌ عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ» (6/124)\nTranslation: And those who commit sins will be afflicted with humiliation from Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1642,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Humiliation",
      "hw": "ذلت",
      "s": "«خِزْی» To fall in people's eyes, disgrace (11 verses: 2:85-2:114-5:33-5:41-9:63-10:98-11:66-16:27-22:9-39:26-41:16)",
      "d": "«خِزْی» means disgrace, shame, and falling in the eyes of others due to one's evil deeds. If this feeling is limited to oneself, it is called 'nadāmah' (remorse).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَقَالُوۡا رَبَّنَا لَوۡ لَاۤ اَرۡسَلۡتَ اِلَیۡنَا رَسُوۡلًا فَنَتَّبِعَ اٰیٰتِکَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِ اَنۡ نَّذِلَّ وَ نَخۡزٰی» (20/134)\nTranslation: They will say, 'Our Lord, why did You not send a messenger to us so we could follow Your signs before we are humiliated and disgraced?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1643,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Humiliation",
      "hw": "ذلت",
      "s": "«ھُوْن» means to face humiliation due to being despised (5 verses: 6:93-16:59-25:63-41:17-46:20)",
      "d": "«ھُوْن» means disrespect, humiliation, disgrace (masc.), contempt, insult (minjadd). For example, in the Quran: «یَتَوَارٰی مِنَ الۡقَوۡمِ مِنۡ سُوۡٓءِ مَا بُشِّرَ بِہٖ ؕ اَیُمۡسِکُہٗ عَلٰی ہُوۡنٍ اَمۡ  یَدُسُّہٗ  فِی التُّرَابِ» (16/59) Translation: He hides from the people because of the evil news he has been given: Should he keep her with humiliation or bury her in the dust? And «ھَوْن» (with fatḥa on ہ) means gentleness, and this is a praiseworthy attribute. As Allah says about the attributes of believers: «وَ عِبَادُ  الرَّحۡمٰنِ الَّذِیۡنَ  یَمۡشُوۡنَ عَلَی الۡاَرۡضِ ہَوۡنًا» (25/63) Translation: And the servants of the Most Merciful are those who walk on the earth with gentleness."
    }
  ],
  "354": [
    {
      "id": 1645,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Despicable",
      "hw": "ذلیل",
      "s": "«مَھِیْن» Despicable, fallen in others' eyes due to evil deeds (18 verses: 2:90-3:178-4:14-4:37-4:102-4:151-22:57-31:6-32:8-33:57-34:14-43:52-44:30-45:9-58:5-58:16-68:10-77:20)",
      "d": "«مَھَنَ» means to become insignificant, weak. «مَھِیْن» means insignificant, worthless, despicable, and humiliated. According to Imam Raghb, «مَھِیْن» is a person over whom another human has dominion, making him undignified and humiliated.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَمۡ اَنَا خَیۡرٌ مِّنۡ ہٰذَا الَّذِیۡ ہُوَ مَہِیۡنٌ» (43/52)\nTranslation: (Pharaoh said) Am I not better than this contemptible man?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1646,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Despicable",
      "hw": "ذلیل",
      "s": "«صَاغِرْ» One who descends below the ruler, becoming a subject and acknowledging it (5 verses: 7:13-7:119-9:29-12:32-27:37)",
      "d": "«صِغْر» is the opposite of «کِبْر». «صَغَارٌ» means humiliation. «صَاغِر» means one who holds a secondary position, humiliated with the pride of greatness, forced into subjugation, and acknowledging it.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«حَتّٰی یُعۡطُوا الۡجِزۡیَۃَ عَنۡ ‌یَّدٍ وَّ ہُمۡ صٰغِرُوۡنَ» (9/29)\nTranslation: (Fight them) until they give the jizyah willingly while they are humiliated."
    },
    {
      "id": 1647,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Despicable",
      "hw": "ذلیل",
      "s": "«دَاخِر» To become obedient and submissive with humiliation due to lack of intellect (4 verses: 16:48-27:87-37:18-40:60)",
      "d": "«دَخَرَ» implies three things: helplessness, humiliation, and contempt. «دَاخِرْ» means one who, due to lack of intellect and awareness, accepts humiliation and obedience.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ یَسۡتَکۡبِرُوۡنَ عَنۡ عِبَادَتِیۡ سَیَدۡخُلُوۡنَ جَہَنَّمَ دٰخِرِیۡنَ» (40/60)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who are too proud to worship Me will enter Hell humiliated.\nAt another place, Allah says:\n«وَ یَوۡمَ یُنۡفَخُ فِی الصُّوۡرِ فَفَزِعَ مَنۡ فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ مَنۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اِلَّا مَنۡ شَآءَ اللّٰہُ ؕ وَ کُلٌّ اَتَوۡہُ دٰخِرِیۡنَ» (27/87)\nTranslation: And the Day the Horn is blown, whoever is in the heavens and whoever is on the earth will be terrified except whom Allah wills. And all will come to Him humbled."
    },
    {
      "id": 1649,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Despicable",
      "hw": "ذلیل",
      "s": "«أَسْفَل» Low and despicable compared to the exalted (7 verses: 4:145-8:42-9:40-33:10-37:98-41:29-95:5)",
      "d": "«اَلسَّفْلَۃ» means lowly people, like «دُوْن» and «اَسْفَل», meaning low and despicable. Its opposite is «اَعْلٰی» (exalted).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«نَجۡعَلۡہُمَا تَحۡتَ اَقۡدَامِنَا لِیَکُوۡنَا مِنَ الۡاَسۡفَلِیۡنَ» (41/29)\nTranslation: We will make them the lowest of the low."
    },
    {
      "id": 1650,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Humiliated",
      "hw": "ذلیل",
      "s": "«خَاسِئ» means abused. Most humiliated. (4 verses: 2:65-7:166-23:108-67:4)",
      "d": "«خَسَاَ» has two meanings: (1) meaning weakness and feebleness of sight, and (2) meaning «خَاسِئُ مِنَ الْخَنَازِیْرِ وَ الْکِلَاب» i.e., a despised dog and pig that are not allowed to be let loose among people (Munjid). For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَقَدۡ عَلِمۡتُمُ  الَّذِیۡنَ اعۡتَدَوۡا مِنۡکُمۡ فِی السَّبۡتِ فَقُلۡنَا لَہُمۡ کُوۡنُوۡا قِرَدَۃً خٰسِئِیۡنَ» (2/65). Translation: And (O Jews! You know those among you who transgressed on the Sabbath, so We said to them, 'Be apes, despised.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1651,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "To humiliate",
      "hw": "ذلیل",
      "s": "«اَذَلَّ» means to make the superior subdue the inferior or to humiliate. (3 verses: 3:26-58:20-63:8)",
      "d": "«اَذَلَّ» its opposite is «اَعَزَّ». To subjugate someone (i.e., bring under control). And in it, the aspect of defeat is prominent. Moreover, only the superior can make the inferior defeated. For example, in the Quran: «وَ تُعِزُّ مَنۡ تَشَآءُ وَ تُذِلُّ مَنۡ تَشَآءُ» (3/26). Translation: (O Allah!) You give honor to whom You will and humiliate whom You will."
    },
    {
      "id": 1652,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "To humiliate",
      "hw": "ذلیل",
      "s": "«اَھَانَ» means to insult and humiliate someone due to enmity, and even an equal can do this. (3 verses: 22:18-25:69-89:16)",
      "d": "«اَھَانَ» its opposite is «اَکْرَمَ». Meaning to consider or make someone light or weak due to enmity. And to insult them. And even an equal can do this. And the superior can also (do so) (Faqih 208). For example, in the Quran: «وَ مَنۡ  یُّہِنِ اللّٰہُ  فَمَا لَہٗ  مِنۡ مُّکۡرِمٍ» (22/18). Translation: And whoever Allah humiliates, there is no one to honor them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1653,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "To humiliate",
      "hw": "ذلیل",
      "s": "«اَخْزٰی» to humiliate someone due to their apparent fault. (15 verses: 3:192-3:194-9:2-9:14-11:39-11:78-11:93-15:69-16:27-20:134-26:87-39:40-41:16-59:5-66:8)",
      "d": "«اَخْزٰی» means to humiliate and disgrace, in which a person's own bad deeds are involved, and people are aware of them. For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَا تُخۡزِنَا یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (3/194). Translation: O Allah! Do not disgrace us on the Day of Resurrection."
    },
    {
      "id": 1654,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "To humiliate",
      "hw": "ذلیل",
      "s": "«فَضَحَ» to degrade someone by mentioning their faults, making them fall in others' eyes. (1 verse: 15:68)",
      "d": "«فَضَحَ» to mention someone's faults. To degrade in others' eyes. To humiliate in front of others (Munjid). For example, in the Quran: «قَالَ  اِنَّ ہٰۤؤُلَآءِ ضَیۡفِیۡ فَلَا تَفۡضَحُوۡنِ» (15/68). Translation: He said, 'Indeed, these are my guests, so do not disgrace me (in front of them).'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1656,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "To humiliate",
      "hw": "ذلیل",
      "s": "«کَبَتَ» to humiliate and disgrace someone in a state of anger. (2 verses: 3:127-58:5)",
      "d": "«کَبَتَ» means to turn back with hardship and humiliation (muf) and to humiliate. To turn back. To repel. To reject in anger. To destroy (Munjid). This word comes in the context of humiliating and disgracing in anger. For example, in the Quran: «اِنَّ  الَّذِیۡنَ یُحَآدُّوۡنَ اللّٰہَ  وَ رَسُوۡلَہٗ کُبِتُوۡا کَمَا کُبِتَ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ  قَبۡلِہِمۡ» (58/5). Translation: Those who oppose Allah and His Messenger will be humiliated as those before them were humiliated."
    }
  ],
  "355": [
    {
      "id": 1657,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Responsibility",
      "hw": "ذمہ داری",
      "s": "«ذِمَّۃ» refers to the responsibility of fulfilling a covenant with others. (2 verses: 9:8-9:10)",
      "d": "«ذِمَّۃ» means a type of covenant, loyalty, trust, protection, responsibility, covenant and agreement. «اَنْتَ فِیْ ذِمَّۃِ اللہِ» means 'You are under Allah's protection.' And «ذِمِّی» or «اَھْلِ الذّمّۃ» refers to non-Muslims who, under the covenant, live in Dar al-Islam by paying jizya, enjoying the protection and safety of Muslims (Munjid). Sometimes this word is used merely for covenant and the responsibility of fulfilling it. For example, in the Quran: «لَا یَرۡقُبُوۡنَ فِیۡ مُؤۡمِنٍ اِلًّا وَّ لَا ذِمَّۃً» (9/10). Translation: They do not regard any kinship or covenant with a believer."
    },
    {
      "id": 1658,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Responsibility",
      "hw": "ذمہ داری",
      "s": "«نَحْب» refers to the responsibility of fulfilling a self-imposed obligation. (1 verse: 33:23)",
      "d": "«نَحْب» refers to a vow whose fulfillment is obligatory (muf) and «نَحَبَ الرَّجُل» means a man has made something obligatory upon himself (m. q). So «نَحْب» is a responsibility that a person has voluntarily imposed upon himself, whether it be a vow or a covenant. For example, in the Quran: «فَمِنۡہُمۡ مَّنۡ قَضٰی نَحۡبَہٗ  وَ مِنۡہُمۡ مَّنۡ یَّنۡتَظِرُ» (33/23). Translation: Then among them are those who have fulfilled their obligation (of coming for Jihad) and among them are those who are still waiting."
    }
  ],
  "356": [
    {
      "id": 1659,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night",
      "hw": "رات",
      "s": "«لَیْل» means night. (77 verses: 2:51-2:164-2:187-2:274-3:27-3:113-3:190-6:13-6:60-6:76-6:96-7:54-7:142-10:6-10:24-10:27-10:67-11:81-11:114-13:3-13:10-14:33-15:65-16:12-17:1-17:12-17:78-17:79-20:130-21:20-21:33-21:42-22:61-23:80-24:44-25:47-25:62-27:86-28:71-28:72-28:73-30:23-31:29-34:33-35:13-36:37-36:40-37:138-39:5-39:9-40:61-41:37-41:38-44:3-44:23-45:5-50:40-51:17-52:49-57:6-71:5-73:2-73:6-73:20-74:33-76:26-78:10-79:29-81:17-84:17-89:4-91:4-92:1-93:2-97:1-97:2-97:3)",
      "d": "«لَیْل» is a well-known word meaning night, and its opposite is «نَھَار» meaning day. «لَیْل» refers to the time from sunset to sunrise. And in the Quran, many places mention layl and nahar together. Night is divided into 12 hours. The names of these hours in sequence are: «شَفَقَ ، غَسَقَ ، عَتَمَہ ، دَقَّۃَ ، فَحَّمَہ ، زُلْفَۃ ، زَلْقَۃ ، بَھْرَۃ ، سَحَر ، فَجَر ، صَبَحَ ، صَبَاح» (Fal 292)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1660,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night",
      "hw": "رات",
      "s": "«بَیَاتًا» means to spend the night. (3 verses: 7:4-7:97-10:50)",
      "d": "«بَاتَ» means to spend the night. To pass the night. For example, in the Quran: «وَ الَّذِیۡنَ یَبِیۡتُوۡنَ لِرَبِّہِمۡ سُجَّدًا وَّ قِیَامًا» (25/64). Translation: And those who spend the night in prostration and standing before their Lord. And «بَیَاتًا» means at any time during the night. While sleeping. In a state of sleep. For example, in the Quran: «قُلۡ اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ اِنۡ اَتٰىکُمۡ عَذَابُہٗ بَیَاتًا اَوۡ نَہَارًا» (10/50). Translation: Say, 'Have you considered if Allah's punishment comes to you by night or by day?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1661,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night-related matters",
      "hw": "رات",
      "s": "«بَاتَ» meaning to spend the night, to pass the night, and the place where one spends the night (1 verse: 25:64)",
      "d": "«بَاتَ» meaning to spend the night. To pass the night. And the place where one spends the night. That is the house (i.e., home). (M L)\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ یَبِیۡتُوۡنَ لِرَبِّہِمۡ سُجَّدًا وَّ قِیَامًا» (25/64)\nTranslation: And those who spend the night in prostration and standing before their Lord."
    },
    {
      "id": 1662,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night-related matters",
      "hw": "رات",
      "s": "«بَیَّت» to gather at home after part of the night has passed to consult on a matter (3 verses: 4:81-4:108-27:49)",
      "d": "«بَیَّت» meaning to gather at home after part of the night has passed to consult on a matter (M. L)\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اِذۡ یُبَیِّتُوۡنَ مَا لَا یَرۡضٰی مِنَ الۡقَوۡلِ» (4/108)\nTranslation: When they consult at night about matters which He (Allah) does not approve of.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«قَالُوۡا تَقَاسَمُوۡا بِاللّٰہِ لَنُبَیِّتَنَّہٗ وَ اَہۡلَہٗ ثُمَّ لَنَقُوۡلَنَّ لِوَلِیِّہٖ مَا شَہِدۡنَا مَہۡلِکَ اَہۡلِہٖ» (27/49)\nTranslation: They said, 'Swear by Allah that we will certainly attack him and his family by night, then we will say to his heir, \"We were not present at the death of his family.\"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1663,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night-related matters",
      "hw": "رات",
      "s": "«اَسْرٰی» meaning to travel at night (6 verses: 11:81-15:65-17:1-20:77-26:52-44:23)",
      "d": "«اَسْرٰی» meaning to travel at night. To take away. To lead out.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَسۡرٰی بِعَبۡدِہٖ لَیۡلًا مِّنَ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ اِلَی الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡاَقۡصَا» (17/1)\nTranslation: Glorified is He who took His servant by night from the Sacred Mosque to the Farthest Mosque."
    },
    {
      "id": 1664,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night-related matters",
      "hw": "رات",
      "s": "«طَرَقَ» meaning path (2 verses: 86:1-86:2)",
      "d": "«طَرِیْق» means path and «طَارِق» means the one who travels the path. But in common usage, it particularly refers to the traveler who comes at night. And stars are called «طَارِق» because they generally appear at night. (M F)\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ السَّمَآءِ وَ الطَّارِقِ» (86/1)\nTranslation: By the sky and the night-comer.\nIn this verse, «طَارِق» could refer to stars or the night-visiting guest."
    },
    {
      "id": 1665,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night-related matters",
      "hw": "رات",
      "s": "«نَفَشَ» refers to those sheep/goats that have spread out at night to graze without a shepherd (1 verse: 21:78)",
      "d": "«نَفْشُ الْغَنَم» meaning the scattering of sheep/goats at night to graze without a shepherd. And «اَلنَّفْش» refers to those sheep/goats that have scattered at night to graze without a shepherd. (M F)\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ دَاوٗدَ وَ سُلَیۡمٰنَ اِذۡ یَحۡکُمٰنِ فِی الۡحَرۡثِ اِذۡ نَفَشَتۡ فِیۡہِ غَنَمُ الۡقَوۡمِ» (21/78)\nTranslation: And remember David and Solomon when they were judging in the matter of the field when the sheep of the people had scattered therein at night and grazed."
    },
    {
      "id": 1666,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night-related matters",
      "hw": "رات",
      "s": "«تَھَجَّدَ» to wake up at night to perform voluntary prayers (1 verse: 17:79)",
      "d": "«ھَجَدَ» means both to sleep at night and to wake up (this is from the category of opposite words in lexicon, where words have two distinct and opposite meanings).\nAnd «ھَجَّدَ تَھَجَّدَ» means both to make someone sleep and to wake someone up. To wake from sleep. To sleep at night. To wake up at night and perform prayers. (Minaj)\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ مِنَ الَّیۡلِ فَتَہَجَّدۡ بِہٖ نَافِلَۃً لَّکَ» (17/79)\nTranslation: And during some parts of the night, wake up and perform voluntary prayers for yourself."
    }
  ],
  "357": [
    {
      "id": 1667,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Path. Way",
      "hw": "راستہ",
      "s": "«طَرِیْق» is a general term for path (7 verses: 4:168-4:169-20:63-20:77-20:104-46:30-72:16)",
      "d": "The plural of «طَرِیْق» is «طَرَائِق». This word is used for every type of path (F L 269). This word is also used in both material and spiritual contexts. An example of its material usage is:\nThe divine command is:\n«فَاضۡرِبۡ لَہُمۡ طَرِیۡقًا فِی الۡبَحۡرِ یَبَسًا» (20/77)\nTranslation: (O Moses!) Strike for them a dry path in the sea.\nAnd an example of its spiritual usage is:\nThe divine command is:\n«وَ لَا لِیَہۡدِیَہُمۡ طَرِیۡقًا اِلَّا طَرِیۡقَ جَہَنَّمَ» (4/168)\nTranslation: And He will not guide them except the path of Hell."
    },
    {
      "id": 1668,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Path. Way",
      "hw": "راستہ",
      "s": "«صِرَاط» a path upon which one must tread with caution (45 verses: 1:5-1:6-2:142-2:213-3:51-3:101-4:68-4:175-5:16-6:39-6:87-6:126-6:153-6:161-7:16-7:86-10:25-11:56-14:1-15:41-16:76-16:121-19:36-19:43-20:135-22:24-22:54-23:73-23:74-24:46-34:6-36:4-36:61-36:66-37:23-37:118-38:22-42:52-42:53-43:43-43:61-43:64-48:2-48:20-67:22)",
      "d": "«صُرَاط» refers to a long and sharp-edged sword (Minaj). And it is the path that will be built to cross over Hell, commonly called the Bridge of Sirat. It has been described as being sharper than a sword and thinner than a hair. Thus, «صِرَاط» is the path that must be traversed with utmost vigilance and caution. And there are many dangers surrounding it. The name for traversing this path with such vigilance and caution is Taqwa (piety). The word «صِرَاط» is used in both material and spiritual contexts. In the spiritual sense, its meaning is generally the path of guidance. And according to Abu Halaal, «صِرَاط» means the easy path (F Q L 246). And Allah knows best.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اِہۡدِ نَا الصِّرَاطَ الۡمُسۡتَقِیۡمَ» (1/5)\nTranslation: Our Lord, guide us to the straight path.\nAnd an example of its material usage is:\nThe divine command is:\n«وَ لَا تَقۡعُدُوۡا بِکُلِّ صِرَاطٍ تُوۡعِدُوۡنَ وَ تَصُدُّوۡنَ عَنۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ» (7/86)\nTranslation: And do not sit on every path, threatening and turning people away from the way of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1669,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Path. Way",
      "hw": "راستہ",
      "s": "«سَبِیْل» a path upon which one can walk with ease and upon which there is frequent traffic (157 verses: 2:108-2:154-2:190-2:195-2:217-2:218-2:244-2:246-2:261-2:262-2:273-3:13-3:75-3:97-3:99-3:146-3:157-3:167-3:169-3:195-4:15-4:22-4:34-4:44-4:51-4:74-4:75-4:76-4:84-4:88-4:89-4:90-4:94-4:95-4:98-4:100-4:115-4:137-4:141-4:143-4:150-4:160-4:167-5:12-5:16-5:35-5:54-5:60-5:77-6:55-6:116-6:117-6:153-6:153-7:45-7:86-7:142-7:146-7:148-8:36-8:47-8:60-8:72-8:74-9:5-9:9-9:19-9:20-9:24-9:34-9:38-9:41-9:60-9:81-9:91-9:93-9:111-9:120-10:88-10:89-11:19-12:108-13:33-14:3-14:12-14:30-15:76-16:9-16:15-16:69-16:88-16:94-16:125-17:32-17:42-17:48-17:72-17:84-17:110-18:61-18:63-20:53-21:31-22:9-22:25-22:58-24:22-25:9-25:17-25:27-25:34-25:42-25:44-25:57-27:24-28:22-29:12-29:29-29:38-29:69-31:6-31:15-33:4-33:67-38:26-39:8-40:7-40:11-40:29-40:37-40:38-42:41-42:42-42:44-42:46-43:10-43:37-47:1-47:4-47:32-47:34-47:38-49:15-53:30-57:10-58:16-60:1-61:4-61:11-63:2-68:7-71:20-73:19-73:20-76:3-76:29-80:20)",
      "d": "«سَبِیْل» refers to any path upon which one can walk with ease (M F). «اِبْنُ السَّبِیْل» means traveler and «عَابِرِی سَّبِیْل» (4/43) means wayfarer. Its plural is «سُبُل». And «سبیل» means open road. «اَسْبَلُ الطَّرِیْق» means the path having much traffic. And «اَسْبَلُ الدَّمْعِ وَالْمَطَر» means tears or rain flowing abundantly. Thus, «سَبِیْل» refers to a path upon which there is frequent traffic. (Minaj)\nFor example, in the Quran, Allah Almighty says through the honeybee:\n«فَاسۡلُکِیۡ سُبُلَ رَبِّکِ ذُلُلًا» (16/69)\nTranslation: And follow the ways of your Lord in humility.\nHere, «سُبُل» refers to the natural guidance that Allah has inherently placed in everything, upon which one can proceed with ease. And all are equally traversed. This word is also used in both spiritual and material contexts. The above example is of the spiritual context, and an example of the material context is this:\nThe divine command is:\n«وَ اِنَّہَا لَبِسَبِیۡلٍ مُّقِیۡمٍ» (15/76)\nTranslation: And indeed, it (the city of Lot) is still on a straight path.\nNow observe that for this 'path of guidance', Allah has used all three words «طَرِیْق», «صِرَاط», and «سَبِیْل» in the Quran. «طَرِیْق» is general, used for any path. «صِرَاط» is one that is surrounded by the limits and confines of commands and prohibitions. And «سَبِیْل» is such that when a person embarks upon it with determination, the Sharia has taken into account all kinds of facilities for him, and the number of people traversing it is also large."
    },
    {
      "id": 1670,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Path. Way",
      "hw": "راستہ",
      "s": "«فَجّ» an open path between two mountains (3 verses: 21:31-22:27-71:20)",
      "d": "«فَجَّۃٌ» refers to the opening between two mountains, and «فَجْوَۃ» refers to the valley between two mountains, and «فَجَّ» refers to that open path which passes through that valley and connects the two mountains. The plural of «فَجّ» is «فِحَاج».\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ اَذِّنۡ فِی النَّاسِ بِالۡحَجِّ یَاۡتُوۡکَ رِجَالًا وَّ عَلٰی کُلِّ ضَامِرٍ یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیۡقٍ» (22/27)\nTranslation: And proclaim to the people the Hajj; they will come to you on foot and on every lean camel, coming from every distant path."
    },
    {
      "id": 1671,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Path. Way.",
      "hw": "راستہ",
      "s": "«إمام» main road, open street (6 verses: 2:124, 11:17, 15:79, 17:71, 25:74, 46:12)",
      "d": "«إمام» has two meanings: (1) leader, and (2) main road, broad and open path (manjad). For example, the Quran states: «فَانْتَقَمْنَا مِنْهُمْ ۘ وَ إِنَّهُمَا لَبِإِمَامٍ مُّبِينٍ» (15:79). Translation: So We took retribution from them, and indeed, both [cities] are on a clear highway."
    },
    {
      "id": 1672,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Path. Way.",
      "hw": "راستہ",
      "s": "«نجد» a path that ascends and descends a valley (1 verse: 90:10)",
      "d": "«نجد» has two meanings: (1) valley, and (2) a path that goes up towards a height or comes down from above (fal 269). For example, the Quran states: «وَ هَدَيْنَاهُ النَّجْدَيْنِ فَلَا اقْتَحَمَ الْعَقَبَةَ» (90:10). Translation: And We have shown him the two paths, but he did not undertake the steep ascent."
    }
  ],
  "358": [
    {
      "id": 1675,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To lay a path. To establish.",
      "hw": "رائج",
      "s": "«سنّ» comes to establish every good and bad way. However, in Shariah terminology, «سُنَّة» refers specifically to the actions and sayings of the Messenger of Allah ﷺ (9 verses: 8:38, 15:13, 17:77, 18:55, 33:38, 33:62, 35:43, 40:85, 48:23)",
      "d": "«سنّ» means for something to become established, customary, or to run its proper course (m. l). It is used both as a transitive and intransitive verb. As in the Prophetic Hadith: «مَنْ سَنَّ سُنَّةً»... meaning: whoever establishes a way [of doing things]... It is used in both good and bad senses. When attributed to Allah, it refers to divine law or divine custom. For example, the Quran states: «فَهَلْ يَنْظُرُونَ إِلَّا سُنَّةَ الْأَوَّلِينَ ۚ فَلَنْ تَجِدَ لِسُنَّةِ اللّٰهِ تَبْدِيلًا» (35:43). Translation: Do they await anything but the way of the former peoples? So you will not find any change in the way of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1676,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To Lay a Path. To Establish.",
      "hw": "رائج",
      "s": "«شَرَعَ» means for Allah to set a clear and defined path for His servants through the Prophet. From Adam to Muhammad, changes occurred in this, but now this part of the religion is also unchangeable (in which it cannot be). Because the Prophet was the last prophet and the religion was completed upon him. (4 verses: 5:48-42:13-42:21-45:48)",
      "d": "«شَرَعَ» means a clear and defined path, but it is applied only to divine commands (masc.). And «شَرَعَ لِلْقَوْمِ» means to make a law for the people. And Sharia means Islamic law, divine commands, regulation (minjadd). «شَرَعَ» actually refers to those laws in which Allah changes according to the demands of the times (for more details, see 'Method' and 'Religion'). For example, in the Quran: «شَرَعَ  لَکُمۡ مِّنَ الدِّیۡنِ مَا وَصّٰی بِہٖ نُوۡحًا» (42/13) Translation: He has prescribed for you the same religion which He enjoined upon Noah. However, lexically, this word can also be attributed to non-Allah and false deities. For example, the divine command states: «اَمۡ لَہُمۡ شُرَکٰٓؤُا شَرَعُوۡا  لَہُمۡ مِّنَ الدِّیۡنِ مَا لَمۡ یَاۡذَنۡۢ بِہِ اللّٰہُ» (42/21) Translation: Or do they have partners who have established for them a religion which Allah has not permitted?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1677,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To lay a path. To establish.",
      "hw": "رائج",
      "s": "«ابتدا» to introduce a custom or way into religion, considering it part of it, for which there is no proof in Shariah (1 verse: 57:27)",
      "d": "«الابتداع» means to invent something without imitating or following anyone. And «بدعة» is every new custom and practice that is considered part of religion and entered into it, and for which there is no proof in Shariah. And «ابتدا» means to introduce something new into Shariah by giving it a part and share [in religion]. And the Prophetic Hadith ﷺ states: every innovation is misguidance, even if it is considered good. For example, the Quran states: «وَرَهْبَانِيَّةَ ابْتَدَعُوهَا مَا كَتَبْنَاهَا عَلَيْهِمْ» (57:27). Translation: So they invented monasticism which We did not prescribe for them."
    }
  ],
  "359": [
    {
      "id": 1678,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To please. To be pleased.",
      "hw": "راضی",
      "s": "«رضی» to be pleased, to be happy, is a general word (26 verses: 2:144, 4:24, 5:3, 5:119, 9:38, 9:58, 9:59, 9:83, 9:87, 9:93, 9:96, 9:100, 10:7, 19:6, 19:55, 20:109, 27:19, 33:51, 46:15, 48:18, 58:22, 69:21, 88:9, 89:28, 98:8, 101:7)",
      "d": "«رضی» is a well-known word meaning to be pleased with someone, to be happy, to approve or to express approval. For example, the Quran states: «رَضِيَ اللّٰهُ عَنْهُمْ وَ رَضُوا عَنْهُ» (5:119, 98:8). Translation: Allah is pleased with them and they are pleased with Him."
    },
    {
      "id": 1679,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To please. To be pleased.",
      "hw": "راضی",
      "s": "«طوّع» to make one's heart willingly pleased with a bad deed (8 verses: 2:158, 2:184, 3:83, 5:30, 9:53, 9:79, 13:15, 41:11)",
      "d": "«أطاع» means to obey a command with happiness of heart. And «طوّع» means to make one's heart willingly pleased with a detestable (disliked) act (muf). For example, the Quran states: «فَطَوَّعَتْ لَهُ نَفْسُهُ قَتْلَ أَخِيهِ» (5:30). Translation: So his soul persuaded him to kill his brother."
    },
    {
      "id": 1680,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To please. To be pleased.",
      "hw": "راضی",
      "s": "«اعتب» to complain with the intention of pleasing one who is offended (4 verses: 16:84, 30:57, 41:24, 45:35)",
      "d": "«عتَب» means to reproach someone, to be angry. And «اعتب» means to remove the cause of anger. To appease one who is offended (and this is from the category of opposite words). And «عتاب» means the expression of anger (displeasure) upon spoiling relations of friendship and sympathy (faq l 39). For example, the Quran states: «وَ إِنْ يَسْتَعْتِبُوا فَمَا هُمْ مِنَ الْمُعْتَبِينَ» (41:24). Translation: And if they seek to appease [Allah's anger], they will not be among those who are appeased. (Note: 'Opposites' are words that have two separate meanings which are contrary and contradictory to each other)."
    }
  ],
  "360": [
    {
      "id": 1681,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rank. To attain rank.",
      "hw": "رتبہ",
      "s": "«درجَة» a station of excellence and superiority (18 verses: 2:228, 2:253, 3:163, 4:95, 4:96, 6:83, 6:132, 6:165, 8:4, 9:20, 12:76, 17:21, 20:75, 40:15, 43:32, 46:19, 57:10, 58:11)",
      "d": "«درجَة» means superiority, excellence, rank, degree. The opposite of «درج» is «درک». And these two words are two aspects of the same thing. If one climbs the steps of a ladder upwards towards the roof, those same steps are called «درجات». And when considered from the perspective of going down, those same steps are called «دركات». Hence, the phrases «درجات الجنة» (degrees of Paradise) and «دركات النار» (degrees of Hell) are used (muf). And 'degree' refers to such superiority and excellence that exists from one degree to another. For example, the Quran states: «وَلَهُنَّ مِثْلُ الَّذِي عَلَيْهِنَّ بِالْمَعْرُوفِ ۪ وَلِلرِّجَالِ عَلَيْهِنَّ دَرَجَةٌ» (2:228). Translation: And women shall have rights similar to those against them according to what is reasonable, but men have a degree over them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1682,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rank. To attain rank.",
      "hw": "رتبہ",
      "s": "«زلفی» nearness in honor and status (9 verses: 26:64, 26:90, 34:37, 38:25, 38:40, 39:3, 50:31, 67:27, 81:13)",
      "d": "«زلفی» means nearness in honor, status, and rank (m. l). For example, the Quran states: «وَ إِنَّ لَهُ عِنْدَنَا لَزُلْفَىٰ وَ حُسْنَ مَآبٍ» (38:40). Translation: And indeed, for him is nearness [to Us] and a good place of return. But when this root becomes a noun in the context of actions, it also means nearness in distance. For example, the Almighty says: «وَ أَزْلَفْنَا ثَمَّ الْآخَرِينَ» (26:64). Translation: And We brought the others [i.e., the Egyptians] near as well."
    },
    {
      "id": 1683,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rank; Attaining Rank",
      "hw": "رتبہ",
      "s": "«قَرَّبَ» To grant rank and make oneself close (36 verses: 2:35-2:187-2:222-2:237-3:167-4:11-4:43-4:172-5:8-5:82-6:151-6:152-7:19-7:114-9:28-9:99-12:60-16:77-17:32-17:34-17:57-18:24-18:81-19:52-22:13-26:42-34:37-39:3-46:28-50:16-51:27-56:11-56:85-56:88-83:21-83:28)",
      "d": "«قَرُبَ» means to be near. And to perform an act that becomes a means of nearness in rank. And «قُرْبَان» is that offering (sacrifice) through which the attainment of rank and status is sought.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اتۡلُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  نَبَاَ ابۡنَیۡ اٰدَمَ  بِالۡحَقِّ ۘ اِذۡ قَرَّبَا قُرۡبَانًا» ( 5/27 )\nTranslation: And recite to them, [O Muhammad], the true story of the two sons of Adam when they both offered an offering.\nAt another place, the Divine declaration states:\n«وَ السّٰبِقُوۡنَ  السّٰبِقُوۡنَ اُولٰٓئِکَ  الۡمُقَرَّبُوۡنَ» ( 56/10،11 )\nTranslation: And the forerunners, the forerunners – those are the ones brought near."
    },
    {
      "id": 1684,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rank; Attaining Rank",
      "hw": "رتبہ",
      "s": "«مَکَنَ» When rank is attained along with authority (13 verses: 6:6-7:10-8:71-12:21-12:54-12:56-18:84-18:95-22:41-24:55-28:6-28:57-46:26)",
      "d": "«مَکَنَ» means to be of high rank. And «مَکَان» means place, abode. A place that holds a body. And «مَکَّنَ» means to grant someone authority, to bestow sovereignty. And «مَکِیْن» also means one who resides in a place, and also a person of high rank.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّہٗ  لَقَوۡلُ رَسُوۡلٍ  کَرِیۡمٍ ذِیۡ  قُوَّۃٍ  عِنۡدَ ذِی الۡعَرۡشِ مَکِیۡنٍ» ( 81/19،20 )\nTranslation: Indeed, it is the word of a noble messenger, possessor of power, with the Lord of the Throne, established in rank."
    }
  ],
  "361": [
    {
      "id": 1686,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To Turn (One's Face)",
      "hw": "رخ",
      "s": "«تَوَجَّہَ» To be attentive, to turn towards (1 verse: 28:22)",
      "d": "«وَجْہ» means face, countenance. And «وَجَّہَ» means to send towards something. And «تَوَجَّہَ اِلَیْہِ» means to be attentive, to turn (one's face), to direct one's face towards something (Majid).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَمَّا تَوَجَّہَ  تِلۡقَآءَ مَدۡیَنَ» ( 28/22 )\nTranslation: Then when he turned his face towards Madyan..."
    }
  ],
  "362": [
    {
      "id": 1687,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Worthless; Invalid",
      "hw": "ناکارہ",
      "s": "«نَکِدَ» Something that is difficult to obtain, low in quantity, and deficient in goodness (1 verse: 7:58)",
      "d": "«نَکِدَ» means «قَلِیْلُ الْخَیر» – that in which the aspect of goodness and virtue is little (M. Q). And in the words of Imam Raghib, every thing that is obtained by its seeker with great difficulty. And «نَاقَۃَ نَکِدَاء» is that she-camel which gives little milk and milking her is also difficult (Muf). And «نَکَدَ» means to prevent someone from fulfilling a need, to deprive, or to give very little. And «نَکِدَ الرَّجُل» means to be one who asks too much and has little goodness (Majid). So, «نَکِدَ» is that thing which is difficult to obtain, low in quantity, and deficient in goodness – i.e., little and worthless.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡ خَبُثَ لَا یَخۡرُجُ  اِلَّا نَکِدًا» ( 7/58 )\nTranslation: And whatever land is bad – nothing comes out of it except scanty [production]."
    },
    {
      "id": 1688,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Worthless; Invalid",
      "hw": "ناکارہ",
      "s": "«خَمْط» Bitter, sour, and bad-tasting thing (1 verse: 34:16)",
      "d": "«خَمْط» means every sour or bitter thing. The few fruits of every tree. Every long-thorned tree (Majid).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اُکُلٍ خَمۡطٍ وَّ اَثۡلٍ وَّ شَیۡءٍ مِّنۡ سِدۡرٍ قَلِیۡلٍ» ( 34/16 )\nTranslation: And for both of them [i.e., the two gardens] were fruits and date-palms and pomegranates. And [He] made them [into] gardens of bitter fruit and tamarisk and a few lote trees."
    },
    {
      "id": 1690,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Worthless; Invalid",
      "hw": "ناکارہ",
      "s": "«نَاقِصْ» A defective thing; incomplete (9 verses: 2:155-7:130-9:4-11:84-13:41-21:44-35:11-50:4-73:3)",
      "d": "«نَاقِصْ» means incomplete. «دِرْھمٌ ناقصٌ» means a dirham of deficient weight (Majid) or a debased dirham (M. Q). «نَقْص» also means deficiency, fault, and loss.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ اَخَذۡنَاۤ  اٰلَ فِرۡعَوۡنَ بِالسِّنِیۡنَ وَ نَقۡصٍ مِّنَ الثَّمَرٰتِ» ( 7/130 )\nTranslation: And We certainly seized the people of Pharaoh with years [of famine] and scarcity of fruits that they might be reminded."
    },
    {
      "id": 1691,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Worthless; Invalid",
      "hw": "ناکارہ",
      "s": "«بَخْس» Cheap and worthless thing (7 verses: 2:282-7:85-11:15-11:85-12:20-26:183-72:13)",
      "d": "«بَخْس» means deficient, cheap, contemptible (Majid). And it also means a vile and deficient thing (Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ شَرَوۡہُ بِثَمَنٍۭ بَخۡسٍ دَرَاہِمَ مَعۡدُوۡدَۃٍ» ( 12/20 )\nTranslation: And they sold him for a cheap price, a few dirhams, counted out."
    },
    {
      "id": 1692,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Worthless; Invalid",
      "hw": "ناکارہ",
      "s": "«خَبِیْث» Dirty and impure or unlawful thing (10 verses: 2:267-3:179-4:2-5:100-7:58-7:157-8:37-14:26-21:74-24:26)",
      "d": "«خَبُثَ» means to be filthy and impure, to be worthless, to be useless. And «خَبِیْث» means impure, worthless, detestable. Every corrupt and dirty thing. Its opposite is «طَیّب» (Majid).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَتَبَدَّلُوا الۡخَبِیۡثَ بِالطَّیِّبِ» ( 4/2 )\nTranslation: And do not exchange the bad for the good."
    },
    {
      "id": 1693,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Worthless; Invalid",
      "hw": "ناکارہ",
      "s": "«اَدْنٰی» That which is inferior compared to a good thing (12 verses: 2:61-2:282-4:3-5:108-7:169-30:3-32:21-33:51-33:59-53:9-58:7-73:20)",
      "d": "«اَدْنٰی» Its opposite is «اَعْلٰی». That thing which is deficient or worthless in comparison to a good thing.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالَ اَتَسۡتَبۡدِلُوۡنَ الَّذِیۡ ہُوَ اَدۡنٰی بِالَّذِیۡ ہُوَ خَیۡرٌ» ( 2/61 )\nTranslation: [Moses] said, \"Would you exchange what is inferior for what is good?\""
    }
  ],
  "363": [
    {
      "id": 1695,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rope",
      "hw": "رسی",
      "s": "«حَبْل» Used for all types of rope (6 verses: 3:103-3:112-20:66-26:44-50:16-111:5)",
      "d": "«حَبْل» Its plural is «حَبَال». It means rope and any such thing. «حَبْلُ الْوَرِیْد» means the jugular vein. And «حَبَالَۃُ الْصَیَّاد» means the hunter's snare. There is generality in the usage of this word.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فِیۡ  جِیۡدِہَا حَبۡلٌ مِّنۡ مَّسَدٍ» ( 111/5 )\nTranslation: Around her neck will be a rope of twisted palm fiber."
    },
    {
      "id": 1696,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rope",
      "hw": "رسی",
      "s": "The term «سَبَب» is used specifically for a rope that can be employed as a means for travel or climbing (9 verses: 2:166, 18:84, 18:85, 18:89, 18:92, 22:15, 38:10, 40:36, 40:37).",
      "d": "«سَبَب» refers to the rope used for climbing a date palm (m.f.) and also means 'path', 'journey', 'travel provisions', and the rope for securing travel provisions (munjid). For example, the Quran states: «مَنۡ کَانَ یَظُنُّ اَنۡ لَّنۡ یَّنۡصُرَہُ اللّٰہُ فِی الدُّنۡیَا وَ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ فَلۡیَمۡدُدۡ بِسَبَبٍ اِلَی السَّمَآءِ ثُمَّ لۡیَقۡطَعۡ فَلۡیَنۡظُرۡ ہَلۡ یُذۡہِبَنَّ کَیۡدُہٗ مَا یَغِیۡظُ» (22/15). Translation: 'Whoever thinks that Allah will not aid him in this world and the Hereafter, let him extend a rope to the sky and then cut it off, and let him see whether his stratagem can dispel his rage.'"
    }
  ],
  "364": [
    {
      "id": 1697,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Relative (Close Kin)",
      "hw": "رشتہ دار",
      "s": "«اَقْرَبُوْنَ» refers to close relatives who have a prescribed share in inheritance (23 verses: 2:83, 2:177, 2:180, 2:215, 3:45, 4:7, 4:8, 4:33, 4:36, 4:135, 5:106, 6:152, 8:41, 9:113, 16:90, 17:26, 24:22, 26:214, 30:38, 35:18, 42:23, 59:7, 90:15).",
      "d": "«قَرُبَ» means 'to be near' or 'close'. This word encompasses time, distance, rank, and kinship—essentially a comprehensive meaning. «اَقْرَبَ» means 'closer' or 'more near'. The terms «اَقْرَبُوْنَ», «اَقْرَبِیْن», «ذَا قُرْبٰی», or «ذَوِی الْقُرْبٰی» are specifically used for close relatives. Relatives can be distant or close. Close relatives are those for whom Allah has prescribed a share in inheritance, i.e., sons, daughters, mother, father, husband, wife, and sisters and brothers. For example, the Quran states: «لِلرِّجَالِ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّمَّا تَرَکَ الۡوَالِدٰنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبُوۡنَ» (4/7). Translation: 'For men is a share of what the parents and the closest relatives leave behind.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1698,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Relative (Paternal Lineage)",
      "hw": "رشتہ دار",
      "s": "«نَسَبَ» refers to relatives on the father's side (3 verses: 23:101, 25:54, 37:158).",
      "d": "«نَسَبَ یَنْسُبُ» means 'to mention lineage' or 'to discover lineage'. «اِسْتَنْسَبَ» means 'to mention lineage' or 'to inquire about lineage'. «نَسَب» and «اَنْسَاب» mean 'kinship' or 'relationship' (munjid). 'Nisbah' (lineage) refers to relatives through the father, as lineage is traced through the father. This includes, besides «اَقْرَبُوْن», uncles (chachas) and aunts (phophis) and their offspring. For example, the Quran states: «فَاِذَا نُفِخَ فِی الصُّوۡرِ فَلَاۤ اَنۡسَابَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ یَوۡمَئِذٍ» (23/101). Translation: 'Then when the Horn is blown, there will be no kinship between them that Day.' Imam Raghib notes that 'nisbah' means relatives from either parent (mufradat), i.e., it includes relatives through the mother (maternal uncles/aunts) as well."
    },
    {
      "id": 1699,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Relative (In-Laws)",
      "hw": "رشتہ دار",
      "s": "«صِھْر» means in-laws (1 verse: 25:54).",
      "d": "«صِھْر» means in-laws, i.e., relatives that come into existence as a result of marriage. For a wife, her husband's paternal relatives are in-laws. For a husband, his wife's paternal relatives are in-laws. For example, the Quran states: «وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ مِنَ الۡمَآءِ بَشَرًا فَجَعَلَہٗ نَسَبًا وَّ صِہۡرًا» (25/54). Translation: 'And He it is who created man from water, then made him having lineage and in-law relations.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1700,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Relative (Blood Relations)",
      "hw": "رشتہ دار",
      "s": "«اُولُو الْاَرْحَام» are relatives connected by blood, and their circle is very wide (2 verses: 8:75, 33:6).",
      "d": "«اُولُو الْاَرْحَام» means relatives connected by blood. Their circle is very wide, including paternal uncles and aunts (though in inheritance law, their rank comes after those with fixed shares (dhawi al-furoodh) and the 'asabah). For example, the Quran states: «وَ اُولُوا الۡاَرۡحَامِ بَعۡضُہُمۡ اَوۡلٰی بِبَعۡضٍ فِیۡ کِتٰبِ اللّٰہِ» (8/75). Translation: 'And those related by blood are more entitled to one another in the decree of Allah.' Note: 'Ilm al-fara'idh' is the knowledge through which one determines who the heirs are, who is not, and what share each heir receives. 'Dhawi al-furoodh' are legal heirs whose share is predetermined (no substitution possible). 'Asabah' is an heir whose share is not fixed; if alone, they take the entire estate, and if with a fixed-share heir, they take the remainder."
    },
    {
      "id": 1701,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Relative",
      "hw": "رشتہ دار",
      "s": "«اِلَّ» means the covenant made with relatives (27 verses: 2:144-4:24-5:3-5:119-9:10-9:38-9:58-9:59-9:83-9:87-9:93-9:96-9:100-10:7-19:6-19:55-20:109-27:19-33:51-46:15-48:18-58:22-69:21-88:9-89:28-98:8-101:7)",
      "d": "«اِلَّ» is generally translated as kinship or relationship, but lexically it means the covenant made with relatives. «اِلَّ» means covenant, agreement, neighbor (masc.). And «اِلَّ الرَّجُل» means «جَارَ بِہٖ» i.e., he made him his neighbor (m. q.). For example, in the Quran: «لَا یَرۡقُبُوۡنَ فِیۡ مُؤۡمِنٍ اِلًّا وَّ لَا ذِمَّۃً» (9/10) Translation: They do not regard any bond of kinship or any treaty with a believer. «ذِمَّۃ» correctly means not just a treaty but a treaty of security and protection. And «اِلَّ» means any kind of covenant made with one's neighbors and relatives."
    }
  ],
  "365": [
    {
      "id": 1702,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Pleasure / Approval",
      "hw": "خوشنودی",
      "s": "«رِضْوَان» and «مَرْضَاۃ» are used in the meaning of mere pleasure, while «وَجْہ» includes the aspect of attention along with pleasure (18 verses: 2:207, 2:265, 3:15, 3:162, 3:174, 4:114, 5:2, 5:16, 9:21, 9:72, 9:109, 47:28, 48:29, 57:20, 57:27, 59:8, 60:1, 66:1).",
      "d": "«رَضِیَ» is a well-known word meaning 'to be pleased'. From it, «رِضْوَان», «رَضْوَان», and «مَرْضَاۃ» also come as verbal nouns, meaning 'pleasure', 'approval', or 'satisfaction' (munjid). For example, the Quran states: «یَبۡتَغُوۡنَ فَضۡلًا مِّنۡ رَّبِّہِمۡ وَ رِضۡوَانًا» (5/2). Translation: 'Seeking bounty from their Lord and His pleasure.' At another place, the Divine command states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّبِیُّ لِمَ تُحَرِّمُ مَاۤ اَحَلَّ اللّٰہُ لَکَ ۚ تَبۡتَغِیۡ مَرۡضَاتِ اَزۡوَاجِکَ» (66/1). Translation: 'O Prophet, why do you prohibit what Allah has made lawful for you, seeking the approval of your wives?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1703,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Pleasure / Countenance",
      "hw": "خوشنودی",
      "s": "«وَجْہ» means 'face' (66 verses: 2:112, 2:115, 2:144, 2:148, 2:149, 2:150, 2:177, 2:272, 3:20, 3:106, 3:107, 4:43, 4:47, 4:125, 5:6, 5:108, 6:52, 6:79, 7:29, 8:50, 10:26, 10:27, 10:105, 12:9, 12:93, 12:96, 13:22, 14:50, 16:58, 17:7, 17:97, 18:28, 18:29, 20:111, 21:39, 22:11, 22:72, 23:104, 25:34, 27:90, 28:88, 30:30, 30:38, 30:39, 30:43, 31:22, 33:66, 39:24, 39:60, 43:17, 47:27, 48:29, 51:29, 54:48, 55:27, 67:22, 67:27, 75:22, 75:24, 76:9, 80:38, 80:40, 83:24, 88:2, 88:8, 92:20).",
      "d": "«وَجْہ» means 'face', 'countenance', 'front', 'pleasure', and 'that part of everything which appears first'. «وَجْہُ النَّھَار» means 'the first part of the day' (mufradat, munjid). When a person is angry with someone, they turn their face away from them; when pleased, they turn towards them with more attention. This is the meaning of «وَجْھ» in the sense of pleasure—i.e., seeking someone's pleasure by avoiding angry acts and doing good deeds. For example, the Quran states: «وَ مَا تُنۡفِقُوۡنَ اِلَّا ابۡتِغَآءَ وَجۡہِ اللّٰہِ» (2/272). Translation: 'And whatever you spend is only seeking the countenance of Allah.'"
    }
  ],
  "366": [
    {
      "id": 1704,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To Desire / To Incline",
      "hw": "رغبت",
      "s": "«رَغِبَ» means to desire or to have a heartfelt longing for something and to strive for its attainment (6 verses: 4:127, 9:59, 9:120, 21:90, 68:32, 94:8).",
      "d": "«رَغِبَ» means to desire or to have a heartfelt longing for something and to strive for its attainment (mufradat). For example, the Quran states: «فَاِذَا فَرَغۡتَ فَانۡصَبۡ وَ اِلٰی رَبِّکَ فَارۡغَبۡ» (94/7,8). Translation: 'So when you have finished [your duties], then stand up [for worship] and to your Lord direct your longing.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1705,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To Compete / To Strive in Rivalry",
      "hw": "رغبت",
      "s": "«تَنَافُس» refers to competition in the desire for good deeds (1 verse: 83:26).",
      "d": "«نَفِسَ» means 'to envy'. «نَفَّسَ فِی الْاَمْر» means 'to encourage in an affair'. «تَنَافُس» means 'to vie with one another in boasting' or 'to have a desire to compete in good deeds'—i.e., to strive with a competitive spirit to surpass one another. For example, the Quran states: «یُسۡقَوۡنَ مِنۡ رَّحِیۡقٍ مَّخۡتُوۡمٍ خِتٰمُہٗ مِسۡکٌ ؕ وَ فِیۡ ذٰلِکَ فَلۡیَتَنَافَسِ الۡمُتَنَافِسُوۡنَ» (83/25,26). Translation: 'They will be given to drink a cup [of wine] whose mixture is of Kafur, and in this let the competitors compete.'"
    }
  ],
  "367": [
    {
      "id": 1706,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to place",
      "hw": "رکھنا",
      "s": "«وَضَعَ» is general: placing something whether it is seen or not (7 verses: 3:36, 18:49, 39:69, 46:15, 55:7, 55:10, 94:2)",
      "d": "«وَضَعَ» is the opposite of «رَفَعَ», meaning to lift, to raise. And «وَضَعَ» means to place something gently down. The opposite of «رَفِیْع» (exalted) is «وَضِیْع», meaning a person of no esteem or status. And «وَضَع حَمَل» means to place a burden down, whether it is apparent or hidden.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ وَضَعۡنَا عَنۡکَ وِزۡرَکَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَنۡقَضَ ظَہۡرَکَ» (94:2,3)\nTranslation: And We have removed from you your burden which had broken your back."
    },
    {
      "id": 1707,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To Keep",
      "hw": "رکھنا",
      "s": "«اَلْقٰی» means to place something down such that others cannot see it (66 verses: 2:37-3:44-4:90-4:91-4:94-4:171-5:64-7:115-7:107-7:116-7:117-7:120-7:150-8:12-10:80-10:81-12:10-12:93-12:96-15:19-16:15-16:28-16:86-16:87-17:39-20:20-20:39-20:65-20:66-20:69-20:70-20:87-22:52-22:53-25:8-25:13-26:32-26:43-26:44-26:45-26:46-26:223-27:6-27:10-27:28-27:29-28:7-28:31-28:86-31:10-37:97-38:34-40:15-41:35-41:40-43:53-50:7-50:24-50:26-50:37-54:25-60:1-67:7-67:8-75:15-84:4)",
      "d": "The original meaning of «اَلْقٰی» is 'to throw'. And the difference between 'to keep' and 'to throw' is that in 'to keep', the aspect of gentleness and caution is considered. And if something is done hastily and without caution, it is called 'to throw'. And 'to place' is an intermediate state between the two. Whenever there is an aspect of gentleness and caution in «اَلْقٰی», it also means 'to keep'. Another feature of «اَلْقٰی» is that it refers to placing something that others can see, whereas in «وَضَعَ», this is not necessarily the case. For example, in the Quran: «وَ اَلۡقٰی فِی الۡاَرۡضِ رَوَاسِیَ» (16/15) Translation: And He placed firm mountains on the earth. And He placed (or cast) mountains on the earth (Jalandhari)."
    }
  ],
  "368": [
    {
      "id": 1708,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "color",
      "hw": "رنگ",
      "s": "«لَوْن» refers to natural color (6 verses: 16:13, 16:69, 30:22, 35:27, 35:28, 39:21)",
      "d": "«لَوْن» means natural color, such as black, white, green, red, yellow, blue, etc. Its plural is «اَلْوَان».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مِنَ الۡجِبَالِ جُدَدٌۢ بِیۡضٌ وَّ حُمۡرٌ مُّخۡتَلِفٌ اَلۡوَانُہَا» (35:37)\nTranslation: And among the mountains are streaks white and red, of varying colors."
    },
    {
      "id": 1709,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "color",
      "hw": "رنگ",
      "s": "«صِبْغَۃ» is the color that is applied or dyed, whether material or spiritual (2 verses: 2:138, 23:20)",
      "d": "«صَبَغَ» means to color, to dye. And «صَبَّاغ» means a dyer. The word «صَبَغَہ» is used in both material and spiritual contexts. In a spiritual sense, it means the effect and hue produced on a person by something else. «صَبَّغَ بِالْمَاءِ» means to dye with water (baptism). «تَصَبَّغْ فِیْ دِیْنِہٖ» means for the color of religion to be firmly established on someone; to be firm in religion.\nThe Quran states:\n«صِبۡغَۃَ اللّٰہِ ۚ وَ مَنۡ اَحۡسَنُ مِنَ اللّٰہِ صِبۡغَۃً» (2:138)\nTranslation: [Our religion is] the color of Allah. And who is better than Allah in coloring? [i.e., whose religion is better or who gives a better color?]\nNote: (Baptism: A Christian religious ritual where a non-Christian is made a Christian by immersion in or sprinkling with dyed water)."
    }
  ],
  "369": [],
  "370": [
    {
      "id": 1717,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "fasting person",
      "hw": "روزہ دار",
      "s": "«صَائِم» refers to a fasting person (1 verse: 33:35)",
      "d": "«صَوْم» (its plural is «صِیَام») means fasting. «صَامَ» means to observe fast. That is, from the pre-dawn meal (suhoor) to the sunset meal (iftar), abstaining from eating, drinking, and certain other acts according to Islamic law. And «صَائِم» means a fasting person.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ الصَّآئِمِیۡنَ وَ الصّٰٓئِمٰتِ» (33:35)\nTranslation: And the men who fast and the women who fast."
    },
    {
      "id": 1718,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "fasting person",
      "hw": "روزہ دار",
      "s": "«سَائِح» refers to a fasting person who, besides abstaining from food and drink, also observes other prohibitions (2 verses: 9:112, 66:5)",
      "d": "«سَیْح، اَلسَّاحَۃ» means an open space or the courtyard of a house. And «سَاحَ» means to travel, to tour; to roam in open land; to travel to distant places.\nAnd «سَاحَ» also means to fast and to observe all its rulings, meaning to abstain not only from food and drink but also from the sins of the faculties like eyes, ears, tongue, etc. According to the author of 'Munjid', «سَائِح» refers to a fasting person who resides in the mosque (Munjid).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَلتَّآئِبُوۡنَ الۡعٰبِدُوۡنَ الۡحٰمِدُوۡنَ السَّآئِحُوۡنَ» (9:112)\nTranslation: The repentant, the worshippers, the praisers, the fasting ones."
    }
  ],
  "371": [
    {
      "id": 1719,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop/prevent",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«مَنَعَ» means to stop or prevent with the hand or tongue (13 verses: 2:114, 4:141, 7:12, 9:54, 12:63, 17:59, 17:94, 18:55, 20:92, 21:43, 38:75, 59:2, 107:7)",
      "d": "«مَنَعَ» is primarily used in two meanings:\n(1) To not give (opposite of giving), to be stingy. And «مَنَّاع» means a stingy person.\n(2) To stop someone with the hand or tongue; to not let someone do something; to deprive; to prevent.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ اَظۡلَمُ مِمَّنۡ مَّنَعَ مَسٰجِدَ اللّٰہِ اَنۡ یُّذۡکَرَ فِیۡہَا اسۡمُہٗ» (2:114)\nTranslation: And who is more unjust than he who prevents the name of Allah from being mentioned in His mosques?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1720,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop/prevent",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«نَھٰی» means to stop from evil deeds (18 verses: 3:104, 3:110, 3:114, 4:31, 4:161, 6:26, 6:28, 7:165, 7:166, 9:67, 9:71, 11:116, 16:90, 22:41, 29:45, 58:8, 79:40, 96:9)",
      "d": "«اَلنَّھْی» is generally used for stopping and refraining from evil deeds (munkarat).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اَمَّا مَنۡ خَافَ مَقَامَ رَبِّہٖ وَ نَہَی النَّفۡسَ عَنِ الۡہَوٰی» (79:40)\nTranslation: But as for he who feared the position of his Lord and prevented the soul from [following] desire,"
    },
    {
      "id": 1721,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop/prevent",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«عَوَّقَ» means to prevent someone from good deeds (1 verse: 33:18)",
      "d": "«اَلْعَوْق وَالْعُوْق» means a useless person. «عَوَّقَ» means one who prevents people from good deeds (Munjid).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَدۡ یَعۡلَمُ اللّٰہُ الۡمُعَوِّقِیۡنَ مِنۡکُمۡ وَ الۡقَآئِلِیۡنَ لِاِخۡوَانِہِمۡ ہُلُمَّ اِلَیۡنَا» (33:18)\nTranslation: Allah knows those who hinder among you and those who say to their brothers, 'Come to us.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1722,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop/prevent",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«عَضَلَ» means to keep someone from something in order to gain some benefit (2 verses: 2:232, 4:19)",
      "d": "«عَضَلَ» means to constrict, to prevent (Munjid), to hinder strictly (Mufradat). «عَضُلَہ» means a muscle. «عَضَّلَ» means to cause constriction, to be an obstacle in achieving a goal (Munjid). This word is generally used in the context of a man preventing his wife from marriage, constricting and troubling her, to gain some benefit from that action.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَعۡضُلُوۡہُنَّ لِتَذۡہَبُوۡا بِبَعۡضِ مَاۤ اٰتَیۡتُمُوۡہُنَّ» (4:19)\nTranslation: And do not constrain them [i.e., the women] in order to take back some of what you gave them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1723,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«اَمْسَکَ» to not let something present slip from the hand (22 verses: 2:231-2:256-4:15-5:4-7:170-16:59-16:79-17:100-22:65-31:22-33:37-35:2-35:41-38:39-39:38-39:42-43:21-43:43-60:10-65:2-67:19-67:21)",
      "d": "«اَمْسَکَ» means to cling to something and protect it (muf). This word is generally used when something is already in one's possession and is not let slip from the hand. And «مُمِسْک» also comes in the meaning of miser.\nFor example: In the Quran: «فَاَمۡسِکُوۡہُنَّ بِمَعۡرُوۡفٍ اَوۡ سَرِّحُوۡہُنَّ بِمَعۡرُوۡفٍ» ( 2/231 )\nTranslation: So either keep them (the divorced women) with goodness or release them with goodness."
    },
    {
      "id": 1724,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«صَدَّ» to gradually stop someone from their intention with gentle conduct (37 verses: 2:217-3:99-4:55-4:61-4:160-4:167-5:2-5:91-7:45-7:86-8:34-8:36-8:47-9:34-11:19-13:33-14:3-14:10-16:94-20:16-22:25-27:24-27:43-28:87-29:38-34:32-34:43-40:37-43:37-43:62-47:1-47:32-47:34-48:25-58:16-63:2-63:5)",
      "d": "«صَدَّ» means to stop, repel, prevent. And «صَدَّ عَنْ» means to turn away, incline. (manjad) To stop with gentle conduct (fal 188). Turning away and deviation. In Ibn al-Faris's words: «المیل اِلٰی اَحَدِ الْجَانِبَیْن وَ عَدَلَ عَنْہُ (م ل) وَ صَدّٓ» means «مَنَعَ عَنْ قَصْدِ الشَّیْءُ خَاصَۃٌ» (faqal 92), i.e., to stop someone from their intention specifically. So the word «صَدّ» is used for stopping someone from their purpose with soft policy.\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ تَذُوۡقُوا السُّوۡٓءَ بِمَا صَدَدۡتُّمۡ  عَنۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ» ( 16/94 )\nTranslation: And now taste the evil consequence of what you used to prevent from the way of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1725,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«اَحْصَرَ» to encircle and stop, and to constrict (4 verses: 2:196-2:273-4:90-9:5)",
      "d": "«اَحْصَرَ» means to encircle, to besiege, to make someone's place narrow. And «حِصَار» means fortress. And «حَاصَرَ» means to besiege and prevent reinforcements. (manjad)\nFor example: In the Quran: «لِلۡفُقَرَآءِ الَّذِیۡنَ اُحۡصِرُوۡا فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ لَا یَسۡتَطِیۡعُوۡنَ ضَرۡبًا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» ( 2/273 )\nTranslation: (This spending) is for the poor who are restrained in the way of Allah and cannot travel in the land."
    },
    {
      "id": 1726,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«حَظَرَ» to stop by fencing (1 verse: 17:20)",
      "d": "«حَظَرَ» means to fence around something for its protection or to gather something and fence around it.\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ مَا  کَانَ  عَطَـآءُ  رَبِّکَ  مَحۡظُوۡرًا» ( 17/20 )\nTranslation: And the reward of your Lord is not restricted."
    },
    {
      "id": 1727,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«عَکَفَ» to stop out of reverence from one's intention (8 verses: 2:125-2:187-7:138-20:91-20:97-21:52-22:25-26:71)",
      "d": "«عَکَفَ» means to focus on something with reverence and remain attached to it (muf). To remain confined. To stay stopped. To be imprisoned (manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran: «عَنِ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ  وَ الۡہَدۡیَ مَعۡکُوۡفًا اَنۡ یَّبۡلُغَ مَحِلَّہٗ» ( 48/25 )\nTranslation: They are the ones who disbelieved and prevented you from the Sacred Mosque and prevented the offerings from reaching their place."
    },
    {
      "id": 1728,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«کَفَّ» to stop an attack or defend (5 verses: 4:77-4:91-5:11-21:39-48:24)",
      "d": "«کَفّ» means palm of the hand. And «کَفَّ» means to stop a strike with the palm, to defend, to save, to stop (muf). Then this word started to be used for stopping a strike or for defense.\nFor example: In the Quran: «اِذۡ ہَمَّ قَوۡمٌ اَنۡ یَّبۡسُطُوۡۤا اِلَیۡکُمۡ  اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ فَکَفَّ اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ عَنۡکُمۡ» ( 5/11 )\nTranslation: When a people intended to stretch their hands towards you, so He stopped their hands from you."
    },
    {
      "id": 1729,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«ثَبَّطَ» to stop and delay due to sluggishness (1 verse: 9:46)",
      "d": "«ثَبَّطَ» means to delay in a work. And not to do that work, to remain stopped from it, and to mean delay and sluggishness. «اَثْبَطَہُ الْمَرْض» means illness clings to someone and does not leave (manjad). And «ثَبَّطَہُ الْمَرْض» means illness stopped him (manjad). To be unable to do a work due to delay or sluggishness.\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ لَوۡ  اَرَادُوا الۡخُرُوۡجَ لَاَعَدُّوۡا  لَہٗ  عُدَّۃً وَّ لٰکِنۡ  کَرِہَ  اللّٰہُ  انۡۢبِعَاثَہُمۡ  فَثَبَّطَہُمۡ» ( 9/46 )\nTranslation: And if they had intended to go forth, they would have prepared for it some preparation. But Allah disliked their being sent, so He stopped them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1730,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«ذَادَ» to push away and keep stopped, not let come near (1 verse: 28:23)",
      "d": "«ذَادَ» means to push away, to repel, to not let come near, to keep stopped (muf manjad). And «ذَوَّدَ عَنْ حَسْبِہٖ» means to protect and support someone from oneself (manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ  وَجَدَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِہِمُ  امۡرَاَتَیۡنِ تَذُوۡدٰنِ» ( 28/23 )\nTranslation: And he found besides them two women who were keeping (their flocks) stopped."
    },
    {
      "id": 1731,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«وَزَعَ» to stop for the sake of arrangement and order (3 verses: 27:17-27:83-41:19)",
      "d": "«وَزَعَ» means to stop, to prevent. And «وَزَعَ الْجَیْش» means to keep the army in arranged divisions. And «اَلْاَوْزَع» means groups. Its singular is not used. And «اَلْوَزْعَۃُ» its plural is «وَازِعُ» meaning the helper and protector of the king (manjad). So «وَزَعَ» is used in the meaning of stopping for arrangement and order.\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ حُشِرَ لِسُلَیۡمٰنَ جُنُوۡدُہٗ  مِنَ الۡجِنِّ وَ الۡاِنۡسِ  وَ الطَّیۡرِ  فَہُمۡ  یُوۡزَعُوۡنَ» ( 27/17 )\nTranslation: And gathered for Solomon were his hosts of the jinn, humans, and birds, and they were arranged in groups."
    },
    {
      "id": 1732,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«حَبَسَ» to stop from standing, to stop from going (2 verses: 5:106-11:8)",
      "d": "«حَبَسَ» means to imprison, to protect completely, to prevent (manjad). And to mean to stop someone from rising. (muf)\nFor example: In the Quran: «تَحۡبِسُوۡنَہُمَا مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ الصَّلٰوۃِ» ( 5/106 )\nTranslation: So detain the two of them after the prayer."
    },
    {
      "id": 1733,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«حِجْرًا مَّھْجُوْرًا» is used metaphorically. To seek refuge from harm and loss. (3 verses: 6:138-25:22-25:53)",
      "d": "«حَجَرَ» means hard stone, and «حِجْرًا مَّھْجُوْرًا» is a metaphor. It refers to such a strong barrier that cannot be removed. In pre-Islamic times, it was customary that when someone came whom one feared would cause harm, upon hearing the words «حِجْرًا مَّھْجُوْرًا» (meaning 'we seek refuge from you'), the enemy would say nothing. The Quran has also used this metaphorically:\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«یَوۡمَ یَرَوۡنَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃَ  لَا بُشۡرٰی یَوۡمَئِذٍ لِّلۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ حِجۡرًا مَّحۡجُوۡرًا» (25/22)\nTranslation: On the day they see the angels, there will be no good news for the criminals that day, and they will say, '[May God] keep [you] away and sealed [from us]' (Jalandhari)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1734,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«اِنْتَھٰی» to stop from obscenities and nonsense. (19 verses: 2:192-2:193-2:275-4:171-5:73-5:91-8:19-8:38-8:39-9:12-19:46-26:116-26:167-33:60-36:18-53:14-53:42-59:7-96:15)",
      "d": "«اِنْتَھٰی» means to stop, to return. To adhere to the prohibition of obscenities and nonsense and to abandon them.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ یَصُدَّکُمۡ عَنۡ ذِکۡرِ اللّٰہِ وَ عَنِ الصَّلٰوۃِ ۚ فَہَلۡ اَنۡتُمۡ مُّنۡتَہُوۡنَ» (5/91)\nTranslation: And (so that Satan may) keep you away from the remembrance of Allah and from prayer. Then will you desist?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1735,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«اَکْدٰی» heart becoming hard and stingy after spending a little. (2 verses: 7:58-53:34)",
      "d": "«اَلْکُدْیَۃ» means hard and solid ground, a hard rock. And «حَفَرَ فَاکْدٰی» means he dug until he reached hard ground (mujad). And «کَدّٰی» means to ask, to beg for forgiveness. And «سَاَلَہٗ فَاَکْدٰی» means he asked him but found him as hard as a rock and gave nothing (manjad). So this word has come to mean stopping after a little spending.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ اَعۡطٰی قَلِیۡلًا  وَّ  اَکۡدٰی» (53/34)\nTranslation: He gave a little, then stopped (withheld his hand)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1737,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to stop",
      "hw": "روکنا",
      "s": "«قَلَعَ» to suddenly stop a started task. (1 verse: 11:44)",
      "d": "«قَلَعَ» means to abandon a task, to leave it, and to stop (manjad). To suddenly abandon an ongoing task.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ قِیۡلَ یٰۤاَرۡضُ ابۡلَعِیۡ مَآءَکِ وَ یٰسَمَآءُ اَقۡلِعِیۡ وَ غِیۡضَ الۡمَآءُ» (11/44)\nTranslation: And it was said, 'O earth, swallow your water, and O sky, cease,' and the water subsided."
    }
  ],
  "372": [
    {
      "id": 1738,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "to crush",
      "hw": "روندنا",
      "s": "«حَطَمَ» to crush and pulverize or to break and smash. (1 verse: 27:18)",
      "d": "«حَطَمَ» means to break, to twist. And «حَطُوْم» is a fierce wind that breaks everything and leaves it destroyed. And «حُطَام» is something broken, twisted, or pulverized (manjad). This word is used for crushing something to pieces.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«قَالَتۡ نَمۡلَۃٌ  یّٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّمۡلُ ادۡخُلُوۡا مَسٰکِنَکُمۡ ۚ لَا یَحۡطِمَنَّکُمۡ  سُلَیۡمٰنُ  وَ جُنُوۡدُہٗ  ۙ وَ ہُمۡ  لَا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ» (27/18)\nTranslation: An ant said, 'O ants, enter your dwellings, lest Solomon and his armies crush you while they are unaware.'"
    }
  ],
  "373": [
    {
      "id": 1740,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "splendor",
      "hw": "رونق",
      "s": "«زَھْرَۃ» is used for the external glow and splendor of worldly plants. (1 verse: 20:131)",
      "d": "«زَھْرَۃ» means adornment, sparkle, glitter. And «زَھْرَۃُ الدُّنْیَا» means the external glow and splendor of the world (manjad). This word is generally used for the fleeting attractions and colors of this transient world.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ لَا تَمُدَّنَّ عَیۡنَیۡکَ  اِلٰی مَا مَتَّعۡنَا بِہٖۤ اَزۡوَاجًا مِّنۡہُمۡ زَہۡرَۃَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ  الدُّنۡیَا» (20/131)\nTranslation: And do not extend your eyes toward that which We have given some of them to enjoy, [as] the adornment of the worldly life."
    },
    {
      "id": 1742,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "splendor",
      "hw": "رونق",
      "s": "«بَھْجَۃ» comes for the splendor of plants. (3 verses: 22:5-27:60-50:7)",
      "d": "«بَھْجَۃ» means anything that pleases the heart, and its basic meaning is delight. According to Khalil, it is related to the good color and freshness of something. For humans, it also comes, but it is mostly used for the freshness, verdancy, and bloom of plants, for plants being in full blossom.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ اَنۡزَلَ لَکُمۡ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً ۚ فَاَنۡۢبَتۡنَا بِہٖ حَدَآئِقَ ذَاتَ بَہۡجَۃٍ» (27/60)\nTranslation: And He sent down for you from the sky water, and We grew thereby gardens of beautiful bloom."
    }
  ],
  "374": [
    {
      "id": 1743,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "sand",
      "hw": "ریت",
      "s": "«سَرَاب» that sand which at noon in deserts appears as water due to intense sunlight. (2 verses: 24:39-78:20)",
      "d": "«سَرَاب» is that sand which at noon in forests or deserts appears as water due to the intensity of sunlight. Every drinkable thing is called «شَرَاب». And that which appears to be wine but is not drinkable is called «سَرَاب» (mufrad). Then metaphorically, it is used for any unreal thing, and generally, this word is used for that vast field of sand which, when seen from a distance at an angle in the sunlight, seems to shimmer like water.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«کَسَرَابٍۭ بِقِیۡعَۃٍ یَّحۡسَبُہُ الظَّمۡاٰنُ مَآءً» (24/39)\nTranslation: Like a mirage in a plain which the thirsty one thinks is water."
    },
    {
      "id": 1744,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "sand",
      "hw": "ریت",
      "s": "«کَثِیْب» a mound of loose, slipping sand. (1 verse: 73:14)",
      "d": "«کَثِیْب» a long, wide sandhill (fal 272).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«یَوۡمَ تَرۡجُفُ الۡاَرۡضُ وَ الۡجِبَالُ وَ کَانَتِ الۡجِبَالُ  کَثِیۡبًا مَّہِیۡلًا» (73/14)\nTranslation: The day the earth and the mountains will shake, and the mountains will be like loose sand dunes."
    },
    {
      "id": 1745,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "sand",
      "hw": "ریت",
      "s": "«اَحْقَاف» a vast field comprising many sand dunes. (1 verse: 46:21)",
      "d": "«اَحْقَاف» is the plural of «حَقَفَ», meaning a field with many sand dunes. And «اَحْقَاف» means a vast field spread over hundreds of miles of sand (manjad). And also means the region of inhabited quarter western Yemen, which was the center of the people of Ad (maq).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ اذۡکُرۡ  اَخَا عَادٍ ؕ اِذۡ  اَنۡذَرَ قَوۡمَہٗ بِالۡاَحۡقَافِ» (46/21)\nTranslation: And remember the brother of Ad, when he warned his people in the sandy region of Al-Ahqaf."
    }
  ],
  "375": [
    {
      "id": 1748,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Excess",
      "hw": "زائد",
      "s": "«ضِعْف» means double or more than the original amount. Also see 'increase; to increase' (8 verses: 2:265-7:38-17:75-30:39-33:30-33:68-34:37-38:61)",
      "d": "«ضِعْف» means as much as the thing is and more, double. For example, in the Quran it is: «اِذًا لَّاَذَقۡنٰکَ ضِعۡفَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ وَ ضِعۡفَ الۡمَمَاتِ ثُمَّ لَا تَجِدُ لَکَ عَلَیۡنَا نَصِیۡرًا » (17/75) Translation: And if that were to happen, We would punish you doubly in this world and doubly after death, then you would find no helper against Us. And the plural of «ضِعْف» is «ضِعْفَیْن» which comes for emphasis. For example, in the Quran it is: «کَمَثَلِ جَنَّۃٍۭ بِرَبۡوَۃٍ اَصَابَہَا وَابِلٌ فَاٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا ضِعۡفَیۡنِ» (2/265) Translation: Its example is of a garden on a height; when a downpour strikes it, it yields double the fruit. And «ضَاعَفَ» means to increase something greatly. For example, the divine command is: «وَ اللّٰہُ یُضٰاعِفُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ» (2/261) Translation: And Allah multiplies [reward] for whom He wills."
    }
  ],
  "376": [
    {
      "id": 1750,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To Force",
      "hw": "زبردستی",
      "s": "«جَبَرَ» to correct or fix something with force and pressure (10 verses: 5:22-11:59-14:15-19:14-19:32-26:130-28:19-40:35-50:45-59:23)",
      "d": "«جَبَرَ» has two basic meanings: (1) force (2) correction. That is, to correct something with force and pressure. (Example) «جَبَرَ الْعَظْم» means to set a broken bone, and «جَبَرَ عَلَی الْاَمْر» means to force someone into an affair. Allah Almighty describes His attributes saying: For example, in the Quran it is: «الۡعَزِیۡزُ  الۡجَبَّارُ  الۡمُتَکَبِّرُ» (59/23) Translation: (Allah Almighty) is The Mighty, The Compeller, and The Supreme. Then this word is sometimes used in the meaning of mere force. For example, the divine command is: «وَ  اِذَا  بَطَشۡتُمۡ  بَطَشۡتُمۡ  جَبَّارِیۡنَ» (26/130) Translation: And when you seize [someone], you seize them tyrannically."
    },
    {
      "id": 1752,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To Force",
      "hw": "زبردستی",
      "s": "«سَخَّرَ» to subject something to a purpose by force (24 verses: 2:164-7:54-13:2-14:32-14:33-16:12-16:14-16:79-21:79-22:36-22:37-22:65-29:61-31:20-31:29-35:13-38:18-38:36-39:5-43:13-43:32-45:12-45:13-69:7)",
      "d": "«سَخَّرَ» means to ridicule or mock. And «سَخَّرَ» has two basic meanings: (1) force (2) purposefulness, that is, to take something with force towards a purpose. To force into work. To be bound by command. In this, there is no role for anyone's will or preference. This word is generally used for matters of subjugation in the universe. For example, in the Quran it is: «وَ سَخَّرَ لَکُمُ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ دَآئِبَیۡنِ ۚ  وَ سَخَّرَ لَکُمُ الَّیۡلَ وَ النَّہَارَ» (14/33) Translation: And He has subjected for you the sun and the moon, both continuously [moving] by His command. And He has subjected for you the night and the day. At another place, the divine command is: «وَ رَفَعۡنَا بَعۡضَہُمۡ فَوۡقَ بَعۡضٍ دَرَجٰتٍ لِّیَتَّخِذَ بَعۡضُہُمۡ بَعۡضًا سُخۡرِیًّا» (43/32) Translation: And We have raised some of them above others in degrees so that some may employ others in service."
    },
    {
      "id": 1753,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To Force",
      "hw": "زبردستی",
      "s": "«رَھِقَ» conveys the meaning of force and covering or concealing (9 verses: 10:26-10:27-18:73-68:43-70:44-72:6-72:13-74:17-80:41)",
      "d": "«رَھِقَ» means for one thing to rise over another and cover it. (Example) «رَھِقَہُ الْاَمْر» means an affair has overwhelmed him with force. So in «رَھِقَ» two things are found: (1) force (2) rising and covering or hiding. For example, in the Quran it is: «خَاشِعَۃً  اَبۡصَارُہُمۡ تَرۡہَقُہُمۡ ذِلَّۃٌ» (68/43) Translation: Their eyes will be humbled, and humiliation will cover them."
    }
  ],
  "377": [
    {
      "id": 1754,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Wound",
      "hw": "زخم",
      "s": "«قُرْحٌ» a wound whose effect is limited to the skin (2 verses: 3:140-3:172)",
      "d": "«قُرْحٌ» means sore, blister, or wound. Its plural is «قُرُوْح». This can be from internal or external effects. Meaning sores, blisters, and the wounds caused by them. Then «قُرْحٌ» is also applied to the pain and distress resulting from these wounds. «قُرُوْح» actually refers to wounds whose effect is limited to the skin, whether it be a cut, scratch, or blister. For example, in the Quran it is: «اِنۡ یَّمۡسَسۡکُمۡ قَرۡحٌ فَقَدۡ مَسَّ الۡقَوۡمَ قَرۡحٌ مِّثۡلُہٗ» (3/140) Translation: If you have been wounded, then these people [the disbelievers] have been wounded similarly."
    }
  ],
  "378": [
    {
      "id": 1756,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Time and its Division",
      "hw": "زمانہ",
      "s": "«دَھْر» the time of the universe from creation to the end (2 verses: 45:24-76:1)",
      "d": "«دَھْر» means the time of the universe, the duration of the world. From the beginning of the universe until its end. And Ibn al-Faris says that in «دَھَرَ» the meaning of dominance and «قَھَر» is found, and «دَھْر» i.e., time is named thus because it passes over everything and overcomes it. And «دَھْر» is related to the divine will. The prophetic saying ﷺ is: 'Do not curse time, for indeed Allah is time.' That is, do not speak ill of time because Allah Almighty is time. A person who neither acknowledges God nor His attributes is called a heretic or deist. They believe that time is eternal and everlasting, and there is no life after this one. The doctrine of deism is famous. For example, in the Quran it is: «ہَلۡ  اَتٰی عَلَی الۡاِنۡسَانِ حِیۡنٌ مِّنَ الدَّہۡرِ  لَمۡ  یَکُنۡ شَیۡئًا مَّذۡکُوۡرًا» (76/1) Translation: In time, there was a period when man was not even a thing to be mentioned. That is, during the ages, there was a time when man had no name or sign."
    },
    {
      "id": 1757,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Time and its Division",
      "hw": "زمانہ",
      "s": "«عَصْر» the period from the creation of mankind until the Day of Resurrection (1 verse: 103:1)",
      "d": "In «عَصْر» two meanings are found: (1) the last part of the day. (2) night and day. Era. Time (according to Munajid). That is, from when day and night came into existence until they exist. But in our opinion, this meaning or definition is noteworthy. And the meaning of «عَصْر» should be, 'the period from the creation of mankind until the Day of Resurrection.' The reason is that Allah mentions «عَصْر» as a witness over mankind. And when man did not exist, how can there be testimony? And Allah knows best. For example, in the Quran it is: «وَ الۡعَصۡرِ اِنَّ  الۡاِنۡسَانَ لَفِیۡ خُسۡرٍ» (103/1) Translation: By time, indeed man is in loss. And obviously, night and day existed long before the creation of Adam. According to the above explanation of «دَھْر» and «عَصْر», these words should not be pluralized, but in lexicons, the plural of «دَھْر» is «دُھُوْر» and of «عَصْر» is «عُصُوْر». This is because in common parlance, «دَھر» and «عَصْر» are taken to mean merely a long period of time."
    },
    {
      "id": 1758,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Time and its Division",
      "hw": "زمانہ",
      "s": "«قَرْن» a period of a hundred years; the people of an era; one nation after another; a generation and its period (19 verses: 6:6-10:13-11:116-17:17-19:74-19:98-20:51-20:128-23:31-23:42-25:38-28:43-28:45-28:78-32:26-36:31-38:3-46:17-50:36)",
      "d": "«قَرْن» means a period of a hundred years. The people of an era. One nation after another. The people of a generation and its period. So «قَرْن» is applied to one or two periods and the people of that time, just as the word «قَرْیَۃ» is used for a town and its people. Its plural is «قُرُوْن». In the Quran, this word is generally used for the people of a bygone era. For example, in the Quran it is: «قَالَ  فَمَا  بَالُ  الۡقُرُوۡنِ  الۡاُوۡلٰی» (20/51) Translation: Pharaoh asked Moses, 'What is the condition of the earlier nations?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1759,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Time and its Division",
      "hw": "زمانہ",
      "s": "«حُقْبَۃ» a period of eighty years or more; a long duration; an indefinite period (1 verse: 18:60)",
      "d": "«حُقْبَۃ» is a period of eighty years or more. Long duration, indefinite period. Its plural is «حُقُب» and also «اَحْقَاب». Meaning ages. And according to the author of Furūq al-Lughawiyyah, this word is derived from «حَقِیْبَۃ». And «حَقِیْبَۃ» is the name for that leather bag in which a rider keeps his belongings and carries them with his ride. Therefore, «حَقَب» is not a part of time but a type of container. That is, the time in which deeds and affairs are accomplished (according to Fuqaha 224). For example, in the Quran it is: «حَتّٰۤی اَبۡلُغَ  مَجۡمَعَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ اَوۡ اَمۡضِیَ حُقُبًا» (18/60) Translation: Until I reach the confluence of the two seas, or I spend ages [in travel]."
    },
    {
      "id": 1760,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Time and its Division",
      "hw": "زمانہ",
      "s": "«رَیْبَ الْمَنُوْن» the events of time, generally used in a bad sense (1 verse: 52:30)",
      "d": "«رَیْبَ الْمَنُوْن» refers to the events of time which are generally used in a bad sense. Besides, in the Quran, the idiom «رَیْبَ الْمَنُوْن» meaning 'the rotation of time' is also used. And it refers to the events of time which are generally used in a bad sense, i.e., waiting for calamities—earthly and heavenly—to befall someone (also see 'gardish-e-ayyam'). For example, in the Quran it is: «اَمۡ  یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ  شَاعِرٌ  نَّتَرَبَّصُ بِہٖ  رَیۡبَ الۡمَنُوۡنِ» (52/30) Translation: Or the disbelievers say, 'He is a poet; we await for him the adverse events of time.'"
    }
  ],
  "379": [
    {
      "id": 1761,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and Its Types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "Bar: the part of the earth that is dry (12 verses: 5:96-6:59-6:63-6:97-10:22-17:67-17:68-17:70-27:63-29:65-30:41-31:32)",
      "d": "Bar refers to the dry part of the earth where humans or other land animals live or can live. This part constitutes one-fourth of the earth's total surface area."
    },
    {
      "id": 1762,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and Its Types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "Bahr: the part of the earth that is underwater, i.e., where seas are located. (39 verses: 2:50-2:164-5:96-6:59-6:63-6:97-7:138-7:163-10:22-10:90-14:32-16:14-17:66-17:67-17:70-18:60-18:61-18:63-18:79-18:109-20:77-22:65-24:40-25:53-26:63-27:61-27:63-30:41-31:27-31:31-35:12-42:32-44:24-45:12-52:6-55:19-55:24-81:6-82:3)",
      "d": "Bahr refers to the part of the earth that is underwater, i.e., where seas are located. In terms of area, this part is three times larger than the dry land. Only aquatic animals can live in this part. Bahr also refers to rivers that flow on land. For example, the Quran states: «هُوَ الَّذِیۡ یُسَیِّرُکُمۡ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ» (10/22). Translation: He it is who enables you to travel on land and sea. Various types of dry land mentioned in the Quran include the terms: «جُرُز ، سھُوْل ، سَاہِرَۃ ، صَعِیْد ، قِیْعَۃ ( قوع ) صَفْصَف ، عَرَاء ( عری ) زَلَق ، صَفْوَان ، ( صفو ) فَجْوَۃ ( فج ) صَلْدًا ، سَاحَۃ ( سیح ) رَبْوَۃ ( ربو ) ، نَجْد ، رِیْع ، وَادِی ، مَوَاطِن اور جُدَد»."
    },
    {
      "id": 1763,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and Its Types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "Juruz: meaning dry and barren land (2 verses: 18:8-32:27)",
      "d": "Juruz means dry, barren, and uncultivable land. Such land where rainfall is very low. For example, the Quran states: «اَوَ لَمۡ یَرَوۡا اَنَّا نَسُوۡقُ الۡمَآءَ  اِلَی الۡاَرۡضِ الۡجُرْزِ فَنُخۡرِجُ  بِہٖ زَرۡعًا تَاۡکُلُ مِنۡہُ  اَنۡعَامُہُمۡ وَ اَنۡفُسُہُمۡ» (32/27). Translation: Do they not see that we convey water to the barren land, then we bring forth crops from it which their cattle and they themselves eat?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1765,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and Its Types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "Sahira: the surface of the earth or ground level (1 verse: 79:14)",
      "d": "Sahira means the earth or its surface. It refers to land where there is frequent movement. For example, the Quran states: «فَاِنَّمَا ہِیَ زَجۡرَۃٌ   وَّاحِدَۃٌ فَاِذَا  ہُمۡ  بِالسَّاہِرَۃِ» (79/14). Translation: It will be but a single blast, so they will be brought back to the surface of the earth immediately."
    },
    {
      "id": 1766,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and Its Types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "Sa'id: the upper dry soil of the earth that blows away (4 verses: 4:43-5:6-18:8-18:40)",
      "d": "Sa'id means to ascend. And Sa'id refers to the upper part of the earth. The upper part and the dust that rises from it. Every flat land is Sa'id. It also means the surface of the earth and the dust, etc. For example, the Quran states: «فَلَمۡ  تَجِدُوۡا مَآءً فَتَیَمَّمُوۡا صَعِیۡدًا طَیِّبًا» (5/6). Translation: Then if you do not find water, then take clean earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 1767,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and Its Types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "Qa'iya: meaning an open field (1 verse: 24:39)",
      "d": "Qa'iya and Qa' mean an open field. For example, the Quran states: «اَعۡمَالُہُمۡ کَسَرَابٍۭ بِقِیۡعَۃٍ یَّحۡسَبُہُ الظَّمۡاٰنُ مَآءً» (24/39). Translation: Their works are like a mirage in a plain which the thirsty one thinks to be water."
    },
    {
      "id": 1768,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and Its Types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "Safsaf: meaning a flat and even field (1 verse: 20:106)",
      "d": "Safsaf means a flat and even field. For example, the Quran states: «فَیَذَرُہَا  قَاعًا صَفۡصَفًا لَّا  تَرٰی  فِیۡہَا عِوَجًا  وَّ  لَاۤ   اَمۡتًا» (20:106,107). Translation: Then he will leave it as a level plain, wherein you will see no depression or elevation."
    },
    {
      "id": 1769,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and Its Types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "Ara': a barren field with no shelter (2 verses: 37:145-68:49)",
      "d": "Ara' means naked. And Ara' refers to a field where there is no cover. A small desert. For example, the Quran states: «فَنَبَذۡنٰہُ  بِالۡعَرَآءِ  وَ  ہُوَ  سَقِیۡمٌ» (37/145). Translation: Then we cast him onto a barren shore, and he was sick."
    },
    {
      "id": 1770,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and Its Types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "Zalaq: a slippery field, ground that causes slipping (2 verses: 18:40-68:51)",
      "d": "Zalaq means to slip. And Sa'idan Zalaq means slippery ground, where humans slip. For example, the Quran states: «فَعَسٰی رَبِّیۡۤ اَنۡ یُّؤۡتِیَنِ خَیۡرًا مِّنۡ جَنَّتِکَ وَ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡہَا حُسۡبَانًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فَتُصۡبِحَ صَعِیۡدًا زَلَقًا» (18/40). Translation: It may be that your Lord will give you something better than your garden and send upon it a [torment] from the sky, so it becomes a smooth, slippery ground."
    },
    {
      "id": 1771,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and Its Types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "Safwan: a small rocky hill with a smooth surface (1 verse: 2:264)",
      "d": "Safwan means a small rocky hill with a smooth surface. A rocky land."
    },
    {
      "id": 1772,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "«صَلْدًا» means hard and smooth stone (1 verse: 2:264)",
      "d": "«صَلْدًا» means solid and smooth stone. «رَاْسٌ صَلْدٌ» means bald head and «صَلْدٌ» means dry stone (F L 45). For example, the Quran states: «فَمَثَلُہٗ کَمَثَلِ صَفۡوَانٍ عَلَیۡہِ تُرَابٌ فَاَصَابَہٗ وَابِلٌ فَتَرَکَہٗ صَلۡدًا» (2/264). Translation: The example of that wealth is like a rock on which is a little soil, then a heavy rain strikes it and leaves it bare."
    },
    {
      "id": 1773,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "«فَجْوَۃ» means an open field between two mountains (3 verses: 21:31, 22:27, 71:20)",
      "d": "«فَجْوَۃ» means an open field between two mountains. A valley. And the path that passes through this field is called «فَجّ» (Manjad, M L). For example, the Quran states: «وَ تَرَی الشَّمۡسَ اِذَا طَلَعَتۡ تَّزٰوَرُ عَنۡ کَہۡفِہِمۡ ذَاتَ الۡیَمِیۡنِ وَ اِذَا غَرَبَتۡ تَّقۡرِضُہُمۡ ذَاتَ الشِّمَالِ وَ ہُمۡ فِیۡ فَجۡوَۃٍ مِّنۡہُ» (18/17). Translation: And you would see the sun, when it rose, inclining away from their cave towards the right, and when it set, passing away from them towards the left, while they were in an open space thereof."
    },
    {
      "id": 1774,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "«سَاحَۃ» means an open space attached to or near houses (1 verse: 37:177)",
      "d": "«سَاحَۃ» means an open space attached to or near houses. Courtyard. Yard. Parks, etc. Places for gathering. For example, the Quran states: «اَفَبِعَذَابِنَا یَسۡتَعۡجِلُوۡنَ فَاِذَا نَزَلَ بِسَاحَتِہِمۡ فَسَآءَ صَبَاحُ الۡمُنۡذَرِیۡنَ» (37/176,177). Translation: Do they then await anything other than Our punishment? So when Our punishment comes to them, how evil will be the morning of those who were warned."
    },
    {
      "id": 1775,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "«رَبْوَۃ» means land slightly elevated from the general level and fertile (2 verses: 2:265, 23:50)",
      "d": "«رَبَا» means to increase, to flourish. And «رَبْوَۃ» means elevated land (FL 266). Land slightly elevated from the general level and fertile. For example, the Quran states: «کَمَثَلِ جَنَّۃٍۭ بِرَبۡوَۃٍ اَصَابَہَا وَابِلٌ فَاٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا ضِعۡفَیۡنِ» (2/265). Translation: The example of it is like a garden on a height; heavy rain falls on it and it yields its produce double."
    },
    {
      "id": 1777,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "«رِیْع» means land somewhat elevated from the general level (1 verse: 26:128)",
      "d": "«رِیْع» is the plural of «رِیْعَۃٌ». Such land which is higher than «رَبْوَۃ» and is hard (FL 267). For example, the Quran states: «اَتَبۡنُوۡنَ بِکُلِّ رِیۡعٍ اٰیَۃً تَعۡبَثُوۡنَ» (26/128). Translation: Do you build on every height a monument for vain sport?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1778,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "«وَادِی» means an open and wide space enclosed by mountains where water flows (10 verses: 9:121, 13:17, 14:37, 20:12, 26:225, 27:18, 28:30, 46:24, 79:16, 89:9)",
      "d": "The plural of «وَادِی» is «اَوْدِیَۃ». Such a sloping place situated between mountains. It is wide and spacious. And the water from rain etc. that comes down the mountains also flows in it. Then even the stream flowing in that valley is called a valley. (Muf). For example, the Quran states: «رَبَّنَاۤ اِنِّیۡۤ اَسۡکَنۡتُ مِنۡ ذُرِّیَّتِیۡ بِوَادٍ غَیۡرِ ذِیۡ زَرۡعٍ» (14/37). Translation: Our Lord! I have settled some of my descendants in an uncultivated valley near Your Sacred House."
    },
    {
      "id": 1779,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "«مَوَاطِن» means a battlefield (1 verse: 9:25)",
      "d": "«وَطَنَ» means to reside, i.e., to adopt a place of residence. And «وَطْن» means a human's abode, i.e., a place of living, whether one was born there or not. And «مَوَاطِن» is the plural of «مَوْطِن», meaning homeland. And «مِیْطَان» is the term for the place where horses are left for a distant journey (Manjad). For example, the Quran states: «لَقَدۡ نَصَرَکُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡ مَوَاطِنَ کَثِیۡرَۃٍ» (9/25). Translation: Allah has already given you victory in many battlefields."
    },
    {
      "id": 1780,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth and its types",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "«جُدَد» (plural of «جُدَّۃ») means distinct, hard, and flat pieces of land that appear separate and cut (1 verse: 35:27)",
      "d": "«جَدَّ» means something being new. Cutting something. «جَادَّۃ» means highway, the bend of a road. And «جَدَد» means flat and hard land. And «جُدَّۃ» means a marked way, and its plural is «جُدَد» (Manjad). Thus, «جُدَّہ» refers to such pieces of hard and flat land that appear clearly separate and cut. For example, the Quran states: «وَ مِنَ الۡجِبَالِ جُدَدٌۢ بِیۡضٌ وَّ حُمۡرٌ مُّخۡتَلِفٌ اَلۡوَانُہَا وَ غَرَابِیۡبُ سُوۡدٌ» (35/27). Translation: And among the mountains are streaks white and red, of varying colors, and [some] extremely black."
    },
    {
      "id": 1781,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Leveling the earth",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "«دَکَّ» means to crush inanimate objects and level them to the ground (3 verses: 7:143, 18:98, 89:21)",
      "d": "The meanings of «دَکَّ» basically include two things: (1) to crush, (2) to make level. (M, L) i.e., to crush something and break it into pieces, making it equal to the surface of the earth (Muf). For example, the Quran states: «فَلَمَّا تَجَلّٰی رَبُّہٗ لِلۡجَبَلِ جَعَلَہٗ دَکًّا» (7/143). Translation: So when his Lord manifested Himself to the mountain, He made it level [as if it were] dust. At another instance, the Divine declaration is: «اِذَا دُکَّتِ الۡاَرۡضُ دَکًّا دَکًّا» (89/21). Translation: When the earth is leveled, leveling it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1782,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Leveling the earth",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "«دَمْدَمَ» means to destroy by means of punishment and make level (1 verse: 91:14)",
      "d": "«دَمْدَمُ الشَّیْء» means to make something stick to the ground. And «دَمْدَمَ اللہُ عَلَیْھِمْ» means Allah destroyed them (Manjad). And «دَیْمُوْمَۃ» means desert, wasteland (Muf). For example, the Quran states: «فَدَمۡدَمَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ رَبُّہُمۡ بِذَنۡۢبِہِمۡ فَسَوّٰىہَا» (91/14). Translation: So their Lord destroyed them for their sin and made them equal [in destruction]."
    }
  ],
  "380": [
    {
      "id": 1783,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Chains",
      "hw": "زنجیریں",
      "s": "«سَلَاسِل» is a well-known term for chains (3 verses: 40:71-69:32-76:4)",
      "d": "«سَلَاسِل» is the plural of «سِلْسِلَہ». «سَلَّ» means to pull one thing after another, like drawing a sword from its sheath. And «سلسلہ» means a chain from which one link emerges after another. And «تسلسل» means continuity, i.e., one thing connected to another and proceeding. For example, the Quran says: «ثُمَّ  فِیۡ سِلۡسِلَۃٍ  ذَرۡعُہَا سَبۡعُوۡنَ  ذِرَاعًا  فَاسۡلُکُوۡہُ» (69/32) Translation: Then fasten them with a chain whose length is seventy cubits."
    },
    {
      "id": 1784,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Chains",
      "hw": "زنجیریں",
      "s": "«اَصْفَاد» means collar or chain (2 verses: 14:49-38:38)",
      "d": "«اَصْفَاد» is the plural of «صَفَد». And «صِفَاد» means an iron collar or chain with which prisoners are bound. And «صَفَدَ» means to bind, to imprison. And «اَصْفَدَ» means to imprison. For example, the Quran says: «وَّ اٰخِرِیۡنَ مُقَرَّنِیۡنَ فِی الۡاَصۡفَادِ» (38/38) Translation: And others who are bound in chains."
    },
    {
      "id": 1785,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Chains",
      "hw": "زنجیریں",
      "s": "«اَنْکَال» means reins, fetters, chains (1 verse: 73:12)",
      "d": "«اَنْکَال» is the plural of «نَکْل». It refers to an animal's fetters and iron reins that keep it under control. And «نَکَال» means such an exemplary punishment that one's foot gets caught. And «نَکَّلَ» means to give an exemplary punishment or to put fetters on someone's feet or to give reins. For example, the Quran says: «اِنَّ  لَدَیۡنَاۤ  اَنۡکَالًا وَّ  جَحِیۡمًا  وَّ طَعَامًا ذَا غُصَّۃٍ  وَّ عَذَابًا  اَلِیۡمًا» (73/12) Translation: Indeed, We have fetters and a raging fire and food that chokes and a painful punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 1786,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Chains",
      "hw": "زنجیریں",
      "s": "«اَغْلَال» is general and applies to all meanings, whether handcuffs, chains, or collars (9 verses: 5:64-7:157-12:23-13:5-17:29-34:33-36:8-40:71-76:4)",
      "d": "«اَغْلَال» is the plural of «غُلّ», and its plural «غُلُوْل» also occurs. And «غُلّ» refers to anything with which one's limbs are bound and tied between them, and it applies to handcuffs, chains, and collars all. And «غَلَّ» means to put handcuffs or a collar. And chains are always with all these. For example, the Quran says: «اِنَّاۤ  اَعۡتَدۡنَا  لِلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ سَلٰسِلَا۠ وَ اَغۡلٰلًا  وَّ  سَعِیۡرًا» (76/4) Translation: Indeed, We have prepared for the disbelievers chains and collars and a blazing fire."
    }
  ],
  "381": [
    {
      "id": 1787,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To Give Life",
      "hw": "زندہ",
      "s": "«اَحْیَا» means to give life to any dead person. It is commonly used (53 verses: 2:28-2:73-2:154-2:164-2:243-2:258-2:259-2:260-3:49-3:156-3:169-5:32-6:122-7:158-8:24-9:116-10:56-15:23-16:21-16:65-22:6-22:66-23:37-23:80-25:49-26:81-29:63-30:19-30:24-30:40-30:50-35:9-35:22-36:12-36:33-36:78-36:79-40:11-40:68-41:39-42:9-44:8-45:5-45:26-46:33-50:11-50:43-53:44-57:2-57:17-75:40-77:26-87:13)",
      "d": "«اَحْیَا» means to revive the dead, and its opposite is «اَمَاتَ» meaning death. «حَیِیَ» means to live, to remain alive. It is a well-known term. For example, the Quran says: «کَذٰلِکَ یُحۡیِ اللّٰہُ  الۡمَوۡتٰی  ۙ وَ یُرِیۡکُمۡ اٰیٰتِہٖ» (2/73) Translation: Thus does Allah give life to the dead and show you His signs."
    },
    {
      "id": 1788,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To Give Life",
      "hw": "زندہ",
      "s": "«بَعَثَ» means to give life to and raise the dead lying in graves (27 verses: 2:56-2:259-6:36-6:60-7:14-15:36-16:21-16:38-18:12-18:19-19:15-19:33-22:5-22:7-23:16-23:100-26:87-27:65-30:56-31:28-36:52-37:144-38:79-58:6-58:18-64:7-72:7)",
      "d": "«بَعَثَ» basically has two meanings: (1) to raise, to awaken (2) to send alone. And when this word is used in relation to the dead who lie in graves, its meaning will be to revive them in the graves and lead them to the field of resurrection. For example, the Quran says: Translation: And indeed, the Hour is coming - no doubt about it - and indeed, Allah will raise all those who are in the graves."
    },
    {
      "id": 1789,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To Give Life",
      "hw": "زندہ",
      "s": "«اَنْشَرَ» means to give life, to raise, and to spread (10 verses: 18:16-21:21-42:28-43:11-44:35-74:52-77:3-80:22-81:10-94:1)",
      "d": "«نَشَرَ» basic meaning is to spread, and its opposite is «طَوَی». «نَشَرَ الْمَیِّتَ نَشُوْرًا» means the dead coming back to life. And «اِلَیْہِ النُّشُوْر» means to live, to rise, and to spread – three meanings. That is, people will come alive and spread, and proceed towards it. And «اَنْشَرَ» means to revive and spread in the field of resurrection. For example, the Quran says: «ثُمَّ  اَمَاتَہٗ  فَاَقۡبَرَہٗ ثُمَّ  اِذَا شَآءَ  اَنۡشَرَہٗ» (80/21،22 ) Translation: Then Allah caused him to die and buried him. Then when He wills, He will raise him up."
    },
    {
      "id": 1790,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To Live, Remain, Keep",
      "hw": "زندہ",
      "s": "«حَیِیَ» means to live for every living thing (93 verses: 2:85-2:86-2:96-2:179-2:204-2:212-2:255-3:2-3:14-3:27-3:117-3:185-4:74-4:94-4:109-6:29-6:32-6:70-6:95-6:130-6:162-7:25-7:32-7:51-7:152-8:42-9:38-9:55-10:7-10:23-10:24-10:31-10:64-10:88-10:98-11:15-13:26-13:34-14:3-14:27-16:97-16:107-17:75-18:28-18:45-18:46-18:104-19:15-19:31-19:33-19:66-20:72-20:74-20:97-20:111-20:131-21:30-23:33-23:37-24:33-25:3-25:58-28:60-28:61-28:79-29:25-29:64-30:7-30:19-31:33-33:28-35:5-36:70-39:26-40:39-40:51-40:65-41:16-41:31-42:36-43:32-43:35-45:21-45:24-45:35-46:20-47:36-53:29-57:20-67:2-79:38-87:16-89:24)",
      "d": "«حَیِیَ» means to live, to remain alive. And «حَیٰوۃ» means life. This word has a very broad meaning. Living things are alive, but current research suggests that even inanimate things have life. For example, the Quran says: «اِنۡ ہِیَ  اِلَّا حَیَاتُنَا الدُّنۡیَا نَمُوۡتُ وَ نَحۡیَا وَ مَا نَحۡنُ بِمَبۡعُوۡثِیۡنَ» (23/37) Translation: They say, 'There is only our worldly life; we die and live, and we are not to be resurrected.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1791,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To Live, Remain, Keep",
      "hw": "زندہ",
      "s": "«عَاشَ» means to live for a living being whose life depends on eating and drinking (3 verses: 7:10-15:20-79:11)",
      "d": "«عَاشَ» means to live, to remain. And «عَیْش» is that life which is found in animals. That is, a living being that can live by eating and drinking. Thus, this word is specific compared to «حَیِیَ». Its plural is «مَعَائِش» meaning means of livelihood. For example, the Quran says: «وَ لَقَدۡ مَکَّنّٰکُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ جَعَلۡنَا لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَعَایِشَ» (7/10) Translation: And We have certainly established you in the land and made for you therein means of livelihood."
    },
    {
      "id": 1792,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To Live, Remain, Keep",
      "hw": "زندہ",
      "s": "«اِسْتِحْیَاء» means to let another live (6 verses: 2:49-7:127-7:141-14:6-28:4-40:25)",
      "d": "«اِسْتِحْیَاء» means to be shy as well as to let live or to leave alive. And this word is used when someone is being killed in battle. Allah says: «یُذَبِّحُوۡنَ اَبۡنَآءَکُمۡ وَ یَسۡتَحۡیُوۡنَ نِسَآءَکُمۡ» (2/49) Translation: They slaughter your sons and let your females live. «حَیِیَ» has the verbal noun «حیوۃ» as well. And «حَیَاء» also means shyness."
    }
  ],
  "382": [
    {
      "id": 1794,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Adornment",
      "hw": "زینت",
      "s": "«Zukhruf» means artificial decoration, i.e., fabricated and superficial adornment (4 verses: 6:112-10:24-17:93-43:35)",
      "d": "«Zukhruf» has two meanings: first, superficial and fabricated decoration, and that adornment obtained from external embellishment. «Zukhruf al-kalam» means adorning speech with falsehood (dictionary). For example, the Quran says: «Yūḥī baʿḍuhum ilā baʿḍin zukhrufa l-qawli ghurūran» (6:112). Translation: (Satan) would cast into each other's hearts adorned words to deceive. And the second meaning is the various colors and forms of plants (dictionary), spring and bloom. For example, the Quran says: «Ḥattā idhā akhadhati l-arḍu zukhrufahā» (10:24). Translation: Until the earth becomes adorned with its greenery."
    },
    {
      "id": 1795,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Adornment",
      "hw": "زینت",
      "s": "«Rīsh» means luxurious clothing and adornment obtained from embellishment (1 verse: 7:26)",
      "d": "«Rīsh» means the feathers of birds, especially hawks (dictionary), and «Rayyash» means one who attaches bird feathers to arrows (dictionary). Since bird feathers are like clothing, this word is used metaphorically for luxurious clothing. Embellished garments. For example, the Quran says: «Yā banī ādama qad anzalnā ʿalaykum libāsan yuwārī sawātikum wa rīshan» (7:26). Translation: O children of Adam! We have sent down upon you clothing to cover your private parts and as adornment."
    },
    {
      "id": 1797,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Adornment",
      "hw": "زینت",
      "s": "«Jamāl» is used in all senses: apparent beauty, excellence of character, and adornment of the surroundings (1 verse: 16:6)",
      "d": "«Jamāl» this word is used in all aspects: (1) apparent beauty, (2) excellence of character, (3) adornment and beauty of the surroundings (Faqih 217). In the Quran, this word is used in both meanings for «mu'akhkhar al-dhikr». Essentially, it means goodness in actions, morals, and outward deeds. Later, this word also began to be used for apparent beauty. For example, the Quran says: «Wa lakum fīhā jamālun ḥīna turīḥūna wa ḥīna tasraḥūna» (16:6). Translation: And there is beauty for you in it when you bring them (cattle) home in the evening and when you take them out to pasture in the morning."
    }
  ],
  "383": [
    {
      "id": 1798,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Companion",
      "hw": "ساتھی",
      "s": "«Ṣāḥib» means one who remains together for a long time (87 verses: 2:39-2:81-2:82-2:119-2:217-2:257-2:275-3:116-4:36-4:47-5:10-5:29-5:86-6:71-6:101-7:36-7:42-7:44-7:46-7:47-7:48-7:50-7:184-9:40-9:70-9:113-10:26-10:27-11:23-12:39-12:41-13:5-15:78-15:80-18:9-18:34-18:37-18:76-20:135-22:44-22:51-25:24-25:38-26:61-26:176-29:15-31:15-34:46-35:6-36:13-36:55-38:13-39:8-40:6-40:43-46:14-46:16-50:12-51:59-53:2-54:29-56:8-56:9-56:27-56:38-56:41-56:90-56:91-57:19-58:17-59:20-60:13-64:10-67:10-67:11-68:17-68:48-70:12-72:3-74:31-74:39-80:36-81:22-85:4-90:18-90:19-105:1)",
      "d": "«Ṣāḥib» means one who remains together for a long time, whether this companionship is with a human or an animal, and whether it is temporal or spatial (dictionary). According to Ibn al-Faris, two aspects are found in «ṣaḥaba»: (1) «muqārinah» (being a counterpart) and (2) «muqāribah» (being close or together) (dictionary). The plural of «ṣāḥib» is «aṣḥāb» and its feminine is «ṣāḥibah». According to Sahib al-Furuq al-Lughawiyyah, this word is specifically used for humans (Faqih 235). For example, the Quran says: «Iż humā fī l-ghār iż yaqūlu li-ṣāḥibihi lā taḥzan inna Allāha maʿanā» (9:40). Translation: When the two (Prophet ﷺ and Abu Bakr) were in the cave, he said to his companion (Abu Bakr), 'Do not grieve; indeed, Allah is with us.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1800,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Companion",
      "hw": "ساتھی",
      "s": "«Qarīn» means peer, equal, of the same age (6 verses: 4:38-37:51-43:36-43:38-50:23-50:27)",
      "d": "«Qarīn» means of the same age. And any person who is equal in bravery, strength, or other qualities, and this word is also used for non-living things. For details, see 'Friend'."
    },
    {
      "id": 1801,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Companion",
      "hw": "ساتھی",
      "s": "«Azwāj» means of the same kind. People similar in habits and customs (47 verses: 2:25-2:232-2:234-2:240-3:15-4:12-4:57-6:139-6:143-9:24-13:23-13:38-15:88-16:72-20:53-20:131-23:6-24:6-25:74-26:166-30:21-33:4-33:6-33:28-33:37-33:50-33:52-33:53-33:59-35:11-36:36-36:56-37:22-38:58-39:6-40:8-42:11-43:12-43:70-56:7-60:11-64:14-66:1-66:3-66:5-70:30-78:8)",
      "d": "«Zawj» means pair, husband and wife. Both are «zawj» for each other and together they are «zawj». Its plural is «azwāj». This word is also used in the Quran in the meaning of «qarīn» (companion or of the same kind), i.e., people similar to each other. (See details under 'Various'). For example, the Quran says: «Uḥshurū l-ladhīnaẓalamū wa azwājahum wa mā kānū yaʿbudūn» (37:22). Translation: Gather those who did wrong and their companions and what they used to worship."
    }
  ],
  "384": [
    {
      "id": 1802,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Year",
      "hw": "سال",
      "s": "«ʿĀm» means a year of prosperity and well-being (6 verses: 2:259-9:28-9:37-9:126-12:49-29:14)",
      "d": "«ʿĀm» its plural is «ʿawām», the year in which there is abundance and plenty (dictionary), a year of prosperity and well-being. For example, the Quran says: «Thumma yātī min baʿdi dhālika ʿāmun fīhi yughāthu n-nāsu wa fīhi yaʿṣirūn» (12:49). Translation: Then after that will come a year in which people will have abundant rain and in which they will press (olives or grapes). And in this sense, the word «ʿām» is also used as a prayer. On the occasion of Eid, Arabs say «antum wa kulla ʿamin bikhayr» instead of congratulating each other, meaning 'May your year pass with goodness and well-being.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1804,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Year",
      "hw": "سال",
      "s": "«Ḥawl» means a full cycle of the year from a specific date or lunar calculation (2 verses: 2:233-2:240)",
      "d": "«Ḥāla» its plural is «ḥālāt», meaning to change from one state to another. «Aḥwāl al-dahr» means the cycles of days, the vicissitudes of time. And «ḥāla l-ḥawl» means the passage of a year's period (dictionary). And «ḥawl» means a full cycle of the year, i.e., the period from a specific date in one year to the same date in the next year. Zakat is also paid according to «ḥawl». And in breastfeeding and divorce, the calculation of «ḥawl» is also observed. For example, the Quran says: «Wa waṣiyyatan li-azwājihim matāʿan ilā l-ḥawli ghayra ikhrāj» (2:240). Translation: And a bequest for his wives of maintenance for a year without expulsion."
    },
    {
      "id": 1805,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Year",
      "hw": "سال",
      "s": "«Ḥijaj» is a rough method of counting years (1 verse: 28:27)",
      "d": "«Ḥijaj» is the plural of «ḥajjah» and «ḥajj» means to come and go repeatedly, to have frequent comings and goings (dictionary). From «ḥajjah», «ḥajj» is a repeated noun (i.e., once a year). And since Hajj occurs once a year, the year is called «ḥajj». In the early centuries (i.e., the time of the companions), there was no regular calendar and calculation of days, months, and years. Therefore, common people used to count years by the number of Hajj pilgrimages. For example, the Quran says: «Innī urīdu an unkiḥaka iḥdā abnatayya hātayni ʿalā an tājuranī thamāniya ḥijaj» (28:27). Translation: I wish to marry you to one of my two daughters, on the condition that you serve me for eight years."
    }
  ],
  "385": [
    {
      "id": 1807,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Goods",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«Matāʿ» means any goods from which benefit is derived (34 verses: 2:36-2:236-2:240-2:241-3:14-3:185-3:197-4:77-5:96-7:24-9:38-10:23-10:70-11:3-12:17-12:65-12:79-13:17-13:26-16:80-16:117-21:111-24:29-28:60-28:61-33:53-36:44-40:39-42:36-43:35-56:73-57:20-79:33-80:32)",
      "d": "«Matāʿ» its plural is «amtiʿah» and «mataʿ». It means to derive benefit for a long time (dictionary). And «matāʿ» is any useful thing or any part of a thing that can provide benefit. To take advantage from worldly goods. When the aspect of worldly goods and deriving benefit from them is intended, this word is used. For example, the Quran says: «Wa lakum fī l-arḍi mustaqarrun wa matāʿun ilā ḥīn» (2:36). Translation: And for you in the earth is a place of settlement and provision for a time."
    },
    {
      "id": 1808,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Items",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«اَثَاث» means miscellaneous household items, necessities (2 verses: 16:80-19:74)",
      "d": "«اَثَاث» is the plural of «اَثَاثَۃٌ» but it is generally used as plural, e.g., «اَثَاثُ الْبَیْت» is a famous phrase meaning household items in use, necessities of the house such as utensils, beds, clothes, furniture, etc. All these are included in «اَثَاثُ الْبَیْت». Then this word began to be used for excessive and unnecessary possessions as well. And it also means a shop or warehouse (masc.). Also, any animal or slave that is owned and used personally is also included in «اَثَاثُ الْبَیْت», e.g., horse, cow, camel, etc. (m. q.). For example, in the Quran: «وَ کَمۡ اَہۡلَکۡنَا قَبۡلَہُمۡ مِّنۡ قَرۡنٍ ہُمۡ اَحۡسَنُ  اَثَاثًا  وَّ رِءۡیًا» (19/74) Translation: And how many generations We destroyed before them who were better in equipment and appearance."
    },
    {
      "id": 1809,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Items",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«رَحْل» means equipment that accompanies during travel (3 verses: 12:70-12:75-106:2)",
      "d": "«رَحْل» means to saddle a camel (masc.) and means to migrate, to ride. And «رَحْل» means equipment that accompanies during travel (minjadd). «رَحَلَ» is a word used for setting out on a journey (m. l.). The Prophetic saying: «لَا تَشَدُّوا الرِّحَالَ اِلاَّ لِثَلٰثَۃِ مَسَاجِدٍ» meaning: Do not saddle your camels except for three mosques (the Sacred Mosque, the Prophet's Mosque, and the Aqsa Mosque) for visitation and reward. For example, in the Quran: «جَعَلَ السِّقَایَۃَ  فِیۡ رَحۡلِ اَخِیۡہِ» (12/70) Translation: He placed the measuring cup in his brother's luggage."
    },
    {
      "id": 1810,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Items",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«وِعَاء» means any equipment that is closed or locked (1 verse: 12:76)",
      "d": "«وِعَاء» is the plural of «اَوْعِیَۃ» and «وَعٰی». It means to store something in a bag, etc., and then close it from above. And «اَوْعِیَۃ» is that equipment which, after placing in a container, is closed or locked or sealed (masc.). For example, in the Quran: «فَبَدَاَ بِاَوۡعِیَتِہِمۡ قَبۡلَ وِعَآءِ اَخِیۡہِ ثُمَّ اسۡتَخۡرَجَہَا مِنۡ وِّعَآءِ اَخِیۡہِ» (12/76) Translation: So he began with their bags before his brother's bag, then he brought it out from his brother's bag."
    },
    {
      "id": 1811,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Supplies",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«Jahaaz» is the luggage that a traveler prepares and keeps when embarking on a journey. (2 verses: 12:59-12:70)",
      "d": "«Jahhaza» means to prepare, load, and send luggage (mufrad). And «Jahaaz» is the luggage that a traveler prepares when setting out on a journey. And «Tajhīz» is the luggage prepared for a deceased before burial. And «Jahīz» is the luggage given by parents to a daughter at the time of her marriage departure.\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَلَمَّا جَہَّزَہُمۡ بِجَہَازِہِمۡ» (12/70)\nTranslation: Then when Prophet Yusuf (peace be upon him) prepared his brothers' luggage."
    },
    {
      "id": 1812,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Supplies",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«Zad» is the provisions of food and drink during a journey. (1 verse: 2:197)",
      "d": "«Zada» means increased, surplus, extra supplies (mufrad). And «Zad» generally refers to the road. Zad al-raah (provisions for the journey). During travel, expenses and food/drink supplies. And «Al-muzādata» means a water skin used during travel. And «Mizwadah» means a provision bag. And «Tazawwada» also means to take provisions for the journey (manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ تَزَوَّدُوۡا فَاِنَّ خَیۡرَ الزَّادِ التَّقۡوٰی» (2/197)\nTranslation: And take provisions, for indeed the best provision is piety."
    },
    {
      "id": 1813,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Supplies",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«Aslihah» are weapons and military equipment. (1 verse: 4:102)",
      "d": "«Aslihah» is plural of «Silaah». This word is related to war or battle. Meaning: war equipment, arms and weapons. And everything with which one fights or resists and defends (mufrad).\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَلۡتَقُمۡ طَآئِفَۃٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ مَّعَکَ وَ لۀِیَاۡخُذُوۡۤا اَسۡلِحَتَہُمۡ» (4/102)\nTranslation: Let a group of them stand with you during prayer and let them hold their weapons."
    },
    {
      "id": 1814,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Goods",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«عُدَّۃ» meaning all kinds of equipment and preparations for war (1 verse: 9:46)",
      "d": "«عُدَّۃ» is the plural of «عُدَد» and «عَدَّ». It means to prepare. «اَعَدَّ» and «اَعْتَدَ» mean to prepare and keep ready. And «عُدَّۃٌ» means equipment related to preparation. In the Quran, since this word was used in the context of war preparations, therefore, its meaning includes all kinds of preparations and equipment.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ لَوۡ اَرَادُوا الۡخُرُوۡجَ لَاَعَدُّوۡا لَہٗ عُدَّۃً» (9/46)\nTranslation: And if they had intended to go forth, they would have prepared for it some equipment."
    },
    {
      "id": 1818,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Supplies",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«Ma'un» are small household items for general use. (1 verse: 107:7)",
      "d": "«Al-ma'un» means useful item. And «Ma'un» refers to every usable thing that comes into common people's use. Utensils. Small household items. For example, an axe, pots, or other household goods (manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran: «الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  یُرَآءُوۡنَ وَ یَمۡنَعُوۡنَ الۡمَاعُوۡنَ» (107/7)\nTranslation: And those who show off and do not lend household utensils."
    },
    {
      "id": 1819,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Supplies",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«Hidhr» is means of self-protection. (17 verses: 2:19-2:235-2:243-3:28-3:30-4:71-4:102-5:41-5:49-5:92-9:64-9:122-24:63-28:6-39:9-63:4-64:14)",
      "d": "«Hathara» means to be cautious and careful (m. l). And «Hidhr» is every equipment that provides protection and safety. So every means of protection during war is «Hidhr».\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ لَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اِنۡ کَانَ بِکُمۡ اَذًی مِّنۡ مَّطَرٍ اَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ مَّرۡضٰۤی اَنۡ تَضَعُوۡۤا اَسۡلِحَتَکُمۡ ۚ وَ خُذُوۡا حِذۡرَکُمۡ» (4/102)\nTranslation: And there is no blame on you if you lay down your arms due to rain or illness, but take your precautions."
    },
    {
      "id": 1820,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Goods",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«مَعَایِش» meaning all goods necessary to sustain or maintain life (3 verses: 7:10-15:20-79:11)",
      "d": "«مَعَایِش» is the plural of «مَعِیْشَۃٌ». «عَاش» means to live, to exist. And every goods that is necessary to sustain or maintain life. For example, food, grain, water, provisions, etc. These are called «مَعَایِش».\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ مَکَّنّٰکُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ جَعَلۡنَا لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَعَایِشَ» (7/10)\nTranslation: And We have certainly established you in the land and made for you therein means of livelihood."
    }
  ],
  "386": [
    {
      "id": 1821,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Come Forward",
      "hw": "سامنے",
      "s": "«Aqbal» means to turn towards someone and be in front of them or to come forward. (8 verses: 12:71-28:31-37:27-37:50-37:94-51:29-52:25-68:30)",
      "d": "«Qabala al-makaan» means to turn towards a place. And «Qabil» means two things facing each other or opposite. To confront. And «Qabbala» means to kiss. And «Aqbal» means to turn towards someone and be in front or to come. To face. To approach from the front (manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran: «قَالُوۡا وَ اَقۡبَلُوۡا عَلَیۡہِمۡ  مَّا ذَا  تَفۡقِدُوۡنَ» (12/71)\nTranslation: And they turned towards them saying, 'What is it that you have lost?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1822,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Come Forward",
      "hw": "سامنے",
      "s": "«Baraza» means to come out into an open field. (7 verses: 2:250-3:154-4:81-14:21-14:48-26:91-79:36)",
      "d": "«Barz» means space and open field. And «Baraza» means to come out into an open field (mufrad). And also means to become apparent after obscurity and hiddenness (manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ بَرَزُوۡا لِلّٰہِ جَمِیۡعًا» (14/21)\nTranslation: And all people will come forth before Allah."
    }
  ],
  "387": [
    {
      "id": 1823,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Snake",
      "hw": "سانپ",
      "s": "«Hayyah» is used for all kinds of snakes. (1 verse: 20:20)",
      "d": "«Hayyah» is a common noun. Every kind of snake. Used for both masculine and feminine (fal 160). And according to the author of Munjid, «Hayyah» means a coiling snake. And «Hawaya» refers to intestines that are coiled like a snake. And «Tahawwi al-hayyah» means the snake coils. And «Hawi» is the term for one who recites incantations for a snake (manjad). Both meanings seem correct because every snake generally coils. And probably for this reason it is called «Hayyah».\nFor example, in the Quran: «قَالَ  اَلۡقِہَا یٰمُوۡسٰی فَاَلۡقٰہَا فَاِذَا ہِیَ حَیَّۃٌ  تَسۡعٰی» (20/19,20)\nTranslation: Allah said, 'O Moses, throw it down.' So he threw it down, and suddenly it was a swiftly moving snake."
    },
    {
      "id": 1824,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Snake",
      "hw": "سانپ",
      "s": "«Jaan» is used for slender and long snakes. (7 verses: 15:27-27:10-28:31-55:15-55:39-55:56-55:74)",
      "d": "«Jaan» means jinn, demon, fairy. Strong physique. And every jinn that is in the form of a snake (mufrad). As mentioned in hadith. And Maulana Shabbir Ahmad Uthmani (may Allah have mercy on him) translated it as the swiftness of a snake. A fast and slender snake.\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَلَمَّا رَاٰہَا تَہۡتَزُّ  کَاَنَّہَا جَآنٌّ  وَّلّٰی مُدۡبِرًا  وَّ لَمۡ  یُعَقِّبۡ» (27/10)\nTranslation: When he saw it moving as if it were a swift snake, he turned back and did not look back."
    },
    {
      "id": 1825,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Snake",
      "hw": "سانپ",
      "s": "«Tha'ban» is used for a serpent/dragon. (2 verses: 7:107-26:32)",
      "d": "«Tha'ban» means a serpent. A very large snake (f l 40, 160).\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَاَلۡقٰی عَصَاہُ  فَاِذَا ہِیَ ثُعۡبَانٌ  مُّبِیۡنٌ» (7/107)\nTranslation: He threw his staff, and suddenly it was a clear serpent.\nNow see, Allah used three words for snake in the same incident of the staff turning into a snake: «Hayyah, Jaan, Tha'ban». «Hayyah» for all kinds of snakes. «Jaan» for the initial state of the staff becoming a snake. And «Tha'ban» for its second and final state. And all this happened in an instant."
    }
  ],
  "388": [
    {
      "id": 1826,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "All / Entire",
      "hw": "سب",
      "s": "«کُلّ» means both 'every one' and 'all'. (337 verses: 2:20-2:29-2:31-2:60-2:106-2:109-2:116-2:145-2:148-2:164-2:231-2:259-2:260-2:261-2:266-2:276-2:281-2:282-2:284-2:285-3:7-3:25-3:26-3:29-3:30-3:93-3:119-3:154-3:161-3:165-3:185-3:189-4:11-4:12-4:32-4:33-4:41-4:78-4:85-4:86-4:95-4:126-4:129-4:130-4:176-5:17-5:19-5:40-5:48-5:97-5:117-5:120-6:17-6:25-6:44-6:64-6:67-6:70-6:80-6:84-6:85-6:86-6:99-6:101-6:102-6:108-6:111-6:112-6:123-6:132-6:146-6:154-6:164-7:29-7:31-7:34-7:38-7:46-7:57-7:86-7:89-7:112-7:145-7:146-7:156-7:160-8:12-8:39-8:41-8:54-8:56-8:75-9:5-9:33-9:39-9:115-9:122-9:126-10:22-10:30-10:47-10:49-10:54-10:79-10:97-11:3-11:4-11:6-11:12-11:40-11:57-11:59-11:111-11:120-11:123-12:31-12:76-12:111-13:2-13:3-13:7-13:8-13:16-13:23-13:33-13:38-13:42-14:5-14:15-14:17-14:25-14:34-14:51-15:17-15:19-15:44-16:11-16:36-16:69-16:77-16:84-16:89-16:111-16:112-17:12-17:13-17:20-17:29-17:36-17:38-17:71-17:84-17:89-18:45-18:54-18:79-18:84-19:49-19:69-19:93-19:95-20:15-20:50-20:56-20:98-20:135-21:30-21:33-21:35-21:72-21:79-21:81-21:85-21:93-21:96-21:99-22:2-22:3-22:5-22:6-22:17-22:27-22:34-22:38-22:67-23:27-23:53-23:88-23:91-24:2-24:11-24:35-24:41-24:45-24:64-25:2-25:31-25:39-25:51-26:7-26:37-26:63-26:128-26:222-26:225-27:16-27:23-27:83-27:87-27:88-27:91-28:48-28:57-28:75-28:88-29:20-29:40-29:57-29:62-30:26-30:32-30:50-30:58-31:10-31:18-31:29-31:31-31:32-32:7-32:13-33:27-33:40-33:51-33:52-33:54-33:55-34:7-34:9-34:19-34:21-34:47-35:1-35:12-35:13-35:36-36:12-36:32-36:36-36:40-36:79-36:83-37:7-37:8-38:14-38:19-38:37-38:48-38:73-39:5-39:27-39:62-39:70-40:5-40:7-40:17-40:27-40:35-40:48-40:62-41:12-41:21-41:39-41:53-41:54-42:9-42:12-42:33-43:12-43:35-44:4-44:55-45:7-45:22-45:28-46:19-46:25-46:33-47:15-48:21-48:26-48:28-49:16-50:7-50:8-50:14-50:21-50:24-50:32-51:49-52:21-54:3-54:28-54:42-54:49-54:52-54:53-55:26-55:29-55:52-57:2-57:3-57:10-57:23-58:6-58:7-59:6-61:9-63:4-64:1-64:11-65:3-65:12-66:8-67:1-67:19-68:10-70:38-72:28-74:38-74:52-78:29-80:37-83:12-85:9-86:4-97:4-104:1)",
      "d": "«کُلّ» means 'all', 'entire', and its opposite is «جُزْء». It is used when 'all' is a collection of several units (i.e., numbers from one to nine, decades in numbers before hundred). Then this word is also used for every part, meaning 'every one', 'every person', 'every thing'. For example, in the Quran: «قُلۡ کُلٌّ یَّعۡمَلُ عَلٰی شَاکِلَتِہٖ» (17/84) Translation: Say, 'Every person acts according to his own manner.' And it is also used for such a collection of units, meaning 'all', 'entire'. For example, Allah the Almighty says: «وَ عَلَّمَ اٰدَمَ الۡاَسۡمَآءَ کُلَّہَا» (2/31) Translation: And Allah taught Adam the names of all things."
    },
    {
      "id": 1827,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "All. Entire.",
      "hw": "سب",
      "s": "«کَافَّۃ» means completely whole and entirely all. It is stronger than «کُلّ» and «کامل». (4 verses: 2:208-9:36-9:122-34:28)",
      "d": "«اَلْکَفَافُ» refers to the entire circumference of something. «کَافَّ» is the active participle and «کَافَّۃٌ» is its feminine form (fem). Its usage is of two types.\n(1) When «کُلّ» refers to many units, it is used for that entire collection, and in this respect it is stronger and more complete than «کُلّ».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَاۤ  اَرۡسَلۡنٰکَ  اِلَّا کَآفَّۃً  لِّلنَّاسِ بَشِیۡرًا وَّ نَذِیۡرًا» (34/28)\nTranslation: And (O Muhammad ﷺ) We have sent you as a bringer of glad tidings and a warner to all mankind.\n(2) When «کُلّ» is a single unit, it comes to encompass all its parts. And in this respect it is stronger than «کامل» (fem).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا ادۡخُلُوۡا فِی السِّلۡمِ  کَآفَّۃً» (2/208)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, enter into Islam completely.\nIn this verse, the word «کَافَّۃ» gives both its meanings: entirely all and completely whole."
    },
    {
      "id": 1828,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "All / Entire",
      "hw": "سب",
      "s": "«اَجْمَعُوْن» means all together, collectively, to agree on something. (12 verses: 3:157-3:173-4:23-10:58-10:71-12:15-12:102-15:30-20:64-26:95-38:73-43:32)",
      "d": "«جَمَعَ» means to gather. And «اَجْمَعَ» means all together to do something. And «اَجْمَعَ عَلَی الْاَمْر» means all to agree on a matter. For example, in the Quran: «فَلَمَّا ذَہَبُوۡا بِہٖ  وَ  اَجۡمَعُوۡۤا اَنۡ یَّجۡعَلُوۡہُ  فِیۡ غَیٰبَتِ  الۡجُبِّ» (12/15) Translation: So when they took him away and agreed to put him in the bottom of the well. And «اَجْمَعُوْن» means all together or at the same time collectively to do something. For example, in the Quran: «فَسَجَدَ  الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ  کُلُّہُمۡ  اَجۡمَعُوۡنَ» (15/30) Translation: Then all the angels prostrated together."
    }
  ],
  "389": [
    {
      "id": 1832,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To hand over. To entrust.",
      "hw": "حوالے",
      "s": "«سَلَّمَ» means to hand over something to someone to avoid trouble. (2 verses: 2:233-31:22)",
      "d": "«سَلِمَ» means to be saved from defect and affliction (م ۔ ق), and «سَلَّمَ» also means to say «السلام علیکم», to save from affliction. And «سَلَّمَہٗ اِلٰی فُلَانٍ» means to hand over something to someone, and «سَلَّمہُ الشَّیْءَ فَتَسَلَّمَہٗ» means to entrust someone with something and for that person to accept it (منجد). Thus, «سَلَّمَ» is used for saving from trouble and for handing over.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ اَرَدۡتُمۡ اَنۡ تَسۡتَرۡضِعُوۡۤا اَوۡلَادَکُمۡ فَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ  اِذَا سَلَّمۡتُمۡ مَّاۤ  اٰتَیۡتُمۡ  بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ» (2/233)\nTranslation: And if you wish to have your children nursed, there is no blame upon you when you hand over to the nurses what you have given according to the accepted norm.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«وَّ دِیَۃٌ مُّسَلَّمَۃٌ اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہٖۤ  اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ یَّصَّدَّقُوۡا» (4/92)\nTranslation: And the blood money is to be handed over to the heirs, unless they remit it as charity."
    },
    {
      "id": 1833,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To hand over. To entrust.",
      "hw": "حوالے",
      "s": "«فَوَّضَ» means to entrust a matter to someone and make them the authority. (1 verse: 40:44)",
      "d": "«فَوَّضَ» means to leave something to someone. And «تَفْوِیْضًا اِلَیْہِ الْاَمْر» means to entrust the matter to someone and make them the authority (منجد).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اُفَوِّضُ اَمۡرِیۡۤ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ» (40/44)\nTranslation: And I entrust my affair to Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1834,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To entrust; to hand over",
      "hw": "حوالے",
      "s": "«اِسْتَوْدَعَ» To entrust something as a trust (2 verses: 6:98-11:6)",
      "d": "«وَدَعَ» means to leave. And «اَوْدَعَ الشَّیْ» means to keep something as a trust. And «وَدَّعَ» means to bid farewell to a traveler. And «اِسْتَوْدَعَ فُلَانًا شَیْئًا» means to keep something with someone as a trust, so this handing over is in the capacity of a trust. (Majid)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَنۡشَاَکُمۡ مِّنۡ نَّفۡسٍ وَّاحِدَۃٍ  فَمُسۡتَقَرٌّ وَّ مُسۡتَوۡدَعٌ» ( 6/98 )\nTranslation: And He it is Who has created you from a single soul, then for you is a place of settlement (in the world) and a place of entrustment (in the grave).\nMeaning: You are kept alive in the world for a period, then you are entrusted (to the earth) after being buried in it. (Jalandhariؒ)"
    }
  ],
  "390": [
    {
      "id": 1835,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Truth",
      "hw": "سچ",
      "s": "«صِدْق» Meaning to speak the truth (57 verses: 2:41-2:89-2:91-2:79-2:101-2:177-3:3-3:39-3:50-3:81-3:95-3:152-4:47-4:87-4:122-5:46-5:48-5:113-5:119-6:92-6:115-9:43-10:2-10:93-12:26-17:80-19:50-21:9-26:84-27:27-28:34-29:3-33:8-33:22-33:23-33:24-34:20-35:31-36:52-37:37-37:52-37:105-39:32-39:33-39:74-46:12-46:16-46:30-47:21-48:27-54:55-56:57-61:6-66:12-70:26-75:31-92:6)",
      "d": "«صَدَقَ» means to speak the truth. Its opposite is «کَذَب». That is, not to say anything contrary to fact. It is a well-known word.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَمَنۡ اَظۡلَمُ  مِمَّنۡ  کَذَبَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ وَ  کَذَّبَ بِالصِّدۡقِ اِذۡ جَآءَہٗ» ( 39/32 )\nTranslation: So who is more unjust than he who lies against Allah and denies the truth when it comes to him?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1836,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Truth",
      "hw": "سچ",
      "s": "«حَقّ» Used for truth and reality (252 verses: 2:26-2:42-2:61-2:71-2:91-2:109-2:119-2:121-2:144-2:146-2:147-2:149-2:176-2:180-2:213-2:236-2:241-2:252-2:282-3:3-3:21-3:60-3:62-3:71-3:86-3:102-3:108-3:112-3:154-3:181-4:105-4:122-4:151-4:155-4:170-4:171-5:27-5:48-5:77-5:83-5:84-5:107-5:116-6:5-6:30-6:57-6:62-6:66-6:73-6:91-6:93-6:114-6:141-6:151-7:8-7:30-7:33-7:43-7:44-7:53-7:89-7:105-7:118-7:146-7:159-7:169-7:181-8:4-8:5-8:6-8:7-8:8-8:32-8:74-9:29-9:33-9:48-9:111-10:4-10:5-10:23-10:30-10:32-10:33-10:35-10:36-10:53-10:55-10:76-10:77-10:82-10:94-10:96-10:103-10:108-11:17-11:45-11:79-11:120-12:51-12:100-13:1-13:14-13:17-13:19-14:19-14:22-15:8-15:55-15:64-15:85-16:3-16:36-16:38-16:102-17:16-17:26-17:33-17:81-17:105-18:13-18:21-18:29-18:44-18:56-18:98-19:34-20:114-21:18-21:24-21:55-21:97-21:112-22:6-22:18-22:40-22:54-22:62-22:74-22:78-23:41-23:62-23:70-23:71-23:90-23:116-24:25-24:49-25:26-25:33-25:68-27:79-28:3-28:13-28:39-28:48-28:53-28:63-28:75-29:44-29:68-30:8-30:38-30:47-30:60-31:9-31:30-31:33-32:3-32:13-33:4-33:53-34:6-34:23-34:26-34:43-34:48-34:49-35:5-35:24-35:31-36:7-36:70-37:31-37:37-38:14-38:22-38:26-38:64-38:84-39:2-39:5-39:19-39:41-39:67-39:69-39:71-39:75-40:5-40:6-40:20-40:25-40:55-40:75-40:77-40:78-41:15-41:25-41:53-42:17-42:18-42:24-42:42-43:29-43:30-43:78-43:86-44:39-45:6-45:22-45:29-45:32-46:3-46:7-46:17-46:18-46:20-46:30-46:34-47:2-47:3-48:27-48:28-50:5-50:14-50:19-50:42-51:19-51:23-53:28-56:95-57:16-57:27-60:1-61:9-64:3-69:51-70:24-78:39-84:2-84:5-103:3)",
      "d": "«حَقّ» Its opposite is «بَاطِل». «حَقّ» is every statement or thing that is proven to be true and correct after experience and observation. Reality. Truth (fem.)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«سَنُرِیۡہِمۡ  اٰیٰتِنَا فِی الۡاٰفَاقِ  وَ فِیۡۤ   اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ حَتّٰی یَتَبَیَّنَ  لَہُمۡ  اَنَّہُ  الۡحَقُّ» ( 41/53 )\nTranslation: We will soon show them Our signs in the horizons and in themselves until it becomes clear to them that it (the revelation of the Quran) is the truth."
    }
  ],
  "391": [
    {
      "id": 1837,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Severe",
      "hw": "سخت",
      "s": "«اَشَقّ» Such a hardship that is unbearable (2 verses: 13:34-28:27)",
      "d": "«شَقَّ الْاَمْر» means for an affair to be difficult. And «شَقَّ عَلٰی فُلَانٍ» means to cause hardship for someone (Majid). And the word «اَشَقَّ» generally refers to such hardship that exceeds one's strength or capacity. That hardship which is beyond endurance. Life-threatening.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ لَعَذَابُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ اَشَقُّ» ( 13/34 )\nTranslation: And the punishment of the Hereafter is more severe."
    },
    {
      "id": 1838,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Severe",
      "hw": "سخت",
      "s": "«اَشَدّ» For something to be inherently severe (30 verses: 2:74-2:85-2:165-2:191-2:200-4:66-4:77-4:84-5:82-9:69-9:81-9:97-19:69-20:71-20:127-28:78-30:9-35:44-37:11-40:21-40:46-40:82-41:15-43:8-47:13-48:29-50:36-59:13-73:6-79:27)",
      "d": "«اَشَدُّ» means very strong and powerful, very severe, and «قُوَّۃً فِیْ شَیْءٍ» i.e., to be inherently powerful and severe in something. To be severe in strength, power, and force. Overpowering. Used for body, strength, and punishment.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«یُرَدُّوۡنَ اِلٰۤی اَشَدِّ الۡعَذَابِ» ( 2/85 )\nTranslation: They will be returned to the more severe punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 1839,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Severe",
      "hw": "سخت",
      "s": "«اَدْھٰی» To be severe in terms of calamities and difficulties (1 verse: 54:46)",
      "d": "«دَھِیَ» means to afflict someone with a calamity. And «دَاھِیَۃٌ» means a severe calamity. A very severe matter (Majid). And «دَھِیَ» means for one thing to reach another in an unpleasant way or to plunge into calamity. And «دَوَاھِیَ الدَّھْر» means the accidents of time (M. L.). And «اَدْھٰی» means severe in terms of calamities and difficulties.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ السَّاعَۃُ اَدۡہٰی  وَ  اَمَرُّ» ( 54/46 )\nTranslation: And the Hour (of Judgment) is most severe and most bitter."
    },
    {
      "id": 1840,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Severe",
      "hw": "سخت",
      "s": "«رَابِیَۃ» Increasing at every moment (1 verse: 69:10)",
      "d": "«رَبَا ، رَبْوًا» means to increase, to grow, to flourish, to become more. And «رَابِیَۃ» means that which increases continuously.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَعَصَوۡا  رَسُوۡلَ  رَبِّہِمۡ  فَاَخَذَہُمۡ  اَخۡذَۃً  رَّابِیَۃً» ( 69/10 )\nTranslation: They disobeyed the Messenger of their Lord, so He seized them with a seizure, ever-increasing."
    },
    {
      "id": 1841,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Severe",
      "hw": "سخت",
      "s": "«عَصِیْب» Severe and devoid of good (1 verse: 11:77)",
      "d": "In «عَصَبَ» two meanings are found: (1) The connection and association of one thing with another. (2) Severity. «عَصَبَہ» its plural is «اَعْصَاب» meaning nerves (tendons). And «عُصْبَۃ» is that strong group whose number is ten or more, and they have mutual connection, association, and cohesion, and therefore that group is powerful and strong (M. L.). As the brothers of Prophet Yusuf (peace be upon him) said to their father: «وَنَحْنُ عُصْبَۃً» ( 12/14 ) i.e., we are a powerful group. And «تَعَصُّبْ» refers to the severity of a theory or belief, that a person does not accept it even after knowing the truth. And «عَصِیْب» is that which is both severe and devoid of goodness and well-being.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ لَمَّا جَآءَتۡ رُسُلُنَا لُوۡطًا سِیۡٓءَ بِہِمۡ وَ ضَاقَ بِہِمْ ذَرۡعًا وَّ قَالَ ہٰذَا یَوۡمٌ عَصِیۡبٌ» ( 11/77 )\nTranslation: When Our messengers came to Lut, he was distressed by their presence and felt helpless because of them, and he said, 'This is a day of severe distress.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1842,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Severe",
      "hw": "سخت",
      "s": "«قَمْطَرِیْر» Severe in terms of evil (1 verse: 76:10)",
      "d": "«قَمْطَرِیْر» means causing hearts to be severely restless, impatient, and disturbed (fem.). «قِمْطَر» is that wood which is used for stretching the feet of criminals and for administering punishment (M. Q.). And «قَمْطَرِیْر» means severe evil or intense days (Majid).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِنَّا نَخَافُ مِنۡ رَّبِّنَا یَوۡمًا عَبُوۡسًا قَمۡطَرِیۡرًا» ( 76/10 )\nTranslation: Indeed, we fear from our Lord a day that is frowning and severe."
    },
    {
      "id": 1843,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Severe",
      "hw": "سخت",
      "s": "«قَاسِیَۃ» The severity or hardness of the heart (3 verses: 5:13-22:53-39:22)",
      "d": "The word «قَسْوَۃ» denotes intensity and severity (M. L.). «قَسَا» means to become hard and solid (Majid). «حَجَرٌ قَاسٍ» means a hard stone. And «اَلْقَسْوَۃ» means to be hard-hearted (fem.). Thus, the word «قَسْوَۃ» generally refers to the hardness of the heart, hard-heartedness, and being devoid of gentle and merciful feelings. It is said, «اَلذَّنْبُ مُسْقَاۃٌ لِّلْقَلْبِ» - sin makes the heart hard (Majid).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَوَیۡلٌ  لِّلۡقٰسِیَۃِ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ مِّنۡ ذِکۡرِ اللّٰہِ» ( 39/22 )\nTranslation: So woe to those whose hearts are hardened against the remembrance of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1844,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Severe",
      "hw": "سخت",
      "s": "«غَلِیْظ» meaning harsh-hearted and harsh-tempered (11 verses: 3:159-4:21-4:154-9:73-11:58-14:17-31:24-33:7-41:50-48:29-66:9)",
      "d": "«غَلَظَ» means to be thick, dense, severe, rough, or uneven. And «غَلَظَ الرَّجُل» means a man is angry, ill-tempered, and harsh in speech (Munjid). The opposite of «غَلِیْظ» is «لِیْنٌ» meaning softness. And «غَلِیْظُ الْقَلْب» means a person who is both hard-hearted and ill-tempered, and its plural is «غِلَاظٌ». For example, in the Quran: «عَلَیۡہَا مَلٰٓئِکَۃٌ  غِلَاظٌ شِدَادٌ لَّا یَعۡصُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ مَاۤ  اَمَرَہُمۡ» (66/6) Translation: Severe and harsh angels are appointed over Hell, and they do not disobey Allah in what He commands them."
    }
  ],
  "392": [
    {
      "id": 1847,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Hardship",
      "hw": "سختی",
      "s": "«بَأسَاء» a period of hardship and scarcity (26 verses: 2:177-2:214-4:84-6:42-6:43-6:147-6:148-7:4-7:5-7:94-7:97-7:98-12:110-16:81-17:5-18:2-21:12-21:80-27:33-33:18-40:29-40:84-40:85-48:16-57:25-59:14)",
      "d": "In «بَؤُسَ», the meanings of scarcity and hardship are found. Whether due to war or hunger. The word «بَأس» is also used in the Quran in the meanings of war, e.g., «وَحِیْنَ الْبَاْس» (2/177), and for punishment, e.g., «اِذْجَآءَ ھُمْ بَاْسُنَا» (6/43), and for affliction, e.g., «بَأسًا شَدِیْدًا» (18/2). In all, the meaning of scarcity is found. And «بَأسَآء» refers to a prolonged period of scarcity and hardship, whether it is economic destitution and misery or the severity of war. For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَقَدۡ اَرۡسَلۡنَاۤ  اِلٰۤی  اُمَمٍ مِّنۡ قَبۡلِکَ فَاَخَذۡنٰہُمۡ بِالۡبَاۡسَآءِ وَ الضَّرَّآءِ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَتَضَرَّعُوۡنَ» (6/42) Translation: And We certainly sent messengers to nations before you, then We seized them with hardships and calamities so that they might humble themselves."
    },
    {
      "id": 1848,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Hardship",
      "hw": "سختی",
      "s": "«کَبَد» the human nature that endures hardship throughout life (1 verse: 90:4)",
      "d": "In the word «کَبَد», the meanings of hardship and strength are found (M. L.). And «تَکَبَّد» and «کَابَد» mean to endure hardship (Munjid). «فِیْ کَبَد» is used idiomatically, and it expresses human nature. When a desire arises in a person's heart, he endures various kinds of pain and sorrow to fulfill it, and before it is fulfilled, other desires arise. Then the person becomes prepared to fulfill them and endure pain, and thus his entire life passes. Allah Almighty has expressed this reality as: «لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ فِیۡ  کَبَدٍ» (90/4) Translation: Indeed, We have created man in hardship. Note: In medical science and wisdom, the liver (jigar) is also called kabd."
    }
  ],
  "393": [
    {
      "id": 1849,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Raising the head",
      "hw": "سر",
      "s": "«اَقْمَحَ» such a head that is raised but the eyes are lowered (1 verse: 36:8)",
      "d": "«اَقْمَحَ» means a head that is raised but the eyes are lowered. And «اَقْمَحَ الْبَعِیْر» when a camel, after drinking water, raises its head and keeps its eyes down, that state is called so (F L 186). And when a person wants to look down but due to some compulsion cannot lower his head, it is also called «اَقْمَحَ الرَّجُلُ وَغَضَّ بَصَرُہٗ» (M. Q). For example, in the Quran: «اِنَّا جَعَلۡنَا فِیۡۤ  اَعۡنَاقِہِمۡ  اَغۡلٰلًا فَہِیَ  اِلَی  الۡاَذۡقَانِ فَہُمۡ  مُّقۡمَحُوۡنَ» (36/8) Translation: Indeed, We have placed collars around their necks, reaching up to the chins, so their heads are raised (and they cannot look down)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1850,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Raising the head",
      "hw": "سر",
      "s": "«اَقْنَعَ» head raised and gaze forward or upward (1 verse: 14:43)",
      "d": "«اَقْنَعَ» means to raise the voice or head. To elevate. And «مُقْنِع» means one who raises his head to look (Munjid). For example, in the Quran: «مُہۡطِعِیۡنَ مُقۡنِعِیۡ رُءُوۡسِہِمۡ لَا یَرۡتَدُّ اِلَیۡہِمۡ  طَرۡفُہُمۡ ۚ وَ اَفۡئِدَتُہُمۡ  ہَوَآءٌ» (14/43) Translation: Hastening, with their heads raised, not looking back at them, and their hearts (due to fear) are in suspense."
    }
  ],
  "394": [
    {
      "id": 1852,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Leader",
      "hw": "سردار",
      "s": "«سَیِّد» the leader of a large group (in a good sense) (3 verses: 3:39-12:25-33:67)",
      "d": "«سَادَ» means to be noble, great, to be the leader of a people, to surpass in honor and dignity (Munjid). «سَوَادَ» means a large group, and «سَیّد» is the leader of that large group. And since a leader must be cultured, every noble person can be called a sayyid. And by the same relation, a master and husband are also called «سَیِّد» (Maf). Its plural is «سَادَت» and «سَادَات». This word is used in a good sense. For example, in the Quran: «وَ قَالُوۡا رَبَّنَاۤ  اِنَّاۤ  اَطَعۡنَا سَادَتَنَا وَ کُبَرَآءَنَا  فَاَضَلُّوۡنَا السَّبِیۡلَا» (33/67) Translation: And they will say, 'Our Lord, indeed we obeyed our leaders and our great ones, and they led us astray from the way.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1853,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Leader",
      "hw": "سردار",
      "s": "«مَلَأ» government officials, courtiers, and people who have influence over the people (used in a bad sense) (19 verses: 7:60-7:66-7:75-7:88-7:90-7:109-7:127-10:88-11:27-11:38-12:43-23:24-23:33-27:29-27:32-27:38-28:20-28:38-38:6)",
      "d": "«مَلَا» means to fill, and «مَلَأ» means a group that gathers for something (a command). And it fills the eyes with apparent beauty and elegance, and the hearts with awe (Maf). And its leader who turns the eyes with arrogance and the chest with awe (M Q). In common parlance, «مَلَا» refers to those government officials who, due to royal influence, remain dominant over people. For example, in the Quran: «قَالَ الۡمَلَاُ الَّذِیۡنَ اسۡتَکۡبَرُوۡا مِنۡ قَوۡمِہٖ لَنُخۡرِجَنَّکَ یٰشُعَیۡبُ وَ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا مَعَکَ مِنۡ قَرۡیَتِنَاۤ» (7/88) Translation: The arrogant chiefs of his people said, 'We will surely expel you, O Shu'ayb, and those who believe with you from our town.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1854,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Leader",
      "hw": "سردار",
      "s": "«رَھْط» a short group from the same tribe, a gang of evildoers and its leader (3 verses: 11:91-11:92-27:48)",
      "d": "«رَھْط» is a small group of people from one tribe whose number is less than ten and has no woman in it. Then the leader of this group is also called «رَھْط» (Maf). And it is generally used in a bad sense. And «رَھْط» is also the name of the cloth or rag that a woman keeps aside during menstruation. From this, the idiom «ھُوَ اَذَلُّ مِنَ الرَّھْط» is derived, meaning he is more despicable than the menstrual rag. And when the word «رَھْط» is attributed to a number, then individuals and persons are meant. Like «عِشْرُوْن رَھْطًا» meaning twenty persons (Munjid). For example, in the Quran: «وَ کَانَ فِی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  تِسۡعَۃُ  رَہۡطٍ یُّفۡسِدُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ لَا یُصۡلِحُوۡنَ» (27/48) Translation: And in the city were nine gangs causing corruption in the land and not reforming."
    },
    {
      "id": 1855,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Leader",
      "hw": "سردار",
      "s": "«اَئِمَّۃ» plural of «اِمَام» meaning a leader whose example is followed, whether good or bad (5 verses: 9:12-21:73-28:5-28:41-32:24)",
      "d": "«اَئِمَّۃ» is the plural of «اِمَام». It is a person or book or saying whose example is followed, whether it is a human or his sayings or a book, whether it is on truth or falsehood (Maf). In the form of a human, it generally means a religious leader or the imam of the congregation in prayer. Now, see its examples: Example (1) A book of guidance, e.g., in the Quran: «وَ کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ اَحۡصَیۡنٰہُ  فِیۡۤ   اِمَامٍ  مُّبِیۡنٍ» (36/12) Translation: And We have encompassed all things in a clear Book. Example (2) Imams of guidance, e.g., Allah says: «وَ جَعَلۡنَا مِنۡہُمۡ  اَئِمَّۃً  یَّہۡدُوۡنَ  بِاَمۡرِنَا لَمَّا صَبَرُوۡا» (32/24) Translation: And We made from among them leaders who guided by Our command when they were patient. Example (3) Imams of disbelief, e.g., Allah says: «فَقَاتِلُوۡۤا اَئِمَّۃَ الۡکُفۡرِ ۙ اِنَّہُمۡ لَاۤ اَیۡمَانَ لَہِمۡ» (9/12) Translation: So fight the leaders of disbelief, indeed, their oaths are of no account."
    },
    {
      "id": 1856,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Leader",
      "hw": "سردار",
      "s": "«نَقِیْب» a great man of a people or group, a responsible individual of a tribe who represents it, leader, head (1 verse: 5:12)",
      "d": "«نَقَبَ» means to make a hole in a wall. To dig a tunnel. And «نَقَبَ عَنِ الْاَخْبَار» means to investigate news. And «نَاقَبَ» means to boast about one's deeds. And «نَاقِبْ» means one who knows the conditions of a people. And «مَنْقَبَتْ» means praise and commendation, eulogy and admiration. Noble deeds. And «نَقِیْب» means one who knows the conditions of a people. The leader of a people. A numberdar. A witness and guarantor of the people (Maf. Munjid). This word is also used in a good sense. For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَقَدۡ اَخَذَ اللّٰہُ مِیۡثَاقَ بَنِیۡۤ  اِسۡرَآءِیۡلَ ۚ وَ بَعَثۡنَا مِنۡہُمُ اثۡنَیۡ عَشَرَ نَقِیۡبًا» (5/12) Translation: And Allah had already taken a covenant from the Children of Israel, and We sent from among them twelve leaders."
    }
  ],
  "395": [
    {
      "id": 1857,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Cold. Coldness",
      "hw": "سردی",
      "s": "«شِتَآء» meaning the season of coldness (1 verse: 106:2)",
      "d": "«شِتَآء» means the season of coldness; its opposite is «صَیْف» meaning the season of heat, and «شَتْوِیّ» meaning the rain of winter season (Munjid). For example, in the Quran: «لِاِیۡلٰفِ قُرَیۡشٍ اٖلٰفِہِمۡ رِحۡلَۃَ الشِّتَآءِ وَ الصَّیۡفِ» (106/1,2). Translation: Because the people of Quraysh are accustomed to it. That is, they are accustomed to traveling in the winter and summer seasons (to Yemen and Sham)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1858,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Cold. Coldness",
      "hw": "سردی",
      "s": "«صِرّ» meaning severe cold (1 verse: 3:117)",
      "d": "«صُرَّ الْبَنَات» means plants dying due to cold wind (Munjid), and «صِرّ» means severe cold. The cold that causes shivering. For example, in the Quran: «کَمَثَلِ رِیۡحٍ فِیۡہَا صِرٌّ اَصَابَتۡ حَرۡثَ قَوۡمٍ ظَلَمُوۡۤا اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ فَاَہۡلَکَتۡہُ» (3/117). Translation: Its example is a wind in which there is severe cold that struck the harvest of a people who wronged themselves, so it destroyed it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1859,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Cold. Coldness",
      "hw": "سردی",
      "s": "«صَرْ صَر» meaning severe cold and swift wind that also produces sound (3 verses: 41:16-54:19-69:6)",
      "d": "«صَرْ صَر» means severe cold and swift wind. A wind that is cold, swift, and produces sound. A severe cold wind that howls (M. Q.). For example, in the Quran: «وَ اَمَّا عَادٌ  فَاُہۡلِکُوۡا بِرِیۡحٍ صَرۡصَرٍ عَاتِیَۃٍ» (69/6). Translation: As for 'Ad, they were destroyed by a fierce, howling wind."
    },
    {
      "id": 1860,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Cold. Coldness.",
      "hw": "سردی",
      "s": "«نَفْحَۃ» a gust or puff of cold wind. (1 verse: 21:46)",
      "d": "«نَفَحَ» means the blowing of cold wind. Or the blowing of cold wind. And نَفْحۃ is a feminine noun (marrah). Meaning a puff of cold wind. Its opposite is «لَفْحَۃ» meaning a puff of hot wind.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَئِنۡ مَّسَّتۡہُمۡ نَفۡحَۃٌ مِّنۡ عَذَابِ رَبِّکَ» (21/46)\nTranslation: And if they are touched by even a puff of your Lord's punishment,"
    },
    {
      "id": 1861,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Cold. Coldness",
      "hw": "سردی",
      "s": "«زَمْھَرِیْر» an extremely cold layer or severe cold (1 verse: 76:13)",
      "d": "«اِزْمَھَرَّالْیَوْم» means the day being severely cold. And «زَمْھَرِیْر» means severe cold as well as the layer where intense cold exists (Munjid). For example, in the Quran: «لَا یَرَوۡنَ فِیۡہَا شَمۡسًا وَّ  لَا  زَمۡہَرِیۡرًا» (76/13). Translation: They will not see in it sun or severe cold."
    }
  ],
  "396": [
    {
      "id": 1862,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Rebellion",
      "hw": "سرکشی",
      "s": "«طَغٰی» to exceed one's limits (9 verses: 20:24-20:43-20:45-53:17-53:52-69:11-79:17-79:37-96:6)",
      "d": "«طَغٰی» means to transgress in disobedience, to be extremely disobedient. And «طَغَا الْمَاء» means water rising and overflowing the banks; flooding occurs (Munjid). «طَاغِیَۃ» means an excessive punishment, flood, or severe storm. And «طَاغُوْت» is everything that is worshipped besides Allah (Mufradat), whether it is a system or a personality. Thus, in 'taghyan' (transgression), besides exceeding limits, dominance and severity are also found (Faqir li al-Rahman 190). For example, in the Quran: «کَلَّاۤ  اِنَّ  الۡاِنۡسَانَ  لَیَطۡغٰۤی اَنۡ  رَّاٰہُ  اسۡتَغۡنٰی» (96/6). Translation: No! Indeed, man is rebellious when he sees himself self-sufficient."
    },
    {
      "id": 1863,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Rebellion",
      "hw": "سرکشی",
      "s": "«عَتَا» rebellion due to arrogance (5 verses: 7:77-7:166-25:21-51:44-67:21)",
      "d": "«عُتُوّ» indicates arrogance, meaning rebellion that occurs due to arrogance, and a person, considering himself great, rebels against Allah's command. For example, in the Quran: «بَلۡ لَّجُّوۡا فِیۡ عُتُوٍّ  وَّ نُفُوۡرٍ» (67/21). Translation: But they have gone far in rebellion and aversion."
    },
    {
      "id": 1864,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Rebellion",
      "hw": "سرکشی",
      "s": "«عَلَا» to choose rebellion upon gaining dominance and authority (8 verses: 3:139-17:4-17:43-27:14-27:31-28:4-28:83-44:19)",
      "d": "«عَلَا» means to be elevated, to prevail, to be arrogant (Munjid). To choose rebellion due to gaining dominance and authority, to raise one's head. For example, in the Quran: «لَتُفۡسِدُنَّ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مَرَّتَیۡنِ  وَ لَتَعۡلُنَّ  عُلُوًّا کَبِیۡرًا» (17/4). Translation: You will surely cause corruption in the land twice and will surely become haughty with great arrogance."
    },
    {
      "id": 1865,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Rebellion",
      "hw": "سرکشی",
      "s": "«مَرَدَ» to be rebellious, then to surpass in it, to fly (3 verses: 4:117-9:101-22:3)",
      "d": "«مَرَدَ» means to be disobedient and rebellious. To surpass peers (Munjid). Thus, «مَرَدَ» refers to rebellion where one surpasses others. For example, in the Quran: «اِنۡ یَّدۡعُوۡنَ  اِلَّا شَیۡطٰنًا مَّرِیۡدًا» (4/117). Translation: And they invoke not except a rebellious devil."
    }
  ],
  "397": [],
  "398": [
    {
      "id": 1868,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Tunnel",
      "hw": "سرنگ",
      "s": "«نَفَق» a tunnel with two openings (1 verse: 6:35)",
      "d": "«نَفَق» is a path open on both sides. A tunnel that passes through (F. L. 30), such as a tunnel made through a mountain for railway or traffic. «نَیْفَقُ السَّرَاوِیْل» means the crotch of pajamas, and «نَافِقَاءَ الْیَرْبُوْع» means the burrow of a wild mouse, which has two openings. And «نَافَقَ الْیَرْبُوْعُ وَ نَفَقَ» means the mouse entered the burrow from one opening and exited from the other. For example, in the Quran: «فَاِنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتَ اَنۡ تَبۡتَغِیَ نَفَقًا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اَوۡ  سُلَّمًا فِی السَّمَآءِ» (6/35). Translation: So if you are able to seek a tunnel through the earth or a ladder to the sky."
    },
    {
      "id": 1869,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Tunnel",
      "hw": "سرنگ",
      "s": "«سَرَب» is a tunnel that has only one opening (1 Verse: 18:61)",
      "d": "«سَرَب» refers to a tunnel with a single mouth. And «سَرَبَ» means to move forward by crawling or gliding (F L 30). And «اِنْسَرَبَتِ الْحَیَّۃُ اِلٰی جُحْرِھَا» means a snake crawls into its burrow.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا بَلَغَا مَجۡمَعَ بَیۡنِہِمَا نَسِیَا حُوۡتَہُمَا فَاتَّخَذَ سَبِیۡلَہٗ  فِی الۡبَحۡرِ  سَرَبًا» (18/61)\nTranslation: Then when they reached the meeting point of the two rivers, they forgot their fish, and it made its way into the sea as if through a tunnel."
    }
  ],
  "399": [
    {
      "id": 1870,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sluggishness / To be Sluggish",
      "hw": "سست",
      "s": "«کَسَلَ» To be sluggish due to indifference or lack of interest (2 Verses: 4:142-9:54)",
      "d": "«کَسَلَ» means to feel heavy or sluggish in one's nature due to lack of desire or indifference. To be lazy. To be loose, flabby, or to remain in such a state (intransitive).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا قَامُوۡۤا اِلَی الصَّلٰوۃِ قَامُوۡا کُسَالٰی» (4/142)\nTranslation: And when these (hypocrites) stand up for prayer, they stand up lazily and sluggishly."
    },
    {
      "id": 1871,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sluggishness / To be Sluggish",
      "hw": "سست",
      "s": "«وَھَنَ» To be sluggish due to physical or moral weakness (8 Verses: 3:139-3:146-4:104-47:35-8:18-19:4-29:41-31:14)",
      "d": "«وَھَنَ» means to become sluggish due to physical or moral weakness (intransitive).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَہِنُوۡا فِی ابۡتِغَآءِ الۡقَوۡمِ» (4/104)\nTranslation: And do not be sluggish in pursuing this (disbelieving) people."
    },
    {
      "id": 1872,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sluggishness / To be Sluggish",
      "hw": "سست",
      "s": "«وَنٰی» To be sluggish due to carelessness (1 Verse: 20:42)",
      "d": "«وَنٰی» means to fall short, to be remiss, to be sluggish (Majid). It means not to make an effort despite having the power and capacity to do so.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡہَبۡ اَنۡتَ وَ اَخُوۡکَ بِاٰیٰتِیۡ وَ لَا تَنِیَا فِیۡ  ذِکۡرِیۡ» (20/42)\nTranslation: O Moses! Go you and your brother with My signs and do not be sluggish in remembering Me."
    },
    {
      "id": 1873,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sluggishness / To be Sluggish",
      "hw": "سست",
      "s": "«اِسْتَحْسَرَ» To be sluggish due to fatigue (1 Verse: 21:19)",
      "d": "«حَسَرَ» means to become tired. And «حَسَرَ الْبَصَرَ» means for the sight to become tired, for vision to weaken. And «حَسِیْر» means tired, exhausted (Majid). So, «حَسَرَ» is used for sluggishness that occurs due to fatigue, to become fed up.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ عِنۡدَہٗ  لَا یَسۡتَکۡبِرُوۡنَ عَنۡ عِبَادَتِہٖ وَ لَا یَسۡتَحۡسِرُوۡنَ» (21/19)\nTranslation: And those who are with Him (the angels) do not disdain His worship, nor do they become weary/fed up."
    },
    {
      "id": 1874,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sluggishness / To be Sluggish",
      "hw": "سست",
      "s": "«بَطَّاَ» To be sluggish in movement or habitually sluggish, and then to cause delay (1 Verse: 4:72)",
      "d": "«اَلْبَطْؤُ» means to delay in moving and to be sluggish. And «اِبْطَاءٌ» means sluggishness in movement, laziness, indolence. And «بَطَّاَ» means to be extremely sluggish and to delay (intransitive).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِنَّ مِنۡکُمۡ لَمَنۡ لَّیُبَطِّئَنَّ» (4/72)\nTranslation: And indeed, there are some among you who would certainly delay (intentionally)."
    }
  ],
  "400": [
    {
      "id": 1875,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Travel",
      "hw": "سفر",
      "s": "«سَفَرَ» The general word for traveling (7 Verses: 2:184-2:185-2:283-4:43-5:6-9:42-18:62)",
      "d": "«سَفَرَ» means to depart from one's place of residence (M. L). And it means to cover a distance. This word is general. Whether the travel is for any purpose.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ مَّرۡضٰۤی اَوۡ عَلٰی سَفَرٍ» (4/43)\nTranslation: If you are ill or on a journey."
    },
    {
      "id": 1876,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Travel",
      "hw": "سفر",
      "s": "«سَاحَ» To travel in different directions in a vast field, touring and sightseeing (1 Verse: 9:2)",
      "d": "«سَاحَ الْمَاءَ» means water flows aimlessly. And «سَاحَۃ» means a spacious area. «سَاحَۃُ الدَّار» means the courtyard of the house. An open space adjacent to or near the house (M). And «سَاحَ» means to move around in an open space. Touring and sightseeing, whether for mere recreation or for some other purpose.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَسِیۡحُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اَرۡبَعَۃَ  اَشۡہُرٍ» (9/2)\nTranslation: So travel freely in the land for four months (O disbelievers)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1877,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Travel",
      "hw": "سفر",
      "s": "«ظَعَنَ» To migrate or relocate (1 Verse: 16:80)",
      "d": "«ظَعَنَ» means to migrate. To depart from one place and go to another. To relocate (intransitive, M. L). «ظَعَان» means the rope for tying a camel's howdah (palanquin). «ظُعُوْن» means pack animals (camels that carry loads and move from one place to another). «ظَعِیْنَہ» means a howdah (palanquin). And a woman who often resides in journeys and a howdah.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ جَعَلَ لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ جُلُوۡدِ الۡاَنۡعَامِ بُیُوۡتًا تَسۡتَخِفُّوۡنَہَا یَوۡمَ ظَعۡنِکُمۡ وَ یَوۡمَ اِقَامَتِکُمۡ» (16/80)\nTranslation: And He has made for you from the hides of cattle homes which you find light on the day of your migration and the day of your staying."
    },
    {
      "id": 1878,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Travel",
      "hw": "سفر",
      "s": "«نَفَرَ» To set out on an expedition or to go out to face an enemy (10 Verses: 4:71-9:38-9:39-9:41-9:81-9:122-46:29-18:34-46:29-72:1)",
      "d": "«اَلنَّفِیْر» is a group of fewer than ten men. People who migrate towards battle. And «اَلنَّفِیْرُ الْعَام» means the general mobilization of people against an enemy (Majid). And «نَفَرَ» means to go out on a mission or to face an enemy in battle.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَانۡفِرُوۡا ثُبَاتٍ اَوِ انۡفِرُوۡا جَمِیۡعًا» (4/71)\nTranslation: Then set out (to battle), whether in small groups or all together."
    },
    {
      "id": 1880,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To journey",
      "hw": "سفر",
      "s": "«رَحَلَ» to migrate; to set out on a journey (3 verses: 12:70-12:75-106:2)",
      "d": "«اَلرَّحْل» means kajawa, palan (a seat for riding animals), station, resting place, luggage during travel. And «رَحَل» means to saddle a camel or animal, to ride, to migrate, to set out on a journey. For example, in the Quran: «اٖلٰفِہِمۡ  رِحۡلَۃَ  الشِّتَآءِ  وَ الصَّیۡفِ» (106/2) Translation: To accustom them (the Quraysh) to the journeys of winter and summer."
    }
  ],
  "401": [
    {
      "id": 1881,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To understand; to make understand",
      "hw": "سمجھنا",
      "s": "«شَعَرَ» to grasp the subtlety and delicacy of a matter (27 verses: 2:9-2:12-2:154-3:69-6:26-6:109-6:123-7:95-12:15-12:107-16:21-16:26-16:45-18:19-23:56-26:113-26:202-27:18-27:50-27:65-28:9-28:11-29:53-39:25-39:55-43:66-49:2)",
      "d": "«اَلشَّعْر» means hair, and «شَعَرَ» means to acquire fine knowledge like hair (i.e., to understand the intricacies and nuances of a matter). For example, in the Quran: «وَ مَا یَخۡدَعُوۡنَ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ وَ مَا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ» (2/9) Translation: And they do not deceive except themselves, and they do not perceive."
    },
    {
      "id": 1882,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To understand; to make understand",
      "hw": "سمجھنا",
      "s": "«فَھَمَ» to understand the meanings and implications of a matter (1 verse: 21:79)",
      "d": "«اَلْفَھْم» is the name of that mental faculty by which a person extracts meanings and implications excellently and thoroughly. And «فَھَمَ» means to understand something well, or to comprehend meanings immediately upon hearing. «سَرِیْعُ الْفَھْم» means one who understands quickly; «سَیِّءُ اَلْفَھْم» means dull-witted. «فَھَّم» means to make someone understand the reality of something. For example, in the Quran: «وَ کُنَّا  لِحُکۡمِہِمۡ  شٰہِدِیۡنَ فَفَہَّمۡنٰہَا سُلَیۡمٰنَ» (21/78,79) Translation: And we were witnesses to their judgment, so we made Solomon understand it thoroughly."
    },
    {
      "id": 1883,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To understand; to make understand",
      "hw": "سمجھنا",
      "s": "«فَقَہَ» to derive solutions for similar issues by reflecting on existing examples (20 verses: 4:78-6:25-6:65-6:98-7:179-8:65-9:81-9:87-9:122-9:127-11:91-17:44-17:46-18:57-18:93-20:28-48:15-59:13-63:3-63:7)",
      "d": "«اَلْفِقْہُ» is that knowledge through which one reaches from the present to the unseen (i.e., jurisprudence). It means seeking solutions for presented matters by placing other examples and rulings before oneself. «تَفَقُّہ» means to develop understanding and insight in a matter, and to reach its depths. For example, in the Quran: «اُنۡظُرۡ کَیۡفَ نُصَرِّفُ الۡاٰیٰتِ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَفۡقَہُوۡنَ» (6/65) Translation: Look how We diversify the verses so that they may understand. «فَلَوۡ لَا نَفَرَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فِرۡقَۃٍ مِّنۡہُمۡ طَآئِفَۃٌ  لِّیَتَفَقَّہُوۡا فِی الدِّیۡنِ» (9/122) Translation: So why do not a group from every division among them devote themselves to gaining understanding in the religion?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1884,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To understand; to make understand",
      "hw": "سمجھنا",
      "s": "«عَقَلَ» to comprehend one's benefit and harm, then to devise a plan to choose or avoid it (49 verses: 2:44-2:73-2:75-2:76-2:164-2:170-2:171-2:242-3:65-3:118-5:58-5:103-6:32-6:151-7:169-8:22-10:16-10:42-10:100-11:51-12:2-12:109-13:4-16:12-16:67-21:10-21:67-22:46-23:80-24:61-25:44-26:28-28:60-29:35-29:43-29:63-30:24-30:28-36:62-36:68-37:138-39:43-40:67-43:3-45:5-49:4-57:17-59:14-67:10)",
      "d": "«عَقَلَ» means to be intelligent, to be capable of realizing error. It also means to restrain and forbid. «عِقَال» refers to the fetter (rope) with which a camel's foot is tied. «اَلْمَعْقِل» means a place of refuge, a mountain or fortress where one takes shelter. Thus, the function of intellect is to distinguish between benefit and harm, to devise means to avoid harmful things, to be always prepared for attaining beneficial things and accepting knowledge, and then to reflect. For example, in the Quran: «اَتَاۡمُرُوۡنَ النَّاسَ بِالۡبِرِّ وَ تَنۡسَوۡنَ اَنۡفُسَکُمۡ وَ اَنۡتُمۡ تَتۡلُوۡنَ الۡکِتٰبَ ؕ اَفَلَا تَعۡقِلُوۡنَ» (2/44) Translation: Do you bid people to do right and forget your own selves while you recite the Scripture? Do you not then understand?"
    }
  ],
  "402": [
    {
      "id": 1885,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To hear; to make hear",
      "hw": "سننا",
      "s": "«سَمِعَ» to hear a statement or sound (95 verses: 2:7-2:20-2:75-2:93-2:104-2:171-2:181-2:285-3:181-3:186-3:193-4:46-4:140-5:7-5:83-5:108-6:36-6:46-7:100-7:179-7:195-7:198-8:20-8:21-8:23-8:31-9:6-10:31-10:67-11:20-12:31-15:18-16:65-16:78-16:108-17:36-18:26-18:101-19:38-19:42-19:62-19:98-20:46-20:108-21:45-21:60-21:100-21:102-22:46-23:24-23:78-24:12-24:16-24:51-25:12-25:44-26:72-26:212-26:223-28:36-28:55-28:71-30:23-31:7-32:9-32:12-32:26-35:14-36:25-37:8-38:7-41:4-41:20-41:22-41:26-43:80-45:8-45:23-46:26-46:30-50:37-50:42-56:25-58:1-63:4-64:16-67:7-67:10-67:23-68:51-72:1-72:9-72:13-78:35-88:11)",
      "d": "«سَمِعَ» means to hear a statement or sound with the ears. «اَلسَّمْع» also means the faculty of hearing and the ear itself. For example, in the Quran: «قَدۡ سَمِعَ  اللّٰہُ  قَوۡلَ  الَّتِیۡ تُجَادِلُکَ فِیۡ زَوۡجِہَا» (58/1) Translation: Allah has heard the statement of the woman who disputes with you concerning her husband."
    },
    {
      "id": 1886,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To hear; to make hear",
      "hw": "سننا",
      "s": "«سَمَّاع» to listen with ears pricked for espionage (3 verses: 5:41-5:42-9:47)",
      "d": "«سَامِع» means listener. «سَمَّاع» means spy, one who listens for espionage. For example, in the Quran: «سَمّٰعُوۡنَ لِلۡکَذِبِ سَمّٰعُوۡنَ لِقَوۡمٍ اٰخَرِیۡنَ  ۙ  لَمۡ  یَاۡتُوۡکَ» (5/41) Translation: They are listeners for falsehood, listeners for other people who have not come to you."
    },
    {
      "id": 1887,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To hear; to make hear",
      "hw": "سننا",
      "s": "«اَسْمَعَ» to make someone hear a statement (9 verses: 4:46-8:23-10:42-27:80-27:81-30:52-30:53-35:22-43:40-)",
      "d": "«اَسْمَعَ» means to make another person hear. For example, in the Quran: «اِنَّکَ لَا تُسۡمِعُ الۡمَوۡتٰی وَ لَا تُسۡمِعُ الصُّمَّ الدُّعَآءَ اِذَا وَلَّوۡا مُدۡبِرِیۡنَ» (27/80) Translation: Indeed, you cannot make the dead hear, nor can you make the deaf hear the call when they turn their backs retreating."
    },
    {
      "id": 1888,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To hear; to make hear",
      "hw": "سننا",
      "s": "«اِسْتَمَعَ» to apply one's ear and attempt to hear a sound or statement (16 verses: 6:25-7:204-10:42-17:47-20:13-21:2-22:73-26:15-26:25-39:18-46:29-47:16-50:41-52:38-72:1-72:9)",
      "d": "«اِسْتَمَعَ» means to apply the ear, to listen intently, to try to hear when the sound is not clear. For example, in the Quran: «قُلۡ  اُوۡحِیَ  اِلَیَّ  اَنَّہُ  اسۡتَمَعَ  نَفَرٌ مِّنَ الۡجِنِّ فَقَالُوۡۤا  اِنَّا سَمِعۡنَا قُرۡاٰنًا عَجَبًا» (72/1) Translation: Say, [O Muhammad], 'It has been revealed to me that a group of the jinn listened and said, \"Indeed, we have heard a wondrous Quran.\"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1889,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To hear; to make hear",
      "hw": "سننا",
      "s": "«اَذِنَ» to listen attentively with one's ear applied (2 verses: 84:2-84:5)",
      "d": "«اَذِنَ» means to listen attentively, to hear in order to comply. For example, in the Quran: «وَ اَذِنَتۡ لِرَبِّہَا وَ حُقَّتۡ» (84/2) Translation: And she listened to her Lord and was obligated."
    },
    {
      "id": 1890,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Hear; To Inform",
      "hw": "سننا",
      "s": "«اٰذَنَ» means to inform someone after hearing (6 verses: 2:279, 7:44, 7:167, 12:70, 14:7, 22:27)",
      "d": "«اٰذَنَ» means to inform someone and warn them, to make aware (Majid). For example, the Quran states: «وَ یَوۡمَ  یُنَادِیۡہِمۡ  اَیۡنَ شُرَکَآءِیۡ  ۙ قَالُوۡۤا اٰذَنّٰکَ  ۙ مَا مِنَّا مِنۡ شَہِیۡدٍ» (41:47). Translation: And on the Day He will call them and say, 'Where are My partners?' They will say, 'We have informed You that there is no witness among us.'"
    }
  ],
  "403": [
    {
      "id": 1891,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Reform; To Set Right",
      "hw": "سنوارنا",
      "s": "The word «اِصْلَاحُ» is used for correcting any kind of corruption and setting things right (40 verses: 2:11, 2:160, 2:182, 2:220, 2:224, 2:228, 3:89, 4:16, 4:35, 4:114, 4:128, 4:129, 4:146, 5:39, 6:48, 6:54, 7:35, 7:56, 7:85, 11:88, 17:142, 7:170, 8:1, 10:81, 11:117, 13:23, 16:119, 21:90, 24:5, 26:152, 27:48, 28:19, 33:71, 40:8, 42:40, 46:15, 47:2, 47:5, 49:9, 49:10)",
      "d": "«اِصْلَاحُ» is the opposite of «اَفْسَدَ». It means to correct corruption and disorder. Its use is general for both material and spiritual aspects. For example, the Quran states: «کَفَّرَ عَنۡہُمۡ سَیِّاٰتِہِمۡ  وَ اَصۡلَحَ بَالَہُمۡ» (47:2). Translation: (Allah) has absolved them of their evil deeds and improved their condition. At another place, the divine command is: «وَ لَا تُفۡسِدُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ بَعۡدَ اِصۡلَاحِہَا» (7:56). Translation: And do not cause corruption in the land after its reformation."
    },
    {
      "id": 1892,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Purify; To Refine",
      "hw": "سنوارنا",
      "s": "The word «زَکّٰی» is used for correcting the corruption of the self and then adding superior ethics to it (26 verses: 2:129, 2:151, 2:174, 2:232, 3:77, 3:164, 4:49, 9:103, 18:19, 18:74, 18:81, 19:13, 19:19, 20:76, 24:21, 24:28, 24:30, 35:18, 53:32, 62:2, 79:18, 80:3, 80:7, 87:14, 91:9, 92:18)",
      "d": "«زَکوٰ ، زَکٰی» and «زَکّٰی» linguistically mean for a crop, etc., to increase and grow. And «زَکِیْ مَالَہٗ» means to pay zakat on wealth. And «زَکّٰی نَفْسَہٗ» means to purify one's inner self (Majid). However, Shariah has used the term «تَزْکِیَہ» in the sense of purification and reformation. And tazkiyah al-nafs means to purify the soul from vile ethics (bad morals) and add good ethics. For example, the Quran states: «قَدۡ  اَفۡلَحَ  مَنۡ  زَکّٰىہَا وَ  قَدۡ خَابَ مَنۡ  دَسّٰىہَا» (91:9,10). Translation: He who purifies it (the soul) has succeeded, and he who corrupts it has failed."
    }
  ],
  "404": [
    {
      "id": 1893,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Ride; To Mount",
      "hw": "سوار",
      "s": "«رَکَبَ» means to ride on any mount (10 verses: 2:239, 8:42, 11:41, 11:42, 16:8, 18:71, 29:65, 36:42, 40:79, 43:12)",
      "d": "«رَکَبَ» means to ride on something. On the back of an animal, or a ship, etc. And «رِکَاب» means a mount, a riding camel. And «رَاکِب» means a rider. Generally, it is used for a camel rider (one who rides a camel). And «رَکْب» means a caravan of camel riders. For example, the Quran states: «حَتّٰۤی اِذَا رَکِبَا فِی السَّفِیۡنَۃِ خَرَقَہَا» (18:71). Translation: Until when they both embarked on a ship, he (Khidr) made a hole in it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1895,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Carry; To Mount",
      "hw": "سوار",
      "s": "«حَمَلَ» means to carry a burden and to load. And «حَمَلَ عَلٰی» means to mount (someone) (44 verses: 2:248, 2:286, 6:31, 6:146, 7:176, 7:189, 9:92, 11:40, 12:36, 12:72, 13:8, 16:7, 16:25, 17:3, 17:70, 19:22, 19:27, 19:58, 20:87, 20:100, 20:101, 20:111, 22:2, 23:22, 24:54, 29:12, 29:13, 29:60, 31:14, 33:72, 35:11, 35:18, 36:41, 40:7, 40:80, 41:47, 46:15, 54:13, 62:5, 65:4, 65:6, 69:11, 69:14, 69:17)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «حَمَلَ» is to carry a burden, and «اَحْمَلَ» means to help in carrying a burden. Then, when this burden is of a human and they need to be loaded onto an animal or mount, the word «حَمَلَ» is used in the sense of mounting. For example, the Quran states: «قُلۡتَ لَاۤ  اَجِدُ مَاۤ  اَحۡمِلُکُمۡ  عَلَیۡہِ» (9:92). Translation: You came to me that I should provide you with mounts, and I said, 'I find not with me any mount on which I can carry you.'"
    }
  ],
  "405": [
    {
      "id": 1896,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Except (other than).",
      "hw": "علاوہ",
      "s": "«اِلَّا» in nouns provides the benefit of exception along with restriction. (609 verses: 2:9-2:26-2:32-2:34-2:45-2:78-2:80-2:83-2:85-2:99-2:102-2:111-2:114-2:130-2:132-2:143-2:150-2:160-2:163-2:171-2:174-2:193-2:210-2:213-2:229-2:233-2:235-2:237-2:246-2:249-2:255-2:267-2:269-2:272-2:275-2:282-2:286-3:2-3:6-3:7-3:18-3:19-3:24-3:28-3:41-3:62-3:64-3:65-3:69-3:73-3:75-3:89-3:93-3:102-3:102-3:111-3:112-3:126-3:135-3:144-3:145-3:147-3:185-4:19-4:22-4:23-4:24-4:29-4:43-4:46-4:62-4:64-4:66-4:83-4:84-4:87-4:90-4:92-4:98-4:113-4:114-4:117-4:120-4:142-4:146-4:148-4:155-4:157-4:159-4:169-4:171-5:1-5:3-5:13-5:25-5:34-5:59-5:73-5:75-5:99-5:110-5:117-6:4-6:7-6:17-6:23-6:25-6:26-6:29-6:32-6:38-6:47-6:48-6:50-6:57-6:59-6:80-6:90-6:102-6:106-6:111-6:116-6:119-6:123-6:128-6:138-6:145-6:146-6:148-6:151-6:152-6:158-6:160-6:164-7:5-7:11-7:20-7:42-7:53-7:58-7:82-7:83-7:89-7:94-7:99-7:105-7:126-7:147-7:155-7:158-7:169-7:184-7:187-7:188-8:10-8:16-8:31-8:34-8:35-8:72-8:73-9:4-9:7-9:8-9:10-9:18-9:31-9:32-9:38-9:39-9:40-9:47-9:51-9:52-9:54-9:74-9:79-9:107-9:110-9:114-9:118-9:120-9:121-9:129-10:3-10:5-10:15-10:19-10:32-10:35-10:36-10:45-10:49-10:52-10:61-10:66-10:72-10:83-10:90-10:98-10:100-10:102-10:107-11:2-11:6-11:7-11:11-11:14-11:16-11:26-11:27-11:29-11:36-11:40-11:43-11:47-11:50-11:51-11:54-11:56-11:81-11:88-11:104-11:105-11:107-11:108-11:109-11:116-11:119-12:25-12:31-12:33-12:37-12:40-12:47-12:48-12:53-12:64-12:66-12:67-12:68-12:76-12:79-12:81-12:87-12:104-12:106-12:109-13:14-13:26-13:30-13:38-14:4-14:9-14:10-14:11-14:22-15:4-15:8-15:11-15:18-15:21-15:31-15:40-15:42-15:56-15:59-15:60-15:85-16:2-16:7-16:33-16:35-16:43-16:64-16:77-16:79-16:106-16:127-17:23-17:33-17:34-17:41-17:44-17:47-17:52-17:58-17:59-17:60-17:61-17:62-17:64-17:67-17:76-17:82-17:85-17:87-17:89-17:93-17:94-17:99-17:102-17:105-18:5-18:16-18:22-18:24-18:39-18:49-18:50-18:55-18:56-18:63-19:60-19:62-19:64-19:71-19:87-19:93-20:3-20:8-20:14-20:98-20:103-20:104-20:108-20:109-20:116-21:2-21:3-21:7-21:22-21:25-21:28-21:36-21:58-21:87-21:107-22:30-20:40-22:52-22:65-23:6-23:24-23:25-23:27-23:33-23:37-23:38-23:62-23:83-23:114-23:116-24:3-24:5-24:6-24:31-24:54-25:4-25:8-25:20-25:33-25:41-25:44-25:50-25:56-25:57-25:68-25:70-26:5-26:77-26:89-26:99-26:109-26:113-26:115-26:127-26:137-26:145-26:154-26:164-26:171-26:180-26:186-26:208-26:227-27:11-27:26-27:56-27:57-27:65-27:68-27:75-27:81-27:87-27:90-28:19-28:36-28:58-28:59-28:70-28:80-28:84-28:86-28:88-29:14-29:18-29:24-29:29-29:32-29:33-29:43-29:46-29:47-29:49-29:64-30:8-30:53-30:58-31:28-31:32-33:6-33:12-33:13-33:14-33:16-33:18-33:20-33:22-33:39-33:52-33:53-33:60-34:3-34:14-34:17-34:20-34:21-34:23-34:28-34:33-34:34-34:37-34:43-34:46-34:47-35:3-35:11-35:23-35:24-35:39-35:40-35:42-35:43-36:15-36:17-36:29-36:30-36:44-36:46-36:47-36:49-36:53-36:54-36:69-37:10-37:15-37:35-37:39-37:40-37:59-37:74-37:128-37:135-37:160-37:163-37:164-38:7-38:14-38:15-38:24-38:65-38:70-38:74-38:83-38:87-39:3-39:6-39:68-40:3-40:4-40:13-40:25-40:29-40:37-40:40-40:50-40:56-40:62-40:65-40:78-41:14-41:35-41:43-41:47-42:14-42:23-42:48-42:51-43:7-43:20-43:23-43:27-43:48-43:58-43:59-43:66-43:67-43:86-44:8-44:35-44:39-44:42-44:56-45:17-45:24-45:25-45:32-46:3-46:9-46:17-46:21-46:25-46:35-47:18-47:19-48:15-50:18-51:42-51:52-51:56-53:4-53:23-53:26-53:28-53:29-53:32-53:39-54:34-54:50-55:33-55:60-56:26-56:79-57:20-57:22-57:27-58:2-58:7-58:10-59:14-59:22-59:23-60:4-64:11-64:13-65:1-65:7-67:9-67:19-67:20-68:52-69:36-69:37-70:22-70:30-71:6-71:21-71:24-71:27-71:28-72:23-72:27-73:2-73:9-74:24-74:25-74:31-74:39-74:56-76:30-78:25-78:30-78:38-79:46-81:27-81:29-83:12-84:25-85:8-87:7-88:6-88:23-92:15-92:20-95:6-98:4-98:5-103:3)",
      "d": "«اِلَّا» means but, except. It is a particle of exception. In this form, it can function as an adjective for an indefinite noun.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَاۤ اِلٰہَ اِلَّا ہُوَ الرَّحۡمٰنُ  الرَّحِیۡمُ» (2/163)\nTranslation: There is no deity except Him, the Most Merciful, the Especially Merciful.\nBesides, this word also gives the meaning of restriction (حَصَر).\nFor example, the Almighty says:\n«وَ مَا یَخۡدَعُوۡنَ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ» (2/9)\nTranslation: And they do not deceive except themselves.\nNote 1: (Exception means that the general word at the beginning of the statement, which includes certain things, some of them are excluded from its ruling by «اِلّا» or similar words like «سَوَی ، غَیْرَ، لَیْسَ ، عَدَا ، خَلَا ، حَاشَا».)\nNote 2: (Restriction in Arabic terminology means proving a ruling for one thing and negating it for others; this is also called قصر.)\nNote 3: An indefinite noun is one that is used for all things of the same type."
    },
    {
      "id": 1897,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Other Than; Except",
      "hw": "علاوہ",
      "s": "«غَیْر» is found in nouns with the meaning of negation along with exception (101 verses: 1:7, 2:59, 2:173, 2:230, 2:240, 3:83, 3:85, 3:154, 4:12, 4:24, 4:25, 4:46, 4:56, 4:81, 4:82, 4:95, 4:115, 4:140, 5:1, 5:3, 5:5, 5:77, 5:106, 6:14, 6:40, 6:46, 6:68, 6:93, 6:99, 6:114, 6:141, 6:145, 6:164, 7:53, 7:59, 7:65, 7:73, 7:85, 7:140, 7:162, 8:7, 9:2, 9:3, 9:39, 10:15, 11:46, 11:50, 11:57, 11:61, 11:63, 11:65, 11:76, 11:84, 11:101, 11:108, 11:109, 13:4, 14:37, 14:48, 16:21, 16:52, 16:115, 17:73, 20:22, 22:5, 22:31, 23:6, 23:23, 23:32, 24:27, 24:29, 24:31, 24:60, 26:29, 27:12, 27:22, 28:32, 28:38, 28:71, 28:72, 30:55, 33:53, 35:3, 35:37, 39:28, 39:64, 41:8, 43:18, 47:15, 47:38, 50:31, 51:36, 52:35, 52:43, 56:86, 68:3, 70:28, 70:30, 74:10, 84:25, 95:6)",
      "d": "«غَیْر» sometimes comes only for negation. For example, the Quran states: «وَ ہُوَ فِی الۡخِصَامِ  غَیۡرُ  مُبِیۡنٍ» (43:18). Translation: And it (the idol) is not clear in its disputes. And sometimes it comes for exception. In this case, it can function as a noun of description (ism sifah) (Majid). For example, the divine statement is: «ہَلۡ مِنۡ خَالِقٍ غَیۡرُ اللّٰہِ» (35:3). Translation: Is there any creator besides Allah?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1898,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Besides; Other Than (with inferiority)",
      "hw": "علاوہ",
      "s": "«دُوْن» in nouns, along with exception, also conveys the meaning of inferiority (141 verses: 2:23, 2:94, 2:107, 2:165, 3:28, 3:64, 3:79, 3:118, 4:48, 4:116, 4:117, 4:119, 4:123, 4:139, 4:144, 4:173, 5:76, 5:116, 6:51, 6:56, 6:70, 6:71, 6:108, 7:3, 7:30, 7:37, 7:81, 7:168, 7:194, 7:197, 7:205, 8:60, 9:16, 9:31, 9:116, 10:18, 10:37, 10:38, 10:66, 10:104, 10:106, 11:13, 11:20, 11:55, 11:101, 11:113, 12:40, 13:11, 13:14, 13:16, 16:20, 16:35, 16:73, 16:86, 17:2, 17:56, 17:97, 18:14, 18:15, 18:26, 18:27, 18:43, 18:50, 18:58, 18:93, 18:102, 19:17, 19:48, 19:49, 19:81, 21:24, 21:29, 21:43, 21:66, 21:67, 21:82, 21:98, 22:12, 22:62, 22:71, 22:73, 23:63, 25:3, 25:17, 25:18, 25:55, 26:93, 27:24, 27:43, 27:55, 28:23, 28:81, 29:17, 29:22, 29:25, 29:41, 29:42, 31:11, 31:30, 32:4, 32:21, 33:17, 33:50, 34:22, 34:41, 35:13, 35:40, 36:23, 36:74, 37:23, 37:86, 39:3, 39:15, 39:36, 39:38, 39:43, 39:45, 40:20, 40:66, 40:74, 42:6, 42:9, 42:31, 42:46, 43:45, 43:86, 45:10, 46:4, 46:5, 46:28, 46:32, 48:27, 52:47, 53:58, 55:62, 60:4, 62:6, 67:20, 71:25, 72:11, 72:22)",
      "d": "«دَان» means to be stingy or weak. And «دُوْن» means low, inferior, or lesser in rank and status. And «شَیْءٌ دُوْنٌ» means something contemptible, a worthless thing (Majid). And «دُوْن» means something that is deficient or lacking compared to something else (Mufradat). And when «دُوْن» gives the meaning of 'besides', it also carries the nuance of inferiority and weakness. For example, the Quran states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡا بِطَانَۃً مِّنۡ دُوۡنِکُمۡ» (3:118). Translation: O you who have believed, do not take as intimates those outside your own ranks. Here, the expression of inferiority of other religious groups compared to Muslims is intended. At another place, the divine statement is: «اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یَغۡفِرُ اَنۡ یُّشۡرَکَ بِہٖ وَ یَغۡفِرُ  مَا دُوۡنَ ذٰلِکَ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ» (4:48). Translation: Indeed, Allah does not forgive association with Him, but He forgives what is less than that for whom He wills. Here, the sins referred to are those of a lesser degree than shirk. Similarly, the divine statement is: «مَا لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ مِنۡ وَّلِیٍّ وَّ لَا نَصِیۡرٍ» (2:107). Translation: You have no protector or helper besides Allah. In this verse too, «دُوْن» conveys the meaning of 'besides' along with the nuance of inferiority."
    },
    {
      "id": 1899,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Beyond; Besides (all-encompassing)",
      "hw": "علاوہ",
      "s": "«وَرَاء» comes for exception in an all-directional (all sides) sense (24 verses: 2:91, 2:101, 3:187, 4:24, 4:102, 6:94, 11:71, 11:92, 14:16, 14:17, 18:79, 19:5, 23:7, 23:100, 33:53, 42:51, 45:10, 49:4, 57:13, 59:14, 70:31, 76:27, 84:10, 85:20)",
      "d": "«وَرَاء» is linguistically from the category of words with opposite meanings (addad). Its meanings are 'ahead' and 'behind'. 'On that side' and 'on this side'. 'Here' and 'there'. In this very sense, it also gives the meaning of 'besides'. That is, besides all those sides or things. For example, the Quran states: «فَمَنِ ابۡتَغٰی وَرَآءَ ذٰلِکَ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمُ الۡعٰدُوۡنَ» (23:7). Translation: Then whoever seeks beyond that, they are the transgressors. Which means: Whoever seeks something besides Allah's commands, here or there, ahead or behind, is a wrongdoer. Note: (Linguistic opposites are words that have two separate meanings, and those meanings are opposite and contradictory to each other)."
    }
  ],
  "406": [
    {
      "id": 1901,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Sleep",
      "hw": "سونا",
      "s": "«نَامَ» means (to sleep) sleep; it is the general word for sleeping (9 verses: 2:255, 7:97, 8:43, 25:47, 30:23, 37:102, 39:42, 68:19, 78:9)",
      "d": "«نَامَ» meaning sleep is a well-known word and its use is common (Fasl 292). Sleep or slumber is also a type of death in which the soul (nafs) separates from the body and travels around, and the activity of the five senses diminishes greatly because they become sluggish. Meanwhile, a person's fatigue is removed. And due to mental and physical tranquility, they attain comfort and rest. «نَوْم» means sleep and «مَنَام» means the state of sleep. The state of sleeping. For example, the Quran states: «اَفَاَمِنَ اَہۡلُ الۡقُرٰۤی اَنۡ  یَّاۡتِیَہُمۡ  بَاۡسُنَا بَیَاتًا  وَّ ہُمۡ  نَآئِمُوۡنَ» (7:97). Translation: Do the people of the towns feel secure that Our punishment will come to them at night while they are asleep?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1902,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sleep.",
      "hw": "سونا",
      "s": "«ھَجَعَ» to sleep a deep and heedless sleep. (1 verse: 51:17)",
      "d": "«ھَجَعَ» means to sleep heedlessly (fal 161). To sleep while riding a horse. To become unaware of the world and its contents in sleep. And the author of «الھَجَعَۃ» defines «اَلْھَجَعَۃ» as the light sleep of the first part of the night, but this does not seem correct because he himself says that «اَلْھُجَعُ» means heedless, foolish, and one who sleeps a lot (منجد). Moreover, the Quran does not support this. Therefore, the meanings given by the author of «صَاحِبِ فِقْہُ الْلُغَۃ» seem correct. However, the word «ھَجُوْع» is specific to night sleep, just as daytime sleep is called قیلولہ (m q).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کَانُوۡا  قَلِیۡلًا مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ مَا یَہۡجَعُوۡنَ وَ  بِالۡاَسۡحَارِ ہُمۡ  یَسۡتَغۡفِرُوۡنَ» (51/17,18)\nTranslation: They used to sleep but a little of the night, and in the hours of early dawn they would seek forgiveness."
    },
    {
      "id": 1903,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sleep.",
      "hw": "سونا",
      "s": "«رَقَدَ» to sleep a long and light sleep. (1 verse: 18:18)",
      "d": "«رَقَدَ» means to sleep a long sleep (fal 161). «اَلرُِّقَاد» means pleasant and light sleep (مف). «اَلرُّقَدَۃُ» and «اَلْیَرْقُوْدُ» mean one who sleeps a lot, and «اَلرُّقُوْد» means one who always sleeps (منجد). From all these, it is known that «رَقَدَ» is such a sleep that is long, pleasant, and light. Meaning, a person wakes up at the slightest sound.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ تَحۡسَبُہُمۡ اَیۡقَاظًا وَّ ہُمۡ رُقُوۡدٌ» (18/18)\nTranslation: And you would think them awake while they are asleep."
    },
    {
      "id": 1904,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sleep.",
      "hw": "سونا",
      "s": "«قَالَ» to sleep in the afternoon. (1 verse: 7:4)",
      "d": "«یَقِیْلُ قَیْلًا وَ قَیْلُوْلَۃً» means to sleep in the afternoon. To rest during the day (fal 292).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ کَمۡ مِّنۡ قَرۡیَۃٍ اَہۡلَکۡنٰہَا فَجَآءَہَا بَاۡسُنَا  بَیَاتًا  اَوۡ  ہُمۡ  قَآئِلُوۡنَ» (7/4)\nTranslation: And how many a city We destroyed while its people were asleep at night or while they were taking a midday rest."
    },
    {
      "id": 1905,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sleep.",
      "hw": "سونا",
      "s": "«ضَجَعَ» to lie on one's side to rest, whether sleep comes or not. (3 verses: 3:154-4:34-32:16)",
      "d": "«ضَجَعَ» means to lie on one's side or on one's flank, to rest, whether drowsiness or sleep comes or not (منجد). The state of half-sleep. And «مَضَاجِع» means beds, bedding, and «اَضْجَعَہ» means to make him lie down (م ۔ ق).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«تَتَجَافٰی جُنُوۡبُہُمۡ عَنِ الۡمَضَاجِعِ یَدۡعُوۡنَ رَبَّہُمۡ خَوۡفًا وَّ طَمَعًا» (32/16)\nTranslation: Their sides arise from the beds, calling upon their Lord in fear and hope."
    },
    {
      "id": 1906,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sleep",
      "hw": "سونا",
      "s": "«tahajjad» waking up at night for tahajjud prayer, etc., praying tahajjud at night (1 verse: 17:79)",
      "d": "«hujūd» means sleeping at night and also waking up, sometimes sleeping sometimes waking up (this is from opposite words in language). And spending the night sleeping and waking. And «hajada» means waking up at night to pray (Mujid).\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ مِنَ الَّیۡلِ فَتَہَجَّدۡ بِہٖ نَافِلَۃً  لَّکَ» ( 17/79 )\nTranslation: And during the night, pray with it as an additional act for yourself."
    }
  ],
  "407": [
    {
      "id": 1907,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Blackness / Black Color",
      "hw": "سیاہی",
      "s": "«aswad» meaning black color (3 verses: 2:187-3:106-16:58)",
      "d": "«aswad» black color, its opposite is «abyad» meaning white color. «aswad» is used in the well-known meanings and is common, and its plural is «sūd» and its feminine is «sawdā». \nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ کُلُوۡا وَ اشۡرَبُوۡا حَتّٰی یَتَبَیَّنَ لَکُمُ الۡخَیۡطُ الۡاَبۡیَضُ مِنَ الۡخَیۡطِ الۡاَسۡوَدِ  مِنَ الۡفَجۡرِ» ( 2/187 )\nTranslation: And eat and drink until the white thread of dawn becomes distinct to you from the black thread."
    },
    {
      "id": 1908,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Black. Blackness.",
      "hw": "سیاہی",
      "s": "«غَرَابِیْب» meaning very black. (1 verse: 35:27)",
      "d": "«غُرَاب» means crow; its plural is «غِرْبَان». And «غِرْبِیْب» means very black like a crow; its plural is «غَرَابِیْب» (مف). And «غُرْبِیْب» means a person who dyes his hair black with henna; its plural is «غَرَابِیْب» (م ۔ ق).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مِنَ الۡجِبَالِ جُدَدٌۢ  بِیۡضٌ وَّ حُمۡرٌ  مُّخۡتَلِفٌ اَلۡوَانُہَا وَ غَرَابِیْبُ سُوۡدٌ» (35/27)\nTranslation: And among the mountains are streaks white and red, of varying shades, and [some] extremely black."
    },
    {
      "id": 1909,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Blackness / Black Color",
      "hw": "سیاہی",
      "s": "«aḥwā» meaning greenish-black color (1 verse: 87:5)",
      "d": "«aḥwā» greenish-black color or blackish-red color (Mujid). In the Quran, the words «ghuthā'an aḥwā» are used. «ghuthā» refers to the twigs, leaves, and scum that get stuck in foam, and the river throws that foam and scum to the shore. And when this scum is crushed underfoot repeatedly, its color becomes blackish, and that color is called «aḥwā». \nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَخۡرَجَ  الۡمَرۡعٰی فَجَعَلَہٗ  غُثَآءً  اَحۡوٰی» ( 87/4,5 )\nTranslation: And who brings forth the pasture, then makes it a dark scum."
    },
    {
      "id": 1910,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Blackness. Black",
      "hw": "سیاہی",
      "s": "«اَدْھَم» meaning a deep greenish-black color (1 verse: 55:64)",
      "d": "«دَھَمَ» means something being covered in darkness. And «اَلدُّھْمَۃ» means blackness. For example, in the Quran: «مُدۡہَآ مَّتٰنِ» (55/64) Translation: Both gardens will be very dark green, as if they were black."
    },
    {
      "id": 1911,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Blackness / Black Color",
      "hw": "سیاہی",
      "s": "«qatara» meaning smoke-like color (2 verses: 10:26-80:41)",
      "d": "«qatara al-nar» means the fire produces smoke (Mujid). And «qatara» means dust or dirt that is like smoke, blackish.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ وُجُوۡہٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ عَلَیۡہَا غَبَرَۃٌ تَرۡہَقُہَا قَتَرَۃٌ» ( 80/40,41 )\nTranslation: And on that day, there will be faces covered with dust, and over them will be a blackish smoke."
    },
    {
      "id": 1912,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Ink",
      "hw": "سیاہی",
      "s": "«مِدَاد» means ink, the light with which writing is done (1 verse: 18:109)",
      "d": "«مَدَدْتُ الدَّوَاۃ» means to put ink or light into a pen. And «مِدَادَ» is ink, the light with which writing is done. (Maf)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«قُلۡ لَّوۡ کَانَ الۡبَحۡرُ مِدَادًا لِّکَلِمٰتِ رَبِّیۡ لَنَفِدَ الۡبَحۡرُ  قَبۡلَ اَنۡ تَنۡفَدَ کَلِمٰتُ رَبِّیۡ» (18/109)\nTranslation: (O Prophet, tell the people) Say: If the sea were ink for the words of my Lord, the sea would be exhausted before the words of my Lord are exhausted."
    }
  ],
  "408": [
    {
      "id": 1913,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Straight / Upright",
      "hw": "سیدھا",
      "s": "«مُسْتَقِیْم» balanced, moderate, and straight (41 verses: 1:5-2:142-2:213-3:51-3:101-4:68-4:175-5:16-6:39-6:87-6:126-6:153-6:161-7:16-9:7-10:25-10:89-11:56-15:41-16:76-16:121-17:35-19:36-22:54-22:67-23:73-24:46-26:182-36:4-36:61-37:118-41:6-42:52-43:43-43:61-43:64-46:30-48:2-48:20-67:22-81:28)",
      "d": "«مُسْتَقِیْم» is that which is straight. And balanced and moderate as well. And «قَامَ عَلَی الْاَمْر» means to remain firm and established upon something. And «اَقَامَ الشَّیْ» means to set something up and make it straight.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ زِنُوۡا بِالۡقِسۡطَاسِ الۡمُسۡتَقِیۡمِ» (17/35)\nTranslation: And weigh with a straight balance.\nBecause if the beam of the balance, which is already straight, does not remain parallel to the horizontal line, then the weighing will also not be balanced, even though the beam is and remains straight regardless of whether one pan is tilted down. So here, 'straight' means straight in the vertical direction, i.e., it should also remain parallel. And in terms of geometry, the shortest distance between two points or two places is called a straight line. So the 'Sirat-e-Mustaqeem' (Straight Path) is the path that is straight and has no kind of deviation, flexibility, or incline in it, i.e., it is free from excess and deficiency.\nFor example: In the Quran, we have been taught this supplication:\n«اِہۡدِ نَا الصِّرَاطَ الۡمُسۡتَقِیۡمَ» (1/5)\nTranslation: O Allah, guide us to the Straight Path."
    },
    {
      "id": 1915,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Straight / Upright",
      "hw": "سیدھا",
      "s": "«قَصْد» the correct determination of values and the straight path free from excess and deficiency (3 verses: 9:42-16:9-31:19)",
      "d": "«قَصْد» is the permissible use of something. For example, if a person can take a bath from one bucket of water, and he uses exactly that much, it is 'qasad'. If he uses more, it is 'israf' (extravagance), and if he uses less than the bucket, it is 'bukhl' (stinginess). And to take care of this matter in every transaction and make it a habit is called 'economy' (iqtisad). Now, looking at it spiritually, neither softness nor harshness alone can work in every situation. So, how much harshness or to what extent softness should be applied so that the intended goal is achieved—this is the job of Sharia to tell us.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ  قَصۡدُ السَّبِیۡلِ وَ مِنۡہَا جَآئِرٌ» (16/9)\nTranslation: And to show the Straight Path is upon Allah (besides that), all other paths are crooked.\nNote: The meaning of «قَصْد» is not correctly conveyed by merely 'moderating' or 'making moderate'. Therefore, its meaning is taken as 'straight'."
    },
    {
      "id": 1916,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Straight / Upright",
      "hw": "سیدھا",
      "s": "«سَدِیْدًا» such a thing in which there is no obstruction. Firm, clear, and straight (2 verses: 4:9-33:70)",
      "d": "«سَدُّ» means a barrier, screen, or wall built between two things. And «سُدٌّ» means to plug a crack with stones. And «سِدَاد» is the term for that material with which a rift or crack is filled. And «قَوْلاً سَدِیْدًا» is that speech in which there is no obstruction, defect, corruption, or any complexity and deceitful trickery. It is correct, accurate, true, and straight speech. And its opposite is «قَوْلَ الزُّوْر» (false speech), which has a much wider meaning than just lying.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَلۡیَتَّقُوا اللّٰہَ وَ لۡیَقُوۡلُوۡا قَوۡلًا سَدِیۡدًا» (4/9)\nTranslation: So let them fear Allah and speak straight speech."
    }
  ],
  "409": [
    {
      "id": 1917,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Ladder",
      "hw": "سیڑھی",
      "s": "«سُلَّم» means ladder, staircase (2 verses: 6:35-52:38)",
      "d": "The word «سُلَّم» is common with 'ma'araj' or 'mi'raj'. Although «سُلَّم» is used for a ladder made of bricks and stones on a roof and for wooden staircases. However, «سُلَّم» can be said for that thing which serves as a means to reach a high place, and its plurals are «سَلاَلِمُ» and «سَلَالِیْم». And «اَدْرَاجُ السُّلَم» means the rungs or steps of a ladder (manjada).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَاِنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتَ اَنۡ تَبۡتَغِیَ نَفَقًا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اَوۡ  سُلَّمًا فِی السَّمَآءِ» (6/35)\nTranslation: So if you have the power, then seek a tunnel in the earth or a ladder in the sky."
    },
    {
      "id": 1918,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Ladder",
      "hw": "سیڑھی",
      "s": "«مَعَارِج» means places of ascent (2 verses: 43:33-70:3)",
      "d": "The plural of «مِعْرَاج» is «عَرَجَ», meaning to walk with a limp. And «اَعْرَج» means lame. «عَرَجَ فِی السُّلم» means to climb a ladder. And «مِعْرَاج» means a place of ascent (manjada). So, the word «مِعْرَاج» is more specific than «سُلَّم». It involves the concept of reaching a high place via a ladder, whereas «سُلَّم» merely means a ladder.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَّ مَعَارِجَ عَلَیۡہَا یَظۡہَرُوۡنَ» (43/33)\nTranslation: And (there are) ladders upon which they ascend."
    }
  ],
  "410": [
    {
      "id": 1920,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Learn / To Teach",
      "hw": "سیکھنا",
      "s": "«تَلَقّٰی» to learn something through reception (6 verses: 2:37-7:115-17:39-20:65-27:6-60:1)",
      "d": "«لَقِیَ» means to meet, to encounter, to find, to see. And «تَلَقّٰی» means to receive someone. And «تَلَقَّی الشَّیْءُ مِنْہُ» comes in the meaning of learning something from someone (manjada). And «تَلَقّٰی» means 'ilqa' (casting into the heart) and learning something from that.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَتَلَقّٰۤی اٰدَمُ مِنۡ رَّبِّہٖ کَلِمٰتٍ فَتَابَ عَلَیۡہِ» (2/37)\nTranslation: So Adam learned some words from his Lord, then Allah accepted his repentance."
    }
  ],
  "411": [
    {
      "id": 1922,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Branch",
      "hw": "شاخ",
      "s": "«فَرَعَ» whatever comes out of something besides its origin is its «فَرَع» (1 verse: 14:24)",
      "d": "«فَرَعَ» means branch; its opposite is «اصل» meaning root. The plural of «فَرَعَ» is «فُرُوْع», meaning (tree) branches. And Imam Raghib says that the upper part of everything that emerges from the root is called «فَرَعُ الشَّجَر» (the branch of the tree) (Maf).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«مَثَلًا کَلِمَۃً طَیِّبَۃً  کَشَجَرَۃٍ  طَیِّبَۃٍ اَصۡلُہَا ثَابِتٌ وَّ فَرۡعُہَا فِی  السَّمَآءِ» (14/24)\nTranslation: The example of a good word is like a good tree, whose root is firm and whose branches are in the sky.\nAnd this word is used in both material and spiritual forms. 'Furu'i' (branched) issues are those issues that are based on another thing (the origin) and have been analogized from it. But there is no example of this in the Quran."
    },
    {
      "id": 1924,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Branch",
      "hw": "شاخ",
      "s": "«اَفْنَان» means branches and twigs (1 verse: 55:48)",
      "d": "«اَفْنَان» is the plural of «فَنَن». And «فَنَن» means a very thick and long branch of a tree. And «شَجَرَۃٌ فَنَانٌ» means a tree with very thick and long branches (Muq).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«ذَوَاتَاۤ   اَفۡنَانٍ» (55/48)\nTranslation: Both (trees) are having large branches."
    }
  ],
  "412": [
    {
      "id": 1925,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Evening Times",
      "hw": "شام",
      "s": "«رَوَاح» means the time from after the sun's zenith (noon) until sunset (1 verse: 34:12)",
      "d": "«رَوَاح» begins after the sun's zenith, i.e., after 'zawal' (noon). «رَوَاح» means the latter part of the day, and its opposite is «غُدُوّ» or «غُدْوَۃ», meaning the time of morning (Fal 292). And «اَلْغُدُوُّ وَ الرَّوَاح» are used for the coming and going of the earlier and later parts of the day.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لِسُلَیۡمٰنَ الرِّیۡحَ غُدُوُّہَا شَہۡرٌ وَّ رَوَاحُہَا شَہۡرٌ» (34/12)\nTranslation: And for Solomon (We subjected) the wind: its morning course was a month's journey and its evening course was a month's journey."
    },
    {
      "id": 1926,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Times of the Evening",
      "hw": "شام",
      "s": "«اَصِیْلًا» refers to the time after the afternoon (7 verses: 7:205, 13:15, 24:36, 25:5, 33:42, 48:9, 76:25)",
      "d": "The plural of «اَصِیْلًا» is «اٰصَال». «اَصِیْلًا» means the time after the afternoon (i.e., evening). Its opposite is «بُکْرَۃ», meaning the time of morning (p. 292).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اذۡکُرِ اسۡمَ رَبِّکَ بُکۡرَۃً وَّ اَصِیۡلًا» (76/25)\nTranslation: And remember your Lord in the morning and in the evening."
    },
    {
      "id": 1927,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Times of the Evening",
      "hw": "شام",
      "s": "«عَشِیًّا» refers to the time from after the Maghrib prayer until complete darkness, the time of 'Isha' (14 verses: 3:41, 6:52, 12:16, 18:28, 19:11, 19:62, 24:58, 30:18, 38:18, 38:31, 40:46, 40:55, 43:36, 79:46)",
      "d": "The time of «عَشِی» begins before sunset and its opposite is «اِشْرَاق». Its other opposites are «غُدُوّ» and «بُکْرَۃ».\nNow consider the examples:\nExample 1 - Divine command:\n«اَلنَّارُ یُعۡرَضُوۡنَ عَلَیۡہَا غُدُوًّا وَّ عَشِیًّا» (40/46)\nTranslation: They will be exposed to the Fire morning and evening.\nExample 2 - Divine command:\n«وَ لَا تَطۡرُدِ الَّذِیۡنَ یَدۡعُوۡنَ رَبَّہُمۡ بِالۡغَدٰوۃِ وَ الۡعَشِیِّ یُرِیۡدُوۡنَ وَجۡہَہٗ» (6/52)\nTranslation: And do not drive away those who call upon their Lord morning and evening, seeking His countenance.\nExample 3 - Divine command:\n«وَ اذۡکُرۡ رَّبَّکَ کَثِیۡرًا وَّ سَبِّحۡ بِالۡعَشِیِّ وَ الۡاِبۡکَارِ» (3/41)\nTranslation: And remember your Lord much and glorify Him in the evening and the morning.\nThe time for the 'Isha' prayer, which is specified and prescribed, is from when darkness has fully enveloped until the middle of the night.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«مِنۡ قَبۡلِ صَلٰوۃِ الۡفَجۡرِ وَ حِیۡنَ تَضَعُوۡنَ ثِیَابَکُمۡ مِّنَ الظَّہِیۡرَۃِ وَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ صَلٰوۃِ الۡعِشَآءِ ثَلٰثُ عَوۡرٰتٍ لَّکُمۡ» (24/58)\nTranslation: (There is) no blame upon you for entering your houses before the dawn prayer and when you put aside your garments at noon, and after the 'Isha' prayer. These are three times of privacy for you.\nFor 'evening', the word «اَمْسَا» (masa) is used."
    },
    {
      "id": 1928,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Times of the Evening",
      "hw": "شام",
      "s": "«اَمْسَاَ» means to become evening (1 verse: 30:17)",
      "d": "«مَسَا» means the time of evening. And «اَمْسَاَ» means to do something in the evening, to enter the evening, or to perform an action during the evening time. Its opposite is «اَصْبَحَ», meaning morning, to do something in the morning, to enter the morning, or to perform an action during the morning time.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَسُبۡحٰنَ اللّٰہِ حِیۡنَ تُمۡسُوۡنَ وَ حِیۡنَ تُصۡبِحُوۡنَ» (30/17)\nTranslation: So glorify Allah when you enter the evening and when you enter the morning."
    }
  ],
  "413": [
    {
      "id": 1929,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Perhaps",
      "hw": "شاید",
      "s": "«عَسٰی» is used for strong hope (28 verses: 2:216, 2:246, 4:19, 4:84, 4:99, 5:52, 7:129, 7:185, 9:18, 9:102, 12:21, 12:83, 17:8, 17:51, 17:79, 18:24, 18:40, 19:48, 27:72, 28:9, 28:22, 28:67, 47:22, 49:11, 60:7, 66:5, 66:8, 68:32)",
      "d": "«عَسٰی» is from the verbs of nearness (af'aal muqarabah) and is a static (jamid) verb. It is used only for the past tense and does not come for the present/future (mudaari'). It is used for strong hope in a desirable matter and for fear in an undesirable matter (Manjad).\nFor strong hope in a desirable matter:\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«عَسٰی رَبِّیۡۤ اَنۡ یَّہۡدِیَنِیۡ سَوَآءَ السَّبِیۡلِ» (28/22)\nTranslation: I hope that my Lord will guide me to the right path.\nAnd for fear in an undesirable matter:\nFor example, Divine command states:\n«فَہَلۡ عَسَیۡتُمۡ اِنۡ تَوَلَّیۡتُمۡ اَنۡ تُفۡسِدُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ تُقَطِّعُوۡۤا اَرۡحَامَکُمۡ» (47/22)\nTranslation: (O hypocrites!) Is it any wonder to you if you were to turn back on your heels and cause corruption in the land and sever your ties of kinship?\nNote: Verbs of nearness (af'aal muqarabah) are those verbs that bring the news close to the level of a noun."
    },
    {
      "id": 1930,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Perhaps",
      "hw": "شاید",
      "s": "«لَعَلَّ» is used for a strong possibility (125 verses: 2:21, 2:52, 2:53, 2:56, 2:63, 2:73, 2:150, 2:179, 2:183, 2:185, 2:186, 2:187, 2:189, 2:219, 2:221, 2:242, 2:266, 3:72, 3:103, 3:123, 3:130, 3:132, 3:200, 5:6, 5:35, 5:89, 5:90, 5:100, 6:42, 6:51, 6:65, 6:69, 6:151, 6:152, 6:153, 6:154, 6:155, 7:26, 7:57, 7:63, 7:69, 7:94, 7:130, 7:158, 7:164, 7:168, 7:171, 7:174, 7:176, 7:204, 8:26, 8:45, 8:57, 9:12, 9:122, 11:12, 12:2, 12:46, 12:62, 13:2, 14:25, 14:37, 16:14, 16:15, 16:44, 16:78, 16:81, 16:90, 18:6, 20:44, 20:113, 20:130, 21:13, 21:31, 21:58, 21:61, 21:111, 22:36, 22:77, 23:49, 23:100, 24:1, 24:27, 24:31, 24:56, 24:61, 26:3, 26:40, 26:129, 27:7, 27:46, 28:29, 28:38, 28:43, 28:46, 28:51, 28:73, 30:41, 30:46, 32:3, 32:21, 33:63, 35:12, 36:45, 36:74, 39:27, 39:28, 40:36, 40:67, 41:26, 42:17, 43:3, 43:10, 43:28, 43:48, 44:58, 45:12, 46:27, 49:10, 51:49, 57:17, 59:21, 62:10, 65:1, 80:3)",
      "d": "«لَعَلَّ» is a particle resembling a verb (harf mushbi bil-fi'l). It is used only for a strong possibility.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَا یُدۡرِیۡکَ لَعَلَّ السَّاعَۃَ تَکُوۡنُ قَرِیۡبًا» (33/63)\nTranslation: And what will make you know? Perhaps the Hour is near.\nAnd when it is attributed to Allah (i.e., «لَعَلَّ اللّٰہَ»), its meaning becomes that of obligation (wajib).\nFor example, Divine command states:\n«لَا تَدۡرِیۡ لَعَلَّ اللّٰہَ یُحۡدِثُ بَعۡدَ ذٰلِکَ اَمۡرًا» (65/1)\nTranslation: You do not know; perhaps Allah will bring about after that a (new) matter.\nNote: (Particles resembling verbs: These are particles that resemble a verb. When they enter a nominal sentence, they make the subject (mubtada) accusative and the predicate (khabar) nominative. There are six of them): «إن . أن. كان . لكن ، ليت . لعل»."
    }
  ],
  "414": [
    {
      "id": 1931,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Wine",
      "hw": "شراب",
      "s": "«خَمْر» is a general term for any drink that intoxicates and deprives one of reason and senses (6 verses: 2:219, 5:90, 5:91, 12:36, 12:41, 47:15)",
      "d": "«خَمَرَ» means to cover. The plural of «خِمَار» is «خُمُر», meaning a veil or headscarf with which one can cover the face, etc. Wine is also called «خَمْر» because it covers and destroys reason and senses.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّمَا الۡخَمۡرُ وَ الۡمَیۡسِرُ وَ الۡاَنۡصَابُ وَ الۡاَزۡلَامُ رِجۡسٌ مِّنۡ عَمَلِ الشَّیۡطٰنِ» (5/90)\nTranslation: Intoxicants, gambling, (sacrificing to) stone altars, and divining arrows are but an abomination of Satan's handiwork."
    },
    {
      "id": 1932,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Wine",
      "hw": "شراب",
      "s": "«مَعِیْن» refers to a delicious, delightful, pure, and flawless wine that will be in Paradise (4 verses: 23:50, 37:45, 56:18, 67:30)",
      "d": "«مَعَنَ الْمَاءَ» means for water to flow gradually to the surface of the earth. «مَعَنَ النَّظْر فِی الْاَمْر» means to ponder deeply into a matter (Manjad). And «مَعِیْن» refers to water that is sweet-tasting, delicious, and clear/transparent.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ اِنۡ اَصۡبَحَ مَآؤُکُمۡ غَوۡرًا فَمَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡکُمۡ بِمَآءٍ مَّعِیۡنٍ» (67/30)\nTranslation: Do you see, if your water becomes sunken (into the earth), who then can bring you flowing water? (i.e., a spring of sweet water).\nHowever, in the following verse, the word «کَاۡس» (a filled cup) changes the meaning of «مَعِیْن» to mean delightful wine. Such wine that is free from the harms of «خَمْر». Because the word «کاس» generally refers to a filled cup for wine or for wine itself.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ وِلۡدَانٌ مُّخَلَّدُوۡنَ - بِاَکۡوَابٍ وَّ اَبَارِیۡقَ ۙ وَ کَاۡسٍ مِّنۡ مَّعِیۡنٍ» (56:17-18)\nTranslation: Round about them will (serve) endless (youthful) boys, with goblets, (shining) beakers, and cups (full) of a flowing wine."
    }
  ],
  "415": [
    {
      "id": 1934,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "To Feel Shame / To be Modest",
      "hw": "شرمانا",
      "s": "«اِسْتِحْیَاءَ» means to feel shame/modesty due to haya (modesty) (3 verses: 2:26, 28:25, 33:53)",
      "d": "«حَیِیَ یَحْیٰی حَیٰوۃً» means to be alive. And «حَیَّ یَحَیُّ حَیًّاء» means to be ashamed and to feel shame. From both, the Form V (istif'al) verb «اِسْتِحْیَاء» is derived. It is used in the Quran in both meanings: 'to leave something alive' and 'to feel shame from someone'. It is used in both material and spiritual senses.\nExample of material usage: Divine command states:\n«فَجَآءَتۡہُ اِحۡدٰىہُمَا تَمۡشِیۡ عَلَی اسۡتِحۡیَآءٍ» (28/25)\nTranslation: Then one of the two women came to him, walking shyly (or with modesty).\nExample of spiritual usage: Divine command states:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یَسۡتَحۡیٖۤ اَنۡ یَّضۡرِبَ مَثَلًا مَّا بَعُوۡضَۃً فَمَا فَوۡقَہَا» (2/26)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah is not ashamed to set forth any parable - (be it) that of a mosquito or what is even smaller."
    },
    {
      "id": 1935,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "To Feel Shame / To be Modest",
      "hw": "شرمانا",
      "s": "«اِسْتِنْکَفَ» is a blameworthy trait, meaning to feel shame/disdain out of arrogance and to consider something a source of shame/disgrace (2 verses: 4:172, 4:173)",
      "d": "«نَکِفَ» means to raise one's nose in arrogance. And «اِسْتَنْکَفَ» means to consider something, out of arrogance, as a cause of shame and disgrace (Manjad).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَنۡ یَّسۡتَنۡکِفَ الۡمَسِیۡحُ اَنۡ یَّکُوۡنَ عَبۡدًا لِّلّٰہِ» (4/172)\nTranslation: The Messiah will never be ashamed to be a servant of Allah."
    }
  ],
  "416": [
    {
      "id": 1936,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "To Begin / To Start",
      "hw": "شروع",
      "s": "«بَدَاَ» means to begin an action (16 verses: 2:117, 6:101, 7:29, 9:13, 10:4, 10:34, 12:76, 21:104, 27:64, 29:19, 29:20, 30:11, 30:27, 32:7, 34:49, 85:13)",
      "d": "«بَدَاَ» comes in two meanings: (1) To begin an action, to initiate, to start. (2) To do something before (someone else). And if its attribution is to Allah, its meanings become 'to create for the first time' (its opposite is «عَوْد» meaning to repeat the same action).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَبَدَاَ بِاَوۡعِیَتِہِمۡ قَبۡلَ وِعَآءِ اَخِیۡہِ» (12/76)\nTranslation: Then he began the search in their bags before his brother's bag.\nIn this verse, both meanings of «بَدَاَ» are found. One meaning is that he started the search with the bags of the other brothers. The second is that he searched the bags of the other brothers before searching his brother's bag.\nAlso, Divine command states:\n«اِنَّہٗ ہُوَ یُبۡدِئُ وَ یُعِیۡدُ» (85/13)\nTranslation: He it is Who originates the creation and will repeat it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1937,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "To begin",
      "hw": "شروع",
      "s": "«طَفِقَ» is an incomplete verb, meaning that the actual action is performed by another [verb]. When combined with it, this verb conveys the meaning of beginning. (3 verses: 7:22-20:121-38:33)",
      "d": "«طَفِقَ» is an incomplete verb that requires another verb with it (according to Manjad). It is used in positive sentences. Meaning: to begin.\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ طَفِقَا یَخۡصِفٰنِ عَلَیۡہِمَا مِنۡ وَّرَقِ الۡجَنَّۃِ» (7/22)\nTranslation: And both (Adam and Eve) began to cover themselves with leaves from Paradise.\nAnother instance: «فَطَفِقَ مَسۡحًۢا بِالسُّوۡقِ وَ الۡاَعۡنَاقِ» (38/33)\nTranslation: So he (Solomon) began to stroke their shanks and necks.\nNote: Incomplete verb: A verb that does not indicate the completion of an action or does not complete a matter. Until a noun or adjective other than the subject is attached to it."
    }
  ],
  "417": [
    {
      "id": 1938,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Private part",
      "hw": "شرم گاہ",
      "s": "«فَرْج» is the open space between two things (private part). (7 verses: 21:91-23:5-24:30-24:31-33:35-66:12-70:29)",
      "d": "«فَرْج» has a plural «فُرُوْج» and conveys the concept of spaciousness. «فَرَجَ» means to open, to make spacious, to clear (according to Manjad). And «فَرْج» means the space between two things or between two parts of one thing. Also, «فَرْجُ الطَّرِیْق» means the middle part of the road. A crack in a wall is also called «فَرْج». And the spaciousness between the two legs is also called «فَرْج». Then, metaphorically, the word «فَرْج» is used for the private part. And due to frequent usage, it began to be understood in its literal meaning (as per Muf).\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  لِفُرُوۡجِہِمۡ حٰفِظُوۡنَ» (23/5)\nTranslation: And those who guard their private parts."
    },
    {
      "id": 1939,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Private part",
      "hw": "شرم گاہ",
      "s": "«سَوْءَۃَ» refers to the private parts if they are exposed, and any thing whose exposure is bad. (6 verses: 5:31-7:20-7:22-7:26-7:27-20:121)",
      "d": "«سَوْء ، سُوْء» means anything that is bad from an intellectual or Shariah perspective or appears bad to look at. Accordingly, a person's private parts, if naked, are called «سَوْءَۃَ». And «سَوْءَۃَ» is not applied only to the private part but to all private parts, such as a woman's body and breasts, etc., if they are exposed.\nFor example: In the Quran: «یٰبَنِیۡۤ  اٰدَمَ  قَدۡ  اَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  لِبَاسًا یُّوَارِیۡ سَوۡاٰتِکُمۡ وَ رِیۡشًا» (7/26)\nTranslation: O children of Adam! We have sent down upon you clothing that covers your private parts and as adornment.\nAnother instance: «فَلَمَّا ذَاقَا الشَّجَرَۃَ بَدَتۡ لَہِمَا سَوۡاٰتُہُمَا» (7/22)\nTranslation: When they both tasted the tree, their private parts became exposed to them.\nThen, in the same sense, the word «سَوْءَۃَ» has been used for a corpse, because it too, after some time, if not buried, becomes a repulsive sight.\nFor example: In the Quran: «فَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ غُرَابًا یَّبۡحَثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ لِیُرِیَہٗ کَیۡفَ یُوَارِیۡ سَوۡءَۃَ اَخِیۡہِ» (5/31)\nTranslation: Then Allah sent a crow that scratched in the earth to show him how to cover the private part of his brother."
    }
  ],
  "418": [
    {
      "id": 1940,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Partner",
      "hw": "شریک",
      "s": "«خَلِیْط» means partial partner, i.e., those whose affair is one. (2 verses: 9:102-38:24)",
      "d": "«خَلَطَ» means to mix one thing with another; its opposite is «خَلَصَ» meaning pure, unadulterated, and clear. «اَلْخَلْط» means one who mixes with people. «خَلِیْط» refers to those whose affair is one. And «اَلْخُلْطَۃ» means partnership (according to Manjad). In idiomatic meanings, «خَلِیْط» means 'partial partner', i.e., partners who have some arrangements jointly and some separately. For example, Zaid and Bakr both have separate herds that are their own property, but for their protection, they have jointly taken a place on rent or pay a common herdsman a shared salary. Such partners are called «خَلَیْط» (according to Hadith, Zakat is due on the shared property of such «خُلَطَاء»).\nFor example: In the Quran: «اِنَّ کَثِیۡرًا مِّنَ الۡخُلَطَآءِ لَیَبۡغِیۡ  بَعۡضُہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ» (38/24)\nTranslation: Indeed, many partners wrong each other."
    },
    {
      "id": 1941,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Partner",
      "hw": "شریک",
      "s": "«شَرِیْک» means one who has complete participation in a work. (3 verses: 6:163-17:111-25:2)",
      "d": "«شَرِیْک» means a partner who cannot be separated from another. Partnership can be material and spiritual. Material is like two men being partners in a business with responsibilities such that if one leaves, neither the business can start nor run. In the same sense, the Quran states: «وَّ لَمۡ  یَکُنۡ لَّہٗ  شَرِیۡکٌ فِی الۡمُلۡکِ  وَ لَمْ یَکُنۡ لَّہٗ  وَلِیٌّ  مِّنَ الذُّلِّ» (17/111)\nTranslation: And He has no partner in the kingdom, and He has no protector from humiliation.\nAnd spiritual partnership is like humans and animals sharing in animality. This is an attribute-based partnership. Allah is far above this, as clearly stated in many verses."
    }
  ],
  "419": [
    {
      "id": 1943,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Flame",
      "hw": "شعلہ",
      "s": "«لَھَب» is a general term for flame, the flame of fire. (2 verses: 77:31-111:3)",
      "d": "«لَھَب» means the movement and rising of fire, and the tongue of fire rising (according to Muf). It is used in the well-known sense of flame and is a general term for flame.\nFor example: In the Quran: «سَیَصۡلٰی نَارًا ذَاتَ  لَہَبٍ» (111/3)\nTranslation: He will enter a fire having flames."
    },
    {
      "id": 1945,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Flame",
      "hw": "شعلہ",
      "s": "«مَارِج» is the hottest part above the flame. (1 verse: 55:15)",
      "d": "«مَارِج» is the hottest part of the flame that is free from smoke, the tip of the flame (according to Muf).\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ  خَلَقَ  الۡجَآنَّ مِنۡ مَّارِجٍ  مِّنۡ نَّارٍ» (55/15)\nTranslation: And He created the jinn from a flame of fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 1946,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Flame",
      "hw": "شعلہ",
      "s": "«شَرَر» are small sparks that fly off from a flame. (1 verse: 77:32)",
      "d": "«شَرَر» are small pieces that break off from a large flame and fly away. Sparks, embers (according to Muf).\nFor example: In the Quran: «اِنَّہَا  تَرۡمِیۡ  بِشَرَرٍ  کَالۡقَصۡرِ» (77/32)\nTranslation: It (Hell) will throw sparks as large as castles."
    }
  ],
  "420": [
    {
      "id": 1947,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Doubt and suspicion",
      "hw": "شک",
      "s": "«شَکّ» is the inability to prefer one of two theories due to lack of knowledge. (15 verses: 4:157-10:94-10:104-11:62-11:110-14:9-14:10-27:66-34:21-34:54-38:8-40:34-41:45-42:14-44:9)",
      "d": "«شَکّ» means two theories being equal and balanced in the mind when there is no evidence to prefer one over the other. Essentially, the basis of doubt is ignorance or lack of knowledge (according to Muf).\nFor example: In the Quran: «اَفِی اللّٰہِ شَکٌّ فَاطِرِ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ» (14/10)\nTranslation: Is there doubt about Allah, the Originator of the heavens and the earth?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1948,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Doubt and suspicion",
      "hw": "شک",
      "s": "«شَبَّہَ» means that two or more things are so similar that one cannot distinguish between them correctly. (9 verses: 2:25-2:70-2:118-3:7-4:157-6:99-6:141-13:16-39:23)",
      "d": "«شَبَّہَ» means that two or more things are so similar in appearance or attributes that one cannot properly distinguish between them (according to Muf).\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ مَا قَتَلُوۡہُ وَ مَا صَلَبُوۡہُ وَ لٰکِنۡ شُبِّہَ لَہُمۡ» (4/157)\nTranslation: And they did not kill him, nor did they crucify him, but it was made to appear so to them.\nAnother instance: «اِنَّ الۡبَقَرَ تَشٰبَہَ عَلَیۡنَا» (2/70)\nTranslation: Indeed, the cow has become confusing to us."
    },
    {
      "id": 1949,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Doubt and Suspicion",
      "hw": "شک",
      "s": "«مِرْیَۃ» To make an accepted (acknowledged) truth doubtful through speculative (imaginary) and suspicious matters (4 verses: 11:109, 22:55, 32:23, 41:54)",
      "d": "The word «مِرْیَۃ» has two fundamental meanings: (1) For a truth or theory to be accepted (established), and (2) To persistently cast doubt on that truth through suspicious matters. (M, L) Hence, this word also appears in the meanings of arguing and disputing. And the basis of such an argument is these very matters of doubt.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَبِاَیِّ  اٰلَآءِ  رَبِّکَ  تَتَمَارٰی» (53/55)\nTranslation: So, O human! About which of your Lord's favors will you dispute?\nAnd «مِرْیَۃ» refers to the doubts about a truth created by people.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«فَلَا تَکُنۡ فِیۡ مِرۡیَۃٍ  مِّنۡ لِّقَآئِہٖ» (32/23)\nTranslation: So, do not be in doubt concerning the meeting (with your Lord)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1950,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Doubt and Suspicion",
      "hw": "شک",
      "s": "«مَرِیْج» Sometimes one thought comes, sometimes another, and then the first again, and to remain in doubt on this basis (1 verse: 50:5)",
      "d": "«مَرَجَ» means the mingling of two theories. And «غُصْنٌ مَّرِیۡجٌ» refers to a branch that is intertwined with another (Muf). To be in a state of disorder (Manjad). The matter being confused and complicated. And «مَرَجَ» also means the coming and going of a thought, and a state of agitation (restlessness) (M. L). Thus, this word is a combination of hesitation and agitation.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«بَلۡ کَذَّبُوۡا بِالۡحَقِّ لَمَّا جَآءَہُمۡ فَہُمۡ  فِیۡۤ اَمۡرٍ  مَّرِیۡجٍ» (50/5)\nTranslation: But when the truth came to them, they denied it. So they are (now) in a confused state (of affairs)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1951,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Doubt and Suspicion",
      "hw": "شک",
      "s": "«لَبْس» To mix two theories in such a way that one cannot distinguish between them (7 verses: 2:42, 3:71, 6:9, 6:65, 6:82, 6:137, 50:15)",
      "d": "«لَبَسَ» means commingling and intermingling (i.e., one thing mixing with another and being included within it) (M. L). That is, to confuse two things together and to incorporate one into the other. Such as mixing falsehood with truth and blending some truth into falsehood, thereby making the reality so suspicious that the distinction between truth and falsehood cannot be made. And one who is caught in such a state of doubt and suspicion is called «لَبْس». This word is also used in the context of rejection and in the form of speech (Faq L 249).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«بَلۡ ہُمۡ فِیۡ لَبۡسٍ مِّنۡ خَلۡقٍ جَدِیۡدٍ» (50/15)\nTranslation: Nay, but they are in doubt about a new creation.\nAt another place, the Divine Command states:\n«وَ لَا تَلۡبِسُوا الۡحَقَّ بِالۡبَاطِلِ» (2/42)\nTranslation: And do not mix the truth with falsehood."
    },
    {
      "id": 1952,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Doubt and Suspicion",
      "hw": "شک",
      "s": "«رَیْب» A doubt that also includes agitation, restlessness, and hesitation (18 verses: 2:2, 2:23, 3:9, 3:25, 4:87, 6:12, 9:45, 9:110, 10:37, 17:99, 18:21, 22:5, 22:7, 32:2, 40:59, 42:7, 45:26, 45:32)",
      "d": "«رَیْب» is a doubt that also includes the element of agitation (restlessness). «رَیْبُ الدَّہْر» means the vicissitudes of time. The incidents of time, and «رَیْبُ الْمَنُوْن» means the dangers of life (M, L). And «رَیْب» is a doubt that causes restlessness, hesitation, and unease. It is said: «دَعْ مَا یُرِیْبَکَ اِلٰی مَا لَا یُرِیْبَکَ» meaning: Leave aside what causes you doubt and anxiety, and adopt what involves no doubt or anxiety. «رَیْبَۃ» means grief and sorrow, agitation (restlessness) (M. Q).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّہُمۡ لَفِیۡ شَکٍّ  مِّنۡہُ  مُرِیۡبٍ» (41/45)\nTranslation: Indeed, they are in a doubt about it that disturbs them.\nAt another place, the Divine Command states:\n«ذٰلِکَ  الۡکِتٰبُ لَا رَیۡبَ فِیْہِ» (2:2)\nTranslation: This is the Book about which there is no doubt (or peril)."
    }
  ],
  "421": [
    {
      "id": 1954,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Form and Shape",
      "hw": "صورت",
      "s": "«شَکْل» Things that resemble each other in form and shape (1 verse: 38:58)",
      "d": "«مُشَاکِلَۃ» means to be similar in form and shape (Muf). And «اشکال» means a complexity in a matter where various intermingled forms appear. And a difficulty is said for such a complicated affair. And «شَکَلَ الْاَمْر» means to be dubious. And «شَکْل» means resemblance. Like. Similar. And «اشکال» also means pearls or silver ornaments that are similar to each other. (Manjad)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ اٰخَرُ  مِنۡ شَکۡلِہٖۤ  اَزۡوَاجٌ» (38/58)\nTranslation: And other kinds (of punishments) similar to them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1955,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Form and Shape",
      "hw": "صورت",
      "s": "«صُوْرَت» The external features of a material thing by which it can be recognized and distinguished from other things (1 verse: 82:8)",
      "d": "«صُوْرَت» means the external features of a material thing by which it can be recognized. And it can be distinguished from other things (Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فِیۡۤ  اَیِّ صُوۡرَۃٍ  مَّا شَآءَ  رَکَّبَکَ» (82/8)\nTranslation: Then, in whatever form Allah willed, He composed you."
    },
    {
      "id": 1956,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Form and Shape",
      "hw": "صورت",
      "s": "«تَمْثَال» A likeness, image, statue, or representation of an original thing (2 verses: 21:52, 34:13)",
      "d": "«تَمْثَال» (plural «تَمَاثِیْل , مَثُلَ») means to take on the form and shape of another thing and to stand upright. And «مُمَثَّل» is a thing made according to a model (sample). And «تَمَثَّلَ» means to become in the form of someone, to assume the guise of someone (Muf). And «تَمْثَال» means an image, a picture, or a representation of a thing (Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ قَالَ لِاَبِیۡہِ وَ قَوۡمِہٖ مَا ہٰذِہِ التَّمَاثِیۡلُ  الَّتِیۡۤ  اَنۡتُمۡ  لَہَا  عٰکِفُوۡنَ» (21/52)\nTranslation: When he (Prophet Ibrahim) said to his father and his people: What are these statues to which you are devoted?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1957,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Forming a Shape",
      "hw": "صورت",
      "s": "«صَوَّرَ» To draw a picture, to form a shape (4 verses: 3:6, 7:11, 40:64, 64:3)",
      "d": "«صَوَّرَ» means to draw a picture, to form a shape (Manjad). This word is generally applied to living things, and forming the shape of living things is a special attribute of Allah, the Most High.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ہُوَ  الَّذِیۡ یُصَوِّرُکُمۡ  فِی الۡاَرۡحَامِ  کَیۡفَ یَشَآءُ» (3/6)\nTranslation: He it is Who shapes you in the wombs however He wills."
    },
    {
      "id": 1958,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Forming a Shape",
      "hw": "صورت",
      "s": "«خَلَّقَ» To make the initial sketch and design (210 verses: 2:21, 2:29, 2:164, 2:228, 3:47, 3:49, 3:59, 3:190, 3:191, 4:1, 4:28, 4:119, 5:17, 5:18, 5:110, 6:1, 6:2, 6:73, 6:94, 6:100, 6:101, 6:102, 7:11, 7:12, 7:54, 7:69, 7:181, 7:185, 7:189, 7:191, 9:36, 10:3, 10:4, 10:5, 10:6, 10:34, 11:7, 11:119, 13:5, 13:16, 14:19, 14:32, 15:26, 15:27, 15:28, 15:33, 15:85, 16:3, 16:4, 16:5, 16:8, 16:17, 16:20, 16:48, 16:70, 16:81, 17:49, 17:51, 17:61, 17:70, 17:98, 17:99, 18:37, 18:48, 18:51, 19:9, 19:67, 20:4, 20:50, 20:55, 21:16, 21:33, 21:37, 21:104, 22:5, 22:73, 23:12, 23:14, 23:17, 23:91, 23:115, 24:45, 25:2, 25:3, 25:49, 25:54, 25:59, 26:78, 26:166, 26:184, 27:60, 27:64, 28:68, 29:17, 29:19, 29:20, 29:44, 29:61, 30:8, 30:11, 30:20, 30:21, 30:22, 30:27, 30:30, 30:40, 30:54, 31:10, 31:11, 31:25, 31:28, 32:4, 32:7, 32:10, 34:7, 35:1, 35:3, 35:11, 35:16, 35:40, 36:36, 36:42, 36:68, 36:71, 36:77, 36:78, 36:79, 36:81, 37:11, 37:96, 37:125, 37:150, 38:27, 38:71, 38:75, 38:76, 39:4, 39:5, 39:6, 39:38, 39:62, 40:57, 40:62, 40:67, 41:9, 41:15, 41:21, 41:37, 42:29, 42:49, 43:9, 43:12, 43:16, 43:19, 43:87, 44:38, 44:39, 45:4, 45:22, 46:3, 46:4, 46:33, 49:13, 50:15, 50:16, 50:38, 51:49, 51:56, 52:35, 52:36, 53:45, 54:49, 55:3, 55:14, 55:15, 56:57, 56:59, 57:4, 59:24, 64:2, 64:3, 65:12, 67:2, 67:3, 67:14, 70:19, 70:39, 71:14, 71:15, 74:11, 75:38, 76:2, 76:28, 77:20, 78:8, 79:27, 80:18, 80:19, 82:7, 86:5, 86:6, 87:2, 88:17, 89:8, 90:4, 92:3, 95:4, 96:1, 96:2, 113:2)",
      "d": "«خَلَّقَ» To make the initial sketch and design before the completion of a material thing's form.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ مِنۡ مُّضۡغَۃٍ مُّخَلَّقَۃٍ» (22/5)\nTranslation: Then from a leech-like clot (He creates a formation that is) shaped (in a preliminary form)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1959,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Forming a Shape",
      "hw": "صورت",
      "s": "«تَمَثَّلَ» To assume a guise, to take on a form (1 verse: 19:17)",
      "d": "«تَمَثَّلَ» means to change one's own form and shape to become like the form and shape of another. To assume a guise.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَرۡسَلۡنَاۤ  اِلَیۡہَا رُوۡحَنَا فَتَمَثَّلَ لَہَا بَشَرًا سَوِیًّا» (19/17)\nTranslation: So We sent to her Our spirit, and it assumed for her the form of a perfect man."
    }
  ],
  "422": [
    {
      "id": 1960,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Crack. Fissure",
      "hw": "شگاف",
      "s": "«فُطُوْر» is a long crack that forms from something splitting or tearing (1 verse: 67:3)",
      "d": "«فَطَرَ» means to split or tear something lengthwise. And «اِنْفَطَر» means to crack. «فُطُوْر» refers to a crack whose width is very small compared to its length. A fissure, a crack, a crevice. For example, in the Quran: «فَارۡجِعِ الۡبَصَرَ ۙ ہَلۡ تَرٰی مِنۡ فُطُوۡرٍ» (67/3) Translation: Raise your sight (towards the sky). Do you see any crack?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1961,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Crack. Fissure",
      "hw": "شگاف",
      "s": "«فُرُوْج» refers only to an open space in the middle, whether congenital or occurring later (1 verse: 50:6)",
      "d": "In the meaning of «فَرْج», the concept of spaciousness is found, not splitting or tearing. «فَرَجَ» means to open, to make spacious, to clear. «فَرَجَ» means the space and width between two things or two parts of one thing. «فَرَجَ الطَّرِیْق» means the middle part of the road. An opening or gap, whether congenital or occurring later. For example, in the Quran: «اَفَلَمۡ یَنۡظُرُوۡۤا اِلَی السَّمَآءِ فَوۡقَہُمۡ کَیۡفَ بَنَیۡنٰہَا وَ زَیَّنّٰہَا وَ مَا لَہَا مِنۡ فُرُوۡجٍ» (50/6) Translation: Do they not look at the sky above them, how We have built it and adorned it, and it has no gaps?"
    }
  ],
  "423": [
    {
      "id": 1962,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "City. Settlement",
      "hw": "شہر",
      "s": "«مَدِیْنَۃ» is a settlement where people live under established rules and regulations (14 verses: 7:123-9:101-9:120-12:30-15:67-18:19-18:82-27:48-28:15-28:18-28:20-33:60-36:20-63:8)",
      "d": "«مَدَن» means to reside, to live in a city. And «تَمَدَّن» means to be civilized and refined. «مَدِیْنَۃ» refers to any city where people live together under rules and regulations. Its plural is «مَدَائِن». For example, in the Quran: «وَ جَآءَ مِنۡ اَقۡصَا الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ رَجُلٌ یَّسۡعٰی» (36/20) Translation: And a man came from the farthest part of the city, running."
    },
    {
      "id": 1963,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "City. Settlement",
      "hw": "شہر",
      "s": "«بَلَد» is a city whose boundaries have been defined (14 verses: 2:126-7:57-7:58-14:35-16:7-25:49-27:91-34:15-35:9-43:11-50:11-90:1-90:2-95:3)",
      "d": "The plural of «بَلَد» is «بِلاَد». It refers to any place whose boundaries have been defined and where people reside. For example, in the Quran: «لَاۤ اُقۡسِمُ بِہٰذَا الۡبَلَدِ» (90/1) Translation: I swear by this city (Makkah)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1964,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "City. Settlement",
      "hw": "شہر",
      "s": "«مِصْر» is a city whose boundaries have been defined and which also has a wall or fortification (5 verses: 2:61-10:87-12:21-12:99-43:51)",
      "d": "The plural of «مِصْر» is «مُصُوْر». It means a boundary. It is said: «اِشْتَرٰی فُلَانُ الدَّار بِمُصُوْرِھَا» (So-and-so bought that house with its boundaries). And «مِصْر» means a province (land from which revenue is taken), a district (whose boundaries are defined), and according to some, it is a city where state revenues and charities are distributed. According to some, it is a walled city. Also, «مِصْر» is the name of a country. For example, in the Quran: «اِہۡبِطُوۡا مِصۡرًا فَاِنَّ لَکُمۡ مَّا سَاَلۡتُمۡ» (2/61) Translation: Go down to the city (Egypt), and you will get what you asked for."
    },
    {
      "id": 1965,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Dwellings. Abodes",
      "hw": "شہر",
      "s": "«دِیَار» can refer to a home, village, town, city, country, or even the entire world (16 verses: 2:84-2:85-2:243-2:246-3:195-4:66-8:47-11:67-11:94-17:5-22:40-33:27-59:2-59:8-60:8-60:9)",
      "d": "«دِیَار» is the plural of «دَار». Its plural «دُوْر» also occurs. «دُوْر» means something being surrounded on all sides. «دَار» means house, dwelling. «دَیْر» means the residence of a worshipper. «دَار» in terms of residence has a very broad meaning, applicable to any settlement, town, city, or country. «دَارُ الْحَرْب» means the enemy's land. «دَارُ الْقَرَار» means the Hereafter. «دَارُ الدُّنْیَا» means the home of the world, the entire world. And «دَارَان» or «دَارَیْن» means the world or the Hereafter. For example, in the Quran: «فَاِذَا جَآءَ وَعۡدُ اُوۡلٰىہُمَا بَعَثۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ عِبَادًا لَّنَاۤ اُولِیۡ بَاۡسٍ شَدِیۡدٍ فَجَاسُوۡا خِلٰلَ الدِّیَارِ» (17/5) Translation: Then when the first of the two promises came, We sent against you Our servants given to terrible warfare, who penetrated the dwellings (cities)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1966,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Settlement. Town",
      "hw": "شہر",
      "s": "«قَرْیَۃ» means a large settlement, city, or village, and also its inhabitants (37 verses: 2:58-2:259-4:75-6:123-7:4-7:82-7:88-7:94-7:161-7:163-10:98-12:82-15:4-16:112-17:16-17:58-18:77-21:6-21:11-21:74-21:95-22:45-22:48-25:40-25:51-26:208-27:34-27:56-28:58-29:31-29:34-34:34-36:13-43:23-43:31-47:13-65:8)",
      "d": "The plural of «قَرْیَۃ» is «قُرٰی». It has two meanings: (1) a settlement, (2) the people living in a settlement. This word is used in different contexts individually and collectively. Generally, it applies to any settlement, whether large or small, a village or a city. According to some, it specifically refers to a large settlement. For example, in the Quran: «وَ کَاَیِّنۡ مِّنۡ قَرۡیَۃٍ عَتَتۡ عَنۡ اَمۡرِ رَبِّہَا وَ رُسُلِہٖ» (65/8) Translation: And many a settlement (i.e., its inhabitants) rebelled against the command of their Lord and His messengers. At another place, the Almighty says: «تِلۡکَ الۡقُرٰۤی اَہۡلَکۡنٰہُمۡ لَمَّا ظَلَمُوۡا» (18/59) Translation: Those settlements (now in ruins) We destroyed when they wronged."
    }
  ],
  "424": [
    {
      "id": 1967,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Glass. Crystal",
      "hw": "شیشہ",
      "s": "«زُجَاجَۃ» means glass, crystal, something transparent through which one can see (1 verse: 24:35)",
      "d": "«زُجَاجَۃ» means glass (GLASS), crystal. It is a common term used for a piece of glass or a glass vessel. «اَلزُّجَاجِی» means a glass seller. For example, in the Quran: «اَلۡمِصۡبَاحُ فِیۡ زُجَاجَۃٍ ؕ اَلزُّجَاجَۃُ کَاَنَّہَا کَوۡکَبٌ دُرِّیٌّ» (24/35) Translation: The lamp is within a glass. The glass is as if it were a shining star."
    },
    {
      "id": 1968,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Glass. Crystal",
      "hw": "شیشہ",
      "s": "«قَوَارِیْر» is glass that is made for a specific purpose. Glassware, whether plain or colored (3 verses: 27:44-76:15-76:16)",
      "d": "«قَوَارِیر» is the plural of «قَارُوْرَہ». It means a drinking vessel or a container for dates or raisins. In the terminology of physicians, it refers to a glass vessel (bottle) used by a doctor to examine a patient's urine. «قَارُوْرَہ» refers to any glass vessel made for a purpose, whether for looking at faces, for decorating buildings in colors, or for use in pottery. For example, in the Quran: «وَ یُطَافُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِاٰنِیَۃٍ مِّنۡ فِضَّۃٍ وَّ اَکۡوَابٍ کَانَتۡ قَؔوَارِیۡرَا۠» (76/15) Translation: And there will be circulated among them vessels of silver and goblets which will be of glass."
    }
  ],
  "425": [
    {
      "id": 1969,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "to purify",
      "hw": "صاف",
      "s": "«مَحَّصَ» means to purify something that has been compounded from several elements, where the mixture has thoroughly permeated it (2 verses: 3:141-3:154)",
      "d": "«مَحَّصَ» means to purify something in which a mixture has thoroughly permeated. In material objects, it is used to separate compounds. For example, «مَحَّصَ الذَّھْب» means to purify gold by placing it in a cupel to remove the alloy and impurities of other metals. And spiritually, it is applied by subjecting someone to trials and afflictions to make them pure and clean.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لِیُمَحِّصَ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ یَمۡحَقَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» ( 3/141 )\nTranslation: so that Allah may purify the believers and destroy the disbelievers.\nNote: (cupel is the small cup in which gold and silver are melted.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1972,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "to wipe clean",
      "hw": "صاف",
      "s": "«مَسَحَ» means to wipe away dust and dirt by moving the hand, to brush off, to clean. (3 verses: 4:43-5:6-38:33)",
      "d": "«مَسَحَ» means to move one's hand over something to remove dust and dirt around it, to brush off, to wipe.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَطَفِقَ مَسۡحًۢا بِالسُّوۡقِ وَ الۡاَعۡنَاقِ» (38/33)\nTranslation: So Solomon began to wipe clean the necks and legs of the horses.\nIn Shariah terminology, 'masah' means applying clean soil or water to a place first, then wiping it to clean.\nFor example, Allah says:\n«فَتَیَمَّمُوۡا صَعِیۡدًا طَیِّبًا فَامۡسَحُوۡا بِوُجُوۡہِکُمۡ وَ اَیۡدِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡہُ» (5/6)\nTranslation: So intend clean soil, then wipe your faces and hands with it."
    }
  ],
  "426": [],
  "427": [
    {
      "id": 1975,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "reconciliation",
      "hw": "صلح",
      "s": "«صُلْح» refers to a mutual agreement between parties after a dispute (40 verses: 2:11-2:160-2:182-2:220-2:224-2:228-3:89-4:16-4:35-4:114-4:128-4:129-4:146-5:39-6:48-6:54-7:35-7:56-7:85-11:88-17:142-7:170-8:1-10:81-11:117-13:23-16:119-21:90-24:5-26:152-27:48-28:19-33:71-40:8-42:40-46:15-47:2-47:5-49:9-49:10)",
      "d": "«اَلْاِصْلَاح» is its opposite, meaning corruption or disorder. And «اَصْلَحَ» means to correct disorder. And «صُلْح» refers to a mutual agreement between parties among whom there was previously enmity, dispute, or fighting.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ طَآئِفَتٰنِ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ اقۡتَتَلُوۡا فَاَصۡلِحُوۡا بَیۡنَہُمَا» ( 49/9 )\nTranslation: And if two parties among the believers fight, then make peace between them.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ اِنِ امۡرَاَۃٌ خَافَتۡ مِنۡۢ بَعۡلِہَا نُشُوۡزًا اَوۡ اِعۡرَاضًا فَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡہِمَاۤ  اَنۡ یُّصۡلِحَا بَیۡنَہُمَا صُلۡحًا ؕ وَ الصُّلْحُ  خَیۡرٌ» ( 4/128 )\nTranslation: And if a woman fears from her husband contempt or evasion, there is no blame on them if they arrange a settlement between them. And settlement is good."
    },
    {
      "id": 1976,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "reconciliation",
      "hw": "صلح",
      "s": "«سَلَم» refers to an agreement or peace that occurs before a fight or dispute arises. (6 verses: 4:90-4:91-8:61-16:28-16:87-47:35)",
      "d": "«اَلسَّلْم» means safety, submission. And «سَلَم» means to be saved, to be secure. And «سَلَم» also refers to one who makes peace (manjad). And such an agreement or peace that occurs before a fight or dispute arises. To be obedient.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاِنِ اعۡتَزَلُوۡکُمۡ فَلَمۡ یُقَاتِلُوۡکُمۡ  وَ اَلۡقَوۡا اِلَیۡکُمُ السَّلَمَ ۙ فَمَا جَعَلَ اللّٰہُ لَکُمۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  سَبِیۡلًا» (4/90)\nTranslation: Then if they withdraw from you and do not fight you and offer you peace, then Allah has not made for you a way against them."
    }
  ],
  "428": [
    {
      "id": 1977,
      "a": "ض",
      "h": "guarantor",
      "hw": "ضامن",
      "s": "«کَفِیْل» is a guarantor who is responsible for maintenance and care. (6 verses: 3:37-3:44-16:91-20:40-28:12-38:23)",
      "d": "«کَفَلَ» means to be responsible for someone's maintenance and care, to be a guarantor. And «کَفِیْل» also carries the meaning of taking guarantee for a criminal.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَا کُنۡتَ لَدَیۡہِمۡ  اِذۡ  یُلۡقُوۡنَ اَقۡلَامَہُمۡ اَیُّہُمۡ یَکۡفُلُ مَرۡیَمَ» (3/44)\nTranslation: And you were not with them when they cast their pens to determine which of them would be the guardian of Mary.\nAt another place, Allah says:\n«وَ قَدۡ جَعَلۡتُمُ اللّٰہَ  عَلَیۡکُمۡ  کَفِیۡلًا» (16/91)\nTranslation: And you have certainly made Allah a guarantor for yourselves."
    },
    {
      "id": 1978,
      "a": "ض",
      "h": "guarantor",
      "hw": "ضامن",
      "s": "«زَعِیْم» is a guarantor who is responsible for something on behalf of the government. (2 verses: 12:72-68:40)",
      "d": "«زُعَامَۃ» means leadership, headship. «زَعِیْم» is a person who is responsible or guarantor for something on behalf of the government.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا نَفۡقِدُ صُوَاعَ  الۡمَلِکِ  وَ لِمَنۡ  جَآءَ بِہٖ  حِمۡلُ  بَعِیۡرٍ  وَّ اَنَا  بِہٖ  زَعِیۡمٌ» (12/72)\nTranslation: They said, 'We have lost the measuring bowl of the king, and for whoever brings it is the reward of a camel's load, and I am responsible for it.'"
    }
  ],
  "429": [
    {
      "id": 1979,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "strength",
      "hw": "طاقت",
      "s": "«طَاقَت» is a general term meaning the amount of strength required for a task. (2 verses: 2:249-2:286)",
      "d": "«طَاقَت» is a well-known word and is commonly used. It means courage, strength (POWER) required for a task.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«رَبَّنَا وَ لَا  تُحَمِّلۡنَا مَا لَا طَاقَۃَ لَنَا بِہٖ» (2/286)\nTranslation: Our Lord, do not impose upon us what we have no strength to bear."
    },
    {
      "id": 1980,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "strength",
      "hw": "طاقت",
      "s": "«قُوَّۃ» refers to the innate ability (capability) and potential that exists within something. (26 verses: 2:63-2:93-2:165-7:145-7:171-8:60-9:69-11:52-11:80-16:92-18:39-18:95-19:12-27:33-28:76-28:78-30:9-30:54-35:44-40:21-40:82-41:15-47:13-51:58-81:20-86:10)",
      "d": "«قُوَّۃ» means force, innate ability and potential found in something. Its opposite is «ضُعْف» meaning weakness.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّ مَفَاتِحَہٗ  لَتَنُوۡٓاُ بِالۡعُصۡبَۃِ  اُولِی الۡقُوَّۃِ» (28/76)\nTranslation: Indeed, its keys would be carried by strong men."
    },
    {
      "id": 1981,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "strength",
      "hw": "طاقت",
      "s": "«مِرَّۃ» means intensity. The permanent state of something. Strength. Firmness. (1 verse: 53:6)",
      "d": "«مِرَّۃ» means intensity, the permanent state of something, strength, firmness. (manjad) Intensity and determination. And «ذُوْمِرَّۃ» is a phrase meaning strong and powerful, vigorous. And «مَرِیْر» means a twisted rope.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«عَلَّمَہٗ  شَدِیۡدُ الۡقُوٰی ذُوۡ مِرَّۃٍ ؕ  فَاسۡتَوٰی» (53:5,6)\nTranslation: He was taught by one intense in strength and possessing firmness. So he rose."
    },
    {
      "id": 1982,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "strength",
      "hw": "طاقت",
      "s": "«رُکْن» is a member of a group, association, or organization, an individual of a faction. (3 verses: 11:80-11:113-17:74)",
      "d": "«رُکْن» means a member of a group, association, or organization. And it also means pillar, fortress, support, and is used for assistance.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَ لَوۡ اَنَّ لِیۡ بِکُمۡ قُوَّۃً  اَوۡ اٰوِیۡۤ اِلٰی رُکۡنٍ  شَدِیۡدٍ» (11/80)\nTranslation: He said, 'If only I had strength against you or could take refuge in a strong pillar.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1984,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "to have strength",
      "hw": "طاقت",
      "s": "«اَطَاق» means to be capable of something, to have strength. (1 verse: 2:184)",
      "d": "«اَطَاق» means to have the courage and strength for a task. It is a well-known word.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ یُطِیۡقُوۡنَہٗ فِدۡیَۃٌ طَعَامُ مِسۡکِیۡنٍ» (2/184)\nTranslation: And upon those who are able to fast is an expiation of feeding a poor person."
    },
    {
      "id": 1985,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Have Power",
      "hw": "طاقت",
      "s": "«استطاع» means to have the power to do something. (40 verses: 2:217-2:273-2:282-3:97-4:25-4:98-4:129-5:112-6:35-7:192-7:197-8:60-9:42-10:38-11:13-11:20-11:88-16:73-17:48-17:64-18:41-18:67-18:72-18:75-18:78-18:97-18:101-21:40-21:43-25:9-25:19-26:211-36:50-36:67-36:75-51:45-55:33-58:4-64:16-68:42)",
      "d": "«استطاع الأمر» means to have the power to do something. To be worthy (manjad) and to mean having all the necessary means and resources to accomplish something (muf). Power is limited to one's own self, while capability relates to personal power as well as other means and resources. For example, for Hajj: expenses, transportation, safe route, provision for family, etc.\nFor instance, the Quran says: «وَلِلّٰهِ عَلَى النَّاسِ حِجُّ الْبَيْتِ مَنِ اسْتَطَاعَ إِلَيْهِ سَبِيلًا» (3/97)\nTranslation: And upon the people is the Hajj of the House, for whoever is able to undertake the journey to it.\nTherefore, «استطاع» means to have power and capability, or to be able to do something.\nFor instance, the Quran says: «فَمَا اسْتَطَاعُوا أَنْ يُظْهِرُوهُ وَمَا اسْتَطَاعُوا لَهُ نَقْبًا» (18/97)\nTranslation: Then they had no power to climb over it, nor could they tunnel through it.\nAt another place, God Almighty says: «إِذْ قَالَ الْحَوَارِيُّونَ يَا عِيسَى ابْنَ مَرْيَمَ هَلْ يَسْتَطِيعُ رَبُّكَ أَنْ يُنَزِّلَ عَلَيْنَا مَائِدَةً مِنَ السَّمَاءِ» (5/112)\nTranslation: And (remember) when the disciples said, 'O Jesus, son of Mary, can your Lord send down to us a table from the heaven?'"
    }
  ],
  "430": [
    {
      "id": 1986,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Method / Custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "«طَرِیْقَۃ» refers to those customs and practices which people begin to consider as religious matters. (3 verses: 20:63-20:104-72:16)",
      "d": "«طَرِیْقَۃ» means habit, state, religion (manjad). Every nation and religion is called «طریق». Which a person adopts for doing something, whether good or bad (muf).\nFor instance, the Quran says: «وَ يَذۡہَبَا بِطَرِیۡقَتِکُمُ الۡمُثۡلٰی» (20/63)\nTranslation: And both (Moses and Aaron) will destroy your noble religion.\nAt another place, God Almighty says: «إِذۡ يَقُوۡلُ أَمۡثَلُہُمۡ طَرِیۡقَۃً إِنۡ لَّبِثۡتُمۡ إِلَّا یَوۡمًا» (20/104)\nTranslation: Then the best among them in terms of way/method will say, 'You remained only a day.'\nThus, in Islamic terminology, 'way' refers to those customs and habits which people have given the status of religious slogans."
    },
    {
      "id": 1987,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Method / Custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "«سُنَّۃ» refers to the divine laws that are perpetually in operation in the universe. Or the method which, once its foundation is laid, continues to function. (9 verses: 8:38-15:13-17:77-18:55-33:38-33:62-35:43-40:85-48:23)",
      "d": "«سَنَّ» means for something to become established and run properly (m. l). It is used both as transitive and intransitive. For example, «مَنْ سَنَّ سُنَّۃً» meaning whoever establishes a matter (method, custom, constitution). When attributed to God Almighty, it refers to the divine law (generally called the law of nature).\nFor instance, the Quran says: «فَهَلۡ یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ إِلَّا سُنَّتَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ ۚ فَلَنۡ تَجِدَ لِسُنَّتِ اللّٰہِ تَبۡدِیۡلًا» (35/43)\nTranslation: Do they then await anything but the way of the former peoples? So you will not find any change in Allah's way.\nAnd when only the word 'sunnah' is used, it generally refers to the method established by the Prophet ﷺ, and its plural is «سُنَن». The Prophet's example."
    },
    {
      "id": 1988,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Method / Custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "«اُمَّۃ» refers to a group of people who share the same ideology or belief, and those who think alike. (54 verses: 2:143-2:213-3:104-3:110-3:113-4:41-5:48-5:66-6:38-6:42-6:108-7:34-7:38-7:159-7:160-7:164-7:168-7:181-10:19-10:47-10:49-11:8-11:48-11:118-12:45-13:30-15:5-16:36-16:63-16:84-16:89-16:92-16:93-16:120-21:92-22:34-22:67-23:43-23:44-23:52-27:83-28:23-28:75-29:18-35:24-35:42-40:5-41:25-42:8-43:22-43:23-43:33-45:28-46:18)",
      "d": "«امت» means a group of people with the same belief or ideology (muf). Then this term is also applied to that ideology or belief upon which people agree, whether that ideology or belief is correct or incorrect.\nFor instance, the Quran says: «إِنَّا وَجَدۡنَاۤ آبَاءَنَا عَلٰۤی أُمَّۃٍ وَّ إِنَّا عَلٰۤی آثَارِہِمۡ مُّقۡتَدُوۡنَ» (43/23)\nTranslation: Indeed, we found our fathers upon a certain belief, and indeed we are followers of their footsteps."
    },
    {
      "id": 1989,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Method / Custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "«شَرِیْعَۃ» refers to those divine laws that are changed according to necessity and circumstances. (4 verses: 5:48-42:13-42:21-45:48)",
      "d": "«شَرَع» means for something to emerge or become apparent, like «شَرَعَ الْبَعِیرُ عُنُقَہٗ» meaning the camel raised its neck so that it became visible (m. l). And «شَرَعَ لِلْقَوْم» means to establish a law for the people. And «شَرِیْعَۃ» means Islamic law, divine commands, regulation (manjad). And «شریعت» in the sense of Islamic laws is used. And «شریعت» means a clear and defined path, but its application is only on divine commands (muf). In our opinion, Imam Raghib's definition or meaning is more correct, that the word Sharia does not mean Islamic law but rather God's commands. Because the Prophet ﷺ said that the religion of all prophets is one, but in Sharia, changes occur according to time. Religion's status is like a father, and Sharia's status is like a mother. The Prophet ﷺ said: 'We prophets have the same father but different mothers.' So religion consists of unchanging divine commands from the beginning of creation, like belief in the unseen, God, His angels, His books, and the law of reward and punishment, etc. The commands of prayer, fasting, zakat, and hudud punishments, etc. And the example of Sharia's commands is like the number of prayers, their rak'ahs, and method of performance. Sharia was different for each prophet or messenger, but the religion remained one.\nFor instance, the Quran says: «ثُمَّ جَعَلۡنٰکَ عَلٰی شَرِیۡعَۃٍ مِّنَ الۡاَمۡرِ» (45/18)\nTranslation: Then We have set you on a clear path of the religion."
    },
    {
      "id": 1990,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Method / Custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "«مِنْھَاج» is the method of implementing Sharia commands. Clarity and expanse. (1 verse: 5:48)",
      "d": "«نَھَجَ الْاَمْرُ وَ الطَّرِیْق» means for the matter or path to be clear (manjad). And «مِنْھَاج» means a clear code of conduct (muf). That is, the method of implementing Sharia commands. And this method is also taught to the prophets by God, as proven by authentic hadiths that Angel Jibril came to the Prophet ﷺ for two days, teaching the five daily prayers: first day at the beginning of the time, second day at the end of the time, and said that prayer can be performed at any time between these. This is the minhaj. So the expanse and clarity of Sharia is called «منہاج» (faq l 11).\nFor instance, the Quran says: «لِکُلٍّ جَعَلۡنَا مِنۡکُمۡ شِرۡعَۃً وَّ مِنۡہَاجًا» (5/48)\nTranslation: For each of you We have appointed a divine law and a clear path."
    },
    {
      "id": 1992,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Method / Custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "«شَاکِلَۃ» is one's method of action due to individual inclination. (1 verse: 17:84)",
      "d": "«شَکَلَ» means to be similar or ambiguous. And «شَکُلَ الدَّایَۃ» means to hobble an animal (tying its legs). (manjad) And «اَلنَّاسُ أَشْکَالٌ وَّ أُلَّافٌ» means people are similar and affectionate towards each other (muf). So in the meaning of shape, two things are found: resemblance in form (shak shubah) and restraint. And «شَاکِلَۃ» is that particular style or method which a person adopts based on their natural inclination or tendency. As the Prophet ﷺ said: 'Each person is facilitated for what they were created for.' Meaning everyone is made easy for what they are created for. Example: one person prefers open charity so that others are encouraged to do the same, not showing off, but another person prefers charity in secret. Both methods are permissible and correct. The action is essentially the same, but the method of performing it differs according to each person's preference and expediency (maslahah). This is «شاکلہ».\nFor instance, the Quran says: «قُلۡ کُلٌّ یَّعۡمَلُ عَلٰی شَاکِلَتِہٖ» (17/84)\nTranslation: Say, 'Each acts according to their own manner.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1993,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "method; custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "«مَعْرُوْف» means goodness, kindness; a custom or practice that is liked in society and upon which there is no religious restriction (36 verses: 2:178-2:180-2:228-2:229-2:231-2:232-2:233-2:234-2:235-2:236-2:240-2:241-2:263-3:104-3:110-3:114-4:5-4:6-4:8-4:19-4:25-4:114-7:157-9:67-9:71-9:112-22:41-24:53-31:15-31:17-33:6-33:32-47:21-60:12-65:2-65:6)",
      "d": "«مَعْرُوْف» means goodness, kindness, and its opposite is «مُنْکَر», meaning anything disliked or forbidden by Shariah, evil, bad speech, bad deed. «عُرْف» means to recognize. And معروف is any method, custom, or practice that is well-known in society and considered good, even if there is no specific religious guidance regarding it, such as sitting respectfully before elders and addressing them with 'ji' or 'aap'. These are not commanded in Shariah but are good things. This is معروف.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لِلۡمُطَلَّقٰتِ مَتَاعٌۢ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ» ( 2/241 )\nTranslation: And divorced women also have a right to provision according to custom."
    },
    {
      "id": 1994,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Method / Custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "«خُلُق» refers to those habits or ways that have become deeply ingrained in one's nature. (2 verses: 26:137-68:4)",
      "d": "«خَلْق، خِلْقَت» means the form and shape that is perceived by the eye. And «خُلْق» relates to inner faculties (i.e., mental and spiritual powers not tangible, inner faculties, mental capabilities) and in the meaning of habits and character that are related to insight (intellect, understanding, consciousness) (muf). «خُلْق» and «خُلُق» mean nature, character, innate disposition (manjad). Or that habit and method which has become embedded with one's nature. And its plural is «أخلاق».\nFor instance, the Quran says: «إِنَّ هَذَاۤ إِلَّا خُلُقُ الْأَوَّلِینَ» (26/137)\nTranslation: This is nothing but the way of the ancients."
    }
  ],
  "431": [
    {
      "id": 1995,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Taunt",
      "hw": "طعنہ",
      "s": "«طَعَنَ» means to point out someone's flaw or weakness in a way that pierces like a thorn. (2 verses: 4:46-9:12)",
      "d": "«طَعَنَ» means to wound with a spear, horn, or any sharp, pointed thing (muf). Then this word is used for saying something about a person or in their face that hurts like a spear, i.e., to mention someone's fault in a way that becomes very offensive to them (muf).\nFor instance, the Quran says: «وَ إِن نَّکَثُوۡۤا أَیۡمَانَہُمۡ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ عَہۡدِہِمۡ وَ طَعَنُوۡا فِیۡ دِیۡنِکُمۡ فَقَاتِلُوۡۤا أَئِمَّۃَ الْکُفۡرِ» (9/12)\nTranslation: If they break their oaths after their treaty and attack your religion, then fight the leaders of disbelief."
    },
    {
      "id": 1996,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Slander / Find Fault",
      "hw": "طعنہ",
      "s": "The Arabic word «لَمَزَ» is used in all these meanings: to defame, to accuse, to slander, to disgrace, to find fault. (4 verses: 9:58, 9:79, 49:11, 104:1)",
      "d": "«لَمَزَ» means to find fault or to criticize someone's flaws. To persistently look for someone's faults and, for that purpose, to speak ill of them (backbiting) so that some weak point of theirs is exposed. Then to taunt or mock them about it. It also means to unjustly accuse someone of their actions. (Faqih)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ یَلۡمِزُوۡنَ الۡمُطَّوِّعِیۡنَ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ فِی الصَّدَقٰتِ» (9/79)\nTranslation: And those who find fault with the believers who give charity voluntarily."
    },
    {
      "id": 1997,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Slander / Find Fault",
      "hw": "طعنہ",
      "s": "«ھَمَزَ» means to taunt or mock through hints and allusions. (2 verses: 68:11, 104:1)",
      "d": "«ھَمَزَ» means to make a clicking sound with the tongue, to taunt, to backbite. «ھَامَز» means a great fault-finder. «ھَمَّاز» means one who finds faults and engages in taunting and revilement. «ھَمَزَاتِ الشَّیٰطِیْن» means the instigation and whispers of Satan. «ھَامِز» means one who does evil by making signs with eyes and hands while backbiting. «ھَمَزَ» also means to indicate with the eye, to cut, to strike, and to backbite. «ھَمَزَ الْفَرَس» means to make a horse prance. (Majma', Q.)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ہَمَّازٍ مَّشَّآءٍۭ  بِنَمِیۡمٍ» (68/11)\nTranslation: A taunting, scandal-mongering go-between."
    }
  ],
  "432": [
    {
      "id": 1998,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Put a Collar / Shackle",
      "hw": "طوق",
      "s": "«طَوَّقَ» can be used for a necklace, an ornament for the neck, a noose, an iron ring placed around the neck—it is applicable for all these. (1 verse: 3:180)",
      "d": "«طَوَّقَ» refers to anything that has a circular shape (M. L). A collar, an ornament for the neck, something that encircles. Its plural is «اَطْوَاق». (Majma') So, it means a necklace, a neck ornament, a noose, an iron ring placed around the neck—it can be used for all these. «اِطَّوَّقَ الْحَیَّۃ» means to coil around a snake. «طَوَّقَ» also means to adorn someone with a collar. (Majma')\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«سَیُطَوَّقُوۡنَ مَا بَخِلُوۡا بِہٖ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (3/180)\nTranslation: They will be shackled with what they hoarded on the Day of Resurrection."
    },
    {
      "id": 1999,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Put a Collar / Shackle",
      "hw": "طوق",
      "s": "«غُلّ» means handcuffs or a shackle. (9 verses: 5:64, 7:157, 12:23, 13:5, 17:29, 34:33, 36:8, 40:71, 76:4)",
      "d": "The plural of «غُلّ» is «اَغْلَال». This word is more general than «طوق». «غُلّ» refers to anything with which a person's limbs are bound and tied together (Muf). It applies to handcuffs, chains, and collars alike. «غَلَّ» means to put handcuffs or a shackle on. (Majma')\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«خُذُوۡہُ  فَغُلُّوۡہُ ثُمَّ  الۡجَحِیۡمَ  صَلُّوۡہُ» (69:30-31)\nTranslation: (The command will be given) 'Seize him and shackle him. Then throw him into the Blazing Fire.'"
    }
  ],
  "433": [
    {
      "id": 2000,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Covet / Have Strong Hope",
      "hw": "طمع",
      "s": "«طَمَعَ» means to have a strong hope or desire for something in one's heart. (12 verses: 2:75, 5:84, 7:46, 7:56, 13:12, 26:51, 26:82, 30:24, 32:16, 33:32, 70:38, 74:15)",
      "d": "«طَمَعَ» refers to a strong hope or desire arising in the heart for something (M. L). To have a strong hope.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ مَہَّدۡتُّ لَہٗ  تَمۡہِیۡدًا ثُمَّ  یَطۡمَعُ اَنۡ اَزِیۡدَ» (74:14-15)\nTranslation: And I have smoothed everything for him. Yet he desires that I should give more."
    },
    {
      "id": 2001,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Covet / Have Greed",
      "hw": "طمع",
      "s": "«حِرْص» is the term used when greed or desire for something becomes intense. (5 verses: 2:96, 4:129, 9:128, 12:103, 16:37)",
      "d": "«حِرْص» is when greed or desire for something intensifies (M. L). Be it for one's own benefit or for the benefit of another. (Muf) Greed.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنۡ تَحۡرِصۡ عَلٰی ہُدٰىہِمۡ فَاِنَّ اللّٰہَ  لَا یَہۡدِیۡ مَنۡ یُّضِلُّ» (16:37)\nTranslation: (O Prophet) if you are greedy for their guidance, then indeed Allah does not guide those whom He lets go astray."
    }
  ],
  "434": [
    {
      "id": 2003,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To Traverse (a Path)",
      "hw": "راستہ",
      "s": "The word «عَبَرَ» is specifically used for crossing a path, especially one involving water. The word «قَطَعَ» is general and is used for concluding matters and crossing tracts of land (fields, agricultural land, etc.). (1 verse: 4:43)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «عَبَرَ» is to pass through water, whether by swimming or using a vehicle or a bridge. «عَبْرُ النَّھْر» refers to the side of the river from which one descends to cross it. «عَبَرَ الْعَیْن» means tears to flow. «اَلْعَبَرَات» (plural) means tears. (Muf) Then its usage extended to mean traversing any kind of path, whether it has water or not.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَا جُنُبًا اِلَّا عَابِرِیۡ سَبِیۡلٍ حَتّٰی تَغۡتَسِلُوۡا» (4:43)\nTranslation: And (do not approach prayer while) in a state of major impurity, except those who are travelers on the road (and can perform dry ablution if water is unavailable)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2004,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To Traverse (a Path)",
      "hw": "راستہ",
      "s": "The basic meaning of «قَطَعَ» is to cut and separate. (12 verses: 2:27, 3:127, 5:38, 6:45, 7:72, 8:7, 9:121, 13:25, 22:15, 29:29, 59:5, 69:46)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «قَطَعَ» is to cut and separate. «قَطَعَ النَّھْر» means to cross the river. «قَطَعَ السَّبِیْل» means to rob travelers (i.e., one who ambushes travelers). «قَطَعَ الْوَادِی» means to traverse a valley. «قَطَعَ الْاَمْر» means to finalize a matter or to set a program for its execution. Thus, this word is more general than «عَبَرَ» in the meaning of traversing a path.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ لَا یَقۡطَعُوۡنَ وَادِیًا اِلَّا کُتِبَ لَہُمۡ» (9:121)\nTranslation: And they do not traverse a valley except it is written down for them.\nAt another place, the Divine command states:\n«مَا کُنۡتُ قَاطِعَۃً  اَمۡرًا حَتّٰی تَشۡہَدُوۡنِ» (27:32)\nTranslation: I will not decide any matter until you are present."
    }
  ],
  "435": [
    {
      "id": 2005,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "To Appear / Become Visible",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "«ظَھَرَ» means to become visible in such a way that the eyes can see it. This word is general. (27 verses: 2:85, 6:120, 6:151, 7:33, 9:8, 9:33, 9:48, 13:33, 18:20, 18:22, 18:97, 24:31, 30:7, 30:18, 30:41, 31:20, 34:18, 40:26, 40:29, 43:33, 48:28, 57:3, 57:13, 61:9, 61:14, 66:3, 72:26)",
      "d": "«ظَھَر» means the outer part of anything that can be seen by the eyes. Its opposite is «بَطَن», meaning the inner part of anything that cannot be seen by the eyes. (Muf) And «ظَھَرَ» means for something to become apparent, to manifest, to come forward, and to prevail.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ظَہَرَ الۡفَسَادُ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ بِمَا کَسَبَتۡ اَیۡدِی  النَّاسِ» (30:41)\nTranslation: Corruption has appeared on land and sea because of what the hands of people have earned.\nThen this word is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example, the Divine command states:\n«قُلۡ  اِنَّمَا حَرَّمَ رَبِّیَ الۡفَوَاحِشَ مَا ظَہَرَ  مِنۡہَا وَ  مَا بَطَنَ» (7:33)\nTranslation: Say, 'My Lord has only forbidden immoralities—whether they are open or secret.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2006,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "To Appear / Proclaim",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "«جَھَرَ» means to say something openly or to do something in such a way that others become aware of it. (14 verses: 2:55, 4:148, 4:153, 6:3, 6:47, 7:205, 13:10, 16:75, 17:110, 20:7, 21:110, 49:2, 67:13, 87:7)",
      "d": "«جَھَرَ» means to do something in such a way that others know about it. Its opposite is «اَسرَّ», meaning to conceal. (Muf)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِذۡ قُلۡتُمۡ یٰمُوۡسٰی لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لَکَ حَتّٰی نَرَی اللّٰہَ جَہۡرَۃً» (2:55)\nTranslation: And (O Jews) when you said, 'O Moses! We will not believe you until we see Allah openly.'\nHowever, this word is generally used for making the voice audible and for proclamation. (M. L) A loud prayer (Jahri) is one where the Imam recites aloud, i.e., the Fajr, Maghrib, and Isha prayers. A silent prayer (Sirri) is one where the Imam recites in a low voice that others cannot hear. «جَھَرَ» means to say something so that others hear it. (M. Q)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَا یُحِبُّ اللّٰہُ  الۡجَہۡرَ  بِالسُّوۡٓءِ مِنَ الۡقَوۡلِ اِلَّا مَنۡ ظُلِمَ» (4:148)\nTranslation: Allah does not like the public proclamation of evil except by one who has been wronged."
    },
    {
      "id": 2007,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "to become apparent",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "«بَدَا» means something becoming apparent without intention, which one tries to hide (9 verses: 3:118-6:28-7:22-12:35-20:121-39:47-39:48-45:33-60:4)",
      "d": "«بَدَا» means to become manifestly apparent, and in this, there is no involvement of anyone's intention or will. (Faqih, p. 237)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«بَلۡ بَدَا لَہُمۡ مَّا کَانُوۡا یُخۡفُوۡنَ مِنۡ  قَبۡلُ» ( 6/28 )\nTranslation: Rather, what they used to conceal before has become apparent.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«بَدَتۡ لَہُمَا سَوۡاٰتُہُمَا وَ طَفِقَا یَخۡصِفٰنِ عَلَیۡہِمَا مِنۡ وَّرَقِ الۡجَنَّۃِ» ( 7/22 )\nTranslation: Their private parts became apparent to them, and they began to cover themselves with leaves from Paradise.\nThen this word is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example, the divine command states:\n«ثُمَّ بَدَا لَہُمۡ مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِ مَا رَاَوُا الۡاٰیٰتِ لَیَسۡجُنُنَّہٗ حَتّٰی حِیۡنٍ» ( 12/35 )\nTranslation: Then after seeing the signs, it became clear to them that they should imprison him for a while."
    },
    {
      "id": 2008,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "to become apparent",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "«عَثَرَ» means the truth becoming apparent in the midst of statements (2 verses: 5:107-18:21)",
      "d": "«عَثَرَ» means to slip and fall (intransitive). And «عَثَرَ» is used in the sense of becoming apparent when someone tries to hide something by lying, but accidentally a truth slips out, revealing the reality.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ عُثِرَ عَلٰۤی اَنَّہُمَا اسۡتَحَقَّاۤ اِثۡمًا» ( 5/107 )\nTranslation: Then if it is found that both have earned sin."
    },
    {
      "id": 2009,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "to become apparent",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "«تَبَیَّنَ» means something becoming separate and apparent from another, and clear.\n«اِسْتِبَانَ» is a statement from which meanings become apparent (20 verses: 2:109-2:187-2:256-2:259-3:187-4:115-6:55-8:6-9:43-9:113-9:114-14:45-16:44-16:64-29:38-34:14-37:117-41:53-47:25-47:32)",
      "d": "«بَانَ» means something becoming separate and apparent from another, and clear (transitive). Thus, its meaning encompasses three concepts: (1) separation (i.e., distinction), (2) distance, (3) clarity (i.e., bright, apparent, and clear). And «تَبَیَّنَ» is also used in these meanings.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَدۡ تَّبَیَّنَ الرُّشۡدُ مِنَ الۡغَیِّ» ( 2/256 )\nTranslation: Guidance has become distinct from error.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ لِتَسۡتَبِیۡنَ سَبِیۡلُ  الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ» ( 6/55 )\nTranslation: And so that the path of the criminals becomes apparent."
    },
    {
      "id": 2010,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "to become apparent",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "«حَصْحَص» means something that was hidden due to pressure becomes apparent after the pressure is lifted (1 verse: 12:51)",
      "d": "«حَصْحَص» when something remains hidden due to some pressure and becomes apparent after the pressure is lifted (intransitive), then the word «حَصْحَص» is used.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَتِ امۡرَاَتُ الۡعَزِیۡزِ الۡئٰنَ حَصۡحَصَ الۡحَقُّ ۫ اَنَا رَاوَدۡتُّہٗ عَنۡ  نَّفۡسِہٖ» ( 12/51 )\nTranslation: The wife of the Aziz said, \"Now the truth has become clear. I had indeed tempted him.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 2012,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "to become apparent",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "«شُرَّعًا» means something becoming apparent by stretching out or rising (1 verse: 7:163)",
      "d": "«شَرَعَ» means something coming forward or becoming apparent by stretching out or rising. It is said «شَرَعَ الْبَعِیْرُ عُنُقَہٗ» meaning the camel stretched its neck so that it became noticeably visible. (transitive)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِذۡ تَاۡتِیۡہِمۡ حِیۡتَانُہُمۡ یَوۡمَ سَبۡتِہِمۡ شُرَّعًا» ( 7/163 )\nTranslation: When their fish came to them openly on the day of their Sabbath."
    },
    {
      "id": 2013,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "to make apparent",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "«اَظْھَرَ» means to make apparent (2 verses: 66:3-72:26)",
      "d": "«اَظْھَرَ» means to make apparent, very apparent, extremely clear.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«عٰلِمُ الۡغَیۡبِ فَلَا یُظۡہِرُ عَلٰۤی غَیۡبِہٖۤ اَحَدًا» ( 72/26 )\nTranslation: The Knower of the unseen, He does not reveal to anyone His unseen."
    },
    {
      "id": 2014,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "to make apparent",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "«اَبْدَا» means to make apparent (16 verses: 2:33-2:271-2:284-3:29-3:154-4:149-5:99-5:101-6:91-7:20-12:77-24:29-24:31-28:10-33:37-33:54)",
      "d": "«اَبْدَا» means to make apparent.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اَعۡلَمُ مَا تُبۡدُوۡنَ وَ مَا کُنۡتُمۡ تَکۡتُمُوۡنَ» ( 2/33 )8\nTranslation: And I know what you reveal and what you conceal."
    },
    {
      "id": 2015,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "To Manifest",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "«اَعْثَرَ» means to manifest, to inform, to make aware (1 verse: 18:21)",
      "d": "«اَعْثَرَ» means to manifest, to inform, to make aware.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ کَذٰلِکَ اَعۡثَرۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ لِیَعۡلَمُوۡۤا اَنَّ وَعۡدَ اللّٰہِ حَقٌّ» (18/21)\nTranslation: And thus We made it manifest to them so that they might know that the promise of Allah is true."
    },
    {
      "id": 2016,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "To Manifest",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "«جَھَرَ» means to manifest (14 verses: 2:55-4:148-4:153-6:3-6:47-7:205-13:10-16:75-17:110-20:7-21:110-49:2-67:13-87:7)",
      "d": "«جَھَرَ» means to manifest.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اَسِرُّوۡا  قَوۡلَکُمۡ  اَوِ اجۡہَرُوۡا بِہٖ ؕ اِنَّہٗ  عَلِیۡمٌۢ  بِذَاتِ الصُّدُوۡرِ» (67/13)\nTranslation: Whether you conceal your speech or manifest it, indeed, He is Knowing of that within the breasts."
    },
    {
      "id": 2017,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "To Manifest",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "«اَعْلَنَ» means to manifest (16 verses: 2:77-2:274-11:5-13:22-14:31-14:38-16:19-16:23-27:25-27:74-28:69-35:29-36:76-60:1-64:4-71:9)",
      "d": "«اَعْلَنَ» means to manifest. Its opposite is «اَسَرَّ». It is used for the expression of meanings (i.e., making something known), rarely for bodies (see Lisān al-ʿArab), and does not necessarily require a loud voice (see Fatḥ al-Bārī).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اللّٰہُ یَعۡلَمُ  مَا تُسِرُّوۡنَ وَ مَا  تُعۡلِنُوۡنَ» (16/19)\nTranslation: And Allah knows what you conceal and what you manifest.\nWords for 'manifest' include «ظَاھِر», «عَلَانِیَۃ», and «شُرَّعًا». Details have passed earlier."
    }
  ],
  "436": [
    {
      "id": 2019,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "to become incapable",
      "hw": "عاجز",
      "s": "«عَیَّ» to be unable to continue or redo work due to exhaustion (2 verses: 46:33-50:15)",
      "d": "«عَیَّ» means to become exhausted while working and unable to complete or to lack the strength to redo the same work, or to be unable to do it properly (manjad). And «دَاءٌ عِیَاءٌ» refers to an incurable disease (muf). «عَیَاءُ» is less severe than «عَجْز» (manjad) because initially, one had the capacity to work. For example, in the Quran: «اَفَعَیِیۡنَا بِالۡخَلۡقِ الۡاَوَّلِ ؕ بَلۡ ہُمۡ فِیۡ لَبۡسٍ مِّنۡ خَلۡقٍ جَدِیۡدٍ» (50:15) Translation: Have we become exhausted by the first creation? (No) but these people are in doubt about the new creation."
    }
  ],
  "437": [
    {
      "id": 2023,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "To Show Humility",
      "hw": "عاجزی",
      "s": "«خَضَعَ» means to be obedient and submissive to someone (1 verse: 26:4)",
      "d": "«خَضَعَ» means to be obedient and submissive to someone. «خُضُوْع» means submissive, obedient, compliant with commands, subordinate, very humble. (Mufradāt) And «خَاضِع» means humble. And «رَجُلٌ خَضِیْعٌ» refers to a person who has no regard for disgrace. (Maqayīs) In *khudhūʿ* (humility), the concept of humility is prominent, whereas in *khashāʿ* (fear), the effects on limbs and faculties are prominent.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنۡ نَّشَاۡ نُنَزِّلۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ  اٰیَۃً فَظَلَّتۡ اَعۡنَاقُہُمۡ  لَہَا خٰضِعِیۡنَ» (26/4)\nTranslation: If We will, We could send down upon them a sign from the heaven, and their necks would remain humbled to it."
    }
  ],
  "438": [
    {
      "id": 2026,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "scholar",
      "hw": "عالم",
      "s": "«اَحْبَار» the literate and people of the pen (4 verses: 5:44-5:63-9:31-9:34)",
      "d": "«اَحْبَار» is the plural of «حِبْر» and «حَبْر». It means ink as well as written text. What is written with is also «حِبْر» (like pen, ink, etc.), and what is written is also «حِبْر». And «حِبْر» and «حَبْر» refer to both the writer and the reader. And «اَحْبَار» also means those who read and write or literate people (m. l). And «اَحْبَار» in the Quran is used for both Jews and Christians' literate people. For example, in the Quran: «اِتَّخَذُوۡۤا اَحۡبَارَہُمۡ وَ رُہۡبَانَہُمۡ اَرۡبَابًا مِّنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ» (9:31) Translation: They have taken their scholars and monks as lords besides Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2027,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Scholar",
      "hw": "عالم",
      "s": "«قِسِّیْسِیْن» refers to Christian priests and teachers (1 verse: 5:82)",
      "d": "«قَسَّی الشَّیْ» means to search for and seek something. And «قَسِیْسَۃٌ» means to become a monk or priest (Munjid). «قِسِّیْسِیْن» is the plural of «قَسُّ», meaning Christian priests. Clergy. The rank of «قَسُّ» is between that of an «اُسْقُف» (bishop) and a «شَمَّاس» (deacon) (Munjid).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَتَجِدَنَّ  اَقۡرَبَہُمۡ مَّوَدَّۃً  لِّلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا الَّذِیۡنَ قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّا نَصٰرٰی ؕ ذٰلِکَ بِاَنَّ مِنۡہِمۡ قِسِّیۡسِیۡنَ وَ رُہۡبَانًا» (5/82)\nTranslation: And you will find the nearest in love to those who believe those who say, 'We are Christians.' That is because among them are priests and monks.\nNote: «اُسْقُف» is a senior priest, a Christian religious leader. «شَمَّاس» is a servant of the church whose rank is lower than a priest."
    }
  ],
  "439": [
    {
      "id": 2028,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "places of worship",
      "hw": "عبادت",
      "s": "«صَوَامِع» places of worship for monks (priests) (1 verse: 22:40)",
      "d": "«صَوَامِع» is the plural of «صَوْمِعَہ». It means monastery, places of worship for monks."
    },
    {
      "id": 2029,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "places of worship",
      "hw": "عبادت",
      "s": "«بِیَعٌ» place of worship for Christians (1 verse: 22:40)",
      "d": "«بِیَعٌ» is the plural of «بیعۃ». It means the place of worship for Christians."
    },
    {
      "id": 2030,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "places of worship",
      "hw": "عبادت",
      "s": "«صَلَوٰت» place of worship for Jews (1 verse: 22:40)",
      "d": "«صَلَوٰت» is the plural of «صَلَاۃ». It means places of worship for Jews. The places of worship for Jews are also called «کَنَائِس», plural of «کَنِیْسَہ» (vol. 275), but the Quran uses «صَلٰوۃ» instead of «کَنِیْسَہ» for Jewish places of worship, which is the common term for worship."
    },
    {
      "id": 2031,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "places of worship",
      "hw": "عبادت",
      "s": "«مَسَاجِد» places of worship for Muslims (6 verses: 2:114-2:187-9:17-9:18-22:40-72:18)",
      "d": "«مَسَاجِد» is the plural of «مَسْجِد». It means prostration place, the term used for Muslim places of worship. For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَوۡ لَا دَفۡعُ اللّٰہِ النَّاسَ بَعۡضَہُمۡ بِبَعۡضٍ لَّہُدِّمَتۡ صَوَامِعُ وَ بِیَعٌ وَّ صَلَوٰتٌ وَّ مَسٰجِدُ یُذۡکَرُ فِیۡہَا اسۡمُ اللّٰہِ کَثِیۡرًا» (22:40) Translation: And were it not for Allah's repelling people, some by means of others, the monasteries, churches, synagogues, and mosques wherein Allah's name is frequently remembered would have been demolished."
    }
  ],
  "440": [
    {
      "id": 2032,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Punishment; Chastisement",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«عَذَاب» means pain, punishment, recompense for evil deeds. It is general (306 verses: 2:7-2:10-2:49-2:85-2:86-2:90-2:96-2:104-2:114-2:126-2:162-2:165-2:166-2:174-2:175-2:178-2:201-3:4-3:16-3:21-3:56-3:77-3:88-3:91-3:105-3:106-3:176-3:177-3:178-3:181-3:188-3:191-4:14-4:18-4:25-4:37-4:56-4:93-4:102-4:138-4:147-4:151-4:161-4:173-5:33-5:36-5:37-5:41-5:73-5:80-5:94-5:115-6:15-6:30-6:40-6:47-6:49-6:65-6:70-6:93-6:124-6:157-7:38-7:39-7:59-7:73-7:141-7:156-7:164-7:165-7:167-8:14-8:32-8:35-8:50-8:68-9:3-9:34-9:39-9:52-9:61-9:68-9:74-9:79-9:90-9:101-10:4-10:15-10:50-10:52-10:54-10:70-10:88-10:97-10:98-11:3-11:8-11:20-11:26-11:39-11:48-11:58-11:64-11:76-11:84-11:93-11:103-12:25-12:107-13:34-14:2-14:6-14:7-14:17-14:21-14:22-14:44-15:50-16:26-16:45-16:63-16:85-16:88-16:94-16:104-16:106-16:113-16:117-17:10-17:57-17:58-18:55-18:58-18:87-19:45-19:75-19:79-20:48-20:61-20:71-20:127-20:134-21:46-22:2-22:4-22:9-22:18-22:22-22:25-22:47-22:55-22:57-23:64-23:76-23:77-24:2-24:8-24:11-24:14-24:19-24:23-24:63-25:19-25:37-25:42-25:65-25:69-26:135-26:156-26:158-26:189-26:201-26:204-27:5-27:21-28:64-29:10-29:23-29:29-29:53-29:54-29:55-30:16-31:6-31:7-31:21-31:24-32:14-32:20-32:21-33:8-33:30-33:57-33:68-34:5-34:8-34:12-34:14-34:33-34:38-34:42-34:46-35:7-35:10-35:36-36:18-37:9-37:33-37:38-37:176-38:8-38:26-38:41-38:61-39:13-39:19-39:24-39:25-39:26-39:40-39:47-39:54-39:55-39:58-39:71-40:7-40:45-40:46-40:49-41:16-41:17-41:27-41:50-42:16-42:21-42:26-42:42-42:44-42:45-43:39-43:48-43:50-43:65-43:74-44:11-44:12-44:15-44:30-44:48-44:56-45:8-45:9-45:10-45:11-46:20-46:21-46:24-46:31-46:34-48:16-48:17-48:25-50:26-51:37-52:7-52:18-52:27-52:47-54:16-54:18-54:21-54:30-54:37-54:38-54:39-57:13-57:20-58:4-58:5-58:15-58:16-59:3-59:15-61:10-64:5-65:8-65:10-67:5-67:6-67:28-68:33-70:1-70:11-70:27-70:28-71:1-72:17-73:13-76:31-78:30-78:40-84:24-85:10-88:24-89:13-89:25)",
      "d": "«عَذَبَ الرَّجُل» means he abandoned food and sleep due to intense thirst. And a person who does so is called «عَاذِبٌ» or «عَذُوْبٌ». And «عَذَاب» means to inflict severe pain (Mufradāt). This pain may be physical punishment or mental. And «تَعْذِیب» means to beat with a stick. Some scholars say it simply means to beat or to punish (Mufradāt).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ ۢ  ۬ ۙ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَکۡذِبُوۡنَ» (2/10)\nTranslation: And they will have a painful punishment because they used to deny."
    },
    {
      "id": 2033,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Punishment; Chastisement",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«عِقَاب» means the consequence of a bad deed and its necessary result (20 verses: 2:196-2:211-3:11-5:2-5:98-6:165-7:167-8:13-8:25-8:48-8:52-13:6-13:32-38:14-40:3-40:5-40:22-41:43-59:4-59:7)",
      "d": "«عَقَب» means the back part of the foot or the heel. And «عَاقَبَت» means the end result of everything. And «عَقَبَہٗ» means he followed behind him or pursued him (Mufradāt). The terms «عِقَاب», «عَقُوْبَۃ», and «مُعَاقبَۃ» are applied to the recompense for evil human deeds and the necessary outcome, i.e., the end result, of that evil deed.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ جٰدَلُوۡا بِالۡبَاطِلِ لِیُدۡحِضُوۡا بِہِ الۡحَقَّ فَاَخَذۡتُہُمۡ ۟ فَکَیۡفَ کَانَ عِقَابِ» (40/5)\nTranslation: And they argued by falsehood to refute the truth thereby. So I seized them. Then how was My punishment?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2034,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Punishment; Chastisement",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«بَأس» is a punishment that involves both hardship and tightness (26 verses: 2:177-2:214-4:84-6:42-6:43-6:147-6:148-7:4-7:5-7:94-7:97-7:98-12:110-16:81-17:5-18:2-21:12-21:80-27:33-33:18-40:29-40:84-40:85-48:16-57:25-59:14)",
      "d": "«بَأس» or «بَؤُسَ» carries the meaning of tightness and hardship in its connotations (Lisan al-ʿArab). In the Quran, this word has been used in three meanings: war, punishment, and calamity. And in all three, the concept of tightness and hardship is present. If it is used in the meaning of punishment or chastisement, it will come in the meaning of severe punishment.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَوۡلَاۤ  اِذۡ جَآءَہُمۡ بَاۡسُنَا تَضَرَّعُوۡا» (6/43)\nTranslation: Then why did they not supplicate when Our punishment came to them?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2035,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Punishment; Chastisement",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«نَکِیْر» is an unpleasant, severe, and unexpected punishment (5 verses: 22:44-34:45-35:26-42:47-67:18)",
      "d": "(The opposite of *nakrah* is *maʿrifah*.) It means strangeness (something that causes wonder, a strange thing or deed), foreignness. And «نُکْر» means unpleasant, vile, and irrational. And «مُنْکَر» refers to an act in which Allah's pleasure is not found. And «نَكُرَ الأَمْرُ» means for an affair to become very difficult (Lisan al-ʿArab). And «نَکِیْر» comes in all meanings: unpleasant thing, denial, and punishment. When its meaning is punishment, it refers to an unpleasant punishment that occurs unexpectedly.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ کُذِّبَ مُوۡسٰی فَاَمۡلَیۡتُ لِلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ ثُمَّ  اَخَذۡتُہُمۡ ۚ فَکَیۡفَ کَانَ نَکِیۡرِ» (22/44)\nTranslation: And Moses was denied. Then I granted respite to the disbelievers, then I seized them. And how was My punishment?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2036,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Punishment; Chastisement",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«نَکَال» is an exemplary punishment (3 verses: 2:66-5:38-79:25)",
      "d": "«نَکْل» means an iron collar, a fetter (Maqayīs al-Kalim), a muzzle (i.e., a rope tied in a collar), and anything by which a person is bound and forced to move. Its plural is «اَنْکَال». And «نَکَّلَ» means to shackle someone and to inflict an exemplary punishment on someone. And «نَکَال» means an exemplary punishment by looking at which others take a lesson (Mufradāt).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ السَّارِقُ وَ السَّارِقَۃُ فَاقۡطَعُوۡۤا اَیۡدِیَہُمَا جَزَآءًۢ بِمَا کَسَبَا نَکَالًا مِّنَ  اللّٰہِ» (5/38)\nTranslation: Cut off the hands of the male and female thief as a recompense for what they earned, [as] an exemplary punishment from Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2037,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Punishment. Penalty.",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«Wabal» Severe and continuous punishment (4 verses: 5:95-59:15-64:5-65:9)",
      "d": "«Wabl» in its meaning implies heaviness (i.e., burden) and severity is found. «Al-wabalu» and «al-wabilu» refer to such rain which is thick and heavy in droplets (mufradat) and «wablu bil-asaa» means struck with a staff and repeatedly struck. And «wabil» refers to the stick for washing clothes (m. q.) and «wabal» is such a penalty or recompense which is both severe and abundant.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اَلَمۡ  یَاۡتِکُمۡ نَبَؤُا  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡ قَبۡلُ ۫ فَذَاقُوۡا وَبَالَ  اَمۡرِہِمۡ وَ لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ  اَلِیۡمٌ» ( 64/5 )\nTranslation: Have you not received news of those who disbelieved before? They tasted the consequence of their deeds, and there will be a painful punishment for them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2038,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Punishment. Penalty.",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«Mathulat» Such a memorable punishment that its image comes to mind upon remembrance (1 verse: 13:6)",
      "d": "«Mathal» in its meaning implies two things: (1) comparing a thing with its counterpart, (2) a model according to which something is made. And «al-muthla» means establishing such an example of a memorable punishment that others may desist from committing crimes (m. l), or it means cutting off the nose, ears, or other limbs after killing (m. q). Its plural is «mathulat». And «mathula» means the image of a thing coming to mind. And «mathul» means such a punishment that upon remembering it, its image comes to mind. Example of a memorable punishment.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ یَسۡتَعۡجِلُوۡنَکَ بِالسَّیِّئَۃِ قَبۡلَ الۡحَسَنَۃِ وَ قَدۡ خَلَتۡ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمُ الۡمَثُلٰتُ» ( 13/6 )\nTranslation: And they hasten you towards evil instead of good, while exemplary punishments have already passed before them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2039,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "To punish",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«عَذَّبَ» punishment from Allah for sin (45 verses: 2:284-3:56-3:128-3:129-4:173-5:18-5:40-5:115-5:118-7:164-8:33-8:34-9:14-9:26-9:39-9:55-9:66-9:74-9:85-9:101-9:106-17:15-17:54-17:58-18:86-18:87-20:47-26:138-26:213-27:21-29:21-33:24-33:73-34:35-37:59-48:6-48:14-48:16-48:17-48:25-58:8-59:3-65:8-88:24-89:25)",
      "d": "«عَذَّبَ» punishment from Allah for sin.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَاۤ اَنَّ کَتَبَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمُ الۡجَلَآءَ لَعَذَّبَہُمۡ فِی الدُّنۡیَا ؕ وَ لَہُمۡ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ عَذَابُ النَّارِ» (59/3)\nTranslation: And if Allah had not decreed for them exile, He would have punished them in this world. And for them in the Hereafter is the punishment of the Fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 2040,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "To punish",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«نَکَّلَ» punishment from Allah for sin (1 verse: 4:84)",
      "d": "«نَکَّلَ» punishment from Allah for sin.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ اللّٰہُ اَشَدُّ بَاۡسًا وَّ اَشَدُّ تَنۡکِیۡلًا» (4/84)\nTranslation: And Allah is Severe in penalty and Severe in retribution."
    },
    {
      "id": 2041,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Different types of punishment",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«Husban» Punishment of fire or hail that burns vegetation to ashes (3 verses: 6:96-18:40-55:5)",
      "d": "«Husban» means counting, reckoning. And it means a small arrow (munjad). According to Imam Raghib, it refers to anything that is accounted for and then recompensed accordingly. Some say it means fire and punishment (mufradat). According to Ibn Faris, it also means throwing small arrows and hail (m. l). The following Quranic verse indicates its meaning as a punishment that burns vegetation to ashes, whether it be fire or hail.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡہَا حُسۡبَانًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ  فَتُصۡبِحَ  صَعِیۡدًا  زَلَقًا» ( 18/40 )\nTranslation: And He will send upon it a hailstorm from the sky, and it will become a bare plain."
    },
    {
      "id": 2042,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Different types of punishment",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«Hasib» Violent and fierce wind containing stones (4 verses: 17:68-29:40-54:34-67:17)",
      "d": "«Hasaba al-makaan» means to pave a floor with pebbles. And «ahsaba al-farsu» means the horse ran so much that pebbles flew into the air from its hooves (m. q). «Ardhun hasiyatun» means pebbly ground, and the valley «mu-hassab» is the valley from which pilgrims pick up pebbles. And «hasib» means such a violent and fierce wind that carries pebbles and stones into the air, and also a cloud that showers hail (munjad. m. q).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اَمۡ اَمِنۡتُمۡ مَّنۡ فِی السَّمَآءِ  اَنۡ یُّرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ حَاصِبًا» ( 67/17 )\nTranslation: Do you feel secure from Him who is in the heaven that He will send upon you a wind laden with stones?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2044,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Different types of punishment",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«Rijz» Disturbing punishment (7 verses: 2:59-7:134-7:135-7:162-29:34-34:5-45:11)",
      "d": "«Rijz» fundamentally implies agitation, i.e., restlessness and commotion (m. l). Rijzi poetry refers to poems recited during war to incite agitation (i.e., intensity, severity, force, and dominance). And «rijz» is such a punishment that disturbs and agitates the heart.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَاَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ ظَلَمُوۡا رِجۡزًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَفۡسُقُوۡنَ» ( 2/59 )\nTranslation: So We sent down upon those who did wrong a punishment from the heaven because they were defiantly disobedient."
    }
  ],
  "441": [],
  "442": [
    {
      "id": 2050,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Intellect. Intelligent person.",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "«حِجْر» is the intellect that safeguards from harm (3 verses: 6:138-25:22-25:53)",
      "d": "«حِجْر» means stone; and means every solid and hard thing that provides cover and protection; and also means intellect. And «حَجَرَ» means to encircle something and secure it, and to prevent others from intrusion. And «عَقْل» (intellect) is named «حِجْر» because it also prevents everything that is harmful (M. L.). And «حِجْر» also means obstacle, prohibition, intellect (Manjad). And «ذِیْ حِجْر» means possessor of intellect, or intelligent, or one who has intellect. (See details under 'cover').\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«ہَلۡ فِیۡ ذٰلِکَ قَسَمٌ  لِّذِیۡ حِجۡرٍ» ( 89/5 )\nTranslation: Is not this (the mentioned four things) worthy of being sworn by by those of intellect?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2051,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Intellect. Intelligent person.",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "«عَقْل» is the intellect that safeguards from harm and devises the choice of beneficial things (49 verses: 2:44-2:73-2:75-2:76-2:164-2:170-2:171-2:242-3:65-3:118-5:58-5:103-6:32-6:151-7:169-8:22-10:16-10:42-10:100-11:51-12:2-12:109-13:4-16:12-16:67-21:10-21:67-22:46-23:80-24:61-25:44-26:28-28:60-29:35-29:43-29:63-30:24-30:28-36:62-36:68-37:138-39:43-40:67-43:3-45:5-49:4-57:17-59:14-67:10)",
      "d": "«عَقَلَ» means to possess understanding and discernment; to be capable of realizing error (Manjad). And «عَقَلَ» also means to restrain and prohibit. And «عِقَال» is the fetter with which a camel's foot is tied (Muf). Thus, the function of intellect is to distinguish between benefit and harm; to adopt measures to avoid harmful things (Faq. L. 65); and to always be prepared for beneficial things and for accepting knowledge. Then, to reflect (Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا  لَوۡ  کُنَّا نَسۡمَعُ  اَوۡ نَعۡقِلُ مَا کُنَّا فِیۡۤ   اَصۡحٰبِ السَّعِیۡرِ» ( 67/10 )\nTranslation: And they will say, 'If we had only listened or used our intellect, we would not have been among the companions of the Blaze.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2052,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Intellect. Intelligent person.",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "«حِلْم» is the intellect that maintains control over one's nature and does not allow one to become enraged (16 verses: 2:225-2:235-2:263-3:155-4:12-5:101-9:114-11:75-11:87-17:44-22:59-33:51-35:41-37:101-52:32-64:17)",
      "d": "«حَلُمَ» means to forgive; to be forbearing. And «حَلِیْم» means one of a forbearing temperament; forbearing. And «حِلْم» means gravity; forbearance; i.e., to maintain such control over one's nature that one does not flare up even in a situation of anger. Its plural is «اَحْلاَم» (Muf Manjad). Thus, «حِلْم» is that intellect which maintains control over one's nature and does not allow it to become enraged, i.e., to flare up.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَمۡ  تَاۡمُرُہُمۡ  اَحۡلَامُہُمۡ  بِہٰذَاۤ   اَمۡ  ہُمۡ قَوۡمٌ  طَاغُوۡنَ» ( 52/32 )\nTranslation: Do their intellects command them to this, or are they a transgressing people?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2053,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Intellect. Intelligent person.",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "«اُولِی الْاَلْبَاب» are insightful and quick-understanding people; people who grasp the essence of a matter (16 verses: 2:179-2:197-2:269-3:7-3:190-5:100-12:111-13:19-14:52-38:29-38:43-39:9-39:18-39:21-40:54-65:10)",
      "d": "«اَلْبَاب» is the plural of «لُبّ». And «لُبّ» means the essence, the purest part of something (Faq L 66). And «لَبِیْب» means wise, intelligent. And «اُولِی الْاَلْبَاب» refers to people who, upon hearing something, can extract its essence; people of quick understanding.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِنَّ فِیۡ  ذٰلِکَ لَذِکۡرٰی لِاُولِی الۡاَلۡبَابِ» ( 39/21 )\nTranslation: Indeed, in these examples is a reminder for those of understanding."
    },
    {
      "id": 2054,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Intellect. Intelligent person.",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "«اُولِی الْاَبْصَار» are people who reflect and ponder (3 verses: 3:13-24:44-59:2)",
      "d": "«بَصُرَ» means to see with the eye, and also to see with the eye of the heart (i.e., spiritual insight) (see details under 'to see'). And «اُولِی الْاَبْصَار» means people of vision; people who reflect and ponder, whether they are quick-understanding or not.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَاعۡتَبِرُوۡا یٰۤاُولِی الۡاَبۡصَارِ» ( 59/2 )\nTranslation: O you who have vision! Take heed."
    },
    {
      "id": 2055,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Intellect. Intelligent person.",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "«اُولِی النُّھٰی» are people of profound insight who reach the depths of matters; people of sound opinion (2 verses: 20:54-20:128)",
      "d": "«نُھٰی» means to reach the extremity or limit of something (M. L.). And «نَھُوَ یَنْھُوْا» means to be extremely intelligent, to be perfect in intellect. And «نُھٰی» is the plural of «نُھْیَہ». And «اُولِی النُّھٰی» means people of profound insight; people of sound opinion; experienced (Manjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِنَّ  فِیۡ ذٰلِکَ لَاٰیٰتٍ  لِّاُولِی  النُّہٰی» ( 20/54)\nTranslation: Indeed, in that are signs for those of profound insight."
    }
  ],
  "443": [
    {
      "id": 2058,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Woman",
      "hw": "عورت",
      "s": "«اُنْثٰی» refers to every living female. When the mention is of the genus human being, this word will be used for woman (20 verses: 2:178-3:36-3:195-4:11-4:124-4:176-6:143-6:144-13:8-16:58-16:97-35:11-40:40-41:47-49:13-53:21-53:27-53:45-75:39-92:3)",
      "d": "«اُنْثٰی» means female (as opposed to male or masculine). This word is used for the female of all living beings. And similarly, when the genus human being is mentioned, it refers to woman.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«کُتِبَ عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡقِصۡاصُ فِی الۡقَتۡلٰی ؕ اَلۡحُرُّ بِالۡحُرِّ وَ الۡعَبۡدُ بِالۡعَبۡدِ وَ الۡاُنۡثٰی بِالۡاُنۡثٰی» ( 2/178 )\nTranslation: Retribution is prescribed for you in the case of murder: the free for the free, the slave for the slave, and the woman for the woman."
    }
  ],
  "444": [
    {
      "id": 2061,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Covenant. Promise. Agreement",
      "hw": "عہد",
      "s": "«وَعِیْد» if a promise is related to an evil outcome, it is called a threat; the time or place of the promise is called 'appointed time'. This is generally unilateral (6 verses: 14:14-20:113-50:14-50:20-50:28-50:45)",
      "d": "«وَعِیْد» is a promise that is based on evil and is related to a bad outcome. A threat; a warning. (M. L.)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَذَکِّرۡ بِالۡقُرۡاٰنِ مَنۡ یَّخَافُ وَعِیۡدِ» ( 50/45 )\nTranslation: So remind by the Quran whoever fears My threat.\n«مَوْعِدَۃ : مَوْعِدًا»: All these words derive from «وَعَدَ یَعِدُ». «وَعَدَ یَعِدُ وَعْدًا وَعِدَۃً وَ مَوْعِدًا وَ مَوْعِدَۃً». Their meaning is promise or to promise. (Manjad). They have been used in these meanings in the Quran.\n«مِیْعَاد»: It is an adverbial noun. In a temporal sense, its meaning is the time of the promise; in a locative sense, the place of the promise.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ لَوۡ  تَوَاعَدۡتُمۡ  لَاخۡتَلَفۡتُمۡ  فِی الۡمِیۡعٰدِ» ( 8/42 )\nTranslation: And if you had appointed a time, you would have differed in the appointed time.\nAt another place, the command of Allah Most High is:\n«رَبَّنَاۤ اِنَّکَ جَامِعُ النَّاسِ لِیَوۡمٍ لَّا رَیۡبَ فِیۡہِ ؕ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ  لَا یُخۡلِفُ الۡمِیۡعَادَ» ( 3/9 )\nTranslation: Our Lord, indeed You will gather the people for a Day about which there is no doubt; indeed, Allah does not fail in His promise."
    },
    {
      "id": 2063,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Covenant. Promise. Agreement",
      "hw": "عہد",
      "s": "«ذِمَّۃ» is essentially a type of covenant; making a covenant of protection (2 verses: 9:8-9:10)",
      "d": "«ذِمَّہ» is essentially a type of covenant, i.e., a covenant of fulfillment. It also means security; the responsibility of protection; making a covenant to give someone refuge. And 'Ahl al-Dhimmah' are those people who have been given security in return for jizya.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ اِنۡ  یَّظۡہَرُوۡا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  لَا یَرۡقُبُوۡا فِیۡکُمۡ  اِلًّا وَّ لَا ذِمَّۃً» ( 9/8 )\nTranslation: And if they overcome you, they will not respect any tie of kinship or any covenant in you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2064,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Covenant. Promise. Agreement",
      "hw": "عہد",
      "s": "«اِصْر» is a covenant that is burdensome or difficult due to its binding nature. Whether it is a custom/tradition or a religious law (3 verses: 2:286-3:81-7:157)",
      "d": "«اَصَرَ» means to tie a knot in something; and to forcibly restrain it (M. L.). «اِصْر» means a tied knot; a heavy burden; the bonds of custom/tradition; the limits and restrictions of religious law; a great responsibility. Thus, this word contains the concepts of covenant, burden, and confinement.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ یَضَعُ عَنۡہُمۡ اِصۡرَہُمۡ» ( 7/157 )\nTranslation: And he (the Prophet) removes from them their burden (i.e., the burdensome customs).\nAt another place, the command of Allah Most High is:\n«رَبَّنَا وَ لَا  تَحۡمِلۡ عَلَیۡنَاۤ  اِصۡرًا کَمَا حَمَلۡتَہٗ عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِنَا» ( 2/286 )\nTranslation: Our Lord, do not impose upon us a burden (i.e., the strictures and restrictions of the law) like that which You imposed on those before us."
    },
    {
      "id": 2065,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Covenant. Promise. Agreement.",
      "hw": "عہد",
      "s": "«مِیْثَاق» refers to a covenant that has been made stronger through writing or repetition (23 verses: 2:27-2:63-2:83-2:84-2:93-3:81-3:187-4:21-4:90-4:92-4:154-4:155-5:7-5:12-5:13-5:14-5:70-7:169-8:72-13:20-13:25-33:7-57:8)",
      "d": "«اَلَوَثَاق» refers to the rope or chain with which something is tied and bound. And «مِیْثَاق» is that covenant or pact or agreement which has been confirmed (i.e., made strong and firm) or has been put in writing, binding the parties to the agreement.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِلَّا الَّذِیۡنَ یَصِلُوۡنَ اِلٰی قَوۡمٍۭ بَیۡنَکُمۡ وَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ مِّیۡثَاقٌ» (4/90)\nTranslation: But those who have an alliance with a people between whom and you there is a treaty (of peace)."
    }
  ],
  "445": [
    {
      "id": 2067,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Cave",
      "hw": "غار",
      "s": "«غَار» is a place in mountains where a person can take refuge (2 verses: 9:40-9:57)",
      "d": "«غَوْر» also refers to low-lying ground and depth. «غَارَ الرَّجُل» means the person descended into low-lying ground. And «غَارَ الْمَاءُ» means the water went underground. «غَوْر» means deep. Deep thought. And «غَار» means such a low-lying place or depth where a person can take refuge, whether it is in a mountain or underground.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِذۡ ہُمَا فِی الۡغَارِ اِذۡ یَقُوۡلُ لِصَاحِبِہٖ لَا تَحۡزَنۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ مَعَنَا» (9/40)\nTranslation: When the two (the Prophet ﷺ and Abu Bakr) were in the cave, when the Prophet ﷺ said to his companion, \"Do not grieve; indeed Allah is with us.\"\nAnd «مَغَار ، غَوْر» is a locative noun (makanī) that comes in the meanings of cave. Its plural is «مَغَارَات».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَوۡ یَجِدُوۡنَ مَلۡجَاً اَوۡ مَغٰرٰتٍ اَوۡ مُدَّخَلًا لَّوَلَّوۡا اِلَیۡہِ وَ ہُمۡ یَجۡمَحُوۡنَ» (9/57)\nTranslation: If the hypocrites find a place of refuge (like a fortress) or caves or any hiding places, they will turn towards them, rushing headlong."
    },
    {
      "id": 2068,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Cave",
      "hw": "غار",
      "s": "«Kahf» Such a cave or hollow which is in a mountain and larger than a cave (6 verses: 18:9-18:10-18:11-18:16-18:17-18:25)",
      "d": "«Khauf» is the plural of «kahf». And «kahf» is more specific than a cave. «Kahf» refers to such a cave or hollow which is in a mountain and large (m. l). If it is small, it is called a cave (ghar) (m. q).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اَمۡ حَسِبۡتَ اَنَّ  اَصۡحٰبَ الۡکَہۡفِ وَ الرَّقِیۡمِ ۙ کَانُوۡا  مِنۡ  اٰیٰتِنَا  عَجَبًا» ( 18/9 )\nTranslation: Do you think that the companions of the cave and the scripture were wonders among Our signs?"
    }
  ],
  "446": [
    {
      "id": 2070,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To be heedless. To do.",
      "hw": "غافل",
      "s": "«سَھٰی» means to do another work instead of the original one due to forgetfulness or to add/subtract from it. It is not related to non-intentional acts (2 verses: 51:11-107:5)",
      "d": "«سَھٰی» means to forget. The heart turning to something else. And «سَھْو» means gentleness. Calmness (manjad). «سَھْو» essentially refers to the act that occurs due to heedlessness. If there is no intention involved in it, it is excusable. Like a madman swearing. And if it is done with intention, it is punishable and subject to accountability. (muf) Sajdah al-Sahw is a well-known term, i.e., the prostration performed as compensation for deficiencies in prayer acts due to the attention turning elsewhere. And this word does not pertain to the actions of a non-intentional person. (faql 78)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَوَیۡلٌ لِّلۡمُصَلِّیۡنَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ عَنۡ صَلَاتِہِمۡ سَاہُوۡنَ» (107/4,5)\nTranslation: So woe to those who pray, [but] who are heedless of their prayer."
    }
  ],
  "447": [
    {
      "id": 2073,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To overcome. To be. To do.",
      "hw": "غالب",
      "s": "«ظَھَرَ» means to appear with strength, to become manifest, to be an emerging force (27 verses: 2:85-6:120-6:151-7:33-9:8-9:33-9:48-13:33-18:20-18:22-18:97-24:31-30:7-30:18-30:41-31:20-34:18-40:26-40:29-43:33-48:28-57:3-57:13-61:9-61:14-66:3-72:26)",
      "d": "In the meanings of «ظَھَرَ», two things are fundamental: (1) to become apparent, to come forward, to be manifest. (2) strength. Then this word is used in both material and spiritual contexts.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ظَہَرَ الۡفَسَادُ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ» (30/41)\nTranslation: Corruption has appeared in the land and sea.\nAt another instance, the divine declaration is:\n«حَتّٰی جَآءَ الۡحَقُّ وَ ظَہَرَ اَمۡرُ اللّٰہِ» (9/48)\nTranslation: Until truth came and the command of Allah became dominant.\nThus, «ظَھَرَ» means the appearance of something with strength and power.\nAnd for \"to make dominant\", «اَظْھَرَ» is used.\nFor example: The divine declaration states:\n«ہُوَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَرۡسَلَ رَسُوۡلَہٗ بِالۡہُدٰی وَ دِیۡنِ الۡحَقِّ لِیُظۡہِرَہٗ عَلَی الدِّیۡنِ کُلِّہٖ» (9/33)\nTranslation: It is He who has sent His Messenger with guidance and the religion of truth to make it dominant over all religions."
    },
    {
      "id": 2074,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To overcome. To be. To do.",
      "hw": "غالب",
      "s": "«عَزَّ» means to be powerful, dominant, and strong (1 verse: 38:23)",
      "d": "The opposite of «عَزَّ» is «ذَلَّ», meaning to be subjugated and defeated. «عَزَّ» means to be in a position of authority, i.e., independent. Just as in today's rural setting, the landowner class is in authority (powerful) and the lowly or laborers are under them and weak. This is the correct meaning of «عَزِیْز» (Mighty) and «ذَلِیْل» (Humble).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَقَالَ اَکۡفِلۡنِیۡہَا وَ عَزَّنِیۡ فِی الۡخِطَابِ» (38/23)\nTranslation: And he said, \"Give me charge of her\" and he dominated me in conversation."
    },
    {
      "id": 2075,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To overcome. To be. To do.",
      "hw": "غالب",
      "s": "«غَلَبَ» means to gain superiority (ghalabah) with force and might (27 verses: 2:249-3:12-3:160-4:74-5:23-5:56-7:113-7:119-8:36-8:48-8:65-8:66-12:21-18:21-21:44-23:106-26:40-26:41-26:44-28:35-30:2-30:3-37:116-37:173-41:26-54:10-58:21)",
      "d": "In «غَلَبَ», the meanings of force, coercion, and intensity are found (m. l), i.e., to gain superiority and ascendancy by force. To conquer. And the one who is defeated is one who is forced by force and power. Defeated.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کَمۡ مِّنۡ فِئَۃٍ قَلِیۡلَۃٍ غَلَبَتۡ فِئَۃً کَثِیۡرَۃًۢ بِاِذۡنِ اللّٰہِ» (2/249)\nTranslation: How many a small group has overcome a large group by permission of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2076,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To overcome. To be. To do.",
      "hw": "غالب",
      "s": "«اِسْتَعْلٰی» means to desire to be elevated, to seek superiority and ascendancy (1 verse: 20:64)",
      "d": "«عَلٰی یَعْلو» means to be elevated. And «اِستعْلٰی» means to desire elevation. To seek superiority and ascendancy. And «تَعِلّیْ» means to show pride. This «تَعَلّی» and «استعلی» are generally used in bad connotations. And «عَلَا یَعْلُوْا» is used in both good and bad contexts. And «عَلِیَ یَعْلٰی» comes in a good meaning (muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَجۡمِعُوۡا کَیۡدَکُمۡ ثُمَّ ائۡتُوۡا صَفًّا ۚ وَ قَدۡ اَفۡلَحَ الۡیَوۡمَ مَنِ اسۡتَعۡلٰی» (20/64)\nTranslation: (Pharaoh said) \"So gather your devices and then come in a line. Indeed, he who succeeds today is he who is dominant.\""
    }
  ],
  "448": [
    {
      "id": 2080,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Dust",
      "hw": "غبار",
      "s": "«ھَبَاءً» refers to those fine particles of dust that are always scattered in the air and are not visible (2 verses: 25:23-56:6)",
      "d": "«ھَبْوَۃ» means fine particles of dust (m. l). Such fine particles of soil that are always present in the air and are not even visible.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ قَدِمۡنَاۤ اِلٰی مَا عَمِلُوۡا مِنۡ عَمَلٍ فَجَعَلۡنٰہُ ہَبَآءً مَّنۡثُوۡرًا» (25/23)\nTranslation: And We will advance toward what they did of deeds, so We will make them as scattered dust."
    }
  ],
  "449": [
    {
      "id": 2081,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "«سَخَطَ» means displeasure, dislike; this is the first degree of anger and it always occurs from a superior to an inferior (3 verses: 3:162-5:80-9:58)",
      "d": "«سَخَطَ» means to do something against someone's will. And «سَخْط» means dislike. This is the first degree of anger. (Fall 169) And it always occurs from a superior to an inferior. It can be said: «سَخَطَ الْاَمِیْر عَلَی الْحَاجِب» (the commander is displeased with the gatekeeper), but «سَخَطَ الْحَاجِبِ عَلَی الْاَمِیْر» (the gatekeeper is displeased with the commander) is not said. (Faqīh 106)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَفَمَنِ اتَّبَعَ رِضۡوَانَ اللّٰہِ کَمَنۡۢ بَآءَ بِسَخَطٍ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ» (3/162)\nTranslation: So is he who seeks the pleasure of Allah like him who has earned the anger of Allah?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2082,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "«Ghayz» Such anger that accelerates a person's blood circulation, and this is the second degree of anger; ghayz can also be directed towards oneself (9 verses: 3:119-3:134-9:15-9:120-22:15-25:12-33:25-48:29-67:8)",
      "d": "«Ghayz» is such anger that accelerates a person's blood circulation, and this is the second degree of anger (Fall 169). However, it does not involve retaliatory action nor has it been acted upon. And «ghayz» can be related to one's own self as well (Fiqh 06).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ الۡکٰظِمِیۡنَ الۡغَیۡظَ وَ الۡعَافِیۡنَ عَنِ النَّاسِ» ( 3/134 )\nTranslation: And those who suppress their anger and pardon the people."
    },
    {
      "id": 2083,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "«غَضَبٌ» when a person boils with anger and descends to revenge, whether small or big, it is not related to one's own self but to another's self (20 verses: 1:7-2:61-2:90-3:112-4:93-5:60-7:71-7:150-7:152-7:154-8:16-16:106-20:81-20:86-24:9-42:16-42:37-48:6-58:14-60:13)",
      "d": "«غَضَبٌ» according to the expert in etymology, this word is general and is used for every type of anger (cf. 169). But this definition does not seem correct. The Messenger of Allah ﷺ defined anger as follows:\n«اِتَّقُوْا مِنْ الْغَضَبِ فَاِنَّہٗ جُمْرَۃٌ تُوْقَدُ فِیْ قَلْبِ ابْنِ اٰدَمَ اَلَمْ تَرَوْا اِلَی انْتِفَاخِ اَوْدَاجِہٖ وَجُمْرَۃِ عَیْنَیْہِ»\nTranslation: Be cautious of anger, for it is a spark of fire that burns in the heart of the son of Adam. Do you not see how his veins swell and his eyes turn red?\nAnd obviously, this condition occurs when anger overwhelms a person and he descends to revenge. And Ibn al-Faris has given its meaning as «اَشَدّْ السَّخَط» meaning extreme anger (cf. ML). And the author of Munjid has written the meaning of «غَضِبَ» as to hold malice, to become angry (Munjid) and meaning «the intention to harm the one against whom anger is directed». And «غَضْب» always comes from others, i.e., it can be from a smaller person to a bigger one and from a bigger one to a smaller one (cf. 106).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّحۡلِلۡ عَلَیۡہِ غَضَبِیۡ فَقَدۡ ہَوٰی» ( 20/81 )\nTranslation: And whoever incurs My anger will indeed be destroyed."
    },
    {
      "id": 2084,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "«حَرْد» the quality of vengeful action due to anger; to pounce quickly or to devise a strategy for attack from a distance (i.e., to plan harm or trouble) (1 verse: 68:25)",
      "d": "«حَرِْد» means to be angry with someone. And «حَرَدَ» means to forbid (Munjid). «حَرْد» means overwhelmed by anger (i.e., in a rage) to swiftly attack someone or to devise a strategy for attack (cf. 169). «حَرْد» is actually not the name of any quality of anger, but the quality of that strategy or vengeful action which a person carries out while overcome by rage and fury. And according to Abu Halaal, the meaning of «حَرْد» is, in a state of anger, to distance oneself from the one against whom anger is directed and then bring it to completion (cf. 106).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَّ  غَدَوۡا عَلٰی حَرۡدٍ   قٰدِرِیۡنَ» ( 68/25 )\nTranslation: And they set out in the morning, attacking fiercely, as if they were powerful (over the cultivation)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2086,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To provoke anger",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "«غَاظَ» meaning to provoke anger (3 verses: 9:120-22:15-48:29)",
      "d": "«غَاظَ» meaning to provoke anger. Details have been discussed above.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ لَا یَطَئُوۡنَ مَوۡطِئًا یَّغِیۡظُ الۡکُفَّارَ» ( 9/120 )\nTranslation: And they do not tread any ground that would anger the disbelievers."
    },
    {
      "id": 2087,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To provoke anger",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "«اٰسَفَ» is used to denote provoking anger that creates wrath in the powerful and afflicts the weak with grief and sorrow (5 verses: 7:150-12:84-18:6-20:86-43:55)",
      "d": "«اَلْاَسْف»: such anger that is based on regret and grief. If the anger is towards the weak, it takes the form of rage and fury. And if towards the powerful, it merely results in internal grief and sorrow due to inability to act (Mufradat). And «اَسَفَ» means to lose something and to regret it (cf. ML). Also, «اٰسف» means to provoke anger; to make sad (Munjid).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ  اٰسَفُوۡنَا انۡتَقَمۡنَا مِنۡہِمۡ» ( 43/55 )\nTranslation: Then when they provoked Our anger, We took retribution from them."
    }
  ],
  "450": [
    {
      "id": 2089,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Grief",
      "hw": "غم",
      "s": "«حُزْن» such grief whose cause is an incurable calamity (11 verses: 3:176-5:41-6:33-10:65-12:13-12:84-12:86-21:103-31:23-36:76-58:10)",
      "d": "«حُزْن» means grief, and its opposite is «فَرَح» meaning happiness. «حُزْن» is the state of unrest in a matter. And it expresses a person's state of anxiety. When no remedy for anxiety is found, it takes the form of grief. And «حُزَن» also refers to calamities. Therefore, the grief that befalls due to a calamity is called «حُزْن».\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ ابۡیَضَّتۡ عَیۡنٰہُ مِنَ الۡحُزۡنِ» ( 12/84 )\nTranslation: And his (Jacob's) eyes turned white from grief."
    },
    {
      "id": 2091,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To be grieved; To grieve",
      "hw": "غم",
      "s": "«حَزَنَ» to grieve due to an incident or calamity (31 verses: 2:38-2:62-2:112-2:262-2:274-2:277-3:139-3:153-3:170-5:69-6:48-7:35-7:49-9:40-9:92-10:62-15:88-16:127-19:24-20:40-27:70-28:7-28:8-28:13-29:33-33:51-35:34-39:61-41:30-43:68-46:13-)",
      "d": "«حَزَنَ» means to grieve; to be sad (details have been discussed above).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«لَا تَحۡزَنۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ مَعَنَا» ( 9/40 )\nTranslation: Do not grieve; indeed, Allah is with us."
    },
    {
      "id": 2092,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To be grieved; To grieve",
      "hw": "غم",
      "s": "«اٰسٰی» to grieve over something that has slipped from the hand (i.e., lost) (2 verses: 7:93-57:23)",
      "d": "«اٰسٰی» means to grieve over the loss of something (Mufradat).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«لِّکَیۡلَا تَاۡسَوۡا عَلٰی مَا فَاتَکُمۡ وَ لَا تَفۡرَحُوۡا بِمَاۤ  اٰتٰىکُمۡ» ( 57/23 )\nTranslation: So that you do not grieve over what has escaped you, nor exult over what He has given you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2093,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To be grieved; To grieve",
      "hw": "غم",
      "s": "«اَبْلَسَ» such grief that befalls due to despair in a matter (5 verses: 6:44-23:77-30:12-30:49-43:75)",
      "d": "«اَبْلَسَ» means to become grieved due to intense despair (Mufradat) and also means to be unaware. Grieved and broken-hearted (Munjid), i.e., such grief that befalls due to having despaired in a matter. And Satan is called Iblis because he is despairing and broken-hearted from Allah's mercy.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ اِنۡ کَانُوۡا مِنۡ قَبۡلِ اَنۡ یُّنَزَّلَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنۡ  قَبۡلِہٖ لَمُبۡلِسِیۡنَ» ( 30/49 )\nTranslation: And before it was sent down upon them, from before it, they were in despair."
    },
    {
      "id": 2094,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To be grieved; To grieve",
      "hw": "غم",
      "s": "«اِبْتَئَسَ» for grief to befall due to someone else's unpleasant and unbearable act (2 verses: 11:36-12:69)",
      "d": "In «بِئْس» are found meanings of severity and unpleasantness (Mufradat). And «اِبْتَئَسَ» means to find something unpleasant and to grieve over it (Munjid).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ اُوۡحِیَ  اِلٰی نُوۡحٍ اَنَّہٗ  لَنۡ یُّؤۡمِنَ مِنۡ قَوۡمِکَ اِلَّا مَنۡ قَدۡ اٰمَنَ فَلَا تَبۡتَئِسۡ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَفۡعَلُوۡنَ» ( 11/36 )\nTranslation: And it was revealed to Noah that none of your people will believe except he who has already believed. So do not grieve over what they have been doing."
    }
  ],
  "451": [
    {
      "id": 2098,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "to ponder",
      "hw": "غور",
      "s": "«اِدَّکَرَ» to recall a matter, think and reflect, then derive lessons from it (7 verses: 12:45-54:15-54:17-54:22-54:32-54:40-54:51)",
      "d": "«ذَکَرَ» means to remember something. To retain. And «ذَکَّر» means to remind someone of something in such a way that they derive lessons from it. And «اِدَّکَرَ» means to bring something to mind oneself. To bring into the mind (sing.). To pay attention and ponder over it so that one derives lessons oneself.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ یَسَّرۡنَا الۡقُرۡاٰنَ  لِلذِّکۡرِ  فَہَلۡ مِنۡ مُّدَّکِرٍ» ( 54/17 )\nTranslation: And We have made the Quran easy to understand. So is there anyone who will ponder and reflect?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2099,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "to ponder",
      "hw": "غور",
      "s": "«اِسْتَنْبَط» to deeply contemplate a known matter and derive subsidiary issues or results (1 verse: 4:83)",
      "d": "«اِسْتَنْبَط»: After digging a well, the first water drawn is called «نَبْط». And «نَبْط» means to draw water from the bottom of a well. And «اِسْتَنْبَاط» comes in the meaning of extraction (taking out) (sing.). And «اِسْتَنْبَط» means to reveal after concealment. To extract by choice. To invent. For a jurist to derive something from their own understanding and reasoning (source). «اِسْتَنْبَاط» is actually a type of ijtihad or tafaqquh where one deeply contemplates within known knowledge, reaches its depths, and derives subsidiary issues or results from it.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَوۡ رَدُّوۡہُ  اِلَی الرَّسُوۡلِ وَ اِلٰۤی اُولِی الۡاَمۡرِ مِنۡہُمۡ لَعَلِمَہُ الَّذِیۡنَ یَسۡتَنۡۢبِطُوۡنَہٗ مِنۡہُمۡ» ( 4/83 )\nTranslation: And if they referred the matter to their Messenger or to those in authority among them, those who investigate it from them would have known it."
    }
  ],
  "452": [
    {
      "id": 2101,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "benefit; to give benefit",
      "hw": "فائدہ",
      "s": "«مَتَّعَ» to take benefit from anything that a living being uses to sustain life (33 verses: 2:126-2:196-2:236-4:24-6:128-9:69-10:98-11:3-11:48-11:65-14:30-15:3-15:88-16:55-20:131-21:44-25:18-26:205-26:207-28:61-29:66-30:34-31:24-33:16-33:28-33:49-37:148-39:8-43:29-46:20-47:12-51:43-77:46)",
      "d": "«مَتَاع» means every thing from the provisions of life from which a human or any living being derives benefit to sustain life is «مَتَاع». Its plurals are «أَمْتِعَة» and «مَتَّع» means to benefit from such provisions. \nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اَخۡرَجَ  مِنۡہَا مَآءَہَا وَ  مَرۡعٰہَا وَ الۡجِبَالَ  اَرۡسٰہَا مَتَاعًا  لَّکُمۡ  وَ  لِاَنۡعَامِکُمۡ» ( 79/31،32،33 )\nTranslation: He brought forth from it its water and its pasture and made the mountains its anchors. All this He made for you and your cattle to benefit from.\nAnd «مَتَّعَ» means to give someone such provisions from which they can benefit. To provide benefit.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَّ مَتِّعُوۡہُنَّ ۚ عَلَی الۡمُوۡسِعِ قَدَرُہٗ  وَ عَلَی الۡمُقۡتِرِ قَدَرُہٗ» ( 2/236 )\nTranslation: But give them (the divorced women) something according to custom: the wealthy according to his means and the poor according to his means. This is a duty upon the good.\nAnd «تَمَتَّعَ» means to derive benefit for oneself. To enjoy.\nFor example: The Divine Command says:\n«تَمَتَّعُوۡا فِیۡ  دَارِکُمۡ ثَلٰثَۃَ  اَیَّامٍ» ( 11/65 )\nTranslation: Enjoy yourselves in your homes for three days."
    },
    {
      "id": 2102,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "benefit; to give benefit",
      "hw": "فائدہ",
      "s": "«رَبِحَ» to gain profit from trade (1 verse: 2:16)",
      "d": "«رَبِحَ» is the profit gained from buying and selling (sing.). To have profit in trade. Its opposite is «خَسِرَ» meaning loss.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَمَا رَبِحَتۡ تِّجَارَتُہُمۡ وَ مَا کَانُوۡا مُہۡتَدِیۡنَ» ( 2/16 )\nTranslation: So their trade has not profited them, nor were they guided."
    },
    {
      "id": 2103,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "benefit; to give benefit",
      "hw": "فائدہ",
      "s": "«مَاٰرِب» necessities and means to fulfill them (2 verses: 20:18-24:31)",
      "d": "«اَرْب» means an urgent need without which sustenance is not possible. And effort is made to obtain it (sing.). It also means need, necessity, extremity (source). And «مَارِب ، مَارِبَۃ ، مَارَبَہ» and «مَارُبَۃ» mean need and its fulfillment. And its plural is «مَارَب». And it also means that thing through which the need is fulfilled.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«قَالَ ہِیَ عَصَایَ ۚ اَتَوَکَّؤُا عَلَیۡہَا وَ اَہُشُّ بِہَا عَلٰی غَنَمِیۡ وَ لِیَ فِیۡہَا مَاٰرِبُ  اُخۡرٰی» ( 20/18 )\nTranslation: Moses said, 'It is my staff. I lean on it and beat down leaves with it for my sheep, and I have other needs for it.'"
    }
  ],
  "453": [
    {
      "id": 2105,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "to be granted victory; to grant",
      "hw": "فتح",
      "s": "«اَظْفَرَ» a victory where the enemy's chest is pierced with nails, i.e., victory and subsequent dominance (1 verse: 48:24)",
      "d": "«ظَفَر» means the nails of a human or animal. And «ظَفَرَ فُلَانٌ» means so-and-so pierced his nails into it or gained victory (sing.). And «اَظْفَرَ» means to grant such a victory that the enemy's chest is pierced with nails. That is, victory and subsequent dominance over the enemy. In the words of Ibn al-Faris, it 'indicates subjugation, triumph, and conquest.'\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ کَفَّ  اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ  عَنۡکُمۡ وَ اَیۡدِیَکُمۡ عَنۡہُمۡ بِبَطۡنِ مَکَّۃَ  مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ اَنۡ  اَظۡفَرَکُمۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ» ( 48/24 )\nTranslation: And He is the One Who restrained their hands from you and your hands from them after He granted you victory over them in the valley of Mecca."
    }
  ],
  "454": [
    {
      "id": 2106,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "prosperity; ease",
      "hw": "فراخی",
      "s": "«مَیْسَرَۃ» to pass through easily after hardship (1 verse: 2:280)",
      "d": "«یُسْر» means ease, and its opposite is «عُسْر» meaning hardship. And «مَیْسَرَۃ» means a time of ease. A time when a person can manage their livelihood easily from a financial perspective.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ اِنۡ کَانَ ذُوۡ عُسۡرَۃٍ فَنَظِرَۃٌ اِلٰی مَیۡسَرَۃٍ» ( 2/280 )\nTranslation: And if (the debtor) is in hardship, then grant him respite until a time of ease."
    },
    {
      "id": 2107,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "prosperity; ease",
      "hw": "فراخی",
      "s": "«طَوْل» to be provided with means of livelihood (3 verses: 4:25-9:86-40:3)",
      "d": "«طُوْل» means length, extension, and (temporal) length. And the word «طَوْل» comes in the meaning of bounty and favor which is not merely temporary (sing.). And «طَوْل» means sustenance and expenses for livelihood. Bounty. Grant. Affluence (source).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ مَنۡ لَّمۡ یَسۡتَطِعۡ مِنۡکُمۡ طَوۡلًا اَنۡ یَّنۡکِحَ الۡمُحۡصَنٰتِ الۡمُؤۡمِنٰتِ فَمِنۡ مَّا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ مِّنۡ فَتَیٰتِکُمُ الۡمُؤۡمِنٰتِ » ( 4/25 )\nTranslation: And whoever among you cannot afford to marry free, believing women, then (marry) from those whom your right hands possess of believing slave girls.\nAnd the meaning of «اُوْلُوا الطَّوْل» is those people who can manage their livelihood with ease (9/86)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2108,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "prosperity; ease",
      "hw": "فراخی",
      "s": "«بَسْطَۃ» expansion and spaciousness, whether in something (22 verses: 2:245-2:247-5:11-5:28-6:93-7:69-13:14-13:26-17:29-17:30-18:18-28:82-29:62-30:37-30:48-34:36-34:39-39:52-42:12-42:27-60:2-71:19)",
      "d": "«بَسَطَ» means to open and to spread. Its opposite is also «قَبْض» and «قَدْر». And «بَسْطَۃً» means spaciousness (of place), expansion, and abundance (sing.). Whether this expansion is in wealth and property or in any other thing. This word is used in both material and spiritual contexts.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ زَادَہٗ بَسۡطَۃً فِی الۡعِلۡمِ وَ الۡجِسۡمِ» ( 2/247 )\nTranslation: And Allah has preferred them over you and increased them abundantly in knowledge and physique.\nAt another place, the Divine Command says:\n«اَللّٰہُ یَبۡسُطُ الرِّزۡقَ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ مِنۡ عِبَادِہٖ  وَ یَقۡدِرُ  لَہٗ» ( 29/62 )\nTranslation: Allah extends provision for whom He wills of His servants and restricts it for whom He wills."
    },
    {
      "id": 2111,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "to be spacious; to expand",
      "hw": "فراخی",
      "s": "«وَسِعَ» to have capacity and spaciousness in place and state (27 verses: 2:115-2:233-2:236-2:247-2:255-2:261-2:268-2:286-3:73-4:97-4:100-4:130-5:54-6:80-6:147-6:152-7:42-7:89-7:156-20:98-23:62-24:32-29:56-39:10-40:7-51:47-53:32)",
      "d": "«وَسِعَ» applies to both place and state. It means prosperity, spaciousness, expansion, capacity (CAPACITY).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَسِعَ کُرۡسِیُّہُ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ» ( 2/255 )\nTranslation: His Kursi (Throne) encompasses the heavens and the earth.\nAlso, the Divine Command says:\n«لَا یُکَلِّفُ اللّٰہُ نَفۡسًا اِلَّا وُسۡعَہَا» ( 2/286 )\nTranslation: Allah does not burden a soul beyond its capacity.\nAnd «اَوْسَعَ» means to be very wealthy. And «اَوْسَعَ الْمَوْضَعَ» means to make a place spacious (source).\nFor example: The Divine Command says:\n«وَ السَّمَآءَ  بَنَیۡنٰہَا بِاَیۡىدٍ وَّ اِنَّا لَمُوۡسِعُوۡنَ» ( 51/47 )\nTranslation: And the heaven We constructed with might, and indeed, We are its expanders."
    },
    {
      "id": 2112,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "to spread out",
      "hw": "فراخی",
      "s": "«تَفَسَّحَ» to sit openly in such a way that space becomes available for others (1 verse: 58:11)",
      "d": "«فَسَحَ» means to take wide steps. And «تَفَسَّحَ فِی الْمَجْلِس» means to give space in the gathering. That is, to sit openly in such a way that space becomes available for others (source). For example, in the Quran it is: «اِذَا  قِیۡلَ  لَکُمۡ تَفَسَّحُوۡا فِی  الۡمَجٰلِسِ فَافۡسَحُوۡا یَفۡسَحِ اللّٰہُ  لَکُمۡ» ( 58/11 ) Translation: When it is said to you, 'Sit openly in the gathering,' then sit openly, and Allah will grant you spaciousness."
    }
  ],
  "455": [
    {
      "id": 2113,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "angel",
      "hw": "فرشتہ",
      "s": "«مَلَک» a messenger angel (86 verses: 2:30-2:31-2:34-2:98-2:102-2:161-2:177-2:210-2:248-2:285-3:18-3:39-3:42-3:45-3:80-3:87-3:124-3:125-4:97-4:136-4:166-4:172-6:8-6:9-6:50-6:93-6:111-6:158-7:11-7:20-8:9-8:12-8:50-11:12-11:31-12:31-13:13-13:23-15:7-15:8-15:28-15:30-16:2-16:28-16:32-16:33-16:49-17:40-17:61-17:92-17:95-18:50-20:116-21:103-22:75-23:24-25:7-25:21-25:22-25:25-32:11-33:43-33:56-34:40-35:1-37:150-38:71-38:73-39:75-41:14-41:30-42:5-43:19-43:53-43:60-47:27-53:26-53:27-66:4-66:6-69:17-70:4-74:31-78:38-89:22-97:4)",
      "d": "The plural of «مَلَک» is «مَلٰئِکَۃ». And its root is «لأک», which means to convey a message. «اَلْاَکَۃُ اِلٰی فُلَانٍ» means to convey a message to someone. And «اَلِکْنِیْ» means to give a message from me. And «مَلَأک» and «مَلَک» mean messenger angel (source), and «مَلَک» is used in the sense of angel in Islamic terminology, and it is not specified that it must be a messenger. Angels are appointed by Allah to manage the universe. The angel of clouds, the angel of death. For heaven and hell angels, the words «مَلَک» and «مَلٰئِکَۃ» are used for all, even though they are not messengers. And sometimes when a message from Allah occurs in the form of a hidden call or a hidden caller (i.e., one who calls from the unseen), then the plural form «مَلٰئِکَۃ» is used instead of «مَلَک». For example, in the Quran it is: «اِذۡ قَالَتِ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ یٰمَرۡیَمُ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُبَشِّرُکِ بِکَلِمَۃٍ مِّنۡہُ ٭ۖ اسۡمُہُ الۡمَسِیۡحُ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ» ( 3/45 ) Translation: And when the angels said, 'O Mary! Allah gives you glad tidings of a word from Him, whose name is the Messiah, Jesus, son of Mary.' The reason why the plural form «مَلٰئِکَۃ» is used instead of «مَلَک» at this place or similar places is beyond human comprehension."
    },
    {
      "id": 2114,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "angel",
      "hw": "فرشتہ",
      "s": "«رُوْح» the angel who is appointed by Allah to convey messages to the prophets (20 verses: 2:87-2:253-4:171-5:110-15:29-16:2-16:102-17:85-19:17-21:91-26:193-32:9-38:72-40:15-42:52-58:22-66:12-70:4-78:38-97:4)",
      "d": "Just as the knowledge of the reality of 'spirit' has been given very little to humans, similarly, comprehending the meanings of 'spirit' is beyond human capacity. The word 'spirit' has been used in the Quran to mean mercy, and also to mean revelation and the Quran, and also to mean angel. The angel who is specifically appointed by Allah to convey messages to the prophets is named Jibreel. Allah has called him by the titles of 'spirit', 'the trustworthy spirit', and 'the Messenger'. And the angel who came to Maryam (peace be upon her) and gave Allah's message in human form is referred to as 'spirit' in Surah Maryam, and in Surah Al-Imran, the plural form «مَلٰئِکَۃ» is used instead of «مَلَک». The commentators think that this spirit was Jibreel. It is also possible and agreed that Maryam (peace be upon her) was not a prophetess. Nevertheless, Jibreel (peace be upon him) or some other angel or angels came to her. Conveyed Allah's message and conversed with her. This message was related to Maryam herself. As for conveying to others, that is out of the question; this message had no connection with others that are necessary for matters of prophethood and messengership. For example, in the Quran it is: «فَاَرۡسَلۡنَاۤ  اِلَیۡہَا رُوۡحَنَا فَتَمَثَّلَ لَہَا بَشَرًا سَوِیًّا» ( 19/17 ) Translation: We sent to her Our angel, and he appeared to her as a well-proportioned man."
    }
  ],
  "456": [
    {
      "id": 2115,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "difference",
      "hw": "فرق",
      "s": "«بُعْد» is used for the distance of separation and for difference (9 verses: 9:42-11:44-11:60-11:68-11:95-21:101-23:41-23:44-43:38)",
      "d": "«بَعِد» and «بَعُد» mean to be distant. And the original meaning of «بُعْد» is distance. However, this word is also used in supplications for distance and curse meanings. And when this word is used as an adverb of place, it means difference or distance. For example, in the Quran it is: «حَتّٰۤی اِذَا جَآءَنَا قَالَ یٰلَیۡتَ بَیۡنِیۡ وَ بَیۡنَکَ بُعۡدَ الۡمَشۡرِقَیۡنِ فَبِئۡسَ الۡقَرِیۡنُ» ( 43/38 ) Translation: Until when he comes to us, he will say, 'I wish there were between me and you the distance of the two easts, for an evil companion you are.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2116,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "difference",
      "hw": "فرق",
      "s": "«تَفَاوُت» difference due to two things having different attributes. Incompatibility (1 verse: 67:3)",
      "d": "«تَفَاوُت» means difference, discrepancy, deficiency and excess. And its opposite is «اِسْتَوَاء» meaning evenness, equality, being equivalent. And «اِسْتَوَاء فَاتَ الْاَمْر» means that a matter is past and cannot return. And «تَفَاوَتَ الشَّیْئَیْن» means that two things are different from each other, separate, and incompatible (source). And this word always comes with bad meanings. And «فَات» means that a thing is so far from a person that obtaining it becomes difficult for him. And «تَفَاوُت» means that the attributes of two things are different. So to speak, each attribute negates the other (Muf). For example, in the Quran it is: «مَا تَرٰی فِیۡ  خَلۡقِ الرَّحۡمٰنِ مِنۡ  تَفٰوُتٍ» ( 67/3 ) Translation: You will not see any discrepancy in the creation of the Most Merciful. That is, there is perfect compatibility and harmony in all things of the universe."
    }
  ],
  "457": [
    {
      "id": 2118,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "faction",
      "hw": "فرقہ",
      "s": "«فَرِیْق» that faction for which there is also another faction present or mentioned (29 verses: 2:75-2:85-2:87-2:100-2:101-2:146-2:188-3:23-3:78-3:100-4:77-5:70-6:81-7:30-8:5-9:107-9:117-11:24-16:54-19:73-23:109-24:47-24:48-27:45-30:33-33:13-33:26-34:20-42:7)",
      "d": "«فِرْقَۃ» and «فَرِیْق» are almost synonymous. «فَرِیْق» is used when there is another faction present or mentioned. For example, in the Quran it is: «فَرِیۡقٌ فِی الۡجَنَّۃِ  وَ فَرِیۡقٌ فِی السَّعِیۡرِ» ( 42/7 ) Translation: One faction will be in Paradise and another in the Blaze. At another place, it is stated: «اَیُّ الۡفَرِیۡقَیۡنِ خَیۡرٌ  مَّقَامًا وَّ اَحۡسَنُ نَدِیًّا» ( 19/73 ) Translation: Which of the two factions has a better abode and a more pleasant assembly?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2119,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "faction",
      "hw": "فرقہ",
      "s": "«طَائِفَۃ» a small group of people with the same religion and opinion (19 verses: 3:69-3:72-3:122-3:154-4:81-4:102-4:113-6:156-7:87-8:7-9:66-9:83-9:122-24:2-28:4-33:13-49:9-61:14-73:20)",
      "d": "«طَائِفَۃ» means people of one opinion and religion (source). This word can apply to even the smallest group or an individual. As some commentators say regarding this verse: The divine command is: «وَ اِنۡ طَآئِفَتٰنِ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ اقۡتَتَلُوۡا فَاَصۡلِحُوۡا بَیۡنَہُمَا» ( 49/9 ) Translation: And if two factions of the believers fight, then reconcile between them. In this verse, the word «طَائِفَۃ» is applied to an individual."
    },
    {
      "id": 2120,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "faction",
      "hw": "فرقہ",
      "s": "«زُمَر» meaning small squads, groups (2 verses: 39:71-39:73)",
      "d": "«زُمَر» is the plural of «زُمْرَہ», meaning a group. When a large crowd or army divides into small squads or groups for movement, such groups are called «زُمُر» (see details under 'group'). For example, in the Quran it is: «وَ سِیۡقَ الَّذِیۡنَ اتَّقَوۡا رَبَّہُمۡ  اِلَی الۡجَنَّۃِ زُمَرًا» ( 39/73 ) Translation: And those who feared their Lord will be driven to Paradise in groups."
    },
    {
      "id": 2121,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "faction",
      "hw": "فرقہ",
      "s": "«شِیْعَۃ» a party or faction based on difference of belief (10 verses: 6:65-6:159-15:10-19:69-28:4-28:15-30:32-34:54-37:87-54:51)",
      "d": "«شِیْعَۃ» means party. Faction. Political faction. People from whom a person derives strength and who surround him (Muf). Followers and helpers (source). Such parties or factions are generally based on difference of belief. For example, in the Quran it is: «فَوَجَدَ فِیۡہَا رَجُلَیۡنِ یَقۡتَتِلٰنِ ٭۫ ہٰذَا مِنۡ شِیۡعَتِہٖ وَ ہٰذَا مِنۡ عَدُوِّہٖ» ( 28/15 ) Translation: Then he found in the city two men fighting, this one from his faction and that one from his enemy's faction. And the plural of «شِیْعَۃ» is both «شِیَعًا» and «اَشْیَاعَ». «اَشْیَاع» means people with the same habits and customs, whether past or present. Alike. For example, in the Quran it is: «وَ حِیۡلَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ وَ بَیۡنَ مَا یَشۡتَہُوۡنَ کَمَا فُعِلَ بِاَشۡیَاعِہِمۡ مِّنۡ قَبۡلُ» ( 34/54 ) Translation: And a barrier will be placed between them and what they desire, as was done with their likes before."
    },
    {
      "id": 2122,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "faction",
      "hw": "فرقہ",
      "s": "«اُنَاس» separate groups belonging to different tribes (5 verses: 2:60-7:82-7:160-17:71-27:56)",
      "d": "«اُنَاس» means groups formed according to division (i.e., according to ability and suitability) or separate groups belonging to different tribes (some say there is no difference between «نَاس» and «اُنَاس»). For example, in the Quran it is: «قَدۡ عَلِمَ کُلُّ اُنَاسٍ مَّشۡرَبَہُمۡ» ( 2/60 ) Translation: Every group recognized its drinking place."
    }
  ],
  "458": [
    {
      "id": 2123,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Answering a cry",
      "hw": "فریاد",
      "s": "«Istitab» Such a prayer which Allah grants the honor of acceptance (20 verses: 2:186-3:172-3:195-6:36-7:194-8:9-8:24-11:14-12:34-13:14-13:18-17:52-28:50-28:64-35:14-42:16-42:26-42:38-42:47-46:5)",
      "d": "«Jaba» means to carve a stone. And «ajaba» means to respond to speech, i.e., to answer a question (m. l). And «sa'ala» also comes in two meanings: (1) to inquire about something, (2) to ask for or request something. Therefore, «ajaba» also comes in both meanings: (1) in the sense of answering a question.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«یَوۡمَ یَجۡمَعُ اللّٰہُ الرُّسُلَ فَیَقُوۡلُ مَا ذَاۤ اُجِبۡتُمۡ» ( 5/109 )\nTranslation: On the Day when Allah will gather the messengers, He will say, \"What was your response [from those you were sent to]?\"\n(2) And in the sense of responding to a request, it means to accept.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اَمَّنۡ یُّجِیۡبُ الۡمُضۡطَرَّ اِذَا دَعَاہُ» ( 27/62 )\nTranslation: Who responds to the desperate one when he calls upon Him?\nAnd «istijab» means accepting a prayer, i.e., fulfilling the caller's need or granting his supplication, especially when called upon.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ نُوۡحًا اِذۡ نَادٰی مِنۡ قَبۡلُ فَاسۡتَجَبۡنَا لَہٗ فَنَجَّیۡنٰہُ وَ اَہۡلَہٗ مِنَ الۡکَرۡبِ الۡعَظِیۡمِ» ( 21/76 )\nTranslation: And [mention] Noah when he called [to Us] before, and We responded to him and saved him and his family from the great distress."
    },
    {
      "id": 2124,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Answering the Cry",
      "hw": "فریاد",
      "s": "«اَصْرَخَ» means to scream and call for help in times of distress and to reach the help of the one crying out. (3 verses: 14:22-28:18-35:37)",
      "d": "«صَرَخَ» means to scream. To shout so that one's cry may be heard. And «صَرِیْخ» means to reach the cry (36/43) and «اَصْرَخَ» has the same meaning.\nFor example, in the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَا تَلُوۡمُوۡنِیۡ وَ لُوۡمُوۡۤا اَنۡفُسَکُمۡ ؕ مَاۤ  اَنَا بِمُصۡرِخِکُمۡ وَ مَاۤ  اَنۡتُمۡ بِمُصۡرِخِیَّ» (14/22)\nTranslation: Satan will say to his followers, 'Do not blame me, but blame yourselves. I am not your helper, nor are you my helpers.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2125,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To cry for help",
      "hw": "فریاد",
      "s": "«Istighath» The word istighath is used when a cry for help is presented before Allah or a temporal ruler (4 verses: 8:9-18:29-28:15-46:17)",
      "d": "«Gatha» means to aid and help someone in times of difficulty (m. l). And «ghayth» refers to rain that comes timely and as needed. And «istighath» means to cry out to Allah for such rain, or to seek aid and help from Allah or another ruler in times of difficulty. Istighathah is a well-known term meaning to complain of injustice or oppression before a ruler or court.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اِذۡ تَسۡتَغِیۡثُوۡنَ رَبَّکُمۡ فَاسۡتَجَابَ لَکُمۡ» ( 8/9 )\nTranslation: When you cried out to your Lord for help, He responded to you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2126,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Crying Out",
      "hw": "فریاد",
      "s": "«اِسْتَصْرَخ» is used when people are invited through screaming and calling. (2 verses: 14:22-28:18)",
      "d": "«اِسْتَصْرَخ» means to scream and call out to make one's cry heard by the people and seek their help.\nFor example, in the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاِذَا  الَّذِی اسۡتَنۡصَرَہٗ  بِالۡاَمۡسِ یَسۡتَصۡرِخُہٗ» (28/18)\nTranslation: Then the man who had sought his help the day before, now began to cry out to him."
    }
  ],
  "459": [
    {
      "id": 2127,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Causing Corruption",
      "hw": "فساد",
      "s": "«اَفْسَدَ» can be used even for a single act of corruption, and when «فَسَاد» becomes a habit, then «عَاثَ» is used. And in «نَزَغَ», the fundamental meaning is to interfere, whether in one thing or many. Then, among these, to cause corruption. (47 verses: 2:11-2:12-2:27-2:30-2:60-2:205-2:220-2:251-3:63-5:32-5:33-5:64-7:56-7:74-7:85-7:86-7:103-7:127-7:142-8:73-10:40-10:81-10:91-11:85-11:116-12:73-13:25-16:88-17:4-18:94-21:22-23:71-26:152-26:183-27:14-27:34-27:48-28:4-28:77-28:83-29:30-29:36-30:41-38:28-40:26-47:22-89:12)",
      "d": "«فَسَدَ» means for something to become corrupt, to spoil. And «اَفْسَدَ» means to corrupt something and spoil it. The opposite of «فَسَاد» is «اِصْلَاح». The word «فَسَاد» is used in both material and spiritual contexts.\nFor example, in the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَا تُفۡسِدُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ بَعۡدَ اِصۡلَاحِہَا» (7/56)\nTranslation: And do not cause corruption in the land after its reform."
    },
    {
      "id": 2128,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To cause corruption. To throw.",
      "hw": "فساد",
      "s": "«Atha» Meaning to spread corruption (5 verses: 2:60-7:74-11:85-26:183-29:36)",
      "d": "«Atha» or «aath» means to spread corruption, create disorder and corruption.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ لَا تَعۡثَوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مُفۡسِدِیۡنَ» ( 2/60 )\nTranslation: And do not cause corruption in the land.\n«Tasthawa» some lexicographers have written its root as «ع ث ی», i.e., «athiya yasthu athiyan» (mufradat) which pertains to mental and intellectual corruption, such as spreading false beliefs and ideologies through literature or speeches. And some lexicographers have written its root as «ع ی ث», «aatha ya'ithu athiyan» (mufradat) which indicates physical or material corruption (m. l), such as committing injustice and oppression against someone. In both cases, the negative form «la tasthawa» is used."
    },
    {
      "id": 2129,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To cause corruption; to sow discord.",
      "hw": "فساد",
      "s": "«نَزَغَ» means to sow discord between two things (4 verses: 7:200-12:100-17:53-41:36)",
      "d": "«نَزَغَ» means to sow discord between two things (according to Majid) and means to create a quarrel. To incite to corruption. To create mischief. To instigate a fight. To sow enmity (according to Quran) and means to spoil a matter and interfere in it (according to Mufradat) or to cause corruption by interference.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ اَنۡ  نَّزَغَ  الشَّیۡطٰنُ  بَیۡنِیۡ وَ بَیۡنَ اِخۡوَتِیۡ» (12/100)\nTranslation: After that, Satan had sown discord between me and my brothers."
    }
  ],
  "460": [
    {
      "id": 2130,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To engage in idle talk; to chatter.",
      "hw": "فضول",
      "s": "«اَلْغٰی» means to chatter in such a way that others' words are not heard (11 verses: 2:225-5:89-19:62-23:3-25:72-28:55-41:26-52:23-56:25-78:35-88:11)",
      "d": "«لَغَا» means to speak without thinking or understanding. Idle talk (according to Al-Munjid) and means the chirping of birds. And similarly, to repeatedly mention something (according to Quran). And the meaning of «اَلْغٰی» is to chatter and make noise in such a way that the listener's words are drowned in the noise so that others also cannot hear.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ قَالَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَا تَسۡمَعُوۡا لِہٰذَا الۡقُرۡاٰنِ وَ الۡغَوۡا فِیۡہِ  لَعَلَّکُمۡ تَغۡلِبُوۡنَ» (41/26)\nTranslation: And the disbelievers said, 'Do not listen to this Quran and make noise while it is being recited, so that you may prevail.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2131,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To engage in idle talk; to chatter.",
      "hw": "فضول",
      "s": "«خَاض» means to become immersed in idle talk or actions (9 verses: 4:140-6:68-6:91-9:65-9:69-43:83-52:12-70:42-74:45)",
      "d": "«خَاض» means to immerse. «خَاضَ فِی الْمَاءِ» means to immerse in water. «خَاضَ فِی الْحَدِیْث» means to be engaged in talk (according to Al-Munjid) and means to penetrate into something (according to Majid), i.e., to be fully engrossed in talks or actions. In the Quran, its usage is mostly for remaining occupied with idle actions or talks (according to Mufradat).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ اِذَا  رَاَیۡتَ الَّذِیۡنَ  یَخُوۡضُوۡنَ فِیۡۤ  اٰیٰتِنَا فَاَعۡرِضۡ عَنۡہُمۡ حَتّٰی یَخُوۡضُوۡا فِیۡ حَدِیۡثٍ غَیۡرِہٖ» (6/68)\nTranslation: When you see those who engage in idle talk about Our verses, turn away from them until they engage in a different conversation."
    },
    {
      "id": 2132,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Idle Talk",
      "hw": "فضول",
      "s": "«فَکِہَ» is such jesting from which pleasure is derived. Happy banter. (1 verse: 83:31)",
      "d": "«فَکِہَ» means to engage in happy banter. To laugh and amuse. (fal 145) And «فَکَاہَۃ» means amusing conversations. (minjad) And «تَفَکَّہَ بِعِرْضِ فَلَانٍ» means to enjoy by speaking ill of someone. (minjad) To derive pleasure from conversations.\nFor example, in the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اِذَا  انۡقَلَبُوۡۤا  اِلٰۤی  اَہۡلِہُمُ  انۡقَلَبُوۡا فَکِہِیۡنَ» (83/31)\nTranslation: And when they return to their families, they return jesting."
    },
    {
      "id": 2135,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To spend wastefully; extravagance.",
      "hw": "فضول",
      "s": "«اَسْرَفَ» is used for wasteful spending in permissible matters (19 verses: 5:32-6:141-7:31-7:81-10:12-10:83-17:33-20:127-21:9-25:67-26:151-36:19-39:53-40:28-40:34-40:43-43:5-44:31-51:34)",
      "d": "«سَرَفَ» and «اَسْرَفَ» mean to exceed the limits of moderation (according to Mufradat) and it is used for spending more than necessary in wealth or food and drink. And the limit of moderation is for that which is permissible (i.e., allowed in Sharia) or lawful. Thus, the meaning of israf is to spend more than necessary in permissible matters.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«کُلُوۡا وَ اشۡرَبُوۡا وَ لَا  تُسۡرِفُوۡا» (7/31)\nTranslation: Eat and drink, but do not spend wastefully."
    },
    {
      "id": 2136,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To spend wastefully; extravagance.",
      "hw": "فضول",
      "s": "«بَذَّرَ» means to scatter wealth wastefully and extravagantly. (2 verses: 17:26-17:27)",
      "d": "«بِذْر» and «بَذَرَ» mean seed. And «بَذَّرَ» means to scatter seed. Just as seed is scattered on the earth, similarly if wealth is scattered, it is called «تَبْذِیْر» (according to Mufradat). Thus, whether the need is lawful or unlawful, spending wealth recklessly is called «تَبْذِیْر» (according to Mufradat) and this is also worse than israf.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَا  تُبَذِّرۡ  تَبۡذِیۡرًا اِنَّ الۡمُبَذِّرِیۡنَ کَانُوۡۤا اِخۡوَانَ الشَّیٰطِیۡنِ» (17:26,27)\nTranslation: And do not spend wastefully. Indeed, the wasteful are brothers of the devils."
    },
    {
      "id": 2137,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To grant excellence; to bestow honor.",
      "hw": "فضول",
      "s": "«فَضَّلَ» means for something good to be more or superior. (93 verses: 2:47-2:64-2:90-2:105-2:122-2:198-2:237-2:243-2:251-2:253-2:268-3:73-3:74-3:152-3:170-3:171-3:174-3:180-4:32-4:34-4:37-4:54-4:70-4:73-4:83-4:95-4:113-4:173-4:175-5:2-5:54-6:86-7:39-7:140-8:29-9:28-9:59-9:74-9:75-9:76-10:58-10:60-10:107-11:3-11:27-12:38-13:4-16:14-16:71-17:12-17:21-17:48-17:55-17:66-17:70-17:87-23:24-24:10-24:14-24:20-24:21-24:22-24:32-24:33-24:38-27:15-27:16-27:40-27:73-28:73-30:23-30:45-30:46-33:47-34:10-35:12-35:30-35:32-35:35-40:61-42:22-42:26-44:57-45:12-45:16-48:29-49:8-57:21-57:29-59:8-62:4-62:10-73:20)",
      "d": "«فَضْل» means for a good thing to exceed the moderate degree. And «فَضَّلَ» means to give someone, out of kindness, more than their due in something good (according to Mufradat).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«یٰبَنِیۡۤ  اِسۡرَآءِیۡلَ اذۡکُرُوۡا نِعۡمَتِیَ الَّتِیۡۤ  اَنۡعَمۡتُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ وَ اَنِّیۡ فَضَّلۡتُکُمۡ عَلَی الۡعٰلَمِیۡنَ» (2/122)\nTranslation: O Children of Israel! Remember My favor which I bestowed upon you and that I preferred you over the worlds."
    },
    {
      "id": 2138,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To grant excellence; to bestow honor.",
      "hw": "فضول",
      "s": "«کَرَّمَ» means to instill excellence within something. (14 verses: 12:21-17:62-17:70-21:26-22:18-36:27-37:42-49:13-51:24-70:35-80:13-89:15-89:17-96:3)",
      "d": "«کَرَم» refers to such honor that is inherently present in something or due to its qualities (according to Majid). And «کَرَّمَ» means to instill the essence of excellence within something (according to Mufradat).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ کَرَّمۡنَا بَنِیۡۤ  اٰدَمَ وَ حَمَلۡنٰہُمۡ  فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ» (17/70)\nTranslation: And We have certainly honored the children of Adam and carried them on the land and sea."
    }
  ],
  "461": [
    {
      "id": 2139,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To judge; to decree.",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "«فَتَحَ» is a judgment by which distinction between truth and falsehood is made, complexity is removed, and no party remains in doubt. (7 verses: 7:89-8:19-14:15-26:118-32:28-32:29-34:26)",
      "d": "«فَتَحَ» means to remove restriction and complexity from something (according to Mufradat). Its opposite is «اِغْلَاق» meaning confinement and restriction (according to Majid). And «فَتَحَ» means to grant victory and to judge. A judgment by which distinction between truth and falsehood is made, complexity is removed, and no party remains in doubt.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«رَبَّنَا افۡتَحۡ بَیۡنَنَا وَ بَیۡنَ قَوۡمِنَا بِالۡحَقِّ» (7/89)\nTranslation: Our Lord, judge between us and our people with truth."
    },
    {
      "id": 2140,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To judge; to decree.",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "«فَصَلَ» means to distinguish one thing from another and for it to be distant from it. (6 verses: 37:21-44:40-77:13-77:14-77:38-78:17)",
      "d": "«فَصَلَ» means to distinguish one thing from another (to differentiate) and for it to be distant from it (according to Majid). Thus, in contrast to فتح, «فَصَلَ» is specific. In فتح, there is only distinction, whereas in «فَصَلَ», there are two things: distinction and separation. And this distinction and separation can sometimes be in the same thing, such as a chapter of a book. Similarly, فتح may relate to one thing or to multiple things. (according to Fiqh al-Lughah 113)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«ہٰذَا یَوۡمُ الۡفَصۡلِ ۚ جَمَعۡنٰکُمۡ وَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (77/38)\nTranslation: This is the Day of Judgment; We will gather you and the former peoples."
    },
    {
      "id": 2141,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To judge; to decree.",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "«حَکَمَ» is a judgment by which someone is prevented from oppression and a plan is made to correct them. (43 verses: 2:113-2:213-3:23-3:55-4:58-4:105-4:141-5:1-5:42-5:43-5:44-5:45-5:47-5:48-5:49-5:50-5:95-6:136-7:87-10:35-10:109-12:80-16:59-16:124-21:78-21:112-22:56-22:69-24:48-24:51-29:4-37:154-38:22-38:26-39:3-39:46-40:12-40:48-42:10-45:21-60:10-68:36-68:39)",
      "d": "«حَکَمَ» means 'to prevent from injustice' (according to Majid). A judgment in which oppression and excess are prevented. And means 'to prevent from dispute' (according to Fiqh al-Lughah 156), i.e., a ruling to stop fighting and quarreling.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ دَاوٗدَ  وَ سُلَیۡمٰنَ  اِذۡ یَحۡکُمٰنِ فِی الۡحَرۡثِ» (21/78)\nTranslation: And [mention] David and Solomon when they judged concerning a field."
    },
    {
      "id": 2142,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To Decide",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "«قَضٰی» means to give the final and binding decision of the one who has the power to enforce that command. (58 verses: 2:117-2:200-2:210-3:47-4:65-4:103-6:2-6:8-6:58-6:60-8:42-8:44-10:11-10:19-10:47-10:54-10:71-10:93-11:44-11:110-12:41-12:68-14:22-15:66-17:4-17:23-19:21-19:35-19:39-19:71-20:72-20:114-22:29-27:78-28:15-28:28-28:29-28:44-33:23-33:36-33:37-34:14-35:36-39:42-39:69-39:75-40:20-40:68-40:78-41:12-41:45-42:14-42:21-43:77-45:17-46:29-62:10-80:23)",
      "d": "«یَقْضِیْ قَضْیًا وَ قَضَاءً وَ قَضِیَّۃً» means (1) to be finished with something, to complete it. And (2) to give the final judgment between disputing parties (DECISION). And in the context of judgment, «قَضٰی» is used when the power to enforce the decision is also present. Qazi is a famous word. For example, the Quran says: «فَلَا وَ رَبِّکَ لَا یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ حَتّٰی یُحَکِّمُوۡکَ فِیۡمَا شَجَرَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ ثُمَّ لَا یَجِدُوۡا فِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ حَرَجًا مِّمَّا قَضَیۡتَ» (4/65) Translation: By your Lord, they will not believe until they make you judge in what they dispute among themselves, and then they find no discomfort in their hearts about what you have decided."
    },
    {
      "id": 2143,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To Decide",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "«حَتَمَ» means a decisive and immutable decree, the decision of Divine will (1 Verse: 19:71)",
      "d": "«حَتَمَ» means to decide, to confirm, to ordain something, to make obligatory. And «حَاتِم» means a judge, a deciding ruler, and a judge. «حَتَمَ الْحَاتِمُ كَذَا» means 'the ruler decided that matter'. And «ھٰذا وَلَدٌ حَتَمٌ» means 'this is a boy whose lineage is unquestionable' (Majid). And «حَتْم» means predestination (noun), meaning «حَتْم» is the term for a decree that is final and immutable (Fiqh 187).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ إِنۡ مِّنۡکُمۡ إِلَّا وَارِدُہَا ۚ کَانَ عَلٰی رَبِّکَ حَتۡمًا مَّقۡضِیًّا» (19/71)\nTranslation: And there is not one of you but will pass over it (Hell). This is for your Lord a decree determined."
    }
  ],
  "462": [
    {
      "id": 2144,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To Gain Control",
      "hw": "قابو",
      "s": "«قَدَرَ عَلٰی» means to have power, to gain control; this is a common usage (11 Verses: 2:236-2:264-5:34-13:17-14:18-16:75-16:76-21:87-48:21-57:29-90:5)",
      "d": "«قَدَر، قَدِر (قَدْرًا، قُدْرَۃً) قَدَر» means to manage or devise a plan regarding a matter. «قَدَرَ الرِّزْق» means to distribute sustenance, to restrict in sustenance. And «قَدَرَ عَلَی الشَّیْء» means to have power over something, to gain control over it (Majid).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ ذَاالنُّوۡنِ إِذۡ ذَّہَبَ مُغَاضِبًا فَظَنَّ أَنَّ لَنۡ نَّقۡدِرَ عَلَیۡہِ» (21/87)\nTranslation: And [mention] the man of the fish (Prophet Jonah) when he went away in anger and thought that We would not have power over him."
    },
    {
      "id": 2145,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To Gain Control",
      "hw": "قابو",
      "s": "«اَقْرَنَ» means to have the power over something associated with it (4 verses: 14:49-25:13-38:38-43:13)",
      "d": "«قَرَنَ» means to mix one thing with another, to bind. And «قَرْن» refers to the rope with which two camels are tied (muf). And «اَقْرَنَ» means to combine two things into one and «اَقْرَنَ لِلْاَمْر» means to have power over something and be capable of it. Whereas «اَقْرَنَ عَلَیْہِ» means to be rendered incapable or helpless by something (manjad). Thus, the meaning of having control over something associated is found in «اَقْرَنَ».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡ سَخَّرَ لَنَا ہٰذَا  وَ مَا کُنَّا لَہٗ  مُقۡرِنِیۡنَ» ( 43/13 )\nTranslation: Glorified is He Who has subjected this to us, and we could not have had control over it."
    }
  ],
  "463": [
    {
      "id": 2148,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Caravan",
      "hw": "قافلہ",
      "s": "«سَیَّارَۃ» refers to a group traveling together, a caravan or fellow travelers. This word is general. (3 verses: 5:96-12:10-12:19)",
      "d": "«سَارَ» means to walk, to roam. And «سَیَّارَۃ» means anything that walks or roams continuously or has traveled much (it is an intensive form). Celestial bodies are also called «سَیَّارَات». And in common usage, «سَیَّارَۃ» refers to a group traveling together or fellow travelers. Caravan (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ جَآءَتۡ سَیَّارَۃٌ  فَاَرۡسَلُوۡا وَارِدَہُمۡ فَاَدۡلٰی دَلۡوَہٗ» ( 12/19 )\nTranslation: And a caravan came. They sent their water-drawer, who let down his bucket (into the well)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2149,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Caravan",
      "hw": "قافلہ",
      "s": "«عِیْر» a grain-carrying caravan. (3 verses: 12:70-12:82-12:94)",
      "d": "«عِیْر» refers to any caravan that carries grain. The camels and people carrying food supplies are all included in it (muf). According to scholars of language, it applies whether the caravan consists of camels, horses, or donkeys (f l 16). Also, the caravan of the Himyar tribe is called «عِیْر» (m.q.).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ اَذَّنَ مُؤَذِّنٌ اَیَّتُہَا الۡعِیۡرُ اِنَّکُمۡ لَسٰرِقُوۡنَ» ( 12/70 )\nTranslation: Then a crier announced, \"O caravan people! Indeed, you are thieves.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 2150,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Caravan",
      "hw": "قافلہ",
      "s": "«رَکْب» a mounted caravan on camels or horses. (1 verse: 8:42)",
      "d": "«رَکَبَ» means to ride. And «رِکَاب» means riding. And «رَاکِب» means rider. However, in common usage, the word «رَاکِب» has become specific to camel riders (muf). The plural of «رَاکِب» is «رَکْب , رُکْبَان» and «رُکُوْب» (manjad). And «رَکْبُ» means a caravan of horse riders or camel riders.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ اَنۡتُمۡ بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الدُّنۡیَا وَ ہُمۡ  بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الۡقُصۡوٰی وَ الرَّکۡبُ اَسۡفَلَ  مِنۡکُمۡ» ( 8/42 )\nTranslation: When you were on the near side of the valley, and they were on the far side, and the caravan was below you."
    }
  ],
  "464": [
    {
      "id": 2151,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Grave",
      "hw": "قبر",
      "s": "«قَبْر» is general for a burial place, whether its markers are present or not. (7 verses: 9:84-22:7-35:22-60:13-80:21-82:4-100:9)",
      "d": "«قَبْر» means the place where a dead person is buried in the earth. It is a well-known word, and its plural is «قُبُوْر». And a cemetery (maqbara) is also used in the same meaning, and its plural is maqabir. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تُصَلِّ عَلٰۤی اَحَدٍ مِّنۡہُمۡ مَّاتَ اَبَدًا وَّ لَا تَقُمۡ عَلٰی قَبۡرِہٖ» ( 9/84 )\nTranslation: And do not ever pray [the funeral prayer] over any of them who dies, nor stand by his grave."
    },
    {
      "id": 2152,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Grave",
      "hw": "قبر",
      "s": "«مَرْقَد» means a place of sleep, a resting place. (Metaphorically) used for grave, tomb. (1 verse: 36:52)",
      "d": "«رَقَدَ» means to sleep a light and long sleep. And «مَرْقَد» means a place to rest for a long sleep. A resting place. A place of sleep. This word has been used metaphorically for the grave because the disbelievers will equate the hardship of the Hereafter with the hardship of the grave, calling it a state of rest.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا یٰوَیۡلَنَا مَنۡۢ بَعَثَنَا مِنۡ مَّرۡقَدِنَا» ( 36/52 )\nTranslation: They [the disbelievers] will say, \"O woe to us! Who has raised us from our resting places?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 2153,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Grave",
      "hw": "قبر",
      "s": "«جَدَث» specifically a burial place whose traces are no longer present. (3 verses: 36:51-54:7-70:43)",
      "d": "Although some linguists have not made a clear distinction between «جَدَث» and «قَبْر». However, from the study of the Quran, it is known that the word grave («قَبْر») is general, while «جَدَث» is that grave whose traces have also vanished. Moreover, sometimes it happens that a body is eaten by a wild animal. Sometimes a person drowns in the sea, and sea creatures consume it. Hindus cremate their dead and immerse the ashes in the Ganges. Whatever the case, when the particles of that body are eventually transferred and mix into the earth, that is its «جَدَث». And its plural is «اَجْدَاث». This word appears twice in the Quran, and both times it is for occasions where the very concept of grave markers is impossible.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَوۡمَ یَخۡرُجُوۡنَ  مِنَ الۡاَجۡدَاثِ سِرَاعًا کَاَنَّہُمۡ  اِلٰی نُصُبٍ یُّوۡفِضُوۡنَ» ( 70/43 )\nTranslation: On that Day they will emerge from the graves in haste, as if they were racing to a goalpost.\nThis verse mentions the Day of Resurrection when all traces of graves will have vanished. Another verse also presents the same scene.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ نُفِخَ فِی الصُّوۡرِ فَاِذَا ہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡاَجۡدَاثِ  اِلٰی  رَبِّہِمۡ  یَنۡسِلُوۡنَ» ( 36/51 )\nTranslation: And the Trumpet will be blown; then they will emerge from the graves in haste toward their Lord."
    }
  ],
  "465": [],
  "466": [
    {
      "id": 2157,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tribe and Family",
      "hw": "خاندان",
      "s": "«شُعُوْب» means lineages, such as the offspring of one man, then the offspring of that offspring, eventually forming a single entity. (1 verse: 49:13)",
      "d": "«شُعُوْب» refers to the offspring of one man, then his offspring, and their offspring. Eventually, it forms a single entity. In Arabic, this is called «شَعْب», and «شُعَب» also refers to branches. Its plural is «شُعُوب». The meanings of «شَعْب» are fundamentally two: (1) separation, i.e., division, and (2) gathering. That is, something that eventually divides into many parts, but its origin and foundation are one, and it is also a gathering (m.l.)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2158,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tribe and Family",
      "hw": "خاندان",
      "s": "«قَبَائِل» means brotherhoods, communities. Groups of people of one lineage, nations, many groups. (1 verse: 49:13)",
      "d": "«قَبَائِل» is the plural of «قَبِیْلَہ», meaning brotherhood. Now, this entity or «شَعْب» further divides into many smaller parts called tribes, which maintain connections among themselves. «قَبَائِلُ الرَّأس» means the bones of the head that are connected to each other (manjad). We call this a 'brotherhood' or 'community' in our language.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ جَعَلۡنٰکُمۡ شُعُوۡبًا وَّ قَبَآئِلَ لِتَعَارَفُوۡا ؕ اِنَّ  اَکۡرَمَکُمۡ  عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ  اَتۡقٰکُمۡ» ( 49/13 )\nTranslation: And We have made you into nations and tribes that you may know one another. Indeed, the most noble of you in the sight of Allah is the most righteous of you.\nNote: (By 'tribes' is meant a group of people who, while living within a state, follow a distinct way of life. They have their own specific laws and customs. They reside within their specific territories but are not subject to any law of the state. Globally, the number of tribes is around 150 million, which is about 40% of the world's population.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2159,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tribe and Family",
      "hw": "خاندان",
      "s": "«فَصِیْلَۃ» means family or clan. (1 verse: 70:13)",
      "d": "«فَصِیْلَۃ» means family. Clan. One's own family of a single individual. Members of one household. The people of the house. A small tribe that includes his wife, sons, daughters, siblings, father, mother, etc. (f l 206)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَوَدُّ  الۡمُجۡرِمُ لَوۡ  یَفۡتَدِیۡ مِنۡ عَذَابِ یَوۡمِئِذٍۭ بِبَنِیۡہِ وَ صَاحِبَتِہٖ وَ اَخِیۡہِ وَ فَصِیۡلَتِہِ الَّتِیۡ تُـئۡوِیۡہِ» ( 70/11،12،13 )\nTranslation: The criminal will wish that he could be ransomed from the punishment of that Day by his children, his wife, his brothers, and even the entire family that had sheltered him."
    },
    {
      "id": 2160,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tribe and Family",
      "hw": "خاندان",
      "s": "«رَھْط» refers to a small group of young men from a tribe, numbering between 3 and 9 (3 verses: 11:91, 11:92, 27:48).",
      "d": "«رَھْط» denotes a small group of young men from a tribe, numbering between 3 and 9, and includes no women (FL 205). Such a group, as well as its leader, is also called «رَھْط» (see also 'Leader'). According to the author of Al-Munjid, when a number is added to «رَھْط», it refers to individuals, e.g., «خَمْسَۃُ رَھْطٍ» means five people.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَ یٰقَوۡمِ اَرَہۡطِیۡۤ اَعَزُّ  عَلَیۡکُمۡ  مِّنَ اللّٰہِ» (11/92)\nTranslation: Shu'aib (AS) said, 'O my people! Is the pressure of my brothers upon you mightier than Allah?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2161,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tribe and Family",
      "hw": "خاندان",
      "s": "«عَشِیْرَۃ» is a small tribe consisting of male relatives (5 verses: 4:19, 9:24, 22:13, 26:214, 58:22).",
      "d": "«عَشَرَ» means to live together (ML), and «عَشِیْرَۃ» refers to this small tribe comprising only male relatives, such as sons, daughters, father, grandfather, uncles, aunts, etc. (FL 206).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اَنۡذِرۡ عَشِیۡرَتَکَ  الۡاَقۡرَبِیۡنَ» (26/214)\nTranslation: 'And warn your nearest kinsfolk.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2162,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tribe and Family",
      "hw": "خاندان",
      "s": "«اَسْبَاط» means grandsons and granddaughters; if this term is attributed to the Jews, it refers to a tribe (5 verses: 2:136, 2:140, 3:84, 4:163, 7:160).",
      "d": "«سِبْط» means descendants of descendants, e.g., grandsons and granddaughters (MF). However, this term is more specific to the descendants of daughters. Similarly, «حَفِيْد» is specific to grandsons (Al-Munjid). If this term is attributed to the Jews, it refers to a tribe (Al-Munjid). According to the scholar of language, the status of a tribe that Banu Ismail holds is the same as the status of «سِبْط» in Banu Ishaq (FL 25). In the Quran, the term «اَسْبَاط» appears for the tribes of Banu Ishaq.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ قَطَّعۡنٰہُمُ اثۡنَتَیۡ عَشۡرَۃَ  اَسۡبَاطًا اُمَمًا» (7/160)\nTranslation: 'And We divided them into twelve tribes, communities.'"
    }
  ],
  "467": [
    {
      "id": 2164,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Killing",
      "hw": "قتل",
      "s": "«سَفَکَ» means to kill someone unjustly (2 verses: 2:30, 2:84).",
      "d": "«سَفَکَ» means to shed blood or water. «سَفُوْک» means a liar, and «سَفَّاک» means a bloodshedder (MF, MR). This word is generally used to mean killing someone unjustly.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَتَجۡعَلُ فِیۡہَا مَنۡ یُّفۡسِدُ فِیۡہَا وَ یَسۡفِکُ الدِّمَآءَ» (2/30)\nTranslation: The angels said, 'Will You place upon it one who causes corruption therein and sheds blood?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2166,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Killing",
      "hw": "قتل",
      "s": "«اَثْخَنَ» means to kill without restraint and to continue killing as much as possible (2 verses: 8:67, 47:4).",
      "d": "«ثَخَنَ» means to lift something and estimate its weight (ML). «ثَخُنَ» means to be thick and hard. «اَثْخَنَ فِیْ الْاَرْض» means to go to extremes in bloodshed (Al-Munjid). Thus, «اَثْخَنَ» implies severity during killing and also means mass killing or killing without restraint.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاِذَا  لَقِیۡتُمُ  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا فَضَرۡبَ الرِّقَابِ ؕ حَتّٰۤی  اِذَاۤ  اَثۡخَنۡتُمُوۡہُمۡ فَشُدُّوا الۡوَثَاقَ» (47/4)\nTranslation: 'When you meet the disbelievers, strike their necks until, when you have inflicted severe casualties upon them, bind them firmly.'"
    }
  ],
  "468": [
    {
      "id": 2168,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Step",
      "hw": "قدم",
      "s": "«خُطُوَۃ» is the distance covered by two steps. And «خُطُوَات» means initiatives (STEPS) (4 verses: 2:168, 2:208, 6:142, 24:21).",
      "d": "«خُطُوَۃ», whose plural is «خُطُوَات», means the distance between two steps and also means to transcend and move forward (M, L). «خُطُوَات لَازِمَہ» means necessary initiatives (Al-Munjid). Thus, «خُطُوَات» means initiatives (STEPS), progress, and can also refer to the entire path.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ لَا تَتَّبِعُوۡا خُطُوٰتِ الشَّیۡطٰنِ» (2/168)\nTranslation: 'And do not follow the footsteps of Satan.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2169,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Step",
      "hw": "قدم",
      "s": "«اَثَر» means a footprint; a sign of the path (16 verses: 5:46, 18:6, 18:64, 20:84, 20:96, 30:50, 36:12, 37:70, 40:21, 40:82, 43:22, 43:23, 46:4, 48:29, 57:27, 100:4).",
      "d": "«اَثَر», whose plural is «اٰثَار», means a remaining sign, a footprint (ML). «اٰثَار» means footprints, left marks, traces of the path. Also see 'Sign'. «آثار قدیمہ» means traces and signs of ancient times.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَ ذٰلِکَ مَا کُنَّا نَبۡغِ ٭ۖ فَارۡتَدَّا عَلٰۤی اٰثَارِہِمَا قَصَصًا» (18/64)\nTranslation: [Musa (AS)] said, 'That is what we have been seeking.' So they turned back, retracing their footsteps."
    }
  ],
  "469": [
    {
      "id": 2170,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To Settle",
      "hw": "قرار",
      "s": "«قَرَّ» means to settle in a place, to become established, to reside (8 verses: 19:26, 20:40, 25:74, 28:9, 28:13, 32:17, 33:33, 33:51).",
      "d": "«قَرَّ» means to settle in a place. It also means to become cool. There is a connection between these two meanings: coldness or coolness also seeks tranquility, just as heat and motion seek movement (MF).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ قَرۡنَ فِیۡ بُیُوۡتِکُنَّ وَ لَا تَبَرَّجۡنَ تَبَرُّجَ الۡجَاہِلِیَّۃِ  الۡاُوۡلٰی» (33/33)\nTranslation: 'And stay in your houses and do not display yourselves as [was] the display of the former times of ignorance.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2171,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To Settle",
      "hw": "قرار",
      "s": "«اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی» is used to mean to settle from one state to another (13 verses: 2:29, 7:54, 10:3, 11:44, 13:2, 20:5, 23:28, 25:59, 32:4, 41:11, 43:13, 48:29, 57:4).",
      "d": "«اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی» means to mount something and then sit firmly on it (see 'To Mount'). The fundamental difference between «قَرَّ» and «اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی» is that «اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی» is used to settle from one state to another.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اسۡتَوَتۡ عَلَی الۡجُوۡدِیِّ» (11/44)\nTranslation: That is, the ship of Nuh (AS) came to rest on Mount Judi.\nAlso, Allah says:\n«فَاِذَا اسۡتَوَیۡتَ اَنۡتَ وَ مَنۡ مَّعَکَ عَلَی الۡفُلۡکِ» (23/28)\nTranslation: 'When you and those with you are settled aboard the ship.'\nSimilarly, at another place, Allah says:\n«ثُمَّ اسۡتَوٰی عَلَی الۡعَرۡشِ» (7/54)\nTranslation: 'Then He settled above the Throne.'"
    }
  ],
  "470": [
    {
      "id": 2172,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Various Names of the Quran",
      "hw": "قرآن",
      "s": "«قُرْاٰن» means the Book that is recited repeatedly, frequently, and always (referring to the Noble Quran) (69 verses: 2:185, 4:82, 5:101, 6:19, 7:204, 9:111, 10:15, 10:37, 10:61, 12:2, 12:3, 13:31, 15:1, 15:87, 15:91, 16:98, 17:9, 17:41, 17:45, 17:46, 17:60, 17:78, 17:82, 17:88, 17:89, 17:106, 18:54, 20:2, 20:113, 20:114, 25:30, 25:32, 27:1, 27:6, 27:76, 27:92, 28:85, 30:58, 34:31, 36:2, 36:69, 38:1, 39:27, 39:28, 41:3, 41:26, 41:44, 42:7, 43:3, 43:31, 46:29, 47:24, 50:1, 50:45, 54:17, 54:22, 54:32, 54:40, 55:2, 56:77, 59:21, 72:1, 73:4, 73:20, 75:17, 75:18, 76:23, 84:21, 85:21).",
      "d": "«قَرَءَ» means to read. «قُرْاٰن» is the intensive form (ism mubalaghah), meaning the Book that is recited repeatedly, frequently, and always.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قٓ ۟ ۚ  وَ الۡقُرۡاٰنِ  الۡمَجِیۡدِ » (50/1)\nTranslation: Qaf. By the Glorious Quran."
    },
    {
      "id": 2173,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Different Names of the Quran",
      "hw": "قرآن",
      "s": "«Furqan» is a book that distinguishes between truth and falsehood (7 verses: 2:53, 2:185, 3:4, 8:29, 8:41, 21:48, 25:1)",
      "d": "«Faraq» means to separate, to distinguish. It is an intensive form (ism mubalaghah). Meaning a book that discerns and distinguishes every single aspect of truth and falsehood.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«Tabarakalladhi nazzalal-furqana 'ala 'abdih» (25:1)\nTranslation: Blessed is He who sent down the Criterion (Furqan) upon His Servant."
    },
    {
      "id": 2174,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Different Names of the Quran",
      "hw": "قرآن",
      "s": "«Dhikr» means to remember and to be reminded (181 verses: 2:114, 2:221, 2:269, 2:282, 3:7, 3:58, 5:13, 5:14, 5:91, 6:44, 6:68, 6:69, 6:70, 6:80, 6:90, 6:118, 6:119, 6:121, 6:126, 6:138, 6:152, 7:2, 7:3, 7:26, 7:57, 7:63, 7:69, 7:130, 7:165, 7:201, 8:2, 8:57, 9:126, 10:3, 11:24, 11:30, 11:114, 11:120, 12:42, 12:104, 13:19, 13:28, 14:5, 14:25, 14:52, 15:6, 15:9, 16:13, 16:17, 16:43, 16:44, 16:90, 17:41, 17:46, 18:28, 18:57, 18:70, 18:83, 18:101, 19:2, 20:3, 20:14, 20:34, 20:42, 20:44, 20:99, 20:113, 20:124, 21:2, 21:7, 21:10, 21:24, 21:42, 21:48, 21:50, 21:84, 21:105, 22:35, 23:71, 23:85, 23:110, 24:1, 24:27, 24:37, 25:18, 25:29, 25:50, 25:62, 25:73, 26:5, 26:209, 26:227, 27:62, 28:43, 28:46, 28:51, 29:45, 29:51, 32:4, 32:15, 32:22, 33:34, 33:41, 35:37, 36:11, 36:19, 36:69, 37:3, 37:13, 37:155, 37:168, 38:1, 38:8, 38:29, 38:32, 38:43, 38:46, 38:49, 38:87, 39:9, 39:21, 39:22, 39:23, 39:27, 39:45, 40:13, 40:54, 40:58, 41:41, 43:5, 43:36, 43:44, 44:13, 44:58, 45:23, 47:18, 47:20, 50:8, 50:37, 50:45, 51:49, 51:55, 52:29, 53:29, 54:17, 54:22, 54:25, 54:32, 54:40, 56:62, 56:73, 57:16, 58:19, 62:9, 63:9, 65:10, 68:51, 68:52, 69:12, 69:42, 69:48, 72:17, 73:19, 74:31, 74:49, 74:54, 74:55, 74:56, 76:29, 77:5, 79:43, 80:4, 80:11, 80:12, 81:27, 87:9, 87:10, 88:21, 89:23, 94:4, 79:35)",
      "d": "«Dhikr» and «Tadhkirah»: The opposite of «zakara» (to remember) is «nasiya» (to forget). «Zakara» means to remember and to be reminded, which is the opposite of forgetting. The Quran is called «Dhikr» because it reminds humanity of their innate natural inclination towards good and the covenant of «Alast». Therefore, it is also an admonition. And «Tadhkirah» means both admonition and a reminder in this sense. Also, a ticket for a ride, like a train or airplane, is called «tadhkirah». And a certificate and passport are also called that (Quranic usage).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«A unzila 'alihil-dhikru min baynina» (38:8)\nTranslation: Has the Reminder (Admonition) been sent down upon him from among us?\nFurthermore, Allah the Exalted says:\n«Inna hathihi tadhkirah» (73:19)\nTranslation: Indeed, this Quran is an admonition."
    },
    {
      "id": 2175,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Different Names of the Quran",
      "hw": "قرآن",
      "s": "«Kitabun Mubin» means the clear and luminous book, referring to the Noble Quran (12 verses: 5:15, 6:59, 10:61, 11:6, 12:1, 26:2, 27:1, 27:75, 28:2, 34:3, 43:2, 44:2)",
      "d": "«Bana» means to become distant and separate. «Bayyin» contains three meanings: (1) separation, (2) distance, (3) clarity and lucidity. And «bayyana» means to explain something by clarifying it. And «Kitabun Mubin» means a book in which every matter related to guidance is explained with full clarification and exposition. The clear and luminous book, meaning the Noble Quran.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«Qad ja'akum minallahi nurun wa kitabun mubin» (5:15)\nTranslation: There has come to you from Allah a light and a clear Book."
    },
    {
      "id": 2176,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Different Names of the Quran",
      "hw": "قرآن",
      "s": "«Hadith» means the appearance of something new (28 verses: 4:42, 4:78, 4:87, 4:140, 6:68, 7:185, 12:6, 12:21, 12:101, 12:111, 18:6, 20:9, 23:44, 31:6, 33:53, 34:19, 39:23, 45:6, 51:24, 52:34, 53:59, 56:81, 66:3, 68:44, 77:50, 79:15, 85:17, 88:1)",
      "d": "«Hadatha» means the appearance of something new. Its opposite is «'adam», meaning non-existence, disappearance. And «Hadith» refers to every matter that did not exist before and appears anew. Something new.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«La'allaAllaha yuhdithu ba'da thalika amran» (65:1)\nTranslation: Perhaps Allah will bring about after that a new matter.\nThen, the term «Hadith» is also applied to anything that existed before but had faded from people's minds over time. If it is revived anew, then it is also called «Hadith». Something new. The Quran is called «Hadith» in these very meanings.\nFor example: Allah the Exalted says:\n«Allahu nazzala ahsanal-hadith» (39:23)\nTranslation: Allah has sent down the best statement (Hadith)."
    }
  ],
  "471": [
    {
      "id": 2177,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Sacrificial Animal",
      "hw": "قربانی",
      "s": "«Budn» refers to the sacrificial camels that are slaughtered during Hajj (1 verse: 22:36)",
      "d": "«Budn» is the plural of «budnah». And «badan» refers to the body of every living creature, provided its blood has not dried up (Fal 115). And «badana» and «baddana» mean to be fat. And «budn» means sacrificial camels that are taken to Makkah to be slaughtered (Mufradat). And sacrificial camels are also called «budn» due to their large bodies and fatness (Mufradat).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«W-al-budna ja'alnahā lakum min sha'a'irillah» (22:36)\nTranslation: And We have made the sacrificial camels among the symbols of Allah for you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2178,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Sacrificial Animal",
      "hw": "قربانی",
      "s": "«Nusuk» refers to every type of animal that is slaughtered in Mina (2 verses: 2:196, 6:162)",
      "d": "The word «nasak» implies worship and seeking closeness to Allah. «Nasik» means an ascetic. And «nasiykah» is the term for a sacrificial animal offered to seek closeness to Allah (M. L.). And «nusuk» is the plural of «nasiykah». Then this word became generally associated with Hajj. «Manasikul-Hajj» means the rites and rulings of Hajj. And also the places where these rulings are performed. Similarly, «nusuk» refers to those sacrificial animals that are slaughtered at the place of Mina during the days of Tashriq.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«Faman kāna minkum maridan aw bihi adhan min ra'sihi fa-fidyatun min siyamin aw sadaqatin aw nusukin» (2:196)\nTranslation: Then whoever among you is ill or has an ailment of the head (and must shave his head before the sacrifice), then an expiation by fasting, charity, or sacrifice (nusuk) is due."
    },
    {
      "id": 2179,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Sacrificial Animal",
      "hw": "قربانی",
      "s": "«Hady» is the sacrificial animal that the pilgrim takes with him for slaughter (5 verses: 2:196, 5:2, 5:95, 5:97, 48:25)",
      "d": "«Hady» is the plural of «hadyah». It means the sacrificial animal that is sent towards the Sacred House for slaughter, whether it is a camel, cow, or sheep, and whether it is male or female (Manjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«Wa la tahliqu ru'usakum hatta yablugha al-hadyu mahillah» (2:196)\nTranslation: And do not shave your heads until the sacrificial animal (had-y) reaches its place of slaughter."
    },
    {
      "id": 2180,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Sacrificial Animal",
      "hw": "قربانی",
      "s": "«Qala'id» refers to those sacrificial animals on which a collar or band has been placed (2 verses: 5:2, 5:97)",
      "d": "«Qala'id» is the plural of «qaladah» and «qallada». It means to put a necklace on someone's neck. And «qaladah» means a necklace (Manjad). Then «qaladah» also refers to a sacrificial animal on which a collar or band has been placed as a sign, whether it is related to Hajj or fulfilling a vow.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«Ya ayyuhalladhina amanu la tuhillu sha'a'irillah wa la ash-shahral-harama wa la al-hadya wa la al-qala'id» (5:2)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, do not violate the rites of Allah, nor the sacred month, nor the sacrificial animals, nor the garlands (qala'id) [marking them as sacrificial]."
    }
  ],
  "472": [
    {
      "id": 2182,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Oath. Taking an Oath",
      "hw": "قسم",
      "s": "The word «Yamin» is used for taking an oath, and for removing an accusation, and for strengthening a covenant and pledge (19 verses: 2:224, 2:225, 3:77, 5:53, 5:89, 5:108, 6:109, 9:12, 9:13, 16:38, 16:91, 16:92, 16:94, 24:53, 35:42, 58:16, 63:2, 66:2, 68:39)",
      "d": "«Yamin» comes in the context of clearing oneself from blame.\nA Prophetic Hadith states: «Al-bayyina 'ala al-mudda'i wa al-yamin 'ala al-mudda'i 'alayh» (Sunan Tirmidhi: Hadith 1341)\nTranslation: Abdullah ibn 'Amr (may Allah be pleased with them both) reported that the Messenger of Allah (peace be upon him) said in his sermon: \"The burden of proof is on the claimant, and the oath is on the one who denies (the claim).\"\nMeaning: Presenting evidence is the responsibility of the claimant (the one making the claim). And if they cannot do that, then the oath is upon the one against whom the claim is made.\nAnd «Yamin» also means the right hand. It was the custom of the Arabs that when someone wanted to strengthen a promise or pledge with an oath, the person taking the oath would place their right hand on the other's hand. Hence, the word «Yamin» began to be used for an oath. Its plural is «Ayman» (Mufradat). The word «Yamin» is a borrowed (musta'arah) term for an oath (Faqih 43).\nThen sometimes the Arabs would also place hand over hand merely to add emphasis in speech and take an oath, but it had no relation to reality. Allah the Exalted has declared such oaths as vain and forgivable. And an oath that is in fact based on reality is called «Yamin Mu'niqadah», which is enforceable.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«La yu'akhidhukumullahu bil-lagwi fi aymanikum wa la-yu'akhidhukum bima kasabat qulubukum» (2:225)\nTranslation: Allah will not call you to account for what is unintentional in your oaths, but He will call you to account for what your hearts have earned (i.e., intentional oaths)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2184,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Oath. Taking an Oath",
      "hw": "قسم",
      "s": "«Aliyah» is used for swearing an oath to avoid doing a good deed (1 verse: 24:22)",
      "d": "«Ala (ya'lu aylan)» has essentially two meanings: (1) to be neglectful in a matter and to procrastinate.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«La ya'lunakum khabalan» (3:118)\nTranslation: They will not spare any effort to cause you corruption.\n(2) To take an oath. And «Aliyah» means an oath. An oath that causes trouble and hardship to the one taking it (Mufradat). And according to Ibn al-Faris, it is an oath not to do a good deed (M. L.).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«Wa la ya'tili ulul-fadli minkum was-sa'ati an yu'tu ulil-qurba wal-masakin» (24:22)\nTranslation: And let not those among you who are blessed with means and wealth swear not to give [aid] to their relatives, the poor, and the emigrants for the cause of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2185,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Oath. Taking an oath.",
      "hw": "قسم",
      "s": "«إيلاء» Taking an oath to sever relations with one's wife (1 verse: 2:226)",
      "d": "«آلاء یؤلوا إیلاءً»: meaning to take an oath to live apart from one's wife and discontinue sexual relations (singular). In pre-Islamic times, people used this oath to greatly distress and harass their wives. Sharia has set a maximum period of four months for this, thereby closing the door to this evil.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«لِلَّذِیۡنَ یُؤۡلُوۡنَ مِنۡ نِّسَآئِہِمۡ تَرَبُّصُ اَرۡبَعَۃِ اَشۡہُرٍ» (2/226)\nTranslation: Those who take an oath to sever relations with their wives must wait for four months."
    },
    {
      "id": 2186,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Breaking an oath.",
      "hw": "قسم",
      "s": "«نَکَثَ» is a common and well-known word for breaking an oath (6 verses: 7:135-9:12-9:13-16:92-43:50-48:10)",
      "d": "«نَکَثَ» is a common and well-known word for breaking an oath. Breaking the oath of a contract, sale, or covenant, etc. (dictionary)\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«اَلَا تُقَاتِلُوۡنَ قَوۡمًا نَّکَثُوۡۤا اَیۡمَانَہُمۡ» (9/13)\nTranslation: Will you not fight a people who broke their oaths?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2187,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Breaking an oath.",
      "hw": "قسم",
      "s": "«نَقَضَ» To render an oath ineffective and ruined through tricks and excuses (9 verses: 2:27-4:155-5:13-8:56-13:20-13:25-16:91-16:92-18:77)",
      "d": "«نَقَضَ» means destruction. «نَقْضَ الْبَنَاء» means to demolish a building. «نَقَضَ الْحَبْل» means to untie a rope. «نَقَّضَ الْعَھْد وَ الْاَمْر» means to ruin a covenant or agreement after its firmness through tricks and excuses. And «نَقَّضَ الْاَمْن» means to spread disorder. To ruin peace (dictionary). Thus, the word «نَقَّضَ» is used in a much wider sense than «نَکَثَ» (also see breaking).\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَنۡقُضُوا الۡاَیۡمَانَ بَعۡدَ تَوۡکِیۡدِہَا» (16/91)\nTranslation: And do not break the oaths after their confirmation."
    }
  ],
  "473": [
    {
      "id": 2189,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Fortress",
      "hw": "قلعہ",
      "s": "«حُصُوْن» means fortress, a secure place. «حِصْن» is a fortress that is surrounded and where protection and refuge are arranged (1 Verse: 59:2)",
      "d": "«حُصُوْن» is the plural of «حِصْن», meaning a fortress that is surrounded and where protection and refuge are arranged. And it refers to any place where one can find safety (M. L.). Fortresses that also have trenches, so one can take refuge there, protect oneself, and also confront the enemy.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ ظَنُّوۡۤا أَنَّہُمۡ مَّانِعَتُہُمۡ حُصُوۡنُہُمۡ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ» (59/2)\nTranslation: And they [the Jews] thought that their fortresses would protect them from Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2190,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Fortress",
      "hw": "قلعہ",
      "s": "«صَیَاصِی» Meaning fortresses, places of refuge. Any thing that can be used for one's defense and protection. (1 verse: 33:26)",
      "d": "«صَیَاصِی» is the plural of «صِیْصِیَہ», meaning any such thing through which one can protect oneself. Even a cow's horn is called «صِیْصِیَہ» because it protects itself (singular). Meaning: places of protection or fortresses. Any fortress-like thing. The war fortresses of the Jews.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ اَنۡزَلَ الَّذِیۡنَ ظَاہَرُوۡہُمۡ مِّنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ مِنۡ صَیَاصِیۡہِمۡ وَ قَذَفَ فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِہِمُ الرُّعۡبَ» (33/26)\nTranslation: And Allah brought down those among the People of the Book who had supported the disbelievers from their fortresses and cast terror into their hearts."
    },
    {
      "id": 2191,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Fortress",
      "hw": "قلعہ",
      "s": "«بُرُوْج» Some tall, strong, and dome-shaped building (4 verses: 4:78-15:16-25:61-85:1)",
      "d": "«بُرُوْج» is the plural of «بُرْج», meaning to be visible, to be high. And «بَرَّج» means to build a tower. And «بُرْج» means any tall building with a dome, such as a fortress, domed palace, etc. (dictionary)\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«اَیۡنَ مَا تَکُوۡنُوۡا یُدۡرِکۡکُّمُ الۡمَوۡتُ وَ لَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ  فِیۡ  بُرُوْجٍ مُّشَیَّدَۃٍ» (4/78)\nTranslation: Wherever you are, death will overtake you, even if you are in fortified towers."
    },
    {
      "id": 2192,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Fortress",
      "hw": "قلعہ",
      "s": "«مَحَارِیْب» are places where war-related matters are decided and which are also secure (5 Verses: 3:37-3:39-19:11-34:13-38:21)",
      "d": "«مَحَارِیْب» is the plural of «مِحْرَاب». It means the beginning part of a house, the head of a council, the place where people gather. And «مِحْرَاب» also means a warrior, a fighter, and a brave person (Majid). And any place where war plans or preparations are made, or where fighting can occur. Therefore, it also comes in the meanings of fortress (M. Q).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ لَہٗ مَا یَشَآءُ مِنۡ مَّحَارِیۡبَ وَ تَمَاثِیۡلَ» (34/13)\nTranslation: They [the jinn] worked for him [Sulaiman] as he desired, [building] fortresses and statues."
    }
  ],
  "474": [
    {
      "id": 2193,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Shirt",
      "hw": "قمیص",
      "s": "«قَمِیْص» Meaning clothing, shirt (6 verses: 12:18-12:25-12:26-12:27-12:28-12:93)",
      "d": "«قَمِیْص» means clothing, shirt.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ  کَانَ  قَمِیۡصُہٗ  قُدَّ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ فَکَذَبَتۡ» (12/27)\nTranslation: And if his shirt is torn from the back, then she has lied."
    },
    {
      "id": 2194,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Shirt",
      "hw": "قمیص",
      "s": "«سَرَابِیْل» A shirt or any garment that is worn (2 verses: 14:50-16:81)",
      "d": "«سَرَابِیْل» is the plural of «سریال». It is used for both shirt and pajama. And according to the author of Munjid, it means a shirt or any garment that is worn (dictionary).\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَّ جَعَلَ لَکُمۡ سَرَابِیۡلَ تَقِیۡکُمُ  الۡحَرَّ» (16/81)\nTranslation: And He has made for you garments that protect you from the heat."
    }
  ],
  "475": [
    {
      "id": 2195,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Giving strength",
      "hw": "قوت",
      "s": "«اَیَّدَ» To help someone by providing ample strength (9 verses: 2:87-2:253-5:110-8:26-8:62-9:40-38:17-58:22-61:14)",
      "d": "«الأيَّد» means intense strength (singular). And «أَيَّدَ» means to provide abundant help to someone and to strengthen them, to support.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَاَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ سَکِیۡنَتَہٗ عَلَیۡہِ وَ اَیَّدَہٗ  بِجُنُوۡدٍ لَّمۡ تَرَوۡہَا» (9/40)\nTranslation: Then Allah sent down His tranquility upon him and supported him with armies you did not see."
    },
    {
      "id": 2196,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To Empower",
      "hw": "قوت",
      "s": "«اٰزَرَ» inherently means to give strength to something from one's own essence and make it strong (1 verse: 48:29)",
      "d": "«اَلْاِزْر» means root or foundation. And «اَلْاِزَار» means cloak, garment, veil, curtain, or a wall's backing (a pile of soil built alongside a wall to strengthen it). And «اٰزَرَ الْبَنَات» means the intertwining of plants. And «اَزَّرَ» means to strengthen someone, to impart strength (as in 'minjad'). Thus, the word «اٰزَرَ» is used to denote inherent strengthening of something.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«کَزَرۡعٍ اَخۡرَجَ شَطۡئَہٗ فَاٰزَرَہٗ فَاسۡتَغۡلَظَ فَاسۡتَوٰی عَلٰی سُوۡقِہٖ یُعۡجِبُ الزُّرَّاعَ لِیَغِیۡظَ بِہِمُ الۡکُفَّارَ» (48/29)\nTranslation: Like a crop that produces its shoot, then strengthens it, then it becomes thick, then stands upright on its stem in a way that delights the farmers, so that Allah may ignite the hearts of the disbelievers through their progress."
    },
    {
      "id": 2197,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To Empower",
      "hw": "قوت",
      "s": "«عَزَّزَ» means to give such strength to a subordinate (underling) that they are no longer subordinate (1 verse: 36:14)",
      "d": "«عَزَّ» means honor, and its opposite is «ذَلَّ» meaning humiliation. And «عَزَّ» also means being independent, i.e., not being under someone's authority. And «اَعَزَّ» means to grant honor to someone. And «عَزَّزَ» means to give such strength or assistance to a subordinate that they become respected in society and attain honor. And honor is a state that protects a person from being subordinate or defeated (as per 'Mufradat' and 'Minjad').\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«اِذۡ  اَرۡسَلۡنَاۤ  اِلَیۡہِمُ  اثۡنَیۡنِ  فَکَذَّبُوۡہُمَا فَعَزَّزۡنَا بِثَالِثٍ» (36/14)\nTranslation: When We sent two (messengers) to them, they denied them, so We strengthened them with a third."
    }
  ],
  "476": [
    {
      "id": 2198,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«قِیَامَۃ» means that which is established in every way (70 verses: 2:85-2:113-2:174-2:212-3:55-3:77-3:161-3:180-3:185-3:194-4:87-4:109-4:141-4:159-5:14-5:36-5:64-6:12-7:32-7:167-7:172-10:60-10:93-11:60-11:98-11:99-16:25-16:27-16:92-16:124-17:13-17:58-17:62-17:97-18:105-19:95-20:100-20:101-20:124-21:47-22:9-22:17-22:69-23:16-25:69-28:41-28:42-28:61-28:71-28:72-29:13-29:25-32:25-35:14-39:15-39:24-39:31-39:47-39:60-39:67-41:40-42:45-45:17-45:26-46:5-58:7-60:3-68:39-75:1-75:6)",
      "d": "«قِیَامَۃ» means that which is established in every way. A day or era that will be established to fulfill the demands of truth and justice. Due to the various states and distinctions of that era, the Quran mentions various names for the Day of Resurrection.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«کُلُّ نَفۡسٍ ذَآئِقَۃُ الۡمَوۡتِ ؕ وَ اِنَّمَا تُوَفَّوۡنَ اُجُوۡرَکُمۡ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (3/185)\nTranslation: Every soul shall taste death, and you will be given your full recompense only on the Day of Resurrection."
    },
    {
      "id": 2199,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«اَلسَّاعَۃ» means a specific hour, moment, time (36 verses: 6:31-6:40-7:187-12:107-15:85-16:77-18:21-18:36-19:75-20:15-21:49-22:1-22:7-22:55-25:11-30:12-30:14-30:55-31:34-33:63-34:3-40:46-40:59-41:47-41:50-42:17-42:18-43:61-43:66-43:85-45:27-45:32-47:18-54:1-54:46-79:42)",
      "d": "«سَاعَۃ» means hour. And «اَلسَّاعَۃ» means a specific hour. In the Quran, «اَلسَّاعَۃ» generally refers to the hour when the trumpet will be blown for the first time.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا جَآءَتۡہُمُ السَّاعَۃُ  بَغۡتَۃً  قَالُوۡا یٰحَسۡرَتَنَا عَلٰی مَا فَرَّطۡنَا فِیۡہَا» (6/31)\nTranslation: Until when the Hour comes upon them suddenly, they will say: 'Alas for us for what we neglected therein!'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2200,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«یَوْمُ الدِّیْن» means the day when recompense for deeds will be given (13 verses: 1:3-15:35-26:82-37:20-38:78-51:12-56:56-70:26-74:46-82:15-82:17-82:18)",
      "d": "«یَوْمُ الدِّیْن» is the day or era when everyone will be given reward or punishment for their good or bad deeds. The day when recompense for deeds will be given. The Day of Resurrection.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«مٰلِکِ یَوۡمِ الدِّیۡنِ» (1/3)\nTranslation: The Master of the Day of Recompense."
    },
    {
      "id": 2201,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«یَوْمُ الْخُرُوْج» means the day of emerging from graves (1 verse: 50:42)",
      "d": "«یَوْمُ الْخُرُوْج» is the day of coming out of graves. With the second blowing of the trumpet, the dead will rise from their graves and stand up.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«یَّوۡمَ  یَسۡمَعُوۡنَ الصَّیۡحَۃَ  بِالۡحَقِّ ؕ ذٰلِکَ یَوۡمُ  الۡخُرُوۡجِ» (50/42)\nTranslation: The Day they will hear the cry in truth, that is the Day of coming forth."
    },
    {
      "id": 2202,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«یَوْمُ الْحِسَاب» means the day of reckoning and accounting for people's deeds (4 verses: 38:16-38:26-38:53-40:27)",
      "d": "«یَوْمُ الْحِسَاب» is the day of reckoning and accounting for people's deeds. The day of accountability. And this accounting will be the responsibility of Allah Himself.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«اِنَّ  اِلَیۡنَاۤ  اِیَابَہُمۡ ثُمَّ  اِنَّ  عَلَیۡنَا حِسَابَہُمۡ» (88/25,26)\nTranslation: Indeed, to Us is their return, then indeed, upon Us is their account.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا رَبَّنَا عَجِّلۡ  لَّنَا قِطَّنَا قَبۡلَ یَوۡمِ  الۡحِسَابِ» (38/16)\nTranslation: And they say: 'Our Lord, hasten for us our share [of the punishment] before the Day of Account.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2203,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«یَوْمُ الْفَصْل» means the day of separation between believers and disbelievers (6 verses: 37:21-44:40-77:13-77:14-77:38-78:17)",
      "d": "«یَوْمُ الْفَصْل» is the day of separation. The day when believers and disbelievers will be separated. And this will happen after the judgment is passed. The people of Paradise and the people of Hell will be separated.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«ہٰذَا یَوۡمُ الۡفَصۡلِ ۚ جَمَعۡنٰکُمۡ وَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (77/38)\nTranslation: This is the Day of Separation; We have gathered you and the former [peoples]."
    },
    {
      "id": 2204,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«غَاشِیَۃ» means one thing enveloping or covering another (2 verses: 12:107-88:1)",
      "d": "«غَشِی» refers to a state where a person's senses are lost. And «غَاشِیَۃ» means that thing whose awe will envelop everyone. That which causes loss of senses.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«ہَلۡ  اَتٰىکَ حَدِیۡثُ  الۡغَاشِیَۃِ» (88/1)\nTranslation: Has there come to you the news of the Overwhelming [event]?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2205,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«اَلْوَاقِعَۃ» means that which is about to occur (2 verses: 56:1-69:15)",
      "d": "«اَلْوَاقِعَۃ» means that which will definitely happen. That which is inevitable.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«اِذَا وَقَعَتِ الۡوَاقِعَۃُ لَیۡسَ  لِوَقۡعَتِہَا  کَاذِبَۃٌ» (56:1,2)\nTranslation: When the Inevitable [event] befalls, there will be no denial of its having occurred."
    },
    {
      "id": 2206,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Judgment and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«اَلْحَاقَّۃ» that the establishment of which is demanded by truth. (3 verses: 69:1-69:2-69:3)",
      "d": "«حَقَّ» meaning 'necessary' and 'to be established' (source) and «حَاقَّۃ» meaning that the establishment of which is demanded by truth, enduring reality.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ مَاۤ اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا الۡحَآقَّۃُ» (69/3)\nTranslation: And what do you know what the Inevitable Reality is?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2207,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Judgment and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«صَآخَّۃ» a sound that deafens the ears. (1 verse: 80:33)",
      "d": "«صَآخَّۃ» a sound that deafens the ears (source) such a harsh and shrill sound that bursts the eardrums. This quality will occur at the time of the first blowing of the trumpet.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَتِ الصَّآخَّۃُ» (80/33)\nTranslation: So when the Deafening (the Day of Judgment) comes."
    },
    {
      "id": 2208,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Judgment and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«اٰزِفَۃ» meaning near at hand, about to arrive. (2 verses: 40:18-53:57)",
      "d": "In «اَزِفَ» the meaning of the shortness of time is found (abbreviation) as we say that the time for the train to depart has become short. And «اٰزِفَۃ» meaning near at hand, about to arrive.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ اَنۡذِرۡہُمۡ یَوۡمَ الۡاٰزِفَۃِ» (40/18)\nTranslation: And warn them of the Day that is near at hand."
    },
    {
      "id": 2209,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Judgment and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«قَارِعَۃ» meaning to strike one thing against another so that a sound is produced. (5 verses: 13:31-69:4-101:1-101:2-101:3)",
      "d": "«قَرَعَ» meaning to strike one thing against another so that a sound is produced. And «قَرَعَ الْبَاب» meaning he knocked on the door. And «قَارِعَۃ» meaning the Striking One. And according to Ibn al-Faris, everything that descends upon man with severity is «قَارِعَۃ» (source). The Almighty says:\n«وَ مَاۤ اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا الۡقَارِعَۃُ» (101/3) \"And what do you know what the Striking Calamity is?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 2210,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Judgment and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«طَآمَّۃُ الْکُبْرٰی» a calamity that encompasses all other afflictions. (1 verse: 79:34)",
      "d": "«اَلطَّمُّ» meaning a sea filled with water. And «طَمَّ» meaning to be filled. «طَمَّ الْبِئْرَ» means he filled the well with soil. And «طَامَّۃ» meaning a calamity that encompasses all other afflictions.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَتِ الطَّآمَّۃُ الۡکُبۡرٰی» (79/34)\nTranslation: Then when the Great Overwhelming Calamity comes."
    }
  ],
  "477": [
    {
      "id": 2211,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Prison",
      "hw": "قید",
      "s": "«سِجْن» meaning prison, jail. (7 verses: 12:33-12:35-12:36-12:39-12:41-12:42-12:100)",
      "d": "«سِجْن» meaning prison, jail. It is a well-known word. A place where people sentenced by court are kept in confinement.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَلَبِثَ فِی السِّجۡنِ بِضۡعَ سِنِیۡنَ» (12/42)\nTranslation: Then Joseph remained in the prison for several years."
    },
    {
      "id": 2212,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Prison",
      "hw": "قید",
      "s": "«حَصِیْر» meaning to encircle, to besiege. (1 verse: 17:8)",
      "d": "«حَصَرَ» meaning to encircle something from all sides. To besiege. And «حَصِیْر» meaning a place of confinement for someone.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ جَعَلۡنَا جَہَنَّمَ لِلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ حَصِیۡرًا» (17/8)\nTranslation: And We have made Hell a prison for the disbelievers."
    },
    {
      "id": 2213,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To imprison; to make a captive",
      "hw": "قید",
      "s": "«حَبَسَ» to prevent someone from disposing of their property and needs. (2 verses: 5:106-11:8)",
      "d": "«حَبَسَ» meaning to prevent someone from rising (abbreviation) and «حَبَسَ الشَّیْ» meaning to protect something completely. And «مَحْبَسَۃ» meaning prison. Also the seclusion of ascetics and devotees. «حَابَسَ» meaning to keep someone detained. To keep in custody (source). Also «حَبَسَ» meaning «مَنَعَ عَنِ التَّصَرُّف» (Fiqh 93) i.e., to prevent someone from disposing of their property. And «مَحْبَس» meaning a police station where the accused are kept in custody during investigation (police).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«تَحۡبِسُوۡنَہُمَا مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ الصَّلٰوۃِ فَیُقۡسِمٰنِ بِاللّٰہِ» (5/106)\nTranslation: You detain both of them after the prayer and they will swear by Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2214,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To imprison; to make a captive",
      "hw": "قید",
      "s": "«اَثْبَتَ» to take someone into one's custody by binding them, to place under arrest. (1 verse: 8:30)",
      "d": "«اَثْبَتَ» meaning to bind someone with fetters (source) i.e., to prevent someone from movement by tying them up. And to keep in one's custody.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ اِذۡ یَمۡکُرُ بِکَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لِیُثۡبِتُوۡکَ اَوۡ یَقۡتُلُوۡکَ اَوۡ یُخۡرِجُوۡکَ» (8/30)\nTranslation: And remember, O Muhammad, when the disbelievers were plotting against you to imprison you or kill you or expel you (from your home)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2215,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To imprison; to make a captive",
      "hw": "قید",
      "s": "«اَسَرَ» to make someone a captive by binding them during battle. (4 verses: 2:85-8:67-8:70-33:26-)",
      "d": "The meaning of «اَسَرَ» is also to tie someone with a rope (source). The difference between «اَسَرَ» and «اَثْبَتَ» is that «اَسَرَ» is used only for capturing someone during battle. «اَسِیْر» meaning war captive. And its plurals are «اَسْرٰی» and «اُسَارٰی».\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّاۡتُوۡکُمۡ اُسٰرٰی تُفٰدُوۡہُمۡ وَ ہُوَ مُحَرَّمٌ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اِخۡرَاجُہُمۡ» (2/85)\nTranslation: And if they come to you as captives, you ransom them, although it was forbidden for you to expel them.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«فَرِیۡقًا تَقۡتُلُوۡنَ وَ تَاۡسِرُوۡنَ فَرِیۡقًا» (33/26)\nTranslation: You killed a party of them and took another party captive."
    },
    {
      "id": 2216,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To imprison. To make a prisoner.",
      "hw": "قید",
      "s": "«سَجَنَ» to imprison someone as a punishment by the court after proof of crime (2 verses: 12:25-12:32).",
      "d": "«سَجَنَ» to imprison someone as a punishment by the court after proof of crime. To send to jail. For a judge to imprison someone as punishment for a crime. For example: In the Quran it is: «قَالَتۡ مَا جَزَآءُ مَنۡ اَرَادَ بِاَہۡلِکَ سُوۡٓءًا اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یُّسۡجَنَ اَوۡ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ» ( 12/25 ) Translation: Zulaikha said (to her husband), 'What is the punishment for one who intends evil against your wife except that he be imprisoned or punished painfully?'"
    }
  ],
  "478": [
    {
      "id": 2218,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To cut.",
      "hw": "کاٹنا",
      "s": "«صَرَمَ» to cut fruit clusters with a sharp tool (1 verse: 68:17).",
      "d": "«صَرَمَ» to cut the clusters of trees, etc., with a sharp instrument. «صَارِم» meaning sword and «صَرُمَ» meaning to cut with a sword. And «صَرُوْم» meaning the sword that cuts (meaning from Al-Munjid). For example: In the Quran it is: «اِنَّا  بَلَوۡنٰہُمۡ کَمَا بَلَوۡنَاۤ  اَصۡحٰبَ الۡجَنَّۃِ ۚ اِذۡ  اَقۡسَمُوۡا لَیَصۡرِمُنَّہَا مُصۡبِحِیۡنَ» ( 68/17 ) Translation: We have tried them as We tried the companions of the garden, when they swore they would cut it in the morning."
    },
    {
      "id": 2219,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To cut.",
      "hw": "کاٹنا",
      "s": "«قَطَعَ» to cut any thing and separate it (12 verses: 2:27-3:127-5:38-6:45-7:72-8:7-9:121-13:25-22:15-29:29-59:5-69:46).",
      "d": "«قَطَعَ» meaning to cut a thing and separate a part of it (meaning). For example: In the Quran it is: «مَا قَطَعۡتُمۡ مِّنۡ  لِّیۡنَۃٍ اَوۡ تَرَکۡتُمُوۡہَا قَآئِمَۃً عَلٰۤی اُصُوۡلِہَا فَبِاِذۡنِ اللّٰہِ» ( 59/5 ) Translation: Whatever you cut of palm trees or left standing on their roots, it was by permission of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2220,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To cut.",
      "hw": "کاٹنا",
      "s": "«قَطَّعَ» to cut into pieces (10 verses: 7:124-7:160-7:168-12:31-12:50-13:31-20:71-22:19-26:49-47:15).",
      "d": "«قَطَّعَ» meaning to cut something and make it into pieces. To make small pieces. For example: In the Quran it is: «وَ سُقُوۡا مَآءً حَمِیۡمًا فَقَطَّعَ  اَمۡعَآءَہُمۡ» ( 47/15 ) Translation: And they will be given to drink scalding water which will cut their intestines."
    },
    {
      "id": 2221,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To cut.",
      "hw": "کاٹنا",
      "s": "«بَتَرَ» to cut an animal's tail. To be childless (i.e., whose progeny has ended) (1 verse: 108:3).",
      "d": "«بَتَرَ» this word is specifically for cutting an animal's tail and metaphorically means childless or without offspring, i.e., one who has no children or whose mention in good has perished (meaning). For example: In the Quran it is: «اِنَّ شَانِئَکَ ہُوَ الۡاَبۡتَرُ» ( 108/3 ) Translation: Indeed, your enemy is the one without offspring and without name or mark."
    },
    {
      "id": 2222,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To cut.",
      "hw": "کاٹنا",
      "s": "«بَتْک» to cut or slit ears (1 verse: 4:119).",
      "d": "According to Khalil, «بَتْک» means to cut the ears (cutting the ear). And according to Imam Raghib, it means to slit the ears of animals or cut other organs, hair, etc. (meaning). In distant pre-Islamic times, people used to do such acts as a sign of vows and offerings. For example: In the Quran it is: «وَّ لَاُضِلَّنَّہُمۡ وَ لَاُمَنِّیَنَّہُمۡ وَ لَاٰمُرَنَّہُمۡ فَلَیُبَتِّکُنَّ اٰذَانَ الۡاَنۡعَامِ» ( 4/119 ) Translation: (Satan said) I will surely lead them astray, I will surely arouse in them sinful desires, and I will surely command them so they will slit the ears of cattle."
    },
    {
      "id": 2223,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To cut.",
      "hw": "کاٹنا",
      "s": "«عَضَّ» meaning to bite and cut (2 verses: 3:119-25:27).",
      "d": "«عَضَّ» to cut a living being with teeth (F. L. 110). For example: In the Quran it is: «وَ  یَوۡمَ یَعَضُّ الظَّالِمُ عَلٰی  یَدَیۡہِ یَقُوۡلُ یٰلَیۡتَنِی اتَّخَذۡتُ مَعَ الرَّسُوۡلِ سَبِیۡلًا» ( 25/27 ) Translation: And on the Day when the wrongdoer will bite at his hands and say, 'Oh, I wish I had taken with the Messenger a path.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2224,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To cut.",
      "hw": "کاٹنا",
      "s": "«خَضَدَ» to cut the thorns of a tree and clean it (1 verse: 56:28).",
      "d": "«خَضَدَ الشَّجَرَ» to cut off the thorns of a thorny tree and thus make it clean. To make it thornless (meaning from Al-Munjid). For example: In the Quran it is: «فِیۡ  سِدۡرٍ مَّخۡضُوۡدٍ» ( 56/28 ) Translation: (They will be) in thornless lote trees."
    },
    {
      "id": 2225,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To cut.",
      "hw": "کاٹنا",
      "s": "«جَذَّ» to cut a hard thing into pieces (2 verses: 11:108-21:58).",
      "d": "«جَذَّ» originally means to cut a hard thing and break it into fragments. And «اَلْجِذّ» means a cut piece, a small fragment. And «جُدَاد» or «جُداذ» means a cut piece, a piece of gold. And «اذات» means fine fragments or pieces of a cut thing (meaning from Al-Munjid). And it was used in the Quran in these meanings. «فَجَعَلَہُمۡ جُذٰذًا» (21/58) Translation: So he made them into fragments. Then this word began to be used in the meanings of cutting or breaking. For example: In the Quran it is: «عَطَآءً غَیۡرَ  مَجۡذُوۡذٍ» (11/108) Translation: A gift that is never cut off."
    },
    {
      "id": 2226,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To cut.",
      "hw": "کاٹنا",
      "s": "«عَقَرَ» to cut and inflict a wound (5 verses: 7:77-11:65-26:157-54:29-91:14).",
      "d": "In «عَقَر» the meaning of inflicting a wound is found (M. L.). «اَلْکَلْبُ الْعَقُوْر» meaning the biting dog. And «عَقَرَ النَّخْلَۃ» meaning to cut the palm tree from its root (Al-Munjid). For example: In the Quran it is: «فَکَذَّبُوۡہُ  فَعَقَرُوۡہَا» (91/14) Translation: So they denied him and they cut her hamstring."
    }
  ],
  "479": [
    {
      "id": 2229,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Paper",
      "hw": "کاغذ",
      "s": "«رَقّ» refers to any thin and soft thing that can be written on, whether blank or written. (1 verse: 52:3)",
      "d": "«رَقّ» means thin and soft. And «رِقَّت» refers to the softness of the heart, its opposite is «قساوت» meaning hardness of heart. And «رَقّ» is any thing that is thin and soft, e.g., a leaf, membrane, thin leather, or paper (muf). Thus, this word is general. «رَقّ» and «وَرْق» are synonymous, and its plural is «اَوْرَاق». For example, in the Quran: «وَ کِتٰبٍ مَّسۡطُوۡرٍ فِیۡ  رَقٍّ مَّنۡشُوۡرٍ» (52/2،3) Translation: And by the Book that is spread out in open leaves."
    },
    {
      "id": 2230,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Paper",
      "hw": "کاغذ",
      "s": "«قِرْطَاس» means written paper or documents; the early rag-pulp form of modern paper (1 Verse: 6:7)",
      "d": "«قِرْطَاس» means a written letter or document (Majid), whether it consists of several pages or sheets (M. Q.). 'Qirtas al-abyad' is a famous phrase meaning a clear and complete report issued on an important issue. «قِرْطَاس» actually also refers to that early rag-pulp form of paper which the Egyptians invented. At the time of the Quran's revelation, such paper was available but very rare.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ نَزَّلۡنَا عَلَیۡکَ کِتٰبًا فِیۡ قِرۡطَاسٍ فَلَمَسُوۡہُ بِاَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ» (6/7)\nTranslation: And even if We had sent down to you a written message on paper, and they had touched it with their hands..."
    }
  ],
  "480": [
    {
      "id": 2231,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To be sufficient",
      "hw": "کافی",
      "s": "«کَفٰی» means to be sufficient. To suffice for something and be independent of others. (30 verses: 2:137-3:124-4:6-4:45-4:50-4:55-4:70-4:79-4:81-4:132-4:166-4:171-10:29-13:43-15:95-17:14-17:17-17:65-17:96-21:47-25:31-25:58-29:51-29:52-33:3-33:25-33:39-33:48-46:8-48:28)",
      "d": "«کَفٰی» means to be sufficient. To suffice for something and be independent of others. Sometimes a preposition is added to the subject of «کَفٰی». For example, «کَفٰی بِاللہِ شَہِیْدَا» meaning Allah's testimony is sufficient and complete, making one independent of any other testimony (manjad). And «کَفَایَۃ» is that which is sufficient and makes one independent of others. And «مَکَافَات» means to recompense with an equal or greater favor (manjad). The word «کَفٰی» essentially means to give full recompense and even more. For example, in the Quran: «وَ کَفَی اللّٰہُ  الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ الۡقِتَالَ ؕ وَ کَانَ  اللّٰہُ   قَوِیًّا عَزِیۡزًا» (33/25) Translation: And Allah sufficed for the believers in the matter of fighting, and Allah is Strong, Mighty. A near-synonym of «کَفٰی» is «حَسْب». These two words are so close in meaning that one is used interchangeably without hesitation. For example, in the Quran: «حَسۡبُہٗ جَہَنَّم» (2/206) Translation: So Hell will be sufficient for them. Also, the Divine declaration is: «وَ کَفٰی  بِجَہَنَّم» (4/55) Translation: And the burning of Hell is sufficient. The difference is that if the overall aspect is considered, «کَفٰی» is used. If each individual aspect is considered, «حَسْب» is used. For example, in the Quran: «وَ کَفٰی بِاللّٰہِ حَسِیۡبًا» (4/6) Translation: Indeed, Allah is sufficient as a Reckoner."
    },
    {
      "id": 2232,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Be Sufficient",
      "hw": "کافی",
      "s": "«حَسْب» means to reckon, to count, to enumerate, then to keep an account of it. (11 Verses: 2:206-3:173-5:104-8:62-8:64-9:59-9:68-9:129-39:38-58:8-65:3)",
      "d": "«حَسَبَ» means to reckon, to count, to enumerate, then to keep an account of it. And «حَسَبَ» is a verbal noun, meaning to keep an account of something in consideration of each individual thing. There is no specific word in Urdu for this meaning. Therefore, its translation is taken as 'sufficient' (kafi). However, in Punjabi, there is a word for it: 'eichi bechi', meaning to keep an account of each need. Which conveys this meaning. That is, this matter or this work is sufficient for each of our needs and requirements. In other words, the word «حَسْب» is stronger than «کَفٰی». For example, the Quran states:\n«حَسۡبُنَا اللّٰہُ وَ نِعۡمَ الۡوَکِیۡلُ» (3/173)\nTranslation: Allah is sufficient for us, and He is the best Disposer of affairs."
    }
  ],
  "481": [
    {
      "id": 2234,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To be of use",
      "hw": "کام",
      "s": "«اَغْنٰی» means to be of use and to bring benefit. (10 verses: 7:48-11:101-12:67-15:84-26:207-39:50-40:82-46:26-69:28-111:2)",
      "d": "«اَغْنٰی» means for something to be sufficient and beneficial, so that the need and necessity for another thing ceases. (muf) For example, in the Quran: «مَاۤ  اَغۡنٰی عَنِّیۡ  مَالِیَہۡ ہَلَکَ عَنِّیۡ  سُلۡطٰنِیَہۡ» (69/28،29) Translation: My wealth has not availed me. My authority has gone from me."
    },
    {
      "id": 2235,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Work; to do work",
      "hw": "کام",
      "s": "«فَعَلَ» is an action that may be done intentionally or unintentionally. (85 verses: 2:24-2:68-2:71-2:85-2:197-2:215-2:231-2:234-2:240-2:253-2:279-2:282-3:28-3:40-3:115-3:135-3:188-4:25-4:30-4:66-4:114-4:127-4:147-5:67-5:79-6:112-6:137-6:159-7:28-7:155-7:173-8:73-10:36-10:46-10:106-11:36-11:87-12:32-12:89-14:27-14:45-16:33-16:35-16:50-16:91-18:82-21:23-21:59-21:62-21:63-21:73-22:14-22:18-22:77-24:41-25:68-26:19-26:20-26:74-26:226-27:34-27:88-30:40-33:6-34:54-37:34-37:102-39:70-42:25-46:9-49:6-54:52-58:13-60:1-61:2-61:3-63:9-66:6-75:25-77:18-82:12-83:36-85:7-89:6-105:1)",
      "d": "«فِعْل» is every action that results from an effective agent. The doer's intention may or may not be present, and whether the doer has a material existence or not, this term applies to all. Its plural is «افعال» (muf). And «فَعْلَۃً» means to do an action once. For example, in the Quran: «وَ فَعَلۡتَ فَعۡلَتَکَ الَّتِیۡ فَعَلۡتَ وَ اَنۡتَ مِنَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (26/19) Translation: (Pharaoh said to Moses) And you did an act which you did, and you are among the disbelievers. In this verse, the murder mentioned was unintentional on Moses' part. And for an intentional action: For example, the Divine declaration: «فَافۡعَلُوۡا مَا تُؤۡمَرُوۡنَ» (2/68) Translation: So do what you are commanded."
    },
    {
      "id": 2236,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Work; to do work",
      "hw": "کام",
      "s": "«عَمِلَ» is work done intentionally to fulfill a purpose. (309 verses: 2:25-2:62-2:74-2:82-2:85-2:96-2:110-2:134-2:139-2:140-2:141-2:144-2:149-2:167-2:217-2:233-2:234-2:237-2:265-2:271-2:277-2:283-3:22-3:30-3:57-3:98-3:99-3:120-3:153-3:156-3:163-3:180-3:195-4:17-4:18-4:57-4:94-4:108-4:110-4:122-4:123-4:124-4:128-4:135-4:173-5:5-5:8-5:9-5:53-5:62-5:66-5:69-5:71-5:90-5:93-5:105-6:43-6:54-6:60-6:88-6:108-6:122-6:127-6:132-6:135-7:42-7:43-7:53-7:118-7:129-7:139-7:147-7:153-7:180-8:39-8:47-8:48-8:72-9:9-9:16-9:17-9:37-9:69-9:94-9:102-9:105-9:120-9:121-10:4-10:9-10:12-10:14-10:23-10:41-10:61-10:81-11:7-11:11-11:15-11:16-11:23-11:46-11:78-11:92-11:93-11:111-11:112-11:121-11:123-12:19-12:69-13:29-14:18-14:23-14:42-15:93-16:28-16:32-16:34-16:63-16:93-16:96-16:97-16:111-16:119-17:9-17:84-18:2-18:7-18:30-18:49-18:79-18:88-18:103-18:105-18:107-18:110-19:60-19:96-20:75-20:82-20:112-21:27-21:74-21:82-21:94-22:14-22:23-22:50-22:56-22:68-23:51-23:63-23:100-24:24-24:28-24:38-24:39-24:53-24:55-24:64-25:23-25:70-25:71-26:112-26:168-26:169-26:188-26:216-26:227-27:4-27:19-27:24-27:84-27:90-27:93-28:15-28:55-28:67-28:80-28:84-29:4-29:7-29:8-29:9-29:38-29:55-29:58-30:15-30:41-30:44-30:45-31:8-31:15-31:23-31:29-32:12-32:14-32:17-32:19-33:2-33:9-33:19-33:31-33:71-34:4-34:11-34:12-34:13-34:25-34:33-34:37-35:7-35:8-35:10-35:37-36:35-36:54-36:71-37:39-37:61-37:96-38:24-38:28-39:7-39:35-39:39-39:65-39:70-40:37-40:40-40:58-41:5-41:8-41:20-41:22-41:27-41:33-41:40-41:46-41:50-42:15-42:22-42:23-42:26-43:72-45:15-45:21-45:28-45:29-45:30-45:33-46:14-46:15-46:16-46:19-47:1-47:2-47:4-47:8-47:9-47:12-47:14-47:28-47:30-47:32-47:33-47:35-48:11-48:24-48:29-49:2-49:14-49:18-52:16-52:19-52:21-53:31-56:24-57:4-57:10-58:3-58:6-58:7-58:11-58:13-58:15-59:18-60:3-62:8-63:2-63:11-64:2-64:7-64:8-64:9-65:11-66:7-66:11-67:2-77:43-84:25-85:11-95:6-98:7-99:6-99:7-99:8-103:3)",
      "d": "«عَمْل» is every action that emanates from a living being intentionally, whether good or bad. Its plural is «اَعْمَال» (muf). And the word «عَمَل» also comes in the context of labor and wages. For example, in the Quran: «اَمَّا السَّفِیۡنَۃُ  فَکَانَتۡ لِمَسٰکِیۡنَ یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ» (18/79) Translation: As for the ship, it belonged to some poor people who worked at sea."
    },
    {
      "id": 2237,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Work; to do work",
      "hw": "کام",
      "s": "«صَنَعَ» means to do work with technical skill. (18 verses: 5:14-5:63-7:137-11:16-11:37-11:38-13:31-16:112-18:104-20:39-20:41-20:69-21:80-23:27-24:30-27:88-29:45-35:8)",
      "d": "«صَنَعَ» means to accomplish a task with technical skill. It is more specific than «عَمَلَ» and is not used for animals (muf). And «صَنَّاع» means a craftsman, expert in one's work. For example, in the Quran: «وَ اصۡنَعِ الۡفُلۡکَ بِاَعۡیُنِنَا وَ وَحۡیِنَا» (11/37) Translation: And construct the ship under Our observation and Our inspiration."
    },
    {
      "id": 2238,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Work; to do work",
      "hw": "کام",
      "s": "«صَدَعَ» means to accomplish a task despite difficulties. (5 verses: 15:94-30:43-56:19-59:21-86:12)",
      "d": "«صَدَعَ» means to accomplish a task (manjad), to do something despite hardships and difficulties. And «صَدَعَ بِالْحَقّ» means to proclaim the truth openly. And «صَدَعَ الشَّیْ» means to tear something but not separate it (manjad). For example, in the Quran: «فَاصۡدَعۡ بِمَا تُؤۡمَرُ وَ اَعۡرِضۡ عَنِ الۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ» (15/94) Translation: So proclaim what you are commanded and turn away from the polytheists."
    },
    {
      "id": 2239,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Work; to do work",
      "hw": "کام",
      "s": "«جَرَحَ» generally used for doing a bad action. (1 verse: 6:60)",
      "d": "«جُرْحُ» means a wound. Its plural is «جُرُوْح». And «جَرَحَ» means to inflict a wound. «جَرَحَ بِالِلّسَان» means to wound with the tongue, to cause hurt with speech, to mention someone's faults and defects. And «جَرَحَ الشَّھَادَۃ» means to invalidate testimony (manjad). When this verb is used in the sense of doing an action, it is generally in a negative sense. For example, in the Quran: «وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ یَتَوَفّٰىکُمۡ بِالَّیۡلِ وَ یَعۡلَمُ مَا جَرَحۡتُمۡ بِالنَّہَارِ» (6/60) Translation: And He is the one who takes your souls by night and knows what you have done by day. And «اِجْتَرَحَ» specifically means to commit an action, i.e., to do a deed (muf. manjad). «اِجْتَرَحَ الْاِثْم» means he committed sin. For example, in the Quran: «اَمۡ  حَسِبَ الَّذِیۡنَ اجۡتَرَحُوا  السَّیِّاٰتِ اَنۡ نَّجۡعَلَہُمۡ کَالَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ» (45/21) Translation: Do those who commit evil deeds think that We will make them like those who believed and did righteous deeds?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2240,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Work. To do work.",
      "hw": "کام",
      "s": "«تَعَمَّدَ» means to do something bad knowingly (3 verses: 4:93, 5:95, 33:5)",
      "d": "«عَمَدَ» means to intend something and lean towards it. And «عَمَد» means a pillar; its plural is «عِمَاد». And «عَمُوْد» refers to the wood on which a tent is erected. And «تَعَمَّدَ» means to do something knowingly, i.e., to do something knowing it is bad, and its opposite is «سَھْو». (m.f.) For example, in the Quran: «وَ مَنۡ یَّقۡتُلۡ مُؤۡمِنًا مُّتَعَمِّدًا فَجَزَآؤُہٗ جَہَنَّمُ خٰلِدًا فِیۡہَا» (4/93) Translation: And whoever kills a believer intentionally, his reward is Hell, wherein he will abide forever."
    },
    {
      "id": 2241,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Work. To do work.",
      "hw": "کام",
      "s": "«اَمْر» this word is more general than just 'action' because its application includes speech as well as actions (85 verses: 2:117-2:210-2:275-3:47-3:109-3:128-3:147-3:154-3:159-3:186-4:83-5:95-6:8-6:58-6:159-8:42-8:43-8:44-9:48-9:50-10:3-10:31-10:71-11:44-11:123-12:15-12:18-12:21-12:41-12:83-12:102-13:2-13:31-14:22-15:66-16:77-18:10-18:16-18:21-18:28-18:73-18:82-19:21-19:35-19:39-20:26-20:32-20:62-21:93-22:41-22:67-22:76-23:53-24:62-27:32-27:33-31:17-31:22-32:5-33:36-35:4-36:82-40:44-40:68-42:38-42:43-42:53-43:79-44:4-45:17-45:18-47:26-49:7-50:5-51:4-54:3-54:12-57:5-59:15-64:5-65:3-65:4-65:9-79:5-97:4)",
      "d": "«اَمْر» means work, state, affair, matter, whether in speech or action; its plural is «اُمُوْر». This word is more general than just 'action' because its application includes speech as well as actions. It also applies to matters related to Divine will and decree. (m.f.) For example, in the Quran: «مَا کُنۡتُ قَاطِعَۃً  اَمۡرًا حَتّٰی تَشۡہَدُوۡنِ» (27/32) Translation: (The Queen of Sheba said to the chiefs) I do not decide any matter until you are present (and advise). In this verse, the word 'amr' gives the meanings of work, matter, and affair, and the matter has no existence either in speech or action. And «اَمْر» also means a command. In this sense, its plural is «اَوَامِرْ» and its opposite is «نَوَاھِی». And when «اَمْر» comes as a verb, its meaning is not 'to do' but 'to command'."
    },
    {
      "id": 2242,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Work. To do work.",
      "hw": "کام",
      "s": "«شَاْن» means to do something that is befitting one's status or appropriate to one's condition (2 verses: 24:62, 55:29)",
      "d": "«شَاْن» its plural is «شُؤُوْن», meaning great affairs, states, matters, conditions. And «مِنْ شَانِہٖ کَذَا» means 'to do such a thing is from his nature/disposition' (manj). Thus, 'shan' means to do something that is befitting one's status or appropriate to one's condition. For example, in the Quran: «یَسۡئَلُہٗ مَنۡ فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ ؕ کُلَّ یَوۡمٍ ہُوَ فِیۡ شَاۡنٍ» (55/29) Translation: All who are in the heavens and the earth ask of Him; every day He is upon some affair. At another place, the Divine decree states: «فَاِذَا اسۡتَاۡذَنُوۡکَ لِبَعۡضِ شَاۡنِہِمۡ فَاۡذَنۡ  لِّمَنۡ شِئۡتَ مِنۡہُمۡ» (24/62) Translation: When they ask your permission for some matter, give permission to whom you will among them."
    }
  ],
  "482": [
    {
      "id": 2244,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To be successful. To attain one's goal.",
      "hw": "کامیاب",
      "s": "«فَازَ» means to be saved from a calamity and simultaneously to reach a beloved thing (20 verses: 3:185, 4:13, 4:73, 5:119, 6:16, 9:72, 9:89, 9:100, 9:111, 10:64, 33:71, 37:60, 40:9, 44:57, 45:30, 48:5, 57:12, 61:12, 64:9, 85:11)",
      "d": "«فَازَ» means to be saved from a calamity and simultaneously to reach a beloved thing (faq 273) and also means to obtain good with safety. (m.f.) For example, in the Quran: «فَمَنۡ زُحۡزِحَ عَنِ النَّارِ وَ اُدۡخِلَ الۡجَنَّۃَ فَقَدۡ فَازَ» (3/185) Translation: Whoever is removed away from the Fire and admitted to Paradise, he has indeed attained his goal. «فَازَ»: This word is from the category of 'idhad' (words with opposite meanings). «فَاز» means both to be successful and to be saved, and also to be destroyed or to die. «فَوَّزَ الرَّجُل» means the man died. And «مَفَازَۃٌ» means both a cause or place of success and a cause or place of destruction (manj). As in the aforementioned verse, it has been used in the meaning of a place or cause of destruction. However, this word generally comes in the meanings of being successful by being saved from calamity and attaining the desired object. For example, in the Quran: «یّٰلَیۡتَنِیۡ کُنۡتُ مَعَہُمۡ فَاَفُوۡزَ فَوۡزًا عَظِیۡمًا» (4/73) Translation: The hypocrite will say, 'If only I had been with them, then I would have attained a great success.' Note: (Idhad refers to words that have two separate meanings that are opposite and contradictory to each other.)"
    }
  ],
  "483": [
    {
      "id": 2245,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To tremble, to shake",
      "hw": "کانپنا",
      "s": "«زَلْزَلَ»، «رَجَّ» and «رَجَفَ» all three are generally used for earthquake. «زَلْزَل» is general, «رَجَّ» indicates the initial state, and «رَجَفَ» indicates the intense state. And «مَارَ» indicates the shaking and swaying caused by rapid movement in anything (4 verses: 2:214, 22:1, 33:11, 99:1)",
      "d": "«زَلَّ» means for a foot to slip. And «زَلْزَل» has repetition in the word itself, indicating repetition in meaning, i.e., to slip repeatedly here and there (m.f.). And «زَلْزَلَۃ» means an earthquake, the earth shaking with jolts, moving and trembling here and there (fal 172). This word is specific for earthquake. For example, in the Quran: «اِذَا  زُلۡزِلَتِ الۡاَرۡضُ  زِلۡزَالَہَا» (99/1) Translation: When the earth is shaken with a mighty earthquake."
    },
    {
      "id": 2246,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To tremble, to shake",
      "hw": "کانپنا",
      "s": "«رَجّ» means to give motion to something, to give a jolt (1 verse: 56:4)",
      "d": "«رَجّ» means to give motion to something, to give a jolt (m.f.). This is the initial state of an earthquake (fal 60). For example, in the Quran: «اِذَا  رُجَّتِ الۡاَرۡضُ  رَجًّا» (56/4) Translation: When the earth is shaken with a quake."
    },
    {
      "id": 2247,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To tremble, to shake",
      "hw": "کانپنا",
      "s": "«رَجَفَ» means to be restless and anxious, to be agitated due to fear (6 verses: 7:78, 7:91, 7:155, 29:37, 73:14, 79:6)",
      "d": "«رَجَفَ» its basic meaning is intense agitation (m.l.). «بَحْرٌ رَجَّافٌ» means a turbulent sea. For example, in the Quran: «وَّ الۡمُرۡجِفُوۡنَ فِی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ» (33/60) Translation: And those who spread fear in the city (i.e., those who cause waves of unrest). And when related to the earth, it means severe jolts, the intense state of an earthquake (fal 60). For example, the Divine decree states: «یَوۡمَ تَرۡجُفُ الۡاَرۡضُ وَ الۡجِبَالُ وَ کَانَتِ الۡجِبَالُ  کَثِیۡبًا مَّہِیۡلًا» (73/14) Translation: The Day the earth and the mountains will shake, and the mountains will become a heap of sand pouring down."
    },
    {
      "id": 2248,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To tremble, to shake",
      "hw": "کانپنا",
      "s": "«مَارَ» means for something to shake and tremble back and forth due to rapid movement (2 verses: 52:9, 67:16)",
      "d": "«مَارَ» the basic concept is movement and rapidity. «اَلنَّاقَۃُ تَمُوْرُ فِیْ سَیْرِھَا» means the she-camel moves swiftly raising dust (m.f.). And «مَوْر» means to become dust and fly in the air (fal 31). And «مَارَ الشَّیء» means for something to shake and tremble back and forth due to rapid movement, to lose balance (manj). For example, in the Quran: «یَّوۡمَ تَمُوۡرُ السَّمَآءُ  مَوۡرًا» (52/9) Translation: The Day the heaven will sway with a dreadful swaying."
    }
  ],
  "484": [
    {
      "id": 2249,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "When?",
      "hw": "کب",
      "s": "«اَیَّان» is used to ask about the time of an event (6 verses: 7:187, 16:21, 27:65, 51:12, 75:6, 79:42)",
      "d": "«اَیَّان» comes to ask about the time of an event (m.f.). For example, in the Quran: «یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ السَّاعَۃِ  اَیَّانَ مُرۡسٰہَا» (79/42) Translation: (O Prophet!) they ask you about the Hour, when will it come to pass?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2250,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "When?",
      "hw": "کب",
      "s": "«مَتٰی» this word is used in Arabic grammar for condition and interrogation (9 verses: 2:214, 10:48, 17:51, 21:38, 27:71, 32:28, 34:29, 36:48, 67:25)",
      "d": "«مَتٰی» besides time, it also gives the meaning of condition (m.q.). For example, in the Quran: «مَتٰی ہٰذَا الۡفَتۡحُ  اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰدِقِیۡنَ» (32/28) Translation: If you are truthful, then when will this victory be? At another place, the Divine decree states: «مَتٰی ہٰذَا الۡوَعۡدُ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰدِقِیۡنَ» (36/48) Translation: If you are truthful, then when will this promise be fulfilled?"
    }
  ],
  "485": [
    {
      "id": 2251,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Book",
      "hw": "کتاب",
      "s": "«Kitab» means every written thing, letter, or record; in the well-known sense, it means book (232 verses: 2:2-2:44-2:53-2:78-2:79-2:85-2:87-2:89-2:101-2:105-2:109-2:113-2:121-2:129-2:144-2:145-2:146-2:151-2:159-2:174-2:176-2:177-2:213-2:231-2:235-3:3-3:7-3:19-3:20-3:23-3:48-3:64-3:65-3:69-3:70-3:71-3:72-3:75-3:78-3:79-3:81-3:98-3:99-3:100-3:110-3:113-3:119-3:145-3:164-3:184-3:186-3:187-3:199-4:24-4:44-4:47-4:51-4:54-4:103-4:105-4:113-4:123-4:127-4:131-4:136-4:140-4:153-4:159-4:171-5:5-5:15-5:19-5:44-5:48-5:57-5:59-5:65-5:68-5:77-5:110-6:7-6:20-6:38-6:59-6:89-6:91-6:92-6:114-6:154-6:155-6:156-6:157-7:2-7:37-7:52-7:169-7:170-7:196-8:68-8:75-9:29-9:36-10:1-10:37-10:61-10:94-11:1-11:6-11:17-11:110-12:1-13:1-13:36-13:38-13:39-13:43-14:1-15:1-15:4-16:64-16:89-17:2-17:4-17:13-17:14-17:58-17:71-17:93-18:1-18:27-18:49-19:12-19:16-19:30-19:41-19:51-19:54-19:56-20:52-21:10-22:8-22:70-23:49-23:62-24:33-25:35-26:2-27:1-27:28-27:29-27:40-27:75-28:2-28:43-28:49-28:52-28:86-29:27-29:45-29:46-29:47-29:48-29:51-30:56-31:2-31:20-32:2-32:23-33:6-33:26-34:3-35:11-35:25-35:29-35:31-35:32-35:40-37:117-37:157-38:29-39:1-39:2-39:23-39:41-39:69-40:2-40:53-40:70-41:3-41:41-41:45-42:14-42:15-42:17-42:52-43:2-43:4-43:21-44:2-45:2-45:16-45:28-45:29-46:2-46:4-46:12-46:30-50:4-52:2-56:78-57:16-57:22-57:25-57:26-57:29-59:2-59:11-62:2-68:37-69:19-69:25-74:31-78:29-83:7-83:9-83:18-83:20-84:7-84:10-98:1-98:4-98:6)",
      "d": "«Kitab» means every written thing, letter, or record. In the well-known sense, it means book; its plural is «kutub». For example, the Quran states: «إِذْهَبْ بِكِتَابِي هَذَا» (27/28) Translation: Take this letter of mine."
    },
    {
      "id": 2252,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Book",
      "hw": "کتاب",
      "s": "«Asfar» means large books (commentaries and interpretations of the Torah) (1 verse: 62:5)",
      "d": "«Asfar» is the plural of «sifr»; «sifr» means a large book. It also refers to a part of the Torah (dictionary), and «sufr» means to uncover or reveal something. And «sifr» means a book that unveils truths (mufradāt, fiqh, vol. 241). The large commentaries and interpretations of the Torah. For example, the Quran states: «يَحْمِلُوهَا كَمَثَلِ الْحِمَارِ يَحْمِلُ أَسْفَارًا» (62/5) Translation: Those upon whom the burden of the Torah (its commandments) was placed, but they did not bear it, their example is like that of a donkey carrying heavy books."
    },
    {
      "id": 2253,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Book",
      "hw": "کتاب",
      "s": "«Sijil» means the register where commands are written and preserved, which the judge keeps with him (1 verse: 21:104)",
      "d": "«Sijil» means a register of covenants. The register where commands are recorded and preserved, kept by the judge. Judicial record (dictionary). For example, the Quran states: «يَوْمَ نَطْوِي السَّمَاءَ كَطَيِّ السِّجِلِّ لِلْكُتُبِ» (21/104) Translation: The Day when We will fold the heaven like the folding of a scroll for the books."
    },
    {
      "id": 2254,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Book",
      "hw": "کتاب",
      "s": "«Nuskhah» means a copied book or one from which a copy is made (2 verses: 7:154-45:29)",
      "d": "«Nasakha» means to erase, to abrogate. And «nasakha al-kitab» means to copy the book verbatim. And «nuskhah» refers to that from which a copy is made, or that which has been copied (m. q.). Every nuskhah is a book, but not every book is a nuskhah (fiqh, vol. 240). For example, the Quran states: «وَفِي نُسْخَتِهَا هُدًى وَرَحْمَةٌ لِلَّذِينَ هُمْ لِرَبِّهِمْ يَرْهَبُونَ» (7/154) Translation: And in that copied scripture (Torah) there was guidance and mercy for those who fear their Lord."
    },
    {
      "id": 2255,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Book",
      "hw": "کتاب",
      "s": "«Zubur» means books written in large, bold letters (7 verses: 3:184-16:44-18:96-26:196-35:25-54:43-54:52)",
      "d": "«Zubrah» means a large iron plate or sheet; its plural is «zubur». And «zabara al-kitab» means to write the book in bold letters. And «zibr» is a verbal noun but also used as a noun meaning book, plural «zubur». And «zabur» is the divine book revealed to David (peace be upon him). And «mizbar» means a pen (mufradāt). And «zubara» means to write on stone (mufradāt). And its basic meaning is thickness, i.e., boldness (fiqh, vol. 240). For example, the Quran states: «وَإِنَّهُ لَفِي زُبُرِ الْأَوَّلِينَ» (26/196) Translation: And indeed, it (the Quran) is in the scriptures of the earlier peoples."
    },
    {
      "id": 2256,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Book",
      "hw": "کتاب",
      "s": "«Suhuf» means written leaves that can be compiled into a book (8 verses: 20:133-53:36-74:52-80:13-81:10-87:18-87:19-98:2)",
      "d": "«Suhuf» is the plural of «sahifah». And «sahifah» means a spread-out thing on which something is written (mufradāt), and «sahifah» means a written paper, leaf. And «sihafah» means journalism, and «asraf» means to compile leaves or written sheets into a book. And «mushaf» is its plural «masahif», meaning book, volume (dictionary). For example, the Quran states: «إِنَّ هَذَا لَفِي الصُّحُفِ الْأُولَى صُحُفِ إِبْرَاهِيمَ وَمُوسَى» (87:18-19) Translation: Indeed, this (Quran) is in the former scriptures, the scriptures of Abraham and Moses."
    }
  ],
  "486": [
    {
      "id": 2257,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to cut through; to escape",
      "hw": "بچ",
      "s": "«Zawara» means to come out crookedly (1 verse: 18:17)",
      "d": "«Qawl al-zur» means false, deceitful speech. For example, the Quran states: «وَالَّذِينَ لَا يَشْهَدُونَ الزُّورَ» (25/72) Translation: And those who do not bear false witness. And «azwar» is a person whose heart is crooked (dictionary). And «bi'r zawra» means a well whose digging is crooked. And «zawara» means to be crooked or to come out crookedly."
    },
    {
      "id": 2258,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to cut through; to escape",
      "hw": "بچ",
      "s": "«Qarada» means to cut through and escape, then return to the straight path (1 verse: 18:17)",
      "d": "«Qarada» means to cut through and escape. «Qarada al-makan» means he moved away from that place in various directions. And «qarada fi al-sayr» means to deviate while traveling (dictionary). For example, the Quran states: «وَتَرَى الشَّمْسَ إِذَا طَلَعَتْ تَّزَاوَرُ عَنْ كَهْفِهِمْ ذَاتَ الْيَمِينِ وَإِذَا غَرَبَتْ تَّقْرِضُهُمْ ذَاتَ الشِّمَالِ» (18/17) Translation: And you see the sun when it rises, it deviates from their cave towards the right, and when it sets, it passes them on the left."
    },
    {
      "id": 2259,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to cut through; to escape",
      "hw": "بچ",
      "s": "«Hada» means to cut off, flee far away, and not return to the straight path (6 verses: 9:63-22:25-50:19-58:5-58:20-58:22)",
      "d": "«Hada» means to turn away from the straight path and flee far away (mufradāt, mal). To change direction. For example, the Quran states: «وَجَاءَتْ سَكْرَةُ الْمَوْتِ بِالْحَقِّ ذَلِكَ مَا كُنْتَ مِنْهُ تَحِيدُ» (50/19) Translation: And the pangs of death will come in truth; that is what you used to avoid."
    }
  ],
  "487": [
    {
      "id": 2260,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "How many?",
      "hw": "کتنے",
      "s": "«Kam» This word is known in Arabic grammar as interrogative kam and informative kam (21 verses: 2:211-2:249-2:259-6:6-7:4-17:17-18:19-19:74-19:98-20:128-21:11-23:112-26:7-28:58-32:26-36:31-38:3-43:6-44:25-50:36-53:26)",
      "d": "«Kam» means an indefinite number, i.e., not a specific number. It is used to ask about quantity or duration. It means \"how many\" or \"how much\" when used interrogatively. For example, the Quran states: «قَالَ كَمْ لَبِثْتَ» (2/259) Translation: Allah said, \"How long did you remain?\" Note: «Kam» has two types: (1) Interrogative kam (2) Informative kam. Interrogative kam: used to ask about a number, e.g., «کَمْ رَجُلاً عِنْدَکَ؟» (How many men are with you?). Informative kam: used to state a number, e.g., «کَمْ کُتُب دَرَسْتُ» (I have studied many books)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2261,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "How many?",
      "hw": "کتنے",
      "s": "«کَاَیٍّ» or «کَاَیِّنْ»: This Arabic term is synonymous with the interrogative «کَمْ» (how many?). The difference is that «کَمْ» can appear with or without «مِنْ», whereas «کَاَیٍّ» generally appears with «مِنْ». (7 verses: 3:146, 12:105, 22:45, 22:48, 29:60, 47:13, 65:8)",
      "d": "«کَمْ» and «کَاَیِّن» are close in meaning. The only difference is that «کَاَیِّن» also conveys the sense of abundance or multitude, meaning 'how many indeed', 'so many', i.e., 'many'. It does not function as an interrogative.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ کَاَیِّنۡ مِّنۡ اٰیَۃٍ  فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ یَمُرُّوۡنَ عَلَیۡہَا» (12:105).\nTranslation: 'And there are so many (numerous) signs in the heavens and the earth which they pass by.'\nSee also the entries for 'crookedness' and 'to be crooked'."
    }
  ],
  "488": [
    {
      "id": 2262,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to dig",
      "hw": "کریدنا",
      "s": "«بَحَثَ»: to dig under the earth. (1 verse: 5:31)",
      "d": "«بَحَثَ» means to dig, to excavate, to search for something by digging under the soil.\nFor example, the Quran states: «فَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ غُرَابًا یَّبۡحَثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ لِیُرِیَہٗ کَیۡفَ یُوَارِیۡ سَوۡءَۃَ اَخِیۡہِ» (5:31).\nTranslation: 'Then Allah sent a crow who began to dig in the earth to show him how to hide the shame of his brother.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2263,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to dig up; to exhume",
      "hw": "کریدنا",
      "s": "«بَعْثَرَ»: to dig up and extract something. (2 verses: 82:4, 100:9)",
      "d": "According to Imam Raghib, the word «بُعْثِرَ» is a compound of «بُعِثَ» and «اُثِیْرَ». It means to turn over graves and to raise the dead. «بَعْثَرَ الْمَتَاع» means to turn over and rummage through luggage. «بَعثَرَہٗ» means to inspect, investigate, to bring out and reveal.\nFor example, the Quran states: «اَفَلَا یَعۡلَمُ  اِذَا بُعۡثِرَ مَا فِی الۡقُبُوۡرِ» (100:9).\nTranslation: 'Does he not know that when that which is in the graves is dug up (and brought forth)...'"
    }
  ],
  "489": [
    {
      "id": 2265,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "bitter",
      "hw": "کڑوا",
      "s": "«اُجَاج»: bitter and salty (brackish) water. (3 verses: 25:53, 35:12, 56:70)",
      "d": "«اُجَاج» means very salty and bitter water. «اَجَّ الْمَاءَ» means to make water bitter or salty.\nFor example, the Quran states: «لَوۡ نَشَآءُ  جَعَلۡنٰہُ  اُجَاجًا فَلَوۡ لَا تَشۡکُرُوۡنَ» (56:70).\nTranslation: 'If We willed, We could have made it bitter. Then why are you not grateful?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2266,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "bitter; sour",
      "hw": "کڑوا",
      "s": "«خَمْط»: bitter and sour (acidic), ill-tasting. (1 verse: 34:16)",
      "d": "«خَمْط» means sour, acidic, and every thorny and bitter tree. «خَمۡط» refers to something with a bad taste.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ بَدَّلۡنٰہُمۡ بِجَنَّتَیۡہِمۡ جَنَّتَیۡنِ ذَوَاتَیۡ  اُکُلٍ خَمۡطٍ» (34:16).\nTranslation: 'And We replaced their two gardens with two gardens bearing bitter fruit and thorny plants.'"
    }
  ],
  "490": [
    {
      "id": 2267,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "farmer; cultivator",
      "hw": "کسان",
      "s": "«زُرَّاع»: one who practices agriculture or tilling the land; a farmer, cultivator. (2 verses: 48:29, 56:64)",
      "d": "«زُرَّاع» is the plural of «زَارِع», meaning one who tills the land, a farmer, cultivator. Its usage is general.\nFor example, the Quran states: «کَزَرۡعٍ  اَخۡرَجَ  شَطۡئَہٗ  فَاٰزَرَہٗ  فَاسۡتَغۡلَظَ فَاسۡتَوٰی عَلٰی سُوۡقِہٖ یُعۡجِبُ الزُّرَّاعَ» (48:29).\nTranslation: 'Like a crop that has produced its shoot and thickened and stood firm on its stem, it delights the cultivators.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2268,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "farmer; cultivator (also: disbeliever)",
      "hw": "کسان",
      "s": "«کُفَّار»: In common usage, it refers to those who deny the truth. (1 verse: 57:20)",
      "d": "«کُفَّار» is the plural of «کَافِر». «کُفْر» means to conceal. «کَافِر» has several meanings: (1) one who denies God, (2) one who is ungrateful for God's blessings, (3) one who conceals the truth, living in seclusion. It can also mean 'remote land', 'soil', 'plants', 'cultivator'. «اَلْکَفْرُ» means land remote and far from people, i.e., countryside.\nFor example, the Quran states: «کَمَثَلِ غَیۡثٍ اَعۡجَبَ الۡکُفَّارَ نَبَاتُہٗ» (57:20).\nTranslation: 'Like the growth of vegetation after rain, which delights the cultivators (or: the tillers of the land).'"
    }
  ],
  "491": [
    {
      "id": 2269,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "ship; boat",
      "hw": "کشتی",
      "s": "«جَارِیَۃ»: A ship is called «جَارِیَۃ» in consideration of its movement.\n«سَفِیْنَۃ»: A ship is called «سَفِیْنَۃ» in consideration of its being smooth and comfortable.\n«فُلْک»: A ship is called «فُلْک» in consideration of its being ship-shaped. (5 verses: 42:32, 55:24, 69:11, 81:16, 88:12)",
      "d": "«جَرٰی یَجْرِیْ» means to flow and move. It is used for things that move like water and wind. Hence, a ship is called «جَارِیَۃ» (its plural is «جَوَار»). It refers to a sailing ship that moves according to the direction of wind and water.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ لَہُ  الۡجَوَارِ الۡمُنۡشَئٰتُ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ کَالۡاَعۡلَامِ» (55:24).\nTranslation: 'And his are the ships, lofty on the sea like mountains.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2270,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "ship; boat",
      "hw": "کشتی",
      "s": "«سَفِیْنَۃ»: means ship, boat. (3 verses: 18:71, 18:79, 29:15)",
      "d": "«سَفَنَ» means to peel and make smooth. «سَفَنُ» means a tool for scraping and smoothing. «سَفِیْن» means an adze for splitting wood. «مِسْفن» means scraping tools. «سَفَانَۃ» means the profession of shipbuilding. «سَفِیْنَۃ» means ship, boat. Hence, «سَفِیْنَۃ» refers to a ship that is made smooth and comfortable through planing and smoothing.\nFor example, the Quran states: «اَمَّا السَّفِیۡنَۃُ  فَکَانَتۡ لِمَسٰکِیۡنَ یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ» (18:79).\nTranslation: 'As for the ship, it belonged to some poor people who worked on the sea.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2271,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "ship; boat",
      "hw": "کشتی",
      "s": "«فُلْک»: A ship that carries both passengers and cargo. (23 verses: 2:164, 7:64, 10:22, 10:73, 11:37, 11:38, 14:32, 16:14, 17:66, 22:65, 23:22, 23:27, 23:28, 26:119, 29:65, 30:46, 31:31, 35:12, 36:41, 37:140, 40:80, 43:12, 45:12)",
      "d": "The word «فُلْک» implies something round, circular, and revolving. «فَلْکٌ مِّنَ الْبَحْر» means a whirlpool in the sea where water gathers from all sides and begins to revolve. «فَلَک» means an orbit, the path of revolving celestial bodies, the sky. «اَلْفَلْکَۃ» means anything that is elevated, prominent, and round. Hence, a ship is called «فُلْک» due to its association with revolving. (Its plural form is not used). In the Quran, «فُلْک» is often accompanied by the word «مَشْحُوْن» (laden, loaded). «شَخَن» means to load cargo into a ship and fill it. «اَلشَّحْنَۃ» is the load with which a ship is filled. Thus, «فُلْک» is a ship that carries passengers as well as cargo.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ اِنَّ یوۡنُسَ لَمِنَ الۡمُرۡسَلِیۡنَ . اِذۡ  اَبَقَ  اِلَی الۡفُلۡکِ الۡمَشۡحُوۡنِ» (37:139-140).\nTranslation: 'And indeed, Jonah was among the messengers. When he ran away to the laden ship.'"
    }
  ],
  "492": [
    {
      "id": 2272,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Different Names of the Kaaba",
      "hw": "کعبہ",
      "s": "«کَعْبَۃ» means anything that is built in a cubic shape. (2 verses: 5:95-5:97)",
      "d": "«کَعْبَۃ» means anything that is built in a cubic shape. Hence, the Kaaba is called Kaaba (masc.) because its length, width, and height are all equal. A square or cubical structure (F L 16). For example, the Quran states: «یَحۡکُمُ بِہٖ ذَوَا عَدۡلٍ مِّنۡکُمۡ ہَدۡیًۢا بٰلِغَ الۡکَعۡبَۃِ» (5/95). Translation: Appoint two just men from among you to ensure the offering reaches the Kaaba."
    },
    {
      "id": 2273,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Different Names of the Kaaba",
      "hw": "کعبہ",
      "s": "«اَلْبَیْت» specifically refers to the House, the Honorable Kaaba. (10 verses: 2:125-2:127-2:158-3:97-5:2-5:97-8:35-22:26-52:4-106:3)",
      "d": "«اَلْبَیْت» means a specific house. The Honorable House (Kaaba). For example, the Quran states: «اِذۡ جَعَلۡنَا الۡبَیۡتَ مَثَابَۃً لِّلنَّاسِ وَ اَمۡنًا» (2/125). Translation: When We made the House (Kaaba) a place of return and security for the people."
    },
    {
      "id": 2274,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Different Names of the Kaaba",
      "hw": "کعبہ",
      "s": "«بَیْتُ الْعَتِیْق» means the Ancient House, referring to the Sacred Mosque. (2 verses: 22:29-22:33)",
      "d": "«بَیْتُ الْعَتِیْق» means the Ancient House. «عَتِیْق» refers to something that is old and, along with its age, is associated with honor and dignity, and in which there is no deficiency (mufradat). For example, the Quran states: «وَ لۡیَطَّوَّفُوۡا بِالۡبَیۡتِ الۡعَتِیۡقِ» (22/29). Translation: And let the people perform Tawaf around the Ancient House."
    },
    {
      "id": 2275,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Different Names of the Kaaba",
      "hw": "کعبہ",
      "s": "«حَرَم» refers to things from whose use Sharia has strictly prohibited. (2 verses: 28:57-29:67)",
      "d": "In the meaning of «حَرَم», two aspects are found: (1) «اَلْمَنْعُ الشَّدِیْد» – Haram are those things from whose use Sharia has strictly prohibited, and its opposite is Halal, i.e., that thing upon the use of which there is no restriction. (2) And «حَرَم» and «حَرَام» mean respectable, worthy of etiquette and honor. For example, the Quran states: «اَوَ لَمۡ نُمَکِّنۡ لَّہُمۡ حَرَمًا اٰمِنًا» (28/57). Translation: Did We not establish for them a secure sanctuary (Haram) in the Haram (Sanctuary)?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2277,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Different Names of the Kaaba",
      "hw": "کعبہ",
      "s": "«مَسْجِدُ الْحَرَام» means the Mosque worthy of honor and respect. The Honorable Kaaba. (15 verses: 2:144-2:149-2:150-2:191-2:196-2:217-5:2-8:34-9:7-9:19-9:28-17:1-22:25-48:25-48:27)",
      "d": "«مَسْجِدُ الْحَرَام» means the Mosque worthy of honor and respect. The Honorable House (Kaaba). For example, the Quran states: «سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَسۡرٰی بِعَبۡدِہٖ لَیۡلًا مِّنَ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ اِلَی الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡاَقۡصَا» (17/1). Translation: Glorified is He who took His servant by night from the Sacred Mosque to the Farthest Mosque."
    }
  ],
  "493": [
    {
      "id": 2278,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "All",
      "hw": "کل",
      "s": "«اَمْس» means any day from the past days. (4 verses: 10:24-28:18-28:19-28:82)",
      "d": "«اَمْس» means the day that passed before today. A gone-by yesterday (YESTERDAY). And if it is in the state of an Arabic harakat (vowel), then «اَلْاَمْس» means any day from the past days (manjada). And idiomatically, the word «اَمْس» is also used to refer to the recent past tense. For example, the Quran states: «فَاِذَا الَّذِی اسۡتَنۡصَرَہٗ بِالۡاَمۡسِ یَسۡتَصۡرِخُہٗ» (28/18). Translation: Then, behold, the one who sought his help yesterday is now seeking his help. In this verse, «اَمْس» refers to the gone-by day of yesterday. And in the following verse, the recent past tense is intended. For example, the Quran states: «فَجَعَلۡنٰہَا حَصِیۡدًا کَاَنۡ لَّمۡ تَغۡنَ بِالۡاَمۡسِ» (10/24). Translation: So We made it a mere straw, as if it had never flourished yesterday."
    },
    {
      "id": 2279,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "All",
      "hw": "کل",
      "s": "«غَدْ» means the coming next day. (15 verses: 3:121-6:52-7:205-12:12-13:15-18:23-18:28-24:36-31:34-34:12-40:46-54:26-59:18-68:22-68:25)",
      "d": "«غَدْ» means the coming tomorrow. The next day (TOMORROW). This word, like «اَمْس», also denotes both the coming day and the near future tense. For example, the Quran states: «اَرۡسِلۡہُ مَعَنَا غَدًا یَّرۡتَعۡ وَ یَلۡعَبۡ» (12/12). Translation: (O father) send him with us tomorrow that he may eat and play. In this verse, «غَدًا» is used in the meaning of the coming tomorrow. Similarly, at another place, the Almighty states: «وَ لۡتَنۡظُرۡ نَفۡسٌ مَّا قَدَّمَتۡ لِغَدٍ» (59/18). Translation: And let every soul see what it has sent ahead for tomorrow. In the verse, the word «غَدْ» does not only mean the near future but also refers to the Hereafter, which, according to the Quran, is near."
    }
  ],
  "494": [
    {
      "id": 2280,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Diminish. To Reduce. To Shorten.",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«ظَلَمَ» is used in a wide sense; it comes for every type of deficiency and excess. (128 verses: 2:54-2:57-2:59-2:150-2:165-2:231-2:272-2:279-2:281-3:25-3:108-3:117-3:135-3:161-4:10-4:30-4:40-4:49-4:64-4:77-4:110-4:124-4:148-4:153-4:160-4:168-5:39-6:21-6:45-6:82-6:93-6:131-6:144-6:157-6:160-7:9-7:23-7:37-7:103-7:160-7:162-7:165-7:177-8:25-8:60-9:36-9:70-10:13-10:17-10:44-10:47-10:52-10:54-11:18-11:37-11:67-11:94-11:101-11:113-11:116-11:117-13:6-14:44-14:45-16:33-16:41-16:61-16:85-16:111-16:118-17:59-17:71-18:15-18:33-18:49-18:57-18:59-18:87-19:60-20:111-20:112-21:3-21:47-22:25-22:39-23:27-23:62-25:4-25:19-26:227-27:11-27:14-27:44-27:52-27:85-28:16-29:40-29:46-29:68-30:9-30:29-30:57-31:13-32:22-34:19-34:42-36:54-37:22-38:24-39:32-39:47-39:51-39:69-40:17-40:31-42:41-42:42-43:39-43:65-43:76-45:22-46:12-46:19-51:59-52:47-53:52-61:7-65:1)",
      "d": "«ظَلَمَ» in a wide sense means to keep something in a place other than its rightful place, and its opposite is «عَدْل». That is, whatever is against justice and fairness will be considered Zulm (oppression). Thus, the scope of the word Zulm is very wide. Whether there is deficiency or excess in anything, and no matter how small or large that deficiency/excess is, the term Zulm applies to it all. Additionally, this word is used in both material and spiritual senses. For example, the Quran states: «کِلۡتَا الۡجَنَّتَیۡنِ اٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا وَ لَمۡ تَظۡلِمۡ مِّنۡہُ شَیۡئًا» (18/33). Translation: Both gardens gave their produce and did not diminish anything from it."
    },
    {
      "id": 2281,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Diminish. To Reduce. To Shorten.",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«اَلَا» means to fall short in doing something; not to do a task as it should be done. (1 verse: 3:118)",
      "d": "«اَلَا» means to fall short in doing something; not to perform a task as it ought to be done. To leave a deficiency (mufradat, m l). For example, the Quran states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡا بِطَانَۃً مِّنۡ دُوۡنِکُمۡ لَا یَاۡلُوۡنَکُمۡ خَبَالًا» (3/118). Translation: O you who have believed, do not take as intimates those outside your ranks; they will not spare you [any] ruin."
    },
    {
      "id": 2282,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Diminish. To Reduce. To Shorten.",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«قَصَرَ» means not to do a task as much as it should be done; to be deficient in it. (3 verses: 4:101-7:202-48:27)",
      "d": "«قَصَرَ» means not to do a task as much as it should be done. And in the words of Imam Raghib, it means not to reach the length or extremity of something (mufradat). Not to complete the prescribed amount or count. To do less. To make shorter. For example, the Quran states: «وَ اِذَا ضَرَبۡتُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ فَلَیۡسَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ جُنَاحٌ اَنۡ تَقۡصُرُوۡا مِنَ الصَّلٰوۃِ» (4/101). Translation: And when you travel throughout the land, there is no blame upon you for shortening the prayer."
    },
    {
      "id": 2283,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Alata» means to give less than due in wages or to delay payment (1 verse: 52:21)",
      "d": "«Alata» means to diminish from someone's right (manjada) or to diminish from wages. Not giving full recompense for work or giving it with delay. «Al-qasar wa ibta'» (m. q.)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«مَاۤ  اَلَتۡنٰہُمۡ  مِّنۡ عَمَلِہِمۡ  مِّنۡ شَیۡءٍ» (52/21)\nTranslation: We did not diminish anything from their deeds."
    },
    {
      "id": 2284,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Hadama» means to squeeze, press, or wring a soft thing and to diminish in it, to suppress the right of the weak (2 verses: 20:112, 26:148)",
      "d": "«Hadama» means to squeeze a soft thing, to press, to wring and to diminish in it (m. l) to suppress the right of the weak. To usurp. And «hadim» means soft and delicate also (26/48) and also that which is quickly digested (m. q.)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّعۡمَلۡ مِنَ الصّٰلِحٰتِ وَ ہُوَ مُؤۡمِنٌ فَلَا یَخٰفُ ظُلۡمًا وَّ لَا ہَضۡمًا» (20/112)\nTranslation: And whoever does good deeds while being a believer, will have no fear of injustice or diminishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 2285,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Fatara» means that weakness causes diminishment to occur (2 verses: 21:20, 43:75)",
      "d": "«Fatara» means that weakness occurs in something (m. l) that while doing work, due to tiredness, a decrease in pace occurs or one becomes stagnant.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّ  الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ فِیۡ عَذَابِ جَہَنَّمَ خٰلِدُوۡنَ لَا یُفَتَّرُ عَنۡہُمۡ» (43:74,75)\nTranslation: The criminals will remain in the punishment of Hell forever; it will not be diminished from them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2286,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Qalla» means to decrease in number or quantity (1 verse: 18:39)",
      "d": "«Qalla» basically has two meanings: (1) to be abundant, (2) to be little. Here the second meaning is under discussion. That is, to be little in number or quantity. And its opposite is «kathura» meaning abundant. For example, the Quran states:\n«اِنۡ تَرَنِ  اَنَا  اَقَلَّ  مِنۡکَ  مَالًا  وَّ  وَلَدًا» (18/39)\nTranslation: If you see me as less than you in wealth and children."
    },
    {
      "id": 2287,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Taffafa» means to fill a measuring container slightly less or to keep it small (1 verse: 83:1)",
      "d": "«Taffif» means insignificant and trivial thing. And «Taffafa» means to fill a measuring container a little less or to keep the container slightly small. (muf)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَیۡلٌ   لِّلۡمُطَفِّفِیۡنَ الَّذِیۡنَ  اِذَا  اکۡتَالُوۡا عَلَی النَّاسِ یَسۡتَوۡفُوۡنَ» (83:1,2)\nTranslation: Woe to the defrauders who, when they take a measure from people, take it in full."
    },
    {
      "id": 2288,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Khasira» means to incur loss in trade (25 verses: 4:119-6:12-6:20-6:31-6:140-7:9-7:53-10:45-11:21-11:22-18:103-21:70-22:11-23:103-26:181-27:5-39:15-40:78-40:85-42:45-45:27-55:9-65:9-83:3-103:2)",
      "d": "«Khasira» means to incur loss in capital (muf) this word is generally specific to trade. To incur loss. To suffer loss. And its opposite is «ramija» meaning to gain. And «khasara al-mizan» means to diminish in weight by suppressing someone's right.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا کَالُوۡہُمۡ  اَوۡ وَّزَنُوۡہُمۡ  یُخۡسِرُوۡنَ» (83:3)\nTranslation: And when they measure or weigh for themselves, they diminish."
    },
    {
      "id": 2289,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Naqada» means to decrease, diminish; used in all kinds of contexts for deficiency (9 verses: 2:155-7:130-9:4-11:84-13:41-21:44-35:11-50:4-73:3)",
      "d": "«Naqada» means to decrease, diminish, and its opposite is «zada» meaning increase. And the opposite of «nuqsan» is «ziyada». This word is more general than «khasira». Every loss is a deficiency, but not every deficiency is a loss.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«نِّصۡفَہٗۤ  اَوِ انۡقُصۡ  مِنۡہُ  قَلِیۡلًا . اَوۡ زِدۡ  عَلَیۡہِ  وَ رَتِّلِ الۡقُرۡاٰنَ  تَرۡتِیۡلًا» (73:3,4)\nTranslation: Half of it or a little less, or a little more. And recite the Quran with measured recitation."
    },
    {
      "id": 2290,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Bakhasa» means to give less or inferior in exchange for something good (7 verses: 2:282-7:85-11:15-11:85-12:20-26:183-72:13)",
      "d": "«Bakhs» means deficient, inferior, less (manjada). And «bakhasa» means to give deficient or less in exchange or to give little.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ شَرَوۡہُ بِثَمَنٍۭ بَخۡسٍ دَرَاہِمَ مَعۡدُوۡدَۃٍ» (12/20)\nTranslation: And they sold him for a low price, a few dirhams.\nAt another place, the divine command is:\n«وَ لَا تَبۡخَسُوا النَّاسَ اَشۡیَآءَہُمۡ» (7/85)\nTranslation: And do not give people less than their due in things."
    },
    {
      "id": 2292,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Watra» means to decrease in taking or giving recompense or not to give (1 verse: 47:35)",
      "d": "«Watra» means to wrong, to cause harm. To diminish wealth or right. And «al-witr» and «al-witr» mean to take recompense or to wrong in taking recompense (manjada)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اللّٰہُ  مَعَکُمۡ  وَ لَنۡ یَّتِرَکُمۡ   اَعۡمَالَکُمۡ» (47:35)\nTranslation: And Allah is with you and will never waste your deeds."
    }
  ],
  "495": [
    {
      "id": 2293,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to earn, to gain",
      "hw": "کمائی",
      "s": "«Amila» means to work generally; it also comes in the meanings of earning (309 verses: 2:25-2:62-2:74-2:82-2:85-2:96-2:110-2:134-2:139-2:140-2:141-2:144-2:149-2:167-2:217-2:233-2:234-2:237-2:265-2:271-2:277-2:283-3:22-3:30-3:57-3:98-3:99-3:120-3:153-3:156-3:163-3:180-3:195-4:17-4:18-4:57-4:94-4:108-4:110-4:122-4:123-4:124-4:128-4:135-4:173-5:5-5:8-5:9-5:53-5:62-5:66-5:69-5:71-5:90-5:93-5:105-6:43-6:54-6:60-6:88-6:108-6:122-6:127-6:132-6:135-7:42-7:43-7:53-7:118-7:129-7:139-7:147-7:153-7:180-8:39-8:47-8:48-8:72-9:9-9:16-9:17-9:37-9:69-9:94-9:102-9:105-9:120-9:121-10:4-10:9-10:12-10:14-10:23-10:41-10:61-10:81-11:7-11:11-11:15-11:16-11:23-11:46-11:78-11:92-11:93-11:111-11:112-11:121-11:123-12:19-12:69-13:29-14:18-14:23-14:42-15:93-16:28-16:32-16:34-16:63-16:93-16:96-16:97-16:111-16:119-17:9-17:84-18:2-18:7-18:30-18:49-18:79-18:88-18:103-18:105-18:107-18:110-19:60-19:96-20:75-20:82-20:112-21:27-21:74-21:82-21:94-22:14-22:23-22:50-22:56-22:68-23:51-23:63-23:100-24:24-24:28-24:38-24:39-24:53-24:55-24:64-25:23-25:70-25:71-26:112-26:168-26:169-26:188-26:216-26:227-27:4-27:19-27:24-27:84-27:90-27:93-28:15-28:55-28:67-28:80-28:84-29:4-29:7-29:8-29:9-29:38-29:55-29:58-30:15-30:41-30:44-30:45-31:8-31:15-31:23-31:29-32:12-32:14-32:17-32:19-33:2-33:9-33:19-33:31-33:71-34:4-34:11-34:12-34:13-34:25-34:33-34:37-35:7-35:8-35:10-35:37-36:35-36:54-36:71-37:39-37:61-37:96-38:24-38:28-39:7-39:35-39:39-39:65-39:70-40:37-40:40-40:58-41:5-41:8-41:20-41:22-41:27-41:33-41:40-41:46-41:50-42:15-42:22-42:23-42:26-43:72-45:15-45:21-45:28-45:29-45:30-45:33-46:14-46:15-46:16-46:19-47:1-47:2-47:4-47:8-47:9-47:12-47:14-47:28-47:30-47:32-47:33-47:35-48:11-48:24-48:29-49:2-49:14-49:18-52:16-52:19-52:21-53:31-56:24-57:4-57:10-58:3-58:6-58:7-58:11-58:13-58:15-59:18-60:3-62:8-63:2-63:11-64:2-64:7-64:8-64:9-65:11-66:7-66:11-67:2-77:43-84:25-85:11-95:6-98:7-99:6-99:7-99:8-103:3)",
      "d": "«Amila» means every action that a person intends to do is his action. And since earning is also an action, therefore it is used in those meanings.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَمَّا السَّفِیۡنَۃُ  فَکَانَتۡ لِمَسٰکِیۡنَ یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ» (18:79)\nTranslation: As for the ship, it belonged to some poor people who worked at sea."
    },
    {
      "id": 2294,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Earn; To Gain",
      "hw": "کمائی",
      "s": "«کَسَبَ» means to do some work for the purpose of gaining benefit or profit, whether for oneself or for others (57 Verses: 2:79-2:81-2:134-2:141-2:202-2:225-2:264-2:267-2:281-2:286-3:25-3:155-3:161-4:88-4:111-4:112-5:38-6:3-6:70-6:120-6:129-6:158-6:164-7:39-7:96-9:82-9:95-10:8-10:27-10:52-13:33-13:42-14:18-14:51-15:84-18:58-30:41-31:34-35:45-36:65-39:24-39:48-39:50-39:51-40:17-40:82-41:17-42:22-42:30-42:34-45:10-45:14-45:22-52:21-74:38-83:14-111:2)",
      "d": "«کَسَبَ» is more specific than 'action' for the purpose of earning or gaining profit or good fortune. Meaning to gain benefit or to do some work for good fortune. Whether this work is for oneself or for others. Whether this earning is good or bad, lawful or unlawful. And «کَاسِبْ» means a laborer, a wage-earner, a professional.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ السَّارِقُ وَ السَّارِقَۃُ فَاقۡطَعُوۡۤا أَیۡدِیَہُمَا جَزَآءًۢ بِمَا کَسَبَا» (5/38)\nTranslation: Cut off the hands of the male and female thief as a recompense for what they earned."
    },
    {
      "id": 2295,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Earn; To Gain",
      "hw": "کمائی",
      "s": "«اِکْتَسَب» means to do some work for one's own benefit and profit (4 Verses: 2:286-4:32-24:11-33:58)",
      "d": "«اَکَتَسَبَ» is the work that a human does solely keeping their own interests in mind (Muf).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لِلرِّجَالِ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّمَّا اکۡتَسَبُوۡا ؕ وَ لِلنِّسَآءِ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّمَّا اکۡتَسَبۡنَ» (4/32)\nTranslation: For men is a share of what they have earned, and for women is a share of what they have earned."
    },
    {
      "id": 2296,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Earn; To Gain",
      "hw": "کمائی",
      "s": "«اِقْتَرَفَ» means to do a bad deed, to earn through illicit means (4 Verses: 6:113-6:120-9:24-42:23)",
      "d": "«قَرَفَ» means to remove the scab of a wound. And «اِقْتَرَف» means to do a bad deed, to earn through illicit means. It is an idiom: «الاِعْتِرَافُ یَزِیْلُ الْاِقْتِرَاف» meaning 'confession (of a crime) removes the sin'. So, «اِقْتَرَاف» is used for the deeds of sin and crime.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«إِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ یَکۡسِبُوۡنَ الۡاِثۡمَ سَیُجۡزَوۡنَ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَقۡتَرِفُوۡنَ» (6/120)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who commit sins will be recompensed for what they used to do [i.e., earn]."
    }
  ],
  "496": [
    {
      "id": 2297,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Room",
      "hw": "کمرہ",
      "s": "«حُجْرَۃ» means room. (1 Verse: 49:4)",
      "d": "«حُجْرَۃ» means room. Its plural is «حُجْرَات». And it also means a dining room (M. R.). So, «حُجْرَۃ» is that small room from which the work of the whole house is done. For example, the Quran states:\n«إِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ یُنَادُوۡنَکَ مِنۡ وَّرَآءِ الۡحُجُرٰتِ» (49/4)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who call you from outside the rooms..."
    },
    {
      "id": 2298,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Chamber",
      "hw": "کمرہ",
      "s": "«غُرْفَۃ» meaning lofty chamber (4 verses: 25:75-29:58-34:37-39:20)",
      "d": "«غُرْفَۃ» means lofty chamber (mansion), and «غُرَف» and «غُرَفَات» refer to the dwellings and ranks of Paradise (pl.). It signifies a highly constructed and elevated chamber. For example, the Quran states: «اُولٰٓئِکَ یُجۡزَوۡنَ الۡغُرۡفَۃَ  بِمَا صَبَرُوۡا» (25/75) Translation: Those with such qualities will be granted the highest chambers in return for their patience. (Jalandhari)"
    }
  ],
  "497": [
    {
      "id": 2299,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Weak",
      "hw": "کمزور",
      "s": "«ضَعِیْف» meaning weak, old. Lacking in strength and power. (27 verses: 2:266-2:282-3:146-4:28-4:75-4:76-4:97-4:98-4:127-7:75-7:137-7:150-8:26-8:66-9:91-11:91-14:21-19:75-22:73-28:4-28:5-30:54-34:31-34:32-34:33-40:47-72:24)",
      "d": "«ضَعِیْف» means weak, old. It is a common word. Its opposite is «قَوِی» meaning strong. And «ضَعْف» and «ضُعْف» mean weakness. Their plural forms are «ضُعَفَاء» and «ضِعَاف». For example, the Quran states: «فَاِنۡ کَانَ الَّذِیۡ عَلَیۡہِ الۡحَقُّ سَفِیۡہًا اَوۡ ضَعِیۡفًا» (2/282) Translation: Then if the one upon whom the right is due is foolish or weak."
    },
    {
      "id": 2300,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Weak",
      "hw": "کمزور",
      "s": "«وَاھِیَۃ» weak due to decay (1 verse: 69:16)",
      "d": "«وَھِیَ» means old or weak due to aging, like clothes becoming worn out. And «وَھِیَ» means something becoming loose, its ties loosening. Its compound «اَلْوَھْی» means a hole forming in leather. Thus, this word is used for something becoming worn out, weak, and tearing due to age. The Punjabi word 'bhaga' accurately conveys this meaning. For example, the Quran states: «وَ انۡشَقَّتِ السَّمَآءُ  فَہِیَ یَوۡمَئِذٍ وَّاہِیَۃٌ» (69/16) Translation: And the sky will split, so on that day it will be weak."
    },
    {
      "id": 2302,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Weak",
      "hw": "کمزور",
      "s": "«اَذِلَّۃ» defeated, helpless, weak and destitute people (4 verses: 3:123-5:54-27:34-27:37)",
      "d": "«اَذِلَّۃ» is the plural of «ذَلِیْل» meaning subjugated. Low in honor and status. People of a lower rank in society. Its opposite is «عَزِیْز» meaning powerful, dominant, capable. To make weak: «اِسْتَضْعَفَ» for making and keeping weak, and «اَوْھَنَ» for making sluggish and weak. For example, the Quran states: «وَ لَقَدۡ نَصَرَکُمُ اللّٰہُ بِبَدۡرٍ وَّ اَنۡتُمۡ اَذِلَّۃٌ» (3/123) Translation: Indeed, Allah aided you at Badr when you were weak. Also: «اَنَّ اللّٰہَ  مُوۡہِنُ کَیۡدِ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (8/18) Translation: Indeed, Allah is the One Who weakens the plots of the disbelievers."
    }
  ],
  "498": [
    {
      "id": 2303,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "«طَرْف» the ultimate limit of anything, extremity (5 verses: 3:127-11:114-13:41-20:130-21:44)",
      "d": "«طَرْف» means the ultimate limit of anything. Extremity. The corner of a cubic object. The pointed side. Sight. Direction. Its plural is «اَطْرَاف». For example, the Quran states: «وَ اَقِمِ الصَّلٰوۃَ طَرَفَیِ النَّہَارِ» (11/114) Translation: And establish prayer at the two edges of the day (morning and evening)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2304,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Boundary",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "«حَدّ» the ultimate limit of anything that separates it from other things (9 verses: 2:187-2:229-2:230-4:13-4:14-9:97-9:112-58:4-65:1)",
      "d": "«حَدَّ السِّکِّیْن» means to sharpen a knife. And «حَدُّ السَّیْف» means the edge of a sword. And «حَدّ» means the barrier between two things. «حَدَّ الْمَکَان» means he set the limit of the place. From this comes «حُدُوْدُ اللہ» meaning the commands of Allah, transgression of which leads to sin. For example, the Quran states: «وَ مَنۡ یَّتَعَدَّ حُدُوۡدَ اللّٰہِ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمُ الظّٰلِمُوۡنَ» (2/229) Translation: And those who transgress the limits of Allah, it is they who are the wrongdoers."
    },
    {
      "id": 2305,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "«حَرْف» meaning pointed edge (1 verse: 22:11)",
      "d": "«حَرْفُ الْجَبَل» means the sharp peak of a mountain. The highest summit. They say «فُلَانٌ عَلٰی حَرْفٍ مِنْ اَمْرِہٖ» meaning so-and-so is on the edge of the matter. That is, if anything contrary to will appears, he will withdraw from it (source). The extreme limit of doubt and suspicion.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ مِنَ النَّاسِ مَنۡ یَّعۡبُدُ اللّٰہَ عَلٰی حَرۡفٍ ۚ فَاِنۡ  اَصَابَہٗ  خَیۡرُۨ  اطۡمَاَنَّ بِہٖ ۚ وَ اِنۡ اَصَابَتۡہُ فِتۡنَۃُۨ  انۡقَلَبَ عَلٰی وَجۡہِہٖ» (22/11)\nTranslation: And among people is he who worships Allah on the edge. Then if any good befalls him, he is content with it; but if a trial befalls him, he turns back on his face in despair."
    },
    {
      "id": 2306,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "«اُفْق» meaning where two round things meet at their farthest edges (3 verses: 41:53-53:7-81:23)",
      "d": "«اَفَقَ» means for two things to meet at their farthest and ultimate limit, or to appear joined (m. l). And that joined edge is called the horizon, as in one side is earth and the other is sky. So at the farthest limit of sight where they appear to meet is the horizon. Its plural is «اٰفَاق». And «اٰفاق» means the vastness of the universe, wherein there is ample expanse and distance (muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ ہُوَ  بِالۡاُفُقِ الۡاَعۡلٰی» (53/7)\nTranslation: And he (Gabriel) was at the highest horizon.\nAt another place, the Divine decree says:\n«سَنُرِیۡہِمۡ  اٰیٰتِنَا فِی الۡاٰفَاقِ  وَ فِیۡۤ   اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ» (41/53)\nTranslation: Soon We will show them Our signs in the horizons and within themselves."
    },
    {
      "id": 2307,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "«اَقْطَار» meaning the inner edges and sides of a round object (2 verses: 33:14-55:33)",
      "d": "«قَطَرَ» means to line up in a row. They say «قَطَرَ الْبَعِیْرُ اِلَی الْبَعِیْر» meaning the camels are lined up in a row. And «اَقْطَارَ الدُّنْیَا» means the four corners of the world. In geometry, it refers to the straight line passing through the center that divides a circle into two equal parts (source). Thus, «قَطَرَ» implies both a straight line and a round object. Moreover, such lines can be in thousands, encompassing all edges and sides. Right, left, front, back, up, down, straight and opposite directions—all are included.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ لَوۡ دُخِلَتۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنۡ اَقۡطَارِہَا ثُمَّ سُئِلُوا الۡفِتۡنَۃَ  لَاٰتَوۡہَا وَ مَا تَلَبَّثُوۡا بِہَاۤ   اِلَّا  یَسِیۡرًا» (33/14)\nTranslation: And if people from the edges of the city had entered upon them and they had been asked to commit treason, they would have certainly done it, and they would not have hesitated over it except a little.\nAt another place, the Divine decree says:\n«یٰمَعۡشَرَ الۡجِنِّ وَ الۡاِنۡسِ  اِنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتُمۡ اَنۡ  تَنۡفُذُوۡا مِنۡ  اَقۡطَارِ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ فَانۡفُذُوۡا» (55/33)\nTranslation: O company of jinn and humans, if you are able to pass through the edges of the heavens and the earth, then pass through."
    },
    {
      "id": 2308,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "«اَرْجَاء» meaning the edges of a round object like a well or sky (1 verse: 69:17)",
      "d": "«اَرْجَاء» is the plural of «رَجَا». It means the edge of a round object. «رَجَا الْبِئْر» means the edge of the well. And «رَجَا السَّمَاء» means the edge of the sky (muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَّ الۡمَلَکُ  عَلٰۤی  اَرۡجَآئِہَا ؕ وَ یَحۡمِلُ عَرۡشَ رَبِّکَ فَوۡقَہُمۡ یَوۡمَئِذٍ ثَمٰنِیَۃٌ» (69/17)\nTranslation: And the angels will be on its edges, and on that Day, eight will bear the Throne of your Lord above them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2309,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "«شَفَا» meaning the edge of anything hollow and concave, where standing poses a risk of falling and destruction (2 verses: 3:103-9:109)",
      "d": "«شَفَا» is a proverb for the brink of destruction. «شَفَا» refers to the edge of anything that is hollow and concave inside, and standing on its edge entails a risk of falling and being destroyed (muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ کُنۡتُمۡ عَلٰی شَفَا حُفۡرَۃٍ مِّنَ النَّارِ فَاَنۡقَذَکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا» (3/103)\nTranslation: And you were on the brink of a pit of fire, and He saved you from it.\nAt another place, the Divine decree says:\n«اَمۡ مَّنۡ اَسَّسَ بُنۡیَانَہٗ عَلٰی شَفَا جُرُفٍ ہَارٍ» (9/109)\nTranslation: Or [consider] he who founded his building on the brink of a collapsing pit?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2310,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "«مَعْزل» meaning an edge that provides refuge (1 verse: 11:42)",
      "d": "«عَزَل» means to withdraw, to be on one side, and to escape. In Ibn al-Faris's words, it indicates rescue, delay, and distancing (m. l). That is, «مَعْزل» is the edge to which one goes to be saved from a calamity.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ نَادٰی نُوۡحُۨ  ابۡنَہٗ وَ کَانَ فِیۡ  مَعۡزِلٍ یّٰـبُنَیَّ ارۡکَبۡ مَّعَنَا» (11/42)\nTranslation: And Noah called his son, and he was at an isolated edge. He said, 'O my son, embark with us.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2311,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "«شَاطِیء» meaning one of the two edges of a field or river (1 verse: 28:30)",
      "d": "«شَاطِیء» means one of the two edges of something (m. l). The edge of a river or valley. One side or bank.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ  اَتٰىہَا نُوۡدِیَ مِنۡ شَاطِیَٔ الۡوَادِ الۡاَیۡمَنِ» (28/30)\nTranslation: So when he reached it, he was called from the right bank of the valley."
    },
    {
      "id": 2312,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "«سَاحِل» meaning the edge of a river or sea (1 verse: 20:39)",
      "d": "«سَاحِل» is specifically used for the edge of a river or sea (source).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«فَلۡیُلۡقِہِ الۡیَمُّ بِالسَّاحِلِ» (20/39)\nTranslation: Then the sea will cast it onto the shore."
    },
    {
      "id": 2313,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "«اَقْصَا» meaning the opposite side's edge (5 verses: 8:42-17:1-19:22-28:20-36:20)",
      "d": "«قُصْوَی» implies being distant and remaining far (m. l). And «اَقْصٰی» means the farthest side. The outermost edge.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ جَآءَ مِنۡ اَقۡصَا الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  رَجُلٌ یَّسۡعٰى» (36/20)\nTranslation: And there came from the farthest end of the city a man running."
    },
    {
      "id": 2314,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "«عُدْوَۃ» meaning a distant edge that is elevated (1 verse: 8:42)",
      "d": "«عَدَا» means a distant traveler. And it means the edge of a valley. And «عُدْوَۃ» means a high place, the edge of a valley (source). That is, «عُدْوَۃ» is the edge of a valley or field that is both distant and elevated.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«اِذۡ اَنۡتُمۡ بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الدُّنۡیَا وَ ہُمۡ  بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الۡقُصۡوٰی» (8/42)\nTranslation: When you were at the near edge and they were at the far edge."
    },
    {
      "id": 2315,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "«صَدَفُ» the edge of a mountain (1 Verse: 18:96)",
      "d": "The open field between mountains is called a valley. The edges of the mountains that form the boundaries of this valley are called «صَدَف». Therefore, the translation of «صَدَف» is also taken as the edge of the valley, but 'the edge of the mountain' is its more fitting translation. Hence, Imam Raghib states its meaning is only the edge of the mountain (Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا سَاوٰی بَیۡنَ الصَّدَفَیۡنِ» ( 18/96 )\nTranslation: Until he (Dhul-Qarnayn) made the two mountain edges (the space between them) level."
    }
  ],
  "499": [
    {
      "id": 2316,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Well",
      "hw": "کنواں",
      "s": "«بِئر» meaning well (1 Verse: 22:45)",
      "d": "«بِئر» means well. It is a general term. Whether it is filled (with water) or not (FL 262). One can also call such wells wells even if they have no water (F. L 31).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ بِئۡرٍ  مُّعَطَّلَۃٍ   وَّ  قَصۡرٍ  مَّشِیۡدٍ» ( 22/45 )\nTranslation: And (many) abandoned wells and (many) ruined, splendid palaces."
    },
    {
      "id": 2317,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Well",
      "hw": "کنواں",
      "s": "«جُبّ» a raw well, a well that is only dug and not built with bricks or stones (2 Verses: 12:10-12:15)",
      "d": "«جُبّ» is a well that is only dug. It is not constructed with bricks or stones (F. L 262). A raw well.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَلَمَّا ذَہَبُوۡا بِہٖ  وَ  اَجۡمَعُوۡۤا اَنۡ یَّجۡعَلُوۡہُ  فِیۡ غَیٰبَتِ  الۡجُبِّ» ( 12/15 )\nTranslation: Then when they went away with him and agreed to put him into the bottom of the well (i.e., a deep, dark well)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2318,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Well",
      "hw": "کنواں",
      "s": "«رَسّ» a very large well (2 Verses: 25:38-50:12)",
      "d": "«رَسّ» is a very large well (F. L 39) in which there is a plentiful amount of water (F. L 262).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«کَذَّبَتۡ قَبۡلَہُمۡ قَوۡمُ نُوۡحٍ وَّ اَصۡحٰبُ الرَّسِّ  وَ  ثَمُوۡدُ» ( 50/12 )\nTranslation: Before them, the people of Noah and the companions of the well and Thamud denied."
    }
  ],
  "500": [
    {
      "id": 2319,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Whip",
      "hw": "کوڑا",
      "s": "«سَوْط» a leather whip or scourge (1 Verse: 89:13)",
      "d": "«سَوْط» means a tanned hide. A whip, a scourge (Muf). And «سَاطَ» means to lash with a whip. And «سَوَّاط» means a whip-holding soldier. And «مِسْوَاط» is the name for a horse that does not move without a whip (Manjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَصَبَّ عَلَیۡہِمۡ رَبُّکَ سَوۡطَ عَذَابٍ» ( 89/13 )\nTranslation: So your Lord will rain upon them a scourge of punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 2320,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Scourge",
      "hw": "کوڑا",
      "s": "«جَلْدَۃ» general term for something hard, whether leather or other material, that does not wound when used for striking, whereas a whip or scourge is made of leather (2 verses: 24:2-24:4)",
      "d": "«جِلْد» means the skin of a living being. And «جَلَدَ» means to strike someone on the skin such that the strike's effect does not go beyond the skin. And «جَلْدَۃ» is any thing with which one strikes on the skin, and it is hard but does not wound, whether it is made of something else. «دُرَہ». «اَرْض جَلْدَۃ» means hard ground. And «جَلَّاد» means one who strikes with a scourge. For example, the Quran states: «اَلزَّانِیَۃُ وَ الزَّانِیۡ فَاجۡلِدُوۡا کُلَّ وَاحِدٍ مِّنۡہُمَا مِائَۃَ جَلۡدَۃٍ» (24/2) Translation: The female adulterer and the male adulterer, flog each of them with a hundred scourges."
    }
  ],
  "501": [
    {
      "id": 2321,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Strive",
      "hw": "کوشش",
      "s": "«سَعٰی» to strive for a task (14 Verses: 2:114-2:205-17:19-20:15-20:20-20:66-28:20-36:20-53:39-57:12-66:8-79:22-79:35-80:8)",
      "d": "«سَعِی» means to walk quickly, to run half-running (metaphorically). To be actively engaged in the completion of a good or bad deed.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ اَنۡ  لَّیۡسَ لِلۡاِنۡسَانِ  اِلَّا مَا سَعٰی» ( 53/39 )\nTranslation: And that man will have nothing but what he strives for."
    },
    {
      "id": 2322,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Strive",
      "hw": "کوشش",
      "s": "«جَھَدَ» to employ all means for the completion of a task (27 Verses: 2:218-3:142-5:35-5:54-8:72-8:74-8:75-9:16-9:19-9:20-9:41-9:44-9:73-9:79-9:81-9:86-9:88-16:110-22:78-25:52-29:6-29:8-29:69-31:15-49:15-61:11-66:9)",
      "d": "«جَھَدَ» means to expend all one's possible efforts in the completion of a task. In the words of Ibn al-Faris, «اَصْلُہُ الْمُشَقَّۃُ وَمَا یُقَارِبُہٗ» (M. L).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ جَاہَدُوۡا فِیۡنَا لَنَہۡدِیَنَّہُمۡ سُبُلَنَا» ( 29/69 )\nTranslation: As for those who strive in Our cause, We will surely guide them to Our paths."
    },
    {
      "id": 2323,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Strive",
      "hw": "کوشش",
      "s": "«کَدَحَ» to work through hardships (1 Verse: 84:6)",
      "d": "«اَلْکَدْح»: means scraping and «کَدَحَ» means to work very hard in a task (Manjad) and means to work through hardships. To proceed with difficulty in doing something (Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الۡاِنۡسَانُ  اِنَّکَ کَادِحٌ  اِلٰی رَبِّکَ کَدۡحًا  فَمُلٰقِیۡہِ» ( 84/6 )\nTranslation: O man, indeed you are laboring towards your Lord with great labor, and you will meet Him."
    }
  ],
  "502": [
    {
      "id": 2325,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Who",
      "hw": "کون",
      "s": "«اَیُّ» when used in an interrogative form, attached to pronouns, gives the meaning of 'who' (57 Verses: 3:44-4:11-6:19-6:81-7:185-9:124-11:7-17:57-18:7-18:12-19:69-19:73-26:227-27:38-31:34-40:81-45:6-53:55-55:13-55:16-55:18-55:21-55:23-55:25-55:28-55:30-55:32-55:34-55:36-55:38-55:40-55:42-55:45-55:47-55:49-55:51-55:53-55:55-55:57-55:59-55:61-55:63-55:65-55:67-55:69-55:71-55:73-55:75-55:77-67:2-68:6-68:40-77:12-77:50-80:18-81:9-82:8)",
      "d": "«اَیُّ» when used in an interrogative form, attached to pronouns, gives the meaning of 'who', and the annexation (iḍāfa) in it is obligatory (in which conditional meanings are sometimes found), i.e., who among the mentioned things. It also comes for those of sound intellect.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«لِیَبۡلُوَکُمۡ  اَیُّکُمۡ  اَحۡسَنُ عَمَلًا» ( 67/2 )\nTranslation: So that He may test you [to distinguish] which of you is best in deed.\nAt another place, the command of the Exalted Lord says:\n«لَا تَدۡرُوۡنَ اَیُّہُمۡ اَقۡرَبُ  لَکُمۡ نَفۡعًا» ( 4/11 )\nTranslation: You do not know which of them is nearer to you in benefit."
    }
  ],
  "503": [
    {
      "id": 2326,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Anyone",
      "hw": "کوئی",
      "s": "«اَحَد» used for a part of the whole and generally for rational beings (71 verses: 2:96-2:102-2:136-2:180-2:266-2:285-3:73-3:84-3:91-3:153-4:18-4:43-4:152-5:6-5:20-5:27-5:106-5:115-6:61-7:80-9:4-9:6-9:84-9:127-11:81-12:36-12:41-12:78-15:65-16:58-16:76-17:23-18:19-18:22-18:26-18:32-18:38-18:42-18:47-18:49-18:110-19:26-19:98-23:99-24:6-24:21-24:28-29:28-33:32-33:39-33:40-35:41-38:35-43:17-49:12-59:11-63:10-69:47-72:2-72:7-72:18-72:20-72:22-72:26-89:25-89:26-90:5-90:7-92:19-112:1-112:4)",
      "d": "«اَحَد» means unique, peerless, singular, alone. As in «قُلۡ ہُوَ اللّٰہُ  اَحَدٌ» (112/1). In numerical order, it means one, as in «اَحَدَ» meaning one and «عَشَرَ» meaning ten. Its feminine is «اِحْدٰی». Its third usage is to denote any one part of the whole. It is used both positively and negatively. And generally for rational beings. For example, the Quran states: «فَخُذۡ اَحَدَنَا مَکَانَہٗ» (12/78) Translation: Then take any one of us in his place. And when used negatively, it means 'anyone'. For example, the Quran states: «فَمَا مِنۡکُمۡ  مِّنۡ اَحَدٍ عَنۡہُ حٰجِزِیۡنَ» (69/47) Translation: Then none of you would be a barrier to Us from him."
    }
  ],
  "504": [
    {
      "id": 2328,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "That",
      "hw": "گویا",
      "s": "«اَنْ» when occurring within a sentence, gives the meaning of 'that' or 'as if' (488 verses: 2:26-2:27-2:67-2:75-2:90-2:96-2:105-2:108-2:114-2:125-2:158-2:169-2:177-2:184-2:198-2:210-2:214-2:216-2:224-2:228-2:229-2:230-2:232-2:233-2:235-2:237-2:248-2:254-2:258-2:266-2:267-2:280-2:282-3:28-3:73-3:79-3:80-3:93-3:122-3:124-3:142-3:143-3:145-3:147-3:161-3:188-3:193-4:6-4:19-4:23-4:24-4:25-4:27-4:28-4:29-4:44-4:47-4:48-4:58-4:60-4:66-4:84-4:88-4:90-4:91-4:92-4:99-4:101-4:102-4:113-4:116-4:127-4:128-4:129-4:131-4:135-4:140-4:144-4:150-4:153-4:171-4:172-4:176-5:2-5:3-5:11-5:17-5:19-5:29-5:31-5:33-5:34-5:37-5:41-5:49-5:52-5:59-5:80-5:84-5:91-5:108-5:111-5:112-5:113-5:116-5:117-6:14-6:23-6:25-6:35-6:37-6:51-6:56-6:65-6:70-6:72-6:80-6:111-6:125-6:131-6:145-6:156-6:158-7:5-7:13-7:20-7:33-7:43-7:44-7:46-7:50-7:63-7:69-7:82-7:89-7:97-7:98-7:100-7:105-7:110-7:115-7:117-7:123-7:126-7:129-7:160-7:169-7:172-7:185-8:7-8:26-8:62-8:67-9:13-9:16-9:17-9:18-9:32-9:44-9:52-9:54-9:62-9:64-9:74-9:81-9:85-9:86-9:102-9:108-9:110-9:113-9:118-9:120-10:2-10:10-10:15-10:35-10:37-10:72-10:83-10:87-10:100-10:104-10:105-11:3-11:12-11:14-11:26-11:34-11:46-11:47-11:62-11:69-11:87-11:88-11:89-12:13-12:15-12:21-12:24-12:25-12:37-12:38-12:66-12:76-12:79-12:83-12:94-12:96-12:100-12:107-13:21-13:25-13:31-13:36-13:38-14:5-14:10-14:11-14:22-14:31-14:35-15:31-15:54-16:2-16:15-16:33-16:36-16:40-16:45-16:68-16:92-16:123-17:8-17:16-17:46-17:51-17:59-17:68-17:69-17:74-17:79-17:88-17:94-17:99-17:103-18:24-18:35-18:40-18:55-18:57-18:63-18:66-18:77-18:79-18:80-18:81-18:82-18:86-18:94-18:97-18:102-18:109-19:11-19:35-19:45-19:91-19:92-20:39-20:45-20:59-20:63-20:65-20:71-20:77-20:86-20:94-20:97-20:114-20:134-21:17-21:31-21:57-21:87-22:15-22:22-22:26-22:40-22:65-23:24-23:27-23:32-23:95-23:98-24:8-24:16-24:17-24:19-24:22-24:29-24:36-24:50-24:51-24:60-24:61-24:63-25:18-25:42-25:57-25:62-26:10-26:12-26:14-26:17-26:22-26:35-26:49-26:51-26:52-26:63-26:82-26:197-27:8-27:19-27:38-27:39-27:40-27:45-27:56-27:60-27:72-27:91-27:92-28:5-28:7-28:9-28:10-28:19-28:22-28:27-28:30-28:31-28:33-28:34-28:47-28:67-28:82-28:86-29:2-29:4-29:24-29:29-29:33-30:10-30:20-30:21-30:25-30:43-30:46-30:49-31:10-31:12-31:14-31:15-32:20-33:6-33:36-33:37-33:49-33:50-33:51-33:52-33:53-33:59-33:72-34:11-34:14-34:33-34:43-34:46-35:41-36:40-36:60-36:61-36:81-36:82-37:104-38:4-38:6-38:75-39:4-39:11-39:17-39:54-39:55-39:56-40:26-40:28-40:66-40:78-41:22-42:13-42:47-42:51-43:5-43:33-43:66-44:18-44:19-44:20-45:21-45:25-46:15-46:17-46:33-47:18-47:22-47:29-48:12-48:15-48:24-48:25-49:2-49:6-49:11-49:12-49:17-50:2-51:57-53:26-53:39-55:33-56:61-57:16-57:22-58:3-58:4-58:13-59:2-59:3-60:1-60:7-60:8-60:9-60:10-60:12-61:3-63:10-64:7-65:1-65:4-66:5-66:8-67:16-67:17-68:14-68:22-68:24-68:32-68:49-70:38-70:41-71:1-71:3-72:5-72:7-72:12-72:16-72:28-73:20-74:15-74:37-74:52-74:56-75:4-75:25-75:36-75:40-76:30-79:18-80:2-81:28-81:29-84:14-85:8-90:5-90:7-96:7)",
      "d": "«اَنَّ مُخَفَّفَۃ» when occurring within a sentence, gives the meaning of 'that' or 'as if'. For example, the Quran states: «اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یَسۡتَحۡیٖۤ اَنۡ یَّضۡرِبَ مَثَلًا» (2/26) Translation: Allah does not feel ashamed to set forth a parable."
    },
    {
      "id": 2329,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "As If",
      "hw": "گویا",
      "s": "«کَاَنْ ، کَاَنَّ ، کَاَنَّمَا» all these particles mean 'as if' (36 verses: 2:101-4:73-5:32-6:125-7:92-7:171-7:187-8:6-10:12-10:24-10:27-10:45-11:68-11:95-22:31-24:35-27:10-27:42-28:31-31:7-37:49-37:65-41:34-45:8-46:35-52:24-54:7-54:20-55:58-61:4-63:4-69:7-70:43-74:50-77:33-79:46)",
      "d": "«کَاَنْ ، کَاَنَّ ، کَاَنَّمَا» all these letters are compounds of «کَ» (simile) and «اَنْ» or «اَنَّ». They mean 'as if'. For example, the Quran states: «کَاَنۡ  لَّمۡ یَسۡمَعۡہَا کَاَنَّ فِیۡۤ  اُذُنَیۡہِ  وَقۡرًا» (31/7) Translation: As if he had not heard it, as if there were deafness in his ears. «اَنْ» and «کَاَنْ» are used with verbs, while «اَنَّ» and «کَاَنَّ» are used with nouns, as clear from the above verse. For example, the Quran states: «کَاَنَّمَا یُسَاقُوۡنَ اِلَی الۡمَوۡتِ» (8/6) Translation: As if they were being driven to death."
    },
    {
      "id": 2330,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "That; as if",
      "hw": "گویا",
      "s": "«اَلَّا» is actually «اَنْ ۔ لَا». Meaning 'that not'. (40 آیات: 2:229-2:246-2:282-3:41-3:64-3:170-3:176-3:183-4:3-5:8-5:71-6:119-6:151-7:12-8:34-9:92-9:97-11:2-12:40-14:12-15:32-17:2-17:23-19:10-19:24-19:48-20:89-20:93-20:118-26:3-27:25-27:31-41:14-41:30-46:21-53:38-55:8-57:10-57:29-80:7)",
      "d": "«اَلَّا» is actually «اَنْ ۔ لَا». Meaning 'that not'. It gives this meaning when placed within a sentence.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«تَتَنَزَّلُ عَلَیۡہِمُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ  اَلَّا تَخَافُوۡا وَ لَا تَحۡزَنُوۡا» (41/30)\nTranslation: The angels descend upon them (and say), 'Do not fear and do not grieve.'"
    }
  ],
  "505": [
    {
      "id": 2332,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Where?",
      "hw": "کہاں",
      "s": "«اَنّٰی» comes to ask about place along with state or condition. (28 آیات: 2:223-2:247-2:259-3:37-3:40-3:47-3:165-5:75-6:95-6:101-9:30-10:32-10:34-19:8-19:20-23:89-29:61-34:52-35:3-36:66-39:6-40:62-40:69-43:87-44:13-47:18-63:4-89:23)",
      "d": "«اَنّٰی» comes to ask about both place and condition (mufradat).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«قَالَ یٰمَرۡیَمُ اَنّٰی لَکِ ہٰذَا» (3/37)\nTranslation: (Zachariah, upon seeing this situation, said, 'O Mary! How does this provision come to you?')\nAnd when it comes only for spatial context, it means 'which direction' or 'where'.\nFor example: The divine command is:\n«قٰتَلَہُمُ اللّٰہُ  ۚ ۫  اَنّٰی  یُؤۡفَکُوۡنَ» (9/30)\nTranslation: May Allah kill them; where (or in which direction) do they wander astray?'"
    }
  ],
  "506": [
    {
      "id": 2333,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Stories; Events",
      "hw": "واقعات",
      "s": "«اَسَاطِیْر» baseless events (9 آیات: 6:25-8:31-16:24-23:83-25:5-27:68-46:17-68:15-83:13)",
      "d": "«اَسْطُوْرَہ», «اَسَیْطَرۃ» and «اِسْطَار» are all singular forms of «اَسَاطِیْر». And «اِسْطَار» is derived from «سَطَر». Meaning anything written in lines (i.e., such a text that is in a straight line) or that has been recorded in writing but has no reality. Baseless and unfounded matters (minj) such stories or tales that are not based on reality.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«یَقُوۡلُ  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡۤا اِنۡ ہٰذَاۤ  اِلَّاۤ  اَسَاطِیۡرُ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (6/25)\nTranslation: The disbelievers say, 'This is nothing but the tales of the former people.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2334,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Stories; Events",
      "hw": "واقعات",
      "s": "«اَحَادِیْث» forgotten but instructive events (5 آیات: 12:6-12:21-12:101-23:44-34:19)",
      "d": "«اَحَادِیْث» is the plural of «حَدِیْث». Any matter that occurs and did not exist before is a hadith. Then this word is also applied to events that people have forgotten due to the passage of much time. Instructive old events.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«کُلَّمَا جَآءَ اُمَّۃً  رَّسُوۡلُہَا کَذَّبُوۡہُ  فَاَتۡبَعۡنَا بَعۡضَہُمۡ بَعۡضًا وَّ جَعَلۡنٰہُمۡ اَحَادِیۡثَ» (23/44)\nTranslation: Whenever a messenger came to a nation, they denied him. So We made some of them follow others, and We made them into stories."
    },
    {
      "id": 2335,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Stories; Events",
      "hw": "واقعات",
      "s": "«قَصَص» are events that are famous among common people and transmitted from chest to chest (10 آیات: 3:62-4:164-7:176-12:3-12:5-12:111-16:118-18:64-28:25-40:78)",
      "d": "«قَصَص» is the plural of «قِصَّہ». «قَصَّ» means to follow footsteps. And «قَصَّ» means to narrate an event (m. q). And «قَصَص» refers to events that are famous among common people and transmitted from chest to chest. Spoken events, famous and well-known among all people.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«نَحۡنُ نَقُصُّ عَلَیۡکَ اَحۡسَنَ الۡقَصَصِ» (12/3)\nTranslation: (O Prophet ﷺ!) We relate to you the best of stories."
    }
  ],
  "507": [
    {
      "id": 2336,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Skin",
      "hw": "کھال",
      "s": "«جِلْد» the skin of any living being's body (7 آیات: 4:56-16:80-22:20-39:23-41:20-41:21-41:22)",
      "d": "«جِلْد» is the skin of any living being's body and the upper part of the whole body is its skin or hide (mufradat) and this word is general.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«کُلَّمَا نَضِجَتۡ جُلُوۡدُہُمۡ بَدَّلۡنٰہُمۡ جُلُوۡدًا غَیۡرَہَا» (4/56)\nTranslation: Whenever their skins are roasted/burned, We will replace them with other skins."
    },
    {
      "id": 2337,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Skin",
      "hw": "کھال",
      "s": "«شَوٰی» hands, feet, and the sides of the body (2 آیات: 18:29-70:16)",
      "d": "«شَوٰی» means the sides of the body. Hands, feet, and those organs on which a wound does not cause death. The idiom is «رَمَاہُ فَاَشْوَاہُ» meaning 'I shot an arrow at him, and it hit his sides.' i.e., it did not hit an organ where a wound would cause death (mufradat).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«کَلَّا ؕ اِنَّہَا  لَظٰی نَزَّاعَۃً   لِّلشَّوٰی» (70/15,16)\nTranslation: No! Indeed, it will be a scorching fire, stripping away the skin."
    },
    {
      "id": 2338,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To skin / To peel off",
      "hw": "کھال",
      "s": "«سَلَخَ» is used for removing a temporary skin or veil (1 Verse: 36:37)",
      "d": "«سَلَخَ الْحَیَّۃُ» means a snake shedding its skin. And «سَلَخُ الْحَیَّۃ» means the slough of a snake. And «مِسْلَاخ» also means a snake's slough. And «سَلَخَ الْمِرَاۃ» means a woman removing her own garment. And «سَلَخَ الْخَرُوْف» means to skin a young goat (its hide). Thus, «سَلَخَ» refers to removing a raw skin, raw hide, or a raw veil.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ اٰیَۃٌ  لَّہُمُ الَّیۡلُ   ۚ ۖ نَسۡلَخُ مِنۡہُ النَّہَارَ» ( 36/37 )\nTranslation: And a sign for them is the night; We strip the day from it."
    },
    {
      "id": 2339,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To skin / To peel off",
      "hw": "کھال",
      "s": "«کَشَطَ» is used for removing a firm skin or veil (1 Verse: 81:11)",
      "d": "«کَشَطَ الْعَبِیْر » means to skin a camel. And «کِشَاط» means a removed skin. And «کَشَّاط» means a skinner, a butcher.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ اِذَا  السَّمَآءُ کُشِطَتۡ» ( 81/11 )\nTranslation: And when the sky is stripped (of its covering)."
    }
  ],
  "508": [
    {
      "id": 2340,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To eat (masdar)",
      "hw": "کھانا",
      "s": "«اَکَلَ» is general and is used everywhere for anything that is eaten, whether it is food, bread, sweets, fruit, or any other edible thing (89 Verses: 2:57-2:58-2:60-2:168-2:172-2:174-2:187-2:188-2:275-3:49-3:130-3:183-4:2-4:4-4:6-4:10-4:29-4:161-5:3-5:4-5:62-5:63-5:66-5:75-5:88-5:113-6:118-6:119-6:121-6:141-6:142-7:31-7:73-7:160-7:161-8:69-9:34-10:24-11:64-12:13-12:14-12:17-12:36-12:41-12:43-12:46-12:47-12:48-15:3-16:5-16:14-16:114-20:54-20:81-20:121-21:8-22:28-22:36-23:19-23:21-23:33-23:51-24:61-25:7-25:8-25:20-29:59-32:27-34:14-34:15-35:12-36:33-36:35-36:72-37:66-37:91-40:79-43:73-47:12-49:12-51:27-52:19-56:52-67:15-69:24-69:37-77:43-77:46-89:19)",
      "d": "«اَکَلَ» is a general word and is used everywhere for anything that is eaten, whether it is food, bread, sweets, fruit, or any other edible thing. It is used equally for humans and non-humans. A proverb is «اَکَلَتِ النَّارُ الْحَطَبَ» meaning the fire consumed the firewood.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ مَاۤ اَکَلَ السَّبُعُ اِلَّا مَا ذَکَّیۡتُمۡ» ( 5/3 )\nTranslation: And (forbidden is) that which is devoured by a wild animal, except what you slaughter (before it dies)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2341,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To eat (masdar)",
      "hw": "کھانا",
      "s": "«طَعَمَ» means to eat food (for humans) (27 Verses: 2:61-2:184-2:249-2:259-3:93-5:5-5:75-5:93-5:95-5:96-6:145-12:37-18:19-18:77-21:8-25:7-25:20-33:53-44:44-69:34-69:36-73:13-76:8-80:24-88:6-89:18-107:3)",
      "d": "«طَعَمَ» is used in a much more limited sense compared to «اکل». It means to eat food, to eat bread, to dine. And anything that is eaten as food. And this word is generally used for humans. «طَعَامِیّ» means a bread-seller. And «مَطْعَم» means a hotel, a restaurant.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَاِذَا طَعِمۡتُمۡ فَانۡتَشِرُوۡا وَ لَا مُسۡتَاۡنِسِیۡنَ لِحَدِیۡثٍ» ( 33/53 )\nTranslation: Then when you have eaten, disperse and do not remain lingering for conversation."
    },
    {
      "id": 2342,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To eat (masdar)",
      "hw": "کھانا",
      "s": "«رَتَعَ» means to eat to one's fill; for animals, to graze, to crop (1 Verse: 12:12)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «رَتَعَ» is for animals to graze, to crop. Then, metaphorically, this word is also used for humans eating and drinking to their fill, like animals. That is, to eat a lot like animals.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَرۡسِلۡہُ  مَعَنَا غَدًا یَّرۡتَعۡ وَ یَلۡعَبۡ» ( 12/12 )\nTranslation: (O father!) Send him with us tomorrow that he may eat and play to his heart's content."
    }
  ],
  "509": [
    {
      "id": 2343,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To feed (someone)",
      "hw": "کھلانا",
      "s": "«اَطْعَمَ» means to give food to a person (14 Verses: 5:89-6:14-6:138-22:28-22:36-26:79-36:47-51:57-58:4-74:44-76:8-76:9-90:14-106:4)",
      "d": "«اَطْعَمَ» means to give food to a person.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡ ہُوَ  یُطۡعِمُنِیۡ وَ  یَسۡقِیۡنِ» ( 26/79 )\nTranslation: And He it is Who gives me food and gives me drink."
    }
  ],
  "510": [
    {
      "id": 2345,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Date palm",
      "hw": "کھجور",
      "s": "«نَخْلَة» means a date palm tree (20 Verses: 2:266-6:99-6:141-13:4-16:11-16:67-17:91-18:32-19:23-19:25-20:71-23:19-26:148-36:34-50:10-54:20-55:11-55:68-69:7-80:29)",
      "d": "«نَخْلَة» means a date palm plant or tree.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ ہُزِّیۡۤ  اِلَیۡکِ بِجِذۡعِ النَّخۡلَۃِ» ( 19/25 )\nTranslation: And shake the trunk of the date palm tree towards you.\nAnd «نَخْل» is the plural of «نَخْلَۃ». Date palm trees and their fruit. Dates. The fruit of the date palm.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«جَعَلۡنَا لِاَحَدِہِمَا جَنَّتَیۡنِ مِنۡ اَعۡنَابٍ وَّ حَفَفۡنٰہُمَا بِنَخۡلٍ» ( 18/32 )\nTranslation: We gave one of them two gardens of grapes, and We surrounded them both with date palms.\nAnd «نَخِیْل» refers to a garden or plantation in which date palm trees are abundant.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«اَیَوَدُّ اَحَدُکُمۡ اَنۡ تَکُوۡنَ لَہٗ جَنَّۃٌ مِّنۡ نَّخِیۡلٍ وَّ اَعۡنَابٍ» ( 2/266 )\nTranslation: Would any of you wish to have a garden of date palms and grapes?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2346,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Date palm",
      "hw": "کھجور",
      "s": "«لِیْنَۃ» means 'Ajwa dates (a superior quality of dates) (1 Verse: 59:5)",
      "d": "«لِیْنَۃ» means 'Ajwa (a superior quality of date). Besides this, it also means the tree and fruit of every kind of date.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«مَا  قَطَعۡتُمۡ مِّنۡ  لِّیۡنَۃٍ  اَوۡ  تَرَکۡتُمُوۡہَا قَآئِمَۃً  عَلٰۤی  اُصُوۡلِہَا فَبِاِذۡنِ اللّٰہِ» ( 59/5 )\nTranslation: Whatever date-palms you cut down or left standing on their roots, it was by Allah's leave."
    },
    {
      "id": 2347,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Date palm",
      "hw": "کھجور",
      "s": "«رُطَب» means fresh, ripe dates (2 Verses: 6:59-19:25)",
      "d": "«رُطَب» means fresh, ripe dates (the fruit).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«تُسٰقِطۡ عَلَیۡکِ  رُطَبًا جَنِیًّا» ( 19/25 )\nTranslation: Fresh ripe dates shall fall upon you."
    }
  ],
  "511": [
    {
      "id": 2348,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To stand / To be standing",
      "hw": "کھڑا ",
      "s": "«قَامَ» means to stand; its opposites are «قَعَدَ» and «جَلَسَ» meaning to sit (19 Verses: 2:20-3:191-4:5-4:102-4:103-4:142-5:6-5:97-9:84-9:108-18:14-18:77-25:64-36:8-39:68-51:45-72:19-73:2-74:2)",
      "d": "«قَامَ» means to stand, and its opposites are «قَعَدَ» and «جَلَسَ» meaning to sit. It is a well-known word.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ اِذَا قَامُوۡۤا اِلَی الصَّلٰوۃِ قَامُوۡا کُسَالٰی» ( 4/142 )\nTranslation: And when they stand up for prayer, they stand up lazily.\nAnd «اَقَامَ» means to make someone stand, to establish, to set upright, to put a lying thing in an upright position.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَوَجَدَا فِیۡہَا جِدَارًا یُّرِیۡدُ اَنۡ یَّنۡقَضَّ فَاَقَامَہٗ» ( 18/77 )\nTranslation: Then they found a wall that was about to collapse, and he (Khidr) set it upright."
    },
    {
      "id": 2350,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To make stand; to be",
      "hw": "کھڑا ",
      "s": "«نَتَقَ» to shake something with such force that it remains rooted but leans to one side (1 آیات: 7:171)",
      "d": "«نَتَقَ» means to shake. To raise. To spread. (minj) And to mean to pull something and make it loose (mufradat). And to mean to shake something with such force that it remains rooted but leans to one side (m. l). In Punjabi, for this meaning, the specific word 'Alarna' is used, which expresses its correct meaning.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ اِذۡ نَتَقۡنَا الۡجَبَلَ فَوۡقَہُمۡ کَاَنَّہٗ ظُلَّۃٌ وَّ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہٗ وَاقِعٌۢ بِہِمۡ» (7/171)\nTranslation: And when We raised the mountain over them as if it were a canopy, and they thought it was about to fall upon them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2351,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Make Stand / To Be",
      "hw": "کھڑا ",
      "s": "«نَشَزَ» means to stand up and to move away. To get up. (2 Verses: 2:259, 58:11)",
      "d": "«نَشَزَ» means to stand up. «نَشَزَ الرَّجُل» means the man who was sitting stood up. And «نَشَزَ عَنْ مَکَانِہٖ» means he got up from his place and moved away.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا قِیۡلَ انۡشُزُوۡا فَانۡشُزُوۡا» (58/11)\nTranslation: And when it is said, 'Rise up,' then rise up and move away."
    }
  ],
  "512": [
    {
      "id": 2353,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Open",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "«غَلٰی» means for water to boil due to intense heat. (2 Verses: 44:45, 44:46)",
      "d": "«غَلٰی» means for water to boil and surge upwards due to intense heat. To boil. «غَلٰی الْقَدَر» means for a pot to boil and for its contents to surge up.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یَغۡلِیۡ  فِی الۡبُطُوۡنِ کَغَلۡیِ  الۡحَمِیۡمِ» (44/45, 46)\nTranslation: It will boil in their bellies like the boiling of hot water."
    },
    {
      "id": 2354,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Open",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "«بَسَطَ» means to open and spread. (22 Verses: 2:245, 2:247, 5:11, 5:28, 6:93, 7:69, 13:14, 13:26, 17:29, 17:30, 18:18, 28:82, 29:62, 30:37, 30:48, 34:36, 34:39, 39:52, 42:12, 42:27, 60:2, 71:19)",
      "d": "«بَسَطَ» means to open and spread something, and its opposite is «قبَضَ». And «قَدَر» means to spread and make something vast, to make it spacious.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَللّٰہُ یَبۡسُطُ الرِّزۡقَ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ  وَ یَقۡدِرُ» (13/26)\nTranslation: Allah extends provision for whom He wills and restricts it for whom He wills."
    },
    {
      "id": 2355,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Open",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "«فَتَحَ» means to open a sealed container or to unravel a complex matter. (14 Verses: 2:76, 6:44, 7:40, 7:96, 12:65, 15:14, 21:96, 23:77, 35:2, 38:50, 39:71, 39:73, 54:11, 78:19)",
      "d": "«فَتَحَ» means to remove the complexity of a matter, to open a tied container, and its opposite is «اَغْلَاق».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَمَّا فَتَحُوۡا مَتَاعَہُمۡ وَجَدُوۡا بِضَاعَتَہُمۡ رُدَّتۡ  اِلَیۡہِمۡ» (12/65)\nTranslation: When they opened their baggage, they found their merchandise returned to them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2357,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Open",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "«شَرَحَ» means to explain the meanings of difficult speech and to clarify. (5 Verses: 6:125, 16:106, 20:25, 39:22, 94:1)",
      "d": "«شَرَحَ» means to explain the meanings of difficult speech. According to Ibn al-Faris, two things are fundamental in 'sharh': (1) 'fath' meaning to open, and (2) 'bayān' meaning explanation. 'Sharh al-sadr' means to open the chest, i.e., to understand a difficult and complex matter.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«رَبِّ  اشۡرَحۡ  لِیۡ  صَدۡرِیۡ وَ  یَسِّرۡ لِیۡۤ   اَمۡرِیۡ» (20/25, 26)\nTranslation: O my Lord, expand for me my breast and ease for me my task."
    },
    {
      "id": 2358,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Open",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "«کَشَفَ» means to remove one thing to reveal another. (15 Verses: 6:41, 7:134, 7:135, 10:12, 10:98, 16:54, 17:56, 21:84, 23:75, 27:44, 27:62, 43:50, 44:12, 50:22, 68:42)",
      "d": "«کَشَفَ» means to open, to remove, to unveil, to remove one thing in place of another, and for the first thing to become apparent and manifest.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاَتۡہُ حَسِبَتۡہُ  لُجَّۃً  وَّ کَشَفَتۡ عَنۡ سَاقَیۡہَا» (27/44)\nTranslation: When she saw it, she thought it was a deep pool, and she uncovered her shins."
    },
    {
      "id": 2359,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To open",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "«نَشَطَ» to loosen a knot or joint, etc. (1 آیات: 79:2)",
      "d": "«نَشَطَ» is from the category of antonyms (addad). «نَشَطَ الْحَبْلَ» means to tie a rope in a knot. And «نَشَطَ الْعُقْدَۃ» means to tighten the knot. And «اَلْنَشْط» means a knot that opens easily. (minj) And «نَشَطَ» means to untie a knot (mufradat). So this word is more specific than «حَلَّ». The meaning of «حَلَّ الْعُقٌدَۃ» is the same as that of نشط. Meaning to untie a knot. To loosen a joint. To loosen a knot.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ النّٰزِعٰتِ غَرۡقًا وَّ النّٰشِطٰتِ نَشۡطًا» (79/1,2)\nTranslation: By those who pull forth with force, and by those who untie with ease.\nNote: (The term addad refers to words that have opposite meanings.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2360,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To open",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "«فَرَجَ» to open and make wide (1 آیات: 77:9)",
      "d": "In «فَرْج», the concept of spaciousness is found. «فَرَجَ» means to open. To make wide. To open up. To expand. (For more detail, see shagaf.)\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ اِذَا السَّمَآءُ  فُرِجَتۡ» (77/9)\nTranslation: And when the sky is opened up."
    }
  ],
  "513": [
    {
      "id": 2361,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Cultivate / To Farm",
      "hw": "کھیتی باڑی",
      "s": "«حَرَثَ» means to plow and to sow seeds. (10 Verses: 2:71, 2:205, 2:223, 3:14, 3:117, 6:136, 6:138, 21:78, 42:20, 68:22)",
      "d": "«حَرَثَ» means to plow the land and sow seeds in it, preparing it for cultivation. Its plural is «مِحْرَث» and its collective plural is «مَحَارِث», meaning plowing tools like a plow, etc. Sometimes, cultivation itself is also called «حَرْث».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَنِ  اغۡدُوۡا عَلٰی حَرۡثِکُمۡ  اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰرِمِیۡنَ» (68/22)\nTranslation: If you are reapers (i.e., intend to harvest), then go early to your cultivation."
    },
    {
      "id": 2362,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to cultivate",
      "hw": "کھیتی باڑی",
      "s": "«زَرَعَ» means to irrigate and properly care for (seeds) after planting (10 verses: 6:141-12:47-13:4-14:37-16:11-18:32-32:27-39:21-48:29-56:64)",
      "d": "The original meaning of «زَرَعَ» is 'to grow' or 'to cause to grow'. It also includes planting seeds in the soil, irrigating, and proper care. Metaphorically, cultivation is attributed to humans because they perform the duties of care, though in reality, growth is solely by Allah. (Mufradat) For example, the Quran states: «أَفَرَأَيْتُمْ مَا تَحْرُثُونَ أَأَنْتُمْ تَزْرَعُونَهُ أَمْ نَحْنُ الزَّارِعُونَ» (56/63,64). Translation: 'Do you see what you plow? Is it you who cause it to grow, or are We the Grower?'"
    }
  ],
  "514": [
    {
      "id": 2363,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to pull",
      "hw": "کھینچنا",
      "s": "«مَدّ» means to pull and extend, and to lengthen in such a way that the thing remains connected (9 verses: 2:15-7:202-13:3-19:75-25:45-31:27-56:30-74:12-104:9)",
      "d": "«مَدّ» means to pull something to make it long or extended, and to stretch it while maintaining connection. And 'mudda' means duration or length of time. For example, the Quran states: «وَإِخْوَانُهُمْ يَمُدُّونَهُمْ فِي الْغَيِّ ثُمَّ لَا يُقْصِرُونَ» (7/202). Translation: 'And their brothers extend them in error, and they do not desist.' And «مَدَّدَ» comes as an intensifier. For example: «فِي عَمَدٍ مُّمَدَّدَةٍ» (104/9). Translation: 'In long extended pillars.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2364,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to pull",
      "hw": "کھینچنا",
      "s": "«جَرَّ» means to pull someone on the ground and drag them (1 verse: 7:150)",
      "d": "«جَرَّ» means to pull and drag (on the ground). And «جَیْشٌ جَرَارٌ» means a very large army that is spread over a wide area and advances while being pulled. For example, the Quran states: «وَأَخَذَ بِرَأْسِ أَخِيهِ يَجُرُّهُ إِلَيْهِ» (7/150). Translation: 'And Moses took hold of his brother's head and began to pull him toward himself.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2365,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to pull",
      "hw": "کھینچنا",
      "s": "«اِضطَرَّ» means to forcibly and compellingly pull someone toward a task (8 verses: 2:126-2:173-5:3-6:119-6:145-16:115-27:62-31:24)",
      "d": "«اِضطَرَّ» means to pull someone by force toward a task. To compel and make someone do something by force. For example, the Quran states: «وَمَنْ كَفَرَ فَأُمَتِّعُهُ قَلِيلًا ثُمَّ أَضْطَرُّهُ إِلَى عَذَابِ النَّارِ» (2/126). Translation: 'And whoever disbelieves, I will grant him a little enjoyment; then I will force him to the punishment of the Fire.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2366,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to pull",
      "hw": "کھینچنا",
      "s": "«سَلَخَ» means to pull off the skin (1 verse: 36:37)",
      "d": "«سَلَخَ» means to remove the skin of a living being. To peel off a snake's skin. And according to Ibn al-Faris, to remove something from the skin. And «سَلَخَتِ الشَّهْر» means the month's last day arrives. For example, the Quran states: «وَآیَةٌ لَهُمُ اللَّیْلُ نَسْلَخُ مِنْهُ النَّهَارَ فَإِذَا هُمْ مُظْلِمُونَ» (36/37). Translation: 'And a sign for them is the night; We remove from it the day, and they are left in darkness.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2367,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to pull",
      "hw": "کھینچنا",
      "s": "«نَزَعَ» means to pull something from its place (10 verses: 3:26-7:27-7:43-7:108-11:9-15:47-19:69-26:33-28:75-54:20)",
      "d": "«نَزَعَ» means to pull something from its place, such as pulling the soul from the body, or to extract something by pulling. For example, the Quran states: «وَنَزَعْنَا مَا فِي صُدُورِهِمْ مِنْ غِلٍّ» (7/43). Translation: 'And We will remove from their breasts any sense of bitterness.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2368,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to pull",
      "hw": "کھینچنا",
      "s": "«سَفَعَ» means to pull. «سَفَعَ بِالنَّاصِیَةِ» means to pull by the forelock (hair) (1 verse: 96:15)",
      "d": "«سَفَعَ» means to pull a horse by its forelock. For example, the Quran states: «لَئِنْ لَمْ يَنْتَهِ لَنَسْفَعًا بِالنَّاصِیَةِ» (96/15). Translation: 'If he does not desist, We will surely seize him by the forelock.'"
    }
  ],
  "515": [
    {
      "id": 2370,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to play",
      "hw": "کھیلنا",
      "s": "«لَھٰی» means any act that distracts from the main purpose (14 verses: 4:135-6:32-6:70-7:51-21:17-29:64-31:6-38:26-47:36-53:3-57:20-62:11-79:40-102:1)",
      "d": "«لَھٰی» means amusement and any act done for entertainment. It is more general than «لَعَبَ». «لَھْو» includes playing. And watching play or amusement, etc., are all included. That is, any act that keeps one away from purposeful deeds and causes heart's delight is «لَھْو». And «اَلْھٰی» means such delightful acts that make one neglect the main purpose. For example, the Quran states: «وَمَا الْحَیَاتُ الدُّنْیَا إِلَّا لَعِبٌ وَلَهْوٌ» (6/32). Translation: 'And the life of this world is but play and amusement.'"
    }
  ],
  "516": [
    {
      "id": 2373,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Is it?",
      "hw": "کیا ",
      "s": "«ھَلْ» is an interrogative particle. A question word, meaning 'Is it?' (88 verses: 2:210-2:246-3:154-5:59-5:60-5:91-5:112-6:47-6:50-6:148-6:158-7:44-7:53-7:147-9:52-9:127-10:34-10:35-10:52-10:102-11:14-11:24-12:64-12:89-13:16-14:21-16:33-16:35-16:75-16:76-17:93-18:66-18:94-18:103-19:65-19:98-20:9-20:40-20:120-21:3-21:80-21:108-22:15-26:39-26:72-26:93-26:203-26:221-27:90-28:12-30:28-30:40-34:7-34:17-34:33-35:3-35:43-37:54-39:9-39:29-39:38-40:11-40:47-42:44-43:66-46:35-47:18-47:22-50:30-50:36-51:24-54:15-54:17-54:22-54:32-54:40-54:51-55:60-61:10-67:3-69:8-76:1-79:15-79:18-83:36-85:17-88:1-89:5)",
      "d": "«ھَلْ» is an interrogative particle. It is used with nouns and verbs, not with particles. For example, the Quran states: «هَلْ يَسْتَوِي الْأَعْمَى وَ الْبَصِیرُ» (13/16). Translation: 'Is it that the blind and the seeing can be equal?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2375,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "What?",
      "hw": "کیا ",
      "s": "«مَاذَا» means both 'what' and 'which' (27 verses: 2:26-2:215-2:219-4:39-5:4-5:109-7:110-10:32-10:50-10:101-12:71-16:24-16:30-26:35-27:28-27:33-27:84-28:65-31:11-31:34-34:23-35:40-37:85-37:102-46:4-47:16-74:31)",
      "d": "«مَاذَا» is formed by adding «ذَا» to the interrogative pronoun «مَا», which expands its meanings. It conveys both 'what' and 'which'. It can also be used for those of sound intellect. For example, the Quran states: «یَسْئَلُونَكَ مَا ذَا يُنْفِقُونَ» (2/219). Translation: 'They ask you what (i.e., which wealth) they should spend.' Similarly, in another verse: «مَاذَا أَجَبْتُمُ الْمُرْسَلِینَ» (28/65). Translation: 'What did you answer the messengers?'"
    }
  ],
  "517": [
    {
      "id": 2376,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "How?",
      "hw": "کیسے",
      "s": "«کَیْف» is used to inquire about the quality and essence of something (83 verses: 2:28-2:259-2:260-3:6-3:25-3:86-3:101-3:137-4:21-4:41-4:50-4:62-5:31-5:43-5:64-5:75-6:11-6:24-6:46-6:65-6:81-7:84-7:86-7:93-7:103-7:129-9:7-9:8-10:14-10:35-10:39-10:73-12:109-13:32-14:24-14:45-16:36-17:21-17:48-18:68-19:29-22:44-25:9-25:45-27:14-27:51-27:69-28:40-29:19-29:20-30:9-30:42-30:48-30:50-34:45-35:26-35:44-37:73-37:154-40:5-40:21-40:82-43:25-47:10-47:27-50:6-54:16-54:18-54:21-54:30-67:17-67:18-68:36-71:15-73:17-74:19-74:20-88:17-88:18-88:19-88:20-89:6-105:1)",
      "d": "«کَیْف» comes to ask about the quality and essence of something.\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«اَفَلَا یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ  اِلَی الۡاِبِلِ کَیۡفَ خُلِقَتۡ» (88/17)\nTranslation: Do people not look at the camel how (wonderfully) it is created?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2377,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "How?",
      "hw": "کیسے",
      "s": "«اَنّٰی» comes to ask for the reason of something (28 verses: 2:223-2:247-2:259-3:37-3:40-3:47-3:165-5:75-6:95-6:101-9:30-10:32-10:34-19:8-19:20-23:89-29:61-34:52-35:3-36:66-39:6-40:62-40:69-43:87-44:13-47:18-63:4-89:23)",
      "d": "«اَنّٰی» comes to ask for the reason of something. How come.\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«اَنّٰی یَکُوۡنُ لَہُ الۡمُلۡکُ عَلَیۡنَا» (2/247)\nTranslation: How can the right of kingship be for him over us?"
    }
  ],
  "518": [
    {
      "id": 2378,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Why / Why not",
      "hw": "کیوں",
      "s": "«لِمَ» meaning why (19 verses: 2:91-3:65-3:66-3:70-3:71-3:98-3:99-3:183-4:77-5:18-7:164-9:43-19:42-20:125-27:46-41:21-61:2-61:5-66:1)",
      "d": "«لِمَ» meaning why. For what reason.\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«رَبِّ  لِمَ حَشَرۡتَنِیۡۤ  اَعۡمٰی» (20/125)\nTranslation: My Lord, why have you raised me blind?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2379,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Why / Why not",
      "hw": "کیوں",
      "s": "«لَوْلَا» meaning why not (41 verses: 2:118-4:77-5:63-6:8-6:37-6:43-7:203-9:122-10:20-10:98-11:12-11:116-13:7-13:27-18:15-18:39-20:133-20:134-24:12-24:13-24:16-25:7-25:21-25:32-27:46-28:47-28:48-29:50-41:44-43:31-43:53-46:28-47:20-56:57-56:62-56:70-56:83-56:86-58:8-63:10-68:28)",
      "d": "«لَوْلَا» meaning why not. It is used for reproach (tawbikh) and specification (takhsis). In reproach, it is followed by a past tense verb. For example: «لَوۡ لَا جَآءُوۡ عَلَیۡہِ  بِاَرۡبَعَۃِ شُہَدَآءَ» (24/13) Translation: Why did they not bring four witnesses against him? In specification, it is followed by a present tense verb. For example: «لَوۡ لَا تَسۡتَغۡفِرُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ» (27/46) Translation: Why do you not seek forgiveness from Allah?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2380,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Why / Why not",
      "hw": "کیوں",
      "s": "«لَوْمَا» is called a specification particle in Arabic grammar (1 verse: 15:7)",
      "d": "«لَوْمَا» is a specification particle. It enters with the present tense and gives the meaning of «لَوْلَا».\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«لَوۡ مَا تَاۡتِیۡنَا بِالۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ» (15/7)\nTranslation: Why do you not bring angels to us?"
    }
  ],
  "519": [
    {
      "id": 2382,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Embedding",
      "hw": "گاڑنا",
      "s": "«اَرْسٰی» means to peg like a stake so that more is inside the earth and less outside (11 verses: 13:3-15:19-16:15-21:31-27:61-31:10-34:13-41:10-50:7-77:27-79:32)",
      "d": "«رَسُو» means firm, solid. And «اَرْسٰی» means to fix something in the earth such that most of it is inside and little outside. They say «رَسَا الْوَتْدَ فِی الْاَرْضِ» meaning the stake was fixed in the earth. And «رَاسِیَہ» means mountain; its plural is «رَوَاسِی». «رَاسِیْۃ» refers to mountains that spread over a vast area on earth with most of them underground. And «رَوَاسی» means mountain range. For fixing mountains, Allah has used both «نَصَب» and «رسو».\nFor example: «وَ الۡجِبَالَ  اَرۡسٰہَا» (79/32) Translation: And He fixed the mountains (in the earth).\nAnother place: «وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ مَدَّ الۡاَرۡضَ وَ جَعَلَ  فِیۡہَا رَوَاسِیَ وَ اَنۡہٰرًا» (13/3) Translation: And He is the One who spread the earth and made in it mountains and rivers."
    }
  ],
  "520": [
    {
      "id": 2385,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Rotation (of time)",
      "hw": "زمانہ",
      "s": "«رَیْب» means doubt and «رَیْبَ الْمَنُوْن» is idiomatically used when someone awaits another's bad outcome. Its translation is done as 'rotation of time (events of time)' (1 verse: 52:30)",
      "d": "«رَیْب» means doubt and suspicion, restlessness. (See detailed explanation under doubt and suspicion). As for «مَنَی», it means to test or afflict. «مَنِیَّۃ» signifies death, intention, or divine decree; its plural is «مَنَایَا» and «مَنُوْن» is derived from it. The phrase «رَیْبَ الْمَنُوْن» is idiomatically used when one awaits another's adverse fate, and it is translated as 'the vicissitudes of time (events of time)'.\nFor example: «اَمۡ  یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ  شَاعِرٌ  نَّتَرَبَّصُ بِہٖ  رَیۡبَ الۡمَنُوۡنِ» (52/30)\nTranslation: Or do they say [about the Prophet], 'He is a poet; we await for him a misfortune [i.e., his death]'."
    },
    {
      "id": 2386,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Rotation (of time)",
      "hw": "زمانہ",
      "s": "«دَائِرَۃ» means to circle, to make a cycle, rotation of days and the calamities and afflictions of time (3 verses: 5:52-9:98-48:6)",
      "d": "«دَارَ» means to circle, to make a cycle. And «دَائِرَۃ» is used in two ways: one is the geometric term for a circle, and the other means rotation of days, the calamities and afflictions of time (from majd). Thus, it is also used in a negative sense, implying awaiting calamities upon someone, and its plural is «دوائر».\nFor example: «وَ مِنَ الۡاَعۡرَابِ مَنۡ یَّتَّخِذُ مَا یُنۡفِقُ مَغۡرَمًا وَّ یَتَرَبَّصُ بِکُمُ الدَّوَآئِرَ ؕ عَلَیۡہِمۡ دَآئِرَۃُ  السَّوۡءِ» (9/98)\nTranslation: And among the bedouins are those who consider what they spend as a loss and await [misfortunes] to befall you. The calamities will befall them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2387,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Rotation (of time)",
      "hw": "زمانہ",
      "s": "«دُوْلَۃً ، دَوْلَۃً» is used in good meanings opposite to circle, like days of prosperity (2 verses: 3:140-59:7)",
      "d": "«دُوْلَۃً ، دَوْلَۃً» is used in good meanings opposite to circle (muf). «دَالَ الزَّمَان» means the turning of time from one state to another (from majd). It refers to the circulation of wealth, days of prosperity, and awaiting them. After detailing the distribution of wealth and the deserving, Allah says: «کَیۡ لَا یَکُوۡنَ  دُوۡلَۃًۢ  بَیۡنَ الۡاَغۡنِیَآءِ مِنۡکُمۡ» (59/7) Translation: So that [the wealth] does not become a [mere] circulation among the rich from among you. Another place: «وَ تِلۡکَ الۡاَیَّامُ نُدَاوِلُہَا بَیۡنَ النَّاسِ» (3/140) Translation: And those days [of victory] We alternate among the people."
    }
  ],
  "521": [
    {
      "id": 2388,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Neck",
      "hw": "گردن",
      "s": "«عُنُق» is the general word for neck (9 verses: 8:12-13:5-17:13-17:29-26:4-34:33-36:8-38:33-40:71)",
      "d": "«عُنُق» means neck or throat. A well-known human organ. Its usage is general. Its plural is «اَعْنَاق».\nFor example: «وَ کُلَّ  اِنۡسَانٍ اَلۡزَمۡنٰہُ طٰٓئِرَہٗ  فِیۡ عُنُقِہٖ» (17/13)\nTranslation: And We have bound every human's deeds around his neck."
    },
    {
      "id": 2389,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Neck",
      "hw": "گردن",
      "s": "«jīd» long and beautiful neck (1 verse: 111:5)",
      "d": "«jīd» means thin and long neck (F L 110), a beautiful neck like a deer's.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَّ  امۡرَاَتُہٗ ؕ حَمَّالَۃَ  الۡحَطَبِ فِیۡ  جِیۡدِہَا حَبۡلٌ مِّنۡ مَّسَدٍ» ( 111/4،5 )\nTranslation: And his (Abu Lahab's) wife will carry firewood, and around her neck will be a rope of palm fibers."
    },
    {
      "id": 2390,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Neck",
      "hw": "گردن",
      "s": "«raqabah» neck and its back part, the nape. The bond of slavery (4 verses: 4:92-5:89-58:3-90:13)",
      "d": "«raqabah» means neck or the part behind it (nape), and «raqab» means to put a rope or noose around someone's neck. To supervise and guard. Arabs generally use «juz' usharaf» to mean the whole. Similarly, «raqabah» is taken to mean slave because a slave has a bond of slavery around his neck, and its plural is «riqab» (Munjid, Mufradat). And «tahrīr raqabah» means freeing the neck from the noose, i.e., freeing a slave.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا الۡعَقَبَۃُ فَکُّ رَقَبَۃٍ» ( 90/12،13 )\nTranslation: And do you know what the 'Iqabah' is? It is freeing a neck (i.e., freeing a slave)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2391,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Neck",
      "hw": "گردن",
      "s": "«watīn» the front part of the neck where the carotid artery is (1 verse: 69:46)",
      "d": "«watīn» means the jugular vein. The carotid artery from the heart to the head (F L 114). The side of the neck where the carotid artery is.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَاَخَذۡنَا مِنۡہُ  بِالۡیَمِیۡنِ ثُمَّ  لَقَطَعۡنَا مِنۡہُ  الۡوَتِیۡنَ» ( 69/45،46 )\nTranslation: We would have seized him by the right hand, then cut off his jugular vein (the carotid artery)."
    }
  ],
  "522": [
    {
      "id": 2392,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Seizing",
      "hw": "گرفت",
      "s": "«akhadha» to hold accountable for a disliked act, questioning, or seizing (7 verses: 2:225-2:286-5:89-16:61-18:58-18:73-35:45)",
      "d": "«akhadha» means to take something. To acquire. To encompass. And «akhadha» means to question, to seize, to take (Mufradat), whether it is accountability in speech or action.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«رَبَّنَا لَا تُؤَاخِذۡنَاۤ  اِنۡ نَّسِیۡنَاۤ  اَوۡ اَخۡطَاۡنَا» ( 2/286 )\nTranslation: Our Lord, do not hold us accountable if we forget or make a mistake."
    },
    {
      "id": 2394,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Seizing",
      "hw": "گرفت",
      "s": "«lamah, lāwama» to say bad things, whether the act is bad or not, without the severity like «tathrīb» (11 verses: 5:54-14:22-17:29-17:39-23:6-37:142-51:40-51:54-68:30-70:30-75:2)",
      "d": "«lamah» means to reproach someone for a bad deed. To blame (Mufradat). And it means to warn someone about the consequence of their action (F Q 39). And «lāwam» means blame and fear (Munjid). So «lam» is used when the doer fears being blamed for an action, whether the action itself is good or bad.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یُجَاہِدُوۡنَ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ وَ لَا  یَخَافُوۡنَ لَوۡمَۃَ لَآئِمٍ» ( 5/54 )\nTranslation: They strive in the way of Allah and do not fear the blame of any blamer."
    }
  ],
  "523": [
    {
      "id": 2395,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Heat, Heating, Being Hot",
      "hw": "گرمی",
      "s": "«ṣayf» summer season (1 verse: 106:2)",
      "d": "«ṣayf» means summer season. And «ṣayyafa» means the rain of summer and the grass that grows from it. And «ṣāf» and «ṣayyafa bil-makān» means to spend summer in a place (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اٖلٰفِہِمۡ  رِحۡلَۃَ  الشِّتَآءِ  وَ الصَّیۡفِ» ( 106/2 )\nTranslation: Accustomed to the winter and summer journeys."
    },
    {
      "id": 2396,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Heat, Heating, Being Hot",
      "hw": "گرمی",
      "s": "«ḥarr» heat, the scorching of the sun (2 verses: 9:81-16:81)",
      "d": "«ḥarr» means heat, warmth, whether from fire or sun, i.e., the intensity of sunlight, or from any other cause like friction. However, this word is generally used for the intensity of sunlight. And «ḥarūr» means scorching heat (see also sunlight).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا لَا تَنۡفِرُوۡا فِی الۡحَرِّ ؕ قُلۡ نَارُ جَہَنَّمَ اَشَدُّ حَرًّا» ( 9/81 )\nTranslation: And they said, 'Do not go out in the heat.' Say, 'The fire of Hell is more intense in heat.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2397,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Heat, Heating, Being Hot",
      "hw": "گرمی",
      "s": "«ḥamma, ḥummi» are synonymous and are used in all contexts of heat and intense warmth (22 verses: 6:70-10:4-22:19-26:101-37:67-38:57-40:18-40:72-41:34-44:46-44:48-47:15-48:26-55:44-56:42-56:54-56:93-69:35-70:10-78:25-88:4-101:11)",
      "d": "«ḥamma» and «ḥummi» are so similar in meaning that distinguishing them is difficult. Hence, lexicographers include both under the same root. There are four sources of heat: fire and sun (material), and emotional heat and bodily warmth (spiritual). Both roots are used for all four. The difference is that «ḥamma» is transitive and «ḥummi» is intransitive, but in passive form they become synonymous. For example, «ḥamma al-mā'» means to heat water, and «ḥumma al-rajul» means the man got a fever. «ḥummi» means fever. Both roots are listed under both roots by lexicographers. And «ḥamma al-tannūr» means to heat the oven, and «ḥummi al-nār» means the fire blazed. And «ḥamīm» means hot water or cold water (antonymic roots, etc.). And a hot-tempered friend or relative (related to emotions). And «ḥamma al-ẓahīrah» means the intense heat at noon. And «ḥammah» means a hot spring. And «ḥummah» means a kettle, or ashes, or everything burning in fire. And «ḥammām» means a place for bathing with hot water (Mufradat, Munjid).\nNow consider their examples:\n(1) «لَہُمۡ شَرَابٌ مِّنۡ حَمِیۡمٍ  وَّ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌۢ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَکۡفُرُوۡنَ» ( 6/70 )\nTranslation: For them is a drink of boiling water and a painful torment because they used to disbelieve.\n(2) «وَ لَا یَسۡئَلُ  حَمِیۡمٌ حَمِیۡمًا» ( 70/10 )\nTranslation: And no friend will ask about a friend.\n(3) «وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا ہِیَہۡ نَارٌ حَامِیَۃٌ» ( 101/10،11 )\nTranslation: And do you know what the 'Hawiyah' is? It is a blazing fire.\n(4) «اِذۡ جَعَلَ  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا فِیۡ  قُلُوۡبِہِمُ الۡحَمِیَّۃَ حَمِیَّۃَ  الۡجَاہِلِیَّۃِ» ( 48/26 )\nTranslation: When those who disbelieved put in their hearts the pride of Jahiliyyah (ignorance)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2398,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Heat, Heating, Being Hot",
      "hw": "گرمی",
      "s": "«saqara» to scorch the body with fire or sun's heat (4 verses: 54:48-74:26-74:27-74:42)",
      "d": "«saqara» means to scorch with fire or sun. «saqarat-hu al-shams» means the sun scorched him. Then this word became a proper noun for Hell (Mufradat).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ذُوۡقُوۡا مَسَّ سَقَرَ» ( 54/48 )\nTranslation: So taste the touch of Saqar."
    },
    {
      "id": 2399,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Heat, Heating, Being Hot",
      "hw": "گرمی",
      "s": "«samūm» scorching wind that penetrates the body (3 verses: 15:27-52:27-56:42)",
      "d": "«sam» means a narrow hole like an eye of a needle, or a nostril, or a nasal passage. Also «sam» means deadly poison. And «samūm» means a scorching wind that penetrates the body like poison.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَمَنَّ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡنَا وَ  وَقٰىنَا عَذَابَ السَّمُوۡمِ» ( 52/27 )\nTranslation: So Allah favored us and saved us from the punishment of the scorching wind."
    },
    {
      "id": 2401,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To obtain heat",
      "hw": "گرمی",
      "s": "«اِصْطَلٰی» is used to mean obtaining heat from fire (2 verses: 27:7-28:29)",
      "d": "«صَلَی» means to enter fire. And «اَصْلٰی» and «صَلّٰی» mean to cause to enter fire. And «اِصْطَلٰی» means to obtain heat from fire. To warm by fire. To heat and to warm the body to protect it from cold.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَوۡ اٰتِیۡکُمۡ بِشِہَابٍ قَبَسٍ لَّعَلَّکُمۡ تَصۡطَلُوۡنَ» (27/7)\nTranslation: Or I will bring you a glowing ember so that you may warm yourselves."
    }
  ],
  "524": [
    {
      "id": 2402,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«سُقِط» means something falling from above (6 verses: 6:59-7:149-9:49-17:92-26:187-34:9)",
      "d": "«سُقِط» means the falling of something from a height to the ground. Its usage is general, however, an element of contempt is found in it. For example, «رَجُلٌ سَاقِط» means a despicable man (Manjad).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَا تَسۡقُطُ مِنۡ وَّرَقَۃٍ  اِلَّا یَعۡلَمُہَا» (6/59)\nTranslation: And not a leaf falls but Allah knows it.\nThen, as this word is used literally, it is also used metaphorically.\nFor example, the Almighty says:\n«اَلَا فِی الۡفِتۡنَۃِ سَقَطُوۡا» (9/49)\nTranslation: Behold, they have fallen into temptation.\nAnd «سُقِطَ فِیْ یَدِہٖ» is used idiomatically to mean someone being regretful and ashamed. Only by changing the pronoun, the form changes.\nFor example, the Almighty says:\n«وَ لَمَّا سُقِطَ فِیۡۤ  اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ وَ رَاَوۡا اَنَّہُمۡ قَدۡ ضَلُّوۡا» (7/149)\nTranslation: And when they were regretful and saw that they had gone astray.\nAnd for causing to fall, «اَسْقَطَ» is used.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَسۡقِطۡ عَلَیۡنَا کِسَفًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ  اِنۡ  کُنۡتَ مِنَ  الصّٰدِقِیۡنَ» (26/187)\nTranslation: If you are truthful, then bring down on us a fragment from the sky."
    },
    {
      "id": 2403,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«خَرَّ» means something falling with agitation (i.e., restlessness) and sound (4 verses: 7:143-22:31-34:14-38:24)",
      "d": "«خَرَّ» means something falling with sound and agitation (i.e., restlessness and unease) (m. l.) meaning that at the time of falling, there is restlessness or trembling, and upon falling, a sound is also produced. And «خَرِیْر» means the sound of water falling or dripping (m. l.).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا خَرَّ تَبَیَّنَتِ الۡجِنُّ اَنۡ لَّوۡ کَانُوۡا یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ الۡغَیۡبَ مَا لَبِثُوۡا فِی الۡعَذَابِ الۡمُہِیۡنِ» (34/14)\nTranslation: Then when Solomon fell, the jinn realized that if they had known the unseen, they would not have remained in the humiliating punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 2404,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«ھَدَمَ» means the falling of a building or wall or structure (1 verse: 22:40)",
      "d": "«ھَدَمَ» means the falling of a building or structure (m. l.) and «ھَدَّم» means to demolish a building. To cause to fall. To tear down. «اِنْھِدَام» is a famous word used in the same meaning as «ھَدَم».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَا دَفۡعُ اللّٰہِ النَّاسَ بَعۡضَہُمۡ بِبَعۡضٍ لَّہُدِّمَتۡ صَوَامِعُ وَ بِیَعٌ» (22/40)\nTranslation: And if Allah did not repel some people by others, then monasteries and churches would have been demolished."
    },
    {
      "id": 2405,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«ھَدَّ» the collapse of a building, wall, or structure with a loud crash (1 verse: 19:90)",
      "d": "«ھَدَّ» means for something like a building to collapse and fall to the ground with a crash, producing a sound (M. L.), and also means «شُدُّہُ الْہَدَم» (F. L. 47).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«تَکَادُ السَّمٰوٰتُ یَتَفَطَّرۡنَ مِنۡہُ وَ تَنۡشَقُّ الۡاَرۡضُ وَ تَخِرُّ الۡجِبَالُ ہَدًّا» (19/90)\nTranslation: It is as if the heavens would almost rupture from it, and the earth would split open, and the mountains would fall in pieces."
    },
    {
      "id": 2406,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«اِنْقَضَّ» means a wall or building cracking and falling or being about to fall (10 verses: 2:27-4:155-5:13-8:56-13:20-13:25-16:91-16:92-18:77-94:3)",
      "d": "«اِنْقَضَّ» means a building or wall cracking and falling or being on the verge of falling (f. l. 297). «قَضَّ الْحَائِط» means to cause a wall to fall. And «اِنْقَضَّ الْحَائِط» means the wall cracked and fell (m. q.).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَوَجَدَا فِیۡہَا جِدَارًا یُّرِیۡدُ اَنۡ یَّنۡقَضَّ فَاَقَامَہٗ» (18/77)\nTranslation: Then they found a wall there that was about to collapse, so he (Khidr) set it right."
    },
    {
      "id": 2407,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«ھَبَطَ» means to fall; to descend; to exit. In this word, the aspect of wrath and compulsion (restlessness and unease) is found (8 verses: 2:36-2:38-2:61-2:74-7:13-7:24-11:48-20:123)",
      "d": "«ھَبَطَ» means to fall; to descend; to exit. In this word, the aspect of wrath and compulsion (restlessness and unease) is found (muf). «ھَبَطَ الثَّمَن» means the price fell. «ھَبَطَ الزَّمَان» means time made him poor from rich. «ھَبَطَ الْمَرَض» means disease consumed his flesh and made him thin and weak (Manjad. m. q.). It is used both as intransitive and transitive.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنَّ مِنۡہَا لَمَا یَہۡبِطُ مِنۡ خَشۡیَۃِ اللّٰہِ» (2/74)\nTranslation: And indeed, some of them fall from the fear of Allah.\nThen in «ھَبَطَ», besides wrath and compulsion, sometimes an element of contempt is also found. In that case, it means 'get out' (GETOUT).\nFor example, the Almighty says:\n«قُلۡنَا اہۡبِطُوۡا مِنۡہَا جَمِیۡعًا» (2/38)\nTranslation: We said, 'Get out of it, all of you.'\nThis meaning was expressed by a poet in these words:\nTo exit from Paradise was Adam's custom, hearing it came,\nbut we exited from your neighborhood very dishonorably!\nAnd the following verse:\n«قِیۡلَ یٰنُوۡحُ اہۡبِطۡ بِسَلٰمٍ مِّنَّا» (11/48)\nTranslation: It was said, 'O Noah, disembark with peace from us.'\nI make «بِسَلٰمٍ» with «ھَبِطَ» exclude all aspects of wrath, compulsion, or contempt, and make it according to divine decree."
    },
    {
      "id": 2408,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«وَقَعَ» means in the falling of something, there is also horror and severity (19 verses: 4:100-5:91-7:71-7:118-7:134-7:171-10:51-18:53-27:82-27:85-42:22-51:6-52:7-56:1-56:2-56:75-69:15-70:1-77:7)",
      "d": "«وَقَعَ» means to fall; to be established; to occur. This word generally comes to mention horror, severity, and hardship. And by 'event' is meant an incident in which there is severity (muf).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِذۡ نَتَقۡنَا الۡجَبَلَ فَوۡقَہُمۡ کَاَنَّہٗ ظُلَّۃٌ وَّ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہٗ وَاقِعٌۢ بِہِمۡ» (7/171)\nTranslation: And when We raised the mountain over them as if it were a canopy, and they thought it was about to fall on them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2410,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«ھَوٰی» means to fall from the sky or from a great height (4 verses: 20:81-22:31-53:1-53:53)",
      "d": "«ھَوَا» is a famous word meaning the space between the sky and the earth. And «ھَوٰی» means to fall from space or from a great height to the ground (m. l.) It is also used for the falling of a star (f. l. 297).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ النَّجۡمِ   اِذَا ہَوٰی» (53/1)\nTranslation: By the star when it falls.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«فَکَاَنَّمَا خَرَّ  مِنَ السَّمَآءِ فَتَخۡطَفُہُ الطَّیۡرُ  اَوۡ تَہۡوِیۡ بِہِ الرِّیۡحُ فِیۡ مَکَانٍ  سَحِیۡقٍ» (22/31)\nTranslation: As if he had fallen from the sky, then the bird snatches him away, or the wind carries him to a distant place."
    },
    {
      "id": 2411,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«خَوٰی» means to fall from the void between two things (5 verses: 2:259-18:42-22:45-27:52-69:7)",
      "d": "«خَوٰی» and «ھَوٰی» are close in meaning. The difference is only that «ھَوَا» refers to the empty space between the earth and the sky, while «خَوٰی» refers to any empty space between two things. For example, for the falling of a star, «ھَوَی النَّجْم» is used, similarly «خَوَی النَّجْم» is also used (m. l.). «تَخْوِیَۃ» means to leave an empty space between two things. And «خَوٰی الدَّار» means the falling of a house that is deserted and ruined.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَوۡ کَالَّذِیۡ مَرَّ عَلٰی قَرۡیَۃٍ وَّ ہِیَ خَاوِیَۃٌ عَلٰی عُرُوۡشِہَا» (2/259)\nTranslation: Or like the one who passed by a town, and it had fallen upon its roofs."
    },
    {
      "id": 2412,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«وَجَبَ» to fall with a thud and die, or to fall with a thud while dying (1 verse: 22:36)",
      "d": "«اَلْوَجَبَۃ» means for something to fall with a crash (Manjad), and then the concept of death is also included. They say «ضَرَبَہٗ فَوَجَبَ» meaning 'He struck it and it died' (M. Q.).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاذۡکُرُوا اسۡمَ اللّٰہِ عَلَیۡہَا صَوَآفَّ ۚ فَاِذَا وَجَبَتۡ جُنُوۡبُہَا فَکُلُوۡا مِنۡہَا وَ اَطۡعِمُوا الۡقَانِعَ وَ الۡمُعۡتَرَّ» (22/36)\nTranslation: So mention the name of Allah over them when they are lined up in rows. Then, when their sides fall to the ground, eat from them and feed the contented and the one who asks."
    },
    {
      "id": 2413,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«رَدِيَ ، رَدًي» to fall into a pit and perish (4 verses: 5:3, 20:16, 37:56, 92:11)",
      "d": "«رَدِيَ ، رَدًي» means to throw something down from a height into the ground or into a pit in such a way that it reaches the point of destruction (Maf. M. Q.).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اتَّبَعَ  ہَوٰىہُ  فَتَرۡدٰی» (20/16)\nTranslation: And he followed his own desire, so he will perish.\nAnd «اَرْدَی الرَّجُل» means to throw a man into a well. And «رَدَّی الرَّجُل» means to make a person fall, to destroy (M. Q.).\nFor example, the Lord says:\n«قَالَ تَاللّٰہِ   اِنۡ  کِدۡتَّ  لَتُرۡدِیۡنِ» (37/56)\nTranslation: He will say, 'By Allah, you almost ruined me.' (Jalandhri) You were about to throw me into the pit. (Usmani)\nAnd «تَرَدّٰی» means to fall into a well or pit (M. Q.), and «مُتَرَدِّیَۃ» refers to an animal that falls into a pit or well and dies (5/3).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَا یُغۡنِیۡ عَنۡہُ  مَا لُہٗۤ  اِذَا تَرَدّٰی» (92/11)\nTranslation: And when he falls into the pit of Hell, his wealth will not avail him at all."
    },
    {
      "id": 2414,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«صَرَعَ» to collapse or faint, as from illness or in a boat (1 verse: 69:7)",
      "d": "«صَرَعَ» means to fall to the ground due to agitation, restlessness, and lack of composure (F. L. 130), and also means to fall to the ground due to a head ailment (marghi) (Manjad). «صَرع» refers to a patient falling unconscious to the ground with a crash due to illness. «صَرَعَ» also means to throw one's opponent to the ground in a boat and pin them down (M. Q.).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی ۙ کَاَنَّہُمۡ  اَعۡجَازُ نَخۡلٍ خَاوِیَۃٍ» (69/7)\nTranslation: So you would see the people lying fallen therein as if they were hollow palm trunks."
    },
    {
      "id": 2415,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«تَلّ» to fall face down, i.e., on one's forehead (1 verse: 37:103)",
      "d": "«تَلّ» means to make someone fall on their face, i.e., on their forehead (F. L. 189).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ اَسۡلَمَا وَ تَلَّہٗ  لِلۡجَبِیۡنِ» (37/103)\nTranslation: Then when both had submitted and he (Ibrahim) laid him (Ismail) on his forehead."
    },
    {
      "id": 2416,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«تَعَسَ» to stumble and fall face down, unable to rise (1 verse: 47:8)",
      "d": "«تَعَسَ» means to stumble and fall, and then be unable to get up; to fall into lowliness and be broken (Maf), and also means to fall face down and perish (M. Q.). «تَعَسَ» also means to slip and fall face down. «اَلتَّعْسَۃ» means destruction and (Manjad).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا  فَتَعۡسًا لَّہُمۡ» (47/8)\nTranslation: And those who disbelieve - for them is destruction.\nThey will fall face down. (Usmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2417,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«اِدّٰرَک» to fall down exhausted and helpless (3 verses: 7:38, 10:90, 27:66)",
      "d": "«دَرْک» means for one thing to meet another from behind and then join with it (M. L.). «دَرْک» also refers to the depth of the sea and to the rope that is tied to another to reach the bottom of the water (Maf). Thus, to reach the extremity of something through a means is called «اَدْرَکَ». The Quran states regarding Pharaoh:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَاۤ  اَدۡرَکَہُ الۡغَرَقُ» (10/90) This means that Pharaoh's destination or end was drowning. So causes came together that led him to drowning. The same concept is found in «اِدّٰرَک».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«بَلِ ادّٰرَکَ عِلۡمُہُمۡ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ» (27/66)\nTranslation: Rather, their knowledge has come to an end regarding the Hereafter.\nIt is as if, after gathering all means of knowledge, they will fall down exhausted and helpless.\nAt another place, the Lord says:\n«کُلَّمَا دَخَلَتۡ اُمَّۃٌ  لَّعَنَتۡ اُخۡتَہَا ؕ حَتّٰۤی اِذَا ادَّارَکُوۡا فِیۡہَا جَمِیۡعًا» (7/38)\nTranslation: Every time a nation enters, it will curse its sister (nation) until, when they have all gathered there one after another.\nIt seems the end and extremity is reaching Hell. And the sequence and connection is one group after another entering and falling in."
    },
    {
      "id": 2418,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«اِنْھَمَرَ» to pour down or flow (of water) (1 verse: 54:11)",
      "d": "«ھَمَرَ الْمَاء» means it (water) poured and flowed. «اِنْھَمَرَ الْمَاء» means the water poured and flowed (M. Q.). It means the falling and flowing of water or tears.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَفَتَحۡنَاۤ  اَبۡوَابَ السَّمَآءِ  بِمَآءٍ  مُّنۡہَمِرٍ» (54/11)\nTranslation: So We opened the gates of the sky with water pouring forth."
    },
    {
      "id": 2420,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«سَکَبَ» water pouring continuously and flowing (1 verse: 56:31)",
      "d": "«سَکَبَ الْمَاء» means to pour and cause water to fall. «اَسْکَبَ» means continuous rain. «اَلْاَسْکُوْب» means continuous drizzle. «مَاءٍ مَّسْکُوۡبٍ» means «جَارٍ دَائِمًا» (water flowing continuously) (M. Q.). Thus, in «سَکَبَ», the falling of water etc. from above, flowing, and continuity or perpetuity are three aspects found.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ ظِلٍّ  مَّمۡدُوۡدٍ وَّ مَآءٍ  مَّسۡکُوۡبٍ» (56:30-31)\nTranslation: And extended shade and flowing water."
    }
  ],
  "525": [
    {
      "id": 2421,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to keep as collateral",
      "hw": "گروی",
      "s": "«رَھَنَ» to keep something as security for a loan (3 verses: 2:283, 52:21, 74:38)",
      "d": "«رَھَنَ» means for the borrower to keep something with the lender as security for a loan or debt. To keep as collateral. «رَھْن» means the thing kept as collateral. It is general, whether inanimate or animate. «رِھَانٌ» also refers to something kept as a stake in a contest or as security under a loan (Maf).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ عَلٰی سَفَرٍ وَّ لَمۡ تَجِدُوۡا کَاتِبًا فَرِہٰنٌ مَّقۡبُوۡضَۃٌ» (2/283)\nTranslation: And if you are on a journey and cannot find a scribe, then take a pledge (or collateral) in hand.\nJust as this word is used materially, it is also used spiritually.\nFor example, the Lord says:\n«کُلُّ نَفۡسٍۭ بِمَا کَسَبَتۡ رَہِیۡنَۃٌ» (74/38)\nTranslation: Every person is a hostage to what he has earned."
    },
    {
      "id": 2422,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to surrender to destruction",
      "hw": "گروی",
      "s": "«اَبْسَلَ» means to surrender oneself or a living being as captive or to destruction (slavery). (1 verse: 6:70)",
      "d": "«اَبْسَلَ» means to surrender someone to destruction. To hold as collateral (mansad). To keep as a slave. When the thing held as collateral is a living being, then «اَبْسَلَ» is used, whereas «رَھَنَ» is a general term meaning 'to give as security'. Example: «اَبْسَلَ نَفْسَہٗ لِلْمَوْت» (M. Q). For instance, in the Quran: «وَ ذَکِّرۡ بِہٖۤ  اَنۡ تُبۡسَلَ نَفۡسٌۢ بِمَا کَسَبَتۡ» (6/70). Translation: So remind by it that a soul may not be surrendered to destruction for what it has earned."
    }
  ],
  "526": [
    {
      "id": 2423,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Pit",
      "hw": "گڑھا",
      "s": "«حُفْرَۃ» means pit. Common term (1 verse: 3:103).",
      "d": "«حُفْرَۃ , حَفِیرَۃ» means pit. «حَفَرَ» means to dig a pit. And «حَفْر» means earth dug out from a pit, and «مِحْفَر» is the tool with which a pit is dug (pickaxe). For example, the proverb «مَرْدُوْدٌ فِیْ الْحَافِرَۃ» means 'he reached where the clay was.' For instance, in the Quran: «وَ کُنۡتُمۡ عَلٰی شَفَا حُفۡرَۃٍ مِّنَ النَّارِ فَاَنۡقَذَکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا» (3/103). Translation: And you were on the brink of a pit of fire, so He saved you from it."
    },
    {
      "id": 2424,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "trench",
      "hw": "گڑھا",
      "s": "«جُرُف» means the bank of a river or stream that has been hollowed out by water from within. (1 verse: 9:109)",
      "d": "«جُرُف» means the bank of a river or stream that has been hollowed out by water from within (mansad). A hollow (Punjabi word 'man' or 'mani'). This meaning is accurately conveyed by that word. For example, in the Quran: «اَمۡ مَّنۡ اَسَّسَ بُنۡیَانَہٗ عَلٰی شَفَا جُرُفٍ ہَارٍ» (9/109). Translation: Or who laid the foundations of his building on the edge of a collapsing trench?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2425,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "trench",
      "hw": "گڑھا",
      "s": "«اُخْدُوْد» means a trench, ditch, a long and deep pit dug by oneself. (1 verse: 85:4)",
      "d": "«اَلْخَدّ و اُخْدُوْد» means a long, deep, and rectangular (i.e., with corners) pit dug by oneself. Its plural is «اَخَادِیْد». «اَلْخَدّ» means a water channel. A long pit. And «اَلْخَدَّۃ وَ الْاُخْدُوْد» means pit (mansad). That is, «اُخْدُوْد» is a long, deep, rectangular pit that is self-dug. Trench. Ditch. For example, in the Quran: «قُتِلَ اَصۡحٰابُ الۡاُخۡدُوۡدِ» (85/4). Translation: The people of the trenches were killed. (Note: According to Mansad, the word 'akhdood' is singular, while Jalandhri translated it in plural form.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2426,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Pit",
      "hw": "گڑھا",
      "s": "«غَائِط» means low ground, metaphorically the place for relieving oneself (2 verses: 4:43, 5:6).",
      "d": "«غَوْط» means low ground, and «غَاطَ الْحُفْرَۃ» means to dig a pit deep. And «غَوَّطَ الْبِئْر» means to dig a well deep. And «اَلْغَائِط» means low ground, the place for relieving oneself (from Manjad), and this is a metaphor because a modest person seeks a deep place for urination. For example, in the Quran: «اَوۡ جَآءَ اَحَدٌ مِّنۡکُمۡ مِّنَ الۡغَآئِطِ» (4/43) (5/6). Translation: Or has any of you come from the place of relieving himself?"
    }
  ],
  "527": [
    {
      "id": 2427,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To pass",
      "hw": "گزرنا",
      "s": "«سَبَقَ» means to outstrip others by getting ahead (21 verses: 7:80, 8:59, 8:68, 10:19, 11:40, 11:110, 15:5, 20:99, 20:199, 21:27, 21:101, 23:27, 23:43, 29:4, 29:28, 37:171, 41:45, 42:14, 46:11, 59:10, 79:4).",
      "d": "«سَبَقَ» means to outstrip others by getting ahead. To go ahead (from Mufradat, Maqayees). So «سَبَقَ» necessarily implies having someone behind (i.e., one who is outdone). For example, in the Quran: «رَبَّنَا  اغۡفِرۡ لَنَا وَ لِاِخۡوَانِنَا  الَّذِیۡنَ سَبَقُوۡنَا بِالۡاِیۡمَانِ» (59/10). Translation: Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith. And when it comes in the sense of passing, it means 'to pass before.' That is, after that, many things have passed. For example, God's decree: «کَذٰلِکَ نَقُصُّ عَلَیۡکَ مِنۡ اَنۡۢبَآءِ مَا قَدۡ سَبَقَ» (20/99). Translation: Thus We relate to you some news of what has passed."
    },
    {
      "id": 2428,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To pass",
      "hw": "گزرنا",
      "s": "«خَلَا» means to become empty, to be separate from something else. To pass in a state where no resistance was made (15 verses: 2:134, 2:141, 3:137, 3:144, 5:75, 7:38, 13:6, 13:30, 15:13, 40:85, 41:25, 46:17, 46:18, 46:21, 48:23).",
      "d": "«خَلَا» means to become empty. To be separate from something else (from Mufradat, Lisan). It applies to both time and space (from Mufradat). And «خَلّٰی» means to empty. For example, in the Quran: «فَاِنۡ تَابُوۡا وَ اَقَامُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَ اٰتَوُا الزَّکٰوۃَ فَخَلُّوۡا سَبِیۡلَہُمۡ» (9/5). Translation: But if they repent, establish prayer, and give zakah, then leave their way free. That is, clear their path, move away from it, let them go, or do not resist. And «خَلَاء» means an empty place, and also the empty space between earth and sky. So «خَلَا» implies the passing of something along with the emptiness of place or time. For example, God's decree: «تِلۡکَ اُمَّۃٌ  قَدۡ خَلَتۡ ۚ لَہَا مَا کَسَبَتۡ» (2/141). Translation: That was a nation that has passed; it will have what it earned."
    },
    {
      "id": 2429,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To pass",
      "hw": "گزرنا",
      "s": "«سَلَفَ» when used in the sense of passing, it implies the concept of subsequent generations or similar events that come after (8 verses: 2:275, 4:22, 4:23, 5:95, 8:38, 10:30, 43:56, 69:24).",
      "d": "«سَلَفَ» means to go ahead. And «سَلَفَ الْقَوْم» means to outstrip the people (from Manjad). And «سَلْف» means precedent, i.e., one who has passed away (from Mufradat), and its opposite is «خَلْف». The plural is «اَسْلَاف», meaning passed away righteous ancestors. And «سَلَفِی» is a person who likes to be related to them. And «خَلْف» means unworthy successors who come after. So «سَلَفَ» when used in the sense of passing, it implies the concept of subsequent generations or similar events that come after. For example, in the Quran: «وَ اَنۡ تَجۡمَعُوۡا بَیۡنَ الۡاُخۡتَیۡنِ اِلَّا مَا قَدۡ سَلَفَ» (4/23). Translation: And that you should not take two sisters together in marriage, except what has already passed."
    },
    {
      "id": 2430,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To pass",
      "hw": "گزرنا",
      "s": "«مَرَّ» means to pass by something (9 verses: 2:259, 7:189, 10:12, 11:38, 12:105, 25:72, 27:88, 37:137, 83:30).",
      "d": "«مَرَّ» means to pass by something (from Mufradat). For example, in the Quran: «اَوۡ کَالَّذِیۡ مَرَّ عَلٰی قَرۡیَۃٍ» (2/259). Translation: Or like the one who passed by a town. And «اِسْتَمَرَّ» means to continue passing, to remain in a state or manner, to persist (from Manjad). And «مَرُوْر اَیَّام» means the passing of days. And «مَرَّ» is also used in the Quran in the sense of «اِسْتَمَرَّ». For example, God's decree: «حَمَلَتۡ حَمۡلًا خَفِیۡفًا فَمَرَّتۡ بِہٖ» (7/189). Translation: So she carried him lightly and continued with him. In another place, God's decree: «وَ اِنۡ یَّرَوۡا اٰیَۃً  یُّعۡرِضُوۡا وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡا سِحۡرٌ مُّسۡتَمِرٌّ» (54/2). Translation: And when they see a sign, they turn away and say, 'This is continuous magic.' Similarly, in another place: «یَمُرُّوۡنَ عَلَیۡہَا» (12/105). Translation: They pass by it continually. So «مَرَّ» implies continuity along with passing."
    },
    {
      "id": 2431,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To pass",
      "hw": "گزرنا",
      "s": "«مَضٰی» means that in a past time, something reached its completion (5 verses: 8:38, 15:65, 18:60, 36:67, 43:8).",
      "d": "«مَضٰی» means to pass and go away (from Mufradat). And its opposite is «اِسْتَقْبَلَ», i.e., to come from the front. And «مَضٰی» means to come from the front and pass (from Fiqh, 252). And 'mazi' means past time, and its opposite is 'mustaqbal', i.e., future time. It is used for both events (i.e., something new) or an incident (from Mufradat). And «مَضٰی عَلَی الْاَمْر» means to persist in something (from Manjad). For example, in the Quran: «وَ اِنۡ یَّعُوۡدُوۡا فَقَدۡ مَضَتۡ سُنَّتُ  الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (8/38). Translation: And if they return, then the way of the former people has passed. In another place, God's decree: «حَتّٰۤی اَبۡلُغَ  مَجۡمَعَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ اَوۡ اَمۡضِیَ حُقُبًا» (18/60). Translation: Until I reach the confluence of the two seas or I continue for ages."
    },
    {
      "id": 2432,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To pass",
      "hw": "گزرنا",
      "s": "«اِنْسَلَخَ» means the passing of a lunar month (2 verses: 7:175, 9:5).",
      "d": "«سَلَخَ» means to peel off a skin. And «سَلَخَ» and «اِنْسَلَخَ الشَّھْر» mean that a lunar month has reached its end (from Mufradat). For example, in the Quran: «فَاِذَا انۡسَلَخَ الۡاَشۡہُرُ الۡحُرُمُ» (9/5). Translation: Then when the sacred months have passed."
    }
  ],
  "528": [
    {
      "id": 2433,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Throat",
      "hw": "گلا",
      "s": "«حُلْقُوْم» meaning throat; the place from which an animal is slaughtered (1 verse: 56:83)",
      "d": "«حُلْقُوْم» meaning throat. The place from which an animal is slaughtered. It is a well-known organ; there is no difference in the meanings of «حُلْقُوْم» and «حَلَق». For example, in the Quran: «فَلَوۡ لَاۤ اِذَا بَلَغَتِ الۡحُلۡقُوۡمَ» (56/83) Translation: Then why is it not that when (someone's) soul reaches the throat?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2434,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "throat",
      "hw": "گلا",
      "s": "«حَنَاجِر» means windpipe. Larynx. And «حَنْجَرَہ» refers to the parts related to the food pipe in the throat, in medical terms pharynx, and the part related to the windpipe is larynx. (2 verses: 33:10, 40:18)",
      "d": "«حَنَاجِر» is plural of «حَنْجَرَہ», meaning windpipe. Larynx (mansad). For example, in the Quran: «وَ بَلَغَتِ الۡقُلُوۡبُ الۡحَنَاجِرَ وَ تَظُنُّوۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ  الظُّنُوۡنَا» (33/10). Translation: And the hearts reached the throats, and you used to think about Allah all sorts of conjectures."
    }
  ],
  "529": [
    {
      "id": 2435,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To be lost; not to get",
      "hw": "گم",
      "s": "«فَاتَ» meaning to slip away from an opportunity; to lose hope of obtaining something (3 verses: 3:153, 57:23, 60:11)",
      "d": "«فَاتَ» means for something to slip from one's hand. «فَاتَ الْاَمْر» means the time for doing something slipped away and could not return. For example, in the Quran: «لِّکَیۡلَا تَاۡسَوۡا عَلٰی مَا فَاتَکُمۡ وَ لَا تَفۡرَحُوۡا بِمَاۤ اٰتٰىکُمۡ» (57/23) Translation: So that you do not grieve over what has escaped you, nor exult over what He has given you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2436,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To be lost; not to get",
      "hw": "گم",
      "s": "«فَقَدَ» meaning for something to be temporarily absent, i.e., not found when needed (2 verses: 12:71, 12:72)",
      "d": "«فَقَدَ» means for something to be temporarily absent; not present. Whether it is found later or not. And it means the absence of something despite its existence. It is more specific than «عَدَم». For example, in the Quran: «قَالُوۡا وَ اَقۡبَلُوۡا عَلَیۡہِمۡ مَّا ذَا تَفۡقِدُوۡنَ» (12/71) Translation: They turned towards them and said, 'What is it that you are missing?' And «تَفَقَّدَ» means to check if something is lost. In Imam Raghib's words, to know that something is lost; to search for a lost thing. For example: «وَ تَفَقَّدَ الطَّیۡرَ فَقَالَ مَا لِیَ لَاۤ اَرَی الۡہُدۡہُدَ» (27/20) Translation: And he took a census of the birds and said, 'Why is it that I do not see the hoopoe?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2437,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To be lost; not to get",
      "hw": "گم",
      "s": "«ضَلَّ» basic meaning is to lose the way or to cause to lose the way (163 verses: 1:7-2:16-2:26-2:108-2:175-2:198-2:282-3:69-3:90-3:164-4:44-4:60-4:88-4:113-4:116-4:119-4:136-4:143-4:167-4:176-5:12-5:60-5:77-5:105-6:24-6:39-6:56-6:74-6:77-6:94-6:116-6:117-6:119-6:125-6:140-6:144-7:30-7:37-7:38-7:53-7:60-7:61-7:149-7:155-7:178-7:179-7:186-9:37-9:115-10:30-10:32-10:88-10:108-11:21-12:8-12:30-12:95-13:14-13:27-13:33-14:3-14:18-14:27-14:30-14:36-15:56-16:25-16:36-16:37-16:87-16:93-16:125-17:15-17:67-17:72-17:97-18:17-18:51-18:104-19:38-19:75-20:52-20:79-20:85-20:92-20:123-21:54-22:4-22:9-22:12-23:106-25:17-25:29-25:34-25:42-25:44-26:20-26:86-26:97-26:99-27:81-27:92-28:15-28:50-28:75-28:85-30:29-30:53-31:6-31:11-32:10-33:36-33:67-34:8-34:24-34:50-35:8-36:24-36:47-36:62-37:69-37:71-38:26-39:8-39:22-39:23-39:36-39:37-39:41-40:25-40:33-40:34-40:50-40:74-41:29-41:48-41:52-42:18-42:44-42:46-43:40-45:23-46:5-46:28-46:32-50:27-53:2-53:30-54:24-54:47-56:51-56:92-60:1-62:2-67:9-67:29-68:7-68:26-71:24-71:27-74:31-83:32-93:7)",
      "d": "«ضَلَّ» originally means to lose the way or to cause to lose the way. But sometimes it is used for something to lose itself and join another thing. For example, in the Quran: «وَ قَالُوۡۤا ءَ اِذَا ضَلَلۡنَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ ءَ اِنَّا لَفِیۡ خَلۡقٍ جَدِیۡدٍ» (32/10) Translation: And they say, 'When we are lost in the earth, will we indeed be in a new creation?'"
    }
  ],
  "530": [
    {
      "id": 2438,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To assume; to think",
      "hw": "گمان",
      "s": "«ظَنَّ» has a very wide scope. It applies to all kinds of thoughts and assumptions: suspicion, conjecture, probability, and certainty (58 verses: 2:46-2:78-2:230-2:249-3:154-4:157-6:116-6:148-7:66-7:171-9:118-10:22-10:24-10:36-10:60-10:66-11:27-12:42-12:110-17:52-17:101-17:102-18:35-18:35-18:36-18:53-21:87-22:15-24:12-26:186-28:38-28:39-33:10-34:20-37:87-38:24-38:27-40:37-41:22-41:23-41:48-41:50-45:24-45:32-48:6-48:12-49:12-53:23-53:28-59:2-69:20-72:5-72:7-72:12-75:25-75:28-83:4-84:14)",
      "d": "«ظَنَّ» is what one concludes from signs. If the signs are strong, «ظَنّ» means knowledge and certainty. In this case, «اَنَّ» or «اَنْ» precedes it. Examples: (1) «الَّذِیۡنَ یَظُنُّوۡنَ اَنَّہُمۡ مُّلٰقُوۡا رَبِّہِمۡ» (2/46) Translation: Those who are certain that they will meet their Lord. (2) «وَّ ظَنَّ اَنَّہُ الۡفِرَاقُ» (75/28) Translation: And the dying person is certain that it is the time of separation. (3) «بَلۡ ظَنَنۡتُمۡ اَنۡ لَّنۡ یَّنۡقَلِبَ الرَّسُوۡلُ» (48/12) Translation: But you assumed that the Messenger would never return. When «ظَنّ» means mere suspicion and doubt, «اِنّ» or «اِنْ» precedes it. Another sign is that opposite to «ظَنّ», a word is present as a sign that makes «ظَنّ» mean suspicion and doubt. Examples: (1) «اِنَّ الظَّنَّ لَا یُغۡنِیۡ مِنَ الۡحَقِّ شَیۡئًا» (53/28) Translation: Indeed, assumption does not avail anything against the truth. (2) «اِنۡ نَّظُنُّ اِلَّا ظَنًّا وَّ مَا نَحۡنُ بِمُسۡتَیۡقِنِیۡنَ» (45/32) Translation: We only assume; we are not certain. (3) «الظَّآنِّیۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ ظَنَّ السَّوۡءِ» (48/6) Translation: Those who assume about Allah the worst assumption. Between doubt and certainty, there are degrees of suspicion and probability. And «ظَنّ» is used in all these meanings."
    },
    {
      "id": 2439,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To assume; to think",
      "hw": "گمان",
      "s": "«زَعَمَ» is used for false conjecture (i.e., false assumption and thought) (14 verses: 4:60-6:22-6:94-6:136-6:138-17:56-17:92-18:48-18:52-28:62-28:74-34:22-62:6-64:7)",
      "d": "«زَعَمَ» is used for false conjecture (i.e., false assumption and thought). In Ibn al-Faris's words, 'a statement without truth or certainty'. Wherever this word is used in the Quran, it is only to condemn the one who assumes. For example: «زَعَمَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡۤا اَنۡ لَّنۡ یُّبۡعَثُوۡا» (64/7) Translation: Those who disbelieve assume that they will never be resurrected."
    },
    {
      "id": 2440,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To assume; to think",
      "hw": "گمان",
      "s": "«حَسِبَ» is used for such an assumption where the assumer is hopeful (43 verses: 2:214-2:273-3:78-3:142-3:169-3:178-3:180-3:188-5:71-7:30-8:59-9:16-14:42-14:47-18:9-18:18-18:102-18:104-23:55-23:115-24:11-24:15-24:39-24:57-25:44-27:44-27:88-29:2-29:4-33:20-43:37-43:80-45:21-47:29-58:18-59:14-63:4-75:3-75:36-76:19-90:5-90:7-104:3)",
      "d": "«حَسَب» means to calculate, count. «حَسُبَ» means to be honorable. And «حَسِبَ» means to assume or think. And this word is used for such an assumption where the assumer has hope in his heart, even if he does not give it the rank of certainty. Probable assumption. For example: «اَمۡ حَسِبۡتُمۡ اَنۡ تَدۡخُلُوا الۡجَنَّۃَ وَ لَمَّا یَاۡتِکُمۡ مَّثَلُ الَّذِیۡنَ خَلَوۡا مِنۡ قَبۡلِکُمۡ» (2/214) Translation: Or do you think that you will enter Paradise while such trials as came to those before you have not yet come to you?"
    }
  ],
  "531": [
    {
      "id": 2441,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sin",
      "hw": "گناہ",
      "s": "«ذَنْب» is general; used for every small and big sin (11 verses: 12:29-26:14-29:40-40:3-40:55-47:19-48:2-55:39-67:11-81:9-91:14)",
      "d": "«ذَنْب» means every action whose outcome is bad. And it means 'what follows blame'. Its application is so general that it can be used for minor slips to major sins. Its plural is «ذُنُوب». For example, in the Quran: «اِنَّا فَتَحۡنَا لَکَ فَتۡحًا مُّبِیۡنًا لِّیَغۡفِرَ لَکَ اللّٰہُ مَا تَقَدَّمَ مِنۡ ذَنۡۢبِکَ وَ مَا تَاَخَّرَ» (48/1-2) Translation: Indeed, We have given you a clear conquest so that Allah may forgive you your past and future sins. And obviously, these sins can only be the Prophet's (ﷺ) erroneous judgments, otherwise no Muslim can even conceive of the Prophet (ﷺ) committing any sin intentionally. As in another verse: «عَفَا اللّٰہُ عَنۡکَ ۚ لِمَ اَذِنۡتَ لَہِمۡ» (9/43) Translation: May Allah forgive you! Why did you grant them permission? And the greatest sin is unjust killing, and the word «ذَنْب» is also used for that. For example: «وَ لَہُمۡ عَلَیَّ ذَنۡۢبٌ فَاَخَافُ اَنۡ یَّقۡتُلُوۡنِ» (26/14) Translation: And they have a sin against me, so I fear they will kill me."
    },
    {
      "id": 2442,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sin",
      "hw": "گناہ",
      "s": "«خَطَا» is a sin that occurs unintentionally (13 verses: 2:58-2:81-2:286-4:92-4:112-7:161-17:31-20:73-26:51-26:82-29:12-33:5-71:25)",
      "d": "«خَطَا» is a sin that a person does not intend but happens by accident or error. For example, a hunter aimed at an animal but the arrow hit a person by mistake, causing death. If such an error is punishable, the punishment is reduced, and it is called «خِطْأ» or «خَطْأ». If of another type, Allah forgives and rewards with good deeds, and it is called «خَطَاء». Its plural is «خَطَایَا». «خَطِیْءَ»'s plural is «خَطِیْئَات». It is also used in the same sense. For example, in the Quran: «وَ مَنۡ قَتَلَ مُؤۡمِنًا خَطَئًا فَتَحۡرِیۡرُ رَقَبَۃٍ مُّؤۡمِنَۃٍ وَّ دِیَۃٌ مُّسَلَّمَۃٌ اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہٖۤ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ یَّصَّدَّقُوۡا» (4/92) Translation: And whoever kills a believer by error should free a believing slave and pay blood money to his family unless they remit it as charity. Another verse: «وَّ ادۡخُلُوا الۡبَابَ سُجَّدًا وَّ قُوۡلُوۡا حِطَّۃٌ نَّغۡفِرۡ لَکُمۡ خَطٰیٰکُمۡ» (2/58) Translation: And enter the gate prostrating and say, 'Relieve us of our burdens' (or 'A burden removed'), We will forgive your sins."
    },
    {
      "id": 2443,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sin",
      "hw": "گناہ",
      "s": "«حُوْب» a major sin related to family affairs (1 verse: 4:2)",
      "d": "«اَلْحُوْبَۃ» refers to mother, father, sister, daughter. «اِنَّ لِیْ حُوْبَۃٌ اَعْوَلُھَا» means 'I have young children whom I support' (Manjad). And «حَوْب» means disobedience to parents or parents' negligence in compassion and upbringing of children (M. L.). According to Imam Raghib, committing acts from which one is strictly forbidden is called «حُوْب» (Maf). The basic meaning of «حُوْب» is 'reprimand'. And «حُوْب» is any sin for which the perpetrator deserves reprimand and admonition (Faqih 193).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ لَا تَاۡکُلُوۡۤا اَمۡوَالَہُمۡ  اِلٰۤی اَمۡوَالِکُمۡ ؕ اِنَّہٗ کَانَ حُوۡبًا کَبِیۡرًا» (4/2)\nTranslation: And do not consume the orphans' wealth by mixing it with your own wealth, for indeed, that is a great sin."
    },
    {
      "id": 2444,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sin",
      "hw": "گناہ",
      "s": "«حِنْث» meaning breaking an oath; a major sin related to covenants and pledges (2 verses: 38:44-56:46)",
      "d": "«حِنْث» means false and lying oath; sin and disobedience (Maf). And «حَنَثَ فِی الْیَمِیْن» means to violate an oath (M. L.). And «حَنِثَ» means to incline towards falsehood; to be biased (Manjad). Thus, «حِنْث» refers to a sin related to breaking a covenant, pledge, or oath.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ کَانُوۡا یُصِرُّوۡنَ عَلَی الۡحِنۡثِ الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (56/46)\nTranslation: And they used to persist in the great sin."
    },
    {
      "id": 2445,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sin",
      "hw": "گناہ",
      "s": "«اِثْم» predisposition of the heart towards sin and not refraining from committing it when the opportunity arises (3 verses: 2:283-5:106-76:24)",
      "d": "«اِثْم» means every action that is delayed or prevented from being a act of goodness or reward (Maf M. L.). Its plural is «اٰثَام». Its opposite is «بِرّ» meaning goodness. Also, the lexical meaning of «اِثْم» is 'negligence' (i.e., fault and error) (Faqih 193).\nFor example: The Prophetic ﷺ Hadith says: «اَلْبِرُّ مَا اطْمَاَنَّتْ اِلَیْہِ النَّفْسُ وَ الْاِثْمُ مَا حَاکَ فِیْ صَدْرِکَ»\nTranslation: That is, goodness is that which the heart finds peace in, and «اِثْم» (sin) is that which causes doubt in your chest.\nThus, «اِثْم» is the name of a state where a person's heart turns away from good deeds and inclines towards sinful deeds, and when the opportunity arises, he does not refrain from that sin. That is, «اِثْم» is more related to the heart than the action. And a person with this quality is called «اَثِیْم», whose opposite is «سَلِیْم».\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«تَعَاوَنُوۡا عَلَی الۡبِرِّ وَ التَّقۡوٰی ۪ وَ لَا تَعَاوَنُوۡا عَلَی الۡاِثۡمِ وَ الۡعُدۡوَانِ» (5/2)\nTranslation: Cooperate in righteousness and piety, but do not cooperate in sin and aggression.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«وَ لَا تَکۡتُمُوا الشَّہَادَۃَ ؕ وَ مَنۡ یَّکۡتُمُہَا فَاِنَّہٗۤ اٰثِمٌ قَلۡبُہُ» (2/283)\nTranslation: And do not conceal testimony. And whoever conceals it, then indeed, his heart is sinful."
    },
    {
      "id": 2446,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sin",
      "hw": "گناہ",
      "s": "«اِجْرَام» meaning the consequence or penalty of a major sin (1 verse: 11:35)",
      "d": "«جُرْم» is considered only that act for which a punishment is prescribed by law. But this is not correct according to the Quran nor according to lexicon. «جُرْم ۔ جَرِیْمَۃ» means to be guilty of a major sin. And «اَجْرَمَ» means to be a criminal, to commit a crime. And «اِجْرَام» means the consequence of sin (Manjad). The basic meaning of «جُرْم» is 'cutting off'. And «جُرْم» is every act by which one fails to fulfill an obligatory command or neglects to pay an obligatory due (Faqih 93).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«قُلۡ  اِنِ افۡتَرَیۡتُہٗ فَعَلَیَّ  اِجۡرَامِیۡ وَ اَنَا بَرِیۡٓءٌ  مِّمَّا تُجۡرِمُوۡنَ» (11/35)\nTranslation: (O Prophet) say: If I have invented it, then its penalty is upon me, and I am free from what you commit."
    },
    {
      "id": 2447,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sin",
      "hw": "گناہ",
      "s": "«جُنَاح» its meaning is actually not sin itself, but inclination or leaning towards sin (24 verses: 2:158-2:198-2:229-2:230-2:233-2:234-2:235-2:236-2:240-2:282-4:23-4:24-4:101-4:102-4:128-5:93-24:29-24:58-24:60-24:61-33:5-33:51-33:55-60:10)",
      "d": "«جُنَاح» its meaning is actually not sin itself, but inclination or leaning towards sin. «جَنَحَ» means to incline; to be biased (Manjad). It appears frequently in the Quran, «لَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیْکُمْ ،» or «لَیْسَ عَلَیْکُمْ جُنَاحٌ» meaning there is no harm, no blameworthy matter, etc.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«لَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ  اِنۡ طَلَّقۡتُمُ النِّسَآءَ مَا لَمۡ تَمَسُّوۡہُنَّ» (2/236)\nTranslation: There is no blame upon you if you divorce women whom you have not touched.\nAnd «جَنَاح» (meaning side, wing, flank) is used for inclination towards goodness.\nFor example: The Almighty says:\n«وَ اخۡفِضۡ لَہُمَا جَنَاحَ الذُّلِّ مِنَ الرَّحۡمَۃِ» (17/24)\nTranslation: And lower for them the wing of humility out of mercy.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«وَ اخۡفِضۡ جَنَاحَکَ لِمَنِ اتَّبَعَکَ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ» (26/215)\nTranslation: And lower your wing humbly for the believers who follow you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2448,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sin",
      "hw": "گناہ",
      "s": "«لَمَمْ» minor sins that lead one towards a major sin (1 verse: 53:32)",
      "d": "«لَمَمْ» means small sins that lead towards a major sin and those that assist in that act. And «اَلَمَّ» means to commit minor sins (Manjad). For example, approaching a non-mahram woman before adultery, or free conversation with her, or consulting about theft before committing it—all these are included in the definition of «لَمَمْ».\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ یَجۡتَنِبُوۡنَ کَبٰٓئِرَ الۡاِثۡمِ وَ الۡفَوَاحِشَ  اِلَّا اللَّمَمَ ؕ اِنَّ  رَبَّکَ وَاسِعُ  الۡمَغۡفِرَۃِ» (53/32)\nTranslation: Those who avoid major sins and immoralities, except for minor slips—indeed, your Lord is vast in forgiveness."
    }
  ],
  "532": [
    {
      "id": 2450,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sinner",
      "hw": "گنہگار",
      "s": "«فَاسِق» a disobedient or sinner who considers sin to be sin (37 verses: 2:26-2:99-3:82-3:110-5:25-5:26-5:47-5:49-5:59-5:81-5:108-7:102-7:145-9:8-9:24-9:53-9:67-9:80-9:84-9:96-21:74-24:4-24:55-27:12-28:32-32:18-43:54-46:35-49:6-51:46-57:16-57:26-57:27-59:5-59:19-61:5-63:6)",
      "d": "«فَسَقَ» means to deviate from the path of truth and reform; to become wicked; to step out of obedience (M. L.). Not to consider religious commands (Maf). «فَاسِقٌ» is a term used for a habitual disobedient person; wicked. However, such a person must consider sinful acts as sin and disobedience.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا  الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا  اِنۡ جَآءَکُمۡ فَاسِقٌۢ بِنَبَاٍ فَتَبَیَّنُوۡۤا» (49/6)\nTranslation: O you who have believed! If a wicked person brings you news, verify it."
    },
    {
      "id": 2451,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sinner",
      "hw": "گنہگار",
      "s": "«فَاجِرْ» a sinner and wicked person who has become hardened and does not even consider sin as sin (4 verses: 38:28-71:27-82:14-83:7)",
      "d": "«فَاجِرْ» its plural is «فُجَّار» and its opposite is «اَبْرَار». «فَجَرَ» means to widely tear something. And «فَاجِر» means one who violates religion and commits disobedience; wicked. A sinner who continues to sin and does not repent (Maf). And «فَجَر» means to commit evil acts; to become hardened. And a «فَاجِر» is a sinner who does not even consider sin as sin; a depraved person.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«کَلَّاۤ  اِنَّ  کِتٰبَ الۡفُجَّارِ لَفِیۡ  سِجِّیۡنٍ» (83/7)\nTranslation: No! Indeed, the record of the wicked is in Sijjin."
    }
  ],
  "533": [
    {
      "id": 2452,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Impurity / Filth",
      "hw": "گندگی",
      "s": "«تَفَث» bodily dirt and filth (1 verse: 22:29)",
      "d": "«تَفِثَ» means dirt and filth clinging to something. And «قَضٰی تَفِثَ» means to remove such dirt and filth (Manjad). Abu 'Ubaidah says it refers to cutting nails, trimming mustaches, applying perfume. And it is used for all things forbidden on a Muhrim except marriage (M. L.), meaning bodily cleanliness which includes cutting nails, shaving excess hair, bathing to remove dirt, and then wearing clean clothes and applying perfume, etc., all are included in «قَضٰی تَفِثَ».\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«ثُمَّ لۡیَقۡضُوۡا تَفَثَہُمۡ وَ لۡیُوۡفُوۡا نُذُوۡرَہُمۡ وَ لۡیَطَّوَّفُوۡا بِالۡبَیۡتِ الۡعَتِیۡقِ» (22/29)\nTranslation: Then let them complete their cleanliness, fulfill their vows, and circumambulate the Ancient House."
    },
    {
      "id": 2453,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Impurity / Filth",
      "hw": "گندگی",
      "s": "«رِجْز» satanic whispers that cause disturbance (2 verses: 8:11-74:5)",
      "d": "«رَجَزَ» means to cause disturbance (uneasiness). And «رَجَزَ فُلَانٌ» means he recited poetry in the meter of Rajaz. And Rajaz poetry is that which is recited to encourage during battle. And in «عَذَابٌ مِّنْ رِجْزٍ اَلِیْم», 'Rajz' means that which causes disturbance (uneasiness). And «رِجْز» refers to those satanic whispers that continuously cause disturbance (uneasiness) and evil desires in the heart (Maf. Manjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِذۡ یُغَشِّیۡکُمُ النُّعَاسَ اَمَنَۃً مِّنۡہُ وَ یُنَزِّلُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً  لِّیُطَہِّرَکُمۡ بِہٖ وَ یُذۡہِبَ عَنۡکُمۡ رِجۡزَ الشَّیۡطٰنِ» (8/11)\nTranslation: When He overwhelmed you with drowsiness [giving] security from Him and sent down upon you from the sky rain by which to purify you and remove from you the impurity of Satan.\nHere «رِجۡزَ الشَّیۡطٰنِ» refers to those satanic whispers that could arise in hearts after the defeat at Badr.\n«رُجْز : رِجْز» are essentially the same word (Manjad). And it has the same relationship as «حَمْل» and «حِمْل» or «وَقْر» and «وِقْر» (see details under 'Burden'). And this word is used for all such satanic whispers present in the heart, whether related to worship of other than Allah or evil thoughts.\nFor example: The Almighty says:\n«وَ  ثِیَابَکَ فَطَہِّرۡ وَ الرُّجۡزَ  فَاہۡجُرۡ» (74/4,5)\nTranslation: And your clothing, purify it, and from impurity, keep away."
    },
    {
      "id": 2454,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Impurity. Filth",
      "hw": "گندگی",
      "s": "«رِجْس» The impurity of things that are haram and filthy (9 verses: 5:90-6:125-6:145-7:71-9:95-9:125-10:100-22:30-33:33)",
      "d": "«رِجْس» refers to the impurity of things that the Shariah has declared impure (napaak) or haram (manjid). It is used in both material and spiritual senses.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یَّکُوۡنَ مَیۡتَۃً اَوۡ دَمًا مَّسۡفُوۡحًا اَوۡ لَحۡمَ  خِنۡزِیۡرٍ فَاِنَّہٗ رِجۡسٌ» ( 6/145 )\nTranslation: Except that it be a dead animal, or flowing blood, or the flesh of swine, for indeed, it is impure.\nAt another place, the command of Allah the Most High states:\n«وَ اَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ مَّرَضٌ فَزَادَتۡہُمۡ رِجۡسًا اِلٰی رِجۡسِہِمۡ» ( 9/125 )\nTranslation: And as for those in whose hearts is disease, it has added filth upon their filth.\nHere, «رِجْس» refers to the impurity of disbelief and polytheism. And this is the spiritual usage of «رِجْس». (Also see 'Napaak')"
    }
  ],
  "534": [
    {
      "id": 2456,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To Count",
      "hw": "گننا",
      "s": "«حَسَبَ» To count and maintain order and discipline in it so that there is no error (2 verses: 6:96-55:5)",
      "d": "«یَحْسَبُ ، حَسَابًا ، وَ حُسْبَانًا» means to count and keep an account of it. To maintain order and discipline in counting. (M L) So that there is no discrepancy in the account.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ جَعَلَ الَّیۡلَ سَکَنًا وَّ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ حُسۡبَانًا» ( 6/96 )\nTranslation: He has made the night a place of rest and the sun and moon a means of reckoning."
    },
    {
      "id": 2457,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To Count",
      "hw": "گننا",
      "s": "«اَحْصٰی» meaning to count and to have power over it. To record. To remember (11 verses: 14:34-16:18-18:12-18:49-19:94-36:12-58:6-65:1-72:28-73:20-78:29)",
      "d": "«حَصٰی» means pebbles, and «حَصٰی یَحْصِی» means to throw pebbles. The Arabs, generally not being accountants, used to count with pebbles. Hence, this word began to be used in meanings of counting. In «حَصٰی», two aspects are found: (1) to count, and (2) to have power over it or keep a record of it. To remember it (M. L). And it is more specific than «عَدَّ».\nFor example: The command of Allah the Most High states:\n«اِنۡ تَعُدُّوۡا نِعۡمَتَ اللّٰہِ لَا تُحۡصُوۡہَا» ( 14/34 )\nTranslation: If you should count the favors of Allah, you would not be able to enumerate them.\nAnd sometimes this word also comes for having power over the account.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«عَلِمَ  اَنۡ  لَّنۡ تُحۡصُوۡہُ فَتَابَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ» ( 73/20 )\nTranslation: He knew that you would not be able to do it, so He turned to you in mercy."
    }
  ],
  "535": [
    {
      "id": 2458,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Lap",
      "hw": "گود",
      "s": "«مَھْد» The mother's lap for a breastfeeding child (7 verses: 3:46-5:110-19:29-20:53-30:44-43:10-74:14)",
      "d": "«مَھْد» means cradle. A child's swing. And it means the mother's lap for a breastfeeding child. As long as he is breastfeeding. For the mother's lap is also a cradle for him. And the concept of upbringing or means of upbringing is also found in this word. (See 'Bachhona')\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یُکَلِّمُ النَّاسَ فِی الۡمَہۡدِ وَ کَہۡلًا» ( 3/46 )\nTranslation: He will speak to people in the cradle and in maturity, and he will be a righteous one."
    },
    {
      "id": 2459,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Lap",
      "hw": "گود",
      "s": "«حُجُور» Lap for older children. It refers to a guardian who can impose restrictions on the property and authority of a child under his care (1 verse: 4:23)",
      "d": "«حُجُور» is the plural of «حِجْر». And «حِجْر» means lap. It is said «فُلَانٌ فِیْ حِجْرِ فُلَانٍ» meaning so-and-so was raised and brought up in the lap or care of so-and-so (Manjid). And «فُلَانٌ فِیْ حِجْرِ فُلَانٍ» means that so-and-so is under the supervision of so-and-so. That is, from his side, there is restriction on his property and authorities (Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ رَبَآئِبُکُمُ الّٰتِیۡ فِیۡ  حُجُوۡرِکُمۡ» ( 4/23 )\nTranslation: And your step-daughters who are under your care (i.e., raised by you)."
    }
  ],
  "536": [
    {
      "id": 2461,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Deep. Depth",
      "hw": "گہرائی",
      "s": "«غَوْر» Subterranean depth. Depth from the earth's surface. Low-lying land (2 verses: 18:41-67:30)",
      "d": "«غَارَ» means to go down towards low-lying land. Ghār (cave) is a famous word meaning cave. And «غَوْر» means low-lying land. And it means subterranean depth (Muf). So to speak, the concept of a dwelling with depth is also found in it.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قُلۡ  اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ  اِنۡ  اَصۡبَحَ مَآؤُکُمۡ غَوۡرًا فَمَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡکُمۡ بِمَآءٍ مَّعِیۡنٍ» ( 67/30 )\nTranslation: Say, [O Muhammad], 'Have you considered: if your water were to become sunken [into the earth], then who could bring you [any] flowing water?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2462,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Deep. Depth",
      "hw": "گہرائی",
      "s": "«عَمِیْق» meaning deep. In a general sense (1 verse: 22:27)",
      "d": "«عُمْق» means the depth of anything and its opposite is «اِرْتِفَاع» meaning height. If the distance is in the horizontal (i.e., towards the edge) direction, then it is length or distance. And if it is straight and upwards from the ground, then it is height or «اِرْتِفَاع». And if it is downwards from the ground or if one is standing above, then that same height is «عُمْق» or depth. And «عَمِیْق» means deep.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیۡقٍ» ( 22/27 )\nTranslation: They will come to you from every distant pass.\nSo here, the meaning of 'deep' is due to its relation to the distant «فَجّ». «فَجّ» is the path between two mountains which passes through valleys and hills."
    }
  ],
  "537": [
    {
      "id": 2463,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Watering Place",
      "hw": "گھاٹ",
      "s": "«مَشْرَب» A place for drinking and filling water. Watering place (2 verses: 2:60-7:160)",
      "d": "«مَشْرَب» A place for drinking and filling water. Watering place. This word is general.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَدۡ عَلِمَ کُلُّ اُنَاسٍ مَّشۡرَبَہُمۡ» ( 2/60 )\nTranslation: All the people had come to know their (respective) watering places."
    },
    {
      "id": 2464,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Watering Place",
      "hw": "گھاٹ",
      "s": "«وِرْد» meaning a place to drink water. (4 verses: 11:98-19:86-21:99-28:23)",
      "d": "«وَرَدَ» means to reach the place of water for drinking. And its opposite is «صَدَر», meaning to return from there after drinking water. And «وِرْد» is that water which is prepared for travelers (Muf). Just as we prepare water tanks etc. for giving water to livestock, and «وِرْد» also refers to a thirsty person (19/86).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَقۡدُمُ  قَوۡمَہٗ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ فَاَوۡرَدَہُمُ النَّارَ ؕ وَ بِئۡسَ الۡوِرۡدُ  الۡمَوۡرُوۡدُ» ( 11/98 )\nTranslation: He will precede his people on the Day of Resurrection and will lead them into the Fire. And evil is the watering place to which they will be led."
    }
  ],
  "538": [
    {
      "id": 2465,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Valley",
      "hw": "گھاٹی",
      "s": "«نَجَد» A general word for valley (1 verse: 90:10)",
      "d": "«نَجَد» means valley. Elevated land. Land empty of trees. Elevated path. (Manjid) And «نَجَدَ» means to be clear and elevated (Manjid) and also means elevated and hard land (Muf). «نَجَد» originally means both a valley and the path that ascends or descends from it (Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ ہَدَیۡنٰہُ  النَّجۡدَیۡنِ» ( 90/10 )\nTranslation: And We have shown him the two highways (Jalandhari).\nWe showed him two valleys (Osmani)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2466,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Pass",
      "hw": "گھاٹی",
      "s": "«عَقَبَۃ» refers only to a pass that is difficult to traverse (2 verses: 90:11-90:12)",
      "d": "«عَقَبَۃ» means a difficult path for climbing a mountain (figurative). That is, «عَقَبَۃ» refers specifically to a path that is a pass or a difficult ascent on a mountain. For example, in the Quran: «فَلَا  اقۡتَحَمَ الۡعَقَبَۃَ وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا الۡعَقَبَۃُ فَکُّ رَقَبَۃٍ» (90/11) Translation: But he did not traverse the pass. And what do you know what the pass is? It is the freeing of a neck. However, according to Sahib Munjid, «عَقَبَۃ» means a difficult-to-traverse pass and also a difficult path to ascend."
    }
  ],
  "539": [
    {
      "id": 2467,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "house",
      "hw": "گھر",
      "s": "«بَیْت» means a place where a person resides with his family and spends the night, i.e., overnight stay. (48 verses: 2:125-2:127-2:158-2:189-3:49-3:96-3:97-3:154-4:15-4:81-4:100-5:2-5:97-7:74-8:5-8:35-10:87-11:73-12:23-14:37-15:82-16:68-16:80-17:93-22:26-22:29-22:33-24:27-24:29-24:36-24:61-26:149-27:52-28:12-29:41-33:13-33:33-33:34-33:53-43:33-43:34-51:36-52:4-59:2-65:1-66:11-71:28-106:3)",
      "d": "«بَاتَ» means to spend the night. To stay overnight. And «بَیْت» is the place where one spends the night. Then, technically, 'bait' refers to a place where a person can spend the night with his family and it is their abode and place of refuge. (Maf, M L) The plural of «بَیْت» is «بُیُوْت». For example, in the Quran: «وَ قَرۡنَ فِیۡ بُیُوۡتِکُنَّ وَ لَا تَبَرَّجۡنَ تَبَرُّجَ الۡجَاہِلِیَّۃِ  الۡاُوۡلٰی» (33/33). Translation: (O wives of the Prophet!) And stay in your houses, and do not display yourselves as in the former times of ignorance. And for the Ka'bah, Allah has also used the words «بَیْت» and «اَلْبَیْت». In that too, the mentioned relationship is found. For example, the Prophet's saying: «اَلْخَلْقُ عَیَالُ اللہ» meaning all creation is the family of Allah. And although the Ka'bah is not a place for overnight stay, it is certainly an abode and place of refuge."
    },
    {
      "id": 2468,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "house",
      "hw": "گھر",
      "s": "«مَسْکَن» means only residence, whether it is a place for overnight stay or not, so it is more specific than «بَیْت». (12 verses: 9:24-9:72-14:45-20:128-21:13-27:18-28:58-29:38-32:26-34:15-46:25-61:12)",
      "d": "«سَکَنَ» means to be inhabited. Also, to rest after doing work. And «مَسْکَنْ» is the place where a person takes residence, and giving residence to someone without rent etc. is called 'sukna', and those living in a house are called 'sukn'. Its plural is «سَاکِنٌ». (Maf) And the word «مَسْکَن» only implies residence. So every bait is a maskeen, but not every maskeen is a bait. For example, in the Quran: «فَتِلۡکَ مَسٰکِنُہُمۡ لَمۡ تُسۡکَنۡ مِّنۡۢ  بَعۡدِہِمۡ  اِلَّا قَلِیۡلًا» (28/58). Translation: So those are their houses which have not been inhabited after them except a little."
    },
    {
      "id": 2469,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "house",
      "hw": "گھر",
      "s": "«دَار» is very commonly used for house. When it means house, it refers to the external aspect of the house, as there can be several «بَیْت» within one «دَار» (haveli). (30 verses: 2:94-6:32-6:127-6:135-7:78-7:91-7:145-7:169-10:25-11:65-12:109-13:22-13:24-13:25-13:31-13:42-14:28-16:30-28:37-28:77-28:83-29:37-29:64-33:29-35:35-38:46-40:39-40:52-41:28-59:9)",
      "d": "The plural of «دَار» is «دَوْر» and «دِیَار», meaning house, mansion. The usage of «دَار» is very extensive. It can mean house, haveli, town, city, country, the entire world, and even the hereafter. (For details, see 'city'). And when «دَار» means house, it refers to the external aspect of the house. In English, the word for this is 'HOME'. Also, when «دَار» is used in the meaning of house, its plural is also «دَار». For example, in the Quran: «فَقَالَ تَمَتَّعُوۡا فِیۡ  دَارِکُمۡ ثَلٰثَۃَ  اَیَّامٍ» (11/65). Translation: So (Salih pbuh) said, 'Enjoy yourselves in your houses for three days.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2470,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "house",
      "hw": "گھر",
      "s": "«اَھْل» includes both the house and the household, family, all are included in this meaning. (69 verses: 2:196-2:126-2:217-3:121-4:25-4:35-4:58-4:75-4:92-5:89-6:131-7:83-7:94-7:100-7:123-10:24-11:40-11:45-11:46-11:81-11:117-12:26-12:62-12:65-12:88-12:93-15:65-18:71-18:77-19:16-19:55-20:10-20:29-20:132-21:76-21:84-23:27-24:27-26:169-26:170-27:7-27:34-27:49-27:57-28:4-28:15-28:29-28:59-29:31-29:32-29:33-29:34-35:43-36:50-37:76-37:134-38:43-39:15-42:45-48:11-48:12-48:26-51:26-52:26-66:6-75:33-83:31-84:9-84:13)",
      "d": "The word «اَھْل» is also used in very wide meanings (for details, see 'offspring' and the difference between «اَھْل» and «اٰل»). And in common meanings, «اَہْلُ الرَّجُل» means the people of one's house and family, i.e., wife and children who are under his care and upbringing. Then, just as the word «قَرْیَۃ» is used for both town and townspeople, similarly «اَھْل» is used for both the household and the house. For example, in the Quran: «وَ اِذۡ غَدَوۡتَ مِنۡ اَہۡلِکَ تُبَوِّئُ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ مَقَاعِدَ لِلۡقِتَالِ» (3/121). Translation: And when you set out in the morning from your house to arrange the believers in positions for fighting."
    }
  ],
  "540": [
    {
      "id": 2471,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "hour",
      "hw": "گھڑی",
      "s": "«سَاعَۃ» means any one of the hours of day and night. Time. The Hour (Resurrection). (8 verses: 7:34-9:117-10:45-10:49-16:61-30:55-34:30-46:35)",
      "d": "«سَاعَۃ» means a specific part of time. Hour. Its plural is «سَاعَات». The Arabs have divided the night and day into twelve hours each and given them separate names, details of which have passed in 'day and night'. Even today, the complete time of night and day is divided into 24 hours. So «سَاعَۃ» can also mean an hour. For example, in the Quran: «لَمۡ  یَلۡبَثُوۡۤا اِلَّا سَاعَۃً  مِّنۡ نَّہَارٍ» (46/35). Translation: They did not stay except an hour of the day. And for the clock (WATCH), the word «سَاعَۃ» is also used, and «سَاعَاتِی» means watchmaker. Sometimes «سَاعَۃ» also means duration or times, which can include a whole day or even many days, months, and years. For example, in the Quran: «لَقَدۡ تَّابَ اللّٰہُ عَلَی النَّبِیِّ وَ الۡمُہٰجِرِیۡنَ وَ الۡاَنۡصَارِ الَّذِیۡنِ اتَّبَعُوۡہُ فِیۡ سَاعَۃِ الۡعُسۡرَۃِ» (9/117). Translation: Indeed, Allah has turned to the Prophet and the emigrants and the helpers who followed him in the difficult hour. And «اَلسَّاعَۃ» generally means the Resurrection. For example, Allah says: «حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا جَآءَتۡہُمُ السَّاعَۃُ  بَغۡتَۃً» (6/31). Translation: Until the Hour comes upon them unexpectedly."
    },
    {
      "id": 2472,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "hour",
      "hw": "گھڑی",
      "s": "«اٰنَاء» means the hours of the night. (4 verses: 3:113-20:130-39:9-57:16)",
      "d": "«اٰن» means a part of time. Its plural is «اٰنَاء». And «اَنٰی یَانِیْ» means the time of something to come and its end to reach (Maf). Also, «اَنٰی» means a whole day or a part of it (Mansad), but in the Quran, the word «اٰنَاء» is used three times (3/113), (20/130), (39/9), and all three times the word «لَیْل» (night) comes with it. It is not used with day. Therefore, it can only be understood that «اٰنَاء» is specifically for the hours of the night. For example, in the Quran: «یَّتۡلُوۡنَ اٰیٰتِ اللّٰہِ اٰنَآءَ الَّیۡلِ  وَ ہُمۡ  یَسۡجُدُوۡنَ» (3/113). Translation: They recite the verses of Allah during the hours of the night and they prostrate."
    }
  ],
  "541": [
    {
      "id": 2474,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to enter",
      "hw": "گھسنا",
      "s": "«وَلَجَ» is used for entering a tight place (8 verses: 3:27, 7:40, 22:61, 31:29, 34:2, 35:13, 57:4, 57:6)",
      "d": "«وَلَجَ» means to enter a tight place; to squeeze in (intransitive). For example, the Quran states: «وَ لَا یَدۡخُلُوۡنَ الۡجَنَّۃَ حَتّٰی یَلِجَ الۡجَمَلُ فِیۡ سَمِّ الۡخِیَاطِ» ( 7/40 ). Translation: And they will not enter Paradise until the camel enters the eye of the needle."
    },
    {
      "id": 2475,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to enter",
      "hw": "گھسنا",
      "s": "«جَاسَ» means to enter (a house or shop etc.) for loot and mischief (1 verse: 17:5)",
      "d": "«جَاسَ» means to reach the middle of something (transitive) and to reach the utmost limit in seeking something (intransitive). And «جَاسَ فِی الْبَیْت» means he entered the house for mischief and plunder (transitive). And «جَوَّاس» means one who infiltrates among people to cause mischief (noun). For example, the Quran states: «بَعَثۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  عِبَادًا  لَّنَاۤ   اُولِیۡ  بَاۡسٍ  شَدِیۡدٍ فَجَاسُوۡا خِلٰلَ الدِّیَارِ» ( 17/5 ). Translation: We sent against you Our servants, mighty in prowess, who infiltrated among your dwellings."
    }
  ],
  "542": [
    {
      "id": 2476,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To Drag",
      "hw": "گھسیٹنا",
      "s": "«جَرّ» means to pull something upright so that it starts to drag, and if there is harshness and ruthlessness in this «جَرّ», then it is «عَتَلَ», and if something lying down is pulled, then it is «سَحْب» (1 verse: 7:150)",
      "d": "In «جَرّ», the aspect of pulling is prominent and dragging is less. Horizontally (i.e., along the side) or pulling something upright in such a way that it loses its footing and starts to drag, then this is «جَرّ». For example, in the Quran: «وَ اَخَذَ بِرَاۡسِ اَخِیۡہِ یَجُرُّہٗۤ اِلَیۡہِ» (7/150) Translation: And Moses seized his brother by the head and dragged him toward him. And «جَیْشٌ جَرَّارٌ» is said for a large army that spreads over a wide area and advances as if being pulled or dragged forward."
    },
    {
      "id": 2477,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to drag",
      "hw": "گھسیٹنا",
      "s": "«سَحَبَ» to drag on the ground, to snatch, to control, to take back (2 verses: 40:71, 54:48)",
      "d": "In «سَحَبَ», the aspect of dragging (being pulled along) is prominent, while the aspect of being drawn or pulled is less so. According to Imam Raghib, its meaning is to drag someone face down (muf). When a thing is in a lying position instead of standing, or moves horizontally (sideways) instead of straight, and it is dragged, this is «سَحْب». And «سَحَاب» means cloud. A cloud is called «سَحَاب» because the wind drags it along, and it moves forward as if being dragged (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَوۡمَ یُسۡحَبُوۡنَ فِی النَّارِ عَلٰی وُجُوۡہِہِمۡ» (54:48)\nTranslation: The Day they will be dragged on their faces into the Fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 2478,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to drag",
      "hw": "گھسیٹنا",
      "s": "«عَتَلَ» means to pull forward with extreme force by placing something on the neck (1 verse: 44:47)",
      "d": "«عَتَلَ» implies more severity and ruthlessness compared to «جَرّ» (transitive). According to the expert in language, it means to pull forward with extreme force by placing something on the neck (philology 188). For example, the Quran states: «خُذُوۡہُ فَاعۡتِلُوۡہُ  اِلٰی سَوَآءِ الۡجَحِیۡمِ» ( 44/47 ). Translation: Seize him and drag him to the midst of Hell."
    }
  ],
  "543": [
    {
      "id": 2479,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "horse",
      "hw": "گھوڑا",
      "s": "«خَیْل» a common noun. Its usage is general for horses, for horse riders, and for a group (of horses) (4 verses: 3:14, 8:60, 16:8, 59:6)",
      "d": "«خَیْل» is a common noun (ism jins). That is, it applies to all kinds of horses, whether male or female (muf). Then its usage also applies to a group or herd of horses, like «غَنَم» meaning a flock of sheep. Additionally, it is also used for a horse rider (manj).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ الۡخَیۡلَ وَ الۡبِغَالَ وَ الۡحَمِیۡرَ لِتَرۡکَبُوۡہَا وَ زِیۡنَۃً» (16:8)\nTranslation: And (He created) horses, mules, and donkeys for you to ride and as adornment.\nIn this verse, «خَیْل» is used as a common noun. In the following verse, «خَیْل» is used to mean horse riders or a group of horse riders and horses.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَجۡلِبۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِخَیۡلِکَ وَ رَجِلِکَ» (17:64)\nTranslation: And charge against them with your horsemen and your foot soldiers.\nThe fundamental meaning of «خَیْل» is the movement of various concepts in the mind (m, l). From this, the word «خِیَال» (imagination) is derived. And «الخَیْلَاء» refers to the pride and arrogance a horse rider feels when mounted compared to a pedestrian. From this, the word «تَخَیُّل» (conceit) is derived, meaning to know something with foresight (manj), high-flying."
    },
    {
      "id": 2480,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "horse",
      "hw": "گھوڑا",
      "s": "«صٰفِنٰت» horses that stand on three legs, well-bred and sleek (1 verse: 38:31)",
      "d": "«صٰفِنٰت» is the plural of «صافن». «صَفَنَ الْفَرَس» means a horse stands on three legs in such a way that only the tip of the fourth hoof remains on the ground (manj, muf). And from this, a sleek, well-bred horse is implied.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ عُرِضَ عَلَیۡہِ بِالۡعَشِیِّ الصّٰفِنٰتُ الۡجِیَادُ» (38:31)\nTranslation: When presented to him in the evening were the sleek, excellent (horses)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2481,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "horse",
      "hw": "گھوڑا",
      "s": "«جِیَاد» means swift and excellent horses (1 verse: 38:31)",
      "d": "«جِیَاد» is the plural of «جَیَِّد». «جُوْد» means abundance in something. And «جَوَّاد» means a generous man or woman. And «جَادَ الْفَرْس» means the horse is swift and fast. And «جَیَِّد» also denotes excellence in something. According to the expert in language, «جِیَاد» means swift and excellent horses. (philology 56). For example, the Quran states: «اِذۡ عُرِضَ عَلَیۡہِ بِالۡعَشِیِّ الصّٰفِنٰتُ الۡجِیَادُ» ( 38/31 ). Translation: When the sleek-bodied and swift horses were presented to him in the afternoon."
    },
    {
      "id": 2482,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "horse",
      "hw": "گھوڑا",
      "s": "«عَادِیَات» horses that participate in races and are prepared for battle (1 verse: 100:1)",
      "d": "«عَادِیَات» is the plural of «عَادِیَۃ». «عَادِیَۃٌ» and «عَادِی» are feminine. «عَادِی» means a group prepared for killing and fighting. Horses that charge. And «عَدَ الْفَرْس» means the horse ran a race. And «تَعَادَی الْقَوْم» means the people competed in a race (manj). So, «عَادِیَات» refers to those horses that go to war and are always engaged in competitive races.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الۡعٰدِیٰتِ ضَبۡحًا» (100:1)\nTranslation: By the chargers at dawn, panting (hard)."
    }
  ],
  "544": [
    {
      "id": 2483,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to encircle",
      "hw": "گھیرنا",
      "s": "«حَفَّ» to mean only to encircle or to surround (2 verses: 18:32, 39:75)",
      "d": "«حَفَّ» means to surround something from both sides (muf). And «حَفَّہٗ بکذا» means to encompass or encircle with something (manj). And «مَحِفَّۃ» means an enclosure, a flowing throne with a curtain drawn all around it (m, q).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ حَفَفۡنٰہُمَا بِنَخۡلٍ وَّ جَعَلۡنَا بَیۡنَہُمَا زَرۡعًا» (18:32)\nTranslation: And We surrounded them both with date-palms and placed between them a field of crops.\nAt another place, the Lord Almighty says:\n«وَ تَرَی الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃَ حَآفِّیۡنَ مِنۡ حَوۡلِ الۡعَرۡشِ» (39:75)\nTranslation: And you will see the angels surrounding the Throne from all sides."
    },
    {
      "id": 2484,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to encircle",
      "hw": "گھیرنا",
      "s": "«اَحَاطَ» to encircle with the purpose of protection (7 verses: 2:81, 12:66, 17:60, 18:29, 48:21, 65:12, 72:28)",
      "d": "«اَحَاطَ» means to encircle, to build a wall around, to surround something in such a way that its protection is ensured (muf). In such a way that the thing itself cannot get out, nor can anyone else take it out. Just as the enclosure of a house is made with four walls.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ جَآءَہُمُ الۡمَوۡجُ مِنۡ کُلِّ مَکَانٍ وَّ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہُمۡ اُحِیۡطَ بِہِمۡ» (10:22)\nTranslation: And the waves came upon them from every side, and they thought they were surrounded (by the sea).\nThis word is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example: The Lord Almighty says:\n«بَلٰی مَنۡ کَسَبَ سَیِّئَۃً وَّ اَحَاطَتۡ بِہٖ خَطِیۡٓئَتُہٗ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ اَصۡحٰبُ النَّارِ» (2:81)\nTranslation: Yes indeed! Whoever earns evil and his sins have encompassed him, those are the companions of the Fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 2485,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to encircle",
      "hw": "گھیرنا",
      "s": "«اَحْصَرَ» encirclement and confinement, i.e., to imprison something (4 verses: 2:196, 2:273, 4:90, 9:5)",
      "d": "«اَحْصَرَ» means to besiege, to lay siege, to surround something in such a way that it remains confined and cannot get out (m, l, muf). To imprison, and to prevent any supplies (food, drink), aid (military support), or any kind of help from reaching them from outside.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ احۡصُرُوۡہُمۡ وَ اقۡعُدُوۡا لَہُمۡ کُلَّ مَرۡصَدٍ» (9:5)\nTranslation: And besiege them and lie in wait for them at every ambush site."
    },
    {
      "id": 2486,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to encompass",
      "hw": "گھیرنا",
      "s": "«حَاقَ» means to encompass someone with a calamity (10 verses: 6:10, 11:8, 16:34, 21:41, 35:43, 39:48, 40:45, 40:83, 45:33, 46:26)",
      "d": "«حَاقَ» means for something to descend upon something (transitive) and to descend upon and encompass something (intransitive). It implies a siege that surrounds the besieged. It means for a calamity, affliction, or punishment to descend upon someone, causing them to be surrounded. And «حَیْق» means the recompense of deeds; the bad result of a bad action (noun). Thus, this word is used in a negative sense. For example, the Quran states: «وَ حَاقَ بِہِمۡ  مَّا کَانُوۡا بِہٖ یَسۡتَہۡزِءُوۡنَ» ( 39/48 ). Translation: And the (punishment) they used to mock has encompassed them. At another place, the Almighty says: «وَ لَا یَحِیۡقُ الۡمَکۡرُ السَّیِّیئُ  اِلَّیۡ بِاَہۡلِہٖ» ( 35/43 ). Translation: And the evil plot does not befall except its own people. This part of the mentioned verse is also used as a proverb: \"\"چاہ کن را چاہ درپیش\"\" meaning the one who digs a pit for others falls into it himself."
    }
  ],
  "545": [
    {
      "id": 2487,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Staff",
      "hw": "لاٹھی",
      "s": "«عَصَا» means shepherd's staff. (12 verses: 2:60-7:107-7:117-7:160-20:18-20:66-26:32-26:44-26:45-26:63-27:10-28:31)",
      "d": "«عَصَا» means shepherd's staff. A stout staff. Its plural is «عِصِیّ». \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated: \n«فَاَلۡقٰی عَصَاہُ  فَاِذَا ہِیَ ثُعۡبَانٌ  مُّبِیۡنٌ» ( 7/107 )\nTranslation: So when Moses (peace be upon him) threw his staff, it became a clear serpent."
    },
    {
      "id": 2488,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Staff",
      "hw": "لاٹھی",
      "s": "«مِنْسَأَۃ» means the staff of a sick or weak person. (1 verse: 34:14)",
      "d": "«مِنْسَأَۃ» means the staff of a sick or weak person (see p. 231). \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated: \n«فَلَمَّا قَضَیۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ الۡمَوۡتَ مَا دَلَّہُمۡ عَلٰی مَوۡتِہٖۤ اِلَّا دَآبَّۃُ الۡاَرۡضِ تَاۡکُلُ مِنۡسَاَتَہٗ» ( 34/14 )\nTranslation: Then when We decreed death for Solomon, nothing informed them of his death except the creature of the earth which was eating his staff. \nAnd a staff whose head is bent is called «مِحْجَنْ» (see p. 231). «عَصَا» and «مِنْسَاَۃ» both do not have bent heads. «عَصَا» is a thick and strong staff. And «مِنْسَاَۃ» is a relatively thinner and well-shaped kind of staff."
    }
  ],
  "546": [
    {
      "id": 2489,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "لانا",
      "s": "«جَآءَبِ» means to bring, and its usage is general. (49 verses: 2:87-2:92-3:183-3:184-4:170-5:32-5:70-6:91-6:160-7:43-7:53-7:101-7:116-10:13-10:74-11:69-12:18-12:72-12:100-14:9-19:23-23:70-24:11-24:13-25:4-27:89-27:90-28:37-28:84-28:85-29:39-30:9-30:47-35:25-37:37-37:84-39:33-40:25-40:28-40:34-40:83-43:47-43:63-49:6-50:19-50:21-50:33-51:26-61:6)",
      "d": "«جَآءَبِ» means to bring, and its usage is general. \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated: \n«فَقَدۡ کُذِّبَ رُسُلٌ مِّنۡ قَبۡلِکَ جَآءُوۡ بِالۡبَیِّنٰتِ» ( 3/184 )\nTranslation: So before you, messengers were denied who brought clear proofs."
    },
    {
      "id": 2490,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "لانا",
      "s": "«اَتٰی بِہٖ» to bring as a result or consequence of something. (82 verses: 2:23-2:25-2:106-2:109-2:145-2:148-2:258-3:93-3:161-3:183-4:133-5:52-5:54-5:108-6:35-6:46-7:70-7:112-7:132-7:169-7:203-9:24-9:70-10:38-10:39-11:13-11:32-11:33-12:60-12:66-12:83-12:93-13:38-14:10-14:11-14:19-15:7-15:64-16:76-17:88-17:92-18:15-18:33-18:62-18:96-19:27-19:80-20:10-20:58-20:133-21:5-21:47-21:61-23:71-23:90-24:4-24:13-25:33-26:31-26:37-27:7-27:21-27:37-27:38-27:39-27:40-28:29-28:49-28:71-28:72-31:16-35:16-37:157-40:78-44:10-44:19-44:36-46:22-52:34-52:38-67:30-68:41)",
      "d": "«اَتٰی بِہٖ» to bring as a result or consequence of something. \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated: \n«فَاۡتُوۡا بِسُوۡرَۃٍ مِّنۡ مِّثۡلِہٖ» ( 2/23 )\nTranslation: Then bring a surah like it."
    },
    {
      "id": 2491,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "لانا",
      "s": "«ھَلُمَّ» when used to call and bring. (2 verses: 6:150-33:18)",
      "d": "«ھَلُمَّ» is a verbal noun. Meaning call. That is, to call and bring someone repeatedly. This word is used both as intransitive and transitive. When intransitive, it gives the meaning of coming. \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated: \n« لِاِخۡوَانِہِمۡ ہَلُمَّ اِلَیۡنَا» ( 33/18 )\nTranslation: They say to their brothers, 'Come to us.' \nAnd when used transitively, it gives the meaning of bringing. \nFor example: The command of Allah is: \n«قُلۡ ہَلُمَّ  شُہَدَآءَکُمُ» ( 6/150 )\nTranslation: Say, 'Bring your witnesses.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2492,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "لانا",
      "s": "«ھَاتُوْا» meaning bring here, bring hither. (4 verses: 2:111-21:24-27:64-28:75)",
      "d": "According to linguists, this word is originally «اٰتُوْا», which is the imperative plural masculine present form from «اَتٰی». And this word is used as an imperative noun. According to Ibn al-Faris, its meaning is also to call out. But according to some, its meanings are to bring here or bring quickly. \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated: \n«قُلۡ ہَاتُوۡا بُرۡہَانَکُمۡ  اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰدِقِیۡنَ» ( 2/111 )\nTranslation: Say, 'Bring your proof if you are truthful.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2493,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "لانا",
      "s": "«اَجَآءَ» to bring something forcibly, i.e., by compulsion and helplessness, or to be the cause of bringing. (1 verse: 19:23)",
      "d": "«اَجَآءَ» to bring something forcibly, i.e., by compulsion and helplessness, or to be the cause of bringing. \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated: \n«فَاَجَآءَہَا الۡمَخَاضُ  اِلٰی جِذۡعِ  النَّخۡلَۃِ» ( 19/23 )\nTranslation: Then the pangs of childbirth brought her to the trunk of the palm tree."
    },
    {
      "id": 2494,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "لانا",
      "s": "«اَجْلَبَ» to bring someone forcibly from behind by driving or urging. (1 verse: 17:64)",
      "d": "«جَلَبَ» means to drive and urge something. And «اَجْلَبَ عَلَیْہِ» means to drive someone and make them advance forcibly. \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated: \n«وَ اَجۡلِبۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِخَیۡلِکَ وَ رَجِلِکَ» ( 17/64 )\nTranslation: And bring against them your cavalry and infantry."
    }
  ],
  "547": [
    {
      "id": 2495,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to be fitting",
      "hw": "لائق",
      "s": "«یَنْبَغِیْ» means to be fitting. This word comes for an action for which it is appropriate (i.e., subject to it) (6 verses: 19:92, 25:18, 26:211, 36:40, 36:69, 38:35)",
      "d": "«اِنْبَغٰی» means to be easy and simple. And «ینبغی» means to be fitting, appropriate (noun). And this word comes for an action for which it is subject. They say «اَلنَّارُ یَنْبَغِیْ اَنْ یُّحْرِقَ الثَّوْبَ» meaning it is the characteristic of fire to burn cloth (intransitive). This is the only masculine singular imperfect form used. And it pertains to matters that are inherent or included in nature. Lexically, it is used in both negative and affirmative. Example of negative from the Quran: «لَا الشَّمۡسُ یَنۡۢبَغِیۡ لَہَاۤ اَنۡ تُدۡرِکَ الۡقَمَرَ» ( 36/40 ). Translation: It is not fitting for the sun to overtake the moon. At another place: «وَ مَا عَلَّمۡنٰہُ الشِّعۡرَ وَ مَا یَنۡۢبَغِیۡ لَہٗ» ( 36/69 ). Translation: And We have not taught him poetry, nor is it fitting for him."
    },
    {
      "id": 2496,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To be worthy",
      "hw": "لائق",
      "s": "«اَجْدَر» is an intensive form and it comes for optional matters. (1 verse: 9:97)",
      "d": "«جَدَرَ» means to be worthy and appropriate. And «اَجْدَر» is an intensive form and it comes for optional matters. «جَدِیْرُ الذِّکْر» means worthy of mention. And «جَدِیْرُ الثَّنَاء» means worthy of praise. And it is used when something is suitable for someone's condition and status. \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated: \n«اَلۡاَعۡرَابُ اَشَدُّ کُفۡرًا وَّ نِفَاقًا وَّ اَجۡدَرُ اَلَّا یَعۡلَمُوۡا حُدُوۡدَ  مَاۤ  اَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ» ( 9/97 )\nTranslation: The bedouins are more severe in disbelief and hypocrisy, and it is more fitting that they should not know the limits of what Allah has revealed."
    },
    {
      "id": 2497,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to be worthy",
      "hw": "لائق",
      "s": "'Awla' is used in wider meanings than 'ajdar' and comes only for affirmation in optional matters. (5 verses: 3:68-4:135-8:75-19:70-33:6)",
      "d": "'Wali' means guardian, friend, and one meaning of 'mawali' is heir of the estate. And 'wala' means the estate of a freed slave and the right of guardianship. And 'awla' means more worthy, more suitable, more deserving. It comes for optional matters and only for affirmation. And it is stronger than 'yanbaghi' (m.f.) and only this form is used for it too. And its response will come with 'ba'. And its meaning will be: He is the one who is worthy of it, He is more suitable or deserving.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«ثُمَّ لَنَحۡنُ اَعۡلَمُ بِالَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ اَوۡلٰی بِہَا صِلِیًّا» (19/70)\nTranslation: Then We are also well aware of those who are more worthy of entering Hell.\nAt another place, the divine declaration says:\n«اَلنَّبِیُّ  اَوۡلٰی بِالۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ مِنۡ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ» (33/6)\nTranslation: The Prophet is more worthy of the believers than their own selves.\nAnd if the response of 'awla' comes with 'lam', then this word becomes a reproach, condemnation, and warning. Meaning: destruction, perdition, etc.\nFor example, the divine declaration says:\n«اَوۡلٰی لَکَ  فَاَوۡلٰی» (75/35)\nTranslation: May destruction be for you, then may destruction be for you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2498,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to be worthy",
      "hw": "لائق",
      "s": "'Huqqa' means that doing such a thing is obligatory and deserving for it. (13 verses: 2:228-2:247-5:107-6:81-9:13-9:62-9:108-10:35-10:53-33:37-48:26-84:2-84:5)",
      "d": "'Haqqa' means to be established, to be obligatory. And 'huqqa an yaf'ala kaza' means that doing such a thing is obligatory and deserving for it (m.n.j.) meaning it was its right that it does so. Its usage is only in the affirmative.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اِذَا السَّمَآءُ  انۡشَقَّتۡ وَ اَذِنَتۡ لِرَبِّہَا وَ حُقَّتۡ» (84/1،2)\nTranslation: When the sky splits and listens to its Lord's command, and it is also obligatory for it."
    }
  ],
  "548": [
    {
      "id": 2500,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to wrap, to coil",
      "hw": "لپیٹنا",
      "s": "'Laff' means to place one thing on another and mix them, i.e., to combine. (2 verses: 17:104-75:29)",
      "d": "'Laff' means to mix one thing with another and combine them (m.f.) to layer one thing, then mix by layering another on top, then after that layer the third layer on top (m.l.)\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَ وَعۡدُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ  جِئۡنَا بِکُمۡ  لَفِیۡفًا» (17/104)\nTranslation: Then when the promise of the Hereafter comes, We will bring you all together in a wrapped state.\nAnd for 'to coil', 'iltaffa' will be used. Meaning: to cling and stick to one thing on another.\nFor example, the divine declaration says:\n«وَ الۡتَفَّتِ السَّاقُ بِالسَّاقِ . اِلٰی رَبِّکَ یَوۡمَئِذِ ۣ الۡمَسَاقُ» (75/29)\nTranslation: And the shank will be wrapped with the shank. To your Lord will be the gathering on that day."
    },
    {
      "id": 2501,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to wrap, to coil",
      "hw": "لپیٹنا",
      "s": "'Kawwara' means to wrap in a round shape and to gather. (2 verses: 39:5-81:1)",
      "d": "'Kawwara' means to wrap something like a turban or scarf and turn it up and down. And 'iktaru al-farsi' means the horse turning its tail (m.f.). And for wrapping a scarf, 'laff' is also used. They say 'laffa'tu amamati 'ala ra'si' meaning I wrapped the scarf on my head. It is in the sense that one layer gathers on another. And for wrapping a scarf, the word 'kawwara' is stronger. Because in 'kawwara', both the concepts of gathering and roundness are present, which are found in a scarf.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«یُکَوِّرُ الَّیۡلَ عَلَی النَّہَارِ وَ یُکَوِّرُ النَّہَارَ عَلَی» (39/5)\nTranslation: He wraps the night over the day and wraps the day over the night.\nAt another place, the divine declaration says:\n«اِذَا  الشَّمۡسُ کُوِّرَتۡ» (81/1)\nTranslation: When the sun is wrapped up."
    }
  ],
  "549": [
    {
      "id": 2502,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to hang, to suspend",
      "hw": "لٹکانا",
      "s": "'Adla' means to hang something slowly and gently. (10 verses: 2:188-7:22-12:19-20:40-20:120-28:12-34:7-34:14-53:8-61:10)",
      "d": "'Dala' means to approach something with ease and gentleness (m.l.). 'Dalahu' means to behave with softness and consideration towards someone. And 'dalw' means to pull an empty bucket to lower and raise it in a well. And 'adla dalwahu' means he hung the empty bucket in the well to fill it with water.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ جَآءَتۡ سَیَّارَۃٌ  فَاَرۡسَلُوۡا وَارِدَہُمۡ فَاَدۡلٰی دَلۡوَہٗ» (12/19)\nTranslation: And a caravan came, and they sent their water-drawer, and he let down his bucket.\n'Tadalla' means to hang down by itself with ease and gentleness. They say 'tadallatha al-thamaru mina al-shajari' meaning the fruit hangs down from the tree.\nFor example, the divine declaration says:\n«ثُمَّ  دَنَا فَتَدَلّٰی» (53/8)\nTranslation: Then he drew near and hung down."
    },
    {
      "id": 2503,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to hang, to suspend",
      "hw": "لٹکانا",
      "s": "'Alaqa' means to hang and entangle something. (1 verse: 4:129)",
      "d": "'Alaqa' means to get entangled in something. They say 'alqata al-saydu fi al-ju'alati' meaning the prey got entangled in the net. And 'alaqa' means to hang, to entangle. And 'alaqun' means a hanging thing.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَلَا تَمِیۡلُوۡا کُلَّ الۡمَیۡلِ فَتَذَرُوۡہَا کَالۡمُعَلَّقَۃِ» (4/129)\nTranslation: So do not incline entirely to one side and leave her like the suspended one."
    }
  ],
  "550": [
    {
      "id": 2506,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to take heed, to be cautious",
      "hw": "لحاظ",
      "s": "'Raqiba' is used only for paying attention to something with a stern look or aversion. (3 verses: 9:8-9:10-20:94)",
      "d": "'Raqiba' means to keep an eye on someone's neck. To watch over sternly (m.f.). And also means to supervise, to guard, to wait (m.n.j.), to protect.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«لَا یَرۡقُبُوۡنَ فِیۡ مُؤۡمِنٍ اِلًّا وَّ لَا ذِمَّۃً» (9/10)\nTranslation: They do not regard any kinship or treaty with a believer."
    },
    {
      "id": 2507,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to take heed, to be cautious",
      "hw": "لحاظ",
      "s": "'Ra'a' means to protect something well and pay attention to it. (2 verses: 20:54-28:23)",
      "d": "'Ra'a' means to protect something well and pay attention to it (m.f.) to fulfill a covenant or responsibility and think about it. And 'ra'i' means a shepherd who is in charge of protecting his flock, and also means to protect something and to take measures to ward off external dangers. Its opposite is 'ihmal', meaning grazing the flock without a shepherd (f.q.l. 15).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  لِاَمٰنٰتِہِمۡ وَ عَہۡدِہِمْ رٰعُوۡنَ» (23/8)\nTranslation: And those who are to their trusts and their promises are protectors."
    }
  ],
  "551": [
    {
      "id": 2508,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "army, host",
      "hw": "لشکر",
      "s": "'Jund' means a contingent of recruited armed armies. (7 verses: 19:75-36:28-36:75-37:173-38:11-44:24-67:20)",
      "d": "'Jund' is used for a military army and is a well-known word commonly used. 'Jundi' means military, and 'jannada' means to recruit in the army (m.n.j.). Its plural is 'junud'. Besides 'jund', another common word for army is 'jaysh', whose plural is 'juyush'. It is not used in the Quran, and another word is 'askar', whose plural is 'asakar'. This is also not in the Quran. 'Asakar' and 'juyush' are generally used for those armies that start gathering from different aspects upon the announcement of jihad, whether they have war equipment or not. And 'jund' refers only to an armed army.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا فَصَلَ طَالُوۡتُ بِالۡجُنُوۡدِ» (2/249)\nTranslation: When Talut set out with the armies."
    },
    {
      "id": 2509,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "army, host",
      "hw": "لشکر",
      "s": "'Fawj' means a group that passes quickly. (5 verses: 27:83-38:59-67:8-78:18-110:2)",
      "d": "'Fawj' means a group that passes quickly. A war contingent (m.f.). Its plural is 'afwaj'. And a larger group than 'ta'ifa' is called (f.l. 205), but in the Quran, this word generally comes in the meaning of 'a group'. It does not come in the meaning of a war contingent. Thus, the concept that arises from the word 'fauj' (army) today does not emerge from the Quran.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ یَوۡمَ نَحۡشُرُ مِنۡ کُلِّ اُمَّۃٍ  فَوۡجًا مِّمَّنۡ یُّکَذِّبُ بِاٰیٰتِنَا» (27/83)\nTranslation: And on the Day We will gather from every nation a group of those who denied Our signs."
    },
    {
      "id": 2510,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "army",
      "hw": "لشکر",
      "s": "«حِزْب» means party; political faction (17 verses: 5:56, 11:17, 13:36, 18:12, 19:37, 23:53, 30:32, 33:20, 33:22, 35:6, 38:11, 38:13, 40:5, 40:30, 43:65, 58:19, 58:22)",
      "d": "«حِزْب» means group; party; faction; a group of like-minded people. And «اَحْزَاب» are people whose hearts and deeds are in harmony, even if they do not meet each other. And «حَازَبَ» means to enter a party; to help; to provide strength. And «حَزَّب» means to gather people into groups (verb). And «حِزْب» means a group in which strictness and intensity are found (intransitive). And «حِزْب» essentially refers to a political party. And according to the Quran, there are only two major parties: حزب الله (Party of Allah) and حزب الشيطان (Party of Satan), between whom there is always a confrontation. And حزب الشيطان further divides into many small parties (groups), like the various factions of disbelievers during the Battle of the Trench. Also, حزب means people gathered under one banner (transitive). For example, the Quran states: «یَحۡسَبُوۡنَ الۡاَحۡزَابَ لَمۡ  یَذۡہَبُوۡا ۚ وَ اِنۡ یَّاۡتِ الۡاَحۡزَابُ یَوَدُّوۡا لَوۡ اَنَّہُمۡ بَادُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَعۡرَابِ یَسۡاَلُوۡنَ عَنۡ اَنۡۢبَآئِکُمۡ» ( 33/20 ). Translation: They think the armies have not gone away; and if the armies were to come, they would wish they were in the deserts, inquiring about your news."
    },
    {
      "id": 2511,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "army",
      "hw": "لشکر",
      "s": "«فِئَۃ» means a fighting group that has mutual cooperation among its members (9 verses: 2:249, 3:13, 4:88, 8:16, 8:19, 8:45, 8:48, 18:43, 28:81)",
      "d": "«فَاَیَ الرَّاْسَ فُلَانٌ» means to cut someone's head with a sword (transitive). «فِئَۃ» means a fighting group whose members maintain contact for mutual cooperation (intransitive). For example, the Quran states: «کَمۡ مِّنۡ فِئَۃٍ قَلِیۡلَۃٍ غَلَبَتۡ فِئَۃً  کَثِیۡرَۃًۢ بِاِذۡنِ  اللّٰہِ» ( 2/249 ). Translation: How often a small group has overcome a large group by the permission of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2512,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "army",
      "hw": "لشکر",
      "s": "«نَفِیْر» means people setting out on an expedition or battle (11 verses: 4:71, 9:38, 9:39, 9:41, 9:81, 9:122, 17:6, 46:29, 18:34, 46:29, 72:1)",
      "d": "«نَفَرَ» means to set out for battle or an expedition. «نَفِیْر» has two meanings: (1) people marching to battle (2) a group of less than ten people (noun)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2513,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "army",
      "hw": "لشکر",
      "s": "«ثُبَاتٍ» means a small unit of brave cavalry (1 verse: 4:71)",
      "d": "«ثُبَاتٍ» means brave cavalry whose attack does not miss the target (noun). For example, the Quran states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا خُذُوۡا حِذۡرَکُمۡ فَانۡفِرُوۡا ثُبَاتٍ اَوِ انۡفِرُوۡا جَمِیۡعًا» ( 4/71 ). Translation: O you who have believed, take your precautions and set out in small groups or set out all together."
    }
  ],
  "552": [
    {
      "id": 2514,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Wood",
      "hw": "لکڑی",
      "s": "«حَطَبَ» is wood that is only fit for burning. (2 verses: 72:15-111:4)",
      "d": "«حَطَبَ» is wood that is only fit for burning. Fuel (m. l). For example, the Quran states: «وَّ  امۡرَاَتُہٗ ؕ حَمَّالَۃَ  الۡحَطَبِ» (111/4). Translation: And the wife of Abu Lahab also, who carries firewood on her back."
    },
    {
      "id": 2515,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Wood",
      "hw": "لکڑی",
      "s": "«خَشَبَ» is wood that is useful. (1 verse: 63:4)",
      "d": "«خَشَبَ» is wood that is useful. Wood suitable for use in construction. In the words of Ibn al-Faris, it is hard and thick wood. Its plural is «خُشُب» (TIMBER) (m. l). For example, the Quran states: «کَاَنَّہُمۡ خُشُبٌ مُّسَنَّدَۃٌ» (63/4). Translation: As if they were wooden planks propped up."
    }
  ],
  "553": [
    {
      "id": 2516,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Write",
      "hw": "لکھنا",
      "s": "«خَطَّ» means to draw lines, to mark, and to make them long in length. (1 verse: 29:48)",
      "d": "«خَطَّ» means to draw lines, to mark, and to make them long in length. «مُخَلَّط» means striped cloth and «خَطَّاط» means one who writes a lot (manjad). So, «خَطَّ» essentially means to put down something in the direction of length, regardless of whether it is writing or not. For example, the Quran states: «وَ مَا کُنۡتَ تَتۡلُوۡا مِنۡ قَبۡلِہٖ مِنۡ کِتٰبٍ وَّ لَا تَخُطُّہٗ  بِیَمِیۡنِکَ» (29/48). Translation: Before this, you could neither read any book nor write it with your right hand."
    },
    {
      "id": 2517,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Write",
      "hw": "لکھنا",
      "s": "«سَطَرَ» means to write by forming lines, to write in one line. (4 verses: 17:58-33:6-52:2-68:1)",
      "d": "«سَطَرٌ» means a line, a row, a line of writing (manjad). And «سَطَرَ» means to write in lines, to write by forming lines, to write straight lines. For example, the Quran states: «وَ الۡقَلَمِ وَ مَا یَسۡطُرُوۡنَ» (68/1). Translation: By the pen and what they write."
    },
    {
      "id": 2518,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Write",
      "hw": "لکھنا",
      "s": "«رَقَم» is writing such that the script is clear and thick. (2 verses: 83:9-83:20)",
      "d": "«رَقَم» means to add diacritics (i.e., zabar, zer, pesh) and dots to a book. To write (on cloth). To make an engraving or design. And «مِرْقَمُ» means the instrument for engraving. And «مَرْقُوم» means clearly written (manjad). And «رَقَمَ» means to write in such a way that the script is clear and in thick lines (muf). For example, the Quran states: «کِتٰبٌ مَّرۡقُوۡمٌ یَّشۡہَدُہُ  الۡمُقَرَّبُوۡنَ» (83:20,21). Translation: It is a book written, around which the angels (the nearest to Allah) stand."
    },
    {
      "id": 2519,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Write",
      "hw": "لکھنا",
      "s": "«کَتَبَ» is writing that fully conveys its intended meaning. (40 verses: 2:79-2:178-2:180-2:183-2:187-2:216-2:246-2:282-3:53-3:154-3:181-4:66-4:77-4:81-4:127-5:21-5:32-5:45-5:83-6:12-6:54-7:145-7:156-9:51-9:120-9:121-10:21-19:79-21:105-22:4-36:12-43:19-43:80-52:41-57:27-58:21-58:22-59:3-68:47-98:3)",
      "d": "«کَتَبَ» is writing that is complete in expressing its meaning (m. l). For example, the Quran states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا تَدَایَنۡتُمۡ بِدَیۡنٍ اِلٰۤی اَجَلٍ مُّسَمًّی فَاکۡتُبُوۡہُ» (2/282). Translation: O you who believe! When you contract a debt for a fixed term, write it down."
    }
  ],
  "554": [
    {
      "id": 2520,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To have written / To cause to be written",
      "hw": "لکھوانا",
      "s": "«اِسْتَنْسَخَ» means to give something to be copied. To have written (1 Verse: 45:29)",
      "d": "«نَسْخُ الْکِتَاب» means to copy a book, and «نَسْخَة» is a copy made from the original. «اِسْتَنْسَخَ» means to command writing or copying (Majid) – to copy a book word for word.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ہٰذَا کِتٰبُنَا یَنۡطِقُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ بِالۡحَقِّ ؕ اِنَّا کُنَّا نَسۡتَنۡسِخُ مَا کُنۡتُمۡ تَعۡمَلُوۡنَ» (45/29)\nTranslation: This Our Book will speak the truth about you. Indeed, We used to have recorded (or cause to be recorded) all that you used to do."
    },
    {
      "id": 2522,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To have written / To cause to be written",
      "hw": "لکھوانا",
      "s": "The usage of «اِکْتَتَبَ» is generally for false and forged transcription (1 Verse: 25:5)",
      "d": "«اِکْتَتَبَ» means to write, to have something written, to cause to be written, to request writing (Majid). The word «اِکْتَتَبَ» is generally used in the context of false and fabricated writings (Mufradat).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ قَالُوۡۤا اَسَاطِیۡرُ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ اکۡتَتَبَہَا فَہِیَ تُمۡلٰی عَلَیۡہِ بُکۡرَۃً وَّ اَصِیۡلًا» (25/5)\nTranslation: And they (the disbelievers) say, 'These are the fables of the ancients; he has got them written down, and they are dictated to him morning and evening.'"
    }
  ],
  "555": [
    {
      "id": 2523,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "The writer / The scribe",
      "hw": "لکھنے",
      "s": "«کَاتِب» is general; every person who writes anything is called a scribe (5 Verses: 2:282-2:283-21:94-24:33-82:11)",
      "d": "«کَاتِب» is any person who writes something. This word is well-known and its usage is general.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ عَلٰی سَفَرٍ وَّ لَمۡ تَجِدُوۡا کَاتِبًا فَرِہٰنٌ مَّقۡبُوۡضَۃٌ» (2/283)\nTranslation: And if you are on a journey and cannot find a scribe, then take a pledge in hand (or with security)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2524,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "The writer / The scribe",
      "hw": "لکھنے",
      "s": "«سَفَرَۃ» means those who write blessed and pure writings (1 Verse: 80:15)",
      "d": "«سَفَرَۃ» is the plural of «سَافِر». «اَلسِّفْر» means a book that unveils realities (M. L.), and «اَسْفَار» means the Torah's expositions and interpretations. «سَافِر» is a person who writes or composes such a writing. The angels who write the record of deeds. Those who write divinely inspired writings.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فِیۡ صُحُفٍ مُّکَرَّمَۃٍ مَّرۡفُوۡعَۃٍ مُّطَہَّرَۃٍۭ بِاَیۡدِیۡ سَفَرَۃٍ کِرَامٍۭ بَرَرَۃٍ» (80/13-16)\nTranslation: (This revelation is) in honored, exalted, and purified pages, (written) by the hands of noble, pure, and most honorable scribes."
    }
  ],
  "556": [
    {
      "id": 2525,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous / Successive",
      "hw": "لگاتار",
      "s": "«تَتْرًا» means successive, continuous; one after the other without a break in between (1 Verse: 23:44)",
      "d": "«تَتْرًا» means one after the other in such a way that there is no interval between them (Majid). «تَوَاتُر» and «مُتَوَاتِر» are famous terms meaning that many can be simultaneous, but it is impossible that at any time none exist.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ اَرۡسَلۡنَا رُسُلَنَا تَتۡرًا» (23/44)\nTranslation: Then We sent Our messengers in succession."
    },
    {
      "id": 2526,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous / Successive",
      "hw": "لگاتار",
      "s": "«عَلٰی فَتْرَۃٍ» means the pace of an action becomes slow while doing it, and weakness or deficiency occurs in it (1 Verse: 5:19)",
      "d": "«فَتَرَ» means the pace of an action becomes slow while doing it, and weakness (i.e., feebleness) occurs in it (M. L. Muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ قَدۡ جَآءَکُمۡ رَسُوۡلُنَا یُبَیِّنُ لَکُمۡ عَلٰی فَتۡرَۃٍ مِّنَ الرُّسُلِ» (5/19)\nTranslation: O People of the Book! Our Messenger has come to you, clarifying for you after a break (or interval) in the messengers, lest you say, 'No bearer of good news or warner has come to us.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2527,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous / Successive",
      "hw": "لگاتار",
      "s": "«حُسُوْمًا» means relentless and successive calamity and ill-omen that erases name and trace (1 Verse: 69:7)",
      "d": "«حَسَمَ» means to efface the sign of something and to erase it. «حَسْمُ الدَّاءِ» means to inflict wounds continuously and erase the wound and its sign. «نَاَلَہٗ حُسُوْمًا» means ill-omen erased his name and trace (Muf). And «حَسَمَ» means to cut from the root. «حَسَمَ الْعِرْق» means to cut a vein and cauterize it so blood stops. And «حُسُوْم» means inauspicious, ill-omened (Majid). Thus, the concept of «حُسُوْم» encompasses three meanings: (1) Affliction and ill-omen, (2) Continuity, (3) Annihilation (i.e., erasing and destroying).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اَمَّا عَادٌ فَاُہۡلِکُوۡا بِرِیۡحٍ صَرۡصَرٍ عَاتِیَۃٍ . سَخَّرَہَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ سَبۡعَ لَیَالٍ وَّ ثَمٰنِیَۃَ اَیَّامٍ ۙ حُسُوۡمًا ۙ فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی» (69/6,7)\nTranslation: And as for 'Ad, they were destroyed by a furious, violent wind, which He imposed on them for seven nights and eight days, so you would see the people therein prostrate as if they were trunks of hollow palm trees."
    },
    {
      "id": 2528,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous / Successive",
      "hw": "لگاتار",
      "s": "«رَدِفَ» means one after the other when they are also helpers to each other (2 Verses: 8:9-27:72)",
      "d": "«رَدِفَ» means to be mounted behind someone. «اَرْدَفَ» means to make someone ride behind oneself. To come one after another. To be successive. And «تَرَادَفَ» means to help each other, to be mounted one behind the other (Majid). And «اِرْدَافُ الْمُلُوْک» means the successors of kings (Muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِذۡ تَسۡتَغِیۡثُوۡنَ رَبَّکُمۡ فَاسۡتَجَابَ لَکُمۡ اَنِّیۡ مُمِدُّکُمۡ بِاَلۡفٍ مِّنَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ مُرۡدِفِیۡنَ» (8/9)\nTranslation: When you asked help of your Lord, He answered you, 'Indeed, I will reinforce you with a thousand angels, coming in succession.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2529,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous / Successive",
      "hw": "لگاتار",
      "s": "«دَاَبَ» means to go on continuously with effort and toil (2 Verses: 12:47-14:33)",
      "d": "«دَاَبَ» means to continue doing a thing with effort and toil (Majid). To proceed continuously and without interruption (Muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ سَخَّرَ لَکُمُ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ دَآئِبَیۡنِ» (14/33)\nTranslation: And He has subjected for you the sun and the moon, both constantly pursuing their courses."
    },
    {
      "id": 2530,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous / Successive",
      "hw": "لگاتار",
      "s": "«مُتَتَابِع» means two things of the same kind coming one after the other such that no third thing intervenes between them (2 Verses: 4:92-58:4)",
      "d": "«مُتَتَابِع» means two things coming one after another or being in such a succession that no third thing intervenes between them (Muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَمَنۡ لَّمۡ یَجِدۡ فَصِیَامُ شَہۡرَیۡنِ مُتَتَابِعَیۡنِ» (4/92)\nTranslation: But whoever cannot find (the means for freeing a slave) – then a fast for two consecutive months (is prescribed) as a penalty."
    },
    {
      "id": 2531,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous; Consecutive",
      "hw": "لگاتار",
      "s": "«وَصَّلَ» means to join one thing with another in such a way that the possibility of a pause is completely eliminated (18 verses: 2:27-4:10-4:90-6:136-11:81-13:21-13:25-14:29-17:18-28:35-28:51-38:56-58:8-82:15-84:12-87:12-92:15-111:3)",
      "d": "«وَصَلَ» means to join and connect (m. l), i.e., to mix one thing with another so that it becomes rooted. And «وَصَّلَ» contains an intensive form. And «وَاصِلُ الشَّیء» or «وَاصِلُ بِالشَّیء» means to do something with continuity (manjad). For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَقَدۡ وَصَّلۡنَا لَہُمُ الۡقَوۡلَ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَتَذَکَّرُوۡنَ» (28/51). Translation: And We repeatedly sent them the words (of guidance) so that they might take heed."
    }
  ],
  "557": [
    {
      "id": 2532,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "«رَجَعَ» means for something to return to its beginning or origin (98 verses: 2:18-2:28-2:196-2:210-2:245-2:281-3:55-3:72-3:83-3:109-5:48-5:105-6:36-6:60-6:108-6:164-7:150-7:168-7:174-8:44-9:83-9:94-9:122-10:4-10:23-10:46-10:56-10:70-11:4-11:34-11:123-12:46-12:50-12:62-12:63-12:81-19:40-20:40-20:86-20:89-20:91-21:13-21:35-21:58-21:64-21:95-22:76-23:99-23:115-24:28-24:64-27:28-27:35-27:37-28:39-28:70-28:88-29:8-29:17-29:57-30:11-30:41-31:15-31:23-32:11-32:12-32:21-33:13-34:31-35:4-36:22-36:31-36:50-36:67-36:83-37:68-39:7-39:44-40:77-41:21-41:50-43:28-43:48-43:85-45:15-46:27-50:3-56:87-57:5-57:13-60:10-63:8-67:3-67:4-86:8-86:11-89:28-96:8)",
      "d": "«رَجَعَ» means for something to return to its origin or beginning, whether it is a living being or inanimate, a statement or an action. Also, the intention of the one returning may or may not be involved (muf). A famous saying is: «کُلُّ شَیْءٍ یَرْجِعْ اِلٰی اَصْلِہٖ» meaning everything returns to its origin. Thus, this word is generally used in all respects. For example, in the Quran: «الَّذِیۡنَ اِذَاۤ  اَصَابَتۡہُمۡ مُّصِیۡبَۃٌ   ۙ قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّا لِلّٰہِ وَ  اِنَّاۤ اِلَیۡہِ رٰجِعُوۡنَ» (2/156). Translation: Those who, when a calamity afflicts them, say, 'Indeed, we belong to Allah, and indeed, to Him we will return.' And «اَرْجَعَ» means to bring back. For example, the divine declaration is: «وَ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ تُرۡجَعُ  الۡاُمُوۡرُ» (2/210). Translation: And all matters are returned to Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2533,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "«اٰبَ» means for a living being to return, with or without intention. «اَوَّبَ» means for a living being to return frequently with intention (7 verses: 17:25-38:17-38:19-38:30-38:44-50:32-88:25)",
      "d": "«اٰبَ» is more specific than «رَجَعَ» and applies only to living beings. And «مَاٰب» means place of return, destination (muf. manjad). And «اَیَاب» means to return, to come back, or the journey of return. And «ذِھَاب و اِیَاب» means to go and return. In «اٰبَ», the intention of the one returning is not necessarily involved. For example, in the Quran: «اِنَّ  اِلَیۡنَاۤ  اِیَابَہُمۡ ثُمَّ  اِنَّ  عَلَیۡنَا حِسَابَہُمۡ» (88/25,26). Translation: Indeed, to Us is their return, then indeed, upon Us is their account. And when this verb enters the form of intensiveness, e.g., «اٰوَبَ» and «اَوَّبَ», then the intention of the one returning is also involved. «اَوَّاب» means one who returns, one who frequently reverts. For example, the divine declaration is: «فَاِنَّہٗ  کَانَ  لِلۡاَوَّابِیۡنَ غَفُوۡرًا» (17/25). Translation: Indeed, He is ever Forgiving to those who return (to Him)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2534,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "«تَابَ» means to revert from sinful deeds (62 verses: 2:37-2:54-2:128-2:160-2:187-2:222-3:89-3:90-3:128-4:16-4:17-4:18-4:26-4:27-4:64-4:92-4:146-5:34-5:39-5:71-5:74-6:54-7:153-9:5-9:11-9:15-9:27-9:74-9:102-9:104-9:106-9:117-9:118-9:126-11:3-11:52-11:61-11:90-11:112-13:30-16:119-19:60-20:82-20:122-24:5-24:10-24:31-25:70-25:71-28:67-33:24-33:73-40:3-40:7-42:25-49:12-58:13-66:4-66:8-73:20-85:10-110:3)",
      "d": "«تَابَ» means to return from sinful deeds, to acknowledge sin and resolve not to repeat it, i.e., to repent (muf). And if it is attributed to Allah, it means to accept repentance, to forgive sins, or to be merciful. For example, in the Quran: «اِلَّا الَّذِیۡنَ تَابُوۡا وَ اَصۡلَحُوۡا وَ بَیَّنُوۡا فَاُولٰٓئِکَ اَتُوۡبُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  ۚ وَ اَنَا التَّوَّابُ الرَّحِیۡمُ» (2/160). Translation: But those who repent, reform, and clarify (their matters) - it is they to whom I will turn in forgiveness, and I am the Accepting of repentance, the Merciful."
    },
    {
      "id": 2535,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "«اَنَاب» means to keep returning repeatedly (6 verses: 13:27-31:15-38:24-38:34-39:17-60:4)",
      "d": "«نَابَ اِلَیْہِ» means to keep coming to someone repeatedly. And «نَوْبَۃ» means turn, occasion, opportunity. And «اَنَاب» means to be a substitute, to act as a deputy. And «اَنَابَ اِلَی اللہ» means to repeatedly turn towards Allah and revert (manjad). For example, in the Quran: «رَبَّنَا عَلَیۡکَ تَوَکَّلۡنَا وَ اِلَیۡکَ اَنَبۡنَا» (60/4). Translation: Our Lord, we have put our trust in You and to You we turn (in repentance)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2536,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "«بَاءَ» means to return to a bad state (5 verses: 2:61-2:90-3:112-3:162-8:16)",
      "d": "The basic meanings of «بَوْء» are two: (1) to return, and (2) to be equivalent (m. l). That is, to return in a state where the recompense for one's deeds comes before them. This is generally used in a negative sense, i.e., to return from a good state to a bad state. For example, in the Quran: «وَ بَآءُوۡ بِغَضَبٍ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ  ؕ ذٰلِکَ بِاَنَّہُمۡ کَانُوۡا یَکۡفُرُوۡنَ بِاٰیٰتِ اللّٰہِ وَ یَقۡتُلُوۡنَ النَّبِیّٖنَ بِغَیۡرِ الۡحَقِّ» (2/61). Translation: And they returned with anger from Allah. That is because they used to disbelieve in the signs of Allah and kill the prophets without right. Meaning, their state became such that they deserved to be seized by Allah's anger."
    },
    {
      "id": 2538,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "«صَدَرَ» means to return after quenching thirst at a well or trough (2 verses: 28:23-99:6)",
      "d": "«صَدَرَ» means to return after drinking one's fill from a well or trough. And «اَصْدَر» means to return after being satisfied with water. It is said: «صَدَرَتِ الْاِبِلُ مِنَ الْمَاءِ» meaning the camels returned after drinking water. For example, in the Quran: «قَالَتَا لَا نَسۡقِیۡ حَتّٰی یُصۡدِرَ الرِّعَآءُ» (28/23). Translation: The two girls said, 'We will not water until the shepherds have returned (after watering).' And the opposite of «صَدَرَ» is «وَرَدَ», i.e., to reach the well to drink water (muf). And «وِرْدُ» means both the well and the thirsty one. And «وَارِد» means the person who goes to the well to bring water. For example, in the Quran: «وَ جَآءَتۡ سَیَّارَۃٌ  فَاَرۡسَلُوۡا وَارِدَہُمۡ فَاَدۡلٰی دَلۡوَہٗ» (12/19). Translation: And a caravan came, and they sent their water-drawer, and he let down his bucket."
    },
    {
      "id": 2539,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "«صَارَ» means to ultimately return, to end up (29 verses: 2:126-2:285-3:28-3:162-4:97-4:115-5:18-8:16-9:73-14:30-22:48-22:72-24:42-24:57-25:15-31:14-35:18-40:3-42:15-42:53-48:6-50:43-57:15-58:8-60:4-64:3-64:10-66:9-67:6)",
      "d": "The basic meanings of «صَیْر» are two: (1) return, and (2) outcome (m. l). Details of outcome are discussed elsewhere. It means to ultimately return, to end up, or to revert. For example, in the Quran: «اَلَاۤ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ  تَصِیۡرُ الۡاُمُوۡرُ» (42/53). Translation: Do they not see that all matters ultimately return to Allah?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2541,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "«اِنْقَلَبَ» means to change one's direction or state completely to the opposite of what it was (32 verses: 2:143-2:144-3:127-3:144-3:149-3:174-3:196-5:21-6:110-7:119-7:125-9:48-9:95-12:62-16:46-18:18-18:36-22:11-24:37-24:44-26:50-26:219-26:227-29:21-33:66-40:4-43:14-47:19-48:12-67:4-83:31-84:9)",
      "d": "«قَلَبَ» means to turn or change a direction or state, to invert the upper part to the lower and the lower to the upper, the outer to the inner and the inner to the outer. And «اِنْقَلَبَ» means to change one's state or direction in a way that is completely opposite to the original. To turn around, to reverse, to change (manjad). For example, in the Quran: «سَیَحۡلِفُوۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ لَکُمۡ اِذَا انۡقَلَبۡتُمۡ اِلَیۡہِمۡ» (9/95). Translation: They will swear by Allah to you when you have returned to them (after the treaty)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2542,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "«اَفَاضَ» means to return in a continuous flow or throng (6 verses: 2:199-5:83-7:50-9:92-10:61-46:8)",
      "d": "«فَاضَ الْمَاءَ» means for water to gush out from a place and flow. And «اَفَاضَ الْاِنَاءَ» means to fill a vessel to the brim so that water overflows. By analogy to the overflowing of water, this word is also used for people returning in a flowing crowd (muf). For example, in the Quran: «ثُمَّ  اَفِیۡضُوۡا مِنۡ حَیۡثُ اَفَاضَ النَّاسُ» (2/199). Translation: Then return from where the people have returned."
    }
  ],
  "558": [
    {
      "id": 2544,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "The Preserved Tablet and Its Various Types",
      "hw": "لوح محفوظ",
      "s": "«اللوح المحفوظ» (Al-Lawh al-Mahfuz) is the Preserved Tablet on which the decree (divine knowledge) of the entire universe is inscribed. From this knowledge, Allah grants as much as He wills to whomever He wills. The Preserved Tablet is protected from the interference of creation. Nothing can be stolen from it, nor can there be any alteration (1 Verse: 85:22).",
      "d": "The literal meaning of «اللوح المحفوظ» is simply 'the Preserved Tablet'. Its complete comprehension, i.e., intellectual grasp, is beyond human capacity; however, through narrations, it is known that it is a Tablet or Book in which all matters concerning the decree of the universe are written beforehand, and there is no change or alteration in them. The Quranic verses shed light on it by various names, as listed below:\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«بَلۡ ہُوَ  قُرۡاٰنٌ  مَّجِیۡدٌ فِیۡ  لَوۡحٍ مَّحۡفُوۡظٍ» (85/21,22)\nTranslation: Rather, it is a Glorious Quran, (inscribed) in a Preserved Tablet.\nFrom this, it is known that the Noble Quran has been taken from the Preserved Tablet."
    },
    {
      "id": 2545,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "The Preserved Tablet and Its Various Types",
      "hw": "لوح محفوظ",
      "s": "«أُمُّ الْكِتَاب» (Umm al-Kitab) refers to the Noble Quran, as the source of all divine commands, decrees, and words is the Quran. (3 Verses: 3:7-13:39-43:4)",
      "d": "«أُمُّ الْكِتَاب» refers to the Noble Quran, as the source of all divine commands, decrees, and words is the Quran.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّا جَعَلۡنٰہُ  قُرۡءٰنًا عَرَبِیًّا  لَّعَلَّکُمۡ تَعۡقِلُوۡنَ وَ اِنَّہٗ  فِیۡۤ  اُمِّ الۡکِتٰبِ لَدَیۡنَا لَعَلِیٌّ حَکِیۡمٌ» (43/3,4)\nTranslation: Indeed, We have made it an Arabic Quran that you might understand. And indeed, it is, in the Mother of the Book with Us, exalted in position and full of wisdom.\nBy stating in the Quran that it is in the 'Umm al-Kitab', an important reality is clarified: that the various Books revealed to different Prophets in different times and for different nations and peoples all invited to the same creed. The standard of good and evil is the same, and the principles of morality and civilization are uniform. That is, the religion has been one. As for the Shariah, the divine command regarding change in legal rulings according to circumstances and conditions is:\n«یَمۡحُوا اللّٰہُ مَا یَشَآءُ وَ یُثۡبِتُ   ۚ ۖ وَ عِنۡدَہٗۤ   اُمُّ   الۡکِتٰبِ» (13/39)\nTranslation: Allah eliminates what He wills and confirms what He wills. And with Him is the Mother of the Book.\nThis verse shows that the record of changes and alterations in legal rulings across different times is also present in this Book."
    },
    {
      "id": 2546,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "The Preserved Tablet and Its Various Types",
      "hw": "لوح محفوظ",
      "s": "«إِمَامٌ مُبِین» (Imamun Mubin) is the Preserved Tablet in the sense that everything is written in it beforehand. (1 Verse: 36:12)",
      "d": "«إِمَامٌ مُبِین» is the Preserved Tablet in the sense that everything is written in it beforehand.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ كُلَّ شَیۡءٍ اَحۡصَیۡنٰہُ  فِیۡۤ   إِمَامٍ  مُّبِیۡنٍ» (36/12)\nTranslation: And We have encompassed all things in a clear Book (Imam Mubin)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2547,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "The Preserved Tablet and Its Various Types",
      "hw": "لوح محفوظ",
      "s": "«كِتَابٌ مَّكْنُوْن» (Kitabun Maknun) is the Preserved Tablet in the sense that the details of what is written in it are known to none except Allah. (1 Verse: 56:78)",
      "d": "«كِتَابٌ مَّكْنُوْن» is the Preserved Tablet in the sense that the details of what is written in it are known to none except Allah.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّہٗ   لَقُرۡاٰنٌ   کَرِیۡمٌ فِیۡ  كِتٰبٍ مَّکۡنُوۡنٍ» (56/77,78)\nTranslation: Indeed, it is a noble Quran, in a well-protected Book.\nFrom this verse, it is known that the details of what is written in it are known to no one besides Allah, not even to Gabriel (peace be upon him), who is the means of conveying revelation to the Prophets."
    }
  ],
  "559": [
    {
      "id": 2548,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Female Slave / Male Slave",
      "hw": "غلام",
      "s": "«عَبْد» (Abd) meaning slave. (123 Verses: 2:23-2:90-2:178-2:186-2:207-2:221-3:15-3:20-3:30-3:79-4:118-4:172-5:118-6:18-6:61-6:88-7:32-7:128-7:194-8:41-9:104-10:107-12:24-14:11-14:31-15:40-15:42-15:49-16:2-16:75-17:1-17:3-17:5-17:17-17:30-17:53-17:65-17:96-18:1-18:65-18:102-18:110-19:2-19:30-19:61-19:63-19:93-20:77-21:26-21:105-23:109-24:32-25:1-25:17-25:58-25:63-26:22-26:52-27:15-27:19-27:59-28:82-29:56-29:62-30:48-34:9-34:13-34:39-35:28-35:31-35:32-35:45-36:30-37:40-37:74-37:81-37:111-37:122-37:128-37:132-37:160-37:169-37:171-38:17-38:30-38:41-38:44-38:45-38:83-39:7-39:10-39:16-39:17-39:36-39:46-39:53-40:15-40:31-40:44-40:48-40:85-42:19-42:23-42:25-42:27-42:52-43:15-43:19-43:59-43:68-44:18-44:23-50:8-50:11-53:10-54:9-57:9-66:10-71:27-72:19-76:6-89:29-96:10)",
      "d": "«عَبْد» (Abd) means slave, servant. It also signifies expressing humility and submission. And the word «عَبَادَۃ» (Ibadah) is stronger than «عَبُوْدِیَت» (Ubudiyyah), meaning to express extreme humility and submission. And worship is solely for Allah. Although, in a general sense of subjugation, all creation is a slave («عَبْد») of Allah. However, Allah declares a servant as «عَبْد» who, by his own choice, becomes His sincere servant. And this choice is only for humans and jinn. The plural of «عَبْد» is both «عِبَاد» and «عَبِیْد». Another meaning of «عَبْد» is to become a slave of something. It is also used metaphorically, such as «عَبدُ الدِّرْہم» and «عَبدُ الدِّیْنَار» meaning a slave or devotee of money and wealth, or «عَبدُ الطَّاغُوت». «عَبْد» also means someone's slave, whether acquired by purchase, inheritance, or as war booty. Its opposite is «حُرّ» (Hurr) meaning free. And «عَبَّدَ» means to make someone else a slave (26/22).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلۡحُرُّ بِالۡحُرِّ وَ الۡعَبۡدُ بِالۡعَبۡدِ وَ الۡاُنۡثٰی بِالۡاُنۡثٰی» (2/178)\nTranslation: The free for the free, the slave for the slave, and the female for the female."
    },
    {
      "id": 2549,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Female Slave / Male Slave",
      "hw": "غلام",
      "s": "«أَمَة» (Ama) meaning female slave. (2 Verses: 2:221-24:32)",
      "d": "«أَمَة» is the feminine form of «عَبْد». It means female slave. This word is also used in all the same senses in which «عَبْد» is used. The plural of «أَمَة» is «إِمَاء».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ أَنكِحُوا الأَيَامَى مِنكُمۡ وَ الصَّالِحِینَ مِنۡ عِبَادِكُمۡ وَ إِمَاءِكُمۡ» (24/32)\nTranslation: And marry the unmarried among you and the righteous among your male slaves and female slaves.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ لَا أَمَةٌ مُؤْمِنَةٌ خَيْرٌ مِن مُشْرِكَةٍ وَلَوْ أَعْجَبَتْكُم» (2/221)\nTranslation: And a believing female slave is better than a polytheist woman, even if she pleases you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2550,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Female Slave / Male Slave",
      "hw": "غلام",
      "s": "«رَقَبَۃ» (Raqabah) meaning slave or female slave, regardless of how they come into one's possession. (4 Verses: 4:92-5:89-58:3-90:13)",
      "d": "«رَقَبَۃ» means neck, or the part behind the neck, or the nape. And «رَقَبَ» means to put a rope or noose around someone's neck. The Arabs generally use it to mean the whole person («جُزْءُ أَشَرْف»). Thus, «رَقَبَۃ» is taken to mean a slave, because the noose of slavery is on his neck. Its plural is «رِقَاب». (See Mufradat, Manjad). And the word «رَقَبَۃ» is used equally for both masculine and feminine, i.e., for both a male slave and a female slave.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ آتَی الْمَالَ عَلَى حُبِّهِ ذَوِي الْقُرْبَى وَ الْیَتَامَى وَ الْمَسَاکِینَ وَ ابْنَ السَّبِیلِ وَ السَّائِلِینَ وَ فِی الرِّقَابِ» (2/177)\nTranslation: And those who give wealth, in spite of love for it, to relatives, orphans, the needy, the traveler, those who ask, and for freeing necks (i.e., slaves). (Jalandhari)"
    }
  ],
  "560": [
    {
      "id": 2552,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Take",
      "hw": "لینا",
      "s": "«أَخَذَ» (Akhadha) meaning to acquire something, to take into possession, to seize. (121 Verses: 2:48-2:55-2:63-2:83-2:84-2:93-2:206-2:229-2:255-2:260-2:267-3:11-3:81-3:160-3:187-4:20-4:21-4:71-4:89-4:91-4:102-4:118-4:153-4:154-4:161-5:12-5:14-5:41-5:70-6:42-6:44-6:46-6:70-7:31-7:73-7:78-7:91-7:94-7:95-7:96-7:130-7:144-7:145-7:150-7:154-7:155-7:165-7:169-7:171-7:172-7:199-8:52-8:68-8:70-9:5-9:50-9:103-9:104-10:24-11:56-11:64-11:67-11:94-11:102-12:76-12:78-12:79-12:80-13:32-15:73-15:83-16:46-16:47-16:113-18:77-18:79-19:12-19:78-19:87-20:21-20:39-20:94-22:44-22:48-23:41-23:64-23:76-24:2-26:189-28:40-29:14-29:37-29:40-33:7-33:61-34:51-35:26-36:49-38:44-40:5-40:21-40:22-41:17-43:48-44:47-48:15-48:19-48:20-51:16-51:40-51:44-54:42-55:41-57:8-57:15-59:7-69:10-69:30-69:45-73:16-79:25)",
      "d": "«أَخَذَ» means to acquire something, to take into possession, to seize. (See Mufradat). Its usage is both literal (i.e., for something perceptible by one of the five senses) and metaphorical.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ إِذْ أَخَذَ اللَّهُ مِيثَاقَ النَّبِيِّینَ» (3/81)\nTranslation: And when Allah took the covenant from the Prophets.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَلَمَّا سَكَتَ عَن مُوسَى الْغَضَبُ أَخَذَ الْأَلْوَاحَ» (7/154)\nTranslation: And when the anger subsided from Moses, he took up the tablets."
    },
    {
      "id": 2553,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Take",
      "hw": "لینا",
      "s": "«تَلَقَّی» (Talaqqa) meaning to reach something and take it. (4 Verses: 3:143-21:103-24:15-50:17)",
      "d": "«لَقِیَ» (Laqiya) means to meet, to encounter. And «تَلَقَّی الشَّیْء» means to meet, to receive (See Manjad). So, the meaning of «تَلَقَّی» is to go, meet, and take something.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَا يَحْزُنُهُمُ الْفَزَعُ الْأَكْبَرُ وَ تَتَلَقَّاهُمُ الْمَلَائِكَةُ» (21/103)\nTranslation: The greatest terror will not grieve them, and the angels will meet them (to receive them)."
    }
  ],
  "561": [
    {
      "id": 2555,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Lend/Borrow",
      "hw": "لین دین",
      "s": "«تَدَایَن» (Tadayan) is used for lending and borrowing by hand (i.e., physically handing over). And «أَدَارَ» (Adara) is used for lending and borrowing on credit. (1 Verse: 2:282)",
      "d": "«دَیْن» (Dayn) means loan, credit (see details under 'Adhar'). And «تَدَایَنَ» (Tadayana) means to borrow from each other on credit, to lend and borrow on credit (See Manjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَا أَیُّهَا الَّذِینَ آمَنُوا إِذَا تَدَایَنْتُم بِدَیْنٍ إِلَى أَجَلٍ مُسَمًّی فَاكْتُبُوهُ» (2/282)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when you contract a debt for a specified term, write it down."
    },
    {
      "id": 2556,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Lending and borrowing",
      "hw": "لین دین",
      "s": "«adara» means to circulate, to rotate. (1 verse: 2:282)",
      "d": "«dawar, dara» means to revolve, to circulate. And «adarah» means to circulate, to rotate. And «adara al-shay'» means to take and give something.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ تَکُوۡنَ تِجَارَۃً حَاضِرَۃً  تُدِیۡرُوۡنَہَا بَیۡنَکُمۡ» (2/282)\nTranslation: Yes, if the trade is hand-to-hand (immediate), then you take and give among yourselves (there is no need to write it down)."
    }
  ],
  "562": [
    {
      "id": 2557,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«daraba» means to hit someone with a hand or something else. (13 verses: 2:60-2:61-2:73-3:112-4:34-7:160-8:12-8:50-26:63-37:93-38:44-47:4-47:27)",
      "d": "«daraba» generally, its pattern has «ب», meaning to hit someone with a hand or something else. And after the pattern «ب», the thing is mentioned with which one is hit. That is, the instrument of hitting. This word is commonly used for hitting (f l 188).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ الۡحَجَرَ» (2/60)\nTranslation: So we said to Moses: Strike the rock with your staff."
    },
    {
      "id": 2558,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«wakaza» means to strike with the heel. (1 verse: 28:15)",
      "d": "«wakaza» means to strike with the heel. And according to the scholar of language, to strike with the palm or heel on the chest or side (f l 188).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَوَکَزَہٗ  مُوۡسٰی فَقَضٰی عَلَیۡہِ» (28/15)\nTranslation: So Moses struck him with his heel, and he died."
    },
    {
      "id": 2559,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«sakka» means to slap with the hand on the face. (1 verse: 51:29)",
      "d": "«sakka» means for two things to strike each other with force and intensity so that a sound is produced. «sakka al-baba» means the door's latch striking each other (m l). And it means to slap on the face, to give a slap, to slap the face (f l 188).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَصَکَّتۡ وَجۡہَہَا وَ قَالَتۡ عَجُوۡزٌ  عَقِیۡمٌ» (51/29)\nTranslation: So she (the woman) slapped her face and said, 'Am I an old barren woman?' (that a boy is born?)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2560,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«dalla» means to push. (2 verses: 52:13-107:2)",
      "d": "«dalla» means to push. To repel with force (f l 188).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَذٰلِکَ الَّذِیۡ یَدُعُّ  الۡیَتِیۡمَ» (107/2)\nTranslation: So such a man pushes the orphan."
    },
    {
      "id": 2561,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«damagha» means to strike on the head or brain. (1 verse: 21:18)",
      "d": "«damagha» means to strike someone on the brain or head (muf).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«بَلۡ نَقۡذِفُ بِالۡحَقِّ عَلَی الۡبَاطِلِ فَیَدۡمَغُہٗ» (21/18)\nTranslation: Rather, we cast truth upon falsehood, so it smashes its brain."
    },
    {
      "id": 2562,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«rajama» means to stone from a distance. To stone to death. (6 verses: 11:91-18:20-18:22-19:46-36:18-44:20)",
      "d": "«rajama» means to throw stones or pebbles at someone from a distance. And to throw stones or pebbles at someone from a distance and kill them. To stone to death. It comes in both meanings. And it is used in both material and spiritual senses. «رَجْمًا بِالْغَیْب» (18/22) means also to throw stones without seeing the target, and to speak based on conjecture (m q).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَا رَہۡطُکَ لَرَجَمۡنٰکَ» (11/91)\nTranslation: If it were not for your clan, we would have stoned you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2563,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«waqadha» means to deliver a severe blow with a stick or stone. (1 verse: 5:3)",
      "d": "«waqadha» means to deliver a severe blow with a stick or stone so that it dies. And «waqadh» means severe blow (muf). And «waqadha» means lethal, i.e., delivering a blow that causes destruction (minjad)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2564,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«nataha» means for an animal to strike with its horns. (1 verse: 5:3)",
      "d": "«nataha» means for a bull to strike with its horns. «تَنَاطَعَ الْکَبْشَان» means two rams striking each other. And «نَطِیْح» means struck with horns, an animal that died from horn strike (minjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ الۡمُنۡخَنِقَۃُ وَ الۡمَوۡقُوۡذَۃُ وَ الۡمُتَرَدِّیَۃُ وَ النَّطِیۡحَۃُ» (5/3)\nTranslation: The animal that dies by strangulation, by a violent blow, by a fall, or by horn strike (all these are forbidden to you)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2566,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To kill; to die",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«mata» means the soul separating from the body. It is general. (30 verses: 2:28-2:161-2:258-2:259-3:91-3:144-3:156-6:122-6:162-7:158-9:84-9:116-9:125-10:56-15:23-17:75-22:58-22:66-23:80-26:81-30:40-40:68-44:8-45:21-45:26-47:34-50:43-53:44-57:2-80:21)",
      "d": "«mata» means death, and its opposite is «hayat» meaning life. «mata» means for a living being to lose its soul or power (m l). The separation of soul from the body. To die. In any form.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا وَ مَاتُوۡا وَ ہُمۡ کُفَّارٌ» (2/161)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who disbelieved and died while they were disbelievers.\nAnd «amata» means to cause death to someone else. To end their life.\nFor example: The divine command is:\n«ثُمَّ یُمِیۡتُکُمۡ ثُمَّ یُحۡیِیۡکُمۡ ثُمَّ  اِلَیۡہِ تُرۡجَعُوۡنَ» (2/28)\nTranslation: Then He will cause you to die, then He will give you life, then to Him you will be returned."
    },
    {
      "id": 2567,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Killing / Dying",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«قَتَلَ» means to kill someone unjustly. And «قَتَّل» means to kill in a brutal manner. (77 verses: 2:54-2:61-2:72-2:85-2:87-2:91-2:154-2:178-2:191-2:217-2:251-3:21-3:112-3:144-3:154-3:156-3:157-3:158-3:168-3:169-3:181-3:183-3:195-4:29-4:66-4:74-4:89-4:91-4:92-4:93-4:155-4:157-5:27-5:28-5:30-5:32-5:33-5:70-5:95-6:137-6:140-6:151-7:127-7:141-7:150-8:17-8:30-9:5-9:111-12:9-12:10-17:31-17:33-18:74-20:40-22:58-25:68-26:14-28:9-28:19-28:20-28:33-29:24-33:16-33:26-33:61-40:25-40:26-40:28-47:4-51:10-60:12-74:19-74:20-80:17-81:9-85:4)",
      "d": "«قَتَلَ» means to overpower one living being over another and end its life. In the words of Ibn Faris, it means to kill someone in a state of humiliation (m l). For example, in the Quran: «قَالَ اَقَتَلۡتَ نَفۡسًا زَکِیَّۃًۢ بِغَیۡرِ نَفۡسٍ» (18/74) Translation: Moses (peace be upon him) said to Khidr, 'Have you killed a pure soul without just cause?' And «قَتَّلَ» means to kill by causing pain and inflicting injuries. For example, in the Quran: «قَالَ سَنُقَتِّلُ اَبۡنَآءَہُمۡ وَ نَسۡتَحۡیٖ نِسَآءَہُمۡ» (7/127) Translation: Pharaoh said, 'We will kill their sons and let their daughters live.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2568,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Killing / Dying",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«ھَلَکَ» means to perish, to die helplessly, and it is used for non-living things as well. (63 verses: 2:195-2:205-3:117-4:176-5:17-6:6-6:26-6:47-6:131-7:4-7:129-7:155-7:164-7:173-8:42-8:54-9:42-10:13-11:117-12:85-14:13-15:4-17:16-17:17-17:58-18:59-19:74-19:98-20:128-20:134-21:6-21:9-21:95-22:45-23:48-26:139-26:208-27:49-28:43-28:58-28:59-28:78-28:88-29:31-32:26-36:31-38:3-40:34-43:8-44:37-45:24-46:27-46:35-47:13-50:36-53:50-54:51-67:28-69:5-69:6-69:29-77:16-90:6)",
      "d": "«ھَلَکَ» means to perish (manjad). It applies to both living and non-living things. For living beings, it means to die helplessly. In the words of Ibn Faris, it indicates 'breaking and falling' (m l). To die as a result of an accident. For example, in the Quran: «اِنِ امۡرُؤٌا ہَلَکَ لَیۡسَ لَہٗ وَلَدٌ» (4/176) Translation: If a person dies and has no children. Another verse: «کُلُّ شَیۡءٍ ہَالِکٌ اِلَّا وَجۡہَہٗ» (28/88) Translation: Everything will perish except His Face. And «اَہۡلَکَ» means to cause someone to die in such a miserable or helpless manner. To destroy, to annihilate. For example: «قُلۡ اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ اِنۡ اَہۡلَکَنِیَ اللّٰہُ وَ مَنۡ مَّعِیَ» (67/28) Translation: Say, 'Have you considered if Allah were to destroy me and those with me?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2569,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Killing / Dying",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«صَلَبَ» means to crucify. «صَلَّبَ» means to crucify with torture. (6 verses: 4:157-5:33-7:124-12:41-20:71-26:49)",
      "d": "«صَلَبَ» means to hang on a cross or to crucify. And «صَلَّبَ» means to crucify someone while inflicting additional torture or to hang them in an inverted position to increase suffering. For example, in the Quran: «وَ مَا قَتَلُوۡہُ وَ مَا صَلَبُوۡہُ وَ لٰکِنۡ شُبِّہَ لَہُمۡ» (4/157) Translation: They neither killed nor crucified him, but it was made to appear so to them. And «صَلَّبَ»: For example, Allah says: «فَلَاُقَطِّعَنَّ اَیۡدِیَکُمۡ وَ اَرۡجُلَکُمۡ مِّنۡ خِلَافٍ وَّ لَاُصَلِّبَنَّکُمۡ فِیۡ جُذُوۡعِ النَّخۡلِ» (20/71) Translation: (Pharaoh said to the believing magicians) 'I will surely cut off your hands and feet from opposite sides and crucify you on the trunks of palm trees.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2570,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Killing / Dying",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«ذَبَّحَ» means to kill by inflicting pain intermittently. (9 verses: 2:49-2:67-2:71-5:3-14:6-27:21-28:4-37:102-37:107)",
      "d": "«ذَبَحَ» means to slaughter an animal in the prescribed Islamic manner, to shed blood. And «ذَبَّحَ» means to slaughter while causing pain or to emphasize the act of slaughtering (manjad). In this sense, «ذَبَّحَ» and «قَتَّلَ» become synonymous. For example, in the Quran: «یُذَبِّحُ اَبۡنَآءَہُمۡ وَ یَسۡتَحۡیٖ نِسَآءَہُمۡ» (28/4) Translation: Pharaoh used to slaughter the sons of the Children of Israel and spare their daughters."
    },
    {
      "id": 2571,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Killing / Dying",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«رَجَمَ» means to stone to death. To kill by throwing stones. (6 verses: 11:91-18:20-18:22-19:46-36:18-44:20)",
      "d": "«رَجَمَ» means to throw stones from a distance or to kill by pelting with stones. And «رَجَم» is one of the Hudud (prescribed punishments) in Islam, meaning that a married adulterer or adulteress is to be killed by being pelted with stones from a distance. To stone to death. For example, in the Quran: «لَئِنۡ لَّمۡ تَنۡتَہِ لَاَرۡجُمَنَّکَ» (19/46) Translation: (Azar said to Abraham) 'If you do not desist, I will certainly stone you.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2572,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Killing / Dying",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«اِنْخَنَقَ» means for a living being to die by strangulation. (1 verse: 5:3)",
      "d": "«خَنَقَ» means to strangle. And «خِنَاق» is the rope used for strangling. «خُنَّاق» is the disease where the throat constricts and breathing becomes difficult (manjad). «خَنَقَ» means to strangle severely to the point of death (m q). «مُنْخَنِقٌ» means an animal that dies due to strangulation. For example, in the Quran: «وَ الۡمُنۡخَنِقَۃُ وَ الۡمَوۡقُوۡذَۃُ» (5/3) Translation: And that which dies by strangulation and that which is beaten to death (all these are forbidden)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2573,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Killing / Dying",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«تَوَفّٰی» means to complete the lifespan, to take the soul. This is solely the act of Allah the Almighty or His appointed angels. (30 verses: 2:234-2:240-2:281-3:55-3:161-3:185-3:193-4:15-4:97-5:117-6:60-6:61-7:37-7:126-8:50-10:46-10:104-12:101-13:40-16:28-16:32-16:70-16:111-22:5-32:11-39:42-40:67-40:77-47:27-83:2)",
      "d": "The root «وَفٰی» implies completion and fulfillment of something (m l). «تَوَفّٰی» means to take the soul from the body upon completion of the appointed term, to seize it. This act belongs solely to Allah or His angels, hence it cannot be attributed to a human or any other living being in this sense. For example, Allah says: «تَوَفَّنِیۡ مُسۡلِمًا وَّ اَلۡحِقۡنِیۡ بِالصّٰلِحِیۡنَ» (12/101) Translation: (O Allah!) Cause me to die as a Muslim and join me with the righteous."
    },
    {
      "id": 2574,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To Kill; To Die",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«شَھَادَت» is to give up one's life in the way of Allah. (60 verses: 2:23-2:84-2:133-2:143-2:185-2:204-2:282-3:18-3:52-3:64-3:70-3:81-3:86-3:99-3:140-4:6-4:15-4:69-4:135-4:166-5:8-5:44-5:111-6:19-6:130-6:144-6:150-7:37-7:172-9:107-11:54-12:26-12:81-18:51-19:37-21:61-22:28-22:78-24:2-24:4-24:6-24:8-24:13-24:24-25:72-27:32-27:49-36:65-39:69-41:20-41:21-41:22-43:19-43:86-46:10-57:19-59:11-63:1-65:2-83:21)",
      "d": "«شَھِدَ» means to bear witness, whether that testimony is eyewitness (i.e., seen with the eyes) or from the heart. And «شَاھِدْ» and «شَھِیْد» both come in the meaning of a witness. And the word «شَھِیْد» is also used for one who gives up his life in the way of Allah for the sake of upholding the word of truth. And in this sense, martyrdom is also to give up one's life in the way of Allah, because the belief in the Hereafter and reward and punishment is so firm that he gives his life to bear witness to it. For example, the Quran states: «فَاُولٰٓئِکَ مَعَ الَّذِیۡنَ اَنۡعَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ النَّبِیّٖنَ وَ الصِّدِّیۡقِیۡنَ وَ الشُّہَدَآءِ وَ الصّٰلِحِیۡنَ» (4/69). Translation: Then these are with those upon whom Allah has bestowed His favor: the Prophets, the Siddiqeen (truthful), the Shuhada (martyrs), and the righteous."
    }
  ],
  "563": [
    {
      "id": 2577,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Wealth, Giving",
      "hw": "مال",
      "s": "«رِزْق» means all that which is physical or spiritual sustenance or a means to it. (105 verses: 2:3-2:22-2:25-2:57-2:60-2:126-2:172-2:212-2:233-2:254-3:27-3:37-3:169-4:5-4:8-4:39-5:88-5:114-6:140-6:142-6:151-7:32-7:50-7:160-8:3-8:4-8:26-8:74-10:31-10:59-10:93-11:6-11:88-12:37-13:22-13:26-14:31-14:32-14:37-16:56-16:67-16:71-16:72-16:73-16:75-16:112-16:114-17:30-17:31-17:70-18:19-19:62-20:81-20:131-20:132-22:28-22:34-22:35-22:50-22:58-24:26-24:38-27:64-28:54-28:57-28:82-29:17-29:60-29:62-30:28-30:37-30:40-32:16-33:31-34:4-34:15-34:24-34:36-34:39-35:3-35:29-36:47-37:41-38:54-39:52-40:13-40:40-40:64-42:12-42:19-42:27-42:38-45:5-45:16-50:11-51:22-51:57-56:82-63:10-65:3-65:7-65:11-67:15-67:21-89:16)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «رِزْق» is sustenance or all that which, from a physical or spiritual perspective, serves as a means for human training and reform (maf). Materially, it means that which becomes food after reaching the stomach. «رِزْق» also means fortune, destiny. And «مَرْزُوْق» means fortunate (manjad). And «رُزِقْتُ عِلْمًا» means 'I was granted knowledge.' Then, «رِزْق» also refers to all that which serves as physical or spiritual sustenance for humans. In this sense, rain is also «رِزْق». For example, in the Quran: «وَ فِی السَّمَآءِ رِزۡقُکُمۡ» (51/22) Translation: Your sustenance is in the sky. And «رَزَقَ» means to give sustenance, to feed, or to grant some wealth. «رَزَّاق» is exclusively for Allah, but the attribution of feeding can also be directed to others. For example: «وَ اِذَا حَضَرَ الۡقِسۡمَۃَ اُولُوا الۡقُرۡبٰی وَ الۡیَتٰمٰی وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنُ فَارۡزُقُوۡہُمۡ مِّنۡہُ وَ قُوۡلُوۡا لَہُمۡ قَوۡلًا مَّعۡرُوۡفًا» (4/8) Translation: And when the division of inheritance is attended by those near of kin, orphans, and the needy, give them from it and speak to them kindly."
    },
    {
      "id": 2578,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Wealth, Giving",
      "hw": "مال",
      "s": "«خَیْر» means the good aspect of wealth, i.e., wealth acquired and spent according to Shariah. (170 verses: 2:54-2:61-2:103-2:105-2:106-2:110-2:148-2:158-2:180-2:184-2:197-2:215-2:216-2:220-2:221-2:263-2:269-2:271-2:272-2:273-2:280-3:15-3:26-3:30-3:54-3:104-3:110-3:114-3:115-3:150-3:157-3:178-3:180-3:198-4:19-4:25-4:46-4:59-4:66-4:77-4:114-4:127-4:128-4:149-4:170-4:171-5:48-5:114-6:17-6:32-6:57-6:158-7:12-7:26-7:85-7:87-7:89-7:155-7:169-7:188-8:19-8:23-8:30-8:70-9:3-9:41-9:61-9:74-9:88-9:109-10:11-10:58-10:107-10:109-11:31-11:84-11:86-12:39-12:57-12:59-12:64-12:80-12:109-16:30-16:76-16:95-16:126-17:11-17:35-18:36-18:40-18:44-18:46-18:81-18:95-19:73-19:76-20:73-20:131-21:35-21:73-21:89-21:90-22:11-22:30-22:36-22:58-22:77-23:29-23:56-23:61-23:72-23:109-23:118-24:11-24:12-24:27-24:33-24:60-25:10-25:15-25:24-27:36-27:59-27:89-28:24-28:26-28:60-28:80-28:84-29:16-30:38-33:19-33:25-34:39-35:32-37:62-38:32-38:76-41:40-41:49-42:36-43:32-43:52-43:58-44:37-46:11-47:21-49:5-49:11-50:25-54:43-55:70-58:12-61:11-62:9-62:11-64:16-66:5-68:12-68:32-70:21-70:41-73:20-87:17-93:4-97:3-98:7-99:7-100:8)",
      "d": "«خَیْر» means goodness and all that which is considered good by everyone. Wealth, in its essence, is good, and Allah's granting of wealth to someone is a great blessing because through its proper use and spending according to Shariah, a person can earn many virtues and good deeds. For example, in the Quran: «قُلۡ مَاۤ اَنۡفَقۡتُمۡ مِّنۡ خَیۡرٍ فَلِلۡوَالِدَیۡنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبِیۡنَ وَ الۡیَتٰمٰی وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنِ وَ ابۡنِ‌السَّبِیۡلِ» (2/215) Translation: Say, 'Whatever you spend of good is for parents, relatives, orphans, the needy, and travelers.' But the love of wealth is ingrained in human nature. For example: «وَ اِنَّہٗ لِحُبِّ الۡخَیۡرِ لَشَدِیۡدٌ» (100/8) Translation: Indeed, man is intensely in love with wealth. So when a person neglects the distinction between lawful and unlawful in earning or does not spend it according to Shariah, then this very wealth, which is entirely good, becomes a trial and test for him. For example: «اَنَّمَاۤ اَمۡوَالُکُمۡ وَ اَوۡلَادُکُمۡ فِتۡنَۃٌ» (8/28) Translation: Your wealth and children are a great trial."
    },
    {
      "id": 2580,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Wealth and property, to grant",
      "hw": "مال",
      "s": "«مَغَانِم» refers to wealth obtained after victory over an enemy (9 verses: 4:94-6:146-8:41-8:69-20:18-21:78-48:15-48:19-48:20)",
      "d": "«غَنَم» means a herd of goats. And «اَلْغَنَمُ» means to obtain or acquire a herd of goats. Then this word began to be used for any wealth obtained from an enemy or non-enemy. And «مَغْنَم» is the plural of «مَغَانِم», meaning spoils of war. In Islamic terminology, «مَغْنَم» or spoils refer only to wealth obtained as a result of victory over an enemy. For previous nations, such wealth was prohibited, but in the Shariah of Prophet Muhammad ﷺ, Allah has made it permissible. For example, the Quran says: «فَکُلُوۡا مِمَّا غَنِمۡتُمۡ حَلٰلًا طَیِّبًا» (8/69) Translation: So eat what you have gained as lawful and good. At another place, Allah says: «تَبۡتَغُوۡنَ عَرَضَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ الدُّنۡیَا ۫ فَعِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ مَغَانِمُ کَثِیۡرَۃٌ» (4/94) Translation: You seek the benefit of worldly life, while with Allah are many spoils."
    },
    {
      "id": 2581,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Wealth and property, to grant",
      "hw": "مال",
      "s": "«اَنْفَال» refers to wealth and belongings obtained in battle with disbelievers, which is also called spoils (1 verse: 8:1)",
      "d": "«نَفَل» means spoils of war, gift, grant, excess. Its plural is «اَنْفَال». «نَفْل» means work beyond obligations and necessities. «اَنْفَال» is used for both spoils of war and fay (land conquered without fighting). This word indicates that these are additional grants from Allah to the Ummah of Muhammad, which were not permissible for previous nations. For example, the Quran says: «یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الۡاَنۡفَالِ ؕ قُلِ الۡاَنۡفَالُ لِلّٰہِ وَ الرَّسُوۡلِ» (8/1) Translation: They ask you about the spoils. Say, 'The spoils are for Allah and His Messenger.'"
    }
  ],
  "564": [
    {
      "id": 2582,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Owner",
      "hw": "مالک",
      "s": "«مَالِک» one who has authority of possession and disposal (3 verses: 1:3-3:26-36:71)",
      "d": "«مِلْک» refers to anything that is in someone's possession and no one else has the right to dispose of it. And «مَالِک» means one who has complete possession and authority over something. For example, the Quran says: «مٰلِکِ یَوۡمِ الدِّیۡنِ» (1/3) Translation: Owner of the Day of Judgment."
    },
    {
      "id": 2584,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Owner",
      "hw": "مالک",
      "s": "«اَھْل» household, family, owner of the house (69 verses: 2:196-2:126-2:217-3:121-4:25-4:35-4:58-4:75-4:92-5:89-6:131-7:83-7:94-7:100-7:123-10:24-11:40-11:45-11:46-11:81-11:117-12:26-12:62-12:65-12:88-12:93-15:65-18:71-18:77-19:16-19:55-20:10-20:29-20:132-21:76-21:84-23:27-24:27-26:169-26:170-27:7-27:34-27:49-27:57-28:4-28:15-28:29-28:59-29:31-29:32-29:33-29:34-35:43-36:50-37:76-37:134-38:43-39:15-42:45-48:11-48:12-48:26-51:26-52:26-66:6-75:33-83:31-84:9-84:13)",
      "d": "«اَھْل» means clan, relatives, household, family, wife and children. «اَھْلَ الرَّجُل» means wife, «اَھَلَ الرَّجُل» means to marry. «اَھْل» also means people of the same lineage or religion. It means both household and the house itself. In the following verse, the Quran uses «اَھْل» to mean the owner of the house. For example: «فَانۡکِحُوۡہُنَّ بِاِذۡنِ اَہۡلِہِنَّ» (4/25) Translation: Then marry them with the permission of their owners."
    }
  ],
  "565": [
    {
      "id": 2585,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Mother",
      "hw": "ماں",
      "s": "«وَالِدَۃ» a woman who has given birth (3 verses: 2:233-5:110-19:32)",
      "d": "«وَالِدَۃ» is a woman who has given birth. Mother. This word is used in limited and specific meanings. When both parents are mentioned, the plural «وَالِدَین» is used. Its plural is «وَالِدَات». For example: «وَ الۡوَالِدٰتُ یُرۡضِعۡنَ اَوۡلَادَہُنَّ حَوۡلَیۡنِ کَامِلَیۡنِ» (2/233) Translation: And mothers breastfeed their children for two complete years."
    },
    {
      "id": 2586,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Mother",
      "hw": "ماں",
      "s": "«اُمّ» means biological mother. (29 verses: 3:7-4:11-4:23-5:17-5:75-5:116-6:92-7:150-13:39-16:78-19:28-20:38-20:40-23:50-24:61-28:7-28:10-28:13-31:14-33:4-33:6-39:6-42:7-43:4-46:15-53:32-58:2-80:35-101:9)",
      "d": "The word «اُمّ» is used in a very broad meaning. «اُمّ» means both the biological mother and every thing that becomes the cause of the existence, origination, or reform and training of another thing (muf). The word «اُمّ» is used in the following ways:\n(1) As a biological mother: For example, the Quran states: «وَ اَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ  اِلٰۤی اُمِّ مُوۡسٰۤی اَنۡ  اَرۡضِعِیۡہِ» (28/7). Translation: And We inspired the mother of Moses, saying: Suckle him.\n(2) Just as the word «اَبْ» is used for the biological father as well as the grandfather, great-grandfather, and upwards through generations, similarly the word «اُمّ» is also used. Just as Prophet Adam (AS) is the father of mankind, similarly Hawwa (AS) is the mother of mankind.\n(3) Meaning origin or root. Like Umm al-Kitab (13/39) meaning the original book or the Preserved Tablet. And «اُمُّ الْقُرٰی» (6/92) meaning the central city or metaphorically, the city of Makkah. Also, Umm al-Khaba'ith meaning wine, and Umm al-Amradh meaning constipation. Umm al-Tariq meaning the public road. And Umm al-Nujum meaning the galaxy.\n(4) And as a title of honor. For example, the divine command states: «اَلنَّبِیُّ  اَوۡلٰی بِالۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ مِنۡ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ وَ اَزۡوَاجُہٗۤ  اُمَّہٰتُہُمۡ» (33/6). Translation: The Prophet is closer to the believers than themselves, and his wives are their mothers.\n(5) As a nickname. Then in this nickname, sometimes there is a clear connection, like «Umm Arba' wa Arba'in», and sometimes there is not even a minor connection, like naming a newborn girl Umm Kulthum. However, such nicknames are not mentioned in the Quran."
    }
  ],
  "566": [
    {
      "id": 2587,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To ask/request",
      "hw": "مانگنا",
      "s": "«طَلَبَ» to be eager for a need and search for it (3 verses: 7:54-18:41-22:73)",
      "d": "«طَلَبَ الشَّیْ» means to ask for something. «طِلْب» and «طِلْبَۃ» mean the thing asked for, or the search and effort to obtain something. This word comes in meanings of asking, desiring, and seeking. It is the initial state of asking. For example: «ضَعُفَ الطَّالِبُ وَ الۡمَطۡلُوۡبُ» (22/73) Translation: The seeker and the sought are both weak."
    },
    {
      "id": 2588,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To ask/request",
      "hw": "مانگنا",
      "s": "«سَاَلَ» to be eager for a need and express it to someone (93 verses: 2:61-2:108-2:119-2:134-2:141-2:186-2:189-2:215-2:217-2:219-2:220-2:222-2:273-4:32-4:153-5:4-5:101-5:102-6:90-7:6-7:163-7:187-8:1-8:12-9:65-10:72-10:94-11:29-11:46-11:47-11:51-12:50-12:82-12:104-14:34-15:92-16:43-16:56-16:93-17:85-17:101-18:70-18:76-18:83-20:105-20:132-21:7-21:13-21:23-21:63-23:72-23:113-25:57-25:59-26:109-26:127-26:145-26:164-26:180-28:78-29:13-29:61-29:63-31:25-33:8-33:20-33:53-33:63-34:25-34:47-36:21-38:86-39:38-42:23-43:9-43:19-43:44-43:45-43:87-47:36-47:37-51:12-52:40-55:29-55:39-60:10-67:8-68:46-70:1-70:10-75:6-79:42-102:8)",
      "d": "«سَاَلَ» has two meanings: (1) to ask someone something to get an answer, (2) to ask someone for a needed thing, i.e., to request for wealth or other necessity. And «سُؤْل» means a need for which one is eager and also expresses it. For example: «اِہۡبِطُوۡا مِصۡرًا فَاِنَّ لَکُمۡ مَّا سَاَلۡتُمۡ» (2/61) Translation: Go down to Egypt, for there you will get what you asked for."
    },
    {
      "id": 2589,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To ask/request",
      "hw": "مانگنا",
      "s": "«اِدَّعَ» to be eager for a need and call out to ask for it (3 verses: 36:57-41:31-67:27)",
      "d": "«دَعَا» means to ask, call out, supplicate. And «اِدَّعَ» has emphasis, i.e., to call out and ask for something. For example: «لَہُمۡ فِیۡہَا فَاکِہَۃٌ وَّ لَہُمۡ مَّا یَدَّعُوۡنَ» (36/57) Translation: And they will have fruits therein, and whatever they will ask for."
    },
    {
      "id": 2591,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To ask/request",
      "hw": "مانگنا",
      "s": "«اِعْتَرَّ» meaning to come forward to ask for forgiveness (1 verse: 22:36)",
      "d": "«عَرّ» and «اِعْتَرّ» both mean the same: to seek forgiveness and come forward for it. For example: «وَ اَطۡعِمُوا الۡقَانِعَ وَ الۡمُعۡتَرَّ» (22/36) Translation: And feed the one who does not ask and the one who asks."
    }
  ],
  "567": [
    {
      "id": 2592,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To erase",
      "hw": "مٹانا",
      "s": "«طَمَسَ» To erase by rubbing in such a way that some effects remain (5 verses: 4:47, 10:88, 36:66, 54:37, 77:8)",
      "d": "«طَمَسَ» means to erase by rubbing so that some traces or effects remain. The word «طَمَس» is generally used for the eyes, stars, and the face. The «طَمَس» of eyes and stars is that they become devoid of light, and the «طَمَس» of the face is that it becomes disfigured, i.e., it becomes ugly.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اٰمِنُوۡا بِمَا نَزَّلۡنَا مُصَدِّقًا لِّمَا مَعَکُمۡ مِّنۡ قَبۡلِ اَنۡ نَّطۡمِسَ وُجُوۡہًا» (4/47)\nTranslation: Believe in what We have revealed, confirming that which is with you, before We obliterate (i.e., erase, efface) faces (meaning, erase their eyes, noses, etc.).\nAt another place, the Divine Command states:\n«فَاِذَا النُّجُوۡمُ  طُمِسَتۡ» (77/8)\nTranslation: When the stars are obliterated (lose their light)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2593,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To erase",
      "hw": "مٹانا",
      "s": "«مَحَقَ» To terminate the power of something and render it lifeless (2 verses: 2:276, 3:141)",
      "d": "«مَحَقَ» means to make something weak and feeble, to invalidate it, to make it fruitless and lifeless (m. l.), and also means to be inferior and decrease (m.f.). Its opposite is «رَبْواً» or «رَبِّی», meaning to nurture, to rear, and to cause to grow.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَمۡحَقُ اللّٰہُ الرِّبٰوا وَ یُرۡبِی الصَّدَقٰتِ» (2/276)\nTranslation: Allah effaces (destroys) usury and causes charity to grow."
    },
    {
      "id": 2594,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To erase",
      "hw": "مٹانا",
      "s": "«مَحُو» To terminate in such a way that no trace remains (2 verses: 13:39, 17:12)",
      "d": "«مَحُو» means to erase something so completely that even its signs do not remain. One says «مَحَتِ الرِّیْحُ السَّحَابَ» (The wind carried away the clouds, leaving no trace). Its opposite is «اَثْبَتَ», meaning to establish firmly.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَمۡحُوا اللّٰہُ مَا یَشَآءُ وَ یُثۡبِتُ» (13/39)\nTranslation: Allah effaces what He wills and establishes what He wills."
    },
    {
      "id": 2595,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To erase",
      "hw": "مٹانا",
      "s": "«نَسَخَ» To erase something and replace it with another (2 verses: 2:106, 22:52)",
      "d": "«نَسَخَ» means to cause to perish, to invalidate, to transform, to erase (manj). It also means to remove one thing and bring another in its place (m.f.). The first thing that is removed or erased is called «مَنْسُوخ» (abrogated), and the second thing that replaces it is called «نَاسِخ» (abrogating). Sometimes this word is used merely in the sense of causing to perish or erasing.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَیَنۡسَخُ اللّٰہُ مَا یُلۡقِی الشَّیۡطٰنُ ثُمَّ  یُحۡکِمُ  اللّٰہُ  اٰیٰتِہٖ» (22/52)\nTranslation: So Allah will efface what Satan casts and then Allah will confirm His verses.\nAnd sometimes it is used in the sense of terminating the first thing and bringing another.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«مَا نَنۡسَخۡ مِنۡ اٰیَۃٍ اَوۡ نُنۡسِہَا نَاۡتِ بِخَیۡرٍ مِّنۡہَاۤ  اَوۡ مِثۡلِہَا» (2/106)\nTranslation: We do not abrogate a verse or cause it to be forgotten except that We bring forth [one] better than it or similar to it."
    }
  ],
  "568": [
    {
      "id": 2596,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Dust and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "«تُرَاب» Dry dust; a general term for all kinds of earth (17 verses: 2:264, 3:59, 13:5, 16:59, 18:37, 22:5, 23:35, 23:82, 27:67, 30:20, 35:11, 37:16, 37:53, 40:67, 50:3, 56:47, 78:40)",
      "d": "«تُرَاب» means dust, dry earth that has no moisture (f.l. 31), which the wind blows around. It is a general term for earth.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یَقُوۡلُ الۡکٰفِرُ یٰلَیۡتَنِیۡ  کُنۡتُ تُرٰبًا» (78/40)\nTranslation: And the disbeliever will say, \"Oh, I wish I had been dust.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 2597,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Dust and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "«طِیْن» Wet clay, but without straw in it (12 verses: 3:49, 5:110, 6:2, 7:12, 17:61, 23:12, 28:38, 32:7, 37:11, 38:71, 38:76, 51:33)",
      "d": "«طِیْن» means wet clay, but without straw in it (f.l. 31). Even if its moisture, i.e., wetness, dries up, that dry mud is still called «طِیْن». For example: The Noble Quran states:\nTranslation: And Allah originated the creation of man from clay."
    },
    {
      "id": 2598,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Dust and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "«لَازِب» Clay that sticks to the hand; sticky, adhesive clay (1 verse: 37:11)",
      "d": "«لَازِب» means clay that sticks to the hand (manj), sticky and adhesive clay (f.l. 268).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّا خَلَقۡنٰہُمۡ مِّنۡ طِیۡنٍ لَّازِبٍ» (37/11)\nTranslation: Indeed, We created them from sticky clay."
    },
    {
      "id": 2600,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Dust and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "«صَلْصَال» Dry, crackling, resonant clay (4 verses: 15:26, 15:28, 15:33, 55:14)",
      "d": "«صَلْصَال» is when black, foul-smelling mud becomes completely dry and begins to make a sound or ring when struck slightly (f.l. 168).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ مِّنۡ حَمَاٍ مَّسۡنُوۡنٍ» (15/26)\nTranslation: And We have certainly created man from an extract of clay.\nAt another place, the Divine Command states:\n«خَلَقَ الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ کَالۡفَخَّارِ» (55/14)\nTranslation: He created man from clay like pottery."
    },
    {
      "id": 2601,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Dust and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "«فَخَّار» Baked, resonant clay; pottery (1 verse: 55:14)",
      "d": "«فَخَّار» means pottery. Baked clay (manj), i.e., baked clay or earthenware that rings or sounds when struck. And «فَخَّارِی» means a potter who makes and sells earthenware (manj). The creation of man ultimately came from such clay.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«خَلَقَ الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ کَالۡفَخَّارِ» (55/14)\nTranslation: He created man from clay like pottery."
    },
    {
      "id": 2602,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Dust and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "«صَعِیْد» The upper part of the earth's surface; the dust that rises upon it (4 verses: 4:43, 5:6, 18:8, 18:40)",
      "d": "«صَعَدَ» means to ascend. And «صَعِیْد» means the upper part of the earth's surface and the dust that rises upon it (m.f.). Every smooth ground is «صَعِیْد» (f.l. 16). It also means «وَجْہُ الْاَرْض», i.e., the top layer of earth and dust, etc. (m.l.).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n« فَلَمۡ  تَجِدُوۡا مَآءً فَتَیَمَّمُوۡا صَعِیۡدًا طَیِّبًا» (5/6)\nTranslation: Then if you do not find water, then seek clean earth (for purification)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2603,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Soil and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "«Sulālah» means essence, extract, useful part, something extracted from a thing (2 verses: 23:12-32:8)",
      "d": "«Sulālah» means essence, extract, useful part, something extracted from a thing (see). For example, in the Quran: «وَلَقَدْ خَلَقْنَا الْإِنْسَانَ مِنْ سُلَٰلَةٍ مِّنْ طِينٍ» (23/12) Translation: And We have created man from an extract of clay."
    },
    {
      "id": 2604,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Soil and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "«Tharā» the wet and soft soil of the deepest part of the earth (1 verse: 20:6)",
      "d": "«Tharā» the wet and soft soil of the deepest part of the earth (see F L 31, 167). For example, in the Quran: «لَهُ مَا فِي السَّمَاوَاتِ وَمَا فِي الْأَرْضِ وَمَا بَيْنَهُمَا وَمَا تَحْتَ الثَّرَى» (20/6) Translation: To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth and whatever is between them and whatever is beneath the soil."
    }
  ],
  "569": [
    {
      "id": 2605,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "مجامعت",
      "s": "«Bāshar» means one body's skin touching another body's skin (1 verse: 2:187)",
      "d": "«Bashara» means to skin, «Basharah» means the outer side of skin, and «Bāshar» means one body's skin touching another body's skin; «Bāshar al-marā» means to have intercourse (see). For example, in the Quran: «وَلَا تُبَاشِرُوهُنَّ وَأَنْتُمْ عَاكِفُونَ فِي الْمَسَاجِدِ» (2/187) Translation: And do not have intercourse with them while you are in confinement in the mosques."
    },
    {
      "id": 2606,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "مجامعت",
      "s": "«Qaḍā waṭaran» means to fulfill a need (1 verse: 33:37)",
      "d": "«Waṭar» means need and important necessity (see), and «Qaḍā waṭaran» means to fulfill a need. For example, in the Quran: «فَلَمَّا قَضَىٰ زَيْدٌ مِنْهَا وَطَرًا» (33/37) Translation: So when Zaid had finished his need from her..."
    },
    {
      "id": 2607,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "مجامعت",
      "s": "«Taghashshā» means one thing covering another (1 verse: 7:189)",
      "d": "«Taghashshā» means one thing covering another. For example, in the Quran: «فَلَمَّا تَغَشَّاهَا حَمَلَتْ حَمْلًا خَفِيفًا» (7/189) Translation: So when he covered her, she carried a light burden."
    },
    {
      "id": 2608,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "مجامعت",
      "s": "«Rafath» any speech whose expression is considered shameful (2 verses: 2:187-2:197)",
      "d": "«Rafath» any speech whose expression is considered shameful (see) meaning to be uncovered. To talk about intercourse and related matters. For example, in the Quran: «أُحِلَّ لَكُمْ لَيْلَةَ الصِّيَامِ الرَّفَثُ إِلَىٰ نِسَائِكُمْ» (2/187) Translation: It has been made lawful for you on the night of fasting to have intercourse with your wives."
    },
    {
      "id": 2609,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "مجامعت",
      "s": "«Mass» to touch something or for something to come in contact with the body (56 verses: 2:80-2:214-2:236-2:237-2:275-3:24-3:47-3:120-3:140-3:174-5:73-6:7-6:17-6:49-7:73-7:95-7:188-7:201-8:68-10:12-10:21-10:107-11:10-11:48-11:64-11:113-12:88-15:48-15:54-16:53-17:67-17:83-19:20-19:45-20:97-21:46-21:83-24:14-24:35-26:156-30:33-33:49-35:35-36:18-38:41-39:8-39:49-39:61-41:49-41:50-41:51-50:38-54:48-56:79-70:20-70:21)",
      "d": "«Mass» means to touch something or for something to come in contact with the body (see). For example, in the Quran: «قَالَتْ رَبِّ أَنَّىٰ يَكُونُ لِي وَلَدٌ وَلَمْ يَمْسَسْنِي بَشَرٌ» (3/47) Translation: She said, 'My Lord, how can I have a child when no man has touched me?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2610,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "مجامعت",
      "s": "«Lāmasa» to touch something with fingers or to search with fingers or another body part (2 verses: 4:43-5:6)",
      "d": "«Lamasa» means to touch something with fingers. To search with fingers or another body part (see). For example, in the Quran: «أَوْ لَامَسْتُمُ النِّسَاءَ» (4/43) Translation: Or you have touched women (i.e., had intercourse)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2611,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "مجامعت",
      "s": "«Ṭamath» menstrual blood (2 verses: 55:56-55:74)",
      "d": "«Ṭamath» means menstrual blood (see) and «Ṭamitha yaṭmithu» also means for a woman to be menstruating (see) and for a man to remove the veil of chastity from a woman (see). Essentially, this word is specific for the first act of intercourse (mubāsharah) with someone. For example, in the Quran: «لَمْ يَطْمِثْهُنَّ إِنْسٌ قَبْلَهُمْ وَلَا جَانٌّ» (55/74) Translation: No human has touched them before, nor has any jinn."
    },
    {
      "id": 2612,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To have intercourse",
      "hw": "مجامعت",
      "s": "«Qaruba» to be near (36 verses: 2:35-2:187-2:222-2:237-3:167-4:11-4:43-4:172-5:8-5:82-6:151-6:152-7:19-7:114-9:28-9:99-12:60-16:77-17:32-17:34-17:57-18:24-18:81-19:52-22:13-26:42-34:37-39:3-46:28-50:16-51:27-56:11-56:85-56:88-83:21-83:28)",
      "d": "«Qaruba» means to be near, to go close. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَا تَقْرَبُوهُنَّ حَتَّىٰ يَطْهُرْنَ» (2/222) Translation: And do not approach them until they are pure. See 'to force' for compelling and 'to be restless' for being compelled."
    }
  ],
  "570": [
    {
      "id": 2613,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Assembly",
      "hw": "مجلس",
      "s": "'Majlis' refers to members of the household or friends when they sit together (1 verse: 58:11)",
      "d": "'Majlis', its plural is 'Majalis'. Every place where several people sit together for some purpose. The word 'majlis' for gatherings in homes is well-known. (f l 32. 272) For example: In the Quran it says: «اِذَا قِیۡلَ لَکُمۡ تَفَسَّحُوۡا فِی الۡمَجٰلِسِ فَافۡسَحُوۡا» (58/11) Translation: When you are asked to make room in the assemblies, then make room."
    },
    {
      "id": 2614,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Assembly",
      "hw": "مجلس",
      "s": "'Nadi' refers to specific places such as clubs, gatherings, entertainment venues where assemblies typically engage in undesirable activities (2 verses: 29:29-96:17)",
      "d": "'Nadi' is a gathering of people where conversation and storytelling are the occupation (f l 272). Clubs. Gatherings. Entertainment venues. Centers of vulgarity. And 'Al-Nadwa' meaning prosperity and welfare. National or religious consultation venues. (f l 32) For example: In the Quran it says: «وَ تَاۡتُوۡنَ فِیۡ نَادِیۡکُمُ الۡمُنۡکَرَ» (29/29) Translation: And you commit evil in your assemblies."
    }
  ],
  "571": [
    {
      "id": 2616,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love. To love.",
      "hw": "محبت",
      "s": "'Wadda' means to desire something, to befriend, to love (25 verses: 2:96-2:105-2:109-2:266-3:30-3:69-3:118-4:42-4:73-4:89-4:102-5:82-11:90-15:2-19:96-29:25-30:21-33:20-42:23-60:1-60:2-60:7-68:9-70:11-85:14)",
      "d": "'Wadda' means to desire something, to befriend, to love (Munjid). And this word sometimes comes only in the meanings of desiring and longing (faq l 99). For example: In the Quran it says: «رُبَمَا یَوَدُّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَوۡ کَانُوۡا مُسۡلِمِیۡنَ» (15/2) Translation: There will come a time when the disbelievers will wish that they had been Muslims. And when used in the meanings of love, it signifies intense love. 'Mu'ada' mutual love and affection. Compassion. And 'Wudud' meaning one who loves greatly. And 'Wudd' comes in the meanings of love and affection (Maf). For example: The divine command says: «اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ سَیَجۡعَلُ لَہُمُ الرَّحۡمٰنُ وُدًّا» (19/96) Translation: And those who believe and do righteous deeds, the Most Merciful will create love for them (in the hearts of His creation). At another place, the divine command says: «اِنَّ رَبِّیۡ رَحِیۡمٌ وَّدُوۡدٌ» (11/90) Translation: Indeed, my Lord is Most Merciful and Loving. Thus, the word 'Wadda' when used in the meanings of loving is stronger than 'Habba' (Maf)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2617,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love. To love.",
      "hw": "محبت",
      "s": "'Alafa' means a love that arises from harmony (2 verses: 3:103-8:63)",
      "d": "'Alafa' means to join the disordered parts of something. From this comes the word 'Talif' meaning to create harmony. And 'Ulfat' means a love that arises from harmony (Maf). For example: In the Quran it says: «لَوۡ اَنۡفَقۡتَ مَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ جَمِیۡعًا مَّاۤ اَلَّفۡتَ بَیۡنَ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ» (8/63) Translation: If you spent all that is on the earth, you would not have united their hearts."
    },
    {
      "id": 2618,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love. To love.",
      "hw": "محبت",
      "s": "'Shaghafa Hubbun' such a love that has penetrated to the innermost part of the heart (1 verse: 12:30)",
      "d": "'Shaghafat al-Qalb' means the innermost part of the heart (Maf). And means the covering of the heart (M. L). And 'Shaghafa' means to strike on the covering of his heart. And 'Shaghafa Hubbun' means a love that has penetrated to the innermost part of the heart (Maf) (f l 168). To be madly in love (M. Q). For example: In the Quran it says: «قَدۡ شَغَفَہَا حُبًّا» (12/30) Translation: Her love for him (Joseph) had penetrated her heart."
    }
  ],
  "572": [],
  "573": [
    {
      "id": 2622,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Labor. Toil. To do. To bear.",
      "hw": "محنت",
      "s": "'Amila' means to labor, to work for wages. This word is also common and its usage is common (309 verses: 2:25-2:62-2:74-2:82-2:85-2:96-2:110-2:134-2:139-2:140-2:141-2:144-2:149-2:167-2:217-2:233-2:234-2:237-2:265-2:271-2:277-2:283-3:22-3:30-3:57-3:98-3:99-3:120-3:153-3:156-3:163-3:180-3:195-4:17-4:18-4:57-4:94-4:108-4:110-4:122-4:123-4:124-4:128-4:135-4:173-5:5-5:8-5:9-5:53-5:62-5:66-5:69-5:71-5:90-5:93-5:105-6:43-6:54-6:60-6:88-6:108-6:122-6:127-6:132-6:135-7:42-7:43-7:53-7:118-7:129-7:139-7:147-7:153-7:180-8:39-8:47-8:48-8:72-9:9-9:16-9:17-9:37-9:69-9:94-9:102-9:105-9:120-9:121-10:4-10:9-10:12-10:14-10:23-10:41-10:61-10:81-11:7-11:11-11:15-11:16-11:23-11:46-11:78-11:92-11:93-11:111-11:112-11:121-11:123-12:19-12:69-13:29-14:18-14:23-14:42-15:93-16:28-16:32-16:34-16:63-16:93-16:96-16:97-16:111-16:119-17:9-17:84-18:2-18:7-18:30-18:49-18:79-18:88-18:103-18:105-18:107-18:110-19:60-19:96-20:75-20:82-20:112-21:27-21:74-21:82-21:94-22:14-22:23-22:50-22:56-22:68-23:51-23:63-23:100-24:24-24:28-24:38-24:39-24:53-24:55-24:64-25:23-25:70-25:71-26:112-26:168-26:169-26:188-26:216-26:227-27:4-27:19-27:24-27:84-27:90-27:93-28:15-28:55-28:67-28:80-28:84-29:4-29:7-29:8-29:9-29:38-29:55-29:58-30:15-30:41-30:44-30:45-31:8-31:15-31:23-31:29-32:12-32:14-32:17-32:19-33:2-33:9-33:19-33:31-33:71-34:4-34:11-34:12-34:13-34:25-34:33-34:37-35:7-35:8-35:10-35:37-36:35-36:54-36:71-37:39-37:61-37:96-38:24-38:28-39:7-39:35-39:39-39:65-39:70-40:37-40:40-40:58-41:5-41:8-41:20-41:22-41:27-41:33-41:40-41:46-41:50-42:15-42:22-42:23-42:26-43:72-45:15-45:21-45:28-45:29-45:30-45:33-46:14-46:15-46:16-46:19-47:1-47:2-47:4-47:8-47:9-47:12-47:14-47:28-47:30-47:32-47:33-47:35-48:11-48:24-48:29-49:2-49:14-49:18-52:16-52:19-52:21-53:31-56:24-57:4-57:10-58:3-58:6-58:7-58:11-58:13-58:15-59:18-60:3-62:8-63:2-63:11-64:2-64:7-64:8-64:9-65:11-66:7-66:11-67:2-77:43-84:25-85:11-95:6-98:7-99:6-99:7-99:8-103:3)",
      "d": "'Amal' is every action that a living being does with its will and choice, whether good or bad (Maf). And the word 'Amila' is also used for labor, working for wages, or in other words, earning a livelihood. For example: In the Quran it says: «اَمَّا السَّفِیۡنَۃُ فَکَانَتۡ لِمَسٰکِیۡنَ یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ» (18/79) Translation: And as for the ship, it belonged to some poor people who worked (rowing) on the sea for their livelihood."
    },
    {
      "id": 2623,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Labor. Toil. To do. To bear.",
      "hw": "محنت",
      "s": "'Jahada' means to use all means in doing something (27 verses: 2:218-3:142-5:35-5:54-8:72-8:74-8:75-9:16-9:19-9:20-9:41-9:44-9:73-9:79-9:81-9:86-9:88-16:110-22:78-25:52-29:6-29:8-29:69-31:15-49:15-61:11-66:9)",
      "d": "'Jahada' means to use all means and resources in doing something. Sa'ee Baleeg meaning to make full effort (M. L). For example: In the Quran it says: «وَ مَنۡ جَاہَدَ فَاِنَّمَا یُجَاہِدُ لِنَفۡسِہٖ» (29/6) Translation: And whoever strives, he strives only for himself. And 'Juhd' means the effort that a human can make as far as possible. For example: In the Quran it says: «وَ الَّذِیۡنَ لَا یَجِدُوۡنَ اِلَّا جُہۡدَہُمۡ» (9/79) Translation: And those who do not find (to spend) except their effort."
    },
    {
      "id": 2624,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Labor. Toil. To do. To bear.",
      "hw": "محنت",
      "s": "'Nasaba' such toil that causes fatigue or is a cause of tiredness (6 verses: 9:120-15:48-18:62-35:35-88:3-94:7)",
      "d": "'Nasaba' means toil that tires a person (1) to labor, to toil (2) to become tired. Then this word is used in other meanings as well. For example: In the Quran it says: «لَقَدۡ لَقِیۡنَا مِنۡ سَفَرِنَا ہٰذَا نَصَبًا» (18/62) Translation: Indeed, we have encountered from this journey a great fatigue. At another place, the divine command says: «فَاِذَا فَرَغۡتَ فَانۡصَبۡ وَ اِلٰی رَبِّکَ فَارۡغَبۡ» (94/7,8) Translation: Then when you have finished (your duties), strive (in worship) and turn to your Lord with longing."
    },
    {
      "id": 2627,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Labor. Toil. To do. To bear.",
      "hw": "محنت",
      "s": "'Kurh' meaning forced toil, such toil in which a person's own will and choice have no part (26 verses: 2:216-3:83-4:19-8:8-9:32-9:33-9:46-9:53-9:81-10:82-10:99-13:15-16:62-16:106-20:73-24:33-40:14-41:11-46:15-47:9-47:26-47:28-49:7-49:12-61:8-61:9)",
      "d": "'Kurh' means forced toil. Such toil in which a person's own will and choice have no part, and he dislikes this toil. The opposite of 'Kurh' is 'Ridha wa al-Mahaba' (Maf). For example: In the Quran it says: «حَمَلَتۡہُ اُمُّہٗ کُرۡہًا وَّ وَضَعَتۡہُ کُرۡہًا» (46/15) Translation: His mother carried him with hardship and gave birth to him with hardship. And 'Akraha' means to force someone to do a task or labor that he dislikes. For example: The divine command says: «وَ لَا تُکۡرِہُوۡا فَتَیٰتِکُمۡ عَلَی الۡبِغَآءِ» (24/33) Translation: Do not force your slave girls into prostitution."
    },
    {
      "id": 2628,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Labor. Toil. To do. To bear.",
      "hw": "محنت",
      "s": "'Shiqq' the hardship and toil of labor (6 verses: 13:34-16:7-20:2-20:117-20:123-28:27)",
      "d": "'Shiqq' means such labor or toil that causes fatigue or hardship to the body or soul (Maf). For example: In the Quran it says: «وَ تَحۡمِلُ اَثۡقَالَکُمۡ اِلٰی بَلَدٍ لَّمۡ تَکُوۡنُوۡا بٰلِغِیۡہِ اِلَّا بِشِقِّ الۡاَنۡفُسِ» (16/7) Translation: And they carry your loads to a land you could not reach except with great hardship."
    },
    {
      "id": 2629,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Hardship. Labor. To do. To bear.",
      "hw": "محنت",
      "s": "«شُقَّۃ» is that station which one can reach with difficulty (1 verse: 9:42)",
      "d": "The difference between «شِقّ» and «شُقَّۃ» is like that between «حَمْل» and «حِمْل» or «وَقْر» and «وِقْر» (for details, see 'burden'). That is, the station which one can reach with difficulty (lexical).\nFor example, in the Quran: «لَوۡ کَانَ عَرَضًا قَرِیۡبًا وَّ سَفَرًا قَاصِدًا لَّاتَّبَعُوۡکَ وَ لٰکِنۡۢ بَعُدَتۡ عَلَیۡہِمُ الشُّقَّۃُ» (9/42)\nTranslation: If the gain (spoils) seemed near and the journey easy, they would have followed you, but the station seemed distant to them."
    }
  ],
  "574": [
    {
      "id": 2630,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Opposition. To oppose.",
      "hw": "مخالفت",
      "s": "«خَالَفَ» means to oppose, to turn away (3 verses: 9:83-11:88-24:63)",
      "d": "«خَالَفَ» means to oppose, to turn away (source) and means to go against something and to differ. To do something other than what has been instructed.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ مَاۤ  اُرِیۡدُ اَنۡ اُخَالِفَکُمۡ  اِلٰی مَاۤ اَنۡہٰکُمۡ عَنۡہُ» (11/88)\nTranslation: I do not wish to oppose you in what I forbid you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2631,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Opposition. To oppose.",
      "hw": "مخالفت",
      "s": "«ضَدَّ» two things that are opposite to each other, of the same kind, and can never coexist, like whiteness and blackness, their kind is color or hue (1 verse: 19:82)",
      "d": "«ضَدَّ» means to oppose. And «ضِدّ» means opposite, adversary. Its plural is «اَضّدَاد». Two opposing things are called «ضِدّین». According to Imam Raghib, the definition of «ضِدَّیْن» is: two things that are opposite to each other, of the same kind, and can never coexist, like whiteness and blackness, their kind is color or hue. And according to Ibn Faris, «ضِدَّیْن» are two opposing things whose simultaneous existence is impossible, like day and night. So this word is specific to «خِلَاف». That is, every opposite is a contrary, but not every contrary is an opposite.\nFor example, in the Quran: «کَلَّا ؕ سَیَکۡفُرُوۡنَ  بِعِبَادَتِہِمۡ وَ یَکُوۡنُوۡنَ  عَلَیۡہِمۡ  ضِدًّا» (19/82)\nTranslation: No! They will disbelieve in their worship and will be adversaries to them.\nAnd the word «ضِدّ» itself is from the root 'addada' meaning opposite and adversary. And «ضِدّ» also means similar and counterpart (source).\nNote: (Lexical opposites are words that have two separate meanings that are opposite and contradictory to each other)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2632,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Opposition. To oppose.",
      "hw": "مخالفت",
      "s": "«شَاقَّ» to be hostile and an enemy (5 verses: 4:115-8:13-16:27-47:32-59:4)",
      "d": "«شَاقَّ» means to oppose, to harbor enmity (source). And «شَقّ» means crack, fissure. And «شِقَاق» means separation, distance, split, discord, opposition. Such opposition where each party adopts the opposite stance (lexical), meaning whatever one dislikes, the other party adopts it.\nFor example, in the Quran: «ذٰلِکَ بِاَنَّہُمۡ  شَآقُّوا اللّٰہَ وَ رَسُوۡلَہٗ ۚ وَ مَنۡ یُّشَآقِّ  اللّٰہَ  فَاِنَّ اللّٰہَ شَدِیۡدُ الۡعِقَابِ» (59/4)\nTranslation: That is because they opposed Allah and His Messenger. And whoever opposes Allah, then indeed Allah is severe in punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 2634,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Opposition. To oppose.",
      "hw": "مخالفت",
      "s": "«تَعَاسَرَ» such discord where one party causes hardship for the other (1 verse: 65:6)",
      "d": "«عُسْر» means hardship. And «عَسَّرَ الْاَمْر» means he made the matter difficult for someone and caused him hardship. And «تَعَاسَرَ» means to oppose each other in such a way that the matter becomes difficult for the other (source). In «تَعَاسَرَ», there is no intensity in opposition and enmity, but one party adopts something that causes hardship and trouble for the other.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ اۡتَمِرُوۡا  بَیۡنَکُمۡ بِمَعۡرُوۡفٍ ۚ وَ اِنۡ  تَعَاسَرۡتُمۡ فَسَتُرۡضِعُ  لَہٗۤ   اُخۡرٰی» (65/6)\nTranslation: And consult each other in a fair manner. But if you oppose each other, then another woman will nurse (the child)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2635,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Opposition. To oppose.",
      "hw": "مخالفت",
      "s": "«عَنَدَ» to knowingly oppose the truth and the path of truth (4 verses: 11:59-14:15-50:24-74:16)",
      "d": "«عَنَدَ» means to knowingly oppose the truth and the path of truth (lexical, source). «عَنِیْد» means a person who holds enmity and opposition against the path of truth. And «عَنُوْد» means a person who deviates from the correct path (lexical).\nFor example, in the Quran: «اِنَّہٗ  کَانَ  لِاٰیٰتِنَا عَنِیۡدًا» (74/16)\nTranslation: Indeed, he was an adversary to Our signs."
    }
  ],
  "575": [
    {
      "id": 2636,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Different",
      "hw": "مختلف",
      "s": "«مُخْتَلِف» to be separate, of various kinds or types, different in species (9 verses: 6:141-11:118-16:13-16:69-35:27-35:28-39:21-51:8-78:3)",
      "d": "«اِخْتَلَاف» its opposite is «اِتَّفَاق». «اِخْتَلَاف» means things being separate, of various kinds or types, different in species. Having disagreement (opinion) in a matter.\nFor example, in the Quran: «یَخۡرُجُ مِنۡۢ بُطُوۡنِہَا شَرَابٌ مُّخۡتَلِفٌ اَلۡوَانُہٗ» (16/69)\nTranslation: From their bellies comes a drink (honey) of varying colors.\nAt another place, the divine command states: «وَّ النَّخۡلَ وَ الزَّرۡعَ مُخۡتَلِفًا اُکُلُہٗ» (6/141)\nTranslation: And date-palms and crops, whose fruits are of various kinds."
    },
    {
      "id": 2637,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Different",
      "hw": "مختلف",
      "s": "«شَتّٰی» when the intention is to express the scattered parts of one thing, i.e., separate components (5 verses: 20:53-24:61-59:14-92:4-99:6)",
      "d": "«شَتَّ» means the scattering of something, i.e., components becoming separate. Scattered, i.e., dispersed. Its opposite is «أَلَّفَ» (source) meaning to gather the separate parts of something and arrange them. And «شَتِیْث» means dispersed. Its plural is «شَتّٰی». (source)\nFor example, in the Quran: «تَحۡسَبُہُمۡ جَمِیۡعًا وَّ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ شَتّٰی» (59/14)\nTranslation: You think they are all together, but their hearts are scattered.\nAnd the word «ضِدّ» itself is from the root 'addada' meaning opposite and adversary. And «ضِدّ» also means similar and counterpart (source).\nNote: (Lexical opposites are words that have two separate meanings that are opposite and contradictory to each other)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2638,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Different",
      "hw": "مختلف",
      "s": "«اَزْوَاج» means a pair and every individual of a pair. In common usage, it is used for husband and wife, and it is used for every same-gender pair. (47 verses: 2:25-2:232-2:234-2:240-3:15-4:12-4:57-6:139-6:143-9:24-13:23-13:38-15:88-16:72-20:53-20:131-23:6-24:6-25:74-26:166-30:21-33:4-33:6-33:28-33:37-33:50-33:52-33:53-33:59-35:11-36:36-36:56-37:22-38:58-39:6-40:8-42:11-43:12-43:70-56:7-60:11-64:14-66:1-66:3-66:5-70:30-78:8)",
      "d": "«زَوْج» means a pair and every individual of a pair. For example, the husband is the zawj of the wife, and the wife is the zawj of the husband. And husband and wife together are also one zawj. In every creation where there is the existence of male and female, the concept of zawj is also present. The concept of male and female is known to humans in animals and plants, but this concept is also found in inanimate objects.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ مِنۡ کُلِّ  شَیۡءٍ خَلَقۡنَا زَوۡجَیۡنِ» (51/49). Translation: And of everything We created pairs.\nSince the concept of companionship or partnership is also present in «زَوْج», it is also used for several important groups of living things coming together. In this case, the meaning of zawj becomes kind, category, or sect.\nFor example, the divine command states: «وَّ کُنۡتُمۡ  اَزۡوَاجًا  ثَلٰثَۃً» (56/7). Translation: And you will be divided into three groups.\nAnd the word «اَزْوَاج» is also used for different kinds of same-gender groups. Each such group is considered as one, so the meaning of azwaj will be several kinds of such groups.\nFor example, the divine command states: «وَ لَا تَمُدَّنَّ عَیۡنَیۡکَ  اِلٰۤی مَا مَتَّعۡنَا بِہٖۤ اَزۡوَاجًا مِّنۡہُمۡ» (20/131). Translation: And do not extend your eyes towards that which We have given some classes of them to enjoy."
    }
  ],
  "576": [
    {
      "id": 2640,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Duration",
      "hw": "مدت",
      "s": "«اَمَدَ» is used for a long period and its limit or distance (4 verses: 3:30-18:12-57:16-72:25)",
      "d": "The word «اَمَدَ» comes for a long duration and is used for the limit and purpose of that duration (lexical). This word is used for both time and place. And in the case of place, it means distance (fiqh al-lughah 242).\nFor example, in the Quran: «اَیُّ الۡحِزۡبَیۡنِ اَحۡصٰی  لِمَا  لَبِثُوۡۤا  اَمَدًا» (18/12)\nTranslation: Which of the two groups remembered more the extreme duration they had stayed.\nAt another place, the divine command states: «تَوَدُّ لَوۡ اَنَّ بَیۡنَہَا وَ بَیۡنَہٗۤ اَمَدًۢا بَعِیۡدًا» (3/30)\nTranslation: He will wish that between her and it there were a great distance."
    },
    {
      "id": 2641,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Period",
      "hw": "مدت",
      "s": "‘Iddat’ is a period that must be counted, which is necessary for a divorced woman. This is a technical term (4 verses: 18:22-65:1-65:4-74:31)",
      "d": "Derived from ‘ad’ meaning to count. It refers to the period that is counted and during which a divorced or widowed woman cannot remarry and spends this period in her former husband's house.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ الّٰٓـِٔىۡ یَئِسۡنَ مِنَ  الۡمَحِیۡضِ مِنۡ نِّسَآئِکُمۡ   اِنِ  ارۡتَبۡتُمۡ فَعِدَّتُہُنَّ  ثَلٰثَۃُ اَشۡہُرٍ» (65/4)\nTranslation: And your divorced women who have despaired of menstruation, if you doubt, then their period is three months."
    },
    {
      "id": 2642,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Period",
      "hw": "مدت",
      "s": "‘Ummah’ is a period that has passed in the past (54 verses: 2:143-2:213-3:104-3:110-3:113-4:41-5:48-5:66-6:38-6:42-6:108-7:34-7:38-7:159-7:160-7:164-7:168-7:181-10:19-10:47-10:49-11:8-11:48-11:118-12:45-13:30-15:5-16:36-16:63-16:84-16:89-16:92-16:93-16:120-21:92-22:34-22:67-23:43-23:44-23:52-27:83-28:23-28:75-29:18-35:24-35:42-40:5-41:25-42:8-43:22-43:23-43:33-45:28-46:18)",
      "d": "‘Umm’ means mother and anything that contains all its related things. ‘Ummah’ is used for a period when it has passed.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ قَالَ الَّذِیۡ نَجَا مِنۡہُمَا وَ ادَّکَرَ  بَعۡدَ اُمَّۃٍ» (12/45)\nTranslation: And the one who escaped from among them remembered after a period and said."
    },
    {
      "id": 2645,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Period",
      "hw": "مدت",
      "s": "‘Umur’ is the period from the birth of a living being to the present time (10 verses: 2:96-10:16-15:72-16:70-21:44-22:5-26:18-28:45-35:11-35:37)",
      "d": "‘Amara’ means to inhabit and to populate. ‘Umur’ means the period of inhabiting the body of the soul. The period from the birth of a living being to the present time.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لٰکِنَّاۤ  اَنۡشَاۡنَا قُرُوۡنًا فَتَطَاوَلَ عَلَیۡہِمُ الۡعُمُرُ» (28/45)\nTranslation: But We generated generations, then long periods passed over them."
    }
  ],
  "577": [
    {
      "id": 2646,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Helping: Doing and Willing",
      "hw": "مدد",
      "s": "‘A’ana’ to help someone. General; all forms of assistance (6 verses: 1:4-2:45-2:153-7:128-18:95-25:4)",
      "d": "‘Awn’ means helper. ‘A’ana’ means to lend a hand, to assist. ‘Ta’awwana’ means to help each other. This word is general.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَعِیۡنُوۡنِیۡ بِقُوَّۃٍ  اَجۡعَلۡ بَیۡنَکُمۡ وَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ  رَدۡمًا» (18/95)\nTranslation: Help me with strength, so I may set up a barrier between you and them.\nAnd ‘ista’ana’ means to seek help and cooperation.\nFor example, the Divine command states:\n«اِیَّاکَ نَعۡبُدُ وَ اِیَّاکَ نَسۡتَعِیۡنُ» (1/4)\nTranslation: You alone we worship, and You alone we seek help from."
    },
    {
      "id": 2647,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Helping: Doing and Willing",
      "hw": "مدد",
      "s": "‘Nasara’ to help someone to remove their hardship or oppression (70 verses: 2:48-2:86-2:123-2:214-2:250-2:286-3:13-3:81-3:111-3:123-3:126-3:147-3:160-6:34-7:157-7:192-7:197-8:10-8:26-8:62-8:72-8:74-9:14-9:25-9:40-11:30-11:63-11:113-12:110-18:43-21:39-21:43-21:68-21:77-22:15-22:39-22:40-22:60-23:26-23:39-23:65-25:19-26:93-28:18-28:41-28:81-29:10-29:30-30:5-30:47-36:74-36:75-37:116-39:54-40:29-40:51-41:16-42:46-44:41-46:28-47:7-48:3-52:46-57:25-59:8-59:11-59:12-61:13-67:20-110:1)",
      "d": "‘Nasara’ means to help someone to remove their hardship or oppression. This is more specific than general assistance.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ نَصَرَکُمُ اللّٰہُ بِبَدۡرٍ وَّ اَنۡتُمۡ اَذِلَّۃٌ» (3/123)\nTranslation: And Allah has certainly aided you at Badr while you were weak.\nAnd ‘istanasara’ means to seek help from someone to remove oppression from oneself.\nFor example, the Divine command states:\n«وَ اِنِ اسۡتَنۡصَرُوۡکُمۡ فِی الدِّیۡنِ فَعَلَیۡکُمُ النَّصۡرُ» (8/72)\nTranslation: And if they seek your help in religion, then you must aid them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2648,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Helping: Doing and Willing",
      "hw": "مدد",
      "s": "‘Ayyada’ to strengthen someone through assistance (9 verses: 2:87-2:253-5:110-8:26-8:62-9:40-38:17-58:22-61:14)",
      "d": "‘Al-ayyad’ means strong power. ‘Ayyada’ means to assist someone so that they gain strength and power; to support.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ سَکِیۡنَتَہٗ عَلَیۡہِ وَ اَیَّدَہٗ  بِجُنُوۡدٍ لَّمۡ تَرَوۡہَا» (9/40)\nTranslation: Then Allah sent down His tranquility upon him and supported him with armies you did not see."
    },
    {
      "id": 2649,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Helping: Doing and Willing",
      "hw": "مدد",
      "s": "‘Azara’ to help someone with a sense of reverence (3 verses: 5:12-7:157-48:9)",
      "d": "‘Azara’ means to help someone with a feeling of reverence.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لِّتُؤۡمِنُوۡا بِاللّٰہِ وَ رَسُوۡلِہٖ  وَ تُعَزِّرُوۡہُ وَ تُوَقِّرُوۡہُ» (48/9)\nTranslation: So that you may believe in Allah and His Messenger and support him and revere him."
    },
    {
      "id": 2651,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Helping: Doing and Willing",
      "hw": "مدد",
      "s": "‘Zahara’ to back or provide protection (5 verses: 9:4-28:48-33:26-60:9-66:4)",
      "d": "In ‘zahr’, there are two basic meanings: (1) to be apparent, to come forward, to be evident. And ‘zahr’ means back. ‘Zahara’ means to provide strength upon which one can rely; to back or protect.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اَنۡزَلَ الَّذِیۡنَ ظَاہَرُوۡہُمۡ مِّنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ مِنۡ صَیَاصِیۡہِمۡ» (33/26)\nTranslation: And those from the People of the Book who supported them, Allah brought them down from their fortresses."
    },
    {
      "id": 2652,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Helping: Doing and Willing",
      "hw": "مدد",
      "s": "‘Rafada’ to help the poor through gifts and charity (1 verse: 11:99)",
      "d": "‘Rafada’ means to aid the destitute and poor through gifts and charity.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اُتۡبِعُوۡا فِیۡ ہٰذِہٖ  لَعۡنَۃً وَّ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ ؕ بِئۡسَ الرِّفۡدُ  الۡمَرۡفُوۡدُ» (11/99)\nTranslation: And they were followed in this [world] by a curse and on the Day of Resurrection. Evil is what they were given as a reward."
    },
    {
      "id": 2654,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Helping: Doing and Willing",
      "hw": "مدد",
      "s": "‘Amadda’ to help by increasing the quantity or number of something; to strengthen, to fortify (7 verses: 3:124-3:125-17:6-26:132-26:133-52:22-71:12)",
      "d": "‘Madda’ means to pull, extend, or lengthen something, maintaining its connection. ‘Amadda’ means to help by increasing the quantity or number of something; to provide assistance.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یُمۡدِدۡکُمۡ  بِاَمۡوَالٍ وَّ بَنِیۡنَ» (71/12)\nTranslation: And He will increase you in wealth and children.\nAt another place, the Divine command states:\n«یُمۡدِدۡکُمۡ رَبُّکُمۡ بِخَمۡسَۃِ اٰلٰفٍ مِّنَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ مُسَوِّمِیۡنَ» (3/125)\nTranslation: Then your Lord will reinforce you with five thousand angels, marked."
    }
  ],
  "578": [
    {
      "id": 2656,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Helper",
      "hw": "مددگار",
      "s": "«Hawari» is a special group of helpers for the prophets (4 verses: 3:52-5:111-5:112-61:14)",
      "d": "«Hawari» means white cloth with which clothes etc. are cleaned (m. q.) and also means advisor, relative, helper. Hawari actually refers to those supporters of Prophet Jesus (peace be upon him) who stood by him in difficult times. And the Messenger of Allah (peace be upon him) said that every prophet has a Hawari, and my Hawari is Zubair (may Allah be pleased with him).\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«قَالَ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ  مَرۡیَمَ لِلۡحَوَارِیّٖنَ مَنۡ  اَنۡصَارِیۡۤ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ ؕ قَالَ الۡحَوَارِیُّوۡنَ نَحۡنُ  اَنۡصَارُ اللّٰہِ» ( 61/14 )\nTranslation: Prophet Jesus (peace be upon him) said to the Hawariyun, 'Who are my helpers in calling to Allah?' The Hawariyun said, 'We are helpers of Allah (in His religion).'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2658,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Helper",
      "hw": "مددگار",
      "s": "«Shahid» is one who helps by being present at the occasion and giving testimony in favor of someone (32 verses: 2:143-2:282-3:98-4:33-4:41-4:72-4:79-4:159-4:166-5:117-6:19-10:29-10:46-13:43-16:84-16:89-17:96-22:17-22:78-28:75-29:52-33:55-34:47-41:47-41:53-46:8-48:28-50:21-50:37-58:6-85:9-100:7)",
      "d": "«Shahida» means to bear witness, whether that testimony is ocular or heartfelt—i.e., whether it pertains to sight or insight—and also means to be present (muf. manjad). And «Shahid» is also used for one who comes forward to give testimony in favor of someone before a judge (muf), and it proves to be a means of his help and support.\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«وَ ادۡعُوۡا شُہَدَآءَکُمۡ مِّنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ  اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰادِقِیۡنَ» ( 2/23 )\nTranslation: And call upon those whom you consider helpers besides Allah, if you are truthful."
    },
    {
      "id": 2659,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Helper",
      "hw": "مددگار",
      "s": "«Zahir» is a helper on whom one can rely. Patron. Supporter, helper, assistant (6 verses: 17:88-25:55-28:17-28:86-34:22-66:4)",
      "d": "«Zahr» means back. And it also means mount. Patron. Helper (muf). And «Zahir» means helper. A helper on whom a person relies.\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«فَلَا تَکُوۡنَنَّ  ظَہِیۡرًا  لِّلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» ( 28/86 )\nTranslation: Then never be a helper to the disbelievers."
    },
    {
      "id": 2660,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Helper",
      "hw": "مددگار",
      "s": "«Wazir» is one who lends a hand in times of increased work (2 verses: 20:29-25:35)",
      "d": "«Wizr» means burden; its plural is «Awzar». And «Wazir» is a person who helps and accompanies, one who shares the burden in times of hardship and increased work.\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«وَ اجۡعَلۡ  لِّیۡ  وَزِیۡرًا مِّنۡ  اَہۡلِیۡ» ( 20/29 )\nTranslation: And appoint for me a minister (helper) from among my family."
    },
    {
      "id": 2661,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Helper",
      "hw": "مددگار",
      "s": "«A'ud» is a helper who is a firm hand and arm (2 verses: 18:51-28:35)",
      "d": "«A'ud» means arm. The part from the shoulder to the elbow. And «A'adtuhu» means to hold someone's arm and give him support. In this sense, «A'ud» is used metaphorically to mean helper (muf). Its plural is «A'dad» (manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«وَ مَا کُنۡتُ مُتَّخِذَ  الۡمُضِلِّیۡنَ  عَضُدًا» ( 18/51 )\nTranslation: And I was not one to take the misguiders as helpers."
    }
  ],
  "579": [
    {
      "id": 2662,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To mock",
      "hw": "مذاق",
      "s": "«Istihza» is to mock something by considering it unreasonable and strange (21 verses: 2:14-2:15-4:140-6:5-6:10-9:64-9:65-11:8-13:32-15:11-15:95-16:34-21:41-26:6-30:10-36:30-39:48-40:83-43:7-45:33-46:26)",
      "d": "«Al-haz» means to mock someone internally (muf). And «Istihza» means to mock a person's action that he has not even committed, considering it unreasonable (faq l 212).\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«وَ اِذَا خَلَوۡا اِلٰی شَیٰطِیۡنِہِمۡ  ۙ  قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّا مَعَکُمۡ  ۙ  اِنَّمَا نَحۡنُ مُسۡتَہۡزِءُوۡنَ» ( 2/14 )\nTranslation: When these hypocrites are alone with their evil companions, they say, 'We are with you; we are only mocking.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2663,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To mock",
      "hw": "مذاق",
      "s": "«Sakhkhara» is to mock by mentioning someone's faults with contempt (10 verses: 2:212-6:10-9:79-11:38-21:41-23:110-37:12-37:14-38:63-49:11)",
      "d": "«Maskhar» contains the aspect of humiliation and contempt (m. l). «Sakhkhara» means to take labor (i.e., work without wages) from someone, and also means to humiliate someone, to overpower (manjad), and also means to mock someone by mentioning his faults, intending his degradation and humiliation (faq l 211).\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا  الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا یَسۡخَرۡ قَوۡمٌ مِّنۡ قَوۡمٍ عَسٰۤی اَنۡ یَّکُوۡنُوۡا خَیۡرًا مِّنۡہُمۡ» ( 49/11 )\nTranslation: O you who have believed, let not a people ridicule another people; perhaps they may be better than them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2664,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To mock",
      "hw": "مذاق",
      "s": "«Fanna» is to mock an old person's words by considering them nonsensical (1 verse: 12:94)",
      "d": "«Fand» means weakness of opinion. And «Fanna» means to declare someone as having weak opinion or deficient intellect (i.e., foolish, crazy, insane) (muf). And «Fanida» means to become senile. To become weak-minded due to old age and speak incoherently. And «Fanna» means to reproach someone for an old person's words, to declare them erroneous, to reproach.\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«قَالَ اَبُوۡہُمۡ اِنِّیۡ لَاَجِدُ رِیۡحَ یُوۡسُفَ لَوۡ لَاۤ اَنۡ تُفَنِّدُوۡنِ» ( 12/94 )\nTranslation: Their father said, 'I find the scent of Joseph, if you do not call me senile.'"
    }
  ],
  "580": [
    {
      "id": 2665,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Man",
      "hw": "مرد",
      "s": "«Rajul» is used when the expression of bravery and masculine strength is intended (49 verses: 2:228-2:282-4:1-4:7-4:12-4:32-4:34-4:75-4:98-4:176-5:23-6:9-7:46-7:48-7:63-7:69-7:81-7:155-9:108-10:2-11:78-12:109-16:43-16:76-17:47-18:32-18:37-21:7-23:25-23:38-24:31-24:37-25:8-27:55-28:15-28:20-29:29-33:4-33:23-33:40-34:7-34:43-36:20-38:62-39:29-40:28-43:31-48:25-72:6)",
      "d": "«Rajul» (meaning man) is used when the expression of strength, bravery, and masculinity is intended. «Rijaliyyah» is the verbal noun meaning masculine strength. Its plural is «Rijal». And its feminine is «Nisa'» and «Niswa».\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«اَلرِّجَالُ قَوّٰمُوۡنَ عَلَی النِّسَآءِ بِمَا فَضَّلَ اللّٰہُ بَعۡضَہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ» ( 4/34 )\nTranslation: Men are the protectors and maintainers of women, because Allah has given one of them more strength than the other."
    },
    {
      "id": 2666,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Man",
      "hw": "مرد",
      "s": "«Imra'» is used when one intends to express chivalry, humanity, and moral values (4 verses: 2:102-8:24-78:40-80:34)",
      "d": "«Mar'» (meaning man) person. This word is used when the intention is to refer to humanity-related ethics. «Maru'at» or «Murrat» is the verbal noun meaning humanity, human compassion. And its feminine is «Imra'at» or «Al-Mar'at». Its plural is also «Rijal» (manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«فَیَتَعَلَّمُوۡنَ مِنۡہُمَا مَا یُفَرِّقُوۡنَ بِہٖ بَیۡنَ الۡمَرۡءِ  وَ زَوۡجِہٖ» ( 2/102 )\nTranslation: People learn from them what causes separation between a man and his wife."
    },
    {
      "id": 2667,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "male",
      "hw": "مرد",
      "s": "«ذَکَرَ» is used when the expression of gender is intended (16 verses: 3:36-3:195-4:11-4:124-4:176-6:143-6:144-16:97-26:165-40:40-42:50-49:13-53:21-53:45-75:39-92:3)",
      "d": "«ذَکَرَ» means male, opposite of «اُنْثٰی». Every thing born from a pair, the male among them, whether human, animal, plant, etc. But when referring to humans, it means man, regardless of age. Its plural is «ذَكُوْر» and «ذَکْرَان», opposite «اَنَاث». For example, in the Quran: «قُلۡ ءٰٓالذَّکَرَیۡنِ حَرَّمَ اَمِ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ» (6/144) Translation: Ask them whether Allah has forbidden the males or the females. And elsewhere: «لَیۡسَ الذَّکَرُ کَالۡاُنۡثٰی» (3/36) Translation: The male is not like the female."
    }
  ],
  "581": [
    {
      "id": 2668,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "taste",
      "hw": "مزا",
      "s": "«ذَائِقَۃ» is general meaning to taste. Taste, to taste (5 verses: 3:185-21:35-29:57-37:31-37:38)",
      "d": "«ذَاقَ» means to taste. But this word is generally used in the sense of tasting with the tongue. «ذَائِقَۃ» also means the tasting faculty that is in the tongue. And «ذَوَاق» and «مَذَاق» come in the meanings of taste (manjad). The usage of this word is general. Used in both material and spiritual senses. For example, in the Quran: «کُلُّ نَفۡسٍ ذَآئِقَۃُ الۡمَوۡتِ» (3/185) Translation: Every soul shall taste death."
    },
    {
      "id": 2671,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "pleasure",
      "hw": "مزا",
      "s": "«ھَنَاَ» means wealth that comes without effort, and being pleasant in appearance and delightful. Something being pleasant and delightful (4 verses: 4:4-52:19-69:24-77:43)",
      "d": "«اَلْھَنِیءُ» is that thing which is obtained without toil and is pleasing in results. This word is generally used for food being pleasant (muf). And «ھَنَأ» means to be happy and «ھَنِیءَ الطَّعَام» means to find food delightful. And «ھَنُؤَ» means to obtain without hardship. And «ھَنَّاَ» means to congratulate. And «ھَنیئُ» means pleasant, without effort, freely obtained (manjad). And «ھَنِئ» means such delightful food in which there is no dirt or spoilage (faq 345). Then its usage began for wealth obtained easily. For example, in the Quran: «فَاِنۡ طِبۡنَ لَکُمۡ عَنۡ شَیۡءٍ مِّنۡہُ نَفۡسًا فَکُلُوۡہُ ہَنِیۡٓئًا مَّرِیۡٓئًا» (4/4) Translation: Then if women remit any part of the mahr to you of their own accord, consume it with pleasure and benefit."
    }
  ],
  "582": [],
  "583": [
    {
      "id": 2675,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "traveler",
      "hw": "مسافر",
      "s": "«اِبْنُ السَّبِیِل» is the kunya (nickname) for a traveler until he returns home (8 verses: 2:177-2:215-4:36-8:41-9:60-17:26-30:38-59:7)",
      "d": "«اِبْنُ السَّبِیِل» means (son of the road). This is the nickname for a traveler until he returns home, whether he is traveling or temporarily staying during his journey. For example, in the Quran: «وَ اٰتَی الۡمَالَ عَلٰی حُبِّہٖ ذَوِی الۡقُرۡبٰی وَ الۡیَتٰمٰی وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنَ وَ ابۡنَ السَّبِیۡلِ» (2/177) Translation: And gives wealth, out of love for Him, to relatives, orphans, the needy, and the traveler."
    },
    {
      "id": 2676,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "traveler",
      "hw": "مسافر",
      "s": "«عَابِرِی السَّبِیِل» wayfarer, traveler on the road who is in a state of travel (1 verse: 4:43)",
      "d": "«عَابِرِ» means one who passes, one who traverses. And «عَابِرِی السَّبِیِل» means wayfarer, traveler, one whose journey is ongoing. For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَا جُنُبًا اِلَّا عَابِرِیۡ سَبِیۡلٍ حَتّٰی تَغۡتَسِلُوۡا» (4/43) Translation: And do not approach while in a state of janabah except when passing through (as a traveler) until you have bathed."
    },
    {
      "id": 2677,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "traveler",
      "hw": "مسافر",
      "s": "«مُقْوِیْن» those who move about in search of livelihood (1 verse: 56:73)",
      "d": "«اَلْقَوٰی» means hunger, and «بَاتَ الْقَوٰی» means spending the night hungry. And «اَلْقَاوِیَۃ» means a year of little rain (manjad). And «تَقَاوِی» means scarcity or excess of rain that destroys crops and causes famine (m. q.). «تَقَاوِی» are loans that the government gives to landlords on the condition of installment payment in such a famine year. And «تَقَاوٰی» means spending the night hungry (manjad). And «قُوَّتُ لَا یَمُوت» means such a small amount of food that a person can barely survive. And «مُقْوِیْن» means people traveling in need of sustenance, nomads who keep moving in search of livelihood. For example, in the Quran: «نَحۡنُ جَعَلۡنٰہَا تَذۡکِرَۃً وَّ مَتَاعًا لِّلۡمُقۡوِیۡنَ» (56/73) Translation: We have made it a reminder and a provision for the travelers."
    },
    {
      "id": 2678,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "traveler",
      "hw": "مسافر",
      "s": "«سَیَّارَۃٌ» a caravan of people traveling together (3 verses: 5:96-12:10-12:19)",
      "d": "«سَارَ» means to travel, to move. And «سیّار» is an intensive form meaning one who travels much. And «سَیَّارَہ» means a caravan of fellow travelers, things that move constantly. Caravans, celestial bodies, motor cars, etc. In the Quran, this word has come in the first meaning. For example, in the Quran: «وَ جَآءَتۡ سَیَّارَۃٌ فَاَرۡسَلُوۡا وَارِدَہُمۡ» (12/19) Translation: And a caravan came, and they sent their water-drawer."
    }
  ],
  "584": [
    {
      "id": 2679,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to subjugate",
      "hw": "مسخر",
      "s": "«سَخَّرَ» the word emphasizes the aspect of (restlessness and discomfort) of a thing (24 verses: 2:164-7:54-13:2-14:32-14:33-16:12-16:14-16:79-21:79-22:36-22:37-22:65-29:61-31:20-31:29-35:13-38:18-38:36-39:5-43:13-43:32-45:12-45:13-69:7)",
      "d": "«سَخَّرَ» comes in the sense of forced obedience, i.e., a thing doing the work for which it was created. In this, the will and choice of the obedient (whether animate or inanimate) has no role (muf). For more details, see ''to force''. For example, in the Quran: «وَ تَقُوۡلُوۡا سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡ سَخَّرَ لَنَا ہٰذَا وَ مَا کُنَّا لَہٗ مُقۡرِنِیۡنَ» (43/13) Translation: And say, 'Glory be to Him who has subjected this to us, and we could not have subdued it ourselves.'"
    }
  ],
  "585": [
    {
      "id": 2681,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to subject",
      "hw": "مسلط",
      "s": "«سَلَّطَ» contains two aspects (1) power (2) might, i.e., dominance and with it pressure also. (2 verses: 4:90-59:6)",
      "d": "«سَلِطَ» means to be sharp-tongued. And «سَلَّطَ» contains two aspects (1) power (2) might (m. q.) i.e., dominance and with it pressure also. And «سُلْطان» means king, authority, and clear proof (manjad). For example, in the Quran: «وَّ لٰکِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُسَلِّطُ رُسُلَہٗ عَلٰی مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ» (59/6) Translation: But Allah grants His messengers authority over whom He wills."
    },
    {
      "id": 2682,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to subject",
      "hw": "مسلط",
      "s": "«قَیَّضَ» means to overpower and make someone helpless. (2 verses: 41:25-43:36)",
      "d": "«قَیْض» means the shell of an egg. And «قَیَّضَ» means to overpower and cover something completely, like the shell of an egg covers its content (muf). To overpower and make someone helpless. For example, in the Quran: «وَ مَنۡ یَّعۡشُ عَنۡ ذِکۡرِ الرَّحۡمٰنِ نُقَیِّضۡ لَہٗ شَیۡطٰنًا» (43/36) Translation: And whoever turns away from the remembrance of the Most Merciful, We will assign to him a devil as a companion."
    }
  ],
  "586": [
    {
      "id": 2683,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To be occupied/engaged",
      "hw": "مشغول",
      "s": "«شَغَلَ» is general. To be occupied with a task (2 verses: 36:55-48:11)",
      "d": "«شَغَلَ» refers to a state of preoccupation where a person cannot attend to other tasks. Its opposite is «فَرَغَ».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«سَیَقُوۡلُ لَکَ الۡمُخَلَّفُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡاَعۡرَابِ شَغَلَتۡنَاۤ اَمۡوَالُنَا وَ اَہۡلُوۡنَا» (48/11)\nTranslation: Those of the bedouins who remained behind will say to you, 'We were occupied with our wealth and our families.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2684,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To be occupied/engaged",
      "hw": "مشغول",
      "s": "«خَاضَ» means to be engrossed in a negative sense (9 verses: 4:140-6:68-6:91-9:65-9:69-43:83-52:12-70:42-74:45)",
      "d": "«خَاضَ» means to sink into and become deeply involved in something (e.g., «خَاضَ فِی الْمَاء» means to sink into water, and «خَاضَ فِی الْحَدِیْث» means to be engrossed in talk). It signifies being completely absorbed in a task or conversation. In the Quran, this word is generally used in a negative context, meaning to remain occupied in vain talk or futile actions.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ خُضۡتُمۡ کَالَّذِیۡ خَاضُوۡا ؕ اُولٰٓئِکَ حَبِطَتۡ اَعۡمَالُہُمۡ فِی الدُّنۡیَا وَ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ» (9/69)\nTranslation: And you became like those who were engrossed in falsehood. Those are the ones whose deeds are wasted in this world and the Hereafter.\nAt another place, the Divine declaration is:\n«وَ اِذَا رَاَیۡتَ الَّذِیۡنَ یَخُوۡضُوۡنَ فِیۡۤ اٰیٰتِنَا فَاَعۡرِضۡ عَنۡہُمۡ» (6/68)\nTranslation: When you see those who engage in vain discourse about Our verses, turn away from them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2685,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To be occupied/engaged",
      "hw": "مشغول",
      "s": "«اَفَاضَ» denotes an absorption so intense that one forgets oneself (6 verses: 2:199-5:83-7:50-9:92-10:61-46:8)",
      "d": "«فَاضَ، فَیْض» means for something to flow out easily (e.g., water flowing or gushing), or for something to be abundant. One says «فَاضَ السَّبیل» meaning water is abundant and overflows, and «فَاضَتْ عَیْنَہٗ» meaning his eyes began to overflow with tears. «اَفَاضَ اِنَاءَہٗ» means he filled his vessel so much that water spilled over the brim.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ اَفِیۡضُوۡا مِنۡ حَیۡثُ اَفَاضَ النَّاسُ» (2/199)\nTranslation: Then depart from the place from which the people depart.\nThis refers to moving along with the crowd and its flow. According to the author of 'Munjid', «اَفَاضَ الْقَوْمُ مِنْ مَکَان» means to become scattered and dispersed. And «اَفَاضَ فِی الْحَدِیْثِ» means to be completely absorbed in conversation for a long time.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«وَّ لَا تَعۡمَلُوۡنَ مِنۡ عَمَلٍ اِلَّا کُنَّا عَلَیۡکُمۡ شُہُوۡدًا اِذۡ تُفِیۡضُوۡنَ فِیۡہِ» (10/61)\nTranslation: And whatever you do, We are witnesses over you when you are engrossed in it.\nAccording to Ibn al-Faris, «تَفِیْضُوْنَ فِیْہِ» means 'you are so absorbed that you forget everything else'."
    },
    {
      "id": 2686,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To be occupied/engaged",
      "hw": "مشغول",
      "s": "«سَبَحَ» denotes an absorption characterized by swiftness and intensity due to the multitude of tasks (4 verses: 21:33-36:40-73:7-79:3)",
      "d": "«سَبَحَ» means to swim or float (i.e., to move on water, cross it, traverse it, or reach the other side). According to Imam Raghib, it means for something to pass through water or air swiftly or while swimming.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ کُلٌّ فِیۡ فَلَکٍ یَّسۡبَحُوۡنَ» (36/40)\nTranslation: And each [celestial body] floats in an orbit.\nLater, this word began to be used for performing a task with speed and vigor.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«اِنَّ لَکَ فِی النَّہَارِ سَبۡحًا طَوِیۡلًا» (73/7)\nTranslation: Indeed, for you during the day is a prolonged occupation [with worldly affairs]."
    }
  ],
  "587": [
    {
      "id": 2687,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To plunge into hardship",
      "hw": "مشقت",
      "s": "«اَعْنَتَ» means to cause someone else to fall into a dangerous and difficult task.\nAnd «اِقْتَحَمَ» is used for plunging oneself into a dangerous and difficult task (3 verses: 2:220-3:118-9:128)",
      "d": "«عَنَتَ» means for a person to become entangled in a matter where there is fear of ruin. «اَعْنَتَ» means to cause someone else to fall into such affliction or calamity.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ شَآءَ اللّٰہُ لَاَعۡنَتَکُمۡ» (2/220)\nTranslation: And if Allah had willed, He could have put you into hardship."
    },
    {
      "id": 2688,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To plunge into hardship",
      "hw": "مشقت",
      "s": "«اِقْتَحَمَ» means to plunge oneself, along with hardship, into a matter (2 verses: 38:59-90:11)",
      "d": "«قَحَمَ فِی الْاَمْر» means to enter a matter recklessly without thought. «اِقْتَحَمَ الْاَمْر» means to plunge oneself, with hardship, into a matter. And «اِقْتَحَمَ» means to plunge into a fearsome place.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ہٰذَا فَوۡجٌ مُّقۡتَحِمٌ مَّعَکُمۡ» (38/59)\nTranslation: This is a force that is plunging in with you [into Hell]."
    }
  ],
  "588": [
    {
      "id": 2689,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To consult",
      "hw": "مشورہ",
      "s": "«شَاوَرَ» means to consult. It is general (2 verses: 2:233-3:159)",
      "d": "«شَاوَرَ» means to consult. It involves several people gathering to consider the various aspects of a matter and taking each other's opinions. Its usage is general.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ شَاوِرۡہُمۡ فِی الۡاَمۡرِ ۚ فَاِذَا عَزَمۡتَ فَتَوَکَّلۡ عَلَی اللّٰہِ» (3/159)\nTranslation: And consult them in the matter. Then when you have decided, put your trust in Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2691,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To consult",
      "hw": "مشورہ",
      "s": "«تَنَاجٰی» means secret whispering or counsel between two or a few people (14 verses: 4:114-9:78-12:80-17:47-19:52-20:62-21:3-43:80-58:7-58:8-58:9-58:10-58:12-58:13)",
      "d": "«نَجَو» means a secret between two people. «نَجْوٰی» means a secret talk, a secret, a confidant, or one who shares a secret. «تَنَاجٰی» means to whisper, to whisper specifically, or to make someone a confidant. «نَجِیًّا» means secret consultation.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ یَتَنٰجَوۡنَ بِالۡاِثۡمِ وَ الۡعُدۡوَانِ وَ مَعۡصِیَتِ الرَّسُوۡلِ» (58/8)\nTranslation: They whisper to one another sinful [talk] and transgression and disobedience to the Messenger."
    },
    {
      "id": 2692,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To consult",
      "hw": "مشورہ",
      "s": "«اِئْتَمَرَ» means to agree on a plan after consultation or to conspire to kill someone (2 verses: 28:20-65:6)",
      "d": "«اَمَرَ» means to command. «اِئْتَمَرَ» means to agree on something after mutual consultation and to execute the command. «اِئْتَمَرَ بِفُلَانٍ» means to conspire to kill someone.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ یٰمُوۡسٰۤی اِنَّ الۡمَلَاَ یَاۡتَمِرُوۡنَ بِکَ لِیَقۡتُلُوۡکَ» (28/20)\nTranslation: He said, 'O Moses, indeed the eminent ones are planning to kill you.'"
    }
  ],
  "589": [
    {
      "id": 2693,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To publicize/spread",
      "hw": "مشہور",
      "s": "«اَشَاعَ» means to publicize or spread news, whether good or bad (1 verse: 24:19)",
      "d": "«شَاعَ الْخَبْر» means the news spread and gained strength. «شَاعَ الْقَوْم» means the people became scattered and increased. «اَلْشِیَاعَ» means to scatter and to strengthen. Thus, «شَاعَ» is used for something (good or bad) spreading among people and becoming common. From this, 'ashā'a' (to publicize) is derived.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ یُحِبُّوۡنَ اَنۡ تَشِیۡعَ الۡفَاحِشَۃُ فِی الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ» (24/19)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who like that indecency should be spread [or publicized] among those who have believed will have a painful punishment in this world and the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 2694,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to publicize",
      "hw": "مشہور",
      "s": "«اَذَاعَ» means to spread news, to reveal and disseminate matters related to secrets and confidential affairs (1 verse: 4:83)",
      "d": "«ذَاعَ» means for something to become apparent and spread. And «ذَاعَ الْخَبْر» means the news became apparent and spread. And «رَجُلٌ لِذَاعٌ» means a person who cannot conceal a secret (m. l.). Thus, «اَزَاعَ» is used for revealing something that should not have been revealed. And «اِذَاعَۃ» refers to radio. Because radio also broadcasts news that some countries find undesirable to disclose. Spreading news.\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «وَ اِذَا جَآءَہُمۡ اَمۡرٌ مِّنَ الۡاَمۡنِ اَوِ الۡخَوۡفِ اَذَاعُوۡا بِہٖ» (4/83) Translation: And when the hypocrites receive any news of danger or security, they spread it abroad."
    },
    {
      "id": 2695,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to publicize",
      "hw": "مشہور",
      "s": "«اَرْجَفَ» means to spread something that causes anxiety and unrest (1 verse: 33:60)",
      "d": "«رَجْف» means severe anxiety, i.e., intense unrest (m. l.). And «رَجْفَۃ» means the extreme state of an earthquake. Violent shocks. And «بَحْرٌ رِجَافٌ» means turbulent, i.e., stormy sea (minjadd). And «اَرْجَفَ» means to spread false rumors etc., causing unrest and commotion among people. And «اَرَاجِیْف» means baseless news. Rumors (m. q).\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «لَئِنۡ لَّمۡ یَنۡتَہِ الۡمُنٰفِقُوۡنَ وَ الَّذِیۡنَ فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ مَّرَضٌ وَّ الۡمُرۡجِفُوۡنَ فِی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ لَنُغۡرِیَنَّکَ بِہِمۡ ثُمَّ لَا یُجَاوِرُوۡنَکَ فِیۡہَاۤ اِلَّا قَلِیۡلًا» (33/60)\nTranslation: If the hypocrites and those in whose hearts is a disease and those who spread false rumors in the city do not desist, We will surely incite you against them, then they will not be your neighbors therein except for a little while."
    },
    {
      "id": 2696,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to publicize",
      "hw": "مشہور",
      "s": "«اَھَلَّ» means to raise one's voice mentioning something and to publicize it (4 verses: 2:173-5:3-6:145-16:105)",
      "d": "«اَھَلَّ» means to raise one's voice mentioning something. And «ھِلَال» means the new moon, upon seeing which people call each other and raise their voices (m. l. maf). And «تَھْلِیْل» means saying «لَا اِلٰہَ اِلَّا اللہُ» with a raised voice.\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «اِنَّمَا حَرَّمَ عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡمَیۡتَۃَ وَ الدَّمَ وَ لَحۡمَ الۡخِنۡزِیۡرِ وَ مَاۤ اُہِلَّ بِہٖ لِغَیۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (2/173)\nTranslation: He has only forbidden to you dead animals, blood, the flesh of swine, and that which has been dedicated to other than Allah."
    }
  ],
  "590": [
    {
      "id": 2697,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "firm",
      "hw": "مضبوط",
      "s": "«ثَابِت» means to remain established on one's foundation (2 verses: 14:24-14:27)",
      "d": "«ثَبَّتَ» means to remain firm. To become established. And «ثَبَّتَ عَلَی الْاَمْر» means to persist in an action (minjadd). Its opposite is «زَلّ», meaning not to remain firm on one's foundation. To slip away.\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «مَثَلًا کَلِمَۃً طَیِّبَۃً کَشَجَرَۃٍ طَیِّبَۃٍ اَصۡلُہَا ثَابِتٌ وَّ فَرۡعُہَا فِی السَّمَآءِ» (14/24)\nTranslation: A goodly word is like a goodly tree, whose root is firm and whose branches are in the sky."
    },
    {
      "id": 2699,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "firm",
      "hw": "مضبوط",
      "s": "«مَتِیْن» means for something to be durable in itself (3 verses: 7:183-51:58-68:45)",
      "d": "«مَتِیْن» means for something to be firm and solid in itself and for firmness (i.e., strength and stability) to permeate it. (m. l.) «حَبْلٌ مَّتِیْنٌ» means a firm rope. And «رَأیَ مَتِیْنٌ» means a firm opinion (m. l.).\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «وَ اُمۡلِیۡ لَہُمۡ ؕ اِنَّ کَیۡدِیۡ مَتِیۡنٌ» (68/45)\nTranslation: And I will give them respite. Indeed, my plan is firm."
    },
    {
      "id": 2700,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "firm",
      "hw": "مضبوط",
      "s": "«مُحْکَم» proven by wisdom and experience. Firm. (2 verses: 3:7-47:20)",
      "d": "«اَحْکَمَ» means to make something firm with wisdom and experience (minjadd). According to Imam Raghib, the decisive verses are those in which there is no doubt or ambiguity, either literal or contextual (muf).\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «ہُوَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَنۡزَلَ عَلَیۡکَ الۡکِتٰبَ مِنۡہُ اٰیٰتٌ مُّحۡکَمٰتٌ ہُنَّ اُمُّ الۡکِتٰبِ وَ اُخَرُ مُتَشٰبِہٰتٌ» (3/7)\nTranslation: It is He who has sent down to you the Book. From it are verses [that are] precise - they are the foundation of the Book - and others unspecific."
    },
    {
      "id": 2701,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "firm",
      "hw": "مضبوط",
      "s": "«قَیِّمَۃٌ» such firmness that can be a support for others or serve as a standard for them (2 verses: 98:3-98:5)",
      "d": "«قَامَ» means to stand. And «قَامَ الْاَمْر» means for a matter to come to equilibrium. And «اَقَامَ الْمَائِل» means to straighten the crooked (minjadd). And «قَیَام» and «قَوَام» also refer to that upon which something can stand (muf).\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «وَ لَا تُؤۡتُوا السُّفَہَآءَ اَمۡوَالَکُمُ الَّتِیۡ جَعَلَ اللّٰہُ لَکُمۡ قِیٰمًا» (4/5)\nTranslation: And do not give the foolish your wealth which Allah has made a means of support for you.\nAnd «قَیِّمْ» its feminine is «قَیِّمَۃ», meaning that which other things stand upon. That is, that which maintains and keeps things firm, and that which serves as a standard to distinguish between truth and falsehood.\nFor example, the divine command states: «رَسُوۡلٌ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ یَتۡلُوۡا صُحُفًا مُّطَہَّرَۃً فِیۡہَا کُتُبٌ قَیِّمَۃٌ» (98/2,3)\nTranslation: A messenger from Allah, reciting purified scriptures. Within them are correct/established books."
    },
    {
      "id": 2702,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "firm",
      "hw": "مضبوط",
      "s": "«وُثْقٰی» such firmness that can be trusted (2 verses: 2:256-31:22)",
      "d": "«وَثِقَ یَثِقُ ثِقَۃً» means to trust, to have confidence. And «وَثُقَ یُوْثَقُ وَثَاقَۃً» means to be firm and strong. To be firm. And «اَوْثَقَ» means to bind firmly with a rope. And «ثِقَۃٌ» means trustworthy, reliable. And «اَوْثَقٌ» its feminine is «وُثْقٰی», meaning firm and trustworthy.\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «قَدۡ تَّبَیَّنَ الرُّشۡدُ مِنَ الۡغَیِّ ۚ فَمَنۡ یَّکۡفُرۡ بِالطَّاغُوۡتِ وَ یُؤۡمِنۡۢ بِاللّٰہِ فَقَدِ اسۡتَمۡسَکَ بِالۡعُرۡوَۃِ الۡوُثۡقٰی ٭ لَا انۡفِصَامَ لَہَا» (2/256)\nTranslation: Clear has become the path of truth from falsehood. So whoever disbelieves in false deities and believes in Allah has grasped the most trustworthy handhold, which will never break."
    },
    {
      "id": 2703,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to make firm",
      "hw": "مضبوط",
      "s": "«ثَبَّتَ» means to keep something firm and strong in its place (13 verses: 2:250-3:147-8:11-8:12-8:45-11:120-13:39-14:24-14:27-16:102-17:74-25:32-47:7)",
      "d": "«ثَبَّتَ» means to make something firm in its place. To strengthen. To keep steadfast.\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «یُثَبِّتُ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا بِالۡقَوۡلِ الثَّابِتِ فِی الۡحَیٰوۃِ الدُّنۡیَا وَ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ» (14/27)\nTranslation: Allah will keep firm those who believe with the firm word in the worldly life and in the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 2704,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to make firm",
      "hw": "مضبوط",
      "s": "«اَحْکَم» to purify something from doubt and suspicion through wisdom and experience (2 verses: 11:1-22:52)",
      "d": "«اَحْکَم» means to make something firm in its structure with wisdom, sagacity, and experience. And «حَکِیْم» means «اَلْعَالَمُ بِاِحْکَامِ الْاُمُورِ» (faqill 77).\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «ثُمَّ یُحۡکِمُ اللّٰہُ اٰیٰتِہٖ» (22/52)\nTranslation: Then Allah will establish His verses.\nAnd the decisive verses are those in which there is no literal or contextual doubt or ambiguity."
    },
    {
      "id": 2705,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To make firm; to strengthen",
      "hw": "مضبوط",
      "s": "«اَوْثَقَ» means to make something firm and reliable through something else (3 verses: 12:66-12:80-89:26)",
      "d": "«اَوْثَقَ» means to make a covenant or agreement firm and reliable, or to tie someone firmly with ropes, etc.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ لَا یُوۡثِقُ وَ ثَاقَہٗۤ  اَحَدٌ» (89/26)\nTranslation: And no one will be bound like that.\nAt another place, Allah says:\n«وَ اذۡکُرُوۡا نِعۡمَۃَ اللّٰہِ عَلَیۡکُمۡ وَ مِیۡثَاقَہُ الَّذِیۡ وَاثَقَکُمۡ  بِہٖۤ» (5/7)\nTranslation: And remember the favor of Allah upon you and His covenant with which He has bound you.\nBesides these, the following words also appear in the Quran with similar meanings: for example:\n«شَدَّ ، اَتْقَنَ ، رَبَطَ ، اٰزَرَ ، عَقَّدَ ، وَکَّدَ ، سَنَّدَ ، رَصَّ ، شَیَّد»\nThese words are also used in the same senses."
    },
    {
      "id": 2708,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To make firm; to strengthen",
      "hw": "مضبوط",
      "s": "«رَبَطَ» means to tie firmly (3 verses: 8:11-18:14-28:10)",
      "d": "«رَبَطَ» means to tie firmly; it is an idiom. «رَبَطَ اللہُ عَلٰی قَلْبِہٖ» means Allah strengthened his heart by granting patience. And «رِبَاط» means that with which something is tied. And «رَابِطَہ» means connection, union (see lexicon).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اَصۡبَحَ فُؤَادُ  اُمِّ مُوۡسٰی فٰرِغًا ؕ اِنۡ کَادَتۡ لَتُبۡدِیۡ بِہٖ  لَوۡ لَاۤ  اَنۡ رَّبَطۡنَا عَلٰی قَلۡبِہَا» (28/10)\nTranslation: And the heart of Moses' mother became empty, almost revealing it, had We not strengthened her heart."
    },
    {
      "id": 2709,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To make firm; to strengthen",
      "hw": "مضبوط",
      "s": "«اٰزَرَ» means to strengthen gradually by providing strength (1 verse: 48:29)",
      "d": "«اَلْاِزْر» means root, foundation. And «اَلْاَزَار» means cloak, covering, veil, wall backing. And «اٰزَرَ الْنَبَات» means plants becoming intertwined. And «اَزَّرَہ» means to provide strength, to make firm (see lexicon). Thus, «اٰزَرَ» comes to mean gradually strengthening by giving strength.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کَزَرۡعٍ  اَخۡرَجَ  شَطۡئَہٗ  فَاٰزَرَہٗ» (48/29)\nTranslation: Like a crop that produces its sprout and then strengthens it."
    },
    {
      "id": 2711,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To make firm; to strengthen",
      "hw": "مضبوط",
      "s": "«عَقَّدَ» is used to make covenants, sales, marriages, and all kinds of agreements firm (7 verses: 2:235-2:237-4:33-5:1-5:89-20:27-113:4)",
      "d": "«عَقَدَ» means to tie a knot. And «عَقَدَۃ» means knot, tangle, complex matter. And «عَقَّدُ الْبَیْع وَ الْیَمِیْن» means to make a sale or oath firm (see lexicon). And «عَقْد» means covenant, agreement. Its plural is «عَقُوْد».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَا یُؤَاخِذُکُمُ اللّٰہُ بِاللَّغۡوِ فِیۡۤ  اَیۡمَانِکُمۡ وَ لٰکِنۡ یُّؤَاخِذُکُمۡ بِمَا عَقَّدۡتُّمُ الۡاَیۡمَانَ» (5/89)\nTranslation: Allah will not hold you accountable for meaningless oaths, but He will hold you accountable for what you have firmly affirmed in oaths."
    },
    {
      "id": 2712,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To make firm; to strengthen",
      "hw": "مضبوط",
      "s": "«سَنَّدَ» means to support and strengthen (1 verse: 63:4)",
      "d": "«سَنَدَ» means to trust, rely on, take support. And «سَنَّدَ» means to give support and strengthen (see lexicon), as when the beams of a roof are weak, another wooden beam is placed under them to strengthen the roof.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کَاَنَّہُمۡ خُشُبٌ مُّسَنَّدَۃٌ ؕ یَحۡسَبُوۡنَ  کُلَّ صَیۡحَۃٍ  عَلَیۡہِمۡ» (63/4)\nTranslation: They are like wooden planks propped up (against a wall); they think every cry is against them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2713,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To make firm; to strengthen",
      "hw": "مضبوط",
      "s": "«رَصَّ» means to make something firm by soldering with lead (1 verse: 61:4)",
      "d": "«رَصَّ» means to join one thing with another, to connect and make continuous. And «رَصَاص» means lead. Thus, «رَصَّہٗ» means to make something firm by soldering it with lead.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُحِبُّ الَّذِیۡنَ یُقَاتِلُوۡنَ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِہٖ  صَفًّا کَاَنَّہُمۡ  بُنۡیَانٌ  مَّرۡصُوۡصٌ» (61/4)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah loves those who fight in His cause in ranks, as if they are a solid structure."
    }
  ],
  "591": [
    {
      "id": 2715,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To forgive; to pardon; to show forbearance; to seek forgiveness",
      "hw": "معاف",
      "s": "«عَفَا» means to let go of someone who deserves punishment (28 verses: 2:52-2:109-2:178-2:187-2:237-2:286-3:152-3:155-3:159-4:43-4:99-4:149-4:153-5:13-5:15-5:95-5:101-7:199-9:43-9:66-22:60-24:22-42:25-42:30-42:34-42:40-58:2-64:14)",
      "d": "«عَفَا» means to renounce punishment or retaliation (lexicon). To let go of someone who deserves punishment, not to take retribution for their fault, whether minor or major. (See also the second meaning of «فْو» as 'excess'.)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«عَفَا اللّٰہُ عَنۡکَ ۚ لِمَ اَذِنۡتَ لَہُمۡ» (9/43)\nTranslation: May Allah forgive you, [O Muhammad]. Why did you permit them?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2716,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To forgive; to pardon; to show forbearance; to seek forgiveness",
      "hw": "معاف",
      "s": "«اَصْفَحَ» means to pardon graciously, not letting someone feel their fault (6 verses: 2:109-5:13-15:85-24:22-43:89-64:14)",
      "d": "«اَصْفَحَ» means to pardon, to let go, to not make someone feel their fault, not to even reproach them. This is more difficult than forgiving. And «اَصْفَحَ» is stronger than «عَفَا». «عَفَا» is renouncing punishment, while «اَصْفَحَ» is used for renouncing reproach (lexicon).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاعۡفُوۡا وَ اصۡفَحُوۡا حَتّٰی یَاۡتِیَ اللّٰہُ بِاَمۡرِہٖ» (2/109)\nTranslation: So pardon and graciously overlook until Allah brings His command."
    },
    {
      "id": 2717,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To forgive; to pardon; to show forbearance; to seek forgiveness",
      "hw": "معاف",
      "s": "«غَفَرَ» means Allah's saving His servants from the punishment of their sins, i.e., forgiving them (124 verses: 2:58-2:175-2:199-2:221-2:263-2:268-2:284-2:285-2:286-3:16-3:17-3:31-3:129-3:133-3:135-3:136-3:147-3:157-3:159-3:193-4:48-4:64-4:96-4:106-4:110-4:116-4:137-4:168-5:9-5:18-5:40-5:74-5:118-7:23-7:149-7:151-7:155-7:161-7:169-8:4-8:29-8:33-8:38-8:70-8:74-9:80-9:113-11:3-11:11-11:47-11:52-11:61-11:90-12:29-12:92-12:97-12:98-13:6-14:10-14:41-18:55-19:47-20:73-22:50-23:109-23:118-24:22-24:26-24:62-26:51-26:82-26:86-27:46-28:16-33:35-33:71-34:4-35:7-36:11-36:27-38:24-38:25-38:35-39:53-40:7-40:55-41:6-41:43-42:5-42:37-42:43-45:14-46:31-47:15-47:19-47:34-48:2-48:11-48:14-48:29-49:3-51:18-53:32-57:20-57:21-57:28-59:10-60:4-60:5-60:12-61:12-63:5-63:6-64:14-64:17-66:8-67:12-71:4-71:7-71:10-71:28-73:20-74:56-110:3)",
      "d": "«غَفَرَ» means to cover something with something that protects it from blemish, loss, or harm (lexicon). It is said «غَفَرَ الشَّبَاب بِالْخِضَاب» meaning he covered the whiteness of hair with dye. And «مِغْفَر» means the helmet that soldiers wear on their heads during battle, also called «اَلْغَفَارَۃ». And «اَلْغَفَارَۃ» also refers to the cloth women use under their headscarf to protect it from oil, and the cloth used to wrap arrowheads (lexicon). From Allah, «غُفْرَان» means He covers His servants from the punishment of their sins. And «غَفَرَ» means Allah saves His servants from the punishment of their sins; its form is with «ل». And «غُفْرَان» implies the removal of punishment and makes reward obligatory (fiqh).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّغۡفِرُ الذُّنُوۡبَ اِلَّا اللّٰہُ» (3/135)\nTranslation: And who can forgive sins except Allah?\nAnd to seek forgiveness from Allah for sins, «اِسْتَغْفر» is used, with the relation to Allah, whether His name is mentioned or not.\nFor example, Allah says:\n«سَوَاءٌ  عَلَیۡہِمۡ  اَسۡتَغۡفَرۡتَ لَہُمۡ  اَمۡ لَمۡ تَسۡتَغۡفِرۡ لَہُمۡ» (63/6)\nTranslation: It is all the same for them whether you seek forgiveness for them or not; Allah will not forgive them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2718,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To forgive; to pardon; to show forbearance; to seek forgiveness",
      "hw": "معاف",
      "s": "«تَصَدَّقَ» is used to mean giving up one's right to forgive (3 verses: 2:280-4:92-5:45)",
      "d": "«تَصَدَّقَ» means to relinquish one's right and to forgive someone by giving up one's right to them (lexicon).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ کَانَ ذُوۡ عُسۡرَۃٍ فَنَظِرَۃٌ اِلٰی مَیۡسَرَۃٍ ؕ وَ اَنۡ تَصَدَّقُوۡا خَیۡرٌ لَّکُمۡ» (2/280)\nTranslation: And if the debtor is in difficulty, then grant him respite until it is easy for him. And to remit it as charity is better for you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2719,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To Forgive; To Pardon; To Overlook; To Seek Forgiveness",
      "hw": "معاف",
      "s": "«تَجَاوَزَ» means to overlook, to forgive, and to pardon. (1 verse: 46:16)",
      "d": "«جَازَ» means for something to be permissible, not to be forbidden (m. q). And «جَاوَزَ الْمَکَان» means to go beyond a place. «تَجَاوَزَ عَنْہُ» means to overlook, to forgive. And «تَجَاوَزَ فِی الْاَمْرِ» means to exceed in something (i.e., to go beyond the limit of moderation) (manjad). And it also means to have more fault (i.e., shortcoming and error) but, out of grace and kindness, not to hold accountable (muf). For example, the Quran states: «اُولٰٓئِکَ الَّذِیۡنَ نَتَقَبَّلُ عَنۡہُمۡ  اَحۡسَنَ مَا عَمِلُوۡا وَ نَتَجَاوُزُ عَنۡ سَیِّاٰتِہِمۡ» (46/16). Translation: Those are the ones from whom We accept the best of what they do and overlook their evil deeds."
    },
    {
      "id": 2721,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To forgive, to pardon, to show forbearance, to seek forgiveness.",
      "hw": "معاف",
      "s": "«حِطَّۃٌ» is used to seek forgiveness for sins (2 verses: 2:58, 7:161).",
      "d": "«حَطَّ» means to descend, to be revealed. «حَطَّ السَّعْر» means the price to fall. And «حَطُّ الْحَمْلَ» means to remove the burden from the animal's back. And «اِنْحِطَاط» means to fall in price or in steps (dictionary). And «حَطُّ» means to remove something from above to below. They say «حَطَطْتُ الرَّحَل» I removed the saddle from the riding animal and placed it below. From this, «حِطَّۃٌ» means the request to remove the burden of sins (source). For example, in the Quran: «وَّ قُوۡلُوۡا حِطَّۃٌ نَّغۡفِرۡ لَکُمۡ خَطٰیٰکُمۡ» (2/58) Translation: And say, 'Seek forgiveness for your sins, so We will forgive your sins.'"
    }
  ],
  "592": [
    {
      "id": 2722,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "capacity, status",
      "hw": "حیثیت",
      "s": "«وُجْد» is commonly used for existing supplies (2 verses: 12:75, 65:6).",
      "d": "«وَجَدَ» means to find. And «وُجْد» means existing. That which is present among the necessities of life. For example, the Quran states: «اَسۡکِنُوۡہُنَّ مِنۡ حَیۡثُ سَکَنۡتُمۡ مِّنۡ وُّجۡدِکُمۡ» (65/6) Translation: (Generally) keep the women (during their waiting period) where you dwell, according to your capacity."
    },
    {
      "id": 2723,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "capacity, status",
      "hw": "حیثیت",
      "s": "«سَعَۃ» is used for prosperity and determining its degree (4 verses: 2:247, 4:130, 24:22, 65:7).",
      "d": "«سَعَۃ» means abundance, capacity, prosperity. This word is used to determine the degree of human prosperity. The concept of poverty is not found in it. For example, the Quran states: «لِیُنۡفِقۡ ذُوۡ سَعَۃٍ مِّنۡ سَعَتِہٖ» (65/7) Translation: The person of means should spend according to his means."
    },
    {
      "id": 2724,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "capacity, status",
      "hw": "حیثیت",
      "s": "«قَدَرَ» generally comes for determining poverty and its degree (11 verses: 13:26, 17:30, 28:82, 29:62, 30:37, 34:36, 34:39, 39:52, 42:12, 65:7, 89:16).",
      "d": "«قَدَرَ» this word, in its origin, comes for the state of poverty and determining its degree. For example, the Quran states: «اَللّٰہُ یَبۡسُطُ الرِّزۡقَ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ وَ یَقۡدِرُ» (13/26) Translation: Allah expands the provision for whom He wills and restricts for whom He wills. But this word has also been used by the Quran to determine the degrees of both poverty and prosperity. For example, the divine command is: «عَلَی الۡمُوۡسِعِ قَدَرُہٗ وَ عَلَی الۡمُقۡتِرِ قَدَرُہٗ مَتَاعًۢا بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡف» (2/236) Translation: The wealthy person according to his capacity and the poor person according to his capacity should give this gift in a good manner."
    }
  ],
  "593": [
    {
      "id": 2725,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To appoint, to decree",
      "hw": "مقرر",
      "s": "«فَرَضَ» means to make something obligatory or to decree (11 verses: 2:197, 2:236, 2:237, 4:11, 4:24, 9:60, 24:1, 28:85, 33:38, 33:50, 66:2).",
      "d": "«فَرَضَ» means to cut a hard thing, to pierce, and to mark on a hard thing, like a line on a stone (dictionary). And «فَرَّضَ الْخَشْبَۃَ» means to bore a hole in wood. And «فَرَضَ الْاَمْر» means to make something obligatory or necessary. And «اَلْفَرْض» means the law ordained by Allah or something made obligatory upon oneself (dictionary). And «فَرِیْضَۃً» means something made obligatory, decreed, or settled, such as the dowry for women (dictionary). For example, in the Quran: «لَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ  اِنۡ طَلَّقۡتُمُ النِّسَآءَ مَا لَمۡ تَمَسُّوۡہُنَّ اَوۡ تَفۡرِضُوۡا لَہُنَّ فَرِیۡضَۃً» (2/236) Translation: There is no blame on you if you divorce women before touching them or before appointing for them a decreed amount (dowry)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2726,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To appoint, to decree",
      "hw": "مقرر",
      "s": "«وَکَّلَ» means to appoint someone as one's representative (2 verses: 6:89, 32:11).",
      "d": "«وَکَلَ» means to trust someone in one's affair (dictionary). And «وَکَّل» means to entrust one's affair to someone by trusting them, to make someone one's agent or appointed representative (source, dictionary). For example, in the Quran: «فَاِنۡ یَّکۡفُرۡ بِہَا ہٰۤؤُلَآءِ  فَقَدۡ وَکَّلۡنَا بِہَا قَوْمًا لَّیۡسُوۡا بِہَا بِکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (6/89) Translation: So if these people disbelieve in it, then We have already appointed for it a people who are not disbelievers in it."
    },
    {
      "id": 2727,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To appoint, to decree",
      "hw": "مقرر",
      "s": "«اَجَّلَ» means to set a term or period (45 verses: 2:231, 2:232, 2:234, 2:235, 2:282, 4:77, 6:2, 6:60, 6:128, 7:34, 7:135, 7:185, 10:11, 10:49, 11:3, 11:104, 13:2, 13:38, 14:10, 14:44, 15:5, 16:61, 17:99, 20:129, 22:5, 22:33, 23:43, 28:28, 28:29, 29:5, 29:53, 30:8, 31:29, 35:13, 35:45, 39:5, 39:42, 40:67, 42:14, 46:3, 63:10, 63:11, 65:2, 65:4, 71:4).",
      "d": "«اَجَل» means an appointed period for something. Then the period appointed for human life is also called «اَجَل». The phrase «دَنَا اَجَلُہٗ» means his time of death has approached. And «اَجَّلَ» means to appoint a period for something (source). For example, in the Quran: «وَّ بَلَغۡنَاۤ  اَجَلَنَا الَّذِیۡۤ  اَجَّلۡتَ لَنَا» (6/128) Translation: And we have reached our appointed term which you had appointed for us."
    }
  ],
  "594": [
    {
      "id": 2728,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "fly",
      "hw": "مکھی",
      "s": "«ذُبَاب» means fly (1 verse: 22:73).",
      "d": "«ذُبَاب» means a small fly. And «ذَبَّ عَنْہُ» means to drive flies away from someone, to fly away or to remove accusations. And «مَذِبَّۃ» means a fly swatter. With which flies are driven away. Its plural is «ذُبٌّ و اَذِبَّۃ». For example, the Quran states: «وَ اِنۡ یَّسۡلُبۡہُمُ الذُّبَابُ شَیۡئًا لَّا یَسۡتَنۡقِذُوۡہُ مِنۡہُ» (22/73) Translation: And if the fly should snatch from them a [little] thing, they would not recover it from him."
    },
    {
      "id": 2729,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "fly",
      "hw": "مکھی",
      "s": "«نَحْل» is the generic term for the honey bee (1 verse: 16:68).",
      "d": "«نَحْل» is the plural of «نَحْلَۃٌ», meaning the honey bee is a generic term. It is used for both masculine and feminine. For example, the Quran states: «وَ اَوۡحٰی رَبُّکَ اِلَی النَّحۡلِ اَنِ اتَّخِذِیۡ مِنَ الۡجِبَالِ بُیُوۡتًا وَّ مِنَ الشَّجَرِ وَ مِمَّا یَعۡرِشُوۡنَ» (16/68) Translation: And your Lord inspired the bee, 'Take for yourself among the mountains, houses, and among the trees and [in] that which they construct.'"
    }
  ],
  "595": [
    {
      "id": 2730,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to meet",
      "hw": "ملنا",
      "s": "«لَقِیَ» means two things meeting face-to-face (2 verses: 2:14-2:76)",
      "d": "«لَقِیَ» means to meet face-to-face, to encounter. To come and meet from the front. (m. l.)\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ اِذَا لَقُوا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا قَالُوۡۤا اٰمَنَّا» (2/14)\nTranslation: And when these hypocrites meet the believers, they say, 'We have believed.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2731,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to meet",
      "hw": "ملنا",
      "s": "«لَحَقَ» means to go and join something similar to the first thing (2 verses: 3:170-62:3)",
      "d": "«لَحَقَ» means to go and join something similar to the first thing (m. l.). «لَاحِق» is the thing that joins with the first. The fruit of the second time after the first (source).\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ یَسۡتَبۡشِرُوۡنَ بِالَّذِیۡنَ لَمۡ یَلۡحَقُوۡا بِہِمۡ مِّنۡ خَلۡفِہِمۡ  ۙ اَلَّا خَوۡفٌ عَلَیۡہِمۡ وَ لَا ہُمۡ یَحۡزَنُوۡنَ» (3/170)\nTranslation: And they rejoice in those who have not yet joined them [in martyrdom] from behind them – there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve.\nAt another place, the Lord says:\n«وَّ اٰخَرِیۡنَ مِنۡہُمۡ  لَمَّا یَلۡحَقُوۡا بِہِمۡ» (62/3)\nTranslation: And there are others among them who have not yet joined them. And He is the Exalted in Might, the Wise."
    },
    {
      "id": 2732,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to meet",
      "hw": "ملنا",
      "s": "«وَلِیَ» means two living things being connected without temporal or spatial gap (1 verse: 9:123)",
      "d": "«وَلَی یَلیٰ وَلْیًا» means to be near and close. To be contiguous. To go behind without gap (source). To be connected due to proximity. This word is used in both verbal and spatial contexts. And this proximity is in terms of lineage. Or in terms of religion and friendship. (m.f.)\nExample in the spatial sense is:\nIn the Quran it is:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا قَاتِلُوا الَّذِیۡنَ یَلُوۡنَکُمۡ مِّنَ الۡکُفَّارِ» (9/123)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, fight those who are near you of the disbelievers.\nIts meaning is: fight the disbelievers who are adjacent to you first. Then if they become Muslim or accept obedience, then fight those adjacent to them, and then those living with them. And an example in the temporal sense is not found in the Quran. However, it is clear from the following saying of the Prophet ﷺ:\nProphetic Hadith states:\n«خَیْرُ الْقُرُوْنِ قَرْنِیْ ثُمَّ الَّذِیْنَ یَلُوْنَھُمْ ثُمَّ الَّذِیْنَ یَلُوْنَھُمْ»\nTranslation: The best generation is mine, then those who follow them, then those who follow them!\nAnd this refers to the time of the Prophet ﷺ, then the time of the Companions, then the time of the Successors."
    },
    {
      "id": 2735,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to meet",
      "hw": "ملنا",
      "s": "«تَجَاوَرَ» means one thing meeting another due to being in proximity (1 verse: 13:4)",
      "d": "«جَارَ» means to share shade. Neighbor. And «جَاوَرَ» and «تَجَاوَرَ» mean to be contiguous due to proximity of distance. To be in proximity. To live as neighbors (source). To be side by side. To be in adjacency.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ قِطَعٌ مُّتَجٰوِرٰتٌ» (13/4)\nTranslation: And on the earth are plots [of land] adjacent to one another."
    },
    {
      "id": 2736,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to meet",
      "hw": "ملنا",
      "s": "«رَتَقَ» means to join and become sealed (1 verse: 21:30)",
      "d": "«رَتَقَ» means two or several things to join together and become sealed, to stick together (m. source). And «رَتْقَاء» is the term for a woman whose labia majora are joined in such a way that intercourse is not possible (m.f.)\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«اَوَ لَمۡ  یَرَ الَّذِیۡنَ  کَفَرُوۡۤا  اَنَّ  السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ کَانَتَا رَتۡقًا فَفَتَقۡنٰہُمَا» (21/30)\nTranslation: Have those who disbelieved not considered that the heavens and the earth were a joined entity, and We separated them?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2738,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to meet",
      "hw": "ملنا",
      "s": "«اِشْتَمَلَ» means to gather scattered parts of something into the original thing, to include (2 verses: 6:143-6:144)",
      "d": "«اَلشَّمْل» means the gathered matter. The scattered matter (this is from the lexicon of antonyms). «جَمَعَ اللہُ شَمْلَھُمْ» means Allah gather their scattered affairs. And «فَرَّقَ اللہُ شَمْلَھُمْ» means Allah scatter their gathering. And «شَمِلَ» means to wrap in a garment. And «شَمَلَ» and «شَمِلَ» mean to include everything. To be general (source). And «اِشْتَمَلَ» means to gather the scattered parts of something into the original thing. To include.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«قُلۡ ءٰٓالذَّکَرَیۡنِ حَرَّمَ اَمِ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ اَمَّا اشۡتَمَلَتۡ عَلَیۡہِ اَرۡحَامُ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ ؕ» (6/143)\nTranslation: Say, 'Have you considered: if Allah should make the male [offspring] forbidden or the female, or what the wombs of the females contain?'\nNote: (Lexicon of antonyms refers to words that have two opposite meanings.)"
    }
  ],
  "596": [
    {
      "id": 2739,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to mix",
      "hw": "ملانا",
      "s": "«خَلَطَ» means to mix various things, to blend (2 verses: 9:102-38:24)",
      "d": "«خَلَطَ» means to mix two or more different things together. To blend. To mix up. And its opposite is «خَلَصَ».\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ اٰخَرُوۡنَ اعۡتَرَفُوۡا بِذُنُوۡبِہِمۡ خَلَطُوۡا عَمَلًا صَالِحًا وَّ اٰخَرَ  سَیِّئًا» (9/102)\nTranslation: And others have confessed their sins, mixing a righteous deed with another that is bad."
    },
    {
      "id": 2740,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to join",
      "hw": "ملانا",
      "s": "«اَلْحَقَ» means to join from behind (4 verses: 12:101-26:83-34:27-52:21)",
      "d": "«اَلْحَقَ» means to go and join from behind.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«تَوَفَّنِیۡ مُسۡلِمًا وَّ اَلۡحِقۡنِیۡ  بِالصّٰلِحِیۡنَ» (12/101)\nTranslation: [My Lord] cause me to die a Muslim and join me with the righteous."
    },
    {
      "id": 2741,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to connect",
      "hw": "ملانا",
      "s": "«وَصَلَ» means to mix and join (18 verses: 2:27-4:10-4:90-6:136-11:81-13:21-13:25-14:29-17:18-28:35-28:51-38:56-58:8-82:15-84:12-87:12-92:15-111:3)",
      "d": "«وَصَلَ» means to join two things together so that they become connected (m. l.). «وِصَال» is the opposite of «ھِجْرَان». And (the opposite of connection is disconnection). To mix. To join. This word is used in both material and spiritual contexts. In material sense, it means to reach something. In spiritual sense, it means to join relationships and make them connected.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ یَقۡطَعُوۡنَ مَاۤ اَمَرَ اللّٰہُ بِہٖۤ  اَنۡ یُّوۡصَلَ» (2/27)\nTranslation: And they sever what Allah has ordered to be joined."
    },
    {
      "id": 2742,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to unite",
      "hw": "ملانا",
      "s": "«اَلَّفَ» means to gather scattered parts of the same thing (2 verses: 3:103-8:63)",
      "d": "«اَلَّفَ» means to gather scattered parts of the same thing. To fix and join the scattered thread. And its opposite is «شَتَّ». Meaning to agree with each other's thoughts and to remove differences of hearts and create love. And «اُلْفَت» means heartfelt love. And composition is such a phrase where various parts are collected in the correct places considering precedence and sequence. (m.f.)\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ اَلَّفَ بَیۡنَ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ ؕ لَوۡ اَنۡفَقۡتَ مَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ جَمِیۡعًا مَّاۤ  اَلَّفۡتَ بَیۡنَ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ» (8/63)\nTranslation: And Allah united the hearts of the believers. If you had spent all that is in the earth, you could not have united their hearts."
    },
    {
      "id": 2746,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "mixing",
      "hw": "ملانا",
      "s": "«مَشَجَ» means two similar things mixing together to become one (1 verse: 76:2)",
      "d": "«مَشَجَ» means mixing. Blending and mixing, and «مَشِیْج» means mixed, blended. Its plural is «اَمْشَاج». (Majid) i.e., two similar things mixing together to become one.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّا خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ نُّطۡفَۃٍ  اَمۡشَاجٍ ٭ۖ  نَّبۡتَلِیۡہِ» (76/2)\nTranslation: And We have created man from a mixed drop (i.e., the sperm of both man and woman) which We then test."
    },
    {
      "id": 2747,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To mix",
      "hw": "ملانا",
      "s": "«مَزَجَ» means to mix something into a drink (3 verses: 76:5, 76:17, 83:27).",
      "d": "«مَزَجَ» means to mix something into a drink. And «اَلشَّرَاب» means to mix something into a drink. And what is mixed into a drink is called «مِزْج» and «مِزَاج» (source, dictionary). And in the terminology of «اَطِبَّاء», the quality that results from the mixing of different humors in the body is called مزاج, meaning temperament or condition (dictionary). For example, in the Quran: «وَ یُسۡقَوۡنَ  فِیۡہَا کَاۡسًا کَانَ مِزَاجُہَا زَنۡجَبِیۡلًا» (76/17) Translation: And they will be given cups therein whose mixture will be ginger. In the Quran, there is also mention of two mixtures: كافور and تسنیم."
    },
    {
      "id": 2748,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "mixing",
      "hw": "ملانا",
      "s": "«مَرَجَ» means to mix two similar things in such a way that their individual characteristics remain intact (2 verses: 25:53-55:19)",
      "d": "«مَرَجَ» means two things mixing together in such a way that their individual characteristics also remain intact. «غُصْنٌ مَرِیْجٌ» means intertwined branches, i.e., mixed together. And «اَمْرٌ مَرَیْج» means a complicated and mixed matter in which two or more views are entangled (Mufradat).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«مَرَجَ  الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ یَلۡتَقِیٰنِ» (55/19)\nTranslation: He has released the two seas, meeting together. (Jalandhari) Two flowing seas that meet. (Osmani)"
    }
  ],
  "597": [
    {
      "id": 2752,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "turning away",
      "hw": "منہ",
      "s": "«تَوَلّٰی عَنْ» is used to end friendly relations (12 verses: 7:79-7:93-8:20-12:84-27:28-37:90-37:174-37:178-44:14-51:54-53:29-54:6)",
      "d": "«تَوَلّٰی» means to make someone a friend. And «تَوَلّٰی عَن» means to turn away from friendship. Turning away. Moving away. Leaving (Majid).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ تَوَلَّ عَنۡہُمۡ حَتّٰی حِیۡنٍ» (37/178)\nTranslation: So turn away from them for a time."
    },
    {
      "id": 2753,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "turning away",
      "hw": "منہ",
      "s": "«صَدَفَ» is used for severe turning away (2 verses: 6:46-6:157)",
      "d": "«اَعْرَضَ عَنْہُ و صَدّ» means to turn away severely. And «صَدَف» means a shell, the side of a mountain, and the bend in an ostrich's legs. And in all three, severity and bend are found (Mufradat). Its reward sometimes comes with «عَنْ» (but it gives its meaning even without this particle).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«سَنَجۡزِی الَّذِیۡنَ یَصۡدِفُوۡنَ عَنۡ اٰیٰتِنَا سُوۡٓءَ الۡعَذَابِ  بِمَا  کَانُوۡا  یَصۡدِفُوۡنَ» (6/157)\nTranslation: We will surely recompense those who turn away from Our signs with the worst of punishment for what they used to do.\nAt another place, the Lord says:\n«اُنۡظُرۡ  کَیۡہَ نُصَرِّفُ الۡاٰیٰتِ ثُمَّ ہُمۡ یَصۡدِفُوۡنَ» (6/46)\nTranslation: See how We diversify the verses, yet they turn away."
    }
  ],
  "598": [
    {
      "id": 2754,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "making compatible",
      "hw": "موافقت",
      "s": "«وَفَّقَ» means Allah making circumstances favorable for someone (used in a good sense) (1 verse: 4:35)",
      "d": "«اَلْوَفْق» means compatibility and harmony between two things. And «وَفَّقَ تَوْفِیْقًا» means Allah making circumstances suitable for a matter. This word is not used in a bad sense (Mufradat).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنۡ یُرِیۡدَاۤ  إِصۡلَاحًا یُّوَفِّقِ اللّٰہُ بَیۡنَہُمَا» (4/35)\nTranslation: If both (the spouses) desire reconciliation, Allah will bring about harmony between them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2755,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "making compatible",
      "hw": "موافقت",
      "s": "«وَطَأ عَلَی الْاَمْر» means a human altering something to suit their own desire (used in a bad sense) (1 verse: 9:37)",
      "d": "«وَطَأ» means to trample, crush, or knead something with the foot. And «وَطَأ عَلَی الْاَمْر» means to make a matter easy according to one's own desire (Majid). And this is a human action, generally used in a bad sense.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّمَا النَّسِیۡٓءُ زِیَادَۃٌ فِی الۡکُفۡرِ  یُضَلُّ بِہِ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا یُحِلُّوۡنَہٗ عَامًا وَّ یُحَرِّمُوۡنَہٗ عَامًا لِّیُوَاطِئُوۡا عِدَّۃَ مَا حَرَّمَ اللّٰہُ فَیُحِلُّوۡا مَا حَرَّمَ اللّٰہُ» (9/37)\nTranslation: Indeed, the postponing of restriction is an increase in disbelief by which those who have disbelieved are led astray. They make it lawful one year and unlawful another year to correspond with the number of months that Allah has made sacred, so they make lawful what Allah has made forbidden."
    }
  ],
  "599": [
    {
      "id": 2756,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "موڑنا",
      "s": "«ثَنٰی» means to bend something in one direction, even if it becomes double (1 verse: 11:5)",
      "d": "«اِثْنِیْن» means two, and «ثانی» means second, and «ثَنٰی , یَثْنِیْ» means to double, bend, or fold (Mufradat, Majid).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَلَاۤ  اِنَّہُمۡ  یَثۡنُوۡنَ صُدُوۡرَہُمۡ» (11/5)\nTranslation: Do they not see that they are turning their breasts (bending them)?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2757,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "موڑنا",
      "s": "«لَوٰی» means to bend or twist something, sometimes here and sometimes there (4 verses: 3:78-3:153-4:135-63:5)",
      "d": "«لَوَی الْحَبَل» means to twist a rope. And «لَوٰی یَدَہٗ» means he bent or twisted his hand (Mufradat). And «لِیًّا بِدَیْنِہٖ» means to procrastinate in repaying a debt. And «لِوَاء» means a banner (which flutters sometimes here and sometimes there). And «اَلْاَلْوَاءِ» means the bend of a valley (Majid).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنَّ مِنۡہُمۡ لَفَرِیۡقًا یَّلۡوٗنَ اَلۡسِنَتَہُمۡ بِالۡکِتٰبِ» (3/78)\nTranslation: And indeed, among them is a group who twist their tongues while reciting the Book."
    }
  ],
  "600": [
    {
      "id": 2759,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "compassionate",
      "hw": "مہربان",
      "s": "«رَءُوْف» means the heart swelling with compassion upon seeing someone's hardship (11 verses: 2:143-2:207-3:30-9:117-9:128-16:7-16:47-22:65-24:20-57:9-59:10)",
      "d": "«رَأفَۃ» means tenderness to arise and compassion upon seeing someone's hardship. The heart swelling with compassion upon seeing someone's trouble.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَلزَّانِیَۃُ وَ الزَّانِیۡ فَاجۡلِدُوۡا کُلَّ وَاحِدٍ مِّنۡہُمَا مِائَۃَ جَلۡدَۃٍ ۪ وَّ لَا  تَاۡخُذۡکُمۡ بِہِمَا رَاۡفَۃٌ  فِیۡ  دِیۡنِ اللّٰہِ» (24/2)\nTranslation: The [adulteress] and the [adulterer] - each of them give a hundred lashes, and let not pity for them take you away from the law of Allah.\nAnd «رَءُوْف» means tender-hearted (i.e., compassionate, merciful) whose heart swells upon seeing someone's hardship and is concerned with its removal.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَقَدۡ جَآءَکُمۡ رَسُوۡلٌ مِّنۡ اَنۡفُسِکُمۡ عَزِیۡزٌ عَلَیۡہِ مَا عَنِتُّمۡ حَرِیۡصٌ عَلَیۡکُمۡ بِالۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ رَءُوۡفٌ رَّحِیۡمٌ» (9/128)\nTranslation: O people, there has come to you a Messenger from among yourselves; severe upon him is what you suffer; [he is] concerned for you and for the believers [he is] kind and merciful."
    },
    {
      "id": 2761,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Merciful",
      "hw": "مہربان",
      "s": "«حَنَّان» means a mercy and compassion like that of a mother for her child (1 verse: 19:13).",
      "d": "«اَلْحَنِیْن» means to be inclined towards something compassionately. They say «حَنَتِ المَرْاَۃُ اَوِ النَّاقَۃُ لِوَلَدِھَا» meaning the woman or the she-camel has become inclined or longing for her child (source). And «حَنَّ» means to be merciful and compassionate. And «حَنَّان» means mercy, compassion, and merciful. It is one of the Names of Allah (dictionary). For example, in the Quran: «وَّ حَنَانًا مِّنۡ لَّدُنَّا وَ زَکٰوۃً ؕ وَ کَانَ تَقِیًّا» (19/13) Translation: And (We gave him) compassion and purity from Us, and he was righteous."
    }
  ],
  "601": [
    {
      "id": 2762,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To stamp, to seal",
      "hw": "مہر ",
      "s": "«طَبَعَ» means to stamp or print (11 verses: 4:155, 7:100, 7:101, 9:87, 9:93, 10:74, 16:108, 30:59, 40:35, 47:16, 63:3).",
      "d": "«طَبَعَ» means to reach the extreme of something and to be filled. «تَطَبَّعَ النَّھْر» means the river filled (dictionary). Also, «طَبَعَ» means to stamp. And «طَبَعَ الدَّرَاھِم» means to mint coins. And «مَطْبَع» means a machine for stamping. And «مَطْبُوْع» means something stamped (dictionary). And «طَوَابِع» means postage stamps (postal, postal). So, when something reaches its end or completion, stamping or sealing it is called «طَبَعَ». And it is related to the effectiveness of something (i.e., to be affected, to have an effect) and its being established and necessary (fiqh 56). For example, in the Quran: «بَلۡ طَبَعَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہَا بِکُفۡرِہِمۡ فَلَا یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ  اِلَّا قَلِیۡلًا» (4/155) Translation: Rather, Allah has sealed them due to their disbelief, so they believe not except a little."
    },
    {
      "id": 2763,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To stamp, to seal",
      "hw": "مہر ",
      "s": "«خَتَمَ» means to seal something upon its completion so that nothing can enter or exit it (6 verses: 2:7, 6:46, 33:40, 36:65, 42:24, 45:23).",
      "d": "«خَتَمَ» means to seal, to put a seal on (i.e., to close and seal so that nothing can enter, even if there is a possibility of entry, and nothing can exit). And «خَتَمَ الْاَنَاء» means to close the mouth of a vessel with clay, etc. And «خَتَام» means the thing with which one seals (dictionary). And «خَتَمَ الْقُرآن» means he finished the Quran. So, ختم is related to the completion of something and the cessation of an action or deed (fiqh 56). For example, in the Quran: «خَتَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلٰی قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ وَ عَلٰی سَمۡعِہِمۡ» (2/7) Translation: Allah has sealed their hearts and their hearing."
    }
  ],
  "602": [
    {
      "id": 2764,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To grant respite",
      "hw": "مہلت",
      "s": "«مَھَّلَ» and «اَمْھَلَ» : to gradually and gently increase the respite (indefinite period) (2 verses: 73:11, 86:17).",
      "d": "«مَھَّلَ» means to give respite or to do something gradually. «سَارَ عَلٰی مَھْلٍ» means to walk slowly (dictionary). And «مَھَّل» means to gradually and gently increase the period for someone and not to rush (source). And this period is extended (fiqh 59). For example, in the Quran: «فَمَہِّلِ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ  اَمۡہِلۡہُمۡ رُوَیۡدًا» (86/17) Translation: So give respite to the disbelievers. Give them respite for a little while. In this verse, «مَھَّل» and «اَمْھَل» are used in the same meaning."
    },
    {
      "id": 2765,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To grant respite",
      "hw": "مہلت",
      "s": "«اَمْلٰی» means to lengthen the rope (5 verses: 7:183, 13:32, 22:44, 22:48, 68:45).",
      "d": "«مَلَا» (with a consonant alif) means to prolong life. They say «مَلَاکَ اللہ» may Allah prolong your life. And «مَلَا» means vast desert and also means to continue to benefit for a long time. And «مَلِیٌّ مِنَ الدَّھْر» means a long period (dictionary). So, «مَلِیٌّ» conveys both meanings of length and vastness. And «اَمْلٰی» means to grant respite to someone for a long time. To give respite for a long period (for the oppressor), to lengthen the rope. For example, in the Quran: «وَ  اُمۡلِیۡ   لَہُمۡ  اِنَّ  کَیۡدِیۡ مَتِیۡنٌ» (7/183) Translation: And I will give them respite. Indeed, my plan is firm."
    },
    {
      "id": 2766,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "to grant respite",
      "hw": "مہلت",
      "s": "«نَظِرَۃٌ» means waiting with leniency until a specified time (2 verses: 2:280-37:88)",
      "d": "«نَظَرَ» means to see, to look. And «نَظَرَ فُلَانَا الْمَدِیْن» means to continue looking with leniency at a debtor for the payment of a debt (Munjid). And «اَنْظَار» means to wait for a suitable time to demand something. And this period is conditional (Fiqh 59). For example, the Quran states: «وَ اِنۡ کَانَ ذُوۡ عُسۡرَۃٍ فَنَظِرَۃٌ اِلٰی مَیۡسَرَۃٍ» (2/280). Translation: Then if the debtor is in hardship, grant him respite until ease."
    }
  ],
  "603": [
    {
      "id": 2767,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Guest",
      "hw": "مہمان",
      "s": "«ضَیْف» means guest (6 verses: 11:78-15:51-15:68-18:77-51:24-54:37)",
      "d": "«ضَیْف» means guest. It is a well-known word. Its plurals are «ضَیَاف» and «ضُیُوف». «ضَیْف» can be used as both singular and plural.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاتَّقُوا اللّٰہَ وَ لَا تُخۡزُوۡنِ فِیۡ ضَیۡفِیۡ» ( 11/78 )\nTranslation: So fear Allah and do not disgrace me in my guests."
    },
    {
      "id": 2768,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "guest; delegation",
      "hw": "مہمان",
      "s": "«وَفَدَ» means a delegation, i.e., a royal guest (1 verse: 19:85)",
      "d": "«وَفَدَ» means for people to go as a delegation to a king or ruler (Mufradat). And a delegation means a royal guest. For example, the Quran states: «یَوۡمَ نَحۡشُرُ الۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ  اِلَی الرَّحۡمٰنِ وَفۡدًا» (19/85). Translation: On the Day We gather the righteous before the Most Merciful as honored guests."
    }
  ],
  "604": [
    {
      "id": 2769,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Months",
      "hw": "مہینے",
      "s": "«شُھُوْر» means the months of the year (1 verse: 9:36)",
      "d": "«شُھُوْر» means all months. The maximum number of months.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّ عِدَّۃَ الشُّہُوۡرِ عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ اثۡنَا عَشَرَ شَہۡرًا فِیۡ  کِتٰبِ اللّٰہِ یَوۡمَ خَلَقَ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ» ( 9/36 )\nTranslation: Indeed, the number of months in the sight of Allah is twelve months, in the record of Allah, from the day He created the heavens and the earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 2770,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Months",
      "hw": "مہینے",
      "s": "«اَشْھُرُ» means the specified months (17 verses: 2:185-2:194-2:197-2:217-2:226-2:234-4:92-5:2-5:97-9:2-9:5-9:36-34:12-46:15-58:4-65:4-97:3)",
      "d": "«اَشْھُرُ» means the specified months. Their number is always less than or equal to twelve. When the number is mentioned and is singular, «اَشْھُرُ» is used. «اَشْھُر» is the plural of paucity, which applies to numbers from 3 to 10.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لِلَّذِیۡنَ یُؤۡلُوۡنَ مِنۡ نِّسَآئِہِمۡ تَرَبُّصُ اَرۡبَعَۃِ اَشۡہُرٍ» ( 2/226 )\nTranslation: For those who take an oath not to have sexual relations with their wives is a waiting period of four months."
    }
  ],
  "605": [
    {
      "id": 2771,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Nail / Peg",
      "hw": "میخ",
      "s": "«دُسُر» means nail, peg. (1 Verse: 54:13)",
      "d": "«دُسُر» is the plural of «دِسَار», meaning nail, peg. «دَسَر» means to spear or to drive in a peg. «دِسَار» refers to the small peg driven to fasten, seal, or strengthen something. And «دِسَار» also refers to a rope made from palm bark used to bind a ship. (Nail / Peg)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ  حَمَلۡنٰہُ  عَلٰی ذَاتِ اَلۡوَاحٍ  وَّ دُسُرٍ» ( 54/13 )\nTranslation: And We carried him on a ship made of planks and pegs."
    },
    {
      "id": 2772,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Nail / Peg",
      "hw": "میخ",
      "s": "«اَوْتَاد» means stakes, pegs, wooden pins. (3 Verses: 38:12-78:7-89:10)",
      "d": "«اَوْتَاد» is the plural of «وَتَد». «وَتَد» refers to a large peg or stake, part of which protrudes outward while the larger part is driven into the ground or something. And «وَتَدَان» means the protruding parts of the shoulders (metaphorically, pegs). That is, «وَتَد» is something whose part is sticking out. And «وَتَدَ» means a strong, driven-in peg. «وَتْد» means a wooden peg. And «اَوْتَادُ الْاَرْضِ» means mountains.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَلَمۡ  نَجۡعَلِ الۡاَرۡضَ مِہٰدًا وَّ  الۡجِبَالَ  اَوۡتَادًا» ( 78/6،7 )\nTranslation: Have We not made the earth a resting place and the mountains as stakes?"
    }
  ],
  "606": [
    {
      "id": 2773,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Despair",
      "hw": "نا امید",
      "s": "«یَأَسَ» means to despair. It is general in meanings of hopelessness. «اِسْتَیْئَس» means to lose hope gradually. (4 Verses: 12:80-12:87-12:110-13:31)",
      "d": "«یَأَسَ» means to cut off hope, i.e., to cease hoping for something or to become hopeless regarding it. This can happen before or during the time of desire. «اِسْتَیْئَس» means to gradually end expectations regarding a matter. To finally become hopeless after experience.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّہٗ  لَا یَایۡئَسُ مِنۡ رَّوۡحِ اللّٰہِ  اِلَّا الۡقَوۡمُ  الۡکٰفِرُوۡنَ» ( 12/87 )\nTranslation: None despair of the mercy of Allah except the disbelieving people.\nAnd «اِسْتَیْئَس» means to gradually lose hope in a matter. To finally become hopeless after experience.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا اسۡتَیۡئَسَ الرُّسُلُ وَ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہُمۡ قَدۡ کُذِبُوۡا جَآءَہُمۡ نَصۡرُنَا» ( 12/110 )\nTranslation: Until when the messengers had lost hope and thought that they were denied, Our victory came to them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2774,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Despair",
      "hw": "نا امید",
      "s": "«قَنَطَ» means to despair of good; it is a more severe degree of despair than «یَأَسَ». (5 Verses: 15:56-30:36-39:53-41:49-42:28)",
      "d": "«قَنَطَ» means to despair of good. To break one's hope. And «قُنُوْط» means the most intense form of despair. And «قُنُوْط» as a descriptor refers to a person who is accustomed to considering only the dark aspects and faults of every matter and who rarely ponders the good aspects.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَا یَسۡئَمُ الۡاِنۡسَانُ مِنۡ دُعَآءِ  الۡخَیۡرِ ۫ وَ اِنۡ مَّسَّہُ  الشَّرُّ  فَیَئُوۡسٌ قَنُوۡطٌ» ( 41/49 )\nTranslation: Man does not tire of praying for good, but if evil touches him, he becomes despairing and hopeless."
    },
    {
      "id": 2775,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Despair",
      "hw": "نا امید",
      "s": "«اَبْلَسَ» means a despair that causes one to be afflicted with grief. (5 Verses: 6:44-23:77-30:12-30:49-43:75)",
      "d": "«اَبْلَسَ» means to become grief-stricken due to intense despair. And it also means to be unaware. To be grief-stricken and broken-hearted. When despair leads to grief, this word is used. Satan is also called Iblis because he became despairing and broken-hearted regarding Allah's mercy.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ کَانُوۡا مِنۡ قَبۡلِ اَنۡ یُّنَزَّلَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنۡ  قَبۡلِہٖ لَمُبۡلِسِیۡنَ» ( 30/49 )\nTranslation: And they were despairing before it was sent down upon them, from before it came."
    }
  ],
  "607": [
    {
      "id": 2776,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Impure",
      "hw": "ناپاک",
      "s": "«رِجْسٌ» refers to things declared unlawful by Sharia. (9 Verses: 5:90-6:125-6:145-7:71-9:95-9:125-10:100-22:30-33:33)",
      "d": "«رِجْسٌ» can mean filth as well as impurity. (See details under 'Filth'). It refers to the impurity of things that Sharia has declared haram or impure, whether material or spiritual.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَعۡرِضُوۡا عَنۡہِمۡ ؕ اِنَّہُمۡ  رِجۡسٌ ۫ وَّ مَاۡوٰىہُمۡ  جَہَنَّمُ» ( 9/95 )\nTranslation: So turn away from them. Indeed, they are impure, and their abode is Hell."
    },
    {
      "id": 2777,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Impure / Evil",
      "hw": "ناپاک",
      "s": "«خَبِیْث» means foul things and people whose nature inclines toward vulgarity. (8 Verses: 2:267-3:179-4:2-5:100-7:58-8:37-14:26-24:26)",
      "d": "«خَبِیْث» means impure and filthy. Its opposite is «طَیَّب» meaning pure. «خَبِیْث» is used in both material and spiritual contexts. Materially, it means rubbish and worthless things. «خَبِثُ الْحَدِیْء» means the rust of iron. Additionally, it refers to things that are filthy, rotten, and foul-smelling.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَیَمَّمُوا الۡخَبِیۡثَ مِنۡہُ تُنۡفِقُوۡنَ وَ لَسۡتُمۡ بِاٰخِذِیۡہِ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ تُغۡمِضُوۡا فِیۡہِ» ( 2/267 )\nTranslation: And do not aim toward the defective thereof from which you spend, and you would not take it except that you close your eyes to it.\nAnd in its spiritual usage, «خَبِیْث» refers to a person whose nature is inclined to vulgarity or who is wicked.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«اَلۡخَبِیۡثٰتُ لِلۡخَبِیْثِیۡنَ وَ الۡخَبِیْثُوۡنَ لِلۡخَبِیْثٰتِ» ( 24/26 )\nTranslation: Evil women are for evil men, and evil men are for evil women."
    }
  ],
  "608": [
    {
      "id": 2779,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Detestable",
      "hw": "ناپسندیدہ",
      "s": "«مَکْرُوْہ» is that which a person of sound nature (i.e., one who is composed and of good nature) dislikes. (27 Verses: 2:216-3:83-4:19-8:8-9:32-9:33-9:46-9:53-9:81-10:82-10:99-13:15-16:62-16:106-17:38-20:73-24:33-40:14-41:11-46:15-47:9-47:26-47:28-49:7-49:12-61:8-61:9)",
      "d": "«کَرِہَ» means to dislike something. And «مَکْرُوْہ» is everything that is offensive to a person of sound nature and that nature finds repulsive (unpalatable).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَیُحِبُّ  اَحَدُکُمۡ  اَنۡ یَّاۡکُلَ  لَحۡمَ  اَخِیۡہِ  مَیۡتًا فَکَرِہۡتُمُوۡہُ» ( 49/12 )\nTranslation: Would any of you like to eat the flesh of his dead brother? You would surely detest it!\nThen there are matters that seem detestable on the surface but are actually based on benefit. Sharia has identified such matters.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«کُتِبَ عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡقِتَالُ وَ ہُوَ کُرۡہٌ لَّکُمۡ ۚ وَ عَسٰۤی اَنۡ تَکۡرَہُوۡا شَیۡئًا وَّ ہُوَ خَیۡرٌ لَّکُمۡ» ( 2/216 )\nTranslation: Fighting has been prescribed for you, though it is disliked by you. And perhaps you dislike a thing while it is good for you.\nThus, «مَکْرُوْہ» is that which is disliked by both reason and Sharia.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کُلُّ ذٰلِکَ کَانَ سَیِّئُہٗ عِنۡدَ رَبِّکَ مَکۡرُوۡہًا» ( 17/38 )\nTranslation: All that - its evil is ever, in the sight of your Lord, detestable."
    },
    {
      "id": 2780,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Detestable",
      "hw": "ناپسندیدہ",
      "s": "«اِدَّ» means an extremely detestable matter that causes an uproar. (1 Verse: 19:89)",
      "d": "«اِدَّ» means a most detestable matter that causes an uproar. And «اَرِیْد» means noise, uproar. «اَدَّ الْاَمْر» means a matter becomes burdensome and difficult. «اَدِیْد» means noise, uproar. «اِدّ» means calamity, a horrific event, a difficult task. That is, such a detestable matter that is uproarious.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ قَالُوا  اتَّخَذَ  الرَّحۡمٰنُ  وَلَدًا لَقَدۡ  جِئۡتُمۡ  شَیۡئًا  اِدًّا» ( 19/88،89 )\nTranslation: And they say, \"The Most Merciful has taken a son.\" You have indeed brought forth a terrible thing."
    },
    {
      "id": 2781,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Detestable / Reprehensible",
      "hw": "ناپسندیدہ",
      "s": "«مُنْکِر» is that which society considers ugly and bad. (17 Verses: 3:104-3:110-3:114-5:79-7:157-9:67-9:71-9:112-12:58-16:90-22:41-22:72-24:21-29:29-29:45-31:17-58:2)",
      "d": "«مُنْکَر» means every strange and astonishing matter, every matter that is disliked or forbidden by Sharia, evil matters or evil deeds. And «مُنْکَر» is every matter that society considers ugly and bad.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلۡتَکُنۡ مِّنۡکُمۡ اُمَّۃٌ یَّدۡعُوۡنَ اِلَی الۡخَیۡرِ وَ یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَ یَنۡہَوۡنَ عَنِ الۡمُنۡکَرِ» ( 3/104 )\nTranslation: And let there be from among you a nation who invite to good, enjoin what is right, and forbid what is wrong.\nThen Sharia did not leave «مُنْکَر» merely to the approval and disapproval of society; rather, wherever an incorrect or unlawful matter has become prevalent in society and society does not consider it ugly, Sharia has commanded its rectification.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«وَ تَاۡتُوۡنَ فِیۡ نَادِیۡکُمُ الۡمُنۡکَرَ» ( 29/29 )\nTranslation: And you commit the reprehensible in your meetings."
    },
    {
      "id": 2782,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Disapproved",
      "hw": "ناپسندیدہ",
      "s": "«اِمْر» means an extremely unreasonable, irrational, and un-Islamic matter. (1 Verse: 18:71)",
      "d": "«اِمْر» means every irrational and un-Islamic matter (mansajd) meaning «مُنْکَرًا عَظِیْمًا» (m. q). «اَمِرَ الْاَمْر» means to exceed the limit in an affair or matter (muf). An extremely unreasonable matter.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ اَخَرَقۡتَہَا لِتُغۡرِقَ اَہۡلَہَا ۚ لَقَدۡ جِئۡتَ شَیۡئًا اِمۡرًا» (18/71)\nTranslation: Moses said, 'Did you break it so that its occupants would drown? You have certainly done a most disapproved thing.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2784,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Disapproved",
      "hw": "ناپسندیدہ",
      "s": "«اُفّ» is used idiomatically to express disgust at something bad. (3 Verses: 17:23-21:67-46:17)",
      "d": "«اُفّ» originally refers to every dirty and detestable thing, such as filth, dirt, and nail clippings, etc. But idiomatically, this word is spoken to express disgust at something bad (muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اُفٍّ لَّکُمۡ وَ لِمَا تَعۡبُدُوۡنَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ» (21/67)\nTranslation: 'Fie upon you and upon what you worship besides Allah!'"
    }
  ],
  "609": [
    {
      "id": 2785,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Ignorant",
      "hw": "نادان",
      "s": "«جَاھِلْ» means ignorant, unaware. (10 Verses: 2:67-2:273-6:35-7:199-11:46-12:33-12:89-25:63-28:55-39:64)",
      "d": "«جَاھِلْ» means ignorant, unaware. Its opposite is «عَالِم». Ignorant means a person's mind being empty of knowledge (muf). The reason can be anything (muf). This word is general. For example: The Quran states:\n«یَحۡسَبُہُمُ الۡجَاہِلُ اَغۡنِیَآءَ مِنَ التَّعَفُّفِ» (2/273)\nTranslation: 'The ignorant think them rich because of their abstention.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2786,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Ignorant",
      "hw": "نادان",
      "s": "«سُفَھَاء» means a person of low intellect and poor morals. (6 Verses: 2:13-2:130-2:142-4:5-6:140-7:155)",
      "d": "«سُفَھَاء» is the plural of «سَفِیْھَہ , سَفّہ» meaning a person of low intellect and poor morals. Its opposite is «حِلم» meaning forbearance, tolerance, and gentleness. In the meaning of «سُفَھَاء», two aspects are found: (1) low intellect and (2) having poor morals (m. l). And «سَفِیْہ» means such an ignorant person who, due to lack of intellect, remains incapable of learning or acquiring knowledge, and whose morals are also poor. That is, to object despite not knowing or understanding is his habit; a fool (m. q).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«سَیَقُوۡلُ السُّفَہَآءُ مِنَ النَّاسِ مَا وَلّٰىہُمۡ عَنۡ قِبۡلَتِہِمُ الَّتِیۡ کَانُوۡا عَلَیۡہَا» (2/142)\nTranslation: 'The foolish among the people will say, 'What has turned them away from the direction they used to face?'"
    }
  ],
  "610": [
    {
      "id": 2787,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Displeasure",
      "hw": "ناراضگی",
      "s": "«سَخَطَ» means anger, displeasure. (3 Verses: 3:162-5:80-9:58)",
      "d": "«سَخَطَ» means anger, displeasure. Dislike. Its opposite is «رِضْوَان» meaning contentment and pleasure. And «سَخَطَ» means being unhappy with an action contrary to one's will. Being angry. For example: The Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ اُعۡطُوۡا مِنۡہَا رَضُوۡا وَ اِنۡ لَّمۡ یُعۡطَوۡا مِنۡہَاۤ اِذَا ہُمۡ یَسۡخَطُوۡنَ» (9/58)\nTranslation: 'If they are given some of it, they are pleased; but if they are not given any, they become angry.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2788,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Displeasure",
      "hw": "ناراضگی",
      "s": "«ضِغْن» means enmity, malice, hatred, hostility. (2 Verses: 47:29-47:37)",
      "d": "«ضِغْن» means intense, hidden enmity, strong hatred. Such displeasure that one keeps concealed in the heart. That is, such displeasure that a person does not remove from his heart.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَمۡ حَسِبَ الَّذِیۡنَ فِیۡ  قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ مَّرَضٌ اَنۡ  لَّنۡ یُّخۡرِجَ اللّٰہُ  اَضۡغَانَہُمۡ» (47/29)\nTranslation: 'Or do those in whose hearts is disease think that Allah would never bring forth their malice?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2789,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Displeasure",
      "hw": "ناراضگی",
      "s": "«غِلّ» means grudge, enmity; such displeasure that reaches the level of enmity and is concealed in the heart. (3 Verses: 7:43-15:47-59:10)",
      "d": "In the meaning of «غِلّ», two aspects are found: (1) intensity of hatred, hidden enmity (muf), (2) theft and betrayal. Secretly taking something and keeping it in one's belongings (m. q). And «غِلّ» means grudge, rancor (mansajd).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ نَزَعۡنَا مَا فِیۡ صُدُوۡرِہِمۡ مِّنۡ غِلٍّ» (7/43)\nTranslation: 'And We removed from their breasts any grudge.'"
    }
  ],
  "611": [
    {
      "id": 2790,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Ungrateful",
      "hw": "ناشکرا",
      "s": "«کَفُوْر» means ungrateful for favors. (15 Verses: 11:9-17:27-17:67-17:89-17:99-22:38-22:66-25:50-31:32-34:17-35:36-42:48-43:15-76:3-76:24)",
      "d": "In the meaning of «کَفَرَ», two aspects are found: (1) denying Allah, (2) denying Allah's favors. Being ungrateful for blessings. For the one who denies Allah, the word «کَافِر» is generally used, and for the one who denies His favors, the words «کَفُوْر» or «کَفّار» are generally used. Its opposite is «شاکِر» and «شَکُوْر».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّا ہَدَیۡنٰہُ  السَّبِیۡلَ  اِمَّا شَاکِرًا وَّ اِمَّا کَفُوۡرًا» (76/3)\nTranslation: 'Indeed, We have shown him the way; so whether he is grateful or ungrateful.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2791,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Ungrateful",
      "hw": "ناشکرا",
      "s": "«کَنُوْد» is such an ungrateful person who constantly mentions calamities and difficulties but never even mentions the name of Allah's bestowed favors. (1 Verse: 100:6)",
      "d": "«کَنَدَ» means to be ungrateful, and «کَنُوْد» is used for such an ungrateful person who constantly mentions calamities and difficulties but never even mentions the name of Allah's bestowed favors. Ungrateful. Miser. Ungrateful for favors (mansajd. m. q).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّ  الۡاِنۡسَانَ لِرَبِّہٖ  لَکَنُوۡدٌ» (100/6)\nTranslation: 'Indeed, man is to his Lord ungrateful.'"
    }
  ],
  "612": [
    {
      "id": 2794,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Disobey",
      "hw": "نافرمانی",
      "s": "«فَجَرَ» means to persist in sins recklessly, to sin, to commit evil. (6 Verses: 38:28-71:27-75:5-80:42-82:14-83:7-)",
      "d": "«فَجَرَ» means to widely tear something, and «فَاجِر» is used for a person who is completely immersed in sins. And does not even consider sin as sin, nor inclines towards repentance (muf). Immoral. And «فُجُور» means engrossed in sins. Fornicator (mansajd). And «فَجَرَ» means to be audacious.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّکَ اِنۡ تَذَرۡہُمۡ یُضِلُّوۡا عِبَادَکَ وَ لَا یَلِدُوۡۤا  اِلَّا  فَاجِرًا کَفَّارًا» (71/27)\nTranslation: 'If you leave them, they will mislead Your servants and will not produce except a wicked, ungrateful offspring.'"
    }
  ],
  "613": [
    {
      "id": 2795,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Nose",
      "hw": "ناک",
      "s": "«اَنْف» is used for the body part (nose) (1 verse: 5:45)",
      "d": "«اَنْف» means nose. A well-known body part. Since the nose protrudes, any protruding part of something is also called «اَنْف». For example, «اَنْفُ الْجَبْل» means the protruding part of a mountain (muf).\nFor instance, in the Quran: \n«وَ الۡعَیۡنَ بِالۡعَیۡنِ وَ الۡاَنۡفَ بِالۡاَنۡفِ» (5/45)\nTranslation: An eye for an eye and a nose for a nose."
    },
    {
      "id": 2796,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Nose",
      "hw": "ناک",
      "s": "«خُرْطُوْم» a long and downward-growing nose or the nose of a large and proud man (1 verse: 68:16)",
      "d": "«خُرْطُوْم» means elephant's trunk. And it means a long nose whose front part reaches the fingers, and «اِنْخَرْطَمَ» means to raise the nose, to become angry, to be proud. Its plural is «خَرَاطِیْم». And «خَرَاطِیْمُ الْقَوْم» means the leaders and proud people of the nation (m. m. q).\nFor instance, in the Quran: \n«اِذَا تُتۡلٰی عَلَیۡہِ اٰیٰتُنَا قَالَ اَسَاطِیۡرُالۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ . سَنَسِمُہٗ عَلَی الۡخُرۡطُوۡمِ» (68/15,16)\nTranslation: When Our verses are recited to him, he says, 'These are the fables of the ancients.' We will surely mark him on the nose."
    }
  ],
  "614": [
    {
      "id": 2798,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "name; to name",
      "hw": "نام",
      "s": "«لَقَب» means an attributive name, a name given due to a particular attribute, aside from the real name (1 verse: 49:11)",
      "d": "«لَقَب» means an attributive name, a name given due to a particular attribute aside from the real name. For example, 'Al-Masih' is a title for Prophet Jesus (peace be upon him) who spent his life in itinerant preaching and chose a celibate life (i.e., without a family or wife and children). For example, the Quran states: «اِذۡ قَالَتِ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ یٰمَرۡیَمُ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُبَشِّرُکِ بِکَلِمَۃٍ مِّنۡہُ ٭ۖ اسۡمُہُ الۡمَسِیۡحُ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ» (3/45). Translation: When the angels said, 'O Mary, indeed Allah gives you good tidings of a word from Him, whose name will be the Messiah, Jesus, the son of Mary.' In this verse, 'Al-Masih' is a title. 'Isa' is the actual name, and 'Ibn Maryam' (son of Mary) is the lineage. Since he had no father, Allah the Almighty attributed him to his mother."
    },
    {
      "id": 2799,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Name. Giving a name.",
      "hw": "نام",
      "s": "«نَبَز» a bad nickname, a shameful name (1 verse: 49:11)",
      "d": "«اَلنَّبْز» is also a type of nickname, but it presents a person's bad attributes, whether they exist in him or not, and whether it relates to lineage or character. And «نبز» means to give someone a bad name or nickname (muf. m.).\nFor instance, in the Quran: \n«وَ لَا تَنَابَزُوۡا بِالۡاَلۡقَابِ» (49/11)\nTranslation: And do not call each other by [bad] nicknames."
    },
    {
      "id": 2800,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Name. Giving a name.",
      "hw": "نام",
      "s": "«فُلَانٌ» saying 'so-and-so' instead of mentioning a person's name (1 verse: 25:28)",
      "d": "«فُلَانٌ» its feminine is «فُلَانَۃٌ». It stands in place of a noun. Therefore, when referring to rational beings, the article «ال» can be included. One says «رَکَیْتُ الْفُلَانَ» I rode the so-and-so (male) animal, and «جَلَبْتُ الْفُلَانَۃَ» I milked the so-and-so (female) animal.\nFor instance, in the Quran: \n«یٰوَیۡلَتٰی لَیۡتَنِیۡ لَمۡ اَتَّخِذۡ فُلَانًا خَلِیۡلًا» (25/28)\nTranslation: 'Woe to me! I wish I had not taken so-and-so as a close friend.'"
    }
  ],
  "615": [
    {
      "id": 2801,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "ill-omened; cursed",
      "hw": "نامبارک",
      "s": "«مَشْئَمَۃ» means ill-omened, ill-fated (2 verses: 56:9-90:19)",
      "d": "«شَئَم» means to be ill-omened or accursed. And «شَاءَمَ» means to take the left side (Munjid). The opposite of «شَئَمَ» is «یَمَنَ». 'Yaman' means the right side or the right hand, and also blessing. «شَأمَ» gives the root 'shamat'. And «شَامَت» is that ill-omen or bad luck in which a person's own actions have a greater share. 'Shamat' is a well-known term for the consequences of evil deeds. And «مَشْئَمَۃ» i.e., ill-omened and left-sided, is as if «شَئَمَ» is that ill-omen which manifests as a result of a person's own deeds. For example, the Quran states: «وَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا بِاٰیٰتِنَا ہُمۡ اَصۡحٰبُ الۡمَشۡئَمَۃِ» (90/19). Translation: And those who disbelieve in Our verses are the companions of the left (the ill-omened)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2802,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Blessed Name",
      "hw": "نامبارک",
      "s": "«نَحَسَ» meaning ill-fated or unfortunate (2 verses: 41:16-54:19)",
      "d": "«نَحَسَ» its opposite is «سَعَد». And «سَعَد» means good fortune and in acquiring good, the divine affairs assist and help a person (muf. m. l). And «نَحُوْسَت» is that in which divine will has a greater role. In the terminology of astronomers, «نَحْسَان» refers to Saturn and Mars, and «سَعْدَان» to Jupiter and Venus (m.).\nFor instance, in the Quran: \n«اِنَّاۤ اَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ رِیۡحًا صَرۡصَرًا فِیۡ یَوۡمِ  نَحۡسٍ  مُّسۡتَمِرٍّ» (54/19)\nTranslation: And We sent upon them a screaming wind during a continuous ill-fated day."
    },
    {
      "id": 2803,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Blessed Name",
      "hw": "نامبارک",
      "s": "«حُسُوْم» such a misfortune that is continuous and ongoing until it erases all traces (1 verse: 69:7)",
      "d": "«حُسُوْم» is such a misfortune that is continuous and ongoing until it erases all traces of something. (For details, see continuous.)\nFor instance, in the Quran: \n«سَخَّرَہَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ  سَبۡعَ  لَیَالٍ وَّ ثَمٰنِیَۃَ اَیَّامٍ ۙ حُسُوۡمًا ۙ فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی» (69/7)\nTranslation: He [Allah] subjected it [the wind] to them for seven nights and eight days continuously; then you would see the people [of Thamud] lying dead therein."
    }
  ],
  "616": [
    {
      "id": 2804,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To be saved",
      "hw": "نجات",
      "s": "«نَجٰی» meaning to escape from a calamity (52 verses: 2:49-2:50-6:63-6:64-7:64-7:72-7:83-7:89-7:141-7:165-10:22-10:23-10:73-10:92-10:103-11:58-11:66-11:94-11:116-12:45-12:110-14:6-17:67-19:72-20:40-20:80-21:9-21:71-21:74-21:76-21:88-23:28-26:65-26:119-26:170-27:53-27:57-29:15-29:24-29:32-29:65-31:32-37:76-37:115-37:134-39:61-40:41-41:18-44:30-54:34-61:10-70:14)",
      "d": "The word «نَجَات» is used only for escaping from a calamity. To attain release. In any manner. Its usage is general.\nFor instance, in the Quran: \n«وَ قَالَ الَّذِیۡ نَجَا مِنۡہُمَا وَ ادَّکَرَ  بَعۡدَ اُمَّۃٍ» (12/45)\nTranslation: And the one who escaped from among them [the two prisoners] said, after a long time, 'I will inform you of its interpretation.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2805,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To be saved",
      "hw": "نجات",
      "s": "«فَازَ» meaning to be saved from a calamity and to reach the beloved thing (20 verses: 3:185-4:13-4:73-5:119-6:16-9:72-9:89-9:100-9:111-10:64-33:71-37:60-40:9-44:57-45:30-48:5-57:12-61:12-64:9-85:11)",
      "d": "The word «فَازَ» is used for being saved from a calamity and reaching the beloved thing. (Faq l 273) To attain good with safety (muf).\nFor instance, in the Quran: \n«فَمَنۡ زُحۡزِحَ عَنِ النَّارِ وَ اُدۡخِلَ الۡجَنَّۃَ فَقَدۡ فَازَ» (3/185)\nTranslation: So whoever is removed away from the Fire and admitted into Paradise, he has indeed attained success.\nThen the word «فَازَ» is also from opposite meanings in lexicon. «فَوْز» means both to attain salvation and to perish. «فَوَّزَ الرَّجُل» means the man died. And «مَفَازَۃ» means the cause of salvation, the place of success or the cause of success, the place of perdition or the cause of perdition (m. m. l).\nFor instance, the divine declaration is: \n«فَلَا تَحۡسَبَنَّہُمۡ بِمَفَازَۃٍ مِّنَ الۡعَذَابِ ۚ وَ لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ» (3/188)\nTranslation: So do not think that they will escape from the punishment; and for them is a painful punishment.\nIn this verse, the word «مَفَازَۃ» gives the meaning of the place of perdition and its cause."
    }
  ],
  "617": [
    {
      "id": 2807,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "vows and offerings; sacrifice",
      "hw": "نذر و نیاز",
      "s": "«قُرْبَان» is everything a person gives purely to attain Allah's pleasure and proximity in His way (2 verses: 3:183-5:27)",
      "d": "«قُرْبَانَ الْمَلَک» means the king's companion. And 'qurban' is every thing through which attaining closeness to Allah is intended, whether it is a sacrifice or something else (Munjid). And every kind of vow, offering, and sacrifice made to other than Allah is forbidden because it is also a form of financial worship. (But polytheists also present vows, offerings, and sacrifices to others besides Allah, whom they consider worthy of respect.) For example, the Quran states: «اِذۡ قَرَّبَا قُرۡبَانًا فَتُقُبِّلَ مِنۡ اَحَدِہِمَا وَ لَمۡ یُتَقَبَّلۡ مِنَ الۡاٰخَرِ» (5/27). Translation: When both (Habil and Qabil) offered sacrifices, one was accepted and the other was not."
    }
  ],
  "618": [
    {
      "id": 2808,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Be Soft / To Soften",
      "hw": "نرم",
      "s": "«لَانَ» means softness or flexibility (1 verse: 39:23)",
      "d": "«لَانَ، لِیْن» means to be soft, flexible. (m. l.) And «قَوْلًا لَّیِّنًا» means soft speech (20/44). Thus, this word is used in both material and spiritual contexts. And its opposite is «خَشُونَت» meaning roughness and harshness. For example, in the Quran: «ثُمَّ  تَلِیۡنُ جُلُوۡدُہُمۡ وَ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ  اِلٰی ذِکۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (39/23) Translation: Then their skins and hearts soften towards the remembrance of Allah. And for softening, «اَلَان» is used. For example, the divine declaration is: «وَ اَلَنَّا لَہُ  الۡحَدِیۡدَ اَنِ اعۡمَلۡ سٰبِغٰتٍ وَّ قَدِّرۡ فِی السَّرۡدِ» (34/11) Translation: And We softened iron for him, that he might make wide coats of mail and measure the links (of the chain mail)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2809,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Be Soft / To Soften",
      "hw": "نرم",
      "s": "«اَدْھَنَ» means to soften something with oil (2 verses: 23:20-68:9)",
      "d": "«دُھْن» means oil, ghee, grease. And «اَدْھَنَ» means to soften something by applying oil. And when used metaphorically, it means that in the heart there is something else but with pretense, one adopts softness in speech to deceive the listener. To become lax. To flatter. To practice hypocrisy (m. q.). For example, in the Quran: «وَدُّوۡا  لَوۡ  تُدۡہِنُ  فَیُدۡہِنُوۡنَ» (68/9) Translation: They wish that you would be soft (towards them), then they would also be soft (towards you)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2810,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Be Soft / To Soften",
      "hw": "نرم",
      "s": "«اٰہَ» means heart's softness, i.e., tender-heartedness (2 verses: 9:114-11:75)",
      "d": "«اٰہَ» means to sigh (in illness) and to express regret. And «اَوَّاہٌ» means soft-hearted, tender-hearted. One who sighs and laments with supplication (m. q.). For example, in the Quran: «اِنَّ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ  لَاَوَّاہٌ  حَلِیۡمٌ» (9/114) Translation: Indeed, Abraham was most tender-hearted and forbearing."
    },
    {
      "id": 2811,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Be Soft / To Soften",
      "hw": "نرم",
      "s": "«تَلَطَّفَ» means to adopt caution and softness in performing an action (1 verse: 18:19)",
      "d": "«لَطْفَ» has two meanings: (1) to know small things and pay attention to them, (2) to remove its harmful aspect (see merciful). And «تَلَطّف» means to adopt caution and softness in performing an action. For example, in the Quran: «فَلۡیَاۡتِکُمۡ بِرِزۡقٍ مِّنۡہُ  وَ لۡـیَؔ‍‍‍تَلَطَّفۡ وَ لَا  یُشۡعِرَنَّ  بِکُمۡ  اَحَدًا» (18/19) Translation: So let him bring you provision from it and let him be gentle, and let him not inform anyone about you."
    }
  ],
  "619": [
    {
      "id": 2812,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Be Near / To Bring Near",
      "hw": "نزدیک",
      "s": "«کَادَ» means to be near to doing something but not doing it (21 verses: 2:20-2:71-4:78-7:150-9:117-14:17-17:73-17:76-18:93-19:90-20:15-22:72-24:35-24:43-25:42-28:10-42:5-43:52-67:8-68:51-72:19)",
      "d": "«کَادَ» means to be near to doing an action (muf) and means to be prepared to do an action but did not do it (m. q.). This is from the verbs of nearness and requires another verb with it. Only past and present tense are used. For example, in the Quran: «یَکَادُ الۡبَرۡقُ یَخۡطَفُ اَبۡصَارَہُمۡ» (2/20) Translation: The lightning almost snatches away their sight."
    },
    {
      "id": 2813,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Be Near / To Bring Near",
      "hw": "نزدیک",
      "s": "«قَرُبَ» means to be near; this word is general, used for nearness in distance, time, relation, and status (36 verses: 2:35-2:187-2:222-2:237-3:167-4:11-4:43-4:172-5:8-5:82-6:151-6:152-7:19-7:114-9:28-9:99-12:60-16:77-17:32-17:34-17:57-18:24-18:81-19:52-22:13-26:42-34:37-39:3-46:28-50:16-51:27-56:11-56:85-56:88-83:21-83:28)",
      "d": "«قَرُبَ» means to be near. Its opposite is «بَعُدَ» meaning to be far. «قَرُبَ» is a general term used for nearness in distance, time, relation, and status. Examples: (1) For nearness in distance: «اَوۡ  تَحُلُّ قَرِیۡبًا مِّنۡ دَارِہِمۡ» (13/31) Translation: Or (a calamity) will befall near their homes. (2) For nearness in distance: «وَ لَا تَقۡرَبُوۡہُنَّ حَتّٰی یَطۡہُرۡنَ» (2/222) Translation: Do not approach them until they are pure. (3) For nearness in relation: «لَا نَشۡتَرِیۡ بِہٖ ثَمَنًا وَّ لَوۡ  کَانَ ذَا قُرۡبٰی» (5/106) Translation: We will not take any price for it, even if he is a close relative. (4) For nearness in status: «وَ اَنۡ تَعۡفُوۡۤا اَقۡرَبُ لِلتَّقۡوٰی» (2/237) Translation: To forgive is closer to piety. For nearness in status and time, «اِقْتَرَبَ» is more commonly used. Example: «وَ اسۡجُدۡ وَ اقۡتَرِبۡ» (96/19) Translation: Prostrate and draw near. Another: «اِقۡتَرَبَتِ السَّاعَۃُ  وَ انۡشَقَّ  الۡقَمَرُ» (54/1) Translation: The Hour has drawn near and the moon has split. And for nearness in status, «قَرَّبَ» is specifically used, meaning to bring someone near. Example: «اسۡمُہُ الۡمَسِیۡحُ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ وَجِیۡہًا فِی الدُّنۡیَا وَ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ وَ مِنَ الۡمُقَرَّبِیۡنَ» (3/45) Translation: His name is the Messiah, Jesus son of Mary, distinguished in this world and the Hereafter, and one of those brought near."
    },
    {
      "id": 2814,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Be Near / To Bring Near",
      "hw": "نزدیک",
      "s": "«دَنٰی» is used for nearness in distance and for degradation in status (13 verses: 2:61-2:282-4:3-5:108-7:169-30:3-32:21-33:51-33:59-53:8-53:9-58:7-73:20)",
      "d": "«دَنٰی» is generally used for nearness in distance (faq l 353) and dunya means the state of nearness. The present universe. And its opposite is «آخرت» (hereafter). For example, in the Quran: «ثُمَّ  دَنَا فَتَدَلّٰی» (53/8) Translation: Then he drew near and leaned. And sometimes it is used for degradation in status. «اَدْنٰی» means mean, inferior. And its opposite is «اَعْلٰی». For example, the divine declaration is: «اَتَسۡتَبۡدِلُوۡنَ الَّذِیۡ ہُوَ اَدۡنٰی بِالَّذِیۡ ہُوَ خَیۡرٌ» (2/61) Translation: Do you exchange that which is lower for that which is better? And for nearness in time, «اَدْنٰی» is used in the sense of nearly, approximately. For example, the divine declaration is: «اِنَّ  رَبَّکَ یَعۡلَمُ  اَنَّکَ  تَقُوۡمُ  اَدۡنٰی مِنۡ ثُلُثَیِ الَّیۡلِ» (73/20) Translation: Your Lord knows that you stand prayer nearly two-thirds of the night."
    },
    {
      "id": 2815,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Be Near / To Bring Near",
      "hw": "نزدیک",
      "s": "«اَزِفَ» is used to express the tightness of time (2 verses: 40:18-53:57)",
      "d": "«اَزِفَ» comes for the nearness of time and conveys the meaning of time's tightness. It is said «اَزِفَتِ الشُّخُوْصُ» meaning the time of migration has drawn near (muf). And the Hereafter is called «اٰزِفۃ» because there is little time until its arrival. For example, in the Quran: «وَ اَنۡذِرۡہُمۡ یَوۡمَ الۡاٰزِفَۃِ» (40/18) Translation: And warn them of the Approaching Day."
    },
    {
      "id": 2816,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Be Near / To Bring Near",
      "hw": "نزدیک",
      "s": "«زَلَفَ» is used for nearness in rank and status (9 verses: 26:64-26:90-34:37-38:25-38:40-39:3-50:31-67:27-81:13)",
      "d": "«زَلَفَ» comes for nearness in rank and status (m. l.). For example, in the Quran: «وَ اِنَّ لَہٗ عِنۡدَنَا لَزُلۡفٰی وَ حُسۡنَ مَاٰبٍ» (38/40) Translation: And indeed, for him is nearness to Us and a good place of return. And for bringing near, «اَزْلَفَ» is used, and it does not necessarily convey the meaning of rank and status. For example, the divine declaration is: «وَ  اِذَا  الۡجَنَّۃُ   اُزۡلِفَتۡ» (81/13) Translation: And when Paradise is brought near."
    },
    {
      "id": 2818,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To draw near. To bring close.",
      "hw": "نزدیک",
      "s": "«اِقْتَرَنَ» implies such nearness in time or distance that two things seem joined together (1 verse: 43:53).",
      "d": "«قَرَن» also refers to the rope with which two camels are tied. And «قَرِیْن» means companion (Muf), and «قَرَنَ» means to place one thing near another, and «قَرَنَ الثَّوْرَیْن» means to yoke two oxen together in a Punjabi style. And in «اِقْتَرَنَ», there is emphasis, meaning to bring very close (M. Q.). And in «اِقْتَرَن», one after another immediately, then the third, then the fourth. Thus, the meaning of continuity, succession, or consecution is also found due to this nearness.\nFor example, in the Quran: «اَوۡ جَآءَ مَعَہُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ مُقۡتَرِنِیۡنَ» (43/53)\nTranslation: Or (it happens) that the angels gather and come with him (Jalandhari).\nComing with him, the angels, tied in a bundle (Othmani)."
    }
  ],
  "620": [
    {
      "id": 2821,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Sign. Sign.",
      "hw": "نشانی",
      "s": "«اٰیَۃ» is a sign that, through contemplation, leads to the acquisition of knowledge (353 verses: 2:39-2:41-2:61-2:73-2:99-2:106-2:118-2:129-2:145-2:151-2:164-2:187-2:211-2:219-2:221-2:231-2:242-2:248-2:252-2:259-2:266-3:4-3:7-3:11-3:13-3:19-3:21-3:41-3:49-3:50-3:58-3:70-3:97-3:98-3:101-3:103-3:108-3:112-3:113-3:118-3:164-3:190-3:199-4:56-4:140-4:155-5:10-5:44-5:75-5:86-5:89-5:114-6:4-6:21-6:25-6:27-6:33-6:35-6:37-6:39-6:46-6:49-6:54-6:55-6:65-6:68-6:93-6:97-6:98-6:99-6:105-6:109-6:118-6:124-6:126-6:130-6:150-6:157-6:158-7:9-7:26-7:32-7:35-7:36-7:37-7:40-7:51-7:58-7:64-7:72-7:73-7:103-7:106-7:126-7:132-7:133-7:136-7:146-7:147-7:156-7:174-7:175-7:176-7:177-7:182-7:203-8:2-8:31-8:52-8:54-9:9-9:11-9:65-10:1-10:5-10:6-10:7-10:15-10:17-10:20-10:21-10:24-10:67-10:71-10:73-10:75-10:92-10:95-10:97-10:101-11:1-11:59-11:64-11:96-11:103-12:1-12:7-12:35-12:105-13:1-13:2-13:3-13:4-13:7-13:27-13:38-14:5-15:1-15:75-15:77-15:81-16:11-16:12-16:13-16:65-16:67-16:69-16:79-16:101-16:104-16:105-17:1-17:12-17:59-17:98-17:101-18:9-18:17-18:56-18:57-18:105-18:106-19:10-19:21-19:58-19:73-19:77-20:22-20:23-20:42-20:47-20:54-20:56-20:126-20:127-20:128-20:133-20:134-21:5-21:32-21:37-21:77-21:91-22:16-22:51-22:52-22:57-22:72-23:30-23:45-23:50-23:58-23:66-23:105-24:1-24:18-24:34-24:46-24:58-24:59-24:61-25:36-25:37-25:73-26:2-26:4-26:8-26:15-26:67-26:103-26:121-26:128-26:139-26:154-26:158-26:174-26:190-26:197-27:1-27:12-27:13-27:52-27:81-27:82-27:83-27:84-27:86-27:93-28:2-28:35-28:36-28:45-28:47-28:59-28:87-29:15-29:23-29:24-29:35-29:44-29:47-29:49-29:50-30:10-30:16-30:20-30:21-30:22-30:23-30:24-30:25-30:28-30:37-30:46-30:53-30:58-31:2-31:7-31:31-31:32-32:15-32:22-32:24-32:26-33:34-34:5-34:9-34:15-34:19-34:38-34:43-36:33-36:37-36:41-36:46-37:14-38:29-39:42-39:52-39:59-39:63-39:71-40:4-40:13-40:23-40:35-40:56-40:63-40:69-40:78-40:81-41:3-41:15-41:28-41:37-41:39-41:40-41:44-41:53-42:29-42:32-42:33-42:35-43:46-43:47-43:48-43:69-44:33-45:3-45:4-45:5-45:6-45:8-45:9-45:11-45:13-45:25-45:31-45:35-46:7-46:26-46:27-48:20-51:20-51:37-53:18-54:2-54:15-54:42-57:9-57:17-57:19-58:5-62:2-62:5-64:10-65:11-68:15-74:16-78:28-79:20-83:13-90:19)",
      "d": "«اٰیَۃ» is any sign that, upon reflection, yields knowledge of that thing and its attributes (Muf). For example, if one knows that certain types of signs exist on a particular path, and those signs are found, then one becomes certain that they have found the way and are proceeding correctly. In the Quran, the word 'āyah' is used in three meanings: (1) a sentence of the Quran, (2) a sign (as defined above), (3) a miracle given to prophets. A Quranic sentence also serves as a sign due to its eloquence and rhetoric, proving it is the speech of a being above humanity. Thus, every sentence is a sign, and in the other meanings, they naturally fall under the mentioned verses.\nFor example, in the Quran: «سَنُرِیۡہِمۡ اٰیٰتِنَا فِی الۡاٰفَاقِ وَ فِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ حَتّٰی یَتَبَیَّنَ لَہُمۡ اَنَّہُ الۡحَقُّ» (41/53)\nTranslation: We will show them Our signs in the horizons and within themselves until it becomes clear to them that it (the Quran) is the truth."
    },
    {
      "id": 2823,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Sign. Sign.",
      "hw": "نشانی",
      "s": "«شَرْط» means the existence of a thing or the fulfillment of an act is contingent upon another act or thing: e.g., wudu is a condition for prayer; without it, prayer is not valid (1 verse: 47:18).",
      "d": "«اَشْرَطَ الْاِبِلَ» means to mark a camel for sale and separate it. The plural of «شرط» is «اشراط», meaning sign, mark. The beginning of every thing (Manjad) meaning a specific ruling whose occurrence or fulfillment is linked to another ruling. The other matter is like a sign for it. And «اَشْرَاطُ السَّاعَۃ» means signs of the Hour (Muf).\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَہَلۡ یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ اِلَّا السَّاعَۃَ اَنۡ تَاۡتِیَہُمۡ بَغۡتَۃً ۚ فَقَدۡ جَآءَ اَشۡرَاطُہَا» (47/18)\nTranslation: So do they await anything but the Hour that it should come upon them unexpectedly? But already its signs have come (into effect)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2824,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Sign. Sign.",
      "hw": "نشانی",
      "s": "«نُصُب» means a sign erected on the road, such as a stone, etc. (3 verses: 5:3-70:43-88:19)",
      "d": "«نَصَبَ الشَّیْءِ» means to erect or set up something. «اَلنَّصْب» means a raised banner, an erected sign. «نُصُب» and «نُصْب» mean an erected sign, a road marker (Muf. Manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran: «یَوۡمَ یَخۡرُجُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡاَجۡدَاثِ سِرَاعًا کَاَنَّہُمۡ اِلٰی نُصُبٍ یُّوۡفِضُوۡنَ» (70/43)\nTranslation: On the Day they will emerge from the graves in haste, as if they are rushing toward a sign."
    },
    {
      "id": 2825,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Sign. Sign.",
      "hw": "نشانی",
      "s": "«سِیْمَا» means a distinguishing sign (6 verses: 2:273-7:46-7:48-47:30-48:29-55:41)",
      "d": "«سِیْمَا» means sign, mark. And «سَوَّمَ» means to mark so that one is distinguished from others (Muf). Thus, «سِیْمَا» refers to an emblematic or distinguishing sign.\nFor example, in the Quran: «سِیۡمَاہُمۡ فِیۡ وُجُوۡہِہِمۡ مِّنۡ اَثَرِ السُّجُوۡدِ» (48/29)\nTranslation: Their mark is on their faces from the trace of prostration."
    },
    {
      "id": 2826,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Sign. Sign.",
      "hw": "نشانی",
      "s": "«شَعَائِر» means religious symbols: signs that have a connection to religion (4 verses: 2:158-5:2-22:32-22:36)",
      "d": "«شَعَائِر» is the plural of «شَعِیْرَۃ», meaning religious symbols, i.e., signs given sanctity in a religious context. Things of reverence, places, and symbols. Sha'air of Hajj: the rites and places of Hajj. Sha'air of Allah: signs that Allah has deemed respectable. And Sha'air of Allah also refers to sacrificial animals sent toward the House of Allah.\nFor example, in the Quran: «اِنَّ الصَّفَا وَ الۡمَرۡوَۃَ مِنۡ شَعَآئِرِ اللّٰہِ» (2/158)\nTranslation: Indeed, Safa and Marwah are among the symbols of Allah.\nAt another place, the divine command states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تُحِلُّوۡا شَعَآئِرَ اللّٰہِ وَ لَا الشَّہۡرَ الۡحَرَامَ وَ لَا الۡہَدۡیَ وَ لَا الۡقَلَآئِدَ» (5/2)\nTranslation: O you who believe! Do not violate the symbols of Allah, nor the sacred month, nor the sacrificial animals, nor the garlands."
    }
  ],
  "621": [
    {
      "id": 2828,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To mark. To brand.",
      "hw": "نشان",
      "s": "«وَسَمَ» is used for making inscriptions or marks for beauty or branding (8 verses: 2:273-7:46-7:48-15:75-47:30-48:29-55:41-68:16)",
      "d": "«وَسَمَ» means to mark, to brand (Muf). It also means to inscribe or carve on the body, to tattoo (M. L.). And «وَسَّمَ» means to dye. And «وِسَام» and «وَسْمَہ» are the thing with which a mark is made or color applied. And «وَسِیْم» means beautiful (M. Q.).\nFor example, in the Quran: «سَنَسِمُہٗ عَلَی الۡخُرۡطُوۡمِ» (68/16)\nTranslation: We will surely mark him on the snout (the prominent part of the nose)."
    }
  ],
  "622": [
    {
      "id": 2829,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Advice. To advise. To obtain.",
      "hw": "نصیحت",
      "s": "«نَصَحَ» means to speak or act with goodwill toward someone (5 verses: 7:62-7:79-7:93-9:91-11:34)",
      "d": "«نَصَحَ» means to do good to someone. And «نَصِیْحَۃ» is every word or action in which the goodwill of another is sought (Muf).\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ لَا یَنۡفَعُکُمۡ نُصۡحِیۡۤ اِنۡ اَرَدۡتُّ اَنۡ اَنۡصَحَ لَکُمۡ اِنۡ کَانَ اللّٰہُ یُرِیۡدُ اَنۡ یُّغۡوِیَکُمۡ» (11/34)\nTranslation: And my advice will not benefit you, if I intend to advise you, while Allah intends to misguide you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2830,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "advice; to advise; to receive advice",
      "hw": "نصیحت",
      "s": "«ذَکَّرَ» is advice that refreshes the remembrance of Allah (181 verses: 2:114-2:221-2:269-2:282-3:7-3:58-5:13-5:14-5:91-6:44-6:68-6:69-6:70-6:80-6:90-6:118-6:119-6:121-6:126-6:138-6:152-7:2-7:3-7:26-7:57-7:63-7:69-7:130-7:165-7:201-8:2-8:57-9:126-10:3-11:24-11:30-11:114-11:120-12:42-12:104-13:19-13:28-14:5-14:25-14:52-15:6-15:9-16:13-16:17-16:43-16:44-16:90-17:41-17:46-18:28-18:57-18:70-18:83-18:101-19:2-20:3-20:14-20:34-20:42-20:44-20:99-20:113-20:124-21:2-21:7-21:10-21:24-21:42-21:48-21:50-21:84-21:105-22:35-23:71-23:85-23:110-24:1-24:27-24:37-25:18-25:29-25:50-25:62-25:73-26:5-26:209-26:227-27:62-28:43-28:46-28:51-29:45-29:51-32:4-32:15-32:22-33:34-33:41-35:37-36:11-36:19-36:69-37:3-37:13-37:155-37:168-38:1-38:8-38:29-38:32-38:43-38:46-38:49-38:87-39:9-39:21-39:22-39:23-39:27-39:45-40:13-40:54-40:58-41:41-43:5-43:36-43:44-44:13-44:58-45:23-47:18-47:20-50:8-50:37-50:45-51:49-51:55-52:29-53:29-54:17-54:22-54:25-54:32-54:40-56:62-56:73-57:16-58:19-62:9-63:9-65:10-68:51-68:52-69:12-69:42-69:48-72:17-73:19-74:31-74:49-74:54-74:55-74:56-76:29-77:5-79:43-80:4-80:11-81:27-87:9-87:10-88:21-89:23-94:4-79:35)",
      "d": "«ذَکَرَ» means to remember and to be remembered, and its opposite is «نَسِیَ», meaning to forget. And «ذِکْر» means the presence of something in the heart or on the tongue. And 'tazkirah' means everything by which one's need or necessity is recalled. Certificate, passport, ticket, etc. (Munjid). And the Quran is also called «ذِکْر» and «تَذْکِرَہ» because it also revives the natural call to goodness and the remembrance of the primordial covenant. And «ذِکْر» also refers to advice that becomes a means of remembering Allah, and every thing that refreshes the remembrance of Allah is 'dhikr'. And «ذَکَّرَ» comes in the meanings of advising and directing attention. «ذَکَّرَ الْقَوْم» means he advised the people (Maqayis). For example, the Quran states: «وَّ  ذَکِّرۡ فَاِنَّ  الذِّکۡرٰی تَنۡفَعُ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ» (51/55). Translation: And continue to admonish, for admonition benefits the believers. And for accepting or receiving advice, «تَذَکَّر» is used. For example, the divine command states: «وَ یُبَیِّنُ  اٰیٰتِہٖ لِلنَّاسِ لَعَلَّہُمۡ  یَتَذَکَّرُوۡنَ» (2/221). Translation: And Allah clarifies His verses for the people so that they may take heed."
    },
    {
      "id": 2831,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Advice. To advise. To obtain.",
      "hw": "نصیحت",
      "s": "«وَعَظَ» means to advise through exhortation (arousing desire) and intimidation (instilling fear) (15 verses: 2:66-2:232-2:275-3:138-4:63-4:66-5:46-7:145-10:57-11:120-16:125-24:34-26:136-58:3-65:2)",
      "d": "«وَعَظَ» means to speak of goodness that softens the heart (M. L.), to incline toward piety through threat and promise. Admonition mixed with fear, instilling fear of Allah's punishment and arousing desire for reward (Muf. Manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّاسُ قَدۡ جَآءَتۡکُمۡ مَّوۡعِظَۃٌ مِّنۡ رَّبِّکُمۡ وَ شِفَآءٌ لِّمَا فِی الصُّدُوۡرِ» (10/57)\nTranslation: O mankind! There has come to you an admonition from your Lord and a healing for what is in the breasts."
    },
    {
      "id": 2832,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Advice. To advise. To obtain.",
      "hw": "نصیحت",
      "s": "«وَصّٰی» to guide someone in an advisory manner before an event occurs (18 verses: 2:132-2:180-2:182-2:240-4:11-4:12-4:131-5:106-6:144-6:151-6:152-6:153-19:31-29:8-31:14-36:50-42:13-46:15)",
      "d": "«اَلْوَصِیَّۃ» meaning to guide in an advisory manner before an event occurs (muf)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ وَصِیَّۃٍ یُّوۡصٰی بِہَاۤ اَوۡ دَیۡنٍ» ( 4/12 )\nTranslation: This division of inheritance will be after the execution of the will (of the deceased) that he made or after the repayment of the debt.\nAnd when it is attributed to Allah, its meaning will be to emphasize or command.\nFor example: The divine command is:\n«یُوۡصِیۡکُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡۤ  اَوۡلَادِکُمۡ» ( 4/11 )\nTranslation: Allah commands you regarding the division of inheritance among your children."
    }
  ],
  "623": [
    {
      "id": 2834,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Bounty",
      "hw": "نعمت",
      "s": "«نِعْمَۃ» meaning kindness, mercy done to others (23 verses: 2:211-3:171-3:174-5:7-5:20-8:53-14:6-16:18-16:53-16:71-26:22-29:67-33:9-37:57-39:8-39:49-43:13-49:8-54:35-68:2-68:49-92:19-93:11)",
      "d": "«نِعْمَۃ» meaning kindness, favor, mercy, grace (mujarrad). Such a favor done to others (faqih 158). Its plural is «نِعَمْ». And «اَنْعُمْ نِعْمَۃٌ» is a generic noun, and this word applies equally to all kinds of bounties, small or big, little or much.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«یَسۡتَبۡشِرُوۡنَ بِنِعۡمَۃٍ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ وَ فَضۡلٍ» ( 3/171 )\nTranslation: They rejoice in the bounties and grace of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2835,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Bounty",
      "hw": "نعمت",
      "s": "«نَعْمَۃ» the means and requisites of comfort and ease (2 verses: 44:27-73:11)",
      "d": "«نَعْمَۃ» meaning every thing that causes improvement, abundance, and prosperity in livelihood (m. l). The means and requisites of comfort and ease.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَّ  نَعۡمَۃٍ  کَانُوۡا فِیۡہَا  فٰکِہِیۡنَ» ( 44/27 )\nTranslation: And the comforts in which they used to enjoy."
    },
    {
      "id": 2836,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Bounty",
      "hw": "نعمت",
      "s": "«اٰلَاء» basic requisites of life's necessities (34 verses: 7:69-7:74-53:55-55:13-55:16-55:18-55:21-55:23-55:25-55:28-55:30-55:32-55:34-55:36-55:38-55:40-55:42-55:45-55:47-55:49-55:51-55:53-55:55-55:57-55:59-55:61-55:63-55:65-55:67-55:69-55:71-55:73-55:75-55:77)",
      "d": "«اٰلَاء» is plural of «اِلًی» meaning bounty (muf). («اَلیٰ ۔ یَا لُوْ» meaning to diminish. To bear a deficiency. To be lacking. To leave a deficiency (muf. m l))\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«لَا یَاۡلُوۡنَکُمۡ خَبَالًا» ( 3/118 )\nTranslation: They do not bear any deficiency in your corruption.\nAnd «اَلَاء» refers to those bounties that fulfill human necessities and come continuously, so one does not feel lack of anything in life (faqih 160). And generally it is used in plural because such a bounty is not singular. Therefore «اٰلَاءِیْ» occurs.\nFor example: The divine command is:\n«ذُو الۡعَصۡفِ وَ الرَّیۡحَانُ فَبِاَیِّ  اٰلَآءِ  رَبِّکُمَا تُکَذِّبٰانِ» ( 55/12،13 )\nTranslation: The one with fruits and palm trees with sheaths, and grain with husk, and fragrant flowers. So which of the bounties of your Lord do you both deny?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2837,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To bestow bounty",
      "hw": "نعمت",
      "s": "«اَنْعَمَ» to do kindness and honor. It is general (only used for humans) (63 verses: 1:6-2:40-2:47-2:122-2:150-2:211-2:231-3:103-3:171-3:174-4:69-4:72-5:3-5:6-5:7-5:11-5:20-5:23-5:110-8:53-11:10-12:6-14:6-14:28-14:34-16:18-16:53-16:71-16:72-16:81-16:83-16:112-16:114-16:121-17:83-19:58-26:22-27:19-28:17-29:67-31:20-31:31-33:9-33:37-35:3-37:57-39:8-39:49-41:51-43:13-43:59-44:27-46:15-48:2-49:8-52:29-54:35-68:2-68:49-73:11-89:15-92:19-93:11)",
      "d": "«اَنْعَمَ» meaning to do kindness. To bestow. This word is not used for non-humans. «اَنْعَمَ عَلٰی فَرْسِہٖ» will never occur (m. q). Nor can it be used for oneself (faqih 158).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اِہۡدِ نَا الصِّرَاطَ الۡمُسۡتَقِیۡمَ صِرَاطَ الَّذِیۡنَ اَنۡعَمۡتَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ» ( 1/5،6 )\nTranslation: Guide us to the straight path, the path of those upon whom You have bestowed Your favors.\nAnd «نَعَّمَ» means to bestow bounty upon someone.\nFor example: The divine command is:\n«فَاَمَّا الۡاِنۡسَانُ  اِذَا مَا ابۡتَلٰىہُ  رَبُّہٗ فَاَکۡرَمَہٗ  وَ نَعَّمَہٗ» ( 89/15 )\nTranslation: But as for man, when his Lord tests him and honors him and bestows bounty upon him."
    },
    {
      "id": 2838,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To bestow bounty",
      "hw": "نعمت",
      "s": "«خَوَّلَ» to grant. To bestow. To make owner (3 verses: 6:94-39:8-39:49)",
      "d": "«خَوَّلَ» meaning to grant. To bestow. To make owner (minj). And meaning to grant honor and service (muf).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَّ تَرَکۡتُمۡ مَّا خَوَّلۡنٰکُمۡ  وَرَآءَ  ظُہُوۡرِکُمۡ» ( 6/94 )\nTranslation: And you have left behind what We granted you behind your backs."
    },
    {
      "id": 2839,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To bestow bounty",
      "hw": "نعمت",
      "s": "«اَتْرَفَ» to be intoxicated due to abundance of comfort and ease (3 verses: 11:116-21:13-23:33)",
      "d": "«الترف» meaning abundance of comfort and ease. Abundance of bounties that can lead man astray. And «مُتْرِفْ» means the affluent who are intoxicated by abundance of wealth (muf).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ اتَّبَعَ  الَّذِیۡنَ  ظَلَمُوۡا مَاۤ اُتۡرِفُوۡا فِیۡہِ وَ کَانُوۡا مُجۡرِمِیۡنَ» ( 11/116 )\nTranslation: And those who did wrong followed what they were intoxicated with therein, and they were criminals."
    },
    {
      "id": 2841,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To bestow bounty",
      "hw": "نعمت",
      "s": "«اَقْنٰی» to make rich and satisfy, to give treasure, and according to some, to make poor (1 verse: 53:48)",
      "d": "«اَقْنٰی» meaning to make rich and satisfy (muf. minj). That is, to give so much wealth and property that besides fulfilling needs, one is also satisfied. And meaning to make rich then increase that wealth. To grant treasure (m. q). And according to some lexicographers, «اَقْنٰی» is opposite of «اَغۡنٰی». Meaning to make poor. And «اَقْنٰی» is from the category of opposite words (idhaad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ اَنَّہٗ  ہُوَ  اَغۡنٰی وَ  اَقۡنٰی» ( 53/48 )\nTranslation: And that it is He who enriches and grants treasure (Thana'i). He makes rich and makes poor (Jalandhri).\nNote: (Opposite words are those that have two separate meanings that are opposite to each other.)"
    }
  ],
  "624": [
    {
      "id": 2843,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Loss. To incur loss.",
      "hw": "نقصان",
      "s": "«خَسَارًا» to incur loss in trade. To have reduction in principal (3 verses: 17:82-35:39-71:21)",
      "d": "«خَسَارًا» meaning to have reduction in principal (muf). In a transaction, to have loss instead of profit. To be broken. To be at loss. Its opposite is «رَبِحَ».\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَا یَزِیۡدُ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ  کُفۡرُہُمۡ اِلَّا خَسَارًا» ( 35/39 )\nTranslation: And it does not increase the disbelievers in their disbelief except loss."
    },
    {
      "id": 2844,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "loss; to incur loss",
      "hw": "نقصان",
      "s": "«کَسَاد» means goods not selling in trade; the market becoming sluggish (1 verse: 9:24)",
      "d": "«کَسَاد» means there being no desire to buy something. (M.L.) To become stagnant. Goods not selling in trade. 'Kasada' is a well-known term meaning the market becoming cold or sluggish. For example, the Quran states: «وَ تِجَارَۃٌ تَخۡشَوۡنَ  کَسَادَہَا» (9/24). Translation: And trade about which you fear it will become stagnant."
    },
    {
      "id": 2845,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Loss. To incur loss.",
      "hw": "نقصان",
      "s": "«بَخْس» means receiving inferior and worthless things in exchange for good ones. (7 verses: 2:282-7:85-11:15-11:85-12:20-26:183-72:13)",
      "d": "«بَخْس» means a contemptible and deficient thing. And «یَبْخَس» means to reduce something unjustly (meaning). For example, the Noble Quran states: «فَمَنۡ یُّؤۡمِنۡۢ  بِرَبِّہٖ  فَلَا یَخَافُ بَخۡسًا وَّ لَا رَہَقًا» (72/13). Translation: And whoever believes in his Lord will have no fear of loss or compulsion."
    },
    {
      "id": 2846,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Loss. To incur loss.",
      "hw": "نقصان",
      "s": "«بَوَار» means to be destroyed while incurring loss. (9 verses: 14:28-17:102-25:13-25:14-25:18-35:10-35:29-48:12-84:11)",
      "d": "«بُوْر» and «بَوَار» mean to become extremely diminished and to reach the point of destruction (meaning). Incurring loss until the capital is gradually exhausted and destroyed. For example, the Noble Quran states: «وَ اَنۡفَقُوۡا مِمَّا رَزَقۡنٰہُمۡ سِرًّا وَّ عَلَانِیَۃً  یَّرۡجُوۡنَ  تِجَارَۃً  لَّنۡ تَبُوۡرَ» (35/29). Translation: And spend from what We have provided them, secretly and openly, hoping for a trade that will never be destroyed."
    },
    {
      "id": 2847,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Loss. To incur loss.",
      "hw": "نقصان",
      "s": "«مَغْرَمْ» means to be liable for a debt or fine, to undertake the responsibility of payment from someone. (5 verses: 9:60-9:98-52:40-56:66-68:46)",
      "d": "«اَلْغُرْم» is the financial loss which a person has to bear due to some betrayal or crime, without committing it. Fine (meaning). And «غَرِم» means to pay someone's debt. And «غَرِیْم» means both creditor and debtor (according to Al-Munjid). For example, the Noble Quran states: «اِنَّمَا الصَّدَقٰتُ لِلۡفُقَرَآءِ وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنِ وَ الۡعٰامِلِیۡنَ عَلَیۡہَا وَ الۡمُؤَلَّفَۃِ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ وَ فِی الرِّقَابِ وَ الۡغٰرِمِیۡنَ وَ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ وَ ابۡنِ السَّبِیۡلِ ؕ» (9/60). Translation: Charities are only for the poor and the needy and those employed to collect them and those whose hearts are to be reconciled and for freeing slaves and for those in debt and for the cause of Allah and for the stranded traveler. (50) And «مَغْرَم» and «غُرْم» are synonymous. And «مُغْرَم» is the person upon whom a fine is imposed. For example, the Noble Quran states: «لَوۡ نَشَآءُ  لَجَعَلۡنٰہُ  حُطَامًا فَظَلۡتُمۡ تَفَکَّہُوۡنَ اِنَّا  لَمُغۡرَمُوۡنَ» (56/65,66). Translation: If We willed, We could have made it broken pieces, then you would be lamenting, 'Indeed, we are burdened with debt.'"
    }
  ],
  "625": [
    {
      "id": 2848,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To marry. To arrange marriage.",
      "hw": "نکاح",
      "s": "«نَکَحَ» means the marriage contract, specifically for accountable beings, jinn and humans. (19 verses: 2:221-2:230-2:232-2:235-2:237-4:3-4:6-4:22-4:25-4:127-24:3-24:32-24:33-24:60-28:27-33:49-33:50-33:53-60:10)",
      "d": "«النِّکَاح» is the contract that is established between spouses (meaning) and it pertains only to accountable creations, i.e., humans and jinn. And «نَکَحَ» means to marry oneself. For example, the Noble Quran states: «فَانۡکِحُوۡا مَا طَابَ لَکُمۡ مِّنَ النِّسَآءِ» (4/3). Translation: Then marry those women that please you. And «اَنْکَحَ» means to marry someone else, or to give someone in marriage. For example, the Divine command is: «وَ لَا تُنۡکِحُوا الۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ حَتّٰی یُؤۡمِنُوۡا» (2/221). Translation: And do not marry polytheistic women until they believe."
    },
    {
      "id": 2849,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "to marry; to arrange marriage",
      "hw": "نکاح",
      "s": "«زَوَّجَ» means to pair, to join. It is general. It also includes the concept of divorce after marriage (72 verses: 2:25-2:35-2:102-2:230-2:232-2:234-2:240-3:15-4:1-4:12-4:20-4:57-6:139-6:143-7:19-7:189-9:24-11:40-13:3-13:23-13:38-15:88-16:72-20:53-20:117-20:131-21:90-22:5-23:6-23:27-24:6-25:74-26:7-26:166-30:21-31:10-33:4-33:6-33:28-33:37-33:50-33:52-33:53-33:59-35:11-36:36-36:56-37:22-38:58-39:6-40:8-42:11-42:50-43:12-43:70-44:54-50:7-51:49-52:20-53:45-55:52-56:7-58:1-60:11-64:14-66:1-66:3-66:5-70:30-75:39-78:8-81:7)",
      "d": "«زَوْج» means pair, husband, wife, companion. And «زَوَّج» means to pair, to join. Among animals where male and female are found, each is called the other's «زَوْج». And besides animals, for other things that come in pairs, 'zawj' is used (Mufradat). Its other aspect is that even if divorce does not occur after marriage, the correct meaning of «زَوَّج» is marriage and divorce, or to marry and to pair. And similarly, its meaning is not to marry oneself but to give in marriage. Imam Raghib says that if the object of «زَوَّج» comes with «ب», then it means merely to pair, to establish a sexual relationship is not intended. And this indication is found in «زَوَّجْنَا ھُمْ بِحُوْرٍ عِیْنٍ» that they will be merely companions and partners; otherwise, the Quran would have said «زَوَّجْنٰھُمْ حُوْرًا» instead of «زَوَّجْنٰھُمْ بِحُوْرٍ». As «زَوَّجْتُہٗ اِمْرَأَۃً» is a common expression (Mufradat). And Allah knows best!"
    }
  ],
  "626": [
    {
      "id": 2850,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To exit. To come out.",
      "hw": "نکلنا",
      "s": "«خَرَجَ» means to exit. It is commonly used. (51 verses: 2:74-2:149-2:150-2:240-2:243-4:66-4:100-5:22-5:37-5:61-7:13-7:18-7:58-8:47-9:42-9:47-9:83-12:31-15:34-16:69-18:5-19:11-20:22-22:22-23:20-24:43-24:53-27:12-28:20-28:21-28:32-28:79-30:25-30:48-32:20-34:2-37:64-38:77-41:47-47:16-49:5-54:7-55:22-57:4-59:2-59:11-59:12-60:1-65:1-70:43-86:7-)",
      "d": "«خَرَجَ» means to exit. To come out, and its opposite is «دَخَلَ», a well-known word, and its usage is also common. For example, the Noble Quran states: «لَئِنۡ  اُخۡرِجۡتُمۡ  لَنَخۡرُجَنَّ مَعَکُمۡ» (59/11). Translation: If you are expelled, we will surely exit with you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2851,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To exit. To come out.",
      "hw": "نکلنا",
      "s": "«بَرَزَ» means to exit into the field, to come forward. (7 verses: 2:250-3:154-4:81-14:21-14:48-26:91-79:36)",
      "d": "«بَرَزَ» means to exit and come into the open field. To come forward. To become apparent after obscurity and hiding (according to Al-Munjid). And «بَرْز» means space and open field. And «دَعْوَتِ مُبَارِزَت» means to challenge someone in the field of battle. For example, the Noble Quran states: «وَ لَمَّا بَرَزُوۡا لِجَالُوۡتَ وَ جُنُوۡدِہٖ» (2/250). Translation: And when they emerged for the encounter with Jalut and his troops."
    },
    {
      "id": 2852,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To exit. To come out.",
      "hw": "نکلنا",
      "s": "«نَفَرَ» means to set out for battle or a campaign. (10 verses: 4:71-9:38-9:39-9:41-9:81-9:122-46:29-18:34-46:29-72:1)",
      "d": "«نَفَرَ» means to set out for a campaign or battle. «اَلنَّفْر» is a group of soldiers. A group of three to ten. And «نَفِیْر» means those who set out for battle. «نَفِیْرُ الْعَام» means the general uprising of the people against the enemy (according to Al-Munjid). For example, the Noble Quran states: «فَانۡفِرُوۡا ثُبَاتٍ اَوِ انۡفِرُوۡا جَمِیۡعًا» (4/71). Translation: So set out in companies or set out all together."
    },
    {
      "id": 2854,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To exit. To come out.",
      "hw": "نکلنا",
      "s": "«زَھَقَ» means to flee after defeat or in distress. (1 verse: 17:81)",
      "d": "«زَھَقَ» means to flee (meaning). «زَھَقَ النَّفْس» means the soul exiting the body. And «زَھَقَ الْبَاطِل» means falsehood to flee away (meaning). And «زَاھِقْ» means defeated. One who comes to the encounter and is defeated and flees. Also, «زَھَقَ» is from the category of opposite words (addad). And «زَاھِق» means a very fat animal and also a very thin and weak animal (according to Al-Munjid). Therefore, «زھق» means either to defeat and make flee, or to make weak and exhausted, and flee in both senses. For example, the Noble Quran states: «وَ قُلۡ جَآءَ الۡحَقُّ وَ زَہَقَ الۡبَاطِلُ ؕ اِنَّ الۡبَاطِلَ  کَانَ  زَہُوۡقًا» (17/81). Translation: And say, 'Truth has come and falsehood has fled. Indeed, falsehood is bound to flee.' Note: (addad are words that have two opposite meanings)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2855,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To exit. To come out.",
      "hw": "نکلنا",
      "s": "«نَفَذَ» means to pass through, to exit from one side to the other. (1 verse: 55:33)",
      "d": "«نَفَذَ» means to pass through, to exit from one side to the other. And «نَفَاذ» means power and strength to complete and implement a decree, and to enforce it. To enter and pass through something with force and speed (meaning). For example, the Noble Quran states: «یٰمَعۡشَرَ الۡجِنِّ وَ الۡاِنۡسِ  اِنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتُمۡ اَنۡ  تَنۡفُذُوۡا مِنۡ  اَقۡطَارِ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ فَانۡفُذُوۡا» (55/33). Translation: O company of jinn and humans, if you are able to pass through the regions of the heavens and the earth, then pass through."
    },
    {
      "id": 2856,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "to exit",
      "hw": "نکلنا",
      "s": "«سَلَّلَ» means to slip away secretly (1 verse: 24:63)",
      "d": "«سَلَّلَ» means to exit quietly and stealthily (m. l) to slip away."
    },
    {
      "id": 2857,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "to exit",
      "hw": "نکلنا",
      "s": "«لِوَاذًا» means to exit while avoiding notice (1 verse: 24:63)",
      "d": "«لَاذَ» means to seek shelter (i.e., a place of refuge or hiding). «لَاذَ بِالْجَبَل» means to take shelter in a mountain. To hide. And «لَوْذ» means the side of a mountain, and «مَلَاذ» means a place of refuge or fortress (m. q). «لِوَاذًا» means to exit in search of shelter.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«قَدۡ یَعۡلَمُ  اللّٰہُ  الَّذِیۡنَ  یَتَسَلَّلُوۡنَ مِنۡکُمۡ  لِوَاذًا» (24/63)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah knows those among you who slip away covertly."
    },
    {
      "id": 2858,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "to exit",
      "hw": "نکلنا",
      "s": "«دَفَقَ» means to surge forward with force and power. To leap out (1 verse: 86:6)",
      "d": "«دَفَقَ» means for something to surge forward with force and power. To leap out (m. l).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَلۡیَنۡظُرِ الۡاِنۡسَانُ مِمَّ خُلِقَ خُلِقَ مِنۡ مَّآءٍ  دَافِقٍ» (86/6)\nTranslation: So let man consider from what he is created. He is created from a surging fluid."
    },
    {
      "id": 2859,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "to exit",
      "hw": "نکلنا",
      "s": "«شَرَقَ» means for the sun to rise (14 verses: 2:115-2:142-2:177-2:258-15:73-19:16-24:35-26:28-26:60-38:18-39:69-43:38-55:17-73:9)",
      "d": "«شَرْق» means the sun. Sunrise. The place from which the sun rises. And «شِرْق» means light coming from a crack in a door. And «شَرَقَتِ الشَّمْس» means the sun rose. And «مَشْرِق» means the place of the sun's rising (manjad). Thus, the word «شَرَقَ» is specific to the rising or appearance of the sun, or to something that is exceptionally bright and luminous compared to ordinary planets.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ اَشۡرَقَتِ  الۡاَرۡضُ بِنُوۡرِ رَبِّہَا» (39/69)\nTranslation: And the earth will shine with the light of its Lord.\nAnd «اَشْرَقَ» also means to do something at the time of sunrise.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«فَاَتۡبَعُوۡہُمۡ مُّشۡرِقِیۡنَ» (26/60)\nTranslation: So the Pharaoh's people pursued them at sunrise."
    },
    {
      "id": 2860,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "to rise (of celestial bodies)",
      "hw": "نکلنا",
      "s": "«طَلَعَ» means for stars and planets (including the sun) to rise. It is general (3 verses: 18:17-18:90-97:5)",
      "d": "«طَلَعَ» means for general planets, etc., to rise (manjad), and it includes the sun as well. Thus, the word «طَلَعَ» is general. Whereas «شَرَقَ» comes specifically for the sun's rising. The daughters of the Prophet's (ﷺ) Ansari host sang upon his arrival, the first line of their song was «طَلَعَ الْبَدْرُ عَلَیْنَا» meaning the full moon has risen upon us. In the Quran, the word «طَلَعَ» has not been used for the appearance of planets. However, it appears in relation to dawn (or perhaps the sun), and the light of dawn is, in any case, much less than that of the sun.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«سَلٰم ٌ ۟ ۛ ہِیَ حَتّٰی مَطۡلَعِ  الۡفَجۡرِ» (97/5)\nTranslation: It (the night) is peace until the break of dawn."
    },
    {
      "id": 2861,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "to take out",
      "hw": "نکلنا",
      "s": "«اَخْرَجَ» is general for 'to take out' (101 verses: 2:22-2:36-2:61-2:72-2:84-2:85-2:191-2:240-2:246-2:257-2:267-3:27-3:110-3:195-4:75-5:16-5:110-6:93-6:95-6:99-6:148-7:25-7:27-7:32-7:57-7:82-7:88-7:110-7:123-8:5-8:30-9:40-10:31-12:76-12:100-14:1-14:5-14:13-14:32-15:48-16:14-16:78-17:13-17:76-17:80-18:82-19:66-20:53-20:55-20:57-20:63-20:88-20:117-22:5-22:40-23:35-23:107-24:40-26:35-26:57-26:167-27:25-27:37-27:56-27:67-27:82-30:19-32:27-33:43-35:12-35:27-35:37-36:33-39:21-40:67-43:11-45:35-46:17-47:13-47:29-47:37-48:29-51:35-57:9-59:2-59:8-59:11-59:12-60:1-60:8-60:9-63:8-65:1-65:2-65:11-71:18-78:15-79:29-79:31-87:4-99:2)",
      "d": "«اَخْرَجَ» means to take out. Its usage is general.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِلَّا تَنۡصُرُوۡہُ فَقَدۡ  نَصَرَہُ  اللّٰہُ  اِذۡ اَخۡرَجَہُ الَّذِیۡنَ  کَفَرُوۡا» (9/40)\nTranslation: If you do not aid him, Allah already aided him when those who disbelieved expelled him."
    },
    {
      "id": 2862,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "to take out",
      "hw": "نکلنا",
      "s": "«بَرَّزَ» means to bring forth into the open. (7 verses: 2:250-3:154-4:81-14:21-14:48-26:91-79:36)",
      "d": "«بَرَّزَ» means to take something out and bring it into an open, clear space.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ بُرِّزَتِ  الۡجَحِیۡمُ  لِمَنۡ یَّرٰی» (79/36)\nTranslation: And Hell will be brought forth for whoever sees."
    },
    {
      "id": 2863,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "to take out",
      "hw": "نکلنا",
      "s": "«طَرَد» means to expel someone while considering them contemptible and vile (2 verses: 6:52-11:30)",
      "d": "«طَرَد» means to expel someone while considering them contemptible and vile. To drive away (muf) to repel forcefully (f l 188).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ لَا تَطۡرُدِ الَّذِیۡنَ یَدۡعُوۡنَ رَبَّہُمۡ بِالۡغَدٰوۃِ  وَ الۡعَشِیِّ  یُرِیۡدُوۡنَ وَجۡہَہٗ» (6/52)\nTranslation: And do not drive away those who invoke their Lord morning and evening, seeking His countenance."
    }
  ],
  "627": [
    {
      "id": 2864,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "sight",
      "hw": "نگاہ",
      "s": "«بَصَر» is a general word for sight or gaze (82 verses: 2:7-2:17-2:20-3:13-6:46-6:103-6:104-6:110-7:47-7:179-7:195-7:198-7:201-10:31-10:43-10:67-11:20-14:42-15:15-16:77-16:78-16:108-17:12-17:36-17:59-18:26-19:38-19:42-20:96-21:3-21:97-22:46-23:78-24:30-24:31-24:37-24:43-24:44-27:13-27:54-27:86-28:11-28:72-29:38-32:9-32:12-32:27-33:10-36:9-36:66-37:175-37:179-38:45-38:63-40:61-41:20-41:22-43:51-45:23-46:26-47:23-50:8-50:22-51:21-52:15-53:17-54:7-54:50-56:85-59:2-67:3-67:4-67:23-68:5-68:43-68:51-69:38-69:39-70:11-70:44-75:7-79:9)",
      "d": "«بَصَر» means the eye as well, and the action of the eye, i.e., sight or gaze, and to see. And from this word, only the action of seeing is understood.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَبَصَرُکَ الۡیَوۡمَ حَدِیۡدٌ» (50/22)\nTranslation: So your sight today is sharp."
    },
    {
      "id": 2865,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "gaze",
      "hw": "نگاہ",
      "s": "«طَرْف» means the edge or limit of something (6 verses: 14:43-27:40-37:48-38:52-42:45-55:56)",
      "d": "The word «طَرْف» also refers to the brief duration of an eye blink. And the original meaning of «طَرْف» is the edge or limit of something. «طَرْفُ الْعَیْن» means the blink of an eye, and «طَرْفَۃُ عَیْنٍ» means a period or interval or duration equivalent to the time of one blink. Thus, in «طَرْف», the specification of the act of seeing is not sought; rather, it refers to an extremely short duration.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَنَا اٰتِیۡکَ بِہٖ قَبۡلَ  اَنۡ یَّرۡتَدَّ اِلَیۡکَ طَرۡفُکَ» (27/40)\nTranslation: I can bring it to you before your glance returns to you (i.e., in the blink of an eye).\nThen, due to its frequent usage, this word became synonymous with «بَصَر». Like «طَرْفٌ خَفِیٌّ» (a hidden or furtive glance). And «قٰصِرٰتُ الطَّرۡفِ» (37:48) means those with lowered gazes."
    }
  ],
  "628": [
    {
      "id": 2866,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Guardian",
      "hw": "نگہبان",
      "s": "«حَافِظ» one who protects, one who saves something from being lost or destroyed (29 verses: 2:238-4:34-4:80-6:92-6:104-6:107-9:112-11:57-11:86-12:12-12:55-12:63-12:64-12:81-15:9-21:82-23:5-23:9-33:35-34:21-42:6-42:48-50:4-50:32-70:29-70:34-82:10-83:33-86:4)",
      "d": "«اَحْفَظ» means to save something from being lost or destroyed (manjad). To guard. (m. r.) To try to save something from external dangers. Its opposite is «اَضَاع» meaning to waste. And «حَافِظْ» is a active participle meaning one who protects, and «حَفِیْظ» contains an intensive form, meaning one who protects at all times.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَاللّٰہُ خَیۡرٌ حٰفِظًا» (12/64)\nTranslation: And Allah is the best Guardian.\nSimilarly, at another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ مَاۤ اَنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  بِحَفِیۡظٍ» (11/86)\nTranslation: And I am not a guardian over you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2867,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Guardian",
      "hw": "نگہبان",
      "s": "«رَقِیْب» a guardian who is himself vigilant and aware of every movement of the thing under his care (5 verses: 4:1-5:117-11:93-33:52-50:18)",
      "d": "«رَقَبَۃ» means neck. And «رَقَبَ» means to keep an eye on someone's neck or to supervise and guard them (muf). And «رَقْبَۃٌ» means caution, guardianship, protection, and fear (manjad). Therefore, «رَقِیْب» means a guardian who is himself always vigilant. And nothing that the one under his guardianship does remains hidden from him (faq la 170).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ کُنۡتُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ شَہِیۡدًا مَّا دُمۡتُ فِیۡہِمۡ ۚ فَلَمَّا تَوَفَّیۡتَنِیۡ کُنۡتَ اَنۡتَ الرَّقِیۡبَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ ؕ» (5/117)\nTranslation: And I was a witness over them as long as I remained among them. But when You took me, You were the Watcher over them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2868,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Guardian",
      "hw": "نگہبان",
      "s": "«مُقِیْت» a guardian who possesses full power to protect (1 verse: 4:85)",
      "d": "«قُوَّۃ ، قَاتَ» means to give sustenance. To provide sustenance. To take care of. And «اَقَاتَ» means to have power. To protect. To grant sustenance. And «مُقِیْت» means one in authority, supervisor and guardian (manjad). So, «مُقِیْت» is a supervisor who is also himself in authority. And according to Ibn Faris, three things are found in «مُقِیْت» (1) power over something (2) protection and (3) restraint (m. l.) That is, «مُقِیْت» is the being of authority and power who possesses full strength to protect.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ کَانَ اللّٰہُ  عَلٰی کُلِّ  شَیۡءٍ  مُّقِیۡتًا» (4/85)\nTranslation: And Allah is the Guardian over all things."
    },
    {
      "id": 2870,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Guardian",
      "hw": "نگہبان",
      "s": "«مُھَیْمِن» one who takes under his protection and safeguards (2 verses: 5:48-59:23)",
      "d": "«مُھَیْمِن» Ibn al-Faris and some other lexicographers have derived it from 'amn' meaning one who gives security (m. l.). And «ھَیْمَنَ الطَّائِرُ عَلٰی فَرَاخِہٖ» means the bird has spread its wings over its chicks. And in the meaning of «مُھَیْمِن» two aspects are found (1) to give security from fear to someone (2) not to let someone's right be wasted (m. r.). This word has been used twice in the Quran and has come with both meanings.\nExample 1 - Meaning to take under protection: For example, in the Quran it is said:\n«اَلۡمَلِکُ الۡقُدُّوۡسُ السَّلٰمُ  الۡمُؤۡمِنُ الۡمُہَیۡمِنُ» (59/23)\nTranslation: He is the King (the True and free from all defects), the Holy, the Source of Peace, the Giver of Security, and the Guardian.\nExample 2 - Not letting a right be wasted. For example, the divine command states:\n«وَ اَنۡزَلۡنَاۤ اِلَیۡکَ الۡکِتٰبَ بِالۡحَقِّ مُصَدِّقًا لِّمَا بَیۡنَ یَدَیۡہِ مِنَ الۡکِتٰبِ وَ مُہَیۡمِنًا عَلَیۡہِ» (5/48)\nTranslation: And We have revealed to you, [O Muhammad], the Book in truth, confirming what preceded it of the Scripture and as a guardian over it."
    }
  ],
  "629": [
    {
      "id": 2871,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Swallow",
      "hw": "نگلنا",
      "s": "«بَلَعَ» means to swallow. To take down through the throat. Common usage (1 verse: 11:44)",
      "d": "«بَلْعَم» or «بُلْعُوْم» means throat. The passage for eating food. And «بَلَعَ» means to swallow. To take down through the throat. (muf)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ قِیۡلَ یٰۤاَرۡضُ ابۡلَعِیۡ مَآءَکِ» (11/44)\nTranslation: And it was said, 'O earth, swallow your water.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2872,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Swallow",
      "hw": "نگلنا",
      "s": "«مَرَءَ» means for something to easily reach the stomach (1 verse: 4:4)",
      "d": "«اَلْمَرِئُ» is the name of that passage which goes from the throat to the stomach, through which food reaches the stomach. And «مَرَءَ» means the food easily reached the stomach through that passage (muf). And «مَرِیۡئًا» means food that easily reaches the stomach. (faq la 245)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَاِنۡ طِبۡنَ لَکُمۡ عَنۡ شَیۡءٍ مِّنۡہُ نَفۡسًا فَکُلُوۡہُ ہَنِیۡٓئًا مَّرِیۡٓئًا» (4/4)\nTranslation: But if they, of their own accord, give you a portion thereof, then consume it with pleasure and enjoyment."
    },
    {
      "id": 2873,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Swallow",
      "hw": "نگلنا",
      "s": "«سَاغَ» means for something (food or drink) to go down the throat easily and pleasantly due to its good taste (3 verses: 14:17-16:66-35:12)",
      "d": "«سَاغَ» means for food or drink to go down the throat easily and pleasantly (manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«لَّبَنًا خَالِصًا سَآئِغًا لِّلشّٰرِبِیۡنَ» (16/66)\nTranslation: [And] pure milk, palatable to the drinkers.\nAnd «اَسَاغَ» means to take food or drink down through the throat.\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«وَ یُسۡقٰی مِنۡ مَّآءٍ صَدِیۡدٍ یَّتَجَرَّعُہٗ  وَ لَا یَکَادُ یُسِیۡغُہٗ» (14:17)\nTranslation: He will be given to drink scalding water which will sever his intestines."
    },
    {
      "id": 2874,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Swallow",
      "hw": "نگلنا",
      "s": "«غَصَّ» means for food to get stuck in the throat, i.e., to be unable to swallow (1 verse: 73:13)",
      "d": "«غَصَّ» means for food or water to get stuck in the throat (manjad). For food to get stuck in the throat and be unable to swallow.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اِنَّ  لَدَیۡنَاۤ  اَنۡکَالًا وَّ  جَحِیۡمًا وَّ طَعَامًا ذَا غُصَّۃٍ» (73:12,13)\nTranslation: Indeed, with Us are shackles and burning fire and food that chokes."
    },
    {
      "id": 2875,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Swallow",
      "hw": "نگلنا",
      "s": "«لَقِفَ» means to eat hastily, to swallow without chewing (3 verses: 7:117-20:69-26:45)",
      "d": "«لَقِفَ» means to take something hastily. And «لَقِفَ الطَّعَام» means to eat hastily (manjad). To take something with completeness and alertness. And it is used for taking with hand and mouth. (muf) Meaning to eat hastily. To swallow. (m. q.)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ اَلۡقِ مَا فِیۡ یَمِیۡنِکَ تَلۡقَفۡ مَا صَنَعُوۡا» (20/69)\nTranslation: And throw what is in your right hand; it will swallow what they have crafted."
    },
    {
      "id": 2876,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To Swallow",
      "hw": "نگلنا",
      "s": "«اِلْتَقَمَ» means to gulp down, to make large mouthfuls or to swallow at once (1 verse: 37:142)",
      "d": "«لَقَمَ» means to make a mouthful. As much food as can fit in the mouth at once. To put from hand into mouth. (m. l.) And «اِلْتَقَمَ» means to gulp down hastily (manjad). And means to gulp down by making large mouthfuls (muf).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَالۡتَقَمَہُ  الۡحُوۡتُ وَ ہُوَ  مُلِیۡمٌ» (37/142)\nTranslation: Then the fish swallowed him, while he was blameworthy."
    }
  ],
  "630": [
    {
      "id": 2877,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Bathing. Washing.",
      "hw": "نہانا",
      "s": "«غَسَلَ» and «اِغْتَسَلَ» mean to wash away dirt and filth (3 verses: 5:6-4:43-38:42).",
      "d": "«غَسَلَ» means to wash something and remove dirt and filth.\nFor example: In the Quran: «اِذَا قُمۡتُمۡ اِلَی الصَّلٰوۃِ فَاغۡسِلُوۡا وُجُوۡہَکُمۡ وَ اَیۡدِیَکُمۡ» (5/6)\nTranslation: When you stand for prayer, wash your faces and your hands.\nAnd «اِغْتَسَلَ» means to cleanse the entire body from dirt and filth or to bathe.\nFor example: The command of Allah is: «وَ لَا جُنُبًا اِلَّا عَابِرِیۡ سَبِیۡلٍ حَتّٰی تَغۡتَسِلُوۡا» (4/43)\nTranslation: And [if] one of you is in a state of major impurity, he may not approach [the prayer] until he has bathed, except for a traveler on a journey [who may perform tayammum]."
    },
    {
      "id": 2878,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Bathing. Washing.",
      "hw": "نہانا",
      "s": "«طَھَرَ» and «اِطَّھَرَ» mean to remove impurity as well as dirt (26 verses: 2:25-2:125-2:222-2:232-3:15-3:42-3:55-4:57-5:6-5:41-7:82-8:11-9:103-9:108-11:78-22:26-25:48-27:56-33:33-33:53-56:79-58:12-74:4-76:21-80:14-98:2).",
      "d": "«طَھَرَتْ» is the opposite of «طَمَثَتْ», meaning a woman's state of menstruation. And «طَھْرَت» means being free from menstruation and becoming pure after bathing. The word «طَھَّر» is used in a much broader sense than «غَسَلَ». Purity is of three types: apparent, legal, and spiritual. For example, if urine splashes on clothing, the garment does not become dirty but it becomes impure.\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ ثِیَابَکَ فَطَہِّرۡ» (74/4)\nTranslation: And keep your garments pure.\nThus, «طَھَّر» means both to clean garments from dirt and to purify them from impurity. And this is the difference between «اِطَّھَرَ» (to bathe and become pure) and «اِغْتَسَلَ» (to bathe)."
    }
  ],
  "631": [
    {
      "id": 2879,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "No. Not.",
      "hw": "نہیں",
      "s": "«لَیْسَ» is an incomplete verb in Arabic grammar meaning 'is not' or 'was not' (75 verses: 2:113-2:177-2:189-2:198-2:249-2:272-2:282-3:28-3:36-3:66-3:75-3:113-3:128-3:167-3:182-4:18-4:101-4:123-4:176-5:93-5:116-6:30-6:51-6:53-6:70-6:89-6:122-7:61-7:67-8:51-9:91-11:8-11:16-11:46-11:47-11:78-11:81-15:42-16:99-17:36-17:65-22:10-22:71-24:15-24:29-24:58-24:60-24:61-29:8-29:10-29:68-31:15-33:5-36:81-39:32-39:36-39:37-39:60-40:42-40:43-42:11-43:51-46:32-46:34-48:11-48:17-53:39-53:58-56:2-58:10-69:35-70:2-75:40-88:6-95:8).",
      "d": "«لَیْسَ» is an incomplete verb. It only appears in the past tense and is used with full conjugations, conveying both past and present meanings. For example, «لَسْتَ» means 'you are not' or 'you were not', and «لَسْنَا» means 'we are not' or 'we were not'.\n«ب»، «لَا»، «لَمْ», and «لَنْ»: These three letters, when prefixed to the imperfect verb, negate it. «لَا» merely negates. For example, «لَا یَضْرِبُ» means 'he does not hit' or 'he will not hit'. «لَمْ» negates and also changes the verb to past tense, as in «لَمْ یَضْرِبْ» meaning 'he did not hit'. «لَنْ» negates, specifies the future, and emphasizes negation, as in «لَنْ یَّضْرِبَ» meaning 'he will absolutely never hit'.\n«اِنْ»، «مَا», and «ھَلْ» : These three have their own meanings, but when followed by «اِلَّا», their meanings change to 'not' or 'no'.\nFor example: In the Quran: «اِنۡ اَنۡتُمۡ اِلَّا تَکۡذِبُوۡنَ» (36/15)\nMeaning: 'You are not but liars', i.e., your only work is to lie.\nSimilarly, «مَا مِنْ اِلٰہٍ اِلَّا اللہ» means 'There is no deity but Allah'.\nAnd similarly, in another place: «ہَلۡ کُنۡتُمۡ اِلَّا بَشَرًا رَّسُوۡلًا» (17/93)\nMeaning: 'Am I not but a human messenger?'\nAnd for 'no' or 'not', the following independent particles are used: «لَا»، «لَمَّا»، «بَلٰی»، «کَلَّا»، «اِنَّمَا»، «مَا (نافیہ)», and «لَاتَ»."
    },
    {
      "id": 2880,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "No. Not.",
      "hw": "نہیں",
      "s": "«لَا» means 'no', used in negative responses to positive statements (1204 verses: 1:7-2:2-2:6-2:11-2:12-2:13-2:17-2:18-2:22-2:26-2:30-2:32-2:35-2:38-2:41-2:42-2:48-2:60-2:62-2:68-2:71-2:78-2:80-2:83-2:84-2:86-2:87-2:100-2:101-2:102-2:104-2:105-2:107-2:112-2:113-2:118-2:119-2:120-2:123-2:124-2:132-2:134-2:136-2:141-2:147-2:150-2:152-2:154-2:158-2:162-2:163-2:168-2:169-2:170-2:171-2:173-2:174-2:182-2:185-2:187-2:188-2:190-2:191-2:193-2:195-2:196-2:197-2:203-2:205-2:208-2:216-2:217-2:221-2:222-2:224-2:225-2:228-2:229-2:230-2:231-2:232-2:233-2:234-2:235-2:236-2:237-2:240-2:243-2:249-2:254-2:255-2:256-2:258-2:262-2:264-2:267-2:272-2:273-2:274-2:275-2:276-2:277-2:279-2:281-2:282-2:283-2:285-2:286-3:2-3:5-3:6-3:8-3:9-3:10-3:18-3:25-3:28-3:32-3:57-3:60-3:64-3:66-3:67-3:73-3:75-3:77-3:80-3:84-3:86-3:88-3:102-3:103-3:105-3:111-3:116-3:118-3:119-3:120-3:130-3:139-3:140-3:153-3:154-3:156-3:160-3:161-3:169-3:170-3:171-3:175-3:176-3:178-3:180-3:187-3:188-3:194-3:195-3:196-3:199-4:2-4:5-4:6-4:11-4:18-4:19-4:20-4:22-4:23-4:24-4:25-4:29-4:32-4:34-4:36-4:38-4:40-4:42-4:43-4:46-4:48-4:49-4:53-4:65-4:75-4:77-4:78-4:84-4:87-4:89-4:94-4:95-4:98-4:102-4:104-4:105-4:107-4:108-4:114-4:116-4:121-4:123-4:124-4:127-4:128-4:129-4:135-4:137-4:140-4:142-4:143-4:144-4:148-4:154-4:155-4:168-4:171-4:172-4:173-5:2-5:3-5:5-5:8-5:13-5:19-5:21-5:25-5:26-5:41-5:44-5:48-5:49-5:51-5:54-5:57-5:58-5:64-5:67-5:68-5:69-5:70-5:76-5:77-5:79-5:82-5:84-5:87-5:89-5:95-5:100-5:101-5:103-5:104-5:105-5:106-5:108-5:109-5:115-5:116-6:8-6:12-6:14-6:17-6:19-6:20-6:21-6:25-6:27-6:33-6:34-6:35-6:37-6:38-6:48-6:50-6:51-6:52-6:56-6:59-6:61-6:68-6:70-6:71-6:76-6:80-6:81-6:90-6:91-6:102-6:103-6:106-6:108-6:109-6:113-6:114-6:115-6:121-6:125-6:135-6:136-6:138-6:141-6:142-6:144-6:145-6:147-6:148-6:150-6:151-6:152-6:153-6:158-6:160-6:163-6:164-7:2-7:3-7:17-7:19-7:27-7:28-7:31-7:33-7:34-7:35-7:38-7:40-7:42-7:47-7:49-7:55-7:56-7:58-7:62-7:73-7:74-7:79-7:85-7:86-7:95-7:99-7:100-7:105-7:131-7:142-7:146-7:148-7:150-7:158-7:163-7:169-7:170-7:179-7:182-7:186-7:187-7:188-7:191-7:192-7:193-7:195-7:197-7:198-7:202-7:205-7:206-8:15-8:20-8:21-8:22-8:25-8:27-8:34-8:39-8:46-8:47-8:48-8:55-8:56-8:58-8:59-8:60-8:65-9:6-9:8-9:10-9:12-9:16-9:19-9:23-9:24-9:28-9:29-9:31-9:34-9:36-9:37-9:39-9:40-9:44-9:45-9:49-9:54-9:55-9:66-9:74-9:79-9:80-9:81-9:84-9:85-9:87-9:91-9:92-9:93-9:94-9:96-9:101-9:108-9:109-9:110-9:116-9:118-9:120-9:121-9:126-9:127-9:129-10:7-10:11-10:15-10:16-10:17-10:18-10:26-10:33-10:35-10:36-10:37-10:40-10:42-10:43-10:44-10:47-10:49-10:54-10:55-10:60-10:61-10:62-10:64-10:65-10:68-10:69-10:71-10:77-10:81-10:85-10:88-10:89-10:90-10:94-10:95-10:96-10:100-10:101-10:104-10:105-10:106-10:107-11:14-11:15-11:17-11:22-11:26-11:29-11:31-11:34-11:36-11:37-11:42-11:43-11:46-11:49-11:51-11:52-11:55-11:57-11:64-11:70-11:78-11:81-11:84-11:85-11:89-11:105-11:109-11:112-11:113-11:115-11:118-11:121-12:5-12:10-12:11-12:15-12:21-12:23-12:37-12:38-12:40-12:52-12:56-12:60-12:67-12:68-12:69-12:86-12:87-12:90-12:92-12:96-12:107-12:110-13:1-13:11-13:14-13:16-13:20-13:30-13:31-13:33-13:36-13:37-13:41-14:9-14:17-14:18-14:22-14:31-14:34-14:38-14:42-14:43-14:47-15:13-15:48-15:53-15:55-15:65-15:68-15:69-15:88-16:1-16:2-16:8-16:17-16:18-16:20-16:22-16:23-16:26-16:35-16:37-16:38-16:43-16:45-16:49-16:51-16:56-16:60-16:61-16:62-16:70-16:73-16:74-16:75-16:76-16:78-16:84-16:85-16:91-16:92-16:94-16:95-16:101-16:104-16:105-16:107-16:109-16:111-16:115-16:116-16:127-17:10-17:15-17:22-17:23-17:26-17:29-17:31-17:32-17:33-17:34-17:36-17:37-17:39-17:44-17:45-17:48-17:56-17:68-17:69-17:71-17:75-17:76-17:77-17:82-17:86-17:88-17:99-17:107-17:110-18:5-18:19-18:21-18:22-18:23-18:26-18:27-18:28-18:30-18:38-18:39-18:49-18:51-18:60-18:69-18:70-18:73-18:76-18:93-18:101-18:105-18:108-18:110-19:39-19:42-19:44-19:60-19:62-19:84-19:87-20:8-20:14-20:16-20:21-20:40-20:42-20:46-20:47-20:52-20:58-20:61-20:68-20:69-20:74-20:77-20:81-20:89-20:94-20:97-20:98-20:107-20:108-20:109-20:110-20:112-20:114-20:117-20:118-20:119-20:120-20:123-20:131-20:132-21:7-21:8-21:13-21:19-21:20-21:23-21:24-21:25-21:27-21:28-21:37-21:39-21:40-21:43-21:45-21:47-21:66-21:87-21:89-21:94-21:95-21:100-21:102-21:103-22:7-22:8-22:12-22:26-22:37-22:38-22:46-22:52-22:55-22:67-22:73-23:27-23:44-23:56-23:59-23:62-23:65-23:74-23:88-23:94-23:101-23:108-23:115-23:116-23:117-24:2-24:3-24:4-24:11-24:19-24:21-24:22-24:27-24:28-24:31-24:33-24:35-24:37-24:53-24:55-24:57-24:58-24:60-24:61-24:63-25:3-25:9-25:14-25:19-25:21-25:22-25:33-25:40-25:52-25:55-25:58-25:68-25:72-26:13-26:50-26:87-26:88-26:101-26:151-26:152-26:156-26:181-26:183-26:201-26:202-26:213-26:226-27:4-27:10-27:18-27:20-27:24-27:26-27:37-27:41-27:48-27:50-27:61-27:65-27:70-27:73-27:80-27:82-27:85-28:7-28:9-28:11-28:13-28:23-28:25-28:28-28:31-28:35-28:37-28:39-28:41-28:50-28:55-28:56-28:57-28:66-28:70-28:76-28:77-28:78-28:80-28:82-28:83-28:84-28:86-28:87-28:88-29:2-29:8-29:17-29:22-29:33-29:36-29:46-29:48-29:53-29:60-29:63-30:6-30:30-30:31-30:39-30:43-30:45-30:52-30:56-30:57-30:59-30:60-31:13-31:15-31:18-31:20-31:23-31:25-31:28-31:33-32:2-32:4-32:15-32:17-32:18-32:23-32:29-33:1-33:13-33:15-33:16-33:17-33:18-33:32-33:33-33:36-33:37-33:39-33:48-33:51-33:52-33:53-33:55-33:59-33:60-33:65-33:69-34:3-34:8-34:22-34:23-34:25-34:28-34:30-34:31-34:36-34:37-34:42-34:51-35:2-35:3-35:5-35:8-35:11-35:14-35:18-35:20-35:21-35:22-35:35-35:36-35:39-35:43-35:44-36:7-36:9-36:10-36:21-36:22-36:23-36:31-36:36-36:40-36:43-36:50-36:54-36:60-36:67-36:75-36:76-37:8-37:13-37:25-37:35-37:47-37:92-38:22-38:26-38:35-38:44-38:59-38:60-38:62-39:3-39:6-39:7-39:9-39:20-39:25-39:29-39:43-39:45-39:49-39:53-39:54-39:55-39:61-39:69-40:3-40:4-40:16-40:17-40:18-40:20-40:27-40:28-40:40-40:43-40:52-40:57-40:58-40:59-40:61-40:62-40:65-41:4-41:7-41:16-41:22-41:26-41:30-41:34-41:37-41:38-41:40-41:42-41:44-41:47-41:49-42:7-42:8-42:13-42:15-42:18-42:23-42:31-42:40-42:47-42:52-43:52-43:61-43:62-43:66-43:68-43:75-43:80-43:86-43:88-44:8-44:19-44:39-44:41-44:56-45:10-45:14-45:18-45:22-45:26-45:32-45:35-46:5-46:8-46:9-46:10-46:13-46:19-46:25-46:26-46:32-46:35-47:11-47:13-47:19-47:33-47:35-47:36-47:38-48:15-48:17-48:22-48:27-49:1-49:2-49:4-49:11-49:12-49:14-49:17-50:28-51:28-51:51-51:59-52:15-52:16-52:23-52:29-52:33-52:36-52:46-52:47-53:26-53:27-53:28-53:32-53:60-55:9-55:20-55:33-55:35-55:39-55:56-55:74-56:19-56:25-56:33-56:44-56:61-56:75-56:79-56:85-57:8-57:10-57:15-57:16-57:22-57:23-58:7-58:9-58:14-58:17-58:22-59:6-59:7-59:9-59:10-59:11-59:12-59:13-59:14-59:19-59:20-59:22-59:23-60:1-60:3-60:5-60:8-60:10-60:12-60:13-61:2-61:3-61:5-61:7-62:5-62:7-63:3-63:6-63:7-63:8-63:9-64:13-65:1-65:3-65:6-65:7-65:6-66:6-66:7-66:8-68:8-68:10-68:18-68:24-68:42-68:44-68:48-69:18-69:33-69:34-69:36-69:37-69:38-69:39-69:42-70:10-70:40-71:4-71:13-71:23-71:24-71:26-71:27-71:28-72:3-72:10-72:13-72:18-72:20-72:21-72:26-73:9-74:6-74:28-74:31-74:53-75:1-75:2-75:11-75:16-75:31-76:9-76:13-76:24-77:31-77:35-77:36-77:48-78:24-78:27-78:35-78:37-78:38-81:15-82:19-84:16-84:20-84:21-86:10-87:6-87:13-88:7-88:11-89:17-89:18-89:25-89:26-90:1-90:11-91:15-92:15-93:9-93:10-96:19-107:3-109-2-109:3-109:4-109:5).",
      "d": "«لَا» is extensively used. It is employed in negating positive statements, for responses, for conjunctions, and for repetition.\nFor example: In the Quran: «فَلَا صَدَّقَ وَ لَا صَلّٰی» (75/31)\nTranslation: He neither believed nor prayed.\n(For detailed explanation, refer to any book on Arabic grammar.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2881,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "No. Not.",
      "hw": "نہیں",
      "s": "«لَمَّا» is used for negating a past event (152 verses: 2:17-2:33-2:89-2:101-2:214-2:246-2:249-2:250-2:259-3:36-3:52-3:142-4:77-5:117-6:5-6:44-6:76-6:77-6:78-7:22-7:116-7:126-7:134-7:135-7:143-7:149-7:150-7:154-7:155-7:165-7:166-7:189-7:190-8:48-9:16-9:76-9:114-10:12-10:13-10:23-10:39-10:54-10:76-10:77-10:80-10:81-10:98-11:58-11:66-11:70-11:74-11:77-11:82-11:94-11:101-11:111-12:15-12:22-12:28-12:31-12:50-12:54-12:59-12:63-12:65-12:66-12:68-12:69-12:70-12:80-12:88-12:94-12:96-12:99-14:22-15:61-17:67-18:59-18:61-18:62-19:49-20:11-21:12-25:37-26:21-26:41-26:61-27:8-27:10-27:13-27:36-27:40-27:42-27:44-28:14-28:19-28:22-28:23-28:25-28:29-28:30-28:31-28:36-28:48-29:31-29:33-29:65-29:68-31:32-32:24-33:22-33:37-34:14-34:33-34:43-35:42-36:32-37:102-37:103-38:8-40:25-40:66-40:83-40:84-40:85-41:41-42:44-43:30-43:35-43:47-43:50-43:55-43:57-43:63-46:7-46:24-46:29-49:14-50:5-59:16-61:5-61:6-62:3-66:3-67:27-68:26-68:51-69:11-72:13-72:19-80:23-86:4).",
      "d": "«لَمَّا» generally means 'not yet' or 'had not' in the past tense, used for negating a past event.\nFor example: In the Quran: «وَ لَمَّا یَعۡلَمِ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ جٰہَدُوۡنَ مِنۡکُمۡ» (9/16)\nTranslation: And Allah has not yet known those who have strived among you.\n(For further details, consult a book on Arabic grammar!)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2882,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "No. Not.",
      "hw": "نہیں",
      "s": "«بَلٰی» means 'why not?' (33 verses: 2:49-2:124-2:155-2:249-3:152-3:154-3:186-4:6-5:48-5:94-6:165-7:141-7:163-7:168-8:17-10:30-11:7-14:6-16:92-18:7-21:35-23:30-27:40-33:11-37:106-44:33-47:4-47:31-67:2-68:17-76:2-89:15-89:16).",
      "d": "«بَلٰی» is used when a question is negative and the answer intends to negate that negation, i.e., to affirm positively. It means 'why not?'.\nFor example: In the Quran: «اَلَسۡتُ بِرَبِّکُمۡ ؕ قَالُوۡا بَلٰی» (7/172)\nTranslation: [Allah asked] 'Am I not your Lord?' They said, 'Yes indeed!' (i.e., why not?)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2883,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "No. Not.",
      "hw": "نہیں",
      "s": "«کَلَّا» means 'never' (33 verses: 19:79-19:82-23:100-26:15-26:62-34:27-70:15-70:39-74:16-74:32-74:53-74:54-75:11-75:20-75:26-78:4-78:5-80:11-80:23-82:9-83:7-83:14-83:15-83:18-89:17-78:21-96:6-96:15-96:19-102:3-102:4-102:5-104:4).",
      "d": "«کَلَّا» means 'never'. It is used to emphatically reject a preceding statement. It serves to nullify the previous discourse.\nFor example: In the Quran: «عَمَّ یَتَسَآءَلُوۡنَ عَنِ النَّبَاِ الۡعَظِیۡمِ الَّذِیۡ ہُمۡ فِیۡہِ مُخۡتَلِفُوۡنَ کَلَّا سَیَعۡلَمُوۡنَ ثُمَّ کَلَّا سَیَعۡلَمُوۡنَ» (78/1-5)\nTranslation: What is [the matter with] them that they are in such confusion about the great news? No! They will come to know. Then no! They will come to know."
    },
    {
      "id": 2884,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "No. Not.",
      "hw": "نہیں",
      "s": "«اِنَّمَا» is a restrictive particle in Arabic grammar meaning 'nothing but' or 'only' (137 verses: 2:11-2:14-2:102-2:117-2:137-2:169-2:173-2:181-2:275-3:20-3:47-3:155-3:175-3:178-3:185-4:10-4:17-4:111-4:171-5:27-5:33-5:55-5:90-5:91-6:19-6:36-6:109-6:156-6:159-7:33-7:131-7:173-7:187-7:203-8:2-9:18-9:28-9:37-9:45-9:55-9:60-9:65-9:85-9:93-10:20-10:23-10:24-10:108-11:12-11:33-12:86-13:7-13:19-13:36-13:40-14:42-15:15-16:40-16:51-16:82-16:92-16:95-16:100-16:101-16:103-16:105-16:115-16:124-17:15-18:110-19:19-19:35-19:84-19:97-20:69-20:72-20:90-20:98-21:45-21:108-22:49-23:117-24:51-24:54-24:62-26:153-26:185-27:40-27:91-27:92-28:78-29:6-29:17-29:25-29:50-31:12-32:15-33:33-33:63-34:46-34:50-35:6-35:18-35:28-36:11-36:82-37:19-38:65-39:9-39:10-39:41-39:49-40:39-40:68-41:6-42:42-44:58-46:23-47:36-47:38-48:10-49:10-49:15-51:5-52:16-58:10-60:9-64:12-64:15-66:7-67:26-72:20-76:9-77:7-79:13-79:45-88:21).",
      "d": "«اِنَّمَا» is called a 'word of restriction' in Arabic grammar. It means 'nothing but' or 'only'. It restricts the meaning to a specific thing.\nFor example: In the Quran: «قُلۡ اِنَّمَاۤ اَنَا بَشَرٌ مِّثۡلُکُمۡ یُوۡحٰۤی اِلَیَّ» (18/110)\nTranslation: Say, 'I am only a human being like you, to whom has been revealed [the message].'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2886,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "no; not",
      "hw": "نہیں",
      "s": "«لَات» means 'no' or 'was not' (1 verse: 38:3)",
      "d": "«لَات» comes in the meaning of «لَیْسَ» and is counted among the eloquence of the people of Yemen (after 'la', 't' is extra and its noun is omitted (Munjid)). For example, the Quran states: «فَنَادَوۡا  وَّ  لَاتَ حِیۡنَ مَنَاصٍ» (38/3). Translation: They cried out, while there was no time for refuge. Here, instead of «لَاتَ الْحِیْنَ حِینَ مَنَاص», it is «لَاتَ حِیۡنَ مَنَاص». The first 'حِیْن' is omitted here (Jam' al-Bayan)."
    }
  ],
  "632": [
    {
      "id": 2887,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "New. To become new.",
      "hw": "نیا",
      "s": "«حَدَثَ» means the emergence of something new (8 verses: 2:76-18:70-20:113-21:2-26:5-65:1-93:11-99:4).",
      "d": "«حَدَثَ» is the opposite of «عَدَمَ» (non-existence). It means something new coming into existence, or something that was not new but people forgot it and it reappears as if new.\nFor example: In the Quran: «لَا تَدۡرِیۡ لَعَلَّ اللّٰہَ یُحۡدِثُ بَعۡدَ ذٰلِکَ اَمۡرًا» (65/1)\nTranslation: You do not know; perhaps Allah will bring about after that a new matter."
    },
    {
      "id": 2889,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "New. To be new.",
      "hw": "نیا",
      "s": "«بَدَعَه» To create something new without a precedent, to innovate. (3 verses: 2:117-6:101-46:9)",
      "d": "«بَدَعَہ» has two meanings: (1) to initiate something, and (2) to create something for which there is no prior example or model (M. L.). In this sense, Allah's name is «بَدِیْع», meaning The Originator (who brings something into existence for the first time). And «بِدْعًا» means one who initiates something or a beginning.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«قُلۡ مَا کُنۡتُ بِدۡعًا مِّنَ الرُّسُلِ» (46/9)\nTranslation: Say, [O Muhammad], 'I am not a new [or unprecedented] messenger.'"
    }
  ],
  "633": [
    {
      "id": 2890,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Below",
      "hw": "نیچے",
      "s": "«تَحْت» is an adverbial noun. Meaning: below. (50 verses: 2:25-2:266-3:15-3:136-3:195-3:198-4:13-4:57-4:122-5:12-5:66-5:85-5:119-6:6-6:65-7:43-9:72-9:89-9:100-10:9-13:35-14:23-16:31-18:31-18:82-19:24-20:6-20:76-22:14-22:23-25:10-29:55-29:58-39:16-39:20-41:29-43:51-47:12-48:5-48:17-48:18-57:12-58:22-61:12-64:9-65:11-66:8-66:10-85:11-98:8)",
      "d": "«تَحْت» is an adverbial noun meaning below. Its opposite is «فَوْق», meaning above. It is used in both physical and spiritual senses.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ اَنَّہُمۡ اَقَامُوا التَّوۡرٰىۃَ وَ الۡاِنۡجِیۡلَ وَ مَاۤ اُنۡزِلَ اِلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنۡ رَّبِّہِمۡ لَاَکَلُوۡا مِنۡ فَوۡقِہِمۡ وَ مِنۡ تَحۡتِ اَرۡجُلِہِمۡ» (5/66)\nTranslation: And if they had upheld the Torah and the Gospel and what was revealed to them from their Lord, they would have eaten [provision] from above them and from beneath their feet."
    },
    {
      "id": 2891,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Below",
      "hw": "نیچے",
      "s": "«اَسْفَلَ سَافِل» The lowest part of something, or low in rank and status. Below. Low. Inferior. (7 verses: 4:145-8:42-9:40-33:10-37:98-41:29-95:5)",
      "d": "«اَسْفَلَ» means lower, low, inferior. Its opposite is «اعلٰی», meaning excellent, high, elevated. This word is used in two ways: (1) The lower part of a single thing is called «اَسْفَل» and the upper part «اَعْلٰی», as in «اَسْفَلَہٗ اَغْلَظُ مِنْ اَعْلَاہُ» meaning 'the lower part of it is harder than its upper part.'\nFor rank and status, «اَعْلٰی» denotes highness, and «اَسْفَلَ» denotes lowness and inferiority. Its feminine form is «سُفْلٰی».\nFor example, the saying of the Holy Prophet ﷺ is:\n«اَلْیَدُ الْعُلْیَا خَیْرٌ مِّنْ یَدِ السُّفْلٰی»\nMeaning: The upper hand (the giving hand) is better than the lower hand (the receiving hand).\nIn this hadith, «عُلْیَا» and «سُفْلٰی» are used in a spiritual sense, meaning the hand that gives charity is better than the hand that takes.\nAnd the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ جَعَلَ کَلِمَۃَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوا السُّفۡلٰی ؕ وَ کَلِمَتُ اللّٰہِ ہِیَ الۡعُلۡیَا» (9/40)\nTranslation: And Allah has debased the word of those who disbelieved [i.e., their false claims], and the word of Allah is the highest [i.e., supreme].\nAnd «سَافِل» means low in rank and status, contemptible. And «اَلسِّفْلَۃ» means the lowly people (pl.).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ فِیۡۤ اَحۡسَنِ تَقۡوِیۡمٍ ۫ثُمَّ رَدَدۡنٰہُ اَسۡفَلَ سٰفِلِیۡنَ» (95/4-5)\nTranslation: We have certainly created man in the best of stature; Then We return him to the lowest of the low."
    },
    {
      "id": 2892,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To lower. To keep. To abase.",
      "hw": "نیچے",
      "s": "«خَفَضَ» For something to be pressed down or to press down. To lower the gaze, arm, or side. (4 verses: 15:88-17:24-26:215-56:3)",
      "d": "«خَفَضَ» means to make low, to humble. Its opposite is «رَفَعَ», meaning to elevate. «خافِض» and «رافِع» are both names of Allah, meaning The One Who lowers and The One Who raises. «خَفَضَ الصَّوْت» means he lowered his voice. And «خَفَضَ الْجَنَاحَ» means to keep the wing (arm) low, to humble oneself.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اخۡفِضۡ لَہُمَا جَنَاحَ الذُّلِّ مِنَ الرَّحۡمَۃِ» (17/24)\nTranslation: And lower to them the wing of humility and mercy."
    },
    {
      "id": 2893,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To lower. To keep. To abase.",
      "hw": "نیچے",
      "s": "«غَضَّ» Used for lowering the gaze or voice. (In general circumstances). (4 verses: 24:30-24:31-31:19-49:3)",
      "d": "«غَضَّ» is used for keeping the gaze or voice low. «غَضَّ صَوْتُہٗ» means he lowered his voice. And «غَضَّ بَصَرُہٗ» means he lowered his gaze or restrained it from looking at something forbidden.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«قُلۡ لِّلۡمُؤۡمِنٰتِ یَغۡضُضۡنَ مِنۡ اَبۡصَارِہِنَّ» (24/31)\nTranslation: And tell the believing women to lower [i.e., guard] their gaze.\nAt another place, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اقۡصِدۡ فِیۡ مَشۡیِکَ وَ اغۡضُضۡ مِنۡ صَوۡتِکَ» (31/19)\nTranslation: And be moderate in your pace and lower your voice."
    },
    {
      "id": 2894,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To lower. To keep. To abase.",
      "hw": "نیچے",
      "s": "«قَصَرَ» To restrict the gaze. Not to use the full gaze. (3 verses: 37:48-38:52-55:56)",
      "d": "«قَصَرَ» means not to reach the limit or extent of something (M. L.), to shorten, to do less than required. For example, «صَلٰوۃُ الْقَصْر» (the shortened prayer). And «قَصَرُ الطَّرْف» means the gaze as far as it can see; not to look that far, but to keep the gaze lowered. In these senses, the word is specific for gazes.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ عِنۡدَہُمۡ قٰصِرٰتُ الطَّرۡفِ عِیۡنٌ» (37/48)\nTranslation: And with them will be women with modest, restrained glances."
    },
    {
      "id": 2895,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "To lower. To keep. To abase.",
      "hw": "نیچے",
      "s": "«خَشَعَ» Such a fear whose effects begin to manifest on the limbs and organs. (15 verses: 2:45-3:199-20:108-21:90-23:2-33:35-41:39-42:45-54:7-57:16-59:21-68:43-70:44-79:9-88:2)",
      "d": "«خَشَعَ» originally refers to a fear whose effects begin to manifest on the limbs and organs (M.). These effects can be manifest through the face, voice, or eyes. Therefore, this word is used for lowering them. And for gaze and voice, the word «غَضَّ» is also used. The difference is that if it is in a general state, «غَضَّ» is used, and if it is due to fear, «خَشَعَ» is used.\nFor example, for the gaze, the Noble Quran states:\n«خَاشِعَۃً اَبۡصَارُہُمۡ تَرۡہَقُہُمۡ ذِلَّۃٌ» (70/44)\nTranslation: Their eyes will be humbled, and they will be covered with humility.\nAnd for the voice, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ خَشَعَتِ الۡاَصۡوَاتُ لِلرَّحۡمٰنِ» (20/108)\nTranslation: And the voices will be humbled before the Most Merciful [i.e., they will be low due to fear].\nAnd for the face, the Noble Quran states:\n«وُجُوۡہٌ یَّوۡمَئِذٍ خَاشِعَۃٌ» (88/2)\nTranslation: [Some] faces, that Day, will be humbled."
    }
  ],
  "634": [
    {
      "id": 2896,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Righteous. Virtuous.",
      "hw": "نیک",
      "s": "«صَالِح» One who reforms himself and rectifies all kinds of corruption. (123 verses: 2:25-2:62-2:82-2:130-2:277-3:39-3:46-3:57-3:114-4:34-4:57-4:69-4:122-4:124-4:173-5:9-5:69-5:84-5:93-6:85-7:42-7:168-7:189-7:190-7:196-9:75-9:102-9:120-10:4-10:9-11:11-11:23-11:46-12:9-12:101-13:29-14:23-16:97-16:122-17:9-17:25-18:2-18:30-18:46-18:82-18:88-18:107-18:110-19:60-19:76-19:96-20:75-20:82-20:112-21:72-21:75-21:86-21:94-21:105-22:14-22:23-22:50-22:56-23:51-23:100-24:32-24:55-25:70-25:71-26:83-26:227-27:19-28:27-28:67-28:80-29:7-29:9-29:27-29:58-30:15-30:44-30:45-31:8-32:12-32:19-33:31-34:4-34:11-34:37-35:7-35:10-35:37-37:100-37:112-38:24-38:28-40:40-40:58-41:8-41:33-41:46-42:22-42:23-42:26-45:15-45:21-45:30-46:15-47:2-47:12-48:29-63:10-64:9-65:11-66:4-66:10-68:50-72:11-84:25-85:11-95:6-98:7-103:3)",
      "d": "«صَلَح» means to rectify corruption, and its opposite is «فَسَدَ» (to corrupt) (M. L.). And «صَالِح» means one who purifies himself, one who reforms his soul (M.), one who adopts good deeds and abandons bad ones, and one who remains engaged in striving for his own reformation.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ کَانَ اَبُوۡہُمَا صَالِحًا» (18/82)\nTranslation: And their father was a righteous man.\nAt another place, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تُفۡسِدُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ بَعۡدَ اِصۡلَاحِہَا» (7/56)\nTranslation: And do not cause corruption on the earth after its reformation."
    },
    {
      "id": 2897,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Righteous. Virtuous.",
      "hw": "نیک",
      "s": "«اَبْرَار» This (plural of «بَار») is a person who is always prepared to do good, one who does abundant good deeds. (9 verses: 3:193-3:198-19:14-19:32-76:5-80:16-82:13-83:18-83:22)",
      "d": "«اَبْرَار» is the plural of «بَار». «بِرّ» means to do good on a wide scale (M.). «بِرّ» essentially does not mean goodness itself, but rather the characteristic and innate disposition of being constantly inclined towards goodness. Its opposite is «اِثْم», meaning sin and disobedience.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«لَنۡ تَنَالُوا الۡبِرَّ حَتّٰی تُنۡفِقُوۡا مِمَّا تُحِبُّوۡنَ» (3/92)\nTranslation: You will never attain righteousness until you spend [in the way of Allah] from what you love.\nAnd «بَرَّ» and «بَارّ» is a person whose nature is always prepared to do good, and when an opportunity arises, he does such a good deed. And an accepted Hajj (Hajj-e-Mabrur) is that Hajj which is performed exactly according to the Sunnah of the Prophet ﷺ, without any deficiency.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ بَرًّۢا بِوَالِدَیۡہِ وَ لَمۡ یَکُنۡ جَبَّارًا عَصِیًّا» (19/14)\nTranslation: And [he was] dutiful to his parents, and he was not a rebellious disobedient [person]."
    },
    {
      "id": 2898,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Righteous. Virtuous.",
      "hw": "نیک",
      "s": "«بَرَرَۃٌ» This is an intensive form from «بَار», meaning a person who is always prepared to do exceedingly abundant good. (1 verse: 80:16)",
      "d": "«بَرَرَۃٌ» is the plural of «بَرَّ». It is stronger than «بَارّ» and carries more emphasis (intensiveness).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«بِاَیۡدِیۡ سَفَرَۃٍ کِرَامٍۭ بَرَرَۃٍ» (80/15-16)\nTranslation: [Written] by the hands of noble, righteous scribes."
    },
    {
      "id": 2899,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Righteous / Fortunate",
      "hw": "نیک",
      "s": "«رَشِیْد» one with good habits and conduct. Righteous. (3 verses: 11:78-11:87-11:97)",
      "d": "«رُشْد» means 'steadfastness on the right path' (M. L.), i.e., walking correctly on the path or remaining on the straight path. Its opposite is «غَیّ», meaning to deviate onto a wrong path.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«قَدۡ تَّبَیَّنَ الرُّشۡدُ مِنَ الۡغَیِّ» (2/256)\nTranslation: Guidance has become clearly distinct from misguidance.\nAnd «رَشِیْد» means guided, one with good habits and conduct, righteous.\nFor example, the divine command is:\n«فَاتَّقُوا اللّٰہَ وَ لَا تُخۡزُوۡنِ فِیۡ ضَیۡفِیۡ ؕ اَلَـیۡسَ مِنۡکُمۡ رَجُلٌ رَّشِیْدٌ» (11/78)\nTranslation: Fear Allah and do not disgrace me in front of my guests. Is there not among you a man of good conduct?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2900,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Righteous / Fortunate",
      "hw": "نیک",
      "s": "«سَعِیْد» a person who is naturally good. Fortunate. (1 verse: 11:105)",
      "d": "«سَعِیْد» is a person who is naturally good. That is, fortunate and blessed. Its opposite is «شَقِیّ», meaning wretched. And «سَعَدَ» means good fortune. And the attainment of good with divine assistance in matters of faith (Muf. M. L.).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«یَوۡمَ یَاۡتِ لَا تَکَلَّمُ نَفۡسٌ اِلَّا بِاِذۡنِہٖ ۚ فَمِنۡہُمۡ شَقِیٌّ وَّ سَعِیْدٌ» (11/105)\nTranslation: On the Day when no soul will speak except by His permission, then among them will be the wretched and the fortunate."
    },
    {
      "id": 2902,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Righteous / Fortunate",
      "hw": "نیک",
      "s": "«رَبَّانِی» ascetic. Godly people. Sheikhs of the type of worshippers and ascetics. (3 verses: 3:79-5:44-5:63)",
      "d": "Imam Raghub has discussed this word extensively. Some scholars write its meaning as 'one who nurtures knowledge'. Others relate it to «رَبّ» as «جِسْمٌ» to «جِسْمَانِیٌّ». Similarly, «رَبّ» to «رَبَّانِیٌّ». And its meaning is 'belonging to Allah' or 'pious'. Both meanings are written by Sahib al-Munjid. A great scholar as well as a person of Allah. An 'arif billah' (one who knows Allah) as well. However, the second opinion seems more prevalent. Because in the Quran, «رَبَّانِیُّون» is followed by «اَحْبَار» (scholars) separately (5/44). Similarly, in the Quran, the word «رِبِّیُّوْن» appears (3/146) with the same meaning.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«لَوۡ لَا یَنۡہٰہُمُ الرَّبّٰنِیُّوۡنَ وَ الۡاَحۡبَارُ عَنۡ قَوۡلِہِمُ الۡاِثۡمَ وَ اَکۡلِہِمُ السُّحۡتَ» (5/63)\nTranslation: Why do their rabbis and scholars not forbid them from sinful speech and consuming unlawful earnings?"
    }
  ],
  "635": [
    {
      "id": 2903,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Goodness / Good Deeds",
      "hw": "نیکی",
      "s": "«عُرف ، مَعْرُوْف» every matter that good people of society consider good. (55 verses: 2:89-2:146-2:178-2:180-2:228-2:229-2:231-2:232-2:233-2:234-2:235-2:236-2:240-2:241-2:263-2:273-3:104-3:110-3:114-4:5-4:6-4:8-4:19-4:25-4:114-5:83-6:20-7:46-7:48-7:157-7:199-9:67-9:71-9:112-12:58-12:62-16:83-22:41-22:72-23:69-24:53-27:93-31:15-31:17-33:6-33:32-33:59-47:6-47:21-47:30-55:41-60:12-65:2-65:6-83:24)",
      "d": "«عَرَفَ» means to recognize something, and its opposite is «نَکَرَ», meaning to be surprised or astonished. And «معروف» and «عرف» is every matter that good people of society consider good. The good customs of society. The ways of good people. The national customs that are considered praiseworthy. Such as sitting respectfully before elders and calling them with respect, etc.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«خُذِ الۡعَفۡوَ وَ اۡمُرۡ بِالۡعُرۡفِ وَ اَعۡرِضۡ عَنِ الۡجٰہِلِیۡنَ» (7/199)\nTranslation: (O Muhammad ﷺ!) Choose forgiveness and enjoin what is good, and turn away from the ignorant.\nAt another place, the divine command is:\n«وَلۡتَکُنۡ مِّنۡکُمۡ اُمَّۃٌ یَّدۡعُوۡنَ اِلَی الۡخَیۡرِ وَ یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَ یَنۡہَوۡنَ عَنِ الۡمُنۡکَرِ» (3/104)\nTranslation: And let there be among you a group who invite to good, enjoin what is right, and forbid what is wrong."
    },
    {
      "id": 2904,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Goodness / Good Deeds",
      "hw": "نیکی",
      "s": "«حَسَنَۃٌ» every action that is in accordance with reason and Shariah. (31 verses: 2:201-3:120-4:40-4:78-4:79-4:85-6:160-7:95-7:131-7:156-7:168-9:50-9:52-11:114-13:6-13:22-16:30-16:41-16:122-16:125-25:70-27:46-27:89-28:54-28:84-33:21-39:10-41:34-42:23-60:4-60:6)",
      "d": "«حَسَنَۃٌ» its plural is «حَسَنَات». Every pleasing and praiseworthy action that is in accordance with reason and Shariah. Its opposite is «سَیِّئَۃً», and its plural is «سَیِّئَات».\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«اِنَّ الۡحَسَنٰتِ یُذۡہِبۡنَ السَّیِّاٰتِ» (11/114)\nTranslation: Indeed, good deeds erase bad deeds."
    },
    {
      "id": 2905,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Goodness / Good Deeds",
      "hw": "نیکی",
      "s": "«خَیْر» every action that is desirable to all or whose benefit reaches the people. (170 verses: 2:54-2:61-2:103-2:105-2:106-2:110-2:148-2:158-2:180-2:184-2:197-2:215-2:216-2:220-2:221-2:263-2:269-2:271-2:272-2:273-2:280-3:15-3:26-3:30-3:54-3:104-3:110-3:114-3:115-3:150-3:157-3:178-3:180-3:198-4:19-4:25-4:46-4:59-4:66-4:77-4:114-4:127-4:128-4:149-4:170-4:171-5:48-5:114-6:17-6:32-6:57-6:158-7:12-7:26-7:85-7:87-7:89-7:155-7:169-7:188-8:19-8:23-8:30-8:70-9:3-9:41-9:61-9:74-9:88-9:109-10:11-10:58-10:107-10:109-11:31-11:84-11:86-12:39-12:57-12:59-12:64-12:80-12:109-16:30-16:76-16:95-16:126-17:11-17:35-18:36-18:40-18:44-18:46-18:81-18:95-19:73-19:76-20:73-20:131-21:35-21:73-21:89-21:90-22:11-22:30-22:36-22:58-22:77-23:29-23:56-23:61-23:72-23:109-23:118-24:11-24:12-24:27-24:33-24:60-25:10-25:15-25:24-27:36-27:59-27:89-28:24-28:26-28:60-28:80-28:84-29:16-30:38-33:19-33:25-34:39-35:32-37:62-38:32-38:76-41:40-41:49-42:36-43:32-43:52-43:58-44:37-46:11-47:21-49:5-49:11-50:25-54:43-55:70-58:12-61:11-62:9-62:11-64:16-66:5-68:12-68:32-70:21-70:41-73:20-87:17-93:4-97:3-98:7-99:7-100:8)",
      "d": "«خَیْر» its plural is «خَیْرَات». And its opposite is «شَرّ». «خَیْر» means the perfection of goodness. Actions whose benefit reaches the people (Muf.). Great good deeds. Great actions of goodness. Also, «خَیْر» means an action that is desirable to all (Muf.), such as arranging water for travelers on the road, etc.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَ یَنۡہَوۡنَ عَنِ الۡمُنۡکَرِ وَ یُسَارِعُوۡنَ فِی الۡخَیۡرٰتِ» (3/114)\nTranslation: They enjoin what is right, forbid what is wrong, and hasten towards good deeds."
    },
    {
      "id": 2906,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Goodness / Good Deeds",
      "hw": "نیکی",
      "s": "«بِرّ» the constant inclination of the nature towards goodness at all times. (9 verses: 2:44-2:177-2:189-2:224-3:92-5:2-52:28-58:9-60:8)",
      "d": "«بِرّ» means the constant inclination of the nature towards every good deed and performing it when the opportunity arises. Its opposite is «اِثْم», meaning sin, transgression, moral or religious crime. (For details, see above under 'Righteous').\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«تَعَاوَنُوۡا عَلَی الۡبِرِّ وَ التَّقۡوٰی ۪ وَ لَا تَعَاوَنُوۡا عَلَی الۡاِثۡمِ وَ الۡعُدۡوَانِ» (5/2)\nTranslation: Cooperate in righteousness and piety, but do not cooperate in sin and aggression."
    }
  ],
  "636": [
    {
      "id": 2907,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Abundant / More / Much",
      "hw": "زیادہ",
      "s": "«کَثِیْر» its usage is general. Increase in number or quantity of anything. (71 verses: 2:26-2:109-2:245-2:249-2:269-3:41-3:146-3:186-4:1-4:19-4:82-4:94-4:100-4:114-4:160-5:15-5:32-5:49-5:62-5:64-5:66-5:68-5:71-5:77-5:80-5:81-5:91-6:119-6:137-7:179-8:43-8:45-9:25-9:34-9:82-10:92-11:91-14:36-17:70-20:33-20:34-22:18-22:40-23:19-23:21-25:14-25:38-25:49-26:227-27:15-30:8-33:21-33:35-33:41-36:62-38:24-38:51-41:22-42:30-42:34-43:73-48:19-48:20-49:7-49:12-56:32-57:16-57:26-57:27-62:10-71:24)",
      "d": "«کَثِیْر» means 'more'. It comes in both contexts of quantity and number. And it is used in both material and spiritual senses. Its usage is general. And its opposite is «قَلِیْل», meaning few and little.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ مَنۡ یُّؤۡتَ الۡحِکۡمَۃَ فَقَدۡ اُوۡتِیَ خَیۡرًا کَثِیۡرًا» (2/269)\nTranslation: And whoever is given wisdom has indeed been given much good.\nIn the mentioned verse, «کَثِیْر» is used in a spiritual sense for quantity, and in the following verse fragment, it is used in a tangible sense for number.\nFor example, the divine command is:\n«فَاٰتَیۡنَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا مِنۡہُمۡ اَجۡرَہُمۡ ۚ وَ کَثِیۡرٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ فٰسِقُوۡنَ» (57/27)\nTranslation: So We gave those who believed among them their reward, and many of them were defiantly disobedient.\nAnd «کَوْثَر» implies great abundance. And «تَکَاثُرَ الشَّیْء» means something becomes very abundant. And «رَجُلٌ کَاثِرٌ» means a wealthy man, and «کَوْثَر» means a generous man as well as 'much good'. Moreover, «کَوْثَر» is also the name of a river in Paradise (Muf.).\nFor example, the divine command is:\n«اِنَّاۤ اَعۡطَیۡنٰکَ الۡکَوۡثَرَ» (108/1)\nTranslation: Indeed, We have granted you, [O Muhammad], al-Kawthar."
    },
    {
      "id": 2908,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Abundant / More / Much",
      "hw": "زیادہ",
      "s": "«جَمّ» the gathering of something in large quantity at one place. (1 verse: 89:20)",
      "d": "«جَمّ» means the gathering of something in large quantity at one place (M. L.). «جَمَّ الْبِئْر» means the well has a lot of water. And «جَمَّ الْمِکْیَال» means the measure is filled to the brim (Sahib al-Munjid). Its usage is in both material and spiritual senses.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَّ تُحِبُّوۡنَ الۡمَالَ حُبًّا جَمًّا» (89/20)\nTranslation: And you love wealth with [great] love."
    },
    {
      "id": 2909,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Abundant / More / Much",
      "hw": "زیادہ",
      "s": "«مَرْکُوْم» to be piled up layer upon layer. (2 verses: 8:37-52:44)",
      "d": "«رَکَمَ» means to layer one thing over another. Then over that a third layer, and so on. And when something is gathered in a large quantity or piled up, it is «رُکَام» and «مَرْکُوْم». And «رَکَمَ السَّحَاب» means the clouds became dense (M. Q.). And «سَحَابٌ مَرْکُوم» means dense clouds.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ یَجۡعَلَ الۡخَبِیۡثَ بَعۡضَہٗ عَلَی بَعۡضٍ فَیَرۡکُمَہٗ جَمِیۡعًا» (8/37)\nTranslation: And He will place the wickedness of some upon others and make them into a heap."
    },
    {
      "id": 2910,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Abundant. More. Much.",
      "hw": "زیادہ",
      "s": "«لُبَد» refers to the gathering of scattered parts of something into a heap at one place. (2 verses: 72:19-90:6)",
      "d": "«لِبْد» and «لِبْدَةُ» mean felted hair or wool. A thick woolen cloth. And «مَالٌ لُبْدٌ» means abundant wealth. And «لَبَّدَ شَعْرُہٗ» means to mat someone's hair with gum etc., making it like felt. And «لُبَدَ الشَّیء» means something being like felt (manjadd), i.e., to gather and compress something scattered.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یَقُوۡلُ اَہۡلَکۡتُ مَالًا لُّبَدًا» (90/6)\nTranslation: Man says, \"I have destroyed a heap of wealth.\"\nAnd when attributed to people of intellect, it means crowding so much that there's no space to sit.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«وَّ اَنَّہٗ لَمَّا قَامَ عَبۡدُ اللّٰہِ یَدۡعُوۡہُ کَادُوۡا یَکُوۡنُوۡنَ عَلَیۡہِ لِبَدًا» (72/19)\nTranslation: And when the servant of Allah (Muhammad ﷺ) stood up in worship, the disbelievers crowded around him.\nNote: Namda is the name of that thick cloth made by compressing sheep's hair, wool, or felt with soap etc.; a thick woolen cloth and also a cap."
    },
    {
      "id": 2911,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Abundant. More. Much.",
      "hw": "زیادہ",
      "s": "«رَغَدَ» is used exclusively for the abundance of food and sustenance. (3 verses: 2:35-2:58-16:112)",
      "d": "«رَغَدَ» comes only for sustenance or food. To eat to one's fill or to be provided with abundant sustenance.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ کُلَا مِنۡہَا رَغَدًا حَیۡثُ شِئۡتُمَا» (2/35)\nTranslation: (O Adam and Hawwa) Eat from it (the fruits of Paradise) to your fill, wherever you wish."
    },
    {
      "id": 2912,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Abundant. More. Much.",
      "hw": "زیادہ",
      "s": "«غَدَقَ» is used for the abundance of water when it is also beneficial. (1 verse: 72:16)",
      "d": "«غَدَقَ» means to rain in large quantities and as a blessing.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّ اَنۡ لَّوِ اسۡتَقَامُوۡا عَلَی الطَّرِیۡقَۃِ لَاَسۡقَیۡنٰہُمۡ مَّآءً غَدَقًا» (72/16)\nTranslation: If they had remained steadfast on the path, We would have given them abundant water to drink."
    },
    {
      "id": 2913,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Abundant. More. Much.",
      "hw": "زیادہ",
      "s": "«ثَجَّاج» is used for the pouring and flowing of water in large quantities. (1 verse: 78:14)",
      "d": "«ثَجَّ» means to pour and flow water forcefully. And «ثَجَّاج» means a torrent of water.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّ اَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ الۡمُعۡصِرٰتِ مَآءً ثَجَّاجًا» (78/14)\nTranslation: And We sent down from the rain-bearing clouds water in torrents."
    },
    {
      "id": 2914,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Abundant. More. Much.",
      "hw": "زیادہ",
      "s": "«مَوْفُوْر» comes for the completeness and abundance of something. (1 verse: 17:63)",
      "d": "«وَفَر» comes for the completion (fullness) and abundance of something. And «وَفَّرَ» means to complete, to increase. And «وَفَرَ جَزَاءُہٗ» means he was given his full recompense and some extra.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ اذۡہَبۡ فَمَنۡ تَبِعَکَ مِنۡہُمۡ فَاِنَّ جَہَنَّمَ جَزَآؤُکُمۡ جَزَآءً مَّوۡفُوۡرًا» (17/63)\nTranslation: Allah said: \"Go! Whoever follows you among them, then Hell is your recompense, a recompense in full.\""
    }
  ],
  "637": [
    {
      "id": 2915,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Companions. Those with.",
      "hw": "والا",
      "s": "«اَصْحَاب» means those who have accompanied for a long time or those who give companionship. (70 verses: 2:39-2:81-2:82-2:119-2:217-2:257-2:275-3:116-4:47-5:10-5:29-5:86-6:71-7:36-7:42-7:44-7:46-7:47-7:48-7:50-9:70-9:113-10:26-10:27-11:23-13:5-15:78-15:80-18:9-20:135-22:44-22:51-25:24-25:38-26:61-26:176-29:15-35:6-36:13-36:55-38:13-39:8-40:6-40:43-46:14-46:16-50:12-50:14-51:59-56:8-56:9-56:27-56:38-56:41-56:90-56:91-57:19-58:17-59:20-60:13-64:10-67:10-67:11-68:17-74:31-74:39-85:4-90:18-90:19-105:1)",
      "d": "«اَصْحَاب» is the plural of «صَاحِب», meaning one who has accompanied for a long time or gives companionship. Whether this companionship is with a human, an animal, a place, or a time. Although this word can be used metaphorically in a spiritual sense, generally its use is related to physical companionship. Such as Ashab al-Kahf, Ashab al-Rass, Ashab al-Sabt, Ashab al-Fil, Ashab al-Qubur, Ashab al-Safinah, etc."
    },
    {
      "id": 2916,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Companions. Those with.",
      "hw": "والا",
      "s": "«اٰل» is attributed only to a renowned personality and nobles. Such as Aal Muhammad ﷺ, Aal Ibrahim, Aal Imran. (23 verses: 2:49-2:50-2:248-3:11-3:33-4:54-7:130-7:141-8:52-8:54-12:6-14:6-15:59-15:61-19:6-27:56-28:8-34:13-40:28-40:45-40:46-54:34-54:41)",
      "d": "The word «اٰل» is used only as an attribute for a renowned personality and nobles. Such as Aal Muhammad, Aal Ibrahim, Aal Imran. One can say Aal Fir'aun but cannot say Aal al-Khayyat. And in Aal, all those people are included who consider that noble person as honorable and have mental agreement and unity with him. Thus, Aal Muhammad does not only mean the family of the Prophet ﷺ, but also includes those who have a special connection with him in terms of knowledge and insight. Similarly, Aal Fir'aun means all his officials and those who are mentally aligned with him."
    },
    {
      "id": 2917,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Companions. Those with.",
      "hw": "والا",
      "s": "«اَھْل» means family, household members. Its attribution can be to anything. (51 verses: 2:105-2:109-3:64-3:65-3:69-3:70-3:71-3:72-3:75-3:98-3:99-3:110-3:113-3:199-4:123-4:153-4:159-4:171-5:15-5:19-5:47-5:59-5:65-5:68-5:77-7:96-7:97-7:98-9:101-9:120-11:73-12:109-15:67-16:43-18:77-20:40-21:7-28:12-28:45-29:46-33:13-33:26-33:33-38:64-57:29-59:2-59:7-59:11-74:56-98:1-98:6)",
      "d": "«اَھْل» can also be attributed to non-rational entities, such as Ahl al-Balad (people of the city), Ahl al-Ard (people of the land), Ahl al-Qarya (people of the villages), Ahl al-Bayt, Ahl al-Kitab, Ahl al-Dhikr, and Ahl al-Nar, etc. And when it is attributed to rational beings, it means the people of the house, wife, children, clan, or family. For example, Ahl al-Khayyat means the people of the tailor's house, his family and clan members, which includes his wife as well. (For further distinction between «اَھْل» and «اٰل», see \"Offspring\")"
    }
  ],
  "638": [],
  "639": [
    {
      "id": 2921,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Time",
      "hw": "وقت",
      "s": "«وَقْت، مِیْقَات» means an appointed time or place. (4 verses: 4:103-7:187-15:38-38:81)",
      "d": "«وَقْت» is a well-known word (TIME). «اَلْوَقْت» means «زَمَانٌ مَّعْلُوْمٌ» (a known time). Its plural is «اَوْقَات». In Imam Raghib's words, it is the final limit of time appointed for a task.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قُلۡ اِنَّمَا عِلۡمُہَا عِنۡدَ رَبِّیۡ ۚ لَا یُجَلِّیۡہَا لِوَقۡتِہَاۤ اِلَّا ہُوَ» (7/187)\nTranslation: Say, \"Its knowledge is only with my Lord. He will manifest it at its appointed time; none but He can reveal it.\"\nAnd «مِیْقَات» is a noun of time from «وَقْت». It is used in both temporal and spatial senses. Its plural is «مواقیت». In the following verse, Miqat is used in the temporal sense.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«وَ وٰعَدۡنَا مُوۡسٰی ثَلٰثِیۡنَ لَیۡلَۃً وَّ اَتۡمَمۡنٰہَا بِعَشۡرٍ فَتَمَّ مِیۡقَاتُ رَبِّہٖۤ اَرۡبَعِیۡنَ لَیۡلَۃً» (7/142)\nTranslation: And We appointed for Moses thirty nights, and completed them with ten, so the appointed time of his Lord was fulfilled as forty nights.\nAnd in the following verse, the word Miqat is used in both temporal and spatial senses, meaning both an appointed time and place.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَمَّا جَآءَ مُوۡسٰی لِمِیۡقَاتِنَا وَ کَلَّمَہٗ رَبُّہٗ» (7/143)\nTranslation: And when Moses came at Our appointed time (on Mount Tur) and his Lord spoke to him."
    },
    {
      "id": 2922,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Time",
      "hw": "وقت",
      "s": "«حِیْن» means an unspecified time. (33 verses: 2:36-2:177-5:101-5:106-7:24-10:98-11:5-12:35-14:25-16:6-16:80-21:39-21:111-23:25-23:54-24:58-25:42-26:218-28:15-30:17-30:18-36:44-37:148-37:174-37:178-38:3-38:88-39:42-39:58-51:43-52:48-56:84-76:1)",
      "d": "«حِیْن» refers to the time when a news arrives or something is obtained. It is an indefinite noun. Its plural is «اَحْیَان» and «اَحْیَانًا», meaning sometimes, occasionally.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَکُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مُسۡتَقَرٌّ وَّ مَتَاعٌ اِلٰی حِیۡنٍ» (2/36)\nTranslation: And for you on the earth is a place of settlement and provision for a time.\nAnd after «حِیْن», adding «اِذْ» makes «حِیْنَئِدٍ», which points to a specific time, meaning \"at that time\".\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«وَ اَنۡتُمۡ حِیۡنَئِذٍ تَنۡظُرُوۡنَ» (56/84)\nTranslation: And you, at that time, are looking on."
    },
    {
      "id": 2923,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Time",
      "hw": "وقت",
      "s": "«آن» and «الآن» mean the present time (12 verses: 2:71, 2:187, 3:113, 4:18, 8:66, 10:51, 10:91, 12:51, 20:130, 39:9, 57:16, 72:9)",
      "d": "«انی» or «نی» means the time has arrived; something reaching its utmost limit and maturity.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«أَلَمْ يَأْنِ لِلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا أَنْ تَخْشَعَ قُلُوبُهُمْ لِذِكْرِ اللَّهِ» (57:16)\nTranslation: Has the time not yet come for the believers that their hearts should become humble at the remembrance of Allah?\nAnd «آن» in the plural is «آناء», meaning hours. The definite article «ال» is always prefixed to this word, i.e., «الآن» means the present time, now, at this time.\nFor example, the Divine declaration states:\n«الْآنَ خَفَّفَ اللَّهُ عَنْكُمْ وَ عَلِمَ أَنَّ فِيكُمْ ضَعْفًا»\nTranslation: Now Allah has lightened your burden and knows that there is weakness among you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2924,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Time",
      "hw": "وقت",
      "s": "«آنِفا» means just now, at the very beginning of something, a little while ago (1 verse: 47:16)",
      "d": "«أنف» means nose, and the highest part and origin of anything, i.e., the place of beginning. «أنف الجبل» means the peak of the mountain. «أنف اللحية» means the edge of the beard. «استأنف الشيء» means to take the beginning or start of something and to begin. «استأنف الأمر» means to start an affair anew. And «آنِفا» means just now, at the beginning of something, a little while ago.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالُوا لِلَّذِينَ أُوتُوا الْعِلْمَ مَاذَا قَالَ آنِفًا» (47:16)\nTranslation: They say to those who have been given knowledge, 'What did he say just now (at the start)?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2925,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Time",
      "hw": "وقت",
      "s": "«أجل» means an appointed time and the intervening period until the present time (45 verses: 2:231, 2:232, 2:234, 2:235, 2:282, 4:77, 6:2, 6:60, 6:128, 7:34, 7:135, 7:185, 10:11, 10:49, 11:3, 11:104, 13:2, 13:38, 14:10, 14:44, 15:5, 16:61, 17:99, 20:129, 22:5, 22:33, 23:43, 28:28, 28:29, 29:5, 29:53, 30:8, 31:29, 35:13, 35:45, 39:5, 39:42, 40:67, 42:14, 46:3, 63:10, 63:11, 65:2, 65:4, 71:4)",
      "d": "«أجَلَ» means to delay. «آجِل» and «آجِلَة» mean that which happens after a delay. The Hereafter. «آجِل» is the opposite of «عاجِل», meaning one who hastens, quick. Both words are common. They are generally used in the context of the payment of the dower (mahr) at the time of marriage. «عاجِل» means that which is paid immediately in cash, and «آجِل» means on credit. «أجل» means period, time, death. Thus, the word «أجل» comes to mean the time from the present until a promised or appointed period, and sometimes until death. Its usage is very extensive.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَجَعَلَ لَهُمْ أَجَلًا لَا رَيْبَ فِيهِ» (17:99)\nTranslation: And He has appointed for them a time about which there is no doubt.\nIn this verse, the translation of «أجل» can be as 'time', 'period', 'appointed term', or 'time of death' – all are appropriate here."
    }
  ],
  "640": [
    {
      "id": 2926,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "hand",
      "hw": "ہاتھ",
      "s": "«یَد» means hand, power, and grasp (72 verses: 2:79-2:95-2:195-2:237-2:249-3:26-3:73-3:182-4:43-4:62-4:77-4:91-5:6-5:11-5:28-5:33-5:38-5:64-5:94-6:7-6:93-7:108-7:124-7:149-7:195-8:51-8:70-9:14-9:29-9:52-9:67-11:70-12:31-12:50-14:9-17:29-18:57-20:22-20:71-22:10-23:88-24:24-24:40-25:27-26:33-26:49-27:12-28:32-28:47-30:36-30:41-36:35-36:65-36:71-36:83-38:44-38:45-38:75-42:30-42:48-48:10-48:20-48:24-51:47-57:29-59:2-60:2-62:7-67:1-78:40-80:15-111:1)",
      "d": "«یَد» means hand. This word is originally «یَدَی». Due to 'naqis-i-wawi' (a grammatical rule where the original 'waw' in a word is dropped), 'ی' is dropped. Its dual is «یَدَان» and «یَدَیْن», and the plural is «اَیْدِی». For example, the Quran states: «فَوَیۡلٌ لَّہُمۡ  مِّمَّا کَتَبَتۡ اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ وَ وَیۡلٌ لَّہُمۡ مِّمَّا یَکۡسِبُوۡنَ» (2/79). Translation: So woe to them for what their hands have written and woe to them for what they earn. And since the hand is the most noble and effective among all human organs in terms of power and work, therefore, the word «یَد» also comes in the meanings of power, grasp, and ownership. For example, the divine command states: «اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یَّعۡفُوۡنَ اَوۡ یَعۡفُوَا الَّذِیۡ بِیَدِہٖ عُقۡدَۃُ النِّکَاحِ» (2/237). Translation: Unless they remit it or the one in whose hand is the contract of marriage remits it. And «بَیْنَ یَدَی» and «بَیْنَ اَیْدِی» idiomatically means before, in front of, or present. For example, the divine command states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا نَاجَیۡتُمُ الرَّسُوۡلَ  فَقَدِّمُوۡا بَیۡنَ یَدَیۡ نَجۡوٰىکُمۡ صَدَقَۃً» (58/12). Translation: O you who have believed, when you confer privately with the Messenger, present before your private conversation some charity. At another place, the divine command states: «وَ جَعَلۡنَا مِنۡۢ بَیۡنِ اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ سَدًّا وَّ مِنۡ خَلۡفِہِمۡ سَدًّا» (36/9). Translation: And We placed between them a barrier and behind them a barrier. Moreover, at another place, the divine command states: «فَقُلۡنَا لَہُمۡ کُوۡنُوۡا قِرَدَۃً خٰسِئِیۡنَ . فَجَعَلۡنٰہَا نَکَالًا لِّمَا بَیۡنَ یَدَیۡہَا وَ مَا خَلۡفَہَا» (2/65-66). Translation: And We said to them, 'Be apes, despised.' And We made it a deterrent for those who were present and those who succeeded them. Note: (Naqis-i-Wawi: (a grammatical rule) an Arabic word whose original consonant in the root is 'waw' instead of 'lam' of the word)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2927,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Hand",
      "hw": "ہاتھ",
      "s": "«یمین» means the right hand; it is also used for complete grasp, authority, and oath (23 verses: 16:48, 17:71, 18:17, 18:18, 20:17, 20:69, 29:48, 33:50, 33:52, 34:15, 37:28, 37:93, 39:67, 50:17, 56:27, 56:38, 56:90, 56:91, 69:19, 69:45, 70:37, 74:39, 84:7)",
      "d": "The plural of «یمین» is «أَيْمَان». «یمین» is used in three meanings: (1) «یمین» means the right hand. (2) «یمین» means the right side; its opposite is left. (3) «یمین» means an oath.\nNow, let us see examples:\nFor the right hand, for example, the Quran states:\n«وَمَا تِلْكَ بِيَمِينِكَ يَا مُوسَى» (20:17)\nTranslation: And what is that in your right hand, O Moses?\nAnd for the right side, for example, the Quran states:\n«لَقَدْ كَانَ لِسَبَإٍ فِي مَسْكَنِهِمْ آيَةٌ جَنَّتَانِ عَنْ يَمِينٍ وَ شِمَالٍ» (34:15)\nTranslation: There was for Saba a sign in their dwelling place: two gardens on the right and left.\nThen, just as the word «ید» comes to mean power and grasp, «یمین» comes to mean in a wider sense because the right hand is superior and better than the left in terms of power and function. And 'milk yamin' refers to that over which one has complete grasp and authority. And idiomatically, this word is also used to mean a female slave or a male slave.\nFor example, the Divine declaration states:\n«وَالْمُحْصَنَاتُ مِنَ النِّسَاءِ إِلَّا مَا مَلَكَتْ أَيْمَانُكُمْ» (4:24)\nTranslation: And [also prohibited are] married women, except those whom your right hands possess (i.e., female slaves taken as captives).\nBesides this, it was the custom of the Arabs to strengthen their covenants and oaths by placing their right hand in the right hand of the person they were addressing or striking it. Hence, this word began to be used in the meaning of an oath. And «یمین» is the name of an oath that is taken to strengthen a covenant.\nFor example, the Divine declaration states:\n«أَلَا تُقَاتِلُونَ قَوْمًا نَكَثُوا أَيْمَانَهُمْ» (9:13)\nTranslation: Will you not fight a people who broke their oaths?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2929,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Hand",
      "hw": "ہاتھ",
      "s": "«ذراع» means the part from the elbow to the tip of the middle finger (2 verses: 18:51, 28:35)",
      "d": "«ذراع» means hand; the part from the elbow to the tip of the middle finger. «ذرع الثوب» means to measure the cloth with a «ذراع». «ذَرْعُهُ كَذَا» means its length or measurement is such and such. «ذراع» is a unit of measurement whose length is between 50 centimeters and 70 centimeters (approximately 20 inches to 28 inches). The reason for this difference is that in earlier times, people's heights were taller, which gradually decreased. Some translators also translate «ذراع» as 'cubit'.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ فِي سِلْسِلَةٍ ذَرْعُهَا سَبْعُونَ ذِرَاعًا فَاسْلُكُوهُ» (69:32)\nTranslation: Then in a chain whose length is seventy cubits, drag him."
    }
  ],
  "641": [
    {
      "id": 2930,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Yes",
      "hw": "ہاں",
      "s": "«نعم» means yes; an affirmative answer to a positive question (4 verses: 7:44, 7:114, 26:42, 37:18)",
      "d": "«نعم» means yes. It is a word of affirmation. The answer to a question when both the question and the answer are in a positive sense.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَجَاءَ السَّحَرَةُ فِرْعَوْنَ قَالُوا إِنَّ لَنَا لَأَجْرًا إِنْ كُنَّا نَحْنُ الْغَالِبِينَ . قَالَ نَعَمْ وَ إِنَّكُمْ لَمِنَ الْمُقَرَّبِينَ» (7:114)\nTranslation: The magicians came to Pharaoh and said, 'Indeed, for us is a reward if we are the victorious.' He said, 'Yes, and indeed, you will be of those near [to me].'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2931,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Yes",
      "hw": "ہاں",
      "s": "«اِیْ» is used when giving a positive and emphatic response to a positive question. For example: Yes, indeed, certainly (1 verse: 10:53)",
      "d": "«اِیْ» meaning yes, indeed. Certainly. It is an affirmative word. Used when answering a question positively and emphatically, leaving no room for doubt. And an oath is necessary after it (مف).\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«یَسۡتَنۡۢبِئُوۡنَکَ اَحَقٌّ ہُوَ  ؕ ؔ قُلۡ اِیۡ  وَ رَبِّیۡۤ  اِنَّہٗ  لَحَقٌّ» ( 10/53 )\nTranslation: They ask you whether it (the Hereafter) is true. Say: Yes, indeed! By my Lord, it is certainly true.\nNote: (An affirmative word is one used to affirm something or to respond to a call or question.)"
    }
  ],
  "642": [
    {
      "id": 2933,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To pant",
      "hw": "ہانپنا",
      "s": "«ضبح» means to pant due to running fast (1 verse: 100:1)",
      "d": "«ضبح الفرس» means for a horse, while running at full speed, to make a sound from its lungs (chest cavity).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالْعَادِيَاتِ ضَبْحًا» (100:1)\nTranslation: By the chargers at dawn, panting (as they run)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2934,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to pant",
      "hw": "ہانپنا",
      "s": "«لَھَثَ» refers to panting due to thirst or fatigue (1 verse: 7:176)",
      "d": "«لَھَثَ» means to protrude the tongue out of the mouth and emit a sound from the chest due to severe thirst (مف). To pant and let the tongue hang out due to thirst or fatigue (منجد).\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«فَمَثَلُہٗ  کَمَثَلِ الۡکَلۡبِ ۚ اِنۡ  تَحۡمِلۡ عَلَیۡہِ یَلۡہَثۡ اَوۡ تَتۡرُکۡہُ یَلۡہَثۡ» ( 7/176 )\nTranslation: Its example is like that of a dog: if you chase it away, it pants, or if you leave it, it pants.\nNote: (جَوف means: internal cavity, the space inside something, the inner part of anything that is hollow, a hole.)"
    }
  ],
  "643": [
    {
      "id": 2935,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to remove",
      "hw": "ہٹانا",
      "s": "«دَفَعَ» means to ward off external dangers or attacks in the protection and support of something, and to push away. (4 verses: 2:251-22:40-23:96-41:34)",
      "d": "«دَفَعَ» means to ward off external dangers or attacks in the protection and support of something, and to push away. (Muf, Manjad) «دِفَاع» means protection and support. And «مُدافعَت» means to retaliate.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَا دَفۡعُ اللّٰہِ النَّاسَ بَعۡضَہُمۡ بِبَعۡضٍ» (22/40)\nTranslation: And were it not that Allah repels people, some by means of others...\nAnd when this word is followed by «اِلٰی», it means to hand over something to someone, to entrust, or to give.\nFor example: The command of Allah is:\n«فَادۡفَعُوۡۤا اِلَیۡہِمۡ اَمۡوَالَہُمۡ» (4/6)\nTranslation: Then hand over to them their wealth."
    },
    {
      "id": 2936,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to remove",
      "hw": "ہٹانا",
      "s": "«جَنَّبَ» means to turn someone aside, to remove. It is a general term. (2 verses: 87:11-92:17)",
      "d": "«جَانِب» means side or direction. And «جَنَبَ» and «جَنَّبَ» mean to repel, to remove, to turn aside and save, or to strike on the side. (Manjad)\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ سَیُجَنَّبُہَا  الۡاَتۡقَی الَّذِیۡ یُؤۡتِیۡ مَالَہٗ یَتَزَکّٰی» (92/17)\nTranslation: And the most righteous will be kept away from it (Hell), he who gives his wealth to purify himself."
    },
    {
      "id": 2937,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to remove",
      "hw": "ہٹانا",
      "s": "«زَحْزَحَ» means to save someone from harm by removing them from a place. (2 verses: 2:96-3:185)",
      "d": "«اَلْزَحْزَح» means distant or far. And «زَحْزَحَ» means to remove someone from a place, to push away, to expel. (Muf) And «زَحْزَحَ عَنْ» means to distance from harm.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«فَمَنۡ زُحۡزِحَ عَنِ النَّارِ وَ اُدۡخِلَ الۡجَنَّۃَ فَقَدۡ فَازَ» (3/185)\nTranslation: And whoever is removed from the Fire and admitted to Paradise has indeed succeeded."
    },
    {
      "id": 2938,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to remove",
      "hw": "ہٹانا",
      "s": "«دَرَءَ» means to keep harm away with full force and effort. (4 verses: 3:168-13:22-24:8-28:54)",
      "d": "«دَرَءَ» means to save someone from harm by pushing them away with full force. (Muf) And it means to push forcefully, to remove. (Manjad)\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ یَدۡرَؤُا  عَنۡہَا الۡعَذَابَ اَنۡ تَشۡہَدَ اَرۡبَعَ شَہٰدٰتٍۭ بِاللّٰہِ» (24/8)\nTranslation: And if the woman testifies four times by Allah that he (the accuser) is lying, this will ward off the punishment from her.\nAnd «اِدَّرَءَ» means to shift the blame onto another so that one may be saved from punishment.\nFor example: The command of Allah is:\n«وَ اِذۡ قَتَلۡتُمۡ نَفۡسًا فَادّٰارَءۡتُمۡ فِیۡہَا» (2/72)\nTranslation: And when you killed a soul, then you disputed concerning it..."
    },
    {
      "id": 2939,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to remove",
      "hw": "ہٹانا",
      "s": "«دَعَّ» means to push out with shoves, to remove. (2 verses: 52:13-107:2)",
      "d": "«دَعَّ» means to push out with shoves, to repel harshly. (F L 188)\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«فَذٰلِکَ الَّذِیۡ یَدُعُّ  الۡیَتِیۡمَ» (107/2)\nTranslation: That is the one who repels the orphan."
    },
    {
      "id": 2940,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to remove",
      "hw": "ہٹانا",
      "s": "«دَحَرَ» means to drive out with a push, to expel, regardless of reason. (4 verses: 7:18-17:18-17:39-37:9)",
      "d": "In «دَحَرَ», two basic meanings are found: (1) to drive away, (2) to remove. (M, L) Meaning to drive someone out with a push.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«قَالَ اخۡرُجۡ مِنۡہَا مَذۡءُوۡمًا مَّدۡحُوۡرًا» (7/18)\nTranslation: Allah said: 'Get out of it (Paradise), accursed and expelled!'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2941,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to remove",
      "hw": "ہٹانا",
      "s": "«خَسَأَ» means to drive away with disdain and humiliation. (4 verses: 2:65-7:166-23:108-67:4)",
      "d": "«خَسَّاَ النَّظَر» means the gaze becomes weary and weak. And «خسَأَ الْکَلْب» means to drive away a dog. And «خَاسِیءُ مِنَ الْکِلاَبِ وَ الْخَنَازِیْر» means dogs and pigs that are driven away and kept from approaching people. (Manjad)\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«فَقُلۡنَا لَہُمۡ کُوۡنُوۡا قِرَدَۃً خٰسِئِیۡنَ» (2/65)\nTranslation: So we said to them: 'Be apes, despised and humiliated.'"
    }
  ],
  "644": [
    {
      "id": 2942,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to guide; to find",
      "hw": "ہدایت",
      "s": "«اِھْتَدَی» means to walk on the straight path. (56 verses: 2:16-2:53-2:70-2:135-2:137-2:150-2:157-2:170-3:20-3:103-4:98-5:104-5:105-6:56-6:82-6:97-6:117-6:140-7:30-7:43-7:158-7:178-9:18-10:45-10:108-16:15-16:16-16:125-17:15-17:97-18:17-18:57-19:76-20:82-20:135-21:31-23:49-24:54-27:24-27:41-27:92-28:56-28:64-32:3-34:50-36:21-39:41-43:10-43:22-43:37-43:49-46:11-47:17-53:30-57:26-68:7)",
      "d": "«هُدَى» means to guide someone with grace and favor, to show the path of goodness. (Muf) Its opposite is «ضَلَّ» and «اَضَلَّ», meaning to misguide, to lead astray, to make one lose the good path or obscure it. «ھِدَایَت» has three meanings:\n(1) Innate guidance that Allah has placed in every thing by creation, like a newborn baby's instinct to seek its mother's breast.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«رَبُّنَا الَّذِیۡۤ اَعۡطٰی کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ خَلۡقَہٗ  ثُمَّ  ہَدٰی» (20/50)\nTranslation: Our Lord is He who gave everything its creation and then guided it.\n(2) Turning a person's mind from error to guidance, from disbelief to Islam, from disobedience to obedience to Allah. This occurs through prophets and messengers, but the turning is solely by Allah's will.\nFor example: The command of Allah is:\n«اِنَّکَ لَا تَہۡدِیۡ مَنۡ  اَحۡبَبۡتَ وَ لٰکِنَّ اللّٰہَ یَہۡدِیۡ مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ» (28/56)\nTranslation: (O Muhammad) you cannot guide whom you love, but Allah guides whom He wills.\n(3) Showing the straight path to those who come to Allah's obedience or Islam, and continuing to guide them. This is the primary responsibility of prophets and messengers, and other Muslims participate in it (though it occurs by Allah's decree).\nFor example: The command of Allah is:\n«اَفَاَنۡتَ تَہۡدِی الۡعُمۡیَ وَ لَوۡ کَانُوۡا لَا یُبۡصِرُوۡنَ» (10/43)\nTranslation: Can you guide the blind even though they will not see?\nAnother verse says:\n«وَ اِنَّکَ لَتَہۡدِیۡۤ  اِلٰی صِرَاطٍ مُّسۡتَقِیۡمٍ» (42/52)\nTranslation: And indeed, you (Muhammad) guide to a straight path.\nAnd «اِھْتَدَی» means to find guidance, to walk on the straight path.\nFor example: The command of Allah is:\n«فَمَنِ اہۡتَدٰی فَاِنَّمَا یَہۡتَدِیۡ لِنَفۡسِہٖ» (10/108)\nTranslation: So whoever is guided is only guided for himself."
    },
    {
      "id": 2943,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to guide; to find",
      "hw": "ہدایت",
      "s": "«رَشَدَ» means to adopt good habits and persist on them after choosing the straight path. (13 verses: 2:186-2:256-4:6-7:146-18:10-18:17-18:24-18:66-21:51-72:2-72:10-72:14-72:21)",
      "d": "«رَشَدَ» means a person who comes to the right path and also adopts good conduct. Its opposite is «غوٰی» meaning misguided, one who follows the wrong path. (Q, M) And «رُشْد» means steadfastness on the path of truth, adherence. Its opposite is «غَیّ». (Manjad)\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«اَلَـیۡسَ مِنۡکُمۡ  رَجُلٌ  رَّشِیۡدٌ» (11/78)\nTranslation: Is there not among you a man of good conduct? (Imam translation)"
    }
  ],
  "645": [
    {
      "id": 2944,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "destruction",
      "hw": "ہلاکت",
      "s": "«تَبّ» means to perish. (8 verses: 7:139-11:101-17:7-18:35-25:39-35:29-40:37-111:1)",
      "d": "«تَبّ» means to perish, to break, to cut, to sever; all these meanings are applicable. (Manjad)\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«تَبَّتۡ یَدَاۤ  اَبِیۡ  لَہَبٍ وَّ  تَبَّ» (111/1)\nTranslation: May the hands of Abu Lahab be ruined, and ruined is he."
    },
    {
      "id": 2945,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Destruction",
      "hw": "ہلاکت",
      "s": "«تَعْسَ» means to fall into a pit and perish (1 verse: 47/8)",
      "d": "«تَعْسَ» means to stumble and fall, then be unable to get up; to fall into a pit and perish (singular). For example, in the Quran: «وَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا  فَتَعۡسًا لَّہُمۡ» (47/8). Translation: Perdition be upon those who disbelieve."
    },
    {
      "id": 2946,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Destruction",
      "hw": "ہلاکت",
      "s": "«قُتِلَ» means to kill someone, to cause destruction (18 verses: 3:144-3:154-3:156-3:157-3:158-3:168-3:169-3:195-17:33-22:58-33:61-47:4-51:10-74:19-74:20-80:17-81:9-85:4)",
      "d": "«قَتَلَ» means to kill someone; to separate the soul from the body. And «قُتِل» means to be killed, to perish. For example, in the Quran: «فَقُتِلَ  کَیۡفَ قَدَّرَ ثُمَّ  قُتِلَ  کَیۡفَ قَدَّرَ» (20/74). Translation: Woe to him who made such an (evil) estimate; then woe to him who made such an (evil) estimate."
    },
    {
      "id": 2947,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Destruction",
      "hw": "ہلاکت",
      "s": "«ثَبَرَ» means destruction (4 verses: 17:102-25:13-25:14-84:11)",
      "d": "«ثَبَرَ» means to perish or (for a wound) to become corrupt (singular). And «ثُبُوْر» means destruction. For example, in the Quran: «لَا تَدۡعُوا الۡیَوۡمَ ثُبُوۡرًا وَّاحِدًا وَّ ادۡعُوۡا ثُبُوۡرًا کَثِیۡرًا» (25/14). Translation: Do not call today for one destruction, but call for many destructions."
    },
    {
      "id": 2948,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Destruction",
      "hw": "ہلاکت",
      "s": "«اَوْلٰی» means more worthy, more appropriate, more deserving (3 verses: 47:20-75:34-75:35)",
      "d": "If «اَوْلٰی» comes with «ب», it means more worthy, more appropriate, more deserving. If it comes with «ل», it means destruction, ruin, and perdition. This word is used for warning and intimidation (i.e., to frighten and threaten) and is used for someone who is near destruction so that they may take heed. Moreover, this word generally comes with repetition so that the addressee may reflect on the consequence and try to avoid it (mufrad). For example, in the Quran: «فَلَا  صَدَّقَ  وَ لَا صَلّٰی وَ  لٰکِنۡ  کَذَّبَ وَ تَوَلّٰی ثُمَّ  ذَہَبَ  اِلٰۤی  اَہۡلِہٖ یَتَمَطّٰی اَوۡلٰی لَکَ فَاَوۡلٰی» (75/31-34). Translation: So he neither believed nor prayed; but he denied and turned away. Then he went to his people, swaggering. Woe to you, and woe to you again."
    },
    {
      "id": 2949,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Destruction",
      "hw": "ہلاکت",
      "s": "«وَیْلٌ» This phrase is generally uttered on occasions of regret (38 verses: 2:79-5:31-11:72-14:2-18:49-19:37-20:61-21:14-21:18-21:46-21:97-25:28-28:80-36:52-37:20-38:27-39:22-41:6-43:65-45:7-46:17-51:60-52:11-68:31-77:15-77:19-77:24-77:28-77:34-77:37-77:40-77:45-77:47-77:49-83:1-83:10-104:1-107:4)",
      "d": "«وَیْلٌ» means ruin, destruction, regret, perdition. This word is generally uttered on occasions of regret (mufrad). For example, in the Quran: «وَیۡلٌ   لِّکُلِّ   اَفَّاکٍ  اَثِیۡمٍ» (45/7). Translation: Ruin for every lying sinner."
    }
  ],
  "646": [
    {
      "id": 2950,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To Perish / To Cause to Perish",
      "hw": "ہلاک",
      "s": "«ھَلَکَ» means to perish, to be destroyed; it is general for both living and non-living things (63 verses: 2:195-2:205-3:117-4:176-5:17-6:6-6:26-6:47-6:131-7:4-7:129-7:155-7:164-7:173-8:42-8:54-9:42-10:13-11:117-12:85-14:13-15:4-17:16-17:17-17:58-18:59-19:74-19:98-20:128-20:134-21:6-21:9-21:95-22:45-23:48-26:139-26:208-27:49-28:43-28:58-28:59-28:78-28:88-29:31-32:26-36:31-38:3-40:34-43:8-44:37-45:24-46:27-46:35-47:13-50:36-53:50-54:51-67:28-69:5-69:6-69:29-77:16-90:6)",
      "d": "«ھَلَکَ» means to become non-existent. It is used for both living and non-living things. When used for living beings, it means to die a helpless death, to die an evil death. For example, in the Quran: «کُلُّ  شَیۡءٍ ہَالِکٌ  اِلَّا وَجۡہَہٗ» (28/88). Translation: Everything is perishable except His Face. At another place, the Divine decree states: «اِنِ امۡرُؤٌا ہَلَکَ لَیۡسَ لَہٗ  وَلَدٌ» (4/176). Translation: If a person dies without having any children. And «اَھْلَکَ» means to destroy or annihilate something else. For example, the Divine decree states: «اَلَمۡ یَرَوۡا کَمۡ اَہۡلَکۡنَا مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ مِّنۡ قَرۡنٍ» (6/6). Translation: Do they not see how many generations We destroyed before them?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2951,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to be destroyed / to destroy",
      "hw": "ہلاک",
      "s": "«بَادَ» means a garden becoming completely desolate, utterly destroyed and ruined (1 verse: 18:35)",
      "d": "«اَلْبَیْدَاء» means desert, and its plural is «بِیْد». And «بَادَ» means a garden becoming completely desolate, utterly destroyed and ruined (مف).\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«قَالَ مَاۤ اَظُنُّ اَنۡ تَبِیۡدَ ہٰذِہٖۤ  اَبَدًا» ( 18/35 )\nTranslation: He said: I do not think that this garden will ever be utterly destroyed.\nNote: (لق و وق صحرا : hard and flat land with no trees, grass, or inhabitants; barren, waste.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2952,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To Perish / To Cause to Perish",
      "hw": "ہلاک",
      "s": "«تَرَدّٰی» means to fall into a well or pit and perish (3 verses: 20:16-37:56-92:11-)",
      "d": "«رَدٰی» means to throw something from a height to the ground or to push someone into a pit from the ground so that they reach destruction. For example, in the Quran: «وَ اتَّبَعَ  ہَوٰىہُ  فَتَرۡدٰی» (20/16). Translation: And he followed his desire, so you will perish. And «اَرْدٰی» is transitive, meaning to cause someone else to perish in the same way. For example, the Divine decree states: «قَالَ تَاللّٰہِ  اِنۡ کِدۡتَّ  لَتُرۡدِیۡنِ» (37/56). Translation: He will say: By Allah, you nearly destroyed me. And «تَرَدّٰی» means to fall into a well or pit oneself and reach destruction. For example, in the Quran: «وَ مَا یُغۡنِیۡ عَنۡہُ  مَا لُہٗۤ  اِذَا تَرَدّٰی» (92/11). Translation: And when he falls into the pit (of Hell), his wealth will not avail him at all."
    },
    {
      "id": 2953,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To Perish / To Cause to Perish",
      "hw": "ہلاک",
      "s": "«بَخَعَ» means to perish while consumed by grief (2 verses: 18:6-26:3)",
      "d": "«بَخَعَ» means to destroy oneself due to grief or anger (mufrad, m l); to perish while being consumed. For example, in the Quran: «فَلَعَلَّکَ بَاخِعٌ نَّفۡسَکَ عَلٰۤی اٰثَارِہِمۡ  اِنۡ لَّمۡ  یُؤۡمِنُوۡا بِہٰذَا  الۡحَدِیۡثِ  اَسَفًا» (18/6). Translation: So perhaps you would destroy yourself due to grief over their footsteps if they do not believe in this discourse, out of anguish."
    },
    {
      "id": 2954,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To Perish / To Cause to Perish",
      "hw": "ہلاک",
      "s": "«دَمَّرَ» means to demolish brick by brick; to raze to the ground (8 verses: 7:137-17:16-25:36-26:172-27:51-37:136-46:25-47:10)",
      "d": "«دَمَرَ» means to enter someone's house with evil intent without permission (manjad). And «دَمَّرَ» means to inflict destruction suddenly upon something (mufrad). For example, in the Quran: «فَفَسَقُوۡا فِیۡہَا فَحَقَّ عَلَیۡہَا الۡقَوۡلُ  فَدَمَّرۡنٰہَا  تَدۡمِیۡرًا» (17/16). Translation: They committed corruption in it, so the word (of punishment) was fulfilled against them. So We utterly destroyed them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2955,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To perish / To destroy",
      "hw": "ہلاک",
      "s": "«دَمْدَمَ» means to crush completely, to trample into the ground (1 verse: 91:14)",
      "d": "«دَمْدَمَ الشَیْء» means to make something stick to the ground. And «دَمْدَمَ اللہُ عَلَیْھِم» means Allah destroyed them. Crushed completely (source: Manjad). For example, in the Quran: «فَدَمۡدَمَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  رَبُّہُمۡ بِذَنۡۢبِہِمۡ  فَسَوّٰىہَا» (91/14). Translation: So Allah sent down punishment upon them because of their sins and made them all equal (by destroying them)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2956,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To perish / To destroy",
      "hw": "ہلاک",
      "s": "«تَبَّبَ» means to gradually proceed towards destruction (1 verse: 11:101)",
      "d": "«تَبَّ» is a cursing word. «تَبًّا لَکَ» means 'may destruction be upon you'. Lexically, it means to break, to cut, or to perish. In «تَبَّبَ», the repetition implies repeated meaning, i.e., to continuously step towards destruction (source: Mufradat). For example, in the Quran: «وَ مَا زَادُوۡہُمۡ غَیۡرَ تَتۡبِیۡبٍ» (11/101). Translation: And their (false gods) did not add anything to them except continuous destruction."
    },
    {
      "id": 2957,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To perish / To destroy",
      "hw": "ہلاک",
      "s": "«تَبَّرَّ» means to utterly destroy, to erase completely (3 verses: 7:139, 17:7, 25:39)",
      "d": "«تَبَّرَّ» means to plunder, to utterly destroy, to annihilate (source: Mufradat; Manjad). And «تَبَار» means destruction, ruin. For example, in the Quran: «وَ کُلًّا ضَرَبۡنَا لَہُ  الۡاَمۡثَالَ ۫ وَ کُلًّا  تَبَّرۡنَا تَتۡبِیۡرًا» (25/39). Translation: And We have given him (the disbeliever) all kinds of examples, and We have utterly destroyed them all."
    },
    {
      "id": 2958,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To perish / To destroy",
      "hw": "ہلاک",
      "s": "«بَارَ» means to perish due to decrease in commercial goods (5 verses: 25:18, 35:10, 35:29, 48:12, 71:28)",
      "d": "«بَارَ» its root is «بُوْر» and «بُوَار». It means for commercial goods to become very scarce and near destruction, i.e., «کَسَدَ حَتّٰی فَسَدَ». Gradually proceeding towards destruction (source: Mufradat). Gradually, the original capital diminishes until it perishes. For example, in the Quran: «وَ اَنۡفَقُوۡا مِمَّا رَزَقۡنٰہُمۡ سِرًّا وَّ عَلَانِیَۃً  یَّرۡجُوۡنَ  تِجَارَۃً  لَّنۡ تَبُوۡرَ» (35/29). Translation: And they spend from what We have provided them, secretly and openly, hoping for a trade that will never perish."
    },
    {
      "id": 2959,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To perish / To destroy",
      "hw": "ہلاک",
      "s": "«اَسْحَتَ» means to perish due to wretchedness, poverty, and destitution (1 verse: 20:61)",
      "d": "«سُحْت» means illicit earnings and bribery (source: Mufradat). «سَحَتَ» means to earn illicitly. And «اَسْحَتَتِ التِّجَارَۃ» means for trade goods to have impurity and illicit things mixed in, and «اُسْحِتَ» means to be in need of wealth, to perish (source: Manjad). And «اَسْحَتَ» means to uproot from the foundation (source: Mufradat). So «اَسْحَتَ» will come for destruction due to wretchedness (i.e., due to miserable condition and poverty). For example, in the Quran: «لَا تَفۡتَرُوۡا عَلَی اللّٰہِ  کَذِبًا فَیُسۡحِتَکُمۡ  بِعَذَابٍ» (20/61). Translation: Do not fabricate lies against Allah, lest He destroy you with punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 2961,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To perish / To destroy",
      "hw": "ہلاک",
      "s": "«قَصَمَ» means to break and twist, leaving it broken (1 verse: 21:11)",
      "d": "«قَصَمَ» means to smash, to break and twist, and to destroy by breaking into pieces (source: Mufradat). For example, in the Quran: «وَ کَمۡ قَصَمۡنَا مِنۡ قَرۡیَۃٍ کَانَتۡ ظَالِمَۃً» (21/11). Translation: And how many a town We destroyed that was unjust."
    },
    {
      "id": 2962,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To perish / To destroy",
      "hw": "ہلاک",
      "s": "«فَنٰی» means to lose one's existence, this is more general than «ھَلَکَ» (1 verse: 55:26)",
      "d": "«فَنٰی» means to lose one's existence, to leave nothing remaining, to go into non-existence (source: Mufradat). This is more general than «ھَلَکَ». «ھَلَکَ» includes something becoming corrupt, slipping from hand, dying a bad death, etc., while «فَنٰی» means to completely terminate something's existence. And the opposite of «فَنٰی» is «بَقَا» meaning to remain. For example, in the Quran: «کُلُّ  مَنۡ  عَلَیۡہَا  فَانٍ» (55/26). Translation: Everything on it (the earth) will perish."
    }
  ],
  "647": [
    {
      "id": 2965,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To be light / To make light",
      "hw": "ہلکا",
      "s": "«قَصَدَ» means moderate, balanced, easy compared to difficult (3 verses: 9:42, 16:9, 31:19)",
      "d": "«قَصَدَ» also means to choose the middle path, avoiding excess and deficiency. And «اِقْتِصَاد» means to use wealth or other things in a moderate way. For example, in the Quran: «وَ اقۡصِدۡ فِیۡ  مَشۡیِکَ» (31/19). Translation: And be moderate in your walk. At another place, Allah says: «لَوۡ کَانَ عَرَضًا قَرِیۡبًا وَّ سَفَرًا قَاصِدًا لَّاتَّبَعُوۡکَ» (9/42). Translation: If the goods were nearby and the journey short, they would have followed you. So here «قَاصِدًا» means moderate or the necessary distance. That is, neither too far nor too near, but to avoid comparison and excessive detail, its translation is rendered as 'light'."
    }
  ],
  "648": [
    {
      "id": 2966,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To shake / To shake something",
      "hw": "ہلانا",
      "s": "«حَرَّک» means to give motion, to shake, general usage (1 verse: 75:16)",
      "d": "«حَرَّک» means to give motion, to shake. Its usage is general, for any kind of motion. For example, in the Quran: «لَا تُحَرِّکۡ بِہٖ لِسَانَکَ لِتَعۡجَلَ بِہٖ» (75/16). Translation: (O Muhammad ﷺ!) Do not move your tongue with it (the revelation) to hasten it."
    },
    {
      "id": 2967,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To shake / To shake something",
      "hw": "ہلانا",
      "s": "«ھَزَّ» means to shake a large or heavy thing with a jerk (3 verses: 19:25, 27:10, 28:31)",
      "d": "«ھَزَّ» means to shake a tree so that its fruit falls off (source: Farahidi, p.173). In Punjabi, there is a specific word for it: jhonna or jhona marna. For example, in the Quran: «وَ ہُزِّیۡۤ  اِلَیۡکِ بِجِذۡعِ النَّخۡلَۃِ» (19/25). Translation: And shake the trunk of the palm tree towards you. And «اِھْتَزَّ» means for something to shake or move as if someone has given it a jerk or is jerking it. For example, Allah says: «فَلَمَّا رَاٰہَا تَہۡتَزُّ کَاَنَّہَا جَآنٌّ  وَّلّٰی مُدۡبِرًا» (28/31). Translation: When Moses saw it shaking as if it were a jinn, he turned back and fled."
    },
    {
      "id": 2968,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Shaking / Moving",
      "hw": "ہلانا",
      "s": "«ھَشَّ» means to shake something light or soft with a jerk. (1 verse: 20:18)",
      "d": "«ھَشَّ» and «ھَزَّ» are synonymous. The difference is that «ھَشَّ» is used only for shaking something light or soft. For example, «ھَشَّ الْوَرَق» means to shake leaves (figurative), and «ھَشِیْش» means any soft thing. A man of gentle nature. «ھَشَّ» also means to smile. And «ھَشَّاش» is a person whose face lights up and becomes happy at a minor thing (proverb). The phrase «ہشاش بشاش» is famous.\nFor example, in the Quran: «قَالَ ہِیَ عَصَایَ ۚ اَتَوَکَّؤُا عَلَیۡہَا وَ اَہُشُّ بِہَا عَلٰی غَنَمِیۡ» (18/20)\nTranslation: Moses (peace be upon him) said, 'This is my staff. I lean on it and I also shake leaves from trees for my sheep with it.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2969,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Shaking / Moving",
      "hw": "ہلانا",
      "s": "«لَوّٰی» means to twist or jerk something. (4 verses: 3:78-3:153-4:135-63:5)",
      "d": "«لَوَی الْحَبْل» means to twist a rope. And «لَوَیْتُ الْحَیَّۃُ» means a snake coiling (terminology). «لَوٰی لِسَانَہٗ» means to twist the tongue while speaking so that the meaning becomes distorted (figurative). And «لَوّٰی» means to twist or wring something. To bend. It is used in all these meanings. And «لَوّٰی رَأسَہٗ» means to move the head in a way as if rejecting the addressed person's words. To shake the head.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ اِذَا قِیۡلَ لَہُمۡ تَعَالَوۡا یَسۡتَغۡفِرۡ لَکُمۡ رَسُوۡلُ اللّٰہِ لَوَّوۡا رُءُوۡسَہُمۡ» (63/5)\nTranslation: And when it is said to them, 'Come, the Messenger of Allah will seek forgiveness for you,' they shake their heads."
    },
    {
      "id": 2970,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Shaking / Moving",
      "hw": "ہلانا",
      "s": "«نَغَضَ» means to shake the head due to surprise, mockery, or trembling. This word is specific for shaking the head. (1 verse: 17:51)",
      "d": "«نَغَضَ» means to tremble. To shake. To be restless. And «نَغَضَ رَأسَہٗ» means to shake the head due to surprise, mockery, or trembling. To jerk. (figurative, terminology). And «نَغْض» means one who trembles while walking. One who shakes the head (terminology). And it means to shake the head (F. L. 173). And «اَلْاَنْغَاض» means to move the head (terminology).\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَسَیُنۡغِضُوۡنَ اِلَیۡکَ رُءُوۡسَہُمۡ وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ مَتٰی ہُوَ ؕ قُلۡ عَسٰۤی اَنۡ یَّکُوۡنَ قَرِیۡبًا» (17/51)\nTranslation: So they will shake their heads at you and say, 'When will it be?' Say, 'Perhaps it will be soon.'"
    }
  ],
  "649": [
    {
      "id": 2971,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "harmony / to be in harmony",
      "hw": "ہم آہنگی",
      "s": "«قَرِیْن» means a companion of the same age or close associate (6 verses: 4:38-37:51-43:36-43:38-50:23-50:27)",
      "d": "«قُرُوْن» is the plural of «قَرَن». And «قُرُوْن» means era, period (see details under 'زمانہ'). Hence, «قَرِیْن» is understood as 'of the same age'. And «قَرَن» means a rope with which two camels are tied. «قَرَنَ الثَّوْرَیْن» means to yoke two oxen in Punjabi. Hence, «قَرِیْن» is understood as a close associate, a companion who shares food and drink. Its plural is «قُرَنَاء». And it is often used in a negative sense.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«وَ مَنۡ  یَّکُنِ  الشَّیۡطٰنُ  لَہٗ  قَرِیۡنًا فَسَآءَ  قَرِیۡنًا» ( 4/38 )\nTranslation: And whoever has Satan as a companion—what an evil companion he is!"
    },
    {
      "id": 2972,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Harmony / Being together",
      "hw": "ہم آہنگی",
      "s": "«اَتْرَاب» means friends or companions of the same age and temperament. (3 verses: 38:52-56:37-78:33)",
      "d": "«تُرَاب» means dust, soil. And «تَرِبَ» means to become dusty, also to be poor and needy. And «اَتْرَبَ» means to be wealthy, also to be healthy, and this is from the antonyms (terminology). And «تَارَبَ» means to play together in the dust, to be of the same age, to be friends. And the feminine of «تَرِب» is «تَرِبَۃ». Its plural is «اَتْرَاب». And it means a female friend, of the same age, of the same lineage, of the same group (terminology). «اَتْرَاب» is often used for women (terminology). So atrab refers to such friends and women of the same age among whom there is complete harmony in temperament.\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَجَعَلۡنٰہُنَّ اَبۡکَارًا عُرُبًا اَتۡرَابًا» (37/56)\nTranslation: We have made them virgins, loving and of the same age."
    },
    {
      "id": 2973,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Harmony / Being together",
      "hw": "ہم آہنگی",
      "s": "«سَمِیٌّ» means having the same name. (2 verses: 19:7-19:65)",
      "d": "«اِسْمٌ» means name, and «سَمِیٌّ» means having the same name. Such two or more people who have the same name.\nFor example, in the Quran: «اسۡمُہٗ یَحۡیٰی ۙ لَمۡ نَجۡعَلۡ لَّہٗ مِنۡ قَبۡلُ سَمِیًّا» (19/7)\nTranslation: His name is Yahya. We have not given this name to anyone before him."
    },
    {
      "id": 2974,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Harmony / Being together",
      "hw": "ہم آہنگی",
      "s": "«کُفْو» means equal in rank and status, peer. (1 verse: 112:4)",
      "d": "«کَفَأ، کُفْو» and «کُفٰی» mean equal in rank and status. Peer (terminology). And it means similar, counterpart, pair (terminology). And it means to be of the same rank and status as another. And «کِفَاءٌ» is the piece of cloth that is sewn with another similar piece to form the back of a tent. The word «کُفْو» is generally used during marriage or alliances or in battle. «فُلَانٌ کُفْوٌ لِفَلَانٍ» meaning so-and-so is the pair or peer of so-and-so (figurative).\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ لَمۡ یَکُنۡ لَّہٗ کُفُوًا اَحَدٌ» (112/4)\nTranslation: And there is none equal to Him."
    },
    {
      "id": 2976,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Harmony / Being together",
      "hw": "ہم آہنگی",
      "s": "«ضَاھٰی» means similarity in shape, appearance, or habits. (1 verse: 9:30)",
      "d": "«ضَاھَی الرَّجُل» means a person resembles another in shape or habits. And «ضَھِیٌّ» means a similar person (terminology).\nFor example, in the Quran: «یُضَاہِئُوۡنَ قَوۡلَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا» (9/30)\nTranslation: They imitate the sayings of those who disbelieved."
    }
  ],
  "650": [
    {
      "id": 2977,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Losing Courage",
      "hw": "ہمت",
      "s": "«فَشِلَ» is used for losing heart and courage right from the beginning. (4 verses: 3:122-3:152-8:43-8:46)",
      "d": "«فَشِلَ» means to show cowardice during battle or hardship (terminology). To lose courage. To despair. To show weakness and cowardice.\nFor example, in the Quran: «حَتّٰۤی اِذَا فَشِلۡتُمۡ وَ تَنَازَعۡتُمۡ فِی الۡاَمۡرِ» (3/152)\nTranslation: Until when you became weak and disputed about the matter."
    },
    {
      "id": 2978,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Losing Courage",
      "hw": "ہمت",
      "s": "«اِسْتَکَانَ» is used after expending all effort and then losing courage. (2 verses: 3:146-23:76)",
      "d": "«اِسْتَکَانَ» means to become tired and weak after all effort, finally losing courage. To become helpless. To surrender. To be subdued.\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَمَا وَہَنُوۡا لِمَاۤ اَصَابَہُمۡ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ وَ مَا ضَعُفُوۡا وَ مَا اسۡتَکَانُوۡا» (3/146)\nTranslation: So they did not weaken because of what afflicted them in the cause of Allah, nor did they become weak, nor did they surrender."
    }
  ],
  "651": [
    {
      "id": 2979,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To Level",
      "hw": "ہموار",
      "s": "«سَطَحَ» to spread and to level (1 verse: 88:20)",
      "d": "In the basic meanings of «سَطَحَ», two things are found: (1) to spread or lay out, (2) then to level it. And «سَطَحَ الْبَیْت» means to level the roof of the house. And «مِسْطَحْ» means a tool or instrument for leveling, and «سَطَح» means the upper part of a roof (the flat top) (Manjad). According to Imam Raghib (lex.), «اَعْلَی الْبَیْتِ جُعِلَ سَوِیًّا» (meaning: the highest part of the house was made level). For example, in the Quran: «وَ اِلَی الۡاَرۡضِ کَیۡفَ سُطِحَتۡ» (88/20). Translation: And (do they not look) at the earth, how it is spread out."
    },
    {
      "id": 2980,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To Level",
      "hw": "ہموار",
      "s": "«دَکَّ» to crush into pieces and make level with the ground (3 verses: 7:143, 18:98, 89:21)",
      "d": "The two basic meanings of «دَکَّ» are (1) to crush, (2) then to make it level (lex.) i.e., to make something level with the ground by crushing it. For example, in the Quran: «قَالَ ہٰذَا رَحۡمَۃٌ مِّنۡ رَّبِّیۡ ۚ فَاِذَا جَآءَ وَعۡدُ رَبِّیۡ جَعَلَہٗ دَکَّآءَ ۚ » (18/98). Translation: Dhul-Qarnayn said: This is a mercy from my Lord (that He enabled me to build such a wall). Then when the promise of my Lord comes, He will make it (the wall) level with the ground by crushing it."
    },
    {
      "id": 2981,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To Level",
      "hw": "ہموار",
      "s": "«مَرَّدَ» to make smooth and shiny (1 verse: 27:44)",
      "d": "«مَرِدَ الْغُلَام» means the boy to be beardless. And «مَرَّدَ الْغُصْن» means to smooth the leaves of a branch. And «مَرَّدَ الْبَنَاء» means to make a building smooth and shiny (lex. Manjad). For example, in the Quran: «قَالَ  اِنَّہٗ  صَرۡحٌ مُّمَرَّدٌ مِّنۡ قَوَارِیۡرَ» (27/44). Translation: Solomon said: This is a palace made smooth due to being fitted with glass."
    }
  ],
  "652": [
    {
      "id": 2982,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Always",
      "hw": "ہمیشہ",
      "s": "«سَرْمَد» for something to remain in one state forever without change (2 verses: 28:71-28:72)",
      "d": "«سَرْمَد» means permanent, always (lex.). «سَرْمَدِیّ» means that which has no beginning or end (Manjad). Always remaining in one state without any change (fiqh al-lughah 95). For example, in the Quran: «قُلۡ اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ  اِنۡ جَعَلَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡکُمُ الَّیۡلَ سَرۡمَدًا  اِلٰی یَوۡمِ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ مَنۡ اِلٰہٌ غَیۡرُ اللّٰہِ یَاۡتِیۡکُمۡ بِضِیَآءٍ» (28/71). Translation: Say: Do you see if Allah makes the night upon you permanent until the Day of Resurrection, is there any other god besides Allah who can bring you light?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2984,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To Be Always / To Remain",
      "hw": "ہمیشہ",
      "s": "«خَلَدَ» to remain in one state for a long time without change (84 verses: 2:25-2:39-2:81-2:82-2:162-2:217-2:257-2:275-3:15-3:88-3:107-3:116-3:136-3:198-4:13-4:14-4:57-4:93-4:122-4:169-5:80-5:85-5:119-6:128-7:20-7:36-7:42-9:17-9:22-9:63-9:68-9:72-9:89-9:100-10:26-10:27-10:52-11:23-11:107-11:108-13:5-14:23-16:29-18:108-20:76-20:101-20:120-21:8-21:34-21:99-21:102-23:11-23:103-25:15-25:16-25:69-25:76-26:129-29:58-31:9-32:14-33:65-39:72-39:73-40:76-41:28-43:71-43:74-46:14-47:15-48:5-56:17-57:12-58:17-58:22-59:17-64:9-64:10-65:11-72:23-76:19-98:6-98:8-104:3)",
      "d": "The word «خَلَدَ» does not come for eternity but for something to remain in its initial state for a long time without any change or difference. Because this word comes with «أَبَد» for emphasis, and where only a long period is intended, only «خَلَدَ» is used. The word «أَبَدًا» does not come with it. For example, in the Quran: «اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ وَ الۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ فِیۡ  نَارِ جَہَنَّمَ خٰلِدِیۡنَ فِیۡہَا» (98/6). Translation: And those who disbelieve from the People of the Book and the polytheists will be in the fire of Hell, abiding therein forever. And in the same surah, regarding the reward of believers: «جَزَآؤُہُمۡ عِنۡدَ  رَبِّہِمۡ جَنّٰتُ عَدۡنٍ تَجۡرِیۡ مِنۡ تَحۡتِہَا الۡاَنۡہٰرُ خٰلِدِیۡنَ فِیۡہَاۤ  اَبَدًا» (98/8). Translation: Their reward is with their Lord: Gardens of Eternity beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein forever. And «أَخْلَدَ» and «خَلَّدَ» both are used in the meaning of remaining in one state for a long time or remaining in the same state. For example: «یَحۡسَبُ اَنَّ مَالَہٗۤ  اَخۡلَدَہٗ» (104/3). Translation: He thinks that his wealth will make him live forever. And at another place: «یَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  وِلۡدَانٌ   مُّخَلَّدُوۡنَ» (56/17). Translation: Young serving boys will be going around them, remaining in the same state forever."
    },
    {
      "id": 2985,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To Be Always / To Remain",
      "hw": "ہمیشہ",
      "s": "«وَصَبَ» in which duration (permanence) along with vastness and strength is found (2 verses: 16:52-37:9)",
      "d": "According to Ibn al-Faris, the meaning of «وَصَبَ» is merely the permanence of something in one state, i.e., perpetuity (lex.). And according to the author of Fiqh al-Lughah, it is «شِدَّۃُ الْوَجْع» (fiqh al-lughah 48) i.e., the intensity of pain. And according to the author of Manjad, «اَلْوَاصِب» means a vast desert extending far away, and «وَصَبَ» means to be permanent and firm. And to be «دائِمُ الْمَرِیْض» (Manjad). For example, in the Quran: «وَّ لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ وَّاصِبٌ» (37/9). Translation: And for them is a lasting punishment. See here in the meaning of «واصِبٌ», three aspects are found: permanence, intensity of pain, and vastness. But later, this word left the meaning of «شِدَّۃُ الْوَجْع» and began to be used only in the meanings of intensity or strength and vastness with permanence. For example, the divine saying: «وَ لَہٗ  مَا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ وَ لَہُ الدِّیۡنُ وَاصِبًا» (16/52). Translation: And to Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth, and to Him is the dominion, permanent."
    },
    {
      "id": 2987,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To Be Always / To Remain",
      "hw": "ہمیشہ",
      "s": "«اِسْتَمَرَّ» to remain in one state or way from the beginning (2 verses: 54:2-54:19)",
      "d": "«مَرَّ» means to pass, to go, to pass by something (lex. Manjad). And «اِسْتَمَرَّ» means to remain in one state or way, to perpetuate (Manjad). For example, in the Quran: «وَ اِنۡ یَّرَوۡا اٰیَۃً  یُّعۡرِضُوۡا وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡا سِحۡرٌ مُّسۡتَمِرٌّ» (54/2). Translation: And when the disbelievers see a sign, they turn away and say, 'This is a continuous magic.' (Jalandhari) Magic that has been going on from before (Uthmani)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2988,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To Be Always / To Remain",
      "hw": "ہمیشہ",
      "s": "«دَامَ» to last, to remain established, to be enduring (3 verses: 5:24-13:35-70:23)",
      "d": "The word «دَامَ» does not come for perpetuity but for something to remain from its beginning for a long time without any change or difference. Because this word comes with «أَبَد» for emphasis, and where only a long period is intended, only «دَامَ» is used. The word «أَبَدًا» does not come with it. For example, in the Quran: «قَالُوۡا یٰمُوۡسٰۤی اِنَّنا لَنۡ  نَّدۡخُلَہَاۤ  اَبَدًا مَّا دَامُوۡا فِیۡہَا» (5/24). Translation: The Israelites said: O Moses! As long as those people are present there, we will never enter it."
    },
    {
      "id": 2989,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To Be Always / To Remain",
      "hw": "ہمیشہ",
      "s": "«زَالَ» to cease, to disappear; with negation particles «لَا» and «مَا», it means never (7 verses: 2:217-5:13-9:110-11:118-13:31-21:15-22:55)",
      "d": "«زَالَ» means to cease, to disappear. And «زوال» means to set (like the sun). This word, when combined with the negative particles «لَا» and «مَا», gives the meaning of perpetuity, and it is always used with «لَا» and «مَا» in these meanings (lex.). And it comes as an adverb of time. For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَا تَزَالُ تَطَّلِعُ عَلٰی خَآئِنَۃٍ مِّنۡہُمۡ اِلَّا قَلِیۡلًا مِّنۡہُمۡ» (5/13). Translation: And you will always find among them (Jews) treachery, except for a few of them. And at another place, the divine saying: «فَمَا زَالَتۡ تِّلۡکَ دَعۡوٰىہُمۡ  حَتّٰی  جَعَلۡنٰہُمۡ  حَصِیۡدًا  خٰمِدِیۡنَ» (21/15). Translation: So they continued to call upon Him (their gods) until We made them like a mown field and extinguished embers."
    },
    {
      "id": 2990,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To Be Always / To Remain",
      "hw": "ہمیشہ",
      "s": "«اَبْرَحَ» used only in the imperfect with negation «لَا» or «لَنْ» and conditional «حَتّٰی», as a place adverb (3 verses: 12:80-18:60-20:91)",
      "d": "The opposite of «بَرَحَ» is «بَرَزَ». And «بَرَزَ» means to come forward in an open field. And «بَرَحَ» means to move away from an open field (lex.). Only the imperfect form is used. When combined with the negative words «لَا» or «لَنْ», it is used as an adverb of place. And it is always conditional with «حَتّٰی». For example, in the Quran: «وَ اِذۡ قَالَ مُوۡسٰی لِفَتٰىہُ لَاۤ  اَبۡرَحُ حَتّٰۤی اَبۡلُغَ  مَجۡمَعَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ» (18/60). Translation: And when Moses said to his young companion, 'I will not leave until I reach the meeting point of the two seas.' And at another place, the divine saying: «قَالُوۡا لَنۡ نَّبۡرَحَ عَلَیۡہِ عٰکِفِیۡنَ حَتّٰی یَرۡجِعَ   اِلَیۡنَا مُوۡسٰی» (20/91). Translation: The Israelites said to Aaron, 'We will not leave the place of worship until Moses returns to us.' Note: (Imperfect verb: a verb in which an action or state in the present or future tense is found, such as: comes, goes, does, etc.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2991,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To always be. To remain.",
      "hw": "ہمیشہ",
      "s": "«فَتَا» means to prevent someone from doing something. When the negation particles «لَا» and «مَا» are added to it, it means to continue doing something perpetually. (1 verse: 12:85)",
      "d": "«فَتَا» means to prevent someone from doing something. When «لَا» and «مَا» negation particles are added, it means to continue doing something perpetually. For example, one says «مَا فَتَاَ یَفْعَلُ ذٰلک» meaning 'He continued to do that.' It generally conditions with «حَتّٰی». It is used only in past and imperfect tenses (from Majid). It comes as an adverb of time. This word appears once in the Quran, but there too «لَا» is omitted (hidden) (according to Jalalayn and Jam' al-Bayan).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«قَالُوۡا تَاللّٰہِ تَفۡتَؤُا تَذۡکُرُ یُوۡسُفَ حَتّٰی تَکُوۡنَ حَرَضًا اَوۡ تَکُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡہٰلِکِیۡنَ» (12/85)\nTranslation: The brothers of Yusuf said to their father, 'By Allah! You will continue to remember Yusuf (AS) until you become ill or die.'"
    }
  ],
  "653": [
    {
      "id": 2992,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to laugh",
      "hw": "ہنسنا",
      "s": "«ضَحِکَ» means to laugh with sound, opening the mouth such that teeth become visible. (8 verses: 9:82-11:71-23:110-43:47-53:43-53:60-83:29-83:34)",
      "d": "«ضَحِکَ» means to laugh with sound, opening the mouth such that teeth become visible (from Majid).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ امۡرَاَتُہٗ  قَآئِمَۃٌ  فَضَحِکَتۡ فَبَشَّرۡنٰہَا بِاِسۡحٰقَ» (11/71)\nTranslation: And his wife, who was standing, laughed, so We gave her glad tidings of Ishaq (AS)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2993,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to laugh",
      "hw": "ہنسنا",
      "s": "«تَبَسَّمَ» means to smile. (1 verse: 27:19)",
      "d": "«بَسَمَ» and «تَبَسَّمَ» mean to smile (from Majid). To laugh a little without sound, such that signs of happiness appear.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَتَبَسَّمَ ضَاحِکًا مِّنۡ قَوۡلِہَا» (27/19)\nTranslation: So he (Sulaiman AS) smiled, laughing at her words."
    }
  ],
  "654": [
    {
      "id": 2994,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "«رِیْح» means wind. (18 verses: 3:117-8:46-10:22-12:94-14:18-17:69-21:81-22:31-30:51-33:9-34:12-38:36-41:16-42:33-46:24-51:41-54:19-69:6)",
      "d": "«رِیْح» and «رَوْح» are well-known words for wind. According to Ibn al-Faris, its meaning is wind and movement (M.L.). Although it has been used in the Quran in wider meanings. For example:\n(1) «رِیْح» meaning wind in the well-known sense, which moves (F.L. 172).\nFor example, the divine declaration is:\n«اِنۡ یَّشَاۡ یُسۡکِنِ الرِّیۡحَ» (42/33)\nTranslation: If Allah wills, He can make the wind stationary.\n(2) «رِیْح» meaning scent or fragrance.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اِنِّیۡ لَاَجِدُ رِیۡحَ یُوۡسُفَ» (12/94)\nTranslation: Indeed, I find the scent of Yusuf (AS).\n(3) «رِیْح» meaning terror and awe.\nFor example, the divine declaration is:\n«وَ لَا  تَنَازَعُوۡا فَتَفۡشَلُوۡا  وَ تَذۡہَبَ رِیۡحُکُمۡ» (8/46)\nTranslation: And do not dispute, lest you lose courage and your wind (spirit) depart.\nAnd the plural of «رِیْح» is «رِیَاح». When the phrase «اِرْسَالُ الرِّیَاح» is used, it refers to the winds of mercy. And if «اِرْسَالُ الرِّیْح» is mentioned, i.e., the singular form, then it refers to the wind of punishment (Mufradat). Hence, it is classified accordingly."
    },
    {
      "id": 2995,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "«رَوْح» means mercy. The continuous flowing waves of Allah's favors and bounties. (2 verses: 12:87-56:89)",
      "d": "«رَوْح» means gentle breeze. Mercy. Happiness. Comfort. Help. And «یَوْمٌ رَوْحٌ» means a pleasant day (from Majid). According to Imam Raghib, «رُوْح» and «رَوْح» are essentially the same. And «رُوْح» is applied to breathing. And «اَرَاحَ الْاِنْسَان» means to make a person breathe. And also to attain rest (Mufradat). Contemplating the various meanings of «رُوْح» reveals that its meaning is the continuous flowing wave of Allah's favors and bounties, which becomes a cause of comfort and ease for humans.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«لَا تَایۡئَسُوۡا مِنۡ رَّوۡحِ اللّٰہِ ؕ اِنَّہٗ  لَا یَایۡئَسُ مِنۡ رَّوۡحِ اللّٰہِ  اِلَّا الۡقَوۡمُ  الۡکٰفِرُوۡنَ» (12/87)\nTranslation: Do not despair of Allah's mercy. Indeed, none despairs of Allah's mercy except the disbelieving people."
    },
    {
      "id": 2996,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "«رَیْحَان» fragrant flowers/plants, herbs. (2 verses: 55:12-56:89)",
      "d": "«رَیْحَان» means every fragrant plant. Sustenance. Livelihood (from Majid). And «رَائِحَۃ» means a fragrant scent, and «رَیْحَانَۃ» means a bouquet of flowers (from Majid). Contemplating these meanings shows that if «رَیْحَان» refers to rizq (sustenance) or items of food and drink obtained from agriculture, then they are things whose fragrance and scent are pleasant.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَرَوۡحٌ وَّ رَیۡحَانٌ  ۬ ۙ وَّ جَنَّتُ نَعِیۡمٍ» (56/89)\nTranslation: Then for him are comfort, fragrant flowers, and gardens of bliss.\nAt another place, the divine declaration is:\n«وَ الۡحَبُّ ذُو الۡعَصۡفِ وَ الرَّیۡحَانُ» (55/12)\nTranslation: And the grain with its husk and fragrant flowers."
    },
    {
      "id": 2997,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "«مُبَشِّرَات» winds that bring glad tidings of rain. (1 verse: 30:46)",
      "d": "«مُبَشِّرَات» means winds that bring glad tidings of the descent of mercy or rain. The breeze that is moist and pleasant before the rain (F.L. 254).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ مِنۡ اٰیٰتِہٖۤ  اَنۡ یُّرۡسِلَ الرِّیَاحَ مُبَشِّرٰتٍ وَّ  لِیُذِیۡقَکُمۡ  مِّنۡ  رَّحۡمَتِہٖ» (30/46)\nTranslation: And among His signs is that He sends the winds as glad tidings so that you may taste His mercy."
    },
    {
      "id": 2998,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "«لَوَاقِح» rain-bearing winds. Those winds that carry the burden of water before raining. (1 verse: 15:22)",
      "d": "«لَوَاقِح» is the plural of «لَاقِحَہ» and «لَقِحَ», meaning rain-bearing wind. And this burden can be of two types: (1) the burden of water that winds carry before raining, (2) the burden of male plant's pollen (i.e., seed, pod, grain, or sperm) that it carries and deposits on the female plant (M.L.). In the Quran, this word is used only in the first meaning.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ اَرۡسَلۡنَا الرِّیٰحَ لَوَاقِحَ فَاَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً» (15/22)\nTranslation: And We sent the rain-bearing winds, then We caused water to descend from the sky."
    },
    {
      "id": 2999,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "«عَاصِف» stormy wind carrying dust and chaff. (4 verses: 10:22-14:18-21:81-77:2)",
      "d": "«عَصْف» means chaff. Husk. Dry plants that become crumbled (Mufradat). And «عَاصِفَۃ» is the name for that strong wind or storm that carries chaff or similar things.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا کُنۡتُمۡ فِی الۡفُلۡکِ ۚ وَ  جَرَیۡنَ بِہِمۡ بِرِیۡحٍ طَیِّبَۃٍ وَّ فَرِحُوۡا بِہَا جَآءَتۡہَا رِیۡحٌ عَاصِفٌ وَّ جَآءَہُمُ الۡمَوۡجُ مِنۡ کُلِّ مَکَانٍ وَّ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہُمۡ اُحِیۡطَ بِہِمۡ» (10/22)\nTranslation: Until when you are in the ships, and they sail with them with a good wind and they rejoice therein, there comes upon them a stormy wind, and the waves come upon them from every side, and they think that they are surrounded."
    },
    {
      "id": 3000,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "«حَاصِبٌ» stormy wind carrying stones. (4 verses: 17:68-29:40-54:34-67:17)",
      "d": "«حَصَب» means stones, pebbles. And «حاصِبَۃ» is that strong wind that carries stones and pebbles (F.L. 253). And «اَحْصَبَ الْفَرْس» means the horse runs so fast that stones fly from its hooves (M.Q.).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اَفَاَمِنۡتُمۡ اَنۡ یَّخۡسِفَ بِکُمۡ جَانِبَ الۡبَرِّ اَوۡ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ حَاصِبًا» (17/68)\nTranslation: Then do you feel secure that He will not cause the side of the land to engulf you or send upon you a storm of stones?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3001,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "wind and its types (disastrous winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "«قَاصِف» refers to a windstorm that uproots trees (1 verse: 17:69)",
      "d": "«قَصَفَ» means to break and to snap (م ۔ ل). And «قَاصِف» is that fierce and violent wind which breaks trees, etc. (مف). A windstorm. A thunderous wind.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«فَیُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ قَاصِفًا مِّنَ الرِّیۡحِ فَیُغۡرِقَکُمۡ بِمَا کَفَرۡتُمۡ» ( 17/69 )\nTranslation: Then He will send upon you a violent wind from the sky, which will drown you because of your disbelief."
    },
    {
      "id": 3002,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Winds and their types (disastrous winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "«سَمُوْم» A scorching, intensely hot wind (3 verses: 15/27, 52/27, 56/42)",
      "d": "«سَمُوْم» means an intensely hot wind. A sirocco. A wind that scorches bodies (Fayruz al-Lughah, p. 254).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَمَنَّ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡنَا وَ  وَقٰىنَا عَذَابَ السَّمُوۡمِ» (52/27)\nTranslation: So Allah bestowed favor upon us and saved us from the punishment of the scorching wind."
    },
    {
      "id": 3003,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Winds and their types (disastrous winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "«اِعْصَار» A whirlwind. A violent wind filled with dust and debris that ascends straight towards the sky (1 verse: 2/266)",
      "d": "«اِعْصَار» is a violent wind that whirls in the air (Mufradat). It means a violent wind filled with dust and debris that ascends straight towards the sky (Fayruz al-Lughah, p. 253). A wind-cyclone.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَصَابَہَاۤ اِعۡصَارٌ فِیۡہِ نَارٌ فَاحۡتَرَقَتۡ» (2/266)\nTranslation: Then a whirlwind befell it, in which there was fire, and it was burnt to ashes."
    },
    {
      "id": 3004,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Winds and their types (disastrous winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "«حُسْبَان» A wind-borne calamity or affliction sufficient for settling the account (3 verses: 6/96, 18/40, 55/5)",
      "d": "«حَسَبَ» means to calculate, count, or enumerate. And «حُسْبَان» means a calamity or affliction that is sufficient for settling the account. Different lexicographers have given various meanings for «حُسْبَان». However, it is related to the punishment of wind.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡہَا حُسۡبَانًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ  فَتُصۡبِحَ  صَعِیۡدًا  زَلَقًا» (18/40)\nTranslation: And Allah sends upon it a calamity from the sky, and it becomes a smooth, empty plain."
    },
    {
      "id": 3005,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Winds and their types (disastrous winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "«نَفْحَۃٌ» Meaning a cold blast, a single gust of intensely cold wind (1 verse: 21/46)",
      "d": "«نَفْحَۃٌ» means a cold blast. Like a single puff of wind from a bellows. A blast. A puff. A surge of intensely cold wind. Its opposite is «لَفْحَۃٌ», meaning a surge of hot wind (Fayruz al-Lughah, p. 29).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَئِنۡ مَّسَّتۡہُمۡ نَفۡحَۃٌ مِّنۡ عَذَابِ رَبِّکَ» (21/46)\nTranslation: And if a single puff of your Lord's punishment touches them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3007,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Winds and their types (disastrous winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "«رِیْحُ العَقِیْم» A wind that is devoid of good, wherein there is only harm and no benefit (1 verse: 51/41)",
      "d": "«رِیْحُ العَقِیْم» meaning a wind that does not bring rain or clouds, nor does it scatter seeds (i.e., it does not facilitate growth) (Fayruz al-Lughah, p. 254). A wind devoid of good. A wind that causes only harm. Its opposite is «لَا قِحَہ» (a fertile wind).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ فِیۡ عَادٍ  اِذۡ  اَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمُ  الرِّیۡحَ الۡعَقِیۡمَ» (51/41)\nTranslation: And in 'Ad (was a sign) when We sent upon them the barren, destructive wind."
    }
  ],
  "655": [
    {
      "id": 3008,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to be",
      "hw": "ہونا",
      "s": "«کَانَ» conveys the meaning of past and present, such as: is, became, and was (657 verses: 2:10-2:16-2:34-2:36-2:57-2:59-2:61-2:75-2:89-2:94-2:97-2:98-2:102-2:103-2:111-2:113-2:114-2:134-2:135-2:140-2:141-2:142-2:143-2:170-2:184-2:185-2:196-2:213-2:232-2:280-2:282-3:13-3:24-3:67-3:79-3:93-3:95-3:97-3:110-3:112-3:137-3:145-3:147-3:154-3:156-3:161-3:164-3:179-4:1-4:2-4:6-4:11-4:12-4:16-4:17-4:22-4:23-4:24-4:29-4:30-4:32-4:33-4:34-4:35-4:36-4:39-4:43-4:46-4:47-4:56-4:58-4:66-4:76-4:82-4:85-4:86-4:92-4:94-4:96-4:99-4:100-4:101-4:102-4:103-4:104-4:106-4:107-4:108-4:111-4:113-4:126-4:127-4:128-4:129-4:130-4:131-4:133-4:134-4:135-4:141-4:147-4:148-4:149-4:152-4:158-4:165-4:169-4:170-4:176-5:14-5:44-5:61-5:62-5:63-5:75-5:78-5:79-5:81-5:104-5:106-6:4-6:5-6:10-6:11-6:24-6:28-6:35-6:43-6:49-6:70-6:88-6:108-6:111-6:120-6:122-6:124-6:127-6:129-6:130-6:136-6:138-6:140-6:152-6:157-6:159-6:161-7:5-7:9-7:37-7:39-7:51-7:53-7:64-7:70-7:72-7:82-7:83-7:84-7:86-7:87-7:92-7:96-7:101-7:103-7:118-7:133-7:136-7:137-7:139-7:146-7:147-7:148-7:157-7:160-7:162-7:163-7:165-7:175-7:177-7:180-8:32-8:33-8:34-8:35-8:42-8:44-8:54-8:67-9:9-9:17-9:24-9:42-9:62-9:66-9:69-9:70-9:77-9:81-9:82-9:95-9:113-9:114-9:115-9:120-9:121-9:122-10:2-10:4-10:8-10:12-10:13-10:19-10:30-10:37-10:39-10:42-10:43-10:45-10:63-10:70-10:71-10:73-10:74-10:75-10:93-10:98-10:100-11:7-11:8-11:15-11:16-11:17-11:20-11:21-11:34-11:36-11:42-11:43-11:78-11:116-11:117-12:7-12:20-12:26-12:27-12:38-12:57-12:68-12:69-12:76-12:109-12:111-13:32-13:38-14:10-14:11-14:22-14:46-15:2-15:8-15:11-15:63-15:78-15:81-15:82-15:84-15:93-16:33-16:34-16:36-16:39-16:41-16:87-16:88-16:96-16:97-16:112-16:118-16:120-16:123-16:124-17:3-17:5-17:11-17:18-17:19-17:20-17:25-17:27-17:30-17:31-17:32-17:33-17:34-17:36-17:38-17:42-17:44-17:53-17:57-17:58-17:66-17:67-17:72-17:78-17:81-17:83-17:87-17:88-17:95-17:96-17:100-17:108-18:9-18:28-18:34-18:43-18:45-18:50-18:54-18:79-18:80-18:82-18:98-18:101-18:107-18:109-18:110-19:5-19:8-19:13-19:21-19:28-19:29-19:35-19:41-19:44-19:47-19:51-19:54-19:55-19:56-19:61-19:63-19:64-19:71-19:75-20:129-21:8-21:11-21:22-21:30-21:41-21:47-21:63-21:73-21:74-21:77-21:90-21:99-22:15-22:44-23:46-23:48-23:66-23:91-23:109-24:7-24:9-24:24-24:51-24:62-25:6-25:15-25:16-25:18-25:20-25:26-25:29-25:40-25:54-25:55-25:65-25:67-25:70-26:5-26:6-26:8-26:40-26:63-26:67-26:86-26:103-26:112-26:121-26:139-26:158-26:174-26:189-26:190-26:199-26:206-26:207-27:12-27:14-27:20-27:43-27:48-27:51-27:53-27:56-27:60-27:69-27:82-28:4-28:6-28:8-28:32-28:40-28:59-28:63-28:64-28:68-28:75-28:76-28:81-28:84-29:5-29:7-29:13-29:24-29:29-29:31-29:32-29:33-29:34-29:38-29:39-29:40-29:41-29:64-30:9-30:10-30:13-30:32-30:35-30:42-30:47-30:49-30:55-31:21-32:5-32:17-32:18-32:19-32:24-32:25-33:1-33:2-33:5-33:6-33:9-33:15-33:19-33:20-33:21-33:24-33:35-33:27-33:30-33:34-33:36-33:37-33:38-33:40-33:43-33:50-33:51-33:52-33:53-33:54-33:55-33:59-33:69-33:72-33:73-34:14-34:15-34:21-34:33-34:40-34:41-34:43-34:45-34:54-35:10-35:18-35:26-35:41-35:44-35:45-36:29-36:30-36:46-36:53-36:65-36:70-37:22-37:30-37:35-37:51-37:73-37:116-37:141-37:143-37:167-38:69-38:74-39:8-39:26-39:35-39:43-39:46-39:48-39:50-40:5-40:21-40:22-40:63-40:78-40:82-40:83-41:15-41:17-41:18-41:20-41:25-41:27-41:28-41:48-41:52-42:20-42:46-42:51-43:7-43:25-43:40-43:54-43:69-43:76-43:81-44:27-44:29-44:31-44:37-45:14-45:17-45:25-45:33-46:6-46:10-46:11-46:14-46:16-46:18-46:26-46:28-47:10-47:14-47:21-48:4-48:5-48:7-48:11-48:14-48:15-48:19-48:21-48:24-48:26-49:5-50:27-50:37-51:16-51:17-51:35-51:45-51:46-52:34-53:9-53:52-54:14-54:16-54:18-54:21-54:30-54:31-55:37-56:6-56:24-56:45-56:46-56:47-56:88-56:90-56:92-58:7-58:15-58:22-59:9-59:17-60:4-60:6-62:2-63:2-64:6-65:2-65:9-66:10-66:12-67:18-68:14-68:33-68:41-68:43-69:27-69:33-70:4-70:44-71:10-72:4-72:6-72:15-73:14-73:18-74:16-75:38-76:5-76:7-76:15-76:17-76:22-76:30-77:39-78:17-78:19-78:20-78:21-78:27-83:14-83:29-83:36-84:13-84:15-90:17-96:11-110:3)",
      "d": "«کَانَ» conveys the meaning of past and present, such as: is, became, and was. And its imperfect form is «یَکُون», which conveys the meaning of present and future. According to Ibn al-Faris, the meaning of «کَانَ» is 'to inform about the coming into existence of something'.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«اِلَّاۤ اِبۡلِیۡسَ ؕ اَبٰی وَ اسۡتَکۡبَرَ ٭۫ وَ کَانَ مِنَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» ( 2/34 )\nTranslation: Except Iblis; he refused and was arrogant. And he became of the disbelievers.\nIn another place, the divine declaration is:\n«وَ یَخَافُوۡنَ یَوۡمًا کَانَ شَرُّہٗ  مُسۡتَطِیۡرًا» ( 76/7 )\nTranslation: And they fear a Day whose evil will be widespread.\nMoreover, «کَانَ» also comes in the form of an incomplete verb. When it enters the past tense, it changes it to the remote past (distant meanings). «کَانَ ذَھَبَ» means 'he had gone'. And when it enters the imperfect, it changes it to the continuous past. For example: The divine declaration is:\n«فَاَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ ظَلَمُوۡا رِجۡزًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَفۡسُقُوۡنَ» ( 2/59 )\nTranslation: So We sent upon those who wronged a punishment from the heaven because they used to disobey.\nNote: (Continuous past: that verb which indicates the repeated occurrence or continuation of an action, e.g., he used to come.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3010,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To be / Existence",
      "hw": "ہونا",
      "s": "«صَدَرَ» For an affair to occur; for a decree to be issued, to be promulgated (2 verses: 28/23, 99/6)",
      "d": "«صَدَرَ» means for an affair to occur; for a decree to be issued, to be promulgated. Its opposite is «وَرَدَ», meaning to arrive or come in. And «صُدُوْر» is said after a task is completed successfully and then upon departure (Mufradat).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یَوۡمَئِذٍ یَّصۡدُرُ  النَّاسُ اَشۡتَاتًا  ۬ ۙ لِّیُرَوۡا اَعۡمَالَہُمۡ» (99/6)\nTranslation: On that Day, people will depart in groups to be shown their deeds.\nAt another place, the Divine declaration states:\n«قَالَتَا لَا نَسۡقِیۡ حَتّٰی یُصۡدِرَ الرِّعَآءُ» (28/23)\nTranslation: They said, 'We will not water until the shepherds have departed.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3011,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to happen / to befall",
      "hw": "ہونا",
      "s": "«وَقَعَ» means the occurrence of a calamitous event (19 verses: 4:100-5:91-7:71-7:118-7:134-7:171-10:51-18:53-27:82-27:85-42:22-51:6-52:7-56:1-56:2-56:75-69:15-70:1-77:7)",
      "d": "«وَقَعَ» basically has two meanings: (1) for something to be established, (2) to fall. And an event generally refers to an incident that involves severity and hardship.\nIn the Quran, this word has been used for punishment, detestable things, and calamities (مف).\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«سَاَلَ  سَآئِلٌۢ  بِعَذَابٍ  وَّاقِعٍ» ( 70/1 )\nTranslation: A seeker of truth asked about the impending punishment.\nIn another place, the divine declaration is:\n«وَ وَقَعَ الۡقَوۡلُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِمَا ظَلَمُوۡا» ( 27/85 )\nTranslation: And the decree will be fulfilled against them because of what they used to do."
    }
  ],
  "656": [
    {
      "id": 3012,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Or",
      "hw": "یا",
      "s": "«اَوْ» It comes to indicate one thing out of two or more options (211 verses)",
      "d": "«اَوْ» comes to indicate one thing out of two or more options.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَوۡ کَالَّذِیۡ مَرَّ عَلٰی قَرۡیَۃٍ» (2/259)\nTranslation: Or like the one who passed by a town."
    },
    {
      "id": 3013,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "or",
      "hw": "یا",
      "s": "«اَمْ» is called a conjunction in Arabic grammar. It comes after an interrogative hamzah meaning equality.",
      "d": "«اَمْ» is called a conjunction in Arabic grammar. It comes after an interrogative hamzah meaning equality.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَشَدُّ خَلۡقًا اَمِ السَّمَآءُ» (79/27)\nTranslation: Which is harder to create, you or the sky?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3014,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "or",
      "hw": "یا",
      "s": "«اِمَّا» comes to mention each of two things and is used with repetition.",
      "d": "«اِمَّا» comes to mention each of two things and is used with repetition.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«اِنَّا ہَدَیۡنٰہُ السَّبِیۡلَ اِمَّا شَاکِرًا وَّ اِمَّا کَفُوۡرًا» (76/3)\nTranslation: We have shown man the way; then he is either grateful or ungrateful."
    }
  ],
  "657": [
    {
      "id": 3015,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "to remember. to come. to keep.",
      "hw": "یاد",
      "s": "«ذَکَرَ» means to remember, to keep, to come, to remember in the heart or on the tongue; it is used everywhere and its usage is common.",
      "d": "«ذَکَرَ» means something coming to mind or tongue. Whether a matter remains remembered or comes to mind after forgetting, it is used generally.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«اَوَلَا یَذۡکُرُ الۡاِنۡسَانُ اَنَّا خَلَقۡنٰہُ مِنۡ قَبۡلُ وَلَمۡ یَکُ شَیۡئًا» (19/67)\nTranslation: Does man not remember that We created him before, while he was nothing?\nAnd «اِدَّکَر» means to remember a forgotten past matter.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«وَ قَالَ الَّذِیۡ نَجَا مِنۡہُمَا وَ ادَّکَرَ بَعۡدَ اُمَّۃٍ» (12/45)\nTranslation: And the one who escaped from the two said, and the matter came to his mind after a long time."
    },
    {
      "id": 3016,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "to remember. to come. to keep.",
      "hw": "یاد",
      "s": "«حَفِظَ» means to memorize something verbally, to preserve in the heart, then keep its remembrance and not forget.",
      "d": "«حَفِظَ» means to remember something and then keep its remembrance (to not let it be lost or forgotten). To protect something from being wasted or ruined.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«حٰفِظُوۡا عَلَی الصَّلَوٰتِ وَ الصَّلٰوۃِ الۡوُسۡطٰی» (2/238)\nTranslation: Guard the prayers, and the middle prayer."
    },
    {
      "id": 3017,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "to remember. to come. to keep.",
      "hw": "یاد",
      "s": "«وَعٰی» means to remember and not allow any decrease or increase in it.",
      "d": "«وَعٰی» means to store something in a container and close its mouth. To protect it and not let anything come out of it. And «وِعَاء» means a closed container.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«لِنَجۡعَلَہَا لَکُمۡ تَذۡکِرَۃً وَّ تَعِیَہَاۤ اُذُنٌ وَّاعِیَۃٌ» (69/12)\nTranslation: So that We may make it a reminder for you, and an ear that remembers."
    }
  ],
  "658": [
    {
      "id": 3018,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "to be certain",
      "hw": "یقین",
      "s": "«اَیْقَنَ» means to understand something completely and reach its foundation of proof.",
      "d": "«يَقِنُ» means no doubt or suspicion remains. According to Imam Raghib, «يَقِنُ» means 'to understand something completely and reach its foundation of proof.' Its degree is above knowledge and wisdom. According to Abu Al-Halal Asakri, the degree of certainty is higher than knowledge. He writes: 'Certainty is the soul's tranquility and the heart's coolness with what is known.'\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«وَ بِالۡاٰخِرَۃِ ہُمۡ یُوۡقِنُوۡنَ» (2/4)\nTranslation: (One of the traits of believers is that) they are certain about the Hereafter.\nAnd «اِسْتَیْقَنَ» means certainty gradually coming after experience.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«فَلَمَّا جَآءَتۡہُمۡ اٰیٰتُنَا مُبۡصِرَۃً قَالُوۡا ہٰذَا سِحۡرٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ . وَ جَحَدُوۡا بِہَا وَ اسۡتَیۡقَنَتۡہَاۤ اَنۡفُسُہُمۡ» (27/13-14)\nTranslation: So when Our signs came to them as clear evidence, they said, 'This is clear magic.' And they denied them, while their souls were convinced thereof."
    },
    {
      "id": 3019,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "to be certain",
      "hw": "یقین",
      "s": "«ظَنَّ» means to infer certainty through signs and indications.",
      "d": "«ظَنَّ» essentially comes in the meanings of inferring and guessing through evidence and indications. The weaker the signs and evidence, the weaker the «ظَن». The stronger they are, the stronger the «ظَن». In this case, «ظَن» means strong certainty. Its sign is that after «ظَنَّ», the word «اَنَّ» or «اَنْ» generally comes.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ یَظُنُّوۡنَ اَنَّہُمۡ مُّلٰقُوۡا رَبِّہِمۡ» (2/46)\nTranslation: And give glad tidings to the believers who think they will meet their Lord."
    }
  ],
  "659": [],
  "660": [
    {
      "id": 3022,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "wudu",
      "hw": "وضو",
      "s": "«سَفَرَ» is a general term for travel.",
      "d": "«سَفَرَ» means to depart from one's place of residence and to cover distance. This word is general. Whether the travel is for any purpose.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«وَ إِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ مَّرۡضٰۤی أَوۡ عَلٰی سَفَرٍ» (4/43)\nTranslation: Whether you are ill or on a journey."
    },
    {
      "id": 3023,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "wudu",
      "hw": "وضو",
      "s": "«يمم» is used for intending purification with soil as an alternative to wudu.",
      "d": "«يمم» linguistically means to intend, to resolve, or to turn towards something. In Islamic jurisprudence, and specifically in the context of wudu, «يمم» refers to the intention and act of seeking purification with clean soil when water is unavailable or its use is excused (e.g., due to illness). It is the Shariah alternative to wudu (and ghusl), called tayammum. Its specific nuance is that it is the intention and act of purification with soil instead of water. Allah has granted this concession to Muslims for ease so they can attain purity in all circumstances.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا إِذَا قُمْتُمْ إِلَى الصَّلَاةِ فَاغْسِلُوا وُجُوهَكُمْ وَأَيْدِيَكُمْ إِلَى الْمَرَافِقِ وَامْسَحُوا بِرُءُوسِكُمْ وَأَرْجُلَكُمْ إِلَى الْكَعْبَيْنِ ۚ وَإِن كُنتُمْ جُنُبًا فَاطَّهَّرُوا ۚ وَإِن كُنتُم مَّرْضَىٰ أَوْ عَلَىٰ سَفَرٍ أَوْ جَاءَ أَحَدٌ مِّنكُم مِّنَ الْغَائِطِ أَوْ لَامَسْتُمُ النِّسَاءَ فَلَمْ تَجِدُوا مَاءً فَتَيَمَّمُوا صَعِيدًا طَيِّبًا فَامْسَحُوا بِوُجُوهِكُمْ وَأَيْدِيكُم مِّنْهُ ۚ مَا يُرِيدُ اللَّهُ لِيَجْعَلَ عَلَيْكُم مِّنْ حَرَجٍ وَلَٰكِن يُرِيدُ لِيُطَهِّرَكُمْ وَلِيُتِمَّ نِعْمَتَهُ عَلَيْكُمْ لَعَلَّكُمْ تَشْكُرُونَ» (5/6)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when you rise to pray, wash your faces and your hands up to the elbows, wipe over your heads, and wash your feet up to the ankles. And if you are in a state of janabah, then purify yourselves. But if you are ill or on a journey or one of you comes from the place of relieving himself or you have contacted women and do not find water, then perform tayammum with clean earth. So wipe your faces and hands with it. Allah does not intend to make difficulty for you, but He intends to purify you and complete His favor upon you that you may be grateful."
    },
    {
      "id": 3024,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "wudu",
      "hw": "وضو",
      "s": "«يدي» in the context of wudu refers to that body part (hands) which must be washed up to the elbows for purification.",
      "d": "«يدي» means 'hands'. In the context of wudu, this word indicates the body part (hands) that must be washed up to the elbows as part of the purification ritual. Its meaning relates to the physical organ itself, which is part of fulfilling a religious ruling.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا إِذَا قُمْتُمْ إِلَى الصَّلَاةِ فَاغْسِلُوا وُجُوهَكُمْ وَأَيْدِيَكُمْ إِلَى الْمَرَافِقِ وَامْسَحُوا بِرُءُوسِكُمْ وَأَرْجُلَكُمْ إِلَى الْكَعْبَيْنِ ۚ» (5/6)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when you rise to pray, wash your faces and your hands up to the elbows, wipe over your heads, and wash your feet up to the ankles."
    },
    {
      "id": 3025,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Wudu",
      "hw": "وضو",
      "s": "‘Nasu’ refers to the state of forgetting or neglecting, where a part or condition of wudu is unintentionally omitted, resulting in incomplete wudu.",
      "d": "‘Nasu’ means to forget, overlook, abandon, or leave behind. In the context of wudu, this term describes the condition when a person unintentionally forgets or neglects to perform one of the obligations or sunnahs of wudu, potentially affecting its validity. It highlights human weakness and negligence, indicating that errors can occur even in acts of worship; thus, in such cases, repeating wudu or completing the omitted part becomes necessary.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا بَلَغَا مَجْمَعَ بَيْنِهِمَا نَسِيَا حُوتَهُمَا فَاتَّخَذَ سَبِيلَهُ فِي الْبَحْرِ سَرَبًا» (18 / 61)\nTranslation: Then when they both reached the place where the two rivers met, they forgot their fish, and it took its way into the sea as a sudden disappearance."
    },
    {
      "id": 3026,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Wudu",
      "hw": "وضو",
      "s": "‘Marid’ has no direct linguistic or Shariah connection to the concept of wudu, as wudu is derived from ‘wadhā’ while ‘marid’ means illness.",
      "d": "‘Marid’ means illness, ailment, or defect. This word is completely unrelated to the Shariah or linguistic meaning of wudu (a specific act of purification), as wudu is derived from the Arabic root ‘w-ḍ-ā’ which fundamentally means cleanliness, purity, and radiance. In contrast, ‘marid’ pertains to physical or spiritual sickness and disease. Therefore, using this term in the context of wudu is neither linguistically correct in Arabic nor does it have any basis in Islamic Shariah.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فِي قُلُوبِهِم مَّرَضٌ فَزَادَهُمُ اللَّهُ مَرَضًا ۖ وَلَهُمْ عَذَابٌ أَلِيمٌ بِمَا كَانُوا يَكْذِبُونَ» (2 / 10)\nTranslation: In their hearts is a disease, so Allah has increased their disease, and for them is a painful punishment because they used to lie."
    }
  ],
  "661": [
    {
      "id": 3027,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Naskh",
      "hw": "منسوخ",
      "s": "When ‘khair’ is used in conjunction with the concept of ‘naskh’ (abrogation), it means that the ruling or verse that is abrogated is replaced by something better or similar from Allah.",
      "d": "‘Khair’ means ‘better’ or ‘good’. When this word is used in the context of ‘naskh’, it signifies that when Allah abrogates a ruling or verse, He replaces it with a new ruling or verse that is ‘better’ or equivalent, to fulfill the requirements of wisdom and the interests of the servants. This demonstrates Allah’s wisdom, knowledge, and benevolence towards His creation, that none of His decisions are without purpose; rather, every change carries more goodness and benefit for humanity.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَا نَنسَخْ مِنْ آيَةٍ أَوْ نُنسِهَا نَأْتِ بِخَيْرٍ مِّنْهَا أَوْ مِثْلِهَا ۗ أَلَمْ تَعْلَمْ أَنَّ اللَّهَ عَلَىٰ كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ» (2 / 106)\nTranslation: We do not abrogate a verse or cause it to be forgotten except that We bring forth [one] better than it or similar to it. Do you not know that Allah is over all things competent?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3028,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Naskh",
      "hw": "منسوخ",
      "s": "‘Nasi’ is used to denote the concept of ‘naskh’ by means of abandoning, erasing, or eliminating the effect of a ruling, thereby indicating its abrogation.",
      "d": "‘Nasi’ means ‘to abandon’, ‘to forget’, or ‘to erase from the mind’. When used in the context of ‘naskh’, it refers to terminating a ruling or verse in such a way that it no longer retains its previous status, whether by removing it from people’s minds or by revoking its practical ruling and declaring it void, thus rendering it abrogated. This essentially describes the act of Allah revoking a Shariah ruling or ceasing its application.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَا نَنْسَخْ مِنْ آيَةٍ أَوْ نُنْسِهَا نَأْتِ بِخَيْرٍ مِنْهَا أَوْ مِثْلِهَا أَلَمْ تَعْلَمْ أَنَّ اللَّهَ عَلَى كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ» (2 / 106)\nTranslation: \"Whatever verse We abrogate or cause to be forgotten, We bring a better one or similar to it. Do you not know that Allah is over all things capable?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3029,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Naskh",
      "hw": "منسوخ",
      "s": "‘Ati’ refers to the advent or arrival of a new verse or ruling from Allah, which causes the abrogation of the previous ruling or takes its place.",
      "d": "‘Ati’ means ‘to bring’, ‘to convey’, or ‘to come’. In the context of naskh, this word describes the descent or appearance of a divine ruling, law, or verse that replaces or terminates the previous ruling. It does not directly mean abrogation but indicates how a new ruling or decree ‘comes’ that abrogates the old one. This is part of the process where Allah, in His wisdom, ‘brings’ a better or similar ruling, resulting in the abrogation of the previous one.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَا نَنْسَخْ مِنْ آيَةٍ أَوْ نُنْسِهَا نَأْتِ بِخَيْرٍ مِنْهَا أَوْ مِثْلِهَا أَلَمْ تَعْلَمْ أَنَّ اللَّهَ عَلَى كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ» (2 / 106)\nTranslation: \"Whatever verse We abrogate or cause to be forgotten, We bring a better one or similar to it. Do you not know that Allah is over all things capable?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3030,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "abrogated - abrogation",
      "hw": "منسوخ",
      "s": "When used in the concept of 'abrogated', «مثل» refers to the new ruling or verse that comes in place of the abrogated ruling or verse, and is similar or equivalent to it.",
      "d": "«مثل» means similar, equal, or like. When mentioned in the context of 'abrogated', it refers to the new ruling or verse that Allah reveals in place of a previous abrogated ruling or verse, and this new ruling is similar in its wisdom, effect, or ruling to the previously abrogated one. This indicates that when Allah abrogates a ruling, He replaces it with either something better or something similar, which is more suitable for the servants.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«مَا نَنسَخْ مِنْ آيَةٍ أَوْ نُنسِهَا نَأْتِ بِخَيْرٍ مِّنْهَا أَوْ مِثْلِهَا ۗ أَلَمْ تَعْلَمْ أَنَّ اللَّهَ عَلَىٰ كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ» (البقرة 2 / 106)\nTranslation: 'We do not abrogate a verse or cause it to be forgotten except that We bring forth [one] better than it or similar to it. Do you not know that Allah is over all things competent?'"
    }
  ],
  "662": [
    {
      "id": 3033,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Murtabi'",
      "hw": "متبنیٰ",
      "s": "The word ‘haqq’ in the context of ‘murtabi’ (adopted child) refers to establishing the true lineage and affirming the truth, which negates false claims of parentage.",
      "d": "‘Haqq’ means to establish something as true, to make it a reality, to confirm it, and to uphold the truth. In the concept of ‘murtabi’’, where a child is declared the son of someone other than his biological father, Islam has prohibited this. In this context, ‘haqq’ denotes the truth that Allah establishes through His commands and negates all false claims, including the determination of a child’s true lineage.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَيُحِقُّ اللَّهُ الْحَقَّ بِكَلِمَاتِهِ وَلَوْ كَرِهَ الْمُجْرِمُونَ» (10 / 82)\nTranslation: \"And Allah will establish the truth by His words, even if the criminals dislike it.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3035,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "adopted - adoption",
      "hw": "متبنیٰ",
      "s": "«كون» means the existence of something or the establishment of a state. In the concept of adoption, it indicates the existence or non-existence of the legal or social status that is established regarding the adopted.",
      "d": "«كون» means 'to be', 'to come into existence', or 'to be established'. Although this word is not itself the term 'adopted' (متبنیٰ) nor is it directly derived from it (since 'متبنیٰ' is related to 'ب ن ي'), when the Quran discusses the rulings of adoption, 'كون' is used to clarify the 'being' or 'non-being' of a state related to it. Its specific aspect is that it can be used to express the establishment or non-establishment of the legal or social status of the adopted, or the existence or non-existence of a ruling or difficulty related to it. It expresses the 'coming into existence' or 'being established' of a legal or social reality linked to the concept of adoption, not the act of taking someone into one's care itself.\n\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«لِكَيْ لَا يَكُونَ عَلَى الْمُؤْمِنِينَ حَرَجٌ فِي أَزْوَاجِ أَدْعِيَائِهِمْ إِذَا قَضَوْا مِنْهُنَّ وَطَرًا» (33 / 37)\nTranslation: 'So that there may be no discomfort for the believers concerning the wives of their adopted sons when they have consummated the marriage with them.'\nHere, 'لَا یَکُونَ' (lā yakūn) means 'may not be' or 'may not exist', clarifying that there should be no hardship or discomfort 'established' or 'coming into existence' regarding marrying the former wives of adopted sons. Thus, the verb 'كون' (to be) is expressing the implementation of a ruling regarding adoption and its practical status (i.e., the absence of hardship)."
    }
  ],
  "663": [
    {
      "id": 3037,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Zina",
      "hw": "زنا",
      "s": "The use of ‘kun’ in the context of zina refers to the reality of its existence, meaning its eternal and inherent nature as an immoral and evil act.",
      "d": "‘Kun’ means ‘to be’, ‘to exist’, or ‘to become’. In relation to zina, this word is generally used to describe the eternal and inherent characteristic of the act, i.e., it has always been an immoral and evil act since eternity. This clarifies its unchanging and inherently bad nature, that its wickedness is not temporary or subject to change but is intrinsic to it.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَا تَقْرَبُوا الزِّنَا إِنَّهُ كَانَ فَاحِشَةً وَسَاءَ سَبِيلًا» (17 / 32)\nTranslation: \"And do not approach unlawful sexual intercourse. Indeed, it is ever an abomination and is evil as a way.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3038,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Zina",
      "hw": "زنا",
      "s": "The use of ‘ati’ in relation to zina means to commit or practically carry out that immoral act.",
      "d": "‘Ati’ means ‘to come’, ‘to do’, or ‘to perform’. When this word is used in the context of ‘zina’, it signifies committing that heinous act (zina), carrying it out practically, or being involved in it. This indicates not merely approaching or intending the act but actually its occurrence and giving it practical form. The word explicitly states the regular commission of a sin or immorality.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَالَّلَاتِي يَأْتِينَ الْفَاحِشَةَ مِن نِّسَائِكُمْ فَاسْتَشْهِدُوا عَلَيْهِنَّ أَرْبَعَةً مِّنكُمْ» (4 / 15)\nTranslation: \"And those of your women who commit illegal sexual intercourse - take the evidence of four witnesses from among you.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3040,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Adultery - Adultery",
      "hw": "زنا",
      "s": "«نسو» expresses a desire for complete oblivion, as if one never existed, due to the shameful accusation of adultery or the fear of its social disgrace.",
      "d": "«نسو» lexically means to forget, overlook, or cause to be forgotten. Within the concept of adultery, this word directly describes the moral, social, and psychological effects of the act rather than the act itself. It reflects that intense mental and emotional state where a person, to avoid the infamous charge of adultery or its possible consequences, or due to the extreme shame and humiliation it brings, wishes they had been completely forgotten or never come into existence at all. It points to the desire for total social erasure and self-annihilation that arises in such a situation.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَأَجَاءَهَا الْمَخَاضُ إِلَىٰ جِذْعِ النَّخْلَةِ قَالَتْ يَا لَيْتَنِي مِتُّ قَبْلَ هَٰذَا وَكُنتُ نَسْيًا مَّنسِيًّا» (19 / 14)\nTranslation: Then the pangs of childbirth drove her to the trunk of a palm tree. She said, \"Oh, I wish I had died before this, and had been a thing utterly forgotten!\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3041,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "adultery - adultery",
      "hw": "زنا",
      "s": "When «نكح» is used outside of lawful marriage or in a prohibited relationship, it refers to an illicit sexual act that falls under the category of adultery.",
      "d": "«نكح» means to have sexual relations or to marry. Although this word is generally used in the sense of lawful and religiously sanctioned marriage, when it is used for an illicit or prohibited relationship, it refers to adultery or similar severe immorality (فاحشہ). In this case, the act of 'nikāḥ' becomes illicit and reprehensible, i.e., it becomes forbidden because it is outside the bounds of religious law.\n\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«وَلَا تَنكِحُوا مَا نَكَحَ آبَاؤُكُم مِّنَ النِّسَاءِ إِلَّا مَا قَدْ سَلَفَ ۚ إِنَّهُ كَانَ فَاحِشَةً وَمَقْتًا وَسَاءَ سَبِيلًا» (4 / 22)\nTranslation: 'And do not marry those [women] whom your fathers had married, except what has already occurred. Indeed, it is an immorality, an abomination, and an evil way.'"
    }
  ],
  "664": [
    {
      "id": 3042,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Prosperous - Prosperous",
      "hw": "خوشحال",
      "s": "«ترف» denotes that prosperity or wealth which is based on abundance, luxury, and comfort, and which often leads to negligence, arrogance, or ingratitude.",
      "d": "«ترف» means to live in luxury, to have a very comfortable and pleasurable life, and to be engrossed in worldly comforts. This word does not merely refer to general prosperity but points to an excessive prosperity and wealth that spoils a person, making them overly indulged in ease. The inevitable result of such prosperity is that such people often fall into negligence, pride, ingratitude, and rebellion, turning away from the truth. In the Quran, this word is often used for people who, engrossed in their worldly luxuries, become heedless of the Hereafter and Allah's commands.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَإِذَا أَرَدْنَا أَن نُّهْلِكَ قَرْيَةً أَمَرْنَا مُتْرَفِيهَا فَفَسَقُوا فِيهَا فَحَقَّ عَلَيْهَا الْقَوْلُ فَدَمَّرْنَاهَا تَدْمِيرًا» (17 / 16)\nTranslation: \"And when We intend to destroy a people, We send an order to their affluent ones, but they defiantly disobey therein; so the word [of punishment] comes into effect upon them, and We destroy them utterly.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3043,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Prosperous - Prosperous",
      "hw": "خوشحال",
      "s": "«قري» highlights that aspect of prosperity in which abundance of sustenance and comfort bestow the capacity for hospitality and generosity.",
      "d": "«قري» means hosting a guest, feeding and nurturing them. This word expresses that prosperity and abundance which makes a person or community capable of hospitality and generosity. Although the word «قِرَىٰ» (as hospitality) does not appear explicitly in the Quran, its cognate term «قَرْيَة» (town or city) is often used for towns that were prosperous in their economy or living conditions. Thus, «قري» presents that deep meaning of prosperity which includes not only material comfort but also that generosity and munificence which enables one to consider others and practice the humility of entertaining guests. That is, truly prosperous is one who, in their abundance, keeps an open heart for others.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَكَمْ أَهْلَكْنَا مِن قَرْيَةٍ بَطِرَتْ مَعِيشَتَهَا ۖ فَتِلْكَ مَسَاكِنُهُمْ لَمْ تُسْكَن مِّن بَعْدِهِمْ إِلَّا قَلِيلًا ۖ وَكُنَّا نَحْنُ الْوَارِثِينَ» (28 / 58)\nTranslation: \"And how many a town have We destroyed that was arrogant in its manner of living? Those are their dwellings which have not been inhabited after them except a little; and We are the inheritors.\"\nIn this verse, «قَرْيَةٍ» is mentioned whose \"مَعِيشَتَهَا\" (sustenance/livelihood) they were arrogant about, which reflects their prosperity and comfort. This arrogance included the misuse of that sustenance, which involves not being grateful for Allah's blessings and not fulfilling the rights of others, especially the needy and guests. Thus, the true essence of «قري» (hospitality and generosity) emerges in contrast to that prosperity whose rights were not fulfilled."
    },
    {
      "id": 3044,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Prosperous - Prosperous",
      "hw": "خوشحال",
      "s": "«نذر» does not directly relate to prosperity; rather, this word comes in the meaning of making a vow or warning; however, its connection with prosperity can be established indirectly through a vow made as an expression of gratitude or for seeking blessings.",
      "d": "«نذر» essentially means \"making a vow\" or \"dedicating something to Allah\", and another important meaning is \"to warn\" or \"to threaten\". This word is not directly synonymous with \"prosperous\". However, in the Islamic context, a person makes a vow (نذر) out of gratitude for their attained prosperity and Allah's blessings, or in hope of acquiring future prosperity and blessings. Thus, the act of making a vow can be indirectly linked to a state of prosperity or the desire for it, where a believer intends to sacrifice something to attain Allah's pleasure and additional favor.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَمَا أَنفَقْتُم مِّن نَّفَقَةٍ أَوْ نَذَرْتُم مِّن نَّذْرٍ فَإِنَّ اللَّهَ يَعْلَمُهُ ۗ وَمَا لِلظَّالِمِينَ مِنْ أَنصَارٍ» (2 / 270)\nTranslation: \"And whatever you spend or whatever vow you make, indeed Allah knows it, and the wrongdoers will have no helpers.\"\nExplanation: In this verse, «نذر» refers to a \"vow\" or \"pledge\" made for Allah. Although the verse does not mention «نذر» in the meaning of \"prosperous\", the act of making a vow often arises from a person's own prosperity or better conditions (which are part of prosperity), or in gratitude for them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3046,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Prosperous - Prosperous",
      "hw": "خوشحال",
      "s": "«حقق» when used in the meaning of prosperity, refers to the attainment or fulfillment of a truth, promise, or hope that brings about contentment and ease.",
      "d": "«حقق» means to prove something true, to give it the form of reality, or to fulfill a promise or expectation. When this word is associated with the concept of 'prosperity,' it means the attainment or completion of a truth, right, or purpose that manifests as inner peace, satisfaction, and success, forming the very foundation of an individual's or community's prosperity. It does not directly mean prosperity but describes the process or result that causes it.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَقَدْ صَدَقَ اللَّهُ رَسُولَهُ الرُّؤْيَا بِالْحَقِّ لَتَدْخُلُنَّ الْمَسْجِدَ الْحَرَامَ إِن شَاءَ اللَّهُ آمِنِينَ مُحَلِّقِينَ رُءُوسَكُمْ وَمُقَصِّرِينَ لَا تَخَافُونَ فَعَلِمَ مَا لَمْ تَعْلَمُوا فَجَعَلَ مِن دُونِ ذَلِكَ فَتْحًا قَرِيبًا» (48 / 27)\nTranslation: Allah has confirmed His Messenger's vision with truth: \"You will surely enter al-Masjid al-Haram, if Allah wills, in safety, with your heads shaved and [hair] shortened, not fearing [anyone].\" He knew what you did not know and has arranged before that a conquest near [at hand]."
    }
  ],
  "665": [
    {
      "id": 3047,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Covenant - Covenant",
      "hw": "معاہدہ",
      "s": "«اتي» in the context of a covenant denotes the inevitable fulfillment and practical manifestation of a promise, decree, or its consequences.",
      "d": "«اتي» means \"to come,\" \"to bring,\" or \"to give.\" When used in the concept of a 'covenant' (i.e., a promise or decree), it refers to the certainty of that promise or decree coming to pass and its results becoming manifest in reality. It emphasizes that what has been decided or promised will inevitably occur. It describes the final enforcement of the covenant's terms or the appearance of its outcome, not the covenant itself.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«أَتَىٰ أَمْرُ اللَّهِ فَلَا تَسْتَعْجِلُوهُ ۚ سُبْحَانَهُ وَتَعَالَىٰ عَمَّا يُشْرِكُونَ» (16 / 1)\nTranslation: The command of Allah has come, so do not seek to hasten it. Exalted is He and high above what they associate with Him."
    },
    {
      "id": 3051,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Covenant - Covenant",
      "hw": "معاہدہ",
      "s": "«رضو» refers to a covenant that is based on the mutual consent, pleasure, and complete agreement of the parties involved.",
      "d": "«رضو» means to be pleased, to be content, to approve, or to accept something. When used in the context of a covenant, it clarifies the nature of that covenant as being established through the complete mutual consent, pleasure, and sincere approval of the parties, not under coercion or compulsion. It highlights the free will and genuine willingness of the individuals involved in the covenant, without which no covenant is considered complete and valid in the sight of Shariah. It means the parties have willingly accepted any condition or responsibility.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَإِنْ أَرَادَا فِصَالًا عَن تَرَاضٍ مِّنْهُمَا وَتَشَاوُرٍ فَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَيْهِمَا ۗ» (2 / 233)\nTranslation: But if they both desire weaning by mutual consent and consultation, there is no blame upon them."
    }
  ],
  "666": [
    {
      "id": 3052,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ahmad - Ahmad",
      "hw": "احمد",
      "s": "«جيا» refers to the coming, arrival, and manifestation of Ahmad's prophethood.",
      "d": "«جيا» means \"to come,\" \"to bring (honor),\" or \"to be present.\" This word, when used in the context of Ahmad, specifically points to that blessed advent and manifestation of Prophethood of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) which was foretold in previous heavenly scriptures. Its profound meaning relates to the fulfillment of prophecies and the clarification of the truth. It highlights the reality that the coming of Ahmad (peace be upon him) was not an ordinary event but the fulfillment of a great prophecy that came as a source of guidance for humanity.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَ عِيسَى ابْنُ مَرْيَمَ يَا بَنِي إِسْرَائِيلَ إِنِّي رَسُولُ اللَّهِ إِلَيْكُمْ مُصَدِّقًا لِّمَا بَيْنَ يَدَيَّ مِنَ التَّوْرَاةِ وَمُبَشِّرًا بِرَسُولٍ يَأْتِي مِن بَعْدِي اسْمُهُ أَحْمَدُ ۖ فَلَمَّا جَاءَهُم بِالْبَيِّنَاتِ قَالُوا هَٰذَا سِحْرٌ مُّبِينٌ» (61 / 6)\nTranslation: And [mention] when Jesus, the son of Mary, said, \"O children of Israel, indeed I am the messenger of Allah to you confirming what came before me of the Torah and bringing good tidings of a messenger to come after me, whose name is Ahmad.\" But when he came to them with clear evidences, they said, \"This is obvious magic.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3055,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ahmad - Ahmad",
      "hw": "احمد",
      "s": "In the context of 'Ahmad', the specific meaning of «يدي» emerges as a sign of power, authority, and divine support.",
      "d": "«يدي» means hand or the manifestation of power and authority. This word is derived from the Arabic root 'ي-د-ي' which denotes one's strength, ownership, or control. Unlike other synonyms such as 'كف' (palm) or 'ذراع' (forearm), in 'يدي' the aspect of vastness, encompassment, and complete authority is predominant. For example: The Quran states:\n«إِنَّ ٱلَّذِينَ يُبَايِعُونَكَ إِنَّمَا يُبَايِعُونَ ٱللَّهَ يَدُ ٱللَّهِ فَوْقَ أَيْدِيهِمْ» (48 / 10)\nTranslation: \"Indeed, those who pledge allegiance to you, they are actually pledging allegiance to Allah. The hand of Allah is over their hands.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3056,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ahmad - Ahmad",
      "hw": "احمد",
      "s": "In the context of 'Ahmad', the specific meaning of 'ati' pertains to the prophecy of the advent of prophethood, rather than simply coming or bringing.",
      "d": "'ati' means the occurrence of something or coming with a specific purpose. This word differs from other synonyms like 'jaa' in that it emphasizes the fulfillment of a specific purpose or promise. For example, in the Quran: «وَمُبَشِّرًا بِرَسُولٍ يَأْتِي مِن بَعْدِي اسْمُهُ أَحْمَدُ» (61 / 6) Translation: And [I am] a bringer of good tidings of a messenger to come after me, his name is Ahmad."
    }
  ],
  "667": [
    {
      "id": 3058,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Al-Ahzab - Al-Ahzab",
      "hw": "احزاب",
      "s": "In the context of Al-Ahzab, this word 'kun' describes the specific aspect of the emergence or formation of enemy groups.",
      "d": "'kun' means to come into existence or to manifest a state or condition. This word differs from other synonyms like 'khalq' (to create) or 'wujud' (to exist) in that it emphasizes the process or change of something coming into being. For example, in the Quran: «وَإِذْ يَقُولُ الْمُنَافِقُونَ وَالَّذِينَ فِي قُلُوبِهِم مَّرَضٌ مَّا وَعَدَنَا اللَّهُ وَرَسُولُهُ إِلَّا غُرُورًا * وَإِذْ قَالَت طَّائِفَةٌ مِّنْهُمْ يَا أَهْلَ يَثْرِبَ لَا مُقَامَ لَكُمْ فَارْجِعُوا وَيَسْتَأْذِنُ فَرِيقٌ مِّنْهُمُ النَّبِيَّ يَقُولُونَ إِنَّ بُيُوتَنَا عَوْرَةٌ وَمَا هِيَ بِعَوْرَةٍ ۖ إِن يُرِيدُونَ إِلَّا فِرَارًا * وَلَوْ دُخِلَتْ عَلَيْهِم مِّنْ أَقْطَارِهَا ثُمَّ سُئِلُوا الْفِتْنَةَ لَآتَوْهَا وَمَا تَلَبَّثُوا بِهَا إِلَّا يَسِيرًا» (33 / 12-14) Translation: And when the hypocrites and those in whose hearts was disease said, 'What Allah and His Messenger have promised us is nothing but delusion.' And when a group of them said, 'O people of Yathrib, there is no stability for you, so return.' And another group asked permission of the Prophet, saying, 'Indeed, our houses are exposed,' while they were not exposed. They intended only to flee. And if they had been entered upon from all its borders and then had been asked for aid, they would have done it and not hesitated about it except briefly."
    },
    {
      "id": 3059,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Al-Ahzab - Al-Ahzab",
      "hw": "احزاب",
      "s": "'Haqq' means to establish the truth of Allah and clarify His reality, such as the command in Al-Ahzab to prioritize the fear of Allah.",
      "d": "'Haqq' means to establish something as true and real with full certainty and investigation. This word differs from other words like 'sidq' or 'thabat' in that the aspect of completion, investigation, and being truly real is predominant in 'haqq'. For example, in the Quran: «وَاللَّهُ أَحَقُّ أَن تَخْشَوْهُ» (33 / 37) Translation: And Allah is more worthy that you should fear Him. In this verse, the use of 'ahqqu' refers to giving precedence to Allah's right of worship and fear over all other rights, reflecting the original meaning of 'haqq'."
    },
    {
      "id": 3060,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Al-Ahzab - Al-Ahzab",
      "hw": "احزاب",
      "s": "'Wa'ada' means to make a promise when hope is given to someone.",
      "d": "'Wa'ada' means to promise. To give hope regarding something. It is a well-known word (m. l). And it is unilateral. And 'akhalfa al-wa'd' means to fail to fulfill a promise. For example, in the Quran: «وَ قَالَ  الشَّیۡطٰنُ لَمَّا قُضِیَ الۡاَمۡرُ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ وَعَدَکُمۡ وَعۡدَ الۡحَقِّ وَ وَعَدۡتُّکُمۡ فَاَخۡلَفۡتُکُمۡ» (14 / 22) Translation: And when the command is fulfilled, Satan will say, 'Indeed, Allah promised you a promise of truth, and I promised you, but I failed you.'"
    }
  ],
  "668": [
    {
      "id": 3062,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Al-Ris - Al-Ris",
      "hw": "الرس",
      "s": "In the context of 'Al-Ris', the specific meaning of 'ud' refers to returning or reverting to something, especially the repetition of a negative or disliked action.",
      "d": "'Ud' means to return to a previous state or action. This word means to come again or repetition, but in Arabic, its usage is often in a negative context, such as returning to a bad deed. Unlike other words like 'raja' (to return), 'ud' emphasizes repetition or persistence. For example, in the Quran: «وَمَنۡ عَادَ فَأُو۟لَـٰۤئِكَ أَصۡحَـٰبُ ٱلنَّارِۖ هُمۡ فِیهَا خَـٰلِدُونَ» (2 / 275) Translation: And whoever returns [to usury] - those are the companions of the Fire; they will abide therein eternally."
    },
    {
      "id": 3063,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Al-Ris - Al-Ris",
      "hw": "الرس",
      "s": "'Kaththir' in the context of Al-Ris refers to their abundance of sins and excess, which became the cause of their punishment.",
      "d": "'Kaththir' means an increase in number or quantity, but this word not only indicates quantity but also the aspect of exceeding limits and continuity. Other words like 'zad' or 'namma' do not include such negative intensity or excess. For example, in the Quran: «كَذَّبَتْ قَبْلَهُمْ قَوْمُ نُوحٍ وَأَصْحَابُ الرَّسِّ وَثَمُودُ» (50 / 12) Translation: Before them denied the people of Noah and the companions of the Well and Thamud. In this verse, 'ashab al-Ras' refers to a people who were destroyed due to their abundance of sins and rebellion."
    },
    {
      "id": 3065,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Al-Ris - Al-Ris",
      "hw": "الرس",
      "s": "'Sahib' refers to people who are associated with a specific place or group, such as the People of Al-Ris, which is the name of a nation mentioned in the Quran.",
      "d": "'Sahib' means to accompany, to keep company, or to have a specific connection with a group or place. This word differs from other words like 'qawm' or 'ahl' in that it emphasizes practical and existential companionship rather than merely geographical or familial affiliation. For example, in the Quran: «كَذَّبَتْ قَبْلَهُمْ قَوْمُ نُوحٍ وَأَصْحَابُ الرَّسِّ وَثَمُودُ» (50 / 12) Translation: Before them denied the people of Noah and the companions of the Well and Thamud."
    },
    {
      "id": 3066,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Al-Ris - Al-Ris",
      "hw": "الرس",
      "s": "'Rassasa' means to firmly embed or plant something, and in the context of 'Al-Ris', it refers to a city that was deeply entrenched in misguidance.",
      "d": "'Rassasa' means to embed something in the ground, to fix it, or to establish it permanently. This word differs from other words like 'dafan' (to bury) or 'gharaza' (to penetrate deeply) because it specifically indicates a durable and undeniable existence. In the Quran, this word was used for a people who were so entrenched in their rebellion and misguidance that their destruction became inevitable. For example, in the Quran: «وَعَادًا وَثَمُودَ وَأَصْحَابَ الرَّسِّ» (25 / 38) Translation: And [We destroyed] 'Ad and Thamud and the companions of the Well."
    }
  ],
  "669": [
    {
      "id": 3067,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bay'ah - Bay'ah",
      "hw": "بیعت",
      "s": "In the context of Bay'ah, this word 'bay'' symbolizes a covenant or symbolic transaction of loyalty, where a contract of obedience and support is made.",
      "d": "'Bay'' means to make a contract of giving or receiving. In Bay'ah, this word is used not for material trade but for a spiritual and practical covenant (such as loyalty to the Messenger of Allah ﷺ). It differs from other words like 'shira' (to buy) in that 'bay'' involves the completion of a relationship with mutual consent. For example, in the Quran: «إِنَّ اللَّهَ اشْتَرَىٰ مِنَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ أَنفُسَهُمْ وَأَمْوَالَهُم بِأَنَّ لَهُمُ الْجَنَّةَ» (9 / 111) Translation: Indeed, Allah has purchased from the believers their lives and their properties [in exchange] for that they will have Paradise."
    },
    {
      "id": 3068,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bay'ah - Bay'ah",
      "hw": "بیعت",
      "s": "In the context of Bay'ah, 'ati' signifies the specific act of stepping forward or presenting oneself to accept a covenant or commitment.",
      "d": "'Ati' means to come, bring, or be present for a specific purpose or action. This word differs from other words like 'jaa' (to come) or 'qaddam' (to step forward) in that it emphasizes advancing with a clear purpose or covenant. In Bay'ah, this act is a symbolic movement of loyalty or commitment acceptance. For example, in the Quran: «إِنَّ الَّذِينَ يُبَايِعُونَكَ إِنَّمَا يُبَايِعُونَ اللَّهَ يَدُ اللَّهِ فَوْقَ أَيْدِيهِمْ» (48 / 10) Translation: Indeed, those who pledge allegiance to you, [O Muhammad], are actually pledging allegiance to Allah. The hand of Allah is over their hands."
    },
    {
      "id": 3069,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bay'ah - Bay'ah",
      "hw": "بیعت",
      "s": "«يدي» in the context of Bay'ah signifies the symbolic movement of the hand, which is evidence of the strength of the covenant and practical commitment.",
      "d": "«يدي» means the sign of hand or power, derived from the Arabic word «یَد» (hand). In Bay'ah, this word is not limited to merely joining hands physically, but it includes a pledge of loyalty, obedience, and responsibility. It is different from other words like «قَسَم» (oath) or «عَهْد» (covenant) in that it is a true symbol of practical cooperation and connection. For example: The Quran says: «إِنَّ الَّذِينَ يُبَايِعُونَكَ إِنَّمَا يُبَايِعُونَ اللَّهَ يَدُ اللَّهِ فَوْقَ أَيْدِيهِمْ» (48 / 10) Translation: Indeed, those who pledge allegiance to you, they are actually pledging allegiance to Allah, and the Hand of Allah is over their hands."
    },
    {
      "id": 3070,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bay'ah - Bay'ah",
      "hw": "بیعت",
      "s": "«عهد» in the context of bay'ah signifies a firm covenant and pledge based on mutual consent and responsibility.",
      "d": "«عهد» means to bind something firmly, to establish a promise or obligation. This word is distinguished from other words like 'وعدہ' (promise) or 'قسم' (oath) in that it emphasizes a two-way agreement, legal or moral responsibility, and continuity. For example: The Quran states:\n«الَّذِينَ يَنقُضُونَ عَهْدَ اللَّهِ مِن بَعْدِ مِيثَاقِهِ» (2 / 27)\nTranslation: \"Those who break the covenant of Allah after having firmly bound it.\""
    }
  ],
  "670": [
    {
      "id": 3072,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Unity - Unity",
      "hw": "اتحاد",
      "s": "The distinctive feature of «ولي» is that in unity, it describes not only closeness and friendship but also a strong bond of guardianship and support.",
      "d": "«ولي» means to be near, to become a friend, to guard or supervise. This word differs from others like 'صديق' (friend) or 'نصير' (helper) in that it involves a deep connection of brotherhood, responsibility, and mutual cooperation. In the context of unity, it is not merely superficial association but indicates a connection from the depths of the heart. For example: The Quran states:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا لَا تَتَّخِذُوا الْيَهُودَ وَالنَّصَارَىٰ أَوْلِيَاءَ» (5 / 51)\nTranslation: \"O you who have believed, do not take the Jews and the Christians as allies (or guardians).\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3074,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Unity - Unity",
      "hw": "اتحاد",
      "s": "«سبل» in the context of unity signifies different paths or methods that lead towards a common objective.",
      "d": "«سبل» is linguistically derived from the root س-ب-ل which conveys the meaning of 'path' or 'method'. This word is different from other synonyms like 'طریق' (way) or 'منہج' (method) in that it emphasizes multiple and diverse paths that guide towards mutual harmony and unity. For example: The Quran states:\n«وَأَنَّ هَـٰذَا صِرَاطِي مُسْتَقِيمًا فَاتَّبِعُوهُ ۖ وَلَا تَتَّبِعُوا السُّبُلَ فَتَفَرَّقَ بِكُمْ عَن سَبِيلِهِ» (6 / 153)\nTranslation: \"And that this is My straight path, so follow it; and do not follow the other paths, lest they separate you from His way.\""
    }
  ],
  "671": [
    {
      "id": 3079,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Mihrab - Mihrab",
      "hw": "محراب",
      "s": "The specific meaning of «خشي» in the context of mihrab is to describe the state of worship with God-consciousness and humility.",
      "d": "«خشي» means a respectful fear that arises in the heart due to someone's greatness and awe, expressing deep humility during worship. This word is different from general fear (e.g., خوف, وَجَل) because the element of reverence and love predominates in it. For example: The Quran states:\n«إِذْ نَادَىٰ رَبَّهُ نِدَاءً خَفِيًّا» (19 / 3)\nTranslation: \"When he called his Lord with a quiet invocation.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3080,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Mihrab - Mihrab",
      "hw": "محراب",
      "s": "The specific nuance of «ضرر» in the context of 'mihrab' expresses the concept of causing harm or injury, which includes any kind of physical or spiritual damage.",
      "d": "«ضرر» means to cause harm to someone, to inflict injury, or to worsen their condition. This word is different from other words like 'أذى' (harm) in that 'ضرر' more clearly and severely implies loss, whereas 'أذى' can also denote temporary harm. For example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَا تُضَارُّوهُنَّ لِتُضَيِّقُوا عَلَيْهِنَّ» (الطلاق / 6)\nTranslation: \"And do not harm them to make things difficult for them.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3081,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Mihrab - Mihrab",
      "hw": "محراب",
      "s": "«خنزر» refers to the protrusion or curvature in the structure of the mihrab.",
      "d": "«خنزر» means for something to protrude or to assume a curved shape. This word is different from other words like 'قوس' (arch) or 'انحناء' (bending) in that it specifically describes the roundedness and prominent structure of the mihrab. For example: The Quran states:\n«فَهَنِيئًا لَّكَ وَأَتْبَاعَكَ» (۳۷ / ۵۳)\nTranslation: \"So [it is] good for you and your followers.\" (Note: The word 'فَهَنِيئًا' is not related to the root of 'خنزر', but an example is given in the context to explain the structure of the mihrab. Note: The mention of 'محراب' in the Quran is in Surah Al-Imran (37), but in the mentioned verse, the root 'خنزر' is not used. It is necessary to point out the fundamental error in this analysis: the original root of 'محراب' is 'ح ر ب', which relates to the specific place of worship, while there is no connection of the root 'خنزر' in the Quran. Here, the analysis has been presented based on the incorrect root ('خنزر') provided by the user.)"
    }
  ],
  "672": [
    {
      "id": 3084,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Animals - Animals",
      "hw": "جانور",
      "s": "«حلل» describes the property of being halal in relation to animals, i.e., those animals that are permissible to eat according to Islamic Shariah.",
      "d": "«حلل» means to declare something halal or permissible. This word is derived from the trilateral root ح-ل-ل which encompasses meanings such as analysis (to open), dissolution (to enter), and permissibility (to be lawful). In the context of animals, it is distinguished from other words like 'طیب' (good) or 'مباح' (permitted) in that it is specifically used in contrast to prohibited/haram under the injunctions of Shariah.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«أُحِلَّتْ لَكُم بَهِيمَةُ الْأَنْعَامِ» (5 / 1)\nTranslation: \"The beasts of cattle have been made halal for you (except those that will be recited to you).\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3085,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Animal - Animal",
      "hw": "جانور",
      "s": "«اكل» denotes the characteristic of animals eating, which includes chewing, swallowing, and digesting.",
      "d": "«اكل» means to eat, swallow, or use. This word generally refers to the act of consumption by living beings (particularly animals), which is distinct from other words like «طعام» (food) or «شرب» (drink), as it encompasses the complete process of nourishment. For example: The Quran states: «وَآخَرُ يَعْلُوهُ مِنَ الطَّعَامِ تَأْكُلُهُ الطَّيْرُ» (12 / 36) Translation: And another (in a dream) with a loaf of bread on his head, and birds are eating from it."
    },
    {
      "id": 3086,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Animal - Animal",
      "hw": "جانور",
      "s": "«كلل» denotes animals being surrounded or their collective gathering.",
      "d": "«كلل» means to encircle something, to encompass, or to gather. This word is distinct from synonyms like 'قطيع' (herd) or 'جماعة' (group) in that it specifically emphasizes the complete encirclement or assembly of a group. For example: The Quran states: «وَالطَّيْرَ صَافَّاتٍ كُلٌّ قَدْ عَلِمَ صَلَاتَهُ وَتَسْبِيحَهُ» (24 / 41) Translation: And the birds (prostrate) with wings outspread, each has known its prayer and its glorification. In this verse, 'كلٌّ' refers to each bird's individual inclusion in the assembly and its innate awareness of worship, clarifying the profound meaning of 'كلل'."
    }
  ],
  "673": [
    {
      "id": 3087,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ants - Ants",
      "hw": "چیونٹیاں",
      "s": "The specific meaning of «ودي» pertains to the movement and social life of ants, reflecting their natural harmony and subtle coordination.",
      "d": "«ودي» means to move something with softness and flexibility or to work in harmony for one's purpose. This word differs from other words like «سعي» or «حرکت» in that it does not merely mean physical movement but also includes purposefulness and social balance.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَحُشِرَ لِسُلَيْمَانَ جُنُودُهُ مِنَ الْجِنِّ وَالْإِنسِ وَالطَّيْرِ فَهُمْ يُوزَعُونَ حَتَّىٰ إِذَا أَتَوْا عَلَىٰ وَادِ النَّمْلِ قَالَتْ نَمْلَةٌ يَا أَيُّهَا النَّمْلُ ادْخُلُوا مَسَاكِنَكُمْ» (27 / 14) Translation: And for Solomon, his armies of jinn, humans, and birds were gathered, then they were organized until when they came to the valley of the ants, an ant said: O ants! Enter your dwellings."
    },
    {
      "id": 3089,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ants - Ants",
      "hw": "چیونٹیاں",
      "s": "«اتي» carries a specific meaning referring to the unique collective behavior, precautionary measures, and movement of ants, as described in Surah An-Naml.",
      "d": "«اتي» means to move toward something, to come, or to bring, but this word does not signify mere general movement; rather, it conveys movement that is purposeful, strategic, or part of a collective action. In the context of ants, it highlights their organized method of work, their natural wisdom in avoiding danger, and their ability to warn one another. Other terms (e.g., سَارَ, مَشَى) lack this nuance.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«حَتَّىٰ إِذَا أَتَوْا عَلَىٰ وَادِ النَّمْلِ قَالَتْ نَمْلَةٌ يَا أَيُّهَا النَّمْلُ ادْخُلُوا مَسَاكِنَكُمْ» (27 / 18)\nTranslation: Until when they came upon the valley of the ants, an ant said, 'O ants, enter your dwellings.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3090,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ants - Ants",
      "hw": "چیونٹیاں",
      "s": "«نمل» denotes a specific type of ant that is small and organized, as mentioned in the Quran in the story of Prophet Sulaiman (peace be upon him).",
      "d": "«نمل» means small ants that live socially. This word is distinct from general terms like 'دابۃ' (creature/insect) because it specifically refers to those ants known for their social organization and intelligence. For example: The Quran states: «حَتَّىٰ إِذَا أَتَوْا عَلَىٰ وَادِ النَّمْلِ قَالَتْ نَمْلَةٌ يَا أَيُّهَا النَّمْلُ ادْخُلُوا مَسَاكِنَكُمْ» (27 / 18) Translation: Until when they came upon the valley of the ants, an ant said, 'O ants, enter your dwellings.'"
    }
  ],
  "674": [
    {
      "id": 3092,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Monkey - Monkey",
      "hw": "بندر",
      "s": "«قرد» specifically denotes a type of monkey that is generally associated with a degraded and transformed form.",
      "d": "«قرد» means a monkey that has been transformed from its natural state into a condition of disgrace. This word is distinguished from other synonyms (such as 'سعدان' or 'رِئْوَان') in that it is specifically associated with transformation of form and moral degradation. For example: The Quran states: «وَلَقَدْ عَلِمْتُمُ الَّذِينَ اعْتَدَوْا مِنكُمْ فِي السَّبْتِ فَقُلْنَا لَهُمْ كُونُوا قِرَدَةً خَاسِئِينَ» (2 / 65) Translation: And you have already known those who transgressed among you concerning the Sabbath, so We said to them, 'Be apes, despised.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3093,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Monkey - Monkey",
      "hw": "بندر",
      "s": "«كون» has a specific usage in the Quran in the context of an immediate and divine command for transformation, such as the command to become monkeys.",
      "d": "«كون» means existence, state, or the command for something to be. This word is distinct from other words (such as 'خلق' or 'جعل') in that it emphasizes the immediate or legislative coming into existence of something. For example: The Quran states: «وَلَقَدْ عَلِمْتُمُ الَّذِينَ اعْتَدَوْا مِنكُمْ فِي السَّبْتِ فَقُلْنَا لَهُمْ كُونُوا قِرَدَةً خَاسِئِينَ» (2 / 65) Translation: And you have already known those who transgressed among you concerning the Sabbath, so We said to them, 'Be apes, despised.'"
    }
  ],
  "675": [
    {
      "id": 3097,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Apostasy - Apostasy",
      "hw": "ارتداد",
      "s": "In the context of apostasy, the meaning of «توب» refers to returning from sin to Allah and indicates the acceptance of repentance.",
      "d": "«توب» means to return to Allah with deep remorse and sincerity. This word is distinct from other terms like «إنابة» or «رجوع» in that it specifically emphasizes abandoning sin and complete return to the Lord's mercy, whereas in contrast to apostasy (turning from religion), this act of repentance also includes the aspect of renewing faith.\nFor example, the Quran states: «يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا تُوبُوا إِلَى اللَّهِ تَوْبَةً نَّصُوحًا» (66 / 8) Translation: O you who have believed, repent to Allah with sincere repentance."
    },
    {
      "id": 3098,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Apostasy - Apostasy",
      "hw": "ارتداد",
      "s": "«سبل» in the context of apostasy denotes the paths or ways that lead one to misguidance or deviation.",
      "d": "«سبل» means various paths or ways, often indicating negative and scattered directions. This word differs from other synonyms like «صراط» (clear, straight path) or «طریق» (common path) in that «سبل» implies multiplicity and dispersion, especially used for misleading paths.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَلَا تَتَّبِعُوا السُّبُلَ فَتَفَرَّقَ بِكُمْ عَن سَبِيلِهِ» (6 / 153) Translation: And do not follow the ways, lest you be separated from His way."
    }
  ],
  "676": [
    {
      "id": 3102,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Apostate - Apostate",
      "hw": "مرتد",
      "s": "«هدي» in the context of an apostate describes the specific quality of abandoning the guidance granted by Allah.",
      "d": "«هدي» means guidance or showing the right path. This word is derived from the root 'ہ-د-ی' and is distinct from other words like 'رشد' or 'دعوة' in that it specifically emphasizes divine guidance and heartfelt acceptance. An apostate is one who, after accepting this guidance, turns away from it. For example: The Quran states: «وَمَن يُرِدِ اللَّهُ فِتْنَتَهُ فَلَن تَمْلِكَ لَهُ مِنَ اللَّهِ شَيْئًا ۚ أُولَٰئِكَ الَّذِينَ لَمْ يُرِدِ اللَّهُ أَن يُطَهِّرَ قُلُوبَهُمْ ۚ لَهُمْ فِي الدُّنْيَا خِزْيٌ ۖ وَلَهُمْ فِي الْآخِرَةِ عَذَابٌ عَظِيمٌ» (5 / 41) Translation: And whoever Allah wills to afflict—you cannot for him possess anything from Allah. Those are the ones whose hearts Allah did not will to purify. For them is disgrace in this life, and for them in the Hereafter is a great punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 3104,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Apostate - Apostate",
      "hw": "مرتد",
      "s": "«ردد» specifically means 'to return' or 'to revert', which in the meaning of 'مرتد' (apostate) signifies deviation from religious belief or apostasy.",
      "d": "«ردد» means to return something, to do repeatedly, or to revert to an original state. This word is distinct from synonyms like 'رجع' (general return) in that it specifically conveys the quality of continuity, insistence, or complete deviation. In the context of an apostate, this meaning is centered on abandoning faith and reverting to disbelief. For example: The Quran states: «وَمَن يَرْتَدِدْ مِنكُمْ عَن دِينِهِ فَيَمُتْ وَهُوَ كَافِرٌ فَأُولَٰئِكَ حَبِطَتْ أَعْمَالُهُمْ فِي الدُّنْيَا وَالْآخِرَةِ» (2 / 217) Translation: And whoever of you reverts from his religion and dies while he is a disbeliever—for those, their deeds have become worthless in this world and the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 3106,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Apostate - Apostate",
      "hw": "مرتد",
      "s": "«شطن» in the context of an apostate signifies the severe nature of turning away from faith and straying far from the truth.",
      "d": "«شطن» means to be far away from something, to adopt a rebellious attitude, or to deviate from the path of truth. This word is distinct from other words like 'فسق' or 'کفر' in that it refers to plunging into the depths of falsehood after abandoning faith and becoming a follower of satanic whispers. For example: The Quran states: «وَكَذَٰلِكَ جَعَلْنَا لِكُلِّ نَبِيٍّ عَدُوًّا شَيَاطِينَ الْإِنسِ وَالْجِنِّ» (6 / 112) Translation: And thus We have made for every prophet an enemy—devils from mankind and jinn."
    }
  ],
  "677": [
    {
      "id": 3109,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Arafat - Arafat",
      "hw": "عرفات",
      "s": "«Hady» refers to the sacrificial animal offered during Hajj at Arafat, presented to seek Allah's pleasure.",
      "d": "«Hady» means a sacrificial animal or offering presented in the way of Allah, specifically performed during Hajj at Arafat. The term derives from the root 'h-d-y', whose core meaning is 'guidance' or 'to present an offering'. Unlike other terms like 'ḍaḥiyah' (general sacrifice) or 'qurbān' (vow), 'hady' is particularly associated with the rites of Hajj and the geographical context of Arafat. For example: The Quran states: «وَأَتِمُّوا الْحَجَّ وَالْعُمْرَةَ لِلَّهِ ۚ فَإِنْ أُحْصِرْتُمْ فَمَا اسْتَيْسَرَ مِنَ الْهَدْيِ» (2 / 196) Translation: And complete the Hajj and Umrah for Allah. But if you are prevented, then [offer] what is available of the sacrifice."
    },
    {
      "id": 3110,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Arafat - Arafat",
      "hw": "عرفات",
      "s": "«Baghī» describes a specific state of transgression or injustice in the context of Arafat, exceeding bounds.",
      "d": "«Baghī» means to exceed a limit or norm, to choose the path of oppression or injustice. This word differs from others like 'ẓulm' (oppression) or 'ʿudwān' (aggression) in that 'baghī' generally carries the nuance of arrogance, selfish desire, or deviation from the truth. For example: The Quran states: «وَإِن طَائِفَتَانِ مِنَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ اقْتَتَلُوا فَأَصْلِحُوا بَيْنَهُمَا ۖ فَإِن بَغَتْ إِحْدَاهُمَا عَلَى الْأُخْرَىٰ فَقَاتِلُوا الَّتِي تَبْغِي حَتَّىٰ تَفِيءَ إِلَىٰ أَمْرِ اللَّهِ» (49 / 9) Translation: And if two factions among the believers should fight, then make settlement between them. But if one of them oppresses the other, then fight against the one that oppresses until it returns to the decree of Allah."
    }
  ],
  "678": [
    {
      "id": 3114,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Armor - Armor",
      "hw": "زرہ",
      "s": "«Bās» denotes a specific state of donning armor or preparing for battle, encompassing the concepts of protection and confrontation.",
      "d": "«Bās» means to put on or prepare something, particularly martial equipment or armor. This word differs from others like «libs» (general wearing) in that it is used in the context of danger or confrontation. For example: The Quran states: «وَأَلَنَّا لَهُ الْحَدِيدَ أَنِ اعْمَلْ سَابِغَاتٍ وَقَدِّرْ فِي السَّرْدِ ۖ وَاعْمَلُوا صَالِحًا ۖ إِنِّي بِمَا تَعْمَلُونَ بَصِيرٌ» (34 / 10-11) Translation: And We made for him [David] iron, [commanding], 'Make full coats of mail and calculate [precisely] the links, and work [righteousness]. Indeed, I am seeing what you do.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3115,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Armor - Armor",
      "hw": "زرہ",
      "s": "«Sarbal» signifies the act of making or wearing armor, emphasizing the preparation or use of a protective garment.",
      "d": "«Sarbal» means to put on or prepare something, especially a protective garment like armor. This word differs from others like «libās» (general clothing) or «taqiyyah» (to cover) in that it stresses the preparation of a protective covering and its purpose. For example: The Quran states: «وَجَعَلَ لَكُمْ سَرَابِيلَ تَقِيكُمُ الْحَرَّ وَسَرَابِيلَ تَقِيكُم بَأْسَكُمْ» (16 / 81) Translation: And He has made for you garments which protect you from the heat and garments which protect you from your [own] violence."
    },
    {
      "id": 3116,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Armor - Armor",
      "hw": "زرہ",
      "s": "«Ẓill» in the context of armor conveys the meaning of covering or a protective canopy, indicating something that safeguards.",
      "d": "«Ẓill» means to cover something, to provide shade, or to encircle protectively. This word differs from others like 'ghatā' (complete covering) or 'star' (concealing) in that it specifically emphasizes the concept of protection or a comforting shade. For instance, armor (bakraṭ) is also a type of ẓill (protective covering) that shields the body. For example: The Quran states: «وَظَلَّلْنَا عَلَيْكُمُ الْغَمَامَ» (2 / 57) Translation: And We shaded you with clouds. Here, 'ẓall' describes the cloud canopy that provided protection and comfort to the Children of Israel, highlighting the protective aspect akin to armor."
    }
  ],
  "679": [
    {
      "id": 3118,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Army - Army",
      "hw": "فوج",
      "s": "«Laqī» in the specific sense of an army refers to encountering a group or army in an unexpected or significant battle or meeting.",
      "d": "«Laqī» means to come face-to-face with something or someone directly, especially in unexpected or critical circumstances. This word differs from other synonyms like 'wājaha' (to confront) or 'iltaqā' (to meet) in that it often conveys the meaning of a sudden or inevitable clash, a spiritual experience, or a fated encounter. For example: The Quran states: «يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا إِذَا لَقِيتُمُ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا زَحْفًا فَلَا تُوَلُّوهُمُ الْأَدْبَارَ» (8 / 15) Translation: O you who have believed, when you meet those who disbelieve advancing [for battle], do not turn to them your backs [in flight]."
    },
    {
      "id": 3119,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Army - Army",
      "hw": "فوج",
      "s": "«Jamaʿa» is a general word for gathering. It is used to bring together different parts of one thing or different things together.",
      "d": "«Jamaʿa» is a word that comes for gathering different parts of one thing, or different things together. These things can be animate or inanimate.\nFor example: For animate things: The Divine command states:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ قَالَ لَہُمُ النَّاسُ اِنَّ النَّاسَ قَدۡ جَمَعُوۡا لَکُمۡ» ( 3/173 )\nTranslation: When people came to them and said, 'The disbelievers have gathered a great army against you.'\nAnd for inanimate things: The Divine command states:\n«الَّذِیۡ جَمَعَ مَالًا وَّ عَدَّدَہٗ» ( 104/2 )\nTranslation: Who has gathered wealth and counted it.\nThen the word 'jamaʿa' is used for gathering apparent things. It is also used metaphorically.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَتَوَلّٰی فِرۡعَوۡنُ فَجَمَعَ کَیۡدَہٗ ثُمَّ اَتٰی» ( 20/60 )\nTranslation: Then Pharaoh turned away and gathered his plan, then came [to the confrontation]. (Uthmaniؒ)"
    }
  ],
  "680": [
    {
      "id": 3123,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Particle - Particle",
      "hw": "ذرہ",
      "s": "«Dharrar» means to indicate extremely fine and scattered particles that are negligible in weight and quantity.",
      "d": "«Dharrar» means small, scattered particles dispersed by wind or movement, also carrying nuances of subtlety and weakness. This word differs from other synonyms like «ḥabbah» (grain) or «nuqṭah» (dot) in that it specifically refers to scattered, ungraspable, and extremely minute components. For example: The Quran states: «فَمَن يَعْمَلْ مِثْقَالَ ذَرَّةٍ خَيْرًا يَرَهُۥ» (۹۹/۷) Translation: So whoever does an atom's weight of good will see it."
    },
    {
      "id": 3124,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Particle - Particle",
      "hw": "ذرہ",
      "s": "«Ṣughr» denotes the characteristic of extreme smallness and minuteness in the meaning of a particle.",
      "d": "«Ṣughr» means something is extremely small in volume, quantity, or worth. This word differs from other synonyms like 'daq' (fine) or 'ḥaqīr' (insignificant) in that 'ṣughr' emphasizes the extreme limit of smallness and its inherent weakness. For example: The Quran states: «وَمَن يَعْمَلْ مِثْقَالَ ذَرَّةٍ شَرًّا يَرَهُ» (99 / 8) Translation: And whoever does an atom's weight of evil will see it. In this verse, 'dharrah' is used in the sense of 'ṣughr', indicating an extremely negligible amount of good or evil."
    },
    {
      "id": 3125,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Particle - Particle",
      "hw": "ذرہ",
      "s": "«Kubr» in the context of a particle has been used to mean largeness in size or importance, signifying grandeur and vastness rather than arrogance.",
      "d": "«Kubr» means something is large in volume, quantity, or rank. This word differs from other synonyms like «ʿaẓm» (physical bigness) or «jalāl» (majestic) in that it focuses solely on magnitude or elevated status, not on pride or arrogance. For example: The Quran states: «وَمَا يَعْزُبُ عَن رَّبِّكَ مِن مِّثْقَالِ ذَرَّةٍ فِي الْأَرْضِ وَلَا فِي السَّمَاءِ وَلَا أَصْغَرَ مِن ذَٰلِكَ وَلَا أَكْبَرَ إِلَّا فِي كِتَابٍ مُّبِينٍ» (10 / 61) Translation: And not an atom's weight escapes your Lord on the earth or in the heaven, nor [is there] anything smaller than that or greater, but it is in a clear register."
    },
    {
      "id": 3126,
      "a": "ذ",
      "h": "Particle - Particle",
      "hw": "ذرہ",
      "s": "«كتب» in the context of a particle describes the specific meaning of being decreed or written down by Allah, which encompasses every particle.",
      "d": "«كتب» means to decree something, to issue a written command, or to record in divine knowledge and predestination. This word is distinct from other words like 'قدر' (to determine a measure) or 'خلق' (to create) in that it emphasizes a written decree or eternal knowledge. For example: The Quran states: «وَمَا تَسۡقُطُ مِن وَرَقَةٍ إِلَّا یَعۡلَمُهَا وَلَا حَبَّةࣲ فِی ظُلُمَـٰتِ ٱلۡأَرۡضِ وَلَا رَطۡبࣲ وَلَا یَابِسٍ إِلَّا فِی كِتَـٰبࣲ مُّبِینࣲ» (34 / 3) Translation: And not a leaf falls but He knows it, nor a grain in the darknesses of the earth, nor a thing moist or dry, but it is in a clear record."
    }
  ],
  "681": [
    {
      "id": 3127,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Attraction - Attraction",
      "hw": "پرکشش",
      "s": "The word «zīn» in the meaning of attraction signifies worldly adornment and deception, which is often a means of trial.",
      "d": "«zīn» means to adorn something, make it beautiful, or increase its attractiveness. This word differs from other words like 'ḥusn' (beauty) or 'jamāl' (beauty) in that 'zīn' includes the aspect of artificial or temporary beauty, which can sometimes be deceptive. For example, in the Quran: «إِنَّا جَعَلْنَا مَا عَلَى الْأَرْضِ زِينَةً لَّهَا لِنَبْلُوَهُمْ أَيُّهُمْ أَحْسَنُ عَمَلًا» (18 / 7) Translation: Indeed, We have made what is on the earth as an adornment for it to test them which of them is best in deed."
    },
    {
      "id": 3128,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Attraction - Attraction",
      "hw": "پرکشش",
      "s": "The word «kūn» in the context of attraction signifies the creative structure of the universe and its natural allure.",
      "d": "«kūn» means existence, creation, or the manifestation of something. This word comprehensively describes the aspects of material and spiritual formation, while other words like 'khalq' (to create) or 'jaʿal' (to make) are limited only to the act of creation. In 'kūn', the meanings of continuity, change, and natural allure are inherent. For example, in the Quran: «رَبَّنَا مَا خَلَقْتَ هَٰذَا بَاطِلًا» (3 / 191) Translation: Our Lord, You have not created this in vain. In this verse, the meaning of 'kūn' is reflected through 'khalq' (creation), where the alluring organization of the universe is connected to its purposefulness."
    }
  ],
  "682": [
    {
      "id": 3132,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ayyub - Ayyub",
      "hw": "ایوب",
      "s": "«Raḥmah» in the story of Ayyub (peace be upon him) refers to Allah's special mercy and granting relief after affliction.",
      "d": "«Raḥmah» means deep compassion and tenderness, especially shown towards the afflicted. This word is derived from 'raḥm' (womb), which signifies the depth of emotions and natural connection. Compared to other words like 'raʾfah' (kindness) or 'ʿaṭā' (gift), in 'raḥmah', the aspect of relief after affliction and renewal of connection is predominant. For example, in the Quran: «فَاسْتَجَبْنَا لَهُ فَكَشَفْنَا مَا بِهِ مِن ضُرٍّ وَآتَيْنَاهُ أَهْلَهُ وَمِثْلَهُم مَّعَهُمْ رَحْمَةً مِّنْ عِندِنَا» (21 / 84) Translation: So We responded to him and removed what he was suffering from, and We granted him his family and the like of them with them, as a mercy from Us."
    },
    {
      "id": 3133,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ayyub - Ayyub",
      "hw": "ایوب",
      "s": "«Dhikr» in the story of Ayyub (peace be upon him) particularly emphasizes the remembrance of patience and trial, and deriving lessons from them.",
      "d": "«Dhikr» means to refresh something verbally or spiritually, especially remembering Allah's blessings or the events of the prophets. This word goes beyond mere 'remembering' and clarifies the aspect of practical lessons and admonition. Unlike other words such as 'fikr' (contemplation) or 'tadhkirah' (reminder), 'dhikr' includes an active and purposeful remembrance.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَاذْكُرْ عَبْدَنَا أَيُّوبَ إِذْ نَادَىٰ رَبَّهُ أَنِّي مَسَّنِيَ الشَّيْطَانُ بِنُصْبٍ وَعَذَابٍ» (38 / 41)\nTranslation: And remember Our servant Ayyub, when he called to his Lord, 'Indeed, the devil has afflicted me with hardship and torment.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3134,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Job - Job",
      "hw": "ایوب",
      "s": "«اتي» (Ati) in the name of Job refers to the meaning of repentance and turning to Allah.",
      "d": "«اتي» (Ati) means to bring or to convey, but in the specific context of Job (Ayyub, peace be upon him), this word signifies the state of complete return to Allah and repentance after his trials. It differs from other words like «جاء» (ja'a - to come generally) in that the aspect of purposefulness and completion is predominant. For example: The Quran states: «وَاذْكُرْ عَبْدَنَا أَيُّوبَ إِذْ نَادَىٰ رَبَّهُ أَنِّي مَسَّنِيَ الشَّيْطَانُ بِنُصْبٍ وَعَذَابٍ» (38/41). Translation: And remember Our servant Job when he called to his Lord, 'Indeed, Satan has afflicted me with toil and torment.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3135,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Job - Job",
      "hw": "ایوب",
      "s": "«وهب» (Wahb) signifies the special concept of gifts from Allah to Job (Ayyub, peace be upon him), such as patience and offspring.",
      "d": "«وهب» (Wahb) means to grant without compensation, particularly a bestowal from Allah to His servants. This word differs from other words like «أعطى» (a'ata - to give) or «منح» (manaha - to bestow) in that it includes the special quality of generosity and grace in the act of granting. For example: The Quran states: «وَآتَيْنَاهُ أَهْلَهُ وَمِثْلَهُم مَّعَهُمْ رَحْمَةً مِّنْ عِندِنَا وَذِكْرَىٰ لِلْعَابِدِينَ» (21/84). Translation: And We granted him his family and the like of them with them as a mercy from Us and a reminder for the worshippers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3136,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Job - Job",
      "hw": "ایوب",
      "s": "«ندي» (Nadi) from Job (Ayyub, peace be upon him) expresses the specific meaning of crying out and supplication in the Divine court.",
      "d": "«ندي» (Nadi) means to call out, to cry for help, or to pray in a loud voice. This word differs from other words like «دعا» (du'a - supplication) or «صلا» (salah - prayer) in that it emphasizes turning to the Lord with urgency and humility. Job's (peace be upon him) call during his trials reflects the depth of his connection with Allah alongside his patience. For example: The Quran states: «وَأَيُّوبَ إِذْ نَادَىٰ رَبَّهُ أَنِّي مَسَّنِيَ الضُّرُّ وَأَنتَ أَرْحَمُ الرَّاحِمِينَ» (21/83). Translation: And Job when he called to his Lord, 'Indeed, affliction has touched me, and You are the most merciful of the merciful.'"
    }
  ],
  "683": [
    {
      "id": 3138,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Azar - Azar",
      "hw": "آزر",
      "s": "«ابو» (Abu) in the context of Azar signifies the meaning of a guardian or mentor, rather than a biological father.",
      "d": "«ابو» (Abu) means father, guardian, or mentor. This word in the Arabic language also denotes lineage, relational ties, or educational connection. In contrast to «والد» (walid - biological father), «ابو» is sometimes used for social or spiritual patronage as well. For example: The Quran states: «وَإِذْ قَالَ إِبْرَاهِيمُ لِأَبِيهِ آزَرَ أَتَتَّخِذُ أَصْنَامًا آلِهَةً» (6/74). Translation: And [mention] when Abraham said to his father Azar, 'Do you take idols as deities?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3139,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Azar - Azar",
      "hw": "آزر",
      "s": "«Ḍalal» in the context of Azar describes the severe form of misguidance and deviation from the path of truth, particularly the misguidance that inclines towards polytheism.",
      "d": "«Ḍalal» means to lead someone astray from the path of truth and push them into the depths of misguidance. This word is distinguished from other words like 'ghayy' or 'zallal' in that it indicates systematic and persistent misguidance, while 'zallal' denotes a temporary slip. For example, Azar (the father of Prophet Ibrahim, peace be upon him) is described in the Quran with this attribute when he persists in idolatry.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَ إِبْرَاهِيمُ لِأَبِيهِ آزَرَ أَتَتَّخِذُ أَصْنَامًا آلِهَةً ۖ إِنِّي أَرَاكَ وَقَوْمَكَ فِي ضَلَالٍ مُّبِينٍ» (6 / 74)\nTranslation: And [mention] when Ibrahim said to his father Azar, 'Do you take idols as deities? Indeed, I see you and your people in clear misguidance.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3140,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Azar - Azar",
      "hw": "آزر",
      "s": "«Rāy» means to hold a false belief or misguided opinion, particularly in the case of Azar, who was the father of Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him) and practiced idolatry.",
      "d": "«Rāy» means to understand or insist on something intellectually or doctrinally, even if it is against the truth. This word differs from other words like 'ẓann' (supposition) or 'ʿilm' (certain knowledge) because it expresses merely a mental opinion or a misguided conviction. For example, in the Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَ إِبْرَاهِيمُ لِأَبِيهِ آزَرَ أَتَتَّخِذُ أَصْنَامًا آلِهَةً ۖ إِنِّي أَرَاكَ وَقَوْمَكَ فِي ضَلَالٍ مُّبِينٍ» (6 / 74) Translation: And [mention] when Ibrahim said to his father Azar, 'Do you take idols as deities? Indeed, I see you and your people in clear misguidance.'"
    }
  ],
  "684": [
    {
      "id": 3142,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Babel - Babel",
      "hw": "بابل",
      "s": "«Ḍarar» in the context of Babel has been used in the meanings of harm, affliction, or injustice, which manifest the consequences of human arrogance and pride.",
      "d": "«Ḍarar» means to cause someone physical, financial, or spiritual harm. This word differs from other words like «adhā» (affliction) or «sharr» (evil) in that it specifically refers to practical and evident harm. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَا تُمْسِكُوهُنَّ ضِرَارًا لِّتَعْتَدُوا» (Al-Baqarah / 231) Translation: And do not retain them [i.e., wives] to harm them, that you may transgress."
    },
    {
      "id": 3146,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Babel - Babel",
      "hw": "بابل",
      "s": "«Marā» in the context of Babel has been used in the meanings of trial and testing or proving something.",
      "d": "«Marā» means to present something as a test or proof. This word differs from other synonyms like 'fitnah' (trial) or 'imtihān' (test) in that it particularly highlights the aspect of clarifying a truth or verifying it. For example, in the Quran: «وَمَا أُنزِلَ عَلَى الْمَلَكَيْنِ بِبَابِلَ هَارُوتَ وَمَارُوتَ» (2 / 102) Translation: And what was revealed to the two angels at Babylon, Harut and Marut. In this verse, at the location of 'Babel', reference is made to a test through these two angels, where the meaning of 'marā' relates to trial and confirmation of truth."
    }
  ],
  "685": [
    {
      "id": 3147,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Back - Back",
      "hw": "پیٹھ",
      "s": "«Ẓahr» is used in the meaning of back, which also signifies support, strength, or being behind something, in addition to the physical back.",
      "d": "«Ẓahr» means back or spine, which is the rear part of the human body. This word is derived from the trilateral root ظ-ه-ر, which also contains meanings of strength, support, and concealment. Unlike other synonyms such as 'pusht' (Persian), 'ẓahr' in Arabic has broader meanings, such as the manifestation of something or supporting someone. For example, in the Quran: «وَإِذْ أَخَذَ رَبُّكَ مِن بَنِي آدَمَ مِن ظُهُورِهِمْ ذُرِّيَّتَهُمْ...» (7 / 172) Translation: And [mention] when your Lord took from the children of Adam, from their backs, their descendants..."
    },
    {
      "id": 3149,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Back - Back",
      "hw": "پیٹھ",
      "s": "«Kūn» means to clarify the structure of the back and its creative status in the context of existence or creation.",
      "d": "«Kūn» means existence, state of being, or the fundamental creative quality of something. This word differs from other synonyms like «khalq» (to create) or «ṣanʿ» (to make) in that it not only refers to the general aspect of existence but also expresses the permanent and natural state of something. For example, the back (the structure of humans) is described through «kūn» as its natural and complete existence.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَإِذْ أَخَذَ رَبُّكَ مِن بَنِي آدَمَ مِن ظُهُورِهِمْ ذُرِّيَّتَهُمْ» (38 / 72)\nTranslation: And [mention] when your Lord took from the children of Adam, from their backs, their descendants.\n\n(This verse connects «ẓuhūr» (backs) with the fundamental quality of «kūn» in the context of human creation, where the origin of the human lineage is expressed through the structure of the back.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3151,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Back - Back",
      "hw": "پیٹھ",
      "s": "The term «جزي» in relation to 'back' conveys the specific sense of giving recompense or reward, implying that the result or wage of an action is placed upon the back.",
      "d": "«جزي» means to give the recompense, result, or wage of an action. This word is derived from the Arabic root j-z-y, which is associated with concepts of recompense, accounting, and reward. Unlike words such as 'thawab' (reward) or 'uqbah' (punishment), 'jazi' emphasizes the notion of raising or placing the logical or proportionate consequence of an action. For example, in the Quran: «وَمَا تُجْزَوْنَ إِلَّا مَا كُنتُمْ تَعْمَلُونَ» (الصافات / 39) Translation: You will be recompensed only for what you used to do."
    }
  ],
  "686": [
    {
      "id": 3152,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Backbiting - Backbiting",
      "hw": "غیبت",
      "s": "The term «همز» in backbiting expresses the specific aspect of harming someone's honor through gestures, nods, or whispers.",
      "d": "«همز» means to ridicule someone through gestures, eye signals, silent movements, or facial expressions, thereby humiliating them with a hidden element of evil. It differs from words like 'namimah' (open gossip) or 'buhtan' (false accusation) because it is indirect and non-verbal. For example, in the Quran: «وَيْلٌ لِّكُلِّ هُمَزَةٍ لُّمَزَةٍ» (104 / 1) Translation: Woe to every scorner and mocker. In this verse, 'humazah' refers to the person who, in others' absence, belittles them through contemptuous gestures or facial distortions."
    },
    {
      "id": 3153,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Backbiting - Backbiting",
      "hw": "غیبت",
      "s": "The term «غيب» in backbiting expresses the specific meaning of mentioning someone's faults in their absence.",
      "d": "«غيب» means the state of something or someone being absent, hidden, or unaware of the reality. Unlike words such as 'khufiyah' (secret) or 'mahfuzah' (hidden), it emphasizes mere absence rather than deliberate concealment. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَا يَغْتَب بَّعْضُكُم بَعْضًا» (49 / 12) Translation: And let none of you backbite another."
    },
    {
      "id": 3154,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Backbiting - Backbiting",
      "hw": "غیبت",
      "s": "The term «اخو» in the context of backbiting points to the violation of brotherhood and the sanctity of relationships.",
      "d": "«اخو» means to have a brotherly relationship with someone. In the context of backbiting, this word highlights the severity of this moral sin whereby a person diminishes the honor of their 'brother' (i.e., another human) in their absence. Unlike words such as 'tuhmat' (suspicion) or 'buhtan' (false accusation), it emphasizes the disrespect towards the foundation of relationships. For example, in the Quran: «يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا اجْتَنِبُوا كَثِيرًا مِّنَ الظَّنِّ إِنَّ بَعْضَ الظَّنِّ إِثْمٌ ۖ وَلَا تَجَسَّسُوا وَلَا يَغْتَب بَّعْضُكُم بَعْضًا ۚ أَيُحِبُّ أَحَدُكُمْ أَن يَأْكُلَ لَحْمَ أَخِيهِ مَيْتًا فَكَرِهْتُمُوهُ ۚ وَاتَّقُوا اللَّهَ ۚ إِنَّ اللَّهَ تَوَّابٌ رَّحِيمٌ» (49 / 12) Translation: O you who have believed! Avoid much suspicion, indeed some suspicion is sin. And do not spy or backbite one another. Would any of you like to eat the flesh of his dead brother? You would detest it. And fear Allah; indeed, Allah is Accepting of repentance and Merciful."
    },
    {
      "id": 3156,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Backbiting - Backbiting",
      "hw": "غیبت",
      "s": "The term «حبب» in the context of backbiting expresses the specific meaning of making something beloved or embedding it in the heart.",
      "d": "«حبب» means to instill something into the heart with love or desire, making it likable. Unlike words such as 'uhibb' (to love) or 'wad' (to have affection), it conveys not mere desire but the quality of deeply embedding something in the heart. In the context of condemning backbiting, this term points to the human tendency whereby negative attitudes become internally attractive. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَا تَجَسَّسُوا وَلَا یَغْتَب بَّعْضُکُم بَعْضًا أَیُحِبُّ أَحَدُکُمْ أَن یَأْکُلَ لَحْمَ أَخِیهِ مَیْتًا فَکَرِهْتُمُوهُ» (49 / 12) Translation: And do not spy or let one of you backbite another. Would any of you like to eat the flesh of his dead brother? You would detest it."
    }
  ],
  "687": [
    {
      "id": 3157,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Balance - Balance",
      "hw": "توازن",
      "s": "The term «وزن» conveys the meaning of balance and moderation, reflecting justice and proportion in the universe and human deeds.",
      "d": "«وزن» means to measure, weigh, or set a standard for something. This word expresses the concepts of balance, moderation, and proportion. Unlike words such as 'adl' (justice) or 'qist' (fairness), 'wazn' includes the specific aspect of measurement and quantity. For example, in the Quran: «وَٱلسَّمَآءَ رَفَعَهَا وَوَضَعَ ٱلْمِيزَانَ أَلَّا تَطْغَوْا۟ فِى ٱلْمِيزَانِ» (55 / 7-8) Translation: And the heaven He raised and imposed the balance that you may not transgress within the balance."
    },
    {
      "id": 3158,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Balance - Balance",
      "hw": "توازن",
      "s": "The term «ثَقَلَ» is generally used for a traveler's luggage and other heavy items.",
      "d": "«ثَقَلَ» means a traveler's luggage, load, weight, etc. (Lexicon) and is generally used for material or tangible burden. Its opposite «ثَقِیْل» is «خفیف», meaning light in weight. For example, in the Quran: «اِنۡفِرُوۡا خِفَافًا وَّ ثِقَالًا» (9/41) Translation: March forth, whether light or heavy. And the plural of «ثَقَل» is «اَثقَال». For example, in the Quran: «وَتَحۡمِلُ اَثۡقَالَکُمۡ اِلٰی بَلَدٍ لَّمۡ تَکُوۡنُوۡا بٰلِغِیۡہِ اِلَّا بِشِقِّ الۡاَنۡفُسِ» (16/7) Translation: And they carry your burdens to a land you could not have reached except with great effort. Indeed, your Lord is most Kind, Most Merciful. Furthermore, «ثَقِیْل» in the sense of heavy or burdensome things is sometimes used metaphorically. For example, in the Quran: «اِنَّا سَنُلۡقِیۡ عَلَیۡکَ قَوۡلًا ثَقِیۡلًا» (73/5) Translation: We will soon cast upon you a weighty word. Here «ثَقِیْل» refers to a statement, speech, or command that feels extremely burdensome to nature, and acting upon it requires great courage."
    },
    {
      "id": 3159,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Balance - Balance",
      "hw": "توازن",
      "s": "The term «قِسْط» is used to mean giving someone their full due, whether all at once or in installments.",
      "d": "«قِسْط» means to give someone their full right, i.e., its basic meaning is to avoid injustice. (Lexicon) In this sense, its meaning is to do justice, and its application is to external affairs in establishing justice. Therefore, the standards for weighing and measuring are also called «قِسْط» (see Lexicon 194). For example, in the Quran: «وَاَقِیۡمُوا الۡوَزۡنَ بِالۡقِسۡطِ وَلَا تُخۡسِرُواالۡمِیۡزَانَ» (55/9) Translation: Establish the scales with justice and do not deficient the balance. Then the word «قِسْط» is from the lexicon of opposites. If «قَسَطَ یَقْسُطُ» is used, its meaning is as stated above; if «قَسَطَ یَقْسِطُ» is used, its meaning is to withhold someone's right, act against right, or exceed the right. (Lexicon) (Dictionary). For example, in the Quran: «وَاَمَّا الۡقٰسِطُوۡنَ فَکَانُوۡا لِجَہَنَّمَ حَطَبًا» (72/15) Translation: And as for the unjust, they will be fuel for Hell. (Ottoman?). Then, whether the payment of someone's right is a handful or many parts, the words «قِسْط» and «اَقْسَاط» are used for that. Thus, the word «قِسْط» is used for both total and partial payment of rights. However, in these meanings, its usage is not found in the Quran; but in the chapter of verbs, it comes to mean doing justice. For example, in the Quran: «وَ اَقۡسِطُوۡا ؕ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُحِبُّ الۡمُقۡسِطِیۡنَ» (49/9) Translation: And act justly; indeed Allah loves those who act justly. Note: (Lexicon of opposites) these are words that have two distinct meanings which are opposite and contradictory to each other."
    }
  ],
  "688": [
    {
      "id": 3162,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bed - Bed",
      "hw": "بستر",
      "s": "The term «خوف» in the context of bed expresses the cardiac disturbance and precautionary action linked to fear of Allah's displeasure and punishment.",
      "d": "«خوف» means the disturbance and precautionary state arising in the heart from the thought of loss, calamity, or Allah's punishment. Unlike words such as 'khashyah' (awe-inspiring fear) or 'rahbah' (terror), it expresses an immediate reaction based on possible future danger. For example, in the Quran: «تَتَجَافَىٰ جُنُوبُهُمْ عَنِ الْمَضَاجِعِ يَدْعُونَ رَبَّهُمْ خَوْفًا وَطَمَعًا» (32 / 16) Translation: Their sides forsake their beds, invoking their Lord in fear and hope."
    },
    {
      "id": 3164,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bed - Bed",
      "hw": "بستر",
      "s": "The term «جفو» in the meaning of bed specifically shows the preparation and arrangement of the bed.",
      "d": "«جفو» in Urdu, regarding bed, is the original meaning derived from the Arabic root j-f-w (جَفَو) which yields this term. These words are used for bed anywhere, but this original meaning shows how the bed is prepared, and what lies beneath it. Just as a bed is prepared, likewise a person is prepared with his actions to stand at his respective station. When the preparation of a bed is made, it means that a place of rest is prepared for someone. The meaning of «جفو» is to place someone, together with his preparation, at his station. Its comparison with other words like 'بستر' or 'میز' is that 'بستر' merely denotes a specific place, whereas «جفو» includes the preparation of the related station. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي الْأُمَمِ مِن رَّسُولٍ إِلَىٰ أَهْلِهِ لِيُبَيِّنَ لَهُمْ وَلِيَتَّقُواْ فَمَن تَابَ مِن قَبْلِ أَن يَأْتِيَهُمُ الْعَذَابُ فَقَدْ أَنْجَا اللَّهُ مَنْ أَنْجَا مِنْهُمْ وَمَنْ لَمْ يَتُوبْ فَقَدْ أَخَذَهُمُ الْعَذَابُ وَهُمْ فِي الْبِطَانَةِ مَخْلُوفِينَ» (الأنعام/۱۲۹) Translation: And indeed We sent before you messengers to the nations, to their peoples, to explain to them and to make them fear Allah. Whoever repented before the punishment came to them, Allah saved those whom He saved from them; and whoever did not repent, then the punishment seized them while they were in the depths, dwelling therein."
    }
  ],
  "689": [
    {
      "id": 3167,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "بدوی",
      "s": "The term «Arabs» refers to the Bedouin Arabs who live a desert life and highlights their cultural and linguistic characteristics.",
      "d": "«Arabs» means those people who live in the desert regions of the Arabian Peninsula and whose language, civilization, and traditions are purely Arabic. This word is distinct from urban Arabs (ḥaḍari) who inhabit cities. The life of Bedouin Arabs revolves around the desert, nomadism, and the tribal system. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «الْأَعْرَابُ أَشَدُّ كُفْرًا وَنِفَاقًا» (9/97) Translation: 'The Bedouin Arabs are more severe in disbelief and hypocrisy.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3168,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "بدوی",
      "s": "«Kun» (Be) in the Bedouin context refers to the coming into existence of something or adopting a specific state.",
      "d": "«Kun» means to come into existence, change state, or blend into a specific condition. This word differs from other terms like 'khalq' (to create) or 'wujud' (to exist) in that it emphasizes change or movement rather than mere existence. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «كُن فَيَكُونُ» (36/82) Translation: (Allah) says 'Be,' and it is. This verse clarifies the practical manifestation of 'kun' where every thing in the universe comes into immediate existence by Allah's command, which is also in harmony with the simplicity and natural movement of Bedouin life."
    },
    {
      "id": 3170,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "بدوی",
      "s": "«Rahm» (Mercy) in the Bedouin context expresses the broad meaning of mercy and compassion that transcends family ties and encompasses all creatures.",
      "d": "«Rahm» means that deep love, compassion, and mercy which is part of human nature or the attribute of Rahmaniyyah of Allah. This word is distinguished from other synonyms like 'shafqat' (compassion) or 'meharbani' (kindness) in that it encompasses not only emotional attachment but also practical help and mutual support. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَأَلْفَ بَيْنَ قُلُوبِهِمْ ۚ لَوْ أَنفَقْتَ مَا فِي الْأَرْضِ جَمِيعًا مَّا أَلَّفْتَ بَيْنَ قُلُوبِهِمْ وَلَٰكِنَّ اللَّهَ أَلَّفَ بَيْنَهُمْ ۚ إِنَّهُ عَزِيزٌ حَكِيمٌ» (8/63) Translation: And He united their hearts. If you had spent all that is in the earth, you could not have united their hearts, but Allah united them. Indeed, He is Exalted in Might and Wise. In this verse, the spirit of 'rahim' is manifested as the unity of their hearts and mutual mercy."
    }
  ],
  "690": [],
  "691": [
    {
      "id": 3178,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "پیٹ",
      "s": "«Akul» refers to the act of eating to fill the stomach, which, unlike other terms, emphasizes only the physical consumption of food.",
      "d": "«Akul» means that act of eating which is related to the satisfaction of the stomach and fulfilling physical needs. This word differs from other terms like 'ta'am' (food) or 'sharb' (drinking) in that it highlights only the material aspect of eating and its connection to the stomach. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «يَا أَيُّهَا الرُّسُلِ كُلُوا مِنَ الطَّيِّبَاتِ وَاعْمَلُوا صَالِحًا» (23/51) Translation: O messengers, eat from the good things and do righteous deeds."
    },
    {
      "id": 3179,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "پیٹ",
      "s": "The word «nur» in the context of 'belly' is a sign of spiritual illumination and guidance that enlightens the human inner self.",
      "d": "«Nur» means that divine light which illuminates the outer and inner. This word is derived from the trilateral root 'n-w-r' and differs from other words like 'ḍiya' (bright light) or 'siraj' (lamp) in that it particularly signifies guidance, purity, and spiritual radiance. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «اللَّهُ نُورُ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضِ» (24/35) Translation: Allah is the light of the heavens and the earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 3181,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Thaman - Thaman",
      "hw": "پیٹ",
      "s": "The word 'thaman' in the Quran has been used to mean the price or compensation for something, which in context refers to material gain or worldly greed.",
      "d": "Thaman means compensation, price, or equivalent. This word clarifies the aspect of material benefit, trade, or worldly greed. Unlike other words like 'price' or 'profit', thaman carries a negative connotation, especially when referring to trivial gains taken in exchange for misguidance from Allah's path. For example: The Quran states: «وَشَرَوْهُ بِثَمَنٍ بَخْسٍ دَرَاهِمَ مَعْدُودَةٍ» (12/20) Translation: And they sold him for a cheap price, a few counted dirhams."
    }
  ],
  "692": [
    {
      "id": 3182,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Wasiyat - Wasiyat",
      "hw": "وصیت",
      "s": "The specific meaning of 'wasi' implies entrusting someone with responsibility or advice with continuity and trust.",
      "d": "Wasi means to transfer a command, responsibility, or advice with continuity and trust. This word differs from others like 'ahd' (covenant) or 'amanah' (trust) in that it signifies a strong spiritual or legal relationship between the testator and the beneficiary. For example: The Quran states: «كُتِبَ عَلَيْكُمْ إِذَا حَضَرَ أَحَدَكُمُ الْمَوْتُ إِن تَرَكَ خَيْرًا الْوَصِيَّةُ لِلْوَالِدَيْنِ وَالْأَقْرَبِينَ بِالْمَعْرُوفِ» (2/180) Translation: It is prescribed for you that when death approaches any of you, if he leaves wealth, he should make a will for his parents and near relatives according to custom."
    },
    {
      "id": 3183,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Wasiyat - Wasiyat",
      "hw": "وصیت",
      "s": "In the context of a will, 'tark' denotes the quality of leaving something behind or bequeathing it.",
      "d": "Tark means to leave something behind, to bequeath as inheritance, or to entrust a responsibility. This word differs from other synonyms like 'a'ta' (to give) or 'amr' (to command) in that it clearly refers to actions or wealth that remain after death. For example: The Quran states: «كُتِبَ عَلَيْكُمْ إِذَا حَضَرَ أَحَدَكُمُ الْمَوْتُ إِن تَرَكَ خَيْرًا الْوَصِيَّةُ لِلْوَالِدَيْنِ وَالْأَقْرَبِينَ» (2/180) Translation: It is prescribed for you that when death approaches any of you, if he leaves wealth, he should make a will for his parents and near relatives."
    },
    {
      "id": 3186,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Qarrab - Qarrab",
      "hw": "وصیت",
      "s": "To make oneself proximate by granting rank.",
      "d": "Qarub means to be near. And to perform an action that becomes a means of attaining nearness in rank. And 'qurban' is that offering through which attainment of rank and status is desired. For example: The Quran states: «وَ اتۡلُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ نَبَاَ ابۡنَیۡ اٰدَمَ بِالۡحَقِّ ۘ اِذۡ قَرَّبَا قُرۡبَانًا» (5/27) Translation: And recite to them the true story of the two sons of Adam when they both offered a sacrifice. At another place, the divine command states: «وَ السّٰبِقُوۡنَ السّٰبِقُوۡنَ أُولٰٓئِکَ الۡمُقَرَّبُوۡنَ» (56/10,11) Translation: And the foremost are the foremost. Those are the ones brought near."
    }
  ],
  "693": [
    {
      "id": 3187,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Injeel - Injeel",
      "hw": "انجیل",
      "s": "The word 'kitab' in the context of 'Injeel' refers to the guidance prescribed or written by Allah.",
      "d": "Kitab means to prescribe, decree, or enact in written form. This word is distinguished from others like 'kataba' (to write generally) in that it signifies the compliance and firmness of a divine or legal command. For example: The Quran states: «وَقَفَّيْنَا بِعِيسَى ابْنِ مَرْيَمَ وَآتَيْنَاهُ الْإِنجِيلَ وَجَعَلْنَا فِي قُلُوبِ الَّذِينَ اتَّبَعُوهُ رَأْفَةً وَرَحْمَةً» (57/27) Translation: And We sent Jesus, son of Mary, and gave him the Gospel, and placed in the hearts of those who followed him tenderness and mercy."
    },
    {
      "id": 3188,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Injeel - Injeel",
      "hw": "انجیل",
      "s": "In the context of the Injeel, 'kathir' denotes the abundance and spread of its teachings.",
      "d": "Kathir means to increase in number, quantity, or effect. This word differs from other synonyms like 'zad' (to increase) or 'nama' (to grow) in that it includes aspects of diversity and expansiveness, not just quantity. In the context of the Injeel, it refers to the comprehensive and universal spread of its teachings. For example: The Quran states: «وَاذْكُر رَّبَّكَ كَثِيرًا وَسَبِّحْ بِالْعَشِيِّ وَالْإِبْكَارِ» (3/41) Translation: And remember your Lord frequently and glorify Him in the evening and the morning."
    },
    {
      "id": 3189,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Injeel - Injeel",
      "hw": "انجیل",
      "s": "Ahl refers to those who are followers of the Injeel or among the People of the Book.",
      "d": "Ahl means a group that has a special relationship, ownership, or affiliation with something. This word differs from others like 'qawm' (people) or 'as-hab' (companions) in that it more deeply signifies spiritual, scholarly, or doctrinal affiliation. For example, the Quran instructs the People of the Injeel to judge by what Allah has revealed in it. For instance: The Quran states: «وَلْيَحْكُمْ أَهْلُ الْإِنْجِيلِ بِمَا أَنزَلَ اللَّهُ فِيهِ» (5/47) Translation: And let the People of the Gospel judge by what Allah has revealed therein."
    },
    {
      "id": 3191,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Injeel - Injeel",
      "hw": "انجیل",
      "s": "In the context of the Injeel, 'baghḍ' describes the deep-seated hatred and enmity in hearts that arose among those who deviated from its teachings by Allah's command.",
      "d": "Baghḍ means to have firm hatred or malice in the heart, which expresses a deeper and more enduring feeling of enmity than other words like 'kurh' (dislike) or 'adaawat' (hostility). This word clarifies a psychological and cardiac state. For example: The Quran states: «وَأَطِيعُوا اللَّهَ وَرَسُولَهُ وَلَا تَنَازَعُوا فَتَفْشَلُوا وَتَذْهَبَ رِيحُكُمْ ۖ وَاصْبِرُوا ۚ إِنَّ اللَّهَ مَعَ الصَّابِرِينَ» (8/46) Translation: And obey Allah and His Messenger and do not dispute, lest you lose courage and your departure [from the enemy] be taken away, and be patient. Indeed, Allah is with the patient. (In the background of the prohibition of 'tanaaza'u' in this verse, the state of 'baghḍ' can be understood as causing division and weakness.)"
    }
  ],
  "694": [
    {
      "id": 3192,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "حیاتیات",
      "s": "«Mawh» in the context of biology refers to the basic element or substance that is essential for the formation and sustenance of life.",
      "d": "«Mawh» means the original substance or fundamental component of something, especially that which is naturally or divinely granted. This word is derived from the Arabic root 'm-w-h' which refers to a soft and fluid substance. Unlike other synonyms like 'ma' (water), 'mawh' emphasizes the creative or vital force. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَهُوَ الَّذِي خَلَقَ مِنَ الْمَاءِ بَشَرًا فَجَعَلَهُ نَسَبًا وَصِهْرًا» (25/54) Translation: And He is the One who created from water a human being and made him [having] lineage and marital relationships. In this verse, 'ma' refers to the basic substance of biological origin (sperm), which is close to the meaning of 'mawh'."
    },
    {
      "id": 3193,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Biology - Biology",
      "hw": "حیاتیات",
      "s": "In the context of biology, 'kūn' describes the coming into existence of a thing, its formation, and the evolutionary process.",
      "d": "Kūn means to come into existence, to be, or to transform into a state. This word expresses both the general act of creation and the dynamic aspects of evolution and change. Unlike other words like 'khalaq' (to create), 'kūn' includes the continuity or gradual process of a thing's coming into being. For example: The Quran states: «إِنَّمَا أَمْرُهُ إِذَا أَرَادَ شَيْئًا أَنْ يَقُولَ لَهُ كُنْ فَيَكُونُ» (36/82) Translation: Indeed, His command is only when He intends a thing that He says to it, 'Be,' and it is. This verse clarifies the continuity of existence through Allah's command, rather than the immediacy and completeness of biological creation."
    },
    {
      "id": 3194,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Biology - Biology",
      "hw": "حیاتیات",
      "s": "«كلل» in the context of biology refers to the concept of something being all-encompassing or completely covering, such as a comprehensive analysis of biological systems.",
      "d": "«كلل» means to surround, include completely, or be all-encompassing from every aspect. This word differs from synonyms like «شمل» (to include) or «ضم» (to mix) in that it emphasizes universality and complete coverage. For example: In the Quran: «وَدَانِيَةً عَلَيْهِمْ ظِلَالُهَا وَذُلِّلَتْ قُطُوفُهَا تَذْلِيلًا * وَيُطَافُ عَلَيْهِم بِآنِيَةٍ مِّن فِضَّةٍ وَأَكْوَابٍ كَانَتْ قَوَارِيرَا * قَوَارِيرَ مِن فِضَّةٍ قَدَّرُوهَا تَقْدِيرًا» (76 / 14-16) Translation: And their shades will be close over them, and their fruits will be hanging low (easily accessible). And they will be served with vessels of silver and goblets of crystal. Crystal-clear glasses of silver which they have precisely measured. In this verse, the concept of «كلل» shines in the context of the all-encompassing nature of the fruits and their easy accessibility, symbolizing biological balance."
    },
    {
      "id": 3195,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "حیاتیات",
      "s": "«Shi'a» in the context of biology refers to bringing something into existence or its creation, particularly under Allah's will and wisdom.",
      "d": "«Shi'a» means to intend something, to will it, or to give it existence. This word differs from other terms like 'khalq' (to create) in that it particularly emphasizes will and intention, whereas 'khalq' generally describes the act of creation. For example, in the Quran, Allah's will and creation are mentioned in these words:\n«إِنَّمَا أَمْرُهُ إِذَا أَرَادَ شَيْئًا أَن يَقُولَ لَهُ كُن فَيَكُونُ» (36/82)\nTranslation: When He intends a thing, His command is only to say to it, 'Be,' and it is."
    }
  ],
  "695": [
    {
      "id": 3197,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "پرندے",
      "s": "«Tair» refers to the general form of birds, but in the Quran, it sometimes also alludes to divine signs or fate.",
      "d": "«Tair» means the collective concept of flying creatures, which includes all birds. This word originates from the Arabic root 'ṭ-y-r' (flight) which conveys the meaning of movement and circulation in the air. Unlike other terms like 'ṭa'ir' (a single bird) or 'ʿasfūr' (sparrow), 'ṭair' is general and sometimes carries symbolic meanings, especially in the Quran as signs of divine power.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَأَرْسَلَ عَلَيْهِمْ طَيْرًا أَبَابِيلَ» (105/3)\nTranslation: And Allah sent upon them birds in flocks."
    },
    {
      "id": 3198,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "پرندے",
      "s": "«Kull» in the context of birds describes the characteristic of including each one individually and completely.",
      "d": "«Kull» has the lexical root 'k-l-l' which means to encompass, surround, or include completely. This word differs from other synonyms like 'jamiʿ' (all) in that it collectively encompasses while giving individual attention to each part or member. For example, in the Quran, during the mention of birds, this word is used to highlight their distinct identities and the comprehensiveness of their actions.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«أَلَمْ تَرَ أَنَّ اللَّهَ يُسَبِّحُ لَهُ مَن فِي السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضِ وَالطَّيْرُ صَافَّاتٍ ۖ كُلٌّ قَدْ عَلِمَ صَلَاتَهُ وَتَسْبِيحَهُ» (24/41)\nTranslation: Do you not see that whoever is in the heavens and earth exalts Allah, and the birds with wings spread? Each one has known its [own way of] prayer and exaltation."
    },
    {
      "id": 3199,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Birds - Birds",
      "hw": "پرندے",
      "s": "«راي» in the Quran is used to describe the specific quality of birds' flight and movement.",
      "d": "«راي» means to see something while it is moving or to pay attention to it. This word differs from other words like «طير» (flying bird) in that the aspect of observation and attention is predominant in «راي». For example: In the Quran it is stated: «أَوَلَمْ يَرَوْا إِلَى الطَّيْرِ فَوْقَهُمْ صَافَّاتٍ وَيَقْبِضْنَ» (67 / 19) Translation: Do they not see the birds above them, spreading their wings and folding them?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3200,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "پرندے",
      "s": "«Kun» describes the specific act of the creation of birds and their coming into existence, which is a sign of Allah's perfect power.",
      "d": "«Kun» means to come into existence or to appear in a specific state. This word differs from other terms like 'khalq' (to create) or 'jaʿal' (to make) in that it emphasizes the continuity of a thing's existence and its natural qualities. In the context of birds, it highlights the delicacy of their creation, their ability to fly, and Allah's wisdom in their system of life.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«أَلَمْ يَرَوْا إِلَى الطَّيْرِ مُسَخَّرَاتٍ فِي جَوِّ السَّمَاءِ مَا يُمْسِكُهُنَّ إِلَّا اللَّهُ» (16/79)\nTranslation: Do they not see the birds subjected in the atmosphere of the sky? None holds them except Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 3201,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Birds - Birds",
      "hw": "پرندے",
      "s": "The specific meaning of «اتي» (ati) points to the swift arrival or being brought of birds.",
      "d": "«اتي» (ati) means to come or be brought, especially with immediacy and speed. This word differs from others like 'جاء' (ja'a - to come) in that it expresses movement with purpose and subjugation. For example, in the Quran, this word was used in the context of birds to describe their gathering instantly by Allah's command.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«فَخُذْ أَرْبَعَةً مِّنَ الطَّيْرِ فَصُرْهُنَّ إِلَيْكَ ثُمَّ اجْعَلْ عَلَىٰ كُلِّ جَبَلٍ مِّنْهُنَّ جُزْءًا ثُمَّ ادْعُهُنَّ يَأْتِينَكَ سَعْيًا» (2 / 260)\nTranslation: Then take four birds, incline them to yourself (slaughter them), then place on every hill a portion of them, then call them; they will come to you swiftly."
    }
  ],
  "696": [
    {
      "id": 3202,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Blame - Blame",
      "hw": "ملامت",
      "s": "«لوم» (lawaam) means to admonish someone gently for their fault or shortcoming, which carries an aspect of reform.",
      "d": "«لوم» (lawaam) means to reproach someone for their error or shortcoming using gentle words. It differs from other words like 'توبیخ' (rebuke) or 'عتاب' (chiding) in that it includes an element of gentleness and compassion, not harsh condemnation. For example, the Quran states: «وَلَا أُقْسِمُ بِالنَّفْسِ اللَّوَّامَةِ» (75 / 2)\nTranslation: And I swear by the self-reproaching soul. (Here, 'اللَّوَّامَةِ' refers to the soul that reproaches itself for bad deeds, embodying the meaning of admonition and reform.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3204,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Blame - Blame",
      "hw": "ملامت",
      "s": "In the context of 'blame', the word «كون» (kana) expresses the continuity and persistence of an action or state that becomes a cause for blame.",
      "d": "«كون» (kana) means existence, proof, or the continuity of a state. This word differs from other verbs (like 'فعل' or 'صار') in that it emphasizes the quality of something being or remaining in a certain state, not merely its occurrence. In the Quran, this word is often used to refer to the persistent nature of human deeds or attributes that lead to blame.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَضُرِبَتْ عَلَيْهِمُ الذِّلَّةُ وَالْمَسْكَنَةُ وَبَاءُوا بِغَضَبٍ مِنَ اللَّهِ ۗ ذَٰلِكَ بِأَنَّهُمْ كَانُوا يَكْفُرُونَ بِآيَاتِ اللَّهِ وَيَقْتُلُونَ النَّبِيِّينَ بِغَيْرِ الْحَقِّ ۗ ذَٰلِكَ بِمَا عَصَوْا وَكَانُوا يَعْتَدُونَ» (البقرة / 61)\nTranslation: And humiliation and poverty were imposed upon them, and they became subject to the wrath of Allah. That is because they disbelieved in the signs of Allah and killed the prophets without right. That is because they disobeyed and were transgressing."
    }
  ],
  "697": [
    {
      "id": 3208,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Blood Money (Diyah) - Diyah",
      "hw": "دیت",
      "s": "«حرر» in the context of blood money refers to the value determined and associated with the status of a free individual.",
      "d": "«حرر» means freedom or to free someone from restrictions. In the context of blood money, this word clarifies the specific value prescribed for a free person, which differs from that of a slave or individuals of other statuses. For example, in the Quran, the distinction between the blood money of a free person and a slave is linked to this root. For example: In the Quran it is stated: «یٰۤاَیُّهَا الَّذِیْنَ اٰمَنُوْا كُتِبَ عَلَیْكُمُ الْقِصَاصُ فِی الْقَتْلٰى اَلْحُرُّ بِالْحُرِّ وَالْعَبْدُ بِالْعَبْدِ» (2 / 178) Translation: O you who have believed, prescribed for you is legal retribution for those murdered - the free for the free and the slave for the slave."
    }
  ],
  "698": [
    {
      "id": 3213,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Bones - Bones",
      "hw": "ہڈی",
      "s": "«كون» (kana) expresses the specific aspect of the state of existence of bones or their transformation.",
      "d": "«كون» (kana) means to come into existence or to change into a particular state. This word differs from others like 'خلق' (to create) or 'جعل' (to make) in that it fundamentally describes the process of something coming into being or changing state, not just its outward structure. For example, in the context of bones, 'كون' refers to the stage of their composite existence or formation.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«وَ قَالُوٓا۟ أَئِذَا كُنَّا عِظَـٰمًا وَ رُفَـٰتًا أَءِنَّا لَمَبْعُوثُونَ خَلْقًا جَدِيدًا» (17 / 49)\nTranslation: And they say, 'When we have become bones and crumbled dust, will we indeed be resurrected as a new creation?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3215,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Bones - Bones",
      "hw": "ہڈی",
      "s": "In the context of bones, «موت» (mawt) describes the specific quality of the dissolution of the human body after death and its being revived by Allah's power.",
      "d": "«موت» (mawt) means the end of life and the separation of body and soul. This word is derived from the Arabic root 'م-و-ت', which expresses the general state of transition for any living being. However, in relation to bones, it pertains to the lifeless human structure and the miracle of its revival. Other words like 'وفات' (wafat) or 'رحلت' (rahmat) focus only on the aspect of transition, whereas 'موت' includes a profound concept of physical transformation.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَضَرَبَ لَنَا مَثَلًا وَنَسِيَ خَلْقَهُ قَالَ مَنْ يُحْيِي الْعِظَامَ وَهِيَ رَمِيمٌ» (36 / 78)\nTranslation: And he presents an example for us and forgets his own creation. He says, 'Who will give life to the bones while they are decayed?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3216,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Bone - Bone",
      "hw": "ہڈی",
      "s": "«ترب» refers to the original material of bones, i.e., soil and dust, which indicates the initial state of human creation.",
      "d": "«ترب» means soil, dust, or particles of earth. This word refers to the original material of human creation, which includes the formation of bones. It differs from other words like «عظم» (bone) in that «ترب» emphasizes the basic structure (soil) of creation, whereas «عظم» describes the complete form of the bone. For example, in the Quran: «وَضَرَبَ لَنَا مَثَلًا وَنَسِيَ خَلْقَهُ ۖ قَالَ مَن يُحْيِي الْعِظَامَ وَهِيَ رَمِيمٌ» (36 / 78) Translation: And he presents an example to us and forgets his own creation; he says, 'Who will revive these decayed bones?'"
    }
  ],
  "699": [
    {
      "id": 3217,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Books - Books",
      "hw": "کتابیں",
      "s": "The word «كتب» has been used in the Quran for divinely revealed books and sacred scriptures that are written by Allah and their preservation is their characteristic.",
      "d": "«كتب» means to write, decree, or record a command. This word differs from other synonymous words like «قرأ» (to read) or «خط» (to draw/write) in that «كتب» emphasizes the aspect of destiny, permanent law, or divine revelation. For example, in the Quran: «فِيهَا كُتُبٌ قَيِّمَةٌ» (98 / 3) Translation: In them are firm and correct commands."
    },
    {
      "id": 3218,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Books - Books",
      "hw": "کتابیں",
      "s": "In reference to books, «اتي» (ati) signifies the descent of divine revelation or heavenly scriptures.",
      "d": "«اتي» (ati) in its literal Arabic sense means 'to come' or 'to bring'. However, in Quranic terminology, it is specifically used for the sending down of revelation, commandments, or heavenly books. This word is distinct from synonyms like 'نَزَلَ' (nazala - to descend) in that 'ati' includes the meanings of wisdom, completion, and honor in its arrival.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَلَمَّا جَآءَهُمْ كِتَـٰبٌۭ مِّنْ عِندِ ٱللَّهِ مُصَدِّقٌۭ لِّمَا مَعَهُمْ» (2 / 89)\nTranslation: And when a Book came to them from Allah confirming that which was with them..."
    }
  ],
  "700": [
    {
      "id": 3223,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Botany - Botany",
      "hw": "نباتیات",
      "s": "The meaning of «موه» (mawh) in the context of botany describes the life and growth granted to plants by Allah.",
      "d": "«موه» (mawh) means to grant something as a gift or with a specific quality. This word is distinguished from others like 'اعطا' (to give) or 'خلق' (to create) in that it emphasizes a natural and divine bestowal. In botany, it refers to the earth being given water and life.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَأَنزَلْنَا مِنَ السَّمَاءِ مَاءً بِقَدَرٍ فَأَسْكَنَّاهُ فِي الْأَرْضِ وَإِنَّا عَلَىٰ ذَهَابٍ بِهِ لَقَادِرُونَ» (23 / 18)\nTranslation: And We sent down from the sky water in a measured amount and settled it in the earth. And indeed, We are able to take it away."
    },
    {
      "id": 3224,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Botany - Botany",
      "hw": "نباتیات",
      "s": "In the context of botany, «ليل» (layl) describes the specific role of nighttime in the growth and biological processes of plants.",
      "d": "«ليل» (layl) means the time of night, derived from the Arabic root 'ل-ی-ل'. This word conveys not only the cycle of darkness but also a specific division of time and the circadian rhythm. It differs from other synonyms like 'ظلام' (darkness) in that 'ليل' includes the meaning of a defined period and a natural cycle. In botany, it is deeply connected to the catabolic processes of plants at night (such as respiration) and activities like flower opening.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَآيَةٌ لَّهُمُ اللَّيْلُ نَسْلَخُ مِنْهُ النَّهَارَ فَإِذَا هُم مُّظْلِمُونَ» (36 / 37)\nTranslation: And a sign for them is the night; We remove from it the daylight, and suddenly they are in darkness."
    },
    {
      "id": 3225,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Botany - Botany",
      "hw": "نباتیات",
      "s": "«غشو» (ghashaw) in the context of botany describes the quality of grass or greenery that covers the earth.",
      "d": "«غشو» (ghashaw) means to cover something else or to spread over it. This word is derived from the Arabic root 'غ-ش-و', which conveys the meaning of any kind of veil, covering, or enveloping. In botany, it refers to the density of grass or greenery spread on the earth, such as the growth of crops or wild plants. It differs from other words like 'نبت' (to grow) or 'زرع' (to sow) in that 'غشو' emphasizes spreading and covering.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَأَنبَتْنَا فِيهَا مِن كُلِّ زَوْجٍ بَهِيجٍ» (22 / 5)\nTranslation: And We have produced therein every kind of beautiful pair."
    },
    {
      "id": 3226,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Botany - Botany",
      "hw": "نباتیات",
      "s": "«نهر» in the context of botany indicates the basic role of water sources and the flourishing of plant life.",
      "d": "«نهر» means a flowing water source or river that irrigates the earth and causes the growth of plants. This word differs from other words like «بحر» (sea) or «وادي» (valley) in that it is specifically associated with water flow and fertility. For example, in the Quran: «وَبَشِّرِ الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَعَمِلُوا الصَّالِحَاتِ أَنَّ لَهُمْ جَنَّاتٍ تَجْرِي مِن تَحْتِهَا الْأَنْهَارُ» (2 / 25) Translation: And give good tidings to those who believe and do righteous deeds that they will have gardens beneath which rivers flow."
    }
  ],
  "701": [
    {
      "id": 3227,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bow - Bow",
      "hw": "کمان",
      "s": "The specific Quranic meaning of «ركع» (rak'a) describes the state of bowing in prayer.",
      "d": "«ركع» (rak'a) means to bow in prayer where one places the knees on the ground and straightens the back. It differs from general bending (like 'حَنَى' or 'انحنى') which only indicates physical movement, whereas 'rak'a' includes the intention of worship and the prescribed method.\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَأَقِيمُوا الصَّلَاةَ وَآتُوا الزَّكَاةَ وَارْكَعُوا مَعَ الرَّاكِعِينَ» (2 / 43)\nTranslation: And establish prayer and give zakah and bow with those who bow [in worship]."
    },
    {
      "id": 3228,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bow - Bow",
      "hw": "کمان",
      "s": "The term 'sujud' denotes the specific quality of bending or being humble in worship, which is deeply connected to the spiritual aspect of bowing.",
      "d": "«يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا ارْكَعُوا وَاسْجُدُوا وَاعْبُدُوا رَبَّكُمْ» (22 / 77) Translation: O you who have believed, bow and prostrate and worship your Lord."
    },
    {
      "id": 3229,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bow - Bow",
      "hw": "کمان",
      "s": "The term 'salah' means to worship Allah with humility and concentration in the performance of prayer, reflecting an inner connection that transcends mere physical movements.",
      "d": "«وَأَقِيمُوا الصَّلَاةَ وَآتُوا الزَّكَاةَ وَارْكَعُوا مَعَ الرَّاكِعِينَ» (2 / 43) Translation: And establish prayer, give zakah, and bow with those who bow."
    },
    {
      "id": 3230,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bow - Bow",
      "hw": "کمان",
      "s": "In the context of 'bow', 'tahir' denotes the quality of purity and cleanliness, which includes both material and spiritual cleanliness.",
      "d": "«وَثِيَابَكَ فَطَهِّرْ» (74 / 4) Translation: And purify your clothes."
    },
    {
      "id": 3231,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bow - Bow",
      "hw": "کمان",
      "s": "«طوف» in relation to the bow signifies its rotation and revolution, which indicates the movement of its strings.",
      "d": "«طوف» is the original root of the Urdu word 'کمان' which, together with its Arabic origin, imparts a specific meaning. Its root «طوف» originally means a circle, rotation, or revolution. When 'کمان' is used, the action of rotation and revolution of its strings accompanies it. For translation, synonymous words like 'spread' or 'rotate' are not used. «طوف» is the term that explains the rotation of the bow's strings. For example: In the Quran: «وَإِذَا طَوَّفَتْ عَلَيْهِمُ الْمَلَائِكَةُ» (الحج / 38) Translation: 'And when the angels revolve around them'"
    }
  ],
  "702": [
    {
      "id": 3233,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bracelet - Bracelet",
      "hw": "کنگن",
      "s": "In the context of 'bracelet', 'dhahab' (gold) denotes the precious metal used in ornaments.",
      "d": "«يُحَلَّوْنَ فِيهَا مِنْ أَسَاوِرَ مِن ذَهَبٍ» (18 / 31) Translation: They will be adorned therein with bracelets of gold."
    },
    {
      "id": 3234,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bracelet - Bracelet",
      "hw": "کنگن",
      "s": "'Huly' is a term that denotes bracelets or ornaments, used for adorning and beautifying the body.",
      "d": "«وَاتَّخَذَ قَوْمُ مُوسَىٰ مِن بَعْدِهِ مِنْ حُلِيِّهِمْ عِجْلًا جَسَدًا لَّهُ خُوَارٌ» (7 / 148) Translation: And the people of Moses made from their ornaments a calf - a mere body that lowed."
