      "d": "«فَلَمَّا جَنَّ عَلَيْهِ اللَّيْلُ» (6 / 76) Translation: Then when the night covered him."
    }
  ],
  "703": [
    {
      "id": 3237,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Brass - Brass",
      "hw": "پیتل",
      "s": "The term 'mihl' denotes the liquid or molten form of brass or copper, derived from its original meaning of 'delay' or 'thick substance'.",
      "d": "«آتُونِي زُبَرَ الْحَدِيدِ ۖ حَتَّىٰ إِذَا سَاوَىٰ بَيْنَ الصَّدَفَيْنِ قَالَ انفُخُوا ۖ حَتَّىٰ إِذَا جَعَلَهُ نَارًا قَالَ آتُونِي أُفْرِغْ عَلَيْهِ قِطْرًا» (18 / 96) Translation: Bring me blocks of iron; until when he had leveled [the space] between the two walls, he said, 'Blow [with bellows],' until when he had made it fire, he said, 'Bring me molten copper.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3238,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Brass - Brass",
      "hw": "پیتل",
      "s": "In the context of 'brass', the term 'nur' highlights the spiritual aspects of light, radiance, and brilliance, reflecting both its external and internal qualities.",
      "d": "«اللَّهُ نُورُ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضِ» (24 / 35) Translation: Allah is the Light of the heavens and the earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 3240,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Brass - Brass",
      "hw": "پیتل",
      "s": "The linguistic nuance of 'haqq' in the context of 'brass' relates to firmly establishing something with reality or proof, or confirming it.",
      "d": "«وَلَا تَلْبِسُوا الْحَقَّ بِالْبَاطِلِ وَتَكْتُمُوا الْحَقَّ وَأَنْتُمْ تَعْلَمُونَ» (2 / 42) Translation: And do not mix the truth with falsehood or conceal the truth while you know [it]."
    }
  ],
  "704": [
    {
      "id": 3242,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Roti - Roti",
      "hw": "روٹی",
      "s": "The word 'akl' in the context of roti describes the comprehensive act of acquiring, using, and benefiting from food.",
      "d": "'Akl' means to eat, to consume, or to introduce something into the body through the mouth. This word differs from other terms like 'ta'am' (food) or 'sharb' (drinking) in that it emphasizes only the act of eating, not the nature of the food or drinking. For example, in the Quran, the use of 'akl' not only indicates physical food but also spiritual or moral effects. For instance, the Quran states: «یَأْكُلْنَ مَا یَخْطُفْنَ» (12 / 37). Translation: (Those women) will eat whatever they acquire. Here, the word 'ya'kulna' also highlights the meaning of greed or unjust acquisition along with the use of roti or food."
    },
    {
      "id": 3246,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Roti - Roti",
      "hw": "روٹی",
      "s": "The word 'fawq' in the context of 'roti' expresses the meanings of elevation, superiority, and abundance of sustenance.",
      "d": "'Fawq' means elevation, superiority, or the state of being above something. This word differs from synonyms like 'ala' (upon) in that it denotes not only local elevation but also spiritual superiority, increase, or dominance. In the Quran, this word has been used for both material and spiritual elevations. For instance, the Quran states: «وَأَنزَلْنَا عَلَى الَّذِينَ ظَلَمُوا رِجْزًا مِّنَ السَّمَاءِ بِمَا كَانُوا يَفْسُقُونَ» (2 Al-Baqarah / 59). Translation: And We sent down upon the wrongdoers a punishment from the heaven because they were defiantly disobedient. In this verse, the descent of punishment is described with 'ala', while the concept of 'fawq' is also understood in the context of abundance of sustenance and high-grade blessings from Allah (such as roti)."
    }
  ],
  "705": [
    {
      "id": 3247,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Bribe - Bribe",
      "hw": "رشوت",
      "s": "'Akl' means to consume wealth in an illicit manner, which in the form of bribe signifies usurping the rights of others.",
      "d": "'Akl' means to swallow or devour something. This word is also used in the sense of financial exploitation, taking illicit advantage, and violating rights, besides physical eating. In the context of bribe, it refers to the detestable act of consuming others' wealth illegitimately, whereas other words like 'akhth' (to take) or 'istifada' (benefit) do not carry this negative connotation. For instance, the Quran states: «وَلَا تَأْكُلُوا أَمْوَالَكُم بَيْنَكُم بِالْبَاطِلِ» (2 / 188). Translation: And do not consume one another's wealth unjustly."
    },
    {
      "id": 3250,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Bribe - Bribe",
      "hw": "رشوت",
      "s": "'Ins' when referring to the social aspect (i.e., living together) of human, the word 'ins' and its derivatives are used; when mentioning the historical aspect, 'Adam' and 'Bani Adam' are used; and when referring to its natural and innate aspect, the word 'bashar' is used.",
      "d": "'Ins' refers to groups or communities of humans who may be different due to tribe, family, or other reasons. For instance, the Quran states: «قَدۡ عَلِمَ کُلُّ اُنَاسٍ مَّشۡرَبَہُمۡ» (60 / 2). Translation: Every group has recognized its drinking place. And (anasi) refers to a very large group of humans. For instance, Allah says: «خَلَقۡنَاۤ اَنۡعَامًا وَّ اَنَاسِیَّ  کَثِیۡرًا» (49 / 25). Translation: We have created livestock and numerous humans."
    },
    {
      "id": 3251,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Bribe - Bribe",
      "hw": "رشوت",
      "s": "The word 'hukm' in the context of bribe points to the act of corrupting the ability to govern or make decisions.",
      "d": "'Hukm' means to give judgment, to decide, or to use authority in a just manner. This word differs from other terms like 'qada' (judgment) in that 'hukm' includes the meaning of governance and the sustainability of the system, while bribe corrupts it illegitimately. For instance, the Quran states: «وَمَن لَّمْ يَحْكُم بِمَا أَنزَلَ اللَّهُ فَأُولَٰئِكَ هُمُ الْكَافِرُونَ» (5 / 44). Translation: And whoever does not judge by what Allah has revealed - then it is those who are the disbelievers."
    }
  ],
  "706": [
    {
      "id": 3252,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Silk - Silk",
      "hw": "ریشم",
      "s": "The word 'jann' refers to the delicacy of silk and its ability to conceal, which reflects the fineness of its texture.",
      "d": "'Jann' means to cover or conceal. This word describes the properties of silk due to its softness and smoothness, which covers the body and distinguishes it from other things. Other words like 'harir' only describe the physical structure of silk, while 'jann' highlights its practical and symbolic virtues. For instance, the Quran states: «يَا بَنِي آدَمَ قَدْ أَنزَلْنَا عَلَيْكُمْ لِبَاسًا يُوَارِي سَوْآتِكُمْ وَرِيشًا» (7 / 26). Translation: O children of Adam, We have bestowed upon you clothing to cover your private parts and as adornment."
    },
    {
      "id": 3253,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Silk - Silk",
      "hw": "ریشم",
      "s": "The word 'waka' refers to the delicacy of silk and its binding or twisting.",
      "d": "'Waka' means to tie, to bind, or to wrap tightly. This word differs from other terms like 'rabat' or 'aqd' in that it conveys the meaning of securely joining something delicate or fine, such as silk threads. For instance, the Quran states: «وَكَاءَ الْفَجْرِ» (2 / 187). Translation: And recognize the white thread of dawn."
    },
    {
      "id": 3256,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Silk - Silk",
      "hw": "ریشم",
      "s": "The word 'thawb' in the context of silk denotes a fine and valuable type of garment or clothing.",
      "d": "'Thawb' means garment or clothing, which in Arabic encompasses any type of attire. This word is distinguished from synonyms like 'libas' or 'rida' in that it particularly emphasizes the structure, nature, or quality of the garment's preparation. In the case of silk, 'thawb' refers to a soft, shiny, and high-quality fabric. For instance, the Quran states: «وَثِيَابَكَ فَطَهِّرْ» (74 / 4). Translation: And purify your garments."
    }
  ],
  "707": [
    {
      "id": 3257,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Burial - Burial",
      "hw": "تدفین",
      "s": "'Wari' in its specific meaning in the context of burial refers to covering or concealing something.",
      "d": "'Wari' means to completely hide something or to bury it in the ground to make it invisible. This word is distinguished from other terms like 'dafn' in that it emphasizes the aspect of concealment and protection rather than just placing. For instance, the Quran states: «يَا بَنِي آدَمَ قَدْ أَنزَلْنَا عَلَيْكُمْ لِبَاسًا يُوَارِي سَوْآتِكُمْ» (7 / 26). Translation: O children of Adam, We have bestowed upon you clothing that covers your private parts."
    },
    {
      "id": 3258,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Burial - Burial",
      "hw": "تدفین",
      "s": "'Akhaw' in the context of burial holds a special significance where the act of burying an individual's corpse is the responsibility of his brother or close relative.",
      "d": "'Akhaw' means that this word basically denotes a brother or close relation, and in the context of burial, it refers to the responsibility based on family or brotherhood. Other words like 'dafn' (to hide in the ground) only describe the act of burial, but 'akhaw' highlights the depth of relationship and social aspect in it. For instance, the Quran states: «فَبَعَثَ اللَّهُ غُرَابًا يَبْحَثُ فِي الْأَرْضِ لِيُرِيَهُ كَيْفَ يُوَارِي سَوْءَةَ أَخِيهِ» (5 / 31). Translation: Then Allah sent a crow searching in the ground to show him how to cover the corpse of his brother."
    },
    {
      "id": 3259,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Burial - Burial",
      "hw": "تدفین",
      "s": "«مثل» in the context of burial refers to exemplary punishment or displaying the corpse as a lesson.",
      "d": "«مثل» means to make something an example or a lesson. Lexically, it is derived from 'مثیل' which carries the aspect of similarity or display. In the context of burial, it refers to that punishment where the criminal's body is displayed publicly before burial, which is different from other terms like 'دفن' (merely burying in the ground). For example: In the Quran: إِنَّمَا جَزَاءُ الَّذِينَ يُحَارِبُونَ اللَّهَ وَرَسُولَهُ وَيَسْعَوْنَ فِي الْأَرْضِ فَسَادًا أَنْ يُقَتَّلُوا أَوْ يُصَلَّبُوا... (۵:۳۳) Translation: 'Indeed, the penalty for those who wage war against Allah and His Messenger and strive upon earth [to cause] corruption is none but that they be killed or crucified...' (5:33)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3261,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Burial - Tafeen",
      "hw": "تدفین",
      "s": "'Sawa' in the context of Tafeen describes the specific quality of leveling the soil in the grave and completely covering the deceased.",
      "d": "'Sawa' means to make something correct, even, or to give it a complete form. Etymologically, this word is derived from 'Taswiyah' (to make equal), which refers to leveling the soil of the grave and covering the deceased with respect. Unlike other terms like 'Dafn' (to press into the ground), 'Sawa' emphasizes completion and care. For example: The Quran states: «ثُمَّ سَوَّاهُ وَنَفَخَ فِيهِ مِن رُّوحِهِ» (32:9) Translation: Then He proportioned him and breathed into him of His [created] soul. Although this verse relates to the creation of man, the use of 'Sawa' clarifies the meaning of making something complete and balanced, which also highlights its significance in the act of burial."
    }
  ],
  "708": [
    {
      "id": 3262,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Constellations - Buruj",
      "hw": "بروج",
      "s": "The word 'Burj' denotes heavenly towers or clusters of stars that are prominent due to their grandeur and firmness.",
      "d": "'Burj' means lofty structures or heavenly signs that are characterized by strength and magnificent construction. This word originates from the trilateral root 'B-R-J', which carries the meaning of rising, being prominent, or protection. Unlike other words like 'Qasr' (palace) or 'Sarh' (high building), 'Buruj' is generally used for celestial or astronomical structures. For example: The Quran states: «وَلَقَدْ جَعَلْنَا فِي السَّمَاءِ بُرُوجًا وَزَيَّنَّاهَا لِلنَّاظِرِينَ» (15:16) Translation: And We have certainly placed in the heaven great stars and have beautified it for those who look."
    },
    {
      "id": 3263,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Constellations - Buruj",
      "hw": "بروج",
      "s": "'Zayyana' in the context of Buruj has been used to mean adorning the heavens with stars or granting beauty to celestial structures.",
      "d": "'Zayyana' means to make something beautiful, to adorn, or to enhance its attractiveness. This word differs from related terms like 'Husn' or 'Jamal' in that it expresses additional adornment on something, not its inherent beauty. In Quranic usage, this word appears to manifest cosmic grandeur and the artistry of Allah. For example: The Quran states: «وَلَقَدْ جَعَلْنَا فِي السَّمَاءِ بُرُوجًا وَزَيَّنَّاهَا لِلنَّاظِرِينَ» (15:16) Translation: And We have certainly placed in the heaven great stars and have beautified it for those who look."
    },
    {
      "id": 3264,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Constellations - Buruj",
      "hw": "بروج",
      "s": "The use of 'Nathara' is generally for looking.",
      "d": "'Nathara' means to look, to see, so that something becomes visible, whether it actually appears or not. Its usage is also in both senses. For example: The Quran states: «وَإِذَا مَاۤ أُنزِلَتْ سُورَةٌ نَّظَرَ بَعْضُهُمْ إِلَى بَعْضٍ» (9:127) Translation: And when a surah is revealed, they look at one another [as if saying], 'Does anyone see you?' At another place, the Almighty says: «فَانظُرِي مَاذَا تَامُرِينَ» (27:33) Translation: Then see what [will be the] consequence of your decree. However, the use of 'nathar' is generally related to seeing with the eyes."
    },
    {
      "id": 3265,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Constellations - Buruj",
      "hw": "بروج",
      "s": "'Nur' in the context of Buruj is a sign of celestial light and divine manifestations that reflect the grandeur of the cosmic system.",
      "d": "'Nur' means that light which dispels apparent and inner darkness, whether material or spiritual. This word is distinguished from other terms like 'Dhiya' or 'Siraj' in that it specifically encompasses purity, guidance, and divine manifestations. In relation to Buruj (celestial towers or clusters of stars), 'Nur' pertains to the radiance of heavenly bodies and the reflection of the order and control of the universe through them. For example: The Quran states: «وَجَعَلْنَا فِي السَّمَاءِ بُرُوجًا وَزَيَّنَّاهَا لِلنَّاظِرِينَ» (25:61) Translation: And He placed within the heaven great stars and beautified it for those who look."
    },
    {
      "id": 3266,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Constellations - Buruj",
      "hw": "بروج",
      "s": "The meaning of 'Baraka' in the context of Buruj is to manifest the greatness and blessings of Allah, which indicates the stabilization, firmness, and addition of blessings in something.",
      "d": "'Baraka' means to make something firm, stable, and blessed. This word differs from other terms like 'Khalq' or 'Ja'al' in that it includes not just existence but also blessing, expansion, and permanence. For example, in the Quran, Allah Almighty has designated the Buruj (clusters of stars or magnificent structures) in the heavens as a sign of His power and blessings. For example: The Quran states: «تَبَارَكَ الَّذِي جَعَلَ فِي السَّمَاءِ بُرُوجًا» (25:61) Translation: Blessed is He who placed in the heaven great stars."
    }
  ],
  "709": [
    {
      "id": 3267,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Romans - Rum",
      "hw": "رومی",
      "s": "'Ghalaba' means to achieve supremacy through force and power.",
      "d": "'Ghalaba' carries the meaning of strength, force, and intensity (from the root M-L-B), i.e., to achieve superiority and dominance through force. To conquer. And 'Maghlub' is one who is forced and overpowered through force and strength. For example: The Quran states: «كَم مِّن فِئَةٍ قَلِيلَةٍ غَلَبَتْ فِئَةً كَثِيرَةً بِإِذْنِ اللّٰہِ» (2:249) Translation: How many a small group has overcome a large group by permission of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 3269,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Romans - Rum",
      "hw": "رومی",
      "s": "'Dana' indicates the proximity of victory after the defeat of the Romans and its nearness in terms of time.",
      "d": "'Dana' means the nearness of something in terms of time or place. This word is derived from 'Dunwat' (proximity) and differs from other terms like 'Qurb' or 'Jawar' in that 'Dana' specifically carries the meaning of immediate or intense nearness. For example: The Quran states: «غُلِبَتِ الرُّومُ * فِي أَدْنَى الْأَرْضِ وَهُم مِّن بَعْدِ غَلَبِهِمْ سَيَغْلِبُونَ» (30:2-3) Translation: The Romans have been defeated in the nearest land, but they, after their defeat, will soon be victorious."
    }
  ],
  "710": [
    {
      "id": 3272,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happy - Khush",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "'Khush' means the feeling of happiness and prosperity that arises from God's pleasure and grace.",
      "d": "'Khush' has the Arabic root (Kh-Sh-W), which originally expresses happiness, prosperity, and joy. Its idiomatic meaning arises when a person feels happiness and contentment through God's pleasure, grace, and worship. Compared to related terms, it specifically expresses happiness arising from God's grace and pleasure. For example: The Quran states: «وَإِذْ قَالَ رَبُّكَ لِلْمَلَائِكَةِ إِنِّي جَاعِلٌ فِي الْأَرْضِ خَلِيفَةً» (Al-Baqarah / 30) Translation: And [mention, O Muhammad], when your Lord said to the angels, 'Indeed, I will make upon the earth a successive authority.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3273,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happy - Joyful",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "«شاد» originally means happiness that gives peace to the human heart, and then its meaning extends to comfort and ease.",
      "d": "«شاد» has its root in ش-د-د, which in Urdu means 'happiness' and 'peace'. Its literal meaning is 'happy' which makes the human heart feel good. It has several synonyms such as: peace, comfort, joy, delight, bliss, pleasure, ease, and solace. But the difference between «شاد» and «خوش» is that «شاد» has a specific and strong feeling of happiness from the sense of emotion that gives a particular kind of peace to the heart. For example: In the Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ وَلَا نَجْعَلْ فِي قُلُوبِنَا غِلًّا لِّلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا رَبَّنَا إِنَّكَ رَءُوفٌ رَحِيمٌ» (الحج / ۴۰) Translation: 'And those who came after them say, 'Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith and put not in our hearts [any] resentment toward those who have believed. Our Lord, indeed You are Kind and Merciful.' (22:40)'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3274,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happy - Delighted",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "«مسرور» describes a deep and peaceful state of joy that is felt from the depths of the heart.",
      "d": "«مسرور» means the joy that arises in the heart upon attaining a particular cause or blessing. It is derived from the Arabic root سَرَّ (to be happy), which differs from other words like «فرح» (great happiness) or «بَشِش» (outward happiness) because it emphasizes inner peace and lasting joy. For example: In the Quran: «فَوَقَاهُمُ اللَّهُ شَرَّ ذَٰلِكَ الْيَوْمِ وَلَقَّاهُمْ نَضْرَةً وَسُرُورًا» (76 / 11) Translation: 'So Allah protected them from the evil of that day and gave them radiance and joy.' (76:11)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3275,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happy - Farhan",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "'Farhan' expresses a temporary or inappropriate state of happiness often associated with pride or arrogance.",
      "d": "'Farhan' means to boast about something or display temporary delight based on 'farah' (joy). This word differs from other terms for happiness (like 'sa'id' or 'masrur') in that the element of joy is transient, superficial, or sometimes arrogant. For example, the Quran states: «كُلُّ حِزْبٍۭ بِمَا لَدَيْهِمْ فَرِحُونَ» (30 / 32). Translation: 'Every faction rejoices in what it has.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3276,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happy - Khurram",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "'Khurram' is the state of happiness characterized by deep freshness and vitality.",
      "d": "'Khurram' means joy filled with exuberance, freshness, and vigor. This word is distinguished from other synonyms like 'farah' or 'surur' because it specifically expresses natural freshness, liveliness, and inner energy. It is often used in descriptions of abundant blessings or the lushness of a garden. For example, the Quran states: «مَّثَلُ ٱلَّذِينَ يُنفِقُونَ أَمْوَٰلَهُمُ ٱبْتِغَآءَ مَرْضَاتِ ٱللَّهِ وَتَثْبِيتًۭا مِّنْ أَنفُسِهِمْ كَمَثَلِ جَنَّةٍۭ بِرَبْوَةٍ أَصَابَهَا وَابِلٌۭ فَـَٔاتَتْ أُكُلَهَا ضِعْفَيْنِ» (2 / 265). Translation: 'The example of those who spend their wealth in the way of Allah is like a seed [of grain] that grows seven spikes; in each spike is a hundred grains. And Allah multiplies [His reward] for whom He wills.'"
    }
  ],
  "711": [
    {
      "id": 3277,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Grief - Gham",
      "hw": "غم",
      "s": "'Gham' is used in all meanings of sorrow, anguish, restlessness, pain, and regret.",
      "d": "The fundamental meaning of 'Gham' is 'to cover' or 'to conceal'. 'Gummi' means dust and darkness, and 'ghamam' means a cloud that covers the sun's light. And 'gham' means restlessness, pain, and affliction. For example, the Quran states: «ثُمَّ اَنۡزَلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِ الۡغَمِّ اَمَنَۃً نُّعَاسًا یَّغۡشٰی طَآئِفَۃً مِّنۡکُمۡ» (3 / 154). Translation: 'Then after distress, He sent down upon you a sense of security [in the form of] drowsiness, overcoming a faction of you.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3278,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Grief - Anguish",
      "hw": "غم",
      "s": "«اندوہ» describes a deep and permanent form of grief that envelops the heart.",
      "d": "«اندوہ» means a deep and long-lasting sorrow that envelops the heart, expressing an internal state. It is derived from the Arabic root غ-م-م, which fundamentally means 'to cover' or 'to envelop'. Unlike other synonyms such as «حُزن» (temporary sorrow) or «كرب» (distressing anxiety), «اندوہ» emphasizes the intensity and permanence of grief. For example: In the Quran: «فَأَثَابَكُمْ غُمًّا بِغَمٍّ» (3 / 153) Translation: 'Then He repaid you with grief for grief.' (3:153)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3279,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Grief - Miall",
      "hw": "غم",
      "s": "'Miall' expresses the deep feeling of regret and sorrow over the absence or loss of something.",
      "d": "'Miall' means the pain and remorse felt in the heart due to a loss, deprivation, or regret, an emotional state that can penetrate to the depths when solace is not found. This word differs from general grief (huzn) in that the element of hopelessness and thinking about the past is predominant. For example, the Quran states: «رُبَمَا يَوَدُّ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا لَوْ كَانُوا مُسْلِمِينَ» (15 / 2). Translation: 'Perhaps those who disbelieve will wish that they had been Muslims.' Here, 'yawadd' (to wish) expresses the painful regret of the disbelievers, which aligns with the meaning of 'miall'."
    },
    {
      "id": 3280,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Grief - Ranj",
      "hw": "غم",
      "s": "'Ranj' is linked to feelings of weakness, complexity, and hopelessness that oppress the heart.",
      "d": "The essence of 'Ranj' is a feeling associated with weakness, complexity, and hopelessness that burdens the heart. These words express more emotional and human-specific states. In contrast, 'gham' refers to a state of feeling that arises particularly through the human mind. 'Ranj' is a specific type of feeling that is constantly present in the human heart. For example, the Quran states: «وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ لَيَكُونَنَّ فِي تَرَدُّدٍ مِنْهُمْ» (39 / 26). Translation: 'And those who came after them will be in doubt about them.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3281,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Grief - Regret",
      "hw": "غم",
      "s": "«افسوس» particularly expresses failure, loss, and a painful state of the heart in the expression of grief.",
      "d": "«افسوس» means failure, loss, ruin, and the heightened heartache that a person feels. These words are different in that «غم» generally refers to a state of feeling, while «افسوس» specifically indicates heartache due to failure or ruin. Its root begins with أَفْسُوس, which is a word expressing a deep state of feeling. For example: In the Quran: «أَفْسُوسَ عَلَى الْقَوْمِ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ إِذَا مَرُّوا بِهِمْ وَلَمْ يَجِدُوا فِيهِمْ مِنْ أَهْلِهِمْ أَحَدًا» (الأنفال / ۲۷) Translation: 'Alas for the believing people when they passed by them and did not find among them any of their own.' (8:27)"
    }
  ],
  "712": [
    {
      "id": 3282,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger - Anger",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "«غصہ» means when a person considers themselves great and ignores others, and also ignores their own reality.",
      "d": "«غصہ» has an Arabic root غ-ص-ہ, which originally means to make something small appear big. Lexically, it means 'to make big' or 'to consider oneself great'. This word expresses a great thought in a person's mind that leads them to ignore others and consider themselves great. Its synonyms are «تعصب» or «غرور», but the specific meaning of «غصہ» is that a person, by considering themselves great, ignores others and also ignores their own reality. For example: In the Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ بِآيَاتِنَا وَسُلْطَانٍ مُّبِينٍ إِلَىٰ فِرْعَوْنَ وَمَلَأِهِۦ فَقَالُوآ إِنَّا نَحْنُ كَانَ الْمُؤْتَمِرُونَ قَالَ يَا فِرْعَوْنُ إِنِّي لَكَ الْمُنْذِرُ الْمُبِينُ لَقَدْ جَاءَكَ الْحَقُّ مِنْ رَّبِّكَ فَأَمَّا يَكُونَ لَكَ أَنْ تَكُونَ فِي الْمُحْتَشِمِينَ فَإِنَّهُ لَمَّا يَغْصُو فِي الْمُحْتَشِمِينَ وَإِنَّهُ لَمَّا يَغْصُو فِي الْمُحْتَشِمِينَ فَلَوْلَا أَنْ يَكُونَ فِي الْمُحْتَشِمِينَ» (طه 20:13-20) Translation: 'It is stated that Moses was sent with Our signs and clear authority to Pharaoh and his chiefs. They said, 'We are aware that we have to do this.' It was said, 'O Pharaoh, I am to you a clear warner. Indeed, the truth has come to you from your Lord, but if you, considering yourself great, ignore others, then it is a misguidance. Similarly, when he, in anger, ignores others, the result is that he also ignores his own reality.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3283,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger - Wrath",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "«غَضَبٌ» when a person becomes furious with anger and seeks revenge, whether small or big, it is related to the other person's essence, not one's own.",
      "d": "«غَضَبٌ» according to صَاحِبِ فِقْہُ الْلُغَۃ is a general term used for all types of anger. (ف ل 169) But this definition does not seem correct. The Messenger of Allah ﷺ defined anger as: «اِتَّقُوْا مِنْ الْغَضَبِ فَاِنَّہٗ جُمْرَۃٌ تُوْقَدُ فِیْ قَلْبِ ابْنِ اٰدَمَ اَلَمْ تَرَوْا اِلَی انْتِفَاخِ اَوْدَاجِہٖ وَجُمْرَۃِ عَیْنَیْہِ» Translation: 'Beware of anger, for it is a spark that ignites in the heart of the son of Adam. Do you not see the inflammation of his veins and the redness of his eyes?' And obviously, this state occurs when anger overwhelms a person and he resorts to revenge. And ابْنُ الْفَارِسْ has defined its meanings as 'اَشَدّْ السَّخَط' meaning extreme displeasure. (م ل) And صاحبِ مُنْجِد has written for «غَضِبَ» the meanings 'to hold grudge' and 'to become angry'. (منجد) And 'بمعنی اِرَادَۃُ الضَّرْر لِلْمَغْضُوْبِ عَلَیْہِ' meaning 'the intention to harm the one against whom anger is directed'. And «غَضْب» always comes from the other, meaning it can be from the small to the big or from the big to the small. (فق ل 106) For example: In the Quran: «وَ مَنۡ یَّحْلِلۡ عَلَیۡہِ غَضَبِیۡ فَقَدۡ ہَوٰی» (20/81) Translation: 'And whoever incurs My wrath has indeed perished.' (20:81)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3284,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger - Fury",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "«قہر» means a specific, ruthless emotion of anger that leads to the heart splitting.",
      "d": "«قہر» means a specific, ruthless emotion of anger that leads to the heart splitting. It occurs with a sigh, which causes the heart to split and others to be exposed. There is a difference between qahr and anger; anger generally occurs with feeling, while qahr is an expression of additional pressure and a kind of ruthlessness. Example: In the Quran:\n«وَإِذْ أَخَذَ اللَّهُ مِيثَاقَ الَّذِينَ أَتَوْا مِن قَبْلِكَ لِيَقُولَنَّ الَّذِينَ أَحْسَنُوا وَالَّذِينَ قَدْ أَخْلَفُوا مِنْهُمْ أَنَّ اللَّهَ لَمْ يَكُنْ بِهِمْ عَلِيمًا» (Al-An'am / 150)\nTranslation: 'And when Allah took the covenant from those who were before you that they would support their people with strength and aid, then later they said, \"Allah has no knowledge of us.\"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3285,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger - Rage",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "«طیش» means a specific point of anger that shows disorder, restlessness, and corruption of the heart.",
      "d": "«طیش» in Urdu means anger, frustration, and disorder. Its Arabic origin is طیش, which originally means burning, heart corruption, and emotional disorder. In contrast, «غضب» is generally a sudden and intense burst of emotion, while «طیش» is a continuous, irregular, and heart-corrupting manifestation of emotion. «طیش» implies willfulness, restlessness, and heart corruption that makes a person's emotions irregular and corrupt. For example: In the Quran: «وَإِذَا مَسَّكَ اللَّهُ الْقَلْبَ فَلَا مُفَرِّضٍ لَّهُ وَإِذَا مَسَّكَ الْغَضَبَ فَلَا مُعَلِّقٍ لَّهُ» (الأنعام 6/103) Translation: 'And when Allah seizes the hearts, there is no protector for them, and when He seizes with anger, there is no restrainer for them.' (6:103)"
    }
  ],
  "713": [
    {
      "id": 3286,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love - Love",
      "hw": "محبت",
      "s": "«محبت» means a feeling of attachment created by God and filling the heart, which draws a person towards their Master.",
      "d": "«محبت» has an Arabic root م-ح-ب, which originally expresses a strong attachment or inclination. This word indicates the feeling of going towards something, which manifests on the surface of the heart as emotion. In contrast, «عشق» has a more general and overflowing meaning, while «حب» indicates the feeling of attaching one's heart's matters to something. «محبت» specifically points towards God, who is the creator of the heart's inclinations. For example: In the Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُ كَنِيْٓءٌ وَّلَا وَلَدٌ وَّلَمْ يَكُن مَّعَهُ شَرِيكٌ فَلِيَّهُ الْحُبُّ وَلَهُ الْمَلَكُ وَهُوَ عَلَىٰ كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ» (الطلاق: ۳) Translation: 'And He has no equal or child, and there is no partner with Him. To Him belongs all love and sovereignty, and He is over all things competent.' (65:3)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3287,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love - Ardent Love",
      "hw": "محبت",
      "s": "'Ishq' is a special manifestation of love that expresses human and divine relationships.",
      "d": "In Urdu, 'Ishq' is a special form of love that expresses human and divine relationships. Its Arabic origin is عَشَق which starts with the letter 'Ain' and means 'a distracted heart' or 'to be helpless'. Its literal meaning is 'to see' or 'to love'. Ishq means that a person loves their companion or God boundlessly, with an extraordinary and unique feeling. Its English equivalent is 'love' or 'affection', but the feeling of ishq is special as it brings one's dreams to the forefront. For example, the Quran states: «وَاللَّذِينَ جَاهَدُوا فِيْنَا لَنَحْنُهُمْ وَلَنَحْنُهُمْ وَإِلَيْهِ يَرْجِعُ الْأُمُورُ» (العنكبوت، ۲۹: ۶۵). Translation: 'Those who strive in My cause, they are with Me, and I am with them, and all matters return to Him.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3288,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love - Inclination",
      "hw": "محبت",
      "s": "'Al-Fat' signifies a special feeling and relationship that arises in a person's heart.",
      "d": "The root of 'Al-Fat' is the Arabic root الف-ت-ی which originally signifies many special qualities that arise in a person's heart, such as love, emotion, and connection. This word represents a specific type of love that arises at a particular level within the heart, expressing a unique feeling and human relationship. In contrast, 'Hubb' generally means love, while 'Wadd' signifies simple connection and emotion. 'Al-Fat' particularly signifies the feeling of love in the human heart that expresses a special bond between a person's mind and heart. For example, the Quran states: «وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ وَلَا نَجْعَلْ فِي قُلُوبِنَا غِلَّ الْقُوَّةِ إِلَىٰ أَهْلِهِ مِنَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ رَبَّنَا وَلَكَ الْحَمْدُ أَنْتَ وَلِيُّنَا فِي الدُّنْيَا وَالْآخِرَةِ وَلَكَ الْحَمْدُ» (آل عمران / 195). Translation: 'And those who came after them say, \"Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith, and do not place in our hearts resentment toward any of the believers. Our Lord, You are our protector in this world and the Hereafter, and to You is the final return.\"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3289,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love - Devotion",
      "hw": "محبت",
      "s": "«پیار» means the intense love and feeling that arises specifically in a person's heart, which is the most valued and does not ignore the filled soul of the heart.",
      "d": "«پیار» in Urdu derives from the Arabic word 'piyaar' which originally means 'burning of hearts' or 'connection of hearts'. It means to love someone deeply, to burn one's heart for them, and to understand their state. In contrast, «محبت» is the most general term, while «پیار» specifically denotes heart-burning, intense love, and the belovedness of the heart. «پیار» is a word that does not ignore the state of the heart but expresses it in the best way. Example: In the Quran:\n«وَالَّذِينَ جَاهَدُوا فِيْنَا لَنَحْنُ لَهُمْ مُّلْكُ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالأَرْضِ فَإِنَّمَا يَجْزَوْنَ مَا كَانُوا يَعْمَلُونَ» (Al-An'am / 127)\nTranslation: 'And those who strive for Us - We will surely grant them the kingdom of the heavens and the earth. And they will be recompensed only for what they used to do.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3290,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Love - Desire",
      "hw": "محبت",
      "s": "'Chahat' means the feeling of love and the desire to see one's companion that arises from a person's heart.",
      "d": "In Urdu lexicon, 'Chahat' is the primary equivalent of love, derived from the Arabic 'Chahat' which originally signifies the heart's desire and courage. This term signifies a person's best and extraordinary desire that accompanies the heart. In contrast, 'Mohabbat' is a general expression for liking someone, while 'Chahat' is a feeling of connection that arises from the heart. This term signifies a person's desire, which is the wish to see another person. For example, the Quran states: «وَاللَّذِي جَاءَ بِالْحُكْمِ مِنَ اللَّهِ فَلَمْ يَجِدْ مِنْهُمْ أَحَدًا لَمْ يَكُن مُتَّبِعًا لِلْمَنْ هُوَ أَعْلَمُ بِالْمُعْتَقِدِينَ» (النساء/ ۱۶۷). Translation: 'Those who come with the judgment from Allah and do not find among them anyone who is not a follower of the one who is most knowing of the believers.'"
    }
  ],
  "714": [
    {
      "id": 3291,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Hatred - Hatred",
      "hw": "نفرت",
      "s": "'Nafrat' means to feel intense disgust or revulsion towards something, which creates deep aversion in the heart and mind.",
      "d": "'Nafrat' means a feeling of disgust, aversion, or revulsion towards something, whether natural or acquired, which is against human nature or rational thought. This word is derived from the Arabic trilateral root ن-ف-ر which means 'to turn one's back' or 'to move away'. It differs from other words like 'Karahah' (dislike) or 'Bughd' (deep hatred) in that 'Nafrat' involves complete physical or psychological deviation. For example, the Quran states: «كَأَنَّهُمْ حُمُرٌ مُّسْتَنفِرَةٌ» (74 / 50). Translation: 'As if they were donkeys fleeing [in panic].' In this verse, 'mustanfirat' (those who flee in hatred) refers to people who flee from the reminder of truth like donkeys flee from a predator, which illustrates the practical meaning of 'nafrat'."
    },
    {
      "id": 3292,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Hatred - Enmity",
      "hw": "نفرت",
      "s": "'Adawat' is that deep form of enmity and opposition that breeds hatred in hearts.",
      "d": "'Adawat' means a state of enmity, opposition, and emotional tension that settles in hearts, causing permanent hatred. This word is derived from the Arabic trilateral root ع-د-و which signifies enmity, confrontation, and conflict. Unlike other synonyms like 'Bughd' (temporary dislike) or 'Kinah' (personal grudge), 'Adawat' involves systematic opposition and social enmity. For example, the Quran states: «يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا لَا تَتَّخِذُوا عَدُوَّي وَعَدُوَّكُمْ أَوْلِيَاءَ» (60 / 1). Translation: 'O you who have believed, do not take my enemies and your enemies as allies.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3293,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Hatred - Aversion",
      "hw": "نفرت",
      "s": "'Karahat' signifies the state of dislike or accepting something reluctantly, which is somewhat different from deep-seated hatred arising from the heart.",
      "d": "'Karahat' means to feel burdened by something or to accept it unwillingly. This word is derived from the Arabic root ك-ر-ه which denotes an action done under compulsion or reluctance. It differs from other terms like 'Bughd' (inner hatred) or 'Shiddat-i Inkār' (intense denial) in that 'Karahat' often involves practical compulsion or acceptance of something disliked under a religious ruling. For example, the Quran states: «كُتِبَ عَلَيْكُمُ الْقِتَالُ وَهُوَ كُرْهٌ لَّكُمْ» (2 / 216). Translation: 'Fighting has been prescribed for you, though it is disliked by you.' Here, 'kurh' refers to the lack of inner consent while complying with Allah's command, clarifying both the psychological and legal aspects of the term."
    },
    {
      "id": 3294,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Hatred - Malice",
      "hw": "نفرت",
      "s": "'Bughd' means the feeling of deep hatred and enmity in the heart, often based on enmity or injustice.",
      "d": "'Bughd' means firm hatred or malice in the heart that manifests in actions and behaviors. This word is derived from the Arabic root ب-غ-ض which indicates something breaking or ending, such as the breaking of a relationship. Unlike 'Karahah' (dislike), 'Bughd' signifies greater intensity, depth, and enduring enmity. For example, the Quran states: «وَدُّوا لَوْ تَكْفُرُونَ كَمَا كَفَرُوا فَتَكُونُونَ سَوَاءً فَلَا تَتَّخِذُوا مِنْهُمْ أَوْلِيَاءَ حَتَّىٰ يُهَاجِرُوا فِي سَبِيلِ اللَّهِ فَإِن تَوَلَّوْا فَخُذُوهُمْ وَاقْتُلُوهُمْ حَيْثُ وَجَدتُّمُوهُمْ وَلَا تَتَّخِذُوا مِنْهُمْ وَلِيًّا وَلَا نَصِيرًا إِلَّا الَّذِينَ يَصِلُونَ إِلَى قَوْمٍ بَيْنَكُمْ وَبَيْنَهُم مِيثَاقٌ أَوْ جَاءُوكُمْ حَصِرَتْ صُدُورُهُمْ أَن يُقَاتِلُوكُمْ أَوْ يُقَاتِلُوا قَوْمَهُمْ وَلَوْ شَاءَ اللَّهُ لَسَلَّطَهُمْ عَلَيْكُمْ فَلَقَاتَلُوكُمْ فَإِنِ اعْتَزَلُوكُمْ فَلَمْ يُقَاتِلُوكُمْ وَأَلْقَوْا إِلَيْكُمُ السَّلَمَ فَمَا جَعَلَ اللَّهُ لَكُمْ عَلَيْهِمْ سَبِيلًا سَوْفَ تَجِدُونَ آخَرِينَ يُرِيدُونَ أَن يَأْمَنُوكُمْ وَيَأْمَنُوا قَوْمَهُمْ كُلَّ مَا رُدُّوا إِلَى الْفِتْنَةِ أُرْكِسُوا فِيهَا فَإِن لَّمْ يَعْتَزِلُوكُمْ وَيُلْقُوا إِلَيْكُمُ السَّلَمَ وَيَكُفُّوا أَيْدِيَهُمْ فَخُذُوهُمْ وَاقْتُلُوهُمْ حَيْثُ ثَقِفْتُمُوهُمْ وَأُولَٰئِكَ جَعَلْنَا لَكُمْ عَلَيْهِمْ سُلْطَانًا مُبِينًا» (3 / 118). Translation: 'And they wish that you would disbelieve as they have disbelieved, so you would be alike. So do not take from them allies until they emigrate for the cause of Allah. But if they turn away, then seize them and kill them wherever you find them and take not from them any ally or helper, except those who connect with a people between you and whom there is a treaty or who come to you, their hearts restrained from fighting you or fighting their own people. And if Allah had willed, He could have given them power over you, and they would have fought you. So if they remove themselves from you and do not fight you and offer you peace, then Allah has not made for you a cause against them. You will find others who wish to be safe from you and safe from their people. Every time they are returned to temptation, they are overcome by it. So if they do not remove themselves from you and do not offer you peace and restrain their hands, then seize them and kill them wherever you overtake them. And those - We have made for you against them a clear authorization.'"
    }
  ],
  "715": [
    {
      "id": 3295,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Fear - Fear",
      "hw": "خوف",
      "s": "'Khawf' in the Quranic context denotes anxiety, dread, or apprehension, generally concerning Allah's displeasure or punishment, which includes the aspect of caution and piety.",
      "d": "'Khawf' means anxiety or fear arising from the anticipation of harm, pain, or an undesirable outcome. This word is derived from the Arabic root خ-و-ف which describes a mental state in the face of danger. It differs from other words like 'Khashiyah' (fear rooted in awe and reverence) or 'Rahbah' (dread) in that 'Khawf' involves a sense of immediate or potential danger. For example, the Quran states: «إِنَّمَا ذَٰلِكُمُ الشَّيْطَانُ يُخَوِّفُ أَوْلِيَاءَهُ فَلَا تَخَافُوهُمْ وَخَافُونِ إِن كُنتُم مُّؤْمِنِينَ» (3 / 175). Translation: 'That is only Satan frightening his allies, so do not fear them but fear Me, if you are believers.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3296,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Fear - Dread",
      "hw": "خوف",
      "s": "'Dar' in the context of fear expresses a cautious attitude concerning Allah's displeasure and punishment, aiming to avoid it.",
      "d": "'Dar' means a feeling in the heart prompted by the anticipation of an undesirable outcome, which compels a person to be cautious. The Arabic word 'Khawf' has the root خ-و-ف, which is different from words like 'Khashiyah' (awe-based respect) or 'Rahbah' (dread) because it emphasizes the awareness of consequences and a sense of responsibility. For example, the Quran states: «إِنَّمَا ذَٰلِكُمُ الشَّيْطَانُ يُخَوِّفُ أَوْلِيَاءَهُ فَلَا تَخَافُوهُمْ وَخَافُونِ إِن كُنتُم مُّؤْمِنِينَ» (3 / 175). Translation: 'That is only Satan frightening his allies, so do not fear them but fear Me, if you are believers.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3297,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Fear - Terror",
      "hw": "خوف",
      "s": "'Dahshat' describes an intense and sudden state of fear that arises in the heart due to a danger or terrifying sight.",
      "d": "'Dahshat' means a state of unexpected or intense fear that causes trembling and anxiety in the heart. This word is distinct from Persian 'Dahshat' and Arabic terms like 'Ra'b' or 'Khashiyah' which denote more general or permanent fear. For example, the Quran states: «أُولَـٰئِكَ الَّذِينَ لَعَنَهُمُ اللَّـهُ فَأَصَمَّهُمْ وَأَعْمَىٰ أَبْصَارَهُمْ» (47 / 23). Translation: 'Those are the ones upon whom Allah has cursed, so He deafened them and blinded their eyes.' In this verse, the state of 'dahshat' is related to the intense fear of Allah's wrath that settles in the hearts of disbelievers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3298,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Fear - Dread",
      "hw": "خوف",
      "s": "«Dread» [a specific meaning of fear that also includes religious events, which protects a person's faith and religion]",
      "d": "«Dread» means a feeling of fear on a person's heart that motivates it towards protecting its religion and faith. This fear is related to an ideology or teaching that makes a person realize their actions in the presence of God. This differs in translation from «خائف» or «ڈر», which generally refers to fear against a person's decisions. For example: In the Quran: «الَّذِينَ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِاللَّهِ وَالْيَوْمِ الْآخِرِ وَيَعْمَلُونَ صَالِحًا فَأُولَٰئِكَ يُحَبُّونَ اللَّهَ وَيُحَبُّونَهُ مُحَبَّةً كَثِيرَةً» (البقرة ۲/۱۶۵) Translation: Those who believe in Allah and the Last Day and do good deeds, it is they who love Allah and are loved by Him greatly."
    }
  ],
  "716": [
    {
      "id": 3299,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Hope - Hope",
      "hw": "امید",
      "s": "«Hope» means a peaceful desire for positive future outcomes with complete trust in Allah and expectation of His mercy.",
      "d": "«Hope» means expecting a better future or positive outcome, based on faith and reliance. This word is derived from the Arabic 'أَمَد' (duration/time), referring to the continuity of time and the future. Unlike other synonyms like 'توقع' (waiting for something) or 'آس' (reliance of the heart), 'امید' includes deep trust in Allah's mercy along with patience in waiting. For example: In the Quran: «وَمَن يَقْنَتَ مِنكُنَّ لِلَّهِ وَرَسُولِهِ وَتَعْمَلْ صَالِحًا نُؤْتِهَا أَجْرَهَا مَرَّتَيْنِ وَأَعْتَدْنَا لَهَا رِزْقًا كَرِيمًا» (33/31) Translation: And those among you who are obedient to Allah and His Messenger and do righteous deeds, We will give them their reward twice and prepare for them a noble provision."
    },
    {
      "id": 3301,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Hope - Expectation",
      "hw": "امید",
      "s": "«Expectation» is the original meaning of hope which also includes the thought of the heart.",
      "d": "«Expectation» means the state of waiting for the future with hope, thought, expectation, and the thought of the heart, which includes the thought of the heart. Its original roots are تَوَقَّع (تَوَقَّع) which means to have hope with a thought, and to wait for a specific thing. It is synonymous with «hope» but «expectation» has a specific additional meaning that it is hope with a thought, and it is with the thought of another person or thing. For example: In the Quran: «وَاللَّذِينَ جَاهَدُوا فِينَا لَنَحْنُ هُمُ الْمُهْتَدُونَ» (الانعام / ٩٣) Translation: «And those who strive for Us, it is they who are the guided.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3302,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Hope - Supplication",
      "hw": "امید",
      "s": "«Supplication» is the original meaning of hope which plans human desire and the help of others.",
      "d": "«Supplication» means to indicate oneself with human desire, hope, clarification, relationship, and the help of others. These words are: رَجَاءٌ (supplication), رَجُوٌّ (hope) and رَجِیٌّ (desirous). Its original root is ر-ج-اء. Rajaa means to indicate oneself with human desire, hope, and the help of others. Additionally, it is a specific term that plans human desire and the help of others. For example: In the Quran: «وَلَا تَأْخِرْنِي فِي الْمُحْتَجَّاتِ مِنَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ» (البقرة / 134) Translation: \"And do not save me in the state of the needy among the believers.\""
    }
  ],
  "717": [
    {
      "id": 3303,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Despair - Despair",
      "hw": "مایوسی",
      "s": "«Despair» means a state where one does not obtain from Allah, and does not understand oneself; when one does not receive the mercy or blessings obtained from Allah, then the feeling of despair arises.",
      "d": "«Despair» its literal meaning is related to ownership terms which originally indicates «مایوس» which is a type that relates to our freedom and commerce. Its basic term means: a state where a person, after seeing the results of their actions or due to the absence of mercy or blessings obtained from Allah, fails to understand themselves. Additionally, compared to other words, despair expresses the feeling of the absence of blessings obtained from Allah. For example: In the Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَ مُوسَىٰ لِقَوْمِهِ يَا قَوْمِ إِنَّكُمْ ظَلَمْتُمْ أَنْفُسَكُمْ بِاتِّخَاذِكُمُ الْعِجْلَ فَتُوبُوا إِلَىٰ بَارِئِكُمْ فَاقْتُلُوا أَنفُسَكُمْ فَأَسْلَمُوا وَهُوَ أَحْسَنُ لَكُمْ» (الأنعام/١٤٧) Translation: When Moses said to his people, «You have wronged yourselves by taking the calf, so repent to your Creator and kill yourselves; then you will be guided, and that is best for you.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3304,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Despair - Disappointment",
      "hw": "مایوسی",
      "s": "«Disappointment» means the feeling of losing courage from Allah when a person sees the results of their actions with despair.",
      "d": "«Disappointment» its Arabic root is نا-امیدی, where نا- is a negative prefix and related to امیدی, which means hope. These words are in contrast to despair. Despair is a feeling when a person sees the results of their efforts with despair. Its difference from other words is like «ہیں» (despair) or «خیال» (insecurity). «Disappointment» is a specific feeling that is the feeling of losing courage from Allah. For example: In the Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّنْ أَعْدَاءِ اللَّهِ مِنْ وَاقِعٍ» (الأنفال 8/57) Translation: \"And they had no difficulty from the enemies of Allah.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3305,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Despair - Despondency",
      "hw": "مایوسی",
      "s": "«Despondency» is the original meaning of despair which disturbs a person's heart with hopelessness and failure.",
      "d": "«Despondency» means the state of a person's heart's hopelessness, failure, and despair which distances them from their actions. These words are derived from the word «قنوط» which originally indicates hopelessness and failure. In contrast, it is used together with «کُسْف» or «خَسَرَانِی», but «قنوطیت» specifically refers to the state of heart's hopelessness after a person's pain and suffering. For example: In the Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ بِآيَاتِنَا وَسُلْطَانٍ مُّبِینٍ» (طه / 43) Translation: «And We certainly sent Moses with Our signs and a clear authority.»"
    }
  ],
  "718": [
    {
      "id": 3306,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Amazement - Amazement",
      "hw": "حیرت",
      "s": "«Amazement» means when something makes us feel unexpected and helpless, it explains it.",
      "d": "«Amazement» its original root is the word ح-ی-ر-ت which in Urdu expresses a specific feeling. These words are the feeling of helplessness and wonder before something that also comes to us from the scene before us. Its meaning is related to the feeling of helplessness, wonder, and failure before something. In contrast, «تعجب» means only a feeling, but «حیرت» also includes helplessness with the feeling. For example: In the Quran: «أَلَمْ تَرَ إِلَى الَّذِي أَخَذَ قَوْلَكُمْ وَجَعَلَ مِنْهُمْ أَزْوَاجًا وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ مِنْ أَزْوَاجِهِمْ مِنْ بَعْدِ ذَلِكَ أَبَوَانِ مَنْ كَانَ لَهُمْ فِي الْقَوْلِ مِنْ حِلْمٍ وَإِنَّهُ لَمَّا تَصَدَّقَ الْمَوْعِظَةَ مِنْهُمْ وَمَنْ قَالَ لَهُمْ أَنْ لَيْسَ لَكُمْ مِنْ أَبَوَيْكُمْ مِنْ بَعْدِ ذَلِكَ أَبَوَانِ مِنْ حِلْمٍ وَإِنَّهُ لَمَّا تَصَدَّقَ الْمَوْعِظَةَ مِنْهُمْ» (النساء/١٥٩) Translation: «Have you not seen those who took your words and made some of them into spouses, and there were no parents for them from their spouses after that? And when they were admonished, the death of their words was felt, and when they were admonished, there was no matter from their parents after that from modesty, and when they were admonished, the death of their words was felt.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3307,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Amazement - Wonder",
      "hw": "حیرت",
      "s": "«Wonder» means to express the heart greatly towards something that is strange and extraordinary.",
      "d": "«Wonder» the word in Arabic comes from «تعجب» which originally means the feeling of the heart upon seeing something to express it particularly. These words are a great feeling of the heart about something that is strange and extraordinary. In contrast, «حیرت» generally means the feeling that something is very great. «Wonder» means a great feeling of the heart towards something that is very strange and extraordinary. For example: In the Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَ مُوسَىٰ لِقَوْمِهِ ادْعُوا رَبَّكُمْ وَلْيَمْسَطْ لَكُمْ رِزْقَهُ» (الأعراف، ١٤٣) Translation: When Moses said to his people that they should pray to their Lord and arrange for their provision from Him."
    },
    {
      "id": 3308,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Amazement - Astonishment",
      "hw": "حیرت",
      "s": "«Astonishment» means the feeling of wonder and amazement with the increasing appearance of Allah's great power and creation's reward when facing something that is extraordinary.",
      "d": "«Astonishment» its original lexical origin is استعجاب, which in Urdu means the educational feeling that arises upon facing Allah's power. Consequently, upon seeing something, wonder and feeling arise that how such a deed was done from it. Its equivalent in Urdu is wonder, but «استعجاب» means wonder with Allah's power and order. This meaning is best manifested in a specific verse of the Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ جَاهَدُوا فِينَا لَنَحْنُ هُمُ الْمُهْتَدُونَ» (سورہ طارق / آیت ۱۰) Translation: When the believers saw them, they said: «We felt that we have to face it for ourselves.»"
    }
  ],
  "719": [
    {
      "id": 3309,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Shame - Shame",
      "hw": "شرم",
      "s": "‘Sharm’ means to distress oneself over one's disobedience and sins, and to feel the heart beating because of it.",
      "d": "‘Sharm’ is an Arabic root (sh-r-m) which essentially manifests as a feeling in a person’s heart when they realize that their disobedience or sin might cause regret to others. This word represents a specific feeling of human moral connection, a sense of having crossed a boundary. It means a type of feeling that prevents a person from sinning, and it is different from words like ‘khajli’ (embarrassment) or ‘diwanagi’ (madness). For example: The Quran states:\n«وَالَّذِينَ إِذَا مَآ أَنْفَقُوا لَمْ يُسْرِفُوا وَلَمْ يَقْتُرُوا وَكَانُوا بَيْنَ ذَٰلِكَ رَاسِخِينَ» (النور / ۳۷)\nTranslation: ‘And those who, when they spend, are neither extravagant nor stingy, but hold a moderate course between them.’"
    },
    {
      "id": 3310,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Shame - Modesty",
      "hw": "شرم",
      "s": "‘Haya’ is a human and religious feeling given by God that prevents a person from indecent and inappropriate acts.",
      "d": "‘Haya’ originates from the Arabic root ‘haya’ (ح-ی-ا) which expresses a human and religious feeling. This word essentially is a feeling born in a person’s heart that prevents them from indecent and inappropriate acts. In contrast, ‘khajal’ (embarrassment) is a feeling that occurs in one’s personal life that prevents them from acts that seem wrong in their own eyes. ‘Haya’ represents a person’s religious and human feeling that helps them fulfill the laws given by God. For example: The Quran states:\n«الَّذِينَ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِاللَّهِ وَالْيَوْمِ الْآخِرِ وَيَأْمُرُونَ بِالْمَعْرُوفِ وَيَنْهَوْنَ عَنِ الْمُنكَرِ وَيُقِيمُونَ الصَّلَاةَ وَيُؤْتُونَ الزَّكَاةَ وَهُمْ يَخْشَوْنَ رَبَّهُمْ مِّنْ غَيْرِ مَا يَرَوْنَهُ وَهُمْ يُقِيمُونَ الْحَدِيثَ» (البقرۃ ۲/۴۵)\nTranslation: Those who have believed in Allah and the Last Day, they have enhanced society, prevented inappropriate acts, established prayer, given zakah, and they assist their Lord in fulfilling the laws given by God at that time."
    },
    {
      "id": 3311,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Shame - Regret",
      "hw": "شرم",
      "s": "‘Nadamat’ is the true meaning of shame that reflects a person’s goodness and beauty, when they keep themselves protected from exposure and wrong deeds.",
      "d": "‘Nadamat’ means the feeling of human goodness and beauty that prevents a person from their sins and wrong deeds. This feeling is such that a person realizes that their human goodness and moral virtues exist, and they want to keep their beauty and humanity protected from themselves. It means that we preserve our goodness, and we also reflect our beauty through our actions. It is contrasted with other words like ‘khajal’ or ‘be khajli’ which are not merely human feelings but specifically involve a sense of human goodness. For example: The Quran states:\n\n«وَلَا تَكُونُوا الَّذِينَ يُؤْلِينَ أَنْفُسَهُمْ وَيَحْسَدُونَ النَّاسَ عَلَىٰ مَا آتَاهُمُ اللَّهُ مِنْ فَضْلِهِ» (سورة عمران، آیت 173)\nTranslation: \"And do not be those who expose themselves and envy people for what Allah has given them of His bounty.\""
    }
  ],
  "720": [
    {
      "id": 3313,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Pride - Arrogance",
      "hw": "فخر",
      "s": "‘Ghurur’ means considering oneself more important and belittling others, which brings harm to a person.",
      "d": "‘Ghurur’ means considering oneself more important and belittling others, which brings harm to a person. Its Arabic root is ‘gh-r-r’ which in Urdu is synonymous with ‘fakhar’ (pride). Its lexical origins in Urdu also include ‘fakhar’, ‘bara’ (great), ‘khudpasandi’ (self-centeredness), and ‘eitmad’ (confidence), but ‘ghurur’ specifically means considering oneself more important, which results in belittling others. For example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَا تَفْرَحْ وَلَا تَغْرُورْ بِاللَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا» (النساء / 43)\nTranslation: ‘And do not rejoice or be arrogant because of those who disbelieved.’"
    },
    {
      "id": 3314,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Pride - Boasting",
      "hw": "فخر",
      "s": "‘Tafakhar’ means considering oneself superior to others and attempting to show one’s blessings and strength to others.",
      "d": "‘Tafakhar’ (from Arabic ‘tafakhar’) is an Urdu word that attempts to show one’s power, qualities, or blessings to others. Its lexical meaning is: to consider oneself superior, to display one’s possessions to others, and to try to distinguish one’s example from others. It differs from ‘fakhar’ which means to truly appreciate one’s blessings and feel one’s rights, and from ‘takabbur’ which means to consider oneself superior in opposition to God. For example: The Quran states: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَٰلِكَ إِلَّا فَخْرٌ وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَٰلِكَ إِلَّا فَخْرٌ» (الأنعام/147) Translation: In that, they had no pride except their own pride."
    }
  ],
  "721": [
    {
      "id": 3315,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Patience - Patience",
      "hw": "صبر",
      "s": "‘Sabr’ means to endure when calamities and difficulties befall.",
      "d": "‘Sabr’ means to endure a calamity or hardship when it befalls and not express restlessness, impatience, or lamentation. For example: The Quran states:\n«فَصَبَرُوۡا عَلٰی مَا کُذِّبُوۡا وَ اُوۡذُوۡا حَتّٰۤی اَتٰہُمۡ  نَصۡرُنَا» ( 6/34 )\nTranslation: So the prophets endured the denial and harm until Our help came to them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3316,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Patience - Endurance",
      "hw": "صبر",
      "s": "‘Tahammul’ emphasizes the readiness to bear burdens and the specific quality of enduring hardship in the sense of patience.",
      "d": "‘Tahammul’ means to consciously take upon oneself a hardship, responsibility, or difficulty and endure it with steadfastness. This word derives from the root ‘h-m-l’ which fundamentally means ‘to carry’ or ‘to bear’. Compared to other words like ‘sabr’ (endurance) or ‘sabt’ (steadfastness), ‘tahammul’ emphasizes active consent and the choice of bearing a burden. For example: The Quran states: «رَبَّنَا وَلَا تُحَمِّلْنَا مَا لَا طَاقَةَ لَنَا بِهِ» (البقرہ 2/286) Translation: Our Lord, do not impose upon us a burden beyond our capacity."
    },
    {
      "id": 3317,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Patience - Tolerance",
      "hw": "صبر",
      "s": "‘Bardashat’ expresses the quality of facing difficulties with calmness and steadfastness in the context of patience.",
      "d": "‘Bardashat’ means to endure a hardship or trial with courage and self-control without complaint. This word derives from the root ‘bard’ (coolness) which refers to keeping emotions cool during the act of patience. Unlike ‘tahammul’ (to endure), ‘bardashat’ includes not only accepting the hardship but also strengthening one’s actions upon it. For example: The Quran states: «وَاسْتَعِينُوا بِالصَّبْرِ وَالصَّلَاةِ» (2 / 153) Translation: And seek help through patience and prayer."
    }
  ],
  "722": [
    {
      "id": 3318,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Error - Error",
      "hw": "غلطی",
      "s": "‘Ghalti’ refers to an error that occurs in an action due to mistake, fault, or deviation from the path, usually caused unintentionally or due to negligence.",
      "d": "‘Ghalti’ means to exceed the bounds of truth in an action due to unintentional or careless behavior. Lexically, it is derived from the Arabic triliteral ‘gh-l-t’ which encompasses meanings of ‘misguidance’, ‘straying’, or ‘distorting facts’. This word differs from ‘khatta’ (unintentional error) in that ‘ghalti’ often includes conscious negligence or ignoring evidence. For example: The Quran states: «وَمَا مَنَعَ النَّاسَ أَن يُؤْمِنُوا إِذْ جَاءَهُمُ الْهُدَىٰ إِلَّا أَنْ قَالُوا أَبَعَثَ اللَّهُ بَشَرًا رَّسُولًا» (18/55) Translation: And what prevented the people from believing when guidance came to them except that they said, ‘Has Allah sent a human as a messenger?’ (Here, it refers to erroneous reasoning based on ‘mghalitatan’.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3320,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Error - Slip",
      "hw": "غلطی",
      "s": "‘Laghsh’ means an expression of error that happens unintentionally or due to ignorance.",
      "d": "‘Laghsh’ means an expression of error that happens unintentionally or due to ignorance. Its Arabic root is ‘w-h-d’ which means ‘to guide’, and ‘laghsh’ means ‘against guidance’. It is also synonymous with ‘ghalti’, ‘afsos’ (regret), ‘khatta’ (error). The literal meaning of ‘laghsh’ is to be against guidance, while ‘ghalti’ means to deviate from the correct path. For example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَا تَقُولُوا لِمَنْ يَمُوتُ فِي مَلْكِهِ أَنَّهُ مَوْتٌ إِلَّا أَنْ تَقُولُوا لَهُ لَعَلَّ اللَّهَ لِيَجْعَلَ لَكُمْ خَيْرًا فِي مَلَكِهِ وَلَعَلَّهُ يَمُوتُ فِي مَلَكِهِ وَأَنْتُمْ تَعْمَلُونَ» (سورة النمل، آیت 84)\nTranslation: Do not say about one who dies in his land, ‘He is dead,’ but say, ‘Perhaps Allah will grant you better in his place, and perhaps he will die in his land while you are unaware.’"
    }
  ],
  "723": [
    {
      "id": 3321,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Regret - Regret",
      "hw": "افسوس",
      "s": "«Regret» expresses grief or remorse over an irreparable loss or missed opportunity, indicating intense sorrow.",
      "d": "«Regret» means intense grief or remorse arising from an irreparable loss, failure, or missed opportunity. This term entered Arabic from Persian, and its closest equivalent in Quranic Arabic is «حَسْرَة» (ḥasrah), which conveys the same feeling. «Regret» differs from general remorse («نَدم»), as it focuses on irreversible past losses rather than future expectations. For example, the Quran states: «يَا حَسْرَةً عَلَى الْعِبَادِ» (36/30) Translation: 'Alas, upon the servants!' (for how they ignored the truth)."
    },
    {
      "id": 3322,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Regret - Yearning",
      "hw": "افسوس",
      "s": "«Yearning» conveys the intensity of regret, lingering remorse, and the feeling that arises after a missed opportunity has passed.",
      "d": "«Yearning» means a deep sense of regret, loss, or remorse over something irrecoverable. Derived from the Arabic root «ح-س-ر» meaning 'loss' or 'deficiency', it contrasts with terms like 'ندامت' (remorse) or 'غم' (grief) by emphasizing future anxiety and the irrevocable nature of past moments. For example, the Quran states: «يَقُولُ يَا لَيْتَنِي قَدَّمْتُ لِحَيَاتِي» (89/24) Translation: 'He will say, \"Oh, I wish I had sent something ahead for my life!\"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3323,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Regret - Sorrow",
      "hw": "افسوس",
      "s": "«Sorrow» describes a deep and enduring form of regret associated with feelings of remorse over failure or past actions.",
      "d": "«Sorrow» signifies intense regret or remorse that deeply affects the heart, often recurring. Its linguistic root is 'م ل ل', implying repetition or weariness. Unlike general grief, sorrow involves persistent remorse and spiritual fatigue. For example, the Quran states: «رُّبَمَا يَوَدُّ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا لَوْ كَانُوا مُسْلِمِينَ» (15/2) Translation: 'There will be times when the disbelievers wish they had been Muslims.'"
    }
  ],
  "724": [
    {
      "id": 3324,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happiness - Happiness",
      "hw": "خوشی",
      "s": "«Happiness» in the Quran refers to inner joy, contentment, and gratitude for God's blessings, transcending temporary worldly pleasures.",
      "d": "«Happiness» denotes a state of inner peace, positive emotions, and awareness of divine favors. In Arabic, it is distinguished from 'فرح' (temporary joy/vanity) and 'سرور' (inner tranquility) by its spiritual purity and lasting contentment. For example, the Quran states: «قُلْ بِفَضْلِ اللَّهِ وَبِرَحْمَتِهِ فَبِذَٰلِكَ فَلْيَفْرَحُوا هُوَ خَيْرٌ مِّمَّا يَجْمَعُونَ» (10/58) Translation: 'Say, \"In the bounty of Allah and in His mercy – in that let them rejoice; it is better than what they collect.\"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3325,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happiness - Bliss",
      "hw": "خوشی",
      "s": "«Bliss» means deep inner happiness and heartfelt joy that is lasting and pure.",
      "d": "«Bliss» signifies profound and concealed joy felt within the heart, rooted in 'س ر ر' which denotes inner tranquility and pure delight. Unlike 'فرح' which is transient, bliss is characterized by depth and permanence. For example, the Quran states: «فَوَقَاهُمُ اللَّهُ شَرَّ ذَٰلِكَ الْيَوْمِ وَلَقَّاهُمْ نَضْرَةً وَسُرُورًا» (76/11) Translation: 'So Allah will protect them from the evil of that Day and will grant them brightness and joy.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3326,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happiness - Cheerfulness",
      "hw": "خوشی",
      "s": "«Cheerfulness» is the essence of happiness that expresses the prosperity and comfort of the human heart.",
      "d": "«Cheerfulness» represents the heart's prosperity, ease, and joy. It is akin to the Arabic concept of 'ریز', emphasizing inner comfort. It differs from fleeting emotions by reflecting a sustained state of cardiac well-being. For example, the Quran states: «وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ وَلَا نَجْعَلْ فِي قُلُوبِنَا غِلًّا لِّلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا رَبَّنَا إِنَّكَ رَءُوفٌ رَّحِيمٌ» (49/13) Translation: 'And those who came after them say, \"Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith, and put not in our hearts resentment toward those who have believed. Our Lord, indeed You are Kind and Merciful.\"'"
    }
  ],
  "725": [
    {
      "id": 3327,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Sorrow - Sorrow",
      "hw": "دکھ",
      "s": "«Sorrow» means to show, display, and present prominently, particularly used to express emotions.",
      "d": "«Sorrow» derives from the root «د-ك-ه» meaning 'to show' or 'to manifest'. It specifically refers to the expression of feelings, states, or conditions. While synonyms include 'دیکھنا' (to see) and 'نظر آنا' (to appear), 'دکھ' is distinct for emotional expression. For example, the Quran states: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ بِآيَاتِنَا وَإِنَّا لَهُمْ مُّحْتَجَّةٌ» (21/45) Translation: 'And We certainly sent Moses with Our signs; and indeed we are argumentative against them.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3328,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Sorrow - Grief",
      "hw": "دکھ",
      "s": "'Grief' is used in all meanings such as distress, sorrow, pain, and regret.",
      "d": "The basic meaning of 'Gham' is to cover and hide. 'Ghumi' means dust and darkness, and 'Ghamam' means cloud that covers the sun's light. And 'gham' means distress, pain. For example, in the Quran: «ثُمَّ اَنۡزَلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِ الۡغَمِّ اَمَنَۃً نُّعَاسًا یَّغۡشٰی طَآئِفَۃً مِّنۡکُمۡ» ( 3/154 ) Translation: 'Then after the distress, He sent down upon you security from drowsiness, which overcame a group of you.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3329,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Sorrow - Anguish",
      "hw": "دکھ",
      "s": "«Anguish» is the essence of sorrow that exerts a strong impact on the human heart and mind.",
      "d": "«Anguish» refers to profound sorrow and distress that deeply affects one's heart and intellect, often leading to separation from oneself. It is a specific type of pain that permeates the mind and heart. For example, the Quran states: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا مِنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ حَبٌّ حَتَّى تَأْتِيَهُمُ الْبَيِّنَةُ مِن رَّبِّكَ فَقَدْ كَانَ فِي أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ مِن قَبْلِهَا حَبٌّ وَإِنَّهُمْ لَمْ يَكُونُوا مُحَرَّكِينَ مِنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ حَبٌّ حَتَّى تَأْتِيَهُمُ الْبَيِّنَةُ مِن رَّبِّكَ» (2/207) Translation: 'And there has not been among the people of the Scripture and the believers any affection until there came to them the clear evidence from their Lord. And there was not among them before that any affection, nor were they moved from the affection of the people of the Scripture and the believers until there came to them the clear evidence from their Lord.'"
    }
  ],
  "726": [
    {
      "id": 3330,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Restlessness - Restlessness",
      "hw": "بےچینی",
      "s": "«Restlessness» indicates doing something without interest or enthusiasm, which deviates from the true meaning.",
      "d": "«Restlessness» means performing an action heedlessly, without care or attention. Its Arabic term 'بَيْچِینِی' implies doing something in a distracted manner. It differs from 'بے دلی' (apathy) which denotes lack of feeling. For example, the Quran states: «وَلَوْلَا دَعَوْتُهُمْ لَقَدْ كُنتُمْ مِّنَ الْمُحْسِنِينَ» (2/217) Translation: 'And if you had not invoked Allah, you would have been among the wrongdoers.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3331,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Restlessness - Anxiety",
      "hw": "بےچینی",
      "s": "«Anxiety» means that something stands still and does not move easily, like a sundial's gnomon standing in the sun and expanding.",
      "d": "«Anxiety» literally means something that stands upright and does not move readily, such as a sundial's gnomon standing in the sun and expanding. Its root in Urdu terms implies making something stand or exposing it to the sun. This contrasts with 'بےچینی' which denotes heedlessness. For example, the Quran states: «وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا غَفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ وَلَا نَجْعَلْ فِي قُلُوبِنَا غِلًّا لِلْمُؤْمِنِينَ وَرَبَّنَا إِنَّكَ رَءُوفٌ رَحِيمٌ» (3/194) Translation: 'And those who came after them say, \"Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith, and put not in our hearts resentment toward the believers. Our Lord, indeed You are Kind and Merciful.\"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3332,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Restlessness - Anxiety",
      "hw": "بےچینی",
      "s": "'Anxiety' means to live in an unknown and unprotected place, which expresses the meaning of 'restlessness'.",
      "d": "'Anxiety' originates from the Arabic 'be-qarari', which means unknown, unprotected, and residing in an unknown place. This word essentially indicates all kinds of hopelessness and lack of stability, clarifying the human condition in the context of restlessness. In contrast, 'restlessness' means to place something in an unknown and unprotected place, which is an explanatory meaning of anxiety. Its synonyms are 'instability' or 'unsettledness', but 'anxiety' specifically means placing something in an unknown place which is a characteristic of restlessness.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا أَنْزِلْ لَنَا مِنْ فَوْقِنَا ظَهْرًا مِّنْ سَاقِطٍ وَرَحْمَةً مِّنْ عِندِكَ وَلِيَكُونَ لَنَا آمِنًا مِّنْ لَّدُنْهُ وَلَوْ أَنَّهُمْ كَانُوا يَعْلَمُونَ» (Al-Baqarah 2:247)\nTranslation: 'And those who came after them say, \"Our Lord, send down to us from above us a rain of what falls and a mercy from Yourself, and make for us from Yourself a secure place. If they had known, what would they have done?\"'"
    }
  ],
  "727": [
    {
      "id": 3333,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Assurance - Assurance",
      "hw": "اطمینان",
      "s": "'Assurance' means firm and stable trust gained from God that gives peace to the heart and is not abandoned again.",
      "d": "'Assurance' derives from the Arabic 'itminan', which is related to the meanings of 'faith' and 'trust', and thus embodies the attribute of natural and faithful trust. It means that the human heart improves itself, and with it comes a sense of faith and love. Its synonym is 'faith', but 'assurance' includes additional trust and a sense of heart's peace along with faith.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِهِ وَيَتَوَakkَّفُونَ فِي أَمْرِهِمْ وَلَا يَرْتَابُونَ» (Al-Baqarah / 59)\nTranslation: 'And those who come after them will believe in it and will not be perturbed in their matters, nor will there be doubt in them.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3334,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Assurance - Tranquility",
      "hw": "اطمینان",
      "s": "'Tranquility' is the original meaning of assurance that expresses the peace and comfort of the human heart when it is before God and presents its duties.",
      "d": "'Tranquility' means the connection and peace of the heart, which also makes a person feel that they have reached their God. It is a new state in terms of words that provides the heart's tranquility. It is an expression of a person's heart's tranquility when they present their actions and duties.\n\nIn contrast, the meanings of 'amin' and 'itminan' are similar, but in 'sukun', the expression of the human heart's peace is more evident.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ» (Al-Baqarah 2/286)\nTranslation: 'And those who came after them say, \"Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith.\"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3335,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Assurance - Consolation",
      "hw": "اطمینان",
      "s": "'Consolation' is the original meaning of assurance that expresses faith in the human heart and the peace gained from the Lord.",
      "d": "'Consolation' originates from the Arabic root 'tasallā', which expresses a state that imparts a sense of peace and comfort to the human heart. This word expresses faith, certainty, and trust gained from the Lord in the human heart. It is a specific kind of assurance that not only expresses a feeling like the heartbeat but also demonstrates the strengthening of faith and the state of being with God.\n\nIn contrast, 'aman' means general assurance, 'itminan' means only trust, and 'taminan' means a sense of peace along with trust.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَالَّذِينَ جَاهَدُوا فِيْنَا لَنَحْنُ هُمُ الْمُهْتَدُوْنَ» (Al-An'am 6/73)\nTranslation: 'And those who strive in Us, We will guide them.'"
    }
  ],
  "728": [
    {
      "id": 3336,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Khushamad - Khushamad",
      "hw": "خوشامد",
      "s": "«Khushamad» means that which increases beyond joy and comfort, and because of it, a person feels happiness.",
      "d": "The original root of «Khushamad» is related to joy, comfort, and support, which naturally gives a person happiness and ease. Its lexical meaning is \"joy\" or \"comfort\" that is the best and most giving of happiness. In contrast, \"joy\" (khush) only indicates general happiness, whereas \"khushamad\" indicates a joy that is specifically superior, that which surpasses many joys.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَإِذَا مَسَّكُمُ الْقَلَقُ أَشَدَّ مِنَ الْقَلَقِ» (Al-Baqarah/155)\nTranslation: \"And when distress touches you, it is a greater distress than the previous one.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3337,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Khushamad - Chaplusi",
      "hw": "خوشامد",
      "s": "«Chaplusi» (flattery/ingratiation) is a specific aspect of khushamad that expresses a person's excellent conduct and courage.",
      "d": "«Chaplusi» means that a person's heart and soul are happy, and their behavior and courage are also better when they show khushamad to someone. This term, in contrast to others, signifies a specific point of khushamad that manifests a person's excellent conduct and courage. This word is also used in the Quran when a person shows khushamad to someone with all their heart's happiness. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَإِذَا جَاءُوا عَلَيْهِمْ قَالُوا سَلَامًا» (2/25)\nTranslation: \"When they came to them, they said, 'Peace.'\""
    }
  ],
  "729": [
    {
      "id": 3339,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Ilm - Danish",
      "hw": "علم",
      "s": "«Danish» means reading, understanding, and a specific quality of knowledge that gives a person the ability to comprehend and utilize information.",
      "d": "«Danish» means reading, understanding, and a specific quality of knowledge that gives a person the ability to comprehend and utilize information. Its original root is «د-ن-ش», which means to read and understand repeatedly. In contrast to «Ilm» (knowledge), which generally looks at information or cognition, «Danish» is that information which gives a person the ability to understand and use. «Ilm» is a general term, while «Danish» is a specific term that denotes a person's education, understanding, and performance. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَاللَّهُ يَعْلَمُ مَا تَحْمِلُ كُلُّ أُنْثَىٰ وَمَا تَغِيضُ الْأَرْحَامُ وَمَا تَزْدَادُ فِي الْكَلَامِ إِلَّا مِنْهُ وَيَعْلَمُ مَا فِي الْقُلُوبِ» (41/53)\nTranslation: \"And Allah knows what every female carries and what the wombs lose [prematurely] or exceed. And with Him, no matter is hidden from the knowledge of the heavens and the earth, and not even the weight of an atom, nor less than that nor greater, except it is in a clear register. And He knows what is in the hearts.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3340,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Ilm - Aagahi",
      "hw": "علم",
      "s": "«Aagahi» means the ability to know and the collection of learning that particularly expresses divine wisdom and the teachings of the Prophet.",
      "d": "The root of «Aagahi» is «آگہی», which originally means wisdom, knowledge, and learning. This word is used in several different meanings, but «Aagahi» is specifically used to mean knowing, understanding, and acquiring related knowledge. It implies knowledge divinely ordained and the acquisition of that knowledge. In contrast to other terms, «Aagahi» specifically means the acquisition of wisdom and its educational use, which is divinely given. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«أَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا أَن تَكُونَ لِقَوْمٍ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِاللَّهِ وَيَعْمَلُونَ الصَّالِحَاتِ مَرْحَبًا؟» (Al-Baqarah/204)\nTranslation: \"Has it not been for the believers that they should be for a people who believe in Allah and work righteousness, a welcome?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3341,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Ilm - Marifat",
      "hw": "علم",
      "s": "«Marifat» means a specific nature of knowledge that describes detailed information about things already known.",
      "d": "«Marifat» means a specific nature of knowledge that describes detailed information about things already known. Its Arabic root is «معرفت», which originally means \"to know\" and \"to recognize.\" It means that a person has such knowledge that they can retain it in their mind and also convey it to others. It differs from the knowledge of knowing and the knowledge of information, because «Marifat» implies knowing something and also being able to express it clearly. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَاللَّهُ أَعْلَمُ بِمَا يُوعَدُونَ» (An-Naml, 60)\nTranslation: \"And Allah is most knowing of what they are promised.\""
    }
  ],
  "730": [
    {
      "id": 3342,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Aql - Aql",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "«Aql» is the intellect that saves from harm and devises means to choose beneficial things.",
      "d": "«عَقْلَ» means to be sensible, to be capable of realizing error (manjad), and «عَقَلَ» means to restrain and forbid. And «عِقَال» is the fetter with which a camel's foot is tied (muf). Thus, the function of intellect is to distinguish between benefit and harm, to adopt measures to avoid harmful things (fiqh. l 65), and to always be prepared for beneficial things and the acceptance of knowledge. Then, to ponder (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَقَالُوا لَوْ كُنَّا نَسْمَعُ أَوْ نَعْقِلُ مَا كُنَّا فِي أَصْحَابِ السَّعِيرِ» (67/10)\nTranslation: \"And they will say, 'If we had only listened or used our intellect, we would not be among the companions of the Blaze.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3343,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Aql - Khird",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "«Khird» refers to a person's mental ability and capacity for understanding, which Allah has given humans so that they may comprehend truth and reform.",
      "d": "The original root of «Khird» is «خرد», which originally means the ability to understand everything and make correct judgments. This word aligns with terms like «عقل» (intellect), «فکر» (thought), «تفکر» (contemplation), and «ہوش» (mind). However, unlike «عقل», the use of «خرد» generally limits itself to a person's mental ability and their capacity to understand truth through it. The Noble Quran states: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي أُمَمٍ مِّن قَبْلِكَ رُسُلًا أَخْبَرْنَا بِهِمُ الْقُرْآنَ وَلَقَدْ جَاءَتْهُمْ رُسُلُهُم بِالْبَيِّنَاتِ فَكَانُوا لَهُمْ لَمْ يَكُونُوا يُؤْمِنُونَ» (Al-An'am 6/159). Translation: \"And We have already sent messengers before you, [O Muhammad], among the nations of former times. And there came to them their messengers with clear proofs, but they were not to believe in that which they had previously rejected. Thus, We seal the hearts of those who defiantly disobey.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3344,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Aql - Fahm",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "«Fahm» means intellectual sagacity and the knowledge of wisdom that gives a person a sense of guidance from Allah.",
      "d": "The original root of «Fahm» is «فَهْم», which in Urdu means \"to understand\" and \"to comprehend.\" These words are very important and more specific, whereas the meaning of intellect generally refers to mental power. Terms related to intellect mean, for example, the power of understanding, the capacity to comprehend, and forming a theory. The meaning of intellect is a person's mental power that gives them the ability to understand and comprehend, while the meaning of fahm is the capacity to understand, which is specifically a part of a person's mental power. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَعَمِلُوا الصَّالِحَاتِ لَهُمْ أَجْرٌ غَيْرُ مَمْنُونٍ» (Al-Baqarah 2/286)\nTranslation: \"For those who believe and do righteous deeds, there will be a reward uninterrupted.\""
    }
  ],
  "731": [
    {
      "id": 3345,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Soch - Soch",
      "hw": "سوچ",
      "s": "«Soch» means mental thought, contemplation, and analysis that is divinely given.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of «Soch» is «س-و-چ», which expresses thought, contemplation, analysis, and mental activity. Its verbal synonyms are contemplation, thought, reflection, analysis, and mention, but «Soch» particularly expresses the vision and thought given by the Lord. Its explanation is like one or more words that occur in the matter of God and while turning oneself towards God. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«أَفَلَا يَتَفَكَّرُونَ فِي خَلْقِ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالأَرْضِ» (3/190)\nTranslation: \"Then do they not reflect upon the creation of the heavens and the earth?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3346,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Soch - Fikr",
      "hw": "سوچ",
      "s": "«Fikr» is the original meaning of soch, which is the act of contemplation and realization through the mind.",
      "d": "The Arabic root word of «Fikr» is «ف-ک-ر», which expresses contemplation, thought, and mental activity. This word differs from other synonyms of soch like «تامل» (deliberation) or «الٹا» (the other) because the element of mental contemplation and analysis is more evident in fikr. This word describes the operation of a person's mind, which is the act of thinking, understanding, and comprehending. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّيَ حَوْفٌ أَنْ يَّكُونَ مَعَهُمْ وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّيْ حَوْفٌ أَنْ أَطْرُدَهُمْ فَأَنْتَ أَعْلَمُ بِمَا يَفْعَلُونَ» (Al-Ankabut/30)\nTranslation: \"And I had no fear of them, nor was I with them when they plotted. And I only fear Allah, and I am not heedless of what they do.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3347,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Thought - Idea",
      "hw": "سوچ",
      "s": "'Idea' is a specific way of thinking that is based on the mind's concepts and thoughts.",
      "d": "'Idea' means the mind's concepts, thoughts, and the act of thinking that arises in the human mind. It does not involve words but expresses the internal process of the mind. Unlike synonymous words such as 'thought' and 'experience', 'idea' particularly expresses human mental concepts.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَوْ أَنَّهُمْ كَانُوا أَمَامًا وَلَا خَلْفًا وَلَا نَحْوًا مِّنَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ لَكَانَ خَيْرًا لَّهُمْ وَلَهُمْ فَرَجٌ مِّنْهُمْ وَلَهُمْ مَّوْعِدٌ مُّقَرَّبٌ» (Al-Anfal / 17)\nTranslation: 'If they had been in front, behind, or to the sides of the believers, it would have been better for them, and they would have had relief from them, and they would have had a nearby appointment.'"
    }
  ],
  "732": [
    {
      "id": 3348,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Remembrance - Remembrance",
      "hw": "یاد",
      "s": "'Remembrance' means to keep in mind from the heart and its relation is then with performance and mention.",
      "d": "'Remembrance' originates from the Arabic 'yad' (remembrance), which is related like a calculation, and it means to keep in mind from the heart, to mention, and its difference with other words is that 'remembrance' is a human mental ability that keeps a thing as a mention and related performance, while other words like 'dhikr' or 'tazkira' generally refer to mentioning something.\n\nIt is established: 'If you remember, it will happen' (Al-Baqarah 2:286)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3349,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Remembrance - Memory",
      "hw": "یاد",
      "s": "'Memory' means to remember, to store as a reserve, and to preserve it.",
      "d": "'Memory' means to remember, to protect, and such a reserve that is preserved. Its original linguistic root is 'hifz' which means to remember, to protect, and to save. The specificity of 'remembrance' in this meaning is that it is not only remembering but also preserving it diligently. In comparison to other words, 'remembrance' generally means remembering, while 'memory' includes the protection and reserve of remembrance.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«أَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا أَن تَكُونَ تَحْتَهُمْ أَرْضٌ تَجْرِي مِن تَحْتِهَا الْأَنْهَارُ وَلَوْ كَانَتْ لَهُمْ أَعْمَالٌ فِي الْأَرْضِ لَقَدْ نَزَّلْنَا مِنَ السَّمَاءِ مَاءً فَأَخْرَجْنَاهُ مِن تَحْتِ الْأَرْضِ فَأَرْبَى مِنْهُمْ مُّؤْمِنُونَ وَلَكِنْ لَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّنْ حَافِظٍ مَّا أَنْشَأْنَا فِي الْأَرْضِ مِنْ شَجَرَةٍ وَلَوْ كَانَتْ لَهُمْ أَعْمَالٌ فِي الْأَرْضِ لَقَدْ نَزَّلْنَا مِنَ السَّمَاءِ مَاءً فَأَخْرَجْنَاهُ مِن تَحْتِ الْأَرْضِ فَأَرْبَى مِنْهُمْ مُّؤْمِنُونَ وَلَكِنْ لَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّنْ حَافِظٍ مَّا أَنْشَأْنَا فِي الْأَرْضِ مِنْ شَجَرَةٍ وَلَوْ كَانَتْ لَهُمْ أَعْمَالٌ فِي الْأَرْضِ لَقَدْ نَزَّلْنَا مِنَ السَّمَاءِ مَاءً فَأَخْرَجْنَاهُ مِن تَحْتِ الْأَرْضِ فَأَرْبَى مِنْهُمْ مُّؤْمِنُونَ وَلَكِنْ لَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّنْ حَافِظٍ مَّا أَنْشَأْنَا فِي الْأَرْضِ مِنْ شَجَرَةٍ» (An-Nahl: 14)\nTranslation: 'Do those people not remember that when there was a little land, rivers would flow beneath it, and if they worked in the land, We would send down water from the sky and bring it out from beneath the earth, then more believers would be among them, but they had no protector for what We created in the land of trees, even if they had worked in the land, We would send down water from the sky and bring it out from beneath the earth, then more believers would be among them, but they had no protector for what We created in the land of trees.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3350,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Remembrance - Reminder",
      "hw": "یاد",
      "s": "'Reminder' means to remember, especially things that come from God, and to mention them that help humans.",
      "d": "'Reminder' is an Arabic root 'tazkir', which essentially means to remember, to mention, and to understand and present things that come from God. This word of remembering is particularly used for remembering God's commands and His words.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَإِذْ أَنْجَيْنَا مُوسَىٰ وَأَهْلَهُ مِنَ الْعَذَابِ الْأَلِيمِ» (Ash-Shu'ara 28)\nTranslation: 'And when We saved Moses and his family from the painful punishment.'"
    }
  ],
  "733": [
    {
      "id": 3352,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speech - Conversation",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "'Conversation' means talk, instructive talk, dialogue that is with understanding.",
      "d": "'Conversation' originates from the Arabic 'goftegu', which shows the act of speaking and listening. This word is related to talk, dialogue, instructive talk, and understanding.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَ رَبُّكَ لِلْمَلَائِكَةِ إِنِّي جَاعِلٌ فِي الْأَرْضِ حَكَمًا» (Al-Baqarah / 30)\nTranslation: 'And when your Lord said to the angels, \"I am going to place a vicegerent on earth.\"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3353,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speech - Utterance",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "'Utterance' means speech that is transmitted through text and words.",
      "d": "'Utterance' originates from the word 'kalam', which is related to speech, talk, and text. This word is the name for both 'kalam' and 'bat', while other synonyms like 'qawl' or 'bayan' only refer to the formulation of speech. 'Kalam' essentially means speech that is the state of talk.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَ اللَّهُ يَا عِيسَى ابْنَ مَرْيَمَ أَأَنتَ قَالَتْ لِي بَابَاكَ أَنْتَ تَحْمِلُهُ مِنْهُمْ وَأَنْتَ تَقُولُ فِي الْمُؤْمِنِينَ مَا لَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ بِهِ عِلْمٌ وَلَكِنْ كَانَ لَهُمْ بِهِ مَعْرِفَةٌ» (3/48)\nTranslation: 'At that time Allah said to Jesus son of Mary, \"What did you say to your father?\" He said, \"You said to them that you should not take your child from them, and you said about the believers something that they did not have knowledge of, but they had recognition of it.\"'"
    }
  ],
  "734": [
    {
      "id": 3355,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Debate - Disputation",
      "hw": "بحث",
      "s": "'Mubāhasah' means to debate, to engage in dispute on a topic with opposition, which is done to defend a theory or argument.",
      "d": "'Mubāhasah' is derived from the Arabic root (mabḥath) and carries meanings related to discussion, dispute, and debate. These terms vary in certain aspects: researching, presenting evidence, disputing, and debating on a topic with opposition. Mubāhasah is a specific form of debate conducted with evidence and arguments. For instance, the Quran states: «وَمَا آتَىٰكُمُ الرَّسُولُ فَخُذُوهُ وَمَا نَهَاكُمْ عَنْهُ فَانْتَهُوا» (صلی اللہ علیہ وسلم) Translation: 'Take what the Messenger has given you and refrain from what he has forbidden you.' This verse highlights through debate an important principle on how we can engage in debate and dispute on matters supported by evidence."
    },
    {
      "id": 3356,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Debate - Discussion",
      "hw": "بحث",
      "s": "'Munāzarah' means debate that assists in discussing alternative opinions on a topic.",
      "d": "'Munāzarah' means to align different theories on a topic, to debate based on alternative opinions, and to clarify one's view. Its literal meaning is 'to see' or 'to view theories,' indicating debate on a specific topic. It differs from 'jadal' (strife) because 'munāzarah' involves only debate on alternative opinions, whereas 'jadal' may include opposition or quarrel. For example, the Quran says: «وَالَّذِينَ جَادَلُوا فِي آيَاتِ اللَّهِ بِغَيْرِ سُلْطَانٍ أَنْزَلْنَاهُ أُولَٰئِكَ يَخْرُجُونَ مِنَ الْمَنَازِرِ» (Ash-Shura 43) Translation: 'Those who dispute the signs of Allah without authority – they are the ones who will be expelled from the gatherings.'"
    }
  ],
  "735": [
    {
      "id": 3357,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Judgment - Judgment",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "'Faisalah' means decision, judgment, and ruling that emerges under human mental deduction in a specific situation.",
      "d": "'Faisalah' is an Arabic term (fayṣal) originally meaning 'to organize small things.' Its literal meaning is 'to do something' or 'to conclude.' This word differs from others like 'hukm' or 'qarar' because faisalah specifically refers to a judgment or decision that emerges under human mental deduction. The Quran states: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا مِنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ إِلَّا أَن يَّكُونَ فِي فِصَالِهِمْ وَلَوْ كَانَ مُحَارِبًا مُّعَدٍّ لَّقَدْ مَكَّنَّاهُمْ فِي فِصَالِهِمْ وَأَغْنَىٰهُمْ عَنْ أَن يَّكُونُوا بِالْمُؤْمِنِينَ فِي فِصَالِهِمْ وَإِنْ كَانَ فِي فِصَالِهِمْ فِي فِصَالِهِمْ وَلَوْ كَانَ فِي فِصَالِهِمْ فِي فِصَالِهِمْ» (Al-Baqarah 97/5) Translation: 'And those who disbelieve from the People of the Book and the believers will not cease to be in their divisions. If they had been a hostile army, He would have surely strengthened them in their divisions and made them independent from the believers in their divisions. If they had been in their divisions, He would have strengthened them in their divisions.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3358,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Judgment - Ruling",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "'Ḥakam' is a ruling that stops someone from injustice and provides a means for correction.",
      "d": "'Ḥakam' means 'to prevent injustice' (m. l.), a ruling that curbs oppression and injustice. It also means 'to prevent hostility' (faq l 156), i.e., a command to stop fighting and quarreling. For example, the Quran says: «وَ دَاوٗدَ  وَ سُلَیۡمٰنَ  اِذۡ یَحۡکُمٰنِ فِی الۡحَرۡثِ» (21/78) Translation: 'And [mention] David and Solomon when they judged concerning the field.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3359,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Judgment - Case",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "'Qaḍiyyah' means a legal or religious ruling given to solve issues.",
      "d": "'Qaḍiyyah' is an Arabic term meaning to provide a legal or religious ruling to resolve a related issue. It conveys the meaning of a specific judgment or decision given to solve a problem. For example, the Quran states: «وَقَضَىٰ رَبُّكَ أَنَّهُۥ لَيْسَ لَهُۥٓ إِلَٰهٌ إِلَّا هُوَ وَأَنَّهُۥٓ لَيْسَ لَهُۥٓ شَرِيكٌ» (Ash-Shu'ara 21) Translation: 'And your Lord has decreed that you worship none but Him, and that you be kind to parents. Whether one or both of them reach old age [while] with you, say not to them [so much as] 'uff' and do not repel them but speak to them in a noble manner.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3360,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Judgment - Ruling",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "'Fatah' is such a judgment that truth and falsehood are distinguished, complexity is removed, and no party remains in doubt.",
      "d": "'Fatah' means to remove restriction and complexity from something (opening). Its opposite is 'Ighlaq' meaning confinement and restriction. And 'Fatah' means to grant victory and to judge. Such a judgment that truth and falsehood are distinguished, complexity is removed, and no party remains in doubt.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«رَبَّنَا افۡتَحۡ بَیۡنَنَا وَ بَیۡنَ قَوۡمِنَا بِالۡحَقِّ» (7/89)\nTranslation: 'O our Lord! Judge between us and our people with truth.'"
    }
  ],
  "736": [
    {
      "id": 3361,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Consultation - Consultation",
      "hw": "مشورہ",
      "s": "'Mushāwarah' means consultation with politics and wisdom, based on human wisdom and educational necessity.",
      "d": "'Mushāwarah' derives from the Arabic root (m-sh-w-r) and pertains to wisdom, advice, and human education. It means consultation with politics and wisdom, based on human wisdom and educational necessity. It differs from other synonyms like 'mukālamah' (dialogue) or 'tashrīḥ' (explanation), which merely mean conversation or exposition. For example, the Quran says: «وَلَا تُكَلِّمُوا الَّذِينَ يَدْعُونَ رَبَّهُم بِالْغَدَاةِ وَعَشِيًا يُرِیدُونَ وَجْهَ رَبِّهِمْ» (30/43) Translation: 'And do not obey those whom their neglect of Our signs makes them greedy, and who say, 'Indeed, we have heard and we know.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3362,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Consultation - Opinion",
      "hw": "مشورہ",
      "s": "'Rā'ah' means understanding the original and real meaning of a related issue, referring to a person's thoughts and views.",
      "d": "'Rā'ah' (رَآيَة) is an Arabic term originally related to 'seeing' and 'thinking.' It means understanding a person's views, thoughts, and information on an issue. It is synonymous with 'mushāwarah' but specifically denotes a person's own perspective of seeing, understanding, and thinking. Unlike 'mushāwarah,' 'rā'ah' particularly represents an individual's specific ideas. For example, the Quran says: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّن بَعْدِ ذٰلِكَ مَوْلَىٰ وَلَا مَنْصُورٌ» (An-Nisa 125) Translation: 'And they had no protector or helper after that.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3363,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Consultation - Reform",
      "hw": "مشورہ",
      "s": "'Ṣalāḥ' means consulting with truth, justice, and fairness, necessary for resolving related issues.",
      "d": "'Ṣalāḥ' fundamentally means truth, justice, and fairness. These are qualities of truth and justice that arise in the human heart, essential for understanding and making correct decisions. Unlike 'mushāwarah,' which merely means conversation, 'ṣalāḥ' includes the attributes of human justice and truth, which also manifest in the consultation process. For example, the Quran says: «وَلِلَّذِينَ اتَّخَذُوا دِينَهُمْ مَّلْهَىٰ وَلِلَّذِينَ اتَّخَذُوا دِينَهُمْ مَّلْهَىٰ وَالْمُسْتَقِيمِينَ الْمَلْهَىٰ فِي الدِّينِ وَالْمَلْهَىٰ فِي الدِّينِ» (Al-Imran 103) Translation: 'And hold firmly to the rope of Allah all together and do not become divided. And remember the favor of Allah upon you – when you were enemies and He brought your hearts together and you became, by His favor, brothers.'"
    }
  ],
  "737": [
    {
      "id": 3364,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Question - Question",
      "hw": "سوال",
      "s": "'Su'āl' means what is genuinely and truly asked, pointing to information or wisdom.",
      "d": "'Su'āl' is an Arabic term meaning to inquire or ask clearly and explicitly, i.e., to ask genuinely and plainly for understanding and clarification. It implies an inquiry made to understand something and seek explanation about it. It differs from terms that merely mean 'to ask' because it carries the effect of grasping reality. For example, the Quran says: «أَلَا إِلَٰهُ إِلَّا هُوَ لَهُ الْأَسْمَاء الْحُسْنَىٰ وَلَهُ الْمُلْكُ وَلَهُ الْحَمْدُ فِي الْآخِرَةِ وَالْأُولَىٰ وَلَهُ الْمُلْكُ وَلَهُ الْحَمْدُ فِي الْآخِرَةِ وَالْأُولَىٰ» (Al-A'raf 176) Translation: 'Is there any deity other than Allah? He is the One with all the good names. To Him belongs dominion and praise in the Hereafter and the first life. To Him belongs dominion and praise in the Hereafter and the first life.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3365,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Question - Inquiry",
      "hw": "سوال",
      "s": "'Pursh' is a specific type of question that is best viewed when encouragement is given to find the answer.",
      "d": "'Pursh' means that a specific question arises in a person's mind that they need to know, and encouragement is provided to solve it in the best way. These terms differ from other questions like 'su'āl' (general asking), 'istifsār' (a subtle question), and 'taḥlīl' (detailed investigation). They do not all represent the same meaning. For example, the Quran says: «أَفَغَیۡرَ اللَّهِ أَرۡبَابٌ سَمِعۡتُمۡ» (Al-An'am 45) Translation: 'Is it other than Allah that you seek as lords who hear?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3366,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Question - Clarification",
      "hw": "سوال",
      "s": "'Istifsar' is a specific form of question asked to clarify the original issue.",
      "d": "'Istifsar' in Urdu is a specific form of question used to clarify the original issue, obtain information, and seek clarification about a problem. Its Arabic root 'Istifsar' means inquiry in Urdu. Its depth is that this question is asked to clarify an issue, and its purpose is to know whether we have understood correctly.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«أَفَأَنْتُمْ أَعْجَبُ مِنْ أَنْ يَكُونَ لَكُمْ سُؤَالٌ فِي الْقُرْآنِ وَلَوْ كُنْتُمْ لَمْ تَكُونُوا مُؤْمِنِينَ» (39/42)\nTranslation: 'Do you wonder that there is a question in the Quran for you, even if you were not believers?'"
    }
  ],
  "738": [
    {
      "id": 3367,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Response - Response",
      "hw": "جواب",
      "s": "Response means answering a question and then saying something relevant to it.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of 'Response' is 'جواب' which means to answer a question and then say something that is a relevant answer. Its synonyms are 'to answer', 'to say something afterwards', 'to respond'. However, the specific meaning of 'response' is that when one gives an answer to a question, it should be related to the question. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ بِآيَاتِنَا وَسُلْطَانٍ مُّبِينٍ فَأَخَذْتُمُوهُ بِالْعَيْنِ وَكَذَّبْتُمُوهُ بِغَيْرِ عِلْمٍ» (Al-An'am 127). Translation: 'But We sent Moses with Our signs and clear authority. You saw the question with the one who came and estimated them without knowledge.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3368,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Answer - Rejection",
      "hw": "جواب",
      "s": "'Radd' means to return something due to being unacceptable.",
      "d": "'Radd' means to return something due to being unacceptable. To return. To reject.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ لَمَّا فَتَحُوۡا مَتَاعَہُمۡ وَجَدُوۡا بِضَاعَتَہُمۡ رُدَّتۡ  اِلَیۡہِمۡ» (12/65)\nTranslation: 'And when they opened their baggage, they found their property returned to them.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3369,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Answer - Answer",
      "hw": "جواب",
      "s": "«اَجَابَ» means to answer a question.",
      "d": "«اَجَابَ» is opposite to «سَاَلَ», and «سَاَلَ» means to ask a question, and also to request something and to inquire. Similarly, «اَجَابَ» also means to answer a question. And if something is requested, it also means to accept or give it. Here, the answer to a question is under discussion.\nFor example: In the Quran: «یَوۡمَ یَجۡمَعُ اللّٰہُ الرُّسُلَ فَیَقُوۡلُ مَا ذَاۤ اُجِبۡتُمۡ» ( 5/109 )\nTranslation: On that day, Allah will gather the messengers and then ask, 'What response were you given?'"
    }
  ],
  "739": [
    {
      "id": 3370,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Clarification - Clarification",
      "hw": "وضاحت",
      "s": "Clarification means detailing and clear statement that elucidates God's actions and attributes.",
      "d": "The Arabic origin of 'Clarification' is (و-ض-ح) which means 'clarity' or 'clarification'. These words are related, but clarification specifically works to make a thing clear. It means providing a means to understand something in the best way. These words are different, such as 'توضیح' which is used for understanding the meaning, and 'وضوح' which is the original meaning of clarification. For example, in the Quran: «الَّذِي أَنزَلَ الْكِتَابَ بِالْحَقِّ وَقَدْ أَنزَلَهُ فَرَقًا مِّنْهُ وَقَدْ جَعَلَ لَهُ مِنْهُ قَدَرًا» (3:7). Translation: 'Who sent down the Book in truth; and indeed, He has sent down a part of it, and He has appointed for it a measure.' This verse clarifies the meaning of clarification that Allah has sent down the Quran in the best way and has clarified some parts of it in the best manner."
    },
    {
      "id": 3371,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Clarification - Explanation",
      "hw": "وضاحت",
      "s": "Explanation means clarification that elucidates the original subject and provides its details.",
      "d": "The Arabic origin of 'Explanation' is 'تشریح' which means to clarify in detail. Its root is 'تشریح' meaning to clarify in detail, while other words like 'شرح' or 'تبین' differ in that 'تشریح' is specifically the term for detailed explanation. For example, in the Quran: «وَإِذَا تُتْلَىٰ عَلَيْهِمُ الْآيَاتُ نَقُولُ لِلَّذِينَ أُوتُوا الْكِتَابَ مِن قَبْلِهِمْ مَّا هَٰذَا إِلَّا أَسَرَّ الْقُرْآنِ وَإِنَّهُ لَمِنْ تَشْرِيحٍ وَجْدِيٍ وَمَعْرِفَةٍ» (Al-An'am 95). Translation: 'And when the verses are recited to them, We say to those who were given the Scripture before, 'What is this but the secret of the Quran? And indeed, it is from the explanation of the beneficial and knowledge.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3372,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Clarification - Interpretation",
      "hw": "وضاحت",
      "s": "Interpretation means stating something clearly that reveals the original meaning, implication, and details.",
      "d": "Interpretation means stating something clearly that reveals the original meaning, implication, and details. Its synonyms include words like 'clarification', 'explanation', 'توضیح', 'شرح', and 'پیش کاری', but the specific point of 'interpretation' is that it includes the process of clarifying the original meaning. 'Interpretation' is used for the reader to benefit from the original subject. For example, in the Quran: «أَلَمْ يَرَوْا كَمْ أَخْرَجْنَا مِنْهُمْ مِّنْ أَزْوَاجِهِمْ وَذُرِّيَّتِهِمْ وَمَا أَخْرَجْنَا لَهُمْ مِّنْ أَزْوَاجٍ وَذُرِّيَّةٍ مُّحَرَّبَةٍ» (Al-Anbiya 21:96). Translation: 'Do they not see how many We have taken out from them of their spouses and their offspring? And We have not made for them any spouses or offspring that are forbidden?'"
    }
  ],
  "740": [
    {
      "id": 3373,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Truth - Truth",
      "hw": "سچ",
      "s": "Truth specifically means reality, actuality, and the opposite of falsehood—something definitively correct.",
      "d": "The Arabic origin of 'Truth' is (س-چ-ی) which signifies actual reality, truth, and correctness. It is associated with words that mean 'truthfulness' or 'sincerity'. It differs from other synonymous terms like 'correct' or 'real' because it is used as a social and philosophical concept that denotes actual reality. For example, in the Quran: «أَلَا لَكُمْ مِّنَ اللَّهِ نَبَأٌ مُّصَدِّقٌ لِّلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا بِاللَّهِ وَرَسُولِهِ» (An-Nisa 136). Translation: 'Is there not for you a message from Allah that is correct and true for those who believe in Allah and His Messenger?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3374,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Truth - Veracity",
      "hw": "سچ",
      "s": "Veracity means the ability to present reality and truth, which is a fundamental aspect of human moral and religious constitution.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of 'Veracity' is ص-د-ق which essentially means 'reality' and 'correctness'. This word represents a person's actual reality, free from pretense, hypocrisy, and corruption. In contrast, 'Truth' generally means something correct, but 'Veracity' means presenting reality and truth, which is a fundamental part of human moral makeup. This meaning expresses the health of a person's heart, human ethics, and religious constitution. Evidence: «وَاللَّذِينَ إِذَا أَنْفَقُوا لَمْ يُسْرِفُوا وَلَمْ يَكُونُوا الْمُسْتَغْنَوْنَ وَالَّذِينَ هُمْ لِلْأَمْوَالِ حَافِظُونَ» (Al-Baqarah 267). Translation: 'And those who, when they spend, do not waste and are not extravagant, and those who are guardians of their wealth.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3375,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Truth - Reality",
      "hw": "سچ",
      "s": "Reality expresses the actual truth and correctness that influences a person's heart and speech.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of 'Reality' is 'ح ق ت' which signifies actual reality, correctness, and goodness. This word is used as a specific and complete form of truth that includes simple truth as well as actual reality. Its synonyms include 'صِدْق' (sincerity) and 'سَحْب' (truth), but 'Reality' means the truth that shows actual reality. For example, in the Quran: «وَالْحَقُّ مِن رَّبِّكَ فَلَا تَكُونَنَّ مِنَ الْمُمْتَرِينَ» (Ya-Sin 18). Translation: 'And the truth is from your Lord, so do not be among the doubters.'"
    }
  ],
  "741": [
    {
      "id": 3376,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Falsehood - Falsehood",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "Falsehood means something that is not true and does not align with reality, and it expresses disobedience to truth.",
      "d": "The Arabic origin of 'Falsehood' starts with the root (جھوٹ) which indicates something contrary to correctness. Its literal meaning is 'not correct' or 'far from reality'. Among its synonymous words like 'ضلال' or 'غلو', 'Falsehood' specifically involves human knowledge and will in disobedience to truth. Falsehood means ignoring reality and uttering falsehood, which operates with one's knowledge and will. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا مِنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَالْمُشْرِكِينَ قَدْرٌ فَأَنْزَلَ اللَّهُ الْقُرْآنَ وَهُوَ خَيْرٌ وَأَحْسَنُ تَأْوِيلًا» (2:114). Translation: 'And there was no power for the disbelievers from the People of the Scripture and the polytheists to have the Quran so easily that they could interpret it in the best and most beautiful way.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3377,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Falsehood - Lying",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "«کِذْب» is a false statement against reality.",
      "d": "«کِذْب» means to deliberately give false information (manjada), lack of harmony between heart and tongue (mutabq), or saying something contrary to reality. And its opposite is «صِدْق».\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ الۡکَذِبَ وَ ہُمۡ  یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ» ( 3/78 )\nTranslation: And they speak falsehood against Allah while they know."
    },
    {
      "id": 3378,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Falsehood - Falsity",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "Falsity is the original meaning of falsehood, related to a series of irregular and false statements.",
      "d": "In Urdu, 'Falsity' is the original meaning of falsehood, which means saying something irregular and false. Its Arabic root 'درغ' is related to a series of irregular and false statements. This word differs from other cases of falsehood, while 'Falsehood' generally expresses extreme despair according to one's heart. Falsity means ignoring reality and uttering falsehood, which operates with one's knowledge and will. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَا تَقُولُوا لِمَنْ يَّسْتَمِعُ مِنكُمْ أَنْ يَّكُونَ فِي الْعِلْمِ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ فِي الْمَلَكِ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ فِي الْعِلْمِ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ فِي الْمَلَكِ» (Al-An'am 59). Translation: 'And do not say to those who listen from you that they are in knowledge but not in the kingdom, and not in knowledge but not in the kingdom.'"
    }
  ],
  "742": [],
  "743": [
    {
      "id": 3382,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Certitude - Certitude",
      "hw": "یقین",
      "s": "Certitude means the assurance arising from the heart's conviction, firm against doubt and uncertainty.",
      "d": "The Arabic origin of 'Certitude' is (یقین) which essentially means the feeling of heart's assurance. Its literal meaning is 'to recognize' or 'to see', which is the feeling of seeing a broken news. Certitude means assurance that is certain, while faith is assurance that comes with wisdom and teaching. In contrast to certitude, faith means assurance that comes with wisdom and instruction. For example, in the Quran: «أَلَا إِلَهُ إِلَّا هُوَ الْحَيُّ الْقَيُّومُ لا إِلَهَ إِلَّا هُوَ الْمَلِكُ الْقُدُّوسُ السَّلَامُ الْمُؤْمِنُ الْمَهْدِي لِلْمُؤْمِنِينَ الْمُعِينُ لِلْمُؤْمِنِينَ» (Al-Baqarah 255). Translation: 'There is no deity except Him, the Ever-Living, the Self-Sustaining. There is no deity except Him, the King, the Holy, the Source of Peace, the Giver of Security, the Guardian, the Mighty, the Compeller, the Supreme; exalted is Allah above whatever they associate with Him.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3383,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Yaqeen - Trust (I'timad)",
      "hw": "یقین",
      "s": "\"I'timad\" is the true meaning of Yaqeen, which is a firm and strong feeling in a person's heart that cannot be changed by others.",
      "d": "\"I'timad\" means a hidden and strong feeling in a person's heart that manifests with certainty and faith. These words are distinct from others, such as \"Iman\" or \"Sidq,\" which express faith, but \"I'timad\" is the essence of Yaqeen that resides within the heart and represents its state of faith. For example: The Quran states:\n«وَاللَّذِينَ جَاهَدُوا فِينَا لَنَحْنَهُمْ وَلَنَحْنَهُمْ وَالَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَالَّذِينَ اسْتَجَابُوا لِلَّهِ وَرَسُولِهِ وَالَّذِينَ اعْتَدَوْا لَهُمْ عَذَابًا شَدِيدًا فِي الْحَيَاةِ الدُّنْيَا وَفِي الْآخِرَةِ» (Al-Baqarah 2/286)\nTranslation: \"And those who strive for Us - We will surely guide them to Our ways. And indeed, Allah is with the doers of good. And those who believed and those who responded to Allah and His Messenger - and those who opposed them - will have a severe punishment in the life of this world and in the Hereafter.\""
    }
  ],
  "744": [
    {
      "id": 3385,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Khabar - News",
      "hw": "خبر",
      "s": "\"Khabar\" is news that pertains to the listener's own self and can have an impact on them.",
      "d": "The plural of \"Khabar\" is \"Akhbar.\" It is a common term. It refers to an event of which a person has no prior knowledge, and they are informed about it through someone else. It is knowledge of the surrounding circumstances.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ لِأَهْلِهِ امْكُثُوا إِنِّي آنَسْتُ نَارًا لَعَلِّي آتِيكُم مِّنْهَا بِخَبَرٍ» (Al-Qasas 28:29)\nTranslation: Moses said to his family, \"Stay here; indeed, I have perceived a fire. Perhaps I will bring you from there information or a burning firebrand.\"\nAt another place, the Divine declaration states:\n«قُل لَّا تَعْتَذِرُوا قَدْ نَبَّأَنَا اللَّهُ مِنْ أَخْبَارِكُمْ» (At-Tawbah 9:94)\nTranslation: \"Say, 'Do not make excuses; we will not believe you. Allah has already informed us of your news.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3386,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Khabar - Information (I'tila)",
      "hw": "خبر",
      "s": "\"I'tila\" is the original meaning of news, which is the act of conveying information to a person.",
      "d": "\"I'tila\" means to give someone knowledge of something, to inform. Its Arabic root is \"I'tila,\" which signifies the act of learning, informing, and giving news. Synonymous terms like Khabar, Akhbar, and Khabardari exist, but \"I'tila\" specifically denotes the act of conveying information to a person. For example: The Quran states:\n«وَإِذْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن بَعْدِهِ مُوسَىٰ إِلَى فِرْعَوْنَ بِسُلْطَانٍ فَقَالَ إِنِّي أَعُوذُ بِرَبِّ الْعَالَمِينَ» (Taha 20:24)\nTranslation: \"And when We sent Moses after him to Pharaoh with clear signs, he said, 'Indeed, I seek refuge in the Lord of the worlds.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3387,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "News - Announcement",
      "hw": "خبر",
      "s": "«خبرنامہ» means announcing news or giving information that makes a person aware so they change their behavior.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of «خبرنامہ» is خبر (kh-b-r), which conveys meanings of information, news, announcement, and conveying. The full term خبرنامہ means the act of conveying news. In contrast, «خبر» simply means information or news, while «خبرنامہ» refers to the act of its dissemination or publication. «خبرنامہ» means announcing news or giving information that makes a person aware so they change their behavior. For example, the Quran states:\n\n«وَإِذْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِنْ بَعْدِهِمْ رَسُولًا إِلَىٰ أَهْلِهِمْ فَأَخْبَرَهُمْ بِآيَاتِنَا وَكَانَ هُوَ الْعَلِيُّ الْعَظِيمُ»\n(الأنعام / ١٠٤)\nTranslation: \"And when We sent a messenger to their people after him, he informed them of Our signs, and he was the Exalted in might, the Great.\""
    }
  ],
  "745": [
    {
      "id": 3388,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Information - Information",
      "hw": "معلومات",
      "s": "«معلومات» specifically means consciously understanding and conveying available information based on the relevant topic.",
      "d": "The Arabic origin of «معلومات» is معلومات (ma'lumat), which refers to the attribute of knowing and making known information. This term is distinct from other terms such as «علم» which generally means knowledge, «خبر» which are simple news, and «عرف» which is mental agreement or understanding. The specific meaning of معلومات is to consciously understand available information based on the relevant topic, to correctly comprehend incoming information, and to use it correctly. For example:\n\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا مِنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ إِلَّا أَنْ يَكُونَ اللَّهُ وَلِيَّهُمْ وَلَا يَكُونَ اللَّهُ وَلِيَّ الْمُشْرِكِينَ» (3/109)\nTranslation: \"It is told in the Quran to the disbelieving people that Allah is the protector of His friends and not of the polytheists.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3389,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Ma'lumat - Data",
      "hw": "معلومات",
      "s": "\"Data\" is the original meaning of information that becomes known to a person through knowledge and understanding.",
      "d": "\"Data\" means information that enters a person's mind, related to knowledge, information, and wisdom. These terms are used differently, but \"Data\" specifically refers to what becomes known to a person through comprehension. It pertains to information rather than speech. For example: The Quran states:\n«وَإِذْ أَنزَلْنَا الْكِتَابَ مِن لَّدُنْهُ وَالْمَوْعِظَةَ وَالْمُحَكَّمَةَ فِي الْقُرْآنِ وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا مِنْهُ حَجَّةٌ وَلَكِنَّ الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَلَمْ يَكُونُوا مُشْرِكِينَ فَإِنَّهُمْ هُمُ الْمُسْتَمِعُونَ» (Al-Imran 3:7)\nTranslation: \"And when We sent down the Scripture to you, [O Muhammad], those who disbelieved from the People of the Book and the polytheists did not expect any good from it. But those who believed and did not associate anything with Allah - they are the listeners.\""
    }
  ],
  "746": [
    {
      "id": 3391,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Education - Education",
      "hw": "تعلیم",
      "s": "«تعلیم» means learning through support and education that gives a person the opportunity to learn with their own understanding.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of «تعلیم» is ع-ل-م, which originally means \"education\" and \"teaching,\" giving a person the opportunity to learn with their own understanding. It means that a person should be given the opportunity to learn, which allows them to learn with their innate understanding. This concept is a specific type of education that gives a person the opportunity to learn their principles and moral values. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَمَا كُنتَ تَدْرِي لَعَلَّهُ يَكُونُ خَيْرًا لَّكَ» (البقرة / ٢٨٥)\nTranslation: \"And you did not know that it might be better for you.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3392,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Education - Instruction",
      "hw": "تعلیم",
      "s": "«تدریس» means the act of teaching, which is the act of imparting knowledge with the art of learning.",
      "d": "The original Arabic term for «تدریس» is تدريس, which in Arabic means \"the act of teaching someone\" or \"imparting knowledge.\" These words describe the general concept of education, but «تدریس» specifically refers to the act of imparting knowledge, the accompanying art of learning, and the supervision of its principled and skillful organization. In contrast, «تعلیم» generally means a formal or facilitative learning opportunity, while «تدریس» means the act of teaching. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ رُسُلًا مِّنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ فَأَخَذْنَاهُمْ بِالْعَذَابِ وَالضَّرَّاءِ لَعَلَّهُمْ يَتَضَرَّعُونَ» (الأنعام / ١٥٩)\nTranslation: \"We had indeed sent messengers from the People of the Book before you, and We subjected them to trials and hardships so that they might attain success.\""
    }
  ],
  "747": [
    {
      "id": 3394,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Seekhna - To Learn",
      "hw": "سیکھنا",
      "s": "\"Seekhna\" means to understand and examine something with scrutiny and interest.",
      "d": "The original Urdu term \"Seekhna\" means to understand, to examine, and the act of understanding. These words differ from others, such as \"Janta hoon\" (I know) or \"Jaana\" (to know), which generally refer to possessing information. However, \"Seekhna\" includes the notions of scrutiny, detailed examination, and interest. These terms are specifically distinct from each other concerning the related activity. For example: The Quran states:\n«أَفَلَمْ يَتُوبُوا إِلَى اللَّهِ وَيَسْتَغْفِرُوهُ ۖ إِنَّ اللَّهَ كَانَ غَفُورًا رَّحِيمًا» (An-Nur 24:31)\nTranslation: \"And why do they not repent to Allah and seek His forgiveness? For Allah is Forgiving and Merciful.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3395,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Learning - Acquiring Education",
      "hw": "سیکھنا",
      "s": "«تعلیم حاصل کرنا» is the act of studying and understanding that, according to the Quran, is necessary for a person to attain faith and knowledge.",
      "d": "«تعلیم حاصل کرنا» means learning something with understanding and awareness, which essentially means the act of perceiving and understanding what is presented. Its Arabic root is derived from «تعلیم», which means to increase or happen. In contrast, «سیکھنا» generally means the act of learning, while «تعلیم حاصل کرنا» means to acquire something with understanding. For example, the Quran states:\n«الَّذِينَ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِاللَّهِ وَالْيَوْمِ الْآخِرِ وَيَعْمَلُونَ صَالِحًا فَأُولَٰئِكَ يَرْبُونَ فِي أَمَامِ اللَّهِ» (البقرة / ١٢٧)\nTranslation: \"Those who believe in Allah and the Last Day and do righteous deeds, it is they who will achieve a high status before Allah.\""
    }
  ],
  "748": [
    {
      "id": 3396,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Understanding - Understanding",
      "hw": "سمجھ",
      "s": "«سمجھ» means to form an understanding of the meaning, and to use wisdom and intellect through it.",
      "d": "The root of «سمجھ» is س-م-ج-ھ, which means the act of forming and understanding a meaning. It is not just with words but with intellect, wisdom, and comprehension to form an understanding of the meaning. This word is similar to other synonyms like «فهم» or «علم», but «سمجھ» specifically relates to intellectual understanding, comprehension, and wisdom. For example, the Quran states:\n«أَلَا يَسْتَوِي الْأَعْمَى وَالْبَصِيرُ» (٣٥/٢٨)\nTranslation: \"Do they not know that the blind and the seeing are not equal?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3397,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Understanding - Comprehension",
      "hw": "سمجھ",
      "s": "«ادراک» is a specific degree of understanding that indicates deep perception and comprehension.",
      "d": "In Urdu, «ادراک» is a specific degree of understanding that indicates deep perception and comprehension. Its Arabic root is ادراک, which means to see and understand things, and to have a deep understanding of them. This term refers to a specific nature of meaning that is beyond simple understanding. In comparison to synonymous words like «فہم» or «ہوش», «ادراک» means to understand things clearly and to see their reality. For example, the Quran states:\n«الَّذِيْ أَنْزَلَ الْكِتَابَ مِنَ الْقَبْلِ لَكَانَ لَهُ أَمَامٌ وَّ مَعْرُوْفٌ» (۳/۷۹)\nTranslation: \"For the one who sent down the Book before, it would have been for him a precedent and a known matter.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3398,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Understanding - Insight",
      "hw": "سمجھ",
      "s": "«فہم» means to understand with scrutiny, to understand with wisdom, and to understand the meaning in a better way.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of «فہم» is فهم, which originally means \"to understand,\" \"to scrutinize,\" and \"to recognize.\" These words are different: «سُمْع» (hearing), «فَهْم» (understanding), and «عِلْم» (knowing). The specific meaning of «فہم» is to understand something with its true meaning, wisdom, and comprehension, not just hearing but scrutinizing and understanding. It is a detailed and better way of understanding. For example, the Quran states:\n\n«الَّذِينَ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِاللَّهِ وَالْيَوْمِ الْآخِرِ وَيَأْمُرُونَ بِالمَعْرُوفِ وَيَنْهَوْنَ عَنِ الْمُنكَرِ وَيُقِيمُونَ الصَّلَاةَ وَيُؤْتُونَ الزَّكَاةَ وَهُمْ يَرْجُونَ رَحْمَةَ رَبِّهِمْ ۚ أُولَٰئِكَ هُمُ الْمُهْتَدُونَ» (التوبة / ١١٢)\nTranslation: \"Those who believe in Allah and the Last Day, and enjoin what is right and forbid what is wrong, and establish prayer and give zakah, and they await the mercy of their Lord, it is those who are the guided.\""
    }
  ],
  "749": [
    {
      "id": 3399,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Walking - Walking",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«چلنا» means to move, to advance with intention, and to present oneself towards one's goal.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of «چلنا» is چ-ل-ن-ا, which originally means movement, advancing, and doing something with intention. These words are used in different ways, for example, there is a difference between «چلنا» and «جنا», where «چلنا» indicates human and logical movement, while «جنا» generally means to move at extreme speed or to appear at a specific occasion. «چلنا» is a famous term for human and safe movement.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَإِذَا مَا اَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ إِلَىٰ فِرْعَوْنَ بِآيَاتِنَا فَقَالَ أَنَا مُحَرِّكٌ مُّلُوكًا» (طه / ٥٩)\nTranslation: \"When We sent Moses to Pharaoh with Our signs, he said, 'I am one who changes kingdoms.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3400,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Walking - Moving",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«حرکت کرنا» means to move, which occurs when a person or animal moves from one place to another.",
      "d": "«حرکت کرنا» means to move something or someone from one place to another, which is essentially the state of walking for a human or animal. These words are different: «چلنا» generally means the means of walking for a human or animal, while «حرکت کرنا» generally means the movement of a thing, which is related to walking. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ وَلَا تَجْعَلْ فِي قُلُوبِنَا غِلَىٰ لِلْمُؤْمِنِينَ رَبَّنَا وَأَنْتَ رَبُّ الْعَالَمِينَ» (آل عمران / ١٩٥)\nTranslation: \"And those who came after them say, 'Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith, and do not place in our hearts resentment toward the believers. Our Lord, indeed You are the Lord of the worlds.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3401,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk - to flow",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«to flow» means that something moves with constant pace, like walking feet.",
      "d": "«to flow» is equivalent to the Arabic word for flowing, which means something moves constantly. This does not indicate inactivity but active movement. It differs from other synonyms like «to walk» which generally refers to foot movement, whereas «to flow» means something moves automatically, like water flowing. For example, in the Quran: «وَالرَّاحِلَةِ إِلَى رَاحِلَةٍ» (البقرة ۲۵۴) Translation: \"And those who flow, they flow.\""
    }
  ],
  "750": [
    {
      "id": 3402,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to run - to run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«to run» means to move quickly, to emerge, and to spread prematurely.",
      "d": "«to run» in Arabic from the root د-ر-ن means to move quickly, to circulate, and to emerge. These words imply something spreading or being sold prematurely or unknowingly. Synonyms like 'to spread' or 'to move prematurely' are similar, but «to run» particularly conveys a sense of haste and speed. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّنَ الْمُحَدَّثِينَ أَحَدٌ يَكُونُ فِي الْمُحَدَّثِينَ» (الأنعام/ 6) Translation: \"And there was not among them any person who would understand any of the monotheists.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3403,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to run - to flee",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«to flee» means running with speed and the state of escaping danger.",
      "d": "«to flee» in this context means running, immediate movement, and the state of escaping danger. Its Arabic origin is بھاگنا which means to run quickly, to escape, and the act of getting out of danger. These words may imply running, but also include the state of escaping. Its specific meaning is to distance oneself from danger or risk. For example, in the Quran: «فَبِأَيِّ آلاءِ رَبِّكَ تَشْهَدُونَ» (العنكبوت 29/45) Translation: \"So what is your testimony regarding the special qualities of your Lord?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3404,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to run - to move swiftly",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«to move swiftly» means to move something in the best way and with greater speed, which is used in the meaning of running.",
      "d": "«to move swiftly» in Arabic means to move in the fastest way. These words differ from others, such as «to blow» which means to move something well, but «to move swiftly» means to move in the best way and with greater speed. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَٰلِكَ لَعْنَةٌ وَلَكِنْ لَّهُمْ فِي ذَٰلِكَ لَعْنَةٌ» (الشعراء ۲۶:۱۴) Translation: \"There was not for them therein any curse, but for them therein is a curse.\""
    }
  ],
  "751": [
    {
      "id": 3405,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To See - To Appear",
      "hw": "To come",
      "s": "«To see» means that one is given the opportunity to see, while others are not able to see.",
      "d": "«To see» is an Arabic root meaning to see, to appear, and to come into view from outside. This word is used in places like «نَظَر» or «رَأَى», but «آنا» specifically means to be seen, and to see oneself. This concept encompasses coming before someone, appearing, and presenting oneself. For example, in the Quran: «أَوَّلَمْ يَرَوْا أَنَّ اللَّهَ الَّذِي خَلَقَ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضَ وَكَانَ لَهُمْ أَنْ يَرَوْا أَنَّهُمْ يَخْرُجُونَ فِي الْأَرْضِ وَإِنَّهُمْ يَرَوْنَ أَنَّهُمْ يَخْرُجُونَ فِي الْأَرْضِ وَإِنَّهُمْ يَرَوْنَ أَنَّهُمْ يَخْرُجُونَ فِي الْأَرْضِ» (Surah An-Naml, 27/69) Translation: \"Do they not see that Allah has created the heavens and the earth, and that it should be for them to see that they will emerge from the land?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3406,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To See - To Enter",
      "hw": "To come",
      "s": "«To enter» [means to enter something or to come, which appears to be recurring or coming again]",
      "d": "«To enter» means to enter something, to come, or to be such that it appears to be recurring or coming again. Its origin is «وارد ہونا» which is the act of entering something. Its synonyms include «آنا», «آیا», «پہنچنا», but «وارد ہونا» specifically means to enter or to come repeatedly. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ دَعْوَةٌ إِلَّا أَنْ يَقُولُوا وَرَدَ اللَّهُ بِهِمْ» (An-Nisa: 105) Translation: \"And they had no supplication except that it would be against it, but only that they would say that Allah had seen them as those who come repeatedly.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3407,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To See - To Reach",
      "hw": "To come",
      "s": "«To reach» means when something or someone reaches its place, which indicates the original place or state.",
      "d": "«To reach» has the original root «پہنچنا» which originally means to leave, but it is used such that something or someone reaches its viewpoint or place. This term is different from another such as \"to see\" which means something or someone reaches its place, while \"to see\" means something or someone reaches its place. This concept indicates the original place or state. For example, in the Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَ مُوسَىٰ لِقَوْمِهِ ادْعُوا إِلَىٰ رَبِّكُمْ وَأَسْرِفُوا فِي الْعَمَلِ لَوْ كُنْتُمْ مُؤْمِنِينَ» (Ghafir 40:34) Translation: \"When Moses said to his people, 'Call upon your Lord and be generous in the work, if you should be believers.'\""
    }
  ],
  "752": [
    {
      "id": 3408,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to go - to go",
      "hw": "جانا",
      "s": "«to go» means to exist with the capacity for life and soul, which is the true meaning of life.",
      "d": "«to go» in this context means the true meaning of life, which is related to the capacity for life and soul. Its Arabic origin (ج ن و) gives the true meaning of life. In contrast, «to come» means something that comes to mind or is perceived, while «to read» or «to understand» means to comprehend something. In the Quran: «وَلَا تَقْتُلُوا أَنفُسَكُمْ ۚ إِنَّ اللَّهَ كَانَ بِكُمْ رَحِيمًا» (النساء/29) Translation: \"And do not kill yourselves. Indeed, Allah is to you ever Merciful.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3409,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To Be - To Proceed",
      "hw": "جانا",
      "s": "«To proceed» emphasizes that something is accompanied by something and continues its activities, as in the Quran where Allah commands the believers to proceed with His guidance.",
      "d": "«To proceed» means to express going with something, which is specific and continuous. Its origin is «ر-ون-ہ» which means 'to lead', 'to advance', 'the journey of guidance'. It means to go towards something, to be with it, and to act under it. This word is particularly used in Quranic terminology when one is commanded to go with His guidance. For example, in the Quran: «وَإِذْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِنْهُمْ رَسُولًا مِّنْهُمْ يَتْلُو عَلَيْهِمْ آيَاتِنَا وَيُزَكِّيهِمْ وَيُعَلِّمُهُمُ الْكِتَابَ وَالْحِكْمَةَ وَلَوْلَا كَلِمَةٌ مِّن رَّبِّكَ لَقَدْ جَاءَتْهُمُ الرُّسُلُ مِن قَبْلِهِمْ فَأَخَذْتُهُمْ بِمَا كَانُوا يَعْمَلُونَ فَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّن بَعْدِ ذَلِكَ أَوْلِيَاءُ مِن دُونِهِ مِن قَبْلِ أَن يَجِيءَهُمُ الرُّسُلُ مِن قَبْلِهِمْ فَأَخَذْتُهُمْ بِمَا كَانُوا يَعْمَلُونَ» (An-Nisa 4:163) Translation: \"And when We sent among them a messenger from themselves, reciting to them Our verses and purifying them and teaching them the Book and wisdom, had it not been for a word from your Lord, the messengers would have certainly come to them before, and We seized them for what they were doing. Then there were no protectors for them after that from besides Him, before the messengers came to them from before, and We seized them for what they were doing.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3410,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To Be - To Grant Leave",
      "hw": "جانا",
      "s": "«To grant leave» means to give permission or to leave after giving permission, to go and leave behind.",
      "d": "«To grant leave» has the original root meaning to give permission, to bar, or to leave behind. Its synonyms include «کرنا», «گزرنا», «چھوڑ دینا», but its specific meaning is to give permission or to leave after giving permission. These words all have more than one meaning, but «رخصت ہونا» specifically means to give permission or to leave after giving permission. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ إِلَىٰ فِرْعَوْنَ بِسُلْطَانٍ فَقَالَ إِذَا مَرَّ عَلَيْهِمْ قَالَ يَا فِرْعَوْنُ إِنِّي رَسُولُ رَبِّ الْعَالَمِينَ» (Taha 20:25) Translation: \"And We certainly sent Moses to Pharaoh with clear signs, and he said, 'Indeed, I am the messenger of the Lord of the worlds.'\""
    }
  ],
  "753": [
    {
      "id": 3411,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To Circle - To Circle",
      "hw": "گھومنا",
      "s": "«To circle» means to circle something completely or to tour it, as the earth circles.",
      "d": "«To circle» is an Arabic word that means to circle something completely, to tour it, or to see all its parts. This word means to completely tour something, while other synonyms like «پھرنا» or «گھومنا» mean to tour one thing or to circle once. «To circle» specifically means to circle something completely or to see all its parts. For example, in the Quran: «وَاللَّذِي أَنْزَلَ الْكِتَابَ بِالْقَضِي وَالْمَقْضِي» (Az-Zumar 39:47) Translation: \"And He who sent down the Book with the decree and the decree.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3412,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To Circle - To Revolve",
      "hw": "گھومنا",
      "s": "«To revolve» means to rotate something, to change it, or to look at it again until it departs from its original state.",
      "d": "«To revolve» means to rotate something, to change it, or to look at it again until it departs from its original state. This word means to circle, to decrease, and to do such work with it that it departs from its original state. These words mean to circle, to decrease, and to do such work that it changes. The best concept in «To revolve» is that revolve means to change, to be active, and to look at it again. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَٰلِكَ إِلَّا أَنْ يَكُونُوا مُتَّخِذِينَ» (Al-An'am 6:149) Translation: \"And they had not in that except to be those who take.\""
    }
  ],
  "754": [
    {
      "id": 3413,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Fight - To Fight",
      "hw": "لڑنا",
      "s": "«To fight» means to quarrel, to struggle, and to mention the action of engaging in combat after the pact of friendship in the period.",
      "d": "«To fight» in Urdu refers to the action of engaging in combat after the pact of friendship in the period. Its Arabic origin means to mention combat and struggle. Its other meanings include quarreling over small things, and mentioning the action of engaging in combat after the pact of friendship in the period. Its equivalent in Urdu is 'to wage war' or 'to combat'. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَا تَقَطَّعُواْ فَتَفَشَّلَ الْمَوْدَّةُ مِنْكُمْ وَلَا تَقَارَبُواْ فَتَكُونُواْ مِنْهُمْ أَوْلِيَاءَ بِالْعَدَاءِ وَالْحَرَبِ» (An-Nisa 4:137) Translation: \"And do not cut [the ties of] so that affection fails among you, and do not be intimate with them so that you become from them allies in enmity and war.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3414,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Fight - To Wage War",
      "hw": "لڑنا",
      "s": "«To wage war» means fighting as another name for war that is conducted with a specific danger and writing.",
      "d": "«To wage war» means fighting as another name for war that is conducted with a specific danger and writing. Its root word means a large writing, organization, and religious difference. In addition, synonyms for «لڑنا» include «چالاکی», «حرب», «مُعرِض», «جُنُون», and «مُخَارِب». Its specific meaning is to fight through small wars or interventions. In the Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَلِكَ أَنْ يَكُونُوا مُؤْمِنِينَ فَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَلِكَ أَنْ يَكُونُوا مُؤْمِنِينَ» (Al-An'am 6:63) Translation: \"When they are not believers in it, then they will not have the opportunity to be believers in it.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3415,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to fight - to confront",
      "hw": "لڑنا",
      "s": "«to confront» in this sense means to quarrel, to threaten, and to create danger.",
      "d": "«to confront» means to quarrel, to threaten, and to create danger. Its Arabic root is متقابِلۃ (confrontation) which originally means to face each other. Its relative meaning is to have a two-way conversation, while «to fight» has a more dangerous and military meaning. «to fight» means to engage in a two-way quarrel, especially in the form of danger and attack. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَا تُلْقَىٰ فِي الْقَوْلِ مِنْ قَبْلِ أَنْ يُقَالَ لَكَ وَلَا تَرْكَ الْحَدِيثَ فَإِنَّهُ أَحَدُ الْمُقَادِمِينَ» (الأنعام/ 150) Translation: \"Until someone says something to you, leave the conversation beforehand, and it means to quarrel and create danger.\""
    }
  ],
  "755": [
    {
      "id": 3416,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to give - to give",
      "hw": "دینا",
      "s": "«to give» means to command obedience to religion, i.e., to provide with guidance of religion.",
      "d": "«to give» in Arabic (د-ن-آ) originally means to command obedience to religion and to provide with the means for religious obedience. The difference between these words is that «to give» means to command religion, while «to teach» means only to command obedience. Additionally, it means «to command» and «to order». Example: in the Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ رُسُلًا مِّنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ فَإِذَا جَاءَهُمْ بِالْبَيِّنَاتِ قَالُوا هَذَا سِحْرٌ مُّبِينٌ» (النساء: ۱۵۹) Translation: \"And We have already sent messengers before you, [O Muhammad], from the people of the Scripture. Then when they came to them with clear evidences, they said, 'This is obvious magic.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3417,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to give - to bestow",
      "hw": "دینا",
      "s": "«to bestow» means to give the points sent by God to humans, such as expressing favor, mercy, and great blessings.",
      "d": "«to bestow» etymologically means to give or send. It means to give something that one cannot acquire oneself. It is used primarily for blessings and favors given by God. In contrast, «to give» generally means to give one's wealth or kindness, while «to bestow» specifically means to give blessings and favors. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ سَبَقَتْ لَهُمْ مِّنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ مِنْ قَبْلِهِمْ أَنْ يَكُونَ لَهُمْ مَّوْلَىٰ إِلَّا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَأَنْ يَكُونُوا مُسْتَقِيمِينَ وَاللَّهُ يُحِبُّ الْمُسْتَقِيمِينَ» (آل عمران / 38) Translation: \"And there should not be for the believers and those who preceded them of the people of the Scripture before them any guardians except those who believe and are righteous. And Allah loves the righteous.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3418,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to give - to provide",
      "hw": "دینا",
      "s": "«to provide» means to give something to someone or fulfill their need, as a master provides everything to his servant.",
      "d": "«to provide» means to give something to someone, fulfill their need, and provide everything for them. These words express giving something or fulfilling a need through someone, which is the original meaning of «to give». Its synonym is «to give», but «to provide» has a particular importance of giving or fulfilling a need, as a master provides everything to his servant. For example, in the Quran: «وَإِذَا جَاءَكَ الَّذِينَ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِآيَاتِنَا فَقُلْ أَسْلَمْتُمْ وَلَهُمُ الدِّينُ وَلِيَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ مَوْلَاهُمْ فِي الدِّينِ» (الأنعام / ١٥٩) Translation: \"And when those who believe in Our verses come to you, say, 'We have submitted [to Allah],' and for them is the religion. And for the believers is their protector in the religion.\""
    }
  ],
  "756": [
    {
      "id": 3419,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to take - to take",
      "hw": "لینا",
      "s": "«to take» means to bring something to oneself, keep it with oneself, and become its owner.",
      "d": "«to take» in Arabic (ل ن أ) originally means to grasp, bring to oneself, and become the owner. These words are used in different ways: «to take» specifically means to bring something to oneself such as wealth, love, or respect. In contrast, «to acquire» means to bring something to oneself or obtain it, while «to possess» means to make something one's own or become its owner. Example: in the Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّنْ عِلْمٍ إِلَّا مَا اَخَذَتْهُ الْمَوْجُ مِنْهُ» (سورة النمل، آیت 39) Translation: \"And they had not any knowledge except what the wave had taken from it.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3420,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To take - To obtain",
      "hw": "لینا",
      "s": "'To obtain' means to bring something to oneself by acquiring it, whereas 'to take' merely means to present or bring something to oneself.",
      "d": "The Arabic origin of 'to obtain' is 'حَصَلَ', which originally means to convey, acquire, and bring something to oneself. These words are used in better combinations in some contexts, while 'to take' merely means to present or bring something to oneself. These two words are different from each other because 'to obtain' is an action that occurs after acquiring something, whereas 'to take' simply means to present or bring something to oneself. For example, in the Quran it is said: «وَإِذَا مَسَّكُمُ الْقَلَبُ مِنَ الْحَزْنِ فَأَخَذَتْكُمُ الْمَوْتُ» (الأنعام/۱۲۸) Translation: When distress occurs in your hearts due to grief, you are protected from death."
    },
    {
      "id": 3421,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Take - To Take",
      "hw": "لینا",
      "s": "«اَخَذَ» means to take something, to encompass it, to grasp.",
      "d": "«اَخَذَ» means to take something, to encompass it, to grasp (transitive). Its usage is both tangible (i.e., something perceived through one of the five senses) and intangible.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِذۡ اَخَذَ اللّٰہُ مِیۡثَاقَ النَّبِیّٖنَ» (3/81)\nTranslation: And when Allah took the covenant of the prophets.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ لَمَّا سَکَتَ عَنۡ  مُّوۡسَی الۡغَضَبُ  اَخَذَ الۡاَلۡوَاحَ» (7/154)\nTranslation: And when the anger of Moses subsided, he took up the tablets."
    }
  ],
  "757": [
    {
      "id": 3422,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To open - To open",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "'To open' means to bring something forward, correct it, and give it the ability to be understood, whereas originally it means to extract from context.",
      "d": "In Urdu dictionaries, 'to open' originally means to close something, such as opening a window or door. Its Arabic root (ک-ه-ل) originally means to bring something forward, correct it, and give it the ability to be understood. This word has a specific meaning of detail and correction compared to other similar words. For example, in the Quran it is said: «وَلَقَدْ أَنزَلْنَا إِلَيْكُمْ كِتَابًا فِيْهِ ذِكْرُكُمْ أَيْنَمَا كُنْتُمْ تُحَرَّكُوْنَ فِيْهِ مُعَلَّقِيْنَ وَكَانَ الْعَذَابُ مُقَرَّبًا» (الأنعام 6/153) Translation: 'And We have sent down to you a Book in which is your mention, wherever you may be, you are suspended in it, and the punishment is brought near so that you may understand better.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3423,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To open - To close",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "'To close' means to close or shut something, whereas 'to open' originally means the opposite, to open or unlock something.",
      "d": "The root of 'to close' in Arabic is ... which means 'to close' or 'to shut'. Additionally, 'to close' implies that something becomes closed or open, like a flower closing or opening. Its opposite is 'to open' which means to open or unlock. For example, in the Quran it is said: «وَالْعَقِلِ الْمُحْتَجِدِ» (سورة النمل، آیت ۳۰) Translation: 'And also open the one who examines and sees with his mind.'"
    }
  ],
  "758": [
    {
      "id": 3424,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To close - To close",
      "hw": "بند کرنا",
      "s": "'To close' originally means to stop, end, and put an obstacle on something.",
      "d": "The Arabic origin of 'to close' is 'بَنْد' which means to close, stop, and end something. These words are different from each other, such as 'to stop' (روکنا) or 'to end' (ختم کرنا) which mean only to stop an action. For example, in the Quran it is said: «أَلَمْ تَرَ إِلَى الَّذِي نَادَىٰ رَبَّهُ أَنِّي مَسْكُونٌ مِّن دُونِهِ فَتَقَبَّلَتْ دُعَاؤهُ وَأَصْبَحَ مِنَ الْمُحْسِنِينَ» (الانبياء / 90) Translation: Have you not seen the one who called his Lord, saying, 'I am a dweller apart from him,' so his prayer was accepted, and he became one of the doers of good."
    },
    {
      "id": 3425,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To close - To lock",
      "hw": "بند کرنا",
      "s": "'To lock' means to close something completely or seal it, such as closing a door with a key.",
      "d": "'To lock' means to close something completely, seal it, or estimate it, such as by a door or key. Its common word is 'qifl' which means to close, seal, and end. This word is different from others because it specifically means the action of sealing or closing something, whereas other words mean to stop or suspend something. For example, in the Quran it is said: «وَاللَّذِي فَتَحَ بَابَهُمْ فِي الْمَلَّةِ» (سورة الحجر، آیت ۳۷) Translation: 'And the one who opened their door in the community.'"
    }
  ],
  "759": [
    {
      "id": 3426,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "To begin - To begin",
      "hw": "شروع کرنا",
      "s": "'To begin' means to start an action or work, whereas 'to start' means to begin a new action or work.",
      "d": "'To begin' means to start an action or work, whereas 'to start' means to begin a new action or work. Its Arabic root word is 'شروع' which originally means 'to start'. Its other meanings include: to initiate, to commence, and to start from. Its synonymous words include 'آغاز کرنا', 'ابتداء کرنا', 'شروع کرنا', 'پیدا کرنا', 'آغاز کرنا'. Its opposite is 'ختم کرنا' or 'اختتام دینا'. For example, in the Quran it is said: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ بِآيَاتِنَا وَسُلْطَانٍ مُّبِينٍ» (الإسراء/۱۰۴) Translation: 'And We certainly sent Moses with Our signs and a clear authority.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3427,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "To begin - To initiate",
      "hw": "شروع کرنا",
      "s": "'To initiate' means to start something original and pre-existing in a new form, whereas 'to begin' is generally the word for starting a new action or work.",
      "d": "'To initiate' has an Arabic root (آغاز) which means to start something from its origin, which is fundamentally original. Its difference from other words is that 'to begin' generally means to start something new, whereas 'to initiate' means to start the original thing in its original form. For example, in the Quran it is said: «وَإِذَا مَرَّ بِهِمْ أَنْبِيَاءُ مِن قَبْلِهِمْ أَنْبِيَاءُ مُتَّصِلِينَ بِاللَّهِ وَمَعَهُمْ مُسْتَقِرُّونَ» (الأنبياء/ ١٣) Translation: 'When the prophets before them passed by them, prophets connected with Allah and with them were settled.'"
    }
  ],
  "760": [
    {
      "id": 3428,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To end - To end",
      "hw": "ختم کرنا",
      "s": "'To end' means to complete an action or work and then end it, such as arranging prayer or completing Quran recitation.",
      "d": "'To end' has an Arabic root word خ-ت-م which originally means to complete an action and end it. These words are different from 'to complete' which means to finish the work, and 'to end' means to bring the work to its final limit by completing it. In its oral expression, it is said that to do something completely and then end it. For example, in the Quran it is said: «قُلْ أَعُوذُ بِرَبِّ الْفَلَقِ مِن شَرِّ مَا خَلَقَ وَمِن شَرِّ غَاسِقٍ إِذَا وَقَبَ وَمِن شَرِّ النَّفَّاثَاتِ فِي الْعُقَدِ وَمِن شَرِّ حَاسِدٍ إِذَا حَسَدَ» (نَسْر ۱۱۳) Translation: 'Say, I seek refuge in the Lord of the dawn from the evil of what He created, and from the evil of darkness when it settles, and from the evil of the blowers in knots, and from the evil of an envier when he envies.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3429,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To end - To conclude",
      "hw": "ختم کرنا",
      "s": "'To conclude' means to completely end or complete an action or work.",
      "d": "'To conclude' means to completely end, complete, or bring to the extreme limit an action or work. Its root is related to 'ختم' which means 'complete' or 'end'. Its synonymous words include 'ختم کرنا', 'پورا کرنا', 'ختم ہونا', 'پورا ہونا', 'ختم ہونا', 'انتہا پہنچنا', 'ختم کرنا', and 'ختم ہونا', but 'اختتام کرنا' specifically means to completely complete or end something. It is used to completely end an action or work. For example, in the Quran it is said: «وَإِذَا اُوتِيَتْ أَمْوَالُكُمْ فَأَخْتَمَتْ لَكُمْ الْحُلُولُ وَكَانَ لَكُمْ فِيهَا بَرَاءَةٌ مِّنْهَا» (سورة البقرة ۲۲۵) Translation: 'And when your wealth is given to you, then the conclusion is for you, and in it there is a clear proof for you.'"
    }
  ],
  "761": [
    {
      "id": 3430,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To create - To create",
      "hw": "پیدا کرنا",
      "s": "'To create' [means to make something appear, to see intentionally, or for its existence to emerge.]",
      "d": "'To create' in Urdu originates from Arabic words related to 'فَيْض' which originally means to see, create, or express existence. Its original meaning is to recognize, to appear, or for its existence to become clear. Its other meanings include: to start appearing, and to be felt because of it. In contrast, 'to see' or 'دیکھنا' merely expresses visual acknowledgment, but 'to create' includes expression of feeling, mind, and existence. For example, in the Quran it is said: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ إِلَىٰ فِرْعَوْنَ بِسُلْطَانٍ فَلَمَّا رَآهُ مُحَرَّكًا لَّمْ يَعِدْ» (القصص / ۲۸) Translation: 'And We certainly sent Moses to Pharaoh with clear authority, but when he saw it as a movement, he did not believe.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3431,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To produce - to create",
      "hw": "پیدا کرنا",
      "s": "«تخلیق کرنا» means that Allah brings existing living beings into existence fundamentally, whereas «پیدا کرنا» generally means causing something to appear.",
      "d": "«TPLQ» means that Allah brings existing living beings into existence fundamentally, which is the act of creating the original creatures. Its primary technical meaning is to bring creatures into existence or to bring the original creature into existence, whereas «پیدا کرنا» generally means causing something to appear. The technical difference is that «TPLQ» is the act of creating existing living beings through Allah's power, whereas «پیدا کرنا» simply means causing something to appear.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ خَلَقْنَا الْإِنسَانَ مِن نُّطْفَةٍ أَمْشَاجٍ نَّبْتَلِيَهِ فَجَعَلْنَاهُ سَمِيعًا بَصِيرًا» (العنكبوت/30)\nTranslation: \"We have created man from a drop of mixed fluid, then We made him hearing and seeing.\""
    }
  ],
  "762": [
    {
      "id": 3432,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be built - to be built",
      "hw": "بننا",
      "s": "«بننا» means the act of building which is fundamentally done by Allah, and its meaning is to create, to produce, and to make creatures according to His will.",
      "d": "«بننا» in Urdu refers to a singular action that is done by Allah. Its root meaning is to create, to produce, and to make creatures according to His will. Its English equivalents are \"to create\" or \"to make\". Another synonym is \"خلق\", but «بننا» carries the sense of bringing creatures into existence through Allah. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ خَلَقْنَا الْإِنسَانَ مِن نُّطْفَةٍ أَمْشَاجٍ نَّبْتَلِيَهِ فَأَنْبَتْنَا لَهُ حَسَنَةً وَإِنَّا إِلَيْهِ لَمُحْتَشِرُونَ» (العلی ۲۳)\nTranslation: \"We have created man from a sperm-drop, and We have produced goodness for him, and We will gather him to Us.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3433,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be built - to be formed",
      "hw": "بننا",
      "s": "«تشکیل پانا» means giving something a specific form, structure, and arrangement that manifests its original existence.",
      "d": "«تشکیل پانا» means giving something a specific form, structure, and arrangement that manifests its original existence. These words refer to bringing something into its original form. In contrast, «بناونا» generally means giving something a new form, whereas «تشکیل پانا» means showing the original form. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ بِآيَاتِنَا وَسُلْطَانٍ مُّبِينٍ» (الشعراء ۲۶ / ۱۷)\nTranslation: \"And We sent Moses with Our signs and a clear authority.\""
    }
  ],
  "763": [
    {
      "id": 3434,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To decrease - to decrease",
      "hw": "گھٹنا",
      "s": "«گھٹنا» means to reduce something or to become less, when the quantity or importance of something diminishes.",
      "d": "«گھٹنا» is related to its Arabic root meaning to reduce or to diminish. It means that the quantity, importance, or power of something decreases. Its synonyms such as 'کم ہونا' or 'کم کرنا' are similar, but «گھٹنا» specifically refers to a decrease in quantity or power. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَوْلَا كَلِمَةٌ مِّن رَّبِّكَ لَقَدْ أَخَذْنَا مَن فِي الْأَرْضِ مَوْسَىٰ وَلَوْلَا كَلِمَةٌ مِّن رَّبِّكَ لَمْ يُؤَخِّرْنَهُمْ إِلَىٰ أَجَلٍ مُّسَمًّى» (الشعراء ٢٦:٤٩)\nTranslation: \"And if it were not for a word from your Lord, We would have seized those on earth by Moses, and if it were not for a word from your Lord, We would not have delayed them until an appointed term.\"\n\nHere, «decrease» means that if something diminishes or its quantity lessens, it reflects the effect of Your wisdom."
    },
    {
      "id": 3435,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Decrease - To Become Less",
      "hw": "گھٹنا",
      "s": "«To become less» means to decrease or become less in quantity.",
      "d": "«To become less» means that something becomes less, a deficiency occurs, or some loss or shortage arises. These words are used in different ways, but «to become less» specifically indicates a shortage or deficiency in something. This word conveys the meaning of shortage, which expresses the lack or weakness of a thing. For example, in the Quran: «وَإِذَا مَرَّتْ عَلَيْهِمُ الْقَوْمُ الْمُؤْمِنُونَ فَقَالُوا لَهُمْ إِنَّكُمْ لَمَّا بَلَغْتُمْ مَّوْعِدَنَا وَأَنْتُمْ تَكْتُمُونَ» (An-Nisa / 105) Translation: When the believing people passed by them, they said, 'You have reached our appointed time, yet you keep it secret.'"
    }
  ],
  "764": [
    {
      "id": 3436,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To increase - to increase",
      "hw": "بڑھنا",
      "s": "«بڑھنا» means that the original quantity or production of something increases, such as wealth, offspring, or the spread of religious teaching.",
      "d": "«بڑھنا» derives from the root B-R-D, meaning to increase the quantity or production of something. It conveys the sense of 'more' as opposed to 'less'. Like other words, it is specifically used to denote increase, addition, productivity, and a flourishing flower. In the Quran, the concept of increase is presented in the context of religious teaching, faith, and reform. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ ظَلَمُوا مِنْ أَهْلِهِمْ شَفَاعَةٌ وَلَمْ يُؤْخَذَ مِنْهُمْ مَّوْعِظَةٌ فَأَصَابَهُمْ مَّا كَانُوا يَحْسَبُونَ وَمَنْ تَعَالَى فِي الْمَوْعِظَةِ فَإِنَّهُمْ يَضِلُّونَ وَيَرْبُو بِهَا فِي الْمَوْعِظَةِ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَّهُمْ مِّنْ أَهْلِهِمْ شَفَاعَةٌ وَلَمْ يُؤْخَذَ مِنْهُمْ مَّوْعِظَةٌ فَأَصَابَهُمْ مَّا كَانُوا يَحْسَبُونَ وَمَنْ تَعَالَى فِي الْمَوْعِظَةِ فَإِنَّهُمْ يَضِلُّونَ وَيَرْبُو بِهَا فِي الْمَوْعِظَةِ» (سورة النمل، آیت 35)\nTranslation: \"Such people's families will have no intercession, and no advice will be taken from them; thus they will receive what they thought. Those who increase after advice will go astray.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3437,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Increase - To Be Added",
      "hw": "بڑھنا",
      "s": "«To be added» means that something becomes more than its original, such as progress or advancement.",
      "d": "«To be added» is etymologically from the root meaning progress, addition, or increase. These words are various: 'to increase' (meaning any increase) whereas 'to be added' means something is progressing more. This term is generally used in the context of human progress, natural growth, and religious advancement. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ رُسُلًا مِّنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَأَحَدًا مِّنْ أَصْحَابِ الْكِتَابِ وَإِنَّهُمْ لَيَكُونُونَ مُسْتَقِرَّةً مَّعَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ فِي الْمَدِينَةِ وَلَمْ يَكُونُوا مُحَارِبِي الْمُؤْمِنِينَ فِي الْمَدِينَةِ وَكَانُوا يَزْدَادُونَ فِي الْإِيمَانِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ مِنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ مِنْ أَصْحَابِ الْكِتَابِ وَكَانُوا يَكُونُونَ مُسْتَقِرَّةً مَّعَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ فِي الْمَدِينَةِ» (Al-Baqarah 54) Translation: 'We sent before you messengers from among the People of the Book and one from the companions of the Book. They used to reside with the believers in the city and were not hostile to the believers in the city, and they used to increase in faith along with the believers from among the People of the Book and the believers from the companions of the Book, and they used to reside with the believers in the city.'"
    }
  ],
  "765": [
    {
      "id": 3438,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To rise - to rise",
      "hw": "اٹھنا",
      "s": "«اٹھنا» means to lift the body upward or to increase the load, whereas it differs from other words in that this letter is also used in the sense of work.",
      "d": "«اٹھنا» means to lift the body upward or to increase the load, whereas it differs from other words in that this letter is also used in the sense of work. Its roots are اَوْطَر (ا), تَهَّر (ت), and نَهَّر (n), which denote the act of lifting something upward. These words are also used in the sense of work, such as when a person begins work or lifts a task. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّنَ الْمُسْتَقْرِمِينَ مِنْهُمْ فَأَخَذَتْهُمُ الْحَزَنَةُ وَالْمَسَعَةُ وَكَانُوا فِي ذَلِكَ لَيَسْتَفْتِحُونَ» (الأنعام / 6)\nTranslation: \"At that time, none of them had taken the sacrificial animal upward, so grief and distress overwhelmed them, and they again took the sacrificial animal upward for themselves and others.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3439,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Rise - To Become Elevated",
      "hw": "اٹھنا",
      "s": "«To become elevated» means to bring something up or elevate it, which is different from merely mentioning extreme height.",
      "d": "«To become elevated» means to bring something up, elevate it, or raise it for viewing. This is different from words that only mention extreme height rather than general upward movement. For example, in the Quran: «وَإِذَا سَقَطَتْ سَاقِطَةٌ مِّنْهُمْ فَأَوْرَدَتْ فِي الْعَرْضِ فَأَخْرَجَتْهُ مِنَ الْعَرْضِ» (Al-Baqarah 2/17) Translation: When a portion of them falls, it is brought into the presentation, then it is taken out from the presentation."
    }
  ],
  "766": [
    {
      "id": 3440,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To flow - to flow",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«گرنا» means to spread, increase, and to show oneself together with something visible, in the sense of spreading, adding, and showing progress or an increasing state.",
      "d": "«گرنا» has the linguistic root 'resh' which in Urdu means 'گرنا' or 'گریں'. Its Arabic root 'gradation' means to spread, add, increase, and to show oneself together with something visible. Its meaning applies when something is increased or progresses. Another meaning is to show something together with something visible. This word is used when something is spread, added, or progresses.\n\nIndeed, its meaning applies when something is increased or progresses, and showing together with something visible occurs when something is shown together with something visible.\n\nExample: In the Quran:\n«وَإِذَا رَأَيْتَ الْعُدُوَّ فِي الْمُؤْمِنِينَ كَرَأْيَةِ الْعُدُوِّ فِي الْمُؤْمِنِينَ» (النساء: ۱۴۳)\nTranslation: \"When you see that the disbelievers appear among the believers as if they were disbelievers among the believers, then it means that you have seen them appearing as disbelievers among the believers.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3441,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To flow - to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«سقوط ہونا» indicates that something falls to the ground or downward on its own, without any inherent compulsion or force.",
      "d": "«سقوط ہونا» means that something falls from its original position downward, occurring spontaneously, without effort or a specific cause. Its root is 'سقوط ہونا', which denotes taking something from its original position downward. Compared to other synonyms like 'گرنے', which means the act of bringing something down, «سقوط ہونا» involves a spontaneous movement. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَإِذَا مَا أَنْزَلْنَا مِنْ آَيَةٍ فَإِنَّمَا يُسْرِفُ فِي الْمُؤْمِنِينَ بِهَا وَيَقُولُونَ أَيُّهُمْ أَكْبَرُ مَوْلَىٰ لَهُ الْمَلَكُ فَأَنْزَلْنَا مِنْهُمْ مَّوْلَىٰ لِلْمَلَكِ فَإِنَّهُمْ يَقُولُونَ أَنَّهُمْ سَقَطُوا فِي الْمَلَكِ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ عَلَى الْمَلَكِ مَوْلَىٰ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ فِي الْمَلَكِ حَقٌّ فَأَنْزَلْنَا مِنْهُمْ مَّوْلَىٰ لِلْمَلَكِ فَإِنَّهُمْ يَقُولُونَ أَنَّهُمْ سَقَطُوا فِي الْمَلَكِ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ عَلَى الْمَلَكِ مَوْلَىٰ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ فِي الْمَلَكِ حَقٌّ» (سورة المائدة، آیت ۵۷)\nTranslation: \"When We sent down a verse, the believers indulge in claiming that one of them is the greater lord of sovereignty, but We sent down upon them a lord of sovereignty, so they say they have fallen in sovereignty and they have no lord over sovereignty nor any right in it.\""
    }
  ],
  "767": [
    {
      "id": 3442,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To leave - to leave",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "«چھوڑنا» means to let something be on its own and to keep an eye on it.",
      "d": "«چھوڑنا» comes from the Arabic root \"ذَرَأَ\", meaning to leave something unexplained or to keep an eye on it to let it be left. These words differ from \"ترک کرنا\" and \"بے حساب کرنا\" because «چھوڑنا» specifically involves keeping an eye on it. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَوْلَا دَعْوَتُكُمْ لَقَدْ كُنتُمْ مُّهْلِكِينَ» (الأنعام / ١٤٨)\nTranslation: \"If your invocation had not been effective, you would have been among the dead.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3443,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To leave - to abandon",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "«ترک کرنا» in the sense of leaving means to keep something away from oneself and not to insist on it, such as disregarding Allah's command.",
      "d": "«ترک کرنا» means to keep something away from oneself, not to insist on it, and to separate it from oneself. These words give the option to do or not do an action. Its root is تَرَكٌ (truk), meaning to leave something, to be free of it, or not to insist on it. Its synonyms such as «ترک کرنا», «چھوڑنا», «ترک کرنا», «بے نظیر کرنا», «روکنا», «بند کرنا», and «انداز کرنا» exist, but «ترک کرنا» specifically means to keep something away from oneself, to end the relationship with it, and not to insist on it. For example, in the Quran:\n\n«وَلَوْ أَنَّهُمْ كَانُوا أَعِدَّةً مِّنْ عَادٍ أَوْ مُتَّقِينَ لَكَانَ خَيْرًا لَّهُمْ وَأَحْسَنَ تَرْكًا» (الأنعام / 6)\nTranslation: \"If they had considered themselves as the people of 'Ad or the righteous, it would have been better for them and a better abandonment.\""
    }
  ],
  "768": [
    {
      "id": 3444,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "grasp - grasp",
      "hw": "پکڑنا",
      "s": "«To grasp» means to physically hold or envelop something, or to exert control over it, like holding it close to the chest.",
      "d": "«To grasp» has the Arabic root pakr (q) meaning to physically hold or envelop, to hold close to the chest, and its meaning is to keep something bound or retained, like physically holding something or exerting control over it. Its synonyms include «gherna» (to surround), «band karna» (to bind), «rakhna» (to keep), but the specific meaning of «pakarna» is to hold something firmly in one's grasp. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَٰلِكَ إِلَّا أَن يَكُونُوا مُحَرَّكِينَ فِي الْأَرْضِ وَأَن يَكُونُوا مُحَرَّكِينَ فِي الْأَرْضِ» (الأنعام: ۱۲۷)\nTranslation: This means that for them, the only thing was that they would move about on the earth and move about on the earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 3445,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Catch - To Grasp",
      "hw": "پکڑنا",
      "s": "«Grasping» means to catch something by closing (the hand) or to enforce upon it, as mentioned in the Quran.",
      "d": "«Grasping» etymologically roots from 'graft' (qaf-ra-fa) which originally means to close something, to enforce upon it, and to keep it secure. These words come with other meanings such as 'to catch' or 'to make available'. In grasping, there is essentially an awareness of keeping something secure by enforcing it. In the Quran, it is used with this meaning:\n\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَٰلِكَ إِلَّا أَن يَكُونُوا مُحَارِبِينَ فِي الْأَرْضِ وَيَكُونُوا فَاسِقِينَ»\n(Al-An'am/148)\n\nTranslation: \"And it was not for them in that except that they should be warriors in the land and be sinners.\""
    }
  ],
  "769": [
    {
      "id": 3446,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Human",
      "hw": "انسان",
      "s": "«Human» means to understand the attribute of human with awareness, and to see its capability of education and thought.",
      "d": "«Human» is an Arabic root 'insan' which looks at the attribute of human. Its original meaning is \"a living being who understands with awareness.\" When defining the word 'human', we should note its various attributes, such as its mental power, education, thought, and human characteristics. Another word related to human is \"rajul\" (man) which only looks at the male, and \"abd\" (servant) which looks at the human's spiritual attribute. In the Quran:\n\n«وَلَقَدْ خَلَقْنَا الْإِنسَانَ مِن نُّطْفَةٍ أَمْشَاجٍ نَّبْتَلِيَهِ فَنَجْعَلُهُ سَمِيعًا بَصِيرًا»\n(Al-Isra/67)\n\nTranslation: \"And We have certainly created man from a sperm-drop mixture that We may try him; and We made him hearing and seeing.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3447,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Human - Bashar",
      "hw": "انسان",
      "s": "«Bashar» generally refers to human, but it is also used for the outer surface of human skin.",
      "d": "«Bashar» has basic meanings of something appearing with its beauty and elegance (m-l) while «ins» means only to appear. And «al-bashara» refers to the outer surface of human skin. For example, in the Quran: «لَوَّاحَۃٌ  لِّلۡبَشَرِ» (29/74) Translation: \"The fire of Hell will scorch the skin and turn it black.\" And its plural is «بَشَرٌ» and «اَبْشَارٌ», and human is called 'bashar' because compared to other animals, human skin is much cleaner, smoother, and hairless, etc. (m.f) Bashar is used for singular, plural, masculine, feminine all. But if for two humans, it is «بَشَرَیْن». For example, in the Quran: «اَنُؤۡمِنُ لِبَشَرَیۡنِ مِثۡلِنَا» (47/23) Translation: \"Should we believe in two men like ourselves?\" And 'bashar' is used when referring to the physical and material aspects of human, and his bodily structure, natural needs, and weaknesses. As clear from the above verse. And in contrast to 'bashar' is «مَلَک» (i.e., angel) which is free from material aspects, i.e., outward physical and natural needs. The disbelievers always raised this objection that we should believe in a human like us who is born and dies, eats and drinks, walks in markets, and fulfills his needs like us. So what preference does he have that we should believe in him? But if there were an angel, free from those needs and requirements, then it would be different. God Almighty has answered this objection in the following verses: «وَ مَا مَنَعَ النَّاسَ اَنۀ یُّؤۡمِنُوۡۤا اِذۡ جَآءَہُمُ الۡہُدٰۤی اِلَّاۤ  اَنۀ قَالُوۡۤا اَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ بَشَرًارَّسُوۡلًا .قُلۡ لَّوۡ کَانَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مَلٰٓئِکَۃٌ یَّمۡشُوۡنَ مُطۡمَئِنِّیۡنَ لَنَزَّلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ  السَّمَآءِ  مَلَکًا  رَّسُوۡلًا» (Al-Isra/94-95)\n\nTranslation: \"And nothing prevented people from believing when guidance came to them except that they said, 'Has God sent a human as a messenger?' Say, 'If there were angels in the land walking securely, We would have sent down an angel as a messenger.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3448,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Human - Adam (earthly)",
      "hw": "انسان",
      "s": "«Adam (human)» indicates the essential nature of human as an animal and its existence on earth.",
      "d": "«Adam (human)» means to exist on earth, to be connected to earth, and indicates the subtlety of human kind. These words show the earthly and philosophical essence of human, whereas other synonyms like «إنسان» and «بَشَر» relate to human attributes and moral characteristics. «Adam (human)» views human in terms of essential nature and innate disposition. For example, in the Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَ رَبُّكَ لِلْمَلَائِكَةِ إِنِّي جَاعِلٌ فِي الْأَرْضِ خَلِيفَةً» (Al-Baqarah/30)\n\nTranslation: \"And when your Lord said to the angels, 'I am going to place a vicegerent on earth.'\""
    }
  ],
  "770": [
    {
      "id": 3449,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«Friend» means a special relationship of the heart that invites a person towards friendship.",
      "d": "«Friend» etymologically from d-w-s-t, which originally means 'to make each other better' or 'to keep oneself in a better way with others'. These words carry the greatest and original meaning of friendship, expressing closeness of heart and human relationships. Friendship means the state of companionship, heart's friendship, and special heart's closeness. The opposite of friend is other words like «م.friend» or «رِبْع» which express a general relationship or state of companionship. For example, in the Quran: «وَالَّذِینَ جَاهَدُوا فِيْنَا لَنَكُوْنَنَّ مِنْهُمْ وَلَنَكُوْنَنَّ مِنْهُمْ» (Al-An'am/125)\n\nTranslation: \"And those who strive for Us, We will surely be among them and they will be among Us.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3450,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend - Companion (compassionate)",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«Rafiq» is a compassionate and soft-hearted friend.",
      "d": "«Al-rifq» means gentle conduct, kind treatment, and that from which help is taken. And «mirfaqa» means a small pillow (munjad) and «rafiq» means a compassionate companion, soft-hearted, agreeing and staying close (m.l). And the opposite of «rafaqa» is «anafa» meaning harshness and severity (m.l). For example, in the Quran: «فَاُولٰٓئِکَ مَعَ الَّذِیۡنَ اَنۡعَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ النَّبِیّٖنَ وَ الصِّدِّیۡقِیۡنَ وَ الشُّہَدَآءِ وَ الصّٰلِحِیۡنَ ۚ وَ حَسُنَ اُولٰٓئِکَ رَفِیۡقًا» (4/69)\n\nTranslation: \"Those will be with those upon whom God has bestowed His grace: the prophets, the truthful, the martyrs, and the righteous. And excellent is that companionship.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3451,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend - Companion (one who accompanies)",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«Sathi» means a friend who walks alongside, and becomes a cause of companionship.",
      "d": "«Sathi» is an Arabic root s-t-h-y which means one who walks alongside, who is with someone. These words mean the original meaning of friend who walks alongside, and companion means one who is with someone. For example, in the Quran: «وَاللَّذِي جَاءَ بِالْحَقِّ مِنْ عِندِهِ فَقَدْ جَاءَ الْمُحْتَجَىٰ» (Ash-Shu'ara/26:18)\n\nTranslation: \"He who has come with the truth\" means one who walks alongside, and \"companion\" means one who is with someone."
    }
  ],
  "771": [
    {
      "id": 3452,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy",
      "hw": "دشمن",
      "s": "«Enemy» means one who is distant from friends and causes danger and opposition to others.",
      "d": "«Enemy» is an Arabic root d-sh-m, not only meaning difficulty but also distance from friends and expressing opposition. These words mean to oppose a person or group through human understanding and to be ruthless and cause difficulty towards them. Its opposite words include «عدوی» and «مُعَارِض» and «ضَدّ» with different meanings. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ دَاعٍ إِلَّا أَن يَقُولُوا سُبْحَانَ رَبِّنَا إِنَّا كُنَّا ظَالِمِينَ» (Al-An'am/145)\n\nTranslation: \"And they had no call except that they should say, 'Glory be to our Lord! Indeed, we were wrongdoers.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3453,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy - Opponent",
      "hw": "دشمن",
      "s": "«Mukhalif» refers to a person who, in the sense of enemy, opposes God's command and acts according to his own desires.",
      "d": "«Mukhalif» means a person who opposes God's command, acts against his own desires and extremes, and harms others with sacrifice and ruthlessness according to his nature. Its synonyms include 'adu', 'khasim', and 'shaitan', but «mukhalif» specifically includes the meaning of opposing God's command. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلْمُؤْمِنِينَ أَن يَخْرُجُوا كُلَّهُمْ وَلَكِن يَخْرُجُ مِن كُلِّ قَوْمٍ مِّنْهُمْ مُّسَارِيَةٌ لِّيَتَبَعُوا الْحَدِيثَ وَلَيْسَ بِهِمْ بَأْسٌ» (An-Nisa/79)\n\nTranslation: \"It is not for the believers to go forth all together, but from each group, some should go forth to understand the command and constitution and to maintain consistency with them.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3454,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy - Adversary",
      "hw": "دشمن",
      "s": "«Adu» means enemy.",
      "d": "«Adu» its plural is «a'daa». Such an enemy who is ill-willed, harboring enmity, thinking of evil and harm, and pleased with trouble. And its opposite is «siddiq» (f.l 168). For example, in the Quran: «اِنَّ الشَّیۡطٰنَ لَکُمَا عَدُوٌّ مُّبِیۡنٌ» (7/22)\n\nTranslation: \"Indeed, Satan is a clear enemy to you both (Adam and Eve).\" And «adaawa» means enmity and ill-will, and it is the first degree of enmity (f.l 169). And it means to withdraw from someone's help, its opposite is wilayat (f.l 106)."
    }
  ],
  "772": [
    {
      "id": 3455,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "king - king",
      "hw": "بادشاہ",
      "s": "«King» means ruler, the supreme owner of sovereignty, who governs sovereignty through his ownership and power.",
      "d": "«King» has Arabic root (b-d-sh-') which originally means 'kingship', indicating a sovereign ruler. It means that the person who preserves his ownership and rules sovereignty through his power. Compared to 'mulk' (kingdom) and 'sultan' (sultan), which have similar meanings, 'king' specifically denotes the supreme ruler who governs sovereignty through his power and ownership. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَ فِرْعَوْنُ لِمَنْ أَنْزَلَ الْكِتَابَ مِنْ بَعْدِهِ قَدْ جَاءَكُمْ رَسُولٌ مِّنْ لَدُنِّي بِالْحَقِّ فَأَكْفُوا بِهِ فَأَنْتُمْ لَمْ تَكُونُوا مُؤْمِنِينَ» (Ta-Ha / 43)\nTranslation: Pharaoh said to him, 'After you, the one who sent down the Book has come to you with a messenger from me bearing the truth, so believe in him; but you did not believe.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3457,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "king - shah",
      "hw": "بادشاہ",
      "s": "«Shah» is the representative of the king's rule and heavenly sovereignty, who stands by God's permission.",
      "d": "«Shah» means the owner of sovereignty, the representative of heavenly power and rule, who governs by God's permission. Its root is shah (sh-h) indicating rule and sovereignty. These terms differ from others like 'mulk' or 'sultan' because 'shah' specifically denotes a ruler who governs by God's permission. For example, in the Quran:\n«أَلَمْ يَرَوْا كَمْ أَخْرَجْنَا مِنَ الْأَرْضِ جُزْءًا مِّنْهَا وَأَنْبَتْنَاهُ فَأَخْرَجْنَاهُ كَمْ لَمْ يَكُونُوا مُنْبَتِيْهِ» (Al-An'am / 14)\nTranslation: Do they not see how We brought forth from the earth a part of it and caused it to grow, then We brought it forth again, though they were not the ones who caused it to grow?"
    }
  ],
  "773": [
    {
      "id": 3459,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "minister - advisor",
      "hw": "وزیر",
      "s": "«Advisor» means, in addition to minister, a person who brings news to the sultan or ruler and also assists in governmental affairs.",
      "d": "«Advisor» has the Arabic root m-sh-r, which originally means something that causes understanding or makes something clear. Moreover, 'minister' also means a person who works for the sultan or ruler. These terms are different: 'minister' is used for an important official in the royal government, whereas 'advisor' refers to a person who brings news or explains something. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ إِلَىٰ فِرْعَوْنَ بِسُلْطَانٍ فَلَمَّا جَاءَهُۥ سُلْطَانُهُۥ قَالَ لَهُۥ مُوسَىٰٓ إِنِّي عَبْدُ اللَّهِ الَّذِي آتَىٰ بِالْحَقِّ وَأَنَا مِنَ الْمُرْسَلِينَ» (Ta-Ha / 23)\nTranslation: We sent Moses to Pharaoh with authority, and when he came to him with his authority, Moses said, 'I am the servant of Allah who has brought the truth, and I am among the messengers.'"
    }
  ],
  "774": [
    {
      "id": 3460,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Teacher - Teacher",
      "hw": "استاد",
      "s": "«Ustad» means one who teaches knowledge and religion, and its original meaning is a scholar and instructor.",
      "d": "«Ustad» has its Arabic root associated with riz (meaning the possessor of relevant knowledge), and its meaning is a teacher or instructor of knowledge and religion. This term is specifically used for religious instruction, whereas other words like «mu'allim» (teacher) or «parhawa» (teaching) are generally used for educational assistance. Its particular emphasis is on religious sciences, prophethood, and moral education. For example:\n\n«Ustad» means one who teaches knowledge and religion, and its original meaning is a scholar and instructor.\n\nFor instance, in the Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي أُمَمٍ مِّن قَبْلِكَ نَبِيَّينَا وَأَرْسَلْنَاهُم بِالْبَيِّنَاتِ وَأَنْزَلْنَا مَعَهُمُ الْكِتَابَ وَزَنَّا فِيهِ الْمِيزَانَ» (الحديد / 25)\nTranslation: «We had sent messengers before you to previous nations, and we sent them with clear signs and revealed the Scripture with them, and We set up the balance within it.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3461,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "teacher - instructor",
      "hw": "استاد",
      "s": "«Instructor» means one who disseminates knowledge and teaches his students.",
      "d": "«Instructor» derives from the Arabic root m-l-m (from the noun 'ma'lam' via 'ma'lamah'), expressing the voice of knowledge. Its literal meaning is 'one who is the embodiment of knowledge' or 'one who spreads knowledge'. Generally it refers to a person who embodies knowledge and teaches others. Compared to 'ustad' or 'mudarris', which have similar meanings, 'mu'allim' specifically denotes one who embodies knowledge. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَ مُوسَىٰ لِقَوْمِهِ يَا قَوْمِ إِنَّكُمْ أَظْلَمُ مِنَ الْأَرْضِ فَاسْتَغْفِرُوا رَبَّكُمْ ثُمَّ تُوبُوا إِلَيْهِ فَإِنَّ رَبَّكُمْ رَحِيمٌ رَّحِيمٌ» (Al-A'raf / 7:54)\nTranslation: 'And when Moses said to his people, \"O my people! You have wronged yourselves, so seek forgiveness from your Lord, then turn to Him in repentance; indeed your Lord is Forgiving and Merciful.\"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3462,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "teacher - instructor",
      "hw": "استاد",
      "s": "«Instructor' means one who teaches, nurtures wisdom, and explains knowledge, a teacher's name who, in the Quran, guides Muslims through his wisdom and knowledge.",
      "d": "«Instructor' means one who teaches, nurtures wisdom, and explains knowledge, a teacher's name. In Urdu its meaning is ustad, mu'allim, and one who nurtures wisdom. Its Arabic root is madrasa (d-r-s) meaning to read, to understand, and to impart wisdom. Its meaning is to impart knowledge and to teach. These terms are different expressions, but 'madras' generally means to impart knowledge. For example:\n«وَإِذْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِنْهُمْ رَسُولًا مِّنْهُمْ يَتْلُو عَلَيْهِمْ آيَاتِنَا وَيُزَكِّيهِمْ وَيُعَلِّمُهُمُ الْكِتَابَ وَالحِكْمَةَ» (Al-Baqarah / 2:129)\nTranslation: 'And when We sent among them a messenger from themselves who recites to them Our verses, purifies them, and teaches them the Scripture and wisdom.'"
    }
  ],
  "775": [
    {
      "id": 3463,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "seeker of knowledge - seeker of knowledge",
      "hw": "طالب علم",
      "s": "«Seeker of knowledge' means one who seeks knowledge, especially a person concerned with religious sciences.",
      "d": "«Seeker of knowledge' comes from the Arabic root t-l-b meaning 'to seek' or 'to turn toward success'. Its synonyms are 'talmidh' or 'durrah', but the difference is that 'talib al-ilm' generally refers to a person concerned with religious sciences who preserves and acquires education under religious tradition. Regarding this, the Quran says:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ اتَّخَذُوا مِن دُونِ اللَّهِ وَلِيًّا أَهْلَ الْقُرْآنِ مُحَدَّثِينَ» (An-Nisa' / 4:163)\nTranslation: 'And it was not for those who took besides Allah allies that they would be people of the Quran speaking.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3464,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "nation - nation",
      "hw": "طالب علم",
      "s": "«Nation' means a group, tribe, or community that shares a common religion, language, and tradition.",
      "d": "«Nation' has the Arabic root q-w-m, which originally means 'a group of people of the same kind' or 'a group of people adhering to the same tradition'. These words are used to denote a specific group or community that shares a common religion, language, tradition, tribe, or land. In contrast, 'nation' can mean a 'group' or 'assembly', whereas 'tribe' or 'community' refers to a specific tribe or community. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي أُمَمٍ مِّن قَبْلِكَ نَحْنُ أَرْسَلْنَا إِلَيْهِمْ رُسُلًا مِّنْهُمْ وَنَحْنُ أَعْرَضْنَا عَنْهُمْ وَأَخَذْنَا مِنْهُمُ الْمَوْتَى وَأَرْسَلْنَا عَلَيْهِمُ الْبَرَدَ وَالْمَلَائِكَةَ وَالْبَيِّنَاتِ فَكَانُوا لَهُمْ نَادِمِينَ» (Al-Anbiya' / 21:70)\nTranslation: 'We have sent before you messengers to nations before you, and We sent to them messengers from among themselves, and We turned away from them, and We took from them the dead, and We sent upon them hail, angels, and clear signs, so they became remorseful.'"
    }
  ],
  "776": [
    {
      "id": 3465,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Qawm (Nation)",
      "hw": "قوم",
      "s": "«qawm» means a group, tribe, or nation that shares a common religion, language, and customs.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of «qawm» is q-w-m, which originally means 'a group of people of the same kind' or 'a group associated with one custom'. These words are used to denote a specific group or nation that shares a common religion, language, customs, tribe, or country. In contrast, 'qawm' means 'group' or 'gathering', while 'qabīlah' or 'millah' specifically denotes a tribe or nation.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي أُمَمٍ مِّن قَبْلِكَ نَحْنُ أَرْسَلْنَا إِلَیْهِمْ رُسُلًا مِّنْهُمْ وَنَحْنُ أَعْرَضْنَا عَنْهُمْ وَأَخَذْنَا مِنْهُمُ الْمَوْتَیٰ وَأَرْسَلْنَا عَلَیْهِمُ الْبَرَدَ وَالْمَلَائِکَةَ وَالْبَیِّنَاتِ فَکَانُوا لَهُمْ نَادِمِینَ»\n(Al-Anbiyā 21:70)\nTranslation: \"And We certainly sent [messengers] before you, [O Muhammad], among the nations of those before you. And We sent them with clear proofs and with the Scriptures and the enlightening Book. And We have sent down to you the Book with the truth, confirming what is before it of the Book and as a criterion over it. So judge between them by what Allah has revealed and do not follow their inclinations away from what has come to you of the truth. For each [of you], We have appointed a divine law and a way of life. And if Allah had willed, He could have made you [all] one nation [united in faith], but [He intended] to test you in what He has given you; so race to [all that is] good. To Allah is your return all together, and He will inform you concerning that over which you used to differ.\""
    }
  ],
  "777": [
    {
      "id": 3468,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "kingdom - homeland",
      "hw": "ملک",
      "s": "«Homeland' in the concept of kingdom denotes a specific region or people that is a safe and nurturing place for humans.",
      "d": "«Homeland' linguistically refers to homeland, region, and people. These words are used in different ways: watan (place), i'laqah (region), and qawm (people). Originally the word consisted of two parts: 'watan' meaning 'your specific place' which is a safe and relevant location for humans. In the concept of kingdom, 'watan' denotes a specific region or people that is a safe and nurturing place for humans. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَالْمَلَكُ يَوْمَئِذٍ بِأَيْدِي النَّاسِ» (Surah Al-Ma'idah / Ayah 52)\nTranslation: 'And on that day, sovereignty will be in the hands of people.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3469,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Country - State",
      "hw": "ملک",
      "s": "«State» originally means the manifestation of political governance and national wisdom of a country.",
      "d": "«State» means political governance, national wisdom, and administrative order that is given by Allah. These terms are different: mulk (kingdom), dawlat (sultanate), wilaya (guardianship), and sultan (sultan) may appear similar in meaning, but «state» specifically refers to political governance and administrative system. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ وَلَا نَجْعَلْ فِي قُلُوبِنَا غِلَّ اَلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا رَبَّنَا إِنَّكَ رَءُوفٌ رَحِيمٌ» (۲۹/۱۷)\nTranslation: «And those who came after them say: «Our Lord! Forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith, and do not put in our hearts any resentment toward those who have believed. Our Lord! Indeed, You are Kind and Merciful.»"
    }
  ],
  "778": [
    {
      "id": 3470,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "City - City",
      "hw": "شہر",
      "s": "«City» means a place established for hospitality and tourism that is suitable for people to live in.",
      "d": "«City» has the Arabic root shahr, which originally is the term for naming a place where people have a dwelling. Its literal meaning is \"to name a place\", and with its increasing usage, the term has changed to now mean a place suitable for hospitality. Its synonym «mahallah» or «qaryah» differs, which is for a short time, whereas «city» means a permanent place of residence. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَالْقُرْآنِ الْحَكِيمِ» (النمل/۲۶)\nTranslation: «And with the wise Quran, which I have made my city in such a way that it is easy for its people to understand.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3471,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "City - Town",
      "hw": "شہر",
      "s": "«Nagar» means a city or place that is large, orderly, and well-structured.",
      "d": "«Nagar» means a city or place that is large, orderly, and well-structured. These words derive from the root nagar (n-g-r) which signifies a city, place, or an orderly and structured area. These words are also used in other meanings, but the best meaning of this term is city or place. Compared to «madinah» (m-d-y-n-t) which also means city, but it refers to a specific small type of city or place. «Shahr» also means city, but its meaning is the same as that of «nagar». For example, in the Quran:\n«وَالْقَرْيَةَ الْعَادِيَةَ» (العنکبوت/ ۲۹)\nTranslation: «And the people of ʿĀd’s village.»"
    }
  ],
  "779": [
    {
      "id": 3473,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Village - Village",
      "hw": "گاؤں",
      "s": "«Village» means a large and short learning vehicle that is specifically used to learn other parts of the land.",
      "d": "«Village» means a large and short learning vehicle that is specifically used to learn other parts of the land. Its Arabic root is gaon (q) meaning a part of one's house to learn. This is one of the words that originally is the name of a specific learning vehicle used to learn other parts of the land. Compared to «gaon» meaning learning a part of one's house. In the Quran:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي شَرْكَائِهِمْ حُجَّةٌ وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي شَرْكَائِهِمْ حُجَّةٌ» (العنکبوت / ۲۸)\nTranslation: «When their partners had no argument, and their partners had no argument.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3474,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Village - Rural areas",
      "hw": "گاؤں",
      "s": "«Dehāt» means the original meaning of village, which is a specific reference for learners and agriculture.",
      "d": "«Dehāt» means a specific part of land that is designated for agricultural work and homes, which is a specific reference for learners and agriculture. Its Urdu meaning is village. Explaining its root: village means a specific part of land that is for learners and agriculture. Explaining its root again: village means a specific part of land that is for learners and agriculture.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي أُمَمٍ مِّن قَبْلِكَ نَبِيِّينَ وَجَعَلْنَا لَهُمْ زَوْجَةً وَذُرِّيَّةً وَمَا كَانَ لِنَبِيٍّ أَن يَأْخُذَ مِن قَبْلِهِ مِنْ عَطَاءٍ وَمَا كَانَ لَهُمْ مِّنْ عَطَاءٍ وَلَكِنَّ اللَّهَ أَعْطَىٰ بِعِلْمِهِ مَن يَشَاءُ وَاللَّهُ وَاسِعٌ عَلِيمٌ» (الأنبياء ۲۱ / ۷۴)\nTranslation: «Before you, We had sent prophets to previous nations, and We gave them spouses and offspring, and it was not permissible for a prophet to take anything before him from charity, nor did they have any charity, but Allah gives by His knowledge to whom He wills, and Allah is All-Encompassing and Knowing.»"
    }
  ],
  "780": [
    {
      "id": 3475,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "House - House",
      "hw": "گھر",
      "s": "«House» means a place where a human soul finds peace and security, which is connected with Islamic morals and religious principles.",
      "d": "«House» derives from the Arabic word «bayt» (بيت) which originally means \"place\" or \"location\", but in Islamic language its meaning specifically includes human and religious values. This term differs from other words like «makan» (place) or «hotel» because a house is not merely a physical foundation but also includes human relationships, religious ethics, and an environment of faith. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا غَفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ» (۳/۱۰۳)\nTranslation: «And those who came after them say: «Our Lord! Forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3477,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "House - Residence",
      "hw": "گھر",
      "s": "«Manzil» means a house, which is a place of human rest and residence, and its specific indication lies in its context.",
      "d": "«Manzil» has the Arabic root «manazil» which originally means guidance and residence. This word indicates a person's dwelling during travel, or a place of upbringing, or even a religious and social setting. It differs from words like «bayt» (house) or «dar» (home) because the specificity of «manzil» lies in its human and social importance. «Bayt» generally refers to a place, whereas «dar» pertains to connections with specific individuals. The uniqueness of «manzil» lies in its capacity for human and social organization. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلِلَّذِينَ هَاجَوْا إِلَى الْبَيْتِ الْحَرَامِ مِنْ أَهْلِ الْقُرَىٰ كَمَنْ هَاجَ فِي الْبَيْتِ الْحَرَامِ مِنْ أَهْلِ الْقُرَىٰ» (البقرة / ۱۹۶)\nTranslation: «And those who emigrated to the Sacred House from the people of the towns are like those who emigrated to the Sacred House from the people of the towns.»"
    }
  ],
  "781": [
    {
      "id": 3478,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "People - People",
      "hw": "اہل",
      "s": "«Ahl» means specifically those people who are related to a place, religion, or field and act accordingly.",
      "d": "«Ahl» has the Arabic root «ahl» (أَهْل) which originally means \"such people\" or \"pair\", relating to a specific thing or place. Its difference from other terms is that «ahl» generally refers to people who are associated with a specific place or field, whereas terms like «ulu al-amr» (those in authority) or «al-mu'minun» (the believers) denote specific positions or the quality of faith. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَا تَكُونُوا كَالَّذِينَ تَفَرَّقُوا وَكَانُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ أَحَادِيثَ الْأَهْلِ فِي الْمُلْكِ لَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ مَّعْرِفَةٌ» (الأنعام/ ۱۵۴)\nTranslation: «Do not be like those who split up and had, after them, tales of the people in the kingdom, having no knowledge.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3479,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ahl - Family/Clan",
      "hw": "اہل",
      "s": "«Family/Clan» (Ahl) means a specific tribe or family, indicating a group of individuals who share a common relationship with their companions.",
      "d": "The Arabic origin of «Family/Clan» is 'khadaan', which originally denotes each tribe or family, signifying a group that shares a common bond with its members. This implies that 'Ahl al-khanaan' refers to a specific tribe or family that maintains a shared relationship with its members. This concept is used specifically in the context of a tribe or family, unlike other synonyms which may indicate general relationships or social groups. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَالَّذِینَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ» (Al-Baqarah / 127)\nTranslation: «And those who came after them say: 'Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith.'»"
    }
  ],
  "782": [
    {
      "id": 3480,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Child - Child",
      "hw": "بچہ",
      "s": "«Child» (Bachah) originally signifies the characteristics of a child, namely weakness, tenderness, and sensitivity.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of «Child» is 'bachah', which originally denotes weakness, tenderness, sensitivity, and a series of pleasantness like a flower. These words relate to the meaning of child, but «Bachah» specifically expresses weakness and tenderness. This term is particularly used for individuals who are weak, highly sensitive, or not prepared for very significant tasks. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ» (Al-Baqarah / 127)\nTranslation: «And those who came after them say: 'Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who believed before us.'»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3481,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Child - Infant/Minor",
      "hw": "بچہ",
      "s": "«Infant/Minor» (Tifl) refers to a child who has not yet reached puberty.",
      "d": "The meaning of «Tifl» is to be soft and tender, and «Tiflah» refers to a woman with a delicate body. Thus, as long as a child remains soft and tender, they are considered a «Tifl» (masc.). However, this term specifically refers to children who have not yet become adults. Its plural is 'atfal'. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا بَلَغَ الۡاَطۡفَالُ مِنۡکُمُ الۡحُلُمَ فَلۡیَسۡتَاۡذِنُوۡا کَمَا اسۡتَاۡذَنَ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ» (24 / 59)\nTranslation: «And when your children reach puberty, let them seek permission as those before them used to seek permission.»\nThis verse clarifies that after puberty, a child exits the stage of infancy and enters the stage of adulthood."
    },
    {
      "id": 3482,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Child - Boy/Son",
      "hw": "بچہ",
      "s": "«Boy/Son» (Ladka) denotes the original meaning and fundamental form of a child, understood according to the lineage of birth.",
      "d": "«Ladka» means the sign of the original lineage of birth, which in the Quran fundamentally represents a child. Its residual meanings are those that originate as human. Additionally, its synonyms include «Bachah» (child), «Walad» (offspring), and «Dhakar» (male), but «Ladka» specifically carries the meaning aligned with the original lineage of birth. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَتْ إِمْرَأَةُ عَامِرٍ لِّمَاكَ الْعَمِيَةُ لَوْلَا تَعَرَّفَتْ وَلَوْلَا تَرَكَتْ مَعَهُ فِي الْمَسْجِدِ فَأَخَذَتْ مِنْهُ حَمَلَةً فَكَانَتْ مِنَ الْمُحْسِنِينَ» (Surah Al-Ankabut, Ayah 24)\nTranslation: «When the wife of 'Imran said: 'My Lord, I have vowed to You what is in my womb, so accept this from me. Indeed, You are the Hearing, the Knowing.'» (Note: The provided Urdu description and verse reference seem mismatched; the translation above is a general example from the verse context.)"
    }
  ],
  "783": [
    {
      "id": 3483,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Woman - Woman",
      "hw": "عورت",
      "s": "«Woman» (Aurat) is a specific term denoting femininity, which manifests human ethics in accordance with mercy, tradition, and religious principles.",
      "d": "The Arabic root word for «Woman» is 'A-W-R', which fundamentally denotes characteristics related to femininity. This word refers to the human body, which signifies the state of childbirth and upbringing. In contrast, «Ummah» or «Zunūjah» generally denote human gender, while «Aurat» specifically manifests human ethics, mercy, and religious principles. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّذَٰلِكَ عَلَيْهِمْ حَرَجٌ أَن يُؤْمِنُوا بِاللَّهِ وَرَسُولِهِ وَيَتُوبُوا إِلَيْهِ فَإِنَّ اللَّهَ غَفُورٌ رَّحِيمٌ» (8 / 14)\nTranslation: «And there is no blame upon them for that in which they have been tried, [but] if they believe in Allah and His Messenger and do righteous deeds, then indeed, Allah is Forgiving and Merciful.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3484,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Woman - Lady/Matron",
      "hw": "عورت",
      "s": "«Lady/Matron» (Khatoon) is used to denote an excellent and more specific attribute of a woman, which also emerges from wisdom, courtesy, and ethics.",
      "d": "The original linguistic root of «Lady/Matron» is 'Khatoon', which specifically defines a woman in terms of her nobility, implying 'as a lady should be'—wise, courteous, ethical, and distinguished in her view. This word is related to a woman's life, ethics, wisdom, and courtesy. Compared to other synonyms, it is used specifically to denote an excellent and more specific attribute. For instance, «Aurat» generally defines a woman, but «Khatoon» speaks of her under a more refined and elevated description. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَاللَّذِي جَاءَ بِالْحَقِّ مِنْ عَدُوِّهِ فَهُوَ الْمُحْسِنُ وَالْمُحْسِنَةُ مِنْهُمَا» (An-Nisa: 12)\nTranslation: «And whoever does good, whether male or female, and is a believer—We will surely cause him to live a good life, and We will surely reward them according to the best of what they used to do.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3485,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Woman - Feminine",
      "hw": "عورت",
      "s": "«Feminine» (Niswan) denotes the original meaning of a woman's sexual characteristics, which fundamentally expresses the attribute of being most compassionate and loving in humans.",
      "d": "«Niswan» means the attribute that displays human sexual characteristics, which fundamentally expresses the attribute of being greater, more loving, and compassionate in humans. Its original terminology is used to define human nature and sexual characteristics, whereas other words like 'zawj' (spouse) or 'mar'ah' (woman) specifically denote the attribute of human compassion and love. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَإِذْ أَرْسَلْنَا هُوَ وَإِخْوَتَهُ إِلَىٰ فِرْعَوْنَ وَمَلَئِهِۦ فَقَالُوا أَنَّا رَسُولُ رَبِّ الْعَالَمِينَ» (Ta-Ha / 43)\nTranslation: «And when We sent him and his brother with Our signs to Pharaoh and his establishment, they said, 'Indeed, we are messengers of the Lord of the worlds.'»"
    }
  ],
  "784": [
    {
      "id": 3487,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Man - Human/Person",
      "hw": "مرد",
      "s": "«Human/Person» (Admi) means the original essence of men who are servants of God, and their characteristic is manifested when they live their lives according to God's command.",
      "d": "«Human/Person» (Admi) means the original essence of men who are servants of God, and their characteristic is manifested when they live their lives according to God's command. Its root is originally from 'Adam', who was created by God's name, and in contrast, «Mard» (man) generally includes human ethical and religious attributes in addition to physical masculinity. «Admi» means the original essence of human qualities created by God. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَقَدْ خَلَقْنَا الْإِنسَانَ مِن نُّطْفَةٍ أَمْشَاجٍ نَّبْتَلِيَهِ فَجَعَلْنَاهُ سَمِيعًا بَصِيرًا»\n(Surah Al-Hujurat / 27)\nTranslation: «And We have certainly created man from a sperm-drop mixture that We may try him; and We made him hearing and seeing.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3488,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Man - Man",
      "hw": "مرد",
      "s": "«رَجُلٌ» is used when the expression of bravery and masculine strength is intended.",
      "d": "«رَجُلٌ» (meaning man) is used when the expression of strength, bravery, and masculinity is intended. «رَجُوْلِیَّۃ» is the verbal noun meaning masculine strength. The plural of masculine strength (mujarrad) is «رِجَالٌ». Its feminine is «نِسَاء» and «نِسْوَۆ».\nFor example, in the Quran: «اَلرِّجَالُ قَوّٰمُوۡنَ عَلَی النِّسَآءِ بِمَا فَضَّلَ اللّٰہُ بَعۡضَہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ» (4/34)\nTranslation: Men are the protectors of women, because Allah has given one of them preference over the other."
    }
  ],
  "785": [
    {
      "id": 3489,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Poor - Poor/Needy",
      "hw": "غریب",
      "s": "«Poor/Needy» (Ghareeb) means one who is innocent, carefree, and defenseless, unable to emerge from circumstances beyond their control.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of «Poor/Needy» is Gh-R-B, which originally means 'carefree' or 'defenseless'. Its literal meaning is one who cannot emerge from any problem greater than themselves, defenseless, unaware, and helpless. In contrast, «Miskīn» and «Faqeer» have similar meanings, but «Ghareeb» expresses a particular kind of helplessness and failure. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَالْغَرِيبِ فَیْهِ لَمْ یَکُنْ لَهُ نَقِیّ» (Surah At-Talaq, Ayah 4)\nTranslation: «And for the stranger [in need] there is no blame upon you if you do not provide for him, but if you are able, then provide for him.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3490,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Poor - Needy/Destitute",
      "hw": "غریب",
      "s": "«Needy/Destitute» (Muhtaj) provides another significant meaning in the context of 'poor', expressing the need for assistance.",
      "d": "«Muhtaj» means a person who wants something and has a need for it, related to seeking help or facilitation. Its root emphasizes a person's importance. It denotes someone who has a need to obtain something. This differs from «Ghareeb», which not only means poverty but also implies a need for help. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَالَّذِينَ إِن مَّآ أَنفَقُوآ لَمْ یَکُونُوا مُهَادِینَ وَلَمْ یَکُونُوا مُحْتَاجِینَ إِلَى الْعَمَلِ فَإِنَّ اللَّهَ لَا یُضِلُّ مَنْ ہُوَ مُهَادٍ وَلَا مُحْتَاجٍ إِلَى الْعَمَلِ» (Al-Baqarah / 179)\nTranslation: «And those who spend [in the cause of Allah] are not [to be] extravagant or stingy, but they are [always] between that [excess and deficiency], and those who, when they spend, are neither wasteful nor stingy, but are ever mindful of their Lord's pleasure.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3491,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Poor - Destitute",
      "hw": "غریب",
      "s": "‘مفلس’ means poor and destitute, deprived of wealth and justice, and suffering from lack of resources.",
      "d": "The Arabic origin of ‘مفلس’ is mafils, which is the name for one deprived of wealth and justice and poor. These words are different from each other: ‘فقیر’ generally refers to a poor person, while ‘مفلس’ specifically refers to one who is deprived of wealth and justice and suffers from lack. ‘غریب’ also has a similar meaning but ‘مفلس’ has more emphasis on financial lack and deprivation. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مَّالٌ وَلَا بَنُونَ» (البقرة ۲۸۳) Translation: ‘And they had no wealth and no children.’"
    }
  ],
  "786": [
    {
      "id": 3492,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Leader - Leader",
      "hw": "امیر",
      "s": "‘Amir’ means the head of a nation or people who governs others.",
      "d": "The Arabic origin of ‘Amir’ is amir (أَمِير), which originally means ‘a person who promotes something’ or ‘to be great’. Its literal meaning is ‘to promote something’ or ‘to be the head of something’. In contrast, ‘خادم’ (khadim) is the head of official or administrative services, and ‘ملک’ (malik) is the owner of the kingdom. In this regard, ‘Amir’ essentially refers to the head of a nation or people who governs others. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلْمُؤْمِنِينَ أَن يَّتَّخِذُوا ءَابَاءهُمْ وَأَخْوَاهُمْ أَوْلِيَاءَ فِي الْمَلَكِ» (التوبة / 107) Translation: ‘Believers should not take their fathers and brothers as guardians in the kingdom.’"
    },
    {
      "id": 3493,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Leader - Wealthy",
      "hw": "امیر",
      "s": "‘دولت مند’ (wealthy) is used as a helper and supporter of the leader who serves friends.",
      "d": "The etymological root of ‘دولت مند’ is ‘دولت’ which means wealth, power, and management. Its synonym is ‘مُلْک’ or ‘حکمران’, but ‘دولت مند’ specifically denotes one who provides friendship and service to his friends. It means he serves his friends and manages with regard to friendship. For example, in the Quran: «وَإِذْ قَالَ لَهُمْ عَبْدُ اللَّهِ بْنُ أَبِي وَهْبٍ لِّقَوْمِهِمْ أَنْ تَعَظُّوا فَأَخَذَتْهُمُ الْعَذَابُ مِنْ غَدٍ إِلَى الْمَسَاءِ وَهُوَ دُولَتٌ مَّنْدٌ فِي أَهْلِهِمْ» (سورة النمل، آیت 46) Translation: ‘When Abdullah bin Abi Wahab invited his people to admonition, the punishment seized them from the next night until the day, and he was one who managed friendship among his people.’"
    },
    {
      "id": 3494,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Leader - Affluent",
      "hw": "امیر",
      "s": "‘ثروتمند’ (affluent) denotes the attribute of the leader that, beyond wealth and possessions, he also manages religious and social responsibilities.",
      "d": "In Urdu, ‘ثروتمند’ means: rich, great owner, capitalist, a person who has reached a high position religiously and economically. Its Arabic root is th-r-w-t mand, which literally means ‘distinguished by wealth’, one who possesses abundant wealth. In contrast, ‘ملک’ (malik) is related to ownership, ‘خادم’ (khadim) refers to a person who works for someone, and ‘خالق’ (khaliq) denotes the state of the Creator. For example, in the Quran: «وَإِذْ أَخَذَ اللَّهُ مِيثَاقَ الَّذِينَ أَتَوْا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ لَكَيْنَ مَلَكَتْ أَنفُسَهُمْ فَأَنْتُمْ لَمْ تَكُونُوا بِمَوْلَاكُمْ شَرِكِينَ» (3/186) Translation: ‘And when Allah took the covenant from those who came after them, “You will surely become masters of yourselves,” but you were not partners with your Lord.’"
    }
  ],
  "787": [
    {
      "id": 3495,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Laborer - Laborer",
      "hw": "مزدور",
      "s": "‘Mazdoor’ means worker, a specific term used for official employees in the sense of one who works.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of ‘Mazdoor’ is mazdoor, meaning those who work. These terms are used for workers and official employees. In contrast, other terms like ‘کارکن’ (karkun) or ‘عمیل’ (amal) have similar meanings, but ‘مزدور’ specifically refers to one who works officially or organizationally. ‘Mazdoor’ is used for official employees or household workers.\n\nEvidence:\n«وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ» (البقرة 2/286) Translation: ‘And those who came after them say, “Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith.”’"
    },
    {
      "id": 3496,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Laborer - Worker",
      "hw": "مزدور",
      "s": "‘Karkun’ (worker) refers to a person who works as an assistant to a laborer, taking wages for his work.",
      "d": "‘Karkun’ means worker, laborer; any person who does work is called a karkun. These terms essentially refer to the concept of working, whereas ‘مزدور’ is a specific type of karkun who comes to others to work. Its synonym is ‘کار’ (kaar) which means worker. For example, in the Quran: «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ كَأَحَدٍ فِي الْعَرَضِ مِنْ أَصْحَابِ الْجَنَّةِ وَلَا مِنْ أَصْحَابِ النَّارِ» (الانعام/۱۲۸) Translation: ‘And they had no association with any of the people of the Garden or the people of the Fire.’"
    }
  ],
  "788": [
    {
      "id": 3497,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Trader - Trader",
      "hw": "تاجر",
      "s": "‘Tajir’ means one who buys and sells anything, especially a person who works through financial and commercial transactions.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of ‘Tajir’ is tajar (تجر), which originally means the act of buying and selling something. Its literal meaning is ‘to sell something to another’. These terms are associated with various terms such as ‘متجر’ (tijar - trade), ‘تجار’ (tujjar - merchants), and ‘تجارة’ (tijarah - trade). Its essential meaning is to buy something and sell it to another. ‘Tajir’ means one who buys and sells anything, especially a person who works through financial and commercial transactions. For example, in the Quran: «وَالَّذِينَ يَتَّخِذُونَ مَوْلَىٰهُم مِّن دُونِ اللَّهِ أَرْبَابَ الْأَمْوَالِ وَالْأَبْنَاءِ وَالْأَمْوَالِ وَالْأَبْنَاءِ» (الأنعام / ١٠٨) Translation: ‘Those who take their lords besides Allah, [taking] the owners of wealth and children and the owners of wealth and children.’"
    },
    {
      "id": 3498,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Trader - Usurer",
      "hw": "تاجر",
      "s": "‘Soudagar’ refers to a person who trades for the purpose of gaining profit (benefit or gain), while ‘Tajir’ refers to a general trader or merchant.",
      "d": "The linguistic root of ‘Soudagar’ comes from the Arabic triad s-w-d, which means to trade, to take benefit, or to earn profit. This word is derived from ‘سود’ (sod - profit/interest). In contrast, the root of ‘Tajir’ is t-j-r, which means to travel and trade. The difference between the two terms is that ‘سوداگر’ is more specific and refers to profit-oriented trade, while ‘تاجر’ is a more general term. In the Quran, the word ‘سوداگر’ does not appear as an adjective or independent noun, but the word ‘تاجر’ does appear."
    }
  ],
  "789": [
    {
      "id": 3499,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Time - Time",
      "hw": "وقت",
      "s": "«waqt, miqat» means a fixed time or place.",
      "d": "The word «waqt» is well-known (TIME). «al-waqt» means «a known time» (M.L). «waqt» its plural is «awqat». And according to Imam Raghib's words, for any work, the appointed time's final limit (maf). For example, in the Quran:\n«قُلۡ اِنَّمَا عِلۡمُہَا عِنۡدَ رَبِّیۡ ۚ لَا یُجَلِّیۡہَا لِوَقۡتِہَاۤ اِلَّا ہُوَ» (7/187)\nTranslation: 'Say, \"Its knowledge is only with my Lord; none will reveal it at its time except Him.\"'\nAnd «miqat» is a noun of place derived from «waqt». It is used in both temporal and spatial senses. Its plural is «mawaqit». In the following verse, miqat is used as a temporal noun.\nFor example, a guidance from Allah:\n«وَ وٰعَدۡنَا  مُوۡسٰی ثَلٰثِیۡنَ  لَیۡلَۃً وَّ اَتۡمَمۡنٰہَا بِعَشۡرٍ فَتَمَّ  مِیۡقَاتُ رَبِّہٗ اَرۡبَعِیۡنَ  لَیۡلَۃً» (7/142)\nTranslation: 'And We promised Moses thirty nights, then completed them with ten more, so the appointment of his Lord was completed as forty nights.'\nAnd in the following verse, the word miqat is used both temporally and spatially, meaning the time is fixed and also the place.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ لَمَّا جَآءَ مُوۡسٰی لِمِیۡقَاتِنَا وَ کَلَّمَہٗ رَبُّہٗ» (7/143)\nTranslation: 'Then when Moses came at our appointed time and his Lord spoke with him.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3500,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Time - Era",
      "hw": "وقت",
      "s": "«Era» is used for a specific period or age, expressing a particular duration or period in the context of time.",
      "d": "The linguistic root of «zamanah» is «z-m-n-h» which indicates a specific era or age in the sequence of time. This word differs from «zaman» (general time) and «waqt» (a particular moment) in that «zamanah» usually refers to a long era or age, whereas «waqt» refers to a specific point in time, and «zaman» is used for the concept of time. An example from the Quran:\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَقَالُوا لَوْ كُنَّا سَمِعْنَا أَوْ عَقَلْنَا مَا كُنَّا فِي أَصْحَابِ السَّعِيرِ» (Surah Al-Mulk / 67:10)\nTranslation: 'And they say, \"If we had only listened or used reason, we would not have been among the companions of the Blaze.\"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3501,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Time - Era",
      "hw": "وقت",
      "s": "‘Daur’ refers to a specific temporal period or era.",
      "d": "The word ‘Daur’ originates from the Arabic root د-و-ر, which signifies circulation, cycle, and the passage of time. It is related to ‘وقت’ (time) in that ‘دور’ means a specific temporal period or duration. Its synonyms include ‘زمانہ’ (zamanah - time), ‘عہد’ (ahd - era), and ‘مدت’ (muddat - duration), but the particularity of ‘دور’ is that it describes the cyclical aspect of time, i.e., a complete cycle or period of time. For example:\n\nIn the Quran: «وَقَالَ الَّذِينَ أُوتُوا الْعِلْمَ وَالْإِيمَانَ لَقَدْ لَبِثْتُمْ فِي كِتَابِ اللَّهِ إِلَى يَوْمِ الْبَعْثِ فَهَذَا يَوْمُ الْبَعْثِ وَلَكِنَّكُمْ كُنْتُمْ لَا تَعْلَمُونَ» (الروم / 56) Translation: ‘And those who were given knowledge and faith said, “You remained in the Book of Allah until the Day of Resurrection. This is the Day of Resurrection, but you used not to know.”’"
    }
  ],
  "790": [
    {
      "id": 3502,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Day - Day",
      "hw": "دن",
      "s": "‘Din’ refers to the bright time spent during the presence of the sun, which is expressed in Arabic as ‘یوم’ (yawm).",
      "d": "Etymologically, ‘Din’ is based on the Arabic root ی و م (yawm), which means ‘day’, i.e., a collection of many days, time, and specific moments of time. In Urdu, ‘Din’ entered via Persian and is the Urdu phonetic equivalent of ‘یوم’. In the Quran, it generally means the day of the day or the daily day, while in Arabic, the word ‘یوم’ is more commonly used. Its synonyms include ‘روز’ (roz) and ‘نہار’ (nihar), but ‘Din’ specifically denotes the time of spring and light. Its usage in the Quran is very extensive. For example: «وَاللَّيْلِ إِذَا يَغْشَىٰ وَالنَّهَارِ إِذَا تَجَلَّىٰ» (الليل / ۱-۲) Translation: ‘By the night when it covers and by the day when it appears.’"
    },
    {
      "id": 3503,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Day - Yawm",
      "hw": "دن",
      "s": "Yawm: The combination of day and night, i.e., 24 hours.",
      "d": "Yawm means day. The time from sunset to the next day's sunset. The combination of night and day, 24 hours. The plural of Yawm is Ayyam. Time and periods are calculated by Ayyam.\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَمَنۡ لَّمۡ یَجِدۡ فَصِیَامُ ثَلٰثَۃِ اَیَّامٍ فِی الۡحَجِّ وَ سَبۡعَۃٍ اِذَا رَجَعۡتُمۡ» (2/196)\nTranslation: And whoever cannot find (a sacrifice) should fast for three days during the Hajj and seven when you return.\nAnd this duration of Yawm is for humans. Its concept can only be formed after the creation of the sun and earth; otherwise, with Allah, Yawm's duration is a long period, whether it extends to hundreds of thousands of years according to our calculation.\nFor example, Allah says: «قُلۡ اَئِنَّکُمۡ لَتَکۡفُرُوۡنَ بِالَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ الۡاَرۡضَ فِیۡ یَوۡمَیۡنِ» (41/9)\nTranslation: Do you then disbelieve in Him Who created the earth in two days?\nSimilarly, when Yawm is mentioned in the context of the creation of the earth and heavens, it refers to a long period.\nFor example, Allah says: «وَ اِنَّ یَوۡمًا عِنۡدَ رَبِّکَ کَاَلۡفِ سَنَۃٍ مِّمَّا تَعُدُّوۡنَ» (22/47)\nTranslation: And indeed, a day with your Lord is like a thousand years of what you count.\nAt another place, Allah says: «تَعۡرُجُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ وَ الرُّوۡحُ اِلَیۡہِ فِیۡ یَوۡمٍ کَانَ مِقۡدَارُہٗ خَمۡسِیۡنَ اَلۡفَ سَنَۃٍ» (70/4)\nTranslation: To Him ascend the angels and the Spirit in a day the measure whereof is fifty thousand years.\nSimilarly, Yawm al-Din (the Day of Judgment) will also be a long period, whose duration is mentioned in Hadith as fifty thousand years."
    }
  ],
  "791": [
    {
      "id": 3504,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night - Raat",
      "hw": "رات",
      "s": "Raat refers to the time from sunset until Fajr, and it is more commonly used in everyday language than Layl.",
      "d": "Raat: Linguistic analysis – This is a basic Arabic noun meaning night. Its root is ر-و-ت (r-w-t), meaning to settle or remain. Night's opposition to day and its continuity are its basic characteristics. Its synonyms include Layl and Zalim. Layl is more classical and literary, frequently appearing in the Quran and Hadith, while Raat is more common in everyday speech and carries a sense of rest and tranquility. Zalim is used specifically for a dark night.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَقُرْآنًا فَجْرًا إِنَّ قُرْآنَ الْفَجْرِ كَانَ مَشْهُودًا» (Al-Fajr / 89:1-2)\nTranslation: And (recite) the Quran at dawn. Indeed, the recitation of the Quran at dawn is ever witnessed.\n\n(Another clear example):\n«وَجَعَلْنَا اللَّيْلَ وَالنَّهَارَ آيَتَیْنِ فَمَحَوْنَا آيَةَ اللَّيْلِ وَجَعَلْنَا آيَةَ النَّهَارِ مُبْصِرَةً» (Al-Isra / 17:12)\nTranslation: And We have made the night and the day two signs, and We have obscured the sign of the night and made the sign of the day visible."
    },
    {
      "id": 3505,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night - Shab",
      "hw": "رات",
      "s": "Shab refers to the time after sunset when darkness envelops.",
      "d": "Shab (ش-ب) is a basic Arabic noun meaning night or darkness. It means the entire period of night or the time of darkness. The plural of Shab is Layal or Shayub. Other words like Layl also mean night, but Shab more specifically denotes the time when darkness is at its peak and it is the time for sleep. This word appears in the Quran in many places.\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَاللَّيْلِ إِذَا يَغْشَاهُ» (Al-Fajr / 89:4)\nTranslation: And by the night when it envelops."
    }
  ],
  "792": [
    {
      "id": 3506,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Morning - Subh",
      "hw": "صبح",
      "s": "Subh refers to the time after Fajr when daylight fully appears.",
      "d": "Subh originates from the Arabic trilateral root ص-ب-ح (s-b-h). It means the time of morning (Subh) and refers to the period after Fajr when the light of the sun begins to spread in the sky. It carries the idea of the manifestation and radiance of light. Its form صَبَحَ means 'morning has come'.\n\nThe difference between Subh and its synonyms: Fajr refers to the time of Fajr prayer or the beginning of morning, while Subh refers to the broader period of morning. Namā' also means morning but is more used in Arabic poetry. The word Subh appears in the Quran in several places.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَالصُّبْحِ إِذَا أَشْرَقَ» (Ash-Shams / 1)\nTranslation: And by the morning when it shines."
    },
    {
      "id": 3507,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Morning - Sahar",
      "hw": "صبح",
      "s": "Sahar refers to the time just before Fajr, the transition from darkness to light, which is the origin of the word Subh.",
      "d": "Sahar's basic meaning is magic or sorcery, but in the context of morning, it refers to the time immediately after Fajr, i.e., the early morning. It is derived from the root س-ح-ر (s-h-r), which has multiple meanings including سحر (magic) and سحر (morning time). The distinction from other terms: Fajr refers to the time of Fajr prayer or the start of morning, Subh refers to the entire morning period in a broad sense, and Sahar specifically denotes the delicate moment of transition from darkness to light.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَاللَّيْلِ وَمَا وَسَقَ وَالشَّمْسِ وَمَا غَسَقَ وَالْقَمَرِ إِذَا تَلَاهَا وَالنَّهَارِ إِذَا جَلَّاهَا وَالظِّلِّ وَمَا زَحَاهُ» (Ash-Shams / 91)\n\nTranslation: By the night when it covers, and by the day when it appears, and by that which He created, male and female."
    }
  ],
  "793": [
    {
      "id": 3508,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Evening - Sham",
      "hw": "شام",
      "s": "Sham refers to the time of sunset or the entire evening period.",
      "d": "Sham's linguistic root is from the Arabic مصدر شَمَى (shamā), which points to the time of evening. This word generally means the time after sunset. In contrast, لیل (Layl) means night and نہار (Nahar) means day, while Sham specifically denotes the evening time. Geographically, Sham also refers to the region of Syria/Levant, but in the Quranic context, it is generally used for time.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَالَّلَيْلِ إِذَا يَغْشَاهُ وَالنَّهَارِ إِذَا جَلَّاهُ» (Ash-Shu'ara / 90)\nTranslation: By the night when it envelops and by the day when it appears."
    },
    {
      "id": 3509,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Evening - Maghrib",
      "hw": "شام",
      "s": "Maghrib refers to the west or the direction of sunset, and Sham is related because the Arabian Peninsula is located west of it.",
      "d": "Maghrib's Arabic root is غ-ر-ب (gh-r-b), meaning to set or go west. In the Quran, Maghrib refers to the place of sunset or the western direction. Meanwhile, Sham (Syria/Levant) is a geographical name located northwest of the Arabian Peninsula. In Arabic, Sham is named because it is west (Maghrib) relative to the Arabian land. The difference is that Maghrib is an adjective and direction, while Sham is a specific region's name.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَالَّذِينَ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِمَا أُنْزِلَ إِلَيْكَ وَمَا أُنْزِلَ مِنْ قَبْلِكَ وَبِالْآخِرَةِ هُمْ يُوقِنُونَ»\n(Al-Baqara / 4)\nTranslation: And who believe in what has been revealed to you, [O Muhammad], and what was revealed before you, and of the Hereafter they are certain."
    }
  ],
  "794": [
    {
      "id": 3510,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Today - Aaj",
      "hw": "آج",
      "s": "Aaj in Urdu refers to the present day.",
      "d": "Aaj is actually an Urdu/Hindi word derived from the Sanskrit 'adya' (अद्य), meaning 'this day' or 'present time'. It entered Urdu via Persian. In Arabic, there is no word 'Aaj'; the Arabic equivalent is al-yawm (الْيَوْمُ), which means today. In Urdu, 'Aaj' is very common in temporal contexts and refers to the current or same day. Its synonyms include 'Aaj ke din' and 'is waqt'."
    },
    {
      "id": 3511,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Today - Amrooz",
      "hw": "آج",
      "s": "Amrooz is an Arabic word meaning today, and in Persian-Urdu it appears as 'Aaj'.",
      "d": "Amrooz's linguistic root is from Arabic 'amru' meaning 'day' (yawm). In Urdu, 'Aaj' is derived from Arabic via Persian. Its meaning is 'this day' or 'the present day'. The Quran does not use 'Amrooz' as 'today'; instead, it frequently uses words like Yawm (day)."
    }
  ],
  "795": [
    {
      "id": 3513,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Tomorrow - Farda",
      "hw": "کل",
      "s": "Farda means tomorrow or the time after today, expressing the reality of being separate and distinct from today.",
      "d": "Farda's linguistic root is the Arabic triad ف ر د (f-r-d). The basic meanings of this root are 'to be separate', 'to be alone', or 'to be distinct'. The word 'fard' means 'one' or 'alone', and 'farda' is derived from it, expressing tomorrow as separate and distinct from today.\n\nIts synonyms include 'ghadan' (غداً), which is more common in the Quran. The difference is that 'farda' is more formal and classical Arabic, while 'ghadan' is more general in the Quran and Hadith.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«سَأُرْهِقُهُمْ صَعُودًا» (Maryam / 75)\nTranslation: \"I will make them (tomorrow) climb a difficult ascent.\"\n\n(Here 'sa'urhiqhum' means I will burden them, and 'sa'udan' refers to a steep ascent or difficult path, describing the hardship of the Day of Judgment.)"
    }
  ],
  "796": [
    {
      "id": 3514,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Always - Always",
      "hw": "ہمیشہ",
      "s": "The word 'Hamesha' is actually derived from Persian, which means 'always', but in Arabic, its meaning is eternity and perpetuity.",
      "d": "When analyzing 'Hamesha' scientifically, it is necessary to clarify that this word is originally from Persian, and its origin is from Persian 'hamesha'. In Persian, 'ham' means 'always' and 'shah' means 'like', i.e., 'like always'. In Arabic, the meanings are expressed with 'أَبَدًا' (abadan) and 'دَائِماً' (da'iman).\n\nIn Urdu, 'Hamesha' means 'at all times', 'for always', 'eternally'. Its synonyms include 'hamesha', 'hamesha se', 'hamesha ke liye'.\n\nSince 'Hamesha' is not an Arabic word, therefore, there is no Arabic text of it in the Quran. However, in the Quran, the word 'أَبَدًا' is used for eternity and perpetuity.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «خَالِدِينَ فِيهَا أَبَدًا» (الکهف / ۱۰۸) Translation: They will remain in it forever (eternally)."
    },
    {
      "id": 3515,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Always - دائماً",
      "hw": "ہمیشہ",
      "s": "'Da'iman' is an Arabic word that means constantly, without interruption, and for always, which is used in Urdu as a synonym for 'Hamesha'.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of 'Da'iman' is d-w-m (dal, waw, mim) which means to remain constant, to continue, and to be continuous. This word is derived from 'da'im' which is an adjective meaning constant, always remaining. In Urdu, 'Hamesha' is its complete translation. Other words like 'abadan' (never or for always) and 'sarmadan' (always) differ from this because 'da'iman' is more eloquent and used in Quranic language.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «إِنَّ الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَعَمِلُوا الصَّالِحَاتِ كَانَتْ لَهُمْ جَنَّاتُ الْفِرْدَوْسِ نُزُلًا (۱۰۷) خَالِدِينَ فِيهَا أَبَدًا لَا يَبْغُونَ عَنْهَا حِوَلًا (۱۰۸)» (الكهف / ۱۸) Translation: Indeed, those who believed and did righteous deeds, for them will be the gardens of Paradise as a place of return. They will abide in them forever, they will not desire any change from them."
    }
  ],
  "797": [
    {
      "id": 3516,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Immediately - Immediately",
      "hw": "فوراً",
      "s": "«فوراً» is a recent Arabic noun that is used in the meaning of immediate and without delay.",
      "d": "The linguistic basis of «فوراً» is on the Arabic root «ف-و-ر». This root indicates immediacy, speed, and beginning. Its source is «فَوْرٌ» which expresses immediacy or that very moment.\n\nAmong its synonyms, «الآن», «حالا», «عاجلاً», and «سريعاً» are included, however, in «فوراً» the meaning of particularly more immediate and without delay is found, which is not present in other words in this way.\n\nIn the Quran, its literal usage is not present at all, however, words that express the concept of immediacy such as «سَرِيعٌ» and «حَذِيرٌ» etc. are present."
    },
    {
      "id": 3517,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Immediately - In an immediate manner",
      "hw": "فوراً",
      "s": "«فوری طور پر» means to do something without delay and quickly.",
      "d": "The word «فوری طور پر» is derived from the Arabic root «ف-و-ر» which means speed and haste. It is derived from «فور» (speed). Its meanings are «عجلتاً» i.e., hastily, «بے درنگ» (without delay), and «ہنگامی طور پر» (in an emergency manner).\n\nIts difference from other words is that in «فوراً» both immediacy and speed are specially considered, while other words such as «سريعاً» only indicate speed.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَاسْتَعِينُوا بِالصَّبْرِ وَالصَّلَاةِ ۚ وَإِنَّهَا لَكَبِيرَةٌ إِلَّا عَلَى الْخَاشِعِينَ» (Al-Baqarah / 45)\nTranslation: And seek help through patience and prayer; indeed, it is difficult except for the humble.\n\n(Note: In this verse, instead of «فوراً», the expression of immediacy and humility is conveyed through «إِلَّا عَلَى الْخَاشِعِينَ».)"
    }
  ],
  "798": [
    {
      "id": 3518,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Near - Near",
      "hw": "قریب",
      "s": "«قریب» means to be near to something or time, whether in terms of distance or time.",
      "d": "The linguistic root of «قریب» is «ق ر ب» which means nearness and coming close. This word is frequently used in Arabic for proximity, i.e., nearness. Its meaning also includes an element of «محبت» (love) and «مہربانی» (kindness), because being near actually also expresses closeness of the heart (qinshu).\n\nAnd among the synonyms of «قریب», «ادنى» (adna) and «مقارب» (muqarib) are also included, but the characteristic of «قریب» is that it particularly expresses nearness and closeness, while «ادنى» has more inclination towards inferiority.\n\nIn the Quran, a clear example of «قریب» is found in the statement of Allah:\n\n«إِنَّ رَبَّكَ لَقَرِيبٌ مُجِيبٌ» (Surah Al-Fussilat / 41:51)\n\nTranslation: Indeed, your Lord is near and responsive.\n\nIn this verse, Allah is giving glad tidings to His servants that He is near to them and hears and accepts their prayers. Here the word «قریب» not only expresses temporal or spatial proximity but also points to the spiritual relationship between Allah and the servant."
    },
    {
      "id": 3519,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Near - Nazdīk",
      "hw": "قریب",
      "s": "The word «قریب» is derived from the Arabic root «ق-ر-ب» and its basic meaning is 'near or close,' which indicates the reduction of distance.",
      "d": "«نزدیک» is an Arabic word derived from the root «ق-ر-ب» (qurb). The basic meaning of this root is 'to be near' or 'to be close to something.' Linguistically, this word expresses the reduction of distance, but in the Quran, its metaphorical usage is also frequently found. Its meaning has three basic aspects: first, being near in terms of place; second, being near in terms of time; and third, being near in terms of relationship or connection.\n\nFurthermore, among the synonyms of «قریب», «ادنى» and «سویدا» etc. are included, but the characteristic of «قریب» is that it not only expresses mere distance but also indicates the servant's connection with Allah, as mentioned in the Hadith Qudsi that the servant becomes near to Me when he calls upon Me.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«إِنَّ رَبَّكَ لَقَرِيبٌ مُّجِيبٌ» (Fussilat / 41:51)\nTranslation: Indeed, your Lord is near (close) and He is the One who responds to prayers."
    }
  ],
  "799": [
    {
      "id": 3520,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Era - Era",
      "hw": "دور",
      "s": "«دور» refers to the duration of a specific time or era.",
      "d": "The origin of «دور» is from the Arabic root «د-و-ر» whose basic meaning is rotation, cycle, and succession of time. This word comes in the meaning of «دور» (time, era), and its closest words include «عہد» (covenant, era) and «زمانہ» (time). However, the characteristic of «دور» is that it expresses the continuity of time, i.e., the rotation from one era to another, while «عہد» indicates the beginning or end of a specific era. In the Quran, the word «دور» is used in the meaning of time and era."
    }
  ],
  "800": [
    {
      "id": 3522,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Above - Above",
      "hw": "اوپر",
      "s": "'Upar' is a Persian-origin word used in Urdu meaning 'above / on height', in Arabic its meaning is 'fawq' or 'a'la'.",
      "d": "Linguistically, 'Upar' is originally a Persian word used in Urdu as 'upar / on height / sar-e bala'. Its original source is Persian; in Arabic, its synonymous terms are 'fawq' (fawq) and 'a'la' (a'la). In Urdu, 'upar' is commonly used to describe a location, while in Arabic, 'fawq' is more excellent and used in literature. The Quran uses the Arabic word 'fawq', which is translated as 'upar' (above) in Urdu translation.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «وَهُوَ الَّذِي خَلَقَ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضَ فِي سِتَّةِ أَيَّامٍ وَكَانَ عَرْشُهُ عَلَى الْمَاء» (هود / ۱۱) Translation: And He is the One who created the heavens and the earth in six days, and His throne was on the water.\n\nHere, the Arabic word 'عَلَى الْمَاء' (ala al-ma') is translated in Urdu as 'par / upar' meaning 'on / above'."
    },
    {
      "id": 3523,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Above - بالا",
      "hw": "اوپر",
      "s": "'Bala' denotes the attribute of height, elevated position, and being above.",
      "d": "'Bala' is used in Arabic to mean height and elevated position. Its root is b-l-w (ba, lam, waw) which means to reach height and elevated position. 'Bala' comes directly in Arabic to mean 'above' or 'high', while its synonyms include 'ali' and 'murtafi'. However, 'bala' is characterized by being used more to express the greatness and elevated status of Allah. In Urdu, 'upar' is a common term used for any height, while in Arabic, 'bala' comes more in the context of Allah's elevated position and grandeur. For example: In the Quran, it is said: «سَبِّحِ اسْمَ رَبِّكَ الْأَعْلَى» (الاعلی / 87) Translation: Glorify the name of your Lord, the Most High. In this verse, the word 'الاعلى' (a'la) denotes the most elevated position of Allah, which is harmonious with the meaning of 'bala'."
    }
  ],
  "801": [
    {
      "id": 3524,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Below - Below",
      "hw": "نیچے",
      "s": "'Niche' is actually a Persian word spoken in Urdu, in the Quran, its meaning is expressed with Arabic words like 'asfal', 'taht' and the concept of 'below'.",
      "d": "According to lexical analysis, 'Niche' is originally a Persian word used in Urdu as 'niche', but in Arabic, its synonymous terms are 'asfal' (asfal), 'taht' (taht), and 'safali' (safali). The Arabic word 'asfal' originates from 'safal' which is the opposite of 'above' and its root is s-f-l. 'Taht' originates from h-w-t which means below and beneath. Urdu's 'niche' is the translation of these words, and this concept is found in various verses of the Quran.\n\nDifference from synonyms: 'Asfal' is more used for being below in terms of position or rank, while 'taht' is generally used for being under something.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «وَقِيلَ يَا أَرْضُ ابْلَعِي مَاءَكِ وَيَا سَمَاءُ أَقْلِعِي وَغِيضَ الْمَاءُ» (هود / 44) Translation: And it was said, 'O earth, swallow your water, and O sky, cease,' and the water subsided, and the earth swallowed it.\n\nHere, the description is about the water being below and the earth swallowing it."
    },
    {
      "id": 3525,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Below - زير",
      "hw": "نیچے",
      "s": "'Zair' means to be under or below something, i.e., to be under something.",
      "d": "'Zair' is an Arabic word whose root is zayr. This word is originally a noun that expresses being under or below something. In Arabic, it is used when something is located under another thing or is under it. In contrast, 'fawq' expresses above and 'amam' expresses front. 'Zair' often comes in the Quran in the form of addition (idafa).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «وَاللَّهُ أَعْلَمُ بِمَا يُوعُونَ» (البینة / ۱) Translation: And Allah is most knowing of what they conceal.\n\nHere, the concept of 'zair' is implied in the context of concealment."
    }
  ],
  "802": [
    {
      "id": 3526,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Inside - Inside",
      "hw": "اندر",
      "s": "'Andar' is a Persian word used in Urdu with meanings of 'inside, internal, interior' and is not an Arabic word.",
      "d": "'Andar' is actually derived from the Persian verb 'andardan' which means 'to enter, to be inside'. This word is not of Arabic origin but entered Urdu from Persian. In Arabic, synonyms for 'inside' include «داخل» (d-kh-l), «فی», and «بین». However, in Urdu, this word is very common and is often used in meanings like 'ke andar', 'andaron', and 'batin'. Since the Quran was revealed in Arabic, this word does not appear in any verse due to Persian influence."
    },
    {
      "id": 3527,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Inside - داخل",
      "hw": "اندر",
      "s": "'Dakhil' is an Arabic word meaning 'to enter inside or internally', which is synonymous with Persian/Urdu 'andar'.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of 'Dakhil' is d-kh-l (dal, kha, lam) which means 'entry' i.e., to enter. This word comes in Arabic in contrast between internal and external, where 'dakhil' refers to the internal thing as opposed to the external. Urdu's 'andar' is derived from Persian and means 'andaron' or 'batin'.\n\nIts other synonyms include 'fi', 'bayn', and 'damn', but 'dakhil' is particularly used when expressing the state of entering or being inside something.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «وَمَن يَخْرُجْ مِن بَيْتِهِ مُهَاجِرًا إِلَى اللَّهِ وَرَسُولِهِ ثُمَّ يُدْرِكْهُ الْمَوْتُ فَقَدْ وَقَعَ أَجْرُهُ عَلَى اللَّهِ» (النساء / 100) Translation: And whoever emigrates from his house emigrating to Allah and His Messenger, and then death overtakes him, his reward has become incumbent upon Allah.\n\nHere, the root of 'muhajiran' implies 'dakhil' which expresses entering from one place to another through migration."
    }
  ],
  "803": [
    {
      "id": 3528,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Outside - باہر",
      "hw": "باہر",
      "s": "'Bahar' means apparent, clear, and evident, which describes the external or obvious aspect of something.",
      "d": "'Bahar' originates from the Arabic root b-h-r (ba, ha, ra) which refers to something being apparent, evident, and clear. This word is different from 'kharaj' (outside) and 'zahir' (apparent) because 'bahar' specifically describes the external aspect or state of being evident of something, while 'kharaj' merely means outside and 'zahir' means apparent. The Quran contains words derived from this root.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «وَ لَقَدۡ أَرۡسَلۡنَا مُوسىٰ بِـَٔايٰتِنَآ أَنۡ أَخۡرِجۡ قَوۡمَكَ مِّنَ الظُّلُمٰتِ إِلَى النُّورِ وَ ذَكِّرۡهُمۡ بِأَيَّامِ اللَّهِ ۚ إِنَّ فِي ذَٰلِكَ لَأٓيَاتٍ لِّكُلِّ صَبّارٍ شَكُورٍ» (ابرہیم / 5) Translation: And We certainly sent Moses with Our signs: [saying], 'Bring your people out of the darknesses into the light and remind them of the days of Allah.' Indeed in that are signs for everyone who is patient and grateful.\n\nIn this verse, the word 'النُّور' (nur) is from the b-h-r root, which means bright, clear, and evident."
    },
    {
      "id": 3529,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Outside - خارج",
      "hw": "باہر",
      "s": "'Kharij' lexically means 'to exit outside' or 'to be outside', and it is the Arabic basis for 'bahar', which is the opposite of 'inside'.",
      "d": "'Kharij' is an Arabic masdar (verbal noun) whose meanings are 'to exit outside', 'to be outside', or 'to go towards outside'. This verb comes from 'kharaja' and its derivatives include 'kharaj' (active participle), 'makhraj', 'makharij', and 'khuruj'. In Urdu, 'bahar' is derived from this Arabic root.\n\nIts synonyms include 'barun' and 'aziz', etc., but 'kharij' particularly carries the concept of 'exiting from something' or 'being beyond a limit', which distinguishes it from other words.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «وَإِذَا سَأَلْتُمُوهُنَّ مَتَاعًا فَاسْأَلُوهُنَّ مِن وَرَاءِ حِجَابٍ ذَٰلِكُمْ أَطْهَرُ لِقُلُوبِكُمْ وَقُلُوبِهِنَّ» (الأحزاب / ۵۳) Translation: And when you ask them for something, ask them from behind a partition. That is purer for your hearts and their hearts.\n\nIn this verse, the concept of 'kharaj' is implied in 'wara'i hijab' (behind the partition) meaning to speak from outside."
    }
  ],
  "804": [
    {
      "id": 3530,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Here - Here",
      "hw": "یہاں",
      "s": "'Yahan' is a demonstrative adverb that indicates a place close to the speaker.",
      "d": "Linguistically, the root of 'Yahan' is from Arabic 'huna' (huna) which is related to the system of demonstrative pronouns. In Urdu, 'yahan' is derived from Arabic and is a combination of 'yeh' (this) with the suffix 'an' which indicates spatial proximity. Its synonyms include 'vahan' (there - that place) and 'kahan' (where - interrogative or unknown place). 'Yahan' indicates the immediate vicinity of the speaker, while 'vahan' indicates a distant place, and 'kahan' indicates an interrogative or unknown location. The Quran contains the Arabic equivalent 'huna' (huna).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said: «وَكَذَٰلِكَ أَوۡحَيۡنَا إِلَيۡكَ رُوحًا مِّنۡ أَمۡرِنَاۚ مَاكُنتَ تَدۡرِي مَا الۡكِتَابُ وَلَا الۡإِيمَانُ وَلَٰكِن جَعَلۡنَاهُ نُورًا نَّهۡدِي بِهِۦ مَنۡ نَّشَآءُ مِنۡ عِبَادِنَاۚ وَإِنَّكَ لَتَهۡدِي إِلَىٰ صِرَاطٍ مُّسۡتَقِيمٍ» (الشوری / 42:52) Translation: And similarly, We have revealed to you, [O Muhammad], a spirit [i.e., revelation] from Our command. You did not know what is the Book or [what is] faith, but We have made it a light by which We guide whom We will of Our servants. And indeed, [O Muhammad], you guide to a straight path.\n\nNote: In the Quran, the Arabic word 'huna' (huna) appears, which means 'yahan' in Urdu."
    },
    {
      "id": 3531,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Here - Adhar",
      "hw": "یہاں",
      "s": "«Adhar» refers to pointing towards the place that is near the speaker.",
      "d": "«Adhar» linguistic origin is from the Arabic root «أ-د-ھ-ر» which is used for proximity and direction. It differs from «ہنا» and «ہہنا» because «ادھر» carries a subtle undertone of movement or direction, whereas «ہنا» is purely static location. In Urdu, «یہاں» is actually derived from Arabic «أدھر» and its literal meaning is «this side», i.e., where the speaker is present.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n\n«إِنَّ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا بِآيَاتِنَا سَوْفَ نُدْخِلُهُمْ فِي نَارٍ مَاْ أُخْرِجُوا عَنْهَا وَسَاءَ مَثْوًى» (Maryam / 72)\n\nTranslation: Indeed, those who deny Our signs, We will admit them into a Fire from which they will not be brought out, and wretched is the dwelling."
    }
  ],
  "805": [
    {
      "id": 3532,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "There - There",
      "hw": "وہاں",
      "s": "'Vahan' is an adverb that indicates a distant place.",
      "d": "'Vahan' is actually a word derived from Persian that entered Urdu. Its basis is the Persian word 'vah' (vah: that) which means 'that' or 'those', and the suffix '-an' indicates a place. In Urdu, 'vahan' means 'there' i.e., a place that is far from both the speaker and the listener. In contrast, 'yahan' refers to a place near the speaker, and 'kahan' is used for interrogative or unknown locations. Since 'vahan' is a Persian word and the Quran was revealed in Arabic, this word does not appear in the Quran. However, in Urdu translations, when a verse mentions a distant place, the word 'vahan' is often used."
    },
    {
      "id": 3533,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "There - Adhar",
      "hw": "وہاں",
      "s": "«Adhar» is an Arabic word that indicates direction and place, whereas «whaan» is an Urdu word derived from «woh» to indicate a distant place.",
      "d": "«Adhar» linguistic root is from Arabic root letters and it means direction, side, or this way. In Urdu its meaning is «here», «there», or «this way». Its difference from other synonyms is that «Adhar» carries a sense of direction of movement, whereas «whaan» merely points to a distant place.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n\n«وَإِذۡ قُلۡنَا لِلۡمَلَائِکَةِ ٱسۡجُدُوا۟ لِأٰدَمَ فَسَجَدُوۡا۟ إِلَّاۤ إِبۡلِیسَ كَانَ مِنَ ٱلۡجِنِّ فَفَسَقَ عَنۡ أَمۡرِ رَبِّهِۦۗ أَفَتَتَّخِذُونَهُۥ وَذُرِّیَّتَهُۥ خُلَفَآءَ مِن دُونِی وَهُمۡ لَكُمۡ أَعۡدَآءُۚ بِئۡسَ لِلظَّالِمِینَ بَدَلࣰا» (Al-Kahf / 50)\n\nTranslation: And when We said to the angels, 'Prostrate to Adam,' they prostrated except Iblis. He was among the jinn and defied the command of his Lord. Will you then take him and his offspring as allies instead of Me, while they are your enemies? What a wretched substitute for the wrongdoers.\n\nIn this verse the word «خُلَفَاءَ» appears, which is related to «Adhar» and means successor or one who takes someone's place."
    }
  ],
  "806": [
    {
      "id": 3534,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Everywhere - Everywhere",
      "hw": "ہر جگہ",
      "s": "«ہر جگہ» is a compound in Arabic of «ہر» (har) and «جگہ» (jagah), used for any place or location.",
      "d": "Analyzing the linguistic root of «ہر جگہ», it comprises two words: «ہر» (har), equivalent to Arabic «کُلّ» (kull - every/each), and «جگہ» (jagah), which carries the meaning of Arabic «مَکَان» (makan - place/location). Its plural is «امکنہ» (amkinah). It is absolute and comprehensive, leaving no place excluded. Synonyms include «ہر طرف» or «ہر جانب», but «ہر جگہ» is more explicit in terrestrial and spatial meaning.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَسِیقُوا۟ إِلَى ٱلَّذِیۡۤ أَحۡدَثَ فِی ٱلۡأَرۡضِ هَلۡ مِّن مَّحِیۡثٍ» (Surah Al-Mursalat / 77:25-26)\nTranslation: And they will be driven to the one who has created something new in the earth in every place; is there any savior?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3535,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Every place - Every position",
      "hw": "ہر جگہ",
      "s": "«Every maqam» literal meaning is every position or every place of a position, referring to a specific position or situation.",
      "d": "«Maqam» linguistic root is w-q-f (standing, the place of standing) from which Arabic derives a specific place, position, or situation. Its difference from «jagah» is that «jagah» is a general Urdu-Persian word denoting any place, whereas «maqam» in Arabic refers to a specific place, position, or spiritual station that holds significance.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n\n«وَلِلَّهِ الْمَشۡرِقُ وَالۡمَغۡرِبُۚ فَأَیۡنَمَا تُوَلُّوا۟ فَثَمَّ وَجۡهُ اللَّهِۚ إِنَّ اللَّهَ وَاسِعٌ عَلِیمٌ» (Al-Baqarah / 115)\n\nTranslation: To Allah belong the east and the west; so wherever you turn, there is the Face of Allah. Indeed, Allah is All-Encompassing and Knowing."
    }
  ],
  "807": [
    {
      "id": 3536,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Quickly - Quickly",
      "hw": "جلدی",
      "s": "«Jaldi» means speed, haste, or quickness, derived from the Arabic root (j-l-d) whose basic meaning is skin (leather), from which the sense of haste and quickness developed.",
      "d": "«Jaldi» comes from the Arabic root j-l-d. From this root are derived words such as «jad» (skin), «jalid» (hard), and «jalidi» (haste, speed). Linguistically, «jalidi» means to accomplish a task without delay, swiftly. Its synonyms include «ajalat» (haste), «tez» (speed), «surrat» (speed), and «shataab» (acceleration). However, «jalidi» carries an implicit sense of rash haste or impatience, whereas «tez» simply denotes speed. An example of this word in the Quran:\n\n«وَلَا تَسۡتَعۡجِلُوا۟ بِالۡقُرۡآنِ مِنۡ قَبۡلِ أَنۡ یُقۡضَیٰۤ إِلَیۡکَ وَحۡیُهُۥ» (Ta-Ha / 114)\n\nTranslation: And do not rush in reciting the Quran before its revelation is completed to you."
    },
    {
      "id": 3537,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Quickly - Haste",
      "hw": "جلدی",
      "s": "«Ajlat» means doing something quickly, but it carries a negative connotation of rashness and acting without thought.",
      "d": "«Ajlat» in Arabic is written «ع-ج-ل». It is derived from the verb «عَجِلَ» meaning to do something quickly and without delay. However, it carries an implicit nuance that distinguishes it from synonyms like «sur'ah» (speed). «Sur'ah» merely denotes speed or velocity, whereas «ajlat» implies hasty action, rashness, and sometimes foolish behavior. In Urdu, «jalidi» is borrowed from Arabic and reflects the sense of ajlat. The Quran contains many usages of this word.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n\n«وَقَالُوا لَن نُّؤْمِنَ لَكَ حَتَّى تَفجُرَ لَنَا مِنَ الأَرضِ يَنبُوعًا أَو تَكُونَ لَكَ جَنَّةٌ مِّن نَّخِيلٍ وَعِنبٍ فَتُفَجِّرَ الأَهوارَ فِيهَا وَتَجۡعَلَ لَهُمۡ كُلَّ شَيۡءٍ مُّفَتَّرًا أَو تَقَعَ السَّمَاءُ كَمَا قلتَ عَلَينَا كُتُّابًا أۡو تَأۡتِيَ بِاللَّهِ وَالۡمَلَائِكَةِ قَبِيلًا أَو يَكُونَ لَكَ بَيۡتٌ مِّن زُخۡرُفٍ أَو تَرۡقَىٰ فِي السَّمَاءِ وَلَن نُّؤۡمِنَ لِرُقِيِّكَ حَتَّى تُنَزِّلَ عَلَينا كِتَابًا نَّقرَؤُهُ قُلۡ سُبۡحَانَ رَبِّي هَلۡ كُنتُ إِلَّا بَشَرًا رَّسُولًا وَمَا مَنَعَ النَّاسَ أَن يُؤۡمِنُوا إِذۡ جَاءَهُمُ الۡهُدَىٰ إِلَّا أَن قَالُوا أَبۡعَثَ اللَّهُ بَشَرًا رَّسُولًا قُلۡ لَوۡ كَانَ فِي الۡأَرۡضِ مَلَائِكَةٌ يَمۡشُونَ مُقۡتَدِينَ لَنَزَّلۡنَا عَلَيهِم مِّنَ السَّمَاءِ مَلَكًا رَّسُولًا» (Al-Isra / 17)\n\nTranslation: And they said, 'We will not believe in you until you cause a spring to gush forth from the earth for us, or you have a garden of date palms and vines and make rivers flow therein, or you cause the heaven to fall upon us in pieces as you claimed, or you bring Allah and the angels before us face to face, or you have a house of gold, or you ascend into the heaven—and we will not believe in your ascension until you bring down a book for us to read.' Say: 'Glory be to my Lord! Am I anything but a human messenger?' And what prevented people from believing when guidance came to them, except that they said, 'Has Allah sent a human as a messenger?' Say: 'If there were angels walking on the earth as messengers, We would have sent down an angel from heaven as a messenger.'"
    }
  ],
  "808": [
    {
      "id": 3538,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Monastery - Monastery",
      "hw": "دیر",
      "s": "«Deer» refers to the dwelling of Christian monks, i.e., the house or monastery of Christian monks.",
      "d": "«Deer» linguistic form «dayr» is derived from the Arabic root d-y-r (d-y-r). It originally comes from «dar» meaning house or dwelling. This word specifically denotes the residence of Christian monks (presbyters). Its synonyms include «dayr» (the same word) used for a particular religious establishment of a certain community. It differs from «bi'ah» (church) because «bi'ah» is the place of worship for Christians, whereas «dayr» is the monks' residence.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n\n«وَكَأَيِّن مِّن قَرْيَةٍ عَتَتْ عَنْ أَمْرِ رَبِّهَا وَرُسُلِهِ فَحَاسَبْنَاهَا حِسَابًا شَدِيدًا وَعَذَّبْنَاهَا عَذَابًا نُّكْرًا ﴿٥٨﴾ كُلُوا مِمَّا رَزَقَكُمُ اللَّهُ وَلَا تَطْغَوْا فِيهِ وَاحْذَرُوا النَّارَ الَّتِي أُعِدَّتْ لِلْكَافِرِينَ» (Surah At-Tur 53/58)\n\nTranslation: And how many cities have rebelled against the command of their Lord and His messengers, so We called them to a strict account and punished them with a severe punishment. Eat of what Allah has provided for you, and do not exceed therein, and beware of the Fire which has been prepared for the disbelievers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3539,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Monastery - Delay",
      "hw": "دیر",
      "s": "«Ta'kheer» means delaying an action or event beyond its scheduled time, or being late in timing.",
      "d": "«Ta'kheer» in Arabic is built from the root «أ خ ر» (alif-kha-ra), from which the noun «ta'kheer» (delay) and the active participle «mua'khir» (one who delays) are derived. This word expresses the state where something is behind its natural or appointed time. Its meanings are 'late' or 'being delayed'.\n\nIts synonyms include «ta'akhkhar» (delay) and «ta'weez» (compensation), but «ta'kheer' is generally used for temporal delay, whereas «ta'akhkhar» also includes the notion of falling behind.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n\n«وَلَوْ يُعَجِّلُ اللَّهُ لِلنَّاسِ الشَّرَّ اسْتِعْجَالَهُمْ بِالْخَيْرِ لَقُضِيَ إِلَيْهِمْ أَجَلُهُمْ» (Yunus / 10)\n\nTranslation: And if Allah were to hasten punishment for people as they hasten for good, their terms would have been decreed immediately."
    }
  ],
  "809": [
    {
      "id": 3540,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water - Water",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«Pani» is a word of Persian origin that entered Urdu, whereas in the Quran the Arabic word «ma'» (water) is used instead.",
      "d": "«Pani» actually comes from Persian into Urdu; it is not Arabic. In Arabic, water is expressed by «ma'» (mim with fatha on alif) and also «miyah». The Quran uses only the Arabic word «ma'» for water. In Urdu, «pani» means a liquid, transparent substance that flows on the earth and sustains all living beings. This word is derived from Sanskrit «paniya*».\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n\n«وَجَعَلۡنَا مِنۡہُ الۡحَیۡوٰانَ مَآءً حَیًّا» (Al-Anbiya / 30)\n\nTranslation: And We made from it every living creature."
    },
    {
      "id": 3541,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water - Aab",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«Aab» means water in Arabic, and in Quranic vocabulary it is a sign of life and purity.",
      "d": "«Aab» linguistic root consists of the Arabic letters alif and ba, and its basic meaning is water. In Urdu, «pani» is derived from Sanskrit, whereas in Arabic «aab» is used in compounds like Zamzam water, rainwater, and the water of life. In the Quran, the word «aab» appears in contexts of water’s purity, life, and Allah’s blessings.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n\n«أَوَلَمْ يَرَ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا أَنَّ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضَ كَانَتَا رَتْقًا فَفَتَقْنَاهُمَا وَجَعَلْنَا مِنَ الْمَاءِ كُلَّ شَيْءٍ حَيٍّ أَفَلَا يُؤْمِنُونَ» (Al-Anbiya / 30)\n\nTranslation: Have the disbelievers not seen that the heavens and the earth were a joined entity, then We split them apart and made from water every living thing? Then will they not believe?"
    }
  ],
  "810": [
    {
      "id": 3542,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Fire - Fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«آگ» refers to that which is intensely hot flame, which is a sign of the punishment of Hell.",
      "d": "The word «آگ» is derived from Persian, which is also used in Arabic. In Arabic, words for fire include «نار», «جحيم», and «سعير». «نار» is the original Arabic word, while «آگ» entered from Persian. In the Quran, fire is described as a sign of the punishment of Hell and a mark of the torment for disbelievers and polytheists.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«إِنَّ الْمُتَّقینَ فِی جَنَّاتٍ وَعُیُونٍ آخِذِینَ مَا آتَاهُم رَبُّهُم» (Ad-Dukhan / 17)\nTranslation: Indeed, the righteous will be in gardens and springs, taking what their Lord has given them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3543,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Fire - Aatash",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«Aatash» is an Arabic word used for fire, meaning a flame that denotes both worldly fire and divine punishment.",
      "d": "«Aatash» linguistic root is A-T-SH (أ-ت-ش). It is an old Arabic word denoting a flame and blazing fire. In Urdu 'aag' and Persian 'aatash' derive from this root. Its meaning includes intensity and heat.\n\nCompared to other words like 'nar' (fire) and 'hariq' (conflagration), the difference is that 'nar' is a general term for fire of any kind, whereas 'aatash' emphasizes the flame and heat, and 'hariq' specifically refers to a burning fire.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n\n«إِلَّا مَنْ أَتَى اللَّهَ بِقَلْبٍ سَلِيمٍ» (Ash-Shu'ara / 89)\n\nTranslation: Except the one who comes to Allah with a sound heart.\n\nHere the word 'salim' comes from the root 'salm' meaning safety and health, and it refers to the heart being saved from the trial of fire (aatash)."
    }
  ],
  "811": [
    {
      "id": 3544,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth - Earth",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "«زمین» refers to the stable and spread-out earth that Allah has created and on which He has provided residence for living beings.",
      "d": "The word «زمین» originates from the Arabic root ز م ن. Its original meaning is 'to be stable', i.e., firm and solid. In the word «زمین», this concept is found that it is a spread-out, stable, and habitable surface. Among its synonymous words, 'ارض' (ard) is also included, which comes in the meaning of earth or land, but the difference between the two is that 'ارض' is a general word used for both the expanse of earth and land, whereas «زمین» more often refers to the physical surface of the earth, i.e., the surface of soil and ground. In the Quran, the word «زمین» often comes together with ارض to describe both aspects of earth.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالْأَرْضَ بَعْدَ ذَٰلِكَ دَحَاهَا» (الذاریات ۔ 51)\nTranslation: And after that, He spread out the earth."
    }
  ],
  "812": [
    {
      "id": 3546,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sky - Sky",
      "hw": "Sky",
      "s": "«آسمان» in Arabic relates to height and elevation, and it refers to all the celestial layers above the earth.",
      "d": "The linguistic root of «آسمان» comes from the Arabic letters س-م-و (s-m-w), which convey the meaning of height and elevation. This word is the plural of «سماء» (sama') in Arabic, meaning sky, firmament, or that part above the earth which we see above our heads. Its difference from other words is that «سماء» directly refers to the tangible part of the sky, whereas «جنت» (Jannah) is related to Allah's special reward, and «سقف» (saqf) means merely roof or hood. In the Quran, Allah has described «آسمان» as a sign of His signs and power.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«الَّذِي جَعَلَ لَكُمُ الْأَرْضَ فِرَاشًا وَالسَّمَاءَ بِنَاءً» (الانعام / ۱۶۴)\nTranslation: He (Allah) has made the earth a bed for you and the sky a structure (roof)."
    },
    {
      "id": 3547,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sky - Falak",
      "hw": "Sky",
      "s": "«فلک» refers to the orbits (paths) of planets in space.",
      "d": "The meaning of «فلک» is generally considered to be sky. But in reality, it refers to the orbits of planets in space or the paths in which celestial bodies revolve (م ر ۔ م ل ۔ مف).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ الَّیۡلَ وَ النَّہَارَ وَ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ ؕ کُلٌّ فِیۡ  فَلَکٍ یَّسۡبَحُوۡنَ» (21/33)\nTranslation: And He it is Who created the night and the day, and the sun and the moon; each floating in an orbit."
    }
  ],
  "813": [
    {
      "id": 3548,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind - Wind",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "«ہوا» refers to the movement or blowing of wind, which is among the signs of Allah's power.",
      "d": "The word «ہوا» originates from the Arabic root ہ-و-ی (ہَوَیَ يَہۡوِي), whose original meaning is to blow or to move (wind). These words are derived from «ہَوَاء» (hawāʾ), meaning wind, breeze, or waves of wind. In the Quran, «ہوا» often comes as a sign of Allah's power and might. Other words such as «رِيح» (rīḥ - a strong gust of wind) and «عَاصِف» (āṣif - stormy wind) are different from these. «ہوا» is generally used for moderate wind, whereas «رِيح» is used for stronger wind.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَهُوَ الَّذِي يُرْسِلُ الرِّيَاحَ بُشْرًا بَيْنَ يَدَيْ رَحْمَتِهِ» (الفرقان 25/48)\nTranslation: And He it is Who sends the winds as glad tidings before His mercy."
    }
  ],
  "814": [
    {
      "id": 3550,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Mountain - Mountain",
      "hw": "پہاڑ",
      "s": "«پہاڑ» refers to a high and verdant or barren elevated land that is geologically a high and stable landform.",
      "d": "The word «پہاڑ» is actually not originally from Arabic but is borrowed from Persian and used in Urdu. In Arabic, the words «جَبَل» (jabal) and «طَور» are used for mountain. In Arabic, «جَبَل» means a large elevated land that is high from the earth's surface and has extensive length and width. «پہاڑ» has come into Urdu and Persian with the same meaning and is the semantic equivalent of Arabic «جَبَل», but etymologically different.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالطُّورِ» (الطور / 1)\nTranslation: And by the mountain (Tur) upon which the speech of Allah was revealed to Moses (peace be upon him)."
    },
    {
      "id": 3551,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Mountain - Koh",
      "hw": "پہاڑ",
      "s": "«کوہ» refers to a strong and firm mountain, which is a sign of the earth's structural strength.",
      "d": "What does «کوہ» mean: In Arabic, the root «کوہ» (k-w-h) comes from the meanings of hardness, firmness, and remaining steadfast. This word is used for mountain and its original meaning is a large and hard earthly element that remains firm. Other words such as «جبل» (jabal) are also used for mountain, but «کوہ» emphasizes hardness and firmness. «کوہ» refers to those mountains that protect the earth from sinking and are signs of Allah's power."
    }
  ],
  "815": [
    {
      "id": 3552,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "River - River",
      "hw": "دریا",
      "s": "«دریا» refers to that wide waterway that flows between lands, used for both sea and river.",
      "d": "The origin of «دریا» is Persian, which entered Arabic. In Arabic, the word «بحر» (bahr) is more commonly used for sea, but «دریا» is also found in Arabic and means large water, sea, or river. The difference is that «بحر» is derived from Arabic zakrah (masdar) meaning to be wide or expansive, whereas «دریا» is borrowed from Persian. In the Quran, the word «دریا» appears in very few verses; mostly «بحر» is used.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَهْوَ الَّذِي مَرَجَ الْبَحْرَيْنِ هَذَا عَذْبٌ فُورٌ وَهَذَا مِلْحٌ أُجَاجٌ» (الرحمن / 55)\nTranslation: And He it is Who has merged the two seas, this one sweet and palatable, and that one salty and bitter.\n\nNote: In the Quran, «دریا» is used less, and «بحر» is more common, but the meaning of «دریا» is also sea or wide water."
    },
    {
      "id": 3553,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "River - Rod",
      "hw": "دریا",
      "s": "«رود» refers to that flowing water which flows continuously from one place to another.",
      "d": "The linguistic root «رود» is originally Arabic, meaning to flow or to be in motion. This root ر و د is associated with flowing water. «رود» refers to such flowing water that continuously moves in one direction. In contrast, «نَہَر» (nahr) is more used for limited and artificial waterways, while «عَیۡر» (ʿair) and «وَادی» (wadi) mean very large river and valley respectively. The characteristic of «رود» is that it expresses natural flow.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالْجِبَالَ أَرْسَاهَا» (النازعات / ۳۲)\nTranslation: And He has firmly set the mountains.\n\n(Note: The word «رود» does not appear in the Quran in the form of flowing, but its origin ر و د is connected, which denotes flow and motion, and in Urdu, «دریا» reflects this concept that water flows naturally from one place to another.)"
    }
  ],
  "816": [
    {
      "id": 3554,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Rain - Rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "«بارش» refers to the water that descends from the sky or a downpour that falls on the earth in the form of many droplets.",
      "d": "According to linguistic analysis, «بارش» is derived from the Arabic root ب-ر-ش. The original meaning of this root is 'to scatter' or 'to spread', and «بارش» is its mashdar (verbal noun) that describes the action of scattering rain and falling on the earth. Compared to other words, where «مطر» (matr) and «غیث» (ghaith) are also used for rain, «بارش» specifically emphasizes the falling of rain in many scattered droplets, which distinguishes it from other synonyms."
    },
    {
      "id": 3555,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Rain - Barsat",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "«برسات» refers to the rain of mercy sent down from Allah from the sky that revives the earth.",
      "d": "The root in Arabic for «برسات» is «بر-س-ت», which is associated with the concept of rain. This word is formed from «بر» (meaning to flow or fall) and the suffix «سات», indicating continuity and abundance. Other words like «مطر» (matr) and «غیث» (ghayth) differ in that «برسات» mostly describes the rain that comes in barren (desert) areas, which is a sign of Allah's mercy. In the Quran, Allah has described rain in the context of His blessings and mercy.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَهُوَ الَّذِي يُنَزِّلُ الْغَيْثَ مِن بَعْدِ مَا قَنَطُوا» (الکهف / ۲۸)\nTranslation: And He it is Who sends down rain after they have despaired."
    }
  ],
  "817": [
    {
      "id": 3556,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Substitute",
      "hw": "بادل",
      "s": "The term 'بادل' (badal) is derived from the Arabic root ب-د-ل and means 'one who substitutes', i.e., an alternative or replacement.",
      "d": "The root of 'بادل' is ب-د-ل (badala) which means 'to substitute' or 'to change one thing with another'. These words are derived from 'بدل' (badal), which is formed from the masdar 'بدلت'. Linguistically, 'بادل' is in the active participle form, meaning 'one who substitutes'. Its synonyms include 'مبدل' (mubaddal), 'بدیل' (badil), and 'مستبدل' (mustabdal), but 'بادل' specifically refers to the person or thing that takes the place of another or is engaged in the act of substitution. In the Quran, this root often appears in the context of Allah replacing one nation with another or changing commandments.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَإِذۡ قَالَتۡ أُمَّتُہُمۡ رَبَّنَاۤ أَرۡسِلۡ فِیۡهِمۡ رَسُولࣰا مِّنۡہُمۡ یَتۡلُواۡ عَلَیۡهِمۡۤ آیَاتِكَ وَیُعَلِّمُهُمُ ٱلۡكِتَٰبَ وَٱلۡحِكۡمَةَ وَیُزَكِّیۡهِمۡۚ إِنَّكَ أَنتَ ٱلۡعَزِیزُ ٱلۡحَكِیمُ» (البقرة / 129)\nTranslation: 'And when their people said, \"O our Lord! Send among them a messenger from themselves who will recite Your verses upon them and teach them the Book and wisdom and purify them. Indeed, You are the Exalted in Might, the Wise.\"' Here, the root of 'یُزَكِّیۡهِمۡ' is ز-ك-و which means 'to purify'. However, examples of the root ب-د-ل are found in several Quranic verses where Allah has replaced nations with others."
    },
    {
      "id": 3557,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Badal - Sahab",
      "hw": "بادل",
      "s": "«سَحَاب» is commonly used for clouds in general.",
      "d": "«سَحَبْ» means 'to pull' or 'to draw', and it is commonly used for clouds (see F. L. 454). All types of clouds are called «سَحَاب», however, this term is specifically applied to clouds that are raised by winds and spread in the sky. Thus, it is the initial form of all clouds.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَاللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡۤ اَرۡسَلَ الرِّیٰحَ فَتُثِیۡرُ سَحَابًا» (35/9)\nTranslation: 'And Allah is the One who sends the winds, and they raise the clouds.'"
    }
  ],
  "818": [
    {
      "id": 3558,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Tree",
      "hw": "درخت",
      "s": "The term 'درخت' refers to a woody plant that has branches and a trunk, and it is synonymous with 'شجرہ' in Arabic.",
      "d": "The word 'درخت' is actually derived from Persian and is used in Urdu, while in Arabic the original word is 'شَجَرَة' (shajarah). Its synonyms include 'نَبَات' (nabat) and 'غِرس' (ghirs), but 'شجرہ' specifically refers to a tree that has branches and fruit, while 'نبات' is also used for general plants, and 'غِرس' relates to planting. In the Urdu translation of the Quran, the word 'درخت' appears in verses that in the original Arabic text mean 'شَجَرَة' or 'شَجَرٍ'.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«الَّذِينَ يَذْكُرُونَ اللَّهَ قِيَامًا وَقُعُودًا وَعَلَى جُنُوبِهِمْ وَيَتَفَكَّرُونَ فِي خَلْقِ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضِ رَبَّنَا مَا خَلَقْتَ هَذَا بَاطِلًا سُبْحَانَكَ فَقِنَا عَذَابَ النَّارِ» (آل عمران / 191)\nTranslation: 'Who remember Allah while standing or sitting or [lying] on their sides and give thought to the creation of the heavens and the earth, [saying], \"Our Lord, You did not create this aimlessly; exalted are You [above such a thing]; then protect us from the punishment of the Fire.\"' (In the context of this verse, the mention of Allah's power is evident in the creation of trees and plants.)"
    }
  ],
  "819": [
    {
      "id": 3560,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Flower",
      "hw": "پھول",
      "s": "The word 'پھول' is a Persian-Urdu term that does not exist as an original word in Arabic; its equivalent in Arabic is 'زَهْرَة' (zahrah).",
      "d": "According to lexical analysis, the word 'پھول' entered Urdu from Persian and is not an original Arabic word. In Arabic, for the meaning of 'flower', 'زَهْرَة' (zahrah) and 'وَرْق' (waraq) are used. The root of 'زہرہ' is ز-ھ-ر, which means 'to shine' or 'to bloom'. The Quran refers to this word where Allah has given examples of flowers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3561,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Flower - Gul",
      "hw": "پھول",
      "s": "The word 'گل' is a Persian term used to mean 'flower', although in Arabic, this root has different meanings.",
      "d": "Lexically, the Arabic root 'ج-ل' (jalla) means 'to appear', 'to be majestic', and 'honor and respect'. In Persian, the word 'گل' means 'flower', which is used in Urdu as 'پھول'. In Arabic, for flower, the words 'زَهرَة' and 'وَرد' (which entered Arabic from Persian) are used. The characteristic of this word is that it was transferred from Persian to Urdu and does not have a direct connection with the Arabic root.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالْوَرْدِ وَالْحُورِ» (الوَرد / 1)\nTranslation: 'By the flowers and the houris.' (Here, 'وَرد' refers to the flowers of Paradise.)"
    }
  ],
  "820": [
    {
      "id": 3562,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Leaf",
      "hw": "پتہ",
      "s": "The term 'پتہ' refers to the part of a tree that grows on its branches, and its basic Arabic equivalent is 'ورق'.",
      "d": "The word 'پتہ' is originally derived from Persian and is widely used in Urdu. In Arabic, the original word is 'وَرَق' (waraq), from which 'ورقة' (waraqah) is formed. This root (جذر) is و-ر-ق, which means 'skin' or 'peel', and this same root is also the basis for 'قرطاس' (qirtas - paper). Its synonyms include 'ورق', 'ورقة', and 'عُشب' (green leaf). The difference between 'پتہ' and 'ورق' is that 'ورق' is the original Arabic word, while 'پتہ' is a Persian-Urdu word that is more commonly used in everyday speech.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالَّتِي أَحَاطَتْ بِهِمْ أَوْ عَضَّهُمْ فِي الْغَابَاتِ» (إبراهيم / 18)\nTranslation: 'And that which encompassed them or devoured them in the thickets.'\nNote: The word 'پتہ' is not explicitly mentioned in the Quran, but sources of 'ورق' and the word 'عُشب' (green leaf) are present."
    },
    {
      "id": 3563,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Leaf - Waraq",
      "hw": "پتہ",
      "s": "The term 'ورق' refers to the leaves that grow on trees or the parts of paper on which writing is done.",
      "d": "In Arabic, the initial meaning of 'ورق' is the leaf of a tree and the thin, spread-out layers of paper. This root و-ر-ق indicates thin layers and spread. In Urdu, 'پتہ' is actually derived from the Persian-Arabic 'ورقة' (warqah). Its synonyms include 'ورقة' (warqah - leaf), 'سفیفة' (safiyah - leaf like a boat), and 'صحیفة' (sahifah - written paper). The difference is that 'ورق' is more general and wide-ranging, including both natural and artificial leaves, while 'صحیفة' specifically refers to written paper."
    }
  ],
  "821": [
    {
      "id": 3564,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Egg",
      "hw": "بیج",
      "s": "The word 'بیج' is derived from the Arabic root ب-ي-ج and means 'egg'.",
      "d": "The word 'بیج' is an Arabic noun derived from the root ب-ی-ج. Its basic meaning is 'egg', particularly a bird's egg. This word is synonymous with 'بیض' (bayd), and both are related to the root ب-ی-ض which means 'white'. The word 'بیج' was more commonly used in ancient Arabic, and in the Quran, the form 'بیض' appears more frequently. For egg, Arabic also has 'بَیْضَۃ' (baydatun).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالطَّیْرِ صَافَّاتٍ مَّا لَهُنَّ مِنْ فَرْعٍ وَمِمَّا یَكِیْلُونَ» (الطارق / ۱۹)\nTranslation: 'And by the birds that smooth their feathers, they have no shelter.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3565,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Egg - Seed",
      "hw": "بیج",
      "s": "The word 'تخم' in Arabic comes in the meanings of egg, seed, and offspring, and it is used in the context of both plants and humans.",
      "d": "The word 'تخم' is derived from the Arabic root ت-خ-م and its basic meaning is egg or seed. This word is used for the seeds of plants as well as for the offspring and lineage of humans. Its Urdu synonym is 'بیج', which is derived from Persian. The special thing about 'تخم' is that it is used in Arabic for both aspects of agriculture and lineage, while 'بیج' is more commonly used for the seeds of plants.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«أَمۡ حَسِبۡتَ أَنَّ أَصۡحَـٰبَ الۡکَہۡفِ وَالرَّقِیۡمِ کَانُواۡ مِنۡ ءَالَیۡتِنَا عَجَبًا أَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ أَصۡحَابَ بَقَرَۃٍ مَّا کَانَتۡ لَهُمۡ فِیۡهَا مِنۡ نَّسۡلٍ ذُکۡرًا فَإِمۡسَاکٌۭ بِمَعۡرُوفٍ أَوۡ تَشۡرِیۡدٌۭ بِظُلمٍۚ» (18 / 9)\nTranslation: 'Do you think that the companions of the cave and the inscription were among Our signs a wonder? Or are you among those who believe that the people of the cow had no male offspring in it? So they should hold to what is good or drive away with injustice?'"
    }
  ],
  "822": [
    {
      "id": 3566,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Soil",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "The term 'مٹی' refers to that soft, dust-like substance of the earth from which human creation occurred.",
      "d": "The word 'مٹی' is an Urdu word that actually originates from the Arabic word 'طين' (tin). It means clay or wet soil found on the earth's surface. In Urdu, it is generally called 'مٹی', while in Arabic there are several words such as 'طين' (clay), 'تراب' (dust), and 'أرض' (earth). The difference is that 'مٹی' specifically refers to the soft, sticky soil that is the basic material of human creation, while 'تراب' refers to general dust. In the Quran, Allah created humans from this soil.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«إِنَّ اللَّهَ يُحِبُّ الْمُحْسِنِينَ» (سورۃ البقرہ / 195)\nTranslation: 'Indeed, Allah loves the doers of good.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3567,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Soil - Khak",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "The word 'خاک' is an Arabic term that in Urdu means 'مٹی', i.e., soil, dust, dry earth.",
      "d": "The root of 'خاک' is the Arabic triad خ-و-ک. Its basic meaning is earth, soil, dust, and dry soil. In Urdu, 'مٹی' is originally from Sanskrit/Prakrit, but in Quranic translations, 'خاک' is used and understood to mean 'مٹی'. The difference is that Arabic 'خاک' refers to the dust scattered on the earth's surface and dry soil, while Urdu 'مٹی' generally includes both wet and hard soil. In the Quran, the word 'خاک' also appears in the context of earth and human creation.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَإِنَّ عَلَیۡکُمۡ لَحَافِظِینَ ۙ﴿۱۰﴾ کِرامًا کَاتِبِینَ ۙ﴿۱۱﴾ یَعۡلَمُونَ مَا تَفۡعَلُونَ» (الانفطار 82/10-12)\nTranslation: 'And indeed, upon you are keepers, noble and recording, who know whatever you do.'\n\nAnother clear example:\n«وَمِنۡہُمۡ مَّنۡ یَّقُولُ رَبَّنَاۤ اٰتۡنَا فِی الدُّنۡیَا حَسَنَۃً وَّفِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ حَسَنَۃً وَّقِنَا عَذَابَ النَّارِ» (البقرۃ 2/201)\nTranslation: 'And among them are those who say, \"Our Lord, grant us in this world [that which is] good and in the Hereafter [that which is] good and protect us from the punishment of the Fire.\"'"
    }
  ],
  "823": [
    {
      "id": 3568,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Jungle - Jungle",
      "hw": "جنگل",
      "s": "Jungle refers to a dense forested area filled with wild plants, borrowed from Persian into Urdu.",
      "d": "The word 'jungle' originates from the Persian language and is used similarly in Urdu. In Arabic, its root is different from 'j n l'; Arabic words related to 'jun' pertain to heavenly hosts or jinn. In Urdu and Persian, 'jungle' means a vast area where trees are abundant and wildlife thrives. Its synonyms include 'jungle, junglestan, beshan, jhari', but 'jungle' is the most appropriate and common term.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَكَمْ مِّن شَجَرَةٍ مُّمْبِدَةٍ» (الرحمن / 6)\nTranslation: And how many a tree is there that sheds its leaves.\n\n(Note: The word 'jungle' does not appear explicitly in the Quran, but Allah has described many types of 'shajar' (trees) that indicate wild forest areas.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3569,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Jungle - Ban",
      "hw": "جنگل",
      "s": "Ban refers to the act of building and creation, which in the context of jungle signifies natural settlements and trees.",
      "d": "Ban is an Arabic root meaning to build, construct, and procreate. It appears in Arabic as 'bani' (بَنَى), which denotes building structures or settlements. The Urdu word 'jungle' actually derives from Sanskrit (Sanskrit: जंगल / jhangal) and is not related to the Arabic root 'ban'. However, conceptually, 'ban' can be linked to jungle as a naturally built settlement by Allah, where trees and plants are like constructed edifices. This differs from other Arabic terms like 'ghabah' (غابة), which is used for jungle and has the root 'gh b w'."
    }
  ],
  "824": [
    {
      "id": 3570,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rigistan - Rigistan",
      "hw": "ریگستان",
      "s": "Rigistan refers to land abundant in sand (bajra), i.e., a sandy and desert area.",
      "d": "Rigistan is a Persian-Urdu compound word formed from 'rig' (sand, bajra) and 'stan' (place, land). It means sandy land or desert. Arabic has no exact equivalent, though close terms include 'sahra' (barren, desert land), 'raml' (sand dune), and 'fala' (desolate, remote land). In Urdu, 'rigistan' is borrowed from Persian and applies to areas with abundant sand. The Quran primarily uses terms like 'sahra' and 'ard' to describe such concepts."
    },
    {
      "id": 3571,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rigistan - Sahara",
      "hw": "ریگستان",
      "s": "Sahra literally means barren, sandy, and desert land, used in Urdu as 'rigistan'.",
      "d": "Sahra is an Arabic word meaning barren, sandy, and desert land. It derives from the Arabic root ص-ح-ر (sad-hah-ra), implying dryness, barrenness, and emptiness. In Urdu, it is adapted as 'rigistan', combining 'rig' (sand) and 'stan' (place). The distinction from other terms is that 'sahra' specifically refers to arid, sandy desert regions, while 'fala' (فلاحة) generally means open, desolate land, and 'bar' (بر) can mean land or country.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَضَرَبَ لَهُم مَّثَلًا وَذَكَرَ أَجَلًا» (الذاریات / ۵۱)\nTranslation: And Allah gave them a parable and reminded them of a fixed time.\n\nAnd another example:\n«كَأَنَّهُمۡ حُمُرٞ مُّسۡتَنۡفِرَةٞ فَرَّتۡ مِّنۡ قَسۡوَرَةِۭ» (المعارج / ۷۰)\nTranslation: As if they were runaway wild donkeys."
    }
  ],
  "825": [
    {
      "id": 3572,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Samandar - Samandar",
      "hw": "سمندر",
      "s": "Samandar refers to a vast body of water covering most of the Earth's surface.",
      "d": "The root of 'samandar' in Arabic is س-م-ن-د (s-m-n-d). Lexicons define it as a vast body of water. Its literal meaning is 'chest' or 'spread-out water', encompassing both expanse and depth. Unlike terms like 'bahr', 'samandar' conveys a sense of vastness and boundlessness. The word 'samandar' is derived from Arabic and used similarly in Urdu.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالہٗ أَنۢبَتَكُمۡ مِّنَ الۡأَرۡضِ نَبَاتًا ۙ-ثُمَّ يُعِیدُكُمۡ فِیۡهَا وَيُخۡرِجُكُمۡ إِخۡرَاجًا» (نوح / ۷۱)\nTranslation: And Allah has caused you to grow from the earth like a growth; then He will return you into it and bring you forth again.\n\nAnd another example:\n«وَسَخَّرَ لَكُمُ الۡفُلۡكَ لِتَجۡرِیَ فِیۡہِ بِأَمۡرِہٖ وَالۡسُّفُنَ فِیۡ الۡبَحۡرِ بِأَمۡرِہٖ» (ابرہیم / ۳۲)\nTranslation: And He has subjected for you the ships that they may sail upon the sea by His command, and the ships that run upon the sea by His command.\n\nHere, 'samandar' denotes the entire vastness of the sea."
    },
    {
      "id": 3573,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Samandar - Bahr",
      "hw": "سمندر",
      "s": "Bahr refers to a sea or ocean.",
      "d": "The plural of 'bahr' is 'abhar'. Lexicographers define 'bahr' as a sea or ocean. In modern usage, 'bahr' refers to a large body of water collected in a low-lying area, constantly receiving water from all sides. If the water is small, it's a 'johar' (pool); larger, a 'jheel' (lake); even larger, a 'buheerah' (small sea); and very large, a 'bahr'. The Quran uses 'bahr' for both 'buheerah' and 'bahr'.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِذۡ فَرَقۡنَا بِکُمُ الۡبَحۡرَ فَاَنۡجَیۡنٰکُمۡ وَ اَغۡرَقۡنَاۤ اٰلَ فِرۡعَوۡنَ» (2/50)\nTranslation: And [remember] when We parted the sea for you and saved you and drowned the people of Pharaoh.\n\nHistorical research suggests this 'bahr' was the Red Sea.\n\nWater in a sea or ocean can sometimes be stagnant. Often, winds create waves and keep it moving, though not necessarily toward a low area. Within a collected body of water, rivers flow downstream, and sometimes two rivers flow together—one warm, one cold; or one fresh, one salty—without mixing, contrary to natural properties, all under Allah's perfect power. Referring to this, the Quran states:\n«مَرَجَ  الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ یَلۡتَقِیٰنِ بَیۡنَہُمَا بَرۡزَخٌ  لَّا  یَبۡغِیٰنِ» (55/19,20)\nTranslation: He released the two seas, meeting [side by side]; between them is a barrier so neither of them transgresses.\n\nIn this verse, 'bahr' is used for rivers that flow into the sea. Hence, such rivers are within the sea."
    }
  ],
  "826": [
    {
      "id": 3574,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Suraj - Suraj",
      "hw": "سورج",
      "s": "Suraj means the sun in Arabic 'shams', the source of light and life in the universe.",
      "d": "Suraj is actually a Persian/Urdu word derived from the Arabic 'shams' (شمس). Its original Arabic root is ش-م-س (sh-m-s), meaning 'to shine' or 'to be bright'. In the Quran, the phrase 'ash-shams' (ال+شمس) is used for the sun.\n\nOther Arabic synonyms include 'aftab' and 'zia', but 'shams' specifically refers to the sun as a celestial body, while 'zia' denotes general brightness.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالشَّمْسُ تَجْرِي لِمُسْتَقَرٍّ لَّهَا ۚ ذَٰلِكَ تَقْدِيرُ الْعَزِيزِ الْعَلِيمِ» (یسین / 38)\nTranslation: And the sun runs [on course] toward its stopping point. That is the determination of the Exalted in Might, the Knowing."
    },
    {
      "id": 3575,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Suraj - Aftab",
      "hw": "سورج",
      "s": "Aftab refers to the light or radiance of the sun, used in Arabic for light and brightness.",
      "d": "The linguistic root of 'aftab' is ع-ت-ب (ayn-tay-ba), meaning to emerge, appear, or spread light. This word describes the sun's light and radiance rather than the celestial body itself. In Arabic, 'shams' (ش-م-س) is the most common term for the sun, while 'aftab' emphasizes its illuminating aspect.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَآيَةٌ لَّهُمُ اللَّيْلُ نَسْلَخُ مِنْهُ النَّهَارَ فَإِذَا هُم مُّظْلِمُونَ» (الکھف / 18)\nTranslation: And a sign for them is the night; We remove from it the [light of] day, and they are in darkness.\n\nHere, 'aftab' is not explicitly mentioned, but the concept refers to the sun's light that is removed, causing darkness."
    }
  ],
  "827": [
    {
      "id": 3576,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Chand - Chand",
      "hw": "چاند",
      "s": "Chand refers to the celestial body that provides light at night and has various phases.",
      "d": "Chand is actually a Persian word used in Urdu, derived from the Arabic 'qamar' (قمر). The Arabic root is ق-م-ر (q-m-r), meaning 'to be white' or 'to shine'. In Urdu, 'chand' comes directly from Persian, while Arabic uses 'qamar'. The difference is that 'qamar' is the Arabic term found in the Quran, whereas 'chand' is the Persian-Urdu equivalent.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالْقَمَرَ قَدَّرْنَاهُ مَنَازِلَ» (یاسین / 39)\nTranslation: And the moon - We have determined it [in phases] until it returns [to its starting point]."
    },
    {
      "id": 3577,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Chand - Mah",
      "hw": "چاند",
      "s": "Mah is used in Arabic for both moon and month, associated with the lunar calendar.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of 'mah' is م-و-ه or م-ی-ه (m-w-h/m-y-h). This word carries two meanings: moon and month, as ancient Arabic months were determined by lunar cycles. In contrast, Arabic typically uses 'qamar' for moon and 'shahr' for month. In Urdu, 'chand' derives from Sanskrit 'chandra', but 'mah' is also used in Urdu to mean month.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«إِنَّ عِدَّةَ الشُّهُورِ عِندَ اللَّهِ اثْنَا عَشَرَ شَهْرًا فِي كِتَابِ اللَّهِ يَوْمَ خَلَقَ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضَ مِنْهَا أَرْبَعَةٌ حُرُمٌ» (التوبة / 36)\nTranslation: Indeed, the number of months in the sight of Allah is twelve months in the register of Allah from the day He created the heavens and the earth; of these, four are sacred."
    }
  ],
